window.ICML_PAPERS["68691"] = [{"id":"62178","en":"Towards Execution-Grounded Automated AI Research","ko":"мӢӨн–ү кё°л°ҳ(Execution-Grounded) мһҗлҸҷ AI ResearchлЎң","authors":"Chenglei Si, Zitong Yang, Yejin Choi, Emmanuel J Candes, Diyi Yang, Tatsunori Hashimoto","pos":"#1304","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=j0PagZWEFo","abs":"<p>Automated AI research holds great potential to accelerate scientific discovery.  However, current LLMs often generate plausible-looking but ineffective ideas. Execution grounding may help, but it is unclear whether automated execution is feasible and whether LLMs can learn from the execution feedback.  To investigate these, we first build an automated executor to implement ideas and launch large-scale parallel GPU experiments to verify their effectiveness. We then convert two realistic research problems -- LLM pre-training and post-training -- into execution environments and demonstrate that our automated executor can implement a large fraction of the ideas sampled from frontier LLMs. We analyze two methods to learn from the execution feedback: evolutionary search and reinforcement learning. Execution-guided evolutionary search is sample-efficient: it finds a method that significantly outperforms the GRPO baseline  on post-training, and finds a pre-training recipe that outperforms the nanoGPT baseline  on pre-training, all within just ten search epochs. Frontier LLMs often generate meaningful algorithmic ideas during search, but they tend to saturate early and only occasionally exhibit scaling trends. Reinforcement learning from execution reward, on the other hand, suffers from mode collapse. It successfully improves the average reward of the ideator model but not the upper-bound, due to models converging on simple ideas. We thoroughly analyze the executed ideas and training dynamics to facilitate future efforts.</p>","absKo":"<p>мһҗлҸҷнҷ”лҗң AI м—°кө¬лҠ” кіјн•ҷм Ғ л°ңкІ¬мқ„ к°ҖмҶҚн•  нҒ° мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ м§ҖлӢҲкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ LLMмқҖ к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•ҙ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҘј мһҗмЈј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. execution groundingмқҖ лҸ„мӣҖмқҙ лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, мһҗлҸҷнҷ”лҗң мӢӨн–үмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ңм§Җ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  LLMмқҙ execution feedbackмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§ҖлҠ” м•„м§Ғ л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, лЁјм Җ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳкі  лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ лі‘л ¬ GPU мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мӢӨн–үн•ҙ к·ё нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” мһҗлҸҷ executorлҘј кө¬м¶•н–ҲлӢӨ. ШіЩҫШі л‘җ к°Җм§Җ нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё м—°кө¬ л¬ём ңмқё LLM pre-trainingкіј post-trainingмқ„ execution environmentлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳкі , мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мһҗлҸҷ executorк°Җ frontier LLMм—җм„ң мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ң м•„мқҙл””м–ҙмқҳ мғҒлӢ№ л¶Җл¶„мқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” execution feedbackмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ л°©лІ•, мҰү evolutionary searchмҷҖ reinforcement learningмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. execution-guided evolutionary searchлҠ” sample-efficientн•ҳл©°, post-trainingм—җм„ңлҠ” GRPO baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мғҒнҡҢн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ м°ҫкі , pre-trainingм—җм„ңлҠ” nanoGPT baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳлҠ” pre-training recipeлҘј лӢЁм§Җ 10лІҲмқҳ search epoch м•Ҳм—җ м°ҫм•„лӮёлӢӨ. frontier LLMмқҖ search мӨ‘ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” algorithmic ideaлҘј мһҗмЈј мғқм„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мЎ°кё°м—җ нҸ¬нҷ”лҗҳлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ мһҲкі  scaling trendлҘј ліҙмқҙлҠ” кІҪмҡ°лҠ” л“ңл¬јлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ execution rewardлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ reinforcement learningмқҖ mode collapseлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” ideator modelмқҳ нҸүк·  rewardлҠ” м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң к°ңм„ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, лӘЁлҚёл“Өмқҙ лӢЁмҲңн•ң м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ мғҒн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқҖ к°ңм„ н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨн–үлҗң м•„мқҙл””м–ҙмҷҖ training dynamicsлҘј мІ м ҖнһҲ л¶„м„қн•ҳм—¬ н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬лҘј лҸ•кі мһҗ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64654","en":"Autoregression with Self-Token Prediction","ko":"Self-Token Predictionмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң Autoregression","authors":"Dengsheng Chen, Yangming Shi, Enhua Wu","pos":"#2815","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=LEwd3HJny8","abs":"<p>Conventional autoregressive models achieve causality through next-token prediction, but suffer from prohibitive latency and typically under-perform non-causal alternatives such as masked prediction and diffusion. We propose self-token prediction, which enables predicting a flexible number of tokens per step, and introduce AGARIC, the first spatially causal image generator built on this paradigm. AGARIC delivers markedly faster inference and consistently outperforms prior autoregressive baselines, matching the performance of state-of-the-art non-causal models. Our findings point to self-token prediction as a key step toward unified and efficient multimodal autoregressive modeling.</p>","absKo":"<p>кё°мЎҙ autoregressive modelsлҠ” next-token predictionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ causalityлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ нҒ° latencyлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ҳкі  masked prediction л°Ҹ diffusion к°ҷмқҖ non-causal alternativesліҙлӢӨ лҢҖмІҙлЎң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•ң stepл§ҲлӢӨ мң м—°н•ң к°ңмҲҳмқҳ tokenмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” self-token predictionмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳкі , мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„ мң„м—җ кө¬м¶•н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ spatially causal image generatorмқё AGARICлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. AGARICлҠ” нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” л№ лҘё inferenceлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, мқҙм „ autoregressive baselinesлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мғҒнҡҢн•ҳкі , state-of-the-art non-causal modelsмҷҖ л§һлЁ№лҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” self-token predictionмқҙ нҶөн•©м Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё multimodal autoregressive modelingмқ„ н–Ҙн•ң н•өмӢ¬ лӢЁкі„мһ„мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67212","en":"Position: The Case for Theory-Level Autoformalization","ko":"Position: Theory-Level Autoformalizationм—җ лҢҖн•ң л…јкұ°","authors":"Marcus Min, Deyuan Mike He, Zhaoyu Li, Zixuan Yi, Sharad Malik, Aarti Gupta, Xujie Si, Osbert Bastani","pos":"#4417","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=BoteCHEFUr","abs":"<p>Autoformalization, translating informal natural language into formal, machine-verifiable languages, has been framed as a tool to generate training data for neural theorem provers, with most work focusing on individual statements. This position paper argues for theory-level autoformalization: formalizing complete theories, including axioms, definitions, theorems, proofs, tactics, and their inter-dependencies as structured libraries. We examine the significance of this shift, address 3 alternative views, identify 5 open challenges, and propose 3 promising paths forward.</p>","absKo":"<p>л№„нҳ•мӢқм Ғ мһҗм—°м–ҙлҘј нҳ•мӢқм Ғмқҙкі  кё°кі„ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м–ём–ҙлЎң мҳ®кё°лҠ” autoformalizationмқҖ neural theorem proverлҘј мң„н•ң н•ҷмҠө лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸ„кө¬лЎң н”„л Ҳмқҙл°Қлҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”мңјл©°, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ м—°кө¬лҠ” к°ңлі„ statementм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”м—ҲлӢӨ. ліё нҸ¬м§Җм…ҳ нҺҳмқҙнҚјлҠ” кіөлҰ¬, м •мқҳ, м •лҰ¬, мҰқлӘ…, tactic, к·ёлҰ¬кі  к·ё мғҒнҳё мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң libraryлЎң нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” theory-level autoformalizationмқ„ мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м „нҷҳмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ кІҖнҶ н•ҳкі , м„ё к°Җм§Җ лҢҖм•Ҳм Ғ кҙҖм җмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁл©°, лӢӨм„Ҝ к°Җм§Җ м—ҙлҰ° кіјм ңлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , м„ё к°Җм§Җ мң л§қн•ң н–Ҙнӣ„ кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61162","en":"Group Cognition Learning: Making Everything Better Through Controlled Two-Stage Agents Collaboration","ko":"Group Cognition Learning: м ңм–ҙлҗң 2лӢЁкі„ Agent нҳ‘м—…мңјлЎң лӘЁл“  кІғмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳкё°","authors":"Chunlei Meng, Pengbin Feng, Rong Fu, Hoi Leong Lee, Xiaojing Du, Yuying Li, Zeyu Zhang, Weilin Zhou, Chun Ouyang, Zhongxue Gan","pos":"#4625","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=t9aUiZsQgg","abs":"<p>Centralized multimodal learning commonly compresses language, acoustic, and visual signals into a single fused representation for prediction. While effective, this paradigm suffers from two limitations: modality dominance, where optimization gravitates towards the path of least resistance, ignoring weaker but informative modalities, and spurious modality coupling, where models overfit to incidental cross-modal correlations. To address these, we propose \\textbf{Group Cognition Learning (GCL)}, a governed collaboration paradigm that applies a two-stage protocol after modality-specific encoding. In Stage 1 (Selective Interaction), a Routing Agent proposes directed interaction routes, and an Auditing Agent assigns sample-wise gates to emphasize exchanges that yield positive marginal predictive gain while suppressing redundant coupling. In Stage 2 (Consensus Formation), a Public-Factor Agent maintains an explicit shared factor, and an Aggregation Agent produces the final prediction through contribution-aware weighting while keeping each modality representation as a specialization channel. Extensive experiments on CMU-MOSI, CMU-MOSEI, and MIntRec demonstrate that GCL mitigates dominance and coupling, establishing state-of-the-art results across both regression and classification benchmarks. Analysis experiments further demonstrate the effectiveness of the design.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӨ‘м•ҷм§‘мӨ‘мӢқ multimodal learningмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м–ём–ҙ, мқҢн–Ҙ, мӢңк°Ғ мӢ нҳёлҘј мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мң„н•ң лӢЁмқј fused representationмңјлЎң м••м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң paradigmмқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•ңкі„лҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” modality dominanceлЎң, мөңм Ғнҷ”к°Җ м Җн•ӯмқҙ к°ҖмһҘ м ҒмқҖ кІҪлЎңлЎң м№ҳмҡ°м№ҳл©ҙм„ң м•Ҫн•ҳм§Җл§Ң мң мҡ©н•ң modalityлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” spurious modality couplingмңјлЎң, лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мҡ°м—°н•ң cross-modal correlationм—җ кіјм Ғн•©н•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{Group Cognition Learning (GCL)}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” modality-specific encoding мқҙнӣ„ л‘җ лӢЁкі„ protocolмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” governed collaboration paradigmмқҙлӢӨ. Stage 1(Selective Interaction)м—җм„ңлҠ” Routing Agentк°Җ л°©н–Ҙм„ұмқҙ мһҲлҠ” interaction routeлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳкі , Auditing Agentк°Җ sample-wise gateлҘј н• лӢ№н•ҳм—¬ кёҚм •м Ғмқё marginal predictive gainмқ„ мЈјлҠ” көҗнҷҳмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ мӨ‘ліөлҗң couplingмқ„ м–өм ңн•ңлӢӨ. Stage 2(Consensus Formation)м—җм„ңлҠ” Public-Factor Agentк°Җ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё shared factorлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳкі , Aggregation Agentк°Җ к°Ғ modality representationмқ„ specialization channelлЎң мң м§Җн•ң мұ„ contribution-aware weightingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мөңмў… мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. CMU-MOSI, CMU-MOSEI, MIntRecм—җм„ңмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ GCLмқҙ dominanceмҷҖ couplingмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳм—¬ regressionкіј classification benchmark лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң SOTA кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. л¶„м„қ мӢӨн—ҳ лҳҗн•ң мқҙ м„Өкі„мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61960","en":"FIRE: Learning to Navigate and Act on Real-World Files via Stateful Reinforcement Learning","ko":"FIRE: мғҒнғң кё°л°ҳ к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөмңјлЎң нҳ„мӢӨ м„ёкі„ нҢҢмқј нғҗмғүВ·н–үлҸҷ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Jingyuan Ma, Zheng Li, Rui Li, Siyao Song, Ying Zeng, MINGHAO LI, Zhifang Sui","pos":"#1905","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lHVxzhqYai","abs":"<p>Large language models still struggle to reliably answer questions grounded in real-world files like spreadsheets and slides, where evidence is scattered across irregular layouts and heterogeneous formats. We address this by formalizing File Reasoning, a setting where agents must interact directly with unprocessed files (XLSX, PDF, DOCX, PPTX) within a persistent sandbox. To support this, we introduce a unified data pipeline and release a high-difficulty benchmark of over 400 verifiable tasks that preserve native file structure. Furthermore, we propose a reinforcement learning framework grounded in stateful file execution. We train and release <strong>FIRE</strong> (<strong>F</strong>ile <strong>I</strong>nteractive <strong>R</strong>easoning <strong>E</strong>xpert), a family of models that learn to optimize long-horizon planning using genuine execution feedback from the environment. Unlike stateless tool-use methods, our approach enables agents to recover from errors and adapt to structural ambiguities. Empirical results show that Qwen3-32B-FIRE achieves the strongest performance among open-source models under identical execution constraints.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language modelsлҠ” spreadsheetмҷҖ slidesмІҳлҹј мӢӨм ң нҢҢмқјм—җ к·јкұ°н•ң м§Ҳл¬ём—җ м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң лӢөн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҢҢмқјм—җм„ңлҠ” мҰқкұ°к°Җ л¶Ҳк·ңм№ҷн•ң л Ҳмқҙм•„мӣғкіј мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё нҳ•мӢқ м „л°ҳм—җ нқ©м–ҙм ё мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ File Reasoningмқ„ м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. File ReasoningмқҖ agentк°Җ persistent sandbox м•Ҳм—җм„ң м „мІҳлҰ¬лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ нҢҢмқј(XLSX, PDF, DOCX, PPTX)кіј м§Ғм ‘ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” м„Өм •мқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ нҶөн•© data pipelineмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , мӣҗлһҳмқҳ file structureлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” 400к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кі лӮңлҸ„ taskлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ benchmarkлҘј кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. лӮҳм•„к°Җ stateful file executionм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң reinforcement learning frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҷҳкІҪмңјлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ мӢӨм ң execution feedbackмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ long-horizon planningмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лӘЁлҚёкө°мқё <strong>FIRE</strong> (<strong>F</strong>ile <strong>I</strong>nteractive <strong>R</strong>easoning <strong>E</strong>xpert)лҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. stateless tool-use methodмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ agentк°Җ мҳӨлҘҳм—җм„ң ліөкө¬н•ҳкі  кө¬мЎ°м Ғ лӘЁнҳём„ұм—җ м Ғмқ‘н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј Qwen3-32B-FIREлҠ” лҸҷмқјн•ң execution constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң open-source model мӨ‘ к°ҖмһҘ к°•н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64977","en":"Physics-Informed Self-Supervised Learning on  Efficient Electron-Density Images for Organic Material Property Prediction","ko":"мң кё° мһ¬лЈҢ л¬јм„ұ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ м „мһҗ л°ҖлҸ„ мқҙлҜём§Җ кё°л°ҳ Physics-Informed мһҗкё° м§ҖлҸ„ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Zhixiang Cheng, Hongxin Xiang, Mingquan Liu, Tengfei Ma, Yingzhuo Tu, Wenjie Du, Bosheng Song, Yiping Liu, xiangxiang Zeng","pos":"#801","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=IBDryWLx87","abs":"Precise property prediction of organic materials is pivotal for next-generation electronic and energy devices. In density functional theory (DFT), the electron density (ED) serves as the fundamental determinant of material properties. Yet, establishing it as an input modality for material property prediction has been impeded by two practical barriers: scarce large-scale ED data and the enormous computational complexity of ED representation. To bridge these gaps, we introduce VisionED, an efficient physics-informed model pre-trained on electron-density images. We curate a dataset of 2 million molecules and represent ED as multi-shot images that efficiently encode both geometric and electronic structure. VisionED is then pre-trained on 12 million multi-shot ED images via cross-scale, physics-informed pretext tasks. Empirical evaluations on photovoltaic and organic chromophore datasets show that VisionED outperforms state-of-the-art baselines by up to 27.0\\%, exhibiting superior robustness under distribution shifts and data scarcity. Notably, the model generalizes to unseen device-scale applications, successfully recovering experimental trends and mixing-ratio effects in ternary blends with an average accuracy of 93\\%. Moreover, relative to the previous ED point cloud, the ED image improves performance by 26.2\\% with 2.6$\\times$ fewer memory and 4.6$\\times$ lower time. The code and data are available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/VisionED-AC1B.","absKo":"мң кё° мһ¬лЈҢмқҳ м •л°Җн•ң property predictionмқҖ м°Ём„ёлҢҖ м „мһҗ л°Ҹ м—җл„Ҳм§Җ л””л°”мқҙмҠӨм—җ л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. density functional theory(DFT)м—җм„ң electron density(ED)лҠ” л¬јм§Ҳ нҠ№м„ұмқ„ кІ°м •н•ҳлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё ліҖмҲҳлЎң мһ‘мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мһ¬лЈҢ property predictionмқҳ мһ…л Ҙ modalityлЎң мқҙлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ ED лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ нқ¬мҶҢм„ұкіј ED н‘ңнҳ„мқҳ л§үлҢҖн•ң кі„мӮ° ліөмһЎм„ұмқҙлқјлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ мһҘлІҪм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңм•Ҫлҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” electron-density imageлЎң мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөлҗң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё physics-informed лӘЁлҚёмқё VisionEDлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 200л§Ң к°ң л¶„мһҗмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳкі , кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ кө¬мЎ°мҷҖ м „мһҗ кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” multi-shot imageлЎң EDлҘј н‘ңнҳ„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ VisionEDлҠ” cross-scale, physics-informed pretext taskлҘј нҶөн•ҙ 1200л§Ң к°ңмқҳ multi-shot ED imageлЎң мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөлҗңлӢӨ. photovoltaic л°Ҹ organic chromophore лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨмҰқ нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң VisionEDлҠ” state-of-the-art baselineліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ 27.0\\% мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖмңјл©°, distribution shiftмҷҖ лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶ҖмЎұ мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ңлҸ„ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң robustnessлҘј лӮҳнғҖлғҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мқҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң device-scale applicationмңјлЎңлҸ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ, ternary blendм—җм„ң мӢӨн—ҳм Ғ м¶”м„ёмҷҖ mixing-ratio effectлҘј нҸүк·  м •нҷ•лҸ„ 93\\%лЎң м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң ліөмӣҗн–ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мқҙм „мқҳ ED point cloudмҷҖ л№„көҗн•ҙ, ED imageлҠ” л©”лӘЁлҰ¬лҠ” 2.6$\\times$ лҚ” м ҒкІҢ, мӢңк°„мқҖ 4.6$\\times$ лҚ” м ҒкІҢ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ 26.2\\% н–ҘмғҒмӢңмј°лӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/VisionED-AC1B м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64584","en":"Adaptive Physics Transformer with Fused Global-Local Attention for Subsurface Energy Systems","ko":"м§Җн•ҳ м—җл„Ҳм§Җ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ мң„н•ң Fused Global-Local Attention м Ғмқ‘м Ғ Physics Transformer","authors":"Xin Ju, Hadrian Fung, Yuyan Zhang, Carl Jacquemyn, Matthew Jackson, Randolph Settgast, Sally Benson, Gege Wen","pos":"#1014","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=LxNq36mefe","abs":"The Earth's subsurface is a cornerstone of modern society, providing essential energy resources like hydrocarbons, geothermal, and minerals while serving as the primary reservoir for $CO_2$ sequestration. However, full physics numerical simulations of these systems are notoriously computationally expensive due to geological heterogeneity, high resolution requirements, and the tight coupling of physical processes with distinct propagation time scales. Here we propose the Adaptive Physics Transformer (APT), a geometry-, mesh-, and physics-agnostic neural operator that explicitly addresses these challenges. APT fuses a graph-based encoder to extract high-resolution local heterogeneous features with a global attention mechanism to resolve long-range physical impacts. Our results demonstrate that APT outperforms state-of-the-art architectures in subsurface tasks across both regular and irregular grids with robust super-resolution capabilities. Notably, APT is the first architecture that directly learns from adaptive mesh refinement simulations. We also demonstrate APT's capability for cross-dataset learning, positioning it as a robust and scalable backbone for large-scale subsurface foundation model development.","absKo":"м§Җкө¬мқҳ м§Җн•ҳ кө¬мЎ°лҠ” нҳ„лҢҖ мӮ¬нҡҢмқҳ мҙҲм„қмңјлЎңм„ң, нғ„нҷ”мҲҳмҶҢ, м§Җм—ҙ, кҙ‘л¬јкіј к°ҷмқҖ н•„мҲҳ м—җл„Ҳм§Җ мһҗмӣҗмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” н•ңнҺё $CO_2$ м ҖмһҘмқҳ мЈјмҡ” м ҖмһҘмҶҢ м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҳ full physics numerical simulationsлҠ” м§Җм§Ҳн•ҷм Ғ мқҙм§Ҳм„ұ, лҶ’мқҖ н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ мҡ”кө¬мӮ¬н•ӯ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё м „нҢҢ мӢңк°„ мІҷлҸ„лҘј к°–лҠ” л¬јлҰ¬ кіјм •л“Өмқҳ к°•н•ң кІ°н•© л•Ңл¬ём—җ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ м•…лӘ… лҶ’кІҢ нҒ¬лӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңл“Өмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” geometry-, mesh-, physics-agnostic neural operatorмқё Adaptive Physics Transformer (APT)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. APTлҠ” graph-based encoderлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҙ кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ local heterogeneous featuresлҘј м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкі , global attention mechanismмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ н•ҙмҶҢн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” APTк°Җ regular л°Ҹ irregular grid лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң subsurface task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ state-of-the-art architecturesлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, к°•кұҙн•ң super-resolution лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ APTлҠ” adaptive mesh refinement simulationsлЎңл¶Җн„° м§Ғм ‘ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ architectureмқҙлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” APTмқҳ cross-dataset learning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлҘј лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ subsurface foundation model к°ңл°ңмқ„ мң„н•ң к°•кұҙн•ҳкі  нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң backboneмңјлЎң мң„м№ҳмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ."},{"id":"63674","en":"LatentChem: From Textual CoT to Latent Thinking in Chemical Reasoning","ko":"LatentChem: нҷ”н•ҷ м¶”лЎ м—җм„ң textual CoTм—җм„ң latent thinkingмңјлЎң","authors":"Xinwu Ye, Yicheng Mao, Jia Zhang, Yimeng (Yoyo) Liu, Hao Li, Fang Wu, Zhiwei Li, Yuxuan Liao, Zehong Wang, Zhiyuan Liu, Zhenfei Yin, Li Yuan, Phil Torr, Huan Sun, xiangxiang Zeng, Mengdi Wang, Le Cong, Shenghua Gao, Robert Tang","pos":"#1711","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ul6hU6WkDL","abs":"Current chemical large language models (LLMs) predominantly rely on explicit Chain-of-Thought (CoT) to solve complex reasoning problems. However, forcing nonverbal tacit chemical logic into discrete natural language imposes a fundamental ``modality mismatch,'' creating an artificial bottleneck for reasoning. To investigate this, we introduce LatentChem, a reasoning interface that decouples chemical logic from linguistic generation, enabling the model to process information via continuous thought vectors and dynamic perception. Our investigation reveals a pivotal emergent behavior: spontaneous internalization. When optimized for task success, the model voluntarily abandons verbose textual derivations in favor of implicit latent computation, suggesting that it autonomously identifies the continuous manifold as a more native substrate for chemical logic. This paradigm shift also proves to be a superior computational strategy: LatentChem achieves a 59.88\\% non-tie win rate against the strong CoT baseline on the rigorous ChemCoTBench, while delivering a broad 10.84$\\times$ average speedup across all evaluated benchmarks. This empirically validates that chemical logic is inherently better modeled by continuous latent dynamics than by linear linguistic approximations.","absKo":"нҳ„мһ¬ chemical large language model(LLM)л“ӨмқҖ ліөмһЎн•ң м¶”лЎ  л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мЈјлЎң explicit Chain-of-Thought(CoT)м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ л№„м–ём–ҙм Ғ tacit chemical logicмқ„ мқҙмӮ°м Ғмқё мһҗм—°м–ҙлЎң к°•м ң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ к·јліём Ғмқё ``modality mismatch''лҘј мң л°ңн•ҳм—¬ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң мқёмң„м Ғмқё лі‘лӘ©мқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҷ”н•ҷм Ғ л…јлҰ¬лҘј м–ём–ҙ мғқм„ұмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” reasoning interfaceмқё LatentChemмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ continuous thought vectorмҷҖ dynamic perceptionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м •ліҙлҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м—°кө¬лҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң emergent behaviorмқё spontaneous internalizationмқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮёлӢӨ. task successлҘј мң„н•ҙ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗ  л•Ң, лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мһҘнҷ©н•ң н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мң лҸ„ кіјм •мқ„ мһҗл°ңм ҒмңјлЎң лІ„лҰ¬кі  implicit latent computationмқ„ нғқн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” нҷ”н•ҷм Ғ л…јлҰ¬лҘј мң„н•ң лҚ” мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ substrateлЎң continuous manifoldлҘј мһҗмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң мӢқлі„н•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„ м „нҷҳмқҖ кі„мӮ° м „лһө мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. LatentChemмқҖ м—„кІ©н•ң ChemCoTBenchм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң CoT baselineмқ„ мғҒлҢҖлЎң 59.88%мқҳ non-tie win rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” н•ңнҺё, нҸүк°Җн•ң лӘЁл“  benchmarkм—җм„ң нҸүк·  10.84Г—мқҳ нҸӯл„“мқҖ мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” нҷ”н•ҷм Ғ л…јлҰ¬к°Җ м„ нҳ•м Ғ м–ём–ҙ к·јмӮ¬ліҙлӢӨ continuous latent dynamicsлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§ҒлҗҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лҚ” м Ғн•©н•Ёмқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64931","en":"PnP-Corrector: A Universal Correction Framework for Coupled Spatiotemporal Forecasting","ko":"PnP-Corrector: кІ°н•©лҗң мӢңкіөк°„ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мң„н•ң ліҙнҺём Ғ ліҙм • н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Yuan Gao, Fan Xu, Hao Wu, Yuxu Lu, Penghao Zhao, Fan Zhang, Hao Jia, Yuxuan Liang, Ruijian Gou, Qingsong Wen, Xian Wu, Xiaomeng Huang","pos":"#3904","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=IYtXaU7N6B","abs":"<p>Coupled spatiotemporal forecasting is important for predicting the future evolution of multiple interacting dynamical systems, such as in climate models. However, existing methods are severely constrained by the persistent bottleneck of compounding errors. In coupled systems, errors from each subsystem simulator propagate and amplify one another, a phenomenon we term Reciprocal Error Amplification leading to a rapid collapse of long-range predictions. To address this challenge, we propose a universal framework called PnP-Corrector (Plug-and-Play Corrector). The core idea of our framework is to decouple the physical simulation from the error correction process: it freezes pre-trained physics simulation engines and exclusively trains a lightweight correction agent to proactively counteract the systematic biases emerging from the coupled system. Furthermore, we design an efficient predictive model architecture, DSLCast, to serve as the backbone of this framework. Extensive experiments demonstrate that our method significantly enhances the long-term stability and accuracy of coupled forecasting systems. For instance, in the challenging task of a 300-day global ocean-atmosphere coupled forecast, our PnP-Corrector framework reduces the prediction error of the baseline model by 28% and surpasses state-of-the-art models on several key metrics. Codes link: \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Anonymous_PnP-E365}.</p>","absKo":"<p>кІ°н•©лҗң spatiotemporal forecastingмқҖ climate modelкіј к°ҷмқҙ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ dynamical systemмқҳ лҜёлһҳ м§„нҷ”лҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ лҲ„м Ғ мҳӨм°ЁлқјлҠ” м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё лі‘лӘ©мңјлЎң мқён•ҙ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ м ңм•ҪлҗңлӢӨ. кІ°н•© мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ңлҠ” к°Ғ subsystem simulatorм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ң мҳӨм°Ёк°Җ м„ңлЎң м „нҢҢлҗҳкі  мҰқнҸӯлҗҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ Reciprocal Error Amplificationмқҙлқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мһҘкё° мҳҲмёЎмқҳ кёүкІ©н•ң л¶•кҙҙлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙ кіјм ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PnP-Corrector(Plug-and-Play Corrector)лқјлҠ” лІ”мҡ© н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҠ” л¬јлҰ¬ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳкіј мҳӨм°Ё ліҙм • кіјм •мқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҰү, мӮ¬м „ н•ҷмҠөлҗң physics simulation engineмқҖ кі м •н•ҳкі , кІ°н•© мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” мІҙкі„м Ғ biasм—җ м„ м ңм ҒмңјлЎң лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” кІҪлҹү correction agentл§Ң н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқҳ backboneмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё predictive model architectureмқё DSLCastлҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬ л°©лІ•мқҙ кІ°н•© мҳҲмёЎ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҳ мһҘкё° м•Ҳм •м„ұкіј м •нҷ•м„ұмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, 300мқј global ocean-atmosphere coupled forecastлқјлҠ” м–ҙл Өмҡҙ кіјм ңм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬ PnP-Corrector н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” baseline modelмқҳ prediction errorлҘј 28% мӨ„мқҙкі , м—¬лҹ¬ н•өмӢ¬ м§Җн‘ңм—җм„ң state-of-the-art лӘЁлҚёмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. Codes link: \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Anonymous_PnP-E365}.</p>"},{"id":"61110","en":"HVR-Met: A Hypothesis-Verification-Replaning Agentic System for Extreme Weather Diagnosis","ko":"HVR-Met: к·№н•ң кё°мғҒ м§„лӢЁмқ„ мң„н•ң Hypothesis-Verification-Replanning Agentic System","authors":"Shuo Tang, Jiadong Zhang, Jian Xu, Gengxian Zhou, Qizhao Jin, Qinxuan Wang, Yi Hu, Ning Hu, Hongchang Ren, Lingli He, Jiaolan Fu, Jingtao Ding, Shiming Xiang, Cheng-Lin Liu","pos":"#402","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tb2aPbeg86","abs":"<p>While deep learning-based weather forecasting paradigms have made significant strides, addressing extreme weather diagnostics remains a formidable challenge. This gap exists primarily because the diagnostic process demands sophisticated multi-step logical reasoning, dynamic tool invocation, and expert-level prior judgment. Although agents possess inherent advantages in task decomposition and autonomous execution, current architectures are still hampered by critical bottlenecks: inadequate expert knowledge integration, a lack of professional-grade iterative reasoning loops, and the absence of fine-grained validation and evaluation systems for complex workflows under extreme conditions. To this end, we propose HVR-MetпјҢa multi-agent meteorological diagnostic system characterized by the deep integration of expert knowledge. Its central innovation is the ``Hypothesis-Verification-Replanning'' closed-loop mechanism, which facilitates sophisticated iterative reasoning for anomalous meteorological signals during extreme weather events. To bridge gaps within existing evaluation frameworks, we further introduce a novel benchmark focused on atomic-level subtasks. Experimental evidence demonstrates that the system excels in complex diagnostic scenarios.</p>","absKo":"<p>л”Ҙлҹ¬лӢқ кё°л°ҳ weather forecasting нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙ нҒ° м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈЁм—ҲмқҢм—җлҸ„, extreme weather diagnosticsлҘј лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ л§Өмҡ° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқҖ мЈјлЎң diagnostic processк°Җ м •көҗн•ң multi-step logical reasoning, dynamic tool invocation, к·ёлҰ¬кі  expert-level prior judgmentлҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. agentsлҠ” task decompositionкіј autonomous executionм—җм„ң ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё мһҘм җмқ„ м§ҖлӢҲм§Җл§Ң, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ architecturesлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң лі‘лӘ©м—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңм•Ҫл°ӣкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мҰү, л¶ҖмЎұн•ң expert knowledge integration, м „л¬ё мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ iterative reasoning loop л¶Җмһ¬, к·ёлҰ¬кі  extreme conditions н•ҳмқҳ ліөмһЎн•ң workflowsлҘј мң„н•ң fine-grained validation л°Ҹ evaluation systemмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬к°Җ к·ёкІғмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” expert knowledgeмқҳ к№ҠмқҖ нҶөн•©мқ„ нҠ№м§•мңјлЎң н•ҳлҠ” multi-agent meteorological diagnostic systemмқё HVR-Metмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ нҳҒмӢ мқҖ ``Hypothesis-Verification-Replanning'' closed-loop mechanismмңјлЎң, мқҙлҠ” extreme weather events лҸҷм•Ҳмқҳ anomalous meteorological signalsм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м •көҗн•ң iterative reasoningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ evaluation frameworkмқҳ кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” atomic-level subtasksм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ benchmarkлҸ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм Ғ мҰқкұ°лҠ” мқҙ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҙ ліөмһЎн•ң diagnostic scenarioм—җм„ң лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65039","en":"Benchmarking Physics-Informed Time-Series Models for Operational Global Station Weather Forecasting","ko":"мҡҙмҳҒ м „м§Җкө¬ кҙҖмёЎмҶҢ кё°мғҒ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мң„н•ң Physics-Informed мӢңкі„м—ҙ лӘЁлҚё лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№","authors":"Tao Han, Zhibin Wen, Zhenghao Chen, Dazhao Du, Song Guo, LEI BAI","pos":"#503","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HTlNhKxcrc","abs":"<p>The development of Time-Series Forecasting (TSF) models is often constrained by the lack of comprehensive datasets, especially in Global Station Weather Forecasting (GSWF), where existing datasets are small, temporally short, and spatially sparse. To address this, we introduce WEATHER-5K, a large-scale observational weather dataset that better reflects real-world conditions, supporting improved model training and evaluation. While recent TSF methods perform well on benchmarks, they lag behind operational Numerical Weather Prediction systems in capturing complex weather dynamics and extreme events. We propose PhysicsFormer, a physics-informed forecasting model combining a dynamic core with a Transformer residual to predict future weather states. Physical consistency is enforced via pressureвҖ“wind alignment and energy-aware smoothness losses, ensuring plausible dynamics while capturing complex temporal patterns. We benchmark PhysicsFormer and other TSF models against operational systems across several weather variables, extreme event prediction, and model complexity, providing a comprehensive assessment of the gap between academic TSF models and operational forecasting. The dataset and benchmark implementation are available at: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/WEATHER-5K-BF05.</p>","absKo":"<p>Time-Series Forecasting(TSF) modelмқҳ к°ңл°ңмқҖ мў…мў… нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё datasetмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңм•Ҫлҗҳл©°, нҠ№нһҲ кё°мЎҙ datasetмқҙ мһ‘кі , мӢңк°„м ҒмңјлЎң м§§мңјл©°, кіөк°„м ҒмңјлЎң нқ¬мҶҢн•ң Global Station Weather Forecasting(GSWF)м—җм„ңлҠ” к·ё л¬ём ңк°Җ л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„лӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„ мЎ°кұҙмқ„ лҚ” мһҳ л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ кҙҖмёЎ weather datasetмқё WEATHER-5KлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” н–ҘмғҒлҗң model н•ҷмҠөкіј нҸүк°ҖлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј TSF methodлҠ” benchmarkм—җм„ң мўӢмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, ліөмһЎн•ң weather dynamicsмҷҖ extreme eventлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м„ңлҠ” operational Numerical Weather Prediction systemм—җ л’ӨмІҳм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” dynamic coreмҷҖ Transformer residualмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ҙ future weather stateлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” physics-informed forecasting model PhysicsFormerлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҖ pressure-wind alignmentмҷҖ energy-aware smoothness lossлҘј нҶөн•ҙ к°•м ңлҗҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ ліөмһЎн•ң temporal patternмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нғҖлӢ№н•ң dynamicsлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ weather variable, extreme event prediction, к·ёлҰ¬кі  model complexity м „л°ҳм—җм„ң PhysicsFormerмҷҖ лӢӨлҘё TSF modelмқ„ operational systemкіј л№„көҗн•ҳм—¬ benchmarkн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, academic TSF modelкіј operational forecasting мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ кІ©м°ЁлҘј мў…н•©м ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. datasetкіј benchmark кө¬нҳ„мқҖ лӢӨмқҢм—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/WEATHER-5K-BF05.</p>"},{"id":"60678","en":"Physics-Informed Residual Flows","ko":"л¬јлҰ¬ м •ліҙ кё°л°ҳ Residual Flow","authors":"Jephte Abijuru, Mayank Kumar Nagda, Phil Sidney Ostheimer, Sebastian Vollmer, Marius Kloft, Sophie Fellenz","pos":"#800","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xhZP2hihUq","abs":"<p>Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs) embed physical laws into deep learning models. However, conventional PINNs often suffer from failure modes leading to inaccurate solutions. We trace these failure modes to two structural pathologies: gradient shattering, where gradients degrade with depth and provide little training signal, and flow mismatch, where training pushes predictions along trajectories that diverge from the PDE solution path. We introduce ResPINNs, which reformulate PINNs as residual flows, networks that iteratively refine their own predictions through explicit corrective steps, in the spirit of classical iterative solvers. Our analysis shows that this design mitigates both pathologies by keeping updates aligned with descent and by preserving informative gradients across depth. Extensive experiments on PDE benchmarks confirm that ResPINNs achieve higher accuracy with substantially fewer parameters than conventional architectures.</p>","absKo":"<p>Physics-Informed Neural Networks (PINNs)мқҖ л¬јлҰ¬ лІ•м№ҷмқ„ deep learning modelм—җ лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ м „нҶөм Ғмқё PINNмқҖ мў…мў… м •нҷ•н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ н•ҙлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” failure modeлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң failure modeлҘј л‘җ к°Җм§Җ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ лі‘лҰ¬лЎң м¶”м Ғн•ңлӢӨ: gradient shattering, мҰү к№Ҡмқҙк°Җ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ gradientк°Җ м•Ҫнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ н•ҷмҠө мӢ нҳёлҘј кұ°мқҳ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  flow mismatch, мҰү н•ҷмҠөмқҙ predictionмқ„ PDE н•ҙ кІҪлЎңмҷҖ м–ҙкёӢлӮҳлҠ” trajectoryлҘј л”°лқј мқҙлҸҷмӢңнӮӨлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PINNмқ„ residual flowлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ң ResPINNsлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кі м „м Ғмқё iterative solverмқҳ м •мӢ м—җ л”°лқј, лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё corrective stepмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мһҗмӢ мқҳ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң м •көҗнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” networkмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙ м„Өкі„к°Җ updateлҘј descentмҷҖ м •л ¬лҗң мғҒнғңлЎң мң м§Җн•ҳкі , к№Ҡмқҙм—җ кұёміҗ м •ліҙк°Җ н’Қл¶Җн•ң gradientлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ л‘җ лі‘лҰ¬лҘј лӘЁл‘җ мҷ„нҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. PDE benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ ResPINNsк°Җ кё°мЎҙ architectureліҙлӢӨ нӣЁм”¬ м ҒмқҖ parameterлЎң лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ accuracyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65321","en":"Rethink the Role of Neural Decoders in Quantum Error Correction","ko":"м–‘мһҗ мҳӨлҘҳ м •м •м—җм„ң мӢ кІҪ л””мҪ”лҚ”мқҳ м—ӯн•  мһ¬кі ","authors":"Ge Yan, SHANCHUAN LI, Yuxuan Du","pos":"#802","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EnZFaqg7hx","abs":"Quantum error correction (QEC) is essential for enabling quantum advantages, with decoding as a central algorithmic primitive. Owing to its importance and intrinsic difficulty, substantial effort has been made to QEC decoder design, among which neural decoders have recently emerged as a promising data-driven paradigm. Despite this progress, practical deployment remains hindered by a fundamental accuracyвҖ“latency tradeoff, often on the microsecond timescale. To address this challenge, here we revisit neural decoders for surface-code decoding under explicit accuracyвҖ“latency constraints, considering code distances up to $d=9$ (161 physical qubits). We unify and redesign representative neural decoders into five architectural paradigms and develop an end-to-end compression pipeline to evaluate their deployability and performance on FPGA hardware. Through systematic experiments, we reveal several previously underexplored insights: (i) near-term decoding performance is driven more by data scale than architectural complexity; (ii) appropriate inductive bias is essential for achieving high decoding accuracy; and (iii) INT4 quantization is a prerequisite for meeting microsecond-scale latency requirements on FPGAs. Together, these findings provide concrete guidance toward scalable and real-time neural QEC decoding.","absKo":"м–‘мһҗ error correction (QEC)мқҖ м–‘мһҗ мҡ°мң„лҘј мӢӨнҳ„н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙл©°, decodingмқҖ к·ё н•өмӢ¬ algorithmic primitiveмқҙлӢӨ. к·ё мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұкіј ліём§Ҳм Ғ лӮңмқҙлҸ„ л•Ңл¬ём—җ QEC decoder м„Өкі„м—җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң л…ёл Ҙмқҙ нҲ¬мһ…лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”кі , к·ёмӨ‘ neural decoderлҠ” мөңк·ј мң л§қн•ң data-driven paradigmмңјлЎң л– мҳ¬лһҗлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м§„м „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , мӢӨм ң л°°нҸ¬лҠ” microsecond лӢЁмң„м—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё accuracy-latency tradeoffм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м—¬м „нһҲ м ңм•ҪлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҪ”л“ң кұ°лҰ¬ $d=9$ (161 physical qubit)к№Ңм§ҖлҘј кі л Өн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё accuracy-latency constraint м•„лһҳм—җм„ң surface-code decodingмқ„ мң„н•ң neural decoderлҘј лӢӨмӢң кІҖнҶ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё neural decoderлҘј лӢӨм„Ҝ к°Җм§Җ architectural paradigmмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳкі  мһ¬м„Өкі„н•ҳл©°, FPGA hardwareм—җм„ңмқҳ deployabilityмҷҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң end-to-end compression pipelineмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мІҙкі„м Ғмқё мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙм „м—җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлҚҳ м—¬лҹ¬ нҶөм°°мқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. (i) лӢЁкё° м„ұлҠҘмқҖ architecture complexityліҙлӢӨ data scaleм—җ лҚ” нҒ¬кІҢ мўҢмҡ°лҗңлӢӨ; (ii) лҶ’мқҖ decoding м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл Өл©ҙ м Ғм Ҳн•ң inductive biasк°Җ н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ; (iii) INT4 quantizationмқҖ FPGAм—җм„ң microsecond мҲҳмӨҖ latency мҡ”кө¬лҘј л§ҢмЎұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң м „м ңмЎ°кұҙмқҙлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  мӢӨмӢңк°„мқё neural QEC decodingмқ„ н–Ҙн•ң кө¬мІҙм Ғмқё м§Җм№Ёмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64426","en":"Transforming Weather Data from Pixel to Latent Space","ko":"н”Ҫм…Җм—җм„ң мһ мһ¬ кіөк°„мңјлЎңмқҳ кё°мғҒ лҚ°мқҙн„° ліҖнҷҳ","authors":"Sijie Zhao, Feng Liu, Xueliang Zhang, Hao Chen, Tao Han, JUNCHAO GONG, Ran Tao, Pengfeng Xiao, Xinyu Gu, LEI BAI","pos":"#803","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=NlSWKeQPoZ","abs":"<p>The increasing impact of climate change and extreme weather events has spurred growing interest in deep learning for weather research. However, existing studies often rely on weather data in pixel space, which presents several challenges such as smooth outputs in model outputs, limited applicability to a single pressure-variable subset (PVS), and high data storage and computational costs. To address these challenges, we propose a novel Weather Latent Autoencoder (WLA) that transforms weather data from pixel space to latent space, enabling efficient data representation. By decoupling weather reconstruction from downstream tasks, WLA improves the accuracy and sharpness of weather task model results. The incorporated Pressure-Variable Unified Module transforms multiple PVS into a unified representation, enhancing the adaptability of the model in multiple weather scenarios. Furthermore, weather tasks can be performed in a low-storage latent space of WLA rather than a high-storage pixel space, thus significantly reducing data storage and computational costs. Through extensive experimentation, we demonstrate its superior compression and reconstruction performance, enabling the creation of the ERA5-Latent dataset with unified representations of multiple PVS from ERA5 data. The compressed full PVS in the ERA5-Latent dataset reduces the original 244.34 TB of data to 0.43 TB. The downstream task further demonstrates that task models can apply to multiple PVS with low data costs in latent space and achieve superior performance compared to models in pixel space.</p>","absKo":"<p>кё°нӣ„ ліҖнҷ”мҷҖ к·№н•ң кё°мғҒ нҳ„мғҒмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқҙ м»Өм§Җл©ҙм„ң weather researchлҘј мң„н•ң deep learningм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙҖмӢ¬лҸ„ л№ лҘҙкІҢ лҶ’м•„м§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” лҢҖк°ң pixel spaceмқҳ weather dataм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” model outputмқҳ smooth output, single pressure-variable subset (PVS)м—җ лҢҖн•ң м ңн•ңм Ғмқё м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ, лҶ’мқҖ data storage л°Ҹ computational costмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ л¬ём ңлҘј м•јкё°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” weather dataлҘј pixel spaceм—җм„ң latent spaceлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳм—¬ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё data representationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Weather Latent Autoencoder (WLA)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. weather reconstructionкіј downstream taskлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, WLAлҠ” weather task model кІ°кіјмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ м„ лӘ…лҸ„лҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң нҶөн•©лҗң Pressure-Variable Unified ModuleмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ PVSлҘј н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ unified representationмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳм—¬, лӢӨм–‘н•ң weather scenarioм—җм„ң modelмқҳ м Ғмқ‘м„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, weather taskлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ storageк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ң pixel spaceк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј WLAмқҳ low-storage latent spaceм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмңјлҜҖлЎң, data storageмҷҖ computational costлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң compression л°Ҹ reconstruction м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мһ…мҰқн–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң ERA5 dataлЎңл¶Җн„° multiple PVSмқҳ unified representationмқ„ лӢҙмқҖ ERA5-Latent datasetмқ„ кө¬м¶•н–ҲлӢӨ. ERA5-Latent datasetмқҳ compressed full PVSлҠ” мӣҗлһҳ 244.34 TBмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј 0.43 TBлЎң мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. downstream taskм—җм„ңлҸ„ latent spaceм—җм„ң лӮ®мқҖ data costлЎң multiple PVSм—җ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң task modelмқҙ pixel spaceмқҳ modelліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64960","en":"WIND: Weather Inverse Diffusion for Zero-Shot Atmospheric Modeling","ko":"WIND: Zero-Shot лҢҖкё° лӘЁлҚёл§Ғмқ„ мң„н•ң Weather Inverse Diffusion","authors":"Michael Aich, Andreas FГјrst, Florian Sestak, Carlos Ruiz-Gonzalez, Niklas Boers, Johannes Brandstetter","pos":"#804","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ILk0UMiQ6n","abs":"<p>Deep learning has revolutionized weather and climate modeling, yet the current landscape remains fragmented: highly specialized models are typically trained individually for distinct tasks. To unify this landscape, we introduce WIND, a single pre-trained foundation model capable of replacing specialized baselines across a vast array of tasks. Crucially, in contrast to previous atmospheric foundation models, we achieve this without any task-specific fine-tuning. To learn a robust, task-agnostic prior of the atmosphere, we pre-train WIND with a self-supervised video reconstruction objective, utilizing an unconditional video diffusion model to iteratively reconstruct atmospheric dynamics from a noisy state. At inference, we frame diverse domain-specific problems strictly as inverse problems and solve them via posterior sampling. This unified approach allows us to tackle highly relevant weather and climate problems, including probabilistic forecasting, spatial and temporal downscaling, sparse reconstruction and enforcing conservation laws purely with our pre-trained model. We further demonstrate the model's capacity to generate physically consistent counterfactual storylines of extreme weather events under global warming scenarios. By combining generative video modeling with inverse problem solving, WIND offers a computationally efficient paradigm shift in AI-based atmospheric modeling.</p>","absKo":"<p>Deep learningмқҖ weather and climate modelingмқ„ нҳҒмӢ н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ landscapeлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ л¶„м Ҳлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ. л§Өмҡ° нҠ№нҷ”лҗң modelл“Өмқҙ ліҙнҶө м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё taskлҘј мң„н•ҙ к°ңлі„м ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ landscapeлҘј н•ҳлӮҳлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң taskм—җм„ң specialized baselineмқ„ лҢҖмІҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лӢЁмқј pre-trained foundation modelмқё WINDлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, мқҙм „мқҳ atmospheric foundation modelкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” task-specific fine-tuning м—Ҷмқҙ мқҙлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖкё°мқҳ кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  task-agnosticн•ң priorлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” self-supervised video reconstruction objectiveлЎң WINDлҘј pre-trainн•ҳл©°, unconditional video diffusion modelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ noisy stateлЎңл¶Җн„° atmospheric dynamicsлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. inference мӢңм—җлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң domain-specific problemмқ„ м—„л°ҖнһҲ inverse problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі  posterior samplingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөн•©лҗң м ‘к·јмқҖ probabilistic forecasting, spatial and temporal downscaling, sparse reconstruction, conservation law к°•м ңлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң weather and climate problemмқ„ pre-trained modelл§ҢмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈ° мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ modelмқҙ global warming scenario н•ҳм—җм„ң к·№н•ң кё°мғҒ мӮ¬кұҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң physically consistent counterfactual storylineмқ„ мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. generative video modelingкіј inverse problem solvingмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, WINDлҠ” AI кё°л°ҳ atmospheric modelingм—җ кі„мӮ°м ҒмңјлЎң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„ м „нҷҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60684","en":"Order Matters in Retrosynthesis: Structure-aware Generation via Reaction-Center-Guided Discrete Flow Matching","ko":"Retrosynthesisм—җм„ңлҠ” мҲңм„ңк°Җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ: Reaction-Center-Guided Discrete Flow Matchingмқ„ нҶөн•ң кө¬мЎ° мқёмӢқ мғқм„ұ","authors":"Chenguang Wang, Zihan Zhou, LEI BAI, Tianshu Yu","pos":"#900","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xeH37plPS3","abs":"<p>Template-free retrosynthesis methods treat the task as black-box sequence generation, limiting learning efficiency, while semi-template approaches rely on rigid reaction libraries that constrain generalization. We address this gap with a key insight: atom ordering in neural representations matters.  Building on this insight, we propose a structure-aware template-free framework that encodes the two-stage nature of chemical reactions as a positional inductive bias. By placing reaction center atoms at the sequence head, our method transforms implicit chemical knowledge into explicit positional patterns that the model can readily capture. The proposed RetroDiT backbone, a graph transformer with rotary position embeddings, exploits this ordering to prioritize chemically critical regions. Combined with discrete flow matching, our approach decouples training from sampling and enables generation in 20--50 steps versus 500 for prior diffusion methods. Our method achieves state-of-the-art performance on both USPTO-50k (61.2\\% top-1) and the large-scale USPTO-Full (51.3\\% top-1) with predicted reaction centers. With oracle centers, performance reaches 71.1\\% and 63.4\\% respectively, surpassing foundation models trained on 10 billion reactions while using orders of magnitude less data. Ablation studies further reveal that structural priors outperform brute-force scaling: a 280K-parameter model with proper ordering matches a 65M-parameter model without it.</p>","absKo":"<p>template-free retrosynthesis methodлҠ” taskлҘј black-box sequence generationмңјлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳм—¬ н•ҷмҠө нҡЁмңЁмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗҳкі , semi-template м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҘј м ңм•Ҫн•ҳлҠ” кІҪм§Ғлҗң reaction libraryм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•өмӢ¬ нҶөм°°, мҰү neural representationм—җм„ң atom orderingмқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨлЎң мқҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј н•ҙмҶҢн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” chemical reactionмқҳ two-stage natureлҘј positional inductive biasлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” structure-aware template-free frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. reaction center atomмқ„ sequence headм—җ л°°м№ҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ м•”л¬өм Ғмқё chemical knowledgeлҘј лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мүҪкІҢ нҸ¬м°©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғ positional patternмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. rotary position embeddingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” graph transformerмқё м ңм•Ҳн•ң RetroDiT backboneмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң orderingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ нҷ”н•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ңлӢӨ. discrete flow matchingкіј кІ°н•©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ trainingкіј samplingмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкі , мқҙм „ diffusion methodмқҳ 500 stepм—җ л№„н•ҙ 20--50 stepм—җм„ң generationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ predicted reaction centerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” USPTO-50k (61.2\\% top-1)мҷҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ USPTO-Full (51.3\\% top-1) лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. oracle centerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•  кІҪмҡ° м„ұлҠҘмқҖ к°Ғк°Ғ 71.1\\%мҷҖ 63.4\\%м—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳл©°, 10 billion reactionмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң foundation modelмқ„ нӣЁм”¬ м ҒмқҖ dataлЎң лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. м¶”к°Җ ablation studyлҠ” structural priorк°Җ л¬ҙм°Ёлі„м Ғмқё scalingліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. м Ғм Ҳн•ң orderingмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ 280K-parameter modelмқҖ orderingмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” 65M-parameter modelкіј м„ұлҠҘмқҙ к°ҷм•„м§„лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61952","en":"Multimodal Crystal Flow: Any-to-Any Modality Generation for Unified Crystal Modeling","ko":"Multimodal Crystal Flow: нҶөн•© Crystal modelingмқ„ мң„н•ң Any-to-Any modality generation","authors":"Kiyoung Seong, Sungsoo Ahn, Sehui Han, Changyoung Park","pos":"#901","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lKyD1ulXpY","abs":"<p>Crystal modeling spans a family of conditional and unconditional generation tasks across different modalities, including crystal structure prediction (CSP) and <em>de novo</em> generation (DNG). While recent deep generative models have shown promising performance, they remain largely task-specific, lacking a unified framework that shares crystal representations across different generation tasks. To address this limitation, we propose <em>Multimodal Crystal Flow (MCFlow)</em>, a unified multimodal flow model that realizes multiple crystal generation tasks as distinct inference trajectories via independent time variables for atom types and crystal structures. To enable multimodal flow in a standard transformer model, we introduce a composition- and symmetry-aware atom ordering with hierarchical permutation augmentation, injecting strong compositional and crystallographic priors without explicit structural templates. Experiments on the MP-20 and MPTS-52 benchmarks show that MCFlow achieves competitive performance against task-specific baselines across multiple crystal generation tasks. Our code and inference trajectories are available at <a href=\"https://anonymous.4open.science/r/mcflow-46E4\">https://anonymous.4open.science/r/mcflow-46E4</a>.</p>","absKo":"<p>Crystal modelingмқҖ crystal structure prediction (CSP)кіј <em>de novo</em> generation (DNG)мқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳм—¬, лӢӨм–‘н•ң modalityм—җ кұём№ң мЎ°кұҙл¶Җ л°Ҹ л№„мЎ°кұҙл¶Җ мғқм„ұ нғңмҠӨнҒ¬л“Өмқҳ м§‘н•©мқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј deep generative modelл“Өмқҙ мң л§қн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖм§Җл§Ң, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё мғқм„ұ нғңмҠӨнҒ¬ к°„м—җ crystal representationмқ„ кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳл©°, лҢҖмІҙлЎң task-specificн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <em>Multimodal Crystal Flow (MCFlow)</em>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” atom typeкіј crystal structureлҘј мң„н•ң лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё time variableмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м—¬лҹ¬ crystal generation taskлҘј м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё inference trajectoryлЎң мӢӨнҳ„н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© multimodal flow modelмқҙлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ transformer modelм—җм„ң multimodal flowлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” hierarchical permutation augmentationкіј н•Ёк»ҳ composition- л°Ҹ symmetry-aware atom orderingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё structural template м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ к°•н•ң compositional л°Ҹ crystallographic priorлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ңлӢӨ. MP-20кіј MPTS-52 benchmark мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң MCFlowлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ crystal generation task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ task-specific baselineл“Өкіј кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ codeмҷҖ inference trajectoryлҠ” <a href=\"https://anonymous.4open.science/r/mcflow-46E4\">https://anonymous.4open.science/r/mcflow-46E4</a>м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64075","en":"Mesh Based Simulations with Spatial and Temporal awareness","ko":"кіөк°„м ҒВ·мӢңк°„м Ғ мқёмӢқмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ л©”мӢң кё°л°ҳ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳ","authors":"Paul Garnier, Vincent Lannelongue, Elie Hachem","pos":"#902","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=R8wiI3AnfI","abs":"<p>Machine Learning surrogates for Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD), particularly Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) and Transformers, have become a new important approach for accelerating physics simulations. However, we identify a critical bottleneck in the field: while architectures have advanced significantly, the underlying training paradigms remain bound to naive assumptions, such as node-wise supervision and explicit Euler time-stepping. These legacy choices ignore the stiff dynamics and local flux continuity inherent to numerous partial differential equations resolution methods, such as Finite Element, Difference, or Volume (FEM). In this work, we propose a unified framework to bridge the gap between geometric deep learning and rigorous numerical analysis. We introduce three key innovations: (1) Multi Node Prediction, a novel objective that predicts field values for a node's full local topology, enforcing spatial derivative consistency; (2) Temporal Correction, replacing unstable explicit schemes with a predictorвҖ“corrector via temporal Cross-Attention; and (3) Geometric Inductive Biases, leveraging 3D Rotary Positional Embeddings (RoPE) to robustly capture rotational symmetries in unstructured meshes. We evaluate this framework across three architectures (MeshGraphNet, Transolver, and a Transformer) on diverse physics datasets. Our approach yields consistent improvements in accuracy and stability, particularly in long-horizon rollouts, while producing latent representations that generalize to unseen subtasks such as Wall Shear Stress or Pressure prediction.</p>","absKo":"<p>Computational Fluid Dynamics (CFD)лҘј мң„н•ң Machine Learning surrogate, нҠ№нһҲ Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)мҷҖ TransformersлҠ” л¬јлҰ¬ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л¶„м•јмқҳ м№ҳлӘ…м Ғмқё лі‘лӘ©мқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳлҠ” нҒ¬кІҢ л°ңм „н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, underlying training paradigmмқҖ node-wise supervisionмқҙлӮҳ explicit Euler time-stepping к°ҷмқҖ мҲңм§„н•ң к°Җм •м—җ м—¬м „нһҲ л¬¶м—¬ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң legacy м„ нғқмқҖ Finite Element, Difference, Volume (FEM)кіј к°ҷмқҖ мҲҳл§ҺмқҖ partial differential equation н•ҙлІ•м—җ лӮҙмһ¬н•ң stiff dynamicsмҷҖ local flux continuityлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” geometric deep learningкіј м—„л°Җн•ң numerical analysis мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°лҠ” нҶөн•© н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ нҳҒмӢ мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ: (1) Multi Node Prediction, л…ёл“ңмқҳ м „мІҙ local topologyм—җ лҢҖн•ң field к°’мқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳм—¬ spatial derivative consistencyлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ objective; (2) Temporal Correction, л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ң explicit schemeмқ„ temporal Cross-Attentionмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң predictor-correctorлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқ; (3) Geometric Inductive Biases, л№„кө¬мЎ°м Ғ meshм—җм„ң нҡҢм „ лҢҖм№ӯм„ұмқ„ кІ¬кі н•ҳкІҢ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ 3D Rotary Positional Embeddings (RoPE)лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м„ё к°Җм§Җ м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳ(MeshGraphNet, Transolver, к·ёлҰ¬кі  Transformer)мҷҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң physics datasetм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ м•Ҳм •м„ұ, нҠ№нһҲ long-horizon rolloutм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖмңјл©°, Wall Shear StressлӮҳ Pressure мҳҲмёЎкіј к°ҷмқҖ лҜёкҙҖмёЎ subtasksлЎңлҸ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗҳлҠ” latent representationмқ„ мӮ°м¶ңн–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62001","en":"LoPhyDA: Low-Rank Tensor and Physics Gradient Guided Diffusion for Atmospheric Data Assimilation","ko":"LoPhyDA: atmospheric data assimilationмқ„ мң„н•ң low-rank tensor л°Ҹ physics gradient guided diffusion","authors":"danyang peng, Yang Chen, Yunlong Zhou, Xiaotong Yuan","pos":"#903","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=koxQxCo7Gy","abs":"<p>Data Assimilation (DA) aims to integrate observations with model forecasts to estimate the state of dynamical systems. Despite the widespread application of diffusion-based assimilation methods, they remain constrained by the high dimensionality of atmospheric states and the reliance on imperfect state-observation mappings. This leaves regions lacking observations spatially unconstrained, leading to severe error accumulation and physical inconsistency.. In this paper, we propose LoPhyDA, a diffusion assimilation algorithm dual-guided by low-rank tensor and physical gradients. By leveraging the low-rank property of meteorological field, we employ tensor completion to exploit spatial continuity and dynamic correlations, reconstructing a globally informative dense field from sparse observations to serve as a global prior. This approach mitigates the information deficit inherent in sparse settings. The framework further incorporates physical constraints into the iterative denoising process, utilizing Partial Differential Equation (PDE) residual gradients to rectify the generative trajectory in real-time. Experimental results demonstrate that LoPhyDA outperforms state-of-the-art generative assimilation models in global weather prediction. It achieves robust and physically consistent assimilation, significantly reducing error accumulation in regions lacking observations.</p>","absKo":"<p>Data Assimilation(DA)мқҖ кҙҖмёЎкіј model forecastлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ dynamical systemмқҳ мғҒнғңлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. diffusion-based assimilation methodк°Җ л„җлҰ¬ м Ғмҡ©лҗҳкі  мһҲмқҢм—җлҸ„, лҢҖкё° мғҒнғңмқҳ лҶ’мқҖ м°Ёмӣҗм„ұкіј л¶Ҳмҷ„м „н•ң state-observation mappingм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м—¬м „нһҲ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ кҙҖмёЎмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” мҳҒм—ӯмқҖ кіөк°„м ҒмңјлЎң м ңм•Ҫлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мұ„ лӮЁм•„, мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң error accumulationкіј л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ л№„мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” low-rank tensorмҷҖ physical gradientм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мқҙмӨ‘мңјлЎң guided лҗҳлҠ” diffusion assimilation algorithmмқё LoPhyDAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. meteorological fieldмқҳ low-rank propertyлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ tensor completionмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ кіөк°„м Ғ м—°мҶҚм„ұкіј лҸҷм Ғ мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„лҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ҳкі , sparse observationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° м „м—ӯм ҒмңјлЎң м •ліҙлҘј лӢҙмқҖ dense fieldлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ global priorлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ sparse settingм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң м •ліҙ л¶ҖмЎұмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мқҙ frameworkлҠ” л°ҳліөм Ғ denoising кіјм •м—җ л¬јлҰ¬ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬, Partial Differential Equation(PDE) residual gradientлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мғқм„ұ trajectoryлҘј мӢӨмӢңк°„мңјлЎң ліҙм •н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, LoPhyDAлҠ” global weather predictionм—җм„ң state-of-the-art generative assimilation modelмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң мқјкҙҖлҗң assimilationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, кҙҖмёЎмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ңмқҳ error accumulationмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60540","en":"Learning to Refine: Spectral-Decoupled Iterative Refinement Framework for Precipitation Nowcasting","ko":"Learning to Refine: к°•мҲҳ мҙҲлӢЁкё° мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мң„н•ң мҠӨнҺҷнҠёлҹј л¶„лҰ¬ л°ҳліө м •м ң н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Yunlong Zhou, Chen Zhao, danyang peng, Fanfan Ji, Xiaotong Yuan","pos":"#904","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=zB4xF9tfdm","abs":"<p>Accurate precipitation nowcasting is vital for disaster mitigation, but deep learning methods suffer a key trade-off: regression models produce over-smoothed, spectrally decaying predictions that blur convective details and violate turbulence power laws; diffusion models generate realistic yet unanchored hallucinations lacking physical grounding. We propose Spectral-Decoupled Iterative Refinement (SDIR), a deterministic framework that reformulates nowcasting as progressive frequency-decoupled refinement. SDIR first extracts a stable low-frequency synoptic skeleton, then iteratively refines high-frequency textures under physical constraints, eliminating both blurring and hallucinations. It features a dual-path design: the Synoptic Frequency-Guided Former (SFG-Former) with Scale-Adaptive Transformers for global structure, and the Fourier Residual Refiner (FR-Refiner) with Scale-Conditioned Fourier Neural Operators for fine residuals. A Physically-Consistent Power Spectral Density (PCPSD) loss with dynamic masking enforces turbulence-consistent spectral distribution. Experiments on three benchmarks show SDIR significantly outperforms SOTA in spatial accuracy while achieving spectral fidelity competitive with diffusion-based methods, enabling reliable high-resolution operational nowcasting.</p>","absKo":"<p>м •нҷ•н•ң precipitation nowcastingмқҖ мһ¬лӮң мҷ„нҷ”м—җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, deep learning methodлҠ” н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё trade-offлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. regression modelмқҖ м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкі  spectrally decayingн•ң predictionмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ convective detailмқ„ нқҗлҰ¬кІҢ н•ҳкі  turbulence power lawлҘј мң„л°ҳн•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, diffusion modelмқҖ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ groundingмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң м•өм»Өк°Җ м—ҶлҠ” hallucinationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Spectral-Decoupled Iterative Refinement (SDIR)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” nowcastingмқ„ м җм§„м Ғмқё frequency-decoupled refinementлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” deterministic frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. SDIRлҠ” лЁјм Җ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё low-frequency synoptic skeletonмқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ң л’Ө, л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ң high-frequency textureлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң м •м ңн•ҳм—¬ blurringкіј hallucinationмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkлҠ” мқҙмӨ‘ кІҪлЎң м„Өкі„лҘј нҠ№м§•мңјлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. м „м—ӯ кө¬мЎ°лҘј мң„н•ң Scale-Adaptive TransformerлҘј к°–м¶ҳ Synoptic Frequency-Guided Former (SFG-Former)мҷҖ, лҜём„ё residualмқ„ мң„н•ң Scale-Conditioned Fourier Neural OperatorлҘј к°–м¶ҳ Fourier Residual Refiner (FR-Refiner)мқҙлӢӨ. лҸҷм Ғ maskingмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң Physically-Consistent Power Spectral Density (PCPSD) lossлҠ” turbulence-consistent spectral distributionмқ„ к°•м ңн•ңлӢӨ. м„ё к°ңмқҳ benchmark мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң SDIRлҠ” spatial accuracyм—җм„ң SOTAлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ diffusion-based methodмҷҖ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” spectral fidelityлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ operational nowcastingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65674","en":"HybridOM: Hybrid Physics-Based and Data-Driven Global Ocean Modeling with Efficient Regional Downscaling","ko":"HybridOM: нҡЁмңЁм Ғ м§Җм—ӯ лӢӨмҡҙмҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ н•ҳмқҙлёҢлҰ¬л“ң л¬јлҰ¬ кё°л°ҳ л°Ҹ лҚ°мқҙн„° кё°л°ҳ м „м§Җкө¬ н•ҙм–‘ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ","authors":"Ruiqi Shu, Xiaohui Zhong, Mengyao Fang, Ruijian Gou, Tianrun Gao, Hao Li, Xiaomeng Huang","pos":"#906","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=BJpOvFcCh3","abs":"<p>Global ocean modeling is vital for climate science but struggles to balance computational efficiency with accuracy. Traditional numerical solvers are accurate but computationally expensive, while pure deep learning approaches, though fast, often lack physical consistency and long-term stability. To address this, we introduce HybridOM, a framework integrating a lightweight, differentiable numerical solver as a skeleton to enforce physical laws, with a neural network as the flesh to correct subgrid-scale dynamics. To enable efficient high-resolution modeling, we further introduce a physics-informed regional downscaling mechanism based on flux gating. This design achieves the inference efficiency of AI-based methods while preserving the accuracy and robustness of physical models. Extensive experiments on the GLORYS12V1 and OceanBench dataset validate HybridOM's performance in two distinct regimes: long-term subseasonal-to-seasonal simulation and short-term operational forecasting coupled with the FuXi-2.0 weather model. Results demonstrate that HybridOM achieves state-of-the-art accuracy while maintaining physical consistency, offering a robust solution for next-generation ocean digital twins.</p>","absKo":"<p>Global ocean modelingмқҖ climate scienceм—җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, computational efficiencyмҷҖ accuracy мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. м „нҶөм Ғмқё numerical solverлҠ” м •нҷ•н•ҳм§Җл§Ң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кі , pure deep learning м ‘к·јмқҖ л№ лҘҙм§Җл§Ң мў…мў… physical consistencyмҷҖ long-term stabilityк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кІҪлҹүмқҳ differentiable numerical solverлҘј skeletonмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ physical lawлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳкі , neural networkлҘј fleshлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ subgrid-scale dynamicsлҘј ліҙм •н•ҳлҠ” HybridOMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳн–үн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” flux gating кё°л°ҳмқҳ physics-informed regional downscaling mechanismлҸ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” AI-based methodмқҳ inference efficiencyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ physical modelмқҳ accuracyмҷҖ robustnessлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. GLORYS12V1мҷҖ OceanBench datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ long-term subseasonal-to-seasonal simulationкіј FuXi-2.0 weather modelкіј кІ°н•©лҗң short-term operational forecastingмқҳ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё regimeм—җм„ң HybridOMмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. кІ°кіјлҠ” HybridOMмқҙ physical consistencyлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң state-of-the-art м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, м°Ём„ёлҢҖ ocean digital twinмқ„ мң„н•ң кІ¬кі н•ң н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64833","en":"Graph Rewiring based on Flow Alignment for Improving Fluid Simulation","ko":"мң мІҙ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳ к°ңм„ мқ„ мң„н•ң Flow Alignment кё°л°ҳ Graph Rewiring","authors":"Zenong Li, Wei Xian Lim, Wai Lee Chan, Adams Wai Kin Kong","pos":"#907","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=JLNYVGaR6I","abs":"<p>To overcome computation burden of traditional computational fluid dynamics (CFD) simulations, researchers have explored different architectures to develop physics-informed simulation methods. Among them, graph neural networks (GNN) are most suitable for adopting CFD meshes, which are extensively used in engineering and industrial applications. However, classical GNNs propagate information among neighbour nodes, which highly restrict information exchange within the network. To address this issue, graph rewiring methods have been developed for generic graph problems, but not particular for fluid simulation. PIORF, introducing edges connecting distant nodes, is the first graph rewiring method to do so, and previous experiments have demonstrated its effectiveness against state-of-the-art generic rewiring methods. Nevertheless, in this work, we found that simply connecting all 2-hop nodes can provide competitive performance with PIORF. This result raises three questions: 1) Is physics-informed rewiring really useful for improving flow predictions? 2) Should we consider just local connection, instead of connecting distant nodes? 3) Do we need to change the connections based on input flow for rollout simulations? By thoroughly adopting physical fluid principles, we propose a simple yet very efficient method, Flow Alignment Rewiring (FLARE) technique, which connects 2-hop nodes only when the node direction aligns with input flow direction. Hence, FLARE is a physics-informed local rewiring method, different from PIORF and well-aligned with fluid physics. Extensive numerical experiments on flows over a cylinder and single and tandem airfoil under different flow conditions and deep network architectures demonstrate that FLARE outperforms PIORF and various 2-hop rewiring approaches by a significant margin.</p>","absKo":"<p>м „нҶөм Ғмқё computational fluid dynamics (CFD) мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳмқҳ кі„мӮ° л¶ҖлӢҙмқ„ к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, м—°кө¬мһҗл“ӨмқҖ physics-informed simulation methodлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң architectureлҘј нғҗкө¬н•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёмӨ‘ graph neural networks (GNN)лҠ” кіөн•ҷ л°Ҹ мӮ°м—… мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң нҸӯл„“кІҢ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” CFD meshлҘј мҲҳмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° к°ҖмһҘ м Ғн•©н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кі м „м Ғмқё GNNмқҖ мқём ‘ л…ёл“ңл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ңл§Ң м •ліҙлҘј м „нҢҢн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, л„ӨнҠёмӣҢнҒ¬ лӮҙ м •ліҙ көҗнҷҳмқҙ нҒ¬кІҢ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё graph problemмқ„ мң„н•ң graph rewiring methodк°Җ к°ңл°ңлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, fluid simulationм—җ нҠ№нҷ”лҗң кІғмқҖ м•„лӢҲм—ҲлӢӨ. лЁј л…ёл“ңлҘј м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” edgeлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ң PIORFлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©мӢқмқ„ мІҳмқҢмңјлЎң м Ғмҡ©н•ң graph rewiring methodмқҙл©°, мқҙм „ мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” мөңмІЁлӢЁ мқјл°ҳ rewiring methodл“Өм—җ л№„н•ҙ к·ё нҡЁкіјк°Җ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹјм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” лӢЁмҲңнһҲ лӘЁл“  2-hop nodeлҘј м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” кІғл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ PIORFм—җ н•„м Ғн•ҳлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӮј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ м§Ҳл¬ёмқ„ м ңкё°н•ңлӢӨ. 1) physics-informed rewiringмқҙ flow prediction н–ҘмғҒм—җ м •л§җ мң мҡ©н•ңк°Җ? 2) лЁј л…ёл“ңлҘј м—°кІ°н•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ local connectionл§Ң кі л Өн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ”к°Җ? 3) rollout simulationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ мһ…л Ҙ flowм—җ л”°лқј connectionмқ„ л°”кҝ”м•ј н•ҳлҠ”к°Җ? мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ мң мІҙ мӣҗлҰ¬лҘј мІ м ҖнһҲ л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳм—¬, nodeмқҳ л°©н–Ҙмқҙ мһ…л Ҙ flow л°©н–Ҙкіј м •л ¬лҗ  л•Ңм—җл§Ң 2-hop nodeлҘј м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ л§Өмҡ° нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё л°©лІ•мқё Flow Alignment Rewiring (FLARE) techniqueлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң FLAREлҠ” PIORFмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬ fluid physicsм—җ мһҳ л¶Җн•©н•ҳлҠ” physics-informed local rewiring methodмқҙлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң flow мЎ°кұҙкіј deep network architecture н•ҳм—җм„ң cylinder мЈјліҖ нқҗлҰ„ л°Ҹ single/tandem airfoilм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FLAREк°Җ PIORFмҷҖ м—¬лҹ¬ 2-hop rewiring м ‘к·јлІ•л“Өмқ„ мғҒлӢ№н•ң м°ЁмқҙлЎң лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65357","en":"Global Plane Waves From Local Gaussians: Periodic Charge Densities in a Blink","ko":"көӯмҶҢ GaussianмңјлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ м „м—ӯ нҸүл©ҙнҢҢ: мҲңмӢқк°„мқҳ мЈјкё°м Ғ м „н•ҳ л°ҖлҸ„","authors":"Jonas Elsborg, Felix Aertebjerg, Luca Anthony Thiede, Alan Aspuru-Guzik, Tejs Vegge, Arghya Bhowmik","pos":"#908","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EPKdX56JSc","abs":"We introduce ELECTRAFI, a fast, end-to-end differentiable model for predicting periodic charge densities in crystalline materials. ELECTRAFI constructs anisotropic Gaussians in real space and exploits their closed-form Fourier transforms to analytically evaluate plane-wave coefficients via the Poisson summation formula. This formulation delegates non-local and periodic behavior to analytic transforms, enabling reconstruction of the full periodic charge density with a single inverse FFT. By avoiding explicit real-space grid probing, periodic image summation, and spherical harmonic expansions, ELECTRAFI matches or exceeds state-of-the-art accuracy across periodic benchmarks while being up to $633\\times$ faster than the strongest competing method, reconstructing crystal charge densities in a fraction of a second. When used to initialize DFT calculations, ELECTRAFI reduces total DFT compute cost by up to $\\sim$20 \\%, whereas slower charge density models negate savings due to high inference times. Our results show that accuracy and inference cost jointly determine end-to-end DFT speedups, and motivate our focus on efficiency.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кІ°м •м„ұ л¬јм§Ҳмқҳ periodic charge densityлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң л№ лҘҙкі  end-to-endлЎң differentiableн•ң modelмқё ELECTRAFIлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. ELECTRAFIлҠ” real spaceм—җм„ң anisotropic Gaussianмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , к·ё лӢ«нһҢнҳ• Fourier transformмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ Poisson summation formulaлҘј нҶөн•ҙ plane-wave coefficientлҘј н•ҙм„қм ҒмңјлЎң кі„мӮ°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м •мӢқнҷ”лҠ” л№„көӯмҶҢм Ғмқҙкі  мЈјкё°м Ғмқё кұ°лҸҷмқ„ analytic transformм—җ мң„мһ„н•ҳм—¬, лӢЁмқј inverse FFTл§ҢмңјлЎң м „мІҙ periodic charge densityмқҳ мһ¬кө¬м„ұмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё real-space grid probing, periodic image summation, spherical harmonic expansionмқ„ н”јн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ ELECTRAFIлҠ” periodic benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м •нҷ•лҸ„м—җ л§һлЁ№кұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, к°ҖмһҘ к°•л Ҙн•ң кІҪмҹҒ л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ $633\\times$ л№ лҘҙл©°, crystal charge densityлҘј 1мҙҲмқҳ мқјл¶Җл§Ңм—җ мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. DFT кі„мӮ° мҙҲкё°нҷ”м—җ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗ  кІҪмҡ° ELECTRAFIлҠ” мҙқ DFT кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқ„ мөңлҢҖ м•Ҫ 20 \\%к№Ңм§Җ мӨ„мқҙлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, лҚ” лҠҗлҰ° charge density modelмқҖ лҶ’мқҖ inference time л•Ңл¬ём—җ м Ҳк°җ нҡЁкіјлҘј мғҒмҮ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ inference costк°Җ end-to-end DFT speedupмқ„ н•Ёк»ҳ кІ°м •н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, нҡЁмңЁм„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мҙҲм җмқ„ м •лӢ№нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"66132","en":"GenDA: Generative Data Assimilation on Complex Urban Areas via Classifier-Free Diffusion Guidance","ko":"GenDA: Classifier-Free Diffusion к°ҖмқҙлҚҳмҠӨлҘј нҶөн•ң ліөмһЎн•ң лҸ„мӢң м§Җм—ӯм—җм„ңмқҳ мғқм„ұм Ғ лҚ°мқҙн„° лҸҷнҷ”","authors":"Francisco Giral, ГҒlvaro Sevillano, Ignacio Perez, Ricardo Vinuesa, Soledad Le Clainche","pos":"#909","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=6ctopuLHAy","abs":"Urban wind flow reconstruction is essential for assessing air quality, heat dispersion, and pedestrian comfort, yet remains challenging when only sparse sensor data are available. We propose GenDA, a generative data assimilation framework that reconstructs high-resolution wind fields on unstructured meshes from limited observations. The model employs a multiscale graph-based diffusion architecture trained on computational fluid dynamics (CFD) simulations and interprets classifier-free guidance as a learned posterior reconstruction mechanism: the unconditional branch learns a geometry-aware flow prior, while the sensor-conditioned branch injects observational constraints during sampling. This formulation enables obstacle-aware reconstruction and generalization across unseen geometries, wind directions, and mesh resolutions without retraining. We consider both sparse fixed sensors and trajectory-based observations using the same reconstruction procedure. When evaluated against supervised graph neural network (GNN) baselines and classical reduced-order data assimilation methods, GenDA reduces the relative root-mean-square error (RRMSE) by 25-57% and increases the structural similarity index (SSIM) by 23-33% across the tested meshes. Experiments are conducted on Reynolds-averaged Navier-Stokes (RANS) simulations of a real urban neighborhood in Bristol, United Kingdom, at a characteristic Reynolds number of $\\mathrm{Re}\\approx2\\times10^{7}$, featuring complex building geometry and irregular terrain. The proposed framework provides a scalable path toward generative, geometry-aware data assimilation for environmental monitoring in complex domains.","absKo":"лҸ„мӢңмқҳ wind flow мһ¬кө¬м„ұмқҖ air quality, heat dispersion, pedestrian comfortлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, sparse sensor dataл§Ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•  л•ҢлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м ңн•ңлҗң кҙҖмёЎмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° unstructured mesh мң„мқҳ кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ wind fieldлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” generative data assimilation frameworkмқё GenDAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ modelмқҖ computational fluid dynamics(CFD) simulationмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң multiscale graph-based diffusion architectureлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©°, classifier-free guidanceлҘј н•ҷмҠөлҗң posterior reconstruction mechanismмңјлЎң н•ҙм„қн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, unconditional branchлҠ” geometry-aware flow priorлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , sensor-conditioned branchлҠ” sampling мӨ‘ observational constraintлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ formulationмқҖ мһ¬н•ҷмҠө м—Ҷмқҙ obstacle-aware reconstructionкіј ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң geometry, wind direction, mesh resolution м „л°ҳмқҳ generalizationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°ҷмқҖ reconstruction procedureлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ sparse fixed sensorмҷҖ trajectory-based observationмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ кі л Өн•ңлӢӨ. supervised graph neural network(GNN) baseline л°Ҹ classical reduced-order data assimilation methodмҷҖ л№„көҗн•ң нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң, GenDAлҠ” н…ҢмҠӨнҠён•ң лӘЁл“  meshм—җ кұёміҗ relative root-mean-square error(RRMSE)лҘј 25-57% к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮӨкі  structural similarity index(SSIM)лҘј 23-33% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҳҒкөӯ лёҢлҰ¬мҠӨнӢҖмқҳ мӢӨм ң лҸ„мӢң м§Җм—ӯм—җ лҢҖн•ң Reynolds-averaged Navier-Stokes(RANS) simulationм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үлҗҳл©°, лҢҖн‘ң Reynolds мҲҳлҠ” $\\mathrm{Re}\\approx2\\times10^{7}$мқҙкі , ліөмһЎн•ң кұҙл¬ј нҳ•мғҒкіј л¶Ҳк·ңм№ҷн•ң м§Җнҳ•мқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. м ңм•Ҳн•ң frameworkлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ң нҷҳкІҪ лӘЁлӢҲн„°л§Ғмқ„ мң„н•ң generativeн•ҳкі  geometry-awareн•ң data assimilationмңјлЎң к°ҖлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"60991","en":"G-RANS: Generalizable Residual-Aware Neural Solvers for Sparse Systems","ko":"G-RANS: нқ¬мҶҢ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ мң„н•ң мқјл°ҳнҷ” к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мһ”м°Ё мқёмӢқ Neural Solver","authors":"Weixin Liao, Mingquan Feng, Zhizhou Zhang, Youjia Wu, Yifan Fu, Junchi Yan","pos":"#910","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=uizi6lvkSW","abs":"Neural operators have shown promise in accelerating PDE solvers, yet they remain unreliable for the sparse linear systems induced by discretization due to limited generalization across physical parameters and insufficient accuracy, and hybrid neural iterative schemes face stagnation as the residual distribution evolves over iterations. To address these limitations, we propose G-RANS (Generalizable Residual-Aware Neural Solver), a neuralized iterative paradigm that performs residual-aware subspace corrections by mapping the residual to the matrix graph, generating multi-scale correction subspaces via a residual-aware basis generator, and applying projected updates through a differentiable subspace projection. G-RANS is trained fully self-supervised via progressive bootstrap with multi-stage residual distributions. On sparse FEM systems from a representative suite of second-order elliptic PDEs (Poisson, advection--diffusion, reaction--diffusion, and Helmholtz), G-RANS is robust to severe coefficient shifts (up to $\\pm70\\\\%$) and shows strong cross-equation generalization. G-RANS reaches relative residuals on the order of $10^{-5}$, substantially outperforming end-to-end neural operators, and attains the same target residual with $2$--$4\\times$ less wall-clock time than classical Krylov solvers.","absKo":"Neural operatorлҠ” PDE solverлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мң л§қн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ parameterм—җ лҢҖн•ң м ңн•ңлҗң generalizationкіј м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лЎң мқён•ҙ discretizationмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ң sparse linear systemм—җм„ңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ мӢ лў°м„ұмқҙ лӮ®мңјл©°, hybrid neural iterative schemeмқҖ residual distributionмқҙ iterationм—җ л”°лқј ліҖн•Ём—җ л”°лқј м •мІҙм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” G-RANS (Generalizable Residual-Aware Neural Solver)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” residualмқ„ matrix graphм—җ л§Өн•‘н•ҳкі , residual-aware basis generatorлҘј нҶөн•ҙ multi-scale correction subspaceлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, differentiable subspace projectionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ projected updateлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” residual-aware subspace correctionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” neuralized iterative paradigmмқҙлӢӨ. G-RANSлҠ” multi-stage residual distributionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” progressive bootstrapмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҷ„м „н•ң self-supervised л°©мӢқмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗңлӢӨ. лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё second-order elliptic PDE (Poisson, advection--diffusion, reaction--diffusion, Helmholtz)л“ӨлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ sparse FEM systemм—җм„ң G-RANSлҠ” мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң coefficient shift(мөңлҢҖ $\\pm70\\\\%$)м—җлҸ„ кІ¬кі н•ҳл©° к°•н•ң cross-equation generalizationмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. G-RANSлҠ” $10^{-5}$ мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ relative residualм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳм—¬ end-to-end neural operatorлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, кі м „м Ғмқё Krylov solverліҙлӢӨ wall-clock timeмқҙ $2$--$4\\times$ м ҒкІҢ л“ңлҠ” лҸҷмқј target residualмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"62878","en":"Efficient Training of Boltzmann Generators Using Off-Policy Log-Dispersion Regularization","ko":"Off-Policy Log-Dispersion м •к·ңнҷ”лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң Boltzmann Generator нҡЁмңЁм Ғ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Henrik Schopmans, Christopher von Klitzing, Pascal Friederich","pos":"#911","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cKoqWcyVvd","abs":"<p>Sampling from unnormalized probability densities is a central challenge in computational science. Boltzmann generators are generative models that enable independent sampling from the Boltzmann distribution of physical systems at a given temperature. However, their practical success depends on data-efficient training, as both simulation data and target energy evaluations are costly. To this end, we propose off-policy log-dispersion regularization (LDR), a novel regularization framework that builds on a generalization of the log-variance objective. We apply LDR in the off-policy setting in combination with standard data-based training objectives, without requiring additional on-policy samples. LDR acts as a shape regularizer of the energy landscape by leveraging additional information in the form of target energy labels. The proposed regularization framework is broadly applicable, supporting unbiased or biased simulation datasets as well as purely variational training without access to target samples. Across all benchmarks, LDR improves both final performance and data efficiency, with sample efficiency gains of up to one order of magnitude.</p>","absKo":"<p>м •к·ңнҷ”лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ нҷ•лҘ  л°ҖлҸ„м—җм„ң мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ кі„мӮ°кіјн•ҷм—җм„ң н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё лҸ„м „ кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. Boltzmann generatorsлҠ” мЈјм–ҙм§„ мҳЁлҸ„м—җм„ң л¬јлҰ¬ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҳ Boltzmann distributionмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙмЈјлҠ” generative modelмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ң м„ұлҠҘмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„° нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё н•ҷмҠөм—җ лӢ¬л Ө мһҲлҠ”лҚ°, мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖ лӘ©н‘ң м—җл„Ҳм§Җ нҸүк°Җ лӘЁл‘җ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” off-policy log-dispersion regularization (LDR)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” log-variance objectiveмқҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ” мң„м—җ кө¬м¶•лҗң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ regularization frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LDRмқ„ off-policy м„Өм •м—җм„ң н‘ңмӨҖ лҚ°мқҙн„° кё°л°ҳ н•ҷмҠө objectiveмҷҖ кІ°н•©н•ҳм—¬ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©°, м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё on-policy sampleмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. LDRмқҖ target energy label нҳ•нғңмқҳ м¶”к°Җ м •ліҙлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ energy landscapeмқҳ shape regularizerлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ңлӢӨ. м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ” regularization frameworkлҠ” л§Өмҡ° нҸӯл„“кІҢ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳл©°, unbiased лҳҗлҠ” biased simulation datasetмқҖ л¬јлЎ  target sample м ‘к·јмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” мҲңмҲҳ variational trainingк№Ңм§Җ м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁл“  benchmarkм—җ кұёміҗ LDRмқҖ мөңмў… м„ұлҠҘкіј лҚ°мқҙн„° нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, sample efficiencyлҠ” мөңлҢҖ н•ң мһҗлҰҝмҲҳ л°°к№Ңм§Җ мҰқк°Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64317","en":"Do Neural Operators Forget Geometry? The Forgetting Hypothesis in Deep Operator Learning","ko":"мӢ кІҪ м—°мӮ°мһҗлҠ” кё°н•ҳн•ҷмқ„ мһҠлҠ”к°Җ? мӢ¬мёө м—°мӮ°мһҗ н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ңмқҳ л§қк°Ғ к°Җм„Ө","authors":"Yanming Xia, Angelica Aviles-Rivero","pos":"#913","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OnmYXKZ6oa","abs":"<p>Neural operators perform well on structured domains, yet their behaviour on irregular geometries remains poorly understood. We show that this limitation is not merely an encoding issue, but a depth-wise failure mode inherent to deep operator architectures. We formalise the <em>Geometric Forgetting Hypothesis</em>: due to the Markovian structure of operator layers and their reliance on global mixing mechanisms, neural operators progressively lose access to domain geometry as depth increases. Using layer-wise geometric probing, we demonstrate that both spectral and attention-based operators systematically lose geometric fidelity. We show that this geometric forgetting degrades accuracy, stability, and generalisation. To counteract it, we introduce a lightweight <em>geometry memory injection</em> mechanism that restores geometric constraints at intermediate depths with minimal architectural overhead. This simple intervention consistently mitigates forgetting and exposes a <em>geometric shortcut</em> instability in transformer-based operators, revealing that geometric retention is a structural requirement rather than a design choice.</p>","absKo":"<p>Neural operatorлҠ” кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң domainм—җм„ңлҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, л¶Ҳк·ңм№ҷн•ң geometryм—җм„ңмқҳ лҸҷмһ‘мқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ мһҳ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„к°Җ лӢЁмҲңн•ң encoding л¬ём ңл§Ңмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј, к№ҠмқҖ operator architectureм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң depth-wise failure modeмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <em>Geometric Forgetting Hypothesis</em>лҘј м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. operator layerмқҳ Markovian structureмҷҖ м „м—ӯ mixing mechanismм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙм„ұ л•Ңл¬ём—җ, neural operatorлҠ” depthк°Җ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ domain geometryм—җ лҢҖн•ң м ‘к·јм„ұмқ„ м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң мһғлҠ”лӢӨ. layer-wise geometric probingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, spectral operatorмҷҖ attention-based operator лӘЁл‘җ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң geometric fidelityлҘј мғҒмӢӨн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң geometric forgettingмқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„, м•Ҳм •м„ұ, мқјл°ҳнҷ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мғҒмҮ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ architectural overheadлЎң мӨ‘к°„ depthм—җм„ң geometric constraintлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” кІҪлҹү <em>geometry memory injection</em> л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ к°„лӢЁн•ң к°ңмһ…мқҖ forgettingмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкі  transformer кё°л°ҳ operatorм—җм„ңмқҳ <em>geometric shortcut</em> л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, geometric retentionмқҙ м„Өкі„ м„ нғқмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мҡ”кө¬мӮ¬н•ӯмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63492","en":"CatFlow: Co-generation of Slab-Adsorbate Systems via Flow Matching","ko":"CatFlow: Flow Matchingмқ„ нҶөн•ң мҠ¬лһҳлёҢ-нқЎм°©м§Ҳ мӢңмҠӨн…ң кіөлҸҷ мғқм„ұ","authors":"Minkyu Kim, Nayoung Kim, Honghui Kim, Sungsoo Ahn","pos":"#914","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WikLu7PkNK","abs":"<p>Discovering heterogeneous catalysts tailored for specific reaction intermediates remains a fundamental bottleneck in materials science. While traditional trial-and-error methods and recent generative models have shown promise, they struggle to capture the intrinsic coupling between surface geometry and adsorbate interactions. To address this limitation, we propose CatFlow, a flow matching-based framework for de novo design and structure prediction of heterogeneous catalysts. Our model operates on a primitive cell-based factorized representation of the slab-adsorbate complex, reducing the number of learnable variables by an average of 9.2x while explicitly encoding the surface orientation of the slab-adsorbate interface. Experiments on the Open Catalyst 2020 dataset demonstrate that CatFlow significantly improves the structural fidelity of generated catalysts compared to autoregressive and sequential baselines. Further experiments show that the generated structures accurately capture the adsorption energy distributions of physically plausible interfaces and lie closer to thermodynamic local minima.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҠ№м • reaction intermediateм—җ л§һм¶° мЎ°м •лҗң heterogeneous catalystлҘј л°ңкІ¬н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ materials scienceм—җм„ң к·јліём Ғмқё лі‘лӘ©мқҙлӢӨ. м „нҶөм Ғмқё trial-and-error л°©лІ•кіј мөңк·јмқҳ generative modelмқҙ мң л§қн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмҳҖм§Җл§Ң, мқҙл“ӨмқҖ surface geometryмҷҖ adsorbate interactions мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ couplingмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” heterogeneous catalystмқҳ de novo designкіј structure predictionмқ„ мң„н•ң flow matching кё°л°ҳ frameworkмқё CatFlowлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ slab-adsorbate complexм—җ лҢҖн•ң primitive cell кё°л°ҳ factorized representationм—җм„ң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳл©°, slab-adsorbate interfaceмқҳ surface orientationмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ learnable variableмқҳ мҲҳлҘј нҸүк·  9.2л°° мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. Open Catalyst 2020 datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CatFlowк°Җ autoregressive л°Ҹ sequential baselineм—җ л№„н•ҙ мғқм„ұлҗң catalystмқҳ structural fidelityлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. м¶”к°Җ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мғқм„ұлҗң кө¬мЎ°к°Җ л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң нғҖлӢ№н•ң interfaceмқҳ adsorption energy distributionмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳл©°, thermodynamic local minimumм—җ лҚ” к°Җк№қкІҢ мң„м№ҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64896","en":"Bayesian Rain Field Reconstruction using Commercial Microwave Links and Diffusion Model Priors","ko":"мғҒмҡ© Microwave LinkмҷҖ Diffusion Model PriorлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң Bayesian к°•мҡ°мһҘ мһ¬кө¬м„ұ","authors":"Badr MOUFAD, Albina Ilina, Hai Victor Habi, Salem Lahlou, Yazid Janati, HAGIT MESSER, Eric Moulines","pos":"#915","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ImD44h0ADA","abs":"<p>Commercial Microwave Links (CMLs) offer dense spatial coverage for rainfall sensing but produce path-integrated measurements that make accurate ground-level reconstruction challenging. Existing methods typically oversimplify CMLs as point sensors and neglect the physical power-law relating rainfall to signal attenuation, resulting in degraded performance under heterogeneous precipitation. In this work, we view rain field reconstruction as a Bayesian inverse problem with Diffusion Models (DMs) as high-fidelity spatial priors. We show that diffusion models better preserve key rainfall statistics compared to censored Gaussian processes. Framing rainfall estimation as a Bayesian inverse problem with a DM prior enables training-free posterior sampling using a broad family of methods, including Plug-and-Play, Sequential Monte Carlo, and Replica Exchange methods. Experiments on synthetic and real-world datasets demonstrate consistent improvements over established CML-based reconstruction baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>Commercial Microwave Links (CMLs)лҠ” к°•мҲҳ кҙҖмёЎмқ„ мң„н•ҙ мЎ°л°Җн•ң кіөк°„ м»ӨлІ„лҰ¬м§ҖлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кІҪлЎң м Ғл¶„(path-integrated) мёЎм •мқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҜҖлЎң м§ҖмғҒ мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ м •нҷ•н•ң ліөмӣҗмқҙ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң CMLмқ„ point sensorлЎң кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ лӢЁмҲңнҷ”н•ҳкі , к°•мҲҳмҷҖ мӢ нҳё к°җмҮ  мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ power-lawлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳм—¬ heterogeneous precipitation мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” л№„лҘј Bayesian inverse problemмңјлЎң ліҙкі , Diffusion Models (DMs)лҘј кі м¶©мӢӨлҸ„ spatial priorлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” diffusion modelмқҙ censored Gaussian processм—җ л№„н•ҙ н•өмӢ¬ к°•мҲҳ нҶөкі„лҘј лҚ” мһҳ ліҙмЎҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к°•мҲҳ м¶”м •мқ„ DM priorлҘј к°–лҠ” Bayesian inverse problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙ, Plug-and-Play, Sequential Monte Carlo, Replica Exchange л°©лІ•мқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң нҸӯл„“мқҖ л°©лІ•кө°мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ training-free posterior samplingмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨ. synthetic л°Ҹ real-world datasetм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ нҷ•лҰҪлҗң CML кё°л°ҳ ліөмӣҗ baselineм—җ л№„н•ҙ мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63555","en":"CSOR: Coreset Selection for Object Re-identification via Class Pruning","ko":"CSOR: нҒҙлһҳмҠӨ к°Җм§Җм№ҳкё°лҘј нҶөн•ң к°қмІҙ мһ¬мӢқлі„мҡ© мҪ”м–ҙм…Ӣ м„ нғқ","authors":"Minyoung Oh, Jae-Young Sim","pos":"#4401","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=W3cdjwawR8","abs":"<p>Coreset Selection (CS) aims to extract a small yet representative subset from a large dataset, reducing the complexity of model training. Although CS has been primarily investigated for classification tasks, it is still underexplored for object Re-identification (ReID). In this paper, we first formulate Coreset Selection for Object Re-identification (CSOR) as a joint optimization problem to find both the optimal coreset and the optimal class subset. We identify intra-class diversity as a key factor for effective coreset construction for ReID. Based on this insight, we propose a novel two-stage framework, consisting of Diversity-driven Class Pruning (DCP) and Coverage-Prioritized Sampling (CPS), to address the unique challenges of ReID datasets. First, classes with low feature diversity are pruned to allocate the storage budget to the remaining informative classes. Then, samples are greedily selected in an easy-to-hard class order to maximize feature coverage within each class. Extensive experiments on three person ReID datasets and one vehicle ReID dataset demonstrate that our method consistently outperforms existing CS approaches, establishing a new state-of-the-art in CSOR.</p>","absKo":"<p>Coreset Selection (CS)лҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң мһ‘м§Җл§Ң лҢҖн‘ңм„ұ мһҲлҠ” л¶Җл¶„м§‘н•©мқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳм—¬ лӘЁлҚё н•ҷмҠөмқҳ ліөмһЎлҸ„лҘј мӨ„мқҙлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. CSлҠ” мЈјлЎң л¶„лҘҳ нғңмҠӨнҒ¬лҘј мӨ‘мӢ¬мңјлЎң м—°кө¬лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, object Re-identification (ReID)м—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” лЁјм Җ Object Re-identificationмқ„ мң„н•ң Coreset Selection (CSOR)мқ„ мөңм Ғ coresetкіј мөңм Ғ class subsetмқ„ н•Ёк»ҳ м°ҫлҠ” кіөлҸҷ мөңм Ғнҷ” л¬ём ңлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ReIDм—җм„ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё coreset кө¬м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң н•өмӢ¬ мҡ”мқёмңјлЎң intra-class diversityлҘј мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, ReID лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқҳ кі мң н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ Diversity-driven Class Pruning (DCP)кіј Coverage-Prioritized Sampling (CPS)мңјлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ 2лӢЁкі„ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ feature diversityк°Җ лӮ®мқҖ classлҘј pruningн•ҳм—¬ storage budgetмқ„ лӮҳлЁём§Җмқҳ м •ліҙм„ұ лҶ’мқҖ classм—җ н• лӢ№н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ easy-to-hard class мҲңм„ңлЎң sampleмқ„ greedyн•ҳкІҢ м„ нғқн•ҳм—¬ к°Ғ class лӮҙ feature coverageлҘј к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. м„ё к°ңмқҳ person ReID лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣкіј н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ vehicle ReID лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ кё°мЎҙ CS м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©° CSORм—җм„ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state-of-the-artлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63592","en":"World-Model Inspired Emotion-aware Token Refinement for Training-Free Multimodal Emotion Recognition","ko":"нӣҲл Ё м—ҶлҠ” л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ к°җм • мқёмӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң world-model мҳҒк°җ к°җм • мқём§Җ нҶ нҒ° м •м ң","authors":"Kejun Liu, Yuanyuan Liu, Ke Wang, Zhe Chen, Yibing Zhan, Wei Xiang, Hongyan Zhang","pos":"#1210","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ViQO8FlRFR","abs":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) show promise for Multimodal Emotion Recognition (MER) but often remain unreliable because sparse emotional cues could be easily overwhelmed and affected by redundant context. While fine-tuning is effective, it is usually costly when using large models. Training-free methods like chain-of-thought reasoning provide a practical alternative, but they mostly rely on heuristic prompting to influence the model behaviors and do not explicitly focus on emotion relevant tokens internally, which would allow decision-relevant emotional tokens to be diluted by environmental noise, resulting in unstable predictions. To address this limitation without training, we rethink MER from a world-model perspective that treats emotion as a latent state inferred from noisy and redundant multimodal observations. Under frozen parameters, this view suggests that robustness depends on constraining why and how tokens contribute to inference.  Based on this insight, we propose WETR (World-Model inspired Emotion-aware Token Refinement), a training-free, plug-and-play regulator that reshapes token usage through two mechanisms: Noise-suppressed Token Selection (NTS), which suppresses redundant intra-modal noise, and State-strengthened Token Reweighting (STR), which amplifies decision-relevant emotional tokens. Experiments on multiple MER benchmarks demonstrate that WETR consistently improves accuracy and stability under frozen parameters, which also improves token-level interpretability.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs)лҠ” Multimodal Emotion Recognition (MER)м—җ мң л§қн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, нқ¬мҶҢн•ң к°җм • лӢЁм„ңк°Җ мүҪкІҢ м••лҸ„лҗҳкі  мӨ‘ліөлҗң contextмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л°ӣкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ мӢ лў°м„ұмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§ҖлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. Fine-tuningмқҖ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖнҳ• modelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  л•ҢлҠ” ліҙнҶө л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬лӢӨ. chain-of-thought reasoning к°ҷмқҖ training-free methodлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё лҢҖм•Ҳмқҙм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ heuristic promptingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ model behaviorм—җ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мЈјл©°, лӮҙл¶Җм ҒмңјлЎң emotion кҙҖл Ё tokenм—җ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј decisionм—җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң emotional tokenмқҙ environmental noiseм—җ мқҳн•ҙ нқ¬м„қлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲкі , мҳҲмёЎмқҙ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙ н•ңкі„лҘј training м—Ҷмқҙ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” emotionмқ„ noisyн•ҳкі  мӨ‘ліөм Ғмқё multimodal observationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° м¶”лЎ лҗҳлҠ” latent stateлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” world-model кҙҖм җм—җм„ң MERлҘј лӢӨмӢң мғқк°Ғн•ңлӢӨ. нҢҢлқјлҜён„°к°Җ кі м •лҗң мғҒнғңм—җм„ң мқҙ кҙҖм җмқҖ robustnessк°Җ tokenмқҙ м¶”лЎ м—җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ, мҷң кё°м—¬н•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј м ңм•Ҫн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° лӢ¬л Ө мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” WETR (World-Model inspired Emotion-aware Token Refinement)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” two mechanismмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ token мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” training-free, plug-and-play regulatorмқҙлӢӨ. Noise-suppressed Token Selection (NTS)мқҖ мӨ‘ліөлҗң intra-modal noiseлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳкі , State-strengthened Token Reweighting (STR)мқҖ decision-relevant emotional tokenмқ„ мҰқнҸӯн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ MER benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ WETRк°Җ frozen parameter н•ҳм—җм„ң accuracyмҷҖ stabilityлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, token-level interpretabilityлҸ„ к°ңм„ н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62014","en":"Supervised Classification Heads as Semantic Prototypes: Unlocking Vision-Language Alignment via Weight Recycling","ko":"м§ҖлҸ„ л¶„лҘҳ н—Өл“ңлҘј semantic prototypeлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ weight recyclingмқ„ нҶөн•ң vision-language alignment лӢ¬м„ұ","authors":"David MГ©ndez, Roberto Confalonieri, Natalia DГӯaz-RodrГӯguez","pos":"#1214","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=khWPVCGMsG","abs":"<p>Vision-Language Models (VLMs) excel at tasks like zero-shot classification and cross-modal retrieval by mapping images and text to a shared space, but this requires expensive end-to-end training with massive paired datasets. Current post-hoc alignment methods reduce computational costs by connecting pretrained encoders through lightweight mappings, yet still demand substantial paired data. In this work, we investigate the potential of repurposing the classification heads of pretrained vision models as semantic prototypes. The recycling of these weights, typically discarded after pretraining, unlocks two distinct capabilities: it enables zero-shot alignment by using weights as semantic anchors, and serves as a robust data augmentation strategy by mixing these prototypes with real image-text pairs. We demonstrate that integrating our approach with several state-of-the-art post-hoc alignment techniques consistently boosts accuracy in cross-modal retrieval, zero- and few-shot classification tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Vision-Language Models (VLMs)лҠ” мқҙлҜём§ҖмҷҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлҘј кіөмң  кіөк°„мңјлЎң л§Өн•‘н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ zero-shot classificationкіј cross-modal retrieval к°ҷмқҖ мһ‘м—…м—җм„ң лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” л°©лҢҖн•ң paired datasetмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң кі л№„мҡ© end-to-end trainingмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ post-hoc alignment л°©лІ•мқҖ pretrained encoderлҘј кІҪлҹү mappingмңјлЎң м—°кІ°н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқ„ мӨ„мқҙм§Җл§Ң, м—¬м „нһҲ мғҒлӢ№н•ң м–‘мқҳ paired dataлҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” pretrained vision modelмқҳ classification headлҘј semantic prototypeмңјлЎң мһ¬нҷңмҡ©н•  к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. ліҙнҶө pretraining нӣ„ нҸҗкё°лҗҳлҚҳ мқҙ к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳлҘј мһ¬нҷңмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё кё°лҠҘмқҙ м—ҙлҰ°лӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” мқҙ к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳлҘј semantic anchorлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ zero-shot alignmentлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” мқҙ prototypeмқ„ мӢӨм ң image-text pairмҷҖ нҳјн•©н•ҳм—¬ robust data augmentation м „лһөмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқ„ м—¬лҹ¬ state-of-the-art post-hoc alignment кё°лІ•кіј нҶөн•©н•  л•Ң cross-modal retrieval, zero-shot л°Ҹ few-shot classification мһ‘м—… м „л°ҳм—җм„ң м •нҷ•лҸ„к°Җ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67242","en":"Position: Universal Aesthetic Alignment Narrows Artistic Expression","ko":"Position: ліҙнҺём Ғ лҜён•ҷ м •л ¬мқҖ мҳҲмҲ м Ғ н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ нҳ‘мҶҢн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ","authors":"Wenqi Guo, Qingyun Qian, Khalad Hasan, Shan Du","pos":"#2604","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1gQ4zc1Q8I","abs":"<p>Over-aligning image generation models to a generalized aesthetic preference conflicts with user intent, particularly when \"anti-aesthetic\" outputs are requested for artistic or critical purposes. This adherence prioritizes developer-centered values, compromising user autonomy and aesthetic pluralism. We test this bias by constructing a wide-spectrum aesthetics dataset and evaluating state-of-the-art generation and reward models. This position paper finds that aesthetic-aligned generation models frequently default to conventionally beautiful outputs, failing to respect instructions for low-quality or negative imagery. Crucially, reward models penalize anti-aesthetic images even when they perfectly match the explicit user prompt. We confirm this systemic bias through image-to-image editing and evaluation against real abstract artworks.</p>","absKo":"<p>мқҙлҜём§Җ мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗң лҜём Ғ м„ нҳём—җ м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ м •л ¬мӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқҖ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мқҳлҸ„мҷҖ м¶©лҸҢн•ҳл©°, нҠ№нһҲ мҳҲмҲ м Ғ лҳҗлҠ” л№„нҢҗм Ғ лӘ©м Ғм—җм„ң \"anti-aesthetic\" м¶ңл Ҙмқҙ мҡ”мІӯлҗ  л•Ң лҚ”мҡұ к·ёл ҮлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҲңмқ‘мқҖ developer-centered valuesлҘј мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳм—¬ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мһҗмңЁм„ұкіј лҜём Ғ лӢӨмӣҗм„ұмқ„ нӣјмҶҗн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң aesthetics datasetмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мөңмӢ  generation л°Ҹ reward modelмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ нҺён–Ҙмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ position paperлҠ” aesthetic-aligned generation modelмқҙ кҙҖмҠөм ҒмңјлЎң м•„лҰ„лӢӨмҡҙ м¶ңл ҘмңјлЎң мһҗмЈј кё°ліё м„Өм •лҗҳл©°, лӮ®мқҖ н’Ҳм§ҲмқҙлӮҳ л¶Җм •м Ғ мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” м§ҖмӢңлҘј мЎҙмӨ‘н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң, reward modelмқҖ лӘ…мӢңм Ғ user promptмҷҖ мҷ„лІҪн•ҳкІҢ мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ anti-aesthetic мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј penalizeн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” image-to-image editingкіј мӢӨм ң abstract artworkмҷҖмқҳ л№„көҗ нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң system-wide biasлҘј нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66604","en":"Comp-Attn: Present-and-Align Attention for Compositional Video Genneration","ko":"Comp-Attn: кө¬м„ұм Ғ л№„л””мҳӨ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң Present-and-Align Attention","authors":"Hongyu Zhang, Yufan Deng, Shenghai Yuan, Yian Zhao, Peng Jin, Xuehan Hou, Chang Liu, Jie Chen","pos":"#2712","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2DyKW8qHDL","abs":"<p>In the domain of text-to-video (T2V) generation, reliably synthesizing compositional content involving multiple subjects with intricate relations is still underexplored. The main challenges are twofold: 1) Subject presence, where not all subjects can be presented in the video; 2) Inter-subject relations, where the interaction and spatial relationship between subjects are misaligned. Existing methods adopt techniques, such as inference-time latent optimization or layout control, which fail to address both issues simultaneously. To tackle these problems, we propose \\textbf{Comp-Attn}, a composition-aware cross-attention variant that follows a \\textbf{``Present-and-AlignвҖқ }paradigm: it decouples the two challenges by enforcing subject presence at the condition level and achieving relational alignment at the attention-distribution level. Specifically, 1) We introduce Subject-aware Condition Interpolation (SCI) to reinforce subject-specific conditions and ensure each subject's presence; 2) We propose Layout-forcing Attention Modulation (LAM), which dynamically enforces the attention distribution to align with the relational layout of multiple subjects. Comp-Attn can be seamlessly integrated into various T2V baselines in a training-free manner, boosting T2V-CompBench scores by 15.7\\% and 11.7\\% on Wan2.1-T2V-14B and Wan2.2-T2V-A14B with only a 5\\% increase in inference time. Meanwhile, it also achieves strong performance on VBench and T2I-CompBench, demonstrating its scalability in general video generation and compositional text-to-image (T2I) tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>text-to-video (T2V) generation мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң, ліөмһЎн•ң кҙҖкі„лҘј к°Җм§„ м—¬лҹ¬ subjectлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” compositional contentлҘј м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң н•©м„ұн•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлҠ” м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мЈјмҡ” лӮңм җмқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§ҖлӢӨ. 1) Subject presence: лӘЁл“  subjectк°Җ videoм—җ лӮҳнғҖлӮҳм§Җ м•Ҡмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. 2) Inter-subject relations: subject к°„ interactionкіј кіөк°„м Ғ кҙҖкі„к°Җ м–ҙкёӢлӮ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ inference-time latent optimizationмқҙлӮҳ layout control к°ҷмқҖ кё°лІ•мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙ л‘җ л¬ём ңлҘј лҸҷмӢңм—җ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{Comp-Attn}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” \\textbf{вҖңPresent-and-AlignвҖқ }нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ л”°лҘҙлҠ” composition-aware cross-attention variantлЎң, condition levelм—җм„ң subject presenceлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳкі  attention-distribution levelм—җм„ң relational alignmentлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ л‘җ л¬ём ңлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳм—¬ лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, 1) subject-specific conditionмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳкі  к°Ғ subjectмқҳ мЎҙмһ¬лҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ Subject-aware Condition Interpolation (SCI)мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. 2) attention distributionмқҙ м—¬лҹ¬ subjectмқҳ relational layoutкіј м •л ¬лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” Layout-forcing Attention Modulation (LAM)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Comp-AttnмқҖ training-free л°©мӢқмңјлЎң лӢӨм–‘н•ң T2V baselineм—җ л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ нҶөн•©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, inference timeмқ„ 5\\%л§Ң мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ң Wan2.1-T2V-14BмҷҖ Wan2.2-T2V-A14Bм—җм„ң T2V-CompBench м җмҲҳлҘј к°Ғк°Ғ 15.7\\%, 11.7\\% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. лҸҷмӢңм—җ VBenchмҷҖ T2I-CompBenchм—җм„ңлҸ„ к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, мқјл°ҳ video generationкіј compositional text-to-image (T2I) taskлЎңмқҳ нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62940","en":"AlignVid: Taming Visual Dominance via Training-Free Attention Modulation in Text-guided Image-to-Video Generation","ko":"AlignVid: н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мЎ°кұҙ мқҙлҜём§Җ-л№„л””мҳӨ мғқм„ұм—җм„ң Training-Free Attention ModulationмңјлЎң Visual Dominance мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Yexin Liu, Wenjie Shu, Zile Huang, Haoze Zheng, Yueze Wang, Manyuan Zhang, Jinjing Zhu, Ser-Nam Lim, Harry Yang","pos":"#2814","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bgtUrDtKjF","abs":"<p>Text-guided image-to-video generation has made substantial progress, yet it still struggles to execute text-specified edits that require substantial changes to a reference image (e.g., object addition, deletion, or modification). Empirically, our analysis reveals that this stems from <strong>visual dominance</strong>, where the reference image causes severe attention dispersion, inhibiting the model's ability to incorporate new semantic information. To address this, we propose <strong>AlignVid</strong>, a training-free intervention that re-calibrates the model's internal attention distribution. Drawing on an energy-based perspective of attention, AlignVid employs Attention Scaling Modulation (<strong>ASM</strong>) to reduce attention entropy and concentrate focus on semantic tokens, alongside Guidance Scheduling (<strong>GS</strong>) to maintain generation stability. To rigorously assess this capability, we present <strong>OmitI2V</strong>, a comprehensive benchmark for evaluating prompt adherence across object addition, deletion, and modification. Extensive experiments demonstrate that AlignVid effectively enhances semantic fidelity with negligible computational overhead.</p>","absKo":"<p>Text-guided image-to-video generationмқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈЁм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, м—¬м „нһҲ reference imageм—җ нҒ° ліҖнҷ”лҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” text-specified edit(мҳҲ: object addition, deletion, modification)мқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙкІғмқҙ <strong>visual dominance</strong>м—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҰү, reference imageк°Җ мӢ¬н•ң attention dispersionмқ„ мң л°ңн•ҳм—¬ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ semantic informationмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ м Җн•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚё лӮҙл¶Җ attention distributionмқ„ мһ¬ліҙм •н•ҳлҠ” training-free interventionмқё <strong>AlignVid</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. attentionм—җ лҢҖн•ң energy-based кҙҖм җм—җм„ң м¶ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬, AlignVidлҠ” Attention Scaling Modulation(<strong>ASM</strong>)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ attention entropyлҘј лӮ®м¶”кі  semantic tokenм—җ м§‘мӨ‘мқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳл©°, Guidance Scheduling(<strong>GS</strong>)мқ„ н•Ёк»ҳ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ generation stabilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ м—„кІ©нһҲ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” object addition, deletion, modification м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң prompt adherenceлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” мў…н•© benchmarkмқё <strong>OmitI2V</strong>лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ AlignVidк°Җ кұ°мқҳ м¶”к°Җ кі„мӮ° л¶ҖлӢҙ м—Ҷмқҙ semantic fidelityлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63682","en":"Keep It in Mind: User Centric Continual Spatial Intelligence Reasoning in Egocentric Video Streams","ko":"кё°м–ө мҶҚм—җ лӢҙм•„л‘җкё°: egocentric л№„л””мҳӨ мҠӨнҠёлҰјм—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мӨ‘мӢ¬ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғ кіөк°„ м§ҖлҠҘ м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Yun Wang, Junbin Xiao, Han Lyu, Yifan Wang, Jing Zuo, Zhanjie Zhang, Hong Huang, Dapeng Wu, Angela Yao","pos":"#3012","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=UfVYPA9VnD","abs":"<p>We introduce UCS-Bench, a dataset spanning 170+ hours of egocentric visual observations with 7K+ timestamped questions for diagnosing User-centric Continual Spatial intelligence in egocentric video streams. UCS-Bench targets a new problem that emphasizes dynamic spatial reasoning, long-term memory, and their alignment with users' real-time locations. We propose DirectMe, a framework that incrementally constructs and maintains a structured spatial memory from streaming egocentric observations. DirectMe enables robust tracking and recall of object locations, all relative to user's movement over time. By tightly coupling visual perception with memory updates and spatial reasoning, our approach supports long-horizon queries that require recalling interactions, resolving viewpoint-induced ambiguities, and adaptation to dynamic scenes. Our experiments show that DirectMe significantly improves the spatial reasoning of leading multimodal LLMs; it also surpasses many spatial-aware and long streaming video models. We hope our benchmark and solution will advance spatial intelligence research for egocentric AI assistants. Data and code will be released.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” egocentric video streamм—җм„ң User-centric Continual Spatial intelligenceлҘј м§„лӢЁн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң 7K+к°ңмқҳ timestamped questionкіј 170мӢңк°„ мқҙмғҒмқҳ egocentric visual observationмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқё UCS-BenchлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. UCS-BenchлҠ” лҸҷм Ғмқё spatial reasoning, мһҘкё° кё°м–ө, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мқҙл“Өмқҙ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗл“Өмқҳ мӢӨмӢңк°„ мң„м№ҳмҷҖ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м •л ¬лҗҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л¬ём ңлҘј лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” streaming egocentric observationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° structured spatial memoryлҘј м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң кө¬м¶•н•ҳкі  мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” frameworkмқё DirectMeлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. DirectMeлҠ” мӢңк°„м—җ л”°лҘё мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗмқҳ мӣҖм§Ғмһ„мқ„ кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң к°қмІҙ мң„м№ҳлҘј к°•кұҙн•ҳкІҢ м¶”м Ғн•ҳкі  нҡҢмғҒн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. visual perceptionмқ„ memory update л°Ҹ spatial reasoningкіј кёҙл°Җн•ҳкІҢ кІ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ нҡҢмғҒн•ҳкі , кҙҖм җ м°ЁмқҙлЎң мқён•ң лӘЁнҳём„ұмқ„ н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳл©°, лҸҷм Ғ sceneм—җ м Ғмқ‘н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” мһҘкё° horizon queryлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ DirectMeк°Җ м„ лҸ„м Ғмқё multimodal LLMмқҳ spatial reasoningмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, л§ҺмқҖ spatial-aware л°Ҹ long streaming video modelліҙлӢӨлҸ„ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ benchmarkмҷҖ solutionмқҙ egocentric AI assistantлҘј мң„н•ң spatial intelligence м—°кө¬лҘј м§„м „мӢңнӮӨкё°лҘј кё°лҢҖн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63393","en":"MM-DeepResearch: A Simple and Effective Multimodal Agentic Search Baseline","ko":"MM-DeepResearch: к°„лӢЁн•ҳкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ м—җмқҙм „нҠёнҳ• кІҖмғү лІ мқҙмҠӨлқјмқё","authors":"Huanjin Yao, Qixiang Yin, Min Yang, Ziwang Zhao, Yibo Wang, Haotian Luo, Jingyi Zhang, Jiaxing Huang","pos":"#3014","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XZAOCytvKQ","abs":"<p>We aim to develop a multimodal research agent capable of explicit reasoning and planning, multi-tool invocation, and cross-modal information synthesis, enabling it to conduct deep research tasks. However, we observe three main challenges in developing such agents: (1) scarcity of search-intensive multimodal QA data, (2) lack of effective search trajectories, and (3) prohibitive cost of training with online search APIs. To tackle them, we first propose <strong>Hyper-Search</strong>, a hypergraph-based QA generation method that models and connects visual and textual nodes within and across modalities, enabling to generate search-intensive multimodal QA pairs that require invoking various search tools to solve. Second, we introduce <strong>DR-TTS</strong>, which first decomposes search-involved tasks into several categories according to search tool types, and respectively optimize specialized search tool experts for each tool. It then recomposes tool experts to jointly explore search trajectories via tree search, producing trajectories that successfully solve complex tasks using various search tools. Third, we build an offline search engine supporting multiple search tools, enabling agentic reinforcement learning without using costly online search APIs. With the three designs, we develop <strong>MM-DeepResearch</strong>, a powerful multimodal deep research agent, and extensive results shows its superiority across benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” explicit reasoningкіј planning, multi-tool invocation, cross-modal information synthesisк°Җ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң multimodal research agentлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬ к№Ҡмқҙ мһҲлҠ” research taskлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң agentлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ мЈјмҡ” кіјм ңк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨ. (1) search-intensiveн•ң multimodal QA dataмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұ, (2) нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё search trajectoryмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬, (3) online search APIлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң н•ҷмҠө л№„мҡ©мқҳ кіјлҸ„н•Ёмқҙ к·ёкІғмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, лЁјм Җ <strong>Hyper-Search</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” hypergraph-based QA generation methodлЎңм„ң, modality лӮҙл¶ҖмҷҖ modality к°„м—җ visual nodeмҷҖ textual nodeлҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкі  м—°кІ°н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, н•ҙкІ°мқ„ мң„н•ҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң search tool нҳём¶ңмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң search-intensive multimodal QA pairлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>DR-TTS</strong>лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лЁјм Җ search кҙҖл Ё taskлҘј search tool typeм—җ л”°лқј м—¬лҹ¬ лІ”мЈјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳкі , к°Ғ toolм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ specialized search tool expertлҘј к°Ғк°Ғ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ tool expertлҘј лӢӨмӢң мЎ°н•©н•ҳм—¬ tree searchлҘј нҶөн•ҙ search trajectoryлҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң нғҗмғүн•ҳкі , лӢӨм–‘н•ң search toolмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ ліөмһЎн•ң taskлҘј м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” trajectoryлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. м…Ӣм§ё, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° online search APIлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ agentic reinforcement learningмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м—¬лҹ¬ search toolмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” offline search engineмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„ё к°Җм§Җ м„Өкі„лҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң multimodal deep research agentмқё <strong>MM-DeepResearch</strong>лҘј к°ңл°ңн–Ҳмңјл©°, кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң к·ё мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65336","en":"SkelHCC: A Hyperbolic CLIP-Driven Cache Adaptation Framework for Skeleton-based One-Shot Action Recognition","ko":"SkelHCC: кіЁкІ© кё°л°ҳ One-Shot лҸҷмһ‘ мқёмӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң мҢҚкіЎ CLIP кё°л°ҳ мәҗмӢң м Ғмқ‘ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Yanan Liu, Anqi Zhu, Jingmin Zhu, Jun Liu, Hossein Rahmani, Mohammed Bennamoun, Farid Boussaid, Dan Xu, Qiuhong Ke","pos":"#3907","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ee3Wh716Wm","abs":"<p>Skeleton-based action recognition aims to understand human behaviors from body joint sequences and is especially challenging in the one-shot setting, where only a single labeled exemplar is available for each novel action. A key challenge is learning representations that capture the hierarchical and compositional structure of human motion while aligning effectively with high-level action semantics under extreme data scarcity. Existing approaches, largely based on Euclidean embeddings and low-level motion cues, struggle to model the tree-like organization of skeleton data, limiting cross-modal alignment and generalization to unseen action categories. We propose SkelHCC, a unified skeleton hyperbolic CLIP-driven cache adaptation framework for one-shot skeleton-based action recognition. SkelHCC introduces an Explicitly Hierarchical Hyperbolic CLIP (EH-HCLIP) module that embeds skeleton sequences and action language into a shared hyperbolic space. By leveraging the negative curvature and exponential volume growth of hyperbolic geometry, EH-HCLIP naturally encodes the jointвҖ“partвҖ“body hierarchy of human anatomy and yields structurally consistent cross-modal representations. To support efficient one-shot adaptation, SkelHCC further integrates a training-free LLM-guided Multi-granularity Voting Cache (LMV-Cache) for context-aware inference. Experiments on NTU RGB+D 60, NTU RGB+D 120, and PKU-MMD II demonstrate that SkelHCC consistently outperforms state-of-the-art methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Skeleton-based action recognitionмқҖ body joint sequenceлЎңл¶Җн„° мқёк°„ н–үлҸҷмқ„ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳл©°, novel actionл§ҲлӢӨ лӢЁ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ labeled exemplarл§Ң мЈјм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” one-shot settingм—җм„ң нҠ№нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлҠ” мқёк°„ лҸҷмһ‘мқҳ hierarchicalн•ҳкі  compositionalн•ң кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ к·№лӢЁм Ғмқё data scarcity н•ҳм—җм„ң кі мҲҳмӨҖ action semanticsмҷҖ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м •л ¬лҗҳлҠ” representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң Euclidean embeddingкіј м ҖмҲҳмӨҖ motion cueм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬ skeleton dataмқҳ tree-like organizationмқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘкі , мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ cross-modal alignmentмҷҖ unseen action categoryлЎңмқҳ generalizationмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” one-shot skeleton-based action recognitionмқ„ мң„н•ң unified skeleton hyperbolic CLIP-driven cache adaptation frameworkмқё SkelHCCлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SkelHCCлҠ” skeleton sequenceмҷҖ action languageлҘј кіөмң  hyperbolic spaceм—җ мһ„лІ л”©н•ҳлҠ” Explicitly Hierarchical Hyperbolic CLIP(EH-HCLIP) лӘЁл“Ҳмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. Hyperbolic geometryмқҳ negative curvatureмҷҖ exponential volume growthлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, EH-HCLIPмқҖ мқёк°„ н•ҙл¶Җн•ҷмқҳ jointвҖ“partвҖ“body hierarchyлҘј мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳкі  кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң мқјкҙҖлҗң cross-modal representationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё one-shot adaptationмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, SkelHCCлҠ” context-aware inferenceлҘј мң„н•ң training-free LLM-guided Multi-granularity Voting Cache(LMV-Cache)лҸ„ нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. NTU RGB+D 60, NTU RGB+D 120, PKU-MMD IIм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SkelHCCк°Җ state-of-the-art л°©лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65488","en":"Find, Fix, Reason: Context Repair for Video Reasoning","ko":"м°ҫкі , кі м№ҳкі , м¶”лЎ н•ҳкё°: л№„л””мҳӨ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң л§ҘлқҪ мҲҳлҰ¬","authors":"Haojian Huang, Chuanyu Qin, Yinchuan Li, YINGCONG CHEN","pos":"#3908","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=D7MzX6ts55","abs":"<p>Reinforcement learning has advanced video reasoning in large multi-modal models, yet dominant pipelines either rely on on-policy self-exploration, which plateaus at the modelвҖҷs knowledge boundary, or hybrid replay that mixes policies and demands careful regularization. Dynamic context methods zoom into focused evidence but often require curated pretraining and two-stage tuning, and their context remains bounded by a small modelвҖҷs capability. In contrast, larger models excel at instruction following and multi-modal understanding, can supply richer context to smaller models, and rapidly zoom in on target regions via simple tools. Building on this capability, we introduce an observation-level intervention: a frozen, tool-integrated teacher identifies the missing spatiotemporal dependency and provides a minimal evidence patch (e.g. timestamps, regions etc.) from the original video while the question remains unchanged. The student answers again with the added context, and training updates with a chosen-rollout scheme integrated into GRPO. We further propose a Robust Improvement Reward (RIR) that aligns optimization with two goals: outcome validity through correct answers and dependency alignment through rationales that reflect the cited evidence. Advantages are group-normalized across the batch, preserving on-policy exploration while directing it along causally meaningful directions with minimal changes to the training stack. Experiments on general video and video-reasoning benchmarks show consistent accuracy gains and strong generalization.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң reinforcement learningмқҖ video reasoningмқ„ л°ңм „мӢңмјң мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, мЈјлҘҳ нҢҢмқҙн”„лқјмқёмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң лӘЁлҚёмқҳ knowledge boundaryм—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ м •мІҙлҗҳлҠ” on-policy self-explorationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё policyлҘј м„һкі  м„ёмӢ¬н•ң regularizationмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” hybrid replayм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. Dynamic context л°©лІ•мқҖ м§‘мӨ‘лҗң evidenceлЎң мӢңм•јлҘј мўҒнһҲм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖк°ң м •м ңлҗң pretrainingкіј two-stage tuningмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳл©°, к·ё context м—ӯмӢң мһ‘мқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ capabilityм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ лҚ” нҒ° лӘЁлҚёмқҖ instruction followingкіј multimodal understandingм—җ к°•н•ҳкі , лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ лӘЁлҚём—җ лҚ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң contextлҘј м ңкіөн•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, к°„лӢЁн•ң toolsлҘј нҶөн•ҙ target regionмңјлЎң л№ лҘҙкІҢ zoom inн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң capabilityлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” observation-level interventionмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, frozenлҗң tool-integrated teacherк°Җ л№ м§„ spatiotemporal dependencyлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , questionмқҖ к·ёлҢҖлЎң л‘” мұ„ мӣҗліё videoм—җм„ң мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ evidence patch(мҳҲ: timestamps, regions л“ұ)лҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. studentлҠ” м¶”к°Җлҗң contextмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ лӢӨмӢң лӢөліҖн•ҳкі , trainingмқҖ GRPOм—җ нҶөн•©лҗң chosen-rollout schemeмңјлЎң м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј л‘җ к°Җм§Җ лӘ©н‘ңм—җ л§һм¶”лҠ” Robust Improvement Reward (RIR)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” м •лӢөмқ„ нҶөн•ң outcome validityмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” мқёмҡ©лҗң evidenceлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ” rationaleмқ„ нҶөн•ң dependency alignmentмқҙлӢӨ. мһҘм җмқҖ batch м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ group-normalizedлҗҳл©°, training stackм—җ мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ ліҖкІҪл§Ң к°Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң causalн•ҳкІҢ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң on-policy explorationмқ„ мң м§Җн•ң мұ„ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳ video л°Ҹ video-reasoning benchmark мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң м •нҷ•лҸ„ н–ҘмғҒкіј к°•н•ң generalizationмқҙ нҷ•мқёлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61025","en":"MME-Reasoning: A Broad-Spectrum Benchmark for Evaluating Logical Reasoning in MLLMs","ko":"MME-Reasoning: MLLMмқҳ л…јлҰ¬ м¶”лЎ  нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Jiakang Yuan, Tianshuo Peng, Yilei Jiang, Yiting Lu, Renrui Zhang, Kaituo Feng, Chaoyou Fu, Tao Chen, LEI BAI, Bo Zhang","pos":"#404","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=uQiVJ2vKhL","abs":"<p>Logical reasoning is a fundamental aspect of human intelligence and an essential capability for multimodal large language models (MLLMs). Despite the significant advancement in multimodal reasoning, existing benchmarks fail to comprehensively evaluate their reasoning abilities due to the lack of explicit categorization for logical reasoning types and an unclear understanding of reasoning. To address these issues, we introduce MME-Reasoning, a comprehensive benchmark designed to evaluate the reasoning ability of MLLMs, which covers all three types of reasoning (i.e., inductive, deductive, and abductive). We carefully curate the data to ensure that each question effectively evaluates reasoning ability rather than perceptual skills or knowledge breadth, and extend the evaluation protocols to cover the evaluation of diverse questions. Our evaluation reveals substantial limitations of SoTA MLLMs when subjected to holistic assessments of logical reasoning capabilities. Even the most advanced MLLMs show limited performance in comprehensive logical reasoning, with notable performance imbalances across reasoning types. In addition, we conducted an in-depth analysis of approaches such as ``thinking mode'' and Rule-based RL, which are commonly believed to enhance reasoning abilities. We hope the community can pay more attention to the comprehensive reasoning capabilities of MLLMs instead of only focusing on its subset.</p>","absKo":"<p>л…јлҰ¬м Ғ м¶”лЎ мқҖ мқёк°„ м§ҖлҠҘмқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё мёЎл©ҙмқҙл©°, multimodal large language models (MLLMs)м—җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё лҠҘл ҘмқҙлӢӨ. multimodal reasoningмқҳ нҒ° л°ңм „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , кё°мЎҙ benchmarkлҠ” л…јлҰ¬м Ғ м¶”лЎ  мң нҳ•м—җ лҢҖн•ң лӘ…мӢңм Ғ л¶„лҘҳк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳкі  м¶”лЎ м—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙн•ҙлҸ„лҸ„ л¶ҲлӘ…нҷ•н•ҳм—¬ к·ё reasoning abilityлҘј нҸ¬кҙ„м ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MLLMsмқҳ reasoning abilityлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғ benchmarkмқё MME-Reasoningмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ benchmarkлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ м¶”лЎ  мң нҳ•, мҰү inductive, deductive, abductiveлҘј лӘЁл‘җ нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ м§Ҳл¬ёмқҙ perceptual skillмқҙлӮҳ м§ҖмӢқ лІ”мң„к°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј reasoning abilityлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мӢ мӨ‘н•ҳкІҢ м„ лі„н–Ҳмңјл©°, лӢӨм–‘н•ң м§Ҳл¬ёмқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ evaluation protocolлҸ„ нҷ•мһҘн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіјлҠ” л…јлҰ¬м Ғ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң м „мІҙм Ғ нҸүк°ҖлҘј м Ғмҡ©н–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң SoTA MLLMsмқҳ мғҒлӢ№н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. к°ҖмһҘ л°ңм „лҗң MLLMsмЎ°м°ЁлҸ„ нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё л…јлҰ¬м Ғ м¶”лЎ м—җм„ңлҠ” м ңн•ңм Ғмқё м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, м¶”лЎ  мң нҳ• к°„ м„ұлҠҘ л¶Ҳк· нҳ•лҸ„ л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„лӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨкі  нқ”нһҲ м—¬кІЁм§ҖлҠ” ``thinking mode''мҷҖ Rule-based RL к°ҷмқҖ м ‘к·јлІ•м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мӢ¬мёө л¶„м„қмқ„ мҲҳн–үн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кіөлҸҷмІҙк°Җ м¶”лЎ мқҳ мқјл¶Җ subsetм—җл§Ң м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ MLLMsмқҳ нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё reasoning capabilityм—җ лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ кҙҖмӢ¬мқ„ кё°мҡёмқҙкё°лҘј л°”лһҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61108","en":"Mitigating Perceptual Judgment Bias in Multimodal LLM-as-a-Judge via Perceptual Perturbation and Reward Modeling","ko":"Perceptual Perturbationкіј Reward Modelingмқ„ нҶөн•ң Multimodal LLM-as-a-Judgeмқҳ м§Җк°Ғ нҢҗлӢЁ нҺён–Ҙ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Seojeong Park, Jiho Choi, Junyong Kang, Seonho Lee, Jaeyo Shin, Hyunjung Shim","pos":"#600","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tbqxbGMFUV","abs":"<p>Recent multimodal large language models have demonstrated strong reasoning ability, yet their reliability as automated evaluators remains limited by a critical weakness: when visual evidence conflicts with textual cues, MLLM judges tend to reward plausible narratives over perceptually correct answers. We identify and systematically analyze this phenomenon, which we term \\textit{Perceptual Judgment Bias}. Through controlled visual perturbations, existing multimodal judges frequently anchor on the response text instead of their own visual perception, leading to inconsistent and non-verifiable evaluations. To address this issue, we introduce the \\textit{Perceptually Perturbed Judgment Dataset}, which constructs minimally edited counterfactual responses that isolate perceptual errors and enable verifiable supervision. Building on this dataset, we develop a unified training framework that combines a structured GRPO-based reward with a batch-ranking objective, achieving coherent global ordering without explicit pairwise labels. Experiments across diverse MLLM-as-a-Judge benchmarks show that our approach substantially improves perceptual fidelity, ranking coherence, and alignment with human evaluation. Our results establish a scalable and generalizable pathway for training multimodal judges that are perceptually grounded, interpretable, and robust to visualвҖ“reasoning conflicts.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј multimodal large language modelмқҖ к°•н•ң reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мһҗлҸҷ нҸүк°ҖмһҗлЎңм„ңмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұмқҖ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м•Ҫм җ л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мӢңк°Ғм Ғ мҰқкұ°к°Җ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё лӢЁм„ңмҷҖ м¶©лҸҢн•  л•Ң, MLLM judgeлҠ” perceptually correct answerліҙлӢӨ к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•ң м„ңмҲ мқ„ лҚ” лҶ’кІҢ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ \\textit{Perceptual Judgment Bias}лқјкі  лӘ…лӘ…н•ҳкі  мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. м ңм–ҙлҗң visual perturbationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, кё°мЎҙ multimodal judgeлҠ” мһҗмӢ мқҳ visual perceptionліҙлӢӨ response textм—җ м•өм»Өл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„, мқјкҙҖм„ұ м—Ҷкі  кІҖмҰқ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҸүк°ҖлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м§Җк°Ғ мҳӨлҘҳлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкі  кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң supervisionмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мөңмҶҢ нҺём§‘ counterfactual responseлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ң \\textit{Perceptually Perturbed Judgment Dataset}мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё pairwise label м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң GRPO-based rewardмҷҖ batch-ranking objectiveлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳм—¬ мқјкҙҖлҗң global orderingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© training frameworkлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң MLLM-as-a-Judge benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ perceptual fidelity, ranking coherence, к·ёлҰ¬кі  human evaluationкіјмқҳ м •л ¬мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” perceptually grounded, interpretableн•ҳл©° visual-reasoning conflictм—җ к°•кұҙн•ң multimodal judgeлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  мқјл°ҳнҷ” к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60488","en":"Q-CLIP: Unleashing the Power of Vision-Language Models for Video Quality Assessment through Unified Cross-Modal Adaptation","ko":"Q-CLIP: Unified Cross-Modal Adaptationмқ„ нҶөн•ң Video Quality Assessmentм—җм„ң Vision-Language Modelмқҳ мһ мһ¬л Ҙ н•ҙл°©","authors":"Yachun Mi, Yu Li, Yanting Li, Chen Hui, Tong Zhang, Zhixuan Li, Chenyue Song, Wei Yang Bryan Lim, Shaohui Liu","pos":"#604","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=zmAMq09bFs","abs":"<p>Accurate and efficient Video Quality Assessment (VQA) has long been a key research challenge. Current mainstream VQA methods typically improve performance by pretraining on large-scale classification datasets, followed by fine-tuning on VQA datasets. However, this strategy presents two significant challenges: (1) merely transferring semantic knowledge learned from pretraining is insufficient for VQA, as video quality depends on multiple factors (e.g., semantics, distortion, motion); (2) pretraining on large-scale datasets demands enormous computational resources, often dozens to hundreds of times more than training on VQA datasets. Recently, Contrastive Vision-Language Models (CVLMs) have shown strong generalization across visual tasks and promising potential for quality assessment. In this work, we propose Q-CLIP, the first fully CVLMs-based framework for VQA. Q-CLIP enhances both visual and textual representations through a Shared Cross-Modal Adapter (SCMA), which contains only a minimal number of trainable parameters and is the only component that requires training. This design significantly reduces computational cost. In addition, we introduce a set of five learnable quality-level prompts to guide the CVLMs in perceiving subtle quality variations. Furthermore, we investigate the impact of different frame sampling strategies on VQA performance. Extensive experiments demonstrate that Q-CLIP exhibits excellent performance on several VQA datasets. Code is provided in the supplementary material.</p>","absKo":"<p>м •нҷ•н•ҳкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё Video Quality Assessment (VQA)лҠ” мҳӨлһ«лҸҷм•Ҳ н•өмӢ¬ м—°кө¬ кіјм ңмҳҖлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ мЈјлҘҳ VQA л°©лІ•мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ classification datasetмңјлЎң pretrainingн•ң л’Ө VQA datasetмңјлЎң fine-tuningн•ҳм—¬ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ м „лһөм—җлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң л¬ём ңк°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. (1) pretrainingм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөн•ң semantic knowledgeлҘј лӢЁмҲңнһҲ мқҙм „н•ҳлҠ” кІғл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” VQAм—җ м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. video qualityлҠ” semantics, distortion, motion л“ұ м—¬лҹ¬ мҡ”мқём—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. (2) лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ datasetмңјлЎң pretrainingн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” л§үлҢҖн•ң computational resourceк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мў…мў… VQA datasetмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ мҲҳмӢӯ л°°м—җм„ң мҲҳл°ұ л°° лҚ” нҒ¬лӢӨ. мөңк·ј Contrastive Vision-Language Models (CVLMs)лҠ” visual task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң к°•н•ң generalizationкіј quality assessmentм—җ лҢҖн•ң мң л§қн•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” VQAлҘј мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ fully CVLMs-based frameworkмқё Q-CLIPмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Q-CLIPмқҖ Shared Cross-Modal Adapter (SCMA)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ visual representationкіј textual representationмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, мқҙлҠ” к·№нһҲ м ҒмқҖ мҲҳмқҳ trainable parameterл§Ңмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳкі  н•ҷмҠөмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң мң мқјн•ң кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” computational costлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CVLMsк°Җ лҜёл¬ҳн•ң quality variationмқ„ мқёмӢқн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ 5к°ңмқҳ learnable quality-level prompt м„ёнҠёлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ frame sampling м „лһөмқҳ м°Ёмқҙк°Җ VQA м„ұлҠҘм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Q-CLIPмқҙ м—¬лҹ¬ VQA datasetм—җм„ң мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” supplementary materialм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63999","en":"Taming I2V models for Image HOI Editing:  A Cognitive Benchmark and Agentic Self-Correcting Framework","ko":"Image HOI Editingмқ„ мң„н•ң I2V models лӢӨлЈЁкё°: мқём§Җ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬мҷҖ м—җмқҙм „нӢұ мһҗкё° мҲҳм • н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Jiayi Gao, Qingchao Chen, Yuxin Peng, Yang Liu","pos":"#611","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RtesAw5Cka","abs":"<p>Current image editing methods excels at static attributes but fails at complex Human-Object Interactions (HOI), a critical challenge unaddressed by existing benchmarks that conflate HOI with static attributes, relying on global metrics incapable of simultaneously assessing dynamic interaction validity and entangled human-object pair preservation. Thus, we first introduce HOI-Edit, a comprehensive benchmark with three progressive cognitive levels, which features an automated metric HOI-Eval that first reliably evaluates instance-level interaction by letting VLM Q&amp;A after thinking with images containing grounded Human-Object pair. Considering the task's essence of remodeling dynamic relationships, we benchmark Image-to-Video (I2V) models, finding them inherently suited for dynamic editing due to their temporal generation capabilities. Crucially, beyond superior performance, this capability provides a \"replay of the failure process\", offering unique diagnosability into why errors occur. We thus propose SCPE (Self-Correcting Process Editing), a novel, agentic self-correcting framework that constrains the generation of I2V models through iteratively refined prompts, enabling the generated videos to more accurately present the target HOI. Extracted frames from these videos are the final editing results. On HOI-Edit, SCPE achieves performance competitive with state-of-the-art (SOTA) editing models like Nano Banana on interaction.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„мһ¬ image editing л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ м •м Ғ мҶҚм„ұм—җлҠ” к°•н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, ліөмһЎн•ң Human-Object Interactions(HOI)м—җм„ңлҠ” мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙ benchmarkл“Өмқҙ HOIмҷҖ м •м Ғ мҶҚм„ұмқ„ нҳјлҸҷн•ҳкі , лҸҷм Ғ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҳ мң нҡЁм„ұкіј м–ҪнһҢ human-object pair ліҙмЎҙмқ„ лҸҷмӢңм—җ нҸүк°Җн•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” global metricм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ н•ҙкІ°лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЁјм Җ HOI-Editмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. HOI-EditмқҖ 3к°ңмқҳ м җм§„м Ғ cognitive levelлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғ benchmarkмқҙл©°, grounded Human-Object pairк°Җ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗң мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мӮ¬кі н•ң л’Ө VLMмқҙ Q&amp;AлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳм—¬ instance-level interactionмқ„ лЁјм Җ мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” мһҗлҸҷ metric HOI-Evalмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. кіјм ңмқҳ ліём§Ҳмқҙ лҸҷм Ғ кҙҖкі„мқҳ мһ¬кө¬м„ұм—җ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ кі л Өн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Image-to-Video(I2V) лӘЁлҚёмқ„ benchmarkн–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙл“Өмқҙ мӢңк°„м Ғ мғқм„ұ лҠҘл Ҙ лҚ•л¶„м—җ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лҸҷм Ғ нҺём§‘м—җ м Ғн•©н•ҳлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң, мқҙ лҠҘл ҘмқҖ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ мӢӨнҢЁ кіјм •мқҳ replayлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм—¬ мҳӨлҘҳк°Җ мҷң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҸ…нҠ№н•ң м§„лӢЁ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұлҸ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SCPE(Self-Correcting Process Editing)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SCPEлҠ” л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң м •м ңлҗң promptлҘј нҶөн•ҙ I2V лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мғқм„ұмқ„ м ңм•Ҫн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мғқм„ұлҗң videoк°Җ лӘ©н‘ң HOIлҘј лҚ” м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“ңлҠ”, мғҲлЎңмҡҙ agentic self-correcting frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ videoм—җм„ң м¶”м¶ңн•ң frameмқҙ мөңмў… нҺём§‘ кІ°кіјк°Җ лҗңлӢӨ. HOI-Editм—җм„ң SCPEлҠ” interaction мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң Nano Banana к°ҷмқҖ state-of-the-art(SOTA) нҺём§‘ лӘЁлҚёкіј кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61353","en":"Video-BCI: Bayesian Cognitive Integration of Self-Prior Hypotheses for Video Understanding","ko":"Video-BCI: л№„л””мҳӨ мқҙн•ҙлҘј мң„н•ң Self-Prior к°Җм„Өмқҳ Bayesian Cognitive Integration","authors":"Xing Xi, Yu Qiu, Ronghua Luo, Peixian Chen, peilin tong, Jiahao Liang","pos":"#612","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=r3UhjF8Riy","abs":"<p>Recent progress in vision-language models (VLMs) has driven significant advances in video understanding. However, existing methods often act as naive empiricists, mapping video input directly to output without any mechanism to introspect or challenge inherent bias. In this work, we challenge this paradigm by reframing video reasoning as a Bayesian cognitive process. We propose Video-BCI (Bayesian Cognitive Integration of Self-Prior Hypotheses), a novel framework that first samples a set of Self-Prior Hypotheses to represent the model's intuitive yet potentially biased cognitive state, and then guides the VLMs to perform a critical integration of these priors. This process encourages the model to challenge erroneous majority consensus in cases of high information divergence and to distill superior reasoning chains from its own prior space. The integration is driven by a composite Cognitive Utility Function comprising two intrinsic learning signals: Dialectical Uncertainty Signal (DUS) and Process Tracing Signal (PTS). The DUS incentivizes correct, non-majority judgments by quantifying both the conflict (entropy) among priors and their consensus-challenging strength. The PTS guides the model to trace and learn from reasoning paths within its own priors that lead to better answers, enabling self-driven procedural knowledge distillation. Extensive experiments on six mainstream benchmarks show that Video-BCI achieves new state-of-the-art (SOTA) results across the board. For example, it surpasses the previous best on the MMVU benchmark by 3.8%. Our code will be made publicly available.</p>","absKo":"<p>vision-language model (VLM)мқҳ мөңк·ј м§„м „мқҖ video understandingмқҳ нҒ° л°ңм „мқ„ мқҙлҒҢм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мў…мў… naive empiricistмІҳлҹј лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳм—¬, л№„л””мҳӨ мһ…л Ҙмқ„ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң нҺён–Ҙмқ„ м„ұм°°н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ л¬ём ң мӮјлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳ м—Ҷмқҙ кі§л°”лЎң м¶ңл ҘмңјлЎң л§Өн•‘н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” video reasoningмқ„ Bayesian cognitive processлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„м—җ лҸ„м „н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Video-BCI (Bayesian Cognitive Integration of Self-Prior Hypotheses)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” лЁјм Җ Self-Prior Hypotheses м§‘н•©мқ„ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ҳм—¬ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ м§ҒкҙҖм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң мһ мһ¬м ҒмңјлЎң нҺён–Ҙлҗң мқём§Җ мғҒнғңлҘј н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳкі , мқҙнӣ„ VLMмқҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң priorлҘј л№„нҢҗм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лӢӨ. мқҙ кіјм •мқҖ м •ліҙ divergenceк°Җ нҒ° кІҪмҡ° мһҳлӘ»лҗң majority consensusм—җ лҸ„м „н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мһҘл Өн•ҳкі , мһҗмӢ мқҳ prior spaceм—җм„ң лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң reasoning chainмқ„ м •м ңн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөн•©мқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ intrinsic learning signalлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң ліөн•© Cognitive Utility Functionм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кө¬лҸҷлҗңлӢӨ: Dialectical Uncertainty Signal (DUS)кіј Process Tracing Signal (PTS)мқҙлӢӨ. DUSлҠ” priorл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ conflict(entropy)мҷҖ consensusм—җ лҸ„м „н•ҳлҠ” к°•лҸ„лҘј н•Ёк»ҳ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, м •нҷ•н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ majorityк°Җ м•„лӢҢ нҢҗлӢЁмқ„ мһҘл Өн•ңлӢӨ. PTSлҠ” лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ лӢөмңјлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” мһҗмӢ мқҳ prior лӮҙл¶Җ reasoning pathлҘј м¶”м Ғн•ҳкі  н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬, мһҗкё° мЈјлҸ„м Ғ procedural knowledge distillationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬м„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ мЈјлҘҳ benchmarkм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Video-BCIк°Җ м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state-of-the-art (SOTA) кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, MMVU benchmarkм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ мөңкі  м„ұлҠҘмқ„ 3.8%p лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61914","en":"VlogReward: Learning Multi-Dimensional Evaluation for Vlog Editing","ko":"VlogReward: Vlog нҺём§‘мқ„ мң„н•ң лӢӨм°Ёмӣҗ нҸүк°Җ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Yexiang Liu, Wen Zhong, Sijie Zhu, Xin Gu, Fan Chen, Junxian Duan, Jie Cao, Longyin Wen, Zhenfang Chen","pos":"#613","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lhLgdoemEJ","abs":"<p>The rapid rise of vlogs as a personalized storytelling medium has created a demand for automated systems to evaluate and refine vlog editing plans. However, vlog assessment is highly subjective and remains challenging due to a lack of standardized criteria, dataset and benchmark, and effective reward models. To address these challenges, we define a comprehensive vlog evaluation framework guided by professional vlog creators and product managers, establishing a taxonomy of six key dimensions, <em>i.e.</em>, <em>Creativity</em>, <em>Consistency</em>, <em>Concept Design</em>, <em>Cinematography</em>, <em>Narration</em>, and <em>Pacing</em>. Subsequently, we curate a large-scale dataset of 100k vlog edits and a dedicated benchmark, <strong>VRMBench</strong>, to evaluate the vlog rewarding capabilities of Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs). Finally, we present <strong>VlogReward</strong>, a robust vlog reward model that can provide both fine-grained multi-dimensional scores and actionable feedback for iterative refinement.   Technically, we enhance the Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) framework by introducing an adjustable inter-group comparison reward, which mitigates the \"direction blindness\" issue of standard GRPO and enables the model to better distinguish varied-quality edits.   VlogReward achieves state-of-the-art results that significantly outperform existing MLLMs, including GPT-5 and Gemini-3-Pro.    We hope that our study can help vlog creators and foster automated vlog evaluation and refinement systems.</p>","absKo":"<p>vlogк°Җ к°ңмқёнҷ”лҗң мҠӨнҶ лҰ¬н…”л§Ғ л§ӨмІҙлЎң л№ лҘҙкІҢ л¶ҖмғҒн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, vlog нҺём§‘ кі„нҡҚмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі  к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” мһҗлҸҷнҷ” мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҲҳмҡ”к°Җ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ vlog нҸүк°ҖлҠ” л§Өмҡ° мЈјкҙҖм Ғмқҙл©°, н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗң кё°мӨҖ, datasetкіј benchmark, к·ёлҰ¬кі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё reward modelмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬лЎң мқён•ҙ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м „л¬ё vlog creatorмҷҖ product managerмқҳ м§Җм№Ём—җ л”°лқј нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё vlog нҸүк°Җ frameworkлҘј м •мқҳн•ҳкі , <em>Creativity</em>, <em>Consistency</em>, <em>Concept Design</em>, <em>Cinematography</em>, <em>Narration</em>, <em>Pacing</em>мқҳ м—¬м„Ҝ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ м°ЁмӣҗмңјлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ taxonomyлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң 10л§Ң к°ңмқҳ vlog editлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ datasetкіј, Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs)мқҳ vlog rewarding лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң м „мҡ© benchmarkмқё <strong>VRMBench</strong>лҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, м„ёл°Җн•ң лӢӨм°Ёмӣҗ м җмҲҳмҷҖ л°ҳліөм Ғ к°ңм„ мқ„ мң„н•ң мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н”јл“ңл°ұмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ м ңкіөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кІ¬кі н•ң vlog reward modelмқё <strong>VlogReward</strong>лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мҲ м ҒмңјлЎңлҠ”, мЎ°м Ҳ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң inter-group comparison rewardлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) frameworkлҘј к°•нҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н‘ңмӨҖ GRPOмқҳ \"direction blindness\" л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкі , лӘЁлҚёмқҙ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҳ editлҘј лҚ” мһҳ кө¬л¶„н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. VlogRewardлҠ” GPT-5мҷҖ Gemini-3-ProлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң кё°мЎҙ MLLMл“Өмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©° state-of-the-art кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ліё м—°кө¬к°Җ vlog creatorм—җкІҢ лҸ„мӣҖмқҙ лҗҳкі , мһҗлҸҷнҷ”лҗң vlog нҸүк°Җ л°Ҹ к°ңм„  мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҳ л°ңм „мқ„ мҙүм§„н•ҳкёё кё°лҢҖн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63904","en":"Zero-Shot Text-to-Motion Evaluation using Video Language Models","ko":"л№„л””мҳӨ language modelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң zero-shot text-to-motion нҸүк°Җ","authors":"Yuwen Ji, Donglin Wang, Yue Zhang","pos":"#614","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Sf8ubkiEkW","abs":"<p>Text-to-motion (T2M) generation has emerged as a fundamental task. However, existing evaluation metrics often fail to accurately capture the semantic alignment between textual descriptions and generated 3D motions. In this work, we propose VeMo, a novel evaluation framework that leverages the zero-shot reasoning capabilities of Video-Language Models (VLMs) for T2M assessment. Our basic idea is: render the generated human motion into a skinned video, and then use a VLM for evaluation. To mitigate the information loss inherent in 3D-to-2D projections, we introduce an entropy-based uncertainty analysis that ensures the reliability of the evaluation scores. To address the lack of rigorous standards in the field, we contribute a meta-evaluation benchmark featuring manual annotations of coarse-grained alignment and fine-grained rationales. Extensive experiments demonstrate that VeMo significantly outperforms traditional metrics in human-alignment, offering a scalable and data-independent solution for the reliable assessment of T2M models.</p>","absKo":"Text-to-motion (T2M) generationмқҖ к·јліём Ғмқё taskлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ evaluation metricмқҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё м„ӨлӘ…кіј мғқм„ұлҗң 3D motion мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ semantic alignmentлҘј м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” T2M нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ҙ Video-Language Models (VLMs)мқҳ zero-shot reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ evaluation framework VeMoлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кё°ліё м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҠ” мғқм„ұлҗң human motionмқ„ skinned videoлЎң л ҢлҚ”л§Ғн•ң л’Ө, VLMмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. 3D-to-2D projectionм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң м •ліҙ мҶҗмӢӨмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, нҸүк°Җ м җмҲҳмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” entropy кё°л°ҳ uncertainty analysisлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¶„м•јм—җ м—„л°Җн•ң кё°мӨҖмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, coarse-grained alignmentмҷҖ fine-grained rationaleм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҲҳлҸҷ мЈјм„қмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” meta-evaluation benchmarkлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ VeMoк°Җ human-alignmentм—җм„ң м „нҶөм Ғмқё metricмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, T2M modelмқ„ мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  лҚ°мқҙн„° лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65434","en":"Memory as Dynamics: Learning Reliability-Guided Predictive Models for Online Video Perception","ko":"лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷмңјлЎңм„ңмқҳ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬: мҳЁлқјмқё л№„л””мҳӨ мқёмӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң мӢ лў°м„ұ кё°л°ҳ мҳҲмёЎ лӘЁлҚё н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Minwoo Kim, Sang Min Yoon","pos":"#701","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=DiIUn7KZ2k","abs":"<p>Predictive memory has recently emerged as a powerful mechanism for online video models, enabling temporal reasoning beyond static memory banks. However, we observe a paradoxical phenomenon in which predictive memory often exacerbates drift under occlusion or rapid motion, as inaccurate predictions contaminate the internal state and lead to irreversible identity loss. We identify this failure as a reliability mismatch: generative predictive dynamics are applied uniformly, even when their uncertainty is high and observational evidence is weak.  To address this issue, we reinterpret video memory as a dynamic latent process rather than a static buffer. Building on this insight, we introduce Reliability-guided Predictive Memory (RPM), a framework that explicitly regulates when and how predictive dynamics should influence online video perception. RPM integrates a latent world model based on state-space latent dynamics to generate predictive priors, while employing a reliability-aware fusion policy that adaptively suppresses unreliable predictions during challenging scenarios such as occlusion and re-acquisition.  We instantiate RPM on a SAM2-based foundation video model and evaluate it on challenging visual object tracking benchmarks, a representative instance of online video perception. Experimental results demonstrate that our method significantly reduces drift after occlusion, consistently outperforming strong baselines that rely on either static memory or unconditional predictive modeling. These findings establish that predictive memory is beneficial only when its reliability is explicitly modeled, and define a general principle for robust online video perception.</p>","absKo":"<p>Predictive memoryлҠ” мөңк·ј online video modelм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳмңјл©°, static memory bankлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„  temporal reasoningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” predictive memoryк°Җ occlusionмқҙлӮҳ л№ лҘё motion м•„лһҳм—җм„ң мҳӨнһҲл Ө driftлҘј м•…нҷ”мӢңнӮӨлҠ” м—ӯм„Өм Ғ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ. л¶Җм •нҷ•н•ң predictionмқҙ internal stateлҘј мҳӨм—јмӢңнӮӨкі  лҗҳлҸҢлҰҙ мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” identity lossлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§Җкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мӢӨнҢЁлҘј reliability mismatchлЎң к·ңм •н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, generative predictive dynamicsк°Җ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқҙ лҶ’кі  observational evidenceк°Җ м•Ҫн•ң мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ңлҸ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ м Ғмҡ©лҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” video memoryлҘј static bufferк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј лҸҷм Ғ latent processлЎң мһ¬н•ҙм„қн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” predictive dynamicsк°Җ online video perceptionм—җ м–ём ң, к·ёлҰ¬кі  м–ҙл–»кІҢ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜёміҗм•ј н•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” frameworkмқё Reliability-guided Predictive Memory (RPM)мқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. RPMмқҖ state-space latent dynamicsлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ң latent world modelмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҙ predictive priorлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, occlusionкіј re-acquisition к°ҷмқҖ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” predictionмқ„ м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң м–өм ңн•ҳлҠ” reliability-aware fusion policyлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” RPMмқ„ SAM2-based foundation video model мң„м—җ кө¬нҳ„н•ҳкі , online video perceptionмқҳ лҢҖн‘ңм Ғ мӮ¬лЎҖмқё м–ҙл Өмҡҙ visual object tracking benchmarkм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ occlusion мқҙнӣ„мқҳ driftлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқҙл©°, static memoryлӮҳ unconditional predictive modelingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” predictive memoryк°Җ к·ё мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•  л•Ңм—җл§Ң мң мқөн•ҳл©°, robust online video perceptionмқ„ мң„н•ң мқјл°ҳ мӣҗм№ҷмқ„ м ңмӢңн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60919","en":"MM-Snowball: Evaluating and Mitigating Hallucination Snowballing in Multimodal Multi-turn Dialogue","ko":"MM-Snowball: Multimodal Multi-turn Dialogueм—җм„ң Hallucination Snowballing нҸүк°Җ л°Ҹ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Yue Jiang, Xue JIANG, Lihua Zhang, Zhiqiang Wang, Yuhang Lu, Peng Wang, Bo Han, Feng Zheng, Dingkang Yang","pos":"#702","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vL1xAHOUmd","abs":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) demonstrate remarkable visual understanding, yet their reliability in interactive settings is severely undermined by {hallucination snowballing}: a phenomenon where initial errors amplify across conversational turns, leading to a collapse in coherence. This failure reveals a fundamental vulnerability where models progressively neglect visual grounding in favor of over-relying on polluted textual history. Existing benchmarks are predominantly confined to single-turn VQA or simplistic dialogues, which fail to capture the complex dynamics of error propagation in realistic, long-horizon interactions. To address this, we introduce MM-Snowball, the first benchmark for fine-grained diagnosis of hallucination snowballing within 6-turn dialogues.  Extensive evaluation shows that our benchmark poses a significant challenge even to advanced MLLMs and reveals the inefficacy of existing mitigation methods designed for single-turn tasks. To counteract this degradation, we propose Conflict-Aware Visual Rectification (CAVR). This training-free framework mitigates snowballing through a synergistic dual-mechanism that refreshes visual grounding at the representation level and rectifies output distributions at the logit level, effectively re-anchoring the model to visual facts. Experiments demonstrate that our proposed CAVR achieves state-of-the-art performance, offering a promising path toward more reliable interactive AI.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs)лҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң visual understandingмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм§Җл§Ң, мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұмқҖ {hallucination snowballing} нҳ„мғҒмңјлЎң мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мҙҲкё° мҳӨлҘҳк°Җ лҢҖнҷ” н„ҙмқҙ м§„н–үлҗ мҲҳлЎқ мҰқнҸӯлҗҳм–ҙ coherence л¶•кҙҙлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ мӢӨнҢЁлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мҳӨм—јлҗң textual historyм—җ кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ  visual groundingмқ„ м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң мҶҢнҷҖнһҲ н•ҳлҠ” к·јліём Ғ м·Ём•Ҫм„ұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ benchmarkлҠ” лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ single-turn VQAлӮҳ лӢЁмҲңн•ң dialogueм—җ көӯн•ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм–ҙ, мӢӨм ңмқҳ long-horizon interactionм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” мҳӨлҘҳ м „нҢҢмқҳ ліөмһЎн•ң лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 6-turn dialogue лӮҙм—җм„ң hallucination snowballingмқ„ м„ёл°Җн•ҳкІҢ м§„лӢЁн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ benchmarkмқё MM-Snowballмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ benchmarkлҠ” кі кёү MLLMм—җкІҢлҸ„ мғҒлӢ№н•ң лҸ„м „ кіјм ңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, single-turn taskлҘј мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗң кё°мЎҙ мҷ„нҷ” л°©лІ•мқҳ л№„нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј мғҒмҮ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Conflict-Aware Visual Rectification (CAVR)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ training-free н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” representation мҲҳмӨҖм—җм„ң visual groundingмқ„ к°ұмӢ н•ҳкі  logit мҲҳмӨҖм—җм„ң output distributionмқ„ көҗм •н•ҳлҠ” мӢңл„Ҳм§Җ мһҲлҠ” мқҙмӨ‘ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ snowballingмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл©°, лӘЁлҚёмқ„ visual factм—җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨмӢң м •л ¬мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ң CAVRмқҙ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, ліҙлӢӨ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” interactive AIлҘј н–Ҙн•ң мң л§қн•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61504","en":"Learning Context-Conditioned Predicate Semantics via Prototype Feedback","ko":"Prototype Feedbackмқ„ нҶөн•ң Context-Conditioned Predicate Semantics н•ҷмҠө","authors":"NamGyu Jung, Chang Choi","pos":"#705","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pUs1gPPup4","abs":"<p>In scene graph generation (SGG), a central challenge is modeling polysemous predicates whose meanings shift across contexts. Prior approaches address this issue by decomposing predicates into multiple static prototypes or retrieving semantically similar exemplars. However, these strategies keep predicate representations static and cannot reorganize semantics to reflect the evidence of a given image, leading to systematic confusions in ambiguous contexts. We propose AlignG, which learns context-conditioned predicate semantics via prototype feedback. AlignG infers image-conditioned predicate semantics from the set of relations within each image and feeds the adapted semantics back to recalibrate relation representations while preserving dataset-level semantic coherence. The learning objective anchors context adaptation to global semantic centers, preventing semantic drift while still allowing selective semantic reorganization when the scene provides consistent relational cues. Experiments on VG-150 and GQA-200 show consistent improvements over strong baselines, with F@100 improvements of +1.4 and +2.7 under SGDet. We further visualize per-image prototype similarity shifts and observe coherent context-dependent reorganization where prototypes selectively merge or separate predicates according to scene evidence.</p>","absKo":"<p>scene graph generation(SGG)м—җм„ң н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлҠ” л¬ёл§Ҙм—җ л”°лқј мқҳлҜёк°Җ лӢ¬лқјм§ҖлҠ” polysemous predicateлҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. м„ н–ү м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ predicateлҘј м—¬лҹ¬ к°ңмқҳ static prototypeмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎң мң мӮ¬н•ң exemplarлҘј retrievalн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м „лһөмқҖ predicate representationмқ„ м •м ҒмңјлЎң мң м§Җн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мЈјм–ҙм§„ мқҙлҜём§Җмқҳ evidenceлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ semanticмқ„ мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ м—Ҷкі , к·ё кІ°кіј лӘЁнҳён•ң л¬ёл§Ҙм—җм„ң мІҙкі„м Ғмқё нҳјлҸҷмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” prototype feedbackмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ context-conditioned predicate semanticмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” AlignGлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. AlignGлҠ” к°Ғ мқҙлҜём§Җ лӮҙ relation м§‘н•©мңјлЎңл¶Җн„° image-conditioned predicate semanticмқ„ м¶”лЎ н•ҳкі , м Ғмқ‘лҗң semanticмқ„ лӢӨмӢң мЈјмһ…н•ҳм—¬ relation representationмқ„ мһ¬мЎ°м •н•ҳл©ҙм„ң dataset-level semantic coherenceлҠ” ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҷмҠө лӘ©м ҒмқҖ context adaptationмқ„ global semantic centerм—җ кі м •н•ҳм—¬ semantic driftлҘј л°©м§Җн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, sceneмқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗң relational cueлҘј м ңкіөн•  л•ҢлҠ” м„ нғқм Ғ semantic мһ¬кө¬м„ұмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. VG-150кіј GQA-200м—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SGDetм—җм„ң F@100мқҙ к°Ғк°Ғ +1.4мҷҖ +2.7 н–ҘмғҒлҗҳлҠ” л“ұ к°•л Ҙн•ң baseline лҢҖл№„ мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” imageлі„ prototype similarity ліҖнҷ”лҸ„ мӢңк°Ғнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, prototypeмқҙ scene evidenceм—җ л”°лқј predicateлҘј м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң н•©м№ҳкұ°лӮҳ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ”, л¬ёл§Ҙ мқҳмЎҙм Ғмқҙкі  мқјкҙҖлҗң мһ¬кө¬м„ұмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65848","en":"Intrinsic Gradient Suppression for Label-Noise Prompt Tuning in VisionвҖ“Language Models","ko":"Vision-Language лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң л Ҳмқҙлё” л…ёмқҙмҰҲ н”„лЎ¬н”„нҠё нҠңлӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ Gradient м–өм ң","authors":"Jia-yu Li, Jiaxin Qi, Sheng Zhou, Jianqiang Huang, Xian-Sheng Hua","pos":"#709","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9W17xHFtdQ","abs":"<p>Contrastive vision-language models like CLIP exhibit remarkable zero-shot generalization. However, prompt tuning remains highly sensitive to label noise, as mislabeled samples generate disproportionately large gradients that can overwhelm pre-trained priors.  We argue that because CLIP already provides a near-optimal initialization, adaptation should be inherently conservative, particularly against the extreme gradient updates common in noisy settings.  To this end, we propose Double-Softmax Prompt Tuning (DSPT), a hyperparameter-free method for intrinsic gradient suppression. By applying a sequential probabilistic normalization, DSPT induces a self-adaptive saturation zone that suppresses gradients from high-error noisy samples while maintaining informative updates.  We also provide both theoretical analysis and empirical evidence about how this mechanism achieves adaptive suppression. This design transforms ``gradient vanishing'', traditionally a training bottleneck, into a principled noise-filtering shield for label-noise prompt tuning. Extensive experiments confirm that this simple, drop-in design achieves state-of-the-art robustness across various noisy benchmarks, outperforming methods with complex architectures and handcrafted hyperparameters.</p>","absKo":"<p>CLIPкіј к°ҷмқҖ contrastive vision-language modelмқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ zero-shot generalizationмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ prompt tuningмқҖ label noiseм—җ л§Өмҡ° лҜјк°җн•ңлҚ°, мһҳлӘ» лқјлІЁл§Ғлҗң sampleмқҙ м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ нҒ° gradientлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬ pre-trained priorлҘј м••лҸ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CLIPмқҙ мқҙлҜё кұ°мқҳ мөңм Ғмқҳ initializationмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, adaptationмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмҲҳм Ғмқҙм–ҙм•ј н•ҳл©° нҠ№нһҲ noisy settingм—җм„ң нқ”н•ң к·№лӢЁм Ғмқё gradient updateм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ к·ёлҹ¬н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” intrinsic gradient suppressionмқ„ мң„н•ң hyperparameter-free л°©лІ•мқё Double-Softmax Prompt Tuning (DSPT)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҲңм°Ём Ғ probabilistic normalizationмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, DSPTлҠ” self-adaptive saturation zoneмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬ лҶ’мқҖ errorлҘј к°Җм§„ noisy sampleмқҳ gradientлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мң мҡ©н•ң updateлҠ” мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң мқҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙ м–ҙл–»кІҢ adaptive suppressionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қкіј кІҪн—ҳм Ғ мҰқкұ°лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” м „нҶөм ҒмңјлЎң training bottleneckмңјлЎң м—¬кІЁм§ҖлҚҳ ``gradient vanishing''мқ„ label-noise prompt tuningмқ„ мң„н•ң мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғмқё noise-filtering shieldлЎң м „нҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҙ лӢЁмҲңн•ң drop-in designмқҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң noisy benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art robustnessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, ліөмһЎн•ң architectureмҷҖ мҲҳмһ‘м—… hyperparameterлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65428","en":"Interactive Person Retrieval via Multi-Turn Multimodal Conversation","ko":"лӢӨмӨ‘ н„ҙ л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ лҢҖнҷ”лҘј нҶөн•ң мқён„°лһҷнӢ°лёҢ мқёл¬ј кІҖмғү","authors":"Yang Bai, Tingfeng Wang, Bin Yang, Min Cao, Jinqiao Wang, Mang Ye","pos":"#710","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=DkigZR13tx","abs":"<p>Traditional text-based person retrieval approaches typically rely on single-shot textual queries, which are generally incomplete or vague in real-world scenarios. Recently, chat-based person retrieval methods enable iterative query refinement via question-answering interactions between the system and users. However, these methods fall short of direct user interaction with retrieved candidates during conversation, making it challenging to effectively refine the retrieval results. To address these limitations, we propose multimodal interactive person retrieval (MInterPR), a new retrieval paradigm that allows users to iteratively refine retrieved candidates by providing feedback on visual differences from the target person. To support this task, we establish MInterPEDES, a multimodal conversational dataset constructed by augmenting existing question-answering dialogues with synthesized visual feedbacks. Furthermore, to tackle the challenge of accurate and efficient semantics understanding in multimodal dialogues, we propose a multimodal conversational memory-enhanced framework MNEMO, which incorporates an atomic turn encoding (ATE) module to model each dialogue turn independently, and a dialogue memory aggregation (DMA) module to capture the fine-grained information and cross-turn dependencies. Extensive experiments demonstrate that MNEMO achieves substantial improvements in both retrieval accuracy and generalization ability, highlighting its promising potential in real-world scenarios. The code and dataset will be released to facilitate future research.</p>","absKo":"<p>м „нҶөм Ғмқё text-based person retrieval м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лӢЁмқј м§Ҳмқҳ н…ҚмҠӨнҠём—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мӢӨм ң мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң лҢҖмІҙлЎң л¶Ҳмҷ„м „н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лӘЁнҳён•ҳлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ chat-based person retrieval л°©лІ•мқҖ мӢңмҠӨн…ңкіј мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ к°„мқҳ question-answering мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң м§ҲмқҳлҘј м •көҗнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•мқҖ лҢҖнҷ” мӨ‘ retrieved candidateмҷҖмқҳ м§Ғм ‘м Ғмқё мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳм—¬, retrieval кІ°кіјлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м •м ңн•ҳкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” multimodal interactive person retrieval(MInterPR)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗк°Җ лҢҖмғҒ мқёл¬јкіјмқҳ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ м°Ёмқҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң н”јл“ңл°ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ retrieved candidateлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң м •м ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ retrieval paradigmмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ taskлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ question-answering лҢҖнҷ”лҘј н•©м„ұлҗң visual feedbackмңјлЎң мҰқк°•н•ҳм—¬ кө¬м„ұн•ң multimodal conversational datasetмқё MInterPEDESлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ multimodal dialogueм—җм„ң м •нҷ•н•ҳкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё semantics мқҙн•ҙмқҳ лҸ„м „мқ„ лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ dialogue turnмқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” atomic turn encoding(ATE) лӘЁл“Ҳкіј turn к°„ м„ёл¶Җ м •ліҙ л°Ҹ cross-turn dependencyлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” dialogue memory aggregation(DMA) лӘЁл“Ҳмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң multimodal conversational memory-enhanced framework MNEMOлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ MNEMOк°Җ retrieval м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ мқјл°ҳнҷ” лҠҘл Ҙ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңмқҳ мң л§қн•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ л¶Җк°Ғн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмқҖ н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬лҘј мҙүм§„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61983","en":"Hyperbolic Hierarchical Alignment for Video-Based Visible-Infrared Person Re-Identification","ko":"мҳҒмғҒ кё°л°ҳ visible-infrared person re-identificationмқ„ мң„н•ң hyperbolic hierarchical alignment","authors":"Shuang Li, Changjiang Kuang, Jiaxu Leng, Mingpi Tan, Zhanjie Wu, Shuanglin Yan, Xinbo Gao","pos":"#711","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=l17gjYai4X","abs":"<p>Video-based visible-infrared person re-identification (VVI-ReID) aims to learn robust video-level representations under modality discrepancy. However, existing methods typically rely on Euclidean geometry, which is suboptimal for modeling the complex temporal dynamics within visible and infrared tracklets, as it inevitably distorts the intrinsic hierarchical structure inherent in diverse temporal variations (e.g., occlusion, pose). In this paper, we propose Hyperbolic Hierarchical Alignment (HHA), which unifies spatio-temporal modeling and cross-modality alignment on the Poincar\\'e ball. HHA employs a Hyperbolic Hierarchical Spatio-Temporal Aggregator (HHSA) to organize time-varying cues into low-distortion hierarchical representations via Hyperbolic Geometry Interaction (HGI) and Dual-Geometry Fusion (DGF). Furthermore, we introduce Geometry-Aware Modality Alignment (GMA), which integrates Hyperbolic Modality Alignment (HMA) to couple modality centroids for geometric consistency and Hyperbolic Prototype Alignment (HPA) to anchor both modalities to shared identity prototypes for robust discrimination. Experiments on HITSZ-VCM and BUPTCampus demonstrate state-of-the-art performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>video кё°л°ҳ visible-infrared person re-identification (VVI-ReID)мқҖ modality discrepancy н•ҳм—җм„ң robustн•ң video-level representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң Euclidean geometryм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” visible л°Ҹ infrared tracklet лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ ліөмһЎн•ң temporal dynamicsлҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкё°м—җлҠ” мөңм Ғмқҙ м•„лӢҲл©°, лӢӨм–‘н•ң temporal variation(мҳҲ: occlusion, pose)м—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё hierarchical structureлҘј л¶Ҳк°Җн”јн•ҳкІҢ мҷңкіЎн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” spatio-temporal modelingкіј cross-modality alignmentлҘј Poincar\\'e ball мң„м—җм„ң нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” Hyperbolic Hierarchical Alignment (HHA)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. HHAлҠ” Hyperbolic Hierarchical Spatio-Temporal Aggregator (HHSA)лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ Hyperbolic Geometry Interaction (HGI)мҷҖ Dual-Geometry Fusion (DGF)мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мӢңк°„м ҒмңјлЎң ліҖн•ҳлҠ” cueлҘј мҷңкіЎмқҙ м ҒмқҖ hierarchical representationмңјлЎң мЎ°м§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Geometry-Aware Modality Alignment (GMA)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” Hyperbolic Modality Alignment (HMA)мқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ modality centroidлҘј кІ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ geometric consistencyлҘј нҷ•ліҙн•ҳкі , Hyperbolic Prototype Alignment (HPA)мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ л‘җ modalityлҘј кіөмң  identity prototypeм—җ м •л ¬н•ҳм—¬ к°•мқён•ң discriminationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. HITSZ-VCMкіј BUPTCampusм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63955","en":"Dual-Latent Memory Routing for Vision-Language Reasoning","ko":"л№„м „-м–ём–ҙ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң мқҙмӨ‘ мһ мһ¬ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ лқјмҡ°нҢ…","authors":"Hao-Xuan Ma, Jin-Fei Qi, YiCheng Xiao, Han-Jia Ye","pos":"#714","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=SFWWUr9V7c","abs":"<p>Multimodal large language models (MLLMs) have recently made strong progress in vision-language reasoning, yet their performance often degrades as generations grow longer. A key factor is that they frequently lose track of earlier visual evidence and intermediate constraints under a monolithic growing context. Inspired by how humans separately recall what they see and what they infer when solving complex tasks, we propose DLMR, a parameter-efficient mechanism that equips MLLMs with dual latent memories: a visual memory that compresses image evidence and a reasoning memory that tracks intermediate conclusions and constraints. A router then dynamically decides which memory and how much to reuse during inference, preserving visual grounding while maintaining coherent long-horizon reasoning. DLMR is trained in three stages from latent memory construction to selective router learning while keeping the base MLLM frozen, yielding substantial gains on both general and reasoning benchmarks with only a small number of additional trainable parameters. Further analyses reveal interpretable, state-dependent routing in which the visual and reasoning memories specialize as intended, and demonstrate that this design reduces redundant decoding and improves token efficiency over long generations.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal large language models (MLLMs)лҠ” мөңк·ј vision-language reasoningм—җм„ң нҒ° м§„м „мқ„ ліҙмҳҖм§Җл§Ң, generationмқҙ кёём–ҙм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ мһҗмЈј м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ мҡ”мқё мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” н•ҳлӮҳлЎң м»Өм§ҖлҠ” monolithic context м•„лһҳм—җм„ң мҙҲкё° visual evidenceмҷҖ мӨ‘к°„ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ мһҗмЈј лҶ“м№ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. ліөмһЎн•ң кіјм ңлҘј н’Җ л•Ң мӮ¬лһҢмқҙ ліё кІғкіј м¶”лЎ н•ң кІғмқ„ лі„лҸ„лЎң л– мҳ¬лҰ¬лҠ” л°©мӢқм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MLLMsм—җ dual latent memoriesлҘј л¶Җм—¬н•ҳлҠ” parameter-efficient mechanismмқё DLMRмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” image evidenceлҘј м••м¶•н•ҳлҠ” visual memoryмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” мӨ‘к°„ кІ°лЎ кіј м ңм•Ҫмқ„ м¶”м Ғн•ҳлҠ” reasoning memoryмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ routerк°Җ inference лҸҷм•Ҳ м–ҙлҠҗ memoryлҘј м–јл§ҲлӮҳ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©н• м§Җ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң кІ°м •н•ҳм—¬, coherentн•ң long-horizon reasoningмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң visual groundingмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. DLMRмқҖ base MLLMмқ„ frozen мғҒнғңлЎң мң м§Җн•ң мұ„ latent memory constructionм—җм„ң selective router learningм—җ мқҙлҘҙлҠ” м„ё лӢЁкі„лЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗҳл©°, мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ м¶”к°Җ trainable parameterл§ҢмңјлЎң general л°Ҹ reasoning benchmark лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң нҒ° м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӮёлӢӨ. м¶”к°Җ л¶„м„қмқҖ visual memoryмҷҖ reasoning memoryк°Җ мқҳлҸ„н•ң лҢҖлЎң нҠ№нҷ”лҗҳлҠ” н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң state-dependent routingмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, мқҙ м„Өкі„к°Җ redundant decodingмқ„ мӨ„мқҙкі  кёҙ generationм—җм„ң token efficiencyлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61184","en":"CAST: Modeling Visual State Transitions for Consistent Video Retrieval","ko":"CAST: мқјкҙҖлҗң л№„л””мҳӨ кІҖмғүмқ„ мң„н•ң мӢңк°Ғм Ғ мғҒнғң м „мқҙ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ","authors":"Yanqing Liu, Yingcheng Liu, Fanghong Dong, Budianto Budianto, Cihang Xie, Yan jiao","pos":"#810","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=svtbjHcMzs","abs":"As video content creation shifts towards long-form narratives, retrieving and composing short clips into coherent storylines becomes a critical challenge. Standard retrieval formulations, however, perform context-agnostic retrieval, prioritizing local semantic alignment while neglecting procedural state and identity consistency across time. To address this, we introduce the task of Consistent Video Retrieval (CVR) and establish a rigorous benchmark across YouCook2, COIN, and CrossTask, designed to explicitly evaluate temporal and identity consistency. We propose CAST (Context-Aware State Transition), a lightweight, embedding-agnostic adapter that models procedural progression by predicting a state-conditioned residual update ($\\Delta$) from visual history, decoupling procedural progression from static identity. Extensive experiments demonstrate that CAST yields significant and consistent gains across diverse datasets over standard baselines. Furthermore, we showcase its potential as a plug-and-play consistency verifier, guiding black-box generation models (e.g., Sora, Veo) toward physically plausible continuations.","absKo":"л№„л””мҳӨ мҪҳн…җмё  м ңмһ‘мқҙ long-form narrativeлЎң мқҙлҸҷн•Ём—җ л”°лқј, м§§мқҖ clipмқ„ кІҖмғүн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј мқ‘м§‘л Ҙ мһҲлҠ” storylineмңјлЎң кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё лҸ„м „ кіјм ңк°Җ лҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ н‘ңмӨҖ retrieval formulationмқҖ context-agnostic retrievalмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬, мӢңк°„м—җ кұём№ң procedural stateмҷҖ identity consistencyлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•ң мұ„ көӯмҶҢм Ғмқё semantic alignmentлҘј мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Consistent Video Retrieval (CVR) taskлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , temporal л°Ҹ identity consistencyлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң YouCook2, COIN, CrossTask м „л°ҳмқҳ м—„л°Җн•ң benchmarkлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CAST (Context-Aware State Transition)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” visual historyлЎңл¶Җн„° state-conditioned residual update($\\Delta$)лҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ procedural progressionмқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” lightweight embedding-agnostic adapterлЎң, procedural progressionкіј static identityлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CASTк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetм—җм„ң standard baselineліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мң мқҳлҜён•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CASTмқҳ plug-and-play consistency verifierлЎңм„ңмқҳ мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ мӢңм—°н•ҳл©°, black-box generation model(мҳҲ: Sora, Veo)мқҙ л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•ң continuationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65050","en":"Code2Video: A Code-centric Paradigm for Educational Video Creation","ko":"Code2Video: көҗмңЎмҡ© л№„л””мҳӨ м ңмһ‘мқ„ мң„н•ң Code мӨ‘мӢ¬ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„","authors":"Yanzhe Chen, Kevin Qinghong Lin, Mike Zheng Shou","pos":"#812","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HJ0JFzdwUo","abs":"<p>While recent generative models can synthesize videos in pixel space, they often fail to produce educational videos with precise structures, domain knowledge, and coherent transitions. We argue that this setting is better served by operating in a renderable environment that is explicitly controlled by code. We propose <strong>Code2Video</strong>, a code-centric agent framework that generates educational videos by writing executable Python programs. Code2Video includes three agents: a <em>Planner</em> that converts lecture content into a temporal storyboard, a <em>Coder</em> that turns the storyboard into runnable code with scope-guided auto-fix, and a <em>Critic</em> that refines layout using a VLM guided by <em>visual anchor prompting</em>, <em>i.e.</em>, mappings from target visual outcomes to code edits. For evaluation, we build <strong>MMMC</strong>, a benchmark of professionally produced, discipline-specific educational videos. We assess Code2Video using aesthetic scores (VLM-as-a-Judge), code efficiency, and <strong>TeachQuiz</strong>, an end-to-end metric that measures how well an <em>unlearned</em> VLM can recover knowledge after watching generated videos. Code2Video improves performance by 40% over direct code generation and produces videos comparable to human-crafted tutorials.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·јмқҳ мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ pixel spaceм—җм„ң videoлҘј н•©м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, м •л°Җн•ң кө¬мЎ°, лҸ„л©”мқё м§ҖмӢқ, мқјкҙҖлҗң м „нҷҳмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ көҗмңЎмҡ© videoлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” мў…мў… мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м„Өм •м—җлҠ” codeлЎң лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙлҗҳлҠ” renderable environmentм—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ лҚ” м Ғн•©н•ҳлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң Python programмқ„ мһ‘м„ұн•ҳм—¬ көҗмңЎмҡ© videoлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” code мӨ‘мӢ¬ agent н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё <strong>Code2Video</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Code2VideoлҠ” м„ё к°ңмқҳ agentлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. к°•мқҳ лӮҙмҡ©мқ„ мӢңк°„м Ғ storyboardлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” <em>Planner</em>, storyboardлҘј scope-guided auto-fixмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң codeлЎң л°”кҫёлҠ” <em>Coder</em>, к·ёлҰ¬кі  <em>visual anchor prompting</em>, мҰү лӘ©н‘ң visual outcomeмқ„ code editм—җ л§Өн•‘н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҳ м•ҲлӮҙлҘј л°ӣлҠ” VLMмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ layoutмқ„ м •м ңн•ҳлҠ” <em>Critic</em>мқҙлӢӨ. нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м „л¬ём ҒмңјлЎң м ңмһ‘лҗң, л¶„м•јлі„ көҗмңЎмҡ© videoлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң benchmarkмқё <strong>MMMC</strong>лҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҜём Ғ м җмҲҳ(VLM-as-a-Judge), code нҡЁмңЁм„ұ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мғқм„ұлҗң videoлҘј ліё л’Ө <em>unlearned</em> VLMмқҙ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ м–јл§ҲлӮҳ мһҳ ліөмӣҗн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” end-to-end metricмқё <strong>TeachQuiz</strong>лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ Code2VideoлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. Code2VideoлҠ” м§Ғм ‘ code мғқм„ұ лҢҖл№„ 40% м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мӮ¬лһҢмқҙ м ңмһ‘н•ң tutorialм—җ н•„м Ғн•ҳлҠ” videoлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61117","en":"Interpretability Transfer from Language to Vision via Sparse Autoencoders","ko":"Sparse AutoencoderлҘј нҶөн•ң м–ём–ҙм—җм„ң л№„м „мңјлЎңмқҳ н•ҙм„қк°ҖлҠҘм„ұ м „мқҙ","authors":"Alexey Kravets, Da Li, Chuan Li, Da Chen, Vinay Namboodiri","pos":"#1213","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tVwJRXfSYY","abs":"<p>Recent advances in language model interpretability using sparse autoencoders (SAEs) have yet to effectively translate to the visual domain, mainly due to the difficulty and ambiguity of labeling visual concepts. In this paper, we introduce Visual Interpretability via SAE Transfer Alignment (VISTA), a framework that transfers interpretability from language to vision by constraining a visual projector to map visual tokens into an LLM's pre-existing, labeled textual SAE space. This approach enables visual interpretability without training dedicated vision SAEs. By regularizing the projector using the LLM's SAE reconstruction loss, VISTA achieves a \\textbf{threefold} increase in the matching rate which measures how accurately the most activating textual concepts in the SAE space correspond to semantic elements in the image. Using this framework, we further analyze spatial localization properties of different vision encoders and show that DINOv2 features have significantly stronger localization abilities than other encoders. Leveraging this precision, VISTA enables fine-grained, localized concept steering, allowing specific objects to be removed or replaced while preserving the surrounding scene. This results in improvements of \\textbf{38\\%} in object removal and \\textbf{58\\%} in object replacement tasks over vision-only baselines. These contributions are validated across multiple LLM architectures.</p>","absKo":"<p>sparse autoencoder (SAE)лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң language model interpretabilityмқҳ мөңк·ј м§„м „мқҖ мЈјлЎң visual concept labelingмқҳ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖкіј лӘЁнҳём„ұ л•Ңл¬ём—җ visual domainмңјлЎң нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘлҗҳм§Җ лӘ»н–ҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” Visual Interpretability via SAE Transfer Alignment (VISTA)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkлҠ” visual projectorк°Җ visual tokenмқ„ LLMм—җ мқҙлҜё мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” labeled textual SAE spaceлЎң л§Өн•‘н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м ңм•Ҫн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, languageм—җм„ң visionмңјлЎң interpretabilityлҘј м „мқҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лі„лҸ„мқҳ vision SAEлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ visual interpretabilityлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. LLMмқҳ SAE reconstruction lossлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ projectorлҘј regularizeн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, VISTAлҠ” matching rateлҘј <strong>3л°°</strong> н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. matching rateлҠ” SAE spaceм—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ к°•н•ҳкІҢ нҷңм„ұнҷ”лҗҳлҠ” textual conceptк°Җ мқҙлҜём§Җмқҳ semantic elementмҷҖ м–јл§ҲлӮҳ м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј мёЎм •н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё vision encoderмқҳ spatial localization propertyлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң л¶„м„қн–Ҳмңјл©°, DINOv2 featureк°Җ лӢӨлҘё encoderліҙлӢӨ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” к°•н•ң localization лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м •л°Җм„ұмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ VISTAлҠ” fine-grainedн•ң localized concept steeringмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, мЈјліҖ мһҘл©ҙмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ң мұ„ нҠ№м • objectлҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ көҗмІҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј vision-only baselineм—җ л№„н•ҙ object removal taskм—җм„ң <strong>38\\%</strong>, object replacement taskм—җм„ң <strong>58\\%</strong>мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кё°м—¬лҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ LLM architectureм—җм„ң кІҖмҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66385","en":"Deformba: Vision State Space Model with Adaptive State Fusion","ko":"Deformba: м Ғмқ‘м Ғ мғҒнғң мңөн•©мқ„ к°–лҠ” Vision State Space Model","authors":"Hongyu Ke, Jack Morris, Yongkang Liu, Satoshi Kitai, Kentaro Oguchi, Yi Ding, Haoxin Wang","pos":"#2909","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4Anq3hEfaO","abs":"<p>State Space Models (SSMs) have emerged as a powerful and efficient alternative to Transformers, demonstrating linear-time complexity and exceptional sequence modeling capabilities. However, their application to vision tasks remains challenging. First, existing vision SSMs largely depend on manually designed fixed scanning methods to flatten image patches into sequences, which imposes predefined geometric structures and increases the complexity. Second, the broader adoption of vision SSMs is hindered in domains that require query-based interactions between distinct information streams. This is a result of the inherently causal and self-referential nature of SSMs designed for 1D sequence modeling tasks. This fusion mechanism is indispensable for critical perception tasks such as multi-view 3D fusion. To address these limitations, we propose Deformba, a context adaptive method that dynamically augments the spatial structural information while maintaining the linear complexity of SSMs. Deformba also allows multi-modal fusion, analogous to standard cross attention. To demonstrate the effectiveness and general applicability of Deformba, we test its performance on general 2D vision tasks such as image classification, object detection, instance segmentation, and semantic segmentation, as well as 3D vision tasks like BEV perception. Extensive experiments show that Deformba achieves strong performance across various visual perception benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"<p>State Space Model(SSM)мқҖ Transformerмқҳ к°•л Ҙн•ҳкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё лҢҖм•ҲмңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳмңјл©°, м„ нҳ• мӢңк°„ ліөмһЎлҸ„мҷҖ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң sequence modeling лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ vision taskм—җмқҳ м Ғмҡ©мқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, кё°мЎҙ vision SSMмқҖ мқҙлҜём§Җ patchлҘј sequenceлЎң нҺјм№ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҲҳлҸҷмңјлЎң м„Өкі„лҗң кі м • scanning methodм—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мӮ¬м „м—җ м •мқҳлҗң кё°н•ҳ кө¬мЎ°лҘј к°•м ңн•ҳкі  ліөмһЎм„ұмқ„ мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё м •ліҙ нқҗлҰ„ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ query-based interactionмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ңлҠ” vision SSMмқҳ нҸӯл„“мқҖ мұ„нғқмқҙ м Җн•ҙлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” 1D sequence modeling taskлҘј мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗң SSMмқҳ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң causalн•ҳкі  self-referentialн•ң нҠ№м„ұм—җм„ң кё°мқён•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң fusion mechanismмқҖ multi-view 3D fusionкіј к°ҷмқҖ н•өмӢ¬ perception taskм—җ н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SSMмқҳ linear complexityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң spatial structural informationмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мҰқк°•н•ҳлҠ” context-adaptive method DeformbaлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. DeformbaлҠ” standard cross attentionкіј мң мӮ¬н•ҳкІҢ multi-modal fusionлҸ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. Deformbaмқҳ нҡЁкіјмҷҖ мқјл°ҳм Ғ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙмқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” image classification, object detection, instance segmentation, semantic segmentation к°ҷмқҖ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё 2D vision taskмҷҖ BEV perception к°ҷмқҖ 3D vision taskм—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Deformbaк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң visual perception benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61524","en":"STABLE: Simulation-Ready Tabletop Layout Generation via a SemanticsвҖ“Physics Dual System","ko":"STABLE: Semantics-Physics Dual Systemмқ„ нҶөн•ң Simulation-Ready Tabletop Layout Generation","authors":"Zhen Luo, Yixuan Yang, Xudong XU, Jinkun Hao, Zhaoyang Lyu, Feng Zheng, Jiangmiao Pang, Yanwei Fu","pos":"#3501","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pGpEGZhL7Y","abs":"<p>Generating simulation-ready tabletop scenes from task instructions is an intriguing and promising research direction in the field of Embodied AI. However, existing task-to-scene generation methods rely exclusively on large language models (LLMs) to predict scene layouts, inevitably yielding object collisions or floating due to LLMsвҖҷ inherent limitations in 3D spatial reasoning. In this paper, we present \\textbf{STABLE}, a semanticsвҖ“physics dual-system tailored for simulation-ready tabletop scene generation. STABLE consists of two complementary modules: (i) a \\textbf{Semantic Reasoner}, a fine-tuned LLM trained on a structured tabletop scene dataset to generate coarse layouts from input task instructions, and (ii) a \\textbf{Physics Corrector}, a physics-aware flow-based denoising model that outputs pose updates to refine layouts, which ensures the physical plausibility of scenes while preserves semantic alignment with task instructions. STABLE adopts a progressive generation paradigm: by alternating between the Semantic Reasoner and Physics Corrector, it incrementally expands the scene from task-critical objects to background objects. Experiments demonstrate that STABLE successfully generates simulation-ready tabletop scenes that strictly conform to task instructions and significantly enhances the physical validity of scenes over prior art.</p>","absKo":"мһ‘м—… м§ҖмӢңлЎңл¶Җн„° simulation-ready tabletop sceneмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ Embodied AI л¶„м•јм—җм„ң нқҘлҜёлЎӯкі  мң л§қн•ң м—°кө¬ л°©н–ҘмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙмқҳ task-to-scene generation л°©лІ•мқҖ scene layoutмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҳӨлЎңм§Җ large language model (LLM)м—җл§Ң мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, LLMмқҙ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң к°Җм§„ 3D spatial reasoningмқҳ н•ңкі„лЎң мқён•ҙ к°қмІҙ м¶©лҸҢмқҙлӮҳ floatingмқҙ л¶Ҳк°Җн”јн•ҳкІҢ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” simulation-ready tabletop scene generationм—җ л§һм¶ҳ semantics-physics dual-systemмқё \\textbf{STABLE}мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. STABLEмқҖ мғҒнҳёліҙмҷ„м Ғмқё л‘җ лӘЁл“ҲлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. (i) мһ…л Ҙ task instructionмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° coarse layoutмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ structured tabletop scene datasetмңјлЎң fine-tuningлҗң LLMмқё \\textbf{Semantic Reasoner}, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (ii) pose updateлҘј м¶ңл Ҙн•ҳм—¬ layoutмқ„ м •көҗнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” physics-aware flow-based denoising modelмқё \\textbf{Physics Corrector}лЎң, мқҙлҠ” task instructionкіјмқҳ semantic alignmentлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң sceneмқҳ physical plausibilityлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. STABLEмқҖ progressive generation paradigmмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ңлӢӨ. Semantic ReasonerмҷҖ Physics CorrectorлҘј лІҲк°Ҳм•„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, sceneмқ„ task-critical objectм—җм„ң background objectлЎң м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј STABLEмқҖ task instructionмқ„ м—„кІ©нһҲ мӨҖмҲҳн•ҳлҠ” simulation-ready tabletop sceneмқ„ м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙм „ л°©лІ•л“ӨліҙлӢӨ sceneмқҳ physical validityлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66130","en":"OvisOCR: End-to-End Document Parsing via Aligning Specialized Perception with General Reasoning","ko":"OvisOCR: м „л¬ёнҷ”лҗң м§Җк°Ғкіј мқјл°ҳ м¶”лЎ мқҳ м •л ¬мқ„ нҶөн•ң мў…лӢЁк°„ л¬ём„ң нҢҢмӢұ","authors":"Jun-Peng Jiang, Shiyin Lu, An-Yang Ji, Yinglun Li, Qing-Guo Chen, Zhao Xu, Weihua Luo, Kaifu Zhang, De-Chuan Zhan, Han-Jia Ye","pos":"#4014","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=6dcgmtBYhh","abs":"<p>This paper presents OvisOCR, a lightweight and strictly end-to-end Multimodal Language Model (MLLM) tailored for document parsing. Unlike current methods that rely on complex \"Crop-OCR-Merge\" cascades to handle high-resolution inputs, OvisOCR directly maps full-page visual signals to structured Markdown without localized slicing or layout detection dependencies. Through extensive evaluations on the OmniDoc benchmark, OvisOCR achieves SOTA performance, demonstrating that a compact E2E model can effectively ``digest'' the capabilities of intricate pipelines and surpass specialized and general methods.   Technically, OvisOCR establishes a holistic paradigm that synergizes specialized perception with general reasoning, distilling fine-grained recognition from OCR engines and semantic correction from LLMs into a unified model. To balance the performance across diverse document constituents, we design category-specific reward mechanisms for distinct element types, such as dense text, complex tables, and formulas, and ensure the model enhances its formatting strengths for each modality concurrently. This approach effectively resolves the optimization conflict, guaranteeing that improvements in structural layout parsing do not come at the expense of omitting fine-grained textual details. Empirical results confirm that OvisOCR eliminates the error propagation inherent in split-and-merge architectures, offering a streamlined path for next-generation document intelligence.</p>","absKo":"<p>ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ document parsingмқ„ мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗң кІҪлҹүмқҳ strictly end-to-end Multimodal Language Model(MLLM)мқё OvisOCRлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ мһ…л Ҙмқ„ мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ ліөмһЎн•ң \"Crop-OCR-Merge\" cascadeм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“Өкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, OvisOCRлҠ” м§Җм—ӯм Ғ slicingмқҙлӮҳ layout detection мқҳмЎҙм„ұ м—Ҷмқҙ м „мІҙ нҺҳмқҙм§Җмқҳ visual signalмқ„ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң MarkdownмңјлЎң м§Ғм ‘ л§Өн•‘н•ңлӢӨ. OmniDoc benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ OvisOCRлҠ” SOTA м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, compact E2E modelмқҙ ліөмһЎн•ң pipelineмқҳ м—ӯлҹүмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң ``digest''н•ҳм—¬ м „мҡ© л°©лІ•кіј лІ”мҡ© л°©лІ•мқ„ лӘЁл‘җ лҠҘк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. кё°мҲ м ҒмңјлЎң OvisOCRлҠ” specialized perceptionкіј general reasoningмқ„ мӢңл„Ҳм§Җ мһҲкІҢ кІ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” holistic paradigmмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳл©°, OCR engineмңјлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ fine-grained recognitionкіј LLMмңјлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ semantic correctionмқ„ лӢЁмқј лӘЁлҚёлЎң distillн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң document кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢ м „л°ҳмқҳ м„ұлҠҘ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”кё° мң„н•ҙ dense text, complex tables, formulasмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё element typeм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ category-specific reward mechanismмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ҳкі , modelмқҙ к°Ғ modalityм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ formatting к°•м җмқ„ лҸҷмӢңм—җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ optimization conflictлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳм—¬, structural layout parsingмқҳ к°ңм„ мқҙ м„ёл¶Җ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё м •ліҙлҘј лҲ„лқҪн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖк°ҖлҘј м№ҳлҘҙм§Җ м•ҠлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” OvisOCRк°Җ split-and-merge architectureм—җ лӮҙмһ¬н•ң error propagationмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ҳл©°, м°Ём„ёлҢҖ document intelligenceлҘј н–Ҙн•ң к°„кІ°н•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67239","en":"Position: Human-Centric Vision Requires Topological Generalization Beyond Fixed Skeletal Topologies","ko":"Position: мқёк°„ мӨ‘мӢ¬ л№„м „м—җлҠ” кі м •лҗң кіЁкІ© мң„мғҒмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„  мң„мғҒм Ғ мқјл°ҳнҷ”к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Heming Du, Jiaying Ying, Kaihao Zhang, Tianqing Zhu, Xin Yu","pos":"#4609","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2N3dVx1soP","abs":"<p>In this position paper, we argue that human-centric vision requires skeletal-topology generalization beyond fixed skeletons. Mainstream pose and body pipelines enforce a fixed skeleton graph with an indexed joint list and fixed adjacency, so the fixed joint inventory does not cover structural absence and anatomical absence becomes an ill-posed target for individuals with limb deficiencies. Anatomical absence is not a visibility state, so masking and forced completion can hide structural mismatch and produce hallucinated structure that contaminates downstream reasoning in prosthesis-facing settings. We argue that scaling data and model size alone does not resolve this mismatch while the skeleton schema remains fixed, and this is not a niche concern because these failures affect a large population and reach accessibility-facing systems. We advocate instance-adaptive skeletal topology, where a model jointly predicts joint existence and skeletal connectivity to produce an instance-specific skeleton graph that supports consistent inference and evaluation. We outline measurement upgrades, including existence-aware annotations with explicit absence semantics, skeletal-topology-aware scoring, and hallucination-under-absence penalties, and we close with a call to action for dataset curators, benchmark organizers, and model builders to treat morphological variation as a first-class generalization axis.</p>","absKo":"<p>мқҙ position paperм—җм„ңлҠ” мқёк°„ мӨ‘мӢ¬ visionмқҙ кі м •лҗң skeletonмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ skeletal-topology generalizationмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мЈјлҘҳ pose л°Ҹ body pipelineмқҖ indexed joint listмҷҖ fixed adjacencyлҘј к°–лҠ” кі м • skeleton graphлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, кі м •лҗң joint inventoryлҠ” structural absenceлҘј нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі  limb deficiencyк°Җ мһҲлҠ” к°ңмқём—җкІҢ anatomical absenceлҠ” ill-posed targetмқҙ лҗңлӢӨ. Anatomical absenceлҠ” visibility stateк°Җ м•„лӢҲлҜҖлЎң, maskingкіј forced completionмқҖ structural mismatchлҘј к°ҖлҰҙ мҲҳ мһҲкі  prosthesis-facing settingм—җм„ң downstream reasoningмқ„ мҳӨм—јмӢңнӮӨлҠ” hallucinated structureлҘј л§Ңл“Өм–ҙлӮј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” skeleton schemaк°Җ кі м •лҗң мғҒнғңм—җм„ңлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖ model sizeлҘј нӮӨмҡ°лҠ” кІғл§ҢмңјлЎң мқҙ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢӨнҢЁлҠ” нҒ° м§‘лӢЁм—җ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳкі  accessibility-facing systemм—җк№Ңм§Җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳлҜҖлЎң niche concernмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқјкі  ліёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” instance-adaptive skeletal topologyлҘј м§Җм§Җн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ joint existenceмҷҖ skeletal connectivityлҘј jointly predictн•ҳм—¬ instance-specific skeleton graphлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқјкҙҖлҗң inferenceмҷҖ evaluationмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” explicit absence semanticsлҘј к°–лҠ” existence-aware annotation, skeletal-topology-aware scoring, hallucination-under-absence penaltyлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң measurement upgradeлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, dataset curator, benchmark organizer, model builderк°Җ morphological variationмқ„ first-class generalization axisлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҸ„лЎқ мҙүкө¬н•ҳл©° л§Ҳл¬ҙлҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63839","en":"3DMedAgent: Unified Perception-to-Understanding for 3D Medical Analysis","ko":"3DMedAgent: 3D мқҳлЈҢ л¶„м„қмқ„ мң„н•ң нҶөн•©м Ғ perception-to-understanding","authors":"Ziyue Wang, Linghan Cai, Chang Low, Haofeng Liu, Junde Wu, Jinyu Wang, Rui Wang, Lei Song, Jiang Bian, Jingjing Fu, Yueming Jin","pos":"#515","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=TH6pLxCOQ3","abs":"<p>3D CT analysis spans a continuum from low-level perception to high-level clinical understanding. Existing 3D-oriented analysis methods adopt either isolated task-specific modeling or task-agnostic end-to-end paradigms to produce one-hop outputs, impeding the systematic accumulation of perceptual evidence for downstream reasoning. In parallel, recent multimodal large language models (MLLMs) exhibit improved visual perception and can integrate visual and textual information effectively, yet their predominantly 2D-oriented designs fundamentally limit their ability to perceive and analysis volumetric medical data. To bridge this gap, we propose 3DMedAgent, an unified agent that enables 2D MLLMs to perform general 3D CT analysis without 3D-specific fine-tuning. 3DMedAgent coordinates heterogeneous visual and textual tools through a flexible MLLM agent, progressively decomposing complex 3D analysis into tractable subtasks that transition from global to regional views, from 3D volumes to informative 2D slices, and from visual evidence to structured textual representations. Central to this design, 3DMedAgent maintains a long-term structured memory that aggregates intermediate tool outputs and supports query-adaptive, evidence-driven multi-step reasoning. We further introduce the DeepChestVQA benchmark for evaluating unified perception-to-understanding capabilities in 3D thoracic imaging. Experiments across over 40 tasks demonstrate that 3DMedAgent consistently outperforms general, medical, and 3D-specific MLLMs, highlighting a scalable path toward general-purpose 3D clinical assistants.   Anonymized code and data are available \\href{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/3DMedAgent-D7D7}{here}.</p>","absKo":"<p>3D CT analysisлҠ” low-level perceptionл¶Җн„° high-level clinical understandingм—җ мқҙлҘҙлҠ” м—°мҶҚм„ мқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ 3D-oriented analysis л°©лІ•мқҖ л¶„лҰ¬лҗң task-specific modeling лҳҗлҠ” task-agnostic end-to-end paradigmмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ҙ one-hop outputмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ downstream reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң perceptual evidenceмқҳ мІҙкі„м Ғ м¶•м Ғмқҙ м Җн•ҙлҗңлӢӨ. н•ңнҺё, мөңк·јмқҳ multimodal large language models (MLLMs)мқҖ н–ҘмғҒлҗң visual perceptionмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©° visual м •ліҙмҷҖ textual м •ліҙлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, мЈјлЎң 2D-orientedлЎң м„Өкі„лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм–ҙ volumetric medical dataлҘј м§Җк°Ғн•ҳкі  л¶„м„қн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 3D-specific fine-tuning м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ 2D MLLMsк°Җ general 3D CT analysisлҘј мҲҳн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© agentмқё 3DMedAgentлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. 3DMedAgentлҠ” мң м—°н•ң MLLM agentлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё visual л°Ҹ textual toolмқ„ мЎ°м •н•ҳл©°, ліөмһЎн•ң 3D analysisлҘј м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҙ global viewм—җм„ң regional viewлЎң, 3D volumeм—җм„ң м •ліҙк°Җ н’Қл¶Җн•ң 2D sliceлЎң, к·ёлҰ¬кі  visual evidenceм—җм„ң structured textual representationмңјлЎң м „нҷҳлҗҳлҠ” tractable subtaskлЎң лӮҳлҲҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„Өкі„мқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ intermediate tool outputмқ„ м§‘кі„н•ҳкі  query-adaptive, evidence-driven multi-step reasoningмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” мһҘкё° кө¬мЎ°нҷ” memoryмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң 3D thoracic imagingм—җм„ң нҶөн•©лҗң perception-to-understanding лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң DeepChestVQA benchmarkлҘј мғҲлЎң лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. 40к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ taskм—җ кұём№ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ 3DMedAgentк°Җ general, medical, 3D-specific MLLMsлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, лІ”мҡ© 3D clinical assistantлҘј н–Ҙн•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. мқөлӘ…нҷ”лҗң мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” \\href{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/3DMedAgent-D7D7}{м—¬кё°}м—җм„ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•ҳлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64995","en":"PVDepth: Panoramic Video Depth Estimation via Geometry-Aware Spatiotemporal Adaptation","ko":"PVDepth: Geometry-Aware мӢңкіөк°„ м Ғмқ‘мқ„ нҶөн•ң нҢҢл…ёлқјл§Ҳ л№„л””мҳӨ к№Ҡмқҙ м¶”м •","authors":"Chuanxin Song, Peixi Peng","pos":"#601","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HwYgnZjxUB","abs":"<p>Panoramic video depth estimation is pivotal for applications such as Virtual Reality and World Models. However, advancements in this field are impeded by two primary obstacles: the scarcity of large-scale training data and the unique spatiotemporal challenges of Equirectangular Projection (ERP), which hinder the direct transfer of perspective models.   In this paper, we first present <strong>PanoCARLA</strong>, a large-scale synthetic RGB-D panoramic video dataset, featuring natural motion trajectories and drone-like roaming perspectives.    Building on this foundation, we propose <strong>PVDepth</strong>, an end-to-end framework adapted from perspective video depth models.    To tackle ERP-specific geometric distortions and consequent non-linear temporal dynamics, we introduce two core mechanisms: (1) A <em>Progressive Sphere-aware Noise Initialization</em> strategy that anneals the noise distribution from planar to spherical, guiding the model to adapt to non-uniform information density; and (2) A <em>Cube-rectified Temporal Modeling</em> module that incorporates an auxiliary cubemap temporal branch to rectify non-linear temporal dynamics in the ERP domain.   Extensive experiments demonstrate that PVDepth achieves superior performance, generating geometrically accurate and temporally consistent depth sequences. <em>Code and data will be released.</em></p>","absKo":"<p>Panoramic video depth estimationмқҖ Virtual RealityмҷҖ World Model к°ҷмқҖ applicationм—җм„ң н•өмӢ¬м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ л¶„м•јмқҳ л°ңм „мқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мЈјмҡ” мһҘм• л¬јм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м Җн•ҙлҗңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ training dataмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” perspective modelмқҳ м§Ғм ‘м Ғмқё мқҙм „мқ„ м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” Equirectangular Projection(ERP)мқҳ лҸ…нҠ№н•ң spatiotemporal challengeмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” лЁјм Җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ motion trajectoryмҷҖ л“ңлЎ мІҳлҹј мқҙлҸҷн•ҳлҠ” кҙҖм җмқ„ нҠ№м§•мңјлЎң н•ҳлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ synthetic RGB-D panoramic video datasetмқё <strong>PanoCARLA</strong>лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кё°л°ҳ мң„м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” perspective video depth modelм—җм„ң м Ғмқ‘н•ң end-to-end frameworkмқё <strong>PVDepth</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ERP нҠ№мң мқҳ geometric distortionкіј к·ём—җ л”°лҘё л№„м„ нҳ• temporal dynamicsлҘј лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ mechanismмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. (1) noise distributionмқ„ planarм—җм„ң sphericalлЎң annealн•ҳм—¬ non-uniform information densityм—җ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” <em>Progressive Sphere-aware Noise Initialization</em> м „лһө, (2) ERP domainмқҳ л№„м„ нҳ• temporal dynamicsлҘј ліҙм •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ auxiliary cubemap temporal branchлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” <em>Cube-rectified Temporal Modeling</em> лӘЁл“ҲмқҙлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PVDepthк°Җ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң м •нҷ•н•ҳкі  мӢңк°„м ҒмңјлЎң мқјкҙҖлҗң depth sequenceлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳл©° мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. <em>Code and data will be released.</em></p>"},{"id":"63540","en":"Path-Decoupled Hyperbolic Flow Matching for Few-Shot Adaptation","ko":"м ҒмқҖ мғ· м Ғмқ‘мқ„ мң„н•ң кІҪлЎң л¶„лҰ¬ н•ҳмқҙнҚјліјлҰӯ н”ҢлЎңмҡ° л§Өм№ӯ","authors":"Lin Li, Ziqi Jiang, Gefan Ye, Zhenqi He, Jiahui Li, Jun Xiao, Kwang-Ting Cheng, Long Chen","pos":"#603","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WIO01EdUXo","abs":"<p>Recent advances in cross-modal few-shot adaptation treat visual-semantic alignment as a continuous feature transport problem via Flow Matching (FM). However, we argue that Euclidean-based FM overlooks fundamental limitations of flat geometry, where polynomial volume growth fails to accommodate diverse feature distributions, leading to severe path entanglement. To this end, we propose path-decoupled Hyperbolic Flow Matching (HFM), leveraging the Lorentz manifold's exponential expansion for trajectory decoupling. HFM structures the transport via two key designs: 1) Centripetal hyperbolic alignment: It constructs a centripetal hierarchy by anchoring textual roots, which pushes visual leaves to the boundary to initialize orderly flows. 2) Path-decoupled objective: It acts as a \"semantic guardrail\" rigidly confining trajectories within isolated class-specific geodesic corridors via step-wise supervision. Furthermore, we devise an adaptive diameter-based stopping to prevent over-transportation into the crowded origin based on the intrinsic semantic scale. Extensive ablations on 11 benchmarks have shown that HFM establishes a new state-of-the-art, consistently outperforming its Euclidean counterparts. Our codes and models will be released.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј cross-modal few-shot adaptationмқҳ л°ңм „мқҖ visual-semantic alignmentлҘј Flow Matching (FM)мқ„ нҶөн•ң м—°мҶҚм Ғмқё feature transport л¬ём ңлЎң лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Euclidean-based FMмқҙ нҸүл©ҙ кё°н•ҳмқҳ к·јліём Ғ н•ңкі„лҘј к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, polynomial volume growthлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң feature distributionмқ„ мҲҳмҡ©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҙ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң path entanglementлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” trajectory decouplingмқ„ мң„н•ҙ Lorentz manifoldмқҳ м§ҖмҲҳм Ғ нҷ•мһҘмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” path-decoupled Hyperbolic Flow Matching (HFM)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. HFMмқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ м„Өкі„лҘј нҶөн•ҙ transportлҘј кө¬мЎ°нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ: 1) Centripetal hyperbolic alignment: textual rootлҘј anchorлЎң мӮјм•„ centripetal hierarchyлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, visual leafлҘј boundary мӘҪмңјлЎң л°Җм–ҙ orderly flowлҘј мҙҲкё°нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. 2) Path-decoupled objective: step-wise supervisionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ trajectoryлҘј class-specific geodesic corridorлЎң м—„кІ©н•ҳкІҢ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳм—¬ м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ” \"semantic guardrail\" м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң intrinsic semantic scaleм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬ нҳјмһЎн•ң originмңјлЎңмқҳ over-transportationмқ„ л°©м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ adaptive diameter-based stoppingмқ„ кі м•Ҳн–ҲлӢӨ. 11к°ң benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң ablation кІ°кіј, HFMмқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state-of-the-artлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн–Ҳмңјл©° Euclidean counterpartлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65237","en":"ReVSI: Rebuilding Visual Spatial Intelligence Evaluation for Accurate Assessment of VLM 3D Reasoning","ko":"ReVSI: VLM 3D м¶”лЎ мқҳ м •нҷ•н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң мӢңк°Ғ кіөк°„ м§ҖлҠҘ нҸүк°Җ мһ¬кө¬м¶•","authors":"Yiming Zhang, Jiacheng Chen, Jiaqi Tan, Yongsen Mao, Wenhu Chen, Angel X Chang","pos":"#605","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FTC7najzZT","abs":"<p>Current evaluations of spatial intelligence can be systematically invalid under modern vision-language model (VLM) settings. First, many benchmarks derive question-answer (QA) pairs from point-cloud-based 3D annotations originally curated for traditional 3D perception. When such annotations are treated as ground truth for video-based evaluation, reconstruction and annotation artifacts can miss objects that are clearly visible in the video, mislabel object identities, or corrupt geometry-dependent answers (e.g., size), yielding incorrect or ambiguous QA pairs. Second, evaluations often assume full-scene access, while many VLMs operate on sparsely sampled frames (e.g., 16-64), making many questions effectively unanswerable under the actual model inputs. We improve evaluation validity by introducing ReVSI, a benchmark and protocol that ensures each QA pair is answerable and correct under the model's actual inputs. To this end, we re-annotate object labels and geometry across 413 scenes from 5 datasets to improve data quality, and regenerate all QA pairs with rigorous bias mitigation and human verification using professional 3D visualization and annotation tools. We further enhance evaluation controllability by providing variants across multiple frame budgets (16/32/64/all) and fine-grained object visibility metadata, enabling controlled diagnostic analyses. Evaluations of general and domain-specific VLMs on ReVSI reveal systematic failure modes that are obscured by prior benchmarks, yielding a more reliable and diagnostic assessment of spatial intelligence.</p>","absKo":"<p>кіөк°„ м§ҖлҠҘм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” нҳ„лҢҖ vision-language model (VLM) м„Өм •м—җм„ң мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л¶Җм •нҷ•н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, л§ҺмқҖ benchmarkлҠ” м „нҶөм Ғмқё 3D perceptionмқ„ мң„н•ҙ мӣҗлһҳ кө¬м¶•лҗң point-cloud кё°л°ҳ 3D annotationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° question-answer (QA) pairлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң annotationмқ„ video кё°л°ҳ нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң ground truthлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳл©ҙ, reconstruction л°Ҹ annotation artifact л•Ңл¬ём—җ videoм—җм„ң л¶„лӘ…нһҲ ліҙмқҙлҠ” objectлҘј лҶ“м№ҳкұ°лӮҳ, object identityлҘј мһҳлӘ» л Ҳмқҙлё”л§Ғн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, sizeмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ geometry-dependent answerлҘј мҶҗмғҒмӢңмјң мһҳлӘ»лҗҳкұ°лӮҳ лӘЁнҳён•ң QA pairк°Җ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, нҸүк°ҖлҠ” мў…мў… м „мІҙ scene м ‘к·јмқ„ к°Җм •н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, л§ҺмқҖ VLMмқҖ 16-64к°ңмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ sparsely sampled frameм—җм„ң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мӢӨм ң model input н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” л§ҺмқҖ м§Ҳл¬ёмқҙ мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ лӢөн•  мҲҳ м—ҶкІҢ лҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ QA pairк°Җ modelмқҳ мӢӨм ң input н•ҳм—җм„ң лӢөн•  мҲҳ мһҲкі  мҳ¬л°”лҘҙлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” benchmark л°Ҹ protocolмқё ReVSIлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ нҸүк°Җмқҳ нғҖлӢ№м„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 5к°ң datasetмқҳ 413к°ң scene м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ object labelкіј geometryлҘј мһ¬мЈјм„қн•ҳм—¬ data qualityлҘј к°ңм„ н•ҳкі , м „л¬ём Ғмқё 3D visualization л°Ҹ annotation toolмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң м—„кІ©н•ң bias mitigationкіј human verificationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁл“  QA pairлҘј лӢӨмӢң мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң м—¬лҹ¬ frame budget (16/32/64/all)кіј м„ёл°Җн•ң object visibility metadataм—җ лҢҖн•ң variantлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм—¬ нҸүк°Җмқҳ нҶөм ң к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқҙкі , нҶөм ңлҗң м§„лӢЁ л¶„м„қмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. ReVSIм—җм„ң general л°Ҹ domain-specific VLMмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, кё°мЎҙ benchmarkм—җ мқҳн•ҙ к°Җл ӨмЎҢлҚҳ мІҙкі„м Ғмқё failure modeк°Җ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҳл©°, кіөк°„ м§ҖлҠҘм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҚ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкі  м§„лӢЁм Ғмқё нҸүк°Җк°Җ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63491","en":"Reason, Then Re-reason: Cross-view Revisiting Improves Spatial Reasoning","ko":"м¶”лЎ н•ҳкі  лӢӨмӢң м¶”лЎ н•ҳлқј: көҗм°Ё л·° мһ¬кІҖнҶ к°Җ кіөк°„ м¶”лЎ мқ„ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Chaofan Ma, Zhenjie Mao, Yuhuan Yang, Fanqin Zeng, Yue Shi, Yingjie Zhou, Xiaofeng Cao, Jiangchao Yao","pos":"#606","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WikPLZyyrT","abs":"<p>Spatial reasoning from egocentric videos is inherently challenging because the observable evidence is constrained by the camera trajectory. Existing methods perform spatial reasoning in a single inference pass, forcing models to resolve geometric ambiguity through semantic priors rather than verifiable evidence. We argue that spatial reasoning should be revisitable: conclusions formed under limited evidence should remain open to revision when complementary viewpoints become available. Building on this insight, we propose Reason, then Re-reason (ReRe), a training-free, inference-time framework with two phases: in the Reason Phase, an MLLM forms a spatial hypothesis from the original video; in the Re-reason Phase, it verifies or revises the hypothesis by observing a synthesized novel-view video. To enable effective cross-view revisiting, we design a Geometry-to-Video pipeline that renders strategically complementary novel views from predicted 3D geometry. These views feature an elevated, oblique perspective with scene-spanning coverage, while preserving the MLLM's native video interface without architectural modifications. Extensive evaluations on VSI-Bench demonstrate that ReRe consistently boosts open-source MLLMs to rival proprietary state-of-the-art performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>мһҗкё°мӨ‘мӢ¬м Ғ(egocentric) л№„л””мҳӨлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ spatial reasoningмқҖ кҙҖмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң evidenceк°Җ camera trajectoryм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңм•Ҫлҗҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м–ҙл өлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ spatial reasoningмқ„ лӢЁмқј inference passм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, лӘЁлҚёмқҖ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң evidenceк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј semantic priorлҘј нҶөн•ҙ geometric ambiguityлҘј н•ҙмҶҢн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” spatial reasoningмқҖ лӢӨмӢң кІҖнҶ  к°ҖлҠҘ(revisitable)н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, м ңн•ңлҗң evidence н•ҳм—җм„ң нҳ•м„ұлҗң кІ°лЎ мқҖ complementary viewpointк°Җ мӮ¬мҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ҙм§Ҳ л•Ң мҲҳм •лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ м—ҙл Ө мһҲм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Reason, then Re-reason (ReRe)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” training-free, inference-time frameworkлЎңм„ң л‘җ лӢЁкі„лЎң кө¬м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. Reason Phaseм—җм„ңлҠ” MLLMмқҙ мӣҗліё videoлЎңл¶Җн„° spatial hypothesisлҘј нҳ•м„ұн•ҳкі , Re-reason Phaseм—җм„ңлҠ” synthesized novel-view videoлҘј кҙҖм°°н•ҳм—¬ н•ҙлӢ№ hypothesisлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мҲҳм •н•ңлӢӨ. нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё cross-view revisitingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” predicted 3D geometryлЎңл¶Җн„° м „лһөм ҒмңјлЎң мғҒліҙм Ғмқё novel viewлҘј л ҢлҚ”л§Ғн•ҳлҠ” Geometry-to-Video pipelineмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ viewл“ӨмқҖ scene spanning coverageлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ elevatedн•ң oblique perspectiveлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, architectural modification м—Ҷмқҙ MLLMмқҳ native video interfaceлҘј к·ёлҢҖлЎң ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. VSI-Benchм—җм„ңмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҠ” ReReк°Җ open-source MLLMмқ„ consistentlyн•ҳкІҢ к°•нҷ”н•ҳм—¬ proprietary state-of-the-art performanceм—җ н•„м Ғн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65536","en":"S2GS: Streaming Semantic Gaussian Splatting for Online Scene Understanding and Reconstruction","ko":"S2GS: мҳЁлқјмқё мһҘл©ҙ мқҙн•ҙ л°Ҹ мһ¬кө¬м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мҠӨнҠёлҰ¬л°Қ мқҳлҜё Gaussian Splatting","authors":"Renhe Zhang, Yuyang Tan, Jingyu Gong, Zhizhong Zhang, Lizhuang Ma, Yuan Xie, Xin Tan","pos":"#607","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CbWCaD8tRC","abs":"<p>Existing offline feed-forward methods for joint scene understanding and reconstruction on long image streams often repeatedly perform global computation over an ever-growing set of past observations, causing runtime and GPU memory to increase rapidly with sequence length and limiting scalability. We propose Streaming Semantic Gaussian Splatting (S2GS), a strictly causal, incremental 3D Gaussian semantic field framework: it does not leverage future frames and continuously updates scene geometry, appearance, and instance-level semantics without reprocessing historical frames, enabling scalable online joint reconstruction and understanding. S2GS adopts a geometryвҖ“semantic decoupled dual-backbone design: the geometry branch performs causal modeling to drive incremental Gaussian updates, while the semantic branch leverages a 2D foundation vision model and a query-driven decoder to predict segmentation masks and identity embeddings, further stabilized by query-level contrastive alignment and lightweight online association with an instance memory. Experiments show that S2GS matches or outperforms strong offline baselines on joint reconstruction-and-understanding benchmarks, while significantly improving long-horizon scalability: it processes 1,000+ frames with much slower growth in runtime and GPU memory, whereas offline global-processing baselines typically run out of memory at around 80 frames under the same setting.</p>","absKo":"<p>кёҙ image streamм—җм„ң joint scene understandingкіј reconstructionмқ„ мң„н•ң кё°мЎҙмқҳ offline feed-forward methodлҠ” мў…мў… м җм җ м»Өм§ҖлҠ” кіјкұ° кҙҖмёЎ м§‘н•©м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ global computationмқ„ л°ҳліө мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, sequence lengthк°Җ кёём–ҙм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ runtimeкіј GPU memoryк°Җ л№ лҘҙкІҢ мҰқк°Җн•ҳкі  нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Streaming Semantic Gaussian Splatting (S2GS)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” м—„кІ©н•ң causal, incremental 3D Gaussian semantic field frameworkлЎңм„ң future frameмқ„ м „нҳҖ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, кіјкұ° frameмқ„ лӢӨмӢң мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ scene geometry, appearance, instance-level semanticмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң к°ұмӢ н•ҳм—¬ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң online joint reconstructionкіј understandingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. S2GSлҠ” geometryвҖ“semantic decoupled dual-backbone designмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ңлӢӨ. geometry branchлҠ” causal modelingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҙ incremental Gaussian updateлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳкі , semantic branchлҠ” 2D foundation vision modelкіј query-driven decoderлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ segmentation maskмҷҖ identity embeddingмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң query-level contrastive alignmentмҷҖ instance memoryмҷҖмқҳ lightweight online associationмңјлЎң мқҙлҘј м¶”к°Җм ҒмңјлЎң м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј S2GSлҠ” joint reconstruction-and-understanding benchmarkм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң offline baselineкіј лҸҷл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ к·ё мқҙмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, мһҘкё° мӢңкі„м—ҙ нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқҖ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. лҸҷмқјн•ң м„Өм •м—җм„ң offline global-processing baselineмқҖ лҢҖк°ң м•Ҫ 80 frame л¶Җк·јм—җм„ң л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ л¶ҖмЎұмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, ліё л°©лІ•мқҖ runtimeкіј GPU memory мҰқк°Җк°Җ нӣЁм”¬ мҷ„л§Ңн•ң мғҒнғңлЎң 1,000к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ frameмқ„ мІҳлҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65044","en":"Spike Camera Autofocus via Frequency-Domain Spectral-Centroid Migration","ko":"Frequency-Domain Spectral-Centroid Migrationмқ„ нҶөн•ң Spike Camera Autofocus","authors":"Xijie Xiang, Lin Zhu, Yonghong Tian","pos":"#609","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HNODd5L2Tv","abs":"<p>Autofocus for spike cameras is challenging because their sparse binary measurements do not provide reliable instantaneous gradients, and noise or illumination drift often breaks the unimodal assumptions behind conventional focus measures.  We show that during a focus sweep, the stable sensor-observable cue is a persistent migration of spectral energy in the frequency domain: energy shifts outward toward higher frequencies when approaching focus and recedes under renewed defocus.  Building on this observation, we propose CEN (Centroid-based Energy Navigation), a frequency-domain autofocus method that measures spectral migration via a bounded spectral centroid computed on accumulated spike blocks, without image reconstruction or explicit edge extraction.  To handle multi-peak and irregular responses in real scenes, CEN further performs structure-consistent response identification, selecting the frequency bound whose curve exhibits a clear, localized, interior extremum, followed by robust peak localization using a weighted near-maximum centroid.  Experiments on spike-camera dataset demonstrate that CEN achieves the best overall accuracy and response discriminability across diverse scenes, motion types, and illumination variation patterns.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҠӨнҢҢмқҙнҒ¬ м№ҙл©”лқјм—җм„ң autofocusлҠ” м–ҙл өлӢӨ. нқ¬мҶҢн•ң мқҙм§„ мёЎм •к°’мқҖ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мҲңк°„ кё°мҡёкё° м •ліҙлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі , мһЎмқҢмқҙлӮҳ мЎ°лӘ… л“ңлҰ¬н”„нҠёлҠ” кё°мЎҙ focus measureк°Җ м „м ңн•ҳлҠ” лӢЁлҙүм„ұ(unimodal) к°Җм •мқ„ мүҪкІҢ к№ЁлңЁлҰ¬кё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” focus sweep лҸҷм•Ҳ кҙҖмёЎлҗҳлҠ” м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё sensor-level cueк°Җ мЈјнҢҢмҲҳ мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ңмқҳ мҠӨнҺҷнҠёлҹј м—җл„Ҳм§Җмқҳ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё мқҙлҸҷмқҙлқјлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҰү, focusм—җ к°Җк№ҢмӣҢм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ м—җл„Ҳм§ҖлҠ” лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ мЈјнҢҢмҲҳ мӘҪмңјлЎң л°”к№ҘмңјлЎң мқҙлҸҷн•ҳкі , лӢӨмӢң defocusлҗҳл©ҙ лҗҳлҸҢм•„к°„лӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CEN(Centroid-based Energy Navigation)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. CENмқҖ мқҙлҜём§Җ ліөмӣҗмқҙлӮҳ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё edge extraction м—Ҷмқҙ, лҲ„м Ғлҗң spike block мң„м—җм„ң кі„мӮ°н•ң bounded spectral centroidлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мҠӨнҺҷнҠёлҹј мқҙлҸҷмқ„ мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” мЈјнҢҢмҲҳ мҳҒм—ӯ autofocus л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. мӢӨм ң мһҘл©ҙм—җм„ң лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” лӢӨмӨ‘ н”јнҒ¬ л°Ҹ л№„м •нҳ• л°ҳмқ‘мқ„ лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ, CENмқҖ м¶”к°ҖлЎң structure-consistent response identificationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кіЎм„ мқҙ лҡңл ·н•ҳкі  көӯмҶҢм Ғмқё лӮҙл¶Җ extremumмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” мЈјнҢҢмҲҳ boundлҘј м„ нғқн•ң л’Ө, weighted near-maximum centroidлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кІ¬кі н•ҳкІҢ н”јнҒ¬лҘј көӯмҶҢнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. spike-camera datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CENмқҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мһҘл©ҙ, motion type, мЎ°лӘ… ліҖнҷ” нҢЁн„ҙ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң м „мІҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ response discriminability мёЎл©ҙмқҳ мөңмғҒ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66580","en":"StructMamPose: From Sequential Perception to Structural Reasoning for 3D Human Pose Estimation","ko":"StructMamPose: 3D мқёк°„ мһҗм„ё м¶”м •мқ„ мң„н•ң мҲңм°Ём Ғ м§Җк°Ғм—җм„ң кө¬мЎ°м Ғ м¶”лЎ мңјлЎң","authors":"Jiahong Jiang, Miao Zhang, Leiye Liu, Yao Cui, Jingjing Li, Wei Ji, Yongri Piao, Huchuan Lu","pos":"#610","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2T0kl2qQKB","abs":"<p>Accurately modeling complex temporal and topological dependencies and depth information is critical for monocular 3D human pose estimation, yet existing Mamba-based approaches struggle to fulfill these demands, suffering from internal state update confusion induced by forced sequence flattening and depth modeling confusion inherent to single-view observations. To address this confusion, we propose a StructMamPose framework equipped with Identity Anchoring Mechanism (IAM) and View Transformation Hub (VTH). The IAM injects spatiotemporal identities into the parameter generation network to anchor the selectivity of state update matrices, suppressing spurious connections to enforce feature propagation along valid topological dependencies. The VTH performs internal coordinate rotation to transform implicit depth inference into observable planar features, endowing the model with explicit spatial understanding and multi-view constraints. Experimental results demonstrate that our framework achieves SOTA performance on most datasets.</p>","absKo":"<p>лӢЁм•Ҳ 3D human pose estimationм—җм„ңлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң temporal л°Ҹ topological dependencyмҷҖ depth м •ліҙлҘј м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙмқҳ Mamba кё°л°ҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ к°•м ңлЎң sequenceлҘј flatteningн•ҳлҠ” кіјм •м—җм„ң мң л°ңлҗҳлҠ” internal state update confusionкіј лӢЁмқј мӢңм җ кҙҖмёЎм—җ лӮҙмһ¬н•ң depth modeling confusion л•Ңл¬ём—җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҡ”кө¬лҘј м¶©мЎұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҳјлһҖмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Identity Anchoring Mechanism (IAM)кіј View Transformation Hub (VTH)лҘј к°–м¶ҳ StructMamPose frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. IAMмқҖ spatiotemporal identityлҘј parameter generation networkм—җ мЈјмһ…н•ҳм—¬ state update matrixмқҳ selectivityлҘј anchorн•ҳкі , feature propagationмқҙ мң нҡЁн•ң topological dependencyлҘј л”°лқј м§„н–үлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ spurious connectionмқ„ м–өм ңн•ңлӢӨ. VTHлҠ” internal coordinate rotationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ м•”л¬өм Ғмқё depth inferenceлҘј кҙҖмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң planar featureлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, лӘЁлҚём—җ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё spatial understandingкіј multi-view constraintлҘј л¶Җм—¬н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkк°Җ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ datasetм—җм„ң SOTA м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62065","en":"Zero-shot Active Mapping via Fused 360-BEV Representations and VisionвҖ“Language Models","ko":"Fused 360-BEV н‘ңнҳ„кіј VisionвҖ“Language Models кё°л°ҳ Zero-shot Active Mapping","authors":"Yuanze Wang, Dianxi Shi, Yuetian Wang, Shiming Song, Haikuo Peng, Chunping Qiu, Mengzhu Wang","pos":"#615","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=kBZguFRp1B","abs":"<p>Active mapping enables embodied agents to understand and interact in previously unseen environments. However, most methods struggle to achieve zero-shot generalization to large-scale scenes and lack support for language instructions. We propose a VLM-based active mapping method that achieves zero-shot mapping while facilitating language-driven humanвҖ“agent interaction. First, we introduce a 360-BEV representation that integrates omnidirectional semantics with BEV-aligned geometric structure to enhance scene understanding. Second, we develop a candidate waypoint generation strategy that allows the VLM-driven agent to select informative 2D waypoints in image space and back-project them into executable metric actions in 3D space, enabling the VLM to plan in its strongest modality. Third, we design a VLM-based depth-first exploration agent that decomposes the scenes into explorable regions, selects informative waypoints within each region, and organizes them into a topological tree. The agent follows the depth-first exploration policy to achieve thorough coverage of large-scale scenes. Without task-specific training, our method outperforms the strongest baseline, improving coverage and AUC by approximately 13.25\\% and 14.00\\%, respectively, while enabling language-conditioned interaction.</p>","absKo":"<p>Active mappingмқҖ embodied agentк°Җ мқҙм „м—җ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң нҷҳкІҪмқ„ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкі  мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙмӨҖлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ large-scale sceneм—җ лҢҖн•ң zero-shot generalizationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘкі , language instruction м§Җмӣҗмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” zero-shot mappingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң language-driven humanвҖ“agent interactionмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ҳлҠ” VLM кё°л°ҳ active mapping л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, omnidirectional semanticsмҷҖ BEVм—җ м •л ¬лҗң geometric structureлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ scene understandingмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” 360-BEV representationмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, VLMмқҙ кө¬лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” agentк°Җ image spaceм—җм„ң informativeн•ң 2D waypointлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј 3D spaceм—җм„ң мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң metric actionмңјлЎң back-projectн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” candidate waypoint generation strategyлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬, VLMмқҙ к°ҖмһҘ к°•н•ң modalityм—җм„ң кі„нҡҚмқ„ м„ёмҡё мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. м…Ӣм§ё, sceneмқ„ explore к°ҖлҠҘн•ң regionмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳкі , к°Ғ region лӮҙм—җм„ң informativeн•ң waypointлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј topological treeлЎң мЎ°м§Ғн•ҳлҠ” VLM кё°л°ҳ depth-first exploration agentлҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. agentлҠ” depth-first exploration policyлҘј л”°лқј large-scale sceneмқ„ мІ м ҖнһҲ coverageн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. task-specific training м—Ҷмқҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ к°ҖмһҘ к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳм—¬ coverageмҷҖ AUCлҘј к°Ғк°Ғ м•Ҫ 13.25\\%, 14.00\\% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, language-conditioned interactionлҸ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66146","en":"Learning Global Representation from Queries for Vectorized HD Map Construction","ko":"лІЎн„°нҷ” HD м§ҖлҸ„ кө¬м¶•мқ„ мң„н•ң мҝјлҰ¬лЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ м „м—ӯ н‘ңнҳ„ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Shoumeng Qiu, Xinrun Li, Yang Long, Xiangyang Xue, Varun Ojha, Jian Pu","pos":"#703","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=6Qu03WGp6x","abs":"<p>The online construction of vectorized high-definition (HD) maps is a cornerstone of modern autonomous driving systems. State-of-the-art approaches, particularly those based on the DETR framework, formulate this as an instance detection problem. However, their reliance on independent, learnable object queries results in a predominantly local query perspective, neglecting the inherent global representation within HD maps. In this work, we propose \\textbf{MapGR} (\\textbf{G}lobal \\textbf{R}epresentation learning for HD \\textbf{Map} construction), an architecture designed to learn and utilize a global representations from queries. Our method introduces two synergistic modules: a Global Representation Learning (GRL) module, which encourages the distribution of all queries to better align with the global map through a carefully designed holistic segmentation task, and a Global Representation Guidance (GRG) module, which endows each individual query with explicit, global-level contextual information to facilitate its optimization. Evaluations on the nuScenes and Argoverse2 datasets validate the efficacy of our approach, demonstrating substantial improvements in mean Average Precision (mAP) compared to leading baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>vectorized high-definition(HD) mapsмқҳ мҳЁлқјмқё кө¬м¶•мқҖ нҳ„лҢҖ autonomous driving systemsмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ мҡ”мҶҢмқҙлӢӨ. мөңмӢ  м ‘к·јлІ•, нҠ№нһҲ DETR frameworkм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ мқҙлҘј instance detection л¬ём ңлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё learnable object queryм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” нғ“м—җ мЈјлЎң localн•ң query perspectiveм—җ лЁёл¬јл©°, HD mapм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң global representationмқ„ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” queriesлЎңл¶Җн„° global representationsлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң architectureмқё \\textbf{MapGR}(\\textbf{G}lobal \\textbf{R}epresentation learning for HD \\textbf{Map} construction)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мғҒнҳёліҙмҷ„м Ғ лӘЁл“Ҳмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” carefully designed holistic segmentation taskлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁл“  queryмқҳ л¶„нҸ¬к°Җ global mapкіј лҚ” мһҳ м •л ¬лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” Global Representation Learning(GRL) moduleмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” к°Ғ к°ңлі„ queryм—җ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё global-level contextual informationмқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ҳм—¬ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мҡ©мқҙн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” Global Representation Guidance(GRG) moduleмқҙлӢӨ. nuScenesмҷҖ Argoverse2 datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҳ нҡЁмҡ©мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳл©°, м„ лҸ„м Ғмқё baseline лҢҖл№„ mean Average Precision(mAP)м—җм„ң substantial improvementлҘј ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63237","en":"LaRI: Layered Ray Intersections for Single-view 3D Geometric Reasoning","ko":"LaRI: лӢЁмқј л·° 3D кё°н•ҳ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң кі„мёөм Ғ кҙ‘м„  көҗм°Ё","authors":"Rui Li, Biao Zhang, Zhenyu Li, Federico Tombari, Peter Wonka","pos":"#707","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=YqD2yRftiR","abs":"<p>We present Layered Ray Intersections (LaRI), a fully supervised method for occluded geometry reasoning from a single image. Unlike conventional depth estimation, which is limited to visible surfaces, LaRI predicts multiple surfaces intersected by the camera rays using layered point maps. Compared to the existing approaches that leverage neural implicit representations or iterative refinement, LaRI achieves complete scene reconstruction in one feed-forward pass, enabling efficient and view-aligned geometric reasoning to underpin both object-level and scene-level tasks. We further propose to predict the ray stopping index, which identifies valid intersecting pixels and layers from LaRI's output. To better underpin and evaluate this task, we build an annotation pipeline using rendering engines, construct annotations for five public datasets, including synthetic and real-world data covering 3D objects and scenes. As a generic method, LaRI's performance is validated in object-level and scene-level reconstruction tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢЁмқј мқҙлҜём§ҖлЎңл¶Җн„° occluded geometryлҘј м¶”лЎ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң fully supervised л°©лІ•мқё Layered Ray Intersections(LaRI)лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. к°ҖмӢңм Ғмқё н‘ңл©ҙм—җл§Ң н•ңм •лҗҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ depth estimationкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, LaRIлҠ” layered point mapмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ camera rayк°Җ көҗм°Ён•ҳлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ н‘ңл©ҙмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ңлӢӨ. neural implicit representationмқҙлӮҳ iterative refinementлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•кіј л№„көҗн•  л•Ң, LaRIлҠ” н•ң лІҲмқҳ feed-forward passлЎң мҷ„м „н•ң scene reconstructionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, object-level л°Ҹ scene-level taskлҘј л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  view-alignedн•ң geometric reasoningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң LaRIмқҳ м¶ңл ҘмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° мң нҡЁн•ң көҗм°Ё pixelкіј layerлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” ray stopping index мҳҲмёЎмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ taskлҘј лҚ” мһҳ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳкі  нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” rendering engineмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң annotation pipelineмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳкі , 3D objectмҷҖ sceneмқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” synthetic л°Ҹ real-world dataлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң 5к°ңмқҳ public datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң annotationмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лІ”мҡ© л°©лІ•мңјлЎңм„ң LaRIмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқҖ object-level л°Ҹ scene-level reconstruction taskм—җм„ң кІҖмҰқлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65015","en":"3ViewSense: Spatial and Mental Perspective Reasoning from Orthographic Views in Vision-Language Models","ko":"3ViewSense: Vision-Language лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң м •мӮ¬мҳҒ л·°лЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ кіөк°„ л°Ҹ м •мӢ м Ғ кҙҖм җ м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Shaoxiong Zhan, Yanlin Lai, Zheng Liu, Zijian Lin, Lin Hai, Xiaodong Cai, Shen Li, Wen Huang, Hai-Tao Zheng","pos":"#806","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Hm8OEDKpiO","abs":"<p>Current Large Language Models have achieved Olympiad-level logic, yet Vision-Language Models paradoxically falter on elementary spatial tasks like block counting. This capability mismatch reveals a critical \"spatial intelligence gap,\" where models fail to construct coherent 3D mental representations from 2D observations. We uncover this gap via diagnostic analyses showing the bottleneck is a missing view-consistent spatial interface rather than insufficient visual features or weak reasoning. To bridge this, we introduce <strong>3ViewSense</strong>, a framework that grounds spatial reasoning in Orthographic Views. Drawing on engineering cognition, we propose a \"Simulate-and-Reason\" mechanism that decomposes complex scenes into canonical orthographic projections to resolve geometric ambiguities. By aligning egocentric perceptions with these allocentric references, our method facilitates explicit mental rotation and reconstruction. Empirical results on spatial reasoning benchmarks demonstrate that our method significantly outperforms existing baselines, with consistent gains on occlusion-heavy counting and view-consistent spatial reasoning. The framework also improves the stability and consistency of spatial descriptions, offering a scalable path toward stronger spatial intelligence in multimodal systems.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ Large Language ModelмқҖ Olympiad мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ logicмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, Vision-Language ModelмқҖ paradoxically block countingкіј к°ҷмқҖ кё°мҙҲм Ғмқё spatial taskм—җм„ң м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң capability mismatchлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ 2D observationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° мқјкҙҖлҗң 3D mental representationмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң \"spatial intelligence gap\"мқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” diagnostic analysisлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ gapмқҳ лі‘лӘ©мқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң visual featureлӮҳ м•Ҫн•ң reasoningмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј, view-consistentн•ң spatial interfaceмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬м—җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” spatial reasoningмқ„ Orthographic Viewsм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” frameworkмқё <strong>3ViewSense</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. engineering cognitionм—җм„ң м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң sceneмқ„ canonical orthographic projectionмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҙ geometric ambiguityлҘј н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳлҠ” \"Simulate-and-Reason\" mechanismмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. egocentric perceptionмқ„ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң allocentric referenceмҷҖ м •л ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё mental rotationкіј reconstructionмқ„ мҡ©мқҙн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. spatial reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ кё°мЎҙ baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, occlusionмқҙ л§ҺмқҖ countingкіј view-consistent spatial reasoningм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkлҠ” spatial descriptionмқҳ м•Ҳм •м„ұкіј мқјкҙҖм„ұлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңмјң, multimodal systemм—җм„ң лҚ” к°•н•ң spatial intelligenceлЎң к°ҖлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65758","en":"Beyond Unidirectional Bias: Reciprocal Perspective Calibration in Scene Graph Generation","ko":"лӢЁл°©н–Ҙ нҺён–Ҙмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ң: мһҘл©ҙ к·ёлһҳн”„ мғқм„ұм—җм„ңмқҳ мғҒнҳё кҙҖм җ ліҙм •","authors":"Haifeng Zhao, Wenbo Zhao, Xuemei Luo, Lei-Lei Ma, Dengdi Sun","pos":"#808","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ASFd58CECj","abs":"Scene Graph Generation (SGG) paradigms predominantly model relationships as static, unidirectional mappings ($s \\to o$), effectively treating objects as passive recipients of actions. This formulation suffers from an inherent \\textit{unidirectional bias}, violating the physical reality that visual interactions are intrinsically reciprocal. Consequently, existing models often fail to maintain logical self-consistency when the reasoning anchor shifts from the subject to the object. To rectify this cognitive deficiency, we establish the Mutual-Perspective Inverse Relations (MPIR) principle, positing that a robust visual representation must satisfy logical consistency across dual perspectives. Guided by this principle, we propose the \\textbf{Reciprocal Perspective Calibration (RPC)} framework, a model-agnostic framework that operationalizes MPIR via a novel Adaptive Inverse-Relation Augmentation (AIRA) strategy. Furthermore, we introduce Hypernym-Guided Prompts (HGP) to bridge the gap between semantic context and computational efficiency in vision-language models, enabling precise modeling of inverse relations. Extensive experiments demonstrate that RPC not only achieves competitive performance on standard benchmarks but also significantly enhances the model's capability to understand inverse relations, as verified by a new inverse consistency evaluation protocol, demonstrating the cognitive robustness of our method.","absKo":"Scene Graph Generation (SGG) нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҖ кҙҖкі„лҘј мЈјлЎң staticн•ң лӢЁл°©н–Ҙ л§Өн•‘($s \\to o$)мңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳм—¬, к°қмІҙлҘј н–үлҸҷмқҳ мҲҳлҸҷм Ғ мҲҳмҡ©мһҗлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң formulationмқҖ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғмқё \\textit{unidirectional bias}лҘј к°Җм§Җл©°, мӢңк°Ғм Ғ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҙ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мғҒнҳём ҒмқҙлқјлҠ” л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ нҳ„мӢӨмқ„ мң„л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј кё°мЎҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ м¶”лЎ мқҳ кё°мӨҖм җмқҙ subjectм—җм„ң objectлЎң л°”лҖ” л•Ң л…јлҰ¬м Ғ мһҗкё°мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мқём§Җм Ғ кІ°н•Ёмқ„ л°”лЎңмһЎкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Mutual-Perspective Inverse Relations (MPIR) мӣҗм№ҷмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳл©°, к°•кұҙн•ң visual representationмқҖ л‘җ кҙҖм җ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң л…јлҰ¬м Ғ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ л§ҢмЎұн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мӣҗм№ҷм—җ л”°лқј мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{Reciprocal Perspective Calibration (RPC)} н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Adaptive Inverse-Relation Augmentation (AIRA) м „лһөмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ MPIRмқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•ҳлҠ” model-agnostic frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң vision-language modelм—җм„ң semantic contextмҷҖ computational efficiency мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ Hypernym-Guided Prompts (HGP)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ inverse relationмқ„ м •л°Җн•ҳкІҢ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ RPCк°Җ н‘ңмӨҖ benchmarkм—җм„ң кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј, мғҲлЎңмҡҙ inverse consistency evaluation protocolлЎң кІҖмҰқлҗң л°”мҷҖ к°ҷмқҙ inverse relation мқҙн•ҙ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңмјң, мҡ°лҰ¬ л°©лІ•мқҳ мқём§Җм Ғ к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62489","en":"CoGeoAD: Hierarchical Color-Geometric Fusion with Multi-View Attention for Zero-Shot 3D Anomaly Detection","ko":"CoGeoAD: лӢӨмӨ‘ мӢңм җ мЈјмқҳ кё°л°ҳ кі„мёөм Ғ мғү-кё°н•ҳн•ҷ мңөн•©мқ„ нҶөн•ң м ңлЎңмғ· 3D мқҙмғҒм№ҳ нғҗм§Җ","authors":"Ke Xu, Xinle Wang, Yanning Hou, Xueliang Ma, Juan Xie, Jianfeng Qiu","pos":"#811","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=g95mt3KBRd","abs":"<p>Zero-shot 3D anomaly detection is essential for industrial quality inspection, where labeled anomaly samples are scarce. Meanwhile, existing methods lack an effective mechanism to fuse complementary 2D color images with 3D geometric structures, limiting their ability to detect both surface and structural defects in a unified framework. To address these issues, we propose CoGeoAD, a unified CLIP-based framework that fuses color and geometric features by constructing pixel-aligned paired multi-view images. The framework introduces a Data-Driven Multi-View Attention (MVA) mechanism to adaptively aggregate 3D features and a Multi-Stage Color-Geometric Fusion (MS-CGF) module to hierarchically integrate multi-level features from both modalities. Extensive experiments on the MVTec3D-AD and Eyecandies benchmarks demonstrate that CoGeoAD achieves state-of-the-art performance, effectively capturing both structural and textural anomalies in complex industrial scenarios.</p>","absKo":"<p>zero-shot 3D anomaly detectionмқҖ лқјлІЁмқҙ мһҲлҠ” anomaly sampleмқҙ нқ¬к·Җн•ң мӮ°м—… н’Ҳм§Ҳ кІҖмӮ¬м—җм„ң н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. н•ңнҺё кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ 2D color imageмҷҖ 3D geometric structureлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мңөн•©н•ҳлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳм—¬, н‘ңл©ҙ кІ°н•Ёкіј кө¬мЎ°м Ғ кІ°н•Ёмқ„ лӢЁмқј frameworkм—җм„ң н•Ёк»ҳ нғҗм§Җн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” pixel-aligned paired multi-view imageлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ colorмҷҖ geometric featureлҘј мңөн•©н•ҳлҠ” unified CLIP-based frameworkмқё CoGeoADлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkлҠ” 3D featureлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң м§‘кі„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң Data-Driven Multi-View Attention (MVA) mechanismкіј, л‘җ modalityмқҳ multi-level featureлҘј кі„мёөм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” Multi-Stage Color-Geometric Fusion (MS-CGF) moduleмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. MVTec3D-ADмҷҖ Eyecandies benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CoGeoADк°Җ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, ліөмһЎн•ң мӮ°м—… мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мқҙмғҒкіј м§Ҳк°җ мқҙмғҒмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҸ¬м°©н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64546","en":"Code2Worlds: Empowering Coding LLMs for 4D World Generation","ko":"Code2Worlds: 4D м„ёкі„ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мҪ”л”© LLM к°•нҷ”","authors":"Yi Zhang, Yunshuang Wang, Zeyu Zhang, Hao Tang","pos":"#813","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=MKsxhiUk9M","abs":"<p>Achieving spatial intelligence requires moving beyond visual plausibility to build world simulators grounded in physical laws. While coding LLMs have advanced static 3D scene generation, extending this paradigm to 4D dynamics remains a critical frontier. This task presents two fundamental challenges: multi-scale context entanglement, where monolithic generation fails to balance local object structures with global environmental layouts; and a semantic-physical execution gap, where open-loop code generation leads to physical hallucinations lacking dynamic fidelity. We introduce Code2Worlds, a framework that formulates 4D generation as language-to-simulation code generation. First, we propose a dual-stream architecture that disentangles retrieval-augmented object generation from hierarchical environmental orchestration. Second, to ensure dynamic fidelity, we establish a physics-aware closed-loop mechanism in which a PostProcess Agent scripts dynamics, coupled with a VLM-Motion Critic that performs self-reflection to iteratively refine simulation code. Evaluations on the Code4D benchmark show Code2Worlds outperforms baselines with a 41% SGS gain and 49% higher Richness, while uniquely generating physics-aware dynamics absent in prior static methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>кіөк°„ м§ҖлҠҘ(spatial intelligence)мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл Өл©ҙ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ нғҖлӢ№м„ұмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ң л¬јлҰ¬ лІ•м№ҷм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң world simulatorлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. coding LLMмқҖ м •м Ғмқё 3D scene generationмқ„ л°ңм „мӢңмјң мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ 4D dynamicsлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мөңм „м„  кіјм ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кіјм ңлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ к·јліём Ғ лҸ„м „мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ: н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” multi-scale context entanglementлЎң, лӢЁмқјмІҙм Ғ мғқм„ұмқҙ көӯмҶҢ object structureмҷҖ м „м—ӯ нҷҳкІҪ layoutмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”м§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңмқҙл©°, лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” semantic-physical execution gapмңјлЎң, open-loop code generationмқҙ лҸҷм Ғ м¶©мӢӨлҸ„ м—Ҷмқҙ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ hallucinationмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 4D generationмқ„ language-to-simulation code generationмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё Code2WorldsлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ, retrieval-augmented object generationкіј hierarchical environmental orchestrationмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” dual-stream architectureлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, лҸҷм Ғ м¶©мӢӨлҸ„лҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ PostProcess Agentк°Җ dynamicsлҘј мҠӨнҒ¬лҰҪнҠёнҷ”н•ҳкі , VLM-Motion Criticмқҙ self-reflectionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ simulation codeлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң м •м ңн•ҳлҠ” physics-aware closed-loop mechanismмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. Code4D benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” Code2Worldsк°Җ 41% SGS н–ҘмғҒкіј 49% лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ RichnessлЎң baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙмқҳ м •м Ғ л°©лІ•м—җм„ңлҠ” м—ҶлҚҳ physics-aware dynamicsлҘј лҸ…нҠ№н•ҳкІҢ мғқм„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64262","en":"Decoupling Skeleton and Flesh: Efficient Multimodal Table Reasoning with  Disentangled Alignment and Structure-aware Guidance","ko":"кіЁкІ©кіј мӮҙмқҳ л¶„лҰ¬: л¶„лҰ¬лҗң м •л ¬ л°Ҹ кө¬мЎ° мқёмӢқ мң лҸ„лҘј нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ н‘ң м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Yingjie Zhu, Xuefeng Bai, Kehai Chen, Yang Xiang, Youcheng Pan, Xiaoqiang Zhou, Min zhang","pos":"#814","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PN7l7mBPDO","abs":"<p>Reasoning over table images remains challenging for Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) due to complex layouts and tightly coupled structureвҖ“content information. Existing solutions often depend on expensive supervised training, reinforcement learning, or external tools, limiting efficiency and scalability. This work addresses a key question: <em>how to adapt LVLMs to table reasoning with minimal annotation and no external tools?</em> Specifically, we first introduce DiSCo, a Disentangled StructureвҖ“Content alignment framework that explicitly separates structural abstraction from semantic grounding during multimodal alignment, efficiently adapting LVLMs to tables structures. Building on DiSCo, we further present Table-GLS, a Global-to-Local Structure-guided reasoning framework that performs table reasoning via structured exploration and evidence-grounded inference. Extensive experiments across diverse benchmarks demonstrate that our framework efficiently enhances LVLM's table understanding and reasoning capabilities, particularly generalizing to unseen table structures.</p>","absKo":"Large Vision-Language Models(LVLMs)лҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң layoutкіј к°•н•ҳкІҢ кІ°н•©лҗң structure-content м •ліҙлҘј м§ҖлӢҢ table imageм—җ лҢҖн•ң м¶”лЎ м—җм„ң м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ н•ҙкІ°мұ…мқҖ лҢҖк°ң л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° supervised training, reinforcement learning, лҳҗлҠ” мҷёл¶Җ лҸ„кө¬м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ нҡЁмңЁм„ұкіј нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” н•өмӢ¬ м§Ҳл¬ё, мҰү <em>мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ annotationкіј мҷёл¶Җ лҸ„кө¬ м—Ҷмқҙ LVLMмқ„ table reasoningм—җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮ¬ кІғмқёк°Җ?</em>лҘј лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, лЁјм Җ DiSCoлқјлҠ” Disentangled StructureвҖ“Content alignment frameworkлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ multimodal alignment кіјм •м—җм„ң кө¬мЎ°м Ғ м¶”мғҒнҷ”мҷҖ semantic groundingмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң л¶„лҰ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ LVLMмқ„ table structureм—җ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. DiSCoлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң нғҗмғүкіј evidence-grounded inferenceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ table reasoningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” Global-to-Local Structure-guided reasoning frameworkмқё Table-GLSлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkк°Җ LVLMмқҳ table мқҙн•ҙ л°Ҹ reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, нҠ№нһҲ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң table structureм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ мһҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"64197","en":"Distilling Neuro-Symbolic Programs into 3D Multi-modal LLMs","ko":"мӢ кІҪ-кё°нҳё н”„лЎңк·ёлһЁмқ„ 3D л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ LLMмңјлЎң мҰқлҘҳ","authors":"Wentao Mo, Yang Liu","pos":"#815","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Q3M37WtXsW","abs":"<p>Current 3D spatial reasoning methods face a fundamental trade-off: neuro-symbolic 3D (NS3D) concept learners achieve interpretable reasoning through compositional programs but are constrained to closed-set concept vocabularies and simple programs; end-to-end 3D multi-modal LLMs (3D MLLMs) could handle complex natural language and open-vocabulary concepts but suffer from black-box reasoning without explicit spatial verification. We introduce APEIRIA, a neuro-symbolic 3D MLLM that bridges these paradigms by distilling symbolic reasoning patterns into MLLMs with natural language chain-of-thought (CoT).  Our three-stage curriculum progressively builds reasoning capabilities: (1) 3D perception alignment that grounds object visual-geometric features to the LLM's textual embedding space,  (2) CoT-SFT that teaches systematic query decomposition and stepwise spatial verification from symbolic program traces,  and (3) CoT-RL that extends learned reasoning patterns to open-set concepts and deeply nested instructions. This transfers reasoning patterns rather than concept-specific knowledge,  preserving key NS3D virtues: transparent reasoning traces and modular interchangeability of planning and perception components. Extensive evaluations demonstrate that APEIRIA surpasses previous NS3D methods and matches state-of-the-art 3D MLLMs on 3D spatial reasoning benchmarks, presenting a unified framework combining the systematic reasoning of symbolic methods with the flexibility of modern LLMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ 3D spatial reasoning л°©лІ•мқҖ к·јліём Ғмқё trade-offм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ҙ мһҲлӢӨ. neuro-symbolic 3D(NS3D) concept learnerлҠ” compositional programмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң reasoningмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, closed-set concept vocabularyмҷҖ лӢЁмҲңн•ң programм—җ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ end-to-end 3D multi-modal LLM(3D MLLM)мқҖ ліөмһЎн•ң мһҗм—°м–ҙмҷҖ open-vocabulary conceptмқ„ мІҳлҰ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, лӘ…мӢңм Ғ spatial verificationмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” black-box reasoningмқҳ н•ңкі„лҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһҗм—°м–ҙ chain-of-thought(CoT)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ symbolic reasoning patternмқ„ MLLMм—җ distillн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ мһҮлҠ” neuro-symbolic 3D MLLMмқё APEIRIAлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ 3лӢЁкі„ curriculumмқҖ reasoning capabilityлҘј м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ: (1) 3D perception alignmentлҠ” objectмқҳ visual-geometric featureлҘј LLMмқҳ textual embedding spaceм—җ groundingн•ҳкі , (2) CoT-SFTлҠ” symbolic program traceлЎңл¶Җн„° мІҙкі„м Ғмқё query decompositionкіј лӢЁкі„м Ғ spatial verificationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨл©°, (3) CoT-RLмқҖ н•ҷмҠөлҗң reasoning patternмқ„ open-set conceptкіј к№ҠкІҢ мӨ‘мІ©лҗң instructionмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” concept-specific knowledgeк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј reasoning patternмқ„ м „мқҙмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң, нҲ¬лӘ…н•ң reasoning traceмҷҖ planning л°Ҹ perception componentмқҳ лӘЁл“ҲмӢқ мғҒнҳёкөҗнҷҳм„ұмқҙлқјлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ NS3Dмқҳ мһҘм җмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҠ” APEIRIAк°Җ кё°мЎҙ NS3D л°©лІ•мқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкі  3D spatial reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art 3D MLLMкіј лҸҷл“ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, symbolic methodмқҳ мІҙкі„м Ғ reasoningкіј нҳ„лҢҖ LLMмқҳ мң м—°м„ұмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң нҶөн•© frameworkлҘј м ңмӢңн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66523","en":"BiRQA: Bidirectional Robust Quality Assessment for Images","ko":"BiRQA: мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј мң„н•ң м–‘л°©н–Ҙ кІ¬кі  н’Ҳм§Ҳ нҸүк°Җ","authors":"Aleksandr Gushchin, Dmitriy Vatolin, Anastasia Antsiferova","pos":"#4516","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2xvgJvxPvp","abs":"Full-Reference image quality assessment (FR IQA) is important for image compression, restoration and generative modeling, yet current neural metrics remain slow and vulnerable to adversarial perturbations. We present BiRQA, a compact FR IQA metric model that processes four fast complementary features within a bidirectional multiscale pyramid. A bottom-up attention module injects fine-scale cues into coarse levels through an uncertainty-aware gate, while a top-down cross-gating block routes semantic context back to high resolution. To enhance robustness, we introduce Anchored Adversarial Training, a theoretically grounded strategy that uses clean \"anchor\" samples and a ranking loss to bound pointwise prediction error under attacks. On five public FR IQA benchmarks BiRQA outperforms or matches the previous state of the art (SOTA) while running $\\sim 3 \\times$ faster than previous SOTA models. Under unseen white-box attacks it lifts SROCC from 0.30-0.57 to 0.60-0.84 on KADID-10k, demonstrating substantial robustness gains. To our knowledge, BiRQA is the only FR IQA model combining competitive accuracy with real-time throughput and strong adversarial resilience.","absKo":"<p>Full-Reference image quality assessment (FR IQA)мқҖ image compression, restoration, generative modelingм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ neural metricмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ лҠҗлҰ¬кі  adversarial perturbationм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” bidirectional multiscale pyramid лӮҙм—җм„ң л„Ө к°Җм§Җ л№ лҘё complementary featureлҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” compact FR IQA metric modelмқё BiRQAлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. bottom-up attention moduleмқҖ uncertainty-aware gateлҘј нҶөн•ҙ fine-scale cueлҘј coarse levelм—җ мЈјмһ…н•ҳкі , top-down cross-gating blockмқҖ semantic contextлҘј лӢӨмӢң high resolutionмңјлЎң лқјмҡ°нҢ…н•ңлӢӨ. robustnessлҘј к°•нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кіөкІ© н•ҳм—җм„ң pointwise prediction errorлҘј boundн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ clean \"anchor\" sampleкіј ranking lossлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң к·јкұ° мһҲлҠ” м „лһөмқё Anchored Adversarial Trainingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ public FR IQA benchmarkм—җм„ң BiRQAлҠ” мқҙм „ state of the art (SOTA)лҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мқҙм—җ н•„м Ғн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, мқҙм „ SOTA modelліҙлӢӨ м•Ҫ $\\sim 3 \\times$ лҚ” л№ лҘҙкІҢ лҸҷмһ‘н•ңлӢӨ. ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң white-box attack н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” KADID-10kм—җм„ң SROCCлҘј 0.30-0.57м—җм„ң 0.60-0.84лЎң лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬л Ө, мғҒлӢ№н•ң robustness н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м•„лҠ” н•ң, BiRQAлҠ” кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” accuracyмҷҖ real-time throughput, к°•н•ң adversarial resilienceлҘј кІ°н•©н•ң мң мқјн•ң FR IQA modelмқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63993","en":"Just Noticeable Difference Modeling for Deep Visual Features","ko":"л”Ҙ л№„мЈјм–ј нҠ№м§•мқ„ мң„н•ң just noticeable difference лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ","authors":"Rui Zhao, Wenrui Li, Lin Zhu, Yajing Zheng, Weisi Lin","pos":"#708","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RxjGbyLFT1","abs":"<p>Deep visual features are increasingly used as the interface in vision systems, motivating the need to describe feature characteristics and control feature quality for machine perception. Just-noticeable difference (JND) characterizes the maximum imperceptible distortion for images under human or machine vision. Extending it to deep visual features naturally meets the above demand by providing a task-aligned tolerance boundary in feature space, offering a practical reference for controlling feature quality under constrained resources. We propose FeatJND, a task-aligned JND formulation that predicts the maximum tolerable per-feature perturbation map while preserving downstream task performance. We propose a FeatJND estimator at standardized split points and validate it across image classification, detection, and instance segmentation. Under matched distortion strength, FeatJND-based distortions consistently preserve higher task performance than unstructured Gaussian perturbations, and attribution visualizations suggest FeatJND can suppress non-critical feature regions. As an application, we further apply FeatJND to token-wise dynamic quantization and show that FeatJND-guided step-size allocation yields clear gains over random step-size permutation and global uniform step size under the same noise budget. Our code will be released after publication.</p>","absKo":"<p>Deep visual featureлҠ” vision systemм—җм„ң interfaceлЎң м җм җ лҚ” л§Һмқҙ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳкі  мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙм—җ л”°лқј feature нҠ№м„ұмқ„ м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳкі  machine perceptionмқ„ мң„н•ң feature qualityлҘј м ңм–ҙн•  н•„мҡ”м„ұмқҙ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. Just-noticeable difference (JND)лҠ” мқёк°„ лҳҗлҠ” machine visionм—җм„ң м§Җк°Ғ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң мөңлҢҖ distortionмқ„ нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҘј deep visual featureлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳл©ҙ feature spaceм—җм„ң taskм—җ м •л ¬лҗң tolerance boundaryлҘј м ңкіөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мң„мқҳ мҡ”кө¬лҘј мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ м¶©мЎұн•ҳл©°, м ңн•ңлҗң мһҗмӣҗ н•ҳм—җм„ң feature qualityлҘј м ңм–ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё кё°мӨҖмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” downstream task м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң featureлі„лЎң н—Ҳмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мөңлҢҖ perturbation mapмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” task-aligned JND formulationмқё FeatJNDлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗң split pointм—җм„ң FeatJND estimatorлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳкі , image classification, detection, instance segmentation м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мқҙлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. лҸҷмқјн•ң distortion strengthм—җм„ң FeatJND кё°л°ҳ distortionмқҖ л№„кө¬мЎ°м Ғ Gaussian perturbationліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ task performanceлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©°, attribution visualizationмқҖ FeatJNDк°Җ л№„н•өмӢ¬ feature мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ м–өм ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқ‘мҡ© мӮ¬лЎҖлЎңлҠ” token-wise dynamic quantizationм—җ FeatJNDлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, FeatJNDк°Җ мң лҸ„н•ң step-size н• лӢ№мқҙ лҸҷмқјн•ң noise budgetм—җм„ң random step-size permutation л°Ҹ global uniform step sizeліҙлӢӨ лҡңл ·н•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” publication нӣ„ кіөк°ңн•  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62440","en":"FreeText: Training-Free Text Rendering via Attention Localization and Spectral Glyph Injection","ko":"FreeText: Attention Localization л°Ҹ Spectral Glyph Injection кё°л°ҳ Training-Free Text Rendering","authors":"RuiQiang Zhang, Hengyi Wang, Chang Liu, Guanjie Wang, Zehua Ma, Weiming Zhang","pos":"#713","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gapnJajEfE","abs":"<p>Large-scale text-to-image (T2I) diffusion models excel at open-domain synthesis but still struggle with precise text rendering, especially for multi-line layouts, dense typography, and long-tailed scripts such as Chinese. Prior solutions typically necessitate costly retraining or impose rigid external layout constraints, often compromising aesthetic quality and flexibility. We propose <strong>FreeText</strong>, a training-free, plug-and-play framework that improves text rendering by leveraging intrinsic mechanisms of <em>Diffusion Transformer (DiT)</em> models. <strong>FreeText</strong> decomposes the problem into <em>where to write</em> and <em>what to write</em>. For the former, we localize writing regions by extracting token-wise spatial attribution from image-to-text attention, using sink-like tokens as stable spatial anchors and topology-aware refinement to produce high-confidence masks. For the latter, we introduce Spectral-Modulated Glyph Injection (SGMI), which injects a noise-aligned glyph prior with frequency-domain band-pass modulation to strengthen glyph structure and mitigate semantic leakage (rendering the concept instead of the word). Extensive experiments on Qwen-Image, FLUX.1-dev, and SD3 variants across longText-Benchmark, CVTG, and our CLT-Bench show consistent gains in text readability while maintaining semantic alignment and aesthetic quality, with modest inference overhead.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ text-to-image (T2I) diffusion modelмқҖ open-domain н•©м„ұм—җм„ңлҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮҳм§Җл§Ң, нҠ№нһҲ multi-line layout, dense typography, ChineseмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ long-tailed scriptм—җм„ң м •нҷ•н•ң н…ҚмҠӨнҠё л ҢлҚ”л§ҒмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ н•ҙлІ•мқҖ лҢҖк°ң л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° мһ¬н•ҷмҠөмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ м—„кІ©н•ң мҷёл¶Җ layout м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л¶Җкіјн•ҳм—¬, лҜём Ғ н’Ҳм§Ҳкіј мң м—°м„ұмқ„ нқ¬мғқн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>FreeText</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” <em>Diffusion Transformer (DiT)</em> лӘЁлҚёмқҳ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё л ҢлҚ”л§Ғмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” training-free plug-and-play frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. <strong>FreeText</strong>лҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј <em>м–ҙл””м—җ м“ё кІғмқёк°Җ</em>мҷҖ <em>л¬ҙм—Үмқ„ м“ё кІғмқёк°Җ</em>лЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. м „мһҗмқҳ кІҪмҡ°, image-to-text attentionм—җм„ң token-wise spatial attributionмқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкі  sink-like tokenмқ„ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё spatial anchorлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©°, topology-aware refinementлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҙ лҶ’мқҖ мӢ лў°лҸ„мқҳ maskлҘј мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ writing regionмқ„ көӯмҶҢнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. нӣ„мһҗмқҳ кІҪмҡ°, Spectral-Modulated Glyph Injection (SGMI)мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, frequency-domain band-pass modulationмқҙ м Ғмҡ©лҗң noise-aligned glyph priorлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ glyph кө¬мЎ°лҘј к°•нҷ”н•ҳкі  semantic leakage(лӢЁм–ҙ лҢҖмӢ  к°ңл…җмқ„ л ҢлҚ”л§Ғн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒ)лҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. longText-Benchmark, CVTG, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ CLT-Bench м „л°ҳм—җм„ң Qwen-Image, FLUX.1-dev, SD3 ліҖнҳ•л“Өм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ, modestн•ң inference overheadлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң text readabilityмҷҖ semantic alignment, aesthetic quality лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61692","en":"Rethinking Genomic Modeling Through Optical Character Recognition","ko":"Optical Character Recognitionмқ„ нҶөн•ң Genomic Modeling мһ¬кі ","authors":"Hongxin Xiang, Pengsen Ma, Yunkang Cao, Di Yu, Haowen Chen, Xinyu Yang, xiangxiang Zeng","pos":"#511","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nggzekChuU","abs":"Recent genomic foundation models largely adopt large language model architectures that treat DNA as a one-dimensional token sequence. However, exhaustive sequential reading is structurally misaligned with sparse and discontinuous genomic semantics, leading to wasted computation on low-information background and preventing understanding-driven compression for long contexts. Here, we present \\textsc{OpticalDNA}, a vision-based framework that reframes genomic modeling as OCR-style document understanding. \\textsc{OpticalDNA} renders DNA into structured visual layouts and trains an OCR-capable vision--language model with a \\emph{visual DNA encoder} and a \\emph{document decoder}, where the encoder produces compact, reconstructible visual tokens for high-fidelity compression. Building on this representation, \\textsc{OpticalDNA} defines prompt-conditioned objectives over core genomic primitivesвҖ”reading, region grounding, subsequence retrieval, and masked span completionвҖ”thereby learning layout-aware DNA representations that retain fine-grained genomic information under a reduced effective token budget. Across diverse genomic benchmarks, \\textsc{OpticalDNA} consistently outperforms recent baselines; on sequences up to 450k bases, it achieves the best overall performance with nearly $20\\times$ fewer effective tokens, and surpasses models with up to $985\\times$ more activated parameters while tuning only 256k \\emph{trainable} parameters.","absKo":"Recent genomic foundation modelмқҖ DNAлҘј one-dimensional token sequenceлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” large language model architectureлҘј мЈјлЎң мұ„нғқн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ exhaustive sequential readingмқҖ sparseн•ҳкі  discontinuousн•ң genomic semanticsмҷҖ кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң л§һм§Җ м•Ҡм•„, м •ліҙлҹүмқҙ лӮ®мқҖ backgroundм—җ кі„мӮ°мқ„ лӮӯл№„н•ҳкі  кёҙ contextм—җ лҢҖн•ң understanding-driven compressionмқ„ л°©н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” genomic modelingмқ„ OCR-style document understandingмңјлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” vision-based frameworkмқё \\textsc{OpticalDNA}лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. \\textsc{OpticalDNA}лҠ” DNAлҘј structured visual layoutмңјлЎң л ҢлҚ”л§Ғн•ҳкі , \\emph{visual DNA encoder}мҷҖ \\emph{document decoder}лҘј к°–лҠ” OCR-capable vision--language modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨл©°, encoderлҠ” кі м •л°Җ м••м¶•мқ„ мң„н•ҙ compactн•ҳкі  мһ¬кө¬м„ұ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң visual tokenмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н‘ңнҳ„ мң„м—җм„ң \\textsc{OpticalDNA}лҠ” reading, region grounding, subsequence retrieval, masked span completionмқҙлқјлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ genomic primitiveм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ prompt-conditioned objectiveлҘј м •мқҳн•ҳм—¬, нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё token budgetмқ„ мӨ„мқё мғҒнғңм—җм„ңлҸ„ м„ёл°Җн•ң genomic м •ліҙлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” layout-aware DNA representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң genomic benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң \\textsc{OpticalDNA}лҠ” мөңк·ј baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мөңлҢҖ 450k base кёёмқҙмқҳ sequenceм—җм„ңлҠ” кұ°мқҳ $20\\times$ лҚ” м ҒмқҖ effective tokenмңјлЎң м „мІҙ мөңкі  м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мҳӨм§Ғ 256k к°ңмқҳ \\emph{trainable} parameterл§Ң мЎ°м •н•ҳл©ҙм„ң мөңлҢҖ $985\\times$ лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ activated parameterлҘј к°Җм§„ modelмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63144","en":"Transitive Representation Learning Enhances Histopathology Annotation","ko":"м „мқҙм Ғ н‘ңнҳ„ н•ҷмҠөмқҙ мЎ°м§Ғлі‘лҰ¬ мЈјм„қмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ","authors":"Moritz Schaefer, Zoe Piran, Nils Philipp Walter, Animesh Awasthi, Christoph Bock, Jure Leskovec, Zinaida Good","pos":"#510","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ze7U293Zw4","abs":"<p>AI-driven disease characterization in histopathology promises to assist in clinical decision making, but its performance is limited by the scarcity of detailed annotations. In contrast, single-cell gene expression provides expressive and interpretable labels that compensate this scarcity, but assays are costly and rarely acquired in clinical workflows. To overcome this gap, we propose to bridge these data sources using a trimodal contrastive learning framework that aligns histopathology images, gene expression profiles, and natural-language descriptions. Our training data combines atlas-scale datasets of (i) spatially-resolved gene expression paired with histopathology images, and (ii) single-cell gene expression with curated annotations. Together, these data induce an alignment between image and text modalities, which we leverage for zero-shot image annotation tasks, such as the identification of immune cells. We present a sufficient condition under which this transfer can succeed and assess the performance of our approach against established baselines. We predict cell types at 15.4\\% improved relative AUROC over leading pathology vision language models. Our method also exhibits significant gains across diverse prediction tasks in low-data regimes, when combining training data from all three modality pairs. Our work thus establishes <em>transitive representation learning</em> as an effective strategy to enhance histopathology interpretation.</p>","absKo":"<p>лі‘лҰ¬ мЎ°м§Ғн•ҷм—җм„ң AI-driven disease characterizationмқҖ мһ„мғҒ мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м •мқ„ лҸ•лҠ” лҚ° мң л§қн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, м„ёл°Җн•ң annotationмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұмңјлЎң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ single-cell gene expressionмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¶ҖмЎұмқ„ ліҙмҷ„н•ҳлҠ” н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мһҲкі  н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң labelмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, assay л№„мҡ©мқҙ лҶ’кі  мһ„мғҒ workflowм—җм„ңлҠ” кұ°мқҳ нҡҚл“қлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” histopathology image, gene expression profile, natural-language descriptionмқ„ м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” trimodal contrastive learning frameworkлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң data sourceлҘј м—°кІ°н•  кІғмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ training dataлҠ” (i) histopathology imageмҷҖ м§қм§Җм–ҙм§„ spatially-resolved gene expression, (ii) м •м ңлҗң annotationмқҙ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗң single-cell gene expressionмңјлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң atlas-scale datasetмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°л“ӨмқҖ imageмҷҖ text modality мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ alignmentлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј immune cell identificationкіј к°ҷмқҖ zero-shot image annotation taskм—җ нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң transferк°Җ м„ұкіөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м¶©л¶„ мЎ°кұҙмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , нҷ•лҰҪлҗң baselineкіј л№„көҗн•ҳм—¬ м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” leading pathology vision language model лҢҖл№„ 15.4\\% н–ҘмғҒлҗң relative AUROCлЎң cell typeмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң м„ё к°Җм§Җ modality pairмқҳ лӘЁл“  training dataлҘј кІ°н•©н•  л•Ң, low-data regimeм—җм„ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң prediction task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мң мқҳлҜён•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” histopathology interpretationмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё м „лһөмңјлЎң <em>transitive representation learning</em>мқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63433","en":"MedREK: Retrieval-Based Editing for Medical LLMs with Key-Aware Prompts","ko":"MedREK: нӮӨ мқём§Җ н”„лЎ¬н”„нҠёлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң мқҳлЈҢ LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң кІҖмғү кё°л°ҳ нҺём§‘","authors":"Shujun Xia, Haokun Lin, Yichen WU, Yinan Zhou, Zixuan Li, Zhongwei Wan, Xingrun Xing, Yefeng Zheng, Xiang Li, Caifeng Shan, Zhenan Sun, Quanzheng Li","pos":"#512","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XFHjS8kw6X","abs":"<p>LLMs hold great promise for healthcare applications, but fast-changing medical knowledge can quickly make their outputs outdated or inaccurate, limiting use in high-stakes settings. Model editing can update LLMs without full retraining, but parameter-based methods often break locality and are risky in medicine, making retrieval-based editing a better fit. However, applying model editing methods to the medical domain has two key challenges: (1) retrieval-based methods suffer from representation overlap within the medical knowledge space that causes inaccurate retrieval and reduces editing accuracy; (2) existing medical editing methods are restricted to single-sample edits, while batch-editing remains largely unexplored despite its importance for real-world applications. To address these challenges, we construct MedVersa, an expanded benchmark that evaluates single and batch edits across broader medical coverage under strict locality constraints. We then propose MedREK, a retrieval-based editing framework that integrates a shared queryвҖ“key module for precise matching with an attention-based prompt encoder for informative guidance. Experiments across various medical benchmarks show that our MedREK consistently improves key metrics and provides the first validated solution for batch editing in medical LLMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>LLMмқҖ healthcare applicationм—җм„ң нҒ° к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, л№ лҘҙкІҢ ліҖн•ҳлҠ” medical knowledgeлҠ” к·ё м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ кёҲм„ё outdated лҳҗлҠ” inaccurateн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ high-stakes settingм—җм„ңмқҳ нҷңмҡ©мқ„ м ңн•ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. Model editingмқҖ м „мІҙ retraining м—Ҷмқҙ LLMмқ„ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, parameter-based methodлҠ” localityлҘј к№ЁлңЁлҰ¬кё° мүҪкі  мқҳлЈҢ л¶„м•јм—җм„ңлҠ” мң„н—ҳн•ҳлҜҖлЎң retrieval-based editingмқҙ лҚ” м Ғн•©н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ medical domainм—җ model editing methodлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ°лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңк°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. (1) retrieval-based methodлҠ” medical knowledge space лӮҙ representation overlapмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ л¶Җм •нҷ•н•ң retrievalмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳкі  editing accuracyк°Җ м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. (2) кё°мЎҙ medical editing methodлҠ” single-sample editм—җл§Ң м ңн•ңлҗҳл©°, мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•Ём—җлҸ„ batch-editingмқҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—„кІ©н•ң locality constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң лҚ” л„“мқҖ medical coverageм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ single editкіј batch editмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ benchmarkмқё MedVersaлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ, м •нҷ•н•ң matchingмқ„ мң„н•ң shared queryвҖ“key moduleкіј м •ліҙм„ұ мһҲлҠ” guidanceлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” attention-based prompt encoderлҘј нҶөн•©н•ң retrieval-based editing frameworkмқё MedREKлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң medical benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ MedREKк°Җ н•өмӢ¬ metricмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к°ңм„ н•ҳл©°, medical LLMм—җм„ң batch editingмқ„ мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ кІҖмҰқлҗң solutionмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66590","en":"$\\tau$-Voice: Benchmarking Full-Duplex Voice Agents on Real-World Domains","ko":"$\\tau$-Voice: мӢӨм„ёкі„ лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ң Full-Duplex мқҢм„ұ м—җмқҙм „нҠё лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№","authors":"Soham Ray, Keshav Dhandhania, Victor Barres, Karthik Narasimhan","pos":"#4315","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2Oj6fg0m1j","abs":"Full-duplex voice agentsвҖ”systems that listen and speak simultaneouslyвҖ”are rapidly moving from research to production. However, existing evaluations address conversational dynamics and task completion in isolation. We introduce $\\tau$-voice, a benchmark for evaluating voice agents on grounded tasks with real-world complexity: agents must navigate complex multi-turn conversations, adhere to domain policies, and interact with the environment. The framework extends $\\tau^2$-bench into a novel voice agent benchmark combining verifiable completion of complex grounded tasks, full-duplex interaction, and realistic audioвҖ”enabling direct comparison between voice and text performance. A controllable and realistic voice user simulator provides diverse accents, realistic audio environments, and rich turn-taking dynamics; by decoupling simulation from wall-clock time, the user simulator can use the most capable LLM without real-time constraints. We evaluate task completion (pass@1) and voice interaction quality across 278 tasks: while GPT-5 (reasoning) achieves 80\\%, voice agents reach only 29--42\\% under clean conditions and 19--30\\% under realistic conditions with noise and diverse accentsвҖ”a 50--61pp gap; qualitative analysis confirms 75--90\\% of failures stem from agent behavior, suggesting that observed failures primarily reflect agent behavior under our evaluation setup. $\\tau$-voice provides a reproducible testbed for measuring progress toward voice agents that are natural, conversational, and reliable.","absKo":"н’Җл“Җн”Ңл үмҠӨ voice agent, мҰү лҸҷмӢңм—җ л“Јкі  л§җн•ҳлҠ” мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҖ м—°кө¬ лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң мӢӨм ң л°°нҸ¬лЎң л№ лҘҙкІҢ мқҙлҸҷн•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” лҢҖнҷ” лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷкіј мһ‘м—… мҷ„лЈҢлҘј м„ңлЎң л¶„лҰ¬лҗң л°©мӢқмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” $\\tau$-voiceлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„мқҳ ліөмһЎм„ұмқ„ м§ҖлӢҢ grounded taskм—җм„ң voice agentлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң benchmarkлЎң, agentлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң multi-turn лҢҖнҷ”лҘј нғҗмғүн•ҳкі , лҸ„л©”мқё м •мұ…мқ„ мӨҖмҲҳн•ҳл©°, нҷҳкІҪкіј мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” $\\tau^2$-benchлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм—¬, ліөмһЎн•ң grounded taskмқҳ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мҷ„лЈҢ, full-duplex мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©, к·ёлҰ¬кі  нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё audioлҘј кІ°н•©н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ voice agent benchmarkлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ voice м„ұлҠҘкіј text м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ л№„көҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м ңм–ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё voice user simulatorлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң м–өм–‘, нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё audio нҷҳкІҪ, н’Қл¶Җн•ң turn-taking лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳмқ„ wall-clock timeкіј л¶„лҰ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, user simulatorлҠ” мӢӨмӢңк°„ м ңм•Ҫ м—Ҷмқҙ к°ҖмһҘ к°•л Ҙн•ң LLMмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 278к°ң taskм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ task completion(pass@1)кіј voice мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. GPT-5(reasoning)лҠ” 80\\%лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, voice agentлҠ” к№ЁлҒ—н•ң мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ң 29--42\\%, мһЎмқҢкіј лӢӨм–‘н•ң м–өм–‘мқҙ мһҲлҠ” нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ңлҠ” 19--30\\%м—җ к·ёміҗ 50--61ppмқҳ кІ©м°Ёк°Җ лӮҳнғҖлӮңлӢӨ. м •м„ұ л¶„м„қмқҖ мӢӨнҢЁмқҳ 75--90\\%к°Җ agent behaviorм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗЁмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” кҙҖм°°лҗң мӢӨнҢЁк°Җ мЈјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ нҸүк°Җ м„Өм • н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ agent behaviorлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. $\\tau$-voiceлҠ” мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкі  лҢҖнҷ”м Ғмқҙл©° мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” voice agentлҘј н–Ҙн•ң м§„м „мқ„ мёЎм •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мһ¬нҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң testbedлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"60691","en":"Learning Useful Supervision for Reinforcement Learning in Reasoning Models","ko":"Reasoning Modelм—җм„ң Reinforcement Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң мң мҡ©н•ң Supervision н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Liang CHEN, Xueting Han, Li Shen, Jing Bai, Kam-Fai Wong","pos":"#4312","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xWvj03N4sJ","abs":"<p>Supervised fine-tuning (SFT) and reinforcement learning with verifiable rewards (RLVR) are two widely used post-training paradigms for improving the reasoning ability of large language models (LLMs). Recent methods attempt to integrate SFT and RLVR in a single stage by reweighting or scheduling their objectives. However, such coupling can be counterproductive because supervised updates are not uniformly beneficial for reward optimization, which can diminish reward gains. To address this, we propose \\textsc{BRIDGE}, a scalable framework in which SFT learns to supervise RL by selectively transferring knowledge that improves reward optimization. Specifically, \\textsc{BRIDGE} employs two nested optimization loops during meta-training: the inner loop updates base model parameters using a fused SFT--RL gradient. Concurrently, the outer loop updates a lightweight low-rank adapter (LoRA) to coordinate the two objectives by maximizing a reward-gap signal, defined as the reward of joint SFT--RL training over an RL-only baseline. Across three model scales and five reasoning benchmarks, \\textsc{BRIDGE} consistently outperforms two-stage cold start, naive mixing, and representative single-stage integration baselines, yielding over three points average absolute improvement and more stable training dynamics.</p>","absKo":"<p>Supervised fine-tuning (SFT)кіј reinforcement learning with verifiable rewards (RLVR)лҠ” large language model (LLM)мқҳ reasoning abilityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ҙ л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ post-training paradigmмқҙлӢӨ. мөңк·ј л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳлҘј мһ¬к°ҖмӨ‘н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мҠӨмјҖмӨ„л§Ғн•ҳм—¬ SFTмҷҖ RLVRмқ„ лӢЁмқј лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң нҶөн•©н•ҳл Өкі  мӢңлҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°н•©мқҖ supervised updateк°Җ reward optimizationм—җ мқјлҘ м ҒмңјлЎң мң мқөн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ мҳӨнһҲл Ө м—ӯнҡЁкіјлҘј лӮј мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, reward gainмқ„ к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SFTк°Җ reward optimizationмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” м§ҖмӢқл§Ңмқ„ м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң м „лӢ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ RLмқ„ м§ҖлҸ„н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң frameworkмқё \\textsc{BRIDGE}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, \\textsc{BRIDGE}лҠ” meta-training лҸҷм•Ҳ л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мӨ‘мІ©лҗң optimization loopлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ: inner loopлҠ” fused SFT--RL gradientлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ base model parameterлҘј м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•ңлӢӨ. лҸҷмӢңм—җ outer loopлҠ” reward-gap signal, мҰү RL-only baseline лҢҖл№„ joint SFT--RL trainingмқҳ rewardлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ л‘җ objectiveлҘј мЎ°м •н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ lightweight low-rank adapter (LoRA)лҘј м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•ңлӢӨ. м„ё к°Җм§Җ model scaleкіј лӢӨм„Ҝ к°ң reasoning benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң \\textsc{BRIDGE}лҠ” two-stage cold start, naive mixing, лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё single-stage integration baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, нҸүк·  м ҲлҢҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ 3м җ мқҙмғҒ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  лҚ” м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё training dynamicмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67130","en":"Position: Modular Safety Guardrails Are Necessary for Foundation-Model-Enabled Robots in the Real World","ko":"Position: мӢӨм„ёкі„мқҳ Foundation-Model кё°л°ҳ лЎңлҙҮм—җлҠ” лӘЁл“Ҳнҳ• м•Ҳм „ к°Җл“ңл Ҳмқјмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Joonkyung Kim, Wenxi Chen, Davood Soleymanzadeh, Yi Ding, Xiangbo Gao, Zhengzhong Tu, Ruqi Zhang, Fan Fei, Sushant Veer, Yiwei Lyu, Minghui Zheng, Yan Gu","pos":"#505","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=a4imO33mN1","abs":"<p>The integration of foundation models (FMs) into robotics has accelerated real-world deployment, while introducing new safety challenges arising from open-ended semantic reasoning and embodied physical action. These challenges require safety notions beyond physical constraint satisfaction. In this position paper, we characterize FM-enabled robot safety along three dimensions: action safety (physical feasibility and constraint compliance), decision safety (semantic and contextual appropriateness), and human-centered safety (conformance to human intent, norms, and expectations). We argue that existing approaches, including static verification, monolithic controllers, and end-to-end learned policies, are insufficient in settings where tasks, environments, and human expectations are open-ended, long-tailed, and subject to adaptation over time. To address this gap, we propose modular safety guardrails, consisting of monitoring (evaluation) and intervention layers, as an architectural foundation for comprehensive safety across the autonomy stack. Beyond modularity, we highlight possible cross-layer co-design opportunities through representation alignment and conservatism allocation to enable faster, less conservative, and more effective safety enforcement. We call on the community to explore richer guardrail modules and principled co-design strategies to advance safe real-world physical AI deployment.</p>","absKo":"<p>foundation model (FM)мқ„ roboticsм—җ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” нқҗлҰ„мқҖ мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„ л°°м№ҳлҘј к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” н•ңнҺё, к°ңл°©нҳ• semantic reasoningкіј embodied physical actionм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м•Ҳм „м„ұ л¬ём ңлҘј лӮікі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҠ” physical constraint satisfactionмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” safety notionмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ position paperм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FM-enabled robot safetyлҘј м„ё к°Җм§Җ м°ЁмӣҗмңјлЎң нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ”лӢӨ. action safety (physical feasibilityмҷҖ constraint compliance), decision safety (semantic л°Ҹ contextual appropriateness), human-centered safety (human intent, norm, expectationкіјмқҳ л¶Җн•©м„ұ)мқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” static verification, monolithic controller, end-to-end learned policyлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ task, environment, human expectationмқҙ open-endedн•ҳкі  long-tailedмқҙл©° мӢңк°„м—җ л”°лқј м Ғмқ‘мқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ңлҠ” л¶Ҳм¶©л¶„н•ҳлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” monitoring (evaluation) layerмҷҖ intervention layerлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң modular safety guardrailмқ„ autonomy stack м „л°ҳмқҳ нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғ м•Ҳм „м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң architectural foundationмңјлЎң м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. modularityлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ, representation alignmentмҷҖ conservatism allocationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лҚ” л№ лҘҙкі , лҚң ліҙмҲҳм Ғмқҙл©°, лҚ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё safety enforcementлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” cross-layer co-design кё°нҡҢлҸ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°к°Җ лҚ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң guardrail moduleкіј мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё co-design strategyлҘј нғҗкө¬н•ҳм—¬ м•Ҳм „н•ң мӢӨм ң л¬јлҰ¬ AI л°°м№ҳлҘј л°ңм „мӢңнӮӨкё°лҘј мҡ”мІӯн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62036","en":"Beyond Majority Voting: Self-Reflective Test-Time Reinforcement Learning for LLM Reasoning","ko":"лӢӨмҲҳкІ°мқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ: LLM м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң мһҗкё°л°ҳмҳҒ Test-Time Reinforcement Learning","authors":"Sitong Wu, Haoru Tan, Xichen Zhang, Bin Xia, Shaofeng Zhang, XIAOJUAN QI, Bei Yu, Jiaya Jia","pos":"#4603","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=kSuRY5sCuR","abs":"The core challenge of Test-Time Reinforcement Learning (TTRL) lies in estimating rewards without access to ground-truth supervision. Existing TTRL methods predominantly rely on majority voting to generate pseudo-labels, under the assumption that the most frequent answer among sampled trajectories is correct. However, we observe that this assumption frequently breaks down in complex reasoning tasks, where correct solutions often constitute a logical minority. As a result, rare yet correct trajectories are systematically undervalued by majority-voting-based approaches.  To address this limitation, we propose Self-Reflective Test-Time Reinforcement Learning (SR-TTRL), a novel framework that leverages self-reflective verification to produce high-fidelity pseudo-labels. Specifically, given multiple sampled trajectories for a problem, SR-TTRL first groups trajectories according to their final answers and selects one representative from each group to form a candidate pool. Each candidate trajectory is then summarized to preserve its core reasoning steps while reducing verbosity. Finally, the model performs self-reflection over the candidate pool, critically evaluating and selecting the most plausible trajectory as the pseudo-label.  Empirically, SR-TTRL achieves substantially higher pseudo-label fidelity and sample efficiency than prior majority-voting-based TTRL methods. Extensive experiments across diverse benchmarks and model families demonstrate that SR-TTRL consistently outperforms majority-voting baselines and significantly improves generalization to novel problems. For example, SR-TTRL improves the Pass@1 accuracy of Qwen3-8B on AIME24 from $29.1$ to $55.8$ (a gain of $+26.7$), exceeding standard TTRL by an additional $+9.1$.","absKo":"Test-Time Reinforcement Learning (TTRL)мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлҠ” ground-truth supervision м—Ҷмқҙ rewardлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ TTRL л°©лІ•мқҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ majority votingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ pseudo-labelмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, мғҳн”Ңл§Ғлҗң trajectoryл“Ө мӨ‘ к°ҖмһҘ л№ҲлІҲн•ң лӢөмқҙ м •лӢөмқҙлқјлҠ” к°Җм •мқ„ л‘”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң reasoning taskм—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙ к°Җм •мқҙ мһҗмЈј л¬ҙл„Ҳм§„лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң м •лӢө н•ҙк°Җ л…јлҰ¬м Ғ minorityлҘј мқҙлЈЁлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј, majority-voting-based approachлҠ” л“ңл¬јм§Җл§Ң м •лӢөмқё trajectoryлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң м ҖнҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” self-reflective verificationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ high-fidelity pseudo-labelмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkмқё Self-Reflective Test-Time Reinforcement Learning (SR-TTRL)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м—¬лҹ¬ sampled trajectoryк°Җ мЈјм–ҙм§Җл©ҙ SR-TTRLмқҖ лЁјм Җ мөңмў… лӢөліҖм—җ л”°лқј trajectoryлҘј к·ёлЈ№нҷ”н•ҳкі , к°Ғ к·ёлЈ№м—җм„ң н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ лҢҖн‘ңлҘј м„ нғқн•ҙ candidate poolмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ к°Ғ candidate trajectoryлҘј мҡ”м•Ҫн•ҳм—¬ мһҘнҷ©н•ЁмқҖ мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ң н•өмӢ¬ reasoning stepмқҖ ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң modelмқҙ candidate poolм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ self-reflectionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬, л№„нҢҗм ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ң л’Ө к°ҖмһҘ plausibleн•ң trajectoryлҘј pseudo-labelлЎң м„ нғқн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң SR-TTRLмқҖ кё°мЎҙ majority-voting-based TTRL л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ pseudo-label fidelityмҷҖ sample efficiencyк°Җ нҒ¬кІҢ лҶ’лӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkмҷҖ model familyм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SR-TTRLмқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ majority-voting baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкі , мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л¬ём ңлЎңмқҳ generalizationмқ„ мң мқҳлҜён•ҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ SR-TTRLмқҖ AIME24м—җм„ң Qwen3-8Bмқҳ Pass@1 м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј $29.1$м—җм„ң $55.8$лЎң лҶ’мҳҖмңјл©°($+26.7$), мқҙлҠ” standard TTRLліҙлӢӨ м¶”к°ҖлЎң $+9.1$ н–ҘмғҒлҗң мҲҳм№ҳлӢӨ."},{"id":"68802","en":"mSOP-765k: A Benchmark For Multi-Modal Structured Output Predictions","ko":"mSOP-765k: л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ кө¬мЎ°нҷ” м¶ңл Ҙ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мң„н•ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Bianca Lamm, Janis Keuper","pos":"#1114","abs":"<p>This paper introduces mSOP-765k, a large-scale benchmark for the evaluation of multi-modal Structured Output Prediction (mSOP) pipelines. Besides novel evaluation metrics, the benchmark provides combined training and test datasets with over 765,000 images taken from real-world product advertisements. Each of these images contains product visualizations, textual information like product name or brand, and numerical data such as product weight, price, and discount. All images are annotated with the corresponding structured information in form of dictionaries containing key-value pairs.\nAn initial baseline evaluation, including various LLMs and VLMs, as well as multi-modal RAG approaches, shows that the proposed benchmark provides a challenging problem which can not yet be solved completely by state-of-the-art mSOP methods. The benchmark and dataset are available under a creative-commons license: https://www.msop-765k.org/</p>","absKo":"<p>мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ multi-modal Structured Output Prediction (mSOP) pipelineмқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ benchmarkмқё mSOP-765kлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мғҲлЎңмҡҙ evaluation metricл“Ө мҷём—җлҸ„, мқҙ benchmarkлҠ” мӢӨм ң м ңн’Ҳ кҙ‘кі м—җм„ң мҲҳм§‘н•ң 765,000мһҘ мқҙмғҒмқҳ мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” н•ҷмҠө л°Ҹ н…ҢмҠӨнҠё лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқ„ н•Ёк»ҳ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к°Ғ мқҙлҜём§ҖлҠ” м ңн’Ҳ мӢңк°Ғнҷ”, м ңн’ҲлӘ…мқҙлӮҳ лёҢлһңл“ң к°ҷмқҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё м •ліҙ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  м ңн’Ҳ л¬ҙкІҢ, к°ҖкІ©, н• мқёкіј к°ҷмқҖ мҲҳм№ҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁл“  мқҙлҜём§ҖлҠ” key-value pairлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” dictionary нҳ•нғңмқҳ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” structured informationмңјлЎң мЈјм„қмқҙ лӢ¬л Ө мһҲлӢӨ.\nLLMкіј VLM, к·ёлҰ¬кі  multi-modal RAG м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң мҙҲкё° baseline нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіјлҠ”, м ңм•Ҳн•ң benchmarkк°Җ нҳ„мһ¬ state-of-the-art mSOP methodлЎңлҸ„ м•„м§Ғ мҷ„м „нһҲ н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” лҸ„м „м Ғмқё л¬ём ңлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. benchmarkмҷҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмқҖ creative-commons лқјмқҙм„ мҠӨ н•ҳм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ: https://www.msop-765k.org/</p>"},{"id":"66028","en":"VisualScore: Learning Holistic Visual Quality Scores via Multi-Task Reasoning","ko":"VisualScore: лӢӨмӨ‘ мһ‘м—… м¶”лЎ мқ„ нҶөн•ң м „мІҙм Ғ мӢңк°Ғ н’Ҳм§Ҳ м җмҲҳ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Yiting Lu, Fengbin Guan, Yixin Gao, Yan Zhong, Xinge Peng, Jiakang Yuan, Yihao Liu, Bo Zhang, Xin Li, Zhibo Chen, Weisi Lin","pos":"#1204","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=7kyHU9Yj05","abs":"<p>Image quality assessment (IQA) is inherently multi-mage quality assessment (IQA) is inherently multi-dimensional, yet existing reward models are typically limited to a single task and become unstable when extended to multi-task settings. In particular, heterogeneous reward scales and variances across tasks can lead to conflicting optimization signals during reinforcement learning. We propose VisualScore, a unified visual evaluation framework that formulates multi-task IQA as structured, task-aware reasoning followed by continuous reward optimization. VisualScore produces interpretable rationales together with scalar quality scores under explicit evaluation principles. We construct a reasoning-enhanced reward modeling dataset via rejection sampling and initialize the model through supervised fine-tuning. VisualScore is then optimized with Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) using a Gaussian-based continuous reward. To address multi-task reward conflicts and stabilize training, we introduce standard deviation filtering and entropy gating to normalize task-wise reward signals and suppress noisy updates. Experiments on technical quality, aesthetic quality, and textвҖ“image alignment show that VisualScore improves robustness, generalization, and interpretability, and can effectively guide text-to-image generation at test time without retraining.</p>","absKo":"<p>Image quality assessment (IQA)лҠ” ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң multi-dimensionalн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ reward modelмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң лӢЁмқј taskм—җ н•ңм •лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмңјл©° multi-task settingмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳл©ҙ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҙм§„лӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ task к°„ heterogeneous reward scaleкіј varianceлҠ” reinforcement learning лҸҷм•Ҳ мғҒм¶©н•ҳлҠ” optimization signalмқ„ мң л°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” multi-task IQAлҘј кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң task-aware reasoning л’Өм—җ м—°мҶҚнҳ• reward мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© visual evaluation frameworkмқё VisualScoreлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. VisualScoreлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё evaluation principle н•ҳм—җ н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң rationaleкіј scalar quality scoreлҘј н•Ёк»ҳ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” rejection samplingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ reasoning-enhanced reward modeling datasetмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , supervised fine-tuningмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мҙҲкё°нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ VisualScoreлҠ” Gaussian кё°л°ҳ continuous rewardлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO)мңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. multi-task reward conflictлҘј лӢӨлЈЁкі  н•ҷмҠөмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” taskлі„ reward signalмқ„ м •к·ңнҷ”н•ҳкі  noisy updateлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳлҠ” standard deviation filteringкіј entropy gatingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. technical quality, aesthetic quality, textвҖ“image alignmentм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ VisualScoreк°Җ robustness, generalization, interpretabilityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, мһ¬н•ҷмҠө м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ test timeм—җ text-to-image generationмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м•ҲлӮҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61333","en":"IsoCompute Playbook: Optimally Scaling Sampling Compute for LLM RL","ko":"IsoCompute Playbook: LLM RLмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҳн”Ңл§Ғ Compute мөңм Ғ мҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғ","authors":"Zhoujun Cheng, Yutao Xie, Yuxiao Qu, Amrith Setlur, Shibo Hao, Varad Pimpalkhute, Tongtong Liang, Feng Yao, Zhengzhong Liu, Eric Xing, Virginia Smith, Russ Salakhutdinov, Zhiting Hu, Taylor W. Killian, Aviral Kumar","pos":"#1813","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=rEz2wdNZBJ","abs":"<p>While scaling laws guide compute allocation for LLM pre-training, analogous prescriptions for reinforcement learning (RL) post-training of LLMs remain poorly understood. We study the compute-optimal allocation of sampling compute for on-policy RL methods in LLMs, framing scaling as a compute-constrained optimization over three resources: parallel rollouts per problem, number of problems per batch, and number of update steps. We find that the compute-optimal number of parallel rollouts per problem increases predictably with compute budget and then saturates. This trend holds across both easy and hard problems, though driven by different mechanisms: solution sharpening on easy problems and coverage expansion on hard problems. We further show that increasing the number of parallel rollouts mitigates interference across problems, while the number of problems per batch primarily affects training stability and can be chosen within a broad range. Validated across base models and data distributions, our results recast RL scaling laws as prescriptive allocation rules and provide practical guidance for compute-efficient LLM RL post-training.</p>","absKo":"<p>scaling lawлҠ” LLM pre-trainingмқ„ мң„н•ң compute н• лӢ№мқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, LLMмқҳ reinforcement learning (RL) post-trainingм—җ лҢҖн•ң мң мӮ¬н•ң мІҳл°©мқҖ м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLMм—җм„ң on-policy RL л°©лІ•мқ„ мң„н•ң sampling computeмқҳ compute-optimal н• лӢ№мқ„ м—°кө¬н•ҳл©°, scalingмқ„ л¬ём ңлӢ№ parallel rollout мҲҳ, batchлӢ№ л¬ём ң мҲҳ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  update step мҲҳлқјлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ мһҗмӣҗм—җ лҢҖн•ң compute м ңм•Ҫ мөңм Ғнҷ”лЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¬ём ңлӢ№ compute-optimal parallel rollout мҲҳк°Җ compute budgetкіј н•Ёк»ҳ мҳҲмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ мҰқк°Җн•ң л’Ө нҸ¬нҷ”лҗЁмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ кІҪн–ҘмқҖ мү¬мҡҙ л¬ём ңмҷҖ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ л¬ём ң лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң м„ұлҰҪн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё мӣҗмқёмқҖ лӢӨлҘҙлӢӨ. мү¬мҡҙ л¬ём ңм—җм„ңлҠ” solution sharpeningмқҙ, м–ҙл Өмҡҙ л¬ём ңм—җм„ңлҠ” coverage expansionмқҙ мқҙлҘј мқҙлҒҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң parallel rollout мҲҳлҘј лҠҳлҰ¬л©ҙ л¬ём ң к°„ interferenceк°Җ мҷ„нҷ”лҗҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, batchлӢ№ л¬ём ң мҲҳлҠ” мЈјлЎң training stabilityм—җ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мЈјл©° л„“мқҖ лІ”мң„м—җм„ң м„ нғқн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. base modelкіј data distribution м „л°ҳм—җм„ң кІҖмҰқн•ң кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” RL scaling lawлҘј мІҳл°©м Ғ мһҗмӣҗ н• лӢ№ к·ңм№ҷмңјлЎң мһ¬н•ҙм„қн•ҳл©° compute-efficient LLM RL post-trainingмқ„ мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ м§Җм№Ёмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64225","en":"Multimodal Latent Language Modeling with Next-Token Diffusion","ko":"лӢӨмқҢ нҶ нҒ° Diffusionмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ мһ мһ¬ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ","authors":"Yutao Sun, Hangbo Bao, Wenhui Wang, Zhiliang Peng, Li Dong, Shaohan Huang, Yaoyao Chang, Jianyong Wang, Furu Wei","pos":"#2702","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PnTXyTR2VG","abs":"<p>Multimodal generative models require a unified approach to handle both discrete data (e.g., text and code) and continuous data (e.g., image, audio, video). In this work, we propose Latent Language Modeling (LatentLM), which seamlessly integrates continuous and discrete data using causal Transformers. Specifically, we employ a variational autoencoder (VAE) to represent continuous data as latent vectors and introduce next-token diffusion for autoregressive generation of these vectors. Additionally, we develop -VAE to address the challenges of variance collapse, which is crucial for autoregressive modeling. Extensive experiments demonstrate the effectiveness of LatentLM across various modalities. In image generation, LatentLM surpasses Diffusion Transformers in both performance and scalability. When integrated into multimodal large language models, LatentLM provides a general-purpose interface that unifies multimodal generation and understanding. Experimental results show that LatentLM achieves favorable performance compared to Transfusion and vector quantized models in the setting of scaling up training tokens. In text-to-speech synthesis, LatentLM outperforms the state-of-the-art VALL-E 2 model in speaker similarity and robustness, while requiring 10 fewer decoding steps. The results establish LatentLM as a highly effective and scalable approach to advance large multimodal models.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal generative modelsлҠ” discrete data(мҳҲ: textмҷҖ code)мҷҖ continuous data(мҳҲ: image, audio, video)лҘј лӘЁл‘җ лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ нҶөн•©лҗң м ‘к·јмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” causal TransformerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ continuous dataмҷҖ discrete dataлҘј л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” Latent Language Modeling (LatentLM)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ”, variational autoencoder (VAE)лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ continuous dataлҘј latent vectorлЎң н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳкі , мқҙлҹ¬н•ң vectorмқҳ autoregressive generationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ next-token diffusionмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, autoregressive modelingм—җ н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё variance collapse л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ -VAEлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң modalityм—җм„ң LatentLMмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҜём§Җ мғқм„ұм—җм„ңлҠ” LatentLMмқҙ м„ұлҠҘкіј нҷ•мһҘм„ұ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң Diffusion TransformersлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. multimodal large language modelм—җ нҶөн•©н–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң, LatentLMмқҖ multimodal generationкіј understandingмқ„ н•ҳлӮҳлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” лІ”мҡ© мқён„°нҺҳмқҙмҠӨлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” н•ҷмҠө tokenмқ„ лҠҳлҰ¬лҠ” м„Өм •м—җм„ң LatentLMмқҙ Transfusion л°Ҹ vector quantized лӘЁлҚёкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. text-to-speech н•©м„ұм—җм„ңлҠ” LatentLMмқҙ speaker similarityмҷҖ robustnessм—җм„ң state-of-the-art VALL-E 2 лӘЁлҚёмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ decoding stepмқҖ 10к°ң лҚ” м ҒкІҢ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” LatentLMмқ„ large multimodal modelмқ„ л°ңм „мӢңнӮӨлҠ” л§Өмҡ° нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙкі  нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м ‘к·јмңјлЎң мһҗлҰ¬л§Өк№Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63922","en":"SPARKLING: Balancing Signal Preservation and Symmetry Breaking for Width-Progressive Learning","ko":"SPARKLING: width-progressive learningм—җм„ң мӢ нҳё ліҙмЎҙкіј лҢҖм№ӯ к№Ём§җмқҳ к· нҳ•","authors":"Qifan Yu, Xinyu Ma, Zhijian Zhuo, Minrui Wang, Deyi Liu, Shiyi Zhan, Yiyuan Ma, liang xiang, Xingyan Bin, Di He","pos":"#2803","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=SXJBFREkWi","abs":"Progressive Learning (PL) reduces pre-training computational overhead by gradually increasing model scale. While prior work has extensively explored depth expansion, width expansion remains significantly understudied, with the few existing methods limited to the early stages of training. However, expanding width during the mid-stage is essential for maximizing computational savings, yet it remains a formidable challenge due to severe training instabilities.  Empirically, we show that naive initialization at this stage disrupts activation statistics, triggering loss spikes, while copy-based initialization introduces gradient symmetry that hinders feature diversity. To address these issues, we propose **SPARKLING** (balancing **S**ignal **P**reservation **A**nd symmet**R**y brea**K**ing for width-progressive **L**earn**ING**), a novel framework for mid-stage width expansion. Our method achieves signal preservation via RMS-scale consistency, stabilizing activation statistics during expansion. Symmetry breaking is ensured through asymmetric optimizer state resetting and learning rate re-warmup. Extensive experiments on Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models demonstrate that, across multiple width axes and optimizer families, SPARKLING consistently outperforms training from scratch and reduces training cost by up to 35% under $2\\times$ width expansion.","absKo":"Progressive Learning (PL)мқҖ model scaleмқ„ м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң лҠҳл Ө pre-training computational overheadлҘј мӨ„мһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” depth expansionмқ„ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ҳкІҢ нғҗкө¬н•ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, width expansionмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ м—°кө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳмңјл©°, кё°мЎҙмқҳ лӘҮлӘҮ л°©лІ•лҸ„ training мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„м—җл§Ң м ңн•ңлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ computational savingмқ„ к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳл Өл©ҙ мӨ‘к°„ лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң widthлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң training instability л•Ңл¬ём—җ мқҙлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ л§Өмҡ° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ л¬ём ңмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. кІҪн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мӢңм җм—җм„ң naive initializationмқҙ activation statisticsлҘј көҗлһҖн•ҳм—¬ loss spikeлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, copy-based initializationмқҖ feature diversityлҘј м Җн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” gradient symmetryлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӨ‘к°„ лӢЁкі„ width expansionмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkмқё **SPARKLING**(balancing **S**ignal **P**reservation **A**nd symmet**R**y brea**K**ing for width-progressive **L**earn**ING**)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ RMS-scale consistencyлҘј нҶөн•ҙ signal preservationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ expansion лҸҷм•Ҳ activation statisticsлҘј м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. Symmetry breakingмқҖ л№„лҢҖм№ӯ optimizer state resettingкіј learning rate re-warmupмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ ліҙмһҘлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ width axisмҷҖ optimizer family м „л°ҳм—җм„ң SPARKLINGмқҙ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мІҳмқҢл¶Җн„° лӢӨмӢң н•ҳлҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳл©°, $2\\times$ width expansion н•ҳм—җм„ң training costлҘј мөңлҢҖ 35%к№Ңм§Җ мӨ„мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"65576","en":"SpatioLM: Towards General Physical Spatial Intelligence in Vision-Language Models","ko":"SpatioLM: Vision-Language Modelм—җм„ң мқјл°ҳ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ кіөк°„ м§ҖлҠҘмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"jing wu, Jianhua Wu, Jiayi Guan, Jiahong Chen, Jinghui Lu, Hangjun Ye, Bingzhao Gao, Long Chen","pos":"#2804","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CHavqrN1X9","abs":"<p>Vision-Language Models (VLMs) perform well on commonsense reasoning tasks but struggle with visual spatial reasoning. Most existing solutions introduce extra 3D priors or external spatial encoders, which increase complexity and degrade the underlying VLMs' general-purpose capabilities after spatial fine-tuning. To this end, we propose a parameter-efficient \\textit{\\textbf{Spatio}-vision \\textbf{L}anguage \\textbf{M}odels (SpatioLM)}, that enhances spatial intelligence without extra 3D priors or third-party spatial encoders. Concretely, we design a plug-and-play and non-invasive spatio-vision module that elicits the spatial knowledge inherent in VLMs. Furthermore, we innovatively leverage pseudo depth and camera information as supervision to guide the model in learning physically coherent representations. Extensive experiments show that SpatioLM achieves significant improvements in diverse tasks, including spatial perception and understanding while maintains the general-purpose capabilities. Notably, the model achieves an impressive score of 71.6 on the VSI-Bench (the first model to surpass 70). In addition, it attains competitive performance when transferred to embodied manipulation tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Vision-Language Models(VLMs)мқҖ commonsense reasoning taskм—җм„ңлҠ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, visual spatial reasoningм—җм„ңлҠ” м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ н•ҙкІ°мұ…мқҖ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё 3D priorлӮҳ external spatial encoderлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” ліөмһЎм„ұмқ„ мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮӨкі  spatial fine-tuning мқҙнӣ„ underlying VLMмқҳ general-purpose capabilityлҘј м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м¶”к°Җ 3D priorлӮҳ third-party spatial encoder м—Ҷмқҙ spatial intelligenceлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” parameter-efficient \\textit{\\textbf{Spatio}-vision \\textbf{L}anguage \\textbf{M}odels(SpatioLM)}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” VLMм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң spatial knowledgeлҘј мқҙлҒҢм–ҙлӮҙлҠ” plug-and-playмқҙл©ҙм„ң non-invasiveн•ң spatio-vision moduleмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, pseudo depthмҷҖ camera informationмқ„ supervisionмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ physically coherent representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SpatioLMмқҙ spatial perceptionкіј understandingмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң taskм—җм„ң мқјл°ҳ-purpose capabilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мң мқҳлҜён•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мқҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ VSI-Benchм—җм„ң 71.6мқҙлқјлҠ” мқёмғҒм Ғмқё м җмҲҳлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳмңјл©°(70мқ„ мІҳмқҢмңјлЎң л„ҳмқҖ лӘЁлҚё), embodied manipulation taskлЎң м „мқҙн–Ҳмқ„ л•ҢлҸ„ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65754","en":"UHR-BAT: Budget-Aware Token Compression Vision-Language model for Ultra-High-Resolution Remote Sensing","ko":"UHR-BAT: мҙҲкі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ мӣҗкІ© нғҗмӮ¬лҘј мң„н•ң мҳҲмӮ° мқёмӢқ нҶ нҒ° м••м¶• Vision-Language лӘЁлҚё","authors":"Yunkai Dang, Minxin Dai, Yuekun Yang, Zhangnanli, Wenbin Li, Feng Miao, Yang Gao","pos":"#2806","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=AWPKhE1dbc","abs":"<p>Ultra-high-resolution (UHR) remote sensing imagery couples kilometer-scale context with query-critical evidence that may occupy only a few pixels. Such vast spatial scale leads to a quadratic explosion of visual tokens and hinders the extraction of information from small objects. Previous works utilize direct downsampling, dense tiling, or global topвҖ‘K pruning, which either compromise query-critical image details or incur unpredictable compute. In this paper, we propose UHR-BAT, a query-guided and region-faithful token compression framework to efficiently select visual tokens under strict context budget. Specifically, we leverage text-guided, multi-scale importance estimation for visual tokens, effectively tackling the challenge of achieving precise yet low-cost feature extraction.  Furthermore, by introducing region-wise preserve and merge strategies, we mitigate visual token redundancy, further driving down the computational budget. The experimental results show that UHR-BAT achieves state-of-the-art performance across various benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"Ultra-high-resolution (UHR) remote sensing imageryлҠ” kilometer-scale contextмҷҖ query-critical evidenceлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң evidenceлҠ” лӘҮ к°ңмқҳ pixelм—җл§Ң мЎҙмһ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙмІҳлҹј л°©лҢҖн•ң spatial scaleмқҖ visual tokenмқҳ quadratic explosionмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ҳкі  мһ‘мқҖ objectлЎңл¶Җн„° м •ліҙлҘј м¶”м¶ңн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ direct downsampling, dense tiling, global topвҖ‘K pruningмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҠ” query-criticalн•ң image detailмқ„ мҶҗмғҒмӢңнӮӨкұ°лӮҳ мҳҲмёЎ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң computeлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” м—„кІ©н•ң context budget н•ҳм—җм„ң visual tokenмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң query-guided, region-faithful token compression frameworkмқё UHR-BATлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” visual tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ text-guided multi-scale importance estimationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, м •нҷ•н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м Җл№„мҡ©мқҳ feature extractionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кіјм ңлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң region-wise preserve л°Ҹ merge strategyлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ visual token redundancyлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкі , computational budgetмқ„ лҚ”мҡұ лӮ®м¶ҳлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” UHR-BATк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62086","en":"Unified Multimodal Autoregressive Modeling with Shared ContextвҖ”Visual Tokenizer is Key to Unification","ko":"кіөмң  м»Ён…ҚмҠӨнҠё кё°л°ҳ нҶөн•© л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ мһҗкё°нҡҢк·Җ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ: Visual Tokenizerк°Җ нҶөн•©мқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҙлӢӨ","authors":"Wujian Peng, Lingchen Meng, Yuxuan Cai, Xianwei Zhuang, Yuhuan Yang, Rongyao Fang, Chenfei Wu, Junyang Lin, Zuxuan Wu, Shuai Bai","pos":"#2807","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jwRAIYoVJn","abs":"<p>Unified Multimodal Modeling aims to integrate visual understanding and generation within a single system. However, existing approaches typically rely on two disparate visual tokenizers, which splits the representation space and hinder truly unified modeling. We propose UniAR, a unified autoregressive framework where a single discrete visual tokenizer serves as the key bridge between understanding and generation, enabling a shared context in which the model can directly interpret its own generated visual tokens without additional re-encoding. UniAR adapts a pretrained vision encoder with multi-level feature fusion and a lookup-free bitwise quantization scheme, preserving both high-level semantics and low-level details while scaling the effective visual vocabulary at minimal cost. Building on this, the unified autoregressive model adopts parallel-bitwise-prediction to jointly predict spatially grouped, multi-level visual codes, substantially reducing visual sequence length and accelerating generation. Finally, a diffusion-based visual decoder operates on discrete visual tokens to reconstruct high-fidelity images. Through large-scale pre-training on 1T multimodal tokens, followed by supervised fine-tuning and reinforcement learning, UniAR achieves state-of-the-art performance on text-to-image generation and image editing while remaining competitive on multimodal understanding benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Unified Multimodal ModelingмқҖ visual understandingкіј generationмқ„ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ мӢңмҠӨн…ң м•Ҳм—җм„ң нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё л‘җ к°ңмқҳ visual tokenizerм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ representation spaceлҘј л¶„н• н•ҳкі , м§„м •н•ң unified modelingмқ„ м Җн•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ discrete visual tokenizerк°Җ understandingкіј generation мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ bridgeлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” unified autoregressive frameworkмқё UniARлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё re-encoding м—Ҷмқҙ мһҗмӢ мқҙ мғқм„ұн•ң visual tokenмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ н•ҙм„қн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” shared contextлҘј к°–кІҢ лҗңлӢӨ. UniARлҠ” pretrained vision encoderлҘј multi-level feature fusionкіј lookup-free bitwise quantization schemeмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘мӢңмјң, лҶ’мқҖ мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ semanticкіј лӮ®мқҖ мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ detailмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ л№„мҡ©мңјлЎң effective visual vocabularyлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң unified autoregressive modelмқҖ parallel-bitwise-predictionмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ҳм—¬ spatially groupedлҗң multi-level visual codeлҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң мҳҲмёЎн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ visual sequence lengthлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқҙкі  generationмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң diffusion-based visual decoderлҠ” discrete visual token мң„м—җм„ң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳм—¬ кі м¶©мӢӨлҸ„ мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. 1T multimodal tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ pre-training л’Ө supervised fine-tuningкіј reinforcement learningмқ„ кұ°м№ң UniARлҠ” text-to-image generationкіј image editingм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ multimodal understanding benchmarkм—җм„ңлҸ„ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙмқ„ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62863","en":"Unveiling the Visual Counting Bottleneck in Vision-Language Models","ko":"Vision-Language Modelsмқҳ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ м№ҙмҡҙнҢ… лі‘лӘ© н•ҙмҶҢ","authors":"Xingzhou Pang, Yifan Hou, Junling Wang, Mrinmaya Sachan","pos":"#2808","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cQbg0vf0Gz","abs":"<p>While Large Vision-Language Models (VLMs) excel at interpolation, they suffer catastrophic failures in systematic generalization, most notably in visual counting beyond training distributions. In this work, we investigate this extrapolation bottleneck by deconstructing visual counting into three cognitive stages: object individuation, abstract magnitude representation, and symbolic decoding. Using a controlled environment of synthetic Go game boards, we isolate the specific mechanism of failure. Contrary to the hypothesis that models suffer from perceptual errors, we demonstrate via linear probing that visual backbones maintain robust, linearly separable representations of quantity well into the extrapolation regime. Furthermore, models retain latent magnitude awareness, successfully performing comparative reasoning on quantities they fail to enumerate. We pinpoint the collapse to the Symbolic Decoding stage, where the model fails to project valid visual magnitudes onto discrete tokens. Our findings support a Fractured Magnitude Hypothesis: VLMs fail to acquire a Universal Number Space, instead learning disjoint, modality-specific statistical manifolds that prevent cross-modal grounding for unseen pairings. We validate our findings on the state-of-the-art foundation model, suggesting that bridging the extrapolation gap requires inductive priors that enforce unified magnitude representations rather than simply scaling training data.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Vision-Language Model (VLM)мқҖ interpolationм—җлҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮҳм§Җл§Ң, systematic generalizationм—җм„ңлҠ” м№ҳлӘ…м Ғмқё мӢӨнҢЁлҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, нҠ№нһҲ training distributionмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” visual countingм—җм„ң л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” visual countingмқ„ object individuation, abstract magnitude representation, symbolic decodingмқҳ м„ё cognitive stageлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳм—¬ мқҙ extrapolation bottleneckмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. synthetic Go game boardлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң нҶөм ңлҗң нҷҳкІҪмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мӢӨнҢЁмқҳ нҠ№м • л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚёмқҙ perceptual errorлЎң мқён•ҙ мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨлҠ” к°Җм„Өкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, linear probingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ visual backboneмқҙ extrapolation regimeм—җ л“Өм–ҙк°Җм„ңлҸ„ quantityм—җ лҢҖн•ң кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  linearly separableн•ң representationмқ„ мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ latent magnitude awarenessлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©°, м—ҙкұ°м—җлҠ” мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” quantityм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ л№„көҗ м¶”лЎ мқ„ м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨнҢЁмқҳ мӣҗмқёмқҙ Symbolic Decoding stageм—җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ нҠ№м •н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙ лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мң нҡЁн•ң visual magnitudeлҘј discrete tokenмңјлЎң нҲ¬мҳҒн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°ңкІ¬мқҖ Fractured Magnitude HypothesisлҘј м§Җм§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, VLMмқҖ Universal Number SpaceлҘј нҡҚл“қн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі , лҢҖмӢ  м„ңлЎң л¶„лҰ¬лҗң modality-specific statistical manifoldлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң pairingм—җ лҢҖн•ң cross-modal groundingмқ„ л°©н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” state-of-the-art foundation modelм—җм„ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн–Ҳмңјл©°, extrapolation gapмқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” лӢЁмҲңнһҲ training dataлҘј лҠҳлҰ¬лҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј нҶөн•©лҗң magnitude representationмқ„ к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” inductive priorк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65052","en":"WorldMirror: Universal 3D World Reconstruction with Any-Prior Prompting","ko":"WorldMirror: Any-Prior Promptingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң лІ”мҡ© 3D World мһ¬кө¬м„ұ","authors":"Yifan Liu, Zhiyuan Min, Zhenwei Wang, Junta Wu, Tengfei Wang, Yixuan Yuan, Yawei Luo, Chunchao Guo","pos":"#2811","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HFNJOpXHfm","abs":"<p>We present WorldMirror, a unified feed-forward model for comprehensive 3D geometric prediction tasks.  Unlike existing methods constrained to image-only inputs or customized for a specific task, our framework flexibly integrates diverse geometric priors, including camera poses, intrinsics, and depth maps, while simultaneously generating multiple 3D representations: dense point clouds, multi-view depth maps, camera parameters, surface normals, and 3D Gaussians. Remarkably, prior injection yields universal gains across all tasks, suggesting that input flexibility and multi-task prediction are mutually reinforcing. WorldMirror achieves state-of-the-art performance across diverse benchmarks from camera, point map, depth, and surface normal estimation to novel view synthesis, while maintaining the efficiency of feed-forward inference. Code and models will be publicly available.</p>","absKo":"<p>WorldMirrorлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. WorldMirrorлҠ” нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё 3D geometric prediction taskлҘј мң„н•ң нҶөн•© feed-forward modelмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“Өмқҙ image-only inputм—җ м ңм•Ҫлҗҳкұ°лӮҳ нҠ№м • taskм—җ л§һкІҢ customizedлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлҠ” кІғкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkлҠ” camera poses, intrinsics, depth mapsлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң geometric priorлҘј мң м—°н•ҳкІҢ нҶөн•©н•ҳл©ҙм„ң лҸҷмӢңм—җ dense point clouds, multi-view depth maps, camera parameters, surface normals, 3D Gaussians л“ұ м—¬лҹ¬ 3D representationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ prior injectionмқҖ лӘЁл“  taskм—җм„ң ліҙнҺём Ғмқё м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ к°Җм ёмҳӨл©°, мқҙлҠ” input flexibilityмҷҖ multi-task predictionмқҙ м„ңлЎңлҘј к°•нҷ”н•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. WorldMirrorлҠ” camera, point map, depth, surface normal estimationл¶Җн„° novel view synthesisм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ feed-forward inferenceмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқҖ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. CodeмҷҖ modelмқҖ кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61181","en":"MentisOculi: Revealing the Limits of Reasoning with Mental Imagery","ko":"MentisOculi: м •мӢ м Ғ мӢ¬мғҒмқ„ нҶөн•ң м¶”лЎ мқҳ н•ңкі„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙкё°","authors":"Jana Zeller, ThaddГӨus Wiedemer, Fanfei Li, Thomas Klein, Prasanna Mayilvahanan, Matthias Bethge, Felix Wichmann, Ryan Cotterell, Wieland Brendel","pos":"#2900","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=sxvuK2x3eA","abs":"<p>Frontier models are transitioning from <em>multimodal large language models</em> (MLLMs) that merely ingest visual information to <em>unified multimodal models</em> (UMMs) capable of native interleaved generation. This shift has sparked interest in using intermediate visualizations as a reasoning aid, akin to human <em>mental imagery</em>. Central to this idea is the ability to form, maintain, and manipulate visual representations in a goal-oriented manner. To evaluate and probe this capability, we develop MentisOculi, a procedural, stratified suite of multi-step reasoning problems amenable to visual solution, tuned to challenge frontier models. Evaluating visual strategies ranging from latent tokens to explicit generated imagery, we find they generally fail to improve performance. Analysis of UMMs specifically exposes a critical limitation: While they possess the textual reasoning capacity to solve a task and can sometimes generate correct visuals, they suffer from compounding generation errors and fail to leverage even ground-truth visualizations.  Our findings suggest that despite their inherent appeal, <em>visual thoughts do not yet benefit model reasoning</em>. MentisOculi establishes the necessary foundation to analyze and close this gap across diverse model families.</p>","absKo":"Frontier modelмқҖ лҚ” мқҙмғҒ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ мӢңк°Ғ м •ліҙлҘј л°ӣм•„л“ӨмқҙлҠ” <em>multimodal large language model</em> (MLLM)м—җм„ң, native interleaved generationмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң <em>unified multimodal model</em> (UMM)лЎң м „нҷҳлҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң ліҖнҷ”лҠ” мқёк°„мқҳ <em>mental imagery</em>мҷҖ мң мӮ¬н•ҳкІҢ intermediate visualizationмқ„ м¶”лЎ  ліҙмЎ° мҲҳлӢЁмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° лҢҖн•ң кҙҖмӢ¬мқ„ л¶Ҳлҹ¬мқјмңјмј°лӢӨ. мқҙ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ representationмқ„ лӘ©н‘ң м§Җн–Ҙм ҒмңјлЎң нҳ•м„ұн•ҳкі , мң м§Җн•ҳкі , мЎ°мһ‘н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл ҘмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі  нғҗкө¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” frontier modelмқ„ лҸ„м „н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мЎ°м •лҗң, м Ҳм°Ём Ғмқҙкі  мёөнҷ”лҗң multi-step reasoning problem м„ёнҠёмқё MentisOculiлҘј к°ңл°ңн–ҲлӢӨ. latent tokenл¶Җн„° лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мғқм„ұлҗң мқҙлҜём§Җк№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң visual strategyлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒм—җ кё°м—¬н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ UMMм—җ лҢҖн•ң л¶„м„қмқҖ мӨ‘лҢҖн•ң н•ңкі„лҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мқҙл“ӨмқҖ taskлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  н…ҚмҠӨнҠё м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ к°–м¶”кі  мһҲмңјл©° л•ҢлЎңлҠ” мҳ¬л°”лҘё мӢңк°Ғм Ғ кІ°кіјл¬јмқ„ мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, мғқм„ұ мҳӨлҘҳк°Җ лҲ„м Ғлҗҳкі  ground-truth visualizationмЎ°м°Ё м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” к·ё л§Өл Ҙм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  <em>visual thoughtк°Җ м•„м§Ғ лӘЁлҚё м¶”лЎ м—җ мқҙлЎӯм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ</em>лҠ” м җмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. MentisOculiлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң model family м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мқҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј л¶„м„қн•ҳкі  н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң н•„мҲҳ кё°л°ҳмқ„ л§Ҳл Ён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61725","en":"LynX: Token Interface Alignment for Video+X LLMs","ko":"LynX: Video+X LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң Token Interface м •л ¬","authors":"Jungin Park, Jiyoung Lee, Kwanghoon Sohn","pos":"#2901","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nV8GEDzrSn","abs":"<p>This study introduces an intriguing phenomenon in Video LLMs: rather than merely translating frames into textual embeddings, Video LLMs establish a continuous manifold, token interface, allowing visual tokens to operate as standalone entities within the architecture. Exploiting this discovery, we propose LynX, a scalable framework that integrates novel modalities by repurposing the internalized interface. Departing from conventional paradigms that necessitate heavy modality-specific encoders or paired supervision, LynX employs a lightweight auxiliary pathway in parallel with the frozen vision encoder. By aligning both the attention responses and the statistical distributions using unimodal data alone, our method synchronizes new sensory inputs with intrinsic video priors. Crucially, our distributional alignment ensures manifold compatibility while preserving the integrity of the Video LLMs. Extensive benchmarks demonstrate that LynX achieves state-of-the-art performance and efficiency across audio-visual QA, 3D reasoning, high-frame-rate, and multi-view video understanding. The code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/lynx-DDC8/.</p>","absKo":"<p>ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” Video LLMsм—җм„ң нқҘлҜёлЎңмҡҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҰү, Video LLMsлҠ” лӢЁмҲңнһҲ frameмқ„ textual embeddingмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° к·ём№ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі , continuous manifoldмқё token interfaceлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ҳм—¬ visual tokenмқҙ architecture лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё entityлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°ңкІ¬мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”лҗң interfaceлҘј мһ¬нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ modalityлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң frameworkмқё LynXлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ modality-specific encoderлӮҳ paired supervisionмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ paradigmкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, LynXлҠ” frozen vision encoderмҷҖ лі‘л ¬лЎң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” lightweight auxiliary pathwayлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. unimodal dataл§ҢмңјлЎң attention responseмҷҖ statistical distributionмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ м •л ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ sensory inputмқ„ Video LLMsмқҳ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ priorмҷҖ лҸҷкё°нҷ”н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ distributional alignmentлҠ” manifold compatibilityлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳл©ҙм„ң Video LLMsмқҳ л¬ҙкІ°м„ұмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң benchmark мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң LynXлҠ” audio-visual QA, 3D reasoning, high-frame-rate, multi-view video understanding м „л°ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘкіј нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/lynx-DDC8/ м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65334","en":"KAST-BAR: Knowledge-Anchored Semantically-Dynamic Topology Brain Autoregressive Modeling for Universal Neural Interpretation","ko":"KAST-BAR: лІ”мҡ© мӢ кІҪ н•ҙм„қмқ„ мң„н•ң м§ҖмӢқ кі м • мқҳлҜё лҸҷм Ғ нҶ нҸҙлЎңм§Җ лҮҢ мһҗкё°нҡҢк·Җ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ","authors":"Haoning Wang, Wenchao Yang, Shuai Shen, Yang Li","pos":"#2902","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ee4j4zMir5","abs":"<p>While EEG foundation models have shown significant potential in universal neural decoding across tasks, their advancement remains constrained by the inadequacy modeling of <em>complex spatiotemporal topology</em>, as well as the inherent <em>modality gap</em> between low-level physiological signals and high-level textual semantics.     To address these challenges, we propose a <strong>K</strong>nowledge-<strong>A</strong>nchored <strong>S</strong>emantically-Dynamic <strong>T</strong>opology <strong>B</strong>rain <strong>A</strong>uto<strong>r</strong>egressive Model (KAST-BAR), which dynamically aligns physiological representations derived from multi-level brain topology with an expert-level semantic space.      Specifically, we design a Dual-Stream Hierarchical Attention (DSHA) encoder that accurately captures the brain's intrinsic non-Euclidean topology by modeling local temporal dynamics with global spatial contexts.      On this basis, a Knowledge-Anchored Semantic Profiler (KASP) is proposed to synthesize physically-grounded and instance-level textual profiles, which subsequently drive a Semantic Text-Aware Refiner (STAR) to dynamically reconstruct EEG representations using Latent Expert Queries.      By conducting large-scale pre-training on 21 diverse datasets to build a foundation model, KAST-BAR effectively integrates expert-level medical knowledge into EEG signal representations, consistently achieving state-of-the-art performance across six downstream tasks. Our code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/KAST-BAR</p>","absKo":"<p>EEG foundation modelмқҖ task м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң лІ”мҡ© neural decodingм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, <em>complex spatiotemporal topology</em>лҘј м¶©л¶„нһҲ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі  м ҖмҲҳмӨҖ мғқлҰ¬ мӢ нҳёмҷҖ кі мҲҳмӨҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мқҳлҜё мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё <em>modality gap</em>мқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҙ л°ңм „мқҙ м ңн•ңлҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” multi-level brain topologyм—җм„ң мң лҸ„лҗң мғқлҰ¬ н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ expert-level semantic spaceмҷҖ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” <strong>K</strong>nowledge-<strong>A</strong>nchored <strong>S</strong>emantically-Dynamic <strong>T</strong>opology <strong>B</strong>rain <strong>A</strong>uto<strong>r</strong>egressive Model(KAST-BAR)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” local temporal dynamicsмҷҖ global spatial contextлҘј н•Ёк»ҳ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳм—¬ лҮҢмқҳ кі мң н•ң non-Euclidean topologyлҘј м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” Dual-Stream Hierarchical Attention(DSHA) encoderлҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң к·јкұ°к°Җ мһҲкі  instance-levelмқё textual profileмқ„ н•©м„ұн•ҳлҠ” Knowledge-Anchored Semantic Profiler(KASP)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мқҙнӣ„ Latent Expert QueryлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ EEG representationмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” Semantic Text-Aware Refiner(STAR)лҘј кө¬лҸҷн•ңлӢӨ. 21к°ңмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetм—җм„ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ pre-trainingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ foundation modelмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, KAST-BARлҠ” expert-level medical knowledgeлҘј EEG signal representationм—җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳкі , м—¬м„Ҝ к°ң downstream task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/KAST-BAR м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ</p>"},{"id":"62157","en":"HaloProbe: Bayesian Detection and Mitigation of Object Hallucinations in Vision-Language Models","ko":"HaloProbe: Vision-Language Modelмқҳ к°қмІҙ нҷҳк°Ғм—җ лҢҖн•ң Bayesian нғҗм§ҖмҷҖ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Reihaneh Zohrabi, Hosein Hasani, Akshita Gupta, Mahdieh Baghshah, Anna Rohrbach, Marcus Rohrbach","pos":"#2905","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jGRDp7Moik","abs":"<p>Large vision-language models can produce object hallucinations in image descriptions, highlighting the need for effective detection and mitigation strategies. Prior work commonly relies on the model's attention weights on visual tokens as a detection signal. We reveal that coarse-grained attention-based analysis is unreliable due to hidden confounders, specifically token position and object repetition in a description. This leads to SimpsonвҖҷs paradox: the attention trends reverse when statistics are aggregated. Based on this observation, we introduce HaloProbe, a Bayesian framework that factorizes external description statistics and internal decoding signals to estimate token-level hallucination probabilities. HaloProbe uses balanced training to isolate internal evidence and combines it with learned prior over external features to recover the true posterior. While intervention-based mitigation methods often degrade utility or fluency by modifying modelsвҖҷ internals, we use HaloProbe as an external scoring signal for non-invasive mitigation. Our experiments show that HaloProbe guided decoding reduces hallucinations more effectively than state-of-the-art intervention-based methods while preserving utility.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ vision-language modelмқҖ image descriptionм—җм„ң object hallucinationмқ„ мқјмңјнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё нғҗм§Җ л°Ҹ мҷ„нҷ” м „лһөмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” нқ”нһҲ нғҗм§Җ мӢ нҳёлЎң visual tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ң лӘЁлҚёмқҳ attention weightм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” coarse-grained attention-based analysisк°Җ hidden confounder, нҠ№нһҲ token positionкіј description лӮҙ object repetition л•Ңл¬ём—җ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶмқҢмқ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” SimpsonвҖҷs paradoxлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, нҶөкі„лҘј м§‘кі„н•ҳл©ҙ attention trendк°Җ л°ҳм „лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҷёл¶Җ description нҶөкі„мҷҖ лӮҙл¶Җ decoding signalмқ„ factorizeн•ҳм—¬ token-level hallucination probabilityлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” Bayesian frameworkмқё HaloProbeлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. HaloProbeлҠ” balanced trainingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ лӮҙл¶Җ evidenceлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкі , learned prior over external featuresмҷҖ кІ°н•©н•ҳм—¬ true posteriorлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. intervention-based mitigation methodк°Җ лӘЁлҚё лӮҙл¶ҖлҘј мҲҳм •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ utilityлӮҳ fluencyлҘј м Җн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺмқҖ л°ҳл©ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” HaloProbeлҘј л№„м№ЁмҠөм Ғ мҷ„нҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң мҷёл¶Җ scoring signalлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ HaloProbe guided decodingмқҙ utilityлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң state-of-the-art intervention-based methodліҙлӢӨ hallucinationмқ„ лҚ” нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мӨ„мһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60557","en":"Focusing Where Vision Matters: Selective Training for Large Vision Language Models via Visual Information Gain","ko":"л№„м „мқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кіім—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳкё°: мӢңк°Ғ м •ліҙ мқҙл“қмқ„ нҶөн•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ Vision Language Model м„ нғқм Ғ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Seulbi Lee, Sangheum Hwang","pos":"#2906","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=z1bSFIEexL","abs":"<p>Large Vision Language Models (LVLMs) have achieved remarkable progress, yet they often suffer from language bias, producing answers without relying on visual evidence. While prior work attempts to mitigate this issue through decoding strategies, architectural modifications, or curated instruction data, they typically lack a quantitative measure of how much individual training samples or tokens actually benefit from the image. In this work, we introduce Visual Information Gain (VIG), a perplexity-based metric that measures the reduction in prediction uncertainty provided by visual input. VIG enables fine-grained analysis at both sample and token levels, effectively highlighting visually grounded elements such as colors, spatial relations, and attributes. Leveraging this, we propose a VIG-guided selective training scheme that prioritizes high-VIG samples and tokens. This approach improves visual grounding and mitigates language bias, achieving superior performance with significantly reduced supervision by focusing exclusively on visually informative samples and tokens.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Vision Language Models(LVLMs)мқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈЁм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢңк°Ғм Ғ evidenceм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  лӢөмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” language bias л¬ём ңлҘј мһҗмЈј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” decoding strategy, architecture мҲҳм •, лҳҗлҠ” м •м ңлҗң instruction dataлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл Ө н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, к°ңлі„ training sampleмқҙлӮҳ tokenмқҙ мӢӨм ңлЎң мқҙлҜём§ҖлЎңл¶Җн„° м–јл§ҲлӮҳ мқҙл“қмқ„ м–»лҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң м •лҹүм Ғ мёЎм •мқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” visual inputмқҙ prediction uncertaintyлҘј м–јл§ҲлӮҳ мӨ„мқҙлҠ”м§Җ мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” perplexity-based metricмқё Visual Information Gain(VIG)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. VIGлҠ” sample мҲҳмӨҖкіј token мҲҳмӨҖ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң м„ёл°Җн•ң л¶„м„қмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, мғүмғҒ, кіөк°„ кҙҖкі„, мҶҚм„ұмІҳлҹј мӢңк°Ғм ҒмңјлЎң groundedлҗң мҡ”мҶҢлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң л¶Җк°Ғн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҶ’мқҖ VIG sampleкіј tokenмқ„ мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳлҠ” VIG-guided selective training schemeмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мӢңк°Ғм ҒмңјлЎң м •ліҙлҹүмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ sampleкіј tokenм—җл§Ң м§‘мӨ‘н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ visual groundingмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  language biasлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл©°, нӣЁм”¬ мӨ„м–ҙл“  supervisionмңјлЎңлҸ„ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63514","en":"Finding the Correct Visual Evidence Without Forgetting: Mitigating Hallucination in LVLMs via Inter-Layer Visual Attention Discrepancy","ko":"л§қк°Ғ м—Ҷмқҙ мҳ¬л°”лҘё мӢңк°Ғм Ғ мҰқкұ° м°ҫкё°: л Ҳмқҙм–ҙ к°„ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ м–ҙн…җм…ҳ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлҘј нҶөн•ң LVLMмқҳ нҷҳк°Ғ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Yutong Xie, Zhenglin Hua, Ran Wang, Wing W. Y. Ng, Xizhao Wang, Yuheng Jia","pos":"#2907","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WUjRCkjKC7","abs":"<p>Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) have shown remarkable performance on a wide range of vision-language tasks. Despite this progress, they are still prone to hallucination, generating responses that are semantically coherent but inconsistent with visual content. In this work, we find that LVLMs tend to hallucinate when they pay insufficient attention to the correct visual evidence and gradually forget it during the generation process, leading to more hallucinations. We empirically find that although LVLMs overall attend insufficiently to visual evidence, they exhibit sensitivity to the correct visual evidence in specific layers, with notable inter-layer discrepancy. Motivated by this observation, we propose a novel hallucination mitigation method that enhances visual evidence based on <strong>I</strong>nter-<strong>L</strong>ayer <strong>V</strong>isual <strong>A</strong>ttention <strong>D</strong>iscrepancy (<strong>ILVAD</strong>). Specifically, we obtain the attention weights from early generated tokens to visual tokens across layers and identify the tokens that are repeatedly activated as visual evidence, forming a saliency map. We then enhance attention to visual evidence during generation through the saliency map to reduce visual forgetting. In addition, we leverage the saliency map to obtain attention scores of generated text to visual evidence, in order to select and emphasize text tokens that are strongly grounded in visual evidence. Our method is training-free and plug-and-play. Multiple benchmark evaluations conducted on five recently released models show that our method can consistently mitigate hallucinations in different LVLMs across various model architectures. The code and data used have been submitted to the technique appendix.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Vision-Language Models(LVLMs)лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң vision-language taskм—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м§„м „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , м—¬м „нһҲ hallucinationм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳм—¬ мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” мқјкҙҖлҗҳм§Җл§Ң visual contentмҷҖлҠ” л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” мқ‘лӢөмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” LVLMмқҙ мҳ¬л°”лҘё visual evidenceм—җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мЈјмқҳлҘј кё°мҡёмқҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі  мғқм„ұ кіјм •м—җм„ң мқҙлҘј м җм°Ё мһҠм–ҙлІ„лҰҙ л•Ң hallucinationмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ hallucinationмқҙ мң л°ңлҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң, LVLMмқҖ м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң visual evidenceм—җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мЈјмқҳлҘј кё°мҡёмқҙм§Җ м•Ҡм§Җл§Ң, нҠ№м • layerм—җм„ңлҠ” мҳ¬л°”лҘё visual evidenceм—җ лҜјк°җн•ҳкІҢ л°ҳмқ‘н•ҳл©°, layer к°„ discrepancyк°Җ л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„лӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм°°м—җ лҸҷкё°лҘј л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>I</strong>nter-<strong>L</strong>ayer <strong>V</strong>isual <strong>A</strong>ttention <strong>D</strong>iscrepancy(<strong>ILVAD</strong>)м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬ visual evidenceлҘј к°•нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ hallucination мҷ„нҷ” л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, м—¬лҹ¬ layerм—җ кұёміҗ мҙҲкё° мғқм„ұ tokenм—җм„ң visual tokenмңјлЎңмқҳ attention weightлҘј кө¬н•ҳкі , visual evidenceлЎң л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңм„ұнҷ”лҗҳлҠ” tokenмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳм—¬ saliency mapмқ„ нҳ•м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ saliency mapмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мғқм„ұ мӨ‘ visual evidenceм—җ лҢҖн•ң attentionмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳм—¬ visual forgettingмқ„ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң saliency mapмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мғқм„ұлҗң textк°Җ visual evidenceм—җ м–јл§ҲлӮҳ кё°л°ҳн•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң attention scoreлҘј м–»кі , visual evidenceм—җ к°•н•ҳкІҢ groundingлҗң text tokenмқ„ м„ нғқн•ҙ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ training-freeмқҙл©° plug-and-play л°©мӢқмқҙлӢӨ. мөңк·ј кіөк°ңлҗң 5к°ң modelм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мҲҳн–үн•ң м—¬лҹ¬ benchmark нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң, ліё л°©лІ•мқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң model architectureмқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё LVLMм—җм„ң hallucinationмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҷ„нҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң codeмҷҖ dataлҠ” technique appendixм—җ м ңм¶ңлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64555","en":"Adaptive Residual-Update Steering for Low-Overhead Hallucination Mitigation in Large Vision-Language Models","ko":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ Vision-Language лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң м Җл№„мҡ© Hallucination мҷ„нҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң м Ғмқ‘м Ғ Residual-Update Steering","authors":"Zhengtao Zou, Ya Gao, Jiarui Guan, Bin Li, Pekka Marttinen","pos":"#2912","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=MEqmAlsKwS","abs":"Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) typically process visual inputs as a prefix to the language decoder. As the model autoregressively generates text, this initial visual information inevitably undergoes ``dilution'', leading the model to over-rely on language priors and hallucinate objects. Existing interventions attempt to correct this by contrasting logits or iteratively refining outputs, but they incur prohibitive latency costs. We propose **Residual-Update Directed DEcoding Regulation (RUDDER)**, a framework that counters visual dilution by creating a persistent visual anchor. We extract a robust evidence direction (**CARD**) directly from the model's prefill residual updates, and inject it into the decoding process. This injection is modulated by an adaptive gate, the **Beta Gate**, which acts as a trust mechanism and ensures the visual reminder is applied only when necessary. Experiments on LLaVA-1.5 (7B/13B), Idefics2, InstructBLIP, and Qwen2.5-VL demonstrate that RUDDER consistently mitigates hallucination (with greedy decoding, RUDDER reduces CHAIR$_S$ by an average of **24.4\\%** and CHAIR$_i$ by **23.6\\%** relative) and scales effectively across architectures, all while maintaining **\\&gt;96.0\\%** throughput. The code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/RUDDER-Residual-Update-Directed-DEcoding-Regulation--D5FC.","absKo":"Large Vision-Language Models(LVLMs)лҠ” мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң visual inputмқ„ language decoderмқҳ prefixлЎң мІҳлҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚёмқҙ autoregressiveн•ҳкІҢ textлҘј мғқм„ұн• мҲҳлЎқ, мқҙ мҙҲкё° visual informationмқҖ н•„м—°м ҒмңјлЎң ``dilution''мқ„ кІӘм–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ language priorм—җ кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкі  objectлҘј hallucinateн•ҳкІҢ лҗңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ к°ңмһ… л°©лІ•мқҖ logitsлҘј л№„көҗн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң м •м ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҘј көҗм •н•ҳл Ө н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, latency л№„мҡ©мқҙ л„Ҳл¬ҙ нҒ¬лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” visual dilutionмқ„ м–өм ңн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё visual anchorлҘј л§Ңл“ңлҠ” **Residual-Update Directed DEcoding Regulation (RUDDER)**мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҳ prefill residual updateм—җм„ң м§Ғм ‘ к°•кұҙн•ң evidence direction(**CARD**)мқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳм—¬ decoding кіјм •м—җ мЈјмһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мЈјмһ…мқҖ adaptive gateмқё **Beta Gate**м—җ мқҳн•ҙ мЎ°м Ҳлҗҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” trust mechanismмңјлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҙ visual reminderк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•  л•Ңл§Ң м Ғмҡ©лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. LLaVA-1.5(7B/13B), Idefics2, InstructBLIP, Qwen2.5-VLм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ RUDDERк°Җ hallucinationмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҷ„нҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјл©°(greedy decoding кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң, RUDDERлҠ” CHAIR$_S$лҘј нҸүк· м ҒмңјлЎң **24.4\\%**, CHAIR$_i$лҘј **23.6\\%** к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮҙ), м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳ м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘлҗҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ **&gt;96.0\\%** throughputмқ„ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/RUDDER-Residual-Update-Directed-DEcoding-Regulation--D5FC м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"63095","en":"Agent0-VL: Exploring Self-Evolving Agent for Tool-Integrated Vision-Language Reasoning","ko":"Agent0-VL: лҸ„кө¬ нҶөн•© Vision-Language м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң мһҗкё° м§„нҷ” м—җмқҙм „нҠё нғҗкө¬","authors":"Jiaqi Liu, Kaiwen Xiong, Peng Xia, Yiyang Zhou, Haonian Ji, Lu Feng, Siwei Han, Mingyu Ding, Huaxiu Yao","pos":"#3513","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=aA02f0y0LY","abs":"<p>Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) have achieved remarkable progress in multimodal reasoning tasks; however, their learning remains constrained by the limitations of human-annotated supervision. Recent self-rewarding approaches attempt to overcome this constraint by allowing models to act as their own critics or reward providers. Yet, purely text-based self-evaluation struggles to verify complex visual reasoning steps and often suffers from evaluation hallucinations. To address these challenges, inspired by recent advances in tool-integrated reasoning, we propose Agent0-VL, a self-evolving vision-language agent that achieves continual improvement with tool-integrated reasoning. Agent0-VL incorporates tool usage not only into reasoning but also into self-evaluation and self-repair, enabling the model to introspect, verify, and refine its reasoning through evidence-grounded analysis. It unifies two synergistic roles within a single LVLM: a Solver that performs multi-turn tool-integrated reasoning, and a Verifier that generates structured feedback and fine-grained self-rewards through tool-grounded critique. These roles interact through a Self-Evolving Reasoning Cycle, where tool-based verification and reinforcement learning jointly align the reasoning and evaluation distributions for stable self-improvement. Through this zero-external-reward evolution, Agent0-VL aligns its reasoning and verification behaviors without any human annotation or external reward models, achieving continual self-improvement. Experiments on chart reasoning, geometric problem solving, and visual scientific analysis show that Agent0-VL achieves an 12.5% improvement over the Qwen-VL base model.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs)мқҖ multimodal reasoning taskм—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ л°ңм „мқ„ мқҙлӨҳм§Җл§Ң, м—¬м „нһҲ мқёк°„ мЈјм„қ кё°л°ҳ supervisionмқҳ н•ңкі„м—җ мқҳн•ҙ н•ҷмҠөмқҙ м ңм•ҪлҗңлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ self-rewarding м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мҠӨмҠӨлЎң critic лҳҗлҠ” reward provider м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ҳкІҢ н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ңм•Ҫмқ„ к·№ліөн•ҳкі мһҗ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҲңмҲҳн•ң text-based self-evaluationмқҖ ліөмһЎн•ң visual reasoning stepмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘкі , мў…мў… evaluation hallucinationмқҳ л¬ём ңлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҸ„м „мқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мөңк·ј tool-integrated reasoningмқҳ л°ңм „м—җ м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” tool-integrated reasoningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң к°ңм„ лҗҳлҠ” self-evolving vision-language agentмқё Agent0-VLмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Agent0-VLмқҖ tool usageлҘј reasoningлҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј self-evaluationкіј self-repairм—җлҸ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬, evidence-grounded analysisлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мҠӨмҠӨлЎңлҘј introspectн•ҳкі , кІҖмҰқн•ҳкі , м •көҗнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ LVLM м•Ҳм—җм„ң мғҒнҳё мӢңл„Ҳм§ҖлҘј лӮҙлҠ” л‘җ м—ӯн• мқ„ нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. SolverлҠ” multi-turn tool-integrated reasoningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , VerifierлҠ” tool-grounded critiqueлҘј нҶөн•ҙ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң feedbackкіј fine-grained self-rewardлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м—ӯн• л“ӨмқҖ Self-Evolving Reasoning Cycleмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳл©°, м—¬кё°м„ң tool-based verificationкіј reinforcement learningмқҙ н•Ёк»ҳ reasoning л¶„нҸ¬мҷҖ evaluation л¶„нҸ¬лҘј м •л ¬н•ҳм—¬ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё self-improvementлҘј мқҙлҒҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң zero-external-reward evolutionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ Agent0-VLмқҖ мқёк°„ мЈјм„қмқҙлӮҳ external reward model м—Ҷмқҙ reasoningкіј verification behaviorлҘј м •л ¬н•ҳкі , м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё self-improvementлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. chart reasoning, geometric problem solving, visual scientific analysis мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң Agent0-VLмқҖ Qwen-VL base model лҢҖл№„ 12.5% н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62609","en":"Probing Newtonian Mechanics in Video Generative Models with Real Physical Systems","ko":"мӢӨм ң л¬јлҰ¬ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң Video Generative Modelsмқҳ Newtonian Mechanics л¶„м„қ","authors":"Antonios Tragoudaras, Daniil Cherniavskii, Chenyu Zhang, Antonis Vozikis, Thijmen Nijdam, Derck Prinzhorn, MГЎrk BodrГЎcska, Nicu Sebe, Andrii Zadaianchuk, Efstratios Gavves","pos":"#4611","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=f4xAzcMug6","abs":"<p>Recent advances in image and video generation raise hopes that these models possess world modeling capabilitiesвҖ”the ability to generate realistic, physically plausible videos. This could revolutionize applications in robotics, autonomous driving, and scientific simulation. However, before treating these models as world models, we must ask: Do they adhere to physical laws?  Current evaluation methods rely on subjective judgments or trajectory matching, limiting their usage for physical reasoning estimation, where many generations could be physically plausible.  Thus, we introduce <strong>Morpheus</strong>, one of the first physics-informed evaluation frameworks for measuring the ability of video generation models to comprehend Newtonian dynamics. <strong>Morpheus</strong> features 130 real-world videos capturing physical phenomena, guided by conservation laws. Using those as conditioning for video generation, we assess physical plausibility leveraging interpretable metrics evaluated with respect to infallible conservation laws known per physical setting, leveraging advances in physics-informed neural networks and vision-language foundation models. Importantly, <strong>Morpheus</strong> targets controlled Newtonian rigid-body settings to enable quantitative checks. Our findings reveal that even with advanced prompting and video conditioning, contemporary models struggle to encode physical principles despite generating aesthetically pleasing videos.</p>","absKo":"<p>мқҙлҜём§Җ л°Ҹ л№„л””мҳӨ мғқм„ұмқҳ мөңк·ј л°ңм „мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„лҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙ, мҰү нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқҙкі  л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•ң л№„л””мҳӨлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ к°–м¶”кі  мһҲмқ„ кІғмқҙлқјлҠ” кё°лҢҖлҘј л¶Ҳлҹ¬мқјмңјмј°лӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лЎңліҙнӢұмҠӨ, мһҗмңЁмЈјн–ү, кіјн•ҷ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳмқҳ мқ‘мҡ©мқ„ нҳҒмӢ н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ world modelлЎң к°„мЈјн•ҳкё° м „м—җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¬јлҰ¬ лІ•м№ҷмқ„ л”°лҘҙлҠ”м§Җ л¬јм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ нҸүк°Җ л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјкҙҖм Ғ нҢҗлӢЁмқҙлӮҳ trajectory matchingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, л§ҺмқҖ мғқм„ұ кІ°кіјк°Җ л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң нғҖлӢ№н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” л¬јлҰ¬ м¶”лЎ  м¶”м •м—җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкё°м—җлҠ” н•ңкі„к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” video generation modelмқҙ Newtonian dynamicsлҘј мқҙн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мёЎм •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ physics-informed нҸүк°Җ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳмқё <strong>Morpheus</strong>лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. <strong>Morpheus</strong>лҠ” ліҙмЎҙ лІ•м№ҷм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м•ҲлӮҙлҗҳлҠ” л¬јлҰ¬ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ң 130к°ңмқҳ мӢӨм ң л№„л””мҳӨлҘј нҠ№м§•мңјлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј video generationмқҳ conditioningмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, к°Ғ л¬јлҰ¬ нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң м•Ңл Өм§„ мҳӨлҘҳ м—ҶлҠ” ліҙмЎҙ лІ•м№ҷмқ„ кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң нҸүк°ҖлҗҳлҠ” н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң metricмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•Ёмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳл©°, physics-informed neural networksмҷҖ vision-language foundation modelsмқҳ л°ңм „мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ <strong>Morpheus</strong>лҠ” м •лҹүм Ғ кІҖмҰқмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м ңм–ҙлҗң Newtonian rigid-body м„Өм •мқ„ лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°ңкІ¬мқҖ кі лҸ„нҷ”лҗң promptingкіј video conditioningмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„, нҳ„лҢҖ лӘЁлҚёл“ӨмқҖ лҜём ҒмңјлЎң лӣ°м–ҙлӮң л№„л””мҳӨлҘј мғқм„ұн•Ём—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  л¬јлҰ¬ мӣҗлҰ¬лҘј мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62867","en":"Fair-FedMOE: Group-Fair One-Shot Federated Learning via Prototype-Guided Experts for Medical Imaging Analysis","ko":"Fair-FedMOE: Prototype-Guided Expert кё°л°ҳ мқҳлЈҢ мҳҒмғҒ л¶„м„қмқҳ к·ёлЈ№ кіөм • One-Shot Federated Learning","authors":"Lingzhao Meng, Shuai Guo, Weishan Zhang, Zengxiang Li, Han Yu, Nan Liu, Daniel Ting, Yuru Liu, Tao Chen, Shudong Wang","pos":"#513","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cPmaaJ3MY3","abs":"<p>Group fairness can ensure equitable performance across different demographic subgroups for medical image analysis. However, the current fine-tuned foundation models (FMs) exhibit significant subgroup disparity. One-shot federated learning (OFL) can potentially mitigate this by leveraging cross-institutional data diversity within a single communication round. But heterogeneous distributions across medical institutions may cause OFL local models to diverge severely, resulting in parameter conflicts that amplify disparity upon aggregation. To address these challenges, we propose Fair-FedMOE, a group-fair OFL framework for medical FMs. During local training, Fairness-aware Expert Routing routes samples to group-specific experts via learnable prototypes, enabling subgroup-specialized learning to capture group-specific features without inter-group interference. During model aggregation, Prototype-guided Differential Aggregation computes personalized weights based on prototype similarity and applies differentiated aggregation strategies to filter conflicting updates. We propose RES-AUC, a Rawlsian justice-inspired metric based on worst-group performance that remains stable as groups increase. Comprehensive experiments on diverse retinal datasets covering different modalities and diseases, using retinal-specific and general-purpose FMs, show consistent fairness gains without sacrificing accuracy. Code available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Fair-FedMOE-2624.</p>","absKo":"<p>Group fairnessлҠ” medical image analysisм—җм„ң м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё demographic subgroup к°„мқҳ кіөм •н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ нҳ„мһ¬ fine-tuned foundation model (FM)мқҖ subgroup к°„ кІ©м°Ёк°Җ мғҒлӢ№н•ҳлӢӨ. One-shot federated learning (OFL)мқҖ лӢЁмқј communication round лӮҙм—җм„ң кё°кҙҖ к°„ лҚ°мқҙн„° лӢӨм–‘м„ұмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•  мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. н•ҳм§Җл§Ң medical institution к°„ heterogeneityлҠ” OFL local modelмқҙ мӢ¬н•ҳкІҢ л°ңмӮ°н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Ө мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј aggregation мӢң parameter conflictк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” medical FMмқ„ мң„н•ң group-fair OFL frameworkмқё Fair-FedMOEлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Local training лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң Fairness-aware Expert RoutingмқҖ н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн•ң prototypeмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ sampleмқ„ group-specific expertлЎң лқјмҡ°нҢ…н•ҳм—¬, subgroup-specific learningмқҙ inter-group interference м—Ҷмқҙ group-specific featureлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. Model aggregation лӢЁкі„м—җм„ңлҠ” Prototype-guided Differential Aggregationмқҙ prototype similarityлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң personalized weightлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳкі , м¶©лҸҢн•ҳлҠ” updateлҘј кұёлҹ¬лӮҙкё° мң„н•ҙ differentiated aggregation strategyлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” group мҲҳк°Җ мҰқк°Җн•ҙлҸ„ м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң мң м§ҖлҗҳлҠ” worst-group performance кё°л°ҳмқҳ Rawlsian justice-inspired metricмқё RES-AUCлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё modalityмҷҖ м§Ҳнҷҳмқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң retinal datasetм—җм„ң retinal-specific л°Ҹ general-purpose FMмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң мў…н•© мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мқјкҙҖлҗң fairness н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. Code available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Fair-FedMOE-2624.</p>"},{"id":"64846","en":"A robust PPG foundation model using multimodal physiological supervision","ko":"л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ мғқлҰ¬ к°җлҸ…мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң к°•кұҙн•ң PPG Foundation Model","authors":"Eloy Geenjaar, Vince Calhoun, scott daly, Gouthaman KV, Lie Lu, Trisha Mittal, Daniel P. Darcy","pos":"#514","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=JF4045xnhl","abs":"<p>Photoplethysmography (PPG), a non-invasive measure of changes in blood volume, is widely used in both wearable devices and clinical settings. Recent PPG foundation models either use open-source ICU datasets with pretraining paradigms that require high-quality data and thus complicate generalization to field-like data, or use closed-source field-like PPG data. In contrast, we propose a PPG foundation model that does not require high-quality or field-like pretraining data, and instead leverages accompanying electrocardiogram and respiratory signals in ICU datasets to select contrastive samples during pretraining. Our approach allows the model to retain and learn from noisy PPG segments, improving robustness at inference. Our model, pretrained on 3x fewer subjects than existing state-of-the-art approaches, achieves performance improvements on 14 out of 15 diverse downstream tasks, including field-like daily activity and heart rate prediction. Our results demonstrate that multimodal supervision can leverage the multimodal nature of clinical data to develop robust PPG foundation models that generalize better to consumer-level data.</p>","absKo":"<p>Photoplethysmography(PPG)лҠ” нҳҲм•Ўлҹү ліҖнҷ”мқҳ л№„м№ЁмҠөм Ғ мёЎм • л°©лІ•мңјлЎң, мӣЁм–ҙлҹ¬лё” кё°кё°мҷҖ clinical setting лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ PPG foundation modelмқҖ open-source ICU datasetмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҗҳ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҙ field-like dataлЎңмқҳ generalizationмқ„ м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” pretraining paradigmмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, closed-source field-like PPG dataлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ л°ҳн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ лҳҗлҠ” field-like pretraining dataлҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” PPG foundation modelмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, лҢҖмӢ  ICU datasetм—җ н•Ёк»ҳ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” electrocardiogramкіј respiratory signalмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ pretraining мӨ‘ contrastive sampleмқ„ м„ нғқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ noisy PPG segmentлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳкі  н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳм—¬ inference мӢң robustnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ state-of-the-art м ‘к·јлІ•ліҙлӢӨ 3л°° м ҒмқҖ subjectлЎң pretrainedлҗң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ field-like daily activityмҷҖ heart rate predictionмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң 15к°ңмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң downstream task мӨ‘ 14к°ңм—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” multimodal supervisionмқҙ clinical dataмқҳ multimodalн•ң нҠ№м„ұмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ, consumer-level dataм—җ лҚ” мһҳ generalizeн•ҳлҠ” robustн•ң PPG foundation modelмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64925","en":"Learning 3D-Gaussian Simulators from RGB Videos","ko":"RGB л№„л””мҳӨлЎңл¶Җн„° 3D-Gaussian Simulator н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Mikel Zhobro, Andreas RenГ© Geist, Georg Martius","pos":"#706","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Icj19tWHI1","abs":"<p>Realistic simulation is critical for applications ranging from robotics to animation. Video generation models have emerged as a way to capture real-world physics from data, but they often face challenges in maintaining spatial consistency and object permanence, relying on memory mechanisms to compensate. As a complementary direction, we present 3DGSim, a learned 3D simulator that directly learns physical interactions from multi-view RGB videos. 3DGSim adopts MVSplat to learn a latent particle-based representation of 3D scenes, a Point Transformer for the particle dynamics, a Temporal Merging module for consistent temporal aggregation, and Gaussian Splatting to produce novel view renderings. By jointly training inverse rendering and dynamics forecasting, 3DGSim embeds physical properties into point-wise latent features. This enables the model to capture diverse behaviors, from rigid and elastic to cloth-like dynamics and boundary conditions (e.g., fixed cloth corners), while producing realistic lighting effects. We show that 3DGSim can generate physically plausible results even in out of distribution cases, e.g. ground removal or multi-object interactions, despite being trained only on single-body collisions.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳмқҖ roboticsл¶Җн„° animationм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. video generation modelмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎңл¶Җн„° мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„мқҳ л¬јлҰ¬лҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ л°©лІ•мңјлЎң л– мҳ¬лһҗм§Җл§Ң, кіөк°„м Ғ мқјкҙҖм„ұкіј object permanenceлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„ мқҙлҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ memory mechanismм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң ліҙмҷ„м Ғ л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” multi-view RGB videoлЎңл¶Җн„° л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ м§Ғм ‘ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” learned 3D simulatorмқё 3DGSimмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. 3DGSimмқҖ MVSplatмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ 3D sceneмқҳ latent particle-based representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , Point TransformerлЎң particle dynamicsлҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳл©°, Temporal Merging moduleлЎң мқјкҙҖлҗң temporal aggregationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , Gaussian SplattingмңјлЎң novel view renderingмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. inverse renderingкіј dynamics forecastingмқ„ кіөлҸҷ н•ҷмҠөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, 3DGSimмқҖ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ нҠ№м„ұмқ„ point-wise latent featureм—җ лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ rigid л°Ҹ elasticл¶Җн„° cloth-like dynamicsмҷҖ fixed cloth corners к°ҷмқҖ boundary conditionк№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң кұ°лҸҷмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё мЎ°лӘ… нҡЁкіјлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 3DGSimмқҙ single-body collisionл§ҢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗҳм—ҲмқҢм—җлҸ„ ground removalлӮҳ multi-object interactionкіј к°ҷмқҖ out-of-distribution caseм—җм„ңлҸ„ л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң нғҖлӢ№н•ң кІ°кіјлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63725","en":"Holi-Spatial: Evolving Video Streams into Holistic 3D Spatial Intelligence","ko":"Holi-Spatial: л№„л””мҳӨ мҠӨнҠёлҰјмқ„ мҙқмІҙм Ғ 3D кіөк°„ м§ҖлҠҘмңјлЎң м§„нҷ”мӢңнӮӨкё°","authors":"Yuanyuan Gao, Hao Li, Yifei Liu, Xinhao Ji, Yuning Gong, Yuanjun Liao, Fangfu Liu, Manyuan Zhang, Yuchen Yang, Dan Xu, Xue Yang, Huaxi Huang, Hongjie Zhang, Ziwei Liu, Xiao Sun, Dingwen Zhang, Zhihang Zhong","pos":"#712","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=UGAP2F6FfV","abs":"<p>The pursuit of spatial intelligence fundamentally relies on access to large-scale, fine-grained 3D data. However, existing approaches predominantly construct spatial understanding benchmarks by generating questionвҖ“answer (QA) pairs from a limited number of manually annotated datasets, rather than systematically annotating new large-scale 3D scenes from raw web data. As a result, their scalability is severely constrained, and model performance is further hindered by domain gaps inherent in these narrowly curated datasets. In this work, we propose \\textbf{Holi-Spatial}, the first fully automated, large-scale, spatially-aware multimodal dataset, constructed from raw video inputs without human intervention, using the proposed data curation pipeline. Holi-Spatial supports multi-level spatial supervision, ranging from geometrically accurate 3D Gaussian Splatting (3DGS) reconstructions with rendered depth maps to object-level and relational semantic annotations, together with corresponding spatial QuestionвҖ“Answer (QA) pairs. Following a principled and systematic pipeline, we further construct \\textbf{Holi-Spatial-4M}, the first large-scale, high-quality 3D semantic dataset, containing 12K optimized 3DGS scenes, 1.3M 2D masks, 320K 3D bounding boxes, 320K instance captions, 1.2M 3D grounding instances, and 1.2M spatial QA pairs spanning diverse geometric, relational, and semantic reasoning tasks. Holi-Spatial demonstrates exceptional performance in data curation quality, significantly outperforming existing feed-forward and per-scene optimized methods on datasets such as ScanNet, ScanNet++, and DL3DV. Furthermore, fine-tuning Vision-Language Models (VLMs) on spatial reasoning tasks using this dataset has also led to substantial improvements in model performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>spatial intelligenceлҘј м¶”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁмқҳ м •көҗн•ң 3D лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җ лҢҖн•ң м ‘к·јм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мӣҗмӢң web dataлЎңл¶Җн„° мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ 3D sceneмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мЈјм„қн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , мЈјлЎң м ңн•ңлҗң мҲҳмқҳ мҲҳмһ‘м—… мЈјм„қ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң questionвҖ“answer (QA) pairлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬ spatial understanding benchmarkлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқҖ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ м ңм•Ҫлҗҳл©°, лӘЁлҚё м„ұлҠҘ лҳҗн•ң мқҙл ҮкІҢ мўҒкІҢ м„ лі„лҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ лӮҙмһ¬н•ң domain gapмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ лҚ” м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ” data curation pipelineмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ human intervention м—Ҷмқҙ raw video inputмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° кө¬м¶•н•ң, мөңмҙҲмқҳ мҷ„м „ мһҗлҸҷнҷ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ spatially-aware multimodal datasetмқё \\textbf{Holi-Spatial}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Holi-SpatialмқҖ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң м •нҷ•н•ң 3D Gaussian Splatting (3DGS) reconstructionкіј rendered depth mapл¶Җн„° object-level л°Ҹ relational semantic annotation, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мқҙм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” spatial QuestionвҖ“Answer (QA) pairм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨмёөм Ғмқё spatial supervisionмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқҙкі  мІҙкі„м Ғмқё pipelineмқ„ л”°лқј, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң geometric, relational, semantic reasoning taskлҘј м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” 12K optimized 3DGS scene, 1.3M 2D mask, 320K 3D bounding box, 320K instance caption, 1.2M 3D grounding instance, 1.2M spatial QA pairлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ 3D semantic datasetмқё \\textbf{Holi-Spatial-4M}лҸ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. Holi-SpatialмқҖ data curation н’Ҳм§Ҳм—җм„ң нғҒмӣ”н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, ScanNet, ScanNet++, DL3DVмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ datasetм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ feed-forward л°Ҹ per-scene optimized methodлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мқҙ datasetмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ spatial reasoning taskлЎң Vision-Language Models (VLMs)лҘј fine-tuningн•ҳл©ҙ лӘЁлҚё м„ұлҠҘмқҙ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62661","en":"The Illusion of Generalization: Instruction-Following, Task Bias and Contamination in Tabular Language Model Evaluation","ko":"мқјл°ҳнҷ”мқҳ нҷҳмғҒ: Tabular Language Model Evaluationм—җм„ң Instruction-Following, Task Bias, Contamination","authors":"Aditya Gorla, Ratish Surendran Puduppully","pos":"#2805","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ea2kQkdQA7","abs":"<p>Tabular Language Models (TLMs) have been claimed to achieve emergent generalization for tabular prediction. We conduct a systematic re-evaluation of Tabula-8B as a representative TLM, utilizing 165 datasets from the UniPredict benchmark. Our investigation reveals three findings. First, binary and categorical classification achieve near-zero median lift over majority-class baselines and strong aggregate performance is driven entirely by quartile classification tasks. Second, top-performing datasets exhibit pervasive contamination, including complete train-test overlap and task-level leakage that evades standard deduplication. Third, instruction-tuning without tabular exposure recovers 92.2\\% of standard classification performance and on quartile classification, format familiarity closes 71.3\\% of the gap with the residual attributable to contaminated datasets. These findings suggest claimed generalization likely reflects evaluation artifacts rather than learned tabular reasoning. We conclude with recommendations for strengthening TLM evaluation.</p>","absKo":"<p>Tabular Language Models (TLMs)к°Җ tabular predictionм—җм„ң emergent generalizationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘлҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”мҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” UniPredict benchmarkмқҳ 165к°ң datasetмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё TLMмқё Tabula-8BлҘј лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң мІҙкі„м Ғмқё мһ¬нҸүк°ҖлҘј мҲҳн–үн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мЎ°мӮ¬м—җм„ңлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ кІ°кіјк°Җ л“ңлҹ¬лӮ¬мҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, binary л°Ҹ categorical classificationмқҖ majority-class baseline лҢҖл№„ median liftк°Җ кұ°мқҳ 0м—җ к°Җк№қкі , к°•н•ң aggregate performanceлҠ” м „м ҒмңјлЎң quartile classification taskм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мЈјлҸ„лҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, мөңкі  м„ұлҠҘ datasetл“Өм—җм„ңлҠ” train-test мҷ„м „ мӨ‘ліөкіј standard deduplicationмқ„ нҡҢн”јн•ҳлҠ” task-level leakageлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң contaminationмқҙ кҙҖм°°лҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. м…Ӣм§ё, tabular exposure м—Ҷмқҙ instruction-tuningмқ„ н•ҳл©ҙ standard classification м„ұлҠҘмқҳ 92.2\\%лҘј нҡҢліөн•ҳл©°, quartile classificationм—җм„ңлҠ” format familiarityк°Җ кІ©м°Ёмқҳ 71.3\\%лҘј л©”мҡ°кі , лӮҳлЁём§ҖлҠ” contaminated datasetм—җ кё°мқён•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” мЈјмһҘлҗң generalizationмқҙ н•ҷмҠөлҗң tabular reasoningмқҙлқјкё°ліҙлӢӨ evaluation artifactлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•  к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ лҶ’мқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң TLM evaluationмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң к¶Ңкі  мӮ¬н•ӯмқ„ м ңмӢңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64276","en":"Efficient Diffusion Models via Time Step Optimization with Consistent Training and Inference Constraints","ko":"мқјкҙҖлҗң н•ҷмҠө л°Ҹ м¶”лЎ  м ңм•Ҫмқ„ нҶөн•ң мӢңк°„ лӢЁкі„ мөңм Ғнҷ” кё°л°ҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Diffusion лӘЁлҚё","authors":"Zihao Cheng, Binrui Wu, Yuesen Liao, Weizhong Zhang","pos":"#2711","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PFJEIhUh1y","abs":"<p>Diffusion probabilistic models (DPMs)вҖҷ sampling process is often inefficient, requiring hundreds to thousands of iterative steps to accurately approximate the diffusion trajectory. This inefficiency limits their practical applicability. Although recent advances in sampling efficiencyвҖ”such as numerical solvers for diffusion ordinary differential equations (ODEs)вҖ”have made progress, significant challenges remain: training-free numerical solvers suffer from the suboptimality of manually designed timestep selection rules and the inherent inconsistency between the forward diffusion process (typically involving thousands of steps) and the reverse denoising process (usually limited to tens of steps). Since timestep selection is inherently a discrete problem and cannot be optimized via gradients, we propose an innovative approachвҖ”reparameterizing the timestep scheduling through probabilistic masking, thereby enabling gradient-based optimization of sampling timesteps. To circumvent backpropagation, we employ policy gradient methods. Furthermore, to address the inconsistency between forward diffusion (training) and reverse denoising (inference), we extend this framework into a bilevel optimization paradigm: the inner loop performs additional lightweight training on the model at specific timesteps determined by the outer mask to align forward and reverse processes, while the outer loop optimizes the timestep distribution via probabilistic masking and policy gradient based on generation quality. Under mild assumptions, we theoretically analyze the convergence of the proposed algorithm. Extensive experiments across diverse datasets and samplers demonstrate that this framework effectively enhances sampling efficiency and generation quality while maintaining compatibility with various DPM architectures and advanced ODE solvers.</p>","absKo":"<p>Diffusion probabilistic model(DPM)мқҳ sampling processлҠ” мў…мў… л№„нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙл©°, diffusion trajectoryлҘј м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ к·јмӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҲҳл°ұм—җм„ң мҲҳмІң лӢЁкі„мқҳ л°ҳліөмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л№„нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқҖ мӢӨм ң м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. diffusion ordinary differential equation(ODE)мқ„ мң„н•ң numerical solverмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ мөңк·јмқҳ sampling efficiency л°ңм „мқҖ м§„м „мқ„ ліҙмҳҖм§Җл§Ң, м—¬м „нһҲ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кіјм ңк°Җ лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. training-free numerical solverлҠ” мҲҳлҸҷмңјлЎң м„Өкі„лҗң timestep selection ruleмқҳ мөңм Ғ мқҙн•ҳ м„ұлҠҘкіј, forward diffusion process(ліҙнҶө мҲҳмІң лӢЁкі„)мҷҖ reverse denoising process(ліҙнҶө мҲҳмӢӯ лӢЁкі„) мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлЎң м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. timestep selectionмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң discrete problemмқҙлҜҖлЎң gradientлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•  мҲҳ м—Ҷкё°м—җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” sampling timestepмқҳ gradient-based optimizationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ probabilistic maskingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ timestep schedulingмқ„ reparameterizeн•ҳлҠ” нҳҒмӢ м Ғ м ‘к·јмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. backpropagationмқ„ мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ policy gradient methodлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, forward diffusion(training)кіј reverse denoising(inference) к°„мқҳ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мқҙ frameworkлҘј bilevel optimization paradigmмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. inner loopлҠ” outer maskк°Җ кІ°м •н•ң нҠ№м • timestepм—җм„ң лӘЁлҚём—җ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё кІҪлҹү н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ forwardмҷҖ reverse processлҘј м •л ¬н•ҳкі , outer loopлҠ” мғқм„ұ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң probabilistic maskingкіј policy gradientлҘј нҶөн•ҙ timestep distributionмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. м•Ҫн•ң к°Җм • н•ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м ңм•Ҳн•ң м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҳ мҲҳл ҙмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetкіј samplerм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҙ frameworkк°Җ м—¬лҹ¬ DPM architecture л°Ҹ кі кёү ODE solverмҷҖмқҳ нҳёнҷҳм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң sampling efficiencyмҷҖ generation qualityлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62666","en":"Vision in One Vector: Implicit Visual Compression with Diffusion Foundation Models","ko":"Vision in One Vector: Diffusion Foundation Models кё°л°ҳ м•”мӢңм Ғ Visual Compression","authors":"Jiajun He, Zongyu Guo, Zhaoyang Jia, Xiaoyi Zhang, Jiahao Li, Xiao Li, Bin Li, Jose Miguel Hernandez-Lobato, Yan Lu","pos":"#2512","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eYICUJ62hg","abs":"<p>Modern visual generative models acquire rich visual knowledge through large-scale training, yet existing visual representations (such as pixels, latents, or tokens) remain external to the model and cannot directly exploit this knowledge for compact storage or reuse. In this work, we introduce a new visual representation framework that encodes a signal as a function,  which is parametrized by low-rank adaptations attached to a frozen visual generative model. Such implicit representations are learned by compressing the visual signal, e.g., an 81-frame video, into a single compact vector, achieving strong perceptual video compression at extremely low bitrates. Beyond basic compression, the functional nature of this representation enables inference-time scaling and control, allowing additional refinement on the compression performance. More broadly, as the implicit representations directly act as a function of the generation process, this suggests a unified framework bridging visual compression and generation.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖ visual generative modelмқҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ н’Қл¶Җн•ң visual knowledgeлҘј нҡҚл“қн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ visual representation(мҳҲ: pixel, latent, token)мқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ лӘЁлҚё мҷёл¶Җм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳл©°, мқҙ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ compact storageлӮҳ reuseм—җ м§Ғм ‘ нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ м—ҶмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” frozen visual generative modelм—җ м—°кІ°лҗң low-rank adaptationмңјлЎң л§Өк°ңліҖмҲҳнҷ”лҗң functionмңјлЎң signalмқ„ мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ visual representation frameworkлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң implicit representationмқҖ мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ 81-frame videoмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ visual signalмқ„ лӢЁмқј compact vectorлЎң м••м¶•н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н•ҷмҠөлҗҳл©°, к·№нһҲ лӮ®мқҖ bitrateм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң perceptual video compressionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кё°ліём Ғмқё compressionмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ, мқҙ representationмқҳ functional natureлҠ” inference-time scalingкіј controlмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬ compression performanceлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң refinementн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҚ” л„“кІҢ ліҙл©ҙ, implicit representationмқҙ мғқм„ұ кіјм •мқҳ functionмңјлЎң м§Ғм ‘ мһ‘лҸҷн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җм—җм„ң visual compressionкіј generationмқ„ м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј мӢңмӮ¬н•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66608","en":"Vector Quantization using Gaussian Variational Autoencoder","ko":"Gaussian Variational AutoencoderлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң лІЎн„° м–‘мһҗнҷ”","authors":"Tongda Xu, Wendi Zheng, Jiajun He, Jose Miguel Hernandez-Lobato, Yan Wang, Ya-Qin Zhang, Jie Tang","pos":"#2513","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2CQkqiZ6p9","abs":"<p>Vector-quantized variational autoencoders (VQ-VAEs) are discrete autoencoders that compress images into discrete tokens. However, they are difficult to train due to discretization. In this paper, we propose a simple yet effective technique dubbed <strong>Gaussian Quant (GQ)</strong>, which first trains a Gaussian VAE under certain constraints and then converts it into a VQ-VAE without additional training. For conversion, GQ generates random Gaussian noise as a codebook and finds the closest noise vector to the posterior mean. Theoretically, we prove that when the logarithm of the codebook size exceeds the bits-back coding rate of the Gaussian VAE, a small quantization error is guaranteed. Practically, we propose a heuristic to train Gaussian VAEs for effective conversion, named the target divergence constraint (TDC). Empirically, we show that GQ outperforms previous VQ-VAEs, such as VQGAN, FSQ, LFQ, and BSQ, on both UNet and ViT architectures. Furthermore, TDC also improves previous Gaussian VAE discretization methods, such as TokenBridge. The source code is provided in the supplementary materials.</p>","absKo":"<p>Vector-quantized variational autoencoder (VQ-VAE)лҠ” мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј discrete tokenмңјлЎң м••м¶•н•ҳлҠ” discrete autoencoderмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ discretization л•Ңл¬ём—җ н•ҷмҠөмқҙ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” <strong>Gaussian Quant (GQ)</strong>лқјлҠ” к°„лӢЁн•ҳм§Җл§Ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё кё°лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. GQлҠ” лЁјм Җ нҠ№м • м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ң Gaussian VAEлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ң л’Ө, м¶”к°Җ н•ҷмҠө м—Ҷмқҙ мқҙлҘј VQ-VAEлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліҖнҷҳ кіјм •м—җм„ң GQлҠ” random Gaussian noiseлҘј codebookмңјлЎң мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , posterior meanм—җ к°ҖмһҘ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ noise vectorлҘј м°ҫлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” codebook sizeмқҳ лЎңк·ёк°Җ Gaussian VAEмқҳ bits-back coding rateлҘј мҙҲкіјн•ҳл©ҙ мһ‘мқҖ quantization errorк°Җ ліҙмһҘлҗЁмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨл¬ҙм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё ліҖнҷҳмқ„ мң„н•ҙ Gaussian VAEлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” heuristicмқё target divergence constraint (TDC)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң GQлҠ” UNet л°Ҹ ViT architecture лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң VQGAN, FSQ, LFQ, BSQмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ кё°мЎҙ VQ-VAEлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң TDCлҠ” TokenBridgeмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ кё°мЎҙ Gaussian VAE discretization л°©лІ•лҸ„ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. source codeлҠ” supplementary materialм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60808","en":"PISCES: Annotation-free Text-to-Video Post-Training via Optimal Transport-Aligned Rewards","ko":"PISCES: Optimal Transport м •л ¬ ліҙмғҒмқ„ нҶөн•ң мЈјм„қ м—ҶлҠ” Text-to-Video мӮ¬нӣ„ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Minh-Quan Le, Gaurav Mittal, Cheng Zhao, Xianfeng GU, Samaras Dimitris, Mei Chen","pos":"#2600","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=wSfc8mDEjM","abs":"Text-to-video (T2V) generation aims to synthesize videos with high visual quality and temporal consistency that are semantically aligned with input text. Reward-based post-training has emerged as a promising direction to improve the quality and semantic alignment of generated videos. However, recent methods either rely on large-scale human preference annotations or operate on misaligned embeddings from pre-trained vision-language models, leading to limited scalability or suboptimal supervision. We present $\\texttt{PISCES}$, an annotation-free post-training algorithm that addresses these limitations via a novel Dual Optimal Transport (OT)-aligned Rewards module. To align reward signals with human judgment, $\\texttt{PISCES}$ uses OT to bridge text and video embeddings at both distributional and discrete token levels, enabling reward supervision to fulfill two objectives: (i) a Distributional OT-aligned Quality Reward that captures overall visual quality and temporal coherence; and (ii) a Discrete Token-level OT-aligned Semantic Reward that enforces semantic, spatio-temporal correspondence between text and video tokens. To our knowledge, $\\texttt{PISCES}$ is the first to improve annotation-free reward supervision in generative post-training through the lens of OT. Experiments on both short- and long-video generation show that $\\texttt{PISCES}$ outperforms both annotation-based and annotation-free methods on VBench across Quality and Semantic scores, with human preference studies further validating its effectiveness. We show that the Dual OT-aligned Rewards module is compatible with multiple optimization paradigms, including direct backpropagation and reinforcement learning fine-tuning.","absKo":"Text-to-video (T2V) generationмқҖ мһ…л Ҙ textмҷҖ мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎң м •л ¬лҗң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҳ visual qualityмҷҖ temporal consistencyлҘј к°Җм§„ videoлҘј н•©м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. reward-based post-trainingмқҖ мғқм„ұлҗң videoмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳкіј semantic alignmentлҘј лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң л– мҳ¬лһҗлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мөңк·ј л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ human preference annotationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ pre-trained vision-language modelм—җм„ң лӮҳмҳЁ misaligned embeddingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ, нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқҳ н•ңкі„ лҳҗлҠ” мөңм Ғ мқҙн•ҳмқҳ supervisionмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Dual Optimal Transport (OT)-aligned Rewards moduleмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” annotation-free post-training algorithmмқё $\\texttt{PISCES}$лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. reward signalмқ„ human judgmentмҷҖ м •л ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, $\\texttt{PISCES}$лҠ” OTлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ distributional levelкіј discrete token level лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң textмҷҖ video embeddingмқ„ м—°кІ°н•ҳл©°, reward supervisionмқҙ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ лӘ©н‘ңлҘј м¶©мЎұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ: (i) м „мІҙм Ғмқё visual qualityмҷҖ temporal coherenceлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” Distributional OT-aligned Quality Reward, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (ii) textмҷҖ video token мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ semantic, spatio-temporal correspondenceлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” Discrete Token-level OT-aligned Semantic Reward. мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м•„лҠ” н•ң, $\\texttt{PISCES}$лҠ” OT кҙҖм җм—җм„ң generative post-trainingмқҳ annotation-free reward supervisionмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁ мөңмҙҲмқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. short-videoмҷҖ long-video generation лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ $\\texttt{PISCES}$к°Җ VBenchмқҳ Quality л°Ҹ Semantic scoreм—җм„ң annotation-based л°©лІ•кіј annotation-free л°©лІ• лӘЁл‘җлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, human preference studyк°Җ к·ё нҡЁкіјлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң мһ…мҰқн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Dual OT-aligned Rewards moduleмқҙ direct backpropagationкіј reinforcement learning fine-tuningмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м—¬лҹ¬ optimization paradigmкіј нҳёнҷҳлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"61197","en":"Personalized Image Generation via Human-in-the-loop Bayesian Optimization","ko":"Human-in-the-Loop Bayesian Optimizationмқ„ нҶөн•ң к°ңмқёнҷ” мқҙлҜём§Җ мғқм„ұ","authors":"Rajalaxmi Rajagopalan, Debottam Dutta, Yu-Lin Wei, Romit Roy Choudhury","pos":"#2601","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=sq3JUR4IDd","abs":"Imagine Alice has a specific image $x^\\ast$ in her mind, say, the view of the street in which she grew up during her childhood. To generate that exact image, she guides a generative model with multiple rounds of prompting and arrives at an image $x^{p*}$. Although $x^{p*}$ is reasonably close to $x^\\ast$, Alice finds it difficult to close that gap using language prompts. This paper aims to narrow this gap by observing that even after language has reached its limits, humans can still tell when a new image $x^+$ is closer to $x^\\ast$ than $x^{p*}$.  Leveraging this observation, we develop **MultiBO** (Multi-Choice Preferential Bayesian Optimization) that carefully generates $K$ new images as a function of $x^{p*}$, gets preferential feedback from the user, uses the feedback to guide the diffusion model, and ultimately generates a new set of $K$ images. We show that within $B$ rounds of user feedback, it is possible to arrive much closer to $x^\\ast$, even though the generative model has no information about $x^\\ast$. Qualitative scores from $30$ users, combined with quantitative metrics compared across $5$ baselines, show promising results, suggesting that multi-choice feedback from humans can be effectively harnessed for personalized image generation.","absKo":"м•ЁлҰ¬мҠӨк°Җ л§ҲмқҢмҶҚм—җ нҠ№м •н•ң мқҙлҜём§Җ $x^\\ast$, мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ м–ҙлҰ° мӢңм Ҳ мһҗлһҖ кұ°лҰ¬мқҳ н’ҚкІҪмқ„ л– мҳ¬лҰ°лӢӨкі  н•ҳмһҗ. к·ё м •нҷ•н•ң мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, к·ёл…ҖлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ м°ЁлЎҖмқҳ promptingмңјлЎң generative modelмқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳкі  мқҙлҜём§Җ $x^{p*}$м—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ңлӢӨ. $x^{p*}$лҠ” $x^\\ast$м—җ кҪӨ к°Җк№қм§Җл§Ң, м•ЁлҰ¬мҠӨлҠ” м–ём–ҙ promptл§ҢмңјлЎң к·ё к°„к·№мқ„ лҚ” мўҒнһҲкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨкі  лҠҗлӮҖлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ м–ём–ҙк°Җ н•ңкі„м—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ң л’Өм—җлҸ„, мӮ¬лһҢл“Өмқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мқҙлҜём§Җ $x^+$к°Җ $x^{p*}$ліҙлӢӨ $x^\\ast$м—җ лҚ” к°Җк№қлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ м—¬м „нһҲ нҢҗлӢЁн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” кҙҖм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬ к·ё к°„к·№мқ„ мӨ„мқҙкі мһҗ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм°°мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” **MultiBO** (Multi-Choice Preferential Bayesian Optimization)лҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. MultiBOлҠ” $x^{p*}$мқҳ н•ЁмҲҳлЎңм„ң $K$к°ңмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј мӢ мӨ‘н•ҳкІҢ мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлЎңл¶Җн„° preference feedbackмқ„ л°ӣмқҖ л’Ө, к·ё н”јл“ңл°ұмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ diffusion modelмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳл©°, к¶Ғк·№м ҒмңјлЎң $K$к°ңмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мқҙлҜём§Җ м§‘н•©мқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” $B$ лқјмҡҙл“ңмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ н”јл“ңл°ұ м•Ҳм—җ, generative modelмқҙ $x^\\ast$м—җ лҢҖн•ң м •ліҙлҘј м „нҳҖ к°–кі  мһҲм§Җ м•ҠлҚ”лқјлҸ„, $x^\\ast$м—җ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” к°Җк№қкІҢ лҸ„лӢ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. 30лӘ…мқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлЎңл¶Җн„° м–»мқҖ qualitative scoreмҷҖ 5к°ңмқҳ baselineкіј л№„көҗн•ң quantitative metricмқҖ кі л¬ҙм Ғмқё кІ°кіјлҘј ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, мӮ¬лһҢмқҳ multi-choice feedbackмқ„ personalized image generationм—җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64344","en":"PolyFlow: Safe and Efficient Polytope-Constrained Flow Matching with Constraint Embedding and Projection-free Update","ko":"PolyFlow: м ңм•Ҫ мһ„лІ л”© л°Ҹ нҲ¬мҳҒ л¶Ҳн•„мҡ” м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҘј нҶөн•ң м•Ҳм „н•ҳкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё нҸҙлҰ¬нҶ н”„ м ңм•Ҫ нқҗлҰ„ л§Өм№ӯ","authors":"Jianming Ma, Qiyue Yang, Yang Zhang, Liyun Yan, Zhanxiang Cao, Yazhou Zhang, Yue Gao","pos":"#2602","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OXLYBkYs4X","abs":"<p>While flow-based generative models have demonstrated strong performance across a wide range of domains, deploying them in safety-critical physical systems remains challenging due to strict constraint requirements. Existing approaches typically enforce safety through post-hoc corrections, which incur substantial computational overhead and may distort the learned distribution. We propose PolyFlow, a polytope-constrained flow matching framework that embeds constraints directly into the model and flow dynamics. PolyFlow introduces a discrete-time flow formulation and a projection-free architecture, which eliminate the numeration error and guarantee strict satisfaction of arbitrary polyhedral constraints, without the need for expensive iterative solvers. Experimental results show that PolyFlow achieves zero constraint violation while maintaining high distributional fidelity across a range of planning and control tasks. Compared to state-of-the-art constrained generation baselines, PolyFlow significantly reduces inference latency and demonstrates a favorable trade-off between safety, efficiency, and generative quality.</p>","absKo":"<p>flow-based generative modelмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, м—„кІ©н•ң constraint мҡ”кө¬мӮ¬н•ӯ л•Ңл¬ём—җ safety-critical physical systemм—җ л°°нҸ¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ ліҙнҶө post-hoc correctionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ safetyлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мғҒлӢ№н•ң кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳкі  н•ҷмҠөлҗң л¶„нҸ¬лҘј мҷңкіЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м ңм•Ҫмқ„ modelкіј flow dynamicsм—җ м§Ғм ‘ лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” polytope-constrained flow matching frameworkмқё PolyFlowлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. PolyFlowлҠ” discrete-time flow formulationкіј projection-free architectureлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ numeration errorлҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳкі , л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° iterative solver м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ мһ„мқҳмқҳ polyhedral constraintлҘј м—„кІ©нһҲ л§ҢмЎұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј PolyFlowлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ distributional fidelityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лӘЁл“  constraint violationмқ„ 0мңјлЎң лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. planning л°Ҹ control task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art constrained generation baselineкіј л№„көҗн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң, PolyFlowлҠ” inference latencyлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқҙкі  safety, efficiency, generative quality мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң мң лҰ¬н•ң trade-offлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62923","en":"Pose-ICL: 3D-Aware In-Context Learning for Pose-Controllable Subject Customization","ko":"Pose-ICL: мһҗм„ё м ңм–ҙ мЈјмІҙ м»ӨмҠӨн„°л§Ҳмқҙм§•мқ„ мң„н•ң 3D-Aware In-Context Learning","authors":"Xuan Han, Yihao Zhao, Mingyu You","pos":"#2603","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=boZd8pG5E2","abs":"<p>Subject Customization is a foundational task in modern image generation. By providing a few reference images and a text prompt, users can generate images of a specific object in any desired scene. However, existing methods still struggle to achieve effective pose control for customized subjects. In practice, they often exhibit inaccurate poses or inconsistent cross-pose appearances. These limitations suggest that understanding objects in a volumetric manner remains a significant challenge for 2D-native backbones. To address this challenge, we propose Pose-ICL, a tuning-free framework that leverages 3D-aware In-Context Learning (ICL) to directly adapt to new subjects through multiple paired image-pose references. Its core mechanism, Surface-Anchored Position Embedding (SAPE), equips the model with explicit 3D awareness by anchoring image tokens to the surface coordinates of a volumetric bounding box. Dedicated refinements ensure its seamless compatibility with existing DiT models. Extensive evaluations on both 3D assets and real-world subjects demonstrate that Pose-ICL significantly outperforms current methods in both pose accuracy and identity consistency.</p>","absKo":"Subject CustomizationмқҖ нҳ„лҢҖ image generationмқҳ кё°ліём Ғмқё мһ‘м—…мқҙлӢӨ. лӘҮ мһҘмқҳ reference imageмҷҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё promptлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©ҙ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлҠ” мӣҗн•ҳлҠ” м–ҙл–Ө мһҘл©ҙм—җм„ңл“  нҠ№м • к°қмІҙмқҳ мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ customized subjectм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё pose controlмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” л¶Җм •нҷ•н•ң poseлӮҳ pose к°„ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” appearanceлҘј мһҗмЈј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҠ” к°қмІҙлҘј volumetricн•ҳкІҢ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ 2D-native backboneм—җкІҢ м—¬м „нһҲ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң лҸ„м „мһ„мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лҸ„м „мқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ paired image-pose referenceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ subjectм—җ м§Ғм ‘ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° 3D-aware In-Context Learning (ICL)мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” tuning-free frameworkмқё Pose-ICLмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё н•өмӢ¬ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқё Surface-Anchored Position Embedding (SAPE)мқҖ image tokenмқ„ volumetric bounding boxмқҳ surface coordinateм—җ кі м •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лӘЁлҚём—җ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё 3D мқёмӢқмқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ңлӢӨ. м „мҡ© refinementлҠ” кё°мЎҙ DiT лӘЁлҚёкіјмқҳ л§ӨлҒ„лҹ¬мҡҙ нҳёнҷҳм„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. 3D assetкіј real-world subject лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҠ” Pose-ICLмқҙ pose accuracyмҷҖ identity consistency м–‘мӘҪм—җм„ң нҳ„мһ¬ л°©лІ•мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66180","en":"Primal-Spectral Generative Modeling: Fast Analytical Generation via Pseudoinverse LГ©vy Inversion","ko":"Primal-Spectral мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ: мң мӮ¬м—ӯн–үл ¬ LГ©vy м—ӯліҖнҷҳмқ„ нҶөн•ң л№ лҘё н•ҙм„қм Ғ мғқм„ұ","authors":"Zhiyuan Ouyang, Simei Huang, Zuokai Wen, Xiangyun Zhang, Junchi Yan","pos":"#2605","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=62GA9BSI5t","abs":"A probability distribution $\\mathbb{P}$ is a measure on a $\\sigma$-algebra, assigning mass to sets rather than points. This poses a challenge for the training of neural networks, which often struggle to reconstruct the global topology of continuous manifolds from sparse samples. We mitigate this issue by innovatively transforming $\\mathbb{P}$ into a continuous function via spectral methods, providing theoretical guarantees for the convergence of the learned distribution to the true distribution. Specifically, we introduce a network, PriSpecNet, with a single-function evaluation (1-NFE) Pseudoinverse LГ©vy Inversion (PiLI) solver that regards generation as a fast analytical problem, eliminating the need for iterative numerical integration. By reformulating the generation in the spectral domain, we bypass the computationally expensive sampling trajectory while maintaining full compatibility with the stochastic interpolants. We test our PriSpecNet in two applications. For time series, it unifies generation and forecasting, outperforming state-of-the-art (SOTA) baselines with Context-FID reductions of 50.0\\%, 41.5\\%, 80.6\\%, and 63.1\\% on Sines, Solar, ETTh, and Stock benchmarks, respectively, also decreasing forecasting MSE by 29.8\\% on Solar and 23.8\\% on Stock. For vision on ImageNet $256 \\times 256$, 1-NFE PiLI achieves a competitive FID of **1.66** using only **26** Gflops, representing a **170**  $\\times$ reduction in total Gflops compared to the 4,436 Gflops required by the advanced 25-NFE DPM-Solver++.","absKo":"нҷ•лҘ л¶„нҸ¬ \\(\\mathbb{P}\\)лҠ” \\(\\sigma\\)-algebra мң„мқҳ measureлЎңм„ң, м җмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј м§‘н•©м—җ massлҘј н• лӢ№н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” sparse sampleлЎңл¶Җн„° continuous manifoldмқҳ global topologyлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° neural networkк°Җ мў…мў… м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” м җм—җм„ң, neural network н•ҷмҠөм—җ лҸ„м „мқҙ лҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” spectral methodлҘј нҶөн•ҙ \\(\\mathbb{P}\\)лҘј м—°мҶҚ н•ЁмҲҳлЎң нҳҒмӢ м ҒмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкі , н•ҷмҠөлҗң л¶„нҸ¬к°Җ м§„м§ң л¶„нҸ¬лЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ңлӢӨлҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” generationмқ„ л№ лҘё analytical problemмңјлЎң к°„мЈјн•ҳлҠ” single-function evaluation (1-NFE) Pseudoinverse LГ©vy Inversion (PiLI) solverлҘј к°–м¶ҳ л„ӨнҠёмӣҢнҒ¬ PriSpecNetмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, л°ҳліөм Ғмқё мҲҳм№ҳм Ғл¶„мқҳ н•„мҡ”лҘј м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. spectral domainм—җм„ң generationмқ„ мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, stochastic interpolantмҷҖмқҳ мҷ„м „н•ң нҳёнҷҳм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° sampling trajectoryлҘј мҡ°нҡҢн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PriSpecNetмқ„ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ applicationм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. time seriesмқҳ кІҪмҡ°, мқҙлҠ” generationкіј forecastingмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳл©° Sines, Solar, ETTh, Stock benchmarkм—җм„ң Context-FIDлҘј к°Ғк°Ғ 50.0\\%, 41.5\\%, 80.6\\%, 63.1\\% к°җмҶҢмӢңмјң state-of-the-art (SOTA) baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкі , SolarмҷҖ Stockм—җм„ң forecasting MSEлҘј к°Ғк°Ғ 29.8\\%мҷҖ 23.8\\% лӮ®м¶ҳлӢӨ. ImageNet \\(256 \\times 256\\)м—җ лҢҖн•ң vision settingм—җм„ңлҠ” 1-NFE PiLIк°Җ лӢЁм§Җ **26** Gflopsл§Ңмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” FID **1.66**мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” кі кёү 25-NFE DPM-Solver++м—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң 4,436 GflopsмҷҖ л№„көҗн•ҙ мҙқ GflopsлҘј **170** \\(\\times\\) мӨ„мқё кІғмқҙлӢӨ."},{"id":"61130","en":"Principled RL for Flow Matching Emerges From the Chunk-level Policy Optimization","ko":"Chunk-Level Policy Optimizationм—җм„ң л“ұмһҘн•ҳлҠ” Flow Matchingмқ„ мң„н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғ RL","authors":"Yifu Luo, Haoyuan Sun, Xinhao Hu, Penghui Du, Keyu Fan, Bo Li, Sinan Du, Xu Wan, Zhiyu Chen, Bo Xia, Tiantian Zhang, Yongzhe Chang, Kai Wu, Kun Gai, Xueqian Wang","pos":"#2606","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tPd6GmXPbd","abs":"Recent Progress in post-training flow matching for text-to-image (T2I) generation with Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) has demonstrated strong potential. However, it is hindered by a critical limitation: inaccurate advantage attribution. In this work, we argue that aggregating consecutive timesteps into a coherent `chunk' and shifting the policy optimization paradigm from GRPO's step level to the chunk level can effectively mitigate the negative impact of this issue. Building on this insight, we propose Group Chunking Policy Optimization (GCPO), the first chunk-level reinforcement learning approach for post-training flow matching. Extensive experiments demonstrate that GCPO achieves superior performance on both standard T2I benchmarks and preference alignment, with up to $43\\%$ additional gains over GRPO, highlighting the promise of chunk-level policy optimization.","absKo":"н…ҚмҠӨнҠё-мқҙлҜём§Җ(T2I) generationмқ„ мң„н•ң post-training flow matchingм—җм„ң Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң мөңк·јмқҳ м§„м „мқҖ к°•н•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҠ” л¶Җм •нҷ•н•ң advantage attributionмқҙлқјлҠ” м№ҳлӘ…м Ғмқё н•ңкі„м—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңм•ҪлҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” м—°мҶҚлҗң timestepмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗң `chunk'лЎң м§‘кі„н•ҳкі , policy optimization paradigmмқ„ GRPOмқҳ step levelм—җм„ң chunk levelлЎң мқҙлҸҷмӢңнӮӨл©ҙ мқҙ л¬ём ңмқҳ л¶Җм •м Ғ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” post-training flow matchingмқ„ мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ chunk-level reinforcement learning м ‘к·јлІ•мқё Group Chunking Policy Optimization (GCPO)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ GCPOк°Җ н‘ңмӨҖ T2I benchmarkмҷҖ preference alignment лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, GRPO лҢҖл№„ мөңлҢҖ $43\\%$мқҳ м¶”к°Җ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ҙ, chunk-level policy optimizationмқҳ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"65268","en":"SJD-SV: Speculative Jacobi Decoding with Semantics Verification for Autoregressive Image Generation","ko":"SJD-SV: мһҗкё°нҡҢк·Җ мқҙлҜём§Җ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мқҳлҜё кІҖмҰқ кё°л°ҳ Speculative Jacobi Decoding","authors":"Baoquan Zhang, Bingqi Shan, Shihao Fang, Kenghong Lin, Xutao Li, Yunming Ye","pos":"#2611","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FECofldBP8","abs":"<p>Speculative Jacobi Decoding (SJD) is an important approach for accelerating autoregressive image generation. Although SJD has shown superior performance, recent studies point out that it usually suffers from a token ambiguity issue during token verification but its reason can not be well explained. To figure out this reason,  in this paper, we conduct a visualization analysis on vision token and find that different from text tokens, vision tokens generally corresponds to some local, small, and unclear vision details, which means only using single token is difficult to accurately express a certain semantic, thereby causing token ambiguity issue. To this end, we propose a novel Speculative Jacobi Decoding with Semantics Verification (called SJD-SV), for accelerating autoregressive image generation.  The key idea is that leveraging the strong correction characters between tokens to recognize semantic-aware token subsequence and then instead of perform token-by-token verification, turning to perform verification on semantic-aware token subsequence level for accelerating image generation. In particular, our method is plug-in, which can be directly integrated into existing SJD and its variants. Extensive experiments on various datasets show that existing SJD methods achieve significant performance improvement after integrating our SJD-SV method.</p>","absKo":"<p>Speculative Jacobi Decoding (SJD)мқҖ autoregressive image generationмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙлӢӨ. SJDлҠ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, мөңк·ј м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ token verification кіјм •м—җм„ң token ambiguity л¬ём ңлҘј мһҗмЈј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨкі  м§Җм Ғн•ҙ мҷ”мңјлӮҳ, к·ё мқҙмң лҠ” м¶©л¶„нһҲ м„ӨлӘ…лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӣҗмқёмқ„ л°қнһҲкё° мң„н•ҙ, ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” vision tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢңк°Ғнҷ” л¶„м„қмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , text tokenкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬ vision tokenмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мқјл¶Җ көӯмҶҢм Ғмқҙкі  мһ‘мңјл©° л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н•ң мӢңк°Ғм Ғ м„ёл¶Җ м •ліҙм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лӢЁмқј tokenл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” нҠ№м • semanticмқ„ м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ мқҳлҜён•ҳл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј token ambiguity л¬ём ңк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” autoregressive image generationмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Speculative Jacobi Decoding with Semantics Verification, мҰү SJD-SVлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҠ” token к°„мқҳ к°•н•ң correction characteristicsлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ semantic-aware token subsequenceлҘј мқёмӢқн•ҳкі , token-by-token verification лҢҖмӢ  semantic-aware token subsequence мҲҳмӨҖм—җм„ң verificationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ image generationмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ plug-in л°©мӢқмңјлЎң, кё°мЎҙ SJD л°Ҹ к·ё ліҖнҳ•л“Өм—җ м§Ғм ‘ нҶөн•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ кё°мЎҙ SJD л°©лІ•л“Өмқҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ SJD-SV л°©лІ•мқ„ нҶөн•©н•ң л’Ө нҳ„м Җн•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62834","en":"Semantic-Aware Motion Encoding for Topology-Agnostic Character Animation","ko":"Topology-Agnostic мәҗлҰӯн„° Animationмқ„ мң„н•ң Semantic-Aware Motion Encoding","authors":"Zongye Zhang, Yuzhuo Cui, Qingjie Liu, Yunhong Wang","pos":"#2612","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cmFlwBI4Ov","abs":"<p>Generalizing motion representation across diverse characters remains challenging due to significant topological variations in skeletal structures across datasets and species, which hinders the development of scalable generative models. To bridge this gap, we propose a Semantic-Aware Topology-Agnostic framework that learns a unified latent manifold shared by disparate species. Unlike methods relying on fixed hierarchies or rigid padding strategies, our approach leverages a semantic modulation mechanism to align functional joint correspondences, thereby decoupling motion from topology. This design enables the construction of a continuous, generative-friendly motion space from large-scale, unaligned raw BVH data. Experiments on human and animal datasets demonstrate that our framework achieves high-fidelity reconstruction and supports downstream text-to-motion tasks. Notably, the model unlocks emergent capabilities, enabling zero-shot cross-species retargeting without paired data.</p>","absKo":"<p>лӢӨм–‘н•ң мәҗлҰӯн„° м „л°ҳмңјлЎң motion representationмқ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣкіј мў…(species) к°„ skeletal structureмқҳ мғҒлӢ№н•ң topological variation л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өкі , мқҙлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң generative modelмқҳ к°ңл°ңмқ„ м Җн•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё мў…мқҙ кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© latent manifoldлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” Semantic-Aware Topology-Agnostic frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кі м •лҗң hierarchyлӮҳ кІҪм§Ғлҗң padding strategyм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•кіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ semantic modulation mechanismмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ кё°лҠҘм Ғ joint correspondenceлҘј м •л ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ motionмқ„ topologyмҷҖ л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁмқҳ м •л ¬лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ raw BVH dataлЎңл¶Җн„° м—°мҶҚм Ғмқҙкі  generative-friendlyн•ң motion spaceлҘј кө¬м¶•н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқёк°„ л°Ҹ лҸҷл¬ј лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkк°Җ лҶ’мқҖ fidelityмқҳ reconstructionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  downstream text-to-motion taskлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, мқҙ modelмқҖ emergent capabilityлҘј м—ҙм–ҙ мЈјм–ҙ, paired data м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ zero-shot cross-species retargetingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62660","en":"Speculative Coupled Decoding for Training-Free Lossless Acceleration of Autoregressive Visual Generation","ko":"Training-Free Lossless Acceleration of Autoregressive Visual Generationмқ„ мң„н•ң Speculative Coupled Decoding","authors":"Junhyuk So, Hyunho Kook, Chaeyeon Jang, Eunhyeok Park","pos":"#2613","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ea4sx1kxDz","abs":"<p>Autoregressive (AR) modeling has recently emerged as a promising new paradigm in visual generation, but its practical adoption is severely constrained by the slow inference speed of per-token generation, which often requires thousands of steps to produce a single sample. While several Speculative Decoding (SD)-based methods have been proposed to solve this problem by generating multiple tokens in a single forward step, they suffer from limited speedup, degraded quality, or require the training of a draft model. To solve these problems, we propose a new training-free, lossless SD framework, Speculative Coupled Decoding (SCD), by extending the recently proposed Speculative Jacobi Decoding (SJD). While SJD shows strong potential for accelerating AR generation by combining Jacobi iteration and SD, we found that its acceptance rate is still significantly limited due to the instability arising from the independent sampling process used during draft token generation. To overcome this, we introduce an information-theoretic approach, Coupling, which stabilizes the drafting trajectory of SJD by maximizing the probability of sampling identical draft tokens across consecutive iterations, significantly enhancing the acceptance rate while preserving its lossless property. Remarkably, this method requires only a single-line modification to the existing algorithm with almost zero overhead, yet achieves substantial performance gains, delivering up to a 4.2Г— speedup in image generation and 13.6Г— speedup in video generation compared to standard AR decoding, without any degradation or the need for additional training.</p>","absKo":"<p>Autoregressive (AR) modelingмқҖ мөңк·ј visual generationм—җм„ң мң л§қн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҶ нҒ°лі„ мғқм„ұмқҳ лҠҗлҰ° inference мҶҚлҸ„ л•Ңл¬ём—җ мӢӨм ң м Ғмҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кІҢ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ л°©мӢқмқҖ мў…мў… лӢЁмқј sampleмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мҲҳмІң stepмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ Speculative Decoding (SD)-кё°л°ҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ н•ң лІҲмқҳ forward stepм—җм„ң м—¬лҹ¬ tokenмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҙ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкі мһҗ м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, speedupмқҙ м ңн•ңм Ғмқҙкұ°лӮҳ qualityк°Җ м Җн•ҳлҗҳкұ°лӮҳ draft modelмқҳ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңк·ј м ңм•Ҳлҗң Speculative Jacobi Decoding (SJD)мқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм—¬ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ training-free, lossless SD frameworkмқё Speculative Coupled Decoding (SCD)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SJDлҠ” Jacobi iterationкіј SDлҘј кІ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ AR generation к°ҖмҶҚм—җ к°•н•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, draft token мғқм„ұ мӨ‘ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” лҸ…лҰҪ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғ кіјм •м—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” instability л•Ңл¬ём—җ acceptance rateк°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ нҒ¬кІҢ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—°мҶҚ iteration мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң лҸҷмқјн•ң draft tokenмқ„ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•  нҷ•лҘ мқ„ мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ SJDмқҳ drafting trajectoryлҘј м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкі  acceptance rateлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ lossless propertyлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” information-theoretic approachмқё Couplingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„ мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ кё°мЎҙ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳм—җ н•ң мӨ„л§Ң мҲҳм •н•ҳл©ҙ лҗҳл©° кұ°мқҳ м¶”к°Җ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңк°Җ м—ҶмқҢм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  мғҒлӢ№н•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ AR decodingкіј л№„көҗн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң image generationм—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ 4.2л°°, video generationм—җм„ң 13.6л°°мқҳ speedupмқ„ м¶”к°Җ н•ҷмҠөмқҙлӮҳ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳ м—Ҷмқҙ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62801","en":"The Latent Color Subspace: Emergent Order in High-Dimensional Chaos","ko":"мһ мһ¬ Color Subspace: кі м°Ёмӣҗ м№ҙмҳӨмҠӨм—җм„ңмқҳ Emergent Order","authors":"Mateusz Pach, Jessica Bader, Quentin Bouniot, Serge Belongie, Zeynep Akata","pos":"#2614","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=d93mcbLGhV","abs":"<p>Text-to-image generation models have advanced rapidly, yet achieving fine-grained control over generated images remains difficult, largely due to limited understanding of how semantic information is encoded. We develop an interpretation of the color representation in the Variational Autoencoder latent space of FLUX.1 [Dev], revealing a structure reflecting Hue, Saturation, and Lightness. We verify our Latent Color Subspace (LCS) interpretation by demonstrating that it can both predict and explicitly control color, introducing a fully training-free method in FLUX based solely on closed-form latent-space manipulation.</p>","absKo":"<p>Text-to-image generation modelмқҖ л№ лҘҙкІҢ л°ңм „н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мғқм„ұлҗң мқҙлҜём§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң fine-grained controlмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. к·ё мЈјлҗң мқҙмң лҠ” semantic informationмқҙ м–ҙл–»кІҢ encodingлҗҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙн•ҙк°Җ м ңн•ңм Ғмқҙкё° л•Ңл¬ёмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FLUX.1 [Dev]мқҳ Variational Autoencoder latent spaceм—җм„ң color representationм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•ҙм„қмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬, Hue, Saturation, LightnessлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ” кө¬мЎ°лҘј л°қнҳҖлғ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Latent Color Subspace (LCS) н•ҙм„қмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мқҙ н•ҙм„қмқҙ colorлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„ лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙн•  мҲҳлҸ„ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, closed-form latent-space manipulationл§Ңмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң мҷ„м „н•ң training-free л°©лІ•мқ„ FLUXм—җ лҸ„мһ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66004","en":"Unpaired Visual Editing with Self-Consistent Flow Matching","ko":"мһҗкё° мқјкҙҖ Flow Matchingмқ„ нҶөн•ң м§қ м—ҶлҠ” мӢңк°Ғ нҺём§‘","authors":"Yoad Tewel, Yuval Atzmon, Gal Chechik, Lior Wolf","pos":"#2615","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=80gMhZMWZy","abs":"<p>Modern generative models possess a deep understanding of visual content, yet training them for image editing typically requires massive datasets of paired examples. This limits scalability, especially for video editing where collecting paired data is prohibitively expensive. We propose a general framework for unpaired training of flow matching editing models. It leverages the base model's knowledge without any external signal. Our approach pairs instruction-following cues extracted from the frozen model with cycle-consistency for structure preservation. To make this tractable, we propose to route gradients from downstream losses over clean predictions to noisy training states. We demonstrate state-of-the-art results on challenging data-scarce image and video editing scenarios. Extensive evaluations and user studies show that our method effectively generalizes to unseen domains and outperforms supervised baselines trained on millions of samples. Analysis reveals that our gradient routing bridges the train-inference gap, and extracting semantic cues from a base model provides a robust training signal that obviates the need for external reward models.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖмқҳ generative modelмқҖ visual contentлҘј к№Ҡмқҙ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, image editingмқ„ мң„н•ҙ н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨл Өл©ҙ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң paired exampleмқҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ datasetмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ҳл©°, нҠ№нһҲ paired data мҲҳм§‘ л№„мҡ©мқҙ м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ нҒ° video editingм—җм„ңлҠ” лҚ”мҡұ к·ёл ҮлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӮ¬м „ мӢ нҳё мҷёл¶Җмқҳ м–ҙл–Ө мӢ нҳёлҸ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  base modelмқҳ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ”, unpaired trainingмқ„ мң„н•ң мқјл°ҳм Ғ frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ frozen modelм—җм„ң м¶”м¶ңн•ң instruction-following cueмҷҖ structure preservationмқ„ мң„н•ң cycle-consistencyлҘј кІ°н•©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј tractableн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өкё° мң„н•ҙ, downstream lossм—җм„ң лӮҳмҳЁ gradientлҘј clean predictionмқ„ кұ°міҗ noisy training stateлЎң м „лӢ¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лқјмҡ°нҢ…н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң к№ҢлӢӨлЎңмҡҙ image л°Ҹ video editing мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң state-of-the-art кІ°кіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖмҷҖ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м—°кө¬лҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң domainмңјлЎңлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳл©°, мҲҳл°ұл§Ң к°ң sampleлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң supervised baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. л¶„м„қ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ gradient routingмқҖ train-inference gapмқ„ л©”мҡ°кі , base modelм—җм„ң semantic cueлҘј м¶”м¶ңн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ мҷёл¶Җ reward modelмқҙ н•„мҡ” м—ҶлҠ” кІ¬кі н•ң training signalмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64035","en":"FunPhase: A Periodic Functional Autoencoder for Motion Generation via Phase Manifolds","ko":"FunPhase: мң„мғҒ л§ӨлӢҲнҸҙл“ңлҘј нҶөн•ң лӘЁм…ҳ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мЈјкё°м Ғ н•ЁмҲҳнҳ• мҳӨнҶ мқёмҪ”лҚ”","authors":"Marco Pegoraro, Evan Atherton, Bruno Roy, Aliasghar Khani, Arianna Rampini","pos":"#2707","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RWQiuD7RHP","abs":"<p>Learning natural body motion remains challenging due to the strong coupling between spatial geometry and temporal dynamics. Embedding motion in phase manifolds, latent spaces that capture local periodicity, has proven effective for motion prediction; however, existing approaches lack scalability and remain confined to specific settings. We introduce FunPhase, a functional periodic autoencoder that learns a phase manifold for motion and replaces discrete temporal decoding with a function-space formulation, enabling smooth trajectories that can be sampled at arbitrary temporal resolutions. FunPhase unifies motion prediction and generation within a single interpretable phase manifold, enabling motion generation via latent diffusion, generalizes across skeletons and datasets, and supports downstream tasks such as motion super-resolution and partial-body completion. Our model achieves substantially lower reconstruction error than prior periodic autoencoder baselines, achieving uniform improvements of at least 45% across all metrics, while enabling a broader range of applications and performing on par with state-of-the-art motion generation methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ body motionмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ spatial geometryмҷҖ temporal dynamics мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°•н•ң кІ°н•© л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. local periodicityлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” latent spaceмқё phase manifoldм—җ motionмқ„ embeddingн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҖ motion predictionм—җ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё кІғмңјлЎң мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳкі  нҠ№м • м„Өм •м—җл§Ң м ңн•ңлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” motionмқ„ мң„н•ң phase manifoldлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  discrete temporal decodingмқ„ function-space formulationмңјлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ҳлҠ” functional periodic autoencoderмқё FunPhaseлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мһ„мқҳмқҳ temporal resolutionм—җм„ң мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” л¶Җл“ңлҹ¬мҡҙ trajectoryлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. FunPhaseлҠ” motion predictionкіј generationмқ„ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң phase manifold м•Ҳм—җм„ң нҶөн•©н•ҳкі , latent diffusionмқ„ нҶөн•ң motion generationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, skeletonкіј dataset м „л°ҳмңјлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗҳкі , motion super-resolution л°Ҹ partial-body completionкіј к°ҷмқҖ downstream taskлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ modelмқҖ мқҙм „ periodic autoencoder baselineліҙлӢӨ reconstruction errorк°Җ мғҒлӢ№нһҲ лӮ®мңјл©°, лӘЁл“  metricм—җм„ң мөңмҶҢ 45%мқҳ мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ лҚ” л„“мқҖ лІ”мң„мқҳ applicationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі  state-of-the-art motion generation methodмҷҖ лҸҷл“ұн•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64244","en":"Enhancing Train-Free Infinite-Frame Generation for Consistent Long Videos","ko":"мқјкҙҖлҗң кёҙ мҳҒмғҒмқ„ мң„н•ң н•ҷмҠө л¶Ҳн•„мҡ” л¬ҙн•ң н”„л Ҳмһ„ мғқм„ұ к°•нҷ”","authors":"xiaokun Feng, Jiashu Zhu, Meiqi Wu, Chubin Chen, Fangyuan Mao, Haiyang Guo, Jiahong Wu, Xiangxiang Chu, Kaiqi Huang","pos":"#2710","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PasiyntPbd","abs":"<p>Without incurring significant computational overhead, train-free long video generation aims to enable foundation video generation models to produce longer videos. Frame-level autoregressive frameworks, e.g., FIFO-diffusion, offer the advantage of generating infinitely long videos with constant memory consumption. However, the mismatch between training and inference, coupled with the challenge of maintaining long-term consistency, limits the effective utilization of foundation models.  To mitigate these concerns, we propose MIGA, a novel infinite-frame long video generation method.  Firstly, we propose an effective two-stage alignment mechanism that mitigates the training-inference gap by reducing the excessive noise span fed to the model. We then introduce an innovative dual consistency enhancement mechanism, where the self-reflection approach corrects early high-noise frames and the long-range frame guidance approach leverages later low-noise frames with broad coverage to steer generation, jointly improving temporal consistency.  Extensive experiments on VBench and NarrLV demonstrate the state-of-the-art performance of MIGA.</p>","absKo":"нҒ° кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ң м—Ҷмқҙ, train-free long video generationмқҖ foundation video generation modelмқҙ лҚ” кёҙ videoлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. FIFO-diffusionкіј к°ҷмқҖ frame-level autoregressive frameworkлҠ” constant memory consumptionмңјлЎң л¬ҙн•ңнһҲ кёҙ videoлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” мһҘм җмқ„ м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ trainingкіј inferenceмқҳ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мһҘкё° мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқҙ кІ°н•©лҗҳм–ҙ foundation modelмқҳ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё нҷңмҡ©мқ„ м ңн•ңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҡ°л ӨлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¬ҙн•ң frame кё°л°ҳмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ long video generation л°©лІ•мқё MIGAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚём—җ мһ…л ҘлҗҳлҠ” кіјлҸ„н•ң noise spanмқ„ мӨ„м—¬ training-inference gapмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё two-stage alignment mechanismмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ, self-reflection л°©мӢқмқҙ мҙҲкё°мқҳ high-noise frameмқ„ көҗм •н•ҳкі  long-range frame guidance л°©мӢқмқҙ нҸӯл„“мқҖ лІ”мң„лҘј к°Җм§„ мқҙнӣ„мқҳ low-noise frameмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мғқм„ұ кіјм •мқ„ мқҙлҒ„лҠ”, мғҲлЎңмҡҙ dual consistency enhancement mechanismмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л‘җ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ н•Ёк»ҳ temporal consistencyлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮөлӢҲлӢӨ. VBenchмҷҖ NarrLVм—җм„ңмқҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ MIGAмқҳ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66188","en":"Calibrating Generative Models to Distributional Constraints","ko":"мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ л¶„нҸ¬м Ғ м ңм•Ҫм—җ л§һм¶° ліҙм •н•ҳкё°","authors":"Henry Smith, Nathaniel Diamant, Brian Trippe","pos":"#2713","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5yXKRaNI2R","abs":"<p>Generative models frequently suffer miscalibration, wherein statistics of the sampling distribution such as class probabilities deviate from desired values. We frame calibration as a constrained optimization problem and seek the closest model in Kullback-Leibler divergence satisfying calibration constraints. To address the intractability of imposing these constraints exactly, we introduce two surrogate objectives for fine-tuning: (1) the relax loss, which replaces the constraint with a miscalibration penalty, and (2) the reward loss, which converts calibration into a reward fine-tuning problem. We demonstrate that these approaches substantially reduce calibration error across hundreds of simultaneous constraints and models with up to nine billion parameters, spanning applications in protein design, image generation, and language modeling.</p>","absKo":"<p>мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мһҗмЈј miscalibrationмқ„ кІӘмңјл©°, мқҙл•Ң class probability к°ҷмқҖ sampling distributionмқҳ нҶөкі„лҹүмқҙ мӣҗн•ҳлҠ” к°’м—җм„ң лІ—м–ҙлӮңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” calibrationмқ„ constrained optimization problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , calibration constraintлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•ҳлҠ” Kullback-Leibler divergence кё°мӨҖм—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ м°ҫлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ңм•Ҫмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ л¶Җкіјн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ лӢӨлЈЁкё° м–ҙл өкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, fine-tuningмқ„ мң„н•ң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ surrogate objectiveлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ: (1) constraintлҘј miscalibration penaltyлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ҳлҠ” relax loss, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (2) calibrationмқ„ reward fine-tuning л¬ём ңлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” reward loss. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ лӢЁл°ұм§Ҳ м„Өкі„, мқҙлҜём§Җ мғқм„ұ, м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғм—җ кұёміҗ, мөңлҢҖ 90м–ө нҢҢлқјлҜён„° к·ңлӘЁмқҳ лӘЁлҚёкіј мҲҳл°ұ к°ңмқҳ лҸҷмӢң м ңм•Ҫм—җм„ң calibration errorлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63728","en":"Bi-Anchor Interpolation Solver for Accelerating Generative Modeling","ko":"мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ к°ҖмҶҚмқ„ мң„н•ң Bi-Anchor Interpolation Solver","authors":"Hongxu CHEN, Hongxiang Li, Zhen Wang, Long Chen","pos":"#2714","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=UDS2siRAyT","abs":"<p>Flow Matching (FM) models have emerged as a leading paradigm for high-fidelity synthesis. However, their reliance on iterative Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) solving creates a significant latency bottleneck. Existing solutions face a dichotomy: training-free solvers suffer from significant performance degradation at low Neural Function Evaluations (NFEs), while training-based methods incur prohibitive training costs and lack plug-and-play versatility. To bridge this gap, we propose the Bi-Anchor Interpolation Solver (BA-solver). BA-solver retains the versatility of standard training-free solvers while achieving significant acceleration by introducing a lightweight SideNet (1-2% backbone size) alongside the frozen backbone. Specifically, our method is founded on two synergistic components: 1) Bidirectional Temporal Perception, where the SideNet learns to approximate both future and historical velocities without retraining the heavy backbone; and 2) Bi-Anchor Velocity Integration, which utilizes the SideNet with two anchor velocities to efficiently approximate intermediate velocities for batched high-order integration. By utilizing the backbone to establish high-precision вҖңanchorsвҖқ and the SideNet to densify the trajectory, BA-solver enables large step sizes with minimized error. Empirical results on ImageNet-256 demonstrate that BA-solver achieves generation quality comparable to 100+ NFEs Euler solver in just 10 NFEs and maintains high fidelity in as few as 5 NFEs, incurring negligible training costs. Furthermore, BA-solver ensures seamless integration with existing generative pipelines, facilitating downstream tasks such as image editing.</p>","absKo":"<p>Flow Matching (FM) modelмқҖ кі м¶©мӢӨлҸ„ synthesisмқҳ м„ лҸ„м Ғ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң л– мҳ¬лһҗлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ iterative Ordinary Differential Equation (ODE) solvingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң latency лі‘лӘ©мқҙ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ н•ҙкІ°мұ…мқҖ м–‘л¶„лҗң н•ңкі„лҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. training-free solverлҠ” лӮ®мқҖ Neural Function Evaluations (NFEs)м—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳк°Җ нҒ¬кі , training-based methodлҠ” м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ нҒ° training costмҷҖ plug-and-play versatilityмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬лқјлҠ” л¬ём ңк°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Bi-Anchor Interpolation Solver (BA-solver)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. BA-solverлҠ” кі м •лҗң backbone мҳҶм—җ кІҪлҹү SideNet(л°ұліё нҒ¬кё°мқҳ 1-2%)мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, н‘ңмӨҖ training-free solverмқҳ лӢӨмһ¬лӢӨлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мғҒлӢ№н•ң к°ҖмҶҚмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ мғҒнҳё ліҙмҷ„м Ғмқё л‘җ кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. 1) Bidirectional Temporal PerceptionмқҖ SideNetмқҙ л¬ҙкұ°мҡҙ backboneмқ„ мһ¬н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ лҜёлһҳмҷҖ кіјкұ°мқҳ velocityлҘј лӘЁл‘җ к·јмӮ¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©°, 2) Bi-Anchor Velocity IntegrationмқҖ л‘җ anchor velocityлҘј к°Җм§„ SideNetмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ batched high-order integrationмқ„ мң„н•ң мӨ‘к°„ velocityлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң к·јмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. backboneмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кі м •л°Җ вҖңanchorвҖқлҘј м„Өм •н•ҳкі  SideNetмңјлЎң trajectoryлҘј мЎ°л°Җнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, BA-solverлҠ” мҳӨм°ЁлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ң мұ„ нҒ° step sizeлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. ImageNet-256м—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨмҰқ кІ°кіјлҠ” BA-solverк°Җ 10 NFEл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ 100+ NFE Euler solverм—җ мӨҖн•ҳлҠ” мғқм„ұ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , 5 NFE м •лҸ„л§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ лҶ’мқҖ м¶©мӢӨлҸ„лҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң training costлҠ” кұ°мқҳ л“Өм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң BA-solverлҠ” кё°мЎҙ generative pipelineкіјмқҳ мӣҗнҷңн•ң нҶөн•©мқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳм—¬ image editingкіј к°ҷмқҖ downstream taskлҘј мҡ©мқҙн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63294","en":"PromptRL: Prompt Matters in RL for Flow-Based Image Generation","ko":"PromptRL: Flow кё°л°ҳ мқҙлҜём§Җ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң RLм—җм„ң н”„лЎ¬н”„нҠёк°Җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Fu-Yun Wang, Han Zhang, MichaГ«l Gharbi, Hongsheng Li, Taesung Park","pos":"#3614","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=YKamMflrv7","abs":"Flow matching models (FMs) have revolutionized text-to-image (T2I) generation, with reinforcement learning (RL) serving as a critical post-training strategy for alignment with  reward objectives. In this research, we show that current RL pipelines for FMs suffer from two underappreciated yet important limitations:  sample inefficiency due to insufficient generation diversity, and pronounced prompt overfitting, where models memorize specific training formulations and exhibit dramatic performance collapse when evaluated on semantically equivalent but stylistically varied prompts. We present \\textbf{PromptRL} (\\textbf{P}rompt \\textbf{M}atters in \\textbf{RL} for Flow-Based Image Generation), a framework that incorporates language models (LMs) as trainable prompt refinement agents directly within the flow-based RL optimization loop. This design yields two complementary benefits: rapid development of sophisticated prompt rewriting capabilities and, critically, a synergistic training regime that reshapes the optimization dynamics. PromptRL achieves state-of-the-art performance across multiple benchmarks, obtaining scores of 0.97 on GenEval, 0.98 on OCR accuracy, and 24.05 on PickScore.   Furthermore, we validate the effectiveness of our RL approach on large-scale image editing models, improving the EditReward of FLUX.1-Kontext from 1.19 to 1.43 with only 0.06 million rollouts, surpassing Gemini 2.5 Flash Image (also known as Nano Banana), which scores 1.37, and achieving comparable performance with ReasonNet (1.44), which relied on fine-grained data annotations along with a complex multi-stage training. Our extensive experiments empirically demonstrate that PromptRL consistently achieves higher performance ceilings while requiring over 2$\\times$ fewer rollouts compared to naive flow-only RL.","absKo":"Flow matching models (FMs)лҠ” text-to-image (T2I) мғқм„ұмқ„ нҳҒмӢ н–Ҳмңјл©°, reinforcement learning (RL)мқҖ ліҙмғҒ лӘ©н‘ңмҷҖмқҳ м •л ¬мқ„ мң„н•ң н•өмӢ¬ post-training м „лһөмңјлЎң мһҗлҰ¬ мһЎм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ FMsлҘј мң„н•ң RL нҢҢмқҙн”„лқјмқёмқҙ кіјмҶҢнҸүк°Җлҗҳм–ҙ мҳЁ л‘җ к°Җм§Җмқҙм§Җл§Ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң н•ңкі„, мҰү мғқм„ұ лӢӨм–‘м„ұ л¶ҖмЎұмңјлЎң мқён•ң sample inefficiencyмҷҖ, лӘЁлҚёмқҙ нҠ№м • training formulationмқ„ м•”кё°н•ҳм—¬ мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” лҸҷл“ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң л¬ёмІҙк°Җ лӢӨлҘё promptм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җлҗ  л•Ң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ кёүкІ©нһҲ л¶•кҙҙн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„м Җн•ң prompt overfittingмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” language models (LMs)лҘј н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн•ң prompt refinement agentлЎңм„ң flow кё°л°ҳ RL optimization loop лӮҙл¶Җм—җ м§Ғм ‘ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё \\textbf{PromptRL} (\\textbf{P}rompt \\textbf{M}atters in \\textbf{RL} for Flow-Based Image Generation)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мғҒнҳёліҙмҷ„м Ғ мқҙм җмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ: м •көҗн•ң prompt rewriting кё°лҠҘмқ„ л№ лҘҙкІҢ к°ңл°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲкі , лҚ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳкІҢлҠ” optimization dynamicsлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” мӢңл„Ҳм§Җ н•ҷмҠө мІҙкі„лҘј нҳ•м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. PromptRLмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ GenEvalм—җм„ң 0.97, OCR accuracyм—җм„ң 0.98, PickScoreм—җм„ң 24.05лҘј м–»м—ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ image editing modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ RL м ‘к·јлІ•мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳм—¬, FLUX.1-Kontextмқҳ EditRewardлҘј лӢЁ 0.06 million rolloutsлЎң 1.19м—җм„ң 1.43мңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңмј°мңјл©°, 1.37мқ„ кё°лЎқн•ң Gemini 2.5 Flash Image (aka Nano Banana)лҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкі , м„ёл°Җн•ң data annotationкіј ліөмһЎн•ң multi-stage trainingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ 1.44лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ң ReasonNetкіј мң мӮ¬н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PromptRLмқҙ naive flow-only RLкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ 2$\\times$ мқҙмғҒ м ҒмқҖ rolloutsл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ performance ceilingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"66617","en":"Infinite-World: Scaling Interactive World Models to 1000-Frame Horizons via Pose-Free Hierarchical Memory","ko":"Infinite-World: Pose-Free кі„мёөм Ғ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬лҘј нҶөн•ң лҢҖнҷ”нҳ• World Modelмқ„ 1000-Frame м§ҖнҸүмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘ","authors":"Ruiqi Wu, Xuanhua He, Meng Cheng, Tianyu Yang, Yong Zhang, Zhuoliang Kang, Xunliang Cai, Xiaoming Wei, Chunle Guo, Chongyi Li, Ming-Ming Cheng","pos":"#4005","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=27m3BuajLs","abs":"<p>We propose <strong>Infinite-World</strong>, a robust interactive world model capable of maintaining coherent visual memory over <strong>1000+ frames</strong> in complex real-world environments. While existing world models can be efficiently optimized on synthetic data with perfect ground-truth, they lack an effective training paradigm for real-world videos due to noisy pose estimations and the scarcity of viewpoint revisits. To bridge this gap, we first introduce a <strong>Hierarchical Pose-free Memory Compressor (HPMC)</strong> that recursively distills historical latents into a fixed-budget representation. By jointly optimizing the compressor with the generative backbone, HPMC enables the model to autonomously anchor generations in the distant past with bounded computational cost, eliminating the need for explicit geometric priors. Second, we propose an <strong>Uncertainty-aware Action Abstraction</strong> module that discretizes continuous motion into a tri-state logic. This strategy maximizes the utilization of raw video data while shielding the deterministic action space from being corrupted by noisy trajectories, ensuring robust action-response learning. Furthermore, guided by insights from a pilot toy study, we employ a <strong>Revisit-Dense Finetuning Strategy</strong> using a compact, 30-minute dataset to efficiently activate the modelвҖҷs long-range loop-closure capabilities. Extensive experiments, including objective metrics and user studies, demonstrate that Infinite-World achieves superior performance in visual quality, action controllability, and spatial consistency. Our code and data will be released.</p>","absKo":"<p><strong>Infinite-World</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң <strong>1000+ н”„л Ҳмһ„</strong>м—җ кұёміҗ мқјкҙҖлҗң мӢңк°Ғм Ғ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬лҘј мң м§Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” к°•кұҙн•ң interactive world modelмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ world modelмқҖ perfect ground-truthлҘј к°Җм§„ synthetic dataм—җм„ңлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, noisy pose estimationкіј viewpoint revisitsмқҳ нқ¬мҶҢм„ұ л•Ңл¬ём—җ мӢӨм ң мҳҒмғҒм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё н•ҷмҠө нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, лЁјм Җ <strong>Hierarchical Pose-free Memory Compressor (HPMC)</strong>лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лӘЁл“ҲмқҖ кіјкұ° latentлҘј кі м •лҗң мҳҲмӮ°мқҳ н‘ңнҳ„мңјлЎң мһ¬к·Җм ҒмңјлЎң м••м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. compressorлҘј generative backboneкіј н•Ёк»ҳ кіөлҸҷ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, HPMCлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё geometric prior м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ м ңн•ңлҗң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мңјлЎң лЁј кіјкұ°мқҳ мһҘл©ҙм—җ мғқм„ұ кІ°кіјлҘј мһҗмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң м•өм»Өл§Ғн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, continuous motionмқ„ tri-state logicмңјлЎң мқҙмӮ°нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” <strong>Uncertainty-aware Action Abstraction</strong> лӘЁл“Ҳмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м „лһөмқҖ мӣҗмӢң video dataмқҳ нҷңмҡ©мқ„ к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, noisy trajectoryлЎңл¶Җн„° deterministic action spaceк°Җ мҳӨм—јлҗҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ л°©м§Җн•ҳм—¬ к°•кұҙн•ң action-response learningмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, pilot toy studyм—җм„ң м–»мқҖ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, к°„кІ°н•ң 30л¶„ л¶„лҹүмқҳ datasetмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң <strong>Revisit-Dense Finetuning Strategy</strong>лҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ loop-closure лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. к°қкҙҖм Ғ м§Җн‘ңмҷҖ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м—°кө¬лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Infinite-Worldк°Җ visual quality, action controllability, spatial consistencyм—җм„ң мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ codeмҷҖ dataлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66559","en":"XSpecMesh: Quality-Preserving Auto-Regressive Mesh Generation Acceleration via Multi-Head Speculative Decoding","ko":"XSpecMesh: лӢӨмӨ‘ н—Өл“ң м¶”мёЎ л””мҪ”л”©мқ„ нҶөн•ң н’Ҳм§Ҳ ліҙмЎҙ мһҗкё°нҡҢк·Җ л©”мӢң мғқм„ұ к°ҖмҶҚ","authors":"Dian Chen, Yansong Qu, Xinyang Li, Ming Li, Shengchuan Zhang","pos":"#4007","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2eKOeHaNZG","abs":"Current auto-regressive models can generate high-quality, topologically precise meshes; however, they necessitate thousandsвҖ”or even tens of thousandsвҖ”of next-token predictions during inference, resulting in substantial latency. We introduce XSpecMesh, a quality-preserving acceleration method for auto-regressive mesh generation models. XSpecMesh employs a lightweight, multi-head speculative decoding scheme to predict multiple tokens in parallel within a single forward pass, thereby accelerating inference. We further propose a verification and resampling strategy: the backbone model verifies each predicted token and resamples any tokens that do not meet the quality criteria. In addition, we propose a distillation strategy that trains the lightweight decoding heads by distilling from the backbone model, encouraging their prediction distributions to align and improving the success rate of speculative predictions. Extensive experiments demonstrate that our method achieves a $1.7\\times$ speedup without sacrificing generation quality. Our code will be released.","absKo":"нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ auto-regressive modelмқҖ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҳ, topologically preciseн•ң meshлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ inference лҸҷм•Ҳ мҲҳмІң лІҲ, мӢ¬м§Җм–ҙ мҲҳл§Ң лІҲмқҳ next-token predictionмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳлҜҖлЎң мғҒлӢ№н•ң latencyк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” auto-regressive mesh generation modelмқ„ мң„н•ң quality-preserving acceleration л°©лІ•мқё XSpecMeshлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. XSpecMeshлҠ” н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ forward pass м•Ҳм—җм„ң м—¬лҹ¬ tokenмқ„ лі‘л ¬лЎң мҳҲмёЎн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ lightweight, multi-head speculative decoding schemeмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ inferenceлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” verification л°Ҹ resampling strategyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ: backbone modelмқҙ к°Ғ мҳҲмёЎ tokenмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкі , quality кё°мӨҖмқ„ м¶©мЎұн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” tokenмқҖ лӢӨмӢң мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, backbone modelлЎңл¶Җн„° distillationн•ҳм—¬ lightweight decoding headлҘј н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨлҠ” distillation strategyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙл“Өмқҳ prediction distributionмқҙ лҚ” мһҳ м •л ¬лҗҳкі  speculative predictionмқҳ м„ұкіөлҘ мқҙ н–ҘмғҒлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬ л°©лІ•мқҙ generation qualityлҘј нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң $1.7\\times$мқҳ speedupмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ."},{"id":"65769","en":"When Do Diffusion Models learn to Generate Multiple Objects?","ko":"Diffusion лӘЁлҚёмқҖ м–ём ң лӢӨмӨ‘ к°қмІҙ мғқм„ұмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ”к°Җ?","authors":"Yujin Jeong, Arnas Uselis, Iro Laina, Seong Joon Oh, Anna Rohrbach","pos":"#2511","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=AKrhb31pI7","abs":"<p>Text-to-image diffusion models achieve impressive visual fidelity, yet they remain unreliable in multi-object generation. Despite extensive empirical evidence of these failures, the underlying causes remain unclear. We begin by asking how much of this limitation arises from the data itself. To disentangle data effects, we consider two regimes across different dataset sizes: (1) concept generalization, where each individual concept is observed during training under potentially imbalanced data distributions, and (2) compositional generalization, where specific combinations of concepts are systematically held out. To study these regimes, we introduce mosaic  (Multi-Object Spatial relations, AttrIbution, Counting), a controlled framework for dataset generation. By training diffusion models on mosaic, we find that scene complexity plays a dominant role rather than concept imbalance, and that counting is uniquely difficult to learn in low-data regimes. Moreover, compositional generalization collapses as more concept combinations are held out during training. These findings highlight fundamental limitations of diffusion models and motivate stronger inductive biases and data design for robust multi-object compositional generation.</p>","absKo":"<p>text-to-image diffusion modelмқҖ мқёмғҒм Ғмқё visual fidelityлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, multi-object generationм—җм„ңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ мӢ лў°н•ҳкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢӨнҢЁм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨмҰқм Ғ мҰқкұ°м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , к·јліё мӣҗмқёмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ н•ңкі„мқҳ м–ҙлҠҗ м •лҸ„к°Җ лҚ°мқҙн„° мһҗмІҙм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗҳлҠ”м§Җ л¬»лҠ” кІғмңјлЎң л…јмқҳлҘј мӢңмһ‘н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ°мқҙн„° нҡЁкіјлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё dataset sizeм—җ кұём№ң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ regimeмқ„ кі л Өн•ңлӢӨ. (1) к°ңлі„ conceptлҠ” н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ кҙҖм°°лҗҳм§Җл§Ң лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶„нҸ¬лҠ” л¶Ҳк· нҳ•н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” concept generalization, (2) нҠ№м • concept мЎ°н•©мқҙ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң м ңмҷёлҗҳлҠ” compositional generalizationмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң regimeмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„° мғқм„ұмҡ© нҶөм ңлҗң frameworkмқё mosaic(Multi-Object Spatial relations, AttrIbution, Counting)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. mosaicмңјлЎң diffusion modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ң кІ°кіј, concept imbalanceліҙлӢӨ scene complexityк°Җ м§Җл°°м Ғмқё м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ҳл©°, countingмқҖ low-data regimeм—җм„ң нҠ№нһҲ л°°мҡ°кё° м–ҙл өлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ concept мЎ°н•©мқҙ м ңмҷёлҗ мҲҳлЎқ compositional generalizationмқҖ л¶•кҙҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” diffusion modelмқҳ к·јліём Ғ н•ңкі„лҘј к°•мЎ°н•ҳл©°, кІ¬кі н•ң multi-object compositional generationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ лҚ” к°•н•ң inductive biasмҷҖ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„° м„Өкі„лҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64460","en":"Variational Bayesian Flow Network for Graph Generation","ko":"к·ёлһҳн”„ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң ліҖл¶„ лІ мқҙм§Җм•Ҳ нқҗлҰ„ л„ӨнҠёмӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Yida Xiong, Jiameng Chen, Xiuwen Gong, Jia Wu, Shirui Pan, wenbin Hu","pos":"#2514","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=NNU8cO5wte","abs":"<p>Graph generation aims to sample discrete node and edge attributes while satisfying coupled structural constraints. Diffusion models for graphs often adopt largely factorized forward-noising, and many flow-matching methods start from factorized reference noise and coordinate-wise interpolation, so nodeвҖ“edge coupling is not encoded by the generative geometry and must be recovered implicitly by the core network, which can be brittle after discrete decoding. Bayesian Flow Networks (BFNs) evolve distribution parameters and naturally support discrete generation. But classical BFNs typically rely on factorized beliefs and independent channels, which limit geometric evidence fusion. We propose Variational Bayesian Flow Network (VBFN), which performs a variational lifting to a tractable joint Gaussian variational belief family governed by structured precisions. Each Bayesian update reduces to solving a symmetric positive definite linear system, enabling coupled node and edge updates within a single fusion step. We construct sample-agnostic sparse precisions from a representation-induced dependency graph, thereby avoiding label leakage while enforcing nodeвҖ“edge consistency. On synthetic and molecular graph datasets, VBFN improves fidelity and diversity, and surpasses baseline methods. The reproducible code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/VBFN-D6B0/.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph generationмқҖ кІ°н•©лҗң structural constraintлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң discrete node л°Ҹ edge attributeлҘј мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. graphлҘј мң„н•ң diffusion modelмқҖ мў…мў… лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ factorizedлҗң forward-noisingмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ҳкі , л§ҺмқҖ flow-matching л°©лІ•мқҖ factorized reference noiseмҷҖ coordinate-wise interpolationм—җм„ң м¶ңл°ңн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, node-edge couplingмқҙ generative geometryм—җ мқёмҪ”л”©лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©° core networkк°Җ мқҙлҘј м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң ліөмӣҗн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” discrete decoding мқҙнӣ„ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. Bayesian Flow Network (BFN)мқҖ distribution parameterлҘј м§„нҷ”мӢңнӮӨл©° discrete generationмқ„ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кі м „м Ғмқё BFNмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң factorized beliefмҷҖ independent channelм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ geometric evidence fusionмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң precisionмңјлЎң м§Җл°°лҗҳлҠ” tractableн•ң joint Gaussian variational belief familyлЎң ліҖл¶„м Ғ liftingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” Variational Bayesian Flow Network (VBFN)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. к°Ғ Bayesian updateлҠ” лҢҖм№ӯ м–‘мқҳ м •л¶Җнҳё(symmetric positive definite) linear systemмқ„ н‘ёлҠ” л¬ём ңлЎң нҷҳмӣҗлҗҳм–ҙ, лӢЁмқј fusion step лӮҙм—җм„ң кІ°н•©лҗң node л°Ҹ edge updateлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” representation-induced dependency graphлЎңл¶Җн„° sample-agnostic sparse precisionмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ label leakageлҘј н”јн•ҳл©ҙм„ң node-edge мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ к°•м ңн•ңлӢӨ. synthetic л°Ҹ molecular graph datasetм—җм„ң VBFNмқҖ fidelityмҷҖ diversityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі , baseline methodлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мһ¬нҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/VBFN-D6B0/ м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63546","en":"Responsible Text-to-Image Diffusion: Interpretable and Linearly Controllable Semantics for Fair and Safe Generation","ko":"мұ…мһ„ мһҲлҠ” Text-to-Image нҷ•мӮ°: кіөм •н•ҳкі  м•Ҳм „н•ң мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  м„ нҳ•м ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мқҳлҜё","authors":"Sayedmoslem Shokrolahi, Jae-Mo Kang, Il-Min Kim","pos":"#2608","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=W9ltOfYnhY","abs":"<p>Text-to-image (T2I) diffusion models (DMs) have achieved remarkable generative quality but still exhibit the risk to produce biased and inappropriate images. A promising line of prior work aims to mitigate this issue by learning interpretable and linearly controllable concepts from semantic spaces, such as the U-Net bottleneck. However, these methods rely entirely on the bottleneck layer in U-Net and therefore cannot be directly applied to modern ViT-based DMs, including FLUX and PixArt. In this work, we present a model agnostic framework for discovering interpretable and linearly controllable semantic attributes across any T2I DMs backbone. We first show that multi-modal attention heads in ViT-based DMs encode interpretable and (near) linear semantic structures similar to those in the U-Net bottleneck. Based on this insight, we introduce a method that learns external concept vectors, which are added to the multi-modal attention heads for ViT-based DMs or to the bottleneck layer for U-Net-based DMs, while keeping the pretrained model frozen. Experiments across SDXL, SD3.5, PixArt, and FLUX demonstrate that these concept vectors provide interpretability, linearity, and highly improved fairness while preserving visual fidelity. The code is included in the supplementary material.</p>","absKo":"<p>Text-to-image (T2I) diffusion models (DMs)мқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ мғқм„ұ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, м—¬м „нһҲ нҺён–Ҙлҗҳкұ°лӮҳ л¶Җм Ғм Ҳн•ң мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мң„н—ҳмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬мқҳ мң л§қн•ң л°©н–ҘмқҖ U-Net bottleneckкіј к°ҷмқҖ semantic spaceм—җм„ң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  м„ нҳ•м ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң к°ңл…җмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•мқҖ м „м ҒмңјлЎң U-Netмқҳ bottleneck layerм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, FLUXмҷҖ PixArtлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң нҳ„лҢҖм Ғмқё ViT кё°л°ҳ DMsм—җлҠ” м§Ғм ‘ м Ғмҡ©н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” м–ҙл–Ө T2I DMs backboneм—җлҸ„ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң, н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  м„ нҳ•м ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң semantic attributeлҘј л°ңкІ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң model-agnostic frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ ViT кё°л°ҳ DMsмқҳ multi-modal attention headк°Җ U-Net bottleneckкіј мң мӮ¬н•ң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  (кұ°мқҳ) м„ нҳ•м Ғмқё semantic structureлҘј мқёмҪ”л”©н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, pretrained modelмқҖ кі м •н•ң мұ„ ViT кё°л°ҳ DMsмқҳ multi-modal attention head лҳҗлҠ” U-Net кё°л°ҳ DMsмқҳ bottleneck layerм—җ лҚ”н•ҙм§ҖлҠ” external concept vectorлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SDXL, SD3.5, PixArt, FLUX м „л°ҳмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң concept vectorк°Җ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ м¶©мӢӨлҸ„лҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ, м„ нҳ•м„ұ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗң fairnessлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” ліҙм¶© мһҗлЈҢм—җ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61676","en":"RevealLayer: Disentangling Hidden and Visible Layers via Occlusion-Aware Image Decomposition","ko":"RevealLayer: Occlusion-Aware Image Decompositionмқ„ нҶөн•ң Hidden LayerмҷҖ Visible Layer л¶„лҰ¬","authors":"Binhao Wang, Shihao Zhao, Bo Cheng, Qiuyu Ji, YuhangMa, Liebucha Wu, Shanyuan Liu, Dawei Leng, Yuhui Yin","pos":"#2610","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nqmb8hv39b","abs":"<p>Recent diffusion-based approaches have made substantial progress in image layer decomposition.  However, accurately decomposing complex natural images remains challenging due to difficulties in occlusion completion, robust layer disentanglement, and precise foreground boundaries. Moreover, the scarcity of high-quality multi-layer natural image datasets limits advancement.  To address these challenges, we propose <strong>RevealLayer</strong>, a diffusion-based framework that decomposes an RGB image into multiple RGBA layers, enabling precise layer separation and reliable recovery of occluded content in natural images. RevealLayer incorporates three key components: (1) a <strong>Region-Aware Attention</strong> module to disentangle hidden and visible layers; (2) an <strong>Occlusion-Guided Adapter</strong> to leverage contextual information to enhance overlapping regions; and (3) a <strong>composite loss</strong> to enforce sharp alpha boundaries and suppress residual artifacts.  To support training and evaluation, we introduce <strong>RevealLayer-100K</strong>, a high-quality multi-layer natural image constructed through a collaboration between automated algorithms and human annotation, and further establish <strong>RevealLayerBench</strong> for benchmarking layer decomposition in general natural scenes. Extensive experiments demonstrate that RevealLayer consistently outperforms existing approaches in layer decomposition.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј diffusion-based м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ image layer decompositionм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈЁм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ occlusion completion, robust layer disentanglement, м •нҷ•н•ң foreground boundaryлқјлҠ” м–ҙл ӨмӣҖ л•Ңл¬ём—җ ліөмһЎн•ң мһҗм—° мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ л¶„н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. лҚ”мҡұмқҙ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ multi-layer natural image datasetмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұмқҖ л°ңм „мқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>RevealLayer</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” RGB мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј м—¬лҹ¬ RGBA layerлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳм—¬ мһҗм—° мқҙлҜём§Җм—җм„ң м •л°Җн•ң layer separationкіј к°Җл Өм§„ лӮҙмҡ©мқҳ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” ліөмӣҗмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” diffusion-based frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. RevealLayerлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. (1) hidden layerмҷҖ visible layerлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң <strong>Region-Aware Attention</strong> module, (2) overlapping regionмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ҙ contextual informationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” <strong>Occlusion-Guided Adapter</strong>, (3) sharp alpha boundaryлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳкі  residual artifactлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳлҠ” <strong>composite loss</strong>мқҙлӢӨ. н•ҷмҠөкіј нҸүк°ҖлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһҗлҸҷнҷ” м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳкіј мқёк°„ мЈјм„қмқҳ нҳ‘л Ҙмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кө¬м¶•н•ң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ multi-layer natural imageмқё <strong>RevealLayer-100K</strong>лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ҳкі , мқјл°ҳ мһҗм—° мһҘл©ҙм—җм„ңмқҳ layer decomposition лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№мқ„ мң„н•ң <strong>RevealLayerBench</strong>лҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң л§Ҳл Ён•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ RevealLayerк°Җ layer decompositionм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62637","en":"On the Collapse of Generative Paths: A Criterion and Correction for Diffusion Steering","ko":"Generative Pathsмқҳ л¶•кҙҙ: Diffusion SteeringлҘј мң„н•ң кё°мӨҖкіј ліҙм •","authors":"Ziseok Lee, Minyeong Hwang, Sanghyun Jo, Wooyeol Lee, Jihyung Ko, Young Bin Park, Jae-Mun Choi, Eunho Yang, Kyungsu Kim","pos":"#2700","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=emv2qsi3TG","abs":"<p>Inference-time steering adapts pretrained diffusion and flow models to new tasks without retraining, often utilizing ratio-of-densities constructions that reweight time-indexed marginals with fixed exponents. We identify Marginal Path Collapse, a failure mode in which the intermediate density defined by such compositions becomes non-normalizable despite valid endpoints. This collapse can arise when composing heterogeneous experts trained with mismatched noise schedules (and/or negative exponents / partial supports). To address this, we provide (i) a necessary-and-sufficient Path Existence Criterion that characterizes when the composed intermediate densities are mathematically well-defined, and (ii) Adaptive path Correction with Exponents (ACE), which generalizes FeynmanвҖ“Kac steering to support time-varying exponents. Our analysis reveals that ACE controls the quantile radius of the intermediate distributions, providing a theoretical mechanism for path stabilization observed in experiments. On flexible-pose scaffold decoration, a drug design task composed of de-novo, conformer, and protein-conditioned experts, ACE prevents collapse and significantly outperforms constant-exponent baselines. Furthermore, ACE improves attribute success rates in compositional image generation, establishing it as a general framework for compositional sampling.</p>","absKo":"<p>inference-time steeringмқҖ pretrained diffusion л°Ҹ flow modelмқ„ retraining м—Ҷмқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskм—җ м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮӨл©°, мў…мў… time-indexed marginalмқ„ кі м •лҗң exponentлЎң мһ¬к°ҖмӨ‘н•ҳлҠ” ratio-of-densities кө¬м„ұмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Marginal Path CollapseлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң compositionмңјлЎң м •мқҳлҗң intermediate densityк°Җ м–‘ лҒқм җмқҖ мң нҡЁн•Ём—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  non-normalizableн•ҙм§ҖлҠ” failure modeмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң collapseлҠ” noise scheduleмқҙ м„ңлЎң л§һм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” heterogeneous expertлҘј compositionн•  л•Ң, к·ёлҰ¬кі /лҳҗлҠ” negative exponentлӮҳ partial supportк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•  л•Ң л°ңмғқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” (i) composed intermediate densityк°Җ м–ём ң мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң мһҳ м •мқҳлҗҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ” н•„мҡ”м¶©л¶„н•ң Path Existence Criterion, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (ii) time-varying exponentлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ FeynmanвҖ“Kac steeringмқ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ң Adaptive path Correction with Exponents (ACE)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ ACEк°Җ intermediate distributionмқҳ quantile radiusлҘј м ңм–ҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, мқҙлҠ” мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң кҙҖм°°лҗң path stabilizationмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. flexible-pose scaffold decoration, мҰү de-novo, conformer, protein-conditioned expertлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң drug design taskм—җм„ң ACEлҠ” collapseлҘј л°©м§Җн•ҳкі  constant-exponent baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ ACEлҠ” compositional image generationм—җм„ң attribute success rateлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңмјң, мқҙлҘј compositional samplingмқ„ мң„н•ң мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё frameworkлЎң нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61626","en":"Nonparametric Data Attribution for Diffusion Models","ko":"Diffusion Modelмқ„ мң„н•ң л№„лӘЁмҲҳм Ғ лҚ°мқҙн„° Attribution","authors":"Yutian Zhao, Chao Du, Xiaosen Zheng, Tianyu Pang, Min Lin","pos":"#2701","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=oP3gus0Sl3","abs":"<p>Data attribution for generative models seeks to quantify the influence of individual training examples on model outputs. Existing methods for diffusion models typically require access to model gradients or retraining, limiting their applicability in proprietary or large-scale settings. We propose a <em>nonparametric</em> attribution method that operates entirely on data, measuring influence via patch-level similarity between generated and training images. Our approach is grounded in the analytical form of the optimal score function and naturally extends to multiscale representations, while remaining computationally efficient through convolution-based acceleration. In addition to producing spatially interpretable attributions, our framework uncovers patterns that reflect intrinsic relationships between training data and outputs, independent of any specific model. Experiments demonstrate that our method achieves strong attribution performance, closely matching gradient-based approaches and substantially outperforming existing nonparametric baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ data attributionмқҖ к°ңлі„ н•ҷмҠө мҳҲм ңк°Җ лӘЁлҚё м¶ңл Ҙм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. diffusion modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң model gradientsм—җ лҢҖн•ң м ‘к·јмқҙлӮҳ мһ¬н•ҷмҠөмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, proprietaryн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғқм„ұ мқҙлҜём§ҖмҷҖ н•ҷмҠө мқҙлҜём§Җ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ patch-level similarityлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ”, лҚ°мқҙн„°л§ҢмңјлЎң мҷ„м „нһҲ лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” <em>nonparametric</em> attribution methodлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ optimal score functionмқҳ analytical formм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳл©°, convolution кё°л°ҳ к°ҖмҶҚмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кі„мӮ°м ҒмңјлЎң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё мғҒнғңлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ multiscale representationмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘлҗңлӢӨ. кіөк°„м ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң attributionмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғ мҷём—җлҸ„, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkлҠ” нҠ№м • modelкіј л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳкІҢ н•ҷмҠө лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖ м¶ңл Ҙ к°„мқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғ кҙҖкі„лҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ” нҢЁн„ҙмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң attribution м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ gradient-based approachмҷҖ л§Өмҡ° мң мӮ¬н•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ кё°мЎҙ nonparametric baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мғҒнҡҢн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64469","en":"Mitigating Noise-Induced Layout Priors for Object Counting in Diffusion Models","ko":"Diffusion лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң к°қмІҙ кі„мҲҳлҘј мң„н•ң л…ёмқҙмҰҲ мң л°ң л Ҳмқҙм•„мӣғ мӮ¬м „ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Xiaoling Gu, Xuelong Li, Shengqi Wu, Yongkang Wong, wu, Huan Li, Zhou Yu, Mohan Kankanhalli","pos":"#2703","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=NJHPCVfC2n","abs":"<p>Despite remarkable progress in text-to-image diffusion models, accurately generating the specified number of objects remains a persistent challenge. We identify the initial noise as a primary determinant of spatial layout formation, with early-stage cross-attention serving as the key mechanism that mediates the propagation of noise-induced structures throughout the denoising process. We formalize this phenomenon as the \\textbf{\\textit{Noise-Induced Layout Prior}}. Leveraging this insight, we propose a novel training-free framework for object counting in diffusion models. Our approach consists of two key components: (1) a \\emph{Count-Aware Noise Adjustment Strategy}, which explicitly manipulates the initial latent noise to align layout formation with the target object count, and (2) an \\emph{Attention-Guided Layout Consistency Strategy}, which performs test-time optimization on early-stage cross-attention to further stabilize layout formation during denoising. Extensive experiments on both single-category and multi-category benchmarks demonstrate that our method consistently outperforms strong diffusion baselines and state-of-the-art object count control methods in terms of counting accuracy and image quality.</p>","absKo":"<p>text-to-image diffusion modelмқҳ лҲҲл¶ҖмӢ  л°ңм „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , м§Җм •лҗң мҲҳмқҳ objectлҘј м •нҷ•нһҲ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё лӮңм ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” initial noiseк°Җ spatial layout нҳ•м„ұмқҳ мЈјмҡ” кІ°м • мҡ”мқёмһ„мқ„ нҷ•мқён–Ҳмңјл©°, мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„ cross-attentionмқҙ denoising кіјм • м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ noise-induced structureмқҳ м „нҢҢлҘј л§Өк°ңн•ҳлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмңјлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ \\textbf{\\textit{Noise-Induced Layout Prior}}лЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” diffusion modelм—җм„ң object countingмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ training-free frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. (1) \\emph{Count-Aware Noise Adjustment Strategy}лҠ” мҙҲкё° latent noiseлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ҳм—¬ layout нҳ•м„ұмқҙ лӘ©н‘ң object countмҷҖ мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳл©°, (2) \\emph{Attention-Guided Layout Consistency Strategy}лҠ” мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„ cross-attentionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ test-time optimizationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ denoising лҸҷм•Ҳ layout нҳ•м„ұмқ„ лҚ”мҡұ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. лӢЁмқј лІ”мЈј л°Ҹ лӢӨмӨ‘ лІ”мЈј benchmark лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ counting accuracyмҷҖ image quality мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң diffusion baseline л°Ҹ state-of-the-art object count control methodлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62677","en":"Manifold-Optimal Guidance: A Unified Riemannian Control View of Diffusion Guidance","ko":"Manifold-Optimal Guidance: Diffusion Guidanceмқҳ нҶөн•©м Ғ Riemannian м ңм–ҙ кҙҖм җ","authors":"Zexi Jia, Pengcheng Luo, Zhengyao Fang, Jinchao Zhang, Jie Zhou","pos":"#2704","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eSxGdQ0zwG","abs":"<p>Classifier-Free Guidance (CFG) serves as the de facto control mechanism for conditional diffusion, yet high guidance scales notoriously induce oversaturation, texture artifacts, and structural collapse. We attribute this failure to a geometric mismatch: standard CFG performs Euclidean extrapolation in ambient space, inadvertently driving sampling trajectories off the high-density data manifold. To resolve this, we present Manifold-Optimal Guidance (MOG), a framework that reformulates guidance as a local optimal control problem. MOG yields a closed-form, geometry-aware Riemannian update that corrects off-manifold drift without requiring retraining. Leveraging this perspective, we further introduce Auto-MOG, a dynamic energy-balancing schedule that adaptively calibrates guidance strength, effectively eliminating the need for manual hyperparameter tuning. Extensive validation demonstrates that MOG yields superior fidelity and alignment compared to baselines, with virtually no added computational overhead.</p>","absKo":"<p>Classifier-Free Guidance (CFG)лҠ” мЎ°кұҙл¶Җ diffusionмқҳ мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ н‘ңмӨҖ м ңм–ҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмңјлЎң м“°мқҙм§Җл§Ң, лҶ’мқҖ guidance scaleмқҖ кіјлҸ„н•ң мұ„лҸ„, texture artifact, кө¬мЎ° л¶•кҙҙлҘј мқјмңјнӮӨлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң м•…лӘ… лҶ’лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢӨнҢЁлҘј кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлЎң м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ CFGлҠ” ambient spaceм—җм„ң Euclidean extrapolationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј мғҳн”Ңл§Ғ к¶Өм Ғмқҙ кі л°ҖлҸ„ лҚ°мқҙн„° manifoldм—җм„ң лІ—м–ҙлӮҳкІҢ лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Manifold-Optimal Guidance (MOG)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. MOGлҠ” guidanceлҘј көӯмҶҢ мөңм Ғм ңм–ҙ л¬ём ңлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. MOGлҠ” retraining м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ off-manifold driftлҘј ліҙм •н•ҳлҠ”, кё°н•ҳн•ҷмқ„ кі л Өн•ң closed-form Riemannian updateлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм җм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ Auto-MOGлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. Auto-MOGлҠ” guidance к°•лҸ„лҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң ліҙм •н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷм Ғ energy-balancing scheduleлЎң, мҲҳлҸҷ hyperparameter tuningмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ кІҖмҰқ кІ°кіј, MOGлҠ” м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё computational overheadлҘј кұ°мқҳ лҠҳлҰ¬м§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң baselinesліҙлӢӨ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң fidelityмҷҖ alignmentлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65292","en":"HIVE-3D: Hierarchical Voxel Enhancement for High-Quality 3D Scene Generation","ko":"HIVE-3D: кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ 3D мһҘл©ҙ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң кі„мёөм Ғ ліөм…Җ н–ҘмғҒ","authors":"Bin Zang, Rengan Xie, Xiaoliang Luo, Zhiyuan Fang, Shi Li, Lvchun Wang, Wei Yu, Yi Zhao, Yuchi Huo, Tian Xie, Wenting Zheng","pos":"#2706","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=F3AYj7Znav","abs":"<p>Recently, a line of works can generate impressive 3D objects from a single image, but they are limited by restricted representation resolution, making them unsuitable for 3D scene generation. In this work, we introduce \\name, a novel method for high-quality 3D scene generation based on hierarchical voxel enhancement framework. Specifically, given a single scene image as input, we first produce a coarse initial scene, then introduce image segmentation and attention-based retrieval to align 2D image components with 3D scene components. Subsequently, we organize these scene relations into a hierarchical component tree, where nodes closer to the leaves denote finer-grained components. Finally, we propose a voxel super-resolution model that generates refined voxels for the target instance while maintaining strong consistency with the coarse voxels. Equipped with this model, we perform coarse-to-fine hierarchical super-resolution on images and voxels for each component, producing a high-resolution and high-quality 3D scene. Extensive experiments demonstrate that our method significantly outperforms previous approaches, achieving state-of-the-art performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј мқјл¶Җ м—°кө¬лҠ” лӢЁмқј мқҙлҜём§ҖлЎңл¶Җн„° мқёмғҒм Ғмқё 3D objectлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, representation resolutionмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм–ҙ 3D scene generationм—җлҠ” м Ғн•©н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” hierarchical voxel enhancement frameworkлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ 3D scene generationмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л°©лІ• \\nameмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, лӢЁмқј scene imageлҘј мһ…л ҘмңјлЎң л°ӣм•„ лЁјм Җ кұ°м№ң мҙҲкё° sceneмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ң л’Ө, image segmentationкіј attention-based retrievalмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ 2D image componentмҷҖ 3D scene componentлҘј м •л ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң scene relationмқ„ hierarchical component treeлЎң мЎ°м§Ғн•ҳл©°, leafм—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ nodeмқјмҲҳлЎқ лҚ” м„ёл°Җн•ң componentлҘј мқҳлҜён•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, coarse voxelкіј к°•н•ң consistencyлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң target instanceм—җ лҢҖн•ң refined voxelмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” voxel super-resolution modelмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ componentм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ imageмҷҖ voxelм—җм„ң coarse-to-fine hierarchical super-resolutionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„мқҙл©ҙм„ң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳмқё 3D sceneмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©° state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64894","en":"Exploring Data-Free LoRA Transferability for Video Diffusion Models","ko":"Video Diffusion Modelмқ„ мң„н•ң Data-Free LoRA мқҙм „м„ұ нғҗкө¬","authors":"Yuchen Wang, Wenliang Zhong, Lichen Bai, zikai ZHOU, Shitong Shao, Bojun Cheng, Shuo Chen, Shuo Yang, Zeke Xie","pos":"#2709","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Imry2qitdt","abs":"<p>Video diffusion models leveraging step distillation or causal distillation have achieved remarkable performance. However, adapting existing LoRAs to these variants remains a critical challenge due to weight space mismatches. We observe that direct application leads to style degradation and structural collapse, yet the underlying mechanisms  remain poorly understood. To fill this gap, we delve into the weight space and identify that the incompatibility stems from spectral interference within shared functional clusters defined over singular subspaces. Specifically, our analysis reveals that while both paradigms respect spectral rigidity, they establish conflicting routing pathways that clash through constructive overload or destructive cancellation. To address this issue, we propose Cluster-Aware Spectral Arbitration (CASA), a data-free framework that dynamically arbitrates between safeguarding the target's manifold and restoring LoRA alignment based on spectral density. Extensive experiments demonstrate that CASA effectively mitigates artifacts and revives LoRA functionality. Our code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CASA/.</p>","absKo":"<p>step distillation лҳҗлҠ” causal distillationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” video diffusion modelмқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ LoRAлҘј мқҙлҹ¬н•ң ліҖнҳ•м—җ л§һкІҢ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ weight space mismatch л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м§Ғм ‘ м Ғмҡ©н•  кІҪмҡ° style degradationкіј structural collapseк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё к·јліё л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳмқҢмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” weight spaceлҘј к№Ҡмқҙ мӮҙнҺҙліҙкі , л№„м–‘лҰҪм„ұмқҳ мӣҗмқёмқҙ singular subspace мң„м—җм„ң м •мқҳлҗң shared functional cluster лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ spectral interferenceм—җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°қнҳҖлғҲлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ л‘җ paradigm лӘЁл‘җ spectral rigidityлҘј л”°лҘҙм§Җл§Ң, constructive overload лҳҗлҠ” destructive cancellationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м¶©лҸҢн•ҳлҠ” мғҒл°ҳлҗң routing pathwayлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Cluster-Aware Spectral Arbitration (CASA)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” spectral densityм—җ л”°лқј targetмқҳ manifoldлҘј ліҙнҳён• м§Җ LoRA alignmentлҘј ліөмӣҗн• м§Җ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мӨ‘мһ¬н•ҳлҠ” data-free frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CASAк°Җ artifactлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкі  LoRA кё°лҠҘмқ„ лҗҳмӮҙлҰ°лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ң: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CASA/.</p>"},{"id":"60565","en":"Beyond Pixel Context Windows: Neural World Simulators with Persistent 3D State","ko":"н”Ҫм…Җ м»Ён…ҚмҠӨнҠё мңҲлҸ„мҡ°лҘј л„ҳм–ҙ: м§ҖмҶҚм Ғ 3D мғҒнғңлҘј к°–лҠ” мӢ кІҪ мӣ”л“ң мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙн„°","authors":"Samuel Garcin, Tom Walker, Steven McDonagh, Tim Pearce, Hakan Bilen, Tianyu He, Kaixin Wang, Jiang Bian","pos":"#2715","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=yyitz0hJqK","abs":"<p>Interactive world models continually generate video by responding to a user's actions, enabling open-ended generation capabilities. However, existing models typically lack a 3D representation of the environment, meaning 3D consistency must be implicitly learned from data, and spatial memory is restricted to limited temporal context windows. This results in an unrealistic user experience, and presents significant obstacles to down-stream tasks such as training agents. To address this, we present PERSIST, a new paradigm of world model which simulates the evolution of a latent 3D scene: environment, camera and renderer. This allows us to synthesize new frames with persistent spatial memory and consistent geometry. Our approach achieves substantial improvements in spatial memory, 3D consistency, and long-horizon video generation quality over existing methods, producing coherent and evolving 3D worlds.</p>","absKo":"<p>interactive world modelмқҖ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗмқҳ н–үлҸҷм—җ л°ҳмқ‘н•ҳл©ҙм„ң л№„л””мҳӨлҘј м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬, open-ended generation лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң нҷҳкІҪмқҳ 3D representationмқҙ м—Ҷм–ҙ 3D мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎңл¶Җн„° м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҙм•ј н•ҳл©°, spatial memoryлҸ„ м ңн•ңлҗң temporal context windowм—җ көӯн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” л№„нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ кІҪн—ҳмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ҳкі , agent н•ҷмҠөкіј к°ҷмқҖ downstream taskм—җ нҒ° мһҘм• к°Җ лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” latent 3D sceneмқҳ м§„нҷ”лҘј мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ world model нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқё PERSISTлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҖ environment, camera, rendererлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ persistent spatial memoryмҷҖ мқјкҙҖлҗң geometryлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameмқ„ н•©м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“Өм—җ л№„н•ҙ spatial memory, 3D consistency, long-horizon video generation qualityм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң к°ңм„ мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мқјкҙҖлҗҳкі  м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” 3D worldлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66226","en":"Training-Free Adaptation of Diffusion Models via Doob's $h$-Transform","ko":"Doobмқҳ $h$-ліҖнҷҳмқ„ нҶөн•ң Diffusion Modelмқҳ нӣҲл Ё л¶Ҳн•„мҡ” м Ғмқ‘","authors":"Qijie Zhu, Zeqi Ye, Han Liu, Zhaoran Wang, Minshuo Chen","pos":"#2812","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5cu1ynhwTJ","abs":"Adaptation methods have been a workhorse for unlocking the transformative power of pre-trained diffusion models in diverse applications. Existing approaches often abstract adaptation objectives as a reward function and steer diffusion models to generate high-reward samples. However, these approaches can incur high computational overhead due to additional training, or rely on stringent assumptions on the reward such as differentiability. Moreover, despite their empirical success, theoretical justification and guarantees are seldom established. In this paper, we propose $\\texttt{DOIT}$ ($\\textbf{D}$oob-$\\textbf{O}$riented $\\textbf{I}$nference-time $\\textbf{T}$ransformation), a training-free and computationally efficient adaptation method that applies to generic, non-differentiable rewards. The key framework underlying our method is a measure transport formulation that seeks to transport the pre-trained generative distribution to a high-reward target distribution. We leverage Doob's $h$-transform to realize this transport, which induces a dynamic correction to the diffusion sampling process and enables efficient simulation-based computation without modifying the pre-trained model. Theoretically, we establish a high probability convergence guarantee to the target high-reward distribution via characterizing the approximation error in the dynamic Doob's correction. Empirically, on D4RL offline RL benchmarks, our method consistently outperforms state-of-the-art baselines while preserving sampling efficiency.","absKo":"Adaptation л°©лІ•мқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң applicationм—җм„ң pre-trained diffusion modelмқҳ transformative powerлҘј лҒҢм–ҙлӮҙлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ workhorseмҳҖлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ adaptation objectiveлҘј ліҙнҶө reward functionмңјлЎң м¶”мғҒнҷ”н•ҳкі , diffusion modelмқҙ high-reward sampleмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јмқҖ м¶”к°Җ trainingмңјлЎң мқён•ң лҶ’мқҖ кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, rewardк°Җ differentiableн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м—„кІ©н•ң к°Җм •м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мӢӨм ң кІҪн—ҳм Ғ м„ұкіөм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , мқҙлЎ м Ғ м •лӢ№нҷ”мҷҖ ліҙмһҘмқҖ кұ°мқҳ нҷ•лҰҪлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” genericн•ҳкі  non-differentiableн•ң rewardм—җ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң training-freeмқҙмһҗ кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё adaptation methodмқё $\\texttt{DOIT}$($\\textbf{D}$oob-$\\textbf{O}$riented $\\textbf{I}$nference-time $\\textbf{T}$ransformation)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ frameworkлҠ” pre-trained generative distributionмқ„ high-reward target distributionмңјлЎң transportн•ҳл ӨлҠ” measure transport formulationмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Doobмқҳ $h$-transformмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң transportлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” diffusion sampling processм—җ dynamic correctionмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳкі  pre-trained modelмқ„ мҲҳм •н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ efficient simulation-based computationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” dynamic Doob correctionмқҳ approximation errorлҘј нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ target high-reward distributionмңјлЎңмқҳ high probability convergence guaranteeлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” D4RL offline RL benchmarkм—җм„ң sampling efficiencyлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65253","en":"3D MeanFlow: One-Step Point Cloud Completion and Generation via Average-Velocity Transport","ko":"3D MeanFlow: нҸүк·  мҶҚлҸ„ мҲҳмҶЎмқ„ нҶөн•ң One-Step нҸ¬мқёнҠё нҒҙлқјмҡ°л“ң мҷ„м„ұ л°Ҹ мғқм„ұ","authors":"Haowen Zhong, Jiujun Cheng, Haowen Wang, Chao Wei, Lu Yang, Qichao Mao, Shangce Gao","pos":"#2813","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FKFaO6Qqns","abs":"<p>Point cloud completion and generation are important across many 3D tasks, where both fidelity and sampling efficiency matter. Prevailing high-fidelity approaches rely on long sampling schedules, which incur substantial inference latency. Few-step alternatives typically use rectification or distillation, leading to multi-stage training pipelines and potential quality trade-offs. We present 3D MeanFlow (3DMF), a distillation-free model that performs one-step average-velocity transport for point cloud completion and generation. We optimize an instantaneous-average consistency objective and impose a shape-level constraint to stabilize training. Additionally, we introduce PointPlug, integrating completion into 3D object detectors and evaluating its impact. PointPlug uses adaptive selection that balances benefit and latency. Across standard benchmarks, 3DMF achieves one-step sampling with an order-of-magnitude speedup while maintaining competitive fidelity. On nuScenes and KITTI, inserting PointPlug improves all evaluated detectors under comparable settings.</p>","absKo":"<p>Point cloud completionкіј generationмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ 3D task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳл©°, fidelityмҷҖ sampling efficiencyк°Җ лӘЁл‘җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ кі -fidelity approachesлҠ” кёҙ sampling scheduleм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ мғҒлӢ№н•ң inference latencyлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. Few-step лҢҖм•ҲмқҖ ліҙнҶө rectificationмқҙлӮҳ distillationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, multi-stage training pipelineкіј мһ мһ¬м Ғмқё quality trade-offлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” point cloud completionкіј generationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ one-step average-velocity transportлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” distillation-free modelмқё 3D MeanFlow (3DMF)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” instantaneous-average consistency objectiveлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳкі  shape-level constraintлҘј л¶Җкіјн•ҳм—¬ trainingмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. м¶”к°ҖлЎң, completionмқ„ 3D object detectorsм—җ нҶөн•©н•ҳкі  к·ё мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” PointPlugлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. PointPlugлҠ” benefitкіј latencyмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” adaptive selectionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ benchmarks м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, 3DMFлҠ” кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” fidelityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң one-step samplingкіј order-of-magnitude мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. nuScenesмҷҖ KITTIм—җм„ңлҠ” PointPlugлҘј мӮҪмһ…н•ҳл©ҙ л№„көҗ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м„Өм •м—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ң лӘЁл“  detectorмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ н–ҘмғҒлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63838","en":"SDiDпјҡShared diffusion prior for efficient distributed stereo image compression","ko":"SDiD: нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё л¶„мӮ° stereo image compressionмқ„ мң„н•ң кіөмң  diffusion prior","authors":"Yichong Xia, Yimin Zhou, Zongyu Li, Shiyu Qin, Mingyao Hong, Bin Chen, Haoqian Wang","pos":"#3607","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=THGrvEnELu","abs":"<p>Stereo vision is widely utilized in automotive imagery and 3D reconstruction, creating a demand for compressing stereo images. Existing methods for stereo image compression often employ VAE-like architectures based on distortion optimization, leading to subpar perceptual quality at low bitrates. While generative compression excels in high perceptual fidelity at low bitrates, it struggles to maintain consistency across viewpoints, making decoded images less useful for critical downstream tasks. To address this, we introduce SDiD, a distributed stereo image compression architecture based on shared pre-trained diffusion priors. We employ a diffusion prior alignment module to efficiently obtain the main-view-prior from the foundation diffusion, and utilize a prior transformation structure to enable the auxiliary view to achieve reliable and fast perceptual enhancement while maintaining consistency. Through extensive experiments, we demonstrate that SDiD outperforms existing methods in perceptual quality across multiple datasets. Even at extremely low bitrates, SDiD can accurately recover depth information between decoded images. On the InStereo2K dataset, SDiD requires only one-third of the bits compared to the state-of-the-art baseline (0.02 bpp vs. 0.06 bpp) to reconstruct image pairs with similar depth information.</p>","absKo":"<p>Stereo visionмқҖ automotive imageryмҷҖ 3D reconstructionм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ нҷңмҡ©лҗҳл©°, мқҙм—җ л”°лқј stereo image compressionм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҲҳмҡ”к°Җ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ stereo image compression л°©лІ•мқҖ distortion optimizationм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң VAE-like architectureлҘј мЈјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, лӮ®мқҖ bitrateм—җм„ң perceptual qualityк°Җ л–Ём–ҙм§ҖлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. Generative compressionмқҖ лӮ®мқҖ bitrateм—җм„ң лҶ’мқҖ perceptual fidelityлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° к°•м җмқ„ к°Җм§Җм§Җл§Ң, viewpoint к°„ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°лҠ” м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқҙ мһҲм–ҙ ліөмӣҗлҗң мқҙлҜём§Җк°Җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң downstream taskм—җ лҚң мң мҡ©н•ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” shared pre-trained diffusion priorлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ң distributed stereo image compression architectureмқё SDiDлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” diffusion prior alignment moduleмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ foundation diffusionм—җм„ң main-view-priorлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң м–»кі , prior transformation structureлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ auxiliary viewк°Җ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкі  л№ лҘё perceptual enhancementлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ SDiDк°Җ м—¬лҹ¬ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ perceptual qualityк°Җ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к·№лҸ„лЎң лӮ®мқҖ bitrateм—җм„ңлҸ„ SDiDлҠ” decoded image к°„ depth informationмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ ліөмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. InStereo2K лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң SDiDлҠ” state-of-the-art baseline(0.02 bpp vs. 0.06 bpp)кіј л№„көҗн•ҙ лӢЁ 1/3мқҳ bitл§ҢмңјлЎң мң мӮ¬н•ң depth informationмқ„ к°Җм§„ image pairлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65566","en":"Flex-Forcing: Towards a Unified Autoregressive and Bidirectional Video Diffusion Model","ko":"Flex-Forcing: нҶөн•© мһҗкё°нҡҢк·Җ л°Ҹ м–‘л°©н–Ҙ Video Diffusion Modelмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Xinyin Ma, Julius Berner, Chao Liu, Arash Vahdat, Weili Nie, Xinchao Wang","pos":"#3909","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=COGc3MSR7n","abs":"<p>Recent progress in large-scale generative models has substantially advanced video generation, yet existing methods remain constrained by a rigid inference paradigm. Bidirectional diffusion models excel at global coherence and visual fidelity but suffer from slow inference, while autoregressive models offer efficient and streaming generation at the cost of long-range consistency and exposure bias. We introduce Flex-Forcing, a unified training and inference framework that enables a video diffusion model to seamlessly operate under both bidirectional and autoregressive generation regimes. The core idea is a flexible chunking mechanism jointly defined over the temporal axis and denoising steps. This design allows the model to (1) perform flexible chunking according to different device budgets, (2) perform bidirectional inference across chunks for global structure planning, while generating frames autoregressively within each chunk for efficient and fine-grained synthesis, and (3) perform any-order, any-timestep autoregressive generation without the strict causal constraint. Extensive experiments on multiple video generation benchmarks demonstrate that Flex-Forcing achieves consistently better video quality, long-video stability than strong baselines with a rigid inference schedule, while offering faster inference.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ generative modelмқҳ мөңк·ј м§„м „мқҖ video generationмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ л°ңм „мӢңмј°м§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ кІҪм§Ғлҗң inference paradigmм—җ м ңм•ҪлҗңлӢӨ. Bidirectional diffusion modelмқҖ global coherenceмҷҖ visual fidelityм—җм„ңлҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮҳм§Җл§Ң inferenceк°Җ лҠҗлҰ¬кі , autoregressive modelмқҖ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  streaming generationмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ  long-range consistencyмҷҖ exposure biasлқјлҠ” лҢҖк°ҖлҘј м№ҳлҘёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” video diffusion modelмқҙ bidirectional generation regimeкіј autoregressive generation regime лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ лҸҷмһ‘н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© training л°Ҹ inference frameworkмқё Flex-Forcingмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҠ” temporal axisмҷҖ denoising step мң„м—җм„ң кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң м •мқҳлҗҳлҠ” мң м—°н•ң chunking mechanismмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ (1) м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё device budgetм—җ л”°лқј мң м—°н•ҳкІҢ chunkingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , (2) chunk к°„м—җлҠ” global structure planningмқ„ мң„н•ҙ bidirectional inferenceлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳл©ҙм„ң к°Ғ chunk лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ңлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  м„ёл°Җн•ң synthesisлҘј мң„н•ҙ frameмқ„ autoregressively мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, (3) м—„кІ©н•ң causal constraint м—Ҷмқҙ any-order, any-timestep autoregressive generationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ video generation benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Flex-Forcingмқҙ к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ video qualityмҷҖ long-video stabilityлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” л№ лҘё inferenceлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63600","en":"Learning Discrete Diffusion on Graphs via Free-Energy Gradient Flows","ko":"мһҗмң м—җл„Ҳм§Җ кё°мҡёкё° нқҗлҰ„мқ„ нҶөн•ң к·ёлһҳн”„ мғҒ мқҙмӮ° нҷ•мӮ° н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Dario Rancati, Jan Maas, Francesco Locatello","pos":"#4504","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=VaQZwmnPGv","abs":"Diffusion-based models on continuous spaces have seen substantial recent progress through the mathematical framework of gradient flows, leveraging the Wasserstein-2 (${W}_2$) metric via the Jordan-Kinderlehrer-Otto (JKO) scheme. Despite the increasing popularity of diffusion models on discrete spaces using continuous-time Markov chains, a parallel theoretical framework based on gradient flows has remained elusive due to intrinsic challenges in translating the ${W}_2$ distance directly into these settings. In this work, we propose the first successful approach addressing these challenges, leveraging an appropriate metric $W_K$ on the simplex of probability distributions, which enables us to interpret widely used discrete diffusion paths, such as the discrete heat equation, as gradient flows of specific free-energy functionals. Through this theoretical insight, we introduce a novel methodology for learning diffusion dynamics over discrete spaces, which recovers the underlying functional directly by leveraging first-order optimality conditions for the JKO scheme. The resulting method optimizes a simple quadratic loss, trains extremely fast, does not require individual sample trajectories, and only needs a numerical preprocessing computing $W_K$-geodesics. We validate our method through extensive numerical experiments on synthetic data, showing that we can recover the underlying functional for a variety of graph classes.","absKo":"м—°мҶҚ кіөк°„м—җм„ңмқҳ diffusion-based modelмқҖ Jordan-Kinderlehrer-Otto (JKO) schemeмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ Wasserstein-2 (${W}_2$) metricмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” gradient flowмқҳ мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ frameworkлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мөңк·ј нҒ° м§„м „мқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. continuous-time Markov chainмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” discrete spaceм—җм„ңмқҳ diffusion modelмқҖ м җм җ лҚ” л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳкі  мһҲм§Җл§Ң, ${W}_2$ distanceлҘј мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„Өм •м—җ м§Ғм ‘ мҳ®кё°кё° м–ҙл өлӢӨлҠ” ліём§Ҳм Ғ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖ л•Ңл¬ём—җ gradient flowм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң лі‘л ¬ мқҙлЎ м Ғ frameworkлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м ңмӢңлҗҳм§Җ лӘ»н–ҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ м„ұкіөм Ғмқё м ‘к·јмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. нҷ•лҘ  л¶„нҸ¬ simplex мң„мқҳ м Ғм Ҳн•ң metric $W_K$лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, discrete heat equationкіј к°ҷмқҙ л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” discrete diffusion pathлҘј нҠ№м • free-energy functionalмқҳ gradient flowлЎң н•ҙм„қн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” discrete spaceм—җм„ңмқҳ diffusion dynamicsлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л°©лІ•лЎ мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, JKO schemeмқҳ first-order optimality conditionмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ underlying functionalмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ лӢЁмҲңн•ң quadratic lossлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳл©°, л§Өмҡ° л№ лҘҙкІҢ н•ҷмҠөлҗҳкі , к°ңлі„ sample trajectoryлҘј н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, $W_K$-geodesicsлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” мҲҳм№ҳм Ғ preprocessingл§Ң н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” synthetic dataм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң graph classм—җм„ң underlying functionalмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65824","en":"Learning Manifold Data with Flow Matching","ko":"Flow Matchingмқ„ нҶөн•ң лӢӨм–‘мІҙ лҚ°мқҙн„° н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Sophia Pi, Mingcheng Lu, Jerry Yao-Chieh Hu, Maojiang Su, Weimin Wu, Han Liu","pos":"#4624","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9mA5d705Gd","abs":"<p>We study flow-matching transformers when data lie on a low-dimensional manifold.  Our key insight is a flow decomposition that splits motion along the manifold from motion off the manifold.  The scheme works for first- and higher-order flow matching and ties model complexity to the intrinsic manifold dimension.  Building on these, we establish tighter sample-complexity bounds for velocity approximation, velocity estimation, and distribution estimation. These bounds meet near-minimax rates for flow-matching transformers of any order. Our results show how flow-matching transformers escape the curse of dimensionality by utilizing intrinsic data structure.</p>","absKo":"лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ м Җм°Ёмӣҗ manifold мң„м—җ лҶ“м—¬ мһҲмқ„ л•Ңмқҳ flow-matching transformerлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ нҶөм°°мқҖ manifoldлҘј л”°лқјк°ҖлҠ” motionкіј manifold л°–мңјлЎң лІ—м–ҙлӮҳлҠ” motionмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” flow decompositionмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ schemeмқҖ first-orderмҷҖ higher-order flow matching лӘЁл‘җм—җ м Ғмҡ©лҗҳл©° model complexityлҘј intrinsic manifold dimensionкіј м—°кІ°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” velocity approximation, velocity estimation, distribution estimationм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҚ” нғҖмқҙнҠён•ң sample-complexity boundлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ boundлҠ” м–ҙл–Ө м°ЁмҲҳмқҳ flow-matching transformerм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ кұ°мқҳ minimax rateлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” flow-matching transformerк°Җ intrinsic data structureлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ dimensionality curseлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ лІ—м–ҙлӮҳлҠ”м§Җ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64790","en":"ReTabSyn: Realistic Tabular Data Synthesis via Reinforcement Learning","ko":"ReTabSyn: Reinforcement Learningмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҳ„мӢӨм Ғ Tabular лҚ°мқҙн„° н•©м„ұ","authors":"Xiaofeng Lin, Seungbae Kim, Zhuoya Li, Zachary DeSoto, Charles Fleming, Guang Cheng","pos":"#4517","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=JmfyJj8aBf","abs":"Deep generative models can help with data scarcity and privacy by producing synthetic training data, but they struggle in low-data, imbalanced tabular settings to fully learn the complex data distribution.  We argue that striving for the full joint distribution could be overkill; for greater data efficiency, models should prioritize learning the conditional distribution $P(y\\mid \\bm{X})$, as suggested by recent theoretical analysis. Therefore, we overcome this limitation with \\textbf{ReTabSyn}, a \\textbf{Re}inforced \\textbf{Tab}ular \\textbf{Syn}thesis pipeline that provides direct feedback on feature correlation preservation during synthesizer training.  This objective encourages the generator to prioritize the most useful predictive signals when training data is limited, thereby strengthening downstream model utility.  We empirically fine-tune a language model-based generator using this approach, and across benchmarks with small sample sizes, class imbalance, and distribution shift, ReTabSyn consistently outperforms state-of-the-art baselines.  Moreover, our approach can be readily extended to control various aspects of synthetic tabular data, such as applying expert-specified constraints on generated observations.","absKo":"л”Ҙ мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ synthetic training dataлҘј мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶ҖмЎұкіј н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, low-dataмқҳ imbalanced tabular settingм—җм„ңлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶„нҸ¬лҘј м¶©л¶„нһҲ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м „мІҙ joint distributionмқ„ мҷ„м „нһҲ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл ӨлҠ” мӢңлҸ„лҠ” кіјлҸ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, лҚ” нҒ° data efficiencyлҘј мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” мөңк·ј мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қмқҙ мӢңмӮ¬н•ҳл“Ҝ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ conditional distribution $P(y\\mid \\bm{X})$ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мҡ°м„ н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” synthesizer training лҸҷм•Ҳ feature correlation ліҙмЎҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң м§Ғм ‘м Ғмқё н”јл“ңл°ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” \\textbf{ReTabSyn}, мҰү \\textbf{Re}inforced \\textbf{Tab}ular \\textbf{Syn}thesis pipelineмңјлЎң мқҙ н•ңкі„лҘј к·№ліөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лӘ©н‘ңлҠ” м ңн•ңлҗң training data нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң generatorк°Җ к°ҖмһҘ мң мҡ©н•ң predictive signalмқ„ мҡ°м„ н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬ downstream model utilityлҘј к°•нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м ‘к·јмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ language model кё°л°ҳ generatorлҘј мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң fine-tuneн–Ҳкі , мҶҢн‘ңліё, class imbalance, distribution shiftлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җм„ң ReTabSynмқҙ state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ мғқм„ұлҗң кҙҖмёЎм№ҳм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м „л¬ёк°Җк°Җ м§Җм •н•ң constraintлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмІҳлҹј synthetic tabular dataмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мёЎл©ҙмқ„ м ңм–ҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мҶҗмүҪкІҢ нҷ•мһҘлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"63683","en":"Smoothness Errors in Dynamics Models and How to Avoid Them","ko":"лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ л§ӨлҒ„лҹ¬мӣҖ мҳӨлҘҳмҷҖ мқҙлҘј н”јн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•","authors":"Edward Berman, Luisa Li, Jung Yeon Park, Robin Walters","pos":"#2200","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Uf3SMkP2Wd","abs":"<p>Modern neural networks have shown promise for solving partial differential equations over surfaces, often by discretizing the surface as a mesh and learning with a mesh-aware graph neural network. However, graph neural networks suffer from oversmoothing, where a node's features become increasingly similar to those of its neighbors. Unitary graph convolutions, which are mathematically constrained to preserve smoothness, have been proposed to address this issue. Despite this, in many physical systems, such as diffusion processes, smoothness naturally increases and unitarity may be overconstraining. In this paper, we systematically study the smoothing effects of different GNNs for dynamics modeling and prove that unitary convolutions hurt performance for such tasks. We propose relaxed unitary convolutions that balance smoothness preservation with the natural smoothing required for physical systems. We also generalize unitary and relaxed unitary convolutions from graphs to meshes. In experiments on PDEs such as the heat and wave equations over complex meshes and on weather forecasting, we find that our method outperforms several strong baselines, including mesh-aware transformers and equivariant neural networks. Our code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/rayleigh_analysis-BD52/README.md .</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖ neural networkлҠ” surface мң„м—җм„ң partial differential equationмқ„ н‘ёлҠ” лҚ° мң л§қн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—Ҳмңјл©°, нқ”нһҲ surfaceлҘј meshлЎң мқҙмӮ°нҷ”н•ҳкі  mesh-aware graph neural networkлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ graph neural networkлҠ” oversmoothing л¬ём ңлҘј кІӘлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙл•Ң nodeмқҳ featureк°Җ мқҙмӣғл“Өмқҳ featureмҷҖ м җм җ лҚ” мң мӮ¬н•ҙм§„лӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң smoothnessлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м ңм•Ҫлҗң unitary graph convolutionмқҖ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹјм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  diffusion processмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ л§ҺмқҖ physical systemм—җм„ңлҠ” smoothnessк°Җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ мҰқк°Җн•ҳл©°, unitarityлҠ” кіјлҸ„н•ң м ңм•Ҫмқҙ лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” dynamics modelingмқ„ мң„н•ң м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё GNNмқҳ smoothing effectлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң м—°кө¬н•ҳкі , мқҙлҹ¬н•ң taskм—җм„ң unitary convolutionмқҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м Җн•ҙн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” smoothness ліҙмЎҙкіј physical systemм—җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ мҡ”кө¬лҗҳлҠ” smoothing мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” relaxed unitary convolutionмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң graphм—җм„ң meshлЎң unitary л°Ҹ relaxed unitary convolutionмқ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. ліөмһЎн•ң mesh мң„мқҳ heat equationкіј wave equation к°ҷмқҖ PDE л°Ҹ weather forecasting мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ mesh-aware transformerмҷҖ equivariant neural networkлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м—¬лҹ¬ к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/rayleigh_analysis-BD52/README.md м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63212","en":"SimGFM: Simplifying Discrete Flow Matching for Graph Generation","ko":"SimGFM: к·ёлһҳн”„ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мқҙмӮ° Flow Matching лӢЁмҲңнҷ”","authors":"Chunyu Luo, Yuankai Luo, Xiao-Ming Wu, Lei Shi","pos":"#2300","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Z3xgDd5B2L","abs":"<p>Discrete Flow Matching (DFM) presents a promising approach for graph generation; however, existing adaptations often introduce substantial complexity by incorporating task-specific heuristics, compromising the continuity equation and significantly expanding the hyperparameter space. Moreover, their sampling efficiency remains limited, as the required number of steps is often comparable to diffusion models, diminishing DFMвҖҷs practical advantages. To address these limitations, we propose SimGFM, a simplified graph DFM for graph generation. Leveraging characteristic patterns in graph-generation trajectories, SimGFM relies only on the scheduler and rate matrix, eliminating heavy heuristics and hyperparameter tuning, and achieves large step reductions while preserving SOTA results. SimGFM achieves strong empirical results: on QM9, it matches prior models requiring 500вҖ“1000 steps with only 10 steps, and on most datasets, its performance at 50 steps matches or surpasses these baselines, demonstrating both efficiency and competitiveness.</p>","absKo":"<p>Discrete Flow Matching(DFM)мқҖ graph generationмқ„ мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙмқҳ adaptationмқҖ task-specific heuristicмқ„ нҸ¬н•ЁмӢңмјң мғҒлӢ№н•ң ліөмһЎм„ұмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һкі , continuity equationмқ„ нӣјмҶҗн•ҳл©°, hyperparameter spaceлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ”кө¬лӮҳ sampling efficiencyлҸ„ м—¬м „нһҲ м ңн•ңм ҒмқёлҚ°, н•„мҡ”н•ң step мҲҳк°Җ diffusion modelкіј л№„мҠ·н•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқё кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„ DFMмқҳ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ мһҘм җмқ„ м•Ҫнҷ”мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” graph generationмқ„ мң„н•ң лӢЁмҲңнҷ”лҗң graph DFMмқё SimGFMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. graph-generation trajectoryмқҳ нҠ№м§•м Ғ нҢЁн„ҙмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” SimGFMмқҖ schedulerмҷҖ rate matrixл§Ңмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ л¬ҙкұ°мҡҙ heuristicкіј hyperparameter tuningмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ҳкі , SOTA кІ°кіјлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң нҒ° step reductionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. SimGFMмқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң мӢӨн—ҳм Ғ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. QM9м—җм„ңлҠ” 500~1000 stepмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ лӘЁлҚёл“Өкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ лӢЁ 10 stepмңјлЎң лҸҷл“ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ңлҠ” 50 stepм—җм„ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң baselineкіј к°ҷкұ°лӮҳ лҚ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, нҡЁмңЁм„ұкіј кІҪмҹҒл Ҙмқ„ лҸҷмӢңм—җ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65852","en":"S$^3$GNN: Efficient Global Mixing and Local Message Passing for Long-Range Graph Learning","ko":"S$^3$GNN: мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ к·ёлһҳн”„ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ м „м—ӯ нҳјн•©кіј көӯмҶҢ л©”мӢңм§Җ м „лӢ¬","authors":"Dai Shi, Linhan Luo, Luke Thompson, Lequan Lin, Andi Han, Junbin Gao, Jose Miguel Hernandez-Lobato","pos":"#2303","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9SCVnAxoKK","abs":"Message-passing neural networks (MPNNs) often suffer from an information bottleneck when capturing long-range dependencies, leading to the oversquashing (OSQ) phenomenon. Alongside spatial connectivity enrichment (e.g., rewiring), recent studies have shown that spectral filtering can yield strong long-range learning outcomes, as spectral operators enable global information mixing that alleviates OSQ. These approaches achieve this either by stabilizing the Jacobian energies in deep propagation or by guaranteeing OSQ mitigation under strong theoretical assumptions. We revisit these conclusions and show that the associated Jacobian sensitivity lower bound is generally difficult to achieve in practice. We then propose S$^3$GNN, which mitigates OSQ without such restrictive assumptions by lightweightly reintroducing omitted components with substantially lower computational complexity, while standard stability constraints on feature transformations remain effective under our new dynamics. Extensive experiments across diverse domains (e.g., long-range benchmarks, KGQA, and mesh-based fluid dynamics) demonstrate that S$^3$GNN achieves up to an order-of-magnitude error reduction with up to 50\\% fewer parameters. Our code can be found in https://anonymous.4open.science/r/S3GNN-2359.","absKo":"Message-passing neural network (MPNN)мқҖ кёҙ лІ”мң„мқҳ мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•  л•Ң м •ліҙ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ кІӘлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һмңјл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј oversquashing (OSQ) нҳ„мғҒмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. кіөк°„м Ғ м—°кІ°м„ұ н–ҘмғҒ(мҳҲ: rewiring)кіј н•Ёк»ҳ, мөңк·ј м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ spectral filteringмқҙ к°•л Ҙн•ң long-range н•ҷмҠө м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӮј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” spectral operatorк°Җ м „м—ӯ м •ліҙ нҳјн•©мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬ OSQлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јмқҖ к№ҠмқҖ propagationм—җм„ң Jacobian energyлҘј м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, к°•н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ к°Җм • н•ҳм—җ OSQ мҷ„нҷ”лҘј ліҙмһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°лЎ мқ„ мһ¬кІҖнҶ н•ҳкі , кҙҖл Ё Jacobian sensitivity lower boundк°Җ мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. ШіЩҫШі мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” S$^3$GNNмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ңн•ңм Ғ к°Җм • м—Ҷмқҙ OSQлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл©°, мғқлһөлҗң кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢлҘј нӣЁм”¬ лӮ®мқҖ кі„мӮ° ліөмһЎлҸ„лЎң к°ҖліҚкІҢ лӢӨмӢң лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҙлӢӨ. н•ңнҺё feature transformationм—җ лҢҖн•ң н‘ңмӨҖ stability constraintлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷ н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ м—¬м „нһҲ нҡЁкіјм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң лҸ„л©”мқё(мҳҲ: long-range benchmark, KGQA, mesh-based fluid dynamics)м—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ S$^3$GNNмқҙ мөңлҢҖ 50\\% м ҒмқҖ parameterлЎң мөңлҢҖ н•ң мһҗлҰҝмҲҳ нҒ¬кё°мқҳ error reductionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/S3GNN-2359 м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"62202","en":"RAPNet: Accelerating Algebraic Multigrid with Learned Sparse Corrections","ko":"RAPNet: н•ҷмҠөлҗң нқ¬мҶҢ ліҙм •(Learned Sparse Corrections)мңјлЎң Algebraic Multigrid к°ҖмҶҚ","authors":"Yali Fink, Ido Ben-Yair, Lars Ruthotto, Eran Treister","pos":"#2306","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=iiNPaOvuwj","abs":"<p>The scalable solution of large sparse linear systems is a bottleneck in scientific computing and graph analysis. While algebraic multigrid (AMG) offers optimal linear scaling, its performance is severely constrained by the trade-off between the sparsity and convergence quality of coarse-grid operators. Classical AMG heuristics struggle to balance these objectives, often sacrificing stability for sparsity. We propose RAPNet, a graph neural network (GNN) framework that resolves this trade-off by learning to generate sparse, robust coarse operators directly from the sparse algebraic system. Key to our approach is a level-wise training strategy that enables learning from small subgraphs and generalization to million-node domains, bypassing the bottlenecks of prior neural AMG attempts. RAPNet executes exclusively during the solver setup phase, ensuring that the solve phase retains its favorable computational properties. We show that our method outperforms classical non-Galerkin baselines on diverse PDE discretizations and graph Laplacians, making it particularly effective for multi-query tasks such as eigenproblems, time-dependent simulations, and inverse or design problems.</p>","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ sparse linear systemмқҳ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н•ҙлІ•мқҖ scientific computingкіј graph analysisм—җм„ң лі‘лӘ©мңјлЎң мһ‘мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. Algebraic multigrid (AMG)лҠ” мөңм Ғмқҳ м„ нҳ• мҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, coarse-grid operatorмқҳ sparsityмҷҖ convergence quality к°„ trade-off л•Ңл¬ём—җ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. кі м „м Ғмқё AMG heuristicмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘ©н‘ңлҘј к· нҳ• мһҲкІҢ л§һм¶”лҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘмңјл©°, мў…мў… sparsityлҘј мң„н•ҙ stabilityлҘј нқ¬мғқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” sparse algebraic systemмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° sparseн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ robustн•ң coarse operatorлҘј м§Ғм ‘ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” graph neural network (GNN) frameworkмқё RAPNetмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬ мқҙ trade-offлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ мһ‘мқҖ subgraphлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  million-node domainмңјлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” level-wise training strategyмқҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙ neural AMG мӢңлҸ„мқҳ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ мҡ°нҡҢн•ңлӢӨ. RAPNetмқҖ мҳӨм§Ғ solver setup phaseм—җм„ңл§Ң мӢӨн–үлҗҳлҜҖлЎң, solve phaseк°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ мң лҰ¬н•ң кі„мӮ° нҠ№м„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң PDE discretizationкіј graph Laplacianм—җм„ң classical non-Galerkin baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, eigenproblem, time-dependent simulation, inverse лҳҗлҠ” design problemкіј к°ҷмқҖ multi-query taskм—җ нҠ№нһҲ нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65858","en":"PhenoBrain: Phenotype-Conditioned Long-Range Communication for Multi-Modal Brain Network Analysis","ko":"PhenoBrain: л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ лҮҢ л„ӨнҠёмӣҢнҒ¬ л¶„м„қмқ„ мң„н•ң н‘ңнҳ„нҳ• мЎ°кұҙл¶Җ мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ нҶөмӢ ","authors":"Lingyuan Meng, KE LIANG, Hao Li, Meng Liu, Weijia Shi, Miaomiao Li, Yang Gao, Xinwang Liu","pos":"#2308","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9NqKL9QQ4a","abs":"<p>Multi-modal brain network analysis aims to predict neuropsychiatric status from functional connectomes with heterogeneous phenotypes. However, most existing methods treat phenotypes as auxiliary features and perform late fusion, implicitly assuming that the connectome representation should be learned in the same way regardless of phenotype. However, in clinical neuroscience the same functional connectivity pattern may support different conclusions under different phenotype contexts. To bridge this gap, we propose PhenoBrain, a novel framework for multi-modal brain network analysis that injects phenotype information at the mechanism level rather than only at the classifier level. Specifically, we propose a phenotype-conditioned long-range routing mechanism, which learns a subject-specific multi-hop communication kernel to model long-range connectome interactions. Furthermore, we propose a phenotypic-guided attention mechanism regulation method, which uses phenotypic information as a conditional prior to regulate the learning process of attention in brain networks. To verify the effectiveness of our method, we constructed two multi-modal brain network analysis datasets based on open-source image data. Extensive experiments demonstrate that PhenoBrain achieves state-of-the-art performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>лӢӨмӨ‘ лӘЁлӢ¬ brain network л¶„м„қмқҖ heterogeneous phenotypeмқ„ к°Җм§„ functional connectomeмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° neuropsychiatric мғҒнғңлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ phenotypeмқ„ ліҙмЎ° featureлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳкі  late fusionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳл©°, phenotypeкіј л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳкІҢ connectome representationмқҙ лҸҷмқјн•ң л°©мӢқмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗҳм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң к°Җм •н•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳм§Җл§Ң мһ„мғҒ мӢ кІҪкіјн•ҷм—җм„ңлҠ” лҸҷмқјн•ң functional connectivity patternмқҙ phenotype contextм—җ л”°лқј м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё кІ°лЎ мқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” phenotype м •ліҙлҘј classifier мҲҳмӨҖмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј mechanism мҲҳмӨҖм—җм„ң мЈјмһ…н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лӢӨмӨ‘ лӘЁлӢ¬ brain network л¶„м„қ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ PhenoBrainмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” phenotype-conditioned long-range routing mechanismмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬ subject-specific multi-hop communication kernelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  long-range connectome interactionмқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, phenotypic-guided attention mechanism regulation л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬ phenotype м •ліҙлҘј conditional priorлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ brain networkм—җм„ң attentionмқҳ н•ҷмҠө кіјм •мқ„ мЎ°м Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҳӨн”ҲмҶҢмҠӨ мқҙлҜём§Җ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң л‘җ к°ңмқҳ лӢӨмӨ‘ лӘЁлӢ¬ brain network л¶„м„қ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқ„ кө¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PhenoBrainмқҙ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62936","en":"On the Expressive Power of GNNs to Solve Linear SDPs","ko":"м„ нҳ• SDPsлҘј н’Җкё° мң„н•ң GNNмқҳ н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ","authors":"Chendi Qian, Christopher Morris","pos":"#2309","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bjvLKXsTMK","abs":"<p>Semidefinite programs (SDPs) are a powerful framework for convex optimization and for constructing strong relaxations of hard combinatorial problems. However, solving large SDPs can be computationally expensive, motivating the use of machine learning models as fast computational surrogates. Graph neural networks (GNNs) are a natural candidate in this setting due to their sparsity-awareness and ability to model variable-constraint interactions. In this work, we study what expressive power is sufficient to recover optimal SDP solutions. We first prove negative results showing that standard GNN architectures fail on recovering linear SDP solutions. We then identify a more expressive architecture that captures the key structure of SDPs and can, in particular, emulate the updates of a standard first-order solver. Empirically, on both synthetic and SDPLIB benchmarks of various classes of SDPs, this more expressive architecture achieves consistently lower prediction error and objective gap than theoretically weaker baselines. Finally, using the learned high-quality predictions to warm-start the first-order solver yields practical speedups of up to 80%.</p>","absKo":"<p>Semidefinite program(SDP)мқҖ convex optimizationкіј м–ҙл Өмҡҙ мЎ°н•© мөңм Ғнҷ” л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•л Ҙн•ң relaxationмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мң мҡ©н•ң н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ SDPлҘј н‘ёлҠ” кІғмқҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ л§Өмҡ° нҒ¬лҜҖлЎң, л№ лҘё кі„мӮ° лҢҖлҰ¬ лӘЁлҚёлЎңм„ң machine learning modelмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳл ӨлҠ” лҸҷкё°к°Җ мғқкёҙлӢӨ. Graph neural network(GNN)лҠ” sparsityлҘј мқёмӢқн•ҳкі  ліҖмҲҳ-м ңм•Ҫ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җм—җм„ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„Өм •м—җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ нӣ„ліҙмқҙлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мөңм Ғ SDP н•ҙлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м¶©л¶„н•ң н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқҙ л¬ҙм—Үмқём§Җ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ н‘ңмӨҖ GNN architectureк°Җ м„ нҳ• SDP н•ҙлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӢӨнҢЁн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјлҠ” л¶Җм •м Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң SDPмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкі , нҠ№нһҲ н‘ңмӨҖ first-order solverмқҳ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҘј лӘЁмӮ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лҚ” к°•л Ҙн•ң architectureлҘј мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, лӢӨм–‘н•ң мў…лҘҳмқҳ SDPм—җ лҢҖн•ң synthetic benchmarkмҷҖ SDPLIB benchmark лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мқҙ лҚ” н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мһҲлҠ” architectureлҠ” мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң лҚ” м•Ҫн•ң baselineліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” лӮ®мқҖ prediction errorмҷҖ objective gapмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, н•ҷмҠөлҗң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ мҳҲмёЎк°’мңјлЎң first-order solverлҘј warm-startн•ҳл©ҙ мөңлҢҖ 80%мқҳ мӢӨм ң мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60641","en":"MV-FGAD: Towards Efficient and Effective Federated Graph Anomaly Detection via Multi-view Learning","ko":"MV-FGAD: Multi-view Learningмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё Federated Graph Anomaly Detectionмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Junyi Yan, KE LIANG, Hao Yu, Meng Liu, Hao Tan, Tianrui Liu, Jun-Jie Huang, Xinwang Liu","pos":"#2310","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=yBcY0bY45t","abs":"<p>Federated graph anomaly detection (GAD) aims to identify abnormal nodes in distributed subgraphs through collaborative learning. However, existing methods suffer from two limitations. 1) Their reliance on neighborhood aggregation assumes that anomalous information can be sufficiently captured, which often fails in federated learning with partitioned client subgraphs. 2) They overlook the detection bottleneck caused by weak attribute or structural anomalies. To tackle these challenges, we revisit federated GAD and reveal that weak anomalies exhibit harder-to-detect signals compared to strong anomalies. Specifically, we propose MV-FGAD, an efficient and effective federated GAD framework based on multi-view learning designed to mine anomalies of varying strengths. MV-FGAD introduces a federated knowledge learning module to aggregate and broadcast shared knowledge, which is further exploited to optimize local topological structures. Moreover, it designs a multi-view learning mechanism to capture diverse anomaly patterns, and adopts Mahalanobis distanceвҖ“based scoring strategy to quantify node abnormality across views. Extensive experiments on real-world datasets of varying types and scales demonstrate MV-FGAD's efficiency and effectiveness.</p>","absKo":"<p>Federated graph anomaly detection(GAD)мқҖ л¶„мӮ°лҗң subgraphм—җм„ң abnormal nodeлҘј collaborative learningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•ңкі„лҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨ. 1) neighborhood aggregationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң anomalous informationмқҙ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҸ¬м°©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨкі  к°Җм •н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” partitioned client subgraphлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” federated learningм—җм„ңлҠ” мһҗмЈј мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. 2) м•Ҫн•ң attribute лҳҗлҠ” structural anomalyлЎң мқён•ҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” detection bottleneckмқ„ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” federated GADлҘј мһ¬кІҖнҶ н•ҳкі  weak anomalyк°Җ strong anomalyліҙлӢӨ нғҗм§Җн•ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ signalмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮёлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң к°•лҸ„мқҳ anomalyлҘј л°ңкөҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң multi-view learning кё°л°ҳмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё federated GAD frameworkмқё MV-FGADлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. MV-FGADлҠ” shared knowledgeлҘј aggregateн•ҳкі  broadcastн•ҳлҠ” federated knowledge learning moduleмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” local topological structureлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м¶”к°ҖлЎң нҷңмҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң anomaly patternмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң multi-view learning mechanismмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ҳкі , view м „л°ҳмқҳ node abnormalityлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ Mahalanobis distance кё°л°ҳ scoring strategyлҘј мұ„нғқн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң мң нҳ•кіј к·ңлӘЁм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ MV-FGADмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм„ұкіј нҡЁкіјм„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62265","en":"Discriminative Mixture-of-Experts on Graphs with Reliable Expert Fusion","ko":"мӢ лў° к°ҖлҠҘн•ң Expert Fusionмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ Graphsмқҳ Discriminative Mixture-of-Experts","authors":"Haoyue Deng, Menghui Wang, Yunlong Zhou, Jingyi Liu, Ran Zhang, Chunming Hu, Xiao Wang","pos":"#2401","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=iB1x9F6n3p","abs":"Graph Mixture-of-Experts (Graph-MoE) offers a way to scale GNNs via adaptive capacity allocation, with the goal of allowing different experts to capture diverse graph patterns. Its effectiveness heavily depends on the coordination between routing decisions and expert specialization. However, through extensive empirical study, we identify two critical phenomena. First, discrimination loss occurs on both the expert and routing sides, where GNN experts become highly homogenized and the router collapses to a small subset of experts, failing to reflect diverse graph semantics. Second, routing uncertainty is prevalent, as existing routers produce uncertain expert assignments for most nodes, and such uncertainty exhibits a strong negative correlation with model performance. To address these issues, we propose C$^2$GMoE, a novel **G**raph-**MoE** framework featuring **C**ontrastive routing and **C**onfidence-aware fusion. We introduce a group-wise contrastive routing strategy that provides explicit guidance for routing optimization by aligning node-level routing decisions with semantic clusters while satisfying load-balancing constraints. Moreover, through a theoretical analysis of generalization error, we develop a confidence-aware fusion mechanism that adaptively reweights expert predictions according to their confidence. Extensive experiments across multiple benchmarks demonstrate the effectiveness of our proposed C$^2$GMoE.","absKo":"Graph Mixture-of-Experts(Graph-MoE)лҠ” adaptive capacity allocationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ GNNмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё expertк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң graph patternмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ё нҡЁкіјлҠ” routing decisionкіј expert specialization к°„мқҳ мЎ°м •м—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨмҰқ м—°кө¬лҘј нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң нҳ„мғҒмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, expertмҷҖ routing м–‘мӘҪм—җм„ң discrimination lossк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, GNN expertлҠ” л§Өмҡ° лҸҷм§Ҳнҷ”лҗҳкі  routerлҠ” мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ expertлЎң л¶•кҙҙн•ҳм—¬ лӢӨм–‘н•ң graph semanticsлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, routing uncertaintyк°Җ л„җлҰ¬ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, кё°мЎҙ routerлҠ” лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ nodeм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨн•ң expert assignmentлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқҖ model performanceмҷҖ к°•н•ң мқҢмқҳ мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„лҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Contrastive routingкіј Confidence-aware fusionмқ„ нҠ№м§•мңјлЎң н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ **G**raph-**M**oE frameworkмқё C$^2$GMoEлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” node-level routing decisionмқ„ semantic clusterмҷҖ м •л ¬н•ҳл©ҙм„ң load-balancing constraintлҘј л§ҢмЎұмӢңнӮӨлҠ” group-wise contrastive routing strategyлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ routing мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң лӘ…мӢңм Ғ м§Җм№Ёмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ generalization errorм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ confidence-aware fusion mechanismмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬, expert predictionмқ„ к·ё мӢ лў°лҸ„м—җ л”°лқј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬к°ҖмӨ‘н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ң C$^2$GMoEмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63558","en":"Dual-channel Dynamic Graph Neural Networks with Adaptive Adjacency Learning and Multi-scale Representation Fusion","ko":"м Ғмқ‘м Ғ мқём ‘м„ұ н•ҷмҠөкіј лӢӨмӨ‘ мҠӨмјҖмқј н‘ңнҳ„ мңөн•©мқ„ к°–лҠ” мқҙмӨ‘ мұ„л„җ лҸҷм Ғ к·ёлһҳн”„ мӢ кІҪл§қ","authors":"Youqing Wang, Jiahao Long, Tianxiang Zhao, Man Cao, Mengyuan Xin, Jiapu Wang, Junbin Gao, Jipeng Guo","pos":"#2402","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=W2AcLgOlvX","abs":"<p>Graph neural networks (GNNs) have been demonstrated to be powerful tools for analyzing structural graph data. However, most existing methods usually rely on fixed adjacency structures for information propagation, lacking strong adaptability to the latent semantic relationships that exist but are not explicitly connected in graph, especially in complementary high-pass and low-pass filtering views. To this end, this paper proposes a novel Dual-channel Dynamic Graph Neural Network (DCD-GNN), mainly consisting of parallel representation learning channels: a static structure-preserving channel and a dynamic adjacency-enhancing channel. The dynamic channel exploits both low-pass structural filtering and high-pass personalized detail via self-attention adjacency learning and then integrates them for comprehensive semantic modeling, while the static channel maintains structural stability. Both channels employ a multi-scale representation fusion mechanism and are finally fused into a unified and discriminative node embedding representation. Extensive experiments on various graph benchmark datasets verify the superiority of DCD-GNN in discriminative graph representation learning.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph neural networks (GNNs)лҠ” кө¬мЎ°м Ғ graph dataлҘј л¶„м„қн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° к°•л Ҙн•ң лҸ„кө¬мһ„мқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ м •ліҙ м „нҢҢлҘј мң„н•ҙ кі м •лҗң adjacency structureм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„, graphм—җлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м—°кІ°лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм§Җ м•Ҡм§Җл§Ң мһ мһ¬м ҒмңјлЎң мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” semantic relationship, нҠ№нһҲ complementary high-pass л°Ҹ low-pass filtering viewм—җ лҢҖн•ң м Ғмқ‘м„ұмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ мЈјлЎң лі‘л ¬ representation learning channelлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Dual-channel Dynamic Graph Neural Network (DCD-GNN)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, static structure-preserving channelкіј dynamic adjacency-enhancing channelмқҙлӢӨ. dynamic channelмқҖ self-attention adjacency learningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ low-pass structural filteringкіј high-pass personalized detailмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ нҷңмҡ©н•ң л’Ө мқҙлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё semantic modelingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , static channelмқҖ structural stabilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. л‘җ channelмқҖ лӘЁл‘җ multi-scale representation fusion mechanismмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©°, мөңмў…м ҒмңјлЎң unifiedн•ҳкі  discriminativeн•ң node embedding representationмңјлЎң мңөн•©лҗңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң graph benchmark datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ discriminative graph representation learningм—җм„ң DCD-GNNмқҳ мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65714","en":"Error-Driven Graph Augmentation for Mesh-Based PDE Surrogates","ko":"л©”мү¬ кё°л°ҳ PDE лҢҖлҰ¬ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мң„н•ң мҳӨлҘҳ мң лҸ„ к·ёлһҳн”„ мҰқк°•","authors":"Xuan Minh Vuong Nguyen, Nissrine Akkari, Fabien Casenave, Jonathan Viquerat, Elie Hachem","pos":"#2404","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=AuX7hzqCyy","abs":"<p>Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) on meshes have emerged as promising surrogates for computational mechanics, but standard local message passing struggles to propagate information across unstructured meshes, leading to large errors in regions with complex physics (e.g., shocks, wakes, boundary layers). Existing approaches enlarge connectivity with long-range edges chosen <em>a priori</em> via geometric heuristics or random sampling, which lack a mechanism to prioritize high-error regions and often introduce redundant communication. We propose <strong>MiSe-GNN</strong>, a dual-head architecture that adaptively augments graph connectivity using model-predicted <em>a posteriori</em> errors. MiSe-GNN jointly predicts physical fields and a node-wise error indicator; the predicted error is periodically converted into a hierarchy of additional edges via an adaptive tree that links high-error nodes to spatial pivots at multiple scales. This error-guided connectivity concentrates message passing where the surrogate is uncertain while keeping the graph sparse elsewhere, yielding a transparent and physically interpretable graph-space analogue of adaptive mesh refinement. Across industrial CFD and CSD benchmarks, MiSe-GNN consistently improves accuracy and accuracyвҖ“compute trade-offs over strong baselines, and qualitative analyses show that it routes communication toward physically challenging regions. These results establish <em>error-guided edge augmentation</em> as a robust and general design principle for long-range message passing in physics-aware GNNs.</p>","absKo":"<p>mesh мғҒмқҳ Graph Neural Network (GNN)лҠ” computational mechanicsлҘј мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң surrogateлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, н‘ңмӨҖ local message passingмқҖ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ mesh м „л°ҳм—җ м •ліҙлҘј м „нҢҢн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘм–ҙ, ліөмһЎн•ң л¬јлҰ¬ нҳ„мғҒ(мҳҲ: shock, wake, boundary layer)мқҙ мһҲлҠ” мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң нҒ° мҳӨм°ЁлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ heuristicмқҙлӮҳ random samplingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ <em>a priori</em>лЎң м„ нғқн•ң long-range edgeлЎң connectivityлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, high-error regionмқ„ мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙ м—Ҷкі  мў…мў… мӨ‘ліөлҗҳлҠ” communicationмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” modelмқҙ мҳҲмёЎн•ң <em>a posteriori</em> errorлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ graph connectivityлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мҰқк°•н•ҳлҠ” dual-head architectureмқё <strong>MiSe-GNN</strong>мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. MiSe-GNNмқҖ physical fieldмҷҖ node-wise error indicatorлҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң мҳҲмёЎн•ҳл©°, мҳҲмёЎлҗң errorлҠ” adaptive treeлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мЈјкё°м ҒмңјлЎң м—¬лҹ¬ scaleм—җм„ң high-error nodeлҘј spatial pivotкіј м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” м¶”к°Җ edgeмқҳ кі„мёө кө¬мЎ°лЎң ліҖнҷҳлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң error-guided connectivityлҠ” surrogateк°Җ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨн•ң кіім—җ message passingмқ„ м§‘мӨ‘мӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лӮҳлЁём§Җ graphлҠ” sparseн•ҳкІҢ мң м§Җн•ҳм—¬, adaptive mesh refinementмқҳ нҲ¬лӘ…н•ҳкі  л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң graph-space лҢҖмқ‘л¬јмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мӮ°м—…мҡ© CFD л°Ҹ CSD benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң MiSe-GNNмқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң baseline лҢҖл№„ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„-м—°мӮ° trade-offлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, м •м„ұм Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ communicationмқҙ л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң м–ҙл Өмҡҙ мҳҒм—ӯмңјлЎң н–Ҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лқјмҡ°нҢ…н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” <em>error-guided edge augmentation</em>мқҙ physics-aware GNNм—җм„ң long-range message passingмқ„ мң„н•ң кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м„Өкі„ мӣҗлҰ¬мһ„мқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62111","en":"Full-Spectrum Graph Neural Network: Expressive and Scalable","ko":"Full-Spectrum Graph Neural Network: н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мһҲкі  нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ","authors":"Xiaohan Wang, Deyu Bo, Longlong Li, Kelin Xia","pos":"#2406","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jk7P5ppKxD","abs":"<p>It is well established that spectral graph neural networks (GNNs) can universally approximate node signals; however, their expressive power remains bounded by the 1-dimensional WeisfeilerвҖ“Lehman test, which is mirrored in their lack of universality for higher-order signals. To go beyond this bound, we propose the Full-Spectrum GNN (FSpecGNN), a second-order generalization of classical spectral GNNs. FSpecGNN advances spectral filtering in two perspectives: (1) it lifts the signal from the node domain to the node-pair domain; and (2) it extends the univariate spectral filter over eigenvalues to a bivariate filter over eigenvalue pairs. We show that classical spectral GNNs arise as a diagonal special case of FSpecGNN, and prove that FSpecGNN can be more expressive than Local 2-GNN while universally approximating node-pair signals, the latter being particularly beneficial for heterophilic graph learning. Moreover, FSpecGNN admits scalable implementations that avoid explicit node-pair-level computations; combined with a low-rank approximation that reduces full-spectrum convolution to a combination of polynomial spectral filters, it enables learning on large graphs. Empirically, FSpecGNN validates the predicted expressivity and delivers strong performance on heterophilic benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Spectral graph neural networks (GNNs)к°Җ node signalмқ„ ліҙнҺём ҒмңјлЎң к·јмӮ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқҖ мһҳ м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к·ё н‘ңнҳ„л ҘмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ 1-dimensional WeisfeilerвҖ“Lehman testм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңн•ңлҗҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” higher-order signalм—җ лҢҖн•ң л№„ліҙнҺём„ұкіјлҸ„ лҢҖмқ‘лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ н•ңкі„лҘј л„ҳм–ҙк°Җкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кі м „м Ғмқё spectral GNNмқҳ second-order generalizationмқё Full-Spectrum GNN(FSpecGNN)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. FSpecGNNмқҖ spectral filteringмқ„ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. (1) signalмқ„ node domainм—җм„ң node-pair domainмңјлЎң лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬лҰ¬кі , (2) eigenvalueм—җ лҢҖн•ң univariate spectral filterлҘј eigenvalue pairм—җ лҢҖн•ң bivariate filterлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” classical spectral GNNмқҙ FSpecGNNмқҳ diagonal special caseлЎң мң лҸ„лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , FSpecGNNмқҙ node-pair signalмқ„ ліҙнҺём ҒмңјлЎң к·јмӮ¬н•ҳл©ҙм„ң Local 2-GNNліҙлӢӨ лҚ” н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқҙ нҒҙ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. нӣ„мһҗлҠ” нҠ№нһҲ heterophilic graph learningм—җ мң лҰ¬н•ҳлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң FSpecGNNмқҖ explicit node-pair мҲҳмӨҖ кі„мӮ°мқ„ н”јн•ҳлҠ” scalable implementationмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳл©°, full-spectrum convolutionмқ„ polynomial spectral filterмқҳ мЎ°н•©мңјлЎң мӨ„мқҙлҠ” low-rank approximationкіј кІ°н•©н•ҳл©ҙ large graphм—җм„ңмқҳ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң FSpecGNNмқҖ мҳҲмёЎлҗң н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкі  heterophilic benchmarkм—җм„ң к°•н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63030","en":"Graph Alignment for Benchmarking Graph Neural Networks and Learning Positional Encodings","ko":"к·ёлһҳн”„ мӢ кІҪл§қ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№кіј мң„м№ҳ мқёмҪ”л”© н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң к·ёлһҳн”„ м •л ¬","authors":"Adrien Lagesse, Marc Lelarge","pos":"#2408","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=alkWXGgvYP","abs":"<p>We propose a novel benchmarking methodology for graph neural networks (GNNs) based on the graph alignment problem, a combinatorial optimization task that generalizes graph isomorphism by aligning two unlabeled graphs to maximize overlapping edges. We frame this problem as a self-supervised learning task and present several methods to generate graph alignment datasets using synthetic random graphs and real-world graph datasets from multiple domains. For a given graph dataset, we generate a family of graph alignment datasets with increasing difficulty, allowing us to rank the performance of various architectures. Our experiments prove that there is an optimal task difficulty for having a statistically relevant ranking of different models and that, even on a structure-only task, anisotropic models perform better compared to isotropic ones. To further prove that our synthetic task capture meaningful information, we show its effectiveness for self-supervised GNN pre-training: the learned node embeddings can be leveraged as positional encodings by transformers for graph regression or can be used to reconstruct the full structure of the graph with 98% accuracy. To support reproducibility and further research, we provide an open-source Python package to generate graph alignment datasets and benchmark new GNN architectures.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” graph neural network(GNN)лҘј мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ benchmarking methodologyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” graph alignment problem, мҰү л‘җ к°ңмқҳ unlabeled graphлҘј м •л ¬н•ҙ overlap edgeлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мЎ°н•© мөңм Ғнҷ” л¬ём ңм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҠ” graph isomorphismмқ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј self-supervised learning taskлЎң м •мқҳн•ҳкі , synthetic random graphмҷҖ м—¬лҹ¬ лҸ„л©”мқёмқҳ мӢӨм ң graph datasetмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ graph alignment datasetмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мЈјм–ҙм§„ graph datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӮңмқҙлҸ„к°Җ м җм җ мҰқк°Җн•ҳлҠ” graph alignment dataset familyлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң architectureмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мҲңмң„нҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё modelмқ„ нҶөкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мң мқҳлҜён•ҳкІҢ мҲңмң„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” мөңм Ғмқҳ task difficultyк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳл©°, кө¬мЎ°л§Ңмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” taskм—җм„ңлҸ„ isotropic modelліҙлӢӨ anisotropic modelмқҙ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ synthetic taskк°Җ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” м •ліҙлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•Ёмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң ліҙмқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, self-supervised GNN pre-trainingм—җм„ңмқҳ нҡЁмҡ©мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. н•ҷмҠөлҗң node embeddingмқҖ graph regressionм—җм„ң transformerмқҳ positional encodingмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲкі , graphмқҳ м „мІҙ кө¬мЎ°лҘј 98% м •нҷ•лҸ„лЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°лҸ„ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мһ¬нҳ„м„ұкіј нӣ„мҶҚ м—°кө¬лҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, graph alignment datasetмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳкі  мғҲлЎңмҡҙ GNN architectureлҘј benchmarkн•ҳлҠ” мҳӨн”ҲмҶҢмҠӨ Python packageлҸ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61479","en":"Graph Neural Networks Are Not Continuous Across Graph Resolutions","ko":"Graph Neural NetworksлҠ” Graph Resolution м „л°ҳм—җм„ң м—°мҶҚм Ғмқҙм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ","authors":"Christian Koke, Abhishek Saroha, Yuesong Shen, Marvin Eisenberger, Bastian Rieck, Michael Bronstein, Daniel Cremers","pos":"#2410","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=powiRLgonD","abs":"<p>We show that contrary to conventional wisdom in the community, graph neural networks (GNNs) are not continuous with respect to all natural modes of graph convergence. As a result, GNNs may generate substantially different latent representations for graphs that are very similar. In particular they assign vastly different latent embeddings to graphs that represent the same underlying object at different resolution scales. We trace this failure of continuity back to a structural obstruction arising from commonly used information-propagation schemes. Building on this insight we then derive a principled modification to standard GNN architectures which equips models with continuity across scales. The proposed modification enables consistent integration of distinct resolutions and reliable generalization between them. We systematically validate our theoretical findings in a wide range of numerical experiments.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” communityмқҳ conventional wisdomкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, graph neural networks (GNNs)к°Җ graph convergenceмқҳ лӘЁл“  мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ лӘЁл“ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ continuousн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј, GNNмқҖ л§Өмҡ° мң мӮ¬н•ң graphм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ мғҒлӢ№нһҲ лӢӨлҘё latent representationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ к°ҷмқҖ underlying objectлҘј м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё resolution scaleлЎң н‘ңнҳ„н•ң graphл“Өм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ к·№м ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨлҘё latent embeddingмқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң continuityмқҳ мӢӨнҢЁк°Җ нқ”нһҲ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” information-propagation schemeм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗҳлҠ” structural obstructionмңјлЎң к·ҖкІ°лҗЁмқ„ м¶”м Ғн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ GNN architectureм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғмқё мҲҳм •мқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳм—¬ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ scale м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ continuityлҘј к°–лҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ” мҲҳм •мқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё resolutionмқҳ мқјкҙҖлҗң нҶөн•©кіј к·ёл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” generalizationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң numerical experimentм—җм„ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62553","en":"GraphFLEx: Unsupervised Structure Learning $\\underline{\\text{F}}$ramework for $\\underline{\\text{L}}$arge $\\underline{\\text{Ex}}$panding $\\underline{\\text{Graph}}$s","ko":"GraphFLEx: \\underline{F}ramework for \\underline{L}arge \\underline{Ex}panding \\underline{Graph}s л№„м§ҖлҸ„ Structure Learning","authors":"Mohit Kataria, Nikita Malik, Sandeep Kumar, Jayadeva Jayadeva","pos":"#2411","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=fbFU9TCjra","abs":"<p>Graph structure learning is a core problem in graph-based machine learning, essential for uncovering latent relationships and ensuring model interpretability. However, most existing approaches are ill-suited for large-scale and dynamically evolving graphs, as they often require complete re-learning of the structure upon the arrival of new nodes and incur substantial computational and memory costs. In this work, we propose GraphFLExвҖ”a unified and scalable framework for Graph Structure Learning in Large and Expanding Graphs. GraphFLEx mitigates the scalability bottlenecks by restricting edge formation to structurally relevant subsets of nodes identified through a combination of clustering and coarsening techniques. This dramatically reduces the search space and enables efficient, incremental graph updates. The framework supports 48 flexible configurations by integrating diverse choices of learning paradigms, coarsening strategies, and clustering methods, making it adaptable to a wide range of graph settings and learning objectives. Extensive experiments across 26 diverse datasets and graph neural network architectures demonstrate that GraphFLEx achieves state-of-the-art performance with significantly improved scalability. Our implementation is publicly available here: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Scaling<em>Graph</em>Learning-CB67/README.md.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph structure learningмқҖ graph-based machine learningмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ л¬ём ңлЎң, latent relationshipлҘј л°ңкІ¬н•ҳкі  model interpretabilityлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁмқҙл©ҙм„ң лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” graphм—җ м Ғн•©н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мғҲлЎңмҡҙ nodeк°Җ лҸ„м°©н•  л•Ңл§ҲлӢӨ кө¬мЎ°лҘј мҷ„м „нһҲ лӢӨмӢң н•ҷмҠөн•ҙм•ј н•ҳкі , мғҒлӢ№н•ң кі„мӮ° л°Ҹ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ л№„мҡ©мқҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” Large and Expanding Graphsм—җм„ңмқҳ Graph Structure Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң нҶөн•©м Ғмқҙкі  нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё GraphFLExлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. GraphFLExлҠ” clusteringкіј coarsening кё°мҲ мқҳ мЎ°н•©мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң кҙҖл Ё мһҲлҠ” node subsetм—җл§Ң edge мғқм„ұмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ scalability лі‘лӘ©мқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” search spaceлҘј к·№м ҒмңјлЎң мӨ„мқҙкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё incremental graph updateлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” н•ҷмҠө paradigm, coarsening м „лһө, clustering methodмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң м„ нғқмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ 48к°ңмқҳ мң м—°н•ң configurationмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, лӢӨм–‘н•ң graph settingкіј learning objectiveм—җ м Ғмқ‘н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. 26к°ңмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetкіј graph neural network architecture м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ GraphFLExк°Җ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗң scalabilityмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. кө¬нҳ„мқҖ м—¬кё°м—җм„ң кіөк°ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Scaling<em>Graph</em>Learning-CB67/README.md.</p>"},{"id":"65562","en":"H$^2$CL: Heterogeneity-Aware Hypergraph Contrastive Learning for Robust Representation","ko":"HВІCL: к°•кұҙн•ң н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ мң„н•ң мқҙм§Ҳм„ұ мқём§Җ н•ҳмқҙнҚјк·ёлһҳн”„ лҢҖмЎ° н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Kaixuan Yao, Ting Guo, Ming Li, Feilong Cao","pos":"#2412","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CPEld7VE6T","abs":"<p>In recent years, hypergraph contrastive learning methods have gained widespread attention due to their excellent performance in processing high-order structural data. However, traditional hypergraph learning method often assume that neighboring nodes are homogeneous, which can lead to the mixing of heterogeneous information in highly heterogeneous datasets, thereby affecting node feature representation. To address this issue, this paper proposes a heterogeneity-sensitive hypergraph contrastive learning method. In the view enhancement stage, we introduce a heterogeneity-aware mechanism that masks high-heterogeneity nodes using hyperedges as intermediaries for information filtering. This mechanism weakens the interference of heterogeneous nodes on view consistency, enabling the model to focus more on key features. In the encoding stage, a heterogeneity-sensitive hypergraph encoder is designed. It dynamically adjusts the weights of information propagation through hyperedges in two phases: <code>node-to-hyperedge\" and</code>hyperedge-to-node\". This adjustment allows hyperedges to focus on homogeneous information and feedback the aggregated homogeneous information to the respective nodes. Besides, we provide a theoretical proof that our model is capable of aggregating information based on node heterogeneity using hyperedges as intermediate structures. Extensive experimental results demonstrate that this method effectively reduces the interference of heterogeneous information and improves model performance on multiple benchmark datasets. Our code is availabl at: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/HHCL-F926</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј hypergraph contrastive learning methodлҠ” кі м°Ё кө¬мЎ° лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ л„җлҰ¬ мЈјлӘ©л°ӣкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ м „нҶөм Ғмқё hypergraph learning methodлҠ” мқҙмӣғ nodeк°Җ homogeneousн•ҳлӢӨкі  к°Җм •н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„, мқҙм§Ҳм„ұмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң heterogeneous informationмқҙ м„һмқҙкІҢ лҗҳкі , к·ё кІ°кіј node feature representationм—җ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мӨ„ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ heterogeneity-sensitive hypergraph contrastive learning methodлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. view enhancement лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” hyperedgeлҘј м •ліҙ н•„н„°л§Ғмқҳ мӨ‘к°ңмһҗлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ high-heterogeneity nodeлҘј л§ҲмҠӨнӮ№н•ҳлҠ” heterogeneity-aware mechanismмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ view consistencyм—җ лҢҖн•ң heterogeneous nodeмқҳ к°„м„ӯмқ„ м•Ҫнҷ”мӢңмјң modelмқҙ н•өмӢ¬ featureм—җ лҚ” м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. encoding лӢЁкі„м—җм„ңлҠ” heterogeneity-sensitive hypergraph encoderлҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ encoderлҠ” <code>node-to-hyperedge\" and</code>hyperedge-to-node\"мқҳ л‘җ phaseм—җ кұёміҗ hyperedgeлҘј нҶөн•ң information propagationмқҳ к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мЎ°м •мқҖ hyperedgeк°Җ homogeneous informationм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳкі , м§‘кі„лҗң homogeneous informationмқ„ н•ҙлӢ№ nodeл“Өм—җ лҗҳлҸҢл Ө мӨ„ мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” hyperedgeлҘј intermediate structureлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ node heterogeneityм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ м •ліҙлҘј м§‘кі„н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мқҙ methodк°Җ heterogeneous informationмқҳ к°„м„ӯмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мӨ„мқҙкі  м—¬лҹ¬ benchmark datasetм—җм„ң model м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ң: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/HHCL-F926</p>"},{"id":"65329","en":"Improving Graph Transformers via Global Structural Priors","ko":"м „м—ӯ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мӮ¬м „м •ліҙлҘј нҶөн•ң Graph Transformer к°ңм„ ","authors":"Jiaming Zhuo, Ziyi Ma, Kun Fu, Di Jin, Chuan Wang, Zhen Wang, Xiaochun Cao, Huazhu Fu, Liang Yang","pos":"#2414","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EgfItWD8J8","abs":"<p>By synergizing graph topology with the global expressive power of the attention mechanism, Graph Transformers (GTs) have emerged as a dominant architecture for node classification. However, existing models primarily focus on diverse topology injection mechanisms, specifically score-level and representation-level designs, yet lack a unified theoretical foundation to characterize how these mechanisms shape the representation propagation. To bridge this research gap, this paper unifies these designs under a common Graph Signal Denoising framework, revealing that denoising efficacy (\\textit{i.e.}, representation quality) is fundamentally dictated by the block-diagonal structure of the propagation operator. To instantiate this prior efficiently, this paper introduces a novel Block-Diagonal GT architecture, named \\textsc{BDFormer}, which enforces a block-diagonal constraint via spectral-regularized cross-attention on latent anchors. Specifically, by routing global interactions through these anchors, \\textsc{BDFormer} imposes the spectral block-constraint directly on the anchor-level affinity. Crucially, the learned global affinity guides the pruning of local heterophilous edges, ensuring that both scales synergistically adhere to the target distribution. Extensive evaluations on benchmark datasets demonstrate the scalability and robustness of \\textsc{BDFormer}.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph topologyмҷҖ attention mechanismмқҳ м „м—ӯм Ғ н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқ„ мӢңл„Ҳм§Җ мһҲкІҢ кІ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, Graph Transformer (GT)лҠ” node classificationмқҳ м§Җл°°м Ғмқё architectureлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мЈјлЎң лӢӨм–‘н•ң topology injection mechanism, нҠ№нһҲ score-level л°Ҹ representation-level designм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙ representation propagationмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ нҳ•м„ұн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ” нҶөн•©лҗң мқҙлЎ м Ғ кё°л°ҳмқҖ л¶ҖмЎұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬ кІ©м°ЁлҘј л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң designмқ„ кіөнҶөмқҳ Graph Signal Denoising framework м•„лһҳ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬, denoising нҡЁмңЁм„ұ(\\textit{мҰү}, representation quality)мқҙ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң propagation operatorмқҳ block-diagonal structureм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кІ°м •лҗЁмқ„ л°қнһҷлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ priorлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬нҳ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ latent anchorм—җ лҢҖн•ң spectral-regularized cross-attentionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ block-diagonal constraintлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Block-Diagonal GT architectureмқё \\textsc{BDFormer}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, global interactionмқ„ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң anchorлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лқјмҡ°нҢ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ \\textsc{BDFormer}лҠ” anchor-level affinityм—җ spectral block-constraintлҘј м§Ғм ‘ л¶Җкіјн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬м ҒмңјлЎң, н•ҷмҠөлҗң global affinityлҠ” local heterophilous edgeмқҳ pruningмқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳм—¬, л‘җ scaleмқҙ лӘЁл‘җ target distributionмқ„ мӢңл„Ҳм§Җ мһҲкІҢ л”°лҘҙлҸ„лЎқ н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. benchmark datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҠ” \\textsc{BDFormer}мқҳ scalabilityмҷҖ robustnessлҘј мһ…мҰқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65482","en":"DiP-G: Discrete Prompting for Graph Neural Networks","ko":"DiP-G: Graph Neural NetworkлҘј мң„н•ң мқҙмӮ° н”„лЎ¬н”„нҢ…","authors":"Yumeng Zhao, Huiying Hu, Steve Wen, Junjie Shen, Bei Hua","pos":"#2500","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=DBSVe07H8y","abs":"<p>Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) are increasingly adopting the \"pre-training, adaptation\" paradigm, which first pre-train GNNs on large-scale unlabeled graph data and then adapt them to specific downstream tasks. As a common pattern, graph prompting adapts to the frozen encoder by modifying the input graph structure, rather than fine-tuning the model parameters. However, most existing graph prompting approaches optimize the continuous and weighted adjacency structure in the adaptation phase, while requiring a hard discretization at inference time. This difference causes a train-test mismatch which is particularly harmful in few-shot regimes. To address the issue, we propose <strong>Di</strong>screte <strong>P</strong>rompting for <strong>G</strong>raphs, a discrete prompting framework that directly learns task-specific topology prompts in the combinatorial space. DiP-G operates on multi-hop local candidate subgraphs to ensure scalability, generates hard (k)-sparse prompts through a perturbed Top-(k) solver, and optimizes the  discrete structures using an I-MLE gradient estimator. To improve the efficiency of backward pass, we further introduce an adaptive active-set screening rule that accelerates the target solve and can provably maintain the accuracy of the solution. Extensive experiments conducted on multiple benchmark datasets have validated the effectiveness of our proposed method. Our main code is available in the supplementary materials.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph Neural Networks(GNNs)лҠ” м җм җ лҚ” \"pre-training, adaptation\" paradigmмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ҳкі  мһҲлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” лЁјм Җ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ unlabeled graph dataлЎң GNNмқ„ pre-trainн•ң л’Ө нҠ№м • downstream taskм—җ л§һкІҢ adaptн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҙлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё нҢЁн„ҙмңјлЎң graph promptingмқҖ model parameterлҘј fine-tuningн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ  мһ…л Ҙ graph structureлҘј мҲҳм •н•ҳм—¬ frozen encoderм—җ л§һм¶ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ graph prompting м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ adaptation phaseм—җм„ң continuousн•ҳкі  weightedлҗң adjacency structureлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, inference timeм—җм„ңлҠ” hard discretizationмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м°ЁмқҙлҠ” train-test mismatchлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳл©°, нҠ№нһҲ few-shot regimeм—җм„ң н•ҙлЎӯлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>Di</strong>screte <strong>P</strong>rompting for <strong>G</strong>raphs, мҰү combinatorial spaceм—җм„ң task-specific topology promptsлҘј м§Ғм ‘ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” discrete prompting frameworkмқё DiP-GлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. DiP-GлҠ” нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ multi-hop local candidate subgraph мң„м—җм„ң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳл©°, perturbed Top-(k) solverлҘј нҶөн•ҙ hard (k)-sparse promptлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , I-MLE gradient estimatorлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ discrete structureлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. backward passмқҳ нҡЁмңЁмқ„ лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” target solveлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ н•ҙмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” adaptive active-set screening ruleлҸ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmark datasetм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ң л°©лІ•мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн–ҲлӢӨ. л©”мқё мҪ”л“ңлҠ” supplementary materialsм—җ м ңкіөлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61381","en":"DREAM: Dual-Standard Semantic Homogeneity with Dynamic Optimization for Graph Learning with Label Noise","ko":"DREAM: Label Noiseк°Җ мһҲлҠ” Graph Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң Dynamic Optimization кё°л°ҳ Dual-Standard Semantic Homogeneity","authors":"Yusheng Zhao, Jiaye Xie, Qixin Zhang, Weizhi Zhang, Xiao Luo, Zhiping Xiao, Philip Yu, Ming Zhang","pos":"#2501","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qnKVxU9EmU","abs":"<p>Graph neural networks (GNNs) have been widely used in various graph machine learning scenarios. Existing literature primarily assumes well-annotated training graphs, while the reliability of labels is not guaranteed in real-world scenarios. Recently, efforts have been made to address the problem of graph learning with label noise. However, existing methods often (i) struggle to distinguish between reliable and unreliable nodes, and (ii) overlook the relational information embedded in the graph topology. To tackle this problem, this paper proposes a novel method, Dual-Standard Semantic Homogeneity with Dynamic Optimization (DREAM), for reliable, relation-informed optimization on graphs with label noise. Specifically, we design a relation-informed dynamic optimization framework that iteratively reevaluates the reliability of each labeled node in the graph during the optimization process according to the relation of the target node and other nodes. To measure this relation comprehensively, we propose a dual-standard selection strategy that selects a set of anchor nodes based on both node proximity and graph topology. Subsequently, we compute the semantic homogeneity between the target node and the anchor nodes, which serves as guidance for optimization. We also provide a rigorous theoretical analysis to justify the design of DREAM. Extensive experiments are performed on six graph datasets across various domains under three types of graph label noise against competing baselines, and the results demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed DREAM.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph neural network(GNN)лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң graph machine learning мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л¬ён—ҢмқҖ мЈјлЎң мһҳ мЈјм„қлҗң training graphлҘј к°Җм •н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” labelмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұмқҙ ліҙмһҘлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мөңк·јм—җлҠ” label noiseк°Җ мһҲлҠ” graph learning л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳл ӨлҠ” мӢңлҸ„к°Җ мқҙлЈЁм–ҙмЎҢлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мў…мў… (i) мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” nodeмҷҖ к·ёл Үм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ nodeлҘј кө¬л¶„н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘкі , (ii) graph topologyм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң relational informationмқ„ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ label noiseк°Җ мһҲлҠ” graphм—җм„ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкі  relation-informedн•ң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л°©лІ•мқё Dual-Standard Semantic Homogeneity with Dynamic Optimization(DREAM)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңм Ғнҷ” кіјм • лҸҷм•Ҳ target nodeмҷҖ лӢӨлҘё nodeмқҳ кҙҖкі„м—җ л”°лқј graph лӮҙ к°Ғ labeled nodeмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” relation-informed dynamic optimization frameworkлҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖкі„лҘј нҸ¬кҙ„м ҒмңјлЎң мёЎм •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” node proximityмҷҖ graph topology лӘЁл‘җм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬ anchor node м§‘н•©мқ„ м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” dual-standard selection strategyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ target nodeмҷҖ anchor node мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ semantic homogeneityлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң м§Җм№ЁмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң DREAMмқҳ м„Өкі„лҘј м •лӢ№нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м—„л°Җн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬м„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ graph datasetм—җм„ң м„ё к°Җм§Җ мң нҳ•мқҳ graph label noiseлҘј к°Җм •н•ң мғҒнғңлЎң кІҪмҹҒ baselineл“Өкіјмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн–Ҳмңјл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј м ңм•Ҳн•ң DREAMмқҳ нҡЁкіјм„ұмқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62719","en":"Backward Oversmoothing: why is it hard to train deep Graph Neural Networks?","ko":"Backward Oversmoothing: мҷң deep Graph Neural NetworkлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙк°Җ","authors":"Nicolas Keriven","pos":"#2504","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=dx53sSG8py","abs":"<p>Oversmoothing has long been identified as a major limitation of Graph Neural Networks (GNNs): input node features are smoothed at each layer and converge to a constant non-informative representation, <em>if the weights of the GNN are sufficiently bounded</em>. This assumption is crucial: if, on the contrary, the weights are sufficiently large, then oversmoothing may be compensated. Theoretically, GNN could thus <em>learn</em> to not oversmooth. However, this does not really happen in practice, which prompts us to examine oversmoothing from an <em>optimization</em> point of view.  In this paper, we analyze <em>backward oversmoothing</em>, that is, the notion that backpropagated errors are also subject to oversmoothing from output to input. With non-linearities, we outline the key role of the <em>interaction</em> between forward and backward smoothing. Moreover, we show that, due to backward oversmoothing, GNNs provably exhibit many <em>spurious stationary points</em>: as soon as the <em>last</em> layer is trained, the <em>whole</em> GNN is at a stationary point. As a result, we can exhibit regions where gradients are near-zero while the loss stays high.  Additionally, we prove that this is <em>specific</em> to GNNs, and does not necessarily hold for Multi-Layer Perceptrons.  This paper is a step toward a more complete comprehension of the optimization landscape of GNNs.</p>","absKo":"<p>OversmoothingмқҖ мҳӨлһ«лҸҷм•Ҳ Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)мқҳ мЈјмҡ” н•ңкі„лЎң м•Ңл Өм ё мҷ”лӢӨ. мһ…л Ҙ л…ёл“ң нҠ№м§•мқҖ к°Ғ layerм—җм„ң smoothingлҗҳл©°, <em>GNNмқҳ weightsк°Җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ boundedлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмқ„ л•Ң</em> мғҒмҲҳм Ғмқё л№„м •ліҙм„ұ representationмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ к°Җм •мқҖ л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. л°ҳлҢҖлЎң weightsк°Җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҒ¬лӢӨл©ҙ oversmoothingмқҖ ліҙмғҒлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” GNNмқҙ thus <em>learn</em> to not oversmoothн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” мқҙлҹ° мқјмқҙ кұ°мқҳ мқјм–ҙлӮҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ optimization кҙҖм җм—җм„ң oversmoothingмқ„ мӮҙнҺҙліҙкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ.  ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” <em>backward oversmoothing</em>мқ„ л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” backpropagated errors лҳҗн•ң outputм—җм„ң inputмңјлЎң к°ҖлҠ” кіјм •м—җм„ң oversmoothingмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” к°ңл…җмқҙлӢӨ. л№„м„ нҳ•м„ұмқ„ кі л Өн•  л•Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” forwardмҷҖ backward smoothing мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ <em>interaction</em>мқҙ н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ к°ңкҙ„н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң backward oversmoothing л•Ңл¬ём—җ GNNsлҠ” мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ л§ҺмқҖ <em>spurious stationary points</em>лҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. <em>л§Ҳм§Җл§ү</em> layerк°Җ н•ҷмҠөлҗҳкё°л§Ң н•ҳл©ҙ, <em>м „мІҙ</em> GNNмқҙ stationary pointм—җ лҶ“мқҙкІҢ лҗңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј, lossлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ мғҒнғңлЎң мң м§Җлҗҳл©ҙм„ң gradientsк°Җ кұ°мқҳ zeroм—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ кө¬к°„мқ„ ліҙмқј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.  м¶”к°ҖлЎң, мқҙкІғмқҙ <em>GNNsм—җ нҠ№мң </em>н•ң нҳ„мғҒмқҙл©°, Multi-Layer Perceptronsм—җлҠ” л°ҳл“ңмӢң м„ұлҰҪн•ҳм§ҖлҠ” м•ҠмқҢмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ GNNsмқҳ optimization landscapeлҘј ліҙлӢӨ мҷ„м „н•ҳкІҢ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң н•ң кұёмқҢмқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62385","en":"BOCLOAK: Optimal Transport-Guided Adversarial Attacks on Graph Neural Network-Based Bot Detection","ko":"BOCLOAK: GNN кё°л°ҳ Bot Detection лҢҖмғҒ Optimal Transport-Guided Adversarial Attack","authors":"Kunal Mukherjee, Zulfikar Alom, Tran Gia Bao Ngo, Cuneyt Akcora, Murat Kantarcioglu","pos":"#2505","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=h6vKAlSWJw","abs":"<p>The rise of bot accounts on social media poses significant risks to public discourse. To address this threat, modern bot detectors increasingly rely on Graph Neural Networks (GNNs). However, the effectiveness of these GNN-based detectors in real-world settings remains poorly understood. In practice, attackers continuously adapt their strategies as well as must operate under domain-specific and temporal constraints, which can fundamentally limit the applicability of existing attack methods. As a result, there is a critical need for robust GNN-based bot detection methods under realistic, constraint-aware attack scenarios.   To address this gap, we introduce BOCLOAK to systematically evaluate the robustness of GNN-based social bot detection via both edge editing and node injection adversarial attacks under realistic constraints. BOCLOAK constructs a probability measure over spatio-temporal neighbor features and learns an optimal transport geometry that separates human and bot behaviors. It then decodes transport plans into sparse, plausible edge edits that evade detection while obeying real-world constraints. We evaluate BOCLOAK across three social bot datasets, five state-of-the-art bot detectors, three adversarial defenses, and compare it against four leading graph adversarial attack baselines. BOCLOAK achieves up to 80.13% higher attack success rates while using 99.80% less GPU memory under realistic real-world constraints. Most importantly, BOCLOAK shows that optimal transport provides a lightweight, principled framework for bridging adversarial attacks and real-world bot detection</p>","absKo":"<p>мҶҢм…ң лҜёл””м–ҙм—җм„ң bot accountмқҳ мҰқк°ҖлҠ” кіөм Ғ лӢҙлЎ м—җ мӨ‘лҢҖн•ң мң„н—ҳмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мң„нҳ‘м—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, нҳ„лҢҖмқҳ bot detectorлҠ” м җм җ лҚ” Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң GNN кё°л°ҳ detectorмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҠ” м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎң кіөкІ©мһҗлҠ” м „лһөмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘мӢңмјңм•ј н•ҳл©°, лҸҷмӢңм—җ domain-specific л°Ҹ temporal constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мқҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙ attack methodмқҳ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң м ңн•ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј, нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқҙкі  constraint-awareн•ң attack scenarioм—җм„ң к°•кұҙн•ң GNN кё°л°ҳ bot detection methodм—җ лҢҖн•ң м ҲмӢӨн•ң н•„мҡ”к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„мӢӨм Ғ м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ң edge editingкіј node injection adversarial attackмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ GNN кё°л°ҳ social bot detectionмқҳ robustnessлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” BOCLOAKлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. BOCLOAKлҠ” spatio-temporal neighbor featureм—җ лҢҖн•ң probability measureлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , мқёк°„кіј botмқҳ н–үлҸҷмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” optimal transport geometryлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ transport planмқ„ нқ¬мҶҢн•ҳкі  к°ңм—°м„ұ мһҲлҠ” edge editмңјлЎң л””мҪ”л”©н•ҳм—¬, мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„мқҳ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ мӨҖмҲҳн•ҳл©ҙм„ң detectionмқ„ нҡҢн”јн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ё к°ңмқҳ social bot dataset, лӢӨм„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ state-of-the-art bot detector, м„ё к°ңмқҳ adversarial defense м „л°ҳм—җм„ң BOCLOAKлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі , л„Ө к°ңмқҳ мЈјмҡ” graph adversarial attack baselineкіј л№„көҗн•ңлӢӨ. BOCLOAKлҠ” нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё мӢӨм ң м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ң GPU memoryлҘј 99.80% лҚң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ attack success rateлҘј мөңлҢҖ 80.13%к№Ңм§Җ лҚ” лҶ’кІҢ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. к°ҖмһҘ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳкІҢлҠ”, BOCLOAKк°Җ optimal transportк°Җ adversarial attackкіј мӢӨм ң bot detectionмқ„ м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҲм–ҙ к°ҖліҚкі  мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё frameworkлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ</p>"},{"id":"63825","en":"Adaptive Node Feature Selection for Graph Neural Networks","ko":"к·ёлһҳн”„ мӢ кІҪл§қмқ„ мң„н•ң м Ғмқ‘м Ғ л…ёл“ң нҠ№м„ұ м„ нғқ","authors":"Ali Azizpour, Madeline Navarro, Santiago Segarra","pos":"#2507","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=TOAT4Va5VH","abs":"<p>We propose an adaptive node feature selection approach for graph neural networks (GNNs) that identifies and removes unnecessary features during training. The ability to measure how features contribute to model output is key for interpreting decisions and reducing dimensionality by eliminating unhelpful variables. However, graph-structured data introduces complex dependencies that may be unsuited to classical feature importance metrics. Inspired by this, we present a data-, model-, and task-agnostic method that determines relevant features during training based on changes in validation performance upon permuting feature values. We theoretically motivate our approach by characterizing how the relationships between node data and graph structure influences GNN performance. Empirically, we show that (i) our highly general approach rivals the performance of tailored feature selection approaches that exploit prior assumptions; (ii) we return meaningful feature importance scores well before the GNN is fully trained; and (iii) our scores demonstrably extract relevant properties that inform feature importance for various graph learning settings.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” training лҸҷм•Ҳ л¶Ҳн•„мҡ”н•ң featureлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі  м ңкұ°н•ҳлҠ” graph neural network(GNN)мқ„ мң„н•ң adaptive node feature selection м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. featureк°Җ model outputм—җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ кё°м—¬н•ҳлҠ”м§Җ мёЎм •н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лҠҘл ҘмқҖ кІ°м •мқ„ н•ҙм„қн•ҳкі , лҸ„мӣҖмқҙ лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” ліҖмҲҳлҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳм—¬ м°Ёмӣҗмқ„ мӨ„мқҙлҠ” лҚ° н•өмӢ¬м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ graph кө¬мЎ° лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” кі м „м Ғмқё feature importance metricм—җ м Ғн•©н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м җм—җ м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” feature к°’мқ„ permuteн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң validation performanceк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ ліҖн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң training мӨ‘ кҙҖл Ё featureлҘј кІ°м •н•ҳлҠ” data-, model-, task- agnostic methodлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” node dataмҷҖ graph structure мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ кҙҖкі„к°Җ GNN м„ұлҠҘм—җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” (i) мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л§Өмҡ° мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ мӮ¬м „ к°Җм •мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” л§һм¶Өнҳ• feature selection approachмқҳ м„ұлҠҘм—җ н•„м Ғн•ҳл©°; (ii) GNNмқҙ мҷ„м „нһҲ н•ҷмҠөлҗҳкё° нӣЁм”¬ м „м—җ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” feature importance scoreлҘј л°ҳнҷҳн•ҳкі ; (iii) мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ scoreк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң graph learning settingм—җм„ң feature importanceлҘј л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳлҠ” кҙҖл Ё мҶҚм„ұмқ„ мӢӨм ңлЎң м¶”м¶ңн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60730","en":"Adaptive Memory Retention in Dynamic Graphs","ko":"лҸҷм Ғ к·ёлһҳн”„м—җм„ңмқҳ Adaptive Memory Retention","authors":"Fabrizio De Castelli, Alessio Gravina, Moshe Eliasof, Carola-Bibiane SchГ¶nlieb, Davide Bacciu","pos":"#2508","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=x7NGYPNlgs","abs":"<p>Modeling graphs demands a careful balance between long-range propagation of information across nodes and the controlled dissipation of noisy or redundant signals to ensure stable learning and generalization. This challenge is exacerbated in dynamic graphs, where structural and temporal information interact, leading to uncontrolled information accumulation and amplifying noise, thereby affecting generalization. We introduce LAMP, a dynamic graph model for snapshot-based dynamic graphs that incorporates adaptive, learned dissipation within a principled dynamical systems framework. Our architecture combines impulsive neural ODEs with antisymmetric parameterization to model conservative information flow, alongside data-driven dissipative dynamics that regulate information retention over space and time. This formulation yields stable yet expressive representations and enables effective long-range dependency modeling while avoiding pathological information buildup. We provide a theoretical analysis establishing stability guarantees and characterizing the representational power. Extensive experiments on synthetic and real-world benchmarks demonstrate state-of-the-art performance, particularly on tasks requiring extended-range dependency modeling.</p>","absKo":"<p>к·ёлһҳн”„лҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳл Өл©ҙ л…ёл“ң м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң м •ліҙмқҳ мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ м „нҢҢмҷҖ, м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё н•ҷмҠөкіј generalizationмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мһЎмқҢ лҳҗлҠ” мӨ‘ліө мӢ нҳёмқҳ м ңм–ҙлҗң мҶҢмӮ° мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң мӢ мӨ‘н•ң к· нҳ•мқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҸ„м „мқҖ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ м •ліҙмҷҖ мӢңк°„м Ғ м •ліҙк°Җ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м ңм–ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” м •ліҙ м¶•м Ғкіј мһЎмқҢ мҰқнҸӯмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ҳкі , кІ°көӯ generalizationм—җ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ” dynamic graphм—җм„ң лҚ”мҡұ мӢ¬нҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғмқё dynamical systems framework м•Ҳм—җм„ң adaptiveн•ҳкі  learned dissipationмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ң snapshot-based dynamic graphлҘј мң„н•ң лӘЁлҚё LAMPлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ architectureлҠ” ліҙмЎҙм Ғ м •ліҙ нқҗлҰ„мқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ antisymmetric parameterizationкіј impulsive neural ODEлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳкі , кіөк°„кіј мӢңк°„мқ„ к°ҖлЎңм§ҖлҘҙлҠ” м •ліҙ ліҙмЎҙмқ„ мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” data-driven dissipative dynamicsлҘј н•Ёк»ҳ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң formulationмқҖ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқҙ н’Қл¶Җн•ң representationмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ лӮҙл©°, лі‘лҰ¬м Ғмқё м •ліҙ м¶•м Ғмқ„ н”јн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ dependency modelingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” stability ліҙмһҘмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳкі  representational powerлҘј нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. synthetic л°Ҹ real-world benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ нҠ№нһҲ extended-range dependency modelingмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң taskм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61124","en":"A Graphop Analysis of Graph Neural Networks on Sparse Graphs: Generalization and Universal Approximation","ko":"нқ¬мҶҢ к·ёлһҳн”„м—җм„ң Graph Neural Networkмқҳ Graphop л¶„м„қ: мқјл°ҳнҷ”мҷҖ Universal Approximation","authors":"Ofek Amran, Tom Gilat, Ron Levie","pos":"#2510","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tRsnpaRO0m","abs":"<p>Generalization and approximation capabilities of message passing graph neural networks (MPNNs) are often studied by defining a compact metric on a space of input graphs under which MPNNs are HГ¶lder continuous. Such analyses are of two varieties: 1) when the metric space includes graphs of unbounded sizes, the theory is only appropriate for dense graphs, and, 2) when studying sparse graphs, the metric space only includes graphs of uniformly bounded size. In this work, we present a unified approach, defining a compact metric on the space of graphs of all sizes, both sparse and dense, under which MPNNs are HГ¶lder continuous. This leads to more powerful universal approximation theorems and generalization bounds than previous works. The theory is based on, and extends, a recent approach to graph limit theory called graphop analysis.</p>","absKo":"<p>message passing graph neural network(MPNN)мқҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ” л°Ҹ к·јмӮ¬ лҠҘл ҘмқҖ мў…мў… мһ…л Ҙ graph кіөк°„ мң„м—җ MPNNмқҙ HГ¶lder continuousк°Җ лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” compact metricмқ„ м •мқҳн•ҳм—¬ м—°кө¬лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¶„м„қмқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мң нҳ•мңјлЎң лӮҳлүңлӢӨ. 1) metric spaceк°Җ нҒ¬кё°к°Җ л¬ҙн•ңн•ң graphлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°, мқҙлЎ мқҖ dense graphм—җл§Ң м Ғм Ҳн•ҳкі , 2) sparse graphлҘј м—°кө¬н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ° metric spaceлҠ” нҒ¬кё°к°Җ к· мқјн•ҳкІҢ boundedлҗң graphл§Ң нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” sparseмҷҖ denseлҘј лӘЁл‘җ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” лӘЁл“  нҒ¬кё°мқҳ graph кіөк°„ мң„м—җ compact metricмқ„ м •мқҳн•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•©м Ғ м ‘к·јмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, к·ё м•„лһҳм—җм„ң MPNNмқҙ HГ¶lder continuousк°Җ лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мқҙм „ м—°кө¬ліҙлӢӨ лҚ” к°•л Ҙн•ң universal approximation theoremкіј generalization boundлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙ мқҙлЎ мқҖ graph limit theoryм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңк·ј м ‘к·јлІ•мқё graphop analysisм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳл©° мқҙлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64163","en":"Subspace-Aware Feature Reshaping for Open-Set Graph Class-Incremental Learning","ko":"к°ңл°©нҳ• к·ёлһҳн”„ нҒҙлһҳмҠӨ мҰқл¶„ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң л¶Җл¶„кіөк°„ мқёмӢқ нҠ№м§• мһ¬кө¬м„ұ","authors":"Weichao Zhang, Shuai Zheng, Yeyu Yan, Zhizhe Liu, Zhenfeng Zhu, Yao Zhao","pos":"#3801","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=QKo90eNH3l","abs":"<p>Graph class-incremental learning (GCIL) has emerged to address the challenge of learning from dynamically evolving graphs, which continuously learns new classes over a sequence of tasks while retaining performance on previously seen classes. However, existing GCIL methods assume a closed-set test distribution drawn only from seen tasks. This fundamentally contradicts real-world open-ended scenarios where future unknown classes inevitably emerge. Empirically, we observe that existing GCIL methods falter in such open-set settings due to severe representation drift and generalized overconfidence. To bridge this gap, we investigate the Open-Set GCIL problem and propose \\textbf{SAFER} (\\underline{S}ubspace-\\underline{A}ware \\underline{FE}ature \\underline{R}eshaping), a novel framework that endows GCIL with intrinsic open-set capabilities under a replay-free constraint. Specifically, \\textbf{SAFER} performs subspace-aware feature reshaping with drift-free fingerprints, unifying task routing and open-set rejection into a single energy-based metric. Furthermore, we introduce a geometric space-consistency regularization that explicitly improves intra-class compactness and suppresses cross-task representation drift. Extensive experiments on four benchmarks demonstrate that SAFER outperforms state-of-the-art baselines by margins of up to 5.2\\% in accuracy and 31.3\\% in open-set AUROC, all while maintaining near-zero forgetting under strict no-replay constraints.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph class-incremental learning (GCIL)мқҖ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” graphлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ л“ұмһҘн–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙм „м—җ ліё classм—җ лҢҖн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң task мӢңнҖҖмҠӨлҘј л”°лқј мғҲлЎңмҡҙ classлҘј м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ GCIL л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң ліё taskм—җм„ңл§Ң м¶”м¶ңлҗң closed-set test distributionмқ„ к°Җм •н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лҜёлһҳмқҳ unknown classк°Җ н•„м—°м ҒмңјлЎң л“ұмһҘн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мӢӨ м„ёкі„мқҳ open-ended мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨмҷҖ к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң лӘЁмҲңлҗңлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ GCIL л°©лІ•мқҙ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң representation driftмҷҖ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗң overconfidence л•Ңл¬ём—җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң open-set settingм—җм„ң м ңлҢҖлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Open-Set GCIL л¬ём ңлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкі , replay-free constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң GCILм—җ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё open-set capabilityлҘј л¶Җм—¬н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkмқё \\textbf{SAFER} (\\underline{S}ubspace-\\underline{A}ware \\underline{FE}ature \\underline{R}eshaping)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң \\textbf{SAFER}лҠ” drift-free fingerprintлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң subspace-aware feature reshapingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ task routingкіј open-set rejectionмқ„ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ energy-based metricмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” class лӮҙ мқ‘м§‘лҸ„лҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  cross-task representation driftлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳлҠ” geometric space-consistency regularizationмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. л„Ө к°ңмқҳ benchmarkм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SAFERк°Җ м—„кІ©н•ң no-replay constraintлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ кұ°мқҳ zero forgettingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , м •нҷ•лҸ„м—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ 5.2\\%, open-set AUROCм—җм„ң 31.3\\%к№Ңм§Җ state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62244","en":"Structure-Centric Graph Foundation Model via Geometric Bases","ko":"кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ BaseлҘј нҶөн•ң кө¬мЎ° мӨ‘мӢ¬ Graph Foundation Model","authors":"Xiaodong He, Haolan He, Ruiyi Fang, Ming Sun, zhao kang","pos":"#2201","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=iMrOO18AoP","abs":"<p>Graph foundation models (GFMs) seek transferable representations across graph domains but are limited by structural heterogeneity and incompatible node feature spaces. We propose Structure-Centric Graph Foundation Models (SCGFM), which treat graph topology as the primary source of transferable knowledge. Modeling graphs as metric measure spaces, SCGFM introduces learnable geometric bases that define a shared structural coordinate system. Graphs are aligned to these bases via GromovвҖ“Wasserstein distances, yielding structure-aligned latent representations that accommodate heterogeneous graph topologies. To address feature incompatibility, SCGFM employs a structure-aware feature re-encoding mechanism that unifies node representations without assuming a fixed feature dimensionality or requiring dataset-specific preprocessing. Experiments on graph- and node-level tasks demonstrate strong in-domain and cross-domain generalization, outperforming existing GFM approaches.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph foundation models (GFMs)лҠ” к·ёлһҳн”„ лҸ„л©”мқё м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң м „мқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мқҙм§Ҳм„ұкіј нҳёнҷҳлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” л…ёл“ң feature spaceлЎң мқён•ҙ м ңн•ңмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к·ёлһҳн”„ topologyлҘј м „мқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м§ҖмӢқмқҳ мЈјмҡ” мӣҗмІңмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” Structure-Centric Graph Foundation Models (SCGFM)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлһҳн”„лҘј metric measure spaceлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, SCGFMмқҖ кіөмң  кө¬мЎ° мўҢн‘ңкі„лҘј м •мқҳн•ҳлҠ” н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн•ң geometric basisлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлһҳн”„лҠ” GromovвҖ“Wasserstein distanceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ basisм—җ м •л ¬лҗҳл©°, мқҙлЎңл¶Җн„° мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё к·ёлһҳн”„ topologyлҘј мҲҳмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” structure-aligned latent representationмқҙ мғқм„ұлҗңлӢӨ. feature л№„нҳёнҷҳм„ұмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ SCGFMмқҖ кө¬мЎ°лҘј мқём§Җн•ҳлҠ” feature re-encoding л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, кі м •лҗң feature м°Ёмӣҗмқ„ к°Җм •н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣлі„ м „мІҳлҰ¬лҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ л…ёл“ң н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. graph-level л°Ҹ node-level мһ‘м—…м—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ к°•н•ң in-domain л°Ҹ cross-domain мқјл°ҳнҷ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, кё°мЎҙ GFM м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65990","en":"Towards HierarchyвҖ“Uniformity Equilibrium: Recovering Semantic Depth in Hypergraph Contrastive Learning","ko":"кі„мёө-к· мқјм„ұ к· нҳ•мқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬: н•ҳмқҙнҚјк·ёлһҳн”„ лҢҖмЎ° н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ңмқҳ мқҳлҜём Ғ к№Ҡмқҙ ліөмӣҗ","authors":"Ruiting Zhao, Ming Li, Lixin Cui, Lu Bai, Feilong Cao, Ke Lv, Pietro LiГі","pos":"#2202","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=88qwqo7VSK","abs":"<p>Hypergraph contrastive learning is an effective paradigm for representation learning on higher-order relational data, yet existing methods largely ignore that hyperedges link nodes with multi-level semantics. Standard contrastive objectives emphasize instance discrimination via hyperspherical uniformity and tend to push embeddings apart in an indiscriminate manner. We show that this leads to a <em>HierarchyвҖ“Uniformity Conflict</em>, whose geometric manifestation is <em>Semantic Flattening</em>, where the semantic depth of hyperedges collapses into a nearly flat cloud of instances. To address this issue, we introduce <strong>HyperDepth</strong>, a hypergraph contrastive learning framework that moves representations towards a hierarchyвҖ“uniformity equilibrium by jointly coordinating spectral and geometric signals. HyperDepth employs a decoupled spectral encoding scheme with adaptive gating so that high-frequency components focus on local instance discrimination while low-frequency components capture global hierarchical structure. On top of this, an energy-based hierarchical Alignment module attaches a learnable prototype tree to the representation space and minimizes an interpretable energy functional to recover the semantic depth of hyperedges. Theoretically, under a mild frequency-separation assumption, we show that the local contrastive and global hierarchical objectives operate on orthogonal spectral components and admit equilibrium embeddings that preserve semantic depth while still retaining instance-level discrimination. Experiments on 15 hypergraph datasets and 17 supervised and self-supervised baselines, spanning homophilic and heterophilic regimes, show that HyperDepth attains strong performance with the best average rank.</p>","absKo":"<p>Hypergraph contrastive learningмқҖ higher-order relational dataм—җм„ң representation learningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ hyperedgeк°Җ лӢӨмёөм Ғ мқҳлҜёлҘј к°Җм§„ л…ёл“ңлҘј м—°кІ°н•ңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ лҢҖмІҙлЎң л¬ҙмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ contrastive objectiveлҠ” hyperspherical uniformityлҘј нҶөн•ҙ instance discriminationмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ҳл©°, л¬ҙм°Ёлі„м ҒмңјлЎң embeddingмқ„ м„ңлЎң л°Җм–ҙлӮҙлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙкІғмқҙ <em>HierarchyвҖ“Uniformity Conflict</em>лҘј м•јкё°н•ҳл©°, к·ё кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ н‘ңнҳ„мқҖ <em>Semantic Flattening</em>мңјлЎң, hyperedgeмқҳ semantic depthк°Җ кұ°мқҳ нҸүнҸүн•ң instance кө¬лҰ„мңјлЎң л¶•кҙҙлҗҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” spectral signalкіј geometric signalмқ„ н•Ёк»ҳ мЎ°мңЁн•ҳм—¬ representationмқ„ hierarchyвҖ“uniformity equilibriumмңјлЎң мқҙлҸҷмӢңнӮӨлҠ” hypergraph contrastive learning frameworkмқё <strong>HyperDepth</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. HyperDepthлҠ” adaptive gatingмқҙ м Ғмҡ©лҗң decoupled spectral encoding schemeмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, high-frequency componentлҠ” көӯмҶҢ instance discriminationм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳкі  low-frequency componentлҠ” м „м—ӯ кі„мёө кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м—җ лҚ”н•ҙ, energy-based hierarchical Alignment moduleмқҖ н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн•ң prototype treeлҘј representation spaceм—җ л¶Җм°©н•ҳкі , н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң energy functionalмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ hyperedgeмқҳ semantic depthлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң, мҷ„л§Ңн•ң frequency-separation assumption н•ҳм—җм„ң көӯмҶҢ contrastive objectiveмҷҖ м „м—ӯ hierarchical objectiveк°Җ м§Ғкөҗн•ҳлҠ” spectral component мң„м—җм„ң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳл©°, instance-level discriminationмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ semantic depthлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” equilibrium embeddingмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. homophilic л°Ҹ heterophilic regimeмқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” 15к°ңмқҳ hypergraph datasetкіј 17к°ңмқҳ supervised л°Ҹ self-supervised baselineм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, HyperDepthк°Җ мөңкі мқҳ нҸүк·  мҲңмң„мҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65826","en":"View Space: Learning Representation across Arbitrary Graphs","ko":"View Space: мһ„мқҳмқҳ к·ёлһҳн”„м—җ кұём№ң н‘ңнҳ„ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Dooho Lee, Myeong Kong, Minho Jeong, Jaemin Yoo","pos":"#2203","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9klc62KROH","abs":"<p>Generalizing pretrained models to unseen datasets without retraining is a central challenge toward foundation models. Achieving fully inductive inference on numerical data is particularly difficult due to large variations in feature dimensionality and semantics across datasets. We observe that, in the presence of graph structure, numerical data admits a distinct structure-induced representational axis beyond the feature space, which we formalize as the <em>view space</em>. This view space enables a unified representation of graphs with heterogeneous features and motivates <em>Graph View Transformation</em> (GVT), a class of parametric mappings that can be shared across arbitrary graphs. We instantiate this framework with Recurrent GVT, an architecture for fully inductive node representation learning in node classification. Pretrained on OGBN-Arxiv and evaluated on 27 benchmarks, Recurrent GVT outperforms GraphAny, the prior fully inductive graph model, by +8.93%, and surpasses 12 individually tuned GNNs by at least +3.30%. These results establish the view space as a principled and practical foundation for learning across graphs with heterogeneous feature spaces. Code, datasets, and checkpoints are available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/view-space.</p>","absKo":"мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөлҗң modelмқ„ мһ¬н•ҷмҠө м—Ҷмқҙ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң datasetм—җ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ foundation modelмқ„ н–Ҙн•ң н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. мҲҳм№ҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җм„ң мҷ„м „н•ң inductive inferenceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ dataset м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң feature dimensionalityмҷҖ semanticsмқҳ нҒ° м°Ёмқҙ л•Ңл¬ём—җ нҠ№нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” graph structureк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•  л•Ң мҲҳм№ҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ feature spaceлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ”, кө¬мЎ°к°Җ мң лҸ„н•ң distinct representational axisлҘј н—Ҳмҡ©н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҘј <em>view space</em>лЎң formalizeн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ view spaceлҠ” мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё featureлҘј к°Җм§„ graphлҘј нҶөн•©м ҒмңјлЎң н‘ңнҳ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳкі , мһ„мқҳмқҳ graph к°„м—җ кіөмң лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” parametric mappingмқҳ н•ң лІ”мЈјмқё <em>Graph View Transformation</em> (GVT)мқ„ мқҙлҒҢм–ҙлӮёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ frameworkлҘј node classificationм—җм„ң мҷ„м „ inductive node representation learningмқ„ мң„н•ң architectureмқё Recurrent GVTлЎң кө¬мІҙнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. OGBN-Arxivм—җм„ң мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  27к°ң benchmarkм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, Recurrent GVTлҠ” кё°мЎҙ fully inductive graph modelмқё GraphAnyліҙлӢӨ +8.93% мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳл©°, к°ңлі„м ҒмңјлЎң нҠңлӢқлҗң 12к°ңмқҳ GNNмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ мөңмҶҢ +3.30% мқҙмғҒ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” view spaceк°Җ мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё feature spaceлҘј к°Җм§„ graph м „л°ҳм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё кё°л°ҳмһ„мқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ң, dataset, checkpointлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/view-space м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65162","en":"What Makes a Desired Graph for Relational Deep Learning?","ko":"кҙҖкі„нҳ• л”Ҙлҹ¬лӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң л°”лһҢм§Ғн•ң к·ёлһҳн”„лһҖ л¬ҙм—Үмқёк°Җ?","authors":"Yao Cheng, Siqiang Luo","pos":"#2204","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=GDHVAs2XDQ","abs":"<p>Relational deep learning (RDL) converts relational databases (RDBs) into heterogeneous graphs, but graphs derived directly from database schemas are often not well suited for how graph neural networks (GNNs) perform relational reasoning. We study what makes a relational graph suitable for deep learning and show that schema-derived graphs suffer from two systematic failures: information overload and semantic fragmentation. Through an empirical analysis on real-world databases, we find that effective graphs arise from a task-dependent balance between removing task-irrelevant structure and injecting task-aligned relational connectivity.  Filtering exhibits a non-monotonic effect on performance, while structural injection is beneficial only when it reflects the logic of the downstream task. Based on these findings, we develop an end-to-end structural optimizer that applies both operations to adapt relational graphs automatically.  Across 23 tasks spanning classification, regression, and recommendation, the optimized graphs consistently improve accuracy while often reducing inference cost. Code and data are available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Structural<em>Optimizer</em>RDL-0F74/.</p>","absKo":"<p>Relational deep learning(RDL)мқҖ relational database(RDB)лҘј heterogeneous graphлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, database schemaм—җм„ң м§Ғм ‘ мң лҸ„н•ң graphлҠ” graph neural network(GNN)к°Җ relational reasoningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқм—җ мһҳ л§һм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” relational graphлҘј deep learningм—җ м Ғн•©н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” мҡ”мқёмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ҳкі , schema-derived graphк°Җ м •ліҙ кіјл¶Җн•ҳ(information overload)мҷҖ мқҳлҜё л¶„м Ҳ(semantic fragmentation)мқҙлқјлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мІҙкі„м Ғ мӢӨнҢЁлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мӢӨм ң world databaseм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨмҰқ л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё graphлҠ” taskмҷҖ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ң кө¬мЎ°лҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳлҠ” кІғкіј taskм—җ л§һлҠ” relational connectivityлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ҳлҠ” кІғ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ task-dependent balanceм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗЁмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. FilteringмқҖ м„ұлҠҘм—җ л№„лӢЁмЎ°м Ғ(non-monotonic) мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, structural injectionмқҖ downstream taskмқҳ л…јлҰ¬лҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•  л•Ңм—җл§Ң мң мқөн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°ңкІ¬мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ м—°мӮ°мқ„ лӘЁл‘җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҙ relational graphлҘј мһҗлҸҷмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮӨлҠ” end-to-end structural optimizerлҘј к°ңл°ңн–ҲлӢӨ. classification, regression, recommendationм—җ кұём№ң 23к°ң task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗң graphлҠ” м¶”лЎ  л№„мҡ©мқ„ мў…мў… мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңмј°лӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Structural<em>Optimizer</em>RDL-0F74/ м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64246","en":"Same Graph Cross-Task Transfer in GNNs: Protocols and Predictors","ko":"GNNм—җм„ң лҸҷмқј к·ёлһҳн”„ көҗм°Ё кіјм ң м „мқҙ: н”„лЎңнҶ мҪңкіј мҳҲмёЎ мқёмһҗ","authors":"Neelam Akula, Surbhi Kumar, Murat Kantarcioglu, Baris Coskunuzer","pos":"#2301","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PZJyX9HDA3","abs":"Many real-world graphs support multiple predictive tasks over the same underlying structure, creating an opportunity to reuse supervision across node classification (NC) and link prediction (LP). However, existing evaluations often rely on incompatible splits, observed-graph assumptions, and negative sampling rules, making conclusions about same-graph cross-task transfer unreliable. We formalize same-graph NCвҖ“LP transfer and propose a leakage-free protocol that fixes node and edge splits, uses a shared message-passing graph that excludes evaluated edges, and employs fixed negatives for LP. Across three backbones (GCN, GraphSAGE, GPS), we find transfer is strongly directional and predictable: NC$\\to$LP is consistently beneficial on homophilic graphs, while LP$\\to$NC is fragile and can even degrade accuracy under naive representation reuse. LP$\\to$NC becomes reliably positive mainly in a structure-dominant regime where LP is easy but NC is unsaturated, suggesting LP acts as structural pretraining. Finally, we introduce CoTask Score (CTS) to summarize joint NC+LP utility when a shared encoder must serve both tasks, and show that simple dataset statistics, especially homophily, can guide mechanism choice and help avoid negative transfer.","absKo":"л§ҺмқҖ мӢӨм ң к·ёлһҳн”„лҠ” лҸҷмқјн•ң кё°л°ҳ кө¬мЎ° мң„м—җм„ң м—¬лҹ¬ мҳҲмёЎ кіјм ңлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, node classification (NC)кіј link prediction (LP) к°„м—җ supervisionмқ„ мһ¬нҷңмҡ©н•  кё°нҡҢлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” мў…мў… нҳёнҷҳлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” split, observed-graph к°Җм •, negative sampling к·ңм№ҷм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬, лҸҷмқј к·ёлһҳн”„м—җм„ңмқҳ cross-task transferм—җ лҢҖн•ң кІ°лЎ мқ„ мӢ лў°н•ҳкё° м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” same-graph NCвҖ“LP transferлҘј м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , нҸүк°Җлҗң edgeлҘј м ңмҷён•ң shared message-passing graphлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©°, nodeмҷҖ edge splitмқ„ кі м •н•ҳкі , LPм—җлҠ” fixed negativesлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” leakage-free protocolмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м„ё к°Җм§Җ backbone(GCN, GraphSAGE, GPS) м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” transferк°Җ к°•н•ҳкІҢ л°©н–Ҙм„ұмқ„ к°Җм§Җл©° мҳҲмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мҰү, NC$\\to$LPлҠ” homophilic graphм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мң мқөн•ң л°ҳл©ҙ, LP$\\to$NCлҠ” м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳл©° naive representation reuse н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳлҸ„ мһҲлӢӨ. LP$\\to$NCк°Җ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ м–‘(+)мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј ліҙмқҙлҠ” кІҪмҡ°лҠ” мЈјлЎң кө¬мЎ°к°Җ м§Җл°°м Ғмқё regimeмңјлЎң, мқҙл•Ң LPлҠ” мүҪм§Җл§Ң NCлҠ” м•„м§Ғ нҸ¬нҷ”лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мғҒнғңмқҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” LPк°Җ structural pretrainingмңјлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, shared encoderк°Җ л‘җ кіјм ңлҘј лӘЁл‘җ мҲҳн–үн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң joint NC+LP нҡЁмҡ©мқ„ мҡ”м•Ҫн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ CoTask Score (CTS)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , к°„лӢЁн•ң dataset нҶөкі„, нҠ№нһҲ homophilyк°Җ mechanism м„ нғқмқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳкі  negative transferлҘј н”јн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° лҸ„мӣҖмқҙ лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"63879","en":"ST-TGExplainer: Disentangling Stability and Transition Patterns for Temporal GNN Interpretability","ko":"ST-TGExplainer: temporal GNN н•ҙм„қмқ„ мң„н•ң м•Ҳм •м„ұ л°Ҹ м „мқҙ нҢЁн„ҙ л¶„н•ҙ","authors":"Hongjiang Chen, Xin Zheng, Pengfei Jiao, Huan Liu, Zhidong Zhao, Huaming Wu, Feng Xia, Shirui Pan","pos":"#2302","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=StQUBg3hlS","abs":"<p>Temporal graph neural networks (TGNNs) have gained significant traction in solving real-world temporal graph tasks.  However, their interpretability remains limited, as most TGNNs fail to identify which historical interactions most influence a given prediction. Despite promising progress on interpretable TGNNs, existing methods predominantly focus on previously seen historical interactions, which we term stability patterns, while overlooking newly emerging first-time interactions, which we term transition patterns. Both types of patterns are essential for faithful temporal explanations. To address this limitation, we propose ST-TGExplainer, a self-explainable TGNN that disentangles Stability and Transition patterns in temporal graphs for a more faithful Temporal GNN Explainer. Guided by a disentangled information bottleneck objective, ST-TGExplainer learns a compact explanatory subgraph that remains predictive of the event label while explicitly suppressing label-conditioned redundancy between stability and transition patterns. Extensive experiments demonstrate that ST-TGExplainer achieves strong predictive performance and yields more faithful explanations.</p>","absKo":"<p>Temporal graph neural network (TGNN)мқҖ мӢӨм ң temporal graph taskлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мғҒлӢ№н•ң мЈјлӘ©мқ„ л°ӣм•„мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ TGNNмқҖ мЈјм–ҙм§„ predictionм—җ к°ҖмһҘ нҒ° мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ” кіјкұ° interactionмқҙ л¬ҙм—Үмқём§Җ мӢқлі„н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҙ interpretabilityк°Җ м ңн•ңм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң TGNNм—җ лҢҖн•ң мң л§қн•ң м§„м „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ мЈјлЎң мқҙм „м—җ кҙҖм°°лҗң historical interaction, мҰү мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ stability patternмқҙлқј л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” кІғм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, мғҲлЎӯкІҢ л“ұмһҘн•ҳлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ interaction, мҰү transition patternмқҖ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. л‘җ мў…лҘҳмқҳ pattern лӘЁл‘җ м¶©мӢӨн•ң temporal explanationм—җ н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢңк°„ к·ёлһҳн”„м—җм„ң StabilityмҷҖ Transition patternмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳм—¬ лҚ” м¶©мӢӨн•ң Temporal GNN ExplainerлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” self-explainable TGNNмқё ST-TGExplainerлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. disentangled information bottleneck objectiveмқҳ м§ҖлҸ„лҘј л°ӣм•„, ST-TGExplainerлҠ” event labelмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ stability patternкіј transition pattern мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ label-conditioned redundancyлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м–өм ңн•ҳлҠ” compact explanatory subgraphлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ ST-TGExplainerк°Җ к°•н•ң predictive performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  лҚ” м¶©мӢӨн•ң explanationмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65828","en":"Rethinking Feature Alignment in Generalist Graph Anomaly Detection: A Relational Fingerprint-based Approach","ko":"мқјл°ҳмЈјмқҳ к·ёлһҳн”„ мқҙмғҒ нғҗм§Җм—җм„ңмқҳ нҠ№м§• м •л ¬ мһ¬кі : кҙҖкі„нҳ• м§Җл¬ё кё°л°ҳ м ‘к·ј","authors":"Yujing Liu, Yixin Liu, Yu Zheng, Alan Liew, Xiaofeng Cao, Shirui Pan","pos":"#2304","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9kkby07AvD","abs":"<p>Extending traditional graph anomaly detection (GAD) from one-for-one to one-for-all paradigms, generalist GAD aims to learn a universal detector for identifying anomalies on unseen graphs without graph-specific retraining. Nevertheless, existing approaches primarily focus on aligning heterogeneous features across different data domains via PCA-based projection, which harmonizes feature dimensions but neglects semantic alignment. As a result, GAD models fail to acquire semantically transferable knowledge from source-domain pre-training, and even exhibit negative transfer on unseen graphs. To address this issue, we propose a Relational Fingerprint-based generalist GAD approach (REFI-GAD for short), aligning heterogeneous raw features with a universal and semantics-aware relational fingerprint (REFI) that encodes anomaly-indicative cues from both contextual and structural perspectives. Building on REFI, we design a fingerprint-grounded generalist GAD model, which combines a transformer-based encoder to capture domain-invariant knowledge with an SNR-guided refinement module for domain-specific adaptation. Extensive experiments on 14 datasets demonstrate that REFI-GAD significantly outperforms state-of-the-art methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>м „нҶөм Ғмқё graph anomaly detection(GAD)мқ„ one-for-one нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„м—җм„ң one-for-all нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ң generalist GADлҠ” graph-specific retraining м—Ҷмқҙ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң к·ёлһҳн”„м—җм„ң мқҙмғҒм№ҳлҘј мӢқлі„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лІ”мҡ© нғҗм§Җкё°лҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹјм—җлҸ„ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң PCA кё°л°ҳ projectionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё лҚ°мқҙн„° лҸ„л©”мқё к°„ мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё featureлҘј м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”л©°, feature м°Ёмӣҗмқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” кІғм—җлҠ” лҸ„мӣҖмқҙ лҗҳм§Җл§Ң semantic alignmentлҠ” к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј GAD лӘЁлҚёмқҖ source-domain pre-trainingмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎң м „мқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м§ҖмӢқмқ„ нҡҚл“қн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі , ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң к·ёлһҳн”„м—җм„ңлҠ” мҳӨнһҲл Ө negative transferлҘј ліҙмқҙкё°лҸ„ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Relational Fingerprint кё°л°ҳ generalist GAD м ‘к·јлІ•(мӨ„м—¬м„ң REFI-GAD)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” л¬ёл§Ҙ(contextual)кіј кө¬мЎ°(structural) кҙҖм җ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң anomaly-indicative cueлҘј мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” universalн•ҳкі  semantics-awareн•ң relational fingerprint(REFI)лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё raw featureлҘј м •л ¬н•ңлӢӨ. REFIлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” fingerprint-grounded generalist GAD лӘЁлҚёмқ„ м„Өкі„н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” domain-invariant knowledgeлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” transformer-based encoderмҷҖ domain-specific adaptationмқ„ мң„н•ң SNR-guided refinement moduleмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ңлӢӨ. 14к°ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ REFI-GADк°Җ state-of-the-art л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ мң мқҳлҜён•ҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62610","en":"Rel-MOSS: Towards Imbalanced Relational Deep Learning on Relational Databases","ko":"Rel-MOSS: Relational Databasesм—җм„ң л¶Ҳк· нҳ• Relational Deep Learningмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Jun Yin, Peng Huo, Bangguo Zhu, Hao Yan, Xuchen Wang, Shirui Pan, Chengqi Zhang","pos":"#2305","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=f4k0XsOlCZ","abs":"<p>In recent advances, to enable a fully data-driven learning paradigm on relational databases (RDB), relational deep learning (RDL) is proposed to structure the RDB as a heterogeneous entity graph and adopt the graph neural network (GNN) as the predictive model. However, existing RDL methods neglect the imbalance problem of relational data in RDBs and risk under-representing the minority entities, leading to an unusable model in practice. In this work, we investigate, for the first time, class imbalance problem in RDB entity classification and design the relation-centric minority synthetic over-sampling GNN (<strong>Rel-MOSS</strong>), in order to fill a critical void in the current literature. Specifically, to mitigate the issue of minority-related information being submerged by majority counterparts, we design the relation-wise gating controller to modulate neighborhood messages from each individual relation type. Based on the relational-gated representations, we further propose the relation-guided minority synthesizer for over-sampling, which integrates the entity relational signatures to maintain relational consistency. Extensive experiments on 12 entity classification datasets provide compelling evidence for the superiority of Rel-MOSS, yielding an average improvement of up to 2.46% and 4.00% in terms of <em>Balanced Accuracy</em> and <em>G-Mean</em>, compared with SOTA RDL methods and classic methods for handling class imbalance.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·јмқҳ л°ңм „м—җ л”°лқј, кҙҖкі„нҳ• лҚ°мқҙн„°лІ мқҙмҠӨ(RDB)м—җм„ң мҷ„м „н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„° кё°л°ҳ н•ҷмҠө нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ relational deep learning(RDL)мқҙ м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” RDBлҘј heterogeneous entity graphлЎң кө¬мЎ°нҷ”н•ҳкі  graph neural network(GNN)мқ„ мҳҲмёЎ лӘЁлҚёлЎң мұ„нғқн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ RDL л°©лІ•мқҖ RDB лӮҙ кҙҖкі„нҳ• лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ л¶Ҳк· нҳ• л¬ём ңлҘј к°„кіјн•ҳм—¬ minority entityлҘј м¶©л¶„нһҲ н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•  мң„н—ҳмқҙ мһҲмңјл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” RDB entity classificationм—җм„ң class imbalance л¬ём ңлҘј мөңмҙҲлЎң мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкі , нҳ„мһ¬ л¬ён—Ңмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ relation-centric minority synthetic over-sampling GNN(<strong>Rel-MOSS</strong>)мқ„ м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, minority кҙҖл Ё м •ліҙк°Җ majority мӘҪ н‘ңнҳ„м—җ мқҳн•ҙ мһ кІЁлІ„лҰ¬лҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, к°Ғ к°ңлі„ relation typeм—җм„ң мҳӨлҠ” neighborhood messageлҘј мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” relation-wise gating controllerлҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң relational-gated representationмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” entity relational signatureлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ relational consistencyлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” over-samplingмҡ© relation-guided minority synthesizerлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. 12к°ңмқҳ entity classification datasetм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Rel-MOSSмқҳ мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқ„ к°•л ҘнһҲ мһ…мҰқн•ҳл©°, SOTA RDL л°©лІ• л°Ҹ class imbalanceлҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” кі м „м Ғ л°©лІ•л“Өкіј л№„көҗн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң <em>Balanced Accuracy</em>мҷҖ <em>G-Mean</em> кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң нҸүк·  мөңлҢҖ 2.46%мҷҖ 4.00%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66260","en":"MIMO-LP: A Multi-Input Multi-Output Framework for Subgraph-based Link Prediction","ko":"MIMO-LP: м„ңлёҢк·ёлһҳн”„ кё°л°ҳ л§ҒнҒ¬ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мң„н•ң Multi-Input Multi-Output н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Yixin Song, Guangchi Liu, Xiangyu Xu, Shaofeng Li, Zhen Ling, Yiwei Wang, Yujun Cai","pos":"#2311","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5Ls1FrQflg","abs":"<p>Link prediction (LP) is a fundamental problem in graph learning and can be broadly categorized into node-based and subgraph-based approaches. While subgraph-based LP methods often achieve superior predictive performance by exploiting localized structural information, they suffer from efficiency bottlenecks due to the high computational cost of per-query subgraph message-passing during both training and inference. To address this challenge, we propose MIMO-LP, a Multi-Input Multi-Output (MIMO) framework that accelerates subgraph-based LP. Given a batch of query node pairs and their corresponding subgraphs extracted from a shared full graph, MIMO-LP superposes their message-passing processes into a shared latent space while ensuring minimal interference among them. This design enables MIMO-LP to multiplex multiple queries within a single forward pass during both training and inference, substantially reducing redundant message-passing computations in overlapping subgraph regions. Extensive experiments demonstrate that MIMO-LP achieves a 14x-44x speedup over existing one-to-one subgraph-based methods, while maintaining comparable predictive performance. The code for MIMO-LP will be released publicly.</p>","absKo":"<p>Link prediction (LP)мқҖ graph learningмқҳ кё°ліё л¬ём ңлЎң, нҒ¬кІҢ node-based м ‘к·јкіј subgraph-based м ‘к·јмңјлЎң лӮҳлҲҢ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. Subgraph-based LP л°©лІ•мқҖ м§Җм—ӯм Ғ кө¬мЎ° м •ліҙлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мў…мў… лҚ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң мҳҲмёЎ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, н•ҷмҠөкіј м¶”лЎ  лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң queryлі„ subgraph message-passingм—җ лҶ’мқҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ л“Өкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ нҡЁмңЁм„ұ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” subgraph-based LPлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳлҠ” Multi-Input Multi-Output (MIMO) frameworkмқё MIMO-LPлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кіөмң лҗҳлҠ” м „мІҙ graphм—җм„ң м¶”м¶ңн•ң query node pairмқҳ л°°м№ҳмҷҖ к·ём—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” subgraphк°Җ мЈјм–ҙм§Җл©ҙ, MIMO-LPлҠ” к·ёл“Өмқҳ message-passing кіјм •мқ„ мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ к°„м„ӯл§Ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң кіөмң  latent spaceлЎң superposeн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” MIMO-LPк°Җ н•ҷмҠөкіј м¶”лЎ  лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң лӢЁмқј forward pass м•Ҳм—җ м—¬лҹ¬ queryлҘј multiplexн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳл©°, кІ№м№ҳлҠ” subgraph мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң мӨ‘ліө message-passing кі„мӮ°мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ MIMO-LPк°Җ кё°мЎҙ one-to-one subgraph-based method лҢҖл№„ 14x-44xмқҳ мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ л№„мҠ·н•ң мҳҲмёЎ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. MIMO-LPмқҳ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63596","en":"Learning the Neighborhood: Contrast-Free Multimodal Self-Supervised Molecular Graph Pretraining","ko":"мқҙмӣғ н•ҷмҠө: лҢҖмЎ° м—ҶлҠ” л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ мһҗкё°м§ҖлҸ„ л¶„мһҗ к·ёлһҳн”„ мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Boshra Ariguib, Mathias Niepert, Andrei Manolache","pos":"#2313","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Vbj1jSaqTo","abs":"<p>High-quality molecular representations are essential for property prediction and molecular design, yet large labeled datasets remain scarce. While self-supervised pretraining on molecular graphs has shown promise, many existing approaches either depend on hand-crafted augmentations or complex generative objectives, and often rely solely on 2D topology, leaving valuable 3D structural information underutilized. To address this gap, we introduce C-FREE (<strong>C</strong>ontrast-<strong>F</strong>ree <strong>R</strong>epresentation learning on <strong>E</strong>go-n<strong>e</strong>ts), a simple framework that integrates 2D graphs with ensembles of 3D conformers. C-FREE learns molecular representations by predicting subgraph embeddings from their complementary neighborhoods in the latent space, using fixed-radius ego-nets as modeling units across different conformers. This design allows us to integrate both geometric and topological information within a hybrid Graph Neural Network (GNN)-Transformer backbone, without negatives, positional encodings, or expensive pre-processing. Pretraining on the GEOM dataset, which provides rich 3D conformational diversity, C-FREE achieves state-of-the-art results on MoleculeNet, surpassing contrastive, generative, and other multimodal self-supervised methods. Fine-tuning across datasets with diverse sizes and molecule types further demonstrates that pretraining transfers effectively to new chemical domains, highlighting the importance of 3D-informed molecular representations.</p>","absKo":"<p>кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ molecular representationмқҖ property predictionкіј molecular designм—җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, large labeled datasetмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. Molecular graphм—җ лҢҖн•ң self-supervised pretrainingмқҖ мң л§қн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“Ө мӨ‘ мғҒлӢ№мҲҳлҠ” hand-crafted augmentationмқҙлӮҳ ліөмһЎн•ң generative objectiveм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ 2D topologyм—җл§Ң мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ valuableн•ң 3D structural informationмқ„ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>C</strong>ontrast-<strong>F</strong>ree <strong>R</strong>epresentation learning on <strong>E</strong>go-n<strong>e</strong>ts, мҰү C-FREEлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” 2D graphмҷҖ 3D conformer ensembleмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ң frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. C-FREEлҠ” fixed-radius ego-netмқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ лӢЁмң„лЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё conformerм—җ кұёміҗ latent spaceм—җм„ң к·ё ліҙмҷ„м Ғ neighborhoodлЎңл¶Җн„° subgraph embeddingмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ molecular representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” negative, positional encoding, к°’л№„мӢј м „мІҳлҰ¬ м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ geometric informationкіј topological informationмқ„ кІ°н•©лҗң Graph Neural Network (GNN)-Transformer backbone м•Ҳм—җ нҶөн•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. н’Қл¶Җн•ң 3D conformational diversityлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” GEOM datasetм—җм„ң pretrainingн•ң кІ°кіј, C-FREEлҠ” MoleculeNetм—җм„ң state-of-the-art кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ contrastive, generative л°Ҹ лӢӨлҘё multimodal self-supervised methodлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң нҒ¬кё°мҷҖ molecule typeмқҳ datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң fine-tuningмқҖ pretrainingмқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ chemical domainмңјлЎң нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м „мқҙлҗЁмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, 3D-informed molecular representationмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63979","en":"Learning Long Range Spatio-Temporal Representations over Continuous Time Dynamic Graphs with State Space Models","ko":"State Space ModelsлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң м—°мҶҚ мӢңк°„ лҸҷм Ғ к·ёлһҳн”„мқҳ мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ мӢңкіөк°„ н‘ңнҳ„ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Ayushman Raghuvanshi, Thummaluru Siddartha Reddy, Sundeep Prabhakar Chepuri, Mahesh Chandran","pos":"#2314","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=S2jfT6EMqr","abs":"Continuous-time dynamic graphs (CTDGs) provide a richer framework to capture fine-grained temporal patterns in evolving relational data. Long-range information propagation is a key challenge while learning representations, wherein it is important to retain and update information over long temporal horizons. Existing approaches restrict models to capture one-hop or local temporal neighborhoods and fail to capture multi-hop or global structural patterns. To mitigate this, we derive a parameter-efficient state-space modeling framework for continuous-time dynamic graphs $\\texttt{(CTDG-SSM)}$ from first principles. We first introduce continuous-time Topology-Aware higher order polynomial projection operator ($\\texttt{CTT-HiPPO}$), a novel memory-based reformulation of  $\\texttt{HiPPO}$ to jointly encode temporal dynamics and graph structure. The solution from $\\texttt{CTT-HiPPO}$ are obtained by projecting the classical HiPPO solution through a polynomial of the Laplacian matrix, yielding topology-aware memory updates that admit an equivalent state-space formulation for CTDGs ($\\texttt{CTDG-SSM}$). Then a computationally efficient discrete formulation is obtained using the zero-order hold approach for model implementation.    Across benchmarks on dynamic link prediction, dynamic node classification, and sequence classification, $\\texttt{CTDG-SSM}$ achieves state-of-the-art performance. Notably, it achieves large performance gains on datasets that require long range temporal (LRT) and spatial reasoning.","absKo":"Continuous-time dynamic graph (CTDG)лҠ” м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” relational dataм—җм„ң м„ёл°Җн•ң temporal patternмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң лҚ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң frameworkлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кіјм •м—җм„ң мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ м •ліҙ м „нҢҢлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңмқҙл©°, кёҙ temporal horizonм—җ кұёміҗ м •ліҙлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳкі  к°ұмӢ н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ one-hop лҳҗлҠ” local temporal neighborhoodл§Ң нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м ңн•ңн•ҳл©°, multi-hop лҳҗлҠ” global structural patternмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” first principlesлЎңл¶Җн„° continuous-time dynamic graphлҘј мң„н•ң parameter-efficient state-space modeling frameworkмқё $\\texttt{CTDG-SSM}$мқ„ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” continuous-time Topology-Aware higher order polynomial projection operatorмқё $\\texttt{CTT-HiPPO}$лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” temporal dynamicsмҷҖ graph structureлҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң $\\texttt{HiPPO}$мқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ memory-based reformulationмқҙлӢӨ. $\\texttt{CTT-HiPPO}$мқҳ н•ҙлҠ” classical HiPPO solutionмқ„ Laplacian matrixмқҳ polynomialмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ projectionн•ҳм—¬ м–»мңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” CTDGsм—җ лҢҖн•ң equivalent state-space formulation ($\\texttt{CTDG-SSM}$)мқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” topology-aware memory updateлҘј мӮ°м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ model кө¬нҳ„мқ„ мң„н•ҙ zero-order hold approachлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ кі„мӮ°м ҒмңјлЎң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё discrete formulationмқ„ м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. dynamic link prediction, dynamic node classification, sequence classification benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң $\\texttt{CTDG-SSM}$мқҖ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ long range temporal (LRT) л°Ҹ spatial reasoningмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң datasetм—җм„ң нҒ° м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"61684","en":"Discriminative Attribute Graph Clustering Through Topology-Guided Contrastive Learning","ko":"Topology-Guided Contrastive Learningмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҢҗлі„м Ғ мҶҚм„ұ к·ёлһҳн”„ нҒҙлҹ¬мҠӨн„°л§Ғ","authors":"Ling Ding, Zhizhi Yu, Cuiying Huo","pos":"#2400","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nn5hJFwMPu","abs":"<p>Deep attribute graph clustering aims to learn discriminative node representations by leveraging both node attributes and graph topology to partition nodes into distinct clusters. Although substantial progress has been made in attribute-graph clustering in recent years, two key challenges remain: noisy edges in the original adjacency matrix degrade the quality of information propagation, and redundant feature information across different feature views hampers the learning of discriminative representations. To address these issues, we propose a self-supervised attribute graph clustering method based on topological reconstruction and correlation decorrelation. First, we reconstruct the graph topology by computing intersections between k-nearest neighbors and the original adjacency relationships, while simultaneously leveraging global semantic information from K-means clustering to filter out noisy nodes. This reconstructed topology effectively mitigates information redundancy during feature aggregation in Graph Neural Networks. Second, unlike existing augmentation-based contrastive methods, we treat the feature representations from an auto-encoder (AE) and a graph auto-encoder (GAE) as two complementary natural views. We then apply mutual information minimization and a decorrelation constraint to suppress redundant information between views, yielding more discriminative node representations. Extensive experiments on four widely-used graph datasetsвҖ”ACM, DBLP, CITE, and AMAPвҖ”demonstrate that our method consistently outperforms six state-of-the-art baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>Deep attribute graph clusteringмқҖ node attributeмҷҖ graph topologyлҘј лӘЁл‘җ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ discriminative node representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ л…ёл“ңлҘј м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё clusterлЎң л¶„н• н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј attribute-graph clusteringм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң м§„м „мқҙ мһҲм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. мӣҗлһҳ adjacency matrixмқҳ noisy edgeлҠ” м •ліҙ м „нҢҢмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮӨкі , м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё feature view к°„мқҳ мӨ‘ліөлҗң feature м •ліҙлҠ” discriminative representation н•ҷмҠөмқ„ л°©н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” topological reconstructionкіј correlation decorrelationм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң self-supervised attribute graph clustering methodлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ, k-nearest neighborsмҷҖ мӣҗлһҳ adjacency relationshipмқҳ көҗм§‘н•©мқ„ кі„мӮ°н•ҳм—¬ graph topologyлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, K-means clusteringм—җм„ң м–»мқҖ global semantic informationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ noisy nodeлҘј н•„н„°л§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙл ҮкІҢ мһ¬кө¬м„ұлҗң topologyлҠ” Graph Neural Networksм—җм„ң feature aggregation мӨ‘ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” м •ліҙ мӨ‘ліөмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, кё°мЎҙмқҳ augmentation-based contrastive methodмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, auto-encoder(AE)мҷҖ graph auto-encoder(GAE)м—җм„ң лӮҳмҳЁ feature representationмқ„ м„ңлЎң ліҙмҷ„м Ғмқё л‘җ к°ңмқҳ natural viewлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ mutual information minimizationкіј decorrelation constraintлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ view к°„ мӨ‘ліө м •ліҙлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳкі , лҚ” discriminativeн•ң node representationмқ„ м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” л„Ө к°Җм§Җ graph datasetмқё ACM, DBLP, CITE, AMAPм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ, м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ м—¬м„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65661","en":"Enhancing LLMs for Graph Tasks via Graph-aware LoRA Generation","ko":"Graph мқёмӢқ LoRA мғқм„ұмқ„ нҶөн•ң Graph мһ‘м—…мҡ© LLM к°•нҷ”","authors":"Junshu Sun, Wanxing Chang, Qingming Huang, Shuhui Wang","pos":"#2403","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=BRtDecMvjY","abs":"<p>Graph neural networks (GNNs) tightly couple their input-output parameters to dataset-specific feature spaces and target sets, exhibiting limited transferability across different datasets. In contrast, language models (LMs) generalize flexibly via a unified input-output interface, motivating recent attempts to adapt LMs to graph tasks. However, existing methods struggle to encode whole-graph information, leading to potential information loss and suboptimal graph understanding. In this work, we propose a novel weight-level information injection paradigm for adapting LMs to graph tasks. This paradigm injects whole-graph information by generating task-specific weight updates that interact directly with hidden representations. Instantiating this paradigm following low-rank adaptation (LoRA), we introduce GaRA, a Graph-aware LoRA generation model. GaRA constructs low-rank weight updates conditioned on the original graph structures and constrains the norm of the generated updates, thus injecting whole-graph information and avoiding the optimization bias in the weight generation. Empirical studies demonstrate that GaRA consistently outperforms baselines on zero-shot graph learning tasks. Codes are provided in the supplementary material.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph neural network (GNN)мқҖ мһ…л Ҙ-м¶ңл Ҙ parameterлҘј dataset-specific feature spaceмҷҖ target setм—җ к°•н•ҳкІҢ кІ°н•©н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ к°„ transferabilityк°Җ м ңн•ңм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ language model (LM)мқҖ нҶөн•©лҗң input-output interfaceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мң м—°н•ҳкІҢ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мөңк·ј LMмқ„ graph taskм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл ӨлҠ” мӢңлҸ„к°Җ нҷңл°ңн•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ whole-graph м •ліҙлҘј мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘм–ҙ м •ліҙ мҶҗмӢӨкіј suboptimal graph understandingмқҙ л°ңмғқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” LMмқ„ graph taskм—җ м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ weight-level information injection paradigmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ paradigmмқҖ hidden representationкіј м§Ғм ‘ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” task-specific weight updateлҘј мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ whole-graph м •ліҙлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј low-rank adaptation (LoRA) л°©мӢқмңјлЎң кө¬мІҙнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Graph-aware LoRA generation modelмқё GaRAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. GaRAлҠ” мӣҗлһҳ graph structureм—җ мЎ°кұҙнҷ”лҗң low-rank weight updateлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мғқм„ұлҗң updateмқҳ normмқ„ м ңм•Ҫн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ whole-graph м •ліҙлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ weight generationм—җм„ңмқҳ optimization biasлҘј л°©м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ GaRAк°Җ zero-shot graph learning taskм—җм„ң baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” supplementary materialм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62454","en":"Fixed Aggregation Features Can Rival GNNs","ko":"кі м • Aggregation Featureк°Җ GNNsм—җ н•„м Ғн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢ","authors":"Celia Rubio-Madrigal, Rebekka Burkholz","pos":"#2405","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gSZhNPp103","abs":"<p>Graph neural networks (GNNs) are widely believed to excel at node representation learning through trainable neighborhood aggregations. We challenge this view by introducing Fixed Aggregation Features (FAFs), a training-free approach that transforms graph learning tasks into tabular problems. This simple shift enables the use of well-established tabular methods, offering strong interpretability and the flexibility to deploy diverse classifiers. Across 14 benchmarks, well-tuned multilayer perceptrons trained on FAFs rival or outperform state-of-the-art GNNs and graph transformers on 12 tasksвҖ”often using only mean aggregation. The only exceptions are the Roman Empire and Minesweeper datasets, which typically require unusually deep GNNs. To explain the theoretical possibility of non-trainable aggregations, we connect our findings to KolmogorovвҖ“Arnold representations and discuss when mean aggregation can be sufficient. In conclusion, our results call for (i) richer benchmarks benefiting from learning diverse neighborhood aggregations, (ii) strong tabular baselines as standard, and (iii) employing and advancing tabular models for graph data to gain new insights into related tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph neural network(GNN)мқҖ н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн•ң neighborhood aggregationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ node representation learningм—җ лӣ°м–ҙлӮҳлӢӨкі  л„җлҰ¬ м—¬кІЁм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Fixed Aggregation Features(FAFs)лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ кҙҖм җм—җ лҸ„м „н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” graph learning taskлҘј tabular problemмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” training-free м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ лӢЁмҲңн•ң м „нҷҳмқҖ мһҳ нҷ•лҰҪлҗң tabular methodмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, к°•н•ң interpretabilityмҷҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң classifierлҘј мң м—°н•ҳкІҢ л°°м№ҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мқҙм җмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. 14к°ң benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң FAFsлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң мһҳ нҠңлӢқлҗң multilayer perceptronмқҖ 12к°ң taskм—җм„ң state-of-the-art GNNкіј graph transformerмҷҖ кІ¬мЈјкұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн–Ҳмңјл©°, мў…мў… mean aggregationл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ м¶©л¶„н–ҲлӢӨ. мң мқјн•ң мҳҲмҷёлҠ” Roman EmpireмҷҖ Minesweeper datasetмңјлЎң, мқҙл“ӨмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мң лӮңнһҲ к№ҠмқҖ GNNмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. л№„н•ҷмҠө aggregationмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҘј KolmogorovвҖ“Arnold representationкіј м—°кІ°н•ҳкі  mean aggregationмқҙ м–ём ң м¶©л¶„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җ л…јмқҳн•ңлӢӨ. кІ°лЎ м ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” (i) лӢӨм–‘н•ң neighborhood aggregation н•ҷмҠөмқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ м–»лҠ” лҚ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң benchmark, (ii) standardлЎңм„ңмқҳ к°•л Ҙн•ң tabular baseline, (iii) graph dataм—җ лҢҖн•ң tabular modelмқҳ нҷңмҡ©кіј л°ңм „мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кҙҖл Ё taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ м–»м–ҙм•ј н•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63086","en":"GP2F: Cross-Domain Graph Prompting with Adaptive Fusion of Pre-trained Graph Neural Networks","ko":"GP2F: мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөлҗң к·ёлһҳн”„ мӢ кІҪл§қмқҳ м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мңөн•©мқ„ нҶөн•ң көҗм°Ё лҸ„л©”мқё к·ёлһҳн”„ н”„лЎ¬н”„нҢ…","authors":"Dongxiao He, Wenxuan Sun, Yongqi Huang, Jitao Zhao, Di Jin","pos":"#2407","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=aDYZuNjHsi","abs":"<p>Graph Prompt Learning (GPL) has recently emerged as a promising paradigm for downstream adaptation of pre-trained graph models, mitigating the misalignment between pre-training objectives and downstream tasks. Recently, the focus of GPL has shifted from in-domain to cross-domain scenarios, which is closer to the real world applications, where the pre-training source and downstream target often differ substantially in data distribution. However, why GPLs remain effective under such domain shifts is still unexplored. Empirically, we observe that representative GPL methods are competitive with two simple baselines in cross-domain settings: full fine-tuning (FT) and linear probing (LP), motivating us to explore a deeper understanding of the prompting mechanism. We provide a theoretical analysis demonstrating that jointly leveraging these two complementary branches yields a smaller estimation error than using either branch alone, formally proving that cross-domain GPL benefits from the integration between pre-trained knowledge and task-specific adaptation. Based on this insight, we propose GP2F, a dual-branch GPL method that explicitly instantiates the two extremes: (1) a frozen branch that retains pre-trained knowledge, and (2) an adapted branch with lightweight adapters for task-specific adaptation. We then perform adaptive fusion under topology constraints via a contrastive loss and a topology-consistent loss. Extensive experiments on cross-domain few-shot node and graph classification demonstrate that our method outperforms existing methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph Prompt Learning (GPL)мқҖ мөңк·ј мӮ¬м „ н•ҷмҠөлҗң graph modelмқҳ downstream adaptationмқ„ мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳмңјл©°, pre-training objectiveмҷҖ downstream task мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ misalignmentлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј GPLмқҳ мҙҲм җмқҖ in-domainм—җм„ң cross-domain мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨлЎң мқҙлҸҷн–ҲлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” pre-training sourceмҷҖ downstream targetмқҙ лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶„нҸ¬ мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң мў…мў… нҒ¬кІҢ лӢӨлҘё мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җ лҚ” к°Җк№қлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ domain shift н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ GPLмқҙ мҷң м—¬м „нһҲ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқём§ҖлҠ” м•„м§Ғ к·ңлӘ…лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё GPL л°©лІ•л“Өмқҙ cross-domain м„Өм •м—җм„ң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ лӢЁмҲңн•ң baseline, мҰү full fine-tuning (FT)кіј linear probing (LP)мҷҖ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙмқҙ мһҲмқҢмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” prompting mechanismм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҚ” к№ҠмқҖ мқҙн•ҙлҘј нғҗкө¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лҸҷкё°лҘј л¶Җм—¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л‘җ мғҒліҙм Ғ branchлҘј н•Ёк»ҳ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ м–ҙлҠҗ н•ң branchл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•  л•ҢліҙлӢӨ estimation errorк°Җ лҚ” мһ‘м•„м§„лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , cross-domain GPLмқҙ pre-trained knowledgeмҷҖ task-specific adaptationмқҳ нҶөн•©мңјлЎңл¶Җн„° мқҙмқөмқ„ м–»лҠ”лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ нҳ•мӢқм ҒмңјлЎң мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” GP2FлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” л‘җ к·№лӢЁмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬нҳ„н•ҳлҠ” dual-branch GPL л°©лІ•мңјлЎң, (1) pre-trained knowledgeлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” frozen branchмҷҖ (2) task-specific adaptationмқ„ мң„н•ң lightweight adapterлҘј к°Җм§„ adapted branchлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ contrastive lossмҷҖ topology-consistent lossлҘј нҶөн•ҙ topology constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң adaptive fusionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. cross-domain few-shot node л°Ҹ graph classificationм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60661","en":"Graph Alignment via Dual-Pass Spectral Encoding and Latent Space Communication","ko":"Dual-Pass Spectral Encodingкіј Latent Space Communicationмқ„ нҶөн•ң Graph Alignment","authors":"Maysam Behmanesh, Erkan Turan, Maks Ovsjanikov","pos":"#2409","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xw09Zi47YC","abs":"<p>Graph alignment, the problem of identifying corresponding nodes across multiple graphs, is fundamental to numerous applications. Most existing unsupervised methods embed node features into latent representations to enable cross-graph comparison without ground-truth correspondences. However, these methods suffer from two critical limitations: the degradation of node distinctiveness due to oversmoothing in GNN-based embeddings, and the misalignment of latent spaces across graphs caused by structural noise, feature heterogeneity, and training instability, ultimately leading to unreliable node correspondences. Our key insight is that rather than balancing these objectives purely in the feature space, a unified framework can simultaneously filter in both feature and map spaces. We propose a novel framework that employs a dual-pass encoder to inject high-frequency discriminability into node features, paired with a geometry-aware functional map module that operates on the correspondence itself. This functional map module learns bijective and isometric transformations that align latent spaces while acting as a low-pass filter on correspondences, enforcing smoothness and robustness as a structural prior in the map space. Extensive experiments on graph benchmarks demonstrate that our method consistently outperforms existing unsupervised alignment baselines, exhibiting superior robustness to structural inconsistencies and challenging alignment scenarios.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph alignmentлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ graph к°„м—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” nodeлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлЎң, мҲҳл§ҺмқҖ мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң кё°ліём ҒмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ unsupervised methodлҠ” ground-truth correspondence м—Ҷмқҙ cross-graph л№„көҗлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ node featureлҘј latent representationмңјлЎң embeddingн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•мқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ м№ҳлӘ…м Ғ н•ңкі„м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ: GNN-based embeddingм—җм„ң oversmoothingмңјлЎң мқён•ң node distinctivenessмқҳ м Җн•ҳ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  structural noise, feature heterogeneity, training instabilityлЎң мқён•ҙ graph к°„ latent spaceк°Җ misalignmentлҗҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлЎң, кІ°көӯ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” node correspondenceлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ нҶөм°°мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘ©н‘ңл“Өмқ„ feature spaceм—җм„ң мҲңмҲҳн•ҳкІҢ к· нҳ• л§һм¶”лҠ” лҢҖмӢ , unified frameworkк°Җ feature spaceмҷҖ map spaceлҘј лҸҷмӢңм—җ н•„н„°л§Ғн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” node featureм—җ high-frequency discriminabilityлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ҳлҠ” dual-pass encoderмҷҖ, correspondence мһҗмІҙм—җ мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” geometry-aware functional map moduleмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ functional map moduleмқҖ latent spaceлҘј м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” bijectiveн•ҳкі  isometricн•ң transformationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ correspondenceм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ low-pass filterлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳм—¬, map spaceм—җм„ң structural priorлЎңм„ң smoothnessмҷҖ robustnessлҘј к°•м ңн•ңлӢӨ. graph benchmark м „л°ҳм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ кё°мЎҙ unsupervised alignment baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, кө¬мЎ°м Ғ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳмҷҖ к№ҢлӢӨлЎңмҡҙ alignment мғҒнҷ©м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64241","en":"Can Computational Reducibility Lead to Transferable Models for Graph Combinatorial Optimization?","ko":"кі„мӮ°м Ғ к°Җм•Ҫм„ұмқҙ к·ёлһҳн”„ мЎ°н•© мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң м „мқҙ к°ҖлҠҘ лӘЁлҚёлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ?","authors":"Semih CantГјrk, Thomas Sabourin, Frederik Wenkel, Michael Perlmutter, Guy Wolf","pos":"#2502","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PbgF8AGP5O","abs":"<p>A key challenge in deriving unified neural solvers for combinatorial optimization (CO) is efficient generalization of models between one set of tasks to new tasks not used during the initial training process. To address it, we first establish a new model, which uses a GCON module as a form of expressive message passing together with energy-based unsupervised loss functions. This model achieves high performance (often comparable with state-of-the-art results) across multiple CO tasks when trained individually on each task. We then leverage knowledge from the computational reducibility literature to propose pretraining and fine-tuning strategies to transfer effectively (a) between MVC, MIS and MaxClique, and (b) in a multi-task learning setting that additionally incorporates MaxCut, MDS and graph coloring. Additionally, in a leave-one-out, multi-task learning setting, we observe that pretraining on all but one task almost always leads to faster convergence on the remaining task when fine-tuning while avoiding negative transfer. Our findings indicate that learning common representations across multiple graph CO problems is viable through the use of expressive message passing coupled with pretraining strategies that are informed by the polynomial reduction literature, thereby taking an important step towards enabling the development of foundational models for neural CO.</p>","absKo":"мЎ°н•© мөңм Ғнҷ”(combinatorial optimization, CO)лҘј мң„н•ң нҶөн•© neural solverлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё кіјм ңлҠ”, мҙҲкё° training кіјм •м—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskлЎң modelмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЁјм Җ GCON moduleмқ„ expressive message passingмқҳ н•ң нҳ•нғңлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі  energy-based unsupervised loss functionмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ modelмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ modelмқҖ к°Ғ taskлі„лЎң к°ңлі„ н•ҷмҠөн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң м—¬лҹ¬ CO task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң лҶ’мқҖ м„ұлҠҘ(мў…мў… state-of-the-art кІ°кіјмҷҖ л№„мҠ·н•ң мҲҳмӨҖ)мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ computational reducibility л¬ён—Ңмқҳ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, (a) MVC, MIS, MaxClique мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (b) MaxCut, MDS, graph coloringк№Ңм§Җ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” multi-task learning settingм—җм„ң нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң transferн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң pretraining л°Ҹ fine-tuning м „лһөмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. м¶”к°ҖлЎң, leave-one-out multi-task learning settingм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•ң taskлҘј м ңмҷён•ң лӮҳлЁём§Җ м „мІҙм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ pretrainingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳл©ҙ, fine-tuning мӢң лӮЁмқҖ taskм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ negative transferлҘј н”јн•ҳл©ҙм„ң кұ°мқҳ н•ӯмғҒ лҚ” л№ лҘё convergenceк°Җ мқјм–ҙлӮңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” polynomial reduction л¬ён—Ңм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣмқҖ pretraining strategyмҷҖ кІ°н•©лҗң expressive message passingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м—¬лҹ¬ graph CO problemм—җ кұём№ң кіөнҶө representation н•ҷмҠөмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, neural COлҘј мң„н•ң foundation model к°ңл°ңлЎң лӮҳм•„к°ҖлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң н•ң кұёмқҢмқ„ м ңмӢңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65891","en":"Beyond Model Base Retrieval: Weaving Knowledge to Master Fine-grained Neural Network Design","ko":"лӘЁлҚё лІ мқҙмҠӨ кІҖмғүмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ң: м„ёл°Җн•ң мӢ кІҪл§қ м„Өкі„ мҲҷлӢ¬мқ„ мң„н•ң м§ҖмӢқ м—®кё°","authors":"Jialiang Wang, Hanmo Liu, Shimin Di, Zhili Wang, Jiachuan Wang, Lei Chen, Xiaofang Zhou","pos":"#2503","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=96VOwRWMQr","abs":"<p>Designing high-performance neural networks for new tasks requires balancing optimization quality with search efficiency. Current methods fail to achieve this balance: neural architectural search is computationally expensive, while model retrieval often yields suboptimal static checkpoints. To resolve this dilemma, we model the performance gains induced by fine-grained architectural modifications as edit-effect evidence and build evidence graphs from prior tasks. By constructing a retrieval-augmented model refinement framework, our proposed M-DESIGN dynamically weaves historical evidence to discover near-optimal modification paths. M-DESIGN features an adaptive retrieval mechanism that quickly calibrates the evolving transferability of edit-effect evidence from different sources. To handle out-of-distribution shifts, we introduce predictive task planners that extrapolate gains from multi-hop evidence, thereby reducing reliance on an exhaustive repository. Based on our model knowledge base of 67,760 graph neural networks across 22 datasets, extensive experiments demonstrate that M-DESIGN consistently outperforms baselines, achieving the search-space best performance in 26 out of 33 cases under a strict budget. Code and data are available at: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/M-DESIGN-245/.</p>","absKo":"<p>мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кіјм ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ кі м„ұлҠҘ neural networkлҘј м„Өкі„н•ҳл Өл©ҙ optimization qualityмҷҖ search efficiency мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶°м•ј н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ мқҙ к· нҳ•мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. neural architectural searchлҠ” кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ л§Өмҡ° нҒ¬кі , model retrievalмқҖ мў…мў… мөңм Ғм—җ лӘ» лҜём№ҳлҠ” static checkpointл§Ң к°Җм ёмҳЁлӢӨ. мқҙ л”ңл Ҳл§ҲлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ёл°Җн•ң architectural modificationмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” performance gainмқ„ edit-effect evidenceлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкі , мқҙм „ taskл“ӨлЎңл¶Җн„° evidence graphлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. retrieval-augmented model refinement frameworkлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ” M-DESIGNмқҖ м—ӯмӮ¬м Ғ evidenceлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м—®м–ҙ кұ°мқҳ мөңм Ғм—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ modification pathлҘј м°ҫм•„лӮёлӢӨ. M-DESIGNмқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё sourceм—җм„ң лӮҳмҳЁ edit-effect evidenceмқҳ ліҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” transferabilityлҘј л№ лҘҙкІҢ ліҙм •н•ҳлҠ” adaptive retrieval mechanismмқ„ нҠ№м§•мңјлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. out-of-distribution shiftлҘј лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” multi-hop evidenceлЎңл¶Җн„° gainмқ„ мҷёмӮҪн•ҳлҠ” predictive task plannerлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, exhaustive repositoryм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙмқ„ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. 22к°ң datasetм—җ кұём№ң 67,760к°ңмқҳ graph neural networkлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң model knowledge baseлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң н•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң, M-DESIGNмқҖ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн–Ҳмңјл©°, м—„кІ©н•ң budget н•ҳм—җм„ң 33к°ң мӮ¬лЎҖ мӨ‘ 26к°ңм—җм„ң search-space мөңм Ғ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. CodeмҷҖ dataлҠ” лӢӨмқҢм—җм„ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•ҳлӢӨ: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/M-DESIGN-245/.</p>"},{"id":"64927","en":"Adaptive Recurrent Message Passing for Test Time Computing on Graphs","ko":"Graphм—җм„ң Test Time Computingмқ„ мң„н•ң м Ғмқ‘м Ғ Recurrent Message Passing","authors":"Junshu Sun, Wanxing Chang, Qingming Huang, Shuhui Wang","pos":"#2506","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ib2IjLO7JW","abs":"<p>Pre-trained foundation models have demonstrated remarkable success in many domains, enabling a unified backbone to generalize across diverse downstream tasks. However, extending this paradigm to graph learning remains challenging due to the intrinsic mismatch between graph data and fixed architectural designs. In this work, we show that this limitation can be overcome via recurrent graph models. To achieve this, we conduct a systematic theoretical analysis, rigorously deriving step dependence as a necessary and sufficient condition for an adaptively convergent recurrent process. Building on this foundation, we propose AdaR, an Adaptive Recurrent graph model, empowering flexible test-time computing on various datasets without changing model parameters. To enable adaptive inference, AdaR explicitly encodes normalized step information and representationвҖ“target relations into the recurrent updates. To ensure convergence of the recurrent process, AdaR employs gradient-based supervision signals that guide representation updates throughout the recurrence. Empirical results demonstrate that AdaR consistently outperforms strong baselines in both inductive and transductive settings. Codes are provided in the supplementary material.</p>","absKo":"<p>pre-trained foundation modelмқҖ л§ҺмқҖ мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м„ұкіөмқ„ кұ°л‘җл©°, лӢӨм–‘н•ң downstream task м „л°ҳм—җ generalizeн•ҳлҠ” н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ unified backboneмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ graph learningмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ graph dataмҷҖ кі м •лҗң architectural design мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳ л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” recurrent graph modelмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј к·№ліөн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мІҙкі„м Ғмқё мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬, adaptively convergent recurrent processм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•„мҡ”м¶©л¶„мЎ°кұҙмңјлЎң step dependenceлҘј м—„л°Җн•ҳкІҢ лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кё°л°ҳ мң„м—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” AdaRмқҙлқјлҠ” Adaptive Recurrent graph modelмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬ лӘЁлҚё parameterлҘј л°”кҫём§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetм—җм„ң flexible test-time computingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. adaptive inferenceлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ AdaRмқҖ normalized step informationкіј representation-target relationмқ„ recurrent updateм—җ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ңлӢӨ. recurrent processмқҳ мҲҳл ҙмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, AdaRмқҖ recurrence м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ representation updateлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” gradient-based supervision signalмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” AdaRмқҙ inductive л°Ҹ transductive setting лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” л¶ҖлЎқ мһҗлЈҢм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61017","en":"A Unifying Relational Perspective on Expressive Lottery Tickets","ko":"н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мһҲлҠ” Lottery Ticketм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҶөн•©м Ғ кҙҖкі„ кҙҖм җ","authors":"Lorenz Kummer, Samir Moustafa, Anatol Ehrlich, Franka Bause, Marco Nennstiel, PrzemysЕӮaw WaЕӮДҷga, Nils M. Kriege","pos":"#2509","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=uWHqeVzNcm","abs":"<p>Graph neural networks (GNNs) are widely used, but how parameter sparsity affects the expressivity of relational (RGNNs) and temporal (TGNNs) variants is poorly understood. The Strong Expressive Lottery Ticket Hypothesis (SELTH) posits the existence of sparse GNNs that preserve Weisfeiler-Leman (WL) expressivity on static graphs. We generalize this existence result to a probabilistic statement for multi-relational and temporal domains via the relational WL (RWL). We prove that sufficiently parameterized RGNNs contain sparse subnetworks that maintain 1-RWL expressivity and derive a lower bound on the probability that a random pruning yields such a subnetwork. We show that common TGNNs and cross-graph message passing schemes admit RGNN reformulations such that they inherit these guarantees and, moreover, that the expressivity of a sparse RGNN is connected to its optimization behavior under common update regimes. Experiments instantiate the bound, compare it to empirical probabilities on synthetic data, and study how pre-training expressivity relates to optimization and prediction quality metrics on temporal and molecular benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Graph neural networks (GNNs)лҠ” л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, parameter sparsityк°Җ relational (RGNNs)кіј temporal (TGNNs) ліҖнҳ•мқҳ expressivityм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҠ” мһҳ м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. Strong Expressive Lottery Ticket Hypothesis (SELTH)лҠ” static graphм—җм„ң Weisfeiler-Leman (WL) expressivityлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” sparse GNNмқҳ мЎҙмһ¬лҘј мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мЎҙмһ¬ кІ°кіјлҘј relational WL (RWL)мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ multi-relational л°Ҹ temporal domainм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҷ•лҘ м Ғ м„ңмҲ лЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м¶©л¶„нһҲ parameterizedлҗң RGNNмқҙ 1-RWL expressivityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” sparse subnetworkлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳкі , random pruningмқҙ к·ёлҹ¬н•ң subnetworkлҘј мғқм„ұн•  нҷ•лҘ м—җ лҢҖн•ң lower boundлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё TGNNкіј cross-graph message passing schemeмқҙ RGNN reformulationмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң ліҙмһҘмқ„ мғҒмҶҚл°ӣмңјл©°, лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ sparse RGNNмқҳ expressivityк°Җ common update regime н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ optimization behaviorмҷҖ м—°кІ°лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙ boundлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳкі  synthetic dataм—җм„ңмқҳ empirical probabilityмҷҖ л№„көҗн•ҳл©°, pre-training expressivityк°Җ temporal л°Ҹ molecular benchmarkм—җм„ң optimizationкіј prediction quality metricкіј м–ҙл–»кІҢ кҙҖл ЁлҗҳлҠ”м§Җ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66087","en":"Are Common Substructures Transferable? Understanding Transferability in Graph Pretraining under Riemannian Geometry","ko":"кіөнҶө н•ҳмң„ кө¬мЎ°лҠ” м „мқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ңк°Җ? Riemannian кё°н•ҳн•ҷ н•ҳм—җм„ң к·ёлһҳн”„ мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөмқҳ м „мқҙ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ мқҙн•ҙ","authors":"Li Sun, Zhenhao Huang, Yiding Wang, Qin Chen, Pietro LiГі, Philip Yu","pos":"#2911","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=793DO6oMn7","abs":"<p>Foundation models have sparked a revolution via a pretraining-adaptation paradigm, with recent efforts extending this success to graphs.  Unlike other modalities, graphs contain rich structural patterns, yet their structural transferability remains poorly understood. Prior studies consider common substructures in the discrete realm, and we are motivated by a fundamental question: Are common substructures transferable? The underlying theory is largely underexplored. In this work, we shift toward learning transferable structures through the lens of functional behavior. Theoretically, we connect transferable substructures to intrinsic geometry of the representation space. However, characterizing such intrinsic geometry has rarely been touched. Grounded in Riemannian geometry, we develop a graph intrinsic geometry learning frameworkвҖ”\\textbf{Neural Vector Bundle}, which enables parsing intrinsic geometry with local coordinates. Building on this, we design \\textbf{\\textsc{Gauge}}, a pretrainable neural architecture that constructs the vector bundle, flattening geometrically compatible local coordinates, and a new Dirichlet loss, which also measures the transfer effort. We empirically validate its superior expressiveness in challenging tasks including zero-shot link prediction and graph isomorphism.</p>","absKo":"<p>foundation modelмқҖ pretraining-adaptation paradigmмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ нҳҒмӢ мқ„ мқјмңјмј°кі , мөңк·ј мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„ұкіөмқ„ graphлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳл ӨлҠ” мӢңлҸ„к°Җ мқҙм–ҙм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. лӢӨлҘё modalityмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬ graphлҠ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң structural patternмқ„ лӢҙкі  мһҲм§Җл§Ң, structural transferabilityлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ мһҳ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  мһҲлӢӨ. м„ н–ү м—°кө¬лҠ” discrete мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң common substructureлҘј кі л Өн–Ҳмңјл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨмқҢмқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё м§Ҳл¬ём—җ мқҳн•ҙ лҸҷкё°лҘј м–»лҠ”лӢӨ: common substructureлҠ” transferableн•ңк°Җ? к·ё мқҙлЎ м Ғ кё°л°ҳмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” functional behaviorмқҳ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң transferable structureлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң м „нҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” transferable substructureлҘј representation spaceмқҳ intrinsic geometryмҷҖ м—°кІ°н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң intrinsic geometryлҘј нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ” мқјмқҖ кұ°мқҳ лӢӨлӨ„м§Җм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. Riemannian geometryм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” graph intrinsic geometry learning frameworkмқё \\textbf{Neural Vector Bundle}мқ„ к°ңл°ңн–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” local coordinateлҘј нҶөн•ҙ intrinsic geometryлҘј н•ҙм„қн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” vector bundleмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , кё°н•ҳм ҒмңјлЎң нҳёнҷҳлҗҳлҠ” local coordinateлҘј нҸүнғ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” pretrainable neural architectureмқё \\textbf{\\textsc{Gauge}}мҷҖ, transfer effortлҸ„ мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Dirichlet lossлҘј м„Өкі„н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” zero-shot link predictionкіј graph isomorphismмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м–ҙл Өмҡҙ taskм—җм„ң к·ё мҡ°мҲҳн•ң expressivenessлҘј мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"68704","en":"Collaborative likelihood-ratio estimation over graphs","ko":"к·ёлһҳн”„ мғҒм—җм„ңмқҳ нҳ‘л Ҙм Ғ мҡ°лҸ„л№„ м¶”м •","authors":"Alejandro de la Concha Duarte, Nicolas Vayatis, Argyris Kalogeratos","pos":"#4204","abs":"This paper introduces the Collaborative Likelihood-ratio Estimation problem, which is relevant for applications involving multiple statistical estimation tasks that can be mapped to the nodes of a fixed graph expressing pairwise task similarity. Each graph node $v$ observes i.i.d data from two unknown node-specific pdfs, $p_{v}$ and $q_{v}$, and the goal is to estimate the likelihood-ratios (or density-ratios), $r_{v}(x)=\\frac{q_{v}(x)}{p_{v}(x)}$, for all $v$. Our contribution is multifold: we present a non-parametric collaborative framework that leverages the graph structure of the problem to solve the tasks more efficiently; we present a concrete method that we call Graph-based Relative Unconstrained Least-Squares Importance Fitting (GRULSIF) along with an efficient implementation; we derive convergence rates that highlight the role of the main variables of the problem. Our theoretical results explicit the conditions under which the collaborative estimation leads to performance gains compared to solving each estimation task independently. Finally, in a series of experiments, we demonstrate that the joint likelihood-ratio estimation of GRULSIF at all graph nodes is more accurate compared to state-of-the-art methods that operate independently at each node, and we verify that the behavior of GRULSIF is in agreement with our theoretical analysis.","absKo":"мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ Collaborative Likelihood-ratio Estimation л¬ём ңлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мҢҚлі„ task similarityлҘј лӮҳнғҖлӮҙлҠ” кі м •лҗң graphмқҳ nodeм—җ л§Өн•‘лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ statistical estimation taskлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” мқ‘мҡ©кіј кҙҖл Ёмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. к°Ғ graph node $v$лҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ м•Ңл Өм§Җм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ node-specific pdf, $p_{v}$мҷҖ $q_{v}$м—җм„ң лӮҳмҳЁ i.i.d. dataлҘј кҙҖмёЎн•ҳл©°, лӘ©н‘ңлҠ” лӘЁл“  $v$м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ likelihood-ratio(лҳҗлҠ” density-ratio) $r_{v}(x)=\\frac{q_{v}(x)}{p_{v}(x)}$лҘј м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кё°м—¬лҠ” лӢӨл©ҙм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¬ём ңмқҳ graph кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ taskлҘј лҚ” нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” non-parametric collaborative frameworkлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң Graph-based Relative Unconstrained Least-Squares Importance Fitting (GRULSIF)мқҙлқј л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” кө¬мІҙм Ғ л°©лІ•кіј нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё кө¬нҳ„мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. лӮҳм•„к°Җ л¬ём ңмқҳ мЈјмҡ” ліҖмҲҳмқҳ м—ӯн• мқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ҳлҠ” мҲҳл ҙлҘ мқ„ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјлҠ” к°Ғ м¶”м • taskлҘј лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” кІғкіј л№„көҗн•ҳм—¬ collaborative estimationмқҙ м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ к°Җм ёмҳӨлҠ” мЎ°кұҙмқ„ лӘ…мӢңн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң мқјл Ёмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң, лӘЁл“  graph nodeм—җм„ңмқҳ GRULSIF joint likelihood-ratio estimationмқҙ к°Ғ nodeм—җм„ң лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” state-of-the-art л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ лҚ” м •нҷ•н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , GRULSIFмқҳ кұ°лҸҷмқҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қкіј мқјм№ҳн•Ёмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"67120","en":"Position: Topological Machine Learning Cannot Progress without Experimental Standards","ko":"Position: Topological Machine LearningмқҖ мӢӨн—ҳ н‘ңмӨҖ м—Ҷмқҙ м§„м „н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨ","authors":"InГ©s Castilla Rieso","pos":"#4207","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cR308G5Znz","abs":"<p>Topological Machine Learning provides strong discriminative power for classification tasks through the use of Topological Data Analysis, and more particularly, Persistent Homology. Although it has strong theoretical appeal, it remains underused by the broader Machine Learning community; criticism often targets the reliance on synthetic data and the absence of shared experimental standards, which makes reported results difficult to compare. Indeed, current empirical evaluations lack a consistent framework for assessing methods: the construction of topological signatures is often opaque, statistical significance testing to validate reported gains, computing times and robustness to perturbations-such as missing data or noise-are often omitted. We assert that <strong>progress in Topological Machine Learning depends on establishing clear and consolidated experimental standards that support meaningful comparison across methods</strong>, articulated through a transparent and reproducible empirical framework including data processing and performance evaluation. We review current practices, highlight their limitations, and propose a set of principles for conducting rigorous and comparable empirical evaluations. Adopting these standards will enable trustworthy studies, clarify the gains of new methods, and ultimately support the broader adoption of Topological Machine Learning by the Machine Learning community.</p>","absKo":"<p>Topological Machine LearningмқҖ Topological Data Analysis, нҠ№нһҲ Persistent Homologyмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ л¶„лҘҳ кіјм ңм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң нҢҗлі„л Ҙмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң л§Өл Ҙм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, лҚ” л„“мқҖ Machine Learning м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°м—җм„ңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҷңмҡ©лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  мһҲлӢӨ. л№„нҢҗмқҖ мў…мў… synthetic dataм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙкіј кіөмң лҗң мӢӨн—ҳ н‘ңмӨҖмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬лҘј кІЁлғҘн•ҳл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ ліҙкі лҗң кІ°кіјлҘј л№„көҗн•ҳкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎң нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ кІҪн—ҳм Ғ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мқјкҙҖлҗң frameworkк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. topological signatureмқҳ кө¬м„ұмқҖ мў…мў… л¶ҲнҲ¬лӘ…н•ҳкі , ліҙкі лҗң м„ұкіј н–ҘмғҒмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң statistical significance testing, кі„мӮ° мӢңк°„, missing dataлӮҳ noiseмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ perturbationм—җ лҢҖн•ң robustnessк°Җ мһҗмЈј лҲ„лқҪлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>Topological Machine Learningмқҳ м§„м „мқҖ л°©лІ• к°„ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” л№„көҗлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” лӘ…нҷ•н•ҳкі  нҶөн•©лҗң мӢӨн—ҳ н‘ңмӨҖмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° лӢ¬л Ө мһҲлӢӨ</strong>кі  мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, лҚ°мқҙн„° мІҳлҰ¬мҷҖ м„ұлҠҘ нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң нҲ¬лӘ…н•ҳкі  мһ¬нҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң empirical frameworkлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј кө¬мІҙнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ кҙҖн–үмқ„ кІҖнҶ н•ҳкі  к·ё н•ңкі„лҘј к°•мЎ°н•ҳл©°, м—„кІ©н•ҳкі  л№„көҗ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң empirical evaluationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мқјл Ёмқҳ мӣҗм№ҷмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н‘ңмӨҖмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ҳл©ҙ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м—°кө¬лҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі , мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ н•ҳл©°, к¶Ғк·№м ҒмңјлЎң Machine Learning м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ° лӮҙм—җм„ң Topological Machine Learningмқҳ ліҙлӢӨ нҸӯл„“мқҖ мұ„нғқмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62474","en":"E2Former-V2: On-the-Fly Equivariant Attention  with Linear Activation Memory","ko":"E2Former-V2: м„ нҳ• Activation MemoryлҘј к°–лҠ” on-the-fly Equivariant Attention","authors":"Lin Huang, Chengxiang Huang, Ziang Wang, Yiyue Du, Chu Wang, Haocheng Lu, Yunyang Li, Xiaoli LIU, Arthur JIANG, Jia Zhang","pos":"#912","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gIUVdEAa3l","abs":"Equivariant Graph Neural Networks (EGNNs) have become a widely used approach for modeling 3D atomistic systems. However, mainstream architectures face critical scalability bottlenecks due to the explicit construction of geometric features or dense tensor products on \\textit{every} edge. To overcome this, we introduce \\textbf{E2Former-V2}, a scalable architecture that integrates algebraic sparsity with hardware-aware execution.  We introduce \\textbf{Equivariant Axis-Aligned Sparsification (EAAS)}, which leverages an $\\mathrm{SO}(3)\\!\\rightarrow\\!\\mathrm{SO}(2)$ change of basis to convert dense Wigner-$6j$ tensor contractions into sparse, parity-based re-indexing operations. Building on this representation, we propose \\textbf{On-the-Fly Equivariant Attention}, a fully node-centric mechanism implemented via a fused Triton kernel. By eliminating materialized edge tensors and maximizing SRAM utilization, our kernel achieves up to \\textbf{20$\\times$ higher TFLOPS} than standard implementations. Experiments on SPICE and OMol25 show that E2Former-V2 preserves predictive accuracy while substantially accelerating inference, demonstrating the practical feasibility of large equivariant transformers on commodity GPUs.","absKo":"Equivariant Graph Neural Networks(EGNNs)лҠ” 3D atomistic systemмқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мЈјлҘҳ architectureлҠ” \\textit{лӘЁл“ } edgeм—җм„ң geometric featureлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬м„ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ dense tensor productлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң нҷ•мһҘм„ұ лі‘лӘ©м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” algebraic sparsityмҷҖ hardware-aware executionмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң architectureмқё \\textbf{E2Former-V2}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{Equivariant Axis-Aligned Sparsification(EAAS)}мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, $\\mathrm{SO}(3)\\!\\rightarrow\\!\\mathrm{SO}(2)$ basis changeлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ dense Wigner-$6j$ tensor contractionмқ„ sparseн•ң parity-based re-indexing operationмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” fused Triton kernelлЎң кө¬нҳ„лҗң мҷ„м „н•ң node-centric mechanismмқё \\textbf{On-the-Fly Equivariant Attention}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. materialized edge tensorлҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳкі  SRAM utilizationмқ„ к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ kernelмқҖ н‘ңмӨҖ кө¬нҳ„ліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ \\textbf{20$\\times$} лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ TFLOPSлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. SPICEмҷҖ OMol25 мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ E2Former-V2к°Җ мҳҲмёЎ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң м¶”лЎ мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ к°ҖмҶҚн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, commodity GPUм—җм„ң large equivariant transformerмқҳ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63123","en":"Shape of Thought: Progressive Object Assembly via Visual Chain-of-Thought","ko":"мғқк°Ғмқҳ нҳ•нғң: мӢңк°Ғм Ғ Chain-of-ThoughtлҘј нҶөн•ң м җм§„м Ғ к°қмІҙ мЎ°лҰҪ","authors":"Yu Huo, Siyu Zhang, Zeng Kun, Haoyue Liu, Owen Lee, Junlin chen, Lu YuQuan, Yifu Guo, Yaodong Liang, Xiaoying Tang","pos":"#1400","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZsJnkEgh6I","abs":"<p>Multimodal models for text-to-image generation have achieved strong visual fidelity, yet they remain brittle under compositional structural constraintsвҖ”notably generative numeracy, attribute binding, and part-level relations. To address these challenges, we propose <strong>Shape-of-Thought (SoT)</strong>, a visual CoT framework that enables <em>progressive shape assembly represented as coherent 2D projections</em> without external engines at inference time. SoT trains a unified multimodal autoregressive model to generate interleaved textual plans and rendered intermediate states, helping the model capture shape-assembly logic without producing explicit geometric representations. To support this paradigm, we introduce <strong>SoT-26K</strong>, a large-scale dataset of grounded assembly traces derived from part-based CAD hierarchies, and <strong>T2S-CompBench</strong>, a benchmark for evaluating structural integrity and trace faithfulness. Fine-tuning on SoT-26K achieves 88.4\\% on component numeracy and 84.8\\% on structural topology, outperforming text-only baselines by around 20\\%. SoT establishes a new paradigm for transparent, process-supervised compositional generation. The code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/16FE/.</p>","absKo":"<p>text-to-image generationмқ„ мң„н•ң multimodal modelмқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң visual fidelityлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, compositional structural constraint, нҠ№нһҲ generative numeracy, attribute binding, part-level relation н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>Shape-of-Thought(SoT)</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” м¶”лЎ  мӢң external engine м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ <em>coherent 2D projectionмңјлЎң н‘ңнҳ„лҗҳлҠ” progressive shape assembly</em>лҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” visual CoT frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. SoTлҠ” нҶөн•© multimodal autoregressive modelмқҙ interleaved textual planкіј rendered intermediate stateлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҷмҠөмӢңмјң, explicit geometric representationмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң shape-assembly logicмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, part-based CAD hierarchyлЎңл¶Җн„° лҸ„м¶ңн•ң grounded assembly traceмқҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ datasetмқё <strong>SoT-26K</strong>мҷҖ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мҷ„кІ°м„ұ л°Ҹ trace faithfulnessлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” benchmarkмқё <strong>T2S-CompBench</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SoT-26KлЎң fine-tuningн•ҳл©ҙ component numeracyм—җм„ң 88.4\\%, structural topologyм—җм„ң 84.8\\%лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, text-only baselineліҙлӢӨ м•Ҫ 20\\% м•һм„ лӢӨ. SoTлҠ” нҲ¬лӘ…н•ҳкі  process-supervisedлҗң compositional generationмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/16FE/ м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61318","en":"Solving Physics Olympiad via Reinforcement Learning on Physics Simulators","ko":"л¬јлҰ¬ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙн„° кё°л°ҳ Reinforcement LearningмңјлЎң л¬јлҰ¬ мҳ¬лҰјн”јм•„л“ң н’Җкё°","authors":"Mihir Prabhudesai, Aryan Satpathy, Yangmin Li, Zheyang Qin, Nikash Bhardwaj, Amir Zadeh, Chuan Li, Katerina Fragkiadaki, Deepak Pathak","pos":"#1403","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=rQ7eobSCZZ","abs":"<p>We have witnessed remarkable advances in LLM reasoning capabilities with the advent of DeepSeek-R1. However, much of this progress has been fueled by the abundance of internet questionвҖ“answer (QA) pairsвҖ”a major bottleneck going forward, since such data is limited in scale and concentrated mainly in domains like mathematics. In contrast, other sciences such as physics lack sufficient large-scale QA datasets to effectively train reasoning-capable models. In this work, we show that physics simulators can serve as a powerful alternative source of supervision for training LLMs for physical reasoning. We generate random scenes in physics engines,  create synthetic questionвҖ“answer pairs from simulated interactions, and train LLMs using reinforcement learning on this synthetic data. Our models exhibit zero-shot sim-to-real transfer to real-world physics benchmarks: for example, training solely on synthetic simulated data improves performance on IPhO (International Physics Olympiad) problems by 5вҖ“10 percentage points across different model sizes. These results demonstrate that physics simulators can act as scalable data generators, enabling LLMs to acquire deep physical reasoning skills beyond the limitations of internet-scale QA data.</p>","absKo":"<p>DeepSeek-R1мқҳ л“ұмһҘкіј н•Ёк»ҳ LLM м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙм—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м§„м „мқ„ лӘ©кІ©н–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м§„м „мқҳ мғҒлӢ№ л¶Җл¶„мқҖ мқён„°л„· question-answer(QA) pairмқҳ н’Қл¶Җн•Ём—җ мқҳн•ҙ мҙүм§„лҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” м•һмңјлЎңмқҳ мЈјмҡ” лі‘лӘ©мқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” к·ңлӘЁк°Җ м ңн•ңм Ғмқҙкі  мЈјлЎң мҲҳн•ҷкіј к°ҷмқҖ лҸ„л©”мқём—җ м§‘мӨ‘лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ physicsмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ лӢӨлҘё кіјн•ҷ л¶„м•јлҠ” м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ modelмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨкё°м—җ м¶©л¶„н•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ QA datasetмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” physics simulatorк°Җ л¬јлҰ¬ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң LLM н•ҷмҠөмқҳ к°•л Ҙн•ң лҢҖмІҙ supervision sourceк°Җ лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” physics engineм—җм„ң л¬ҙмһ‘мң„ sceneмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳлҗң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мңјлЎңл¶Җн„° synthetic question-answer pairлҘј л§Ңл“Өл©°, мқҙ synthetic dataлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ reinforcement learningмңјлЎң LLMмқ„ н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬ modelмқҖ мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„ physics benchmarkлЎңмқҳ zero-shot sim-to-real transferлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, synthetic simulated dataлЎңл§Ң н•ҷмҠөн•ҙлҸ„ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё model sizeм—җм„ң IPhO(International Physics Olympiad) л¬ём ң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ 5~10 percentage point н–ҘмғҒлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” physics simulatorк°Җ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң data generatorлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳм—¬, LLMмқҙ internet-scale QA dataмқҳ н•ңкі„лҘј л„ҳм–ҙ к№ҠмқҖ л¬јлҰ¬ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мҠөл“қн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64575","en":"Symbolic Mixture-of-Experts: Adaptive Skill-based Routing for Heterogeneous Reasoning","ko":"Symbolic Mixture-of-Experts: мқҙм§Ҳм Ғ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң м Ғмқ‘м Ғ Skill кё°л°ҳ Routing","authors":"Justin Chih-Yao Chen, Sukwon Yun, Elias Stengel-Eskin, Tianlong Chen, Mohit Bansal","pos":"#1410","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=M2pbI9uKjW","abs":"<p>Combining existing pre-trained LLMs is a promising avenue for tackling diverse reasoning tasks. However, selecting experts at the task level is often too coarse-grained, as heterogeneous tasks may require different expertise for each instance. To enable instance-level mixing of LLM experts, we propose Symbolic-MoE, a symbolic, text-based, and gradient-free Mixture-of-Experts framework. Symbolic-MoE uses inferred skills, i.e., specialized knowledge such as algebra in mathematics, for expert selection. Each expert is selected based on how relevant its expertise is to the query, and then generates its own reasoning. This results in k outputs from k experts, which are then synthesized into a final high-quality response by an aggregator, chosen based on its ability to integrate diverse outputs. We show that instance-level expert selection improves performance by a large margin but -- when implemented naively -- can introduce a high computational overhead due to the need for constant model loading and offloading. To address this, we implement a batch inference strategy that groups instances based on their assigned experts, ensuring each model will only be loaded once. This allows us to integrate 16 expert models on a single GPU with a time cost comparable to prior multi-agent baselines using 4 GPUs. Through extensive evaluations on diverse benchmarks (MMLU-Pro, GPQA, AIME, and MedMCQA), Symbolic-MoE shows an absolute average improvement of 8.15% over the best baseline. Moreover, Symbolic-MoE generalizes well to unseen tasks and removes the need for expensive multi-round discussions, outperforming discussion baselines with less computation.</p>","absKo":"кё°мЎҙм—җ мӮ¬м „ н•ҷмҠөлҗң LLMл“Өмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң м¶”лЎ  кіјм ңлҘј лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң л°©н–ҘмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ task-levelм—җм„ң expertлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ лҢҖк°ң л„Ҳл¬ҙ кұ°м№ лӢӨ. мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё taskлҠ” instanceл§ҲлӢӨ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё expertiseлҘј мҡ”кө¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. instance-levelм—җм„ң LLM expertлҘј нҳјн•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” symbolicн•ҳкі  text-basedмқҙл©° gradient-freeмқё Mixture-of-Experts frameworkмқё Symbolic-MoEлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Symbolic-MoEлҠ” inferred skill, мҰү мҲҳн•ҷм—җм„ңмқҳ algebraмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ нҠ№нҷ” м§ҖмӢқмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ expertлҘј м„ нғқн•ңлӢӨ. к°Ғ expertлҠ” queryмҷҖмқҳ кҙҖл Ём„ұм—җ л”°лқј м„ нғқлҗң л’Ө, мһҗкё°л§Ңмқҳ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј kк°ңмқҳ expertлЎңл¶Җн„° kк°ңмқҳ outputмқҙ лӮҳмҳӨл©°, мқҙл“ӨмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң м„ нғқлҗң aggregatorм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҳ мөңмў… мқ‘лӢөмңјлЎң н•©м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” instance-level expert selectionмқҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҘј мҲңм§„н•ҳкІҢ кө¬нҳ„н•ҳл©ҙ model loadingкіј offloadingмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң лҶ’мқҖ кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңк°Җ л°ңмғқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” instanceлҘј н• лӢ№лҗң expertлі„лЎң л¬¶лҠ” batch inference strategyлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳм—¬, к°Ғ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ н•ң лІҲл§Ң лЎңл“ңлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӢЁмқј GPUм—җм„ң 16к°ңмқҳ expert modelмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, 4 GPUsлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ multi-agent baselineкіј л№„мҠ·н•ң мӢңк°„ л№„мҡ©мқ„ мң м§Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmark(MMLU-Pro, GPQA, AIME, MedMCQA)м—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ Symbolic-MoEлҠ” мөңмғҒмқҳ baseline лҢҖл№„ м ҲлҢҖ нҸүк·  8.15% н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, Symbolic-MoEлҠ” ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң taskм—җлҸ„ мһҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳл©°, л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° лӢӨнҡҢм°Ё нҶ лЎ мқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠкІҢ н•ҳкі , лҚ” м ҒмқҖ кі„мӮ°мңјлЎң discussion baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63525","en":"The Geometry of Reasoning: Self-Evaluation via Layerwise Trajectory Evolution","ko":"м¶”лЎ мқҳ кё°н•ҳн•ҷ: кі„мёөлі„ к¶Өм Ғ м§„нҷ”лҘј нҶөн•ң мһҗкё°нҸүк°Җ","authors":"Jinhe Bi, Danqi Yan, Yifan Wang, Wenke Huang, Haokun Chen, Guancheng Wan, Mang Ye, Xun Xiao, Hinrich Schuetze, Volker Tresp, Yunpu Ma","pos":"#1414","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WQyrwQwzmK","abs":"<p>Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) enhance performance by generating explicit Chain-of-Thought (CoT) trajectories, yet enabling them to self-evaluate correctness without external supervision remains a critical challenge. Existing methods often rely on ground-truth labels or shallow output probabilities, neglecting the layerwise evolution of the reasoning trajectory. In this work, we introduce \\ourmethod (Geometry of Reasoning), a white-box self-evaluation framework based on layerwise trajectory evolution. \\ourmethod decomposes reasoning fidelity into two complementary dimensions: (1) Geometric Evolution, which synthesizes the first- and second-order evolution of layerwise hidden-state trajectories to quantify geometric progress in reasoning; and (2) Difficulty-Aware Calibration, which utilizes cross-entropy of reasoning progress to normalize the Geometric Evolution against intrinsic query uncertainty. By jointly modeling these factors, \\ourmethod effectively distinguishes the coherent evolution of correct reasoning from the chaotic trajectories of errors. Extensive experiments across eight LRMs and seven benchmarks demonstrate that \\ourmethod consistently outperforms state-of-the-art baselines in AUROC, AUPR, and FPR@95.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Reasoning Models(LRMs)лҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё Chain-of-Thought(CoT) trajectoryлҘј мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨм§Җл§Ң, мҷёл¶Җ supervision м—Ҷмқҙ мҠӨмҠӨлЎң м •лӢөм„ұмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мў…мў… ground-truth labelмқҙлӮҳ м–•мқҖ м¶ңл Ҙ нҷ•лҘ м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬, reasoning trajectoryмқҳ layer-wise evolutionмқ„ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” layer-wise trajectory evolutionмқ„ кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ң white-box self-evaluation frameworkмқё \\ourmethod(Geometry of Reasoning)лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. \\ourmethodлҠ” reasoning fidelityлҘј л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мғҒліҙм Ғмқё м°ЁмӣҗмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. (1) Geometric EvolutionмқҖ layer-wise hidden-state trajectoryмқҳ 1м°Ё л°Ҹ 2м°Ё evolutionмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ reasoningм—җм„ңмқҳ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ м§„м „мқ„ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳкі , (2) Difficulty-Aware CalibrationмқҖ reasoning progressмқҳ cross-entropyлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ query кі мң мқҳ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ Geometric Evolutionмқ„ м •к·ңнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҡ”мҶҢлҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ \\ourmethodлҠ” мҳ¬л°”лҘё reasoningмқҳ мқјкҙҖлҗң evolutionкіј мҳӨлҘҳмқҳ нҳјлһҖмҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ trajectoryлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬л¶„н•ңлӢӨ. 8к°ңмқҳ LRMкіј 7к°ңмқҳ benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ \\ourmethodк°Җ AUROC, AUPR, FPR@95м—җм„ң state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62100","en":"SafeCompass: Dynamic Chain-of-Thought Steering via Inference-Time Safety Signals","ko":"SafeCompass: м¶”лЎ  мӢңм җ м•Ҳм „ мӢ нҳёлҘј нҶөн•ң лҸҷм Ғ Chain-of-Thought мЎ°н–Ҙ","authors":"Zeyang Zhang, HAOTIAN XU, Linbao Li, Qi Sun, Xuebo Liu, YU LI, Cheng Zhuo","pos":"#1501","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jojAir1F71","abs":"Large reasoning models (LRMs) achieve strong performance by explicitly generating chain-of-thought (CoT) reasoning, but this reasoning process can be manipulated by adversarial prompts. Inference-time CoT interventions offer a simple and lightweight approach to improving safety, yet existing methods typically apply static heuristics that ignore the dynamic nature of reasoning, leading to an inherent trade-off between robustness and over-refusal. This paper introduces *SafeCompass*, a plug-and-play framework for dynamically steering chain-of-thought reasoning using inference-time safety signals extracted from internal states. At different reasoning positions, *SafeCompass* derives a latent safety direction through contrastive analysis of internal representations and uses this direction to quantify the modelвҖҷs current safety state. These signals enable selective intervention, allowing the modelвҖҷs reasoning trajectory to be modified only when and where it becomes unsafe. Extensive experiments demonstrate that *SafeCompass* significantly improves robustness, reducing the average attack success rate up to $10\\times$ compared to the best baseline, while preserving general reasoning performance and minimizing over-refusal rates.","absKo":"Large reasoning model (LRM)мқҖ chain-of-thought (CoT) reasoningмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ к°•н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙ reasoning processлҠ” adversarial promptм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мЎ°мһ‘лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. Inference-time CoT interventionмқҖ м•Ҳм „м„ұмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң к°„лӢЁн•ҳкі  к°ҖлІјмҡҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ лҢҖк°ң reasoningмқҳ лҸҷм Ғ нҠ№м„ұмқ„ л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳлҠ” м •м Ғмқё heuristicмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, к°•кұҙм„ұкіј кіјлҸ„н•ң кұ°л¶Җ(over-refusal) мӮ¬мқҙм—җ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ trade-offлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ inference-time safety signalмқ„ internal stateм—җм„ң м¶”м¶ңн•ҳм—¬ chain-of-thought reasoningмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” plug-and-play frameworkмқё *SafeCompass*лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё reasoning мң„м№ҳм—җм„ң *SafeCompass*лҠ” internal representationмқҳ contrastive analysisлҘј нҶөн•ҙ latent safety directionмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкі , мқҙ л°©н–Ҙмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ нҳ„мһ¬ safety stateлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң signalмқҖ selective interventionмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬, лӘЁлҚёмқҳ reasoning trajectoryк°Җ м•Ҳм „н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠкІҢ лҗҳлҠ” мӢңм җкіј мң„м№ҳм—җм„ңл§Ң мқҙлҘј мҲҳм •н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ *SafeCompass*к°Җ к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңмјң, мқјл°ҳ reasoning м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң over-refusal rateлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳкі , best baseline лҢҖл№„ average attack success rateлҘј мөңлҢҖ 10л°°к№Ңм§Җ лӮ®м¶ҳлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62312","en":"ReJump: A Tree-Jump Representation for Analyzing and Improving LLM Reasoning","ko":"ReJump: LLM м¶”лЎ  л¶„м„қ л°Ҹ к°ңм„ мқ„ мң„н•ң Tree-Jump н‘ңнҳ„","authors":"Yuchen Zeng, Shuibai Zhang, Wonjun Kang, Shutong Wu, Lynnix Zou, Ying Fan, Heeju Kim, Ziqian Lin, Jungtaek Kim, HYUNG IL KOO, Dimitris Papailiopoulos, Kangwook Lee","pos":"#1507","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=hlUgEwl3Du","abs":"<p>Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) are Large Language Models (LLMs) explicitly trained to generate long-form Chain-of-Thoughts (CoTs), achieving impressive success on challenging tasks like math and programming. However, their underlying reasoning \"algorithms\" remain poorly understood. To investigate this, we propose <em>ReJump</em>, which represents a reasoning trace as a visitation order over nodes in a tree of intermediate problem-solving steps. Transitions between nodes, which we term <em>jumps</em>, include adjacent moves that capture behaviors such as calculation, and non-adjacent moves that capture behaviors such as backtracking and verification. ReJump enables analyzing LLM reasoning with diverse metrics that quantify exploration, exploitation, overthinking, forgetting, and verification. Using our proposed LLM agent to extract reasoning traces into ReJump format, we evaluate state-of-the-art LRMs on two tasks and find that models with similar accuracy can exhibit distinct reasoning behaviors, while different tasks favor different reasoning styles (e.g., varying balance between exploration and exploitation). To further understand how learning strategies shape reasoning, we use ReJump to compare distilled LRMs with their teachers, CoT-prompted LLMs with LRMs, and to examine reinforcement learning affect reasoning behavior. Finally, we show that ReJump can improve reasoning quality at test time through strategies such as ReJump-guided Best-of-N selection and prompt selection.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Reasoning Model (LRM)мқҖ мҲҳн•ҷкіј н”„лЎңк·ёлһҳл°ҚмІҳлҹј м–ҙл Өмҡҙ taskм—җм„ң мқёмғҒм Ғмқё м„ұкіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ long-form Chain-of-Thought (CoT)лҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң Large Language Model (LLM)мқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к·ё л°”нғ•м—җ мһҲлҠ” reasoning \"algorithm\"мқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <em>ReJump</em>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ReJumpлҠ” reasoning traceлҘј мӨ‘к°„ л¬ём ң н•ҙкІ° лӢЁкі„л“ӨлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ treeм—җм„ңмқҳ л°©л¬ё мҲңм„ңлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ <em>jump</em>лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” node к°„ м „мқҙлҠ” кі„мӮ°кіј к°ҷмқҖ н–үлҸҷмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” мқём ‘ мқҙлҸҷкіј, backtracking л°Ҹ verificationкіј к°ҷмқҖ н–үлҸҷмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” л№„мқём ‘ мқҙлҸҷмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. ReJumpлҠ” exploration, exploitation, overthinking, forgetting, verificationмқ„ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң metricмңјлЎң LLM reasoningмқ„ л¶„м„қн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ң LLM agentлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ reasoning traceлҘј ReJump нҳ•мӢқмңјлЎң м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкі , л‘җ taskм—җм„ң мөңмІЁлӢЁ LRMмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, мң мӮ¬н•ң м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј к°Җм§„ лӘЁлҚёмқҙлқјлҸ„ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё reasoning behaviorлҘј ліҙмқј мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, taskм—җ л”°лқј м„ нҳёлҗҳлҠ” reasoning styleмқҙ лӢӨлҰ„мқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ(мҳҲ: explorationкіј exploitation мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ• м°Ёмқҙ). н•ҷмҠө м „лһөмқҙ reasoningмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ нҳ•м„ұн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ лҚ” мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ReJumpлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ distilled LRMкіј teacherлҘј л№„көҗн•ҳкі , CoT-prompted LLMкіј LRMмқ„ л№„көҗн•ҳл©°, reinforcement learningмқҙ reasoning behaviorм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, ReJump-guided Best-of-N selectionкіј prompt selection к°ҷмқҖ м „лһөмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ ReJumpк°Җ test timeм—җм„ң reasoning qualityлҘј к°ңм„ н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65546","en":"MixReasoning: Switching Modes to Think","ko":"MixReasoning: мӮ¬кі  лӘЁл“ң м „нҷҳн•ҳкё°","authors":"Haiquan Lu, Gongfan Fang, Xinyin Ma, Qi Li, Xinchao Wang","pos":"#1600","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CX6KJksKqR","abs":"<p>Reasoning models enhance performance by tackling problems in a step-by-step manner, decomposing them into sub-problems and exploring long chains of thought before producing an answer. However, applying extended reasoning to every step introduces substantial redundancy, as sub-problems vary widely in difficulty and complexity: a small number of pivotal steps are genuinely challenging and decisive for the final answer, while many others only involve straightforward revisions or simple computations. Therefore, a natural idea is to endow reasoning models with the ability to adaptively respond to this variation, rather than treating all steps with the same level of elaboration. To this end, we propose MixReasoning, a framework that dynamically adjusts the depth of reasoning within a single response. MixReasoning enables fine-grained mode switching by training a lightweight concise LoRA adapter and control its strength to trigger switches based on reasoning difficulty estimated from sliding-window token confidence, yielding human-like transitions between fast and slow reasoning. The resulting chain of thought then becomes a mixture of detailed reasoning on difficult steps and concise inference on simpler ones.  Experiments on AIME24, MATH-500, GPQA, and GSM8K demonstrate that MixReasoning shortens reasoning length by 13\\%--49\\% across benchmarks of varying difficulty, delivering consistent efficiency gains while maintaining performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Reasoning modelмқҖ л¬ём ңлҘј лӢЁкі„м ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкі , н•ҳмң„ л¬ём ңлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳл©°, лӢөмқ„ лӮҙкё° м „м—җ кёҙ chain of thoughtлҘј нғҗмғүн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лӘЁл“  лӢЁкі„м—җ extended reasoningмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ мғҒлӢ№н•ң мӨ‘ліөмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳмң„ л¬ём ңмқҳ лӮңмқҙлҸ„мҷҖ ліөмһЎлҸ„лҠ” л§Өмҡ° лӢӨм–‘н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ лӢЁкі„л§Ңмқҙ мӢӨм ңлЎң м–ҙл өкі  мөңмў… лӢөм—җ кІ°м •м Ғмқҙл©°, лӮҳлЁём§Җ л§ҺмқҖ лӢЁкі„лҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ң мҲҳм •мқҙлӮҳ к°„лӢЁн•ң кі„мӮ°м—җ л¶Ҳкіјн•ҳлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҠ” лӘЁл“  лӢЁкі„лҘј лҸҷмқјн•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ мғҒм„ён•ЁмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , мқҙлҹ¬н•ң ліҖнҷ”м—җ м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң л°ҳмқ‘н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” reasoning modelмқ„ к°–м¶”лҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢЁмқј мқ‘лӢө лӮҙм—җм„ң reasoning depthлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё MixReasoningмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. MixReasoningмқҖ к°ҖлІјмҡҙ concise LoRA adapterлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  к·ё strengthлҘј м ңм–ҙн•ҳм—¬, sliding-window token confidenceлЎң м¶”м •н•ң reasoning difficultyм—җ л”°лқј switchлҘј нҠёлҰ¬кұ°н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, л№ лҘё reasoningкіј лҠҗлҰ° reasoning мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мқёк°„кіј мң мӮ¬н•ң м „нҷҳмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј chain of thoughtлҠ” м–ҙл Өмҡҙ лӢЁкі„м—җм„ңлҠ” мғҒм„ён•ң reasoning, мү¬мҡҙ лӢЁкі„м—җм„ңлҠ” к°„кІ°н•ң inferenceмқҳ нҳјн•©мқҙ лҗңлӢӨ. AIME24, MATH-500, GPQA, GSM8K мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң MixReasoningмқҖ лӮңмқҙлҸ„к°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmark м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ reasoning кёёмқҙлҘј 13\\%--49\\% лӢЁм¶•н•ҳл©ҙм„ң, м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ң мұ„ мқјкҙҖлҗң нҡЁмңЁ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65492","en":"ParaTool: Shifting Tool Representations from Context to Parameters","ko":"ParaTool: лҸ„кө¬ н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ң нҢҢлқјлҜён„°лЎң м „нҷҳн•ҳкё°","authors":"Zekai Yu, Qi Meng, Qizhi Chu, Yu Hao, Chuan Shi, Cheng Yang","pos":"#1614","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=D3lwvOSuQb","abs":"<p>Tool calling extends large language models (LLMs) by enabling grounded interaction with external executable interfaces, thereby supporting environment-coupled problem solving. However, mainstream in-context learning (ICL) approaches typically incorporate detailed tool documentation and usage examples directly into the context. This results in substantial inference overhead and heightened risks of hallucination as the context length grows. Conversely, while tuning-based methods improve general tool-calling capabilities, they often fail to effectively internalize the specific details of previously seen tools, thereby retaining a dependency on in-context documentation. To address these limitations, we propose ParaTool, a framework that projects each tool into a dedicated, loadable set of parameters. By equipping a dynamic integration of these parameterized tools, the LLM can perform tool calling without relying on in-context documents or examples. Specifically, our approach consists of three stages: (1) parametric tool pre-training encapsulates the knowledge of different tools into independent parameter modules; (2) soft tool selection employs a gating network to dynamically weigh and aggregate relevant tool parameters; and (3) parametric tool fine-tuning jointly updates tool parameters to align the training and inference processes. Experiments on Stable ToolBench and BFCL demonstrate that ParaTool significantly outperforms strong ICL-based baselines, achieving superior performance while reducing computational complexity.</p>","absKo":"Tool callingмқҖ large language models (LLMs)к°Җ мҷёл¶Җмқҳ мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң interfacesмҷҖ groundлҗң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ нҷ•мһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, environment-coupled problem solvingмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мЈјлҘҳ in-context learning (ICL) м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лҢҖк°ң мһҗм„ён•ң tool documentationкіј usage examplesлҘј context м•Ҳм—җ м§Ғм ‘ нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ inference overheadк°Җ мғҒлӢ№н•ҙм§Җкі , context lengthк°Җ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ hallucination мң„н—ҳлҸ„ лҶ’м•„м§„лӢӨ. л°ҳлҢҖлЎң tuning-based л°©лІ•мқҖ general tool-calling capabilityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨм§Җл§Ң, мқҙм „м—җ ліё toolл“Өмқҳ кө¬мІҙм Ғмқё м„ёл¶ҖмӮ¬н•ӯмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҙ in-context documentationм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙмқҙ лӮЁлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ toolмқ„ м „мҡ©мқҳ load к°ҖлҠҘн•ң parameter setмңјлЎң нҲ¬мҳҒн•ҳлҠ” frameworkмқё ParaToolмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң parameterized toolsмқҳ лҸҷм Ғ нҶөн•©мқ„ к°–м¶ӨмңјлЎңмҚЁ, LLMмқҖ in-context documentsлӮҳ examplesм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  tool callingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ м„ё лӢЁкі„лЎң кө¬м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. (1) parametric tool pre-trainingмқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё toolл“Өмқҳ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё parameter moduleм—җ лӢҙм•„лӮёлӢӨ; (2) soft tool selectionмқҖ gating networkлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кҙҖл Ё tool parameterлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң к°ҖмӨ‘ л°Ҹ м§‘кі„н•ңлӢӨ; (3) parametric tool fine-tuningмқҖ tool parameterлҘј н•Ёк»ҳ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•ҳм—¬ trainingкіј inference кіјм •мқ„ м •л ¬н•ңлӢӨ. Stable ToolBenchмҷҖ BFCL мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң ParaToolмқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң ICL-based baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, кі„мӮ° ліөмһЎлҸ„лҘј мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64745","en":"How2Everything: Mining the Web for How-to Procedures to Evaluate and Improve LLMs","ko":"How2Everything: LLM нҸүк°Җ л°Ҹ к°ңм„ мқ„ мң„н•ҙ мӣ№м—җм„ң л°©лІ• м Ҳм°Ё л§ҲмқҙлӢқ","authors":"Yapei Chang, Kyle Lo, Mohit Iyyer, Luca Soldaini","pos":"#1809","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=KHzFTDx20C","abs":"<p>Generating step-by-step \"how-to\" procedures is a key LLM capability: how-to advice is commonly requested in chatbots, and step-by-step planning is critical for reasoning over complex tasks.  Yet, measuring and improving procedural validity at scale on real-world tasks remains challenging and understudied. To address this, we introduce How2Everything, a scalable framework to evaluate and improve goal-conditioned procedure generation. Our pipeline How2Mine extracts and rewrites 351K procedures from 980K web pages across 14 topics, and can scale to larger corpora. From this pool we build How2Bench, a 7K-example evaluation set balanced across topics. We also introduce How2Score, an evaluation protocol that uses an LLM judge to detect whether a generation contains any critical failure that would prevent achieving the goal. For low-cost, reproducible evaluation, we distill a frontier judge into an open 8B model achieving 80.5\\% agreement with human annotators. How2Bench reveals clear scaling trends across model size and training stages, providing signal early in pretraining. Finally, RL using How2Score as a reward improves performance on How2Bench by &gt;10 points across three base models without systematic regressions on standard benchmarks, with gains not primarily explained by source-document memorization or superficial format compliance. We release all code and data upon acceptance.</p>","absKo":"<p>лӢЁкі„лі„ \"how-to\" м Ҳм°ЁлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё LLM capabilityмқҙлӢӨ. мұ—лҙҮм—җм„ңлҠ” how-to adviceк°Җ нқ”нһҲ мҡ”мІӯлҗҳл©°, ліөмһЎн•ң taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң м¶”лЎ м—җм„ңлҠ” лӢЁкі„лі„ planningмқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„ taskм—җм„ң procedural validityлҘј лҢҖк·ңлӘЁлЎң мёЎм •н•ҳкі  к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өкі  м¶©л¶„нһҲ м—°кө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” goal-conditioned procedure generationмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі  к°ңм„ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң frameworkмқё How2Everythingмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ pipeline How2MineмқҖ 14к°ң topicм—җ кұём№ң 980K web pageм—җм„ң 351Kк°ңмқҳ procedureлҘј м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкі  мһ¬мһ‘м„ұн•ҳл©°, лҚ” нҒ° corpusлЎңлҸ„ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ poolмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң topic м „л°ҳм—җ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶ҳ 7K-example evaluation setмқё How2BenchлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLM judgeлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мғқм„ұ кІ°кіјк°Җ лӘ©н‘ң лӢ¬м„ұмқ„ л°©н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” м№ҳлӘ…м Ғ мӢӨнҢЁлҘј н•ҳлӮҳлқјлҸ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ”м§Җ нғҗм§Җн•ҳлҠ” evaluation protocolмқё How2ScoreлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лӮ®мқҖ л№„мҡ©мңјлЎң мһ¬нҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ҙ, мөңмІЁлӢЁ judgeлҘј 8B open modelлЎң distillн•ҳм—¬ human annotatorмҷҖ 80.5\\%мқҳ мқјм№ҳлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. How2BenchлҠ” model sizeмҷҖ training stage м „л°ҳм—җм„ң лӘ…нҷ•н•ң scaling trendлҘј ліҙм—¬ мЈјл©°, pretraining мҙҲкё°м—җ мӢ нҳёлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, How2ScoreлҘј rewardлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” RLмқҖ н‘ңмӨҖ benchmarkм—җм„ң мІҙкі„м Ғмқё regression м—Ҷмқҙ м„ё к°ңмқҳ base model м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ How2Bench м„ұлҠҘмқ„ 10м җ мқҙмғҒ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н–ҘмғҒмқҖ мЈјлЎң source-document memorizationмқҙлӮҳ н‘ңл©ҙм Ғмқё format мӨҖмҲҳлЎң м„ӨлӘ…лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мҠ№мқёлҗҳл©ҙ лӘЁл“  codeмҷҖ dataлҘј кіөк°ңн•  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61705","en":"Know Thyself, Know Thy User: Intrinsic Dual-Perspective Reasoning for Role-Playing LLMs","ko":"л„Ҳ мһҗмӢ мқ„ м•Ңкі , мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлҘј м•Ңлқј: Role-Playing LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ мқҙмӨ‘ кҙҖм җ м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Haotong Sun, Yinghui Jiang, Bocheng Xu, Jianye Xie","pos":"#1815","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nbuJuzxigz","abs":"<p>As role-playing Large Language Models (LLMs) become central to personalized AI, they face a fundamental challenge: balancing character authenticity with user satisfaction. Prior dual-process and dual-perspective approaches address this through prompt-level conditioning, auxiliary modules, or inference-time reflection---realizing duality externally rather than within the core attention mechanism. We introduce the KnowSelf-KnowOther Transformer (KSKT), which embeds dual-perspective reasoning directly into the generation process via axial attention that processes self-understanding and other-understanding through separate streams. This intrinsic integration enables token-level dynamic balance rather than post-hoc reconciliation. On CharacterBench, KSKT achieves 6.2% overall improvement over Qwen3-4B-Thinking. On SOTOPIA, KSKT improves Relationship by 19.3% over the base model---the dimension requiring explicit self-other coordination. These results establish intrinsic dual-perspective reasoning as an effective architectural principle for role-playing systems.</p>","absKo":"<p>м—ӯн• к·№ Large Language Models (LLMs)к°Җ personalized AIмқҳ мӨ‘мӢ¬мңјлЎң мһҗлҰ¬ мһЎмңјл©ҙм„ң, мқҙл“ӨмқҖ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё лҸ„м „м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. л°”лЎң мәҗлҰӯн„°мқҳ м§„м •м„ұкіј мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ л§ҢмЎұ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ•мқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ dual-process л°Ҹ dual-perspective м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мқҙлҘј prompt-level conditioning, auxiliary module, лҳҗлҠ” inference-time reflectionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӢӨлЈЁл©°, core attention mechanism лӮҙл¶Җк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј мҷёл¶Җм—җм„ң dualityлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” KnowSelf-KnowOther Transformer (KSKT)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” self-understandingкіј other-understandingмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬лҗң streamмңјлЎң мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” axial attentionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ dual-perspective reasoningмқ„ мғқм„ұ кіјм •м—җ м§Ғм ‘ лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ нҶөн•©мқҖ мӮ¬нӣ„ мЎ°м •(post-hoc reconciliation)мқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј token-level dynamic balanceлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. CharacterBenchм—җм„ң KSKTлҠ” Qwen3-4B-Thinking лҢҖл№„ м „мІҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ 6.2% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. SOTOPIAм—җм„ңлҠ” base model лҢҖл№„ Relationshipмқ„ 19.3% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё self-other coordinationмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң м°ЁмӣҗмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” intrinsic dual-perspective reasoningмқҙ м—ӯн• к·№ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё architectural principleмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61199","en":"EasyBalance: Cross-Layer Load Balancing in Distributed MoE Inference","ko":"EasyBalance: л¶„мӮ° MoE Inferenceм—җм„ңмқҳ Cross-Layer Load Balancing","authors":"Yize Wu, KE GAO, Ling Li, Yanjun Wu","pos":"#1912","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=skvrwTDx3m","abs":"<p>Load Balancing has emerged as a critical problem in expert-parallel distributed inference of Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models. As routing distributions are typically skewed across experts, devices hosting lighter-loaded experts must idle to wait for the heaviest during expert computing, leading to inefficiency. Existing load-balancing approaches primarily rely on expert replication or migration within each layer, which introduce additional overhead and limit their flexibility and scalability. To address this problem, we propose EasyBalance, a \\textbf{cross-layer} load balancing strategy for expert-parallel MoE inference. EasyBalance requires no modifications to the expert-device mapping, enabling instant adaptability and incurring essentially no additional overhead. Our key insights are that (1) experts from other layers can be viewed as naturally redundant, and (2) expert workloads of multiple layers, if from different micro-batches, can be jointly executed. Based on these observations, EasyBalance greedily schedules subsets of cross-layer workloads at each expert-computation stage, while deferring the remaining workloads for future balancing opportunities. Extensive experiments across different models, tasks, and parallelism configurations demonstrate that EasyBalance consistently accelerates expert-parallel inference, reducing GPU idling by uniformly over 40\\%.</p>","absKo":"<p>Load BalancingмқҖ Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) лӘЁлҚёмқҳ expert-parallel distributed inferenceм—җм„ң н•өмӢ¬ л¬ём ңлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. routing distributionмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң expert к°„м—җ м№ҳмҡ°міҗ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, лҚ” к°ҖлІјмҡҙ л¶Җн•ҳмқҳ expertлҘј нҳёмҠӨнҢ…н•ҳлҠ” deviceлҠ” expert кі„мӮ° лҸҷм•Ҳ к°ҖмһҘ л¬ҙкұ°мҡҙ л¶Җн•ҳлҘј к°Җм§„ deviceлҘј кё°лӢӨлҰ¬л©° мң нңҙ мғҒнғңк°Җ лҗҳм–ҙ л№„нҡЁмңЁмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ load-balancing м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң к°Ғ layer лӮҙм—җм„ң expert replication лҳҗлҠ” migrationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” м¶”к°Җ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳкі  мң м—°м„ұкіј нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” expert-parallel MoE inferenceлҘј мң„н•ң <b>cross-layer</b> load balancing м „лһөмқё EasyBalanceлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. EasyBalanceлҠ” expert-device mappingмқ„ мҲҳм •н•  н•„мҡ”к°Җ м—Ҷм–ҙ мҰүк°Ғм Ғмқё м Ғмқ‘м„ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ м¶”к°Җ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј л°ңмғқмӢңнӮӨм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ нҶөм°°мқҖ (1) лӢӨлҘё layerмқҳ expertлҠ” мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ redundancyлЎң ліј мҲҳ мһҲкі , (2) м—¬лҹ¬ layerмқҳ expert workloadлҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё micro-batchм—җм„ң мҳЁ кІҪмҡ° кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң мӢӨн–үлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ EasyBalanceлҠ” к°Ғ expert-computation stageм—җм„ң cross-layer workloadмқҳ л¶Җл¶„м§‘н•©мқ„ нғҗмҡ•м ҒмңјлЎң мҠӨмјҖмӨ„л§Ғн•ҳкі , лӮҳлЁём§Җ workloadлҠ” н–Ҙнӣ„ balancing кё°нҡҢлЎң лҜёлЈ¬лӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң model, task, parallelism configurationм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ EasyBalanceк°Җ expert-parallel inferenceлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳл©°, GPU idlingмқ„ м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң 40\\% мқҙмғҒ мӨ„мқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61605","en":"Compute as Teacher: Turning Inference Compute Into Reference-Free Supervision","ko":"Compute as Teacher: Inference ComputeлҘј Reference-Free SupervisionмңјлЎң м „нҷҳ","authors":"Dulhan Jayalath, Shashwat Goel, Thomas Foster, Parag Jain, Suchin Gururangan, Cheng Zhang, Anirudh Goyal, Alan Schelten","pos":"#2002","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=oWOYBP7uFd","abs":"<p>Where do learning signals come from when there is no ground truth in post-training? We show that inference compute itself can serve as supervision. By generating parallel rollouts and converting them into reference estimates, models can learn without human labelsвҖ”critically, even in non-verifiable domains like healthcare guidance where no programmatic checker exists. We call this framework <em>Compute as Teacher (CaT)</em> and it turns inference-time compute from parallel rollouts into supervision for RL training. The framework has two components: (1) reference estimation which aggregates rollouts into a pseudo-reference answer, and (2) reward derivation which converts that pseudo-reference into RL rewards. For (1), we explore a simple method we call <em>synthesis</em>, but the framework admits any aggregator. For (2), we introduce self-proposed rubrics for non-verifiable domains. These are binary, auditable criteria generated from the pseudo-reference and scored by an LLM judge. On HealthBench, models trained with CaT match or exceed inference-time aggregation quality while using 9Г— less test-time compute. Here, CaT also competes with learning from expert physician annotations, yielding up to +30% relative improvement over the initial policy. The framework extends naturally to verifiable rewards, matching the best existing baselines on MATH-500 in test-time RL and demonstrating 'drop-in' versatility across both types of domains.</p>","absKo":"мӮ¬нӣ„ н•ҷмҠө(post-training)м—җм„ң м •лӢөмқҙ м—Ҷмқ„ л•Ң н•ҷмҠө мӢ нҳёлҠ” м–ҙл””м„ң мҳӨлҠ”к°Җ? мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” inference compute мһҗмІҙк°Җ supervision м—ӯн• мқ„ н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лі‘л ¬ rolloutмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј reference estimateлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мқёк°„ лқјлІЁ м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” programmatic checkerк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” мқҳлЈҢ мЎ°м–ёкіј к°ҷмқҖ non-verifiable domainм—җм„ңлҸ„ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј <em>Compute as Teacher (CaT)</em>лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙл©°, inference-time computeм—җм„ң лӮҳмҳЁ parallel rolloutмқ„ RL trainingмқ„ мң„н•ң supervisionмңјлЎң л°”кҫјлӢӨ. мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” л‘җ кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢлҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨ: (1) rolloutмқ„ pseudo-reference answerлЎң м§‘кі„н•ҳлҠ” reference estimation, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (2) к·ё pseudo-referenceлҘј RL rewardлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” reward derivationмқҙлӢӨ. (1)м—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <em>synthesis</em>лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ң л°©лІ•мқ„ нғҗмғүн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” м–ҙл–Ө aggregatorлҸ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. (2)м—җм„ңлҠ” non-verifiable domainмқ„ мң„н•ң self-proposed rubricмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” pseudo-referenceлЎңл¶Җн„° мғқм„ұлҗҳкі  LLM judgeк°Җ мұ„м җн•ҳлҠ” мқҙм§„м Ғмқҙл©° к°җмӮ¬ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кё°мӨҖмқҙлӢӨ. HealthBenchм—җм„ң CaTлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ 9л°° м ҒмқҖ test-time computeлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ң inference-time aggregation н’Ҳм§Ҳкіј лҢҖл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ к·ё мқҙмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң CaTлҠ” expert physician annotationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғкіјлҸ„ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мҙҲкё° policy лҢҖл№„ мөңлҢҖ +30%мқҳ мғҒлҢҖм Ғ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӮёлӢӨ. мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” verifiable rewardлЎңлҸ„ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ нҷ•мһҘлҗҳм–ҙ, test-time RLм—җм„ң MATH-500мқҳ кё°мЎҙ мөңкі  baselineкіј лҢҖл“ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , л‘җ мң нҳ•мқҳ domain лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң 'drop-in'мңјлЎң м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мң м—°м„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61435","en":"Diving into Kronecker Adapters: Component Design Matters","ko":"Kronecker Adapters к№Ҡмқҙ ліҙкё°: Component Designмқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Jiayu Bai, Danchen Yu, Zhenyu Liao, TianQi Hou, Feng Zhou, Robert Qiu, Zenan Ling","pos":"#2013","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=q8LOhSzOIU","abs":"<p>Kronecker adapters have emerged as a promising approach for fine-tuning large-scale models, enabling high-rank updates through tunable component structures. However, existing work largely treats the component structure as a fixed or heuristic design choice, leaving the dimensions and number of Kronecker components underexplored. In this paper, we identify component structure as a key factor governing the capacity of Kronecker adapters. We perform a fine-grained analysis of both the dimensions and number of Kronecker components. In particular, we show that the alignment between Kronecker adapters and full fine-tuning depends on  component configurations. Guided by these insights, we propose Component Designed Kronecker Adapters (CDKA). We further provide parameter-budgetвҖ“aware configuration guidelines and a tailored training stabilization strategy for practical deployment. Experiments across various natural language processing tasks demonstrate the effectiveness of CDKA.</p>","absKo":"<p>Kronecker adaptersлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ лӘЁлҚё fine-tuningмқ„ мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мңјлЎң л– мҳ¬лһҗмңјл©°, мЎ°м • к°ҖлҠҘн•ң component structureлҘј нҶөн•ҙ high-rank updateлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” component structureлҘј лҢҖмІҙлЎң кі м •лҗң м„Өкі„ лҳҗлҠ” heuristicн•ң м„ нғқмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈЁм–ҙ мҷ”кі , Kronecker componentмқҳ м°Ёмӣҗкіј к°ңмҲҳлҠ” м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” component structureк°Җ Kronecker adaptersмқҳ capacityлҘј мўҢмҡ°н•ҳлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ мҡ”мқёмһ„мқ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Kronecker componentмқҳ м°Ёмӣҗкіј к°ңмҲҳ лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м„ёл°Җн•ң л¶„м„қмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, Kronecker adaptersмҷҖ full fine-tuning к°„мқҳ alignmentк°Җ component configurationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Component Designed Kronecker Adapters(CDKA)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ л°°м№ҳлҘј мң„н•ң parameter-budget-aware configuration guidelineкіј л§һм¶Өнҳ• training stabilization м „лһөмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң natural language processing taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CDKAмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63098","en":"Do LLMs вҖңFeelвҖқ? Emotion Circuits Discovery and Control","ko":"LLMмқҖ 'лҠҗлҒјлҠ”к°Җ'? к°җм • нҡҢлЎң л°ңкІ¬кіј м ңм–ҙ","authors":"Chenxi Wang, Yixuan Zhang, Ruiji Yu, Yufei Zheng, Lang Gao, Zirui Song, Zixiang Xu, Gus xia, Huishuai Zhang, Dongyan Zhao, Xiuying Chen","pos":"#2014","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=a8N0nRG3jA","abs":"As the demand for emotional intelligence in large language models (LLMs) grows, a key challenge lies in understanding the internal mechanisms that give rise to emotional expression and in controlling emotions in generated text. This study addresses three core questions: (1) Do LLMs contain context-agnostic mechanisms shaping emotional expression? (2) What form do these mechanisms take? (3) Can they be harnessed for universal emotion control? We first construct a controlled dataset, $\\textit{SEV}$ (ScenarioвҖ“Event with Valence), to elicit comparable internal states across emotions. Subsequently, we extract context-agnostic emotion directions that reveal consistent, cross-context encoding of emotion (Q1). We identify neurons and attention heads that locally implement emotional computation through analytical decomposition and causal analysis, and validate their causal roles via ablation and enhancement interventions. Next, we quantify each sublayer's causal influence on the modelвҖҷs final emotion representation and integrate the identified local components into coherent global emotion circuits that drive emotional expression (Q2).  Directly modulating these circuits achieves 99.65% emotion-expression accuracy on the test set, surpassing prompting- and steering-based methods (Q3). To our knowledge, this is the first systematic study to uncover and validate emotion circuits in LLMs, advancing both model interpretability and the controllability of emotional intelligence.","absKo":"лҢҖнҳ• м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(LLMs)м—җм„ң emotional intelligenceм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ”кө¬к°Җ м»Өм§Җл©ҙм„ң, н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлҠ” emotional expressionмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙлӮҙлҠ” лӮҙл¶Җ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкі  мғқм„ұлҗң н…ҚмҠӨнҠём—җм„ң к°җм •мқ„ м ңм–ҙн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ м§Ҳл¬ёмқ„ лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. (1) LLMsм—җлҠ” emotional expressionмқ„ нҳ•м„ұн•ҳлҠ” context-agnostic mechanismмқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ”к°Җ? (2) мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ м–ҙл–Ө нҳ•нғңмқёк°Җ? (3) мқҙлҘј universal emotion controlм—җ нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ? лЁјм Җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё к°җм •м—җ кұёміҗ л№„көҗ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң internal stateлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ нҶөм ңлҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқё $\\textit{SEV}$ (ScenarioвҖ“Event with Valence)лҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ context-agnostic emotion directionмқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳм—¬ к°җм •мқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  cross-contextлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ(Q1). лӢӨмқҢмңјлЎң analytical decompositionкіј causal analysisлҘј нҶөн•ҙ к°җм • кі„мӮ°мқ„ көӯмҶҢм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬нҳ„н•ҳлҠ” neuronкіј attention headлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , ablation л°Ҹ enhancement interventionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙл“Өмқҳ causal roleмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң к°Ғ sublayerк°Җ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мөңмў… emotion representationм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” causal influenceлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳкі , мӢқлі„лҗң local componentл“Өмқ„ emotional expressionмқ„ кө¬лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” coherent global emotion circuitмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ(Q2). мқҙлҹ¬н•ң circuitмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳл©ҙ test setм—җм„ң emotion-expression accuracy 99.65%лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, prompting- л°Ҹ steering-based methodлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ(Q3). мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м•„лҠ” н•ң, мқҙлҠ” LLMsм—җм„ң emotion circuitмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•ҳкі  кІҖмҰқн•ң мІ« мІҙкі„м Ғ м—°кө¬лЎң, model interpretabilityмҷҖ emotional intelligenceмқҳ controllabilityлҘј лӘЁл‘җ м§„м „мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ."},{"id":"65125","en":"Does Math Reasoning Improve General LLM Capabilities? Understanding Transferability of LLM Reasoning","ko":"мҲҳн•ҷ м¶”лЎ мқҙ мқјл°ҳ LLM лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ”к°Җ? LLM м¶”лЎ мқҳ м „мқҙ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ мқҙн•ҙ","authors":"Maggie Ziyu Huan, Yuetai Li, Tuney Zheng, Xiaoyu Xu, Seungone Kim, Minxin Du, Radha Poovendran, Graham Neubig, Xiang Yue","pos":"#2015","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=GbOD25IA88","abs":"<p>Math reasoning has become the poster child of progress in large language models (LLMs), with new models rapidly surpassing human-level performance on benchmarks like MATH and AIME. But as math leaderboards improve week by week, it is worth asking: do these gains reflect broader problem-solving ability or just narrow overfitting? To answer this question, we evaluate over 20 open-weight reasoning-tuned models across a broad suite of tasks, including math, scientific QA, agent planning, coding, and standard instruction-following. We surprisingly find that most models that succeed in math fail to transfer their gains to other domains. To rigorously study this phenomenon, we conduct controlled experiments using math-only data with two widely-used methods: Reinforcement Learning (RL) and Supervised Finetuning (SFT) with detailed ablations. On top of the observation that RL-tuned models transfer better than SFT-tuned model, we identify on-policy fine-tuning as the key mechanism underlying cross-domain transfer, regardless of whether the training signal comes from RL or supervised learning. Latent-space representation and token-space distribution shift analyses reveal that off-policy SFT induces substantial representation and output drift, while on-policy RL preserves general-domain structure. Our results suggest a need to rethink the post-training recipes, particularly the reliance on off-policy SFT-distilled data to advance reasoning models.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҲҳн•ҷ м¶”лЎ мқҖ large language models (LLMs) л°ңм „мқҳ лҢҖн‘ң мӮ¬лЎҖк°Җ лҗҳм—Ҳкі , мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лӘЁлҚёл“ӨмқҖ MATHмҷҖ AIME к°ҷмқҖ benchmarkм—җм„ң л№ лҘҙкІҢ мқёк°„ мҲҳмӨҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„°лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҲҳн•ҷ leaderboardк°Җ мЈј лӢЁмң„лЎң к°ңм„ лҗҳлҠ” к°ҖмҡҙлҚ°, мқҙлҹ° н–ҘмғҒмқҙ лҚ” л„“мқҖ л¬ём ң н•ҙкІ° лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқём§Җ, м•„лӢҲл©ҙ мўҒмқҖ лІ”мң„мқҳ overfittingм—җ л¶Ҳкіјн•ң кІғмқём§Җ м§Ҳл¬ён•  н•„мҡ”к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ м§Ҳл¬ём—җ лӢөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҲҳн•ҷ, scientific QA, agent planning, coding, standard instruction-followingмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң task suiteм—җм„ң 20к°ңк°Җ л„ҳлҠ” open-weight reasoning-tuned modelмқ„ нҸүк°Җн–ҲлӢӨ. лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„, мҲҳн•ҷм—җм„ң м„ұкіөн•ң лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ к·ё м„ұкіјлҘј лӢӨлҘё domainмңјлЎң transferн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ м—„л°Җн•ҳкІҢ м—°кө¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” math-only dataлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң controlled experimentлҘј л‘җ к°Җм§Җ л„җлҰ¬ м“°мқҙлҠ” л°©лІ•, мҰү Reinforcement Learning (RL)кіј Supervised Finetuning (SFT)мңјлЎң мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі  detailed ablationмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н–ҲлӢӨ. RL-tuned modelмқҙ SFT-tuned modelліҙлӢӨ transferлҘј лҚ” мһҳн•ңлӢӨлҠ” кҙҖм°°м—җ лҚ”н•ҙ, training signalмқҙ RLм—җм„ң мҳӨл“  supervised learningм—җм„ң мҳӨл“  кҙҖкі„м—Ҷмқҙ, cross-domain transferмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ on-policy fine-tuningмһ„мқ„ л°қнҳҖлғҲлӢӨ. latent-space representationкіј token-space distribution shift л¶„м„қмқҖ off-policy SFTк°Җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң representation л°Ҹ output driftлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, on-policy RLмқҖ general-domain structureлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” post-training recipe, нҠ№нһҲ reasoning modelмқ„ л°ңм „мӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ҙ off-policy SFT-distilled dataм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” кҙҖн–үмқ„ мһ¬кі н•  н•„мҡ”к°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64958","en":"Characterizing, Evaluating, and Optimizing Complex Reasoning","ko":"ліөмһЎн•ң м¶”лЎ мқҳ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”, нҸүк°Җ л°Ҹ мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Haoran Zhang, Yafu Li, Zhi Wang, Zhilin Wang, Shunkai Zhang, Xiaoye Qu, Yu Cheng","pos":"#2100","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=IMFgiWw4jd","abs":"Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) increasingly rely on reasoning traces with complex internal structures. However, existing work lacks a unified answer to three fundamental questions:  (1) what defines high-quality reasoning,  (2) how to reliably evaluate long, implicitly structured reasoning traces, and  (3) how to use such evaluation signals for reasoning optimization. To address these challenges, we provide a unified perspective. (1) We introduce the ME$^2$ principle to characterize reasoning quality along macro- and micro-level concerning efficiency and effectiveness. (2) Built on this principle, we model reasoning traces as directed acyclic graphs (DAGs) and develop a DAG-based pairwise evaluation method, capturing complex reasoning structures. (3) Based on this method, we construct the TRM-Preference dataset and train a Thinking Reward Model (TRM) to evaluate reasoning quality at scale. Experiments show that thinking rewards serve as an effective optimization signal. At test time, selecting better reasoning leads to better outcomes (up to 19.3\\% gain), and during RL training, thinking rewards enhance reasoning and performance (up to 3.9\\% gain) across diverse tasks. Code is available in the supplementary material.","absKo":"Large Reasoning Models (LRMs)лҠ” м җм җ лҚ” ліөмһЎн•ң лӮҙл¶Җ кө¬мЎ°лҘј м§ҖлӢҢ reasoning traceм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” лӢӨмқҢ м„ё к°Җм§Җ к·јліё м§Ҳл¬ём—җ лҢҖн•ң нҶөн•©лҗң лӢөмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. (1) л¬ҙм—Үмқҙ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ reasoningмқ„ м •мқҳн•ҳлҠ”к°Җ, (2) кёёкі  м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң reasoning traceлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ нҸүк°Җн•  кІғмқёк°Җ, (3) к·ёлҹ¬н•ң нҸүк°Җ мӢ нҳёлҘј reasoning optimizationм—җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ нҷңмҡ©н•  кІғмқёк°Җ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҶөн•©лҗң кҙҖм җмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. (1) мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” efficiencyмҷҖ effectivenessлҘј кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң macro-levelкіј micro-level м–‘мӘҪм—җм„ң reasoning qualityлҘј нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ” ME$^2$ мӣҗлҰ¬лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. (2) мқҙ мӣҗлҰ¬м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reasoning traceлҘј directed acyclic graph (DAG)лЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкі  ліөмһЎн•ң reasoning кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” DAG-based pairwise evaluation methodлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. (3) мқҙ л°©лІ•мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң TRM-Preference datasetмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳкі , Thinking Reward Model (TRM)мқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁлЎң reasoning qualityлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” thinking rewardк°Җ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё optimization signalмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. test timeм—җм„ңлҠ” лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ reasoningмқ„ м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ кІ°кіјлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§Җл©°(мөңлҢҖ 19.3\\% н–ҘмғҒ), RL trainingм—җм„ңлҠ” thinking rewardк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң reasoningкіј м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ(мөңлҢҖ 3.9\\% н–ҘмғҒ). мҪ”л“ңлҠ” supplementary materialм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64959","en":"Breaking the Exploration Bottleneck: Rubric-Scaffolded Reinforcement Learning for General LLM Reasoning","ko":"нғҗмғү лі‘лӘ© к№Ёкё°: мқјл°ҳ LLM м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң Rubric-Scaffolded Reinforcement Learning","authors":"Yang Zhou, Sunzhu Li, Shunyu Liu, Wenkai Fang, Kongcheng Zhang, Jiale Zhao, Jingwen Yang, Yihe Zhou, Jianwei Lv, Tongya Zheng, Hengtong Lu, Chen Wei, Xie Yan, Mingli Song","pos":"#2102","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=IM8ZHjhD0v","abs":"<p>Recent advances in Large Language Models (LLMs) have underscored the potential of Reinforcement Learning (RL) to facilitate the emergence of reasoning capabilities. Despite the encouraging results, a fundamental dilemma persists as RL improvement relies on learning from high-quality samples, yet the exploration for such samples remains bounded by the inherent limitations of LLMs. This, in effect, creates an undesirable cycle in which what cannot be explored cannot be learned. In this work, we propose Rubric-Scaffolded Reinforcement Learning (RuscaRL), a novel instructional scaffolding framework designed to break the exploration bottleneck for general LLM reasoning. Specifically, RuscaRL introduces checklist-style rubrics as (1) explicit scaffolding for exploration during rollout generation, where different rubrics are provided as external guidance within task instructions to steer diverse high-quality responses. This guidance is gradually decayed over time, encouraging the model to internalize the underlying reasoning patterns; (2) verifiable rewards for exploitation during model training, where we can obtain robust LLM-as-a-Judge scores using rubrics as references, enabling effective RL on general reasoning tasks. Extensive experiments demonstrate the superiority of the proposed RuscaRL across various benchmarks, effectively expanding reasoning boundaries under the Best-of-N evaluation.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј Large Language Models (LLMs)мқҳ л°ңм „мқҖ Reinforcement Learning (RL)мқҙ reasoning capabilityмқҳ м¶ңнҳ„мқ„ мҙүм§„н•  мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ м§ҖлӢҳмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. кі л¬ҙм Ғмқё кІ°кіјм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , RLмқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқҖ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ sampleлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ёлҹ¬н•ң sampleмқ„ нғҗмғүн•ҳлҠ” лІ”мң„лҠ” LLMмқҳ кі мң н•ң н•ңкі„м—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңм•ҪлҗңлӢӨлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё л”ңл Ҳл§Ҳк°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кІ°көӯ нғҗмғүн•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” кІғмқҖ н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨлҠ” л°”лһҢм§Ғн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мҲңнҷҳмқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё LLM reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң exploration bottleneckмқ„ лҸҢнҢҢн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ instructional scaffolding frameworkмқё Rubric-Scaffolded Reinforcement Learning (RuscaRL)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, RuscaRLмқҖ checklist-style rubricмқ„ лӢӨмқҢ л‘җ к°Җм§ҖлЎң лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. (1) rollout generation лҸҷм•Ҳ explorationмқ„ мң„н•ң лӘ…мӢңм Ғ scaffoldingмңјлЎң, task instruction лӮҙм—җм„ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң rubricмқ„ мҷёл¶Җ guidanceлЎң м ңкіөн•ҳм—¬ лӢӨм–‘н•ң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ responseлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ guidanceлҠ” мӢңк°„мқҙ м§ҖлӮЁм—җ л”°лқј м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң м•Ҫнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ, modelмқҙ underlying reasoning patternмқ„ лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мһҘл Өн•ңлӢӨ. (2) model training лҸҷм•Ҳ exploitationмқ„ мң„н•ң verifiable rewardлЎң, rubricмқ„ referenceлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ robustн•ң LLM-as-a-Judge scoreлҘј м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқјл°ҳ reasoning taskм—җм„ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё RLмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҙм§„лӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җм„ң м ңм•Ҳн•ң RuscaRLмқҳ мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ҳл©°, Best-of-N evaluation н•ҳм—җм„ң reasoning boundaryлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61893","en":"EAPO: Enhancing Policy Optimization with On-Demand Expert Assistance","ko":"EAPO: мҳЁл””л§Ёл“ң м „л¬ёк°Җ м§ҖмӣҗмңјлЎң Policy Optimization к°•нҷ”","authors":"Siyao Song, Cong Ma, Zhihao Cheng, Shiye Lei, MINGHAO LI, Ying Zeng, Huaixiao Tou, Kai Jia","pos":"#215","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=luykjYIvEs","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) have recently advanced in reasoning when optimized with reinforcement learning (RL) under verifiable rewards. Existing methods primarily rely on outcome-based supervision to strengthen internal LLM reasoning, often leading to inefficient exploration and sparse rewards. To mitigate this issue, we propose Expert-Assisted Policy Optimization (EAPO), a novel RL framework that enhances exploration by incorporating multi-turn interactions with external experts during training. Unlike prior methods, where policies reason in isolation, EAPO incentivizes the policy to adaptively determine when and how to consult experts, yielding richer reward signals and more reliable reasoning trajectories. External assistance ultimately internalizes expert knowledge into the policy model, amplifying the modelвҖҷs inherent reasoning capabilities. During evaluation, the policy model has been well-optimized to solve questions independently, producing improved reasoning paths and more accurate solutions. On AIME 2024/2025 and AIMO 2025, EAPO consistently outperforms expert-assisted, expert-distilled, and RL baselines, averaging a 5-point gain over self-exploration RL, and also generalizes to non-math benchmarks, including HumanEval, HLE, GPQA, MMLU, EvalPlus, HotpotQA, and SimpleQA.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language model (LLM)мқҖ мөңк·ј verifiable reward н•ҳм—җм„ң reinforcement learning (RL)мңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗ  л•Ң reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ нҒ¬кІҢ л°ңм „н–ҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң outcome-based supervisionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ LLM лӮҙл¶Җ reasoningмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ л№„нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё explorationкіј sparse rewardк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ мҷёл¶Җ expertмҷҖмқҳ multi-turn interactionмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ explorationмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ RL н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё Expert-Assisted Policy Optimization (EAPO)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м •мұ…мқҙ кі лҰҪлҗң мғҒнғңлЎң reasoningн•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•кіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, EAPOлҠ” м •мұ…мқҙ м–ём ң м–ҙл–»кІҢ expertм—җкІҢ л¬ёмқҳн• м§Җ м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң кІ°м •н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬ лҚ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң reward signalкіј лҚ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” reasoning trajectoryлҘј л§Ңл“Өм–ҙлӮёлӢӨ. мҷёл¶Җмқҳ лҸ„мӣҖмқҖ к¶Ғк·№м ҒмңјлЎң expert knowledgeлҘј policy model лӮҙл¶ҖлЎң лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ҳм—¬, лӘЁлҚё кі мң мқҳ reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. нҸүк°Җ мӢңм—җлҠ” policy modelмқҙ м§Ҳл¬ёмқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мһҳ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ, н–ҘмғҒлҗң reasoning pathмҷҖ лҚ” м •нҷ•н•ң н•ҙлӢөмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. AIME 2024/2025мҷҖ AIMO 2025м—җм„ң EAPOлҠ” expert-assisted, expert-distilled, RL baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, self-exploration RL лҢҖл№„ нҸүк·  5м җ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң HumanEval, HLE, GPQA, MMLU, EvalPlus, HotpotQA, SimpleQAлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң л№„мҲҳн•ҷ benchmarkм—җлҸ„ мһҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62115","en":"AIR: Post-training Data Selection for Reasoning via Attention Head Influence","ko":"AIR: Attention Head InfluenceлҘј нҶөн•ң м¶”лЎ мҡ© нӣ„н•ҷмҠө лҚ°мқҙн„° м„ нғқ","authors":"Jinrui Liu, Kai Hua, Xuanguang Pan, Ge Zhang, Yong Wang, Shuai Ma, Chongyang Tao","pos":"#2209","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jjHZnkDk5l","abs":"<p>LLMs achieve remarkable multi-step reasoning capabilities, yet effectively transferring these skills via post-training distillation remains challenging. Existing data selection methods, ranging from manual curation to heuristics based on length, entropy, or overall loss, fail to capture the causal importance of individual reasoning steps, limiting distillation efficiency. To address this, we propose Attention Influence for Reasoning (AIR), a principled, unsupervised and training-free framework that leverages mechanistic insights of the retrieval head to select high-value post-training data. AIR first identifies reasoning-critical attention heads of an off-the-shelf model, then constructs a weakened reference model with disabled head influence, and finally quantifies the resulting loss divergence as the Attention Influence Score. This score enables fine-grained assessment at both the step and sample levels, supporting step-level weighted fine-tuning and global sample selection. Experiments across multiple reasoning benchmarks show that AIR consistently improves reasoning accuracy, surpassing heuristic baselines and effectively isolating the most critical steps and samples. Our work establishes a mechanism-driven, data-efficient approach for reasoning distillation in LLMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>LLMмқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ multi-step reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, post-training distillationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мқҙм „н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мҲҳлҸҷ м„ лі„л¶Җн„° length, entropy, overall lossм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң heuristicм—җ мқҙлҘҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙ data selection л°©лІ•мқҖ к°ңлі„ reasoning stepмқҳ causal importanceлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҙ distillation нҡЁмңЁмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” retrieval headмқҳ mechanistic insightлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ к°Җм№ҳ лҶ’мқҖ post-training dataлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” мӣҗлҰ¬ кё°л°ҳмқҳ unsupervised л°Ҹ training-free frameworkмқё Attention Influence for Reasoning(AIR)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. AIRлҠ” лЁјм Җ off-the-shelf modelмқҳ reasoning-critical attention headлҘј мӢқлі„н•ң л’Ө, н•ҙлӢ№ headмқҳ influenceлҘј л№„нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•ң weakened reference modelмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң к·ём—җ л”°лҘё loss divergenceлҘј Attention Influence ScoreлЎң м •лҹүнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м җмҲҳлҠ” step мҲҳмӨҖкіј sample мҲҳмӨҖ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң м„ёл°Җн•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬, step-level weighted fine-tuningкіј global sample selectionмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ reasoning benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң AIRлҠ” мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ reasoning accuracyлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, heuristic baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкі  к°ҖмһҘ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң stepкіј sampleмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң л¶„лҰ¬н•ҙлӮёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м—°кө¬лҠ” LLMм—җм„ңмқҳ reasoning distillationмқ„ мң„н•ң mechanism-driven, data-efficientн•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62707","en":"Multimodal Meta-Verifier with Explicit Structured Recalibration","ko":"лӘ…мӢңм Ғ кө¬мЎ° мһ¬ліҙм •мқҙ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗң Multimodal Meta-Verifier","authors":"Xinchen Zhang, Bowei Liu, Jiale Liu, Chufan Shi, Yizhen Zhang, Junhong Liu, Youliang Zhang, Zhiheng Li, Yujiu Yang, Ling Yang","pos":"#2800","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=e1bpZMpANm","abs":"<p>Visual outcomes are increasingly central to multimodal large language models, making reliable and fine-grained verification essential for scaling generalist foundation models. In this work, we investigate <em><strong>multimodal meta-verification</strong></em>, which leverages verifier-generated rationales rather than decision-only signals, and explore how to effectively incorporate meta-verification feedback into multimodal verifier training. We identify two key findings. First, symbolic verifier outputs (e.g., bounding boxes) outperform textual explanations as meta-verification rationales, enabling efficient rule-based reinforcement learning rewards while avoiding reliance on model-based rewards from auxiliary judge models. Second, decoupling reinforcement learning objectives for binary judgment and meta-verification substantially outperforms joint reward optimization, due to intrinsic differences in output structure and learning dynamics. Based on these insights, we train <strong>OmniVerifier-M1</strong>, a generalist visual verifier leveraging symbolic meta-verification and decoupled reinforcement learning. OmniVerifier-M1 provides robust verification and fine-grained error localization, and further enables <strong>M1-TTS</strong>, a verifier-driven agentic generation system achieving dynamic region-level self-correction. This approach paves the way for more reliable, interpretable, and fine-grained multimodal verification, supporting safer and more controllable foundation model deployment.</p>","absKo":"<p>Visual outcomeмқҖ м җм җ лҚ” multimodal large language modelм—җм„ң н•өмӢ¬мқҙ лҗҳкі  мһҲмңјл©°, generalist foundation modelмқҳ нҷ•мһҘмқ„ мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкі  м„ёл°Җн•ң verificationмқҙ н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” decision-only signalмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј verifierк°Җ мғқм„ұн•ң rationaleмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” <em><strong>multimodal meta-verification</strong></em>мқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкі , meta-verification feedbackмқ„ multimodal verifier trainingм—җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ нғҗкө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ кІ°кіјлҘј нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, symbolic verifier output(мҳҲ: bounding box)мқҖ meta-verification rationaleлЎңм„ң textual explanationліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳл©°, auxiliary judge modelмқҳ model-based rewardм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё rule-based reinforcement learning rewardлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, binary judgmentмҷҖ meta-verificationм—җ лҢҖн•ң reinforcement learning objectiveлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳл©ҙ, output structureмҷҖ learning dynamicsмқҳ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ м°Ёмқҙ л•Ңл¬ём—җ joint reward optimizationліҙлӢӨ нӣЁм”¬ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” symbolic meta-verificationкіј decoupled reinforcement learningмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” generalist visual verifierмқё <strong>OmniVerifier-M1</strong>мқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. OmniVerifier-M1мқҖ кІ¬кі н•ң verificationкіј м„ёл°Җн•ң error localizationмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ лҸҷм Ғ region-level self-correctionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” verifier-driven agentic generation systemмқё <strong>M1-TTS</strong>лҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ лҚ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкі , н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳл©°, м„ёл°Җн•ң multimodal verificationмңјлЎң к°ҖлҠ” кёёмқ„ м—ҙм–ҙ, лҚ” м•Ҳм „н•ҳкі  лҚ” м ңм–ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң foundation model л°°м№ҳлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63605","en":"Internalizing Safety Understanding in Large Reasoning Models via Verification","ko":"кІҖмҰқмқ„ нҶөн•ң лҢҖнҳ• м¶”лЎ  лӘЁлҚёмқҳ м•Ҳм „ мқҙн•ҙ лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”","authors":"Yi Zhang, Yuxin Chen, Leheng Sheng, Dongcheng Zhang, Chaochao Lu, Xiang Wang, An Zhang","pos":"#3004","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=VYIegjMzFC","abs":"<p>While explicit Chain-of-Thought (CoT) empowers large reasoning models (LRMs), it enables the generation of riskier final answers. Current alignment paradigms primarily rely on externally enforced compliance, optimizing models to detect malicious prompts rather than evaluating the safety of their own outputs. We argue that this approach remains largely behavioral: our empirical analysis reveals that ostensibly aligned models lack intrinsic safety understanding, often failing to verify their own response safety and remaining vulnerable to adversarial jailbreaks.  To address this fundamental limitation, we propose Safety Internal (SInternal), a framework that internalizes safety specifications by training LRMs exclusively on safety verification tasks to critique their own generated answers using expert reasoning trajectories. We demonstrate that learning to verify induces a strong generalization for response safety, significantly enhancing robustness against out-of-domain jailbreaks. Furthermore, when combined with reinforcement learning, SInternal serves as a superior initialization compared to standard supervised fine-tuning, suggesting that internalizing safety understanding creates a more robust foundation for alignment than merely mimicking safe behaviors. Our codes are available at \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/SInternal-AF60}</p>","absKo":"<p>лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё Chain-of-Thought (CoT)лҠ” large reasoning model (LRM)мқ„ к°•л Ҙн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өм§Җл§Ң, лҚ” мң„н—ҳн•ң мөңмў… лӢөліҖмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“Өкё°лҸ„ н•ңлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ alignment paradigmмқҖ мЈјлЎң мҷёл¶Җм—җм„ң к°•м ңлҗң мӨҖмҲҳм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, м•…м„ұ н”„лЎ¬н”„нҠёлҘј нғҗм§Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•  лҝҗ мһҗмӢ мқҳ м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ м•Ҳм „м„ұ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ҳм§ҖлҠ” м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҙ м—¬м „нһҲ мЈјлЎң behavioral levelм—җ лЁёл¬ёлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨмҰқ л¶„м„қмқҖ кІүліҙкё°м—җ alignedлҗң лӘЁлҚёмЎ°м°Ё лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ м•Ҳм „м„ұ мқҙн•ҙк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳм—¬ мһҗмӢ мқҳ мқ‘лӢө м•Ҳм „м„ұмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі  adversarial jailbreakм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к·јліём Ғ н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” expert reasoning trajectoryлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мҠӨмҠӨлЎң мғқм„ұн•ң лӢөліҖмқ„ л№„нҸүн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м•Ҳм „м„ұ кІҖмҰқ taskм—җл§Ң LRMмқ„ н•ҷмҠөмӢңмјң м•Ҳм „м„ұ лӘ…м„ёлҘј лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё Safety Internal (SInternal)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кІҖмҰқмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ response safetyм—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•н•ң generalizationмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬ out-of-domain jailbreakм—җ лҢҖн•ң robustnessлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ reinforcement learningкіј кІ°н•©н•  кІҪмҡ°, SInternalмқҖ н‘ңмӨҖ supervised fine-tuningліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң мҙҲкё°нҷ”лЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳл©°, м•Ҳм „н•ң н–үлҸҷмқ„ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ лӘЁл°©н•ҳлҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ м•Ҳм „м„ұ мқҙн•ҙлҘј лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ alignmentлҘј мң„н•ң лҚ” кІ¬кі н•ң кё°л°ҳмқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/SInternal-AF60}м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65831","en":"Monitorability as a Free Gift: How RLVR Spontaneously Aligns Reasoning","ko":"кіөм§ң м„ л¬јлЎңм„ңмқҳ лӘЁлӢҲн„° к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ: RLVRмқҙ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мһҗл°ңм ҒмңјлЎң м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ”к°Җ","authors":"Zidi Xiong, Shan Chen, Himabindu Lakkaraju","pos":"#3406","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9hzK071Z3R","abs":"<p>As Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) are increasingly deployed, auditing their chain-of-thought (CoT) traces for safety becomes critical. Recent work has reported that monitorabilityвҖ”the degree to which CoT faithfully and informatively reflects internal computationвҖ”can appear as a \"free gift\" during the early stages of Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR). We make this observation concrete through a systematic evaluation across model families and training domains.  Our results show that this effect is not universal: monitorability improvements are strongly data-dependent. In particular, we demonstrate the critical role of data diversity and instruction-following data during RLVR training. We further show that monitorability is orthogonal to capabilityвҖ”improvements in reasoning performance do not imply increased transparency. Through mechanistic analysis, we attribute monitorability gains primarily to response distribution sharpening (entropy reduction) and increased attention to the prompt, rather than stronger causal reliance on reasoning traces. We also reveal how monitorability dynamics vary with controlled training and evaluation difficulty. Together, these findings provide a holistic view of how monitorability emerges under RLVR, clarifying when gains are likely to occur and when they are not.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Reasoning Model(LRM)мқҙ м җм җ лҚ” л§Һмқҙ л°°нҸ¬лҗЁм—җ л”°лқј, м•Ҳм „м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ҙ chain-of-thought(CoT) traceлҘј к°җмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҙм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” monitorability, мҰү CoTк°Җ лӮҙл¶Җ кі„мӮ°мқ„ м–јл§ҲлӮҳ м¶©мӢӨн•ҳкі  мң мқөн•ҳкІҢ л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј лӮҳнғҖлӮҙлҠ” м •лҸ„к°Җ Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards(RLVR)мқҳ мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң \"free gift\"мІҳлҹј лӮҳнғҖлӮ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨкі  ліҙкі н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ model familyмҷҖ training domainм—җ кұём№ң мІҙкі„м Ғ нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ кҙҖм°°мқ„ кө¬мІҙнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мқҙ нҡЁкіјк°Җ ліҙнҺём Ғмқҙм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, monitorability н–ҘмғҒмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җ к°•н•ҳкІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” RLVR н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң лҚ°мқҙн„° лӢӨм–‘м„ұкіј instruction-following dataмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м—ӯн• мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң monitorabilityлҠ” capabilityмҷҖ м§Ғкөҗм Ғмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, reasoning м„ұлҠҘмқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқҙ transparencyмқҳ мҰқк°ҖлҘј мқҳлҜён•ҳм§ҖлҠ” м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳ л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” monitorability н–ҘмғҒмқҳ мЈјлҗң мӣҗмқёмқ„ лҚ” к°•н•ң reasoning traceм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқёкіјм Ғ мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқҙлқјкё°ліҙлӢӨ, response distribution sharpening(entropy к°җмҶҢ)кіј promptм—җ лҢҖн•ң attention мҰқк°ҖлЎң м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң нҶөм ңлҗң training л°Ҹ evaluation лӮңмқҙлҸ„м—җ л”°лқј monitorability dynamicsк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ лӢ¬лқјм§ҖлҠ”м§ҖлҸ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мқҙ кІ°кіјл“ӨмқҖ RLVR н•ҳм—җм„ң monitorabilityк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң м „мІҙм Ғмқё кҙҖм җмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, м–ём ң н–ҘмғҒмқҙ мқјм–ҙлӮ  к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ лҶ’кі  м–ём ң к·ёл Үм§Җ м•ҠмқҖм§ҖлҘј л¶„лӘ…нһҲ н•ҙмӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64167","en":"Implicit Turn-Wise Policy Optimization for Proactive User-LLM Interaction","ko":"лҠҘлҸҷм Ғ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ-LLM мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ мң„н•ң м•”л¬өм Ғ н„ҙлі„ м •мұ… мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Haoyu Wang, Yuxin Chen, Liang Luo, Buyun Zhang, Ellie Wen, Pan Li","pos":"#3800","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=QJC5WymFK1","abs":"<p>Multi-turn human-AI collaboration is fundamental to deploying interactive services such as adaptive tutoring, conversational recommendation, and professional consultation. However, optimizing these interactions via reinforcement learning is hindered by the sparsity of verifiable intermediate rewards and the high stochasticity of user responses.  To address these challenges, we introduce Implicit Turn-wise Policy Optimization (ITPO).  ITPO leverages an implicit process reward model to derive fine-grained, turn-wise process rewards from sparse outcome signals. Unlike volatile token-level rewards, these turn-level signals exhibit superior robustness and may utilize a normalization mechanism to further enhance training stability.  We evaluate ITPO across three representative multi-turn collaborative tasks: math tutoring, document writing, and medical recommendation. Empirical results demonstrate that ITPO, when combined with PPO, GRPO, or RLOO, consistently achieves improved convergence than existing baselines. Elaborate trajectory analysis confirms that ITPO infers turn-wise preferences that are semantically aligned with human judgment.</p>","absKo":"<p>лӢӨмӨ‘ н„ҙ human-AI collaborationмқҖ adaptive tutoring, conversational recommendation, professional consultationкіј к°ҷмқҖ interactive serviceлҘј л°°нҸ¬н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөмңјлЎң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мӨ‘к°„ ліҙмғҒмқҳ нқ¬мҶҢм„ұкіј мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мқ‘лӢөмқҳ лҶ’мқҖ stochasticity л•Ңл¬ём—җ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Implicit Turn-wise Policy Optimization (ITPO)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ITPOлҠ” implicit process reward modelмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ нқ¬мҶҢн•ң outcome signalлЎңл¶Җн„° м„ёл¶„нҷ”лҗң turn-wise process rewardлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. ліҖлҸҷм„ұмқҙ нҒ° token-level rewardмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң turn-level signalмқҖ лҚ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң robustлҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, м •к·ңнҷ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ н•ҷмҠө м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ITPOлҘј мҲҳн•ҷ нҠңн„°л§Ғ, л¬ём„ң мһ‘м„ұ, мқҳлЈҢ м¶”мІңмқҙлқјлҠ” лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё м„ё к°Җм§Җ лӢӨмӨ‘ н„ҙ нҳ‘м—… кіјм ңм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, ITPOлҘј PPO, GRPO, лҳҗлҠ” RLOOмҷҖ кІ°н•©н•ҳл©ҙ кё°мЎҙ baselineліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ мҲҳл ҙмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м •көҗн•ң trajectory analysisлҠ” ITPOк°Җ мқёк°„ нҢҗлӢЁкіј мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎң м •л ¬лҗң turn-wise preferenceлҘј м¶”лЎ н•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64522","en":"PRM-PBE: Process Reward Model for Reinforcement Learning in Programming-by-Example","ko":"PRM-PBE: мҳҲм ң кё°л°ҳ н”„лЎңк·ёлһҳл°Қм—җм„ң к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң кіјм • ліҙмғҒ лӘЁлҚё","authors":"Yue Fang, Zhi Jin, Jie An, Hongshen Chen, Jiangmeng Li, Xiaohong Chen, Naijun Zhan","pos":"#3902","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=MjjdkgK62z","abs":"<p>Programming-by-Example (PBE), as a typical few-shot inductive reasoning paradigm, aims to synthesize corresponding algorithms from a set of input-output examples. Although Large Language Models (LLMs) have demonstrated strong program synthesis potential, they still remain ineffective when handling complex PBE tasks. Specifically, LLMs often struggle to accurately grasp the underlying intent of examples, resulting in synthesized programs that either partially satisfy the examples or completely deviate from the target. To address these limitations, we introduce a process-supervised reinforcement learning method that provides fine-grained feedback during the synthesis process, improving the ability of LLMs to capture the intended behavior of provided examples. Firstly, we develop a reasoning tree construction method that is used to build a PBE process supervision dataset. Subsequently, we train a process reward model through preference learning to evaluate the effectiveness of reasoning steps. Finally, we introduce a curriculum learning strategy based on the difficulty of PBE tasks, using Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO) to optimize the model. Experimental results on representative PBE benchmarks show that our approach achieves an average pass rate of 56.61\\%, significantly outperforming the state-of-the-art baseline by 8.73\\%.</p>","absKo":"<p>Programming-by-Example (PBE)лҠ” м „нҳ•м Ғмқё few-shot inductive reasoning paradigmмңјлЎңм„ң, мһ…л Ҙ-м¶ңл Ҙ мҳҲмӢң м§‘н•©мңјлЎңл¶Җн„° лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ н•©м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. Large Language Models(LLMs)к°Җ к°•л Ҙн•ң program synthesis мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙмҳҖм§Җл§Ң, ліөмһЎн•ң PBE taskлҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•  л•ҢлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ л№„нҡЁмңЁм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң LLMмқҖ мҳҲмӢңмқҳ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң мқҳлҸ„лҘј м •нҷ•нһҲ нҢҢм•…н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҗмЈј м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘмңјл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј н•©м„ұлҗң programмқҙ мҳҲмӢңмқҳ мқјл¶Җл§Ң л§ҢмЎұмӢңнӮӨкұ°лӮҳ лӘ©н‘ңмҷҖ мҷ„м „нһҲ м–ҙкёӢлӮҳкІҢ лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•©м„ұ кіјм • лҸҷм•Ҳ м„ёл°Җн•ң н”јл“ңл°ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” process-supervised reinforcement learning л°©лІ•мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, LLMмқҙ м ңкіөлҗң мҳҲмӢңмқҳ мқҳлҸ„лҗң лҸҷмһ‘мқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ, PBE process supervision datasetмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” reasoning tree construction л°©лІ•мқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ preference learningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ process reward modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬ reasoning stepмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, PBE taskмқҳ лӮңмқҙлҸ„м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң curriculum learning м „лһөмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , Proximal Policy Optimization (PPO)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ modelмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё PBE benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ нҸүк·  pass rate 56.61\\%лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳмңјл©°, state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ 8.73\\% нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65888","en":"Learning to Discover at Test Time","ko":"н…ҢмҠӨнҠё мӢңм җм—җ л°ңкІ¬н•ҳкё° н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Mert Yuksekgonul, Daniel Koceja, Xinhao Li, Federico Bianchi, Jed McCaleb, Xiaolong Wang, Jan Kautz, Yejin Choi, James Zou, Carlos Guestrin, Yu Sun","pos":"#3913","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=96zNuQrH9Y","abs":"<p>How can we use AI to discover a new state of the art for a scientific problem? Prior work in test-time scaling, such as AlphaEvolve, performs search by prompting a frozen LLM. We perform reinforcement learning at test time, so the LLM can continue to train, but now with experience specific to the test problem. This form of continual learning is quite special, because its goal is to produce one great solution rather than many good ones on average, and to solve this very problem rather than generalize to other problems. Therefore, our learning objective and search subroutine are designed to prioritize the most promising solutions. We call this method Test-Time Training to Discover (TTT-Discover). Following prior work, we focus on problems with continuous rewards. We report results for every problem we attempted, across mathematics, GPU kernel engineering, algorithm design, and biology. TTT-Discover sets the new state of the art in almost all of them: (i) ErdЕ‘s' minimum overlap problem and an autocorrelation inequality; (ii) a GPUMode kernel competition (up to 2Г— faster than prior art); (iii) past AtCoder algorithm competitions; and (iv) denoising problem in single-cell analysis. Our solutions are reviewed by experts or the organizers. All our results are achieved with an open model, OpenAI gpt-oss-120b, and can be reproduced with our publicly available code, in contrast to previous best results that required closed frontier models. Our test-time training runs are performed using Tinker, an API by Thinking Machines, with a cost of only a few hundred dollars per problem.</p>","absKo":"<p>м–ҙл–»кІҢ AIлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кіјн•ҷ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state-of-the-artлҘј л°ңкІ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„к№Ң? AlphaEvolveмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ test-time scalingмқҳ кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” кі м •лҗң LLMм—җ promptлҘј лҚҳм ё searchлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” test timeм—җ reinforcement learningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ LLMмқҙ кі„мҶҚ н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҗҳ, мқҙм ңлҠ” test problemм—җ нҠ№нҷ”лҗң experienceлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң continual learningмқҖ л§Өмҡ° лҸ…нҠ№н•ңлҚ°, к·ё лӘ©н‘ңк°Җ нҸүк· м ҒмңјлЎң л§ҺмқҖ мўӢмқҖ н•ҙлҘј м–»лҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ нӣҢлҘӯн•ң н•ҙлҘј л§Ңл“ңлҠ” лҚ° мһҲкі , лӢӨлҘё л¬ём ңлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј л°”лЎң мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н‘ёлҠ” лҚ° мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ learning objectiveмҷҖ search subroutineмқҖ к°ҖмһҘ мң л§қн•ң solutionмқ„ мҡ°м„ н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л°©лІ•мқ„ Test-Time Training to Discover(TTT-Discover)лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҘј л”°лқј мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” continuous rewardк°Җ мһҲлҠ” л¬ём ңм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” mathematics, GPU kernel engineering, algorithm design, biology м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мӢңлҸ„н•ң лӘЁл“  л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң кІ°кіјлҘј ліҙкі н•ңлӢӨ. TTT-DiscoverлҠ” кұ°мқҳ лӘЁл“  л¬ём ңм—җм„ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state-of-the-artлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мҰү, (i) ErdЕ‘sмқҳ minimum overlap problemкіј autocorrelation inequality, (ii) GPUMode kernel competition(кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ 2л°° л№ лҰ„), (iii) кіјкұ° AtCoder algorithm competition, (iv) single-cell analysisмқҳ denoising problemмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ solutionмқҖ м „л¬ёк°Җ лҳҗлҠ” мЈјмөңмһҗм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кІҖнҶ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. лӘЁл“  кІ°кіјлҠ” open modelмқё OpenAI gpt-oss-120bлЎң лӢ¬м„ұлҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, кіөк°ңлҗң codeлЎң мһ¬нҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мқҙм „мқҳ мөңкі  кІ°кіјк°Җ closed frontier modelмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н–ҲлҚҳ кІғкіј лҢҖмЎ°м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ test-time training runмқҖ Thinking Machinesмқҳ APIмқё TinkerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мҲҳн–үлҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, л¬ём ңлӢ№ л№„мҡ©мқҖ мҲҳл°ұ лӢ¬лҹ¬м—җ л¶Ҳкіјн–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65969","en":"Re-FORC: Adaptive Reward Prediction for Efficient Chain-of-Thought Reasoning","ko":"Re-FORC: нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Chain-of-Thought м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң м Ғмқ‘нҳ• ліҙмғҒ мҳҲмёЎ","authors":"Renos Zabounidis, Aditya Golatkar, Michael Kleinman, Alessandro Achille, Wei Xia, Stefano Soatto","pos":"#3914","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=8NNPSNAvTX","abs":"<p>We propose Re-FORC, an adaptive reward prediction method that, given a context, enables prediction of the expected future rewards as a function of the number of future thinking tokens. Re-FORC trains a lightweight adapter on reasoning models, demonstrating improved prediction with longer reasoning and larger models. Re-FORC enables: 1) early stopping of unpromising reasoning chains, reducing compute by 26\\% while maintaining accuracy, 2) optimized model and thinking length selection that achieves 4\\% higher accuracy at equal compute and 55\\% less compute at equal accuracy compared to the largest model, 3) adaptive test-time scaling, which increases accuracy by 11\\% in high compute regime, and 7\\% in low compute regime. Re-FORC allows dynamic reasoning with length control via cost-per-token thresholds while estimating computation time upfront.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Re-FORCлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Re-FORCлҠ” contextк°Җ мЈјм–ҙмЎҢмқ„ л•Ң, лҜёлһҳмқҳ thinking token мҲҳмқҳ н•ЁмҲҳлЎң кё°лҢҖ лҜёлһҳ rewardлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” adaptive reward prediction л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. Re-FORCлҠ” reasoning model мң„м—җ lightweight adapterлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©°, лҚ” кёҙ reasoningкіј лҚ” нҒ° modelм—җм„ң лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ мҳҲмёЎ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. Re-FORCлҠ” лӢӨмқҢмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ: 1) мң л§қн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ reasoning chainмқ„ мЎ°кё°м—җ мӨ‘лӢЁн•ҳм—¬ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң computeлҘј 26\\% м Ҳк°җ, 2) лҸҷмқјн•ң computeм—җм„ң 4\\% лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ лҸҷмқјн•ң м •нҷ•лҸ„м—җм„ң 55\\% лҚ” м ҒмқҖ computeлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” мөңм Ғмқҳ model л°Ҹ thinking length м„ нғқ, 3) high compute regimeм—җм„ң м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј 11\\% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  low compute regimeм—җм„ң 7\\% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” adaptive test-time scaling. Re-FORCлҠ” кі„мӮ° мӢңк°„мқ„ мӮ¬м „м—җ м¶”м •н•ҳл©ҙм„ң tokenлӢ№ л№„мҡ© мһ„кі„к°’мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ length controlмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң dynamic reasoningмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61056","en":"D-CORE: Incentivizing Task Decomposition in Large Reasoning Models for Complex Tool Use","ko":"D-CORE: ліөмһЎн•ң Tool UseлҘј мң„н•ң лҢҖнҳ• Reasoning Modelмқҳ кіјм ң л¶„н•ҙ мң лҸ„","authors":"Bowen Xu, Shaoyu Wu, Hao Jiang, Kai Liu, Xin Chen, lulu hu, Bin Yang","pos":"#403","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=u7PfRlU5qL","abs":"<p>Effective tool use and reasoning are essential capabilities for large reasoning models (LRMs) to address complex real-world problems. Through empirical analysis, we identify a prevalent \"Lazy Reasoning\" phenomenon, where LRMs frequently engage in repetitive and meaningless reflective reasoning. This occurs primarily due to their inadequate ability to decompose tasks when reasoning in complex tool use scenarios. To address this, we propose a two-stage training framework D-CORE ( Decomposing tasks and  Composing  Reasoning processes) that first incentivize the LRMвҖҷs task decomposition reasoning capability via self-distillation, followed by diversity-aware reinforcement learning (RL) to restore LRM's reflective reasoning capability. D-CORE achieves robust tool-use improvements across diverse benchmarks and model scales. Experiments on BFCLv3 demonstrate superiority of our method: D-CORE-8B reaches 77.7% accuracy, surpassing the best-performing 8B model by 5.7%. Meanwhile, D-CORE-14B establishes a new state-of-the-art at 79.3%, outperforming 70B models despite being 5Г— smaller. The source code and data sample are in the supplementary material.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё лҸ„кө¬ мӮ¬мҡ©кіј м¶”лЎ мқҖ large reasoning models (LRMs)к°Җ ліөмһЎн•ң нҳ„мӢӨ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё лҠҘл ҘмқҙлӢӨ. кІҪн—ҳм Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LRMsк°Җ л°ҳліөм Ғмқҙкі  л¬ҙмқҳлҜён•ң м„ұм°°м Ғ м¶”лЎ мқ„ л№ҲлІҲн•ҳкІҢ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” л„җлҰ¬ нҚјм§„ \"Lazy Reasoning\" нҳ„мғҒмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мЈјлЎң ліөмһЎн•ң лҸ„кө¬ мӮ¬мҡ© мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң м¶”лЎ н•  л•Ң мһ‘м—…мқ„ м Ғм ҲнһҲ л¶„н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЁјм Җ self-distillationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ LRMмқҳ мһ‘м—… л¶„н•ҙ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мһҘл Өн•ҳкі , мқҙм–ҙм„ң diversity-aware reinforcement learning (RL)мңјлЎң LRMмқҳ м„ұм°°м Ғ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҡҢліөмӢңнӮӨлҠ” 2лӢЁкі„ н•ҷмҠө н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ D-CORE (Decomposing tasks and Composing Reasoning processes)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. D-COREлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkмҷҖ model scale м „л°ҳм—җм„ң кІ¬кі н•ң tool-use к°ңм„ мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. BFCLv3 мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬ л°©лІ•мқҳ мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлҠ”лҚ°, D-CORE-8BлҠ” 77.7% м •нҷ•лҸ„м—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳм—¬ кё°мЎҙ мөңкі  м„ұлҠҘ 8B лӘЁлҚёліҙлӢӨ 5.7% н–ҘмғҒлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. н•ңнҺё D-CORE-14BлҠ” 79.3%лЎң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state-of-the-artлҘј мҲҳлҰҪн–Ҳмңјл©°, 5л°° лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ к·ңлӘЁмһ„м—җлҸ„ 70B лӘЁлҚёл“Өмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн–ҲлӢӨ. source codeмҷҖ data sampleмқҖ supplementary materialм—җ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61339","en":"Safety Recovery in Reasoning Models Is Only a Few Early Steering Steps Away","ko":"Reasoning Modelмқҳ м•Ҳм „м„ұ нҡҢліөмқҖ мҙҲкё° Steering лӘҮ лӢЁкі„л©ҙ м¶©л¶„н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Soumya Suvra Ghosal, Souradip Chakraborty, Vaibhav Singh, Furong Huang, Dinesh Manocha, Amrit Singh Bedi","pos":"#501","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=rCbbDqQzai","abs":"Reinforcement learning (RL) based post-training for explicit chain-of-thought (e.g., GRPO) improves the reasoning ability of multimodal large-scale reasoning models (MLRMs).  But recent evidence shows that it can simultaneously degrade safety alignment and increase jailbreak success rates. We propose SafeThink, a lightweight inference-time defense that treats safety recovery as a satisficing constraint rather than a maximization objective. SafeThink monitors the evolving reasoning trace with a safety reward model and conditionally injects an optimized short corrective prefix (\"Wait, think safely\") only when the safety threshold is violated.  In our evaluations across six open-source MLRMs and four jailbreak benchmarks (JailbreakV-28K, Hades, FigStep, and MM-SafetyBench), SafeThink reduces attack success rates by 30-60 % (e.g., LlamaV-o1: 63.33\\% $\\rightarrow$5.74\\% on JailbreakV-28K, R1-OneVision: 69.07\\%$\\rightarrow$5.65\\% on Hades) while preserving reasoning performance (MathVista accuracy: 65.20\\%$\\rightarrow$65.00\\%). A key empirical finding from our experiments is that safety recovery is often only a few steering steps away: intervening in the first $1вҖ“3$ reasoning steps typically suffices to redirect the full generation toward safe completions.","absKo":"explicit chain-of-thoughtлҘј мң„н•ң reinforcement learning (RL) кё°л°ҳ post-training(мҳҲ: GRPO)мқҖ multimodal large-scale reasoning model (MLRM)мқҳ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. н•ҳм§Җл§Ң мөңк·ј мҰқкұ°лҠ” мқҙкІғмқҙ лҸҷмӢңм—җ safety alignmentлҘј м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮӨкі  jailbreak м„ұкіөлҘ мқ„ лҶ’мқј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” safety recoveryлҘј maximization objectiveк°Җ м•„лӢҢ satisficing constraintлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҠ”, к°ҖлІјмҡҙ inference-time л°©м–ҙ кё°лІ• SafeThinkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SafeThinkлҠ” safety reward modelлЎң м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” reasoning traceлҘј лӘЁлӢҲн„°л§Ғн•ҳкі , safety thresholdк°Җ мң„л°ҳлҗ  л•Ңм—җл§Ң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗң м§§мқҖ corrective prefix(\"Wait, think safely\")лҘј мЎ°кұҙл¶ҖлЎң мЈјмһ…н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬м„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ open-source MLRMкіј л„Ө к°ңмқҳ jailbreak benchmark (JailbreakV-28K, Hades, FigStep, MM-SafetyBench) м „л°ҳмқҳ нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң, SafeThinkлҠ” кіөкІ© м„ұкіөлҘ мқ„ 30-60 % к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ(мҳҲ: LlamaV-o1: 63.33\\% $\\rightarrow$5.74\\% on JailbreakV-28K, R1-OneVision: 69.07\\%$\\rightarrow$5.65\\% on Hades) while reasoning performanceлҘј мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ(MathVista м •нҷ•лҸ„: 65.20\\%$\\rightarrow$65.00\\%). мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң лҸ„м¶ңн•ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кІҪн—ҳм Ғ л°ңкІ¬мқҖ safety recoveryк°Җ мў…мў… лӘҮ лІҲмқҳ steering stepл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мІҳмқҢ $1вҖ“3$к°ңмқҳ reasoning stepм—җм„ң к°ңмһ…н•ҳл©ҙ м „мІҙ мғқм„ұмқ„ м•Ҳм „н•ң completion л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң мһ¬мң лҸ„н•ҳкё°м—җ м¶©л¶„н•ҳлӢӨ."},{"id":"61419","en":"FrontierCS: Evolving Challenges for Evolving Intelligence","ko":"FrontierCS: м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” IntelligenceлҘј мң„н•ң м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” Challenges","authors":"Qiuyang Mang, Wenhao Chai, Zhifei Li, Huanzhi Mao, Shang Zhou, Alexander Du, Hanchen Li, Shu Liu, Edwin Chen, Yichuan Wang, Xieting Chu, Zerui Cheng, Yuan Xu, Tian Xia, Zirui Wang, Tianneng Shi, Jianzhu Yao, Yilong Zhao, Qizheng Zhang, Charlie Ruan, Zeyu Shen, Kaiyuan Liu, Zhaoyang Hong, Alex Gu, Ziyi Zhang, Runyuan He, Dong Xing, Zerui Li, Zirong Zeng, Yige Jiang, Lufeng Cheng, Ziyi Zhao, Youran Sun, Suyang Zhong, Junpeng Wang, Donglin Li, Wenyuan Huang, Jialiang Gu, Wesley Zheng, Wangmeiyu Zhang, Ruyi Ji, Xuechang Tu, Zihan Zheng, Zhaozi Wang, Zexing Chen, Jingbang Chen, JIALU ZHANG, Aleksandra Korolova, Peter Henderson, Pramod Viswanath, Vijay Ganesh, Saining Xie, Zhuang Liu, Dawn Song, Sewon Min, Ion Stoica, Joseph E Gonzalez, Jingbo Shang, Alvin Cheung","pos":"#502","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qNlU88p8lP","abs":"<p>We introduce FrontierCS, a benchmark of 240 open-ended problems across diverse areas of computer science, designed and reviewed by experts, including CS PhDs and top-tier competitive programming participants and problem setters.  Unlike existing benchmarks that focus on tasks with known optimal solutions, FrontierCS targets problems where the optimal solution is unknown, but the quality of a solution can be objectively evaluated. Models solve these tasks by implementing executable programs rather than outputting a direct answer. FrontierCS includes algorithmic problems, which are often NP-hard variants of competitive programming problems with objective partial scoring, and research problems with the same property. For each problem, we provide an expert reference solution and an automatic evaluator.  Combining open-ended design, measurable progress, and expert curation,  FrontierCS provides a benchmark at the frontier of computer-science difficulty.  Empirically, we find that frontier reasoning models still lag far behind human experts, and that simply increasing reasoning budgets does not close this gap on open-ended challenges. Moreover, these models struggle to identify internal equivalence classes, and existing agentic frameworks also exhibit brittleness on such problems due to overfitting.  FrontierCS thus offers a new lens into model capabilities on real frontier computer science problems.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FrontierCSлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. FrontierCSлҠ” м»ҙн“Ён„°кіјн•ҷмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мҳҒм—ӯм—җ кұём№ң 240к°ңмқҳ к°ңл°©нҳ• л¬ём ңлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лЎң, CS PhDмҷҖ мөңмғҒмң„ кІҪмҹҒ н”„лЎңк·ёлһҳл°Қ м°ёк°Җмһҗ л°Ҹ л¬ём ң м¶ңм ңмһҗлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м „л¬ёк°Җл“Өмқҙ м„Өкі„н•ҳкі  кІҖнҶ н–ҲлӢӨ. м •лӢөмқҙ м•Ңл Өм§„ кіјм ңм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” кё°мЎҙ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬мҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, FrontierCSлҠ” мөңм Ғн•ҙлҠ” м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲм§Җ м•Ҡм§Җл§Ң н•ҙмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ к°қкҙҖм ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. лӘЁлҚёмқҖ м§Ғм ‘м Ғмқё лӢөмқ„ м¶ңл Ҙн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ  мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н”„лЎңк·ёлһЁмқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіјм ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. FrontierCSлҠ” м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ л¬ём ңмҷҖ м—°кө¬ л¬ём ңлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙл“ӨмқҖ нқ”нһҲ кІҪмҹҒ н”„лЎңк·ёлһҳл°Қ л¬ём ңмқҳ NP-hard ліҖнҳ•мқҙл©° к°қкҙҖм Ғмқё л¶Җл¶„ мұ„м җмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” м„ұм§Ҳмқ„ к°Җм§„лӢӨ. к°Ғ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м „л¬ёк°Җ кё°мӨҖ н•ҙлӢөкіј мһҗлҸҷ нҸүк°Җкё°лҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к°ңл°©нҳ• м„Өкі„, мёЎм • к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м§„м „, м „л¬ёк°Җ нҒҗл Ҳмқҙм…ҳмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ FrontierCSлҠ” м»ҙн“Ён„°кіјн•ҷ лӮңмқҙлҸ„мқҳ мөңм „м„ м—җ мһҲлҠ” лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” frontier reasoning лӘЁлҚёмқҙ м—¬м „нһҲ мқёк°„ м „л¬ёк°Җм—җ л№„н•ҙ нҒ¬кІҢ л’ӨмІҳм§Җл©°, reasoning мҳҲмӮ°мқ„ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ лҠҳлҰ¬лҠ” кІғл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°ңл°©нҳ• лҸ„м „ кіјм ңм—җм„ң мқҙ кІ©м°Ёк°Җ н•ҙмҶҢлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мқҙл“Ө лӘЁлҚёмқҖ лӮҙл¶Җм Ғ лҸҷм№ҳ нҒҙлһҳмҠӨ мӢқлі„м—җлҸ„ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘмңјл©°, кё°мЎҙмқҳ agentic framework м—ӯмӢң кіјм Ғн•© л•Ңл¬ём—җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңм—җм„ң м·Ём•Ҫм„ұмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң FrontierCSлҠ” мӢӨм ң мөңм „м„  м»ҙн“Ён„°кіјн•ҷ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң лӘЁлҚё лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мғҲлЎӯкІҢ мЎ°л§қн•ҳлҠ” л ҢмҰҲлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64660","en":"PETS: A Principled Framework Towards Optimal Trajectory Allocation for Efficient Test-Time Self-Consistency","ko":"PETS: нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Test-Time Self-ConsistencyлҘј мң„н•ң мөңм Ғ Trajectory н• лӢ№мқҳ мӣҗм№ҷм Ғ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Zhangyi Liu, Huaizhi Qu, Xiaowei Yin, He Sun, Yanjun Han, Tianlong Chen, Xinyu Yang","pos":"#115","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=L9jcGvJP2N","abs":"Test-time scaling can improve model performance by aggregating stochastic reasoning trajectories. However, achieving sample-efficient test-time self-consistency under a limited budget remains an open challenge. We introduce PETS (\\textbf{P}rincipled and \\textbf{E}fficient \\textbf{T}est-Time \\textbf{S}elf-Consistency), which initiates a principled study of trajectory allocation through an optimization framework. Central to our approach is the \\emph{self-consistency rate}, a new measure defined as agreement with the infinite-budget majority vote. This formulation makes sample-efficient test-time allocation theoretically grounded and amenable to rigorous analysis. We study both offline and online settings. In the offline regime, where all questions are known in advance, we connect trajectory allocation to crowdsourcing, a classic and well-developed area, by modeling reasoning traces as workers. This perspective allows us to leverage rich existing theory, yielding theoretical guarantees and an efficient majority-voting-based allocation algorithm. In the online streaming regime, where questions arrive sequentially and allocations must be made on the fly, we propose a novel method inspired by the offline framework. Our approach adapts budgets to question difficulty while preserving strong theoretical guarantees and computational efficiency. Experiments show that PETS consistently outperforms uniform allocation. On GPQA, PETS achieves perfect self-consistency in both settings while reducing the sampling budget by up to $75\\\\%$ (offline) and $55\\\\%$ (online) relative to uniform allocation.","absKo":"test-time scalingмқҖ stochastic reasoning trajectoryлҘј м§‘кі„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ model performanceлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ м ңн•ңлҗң budget лӮҙм—җм„ң sample-efficientн•ң test-time self-consistencyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м—ҙлҰ° кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” trajectory allocationмқ„ optimization frameworkлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мӣҗлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң м—°кө¬н•ҳлҠ” PETS (\\textbf{P}rincipled and \\textbf{E}fficient \\textbf{T}est-Time \\textbf{S}elf-Consistency)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ \\emph{self-consistency rate}лЎң, infinite-budget majority voteмҷҖмқҳ мқјм№ҳ м •лҸ„лЎң м •мқҳлҗҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м§Җн‘ңмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ formulationмқҖ sample-efficientн•ң test-time allocationмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң м •лӢ№нҷ”н•ҳкі  м—„л°Җн•ң л¶„м„қмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” offlineкіј online setting лӘЁл‘җлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁл“  м§Ҳл¬ёмқҙ лҜёлҰ¬ мЈјм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” offline regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” reasoning traceлҘј workerлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ trajectory allocationмқ„ crowdsourcingмқҙлқјлҠ” кі м „м Ғмқҙкі  мһҳ м •лҰҪлҗң л¶„м•јмҷҖ м—°кІ°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм җмқҖ н’Қл¶Җн•ң кё°мЎҙ мқҙлЎ мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳм—¬, мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘкіј majority-voting-based allocation algorithmмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. м§Ҳл¬ёмқҙ мҲңм°Ём ҒмңјлЎң лҸ„м°©н•ҳкі  к·ёл•Ңк·ёл•Ң allocationмқ„ н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” online streaming regimeм—җм„ңлҠ”, offline frameworkм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣмқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ к°•н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘкіј кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң question difficultyм—җ л§һкІҢ budgetмқ„ мЎ°м •н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј PETSлҠ” uniform allocationмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. GPQAм—җм„ң PETSлҠ” л‘җ setting лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мҷ„м „н•ң self-consistencyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, uniform allocation лҢҖл№„ sampling budgetмқ„ мөңлҢҖ $75\\\\%$ (offline)мҷҖ $55\\\\%$ (online)к№Ңм§Җ мӨ„мҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63588","en":"Verifying Meta-Awareness via Predictive Rewards in Reasoning Models","ko":"мҳҲмёЎ ліҙмғҒмқ„ нҶөн•ң л©”нғҖ мқёмӢқ кІҖмҰқ","authors":"Yoonjeon Kim, Doohyuk Jang, Eunho Yang","pos":"#1202","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Vl3tXPbjSH","abs":"Recent research on reasoning models explores the meta-awareness of language models, including their ability to determine optimal thinking duration, recognize knowledge boundaries, and structure concept-level thinking. While current large reasoning models depend solely on answer-based verification, we show that adding meta-awareness objectives leads to significant performance gains over models without such meta-knowledge. **MAPR** utilizes a self-generated task of predicting rollout statistics - specifically length, pass-rate, and concepts used - allowing for verification against the actual statistics. Furthermore, by leveraging this self-predictive capability, the model can regulate its reasoning behavior by i) filtering out trivial or unsolvable prompts, ii) reducing lengthy generations that tend to be incorrect, and iii) generating hints relevant to the problem. The results are inspiring: **MAPR** yields significant improvements in both accuracy and training efficiency on various reasoning benchmarks. More specifically, our method can speed up GRPO training by over 1.28$\\times$ to reach the same performance, and achieve 83.18\\% gain in accuracy on AIME25, and a 13.04\\% average gain over six mathematics benchmarks.","absKo":"м¶”лЎ  лӘЁлҚём—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” language modelмқҳ meta-awareness, мҰү мөңм Ғмқҳ мӮ¬кі  мӢңк°„мқ„ кІ°м •н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙ, м§ҖмӢқмқҳ кІҪкі„лҘј мқёмӢқн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙ, к°ңл…җ мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ мӮ¬кі лҘј кө¬мЎ°нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙ л“ұмқ„ нғҗкө¬н•ңлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ reasoning modelмқҖ лӢөліҖ кё°л°ҳ кІҖмҰқм—җл§Ң мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” meta-awareness objectiveлҘј м¶”к°Җн•ҳл©ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң meta-knowledgeк°Җ м—ҶлҠ” modelм—җ л№„н•ҙ нҒ° м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқҙ л°ңмғқн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. **MAPR**мқҖ rollout statistic, кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” length, pass-rate, мӮ¬мҡ©лҗң conceptлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” self-generated taskлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мӢӨм ң statisticкіјмқҳ кІҖмҰқмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мһҗкё° мҳҲмёЎ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ i) мһҗлӘ…н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ н’Җ мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” promptлҘј кұёлҹ¬лӮҙкі , ii) мҳӨлӢөмқҙ лҗҳкё° мү¬мҡҙ кёҙ мғқм„ұмқ„ мӨ„мқҙл©°, iii) л¬ём ңмҷҖ кҙҖл Ёлҗң hintлҘј мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ reasoning behaviorлҘј мЎ°м Ҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. кІ°кіјлҠ” кі л¬ҙм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. **MAPR**мқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ң м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ training efficiency лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мң мқҳлҜён•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ лҸҷмқјн•ң м„ұлҠҘм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳкё°к№Ңм§Җ GRPO trainingмқ„ 1.28$\\times$ мқҙмғҒ л№ лҘҙкІҢ н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, AIME25м—җм„ң м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј 83.18\\% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі , м—¬м„Ҝ к°ң мҲҳн•ҷ benchmarkм—җм„ң нҸүк·  13.04\\%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"66536","en":"Thinking with Geometry: Active Geometry Integration for Spatial Reasoning","ko":"кё°н•ҳн•ҷмңјлЎң мӮ¬кі н•ҳкё°: кіөк°„ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң лҠҘлҸҷм Ғ кё°н•ҳ нҶөн•©","authors":"Haoyuan Li, Qihang Cao, Tao Tang, Kun Xiang, Zihan Guo, Jianhua Han, Jia-Wang Bian, Hang Xu, Xiaodan Liang","pos":"#1310","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2mEC3bPBlS","abs":"<p>Recent progress in spatial reasoning with Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) increasingly leverages geometric priors from 3D encoders. However, most existing integration strategies remain passive: geometry is exposed as a global stream and fused in an indiscriminate manner, which often induces semantic-geometry misalignment and redundant signals. We propose GeoThinker, a framework that shifts the paradigm from passive fusion to active perception. Instead of feature mixing, GeoThinker enables the model to selectively retrieve geometric evidence conditioned on its internal reasoning demands. GeoThinker achieves this through Spatial-Grounded Fusion applied at carefully selected VLM layers, where semantic visual priors selectively query and integrate task-relevant geometry via frame-strict cross-attention, further calibrated by Importance Gating that biases per-frame attention toward task-relevant structures. Comprehensive evaluation results show that GeoThinker sets a new state-of-the-art in spatial intelligence, achieving a peak score of 72.6 on the VSI-Bench. Furthermore, GeoThinker demonstrates robust generalization and significantly improved spatial perception across complex downstream scenarios, including embodied referring and autonomous driving. Our results indicate that the ability to actively integrate spatial structures is essential for next-generation spatial intelligence.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs)мқҳ spatial reasoningм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңк·ј л°ңм „мқҖ 3D encoderм—җм„ң м–»мқҖ geometric priorлҘј м җм җ лҚ” л§Һмқҙ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙмқҳ нҶөн•© м „лһө лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ мҲҳлҸҷм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. geometryлҘј н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ global streamмңјлЎң л…ём¶ңн•ҳкі  л¬ҙм°Ёлі„м ҒмңјлЎң кІ°н•©н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, мў…мў… semantic-geometry misalignmentмҷҖ мӨ‘ліө мӢ нҳёлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҲҳлҸҷм Ғ fusionм—җм„ң лҠҘлҸҷм Ғ perceptionмңјлЎң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м „нҷҳн•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё GeoThinkerлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. feature mixing лҢҖмӢ , GeoThinkerлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҳ лӮҙл¶Җ reasoning мҡ”кө¬м—җ л”°лқј geometric evidenceлҘј м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң retrievalн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. GeoThinkerлҠ” мӢ мӨ‘н•ҳкІҢ м„ нғқлҗң VLM layerм—җ м Ғмҡ©лҗҳлҠ” Spatial-Grounded Fusionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳл©°, semantic visual priorк°Җ frame-strict cross-attentionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ task кҙҖл Ё geometryлҘј м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң м§Ҳмқҳн•ҳкі  нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м—җ мӨ‘мҡ”лҸ„ кё°л°ҳмқҳ Importance Gatingмқ„ м¶”к°Җн•ҳм—¬ frameлі„ attentionмқ„ task кҙҖл Ё кө¬мЎ° мӘҪмңјлЎң нҺён–ҘмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғ нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіј, GeoThinkerлҠ” spatial intelligenceм—җм„ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state-of-the-artлҘј мҲҳлҰҪн•ҳл©° VSI-Benchм—җм„ң мөңкі  м җмҲҳ 72.6мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ GeoThinkerлҠ” embodied referringкіј autonomous drivingмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң ліөмһЎн•ң downstream мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң к°•кұҙн•ң мқјл°ҳнҷ”мҷҖ нҳ„м ҖнһҲ н–ҘмғҒлҗң spatial perceptionмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” кіөк°„ кө¬мЎ°лҘј лҠҘлҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ м°Ём„ёлҢҖ spatial intelligenceм—җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмһ„мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62920","en":"Think in Latent, Explain in Language: Self-Explainable Latent Reasoning","ko":"мһ мһ¬ кіөк°„м—җм„ң мӮ¬кі н•ҳкі  м–ём–ҙлЎң м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳлӢӨ: мһҗкё°м„ӨлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ң Latent Reasoning","authors":"Dayuan Zhao, Shengcao Cao, Yu-Xiong Wang, Liang-Yan Gui","pos":"#1312","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bsgrUQ0RIY","abs":"<p>Latent reasoning has emerged as a powerful alternative to text-based Chain-of-Thought (CoT), offering significant gains in computational efficiency by compressing verbose reasoning into compact embeddings. However, compressing reasoning into the latent space renders the thinking opaque, hindering its interpretability. Current methods present a stark trade-off: they either function as unexplainable вҖңblack boxesвҖқ (e.g., Coconut), where the latent reasoning is not human-readable, or rely on separate post-hoc decoders for explainability (e.g., Heima), introducing architectural overhead and decoupling the explanation from the actual reasoning process. In this work, we present a unified framework for Self-Explainable Latent Reasoning (SELR) that trains a single model to perform efficient and inherently explainable latent reasoning. Our core contribution is a novel multi-task training objective that optimizes for two goals simultaneously: (1) an Answer Loss that optimizes the latent reasoning trajectory to produce accurate final answers, and (2) a CoT Loss that explicitly trains the same model to decode its own latent representations back into human-understandable reasoning steps. This design ensures that generated latent representations are both task-effective and semantically interpretable, eliminating the need for external decoders. We validate the effectiveness of SELR on both Large Language Models (LLMs) and Vision-Language Models (VLMs), demonstrating that SELR achieves superior token efficiency and accuracy compared to baselines, while uniquely providing self-contained explainability without auxiliary models.</p>","absKo":"Latent reasoningмқҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё кё°л°ҳ Chain-of-Thought (CoT)м—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•л Ҙн•ң лҢҖм•ҲмңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳмңјл©°, мһҘнҷ©н•ң reasoningмқ„ compact embeddingмңјлЎң м••м¶•н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм„ұ мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ reasoningмқ„ latent spaceлЎң м••м¶•н•ҳл©ҙ мӮ¬кі  кіјм •мқҙ л¶ҲнҲ¬лӘ…н•ҙм ё н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬ л°©лІ•мқҖ лҡңл ·н•ң trade-offлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҰү, latent reasoningмқҙ мӮ¬лһҢм—җкІҢ мқҪнһҲм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” м„ӨлӘ… л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң вҖңblack boxвҖқлЎң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ(e.g., Coconut), м„ӨлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ҙ лі„лҸ„мқҳ post-hoc decoderм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ(e.g., Heima) кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі  explanationмқ„ мӢӨм ң reasoning processмҷҖ л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м„ӨлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ң latent reasoningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмқј лӘЁлҚёмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” Self-Explainable Latent Reasoning (SELR) нҶөн•© н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кё°м—¬лҠ” л‘җ лӘ©н‘ңлҘј лҸҷмӢңм—җ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ multi-task training objectiveмқҙлӢӨ. (1) latent reasoning trajectoryлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ м •нҷ•н•ң мөңмў… лӢөмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” Answer Loss, (2) к°ҷмқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мһҗмӢ мқҳ latent representationмқ„ мӮ¬лһҢмқҙ мқҙн•ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” reasoning stepмңјлЎң лӢӨмӢң decodeн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” CoT LossмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” мғқм„ұлҗң latent representationмқҙ task-effectiveн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ semantic interpretableн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳл©°, мҷёл¶Җ decoderмқҳ н•„мҡ”лҘј м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Large Language Models (LLMs)мҷҖ Vision-Language Models (VLMs) лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң SELRмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн–Ҳмңјл©°, SELRмқҙ baseline лҢҖл№„ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң token efficiencyмҷҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ auxiliary model м—Ҷмқҙ мһҗмІҙм ҒмңјлЎң м„ӨлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60843","en":"Sparks of Cooperative Reasoning: LLMs as Strategic Hanabi Agents","ko":"нҳ‘л Ҙм Ғ м¶”лЎ мқҳ л¶ҲкҪғ: м „лһөм Ғ Hanabi AgentлЎңм„ңмқҳ LLM","authors":"Mahesh Ramesh, Kaousheik Jayakumar, Aswinkumar Ramkumar, Pavan Thodima, Aniket Rege, Emmanouil-Vasileios Vlatakis-Gkaragkounis","pos":"#1404","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=w8D7UPfQYJ","abs":"<p>Cooperative reasoning under incomplete information remains complex for both humans and multi-agent AI, requiring agents to transcend individual logic in favor of recursive Theory-of-Mind (ToM) and strategic coordination. To investigate these challenges, we conduct a large-scale evaluation of 17 state-of-the-art LLMs (4BвҖ“600B+) on Hanabi card game across 2вҖ“5 players. To examine their limitations, we analyze the impact of context engineering and scaffold robustness, ranging from minimal prompts (Watson setting) to Bayesian-motivated scaffolding (Sherlock setting) and multi-turn working memory (Mycroft setting). Our findings reveal that: (1) top-performing models can autonomously track game states via internal working memory, although not reliably, and (2) cross-play performance scales smoothly with model capability. However, even the best models (scoring вүҲ 15/25) trail specialist human experts (&gt; 20/25). We introduce and release two novel datasets: HanabiLogs (1,520 annotated trajectories) and HanabiRewards (560 games with dense move-level utilities). By fine-tuning a 4B open-weight model (Qwen3-Instruct) on our datasets, we achieve performance gains of up to 156%, bringing performance to within 3 points of a strong proprietary reasoning model (o4-mini) and surpassing the best non-reasoning model (GPT-4.1) by 52%. Crucially, our HanabiRewards RL-finetuned model further generalizes beyond Hanabi, improving performance on a cooperative group-guessing benchmark by 11%, temporal reasoning on EventQA by 6.4%, instruction-following on IFBench-800K by 1.7 Pass@10, and matching AIME 2025 mathematical reasoning Pass@10. Code and datasets are available at {redacted for double blind}.</p>","absKo":"<p>л¶Ҳмҷ„м „н•ң м •ліҙ н•ҳмқҳ cooperative reasoningмқҖ мқёк°„кіј multi-agent AI лӘЁл‘җм—җкІҢ м—¬м „нһҲ ліөмһЎн•ҳл©°, agentк°Җ к°ңлі„ л…јлҰ¬лҘј л„ҳм–ҙ recursive Theory-of-Mind (ToM)кіј м „лһөм Ғ coordinationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҸ„м „ кіјм ңлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 2вҖ“5лӘ…мқҳ н”Ңл Ҳмқҙм–ҙлҘј лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң Hanabi м№ҙл“ң кІҢмһ„м—җм„ң state-of-the-art LLM 17к°ң(4BвҖ“600B+)лҘј лҢҖк·ңлӘЁлЎң нҸүк°Җн–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙл“Өмқҳ н•ңкі„лҘј мӮҙнҺҙліҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ prompt (Watson setting)м—җм„ң Bayesian лҸҷкё°лҘј м§ҖлӢҢ scaffolding (Sherlock setting), multi-turn working memory (Mycroft setting)м—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ context engineeringкіј scaffold robustnessмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л¶„м„қн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” лӢӨмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. (1) мөңкі  м„ұлҠҘ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ лӮҙл¶Җ working memoryлҘј нҶөн•ҙ кІҢмһ„ мғҒнғңлҘј мһҗмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң м¶”м Ғн•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, к·ё мӢ лў°м„ұмқҖ м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. (2) cross-play м„ұлҠҘмқҖ model capabilityм—җ л”°лқј л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ мҰқк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мөңмғҒмң„ лӘЁлҚёмЎ°м°ЁлҸ„(вүҲ 15/25) м „л¬ё мқёк°„ expert(> 20/25)м—җ л’ӨмІҳм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ datasetмқё HanabiLogs(1,520к°ңмқҳ мЈјм„қ мІҳлҰ¬лҗң trajectory)мҷҖ HanabiRewards(мЎ°л°Җн•ң move-level utilityк°Җ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗң 560к°ң кІҢмһ„)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі  кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ datasetмңјлЎң 4B open-weight model (Qwen3-Instruct)мқ„ fine-tuningн•ң кІ°кіј, мөңлҢҖ 156%мқҳ м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳмңјл©°, к°•л Ҙн•ң proprietary reasoning model (o4-mini)ліҙлӢӨ 3м җ мқҙлӮҙк№Ңм§Җ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬лҰ¬кі  мөңкі мқҳ non-reasoning model (GPT-4.1)мқ„ 52% м•һм„°лӢӨ. лҚ”мҡұмқҙ HanabiRewards кё°л°ҳ RL-finetuned modelмқҖ HanabiлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗҳл©°, cooperative group-guessing benchmarkм—җм„ң 11%, EventQAмқҳ temporal reasoningм—җм„ң 6.4%, IFBench-800Kмқҳ instruction-followingм—җм„ң 1.7 Pass@10 н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖкі , AIME 2025 мҲҳн•ҷ м¶”лЎ  Pass@10кіјлҸ„ лҸҷл“ұн•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ datasetмқҖ {redacted for double blind}м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64019","en":"Prompt Optimization with Minimal Unlabeled Input via Meta-Reasoning","ko":"л©”нғҖ м¶”лЎ мқ„ нҶөн•ң мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ л№„лқјлІЁ мһ…л Ҙ кё°л°ҳ н”„лЎ¬н”„нҠё мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Yuran Sun, Chuan Wu","pos":"#1511","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RdbSgk61V0","abs":"<p>Prompt optimization is critical for maximizing the performance of large language models (LLMs). However, it often relies on costly labeled data. Self-supervised methods reduce data dependency, but they suffer from optimization ambiguity or high computational costs. To address these limitations, we propose the Meta-Reasoning Prompt Engineering Agent (MR.PEA), a self-supervised prompt optimization framework that operates with minimal input. MR.PEA leverages meta-reasoning to iteratively build task-specific knowledge, including problem-solving strategies and evaluation criteria, while adaptively retrieving external information to enhance its understanding. This knowledge guides the generation of diverse validation examples, targeted prompt refinement, and comprehensive quality assessments. Experiments on GSM8K and Big-Bench Hard show that MR.PEA outperforms existing baselines, achieving an average performance gain of 7.4% with an optimization cost as low as $0.01 per task.</p>","absKo":"<p>Prompt optimizationмқҖ large language models (LLMs)мқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•өмӢ¬м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҠ” мў…мў… л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° labeled dataм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. self-supervised methodлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„° мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ мӨ„мқҙм§Җл§Ң, мөңм Ғнҷ”мқҳ лӘЁнҳём„ұмқҙлӮҳ лҶ’мқҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙлқјлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ мһ…л Ҙл§ҢмңјлЎң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” self-supervised prompt optimization frameworkмқё Meta-Reasoning Prompt Engineering Agent (MR.PEA)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. MR.PEAлҠ” meta-reasoningмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ л¬ём ң н•ҙкІ° м „лһөкіј нҸүк°Җ кё°мӨҖмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң task-specific knowledgeлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬м¶•н•ҳкі , мқҙн•ҙлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ҙ мҷёл¶Җ м •ліҙлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмғүн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м§ҖмӢқмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң validation example мғқм„ұ, н‘ңм Ғнҷ”лҗң prompt refinement, к·ёлҰ¬кі  нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё н’Ҳм§Ҳ нҸүк°ҖлҘј мқҙлҒҲлӢӨ. GSM8KмҷҖ Big-Bench Hardм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ MR.PEAк°Җ кё°мЎҙ baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, taskлӢ№ $0.01мқҳ лӮ®мқҖ мөңм Ғнҷ” л№„мҡ©мңјлЎң нҸүк·  7.4%мқҳ м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66755","en":"Numina-Lean-Agent: An Open and General Agentic Reasoning System for Formal Mathematics","ko":"Numina-Lean-Agent: нҳ•мӢқ мҲҳн•ҷмқ„ мң„н•ң к°ңл°©нҳ• лІ”мҡ© Agentic м¶”лЎ  мӢңмҠӨн…ң","authors":"Junqi Liu, Zihao Zhou, Zekai Zhu, Marco Dos Santos, Weikun He, jiawei liu, Yunzhou Xie, Junqiao Zhao, Qiufeng Wang, Lihong Zhi, Jia LI, Wenda Li","pos":"#1608","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0bTEd4LpQr","abs":"<p>Agentic systems have recently become the dominant paradigm for formal theorem proving, achieving strong performance by coordinating multiple models and tools. However, existing approaches often rely on task-specific pipelines and trained formal provers, limiting their flexibility and reproducibility. In this paper, we propose the paradigm that directly uses a general coding agent as a formal math reasoner. This paradigm is motivated by (1) A general coding agent provides a natural interface for diverse reasoning tasks beyond proving, (2) Performance can be improved by simply replacing the underlying base model, without training., and (3) MCP enables flexible extension and autonomous calling of specialized tools, avoiding complex design.  Based on this paradigm, we introduce \\textbf{Numina-Lean-Agent}, which combines Claude Code with Numina-Lean-MCP to enable autonomous interaction with Lean, retrieval of relevant theorems, informal proving and auxiliary reasoning tools. Using Claude Opus 4.5 as the base model, Numina-Lean-Agent solves all problems in Putnam 2025 (12/12), matching the best closed-source system. Beyond benchmark evaluation, we further demonstrate its generality by interacting with mathematicians to successfully formalize the BrascampвҖ“Lieb theorem.</p>","absKo":"<p>Agentic systemмқҖ мөңк·ј нҳ•мӢқм Ғ м •лҰ¬ мҰқлӘ…м—җм„ң м§Җл°°м Ғмқё нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙ лҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, м—¬лҹ¬ лӘЁлҚёкіј лҸ„кө¬лҘј мЎ°мңЁн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ task-specific pipelineкіј н•ҷмҠөлҗң formal proverм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„ мң м—°м„ұкіј мһ¬нҳ„м„ұмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лІ”мҡ© coding agentлҘј formal math reasonerлЎң м§Ғм ‘ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҖ (1) лІ”мҡ© coding agentк°Җ мҰқлӘ…м—җ көӯн•ңлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң м¶”лЎ  мһ‘м—…мқ„ мң„н•ң мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ мқён„°нҺҳмқҙмҠӨлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳкі , (2) кё°л°ҳ base modelмқ„ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ көҗмІҙн•ҳлҠ” кІғл§ҢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠө м—Ҷмқҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, (3) MCPк°Җ ліөмһЎн•ң м„Өкі„ м—Ҷмқҙ specialized toolмқҳ мң м—°н•ң нҷ•мһҘкіј мһҗмңЁ нҳём¶ңмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җм—җ мқҳн•ҙ лҸҷкё° л¶Җм—¬лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{Numina-Lean-Agent}лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” Claude CodeмҷҖ Numina-Lean-MCPлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳм—¬ Leanкіјмқҳ мһҗмңЁм Ғ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©, кҙҖл Ё м •лҰ¬ кІҖмғү, informal proving, ліҙмЎ° м¶”лЎ  лҸ„кө¬ мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. base modelлЎң Claude Opus 4.5лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, Numina-Lean-AgentлҠ” Putnam 2025мқҳ лӘЁл“  л¬ём ң(12/12)лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳм—¬ мөңкі мқҳ closed-source systemкіј лҸҷлҘ мқ„ мқҙлЈ¬лӢӨ. лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬ нҸүк°ҖлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҲҳн•ҷмһҗл“Өкіј мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ BrascampвҖ“Lieb theoremмқҳ formalizationм—җ м„ұкіөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ к·ё мқјл°ҳм„ұлҸ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62369","en":"OpenIKLR: Bridging the Reasoning Gap in Open-World Scenarios via Iterative Premise Completion","ko":"OpenIKLR: Iterative Premise CompletionмңјлЎң open-world мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨмқҳ reasoning gap мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Ye Mo, Chuan Zhou, Fengxiang Cheng, Jialin Yu, Fenrong Liu, Liangming Pan, Sheng Zhou, Haoxuan Li, Zhouchen Lin, Phil Torr","pos":"#1610","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=hEcxsQkZpW","abs":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs) demonstrate remarkable performance across various natural language processing tasks but struggle with complex logical reasoning, particularly in real-world settings.  Existing research is largely confined to the closed-world assumption, which posits that all premises required for reasoning are explicitly provided.  However, real-world tasks frequently exhibit open-world characteristics, where the provided information is insufficient to infer a conclusion due to missing premises or implicit commonsense knowledge.  To address this limitation, we propose OpenIKLR, an Open-world Incomplete-Knowledge-aware Logical Reasoning framework that integrates symbolic logic solvers with LLMs.  OpenIKLR first translates natural language into symbolic representations to precisely pinpoint reasoning gaps via a logical solver.  It then iteratively generate a minimal set of necessary missing premises using LLMs.  To ensure these additional premises are both logically sound and factually accurate, we introduce a dual-verification process: logic verification via the solver and fact verification via the LLMs. Extensive experiments demonstrate that OpenIKLR consistently outperforms existing logical reasoning and RAG baselines across multiple backbones and real-world datasets, highlighting its efficacy in handling incomplete information. The code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/ICML26_22398-B5BF/.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs)лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң natural language processing taskм—җм„ң лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, нҠ№нһҲ мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңмқҳ ліөмһЎн•ң logical reasoningм—җлҠ” м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң closed-world assumptionм—җ лЁёл¬јлҹ¬ мһҲлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” м¶”лЎ м—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң лӘЁл“  premiseк°Җ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨкі  к°Җм •н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ң taskлҠ” мў…мў… open-world нҠ№м„ұмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мЈјм–ҙм§„ м •ліҙл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” лҲ„лқҪлҗң premiseлӮҳ м•”л¬өм Ғмқё commonsense knowledge л•Ңл¬ём—җ кІ°лЎ мқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкё°м—җ л¶Ҳм¶©л¶„н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” symbolic logic solverмҷҖ LLMмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ң Open-world Incomplete-Knowledge-aware Logical Reasoning frameworkмқё OpenIKLRмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. OpenIKLRмқҖ лЁјм Җ мһҗм—°м–ҙлҘј symbolic representationмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳм—¬ logic solverлҘј нҶөн•ҙ reasoning gapмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ LLMмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ лҲ„лқҪ premise м§‘н•©мқ„ л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м¶”к°Җ premiseк°Җ л…јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎңлҸ„ нғҖлӢ№н•ҳкі  мӮ¬мӢӨм ҒмңјлЎңлҸ„ м •нҷ•н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” dual-verification processлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, solverлҘј нҶөн•ң logic verificationкіј LLMмқ„ нҶөн•ң fact verificationмқҙлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ OpenIKLRмқҙ м—¬лҹ¬ backboneкіј real-world dataset м „л°ҳм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ logical reasoning л°Ҹ RAG baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, л¶Ҳмҷ„м „н•ң м •ліҙлҘј лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” лҚ° мһҲм–ҙ к·ё нҡЁмҡ©мқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/ICML26_22398-B5BF/ м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61809","en":"OptProver: Bridging Olympiad and Optimization through Continual Training in Formal Theorem Proving","ko":"OptProver: нҳ•мӢқ м •лҰ¬ мҰқлӘ…мқҳ м§ҖмҶҚ н•ҷмҠөмңјлЎң мҳ¬лҰјн”јм•„л“ңмҷҖ мөңм Ғнҷ” м—°кІ°н•ҳкё°","authors":"Chenyi Li, Yanchen Nie, Zhenyu Ming, Gong Zhang, Kun Yuan, Zaiwen Wen","pos":"#1611","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mkHp4ZW01l","abs":"<p>Recent advances in formal theorem proving have focused on Olympiad-level mathematics, leaving undergraduate domains largely unexplored. Optimization, fundamental to machine learning, operations research, and scientific computing, remains underserved by existing provers. Its reliance on domain-specific formalisms (convexity, optimality conditions, and algorithmic analysis) creates significant distribution shift, making naive domain transfer ineffective. We present OptProver, a trained model that achieves robust transfer from Olympiad to undergraduate optimization. Starting from a strong Olympiad-level prover, our pipeline mitigates distribution shift through two key innovations. First, we employ large-scale optimization-focused data curation via expert iteration. Second, we introduce a specialized preference learning objective that integrates perplexity-weighted optimization with a mechanism to penalize valid but non-progressing proof steps. This not only addresses distribution shifts but also guides the search toward efficient trajectories. To enable rigorous evaluation, we construct a novel benchmark in Lean 4 focused on optimization. On this benchmark, OptProver achieves state-of-the-art Pass@1 and Pass@32 among comparably sized models while maintaining competitive performance on general theorem-proving tasks, demonstrating effective domain transfer without catastrophic forgetting.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј formal theorem provingмқҳ м§„м „мқҖ Olympiad мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ мҲҳн•ҷм—җ м§‘мӨ‘лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”кі , н•ҷл¶Җ мҲҳмӨҖ лҸ„л©”мқёмқҖ нҒ¬кІҢ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. machine learning, operations research, scientific computingмқҳ к·јк°„мқё optimizationмқҖ кё°мЎҙ proverл“Өмқҳ м§Җмӣҗмқҙ м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. convexity, optimality condition, algorithmic analysisмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ лҸ„л©”мқё нҠ№нҷ” formalismм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқҖ нҒ° distribution shiftлҘј м•јкё°н•ҳм—¬, лӢЁмҲңн•ң лҸ„л©”мқё м „мқҙлЎңлҠ” нҡЁкіјлҘј ліҙкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Olympiadм—җм„ң н•ҷл¶Җ optimizationмңјлЎңмқҳ кІ¬кі н•ң transferлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” н•ҷмҠөлҗң лӘЁлҚё OptProverлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. к°•л Ҙн•ң Olympiad мҲҳмӨҖ proverм—җм„ң м¶ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ pipelineмқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ нҳҒмӢ мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ distribution shiftлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, expert iterationмқ„ нҶөн•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ optimization мӨ‘мӢ¬ data curationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, validн•ҳм§Җл§Ң м§„н–үмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” proof stepм—җ нҺҳл„җнӢ°лҘј л¶Җкіјн•ҳлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳкіј perplexity-weighted optimizationмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ң нҠ№нҷ” preference learning objectiveлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” distribution shiftлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј, нғҗмғүмқ„ лҚ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё trajectoryлЎң мқҙлҒҲлӢӨ. м—„л°Җн•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” optimizationм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳ Lean 4 кё°л°ҳмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ benchmarkлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ benchmarkм—җм„ң OptProverлҠ” мң мӮ¬н•ң к·ңлӘЁмқҳ лӘЁлҚёл“Ө к°ҖмҡҙлҚ° state-of-the-art Pass@1кіј Pass@32лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мқјл°ҳ theorem proving кіјм ңм—җм„ң кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©°, м№ҳлӘ…м Ғмқё л§қк°Ғ м—Ҷмқҙ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё лҸ„л©”мқё м „мқҙлҘј ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64845","en":"Out-of-Distribution Evaluation of Rule-Based and Strategic Reasoning in Chess Transformers","ko":"Chess Transformerм—җм„ң к·ңм№ҷ кё°л°ҳ л°Ҹ м „лһөм Ғ м¶”лЎ мқҳ Out-of-Distribution нҸүк°Җ","authors":"Anna MГ©szГЎros, Patrik Reizinger, Ferenc HuszГЎr","pos":"#1612","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=JFGUsQ68rG","abs":"<p>Modern decision transformers, trained similarly to LLMs, can achieve strong in-distribution performance in complex sequential domains like chess, but it remains unclear to what extent they reason systematically about rules and strategy. We study the reasoning capabilities of a 270M-parameter chess transformer trained via behavior cloning on standard chess. To investigate its abilities, we construct out-of-distribution test sets ---including board states and variants never seen during training---designed to reveal failures of systematic generalization. Our analysis shows that the model exhibits robust rule-based reasoning, consistently generating legal moves in novel configurations, but its strategic reasoning is more limited. The model generates high-quality moves on curated OOD puzzles and shows basic strategy adaptation in full games. It underperforms symbolic AI algorithms that rely on explicit search, although the performance gap is smaller when playing against human users on Lichess. Moreover, the training dynamics reveals distinct phases in how the model learns to respect the fundamental constraints, suggesting an emergent compositional understanding of the game.</p>","absKo":"<p>LLMкіј мң мӮ¬н•ҳкІҢ н•ҷмҠөлҗң нҳ„лҢҖмқҳ decision transformerлҠ” chessмІҳлҹј ліөмһЎн•ң sequential domainм—җм„ң к°•н•ң in-distribution м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, к·ңм№ҷкіј м „лһөмқ„ м–јл§ҲлӮҳ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң reasoningн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ chessм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ behavior cloningмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң 2м–ө 7мІңл§Ң parameter chess transformerмқҳ reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ н•ң лІҲлҸ„ ліё м Ғ м—ҶлҠ” board stateмҷҖ variantлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҙ systematic generalizationмқҳ мӢӨнҢЁлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң out-of-distribution test setмқ„ кө¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ configurationм—җм„ңлҸ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ legal moveлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ”, к°•кұҙн•ң rule-based reasoningмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, strategic reasoningмқҖ лҚ” м ңн•ңм ҒмқҙлқјлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚёмқҖ м„ лі„н•ң OOD puzzleм—җм„ң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ moveлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , full gameм—җм„ңлҠ” кё°ліём Ғмқё strategy adaptationлҸ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лӘ…мӢңм Ғ searchм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” symbolic AI algorithmліҙлӢӨлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқҙ лӮ®м•ҳмңјл©°, лӢӨл§Ң Lichessм—җм„ң human userлҘј мғҒлҢҖлЎң н”Ңл Ҳмқҙн•  л•ҢлҠ” м„ұлҠҘ кІ©м°Ёк°Җ лҚ” мһ‘м•ҳлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң training dynamicsлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ fundamental constraintлҘј л”°лҘҙлҠ” лІ•мқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кіјм •м—җм„ң м„ңлЎң кө¬л¶„лҗҳлҠ” phaseлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, кІҢмһ„м—җ лҢҖн•ң emergent compositional understandingмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62536","en":"MINIF2F-DAFNY: LLM-Guided Mathematical Theorem Proving via Auto-Active Verification","ko":"MINIF2F-DAFNY: Auto-Active Verification кё°л°ҳ LLM-guided мҲҳн•ҷ м •лҰ¬ мҰқлӘ…","authors":"Mantas Baksys, Sean B Holden, Olivier Bouissou, Stefan Zetzsche","pos":"#1703","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=fj5Ec6g7Ez","abs":"<p>LLMs excel at reasoning, but validating their steps remains challenging. Formal verification offers a solution through mechanically checkable proofs. Interactive theorem provers (ITPs) dominate mathematical reasoning but require detailed low-level proof steps, while auto-active verifiers offer automation but focus on software verification. Recent work has begun bridging this divide by evaluating LLMs for software verification in ITPs, but the complementary directionвҖ”LLMs for mathematical theorem proving in auto-active verifiersвҖ”remains unexplored. We present MINIF2F-DAFNY, the first translation of the widely-used mathematical benchmark miniF2F to an auto-active verifier: Dafny. We find that Dafny's automation alone solves 39-44% of problems with empty proofs, whereas many require substantial proof guidance in ITPs. For remaining problems, we evaluate 7 off-the-shelf LLMs, achieving 55.7% success with the best model (Claude Sonnet 4.5) using modest resources. These results demonstrate effective division of labor: LLMs provide high-level guidance while automation handles low-level details.</p>","absKo":"<p>LLMмқҖ reasoningм—җм„ң лӣ°м–ҙлӮҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё лӢЁкі„лҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. Formal verificationмқҖ mechanically checkable proofлҘј нҶөн•ҙ н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. Interactive theorem prover (ITP)лҠ” мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ reasoningм—җм„ң мЈјлҘҳмқҙм§Җл§Ң мғҒм„ён•ң м ҖмҲҳмӨҖ proof stepмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, auto-active verifierлҠ” мһҗлҸҷнҷ”лҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң software verificationм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” ITPм—җм„ң software verificationмқ„ мң„н•ң LLM нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мӢңмһ‘н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё мғҒліҙм Ғ л°©н–Ҙмқё auto-active verifierм—җм„ңмқҳ мҲҳн•ҷ theorem provingмқ„ мң„н•ң LLM нҷңмҡ©мқҖ м•„м§Ғ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” мҲҳн•ҷ benchmark miniF2FлҘј auto-active verifierмқё DafnyлЎң лІҲм—ӯн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ лІ„м „мқё MINIF2F-DAFNYлҘј аӨӘаҘҚаӨ°аӨёаҘҚаӨӨаҘҒаӨӨн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Dafnyмқҳ мһҗлҸҷнҷ”л§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ л№Ҳ proofлЎң 39-44%мқҳ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, л§ҺмқҖ л¬ём ңлҠ” ITPм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң proof guidanceлҘј н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. лӮЁмқҖ л¬ём ңл“Өм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ 7к°ңмқҳ off-the-shelf LLMмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, м ҒлӢ№н•ң мһҗмӣҗмңјлЎң best modelмқё Claude Sonnet 4.5лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң 55.7%мқҳ м„ұкіөлҘ мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё м—ӯн•  л¶„лӢҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. мҰү, LLMмқҖ кі мҲҳмӨҖ guidanceлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳкі  мһҗлҸҷнҷ”лҠ” м ҖмҲҳмӨҖ м„ёл¶ҖмӮ¬н•ӯмқ„ мІҳлҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60844","en":"HERMES: Towards Efficient and Verifiable Mathematical Reasoning in LLMs","ko":"HERMES: LLMмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ мқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Azim Ospanov, Zijin Feng, Jiacheng Sun, Haoli Bai, SHEN XIN, Farzan Farnia","pos":"#1804","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=w7BZcUc0fJ","abs":"<p>Informal mathematics has been central to modern large language model (LLM) reasoning, offering flexibility and efficient construction of arguments. However, purely informal reasoning is prone to logical gaps and subtle errors that are difficult to detect and correct. In contrast, formal theorem proving provides rigorous, verifiable mathematical reasoning, where each inference step is checked by a trusted compiler, but lacks the exploratory freedom of informal problem-solving. This mismatch leaves current LLM-based math agents without a principled way to combine the strengths of both paradigms. In this work, we introduce Hermes, the first tool-assisted agent that explicitly interleaves informal reasoning with formally verified proofs in Lean. The framework performs intermediate formal checking to prevent reasoning drift and a memory module for proof continuity across multi-step reasoning chains, enabling both exploration and verification. We evaluate Hermes on four challenging mathematical reasoning benchmarks using LLMs of varying parameter scales, from small models to state-of-the-art systems. Across all settings, Hermes reliably improves the reasoning accuracy of base models while substantially reducing reasoning token usage and computational cost compared to reward-based approaches. On difficult datasets such as AIME and HARDMath2, Hermes@1 achieves up to a 40% accuracy improvement while using 80% fewer total inference FLOPs. When scaled at test time, Hermes@5 boosts accuracy further by 20%.</p>","absKo":"<p>л№„кіөмӢқ мҲҳн•ҷмқҖ нҳ„лҢҖ large language model (LLM) м¶”лЎ мқҳ н•өмӢ¬мңјлЎң, мң м—°м„ұкіј нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё л…јмҰқ кө¬м„ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҲңмҲҳн•ң л№„кіөмӢқ м¶”лЎ мқҖ л…јлҰ¬м Ғ кіөл°ұкіј лҜём„ён•ң мҳӨлҘҳм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нғҗм§Җн•ҳкі  мҲҳм •н•ҳкё°к°Җ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. л°ҳлҢҖлЎң formal theorem provingмқҖ к°Ғ inference stepмқҙ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” compilerм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кІҖмҰқлҗҳлҠ” м—„л°Җн•ҳкі  кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, л№„кіөмӢқм Ғ л¬ём ң н•ҙкІ°мқҙ м§ҖлӢҢ нғҗмғүм Ғ мһҗмң лҠ” л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ LLM кё°л°ҳ мҲҳн•ҷ agentк°Җ л‘җ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҳ мһҘм җмқ„ кІ°н•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мӣҗм№ҷм Ғ л°©лІ•мқ„ к°–м§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” HermesлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. HermesлҠ” informal reasoningкіј Leanм—җм„ң formally verified proofлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң көҗм°Ё(interleave)н•ҳлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ tool-assisted agentмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkлҠ” reasoning driftлҘј л°©м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң intermediate formal checkingкіј, multi-step reasoning chain м „л°ҳм—җм„ң proof continuityлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” memory moduleмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ нғҗмғүкіј кІҖмҰқмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң parameter scaleмқҳ LLMмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ, мҶҢнҳ• лӘЁлҚёл¶Җн„° state-of-the-art systemк№Ңм§Җ, л„Ө к°ңмқҳ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ мҲҳн•ҷ м¶”лЎ  benchmarkм—җм„ң HermesлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁл“  м„Өм •м—җм„ң HermesлҠ” base modelмқҳ м¶”лЎ  м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, reward-based approachм—җ л№„н•ҙ reasoning token мӮ¬мҡ©лҹүкіј кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. AIMEмҷҖ HARDMath2 к°ҷмқҖ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ datasetм—җм„ңлҠ” Hermes@1мқҙ мҙқ inference FLOPмқ„ 80% лҚң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ң мөңлҢҖ 40%мқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. test-time scaling мӢң Hermes@5лҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң 20% лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬лҰ°лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64912","en":"Implicit Intelligence - Evaluating Agents on What Users DonвҖҷt Say","ko":"м•”л¬өм Ғ м§ҖлҠҘ - мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗк°Җ л§җн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң Agent нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё°","authors":"Ved Sirdeshmukh, Marc Wetter","pos":"#1811","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=IhdGi9qknL","abs":"<p>Real-world requests to AI agents are fundamentally underspecified. Natural human communication relies on shared context and unstated constraints that speakers expect listeners to infer. Current agentic benchmarks test explicit instruction-following but fail to evaluate whether agents can reason about implicit requirements spanning accessibility needs, privacy boundaries, catastrophic risks, and contextual constraints. We present <strong>Implicit Intelligence</strong>, an evaluation framework testing whether AI agents can move beyond prompt-following to become genuine goal-fulfillers, paired with <strong>Agent-as-a-World (AaW)</strong>, a harness where interactive worlds are defined in human-readable YAML files and simulated by language models. Our scenarios feature apparent simplicity in user requests, hidden complexity in correct solutions, and discoverability of constraints through environmental exploration. Evaluating 16 frontier and open-weight models across 205 scenarios, we find that even the best-performing model achieves only 48.3% scenario pass rate, revealing substantial room for improvement in bridging the gap between literal instruction-following and human-like contextual reasoning.</p>","absKo":"<p>AI agentм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨм ң мҡ”мІӯмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м¶©л¶„нһҲ кө¬мІҙнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ мқёк°„ мқҳмӮ¬мҶҢнҶөмқҖ нҷ”мһҗл“Өмқҙ мІӯмһҗк°Җ м¶”лЎ н•ҙ мЈјкё°лҘј кё°лҢҖн•ҳлҠ” кіөмң лҗң л§ҘлқҪкіј лӘ…мӢңлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ м ңм•Ҫм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ agentic benchmarkлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғ instruction-followingмқ„ мӢңн—ҳн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, agentк°Җ м ‘к·јм„ұ мҡ”кө¬, privacy boundary, catastrophe risk, к·ёлҰ¬кі  л¬ёл§Ҙм Ғ м ңм•Ҫм—җ кұём№ң м•”л¬өм Ғ мҡ”кө¬мӮ¬н•ӯмқ„ м¶”лЎ н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§ҖлҠ” нҸүк°Җн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” AI agentк°Җ лӢЁмҲңн•ң prompt-followingмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ м§„м •н•ң goal-fulfillerк°Җ лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§ҖлҘј мӢңн—ҳн•ҳлҠ” нҸүк°Җ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ <strong>Implicit Intelligence</strong>лҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , мқҙм—җ лҚ”н•ҙ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©м Ғ м„ёкі„к°Җ мӮ¬лһҢмқҙ мқҪмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” YAML нҢҢмқјлЎң м •мқҳлҗҳкі  language modelм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳлҗҳлҠ” harnessмқё <strong>Agent-as-a-World (AaW)</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨлҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мҡ”мІӯмқҳ кІүліҙкё° лӢЁмҲңн•Ё, м •лӢө мҶ”лЈЁм…ҳмқҳ мҲЁкІЁм§„ ліөмһЎм„ұ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  нҷҳкІҪ нғҗмғүмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” нҠ№м„ұмқ„ к°Җм§„лӢӨ. 205к°ң мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң 16к°ңмқҳ frontier л°Ҹ open-weight modelмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, мөңкі  м„ұлҠҘ лӘЁлҚёмЎ°м°Ё scenario pass rateк°Җ 48.3%м—җ к·ёміҗ, л¬ёмһҗ к·ёлҢҖлЎңмқҳ instruction-followingкіј мқёк°„кіј мң мӮ¬н•ң л¬ёл§Ҙм Ғ м¶”лЎ  мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ м—¬м „нһҲ мғҒлӢ№н•ң к°ңм„  м—¬м§Җк°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64524","en":"From Patches to Plans: Reasoning Distillation for Repository-Level Program Repair","ko":"нҢЁм№ҳм—җм„ң кі„нҡҚмңјлЎң: м ҖмһҘмҶҢ мҲҳмӨҖ н”„лЎңк·ёлһЁ ліөкө¬лҘј мң„н•ң м¶”лЎ  мҰқлҘҳ","authors":"Chenglin Li, Yisen Xu, Zehao Wang, Shin Hwei Tan, Tse-Hsun (Peter) Chen","pos":"#1900","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=MjGhDpCtF9","abs":"<p>Repository-level automated program repair (APR) requires long-horizon reasoning over interdependent decisions. However, most LLM-based approaches reconstruct repair reasoning independently for each issue, failing to reuse successful patterns from prior repairs, even though real-world repositories contain many related issues with shared structure or constraints. Existing methods typically rely on forward exploration, which operates under outcome uncertainty, incurs substantial inference-time overhead, and can drift from the final correct patch. We propose Conditional Reasoning Distillation (ConRAD), which leverages in-repository resolved issues by reconstructing repair reasoning backward from verified patches and distilling outcome-consistent, stage-wise repair reasoning plans. Injected at inference time, these plans guide fault localization and patch generation, replacing open-ended exploration with constrained inference without fine-tuning or search. On SWE-Bench Lite, ConRAD improves Pass@1 by 10.4\\% (GPT-4o), 8.6\\% (DeepSeek-V3), and 10.3\\% (GPT-5), demonstrating a scalable inference-time alternative to forward exploration for long-horizon APR.</p>","absKo":"<p>repository-level automated program repair(APR)лҠ” мғҒнҳё мқҳмЎҙм Ғмқё мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң long-horizon reasoningмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ LLM кё°л°ҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ к°Ғ issueл§ҲлӢӨ repair reasoningмқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, мӢӨм ң repositoryм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” мң мӮ¬н•ң кө¬мЎ°лӮҳ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” кҙҖл Ё issueл“Өм—җм„ң м„ұкіөм Ғмқё нҢЁн„ҙмқ„ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң forward explorationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” кІ°кіј л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұ н•ҳм—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳкі , мғҒлӢ№н•ң inference-time overheadлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳл©°, мөңмў…м ҒмңјлЎң мҳ¬л°”лҘё patchм—җм„ң лІ—м–ҙлӮ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” repository лӮҙм—җм„ң н•ҙкІ°лҗң issueлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ кІҖмҰқлҗң patchлЎңл¶Җн„° repair reasoningмқ„ backwardлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , кІ°кіјмҷҖ мқјкҙҖлҗң stage-wise repair reasoning planмқ„ distillн•ҳлҠ” Conditional Reasoning Distillation (ConRAD)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. inference timeм—җ мЈјмһ…лҗҳлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң planмқҖ fault localizationкіј patch generationмқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳм—¬, fine-tuningмқҙлӮҳ search м—Ҷмқҙ open-ended explorationмқ„ м ңм•Ҫлҗң inferenceлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ңлӢӨ. SWE-Bench Liteм—җм„ң ConRADлҠ” Pass@1мқ„ GPT-4oм—җм„ң 10.4\\%, DeepSeek-V3м—җм„ң 8.6\\%, GPT-5м—җм„ң 10.3\\% н–ҘмғҒмӢңмјң, long-horizon APRмқ„ мң„н•ң forward explorationмқҳ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң inference-time лҢҖм•Ҳмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61431","en":"Embodied Task Planning via Graph-Informed Action Generation with Large Lanaguage Model","ko":"Large Language Modelмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң Graph-Informed Action Generation кё°л°ҳ Embodied Task Planning","authors":"Xiang Li, Ning Yan, Masood Mortazavi","pos":"#1908","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qBuZDNyQCM","abs":"While Large Language Models (LLMs) have demonstrated strong zero-shot reasoning capabilities, their deployment as embodied agents still faces fundamental challenges in long-horizon planning. Unlike open-ended text generation, embodied agents must decompose high-level intent into actionable sub-goals while strictly adhering to the logic of a dynamic, observed environment. Standard LLM planners frequently fail to maintain strategy coherence over extended horizons due to context window limitation or hallucinate transitions that violate constraints. We propose GiG, a novel planning framework that structures embodied agents' memory using a $\\underline{G}$raph-$\\underline{i}$n-$\\underline{G}$raph architecture.  Our approach employs a Graph Neural Network (GNN) to encode environmental states into embeddings, organizing these embeddings into action-connected execution trace graphs within a latent memory bank. By clustering these graph embeddings, the framework enables retrieval of structure-aware priors, allowing agents to ground current decisions in relevant past structural patterns. Furthermore, we introduce a novel bounded lookahead module that leverages symbolic transition logic to enhance the agents' planning capabilities through the grounded action projection.  We evaluate our framework on three embodied planning benchmarksвҖ”Robotouille Synchronous, Robotouille Asynchronous, and ALFWorld. Our method outperforms state-of-the-art baselines, achieving Pass@1 performance gains of up to 22\\% on Robotouille Synchronous, 37\\% on Asynchronous, and 15\\% on ALFWorld with comparable or lower computational cost.","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models(LLMs)к°Җ к°•л Ҙн•ң zero-shot reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, embodied agentлЎң л°°м№ҳлҗ  л•ҢлҠ” long-horizon planningм—җм„ң м—¬м „нһҲ к·јліём Ғмқё лҸ„м „м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. м—ҙлҰ° н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мғқм„ұкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, embodied agentлҠ” лҸҷм Ғмқё кҙҖмёЎ нҷҳкІҪмқҳ л…јлҰ¬лҘј м—„кІ©нһҲ л”°лҘҙл©ҙм„ң кі мҲҳмӨҖ мқҳлҸ„лҘј мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң sub-goalлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ LLM plannerлҠ” context windowмқҳ н•ңкі„лЎң мқён•ҙ кёҙ horizonм—җм„ң м „лһөм Ғ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, м ңм•Ҫмқ„ мң„л°ҳн•ҳлҠ” м „мқҙ(transition)лҘј нҷҳк°Ғн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ мһҰлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” GiGлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. GiGлҠ” $\\underline{G}$raph-$\\underline{i}$n-$\\underline{G}$raph м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ embodied agentмқҳ memoryлҘј кө¬мЎ°нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ planning frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ Graph Neural Network (GNN)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ нҷҳкІҪ мғҒнғңлҘј embeddingмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳкі , мқҙлҹ¬н•ң embeddingмқ„ latent memory bank лӮҙмқҳ action-connected execution trace graphлЎң мЎ°м§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ graph embeddingмқ„ clusteringн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, frameworkлҠ” structure-aware priorлҘј кІҖмғүн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳл©°, agentк°Җ нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ кІ°м •мқ„ кҙҖл Ё мһҲлҠ” кіјкұ°мқҳ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ нҢЁн„ҙм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” symbolic transition logicмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ grounded action projectionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ agentмқҳ planning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ bounded lookahead moduleмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Robotouille Synchronous, Robotouille Asynchronous, ALFWorldмқҳ м„ё к°Җм§Җ embodied planning benchmarkм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, мң мӮ¬н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҚ” лӮ®мқҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мңјлЎң Robotouille Synchronousм—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ 22\\%, Asynchronousм—җм„ң 37\\%, ALFWorldм—җм„ң 15\\%мқҳ Pass@1 м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60593","en":"Efficient Multi-Agent Reasoning via Confidence-Guided Adaptive Debate","ko":"мӢ лў°лҸ„ мң лҸ„ м Ғмқ‘нҳ• нҶ лЎ мқ„ нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ л©ҖнӢ° м—җмқҙм „нҠё м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Seungdong Yoa, Ye Seul Sim, Suhee Yoon, Sanghyu Yoon, Dongmin Kim, Soonyoung Lee, Bumsoo Kim, Junhyun Lee","pos":"#1911","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=yh7LGBhFmr","abs":"<p>Multi-agent debate has shown promise for improving the reasoning of large language models, yet recent theory suggests its benefits are highly regime-dependent. While interaction can amplify informative signals under corrective conditions, symmetric debate dynamics are neutral in expectation, often making majority voting preferable. We reconcile these views by arguing that debate is effective only when invoked at the right time and with appropriate structure. Based on this insight, we propose LASE, a leader-centric multi-agent debate framework that selectively engages interaction only in non-neutral regimes. LASE introduces an asymmetric leaderвҖ“supporter architecture that enables directed information flow and selective signal amplification, while defaulting to simple aggregation otherwise. Experiments across diverse reasoning benchmarks show that LASE achieves multi-agent-level performance with near single-agent token cost, substantially improving efficiency over static debate and voting baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>multi-agent debateлҠ” лҢҖнҳ• language modelмқҳ reasoningмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мң л§қн•Ёмқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мөңк·ј мқҙлЎ мқҖ к·ё мқҙм җмқҙ л§Өмҡ° regime-dependentн•ҳлӢӨкі  мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҖ corrective conditionм—җм„ң informative signalмқ„ мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖм№ӯм Ғ debate dynamicsлҠ” кё°лҢҖк°’ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң мӨ‘лҰҪм Ғмқҙм–ҙм„ң, лҢҖмІҙлЎң majority votingмқҙ лҚ” м„ нҳёлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” debateк°Җ м Ғм Ҳн•ң мӢңм җм—җ м Ғм Ҳн•ң кө¬мЎ°мҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ нҳём¶ңлҗ  л•Ңм—җл§Ң нҡЁкіјм ҒмқҙлқјлҠ” мЈјмһҘмңјлЎң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм җмқ„ мЎ°нҷ”мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” neutralн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ regimeм—җм„ңл§Ң м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” leader-centric multi-agent debate frameworkмқё LASEлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. LASEлҠ” directed information flowмҷҖ м„ нғқм Ғ signal amplificationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” л№„лҢҖм№ӯм Ғ leader-supporter architectureлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳл©°, к·ё мҷёмқҳ кІҪмҡ°м—җлҠ” кё°ліём ҒмңјлЎң лӢЁмҲң aggregationм—җ л§ЎкёҙлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ LASEк°Җ кұ°мқҳ single-agent мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ token costлЎң multi-agent мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, static debate л°Ҹ voting baselineліҙлӢӨ нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61111","en":"Diversity Over Frequency: Rethinking Tool Use in Visual Chain-of-Thought Agents","ko":"л№ҲлҸ„ліҙлӢӨ лӢӨм–‘м„ұ: Visual Chain-of-Thought Agentмқҳ Tool Use мһ¬кі ","authors":"Dong-Hee Kim, Reuben Tan, DONGHYUN KIM","pos":"#2012","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=taH7v2Qy8M","abs":"<p>Visual agents employ tools such as zoom-in cropping within visual chains of thought to access fine-grained details. Prior work has primarily demonstrated the effectiveness of these tools on visual search tasks, leaving their applicability to more diverse and complex visual problems underexplored. In this paper, we move beyond visual search and study challenging visual tasks that require advanced spatial understanding and reasoning, such as 3D spatial reasoning, where agents must not only crop or zoom in on relevant regions but also understand how these local details relate to the global context. We identify a tool-use collapse phenomenon: models progressively stop using tools while still achieving higher task accuracy. Moreover, we observe a clear asymmetry: (i) completely eliminating tool use degrades performance, whereas (ii) incentivizing tool use yields only marginal gains despite substantially increasing usage. We find that vanilla training and rewarding tool-use encouragement reduce rollout diversity during training, explaining why higher tool-use does not yield stronger reasoning performance. Motivated by these findings, we encourage diverse rollout exploration by adding an entropy-regularization term to the reinforcement learning objective, which results in the best performance despite tool usage gradually declining during training. Overall, our findings suggest a training-time view of tools as scaffolding, where broader exploration in both text and vision shapes representations that improve despite tool-use collapse.</p>","absKo":"<p>Visual agentsлҠ” м„ёл¶Җ м •ліҙлҘј м ‘к·јн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ visual chain of thought лӮҙм—җм„ң zoom-in croppingкіј к°ҷмқҖ toolsлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң toolsмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј visual search taskм—җм„ң мһ…мҰқн•ҙ мҷ”мңјл©°, лҚ” лӢӨм–‘н•ҳкі  ліөмһЎн•ң visual problemм—җм„ңмқҳ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҖ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” visual searchлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ, 3D spatial reasoningкіј к°ҷмқҙ кі лҸ„нҷ”лҗң spatial understandingкіј reasoningмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” м–ҙл Өмҡҙ visual taskлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң taskм—җм„ң agentsлҠ” кҙҖл Ё мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ cropн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ zoom inн•ҳлҠ” кІғм—җ к·ём№ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі , мқҙлҹ¬н•ң local detailмқҙ global contextмҷҖ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м—°кІ°лҗҳлҠ”м§ҖлҸ„ мқҙн•ҙн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” tool-use collapse нҳ„мғҒмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. мҰү, лӘЁлҚёмқҖ task accuracyк°Җ лҚ” лҶ’м•„м§ҖлҠ” лҸҷм•Ҳм—җлҸ„ м җм°Ё tools мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ л©Ҳм¶ҳлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң лҡңл ·н•ң л№„лҢҖм№ӯм„ұмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ. (i) tool useлҘј мҷ„м „нһҲ м ңкұ°н•ҳл©ҙ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, (ii) tool useлҘј мһҘл Өн•ҳл©ҙ мӮ¬мҡ©лҹүмқҙ мғҒлӢ№нһҲ мҰқк°Җн•Ём—җлҸ„ м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқҖ лҜёлҜён•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” vanilla trainingкіј tool-use encouragementм—җ лҢҖн•ң rewardк°Җ training мӨ‘ rollout diversityлҘј к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮЁлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙкІғмқҙ мҷң лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ tool useк°Җ лҚ” к°•н•ң reasoning performanceлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§Җм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”м§ҖлҘј м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°ңкІ¬м—җ лҸҷкё°л¶Җм—¬лҘј л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” entropy-regularization termмқ„ reinforcement learning objectiveм—җ м¶”к°Җн•ҳм—¬ лӢӨм–‘н•ң rollout explorationмқ„ мһҘл Өн–Ҳмңјл©°, training лҸҷм•Ҳ tool usageк°Җ м җм°Ё к°җмҶҢн•Ём—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  к°ҖмһҘ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” toolsлҘј training-timeм—җм„ң scaffoldingмңјлЎң ліҙлҠ” кҙҖм җмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ҳл©°, textмҷҖ vision лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ңмқҳ лҚ” л„“мқҖ explorationмқҙ tool-use collapseк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” representationsлҘј нҳ•м„ұн•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65266","en":"Beyond Mode Collapse: Distribution Matching for Diverse Reasoning","ko":"Mode CollapseлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ң: лӢӨм–‘н•ң м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң л¶„нҸ¬ л§Өм№ӯ","authors":"Xiaozhe Li, Yang Li, Xinyu Fang, Shengyuan Ding, Peiji Li, Yongkang Chen, Yichuan Ma, TianYi Lyu, Linyang Li, Dahua Lin, Qipeng Guo, Qingwen Liu, Kai Chen","pos":"#2105","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FEmu30g4ts","abs":"<p>On-policy reinforcement learning methods like GRPO suffer from \\emph{mode collapse}: they exhibit reduced solution diversity, concentrating probability mass on a single solution once discovered and ceasing exploration of alternative strategies. We show this stems from reverse KL minimization's mode-seeking behavior, which reinforces the first high-reward trajectory found rather than maintaining a distribution over multiple diverse solutions. We propose DMPO (\\textbf{D}istribution-\\textbf{M}atching \\textbf{P}olicy \\textbf{O}ptimization), which prevents mode collapse through principled approximation of forward KL minimization. DMPO constructs a group-level target distribution over sampled trajectories proportional to their rewards, then aligns the policy distribution to this target. This provides mode-covering behavior without requiring sampling from the intractable global target distribution, enabling sustained exploration throughout training. We validate DMPO on NP-hard combinatorial optimization, where exponentially many feasible solutions exist but only a few approach optimalityвҖ”an ideal testbed for evaluating exploration. DMPO achieves {43.9\\% Quality Ratio on text-based NP-Bench (vs. GRPO's 40.1\\%)} and {43.1\\% on vision-based NP-Bench (vs. 38.4\\%)}вҖ”demonstrating 9\\% and 12\\% relative improvements respectively. These gains generalize to mathematical reasoning (+2.0\\%) and out-of-domain tasks (+2.3\\%), showing that diversity-preserving training enhances general reasoning capabilities across modalities. Our work establishes distribution matching as a practical, principled approach to preventing mode collapse in on-policy RL, with consistent quality improvements demonstrating sustained exploration across diverse reasoning tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>GRPOмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ on-policy reinforcement learning л°©лІ•мқҖ \\emph{mode collapse}лҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мҰү, н•ҙк°Җ л°ңкІ¬лҗҳл©ҙ probability massк°Җ лӢЁмқј solutionм—җ м§‘мӨ‘лҗҳкі  лҢҖм•Ҳ м „лһөм—җ лҢҖн•ң нғҗмғүмқҖ мӨ‘лӢЁлҗҳл©°, solution diversityк°Җ к°җмҶҢн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙкІғмқҙ reverse KL minimizationмқҳ mode-seeking behaviorм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗңлӢӨкі  ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҰү, м—¬лҹ¬ diverse solutionм—җ лҢҖн•ң л¶„нҸ¬лҘј мң м§Җн•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ мІҳмқҢ л°ңкІ¬н•ң high-reward trajectoryлҘј к°•нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” DMPO(\\textbf{D}istribution-\\textbf{M}atching \\textbf{P}olicy \\textbf{O}ptimization)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” forward KL minimizationмқ„ мӣҗлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң к·јмӮ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ mode collapseлҘј л°©м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. DMPOлҠ” sampled trajectoryм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ rewardм—җ л№„лЎҖн•ҳлҠ” group-level target distributionмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ң л’Ө, policy distributionмқ„ мқҙ targetм—җ м •л ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӢӨлЈЁкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ global target distributionм—җм„ң samplingн•  н•„мҡ” м—Ҷмқҙ mode-covering behaviorлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳкі , н•ҷмҠө м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё нғҗмғүмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” DMPOлҘј NP-hard combinatorial optimizationм—җм„ң кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҠ” feasible solutionмқҙ м§ҖмҲҳм ҒмңјлЎң л§Һм§Җл§Ң мөңм Ғн•ҙм—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ кІғмқҖ мҶҢмҲҳм—җ л¶Ҳкіјн•ҳм—¬, нғҗмғүмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мқҙмғҒм Ғмқё testbedмқҙлӢӨ. DMPOлҠ” text-based NP-Benchм—җм„ң 43.9% Quality RatioлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳмңјл©°(GRPOмқҳ 40.1% лҢҖл№„), vision-based NP-Benchм—җм„ңлҠ” 43.1%лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ(38.4% лҢҖл№„). мқҙлҠ” к°Ғк°Ғ 9%мҷҖ 12%мқҳ мғҒлҢҖм Ғ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ мқҳлҜён•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н–ҘмғҒмқҖ mathematical reasoning(+2.0%)кіј out-of-domain task(+2.3%)лЎңлҸ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗҳл©°, diversity-preserving trainingмқҙ modalityлҘј к°ҖлЎңм§Ҳлҹ¬ лҚ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м—°кө¬лҠ” on-policy RLм—җм„ң mode collapseлҘј л°©м§Җн•ҳлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқҙкі  мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғмқё м ‘к·јмңјлЎң distribution matchingмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳл©°, мқјкҙҖлҗң quality н–ҘмғҒмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң reasoning task м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң м§ҖмҶҚм Ғ нғҗмғүмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61871","en":"AВІRBench: An Automatic Paradigm for Formally Verifiable Abstract Reasoning Benchmark Generation","ko":"AВІRBench: нҳ•мӢқ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң Abstract Reasoning лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мһҗлҸҷ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„","authors":"Qingchuan Ma, Yuexiao Ma, Yongkang Xie, Tianyu Xie, Xiawu Zheng, Rongrong Ji","pos":"#2107","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mD8DMkl7Tu","abs":"Abstract reasoning ability reflects the intelligence and generalization  capacity of LLMs to extract and apply abstract rules.  However, accurately measuring this ability remains challenging: existing benchmarks either rely on expensive manual annotation, limiting their scale, or risk measuring memorization rather than genuine reasoning.  To address this, we introduce an automated pipeline named A$^2$RBench, encompassing generation, expansion, evaluation, and analysis. Specifically, in the generation stage, LLMs create diverse tasks demanding genuine reasoning; in the expansion stage, LLMs reuse validated rules and expand new input spaces to generate task variations, achieving scaling. However, such a process may cause hallucinations. To eliminate it, we further establish a theoretical framework and prove that programmatic verificationвҖ”testing whether the inverse operation perfectly reverses the forward operation (cycle consistency)вҖ”guarantees a unique solution. Through extensive evaluations on mainstream LLMs, we find: (1) Current LLMs exhibit fundamental deficiencies in abstract reasoning, with top models significantly underperforming humans on a representative subset (39.8\\% vs. 68.5\\%). (2) Current LLMs fall far short of 2D and 1D in the complexity of generated 3D tasks, revealing their lack of understanding of high-dimensional tasks. (3) Counterintuitively, inputs with higher information complexity can simplify the reasoning process. Code and data are available at: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/A2Rbench.","absKo":"м¶”мғҒм Ғ reasoning лҠҘл ҘмқҖ LLMмқҙ м¶”мғҒ к·ңм№ҷмқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкі  м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” intelligenceмҷҖ generalization capacityлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ benchmarkлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мҲҳлҸҷ мЈјм„қм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ к·ңлӘЁ нҷ•мһҘм—җ н•ңкі„к°Җ мһҲкұ°лӮҳ, м§„м •н•ң reasoningмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј memorizationмқ„ мёЎм •н•  мң„н—ҳмқҙ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” generation, expansion, evaluation, analysisлҘј нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” мһҗлҸҷнҷ” нҢҢмқҙн”„лқјмқё A$^2$RBenchлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң generation лӢЁкі„м—җм„ңлҠ” LLMмқҙ м§„м •н•ң reasoningмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң taskлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , expansion лӢЁкі„м—җм„ңлҠ” кІҖмҰқлҗң к·ңм№ҷмқ„ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ input spaceлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ task variationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬ мҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіјм •мқҖ hallucinationмқ„ мң л°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м¶”к°ҖлЎң мқҙлЎ м Ғ frameworkлҘј м„ёмҡ°кі , programmatic verification, мҰү inverse operationмқҙ forward operationмқ„ мҷ„лІҪн•ҳкІҢ лҗҳлҸҢлҰ¬лҠ”м§Җ кІҖмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” cycle consistencyк°Җ мң мқјн•ң н•ҙлҘј ліҙмһҘн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мЈјлҘҳ LLMм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӢӨмқҢмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. (1) нҳ„мһ¬ LLMмқҖ м¶”мғҒм Ғ reasoningм—җ к·јліём Ғмқё кІ°н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, лҢҖн‘ң subsetм—җм„ң top modelлҸ„ мқёк°„ліҙлӢӨ нҒ¬кІҢ лӮ®мқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ(39.8\\% vs. 68.5\\%). (2) нҳ„мһ¬ LLMмқҖ мғқм„ұлҗң 3D taskмқҳ ліөмһЎм„ұм—җм„ң 2D л°Ҹ 1Dм—җ н•ңм°ё лӘ» лҜёміҗ, кі м°Ёмӣҗ taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙн•ҙ л¶ҖмЎұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лғ…лӢҲлӢӨ. (3) м§ҒкҙҖкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, м •ліҙ ліөмһЎм„ұмқҙ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ мһ…л Ҙмқҙ reasoning кіјм •мқ„ лҚ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Ө мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/A2Rbench м—җм„ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•©лӢҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"65574","en":"AutoTool: Dynamic Tool Selection and Integration for Agentic Reasoning","ko":"AutoTool: м—җмқҙм „нҠё м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң лҸҷм Ғ лҸ„кө¬ м„ нғқ л°Ҹ нҶөн•©","authors":"Jiaru Zou, Ling Yang, Yunzhe Qi, Sirui Chen, Mengting Ai, Ke Shen, Jingrui He, Mengdi Wang","pos":"#2108","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CITSCNrUja","abs":"<p>Agentic reinforcement learning has advanced large language models (LLMs) to reason through long chain-of-thought trajectories while interleaving external tool use. Existing approaches assume a fixed inventory of tools, which limits the adaptability of LLM agents to new or evolving toolsets. We present AutoTool, a training framework that equips LLM agents with dynamic tool-selection capabilities throughout their reasoning trajectories. AutoTool employs a dual-phase optimization pipeline: (i) SFT and RL-based trajectory stabilization for coherent reasoning, and (ii) KL-regularized PlackettвҖ“Luce Ranking to refine consistent multi-step tool selection. We further build a 200k dataset with explicit tool-selection rationales across 1,000+ tools and 100+ tasks spanning mathematics, science, code generation, and multimodal reasoning. Across ten diverse benchmarks, we train two base models, Qwen3-8B and Qwen2.5-VL-7B, with AutoTool. With fewer parameters, AutoTool consistently outperforms advanced LLM agents and tool-integration methods, yielding average gains of 6.4\\% in math &amp;amp; science reasoning, 4.5\\% in search-based QA, 7.7\\% in code generation, and 6.9\\% in multimodal understanding. In addition, AutoTool exhibits stronger generalization by dynamically leveraging unseen tools from evolving toolsets during inference.</p>","absKo":"<p>Agentic reinforcement learningмқҖ large language model(LLM)мқҙ мҷёл¶Җ tool мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ көҗм°ЁмӢңнӮӨл©° кёҙ chain-of-thought trajectoryлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м¶”лЎ н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ л°ңм „мӢңмјң мҷ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ кі м •лҗң tool лӘ©лЎқмқ„ к°Җм •н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, LLM agentк°Җ мғҲлЎӯкұ°лӮҳ м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” toolsetм—җ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reasoning trajectory м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ LLM agentм—җ dynamic tool-selection лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ҳлҠ” н•ҷмҠө н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ AutoToolмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. AutoToolмқҖ л‘җ лӢЁкі„ мөңм Ғнҷ” нҢҢмқҙн”„лқјмқёмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ: (i) мқјкҙҖлҗң reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң SFT л°Ҹ RL кё°л°ҳ trajectory stabilization, (ii) мқјкҙҖлҗң multi-step tool selectionмқ„ м •көҗнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң KL-regularized PlackettвҖ“Luce Ranking. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҲҳн•ҷ, кіјн•ҷ, code generation, multimodal reasoningмқ„ м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” 1,000к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ toolкіј 100к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ taskм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё tool-selection rationaleмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң 20л§Ң к°ң к·ңлӘЁмқҳ datasetмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. 10к°ңмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Qwen3-8BмҷҖ Qwen2.5-VL-7B л‘җ base modelмқ„ AutoToolлЎң н•ҷмҠөн–ҲлӢӨ. лҚ” м ҒмқҖ parameterлЎң, AutoToolмқҖ кі кёү LLM agentмҷҖ tool-integration л°©лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, math &amp;amp; science reasoningм—җм„ң нҸүк·  6.4\\%, search-based QAм—җм„ң 4.5\\%, code generationм—җм„ң 7.7\\%, multimodal understandingм—җм„ң 6.9\\%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң AutoToolмқҖ inference мӨ‘ м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” toolsetм—җм„ң ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң toolмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лҚ” к°•н•ң generalizationмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64174","en":"A Minimal Agent for Automated Theorem Proving","ko":"мһҗлҸҷ м •лҰ¬ мҰқлӘ…мқ„ мң„н•ң мөңмҶҢ м—җмқҙм „нҠё","authors":"Borja Requena, Austin Letson, Krystian Nowakowski, Izan Beltran Ferreiro, Leopoldo Sarra","pos":"#2207","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=QGAOswfVvD","abs":"<p>We propose a minimal agentic baseline that enables systematic comparison across different AI-based theorem prover architectures. This design implements the core features shared among state-of-the-art systems: iterative proof refinement, library search and context management. We evaluate our baseline using qualitatively different benchmarks and compare various popular models and design choices. Our results demonstrate consistent advantages of an iterative approach over multiple single-shot generations, especially in terms of sample efficiency and cost effectiveness. We demonstrate competitive performance compared to state-of-the-art approaches, while using a significantly simpler architecture. We release our open-source implementation as a candidate reference for future research and as an accessible prover for the community.</p>","absKo":"<p>лӢӨм–‘н•ң AI кё°л°ҳ theorem prover м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳ к°„мқҳ мІҙкі„м Ғ л№„көҗлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ agentic baselineмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” мөңмІЁлӢЁ мӢңмҠӨн…ңл“Өмқҙ кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ кё°лҠҘ, мҰү л°ҳліөм Ғ proof refinement, library search, context managementлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё benchmarksлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ baselineмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі , лӢӨм–‘н•ң мқёкё° лӘЁлҚёкіј м„Өкі„ м„ нғқмқ„ л№„көҗн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ лІҲмқҳ single-shot generationліҙлӢӨ л°ҳліөм Ғ м ‘к·јмқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, нҠ№нһҲ sample efficiencyмҷҖ cost effectiveness мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” лӢЁмҲңн•ң м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ state-of-the-art м ‘к·јлІ•кіј кІ¬мӨ„ л§Ңн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬лҘј мң„н•ң нӣ„ліҙ referenceмқҙмһҗ м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°к°Җ нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м ‘к·ј к°ҖлҠҘн•ң proverлЎңм„ң open-source кө¬нҳ„мқ„ кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64323","en":"APE-Bench: Evaluating Automated Proof Engineering for Formal Math Libraries","ko":"APE-Bench: нҳ•мӢқ мҲҳн•ҷ лқјмқҙлёҢлҹ¬лҰ¬лҘј мң„н•ң мһҗлҸҷ мҰқлӘ… кіөн•ҷ нҸүк°Җ","authors":"Huajian Xin, Zheng Yuan, Jacques Fleuriot, Wenda Li","pos":"#2210","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OjeKfGXLOn","abs":"<p>While frontier formal mathematics systems now routinely develop repository-scale proof engineering artifacts requiring multi-file coordination and semantic correctness beyond compilation, existing evaluation benchmarks remain focused on isolated theorem proving. We introduce Automated Proof Engineering (APE), the first systematic framework for evaluating repository-scale proof engineering through dual verification that validates both syntactic compilation and semantic requirement satisfaction in pinned library environments. We present a complete infrastructure comprising APE-Bench, which automatically extracts proof engineering tasks from real library commit histories, and APE-Harness, a unified execution framework based on task contract abstraction. This contract-based design enables standardized evaluation across diverse formal mathematics tasks and fair systematic comparison of different agent implementations (including our APE-Agent reference scaffold alongside Claude Code and Codex CLI) on identical task specifications. We demonstrate the framework's effectiveness through comprehensive evaluation. All code, benchmarks, and infrastructure will be open-sourced.</p>","absKo":"<p>frontier formal mathematics systemмқҖ мқҙм ң м»ҙнҢҢмқјмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” semantic correctnessк°Җ мҡ”кө¬лҗҳлҠ” repository-scale proof engineering artifactлҘј мқјмғҒм ҒмңјлЎң к°ңл°ңн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ нҸүк°Җ benchmarkлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ кі лҰҪлҗң theorem provingм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”кі  мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” repository-scale proof engineeringмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ мІҙкі„м Ғ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё Automated Proof Engineering (APE)мқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ҳл©°, кі м •лҗң library environmentм—җм„ң syntactic compilationкіј semantic requirement satisfactionмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” dual verificationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҷ„м „н•ң мқён”„лқјлЎңм„ң, мӢӨм ң library commit historyм—җм„ң proof engineering taskлҘј мһҗлҸҷ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳлҠ” APE-BenchмҷҖ task contract abstractionмқ„ кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ң нҶөн•© мӢӨн–ү н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ APE-HarnessлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ contract кё°л°ҳ м„Өкі„лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң formal mathematics task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗң нҸүк°ҖлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі , лҸҷмқјн•ң task specification мң„м—җм„ң м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё agent implementation(Claude CodeмҷҖ Codex CLIмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ APE-Agent reference scaffold нҸ¬н•Ё)мқ„ кіөм •н•ҳкі  мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л№„көҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мў…н•© нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁл“  мҪ”л“ң, benchmark, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мқён”„лқјлҠ” мҳӨн”ҲмҶҢмҠӨлЎң кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62135","en":"The Decrypto Benchmark for Multi-Agent Reasoning and Theory of Mind","ko":"Multi-Agent Reasoningкіј Theory of MindлҘј мң„н•ң Decrypto Benchmark","authors":"Andrei Lupu, Timon Willi, Jakob Foerster","pos":"#3504","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jW0Vcidbbw","abs":"<p>As Large Language Models (LLMs) gain agentic abilities, they will have to navigate complex multi-agent scenarios, interacting with human users and other agents in cooperative and competitive settings. This will require new reasoning skills, a crucial one being theory of mind (ToM), or the ability to reason about the \"mental\" states of other agents. However, ToM and other multi-agent abilities in LLMs are poorly understood, since existing benchmarks suffer from narrow scope, data leakage, saturation, and lack of interactivity. We thus propose Decrypto, a game-based benchmark for multi-agent reasoning and ToM drawing inspiration from cognitive science, computational pragmatics and multi-agent reinforcement learning. It is designed to be as easy as possible in all other dimensions, eliminating confounding factors commonly found in other benchmarks. To our knowledge, it is also the first platform for designing interactive ToM experiments.  We validate the benchmark design through comprehensive empirical evaluations of frontier LLMs, robustness studies, and human-AI cross-play experiments. We find that LLM game-playing abilities lag behind humans and simple word-embedding baselines. We then create variants of two classic cognitive science experiments within Decrypto to evaluate three key ToM abilities. Surprisingly, we find that state-of-the-art reasoning models are significantly worse at those tasks than their older counterparts. This demonstrates that Decrypto addresses a crucial gap in current reasoning and ToM evaluations, and paves the path towards better artificial agents. Code at anonymous.4open.science/r/decrypto/.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models(LLMs)к°Җ agentic abilitiesлҘј к°–м¶”кІҢ лҗҳл©ҙм„ң, мқёк°„ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ л°Ҹ лӢӨлҘё agentмҷҖ нҳ‘л Ҙм ҒВ·кІҪмҹҒм Ғ м„Өм •м—җм„ң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң multi-agent мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨлҘј лӢӨлӨ„м•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳл©°, к·ёмӨ‘ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ theory of mind(ToM), мҰү лӢӨлҘё agentмқҳ \"mental\" stateлҘј м¶”лЎ н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл ҘмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ benchmarkл“ӨмқҖ лІ”мң„к°Җ мўҒкі , data leakageмҷҖ saturation л¬ём ңк°Җ мһҲмңјл©°, мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©м„ұмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҙ LLMмқҳ ToM л°Ҹ кё°нғҖ multi-agent лҠҘл ҘмқҖ м ңлҢҖлЎң мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” cognitive science, computational pragmatics, к·ёлҰ¬кі  multi-agent reinforcement learningм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣмқҖ кІҢмһ„ кё°л°ҳ multi-agent reasoning л°Ҹ ToM benchmarkмқё DecryptoлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ benchmarkлҠ” лӢӨлҘё лӘЁл“  м°Ёмӣҗм—җм„ңлҠ” к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н•ң мүҪкІҢ м„Өкі„лҗҳм–ҙ, лӢӨлҘё benchmarkм—җм„ң нқ”нһҲ лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” нҳјлһҖ мҡ”мқёмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м•„лҠ” н•ң, мқҙкІғмқҖ interactive ToM experimentлҘј м„Өкі„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мІ« н”Ңлһ«нҸјмқҙкё°лҸ„ н•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” frontier LLMм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё мӢӨмҰқ нҸүк°Җ, robustness study, к·ёлҰ¬кі  human-AI cross-play experimentлҘј нҶөн•ҙ benchmark м„Өкі„лҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј LLMмқҳ кІҢмһ„ н”Ңл Ҳмқҙ лҠҘл ҘмқҖ мқёк°„кіј лӢЁмҲңн•ң word-embedding baselineліҙлӢӨ л’ӨмІҳм§„лӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң Decrypto м•Ҳм—җм„ң л‘җ к°ңмқҳ кі м „м Ғ cognitive science experimentмқҳ ліҖнҳ•мқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ м„ё к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ ToM лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„, state-of-the-art reasoning modelл“ӨмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіјм ңм—җм„ң лҚ” мҳӨлһҳлҗң лӘЁлҚёліҙлӢӨ нҳ„м ҖнһҲ лӮ®мқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” Decryptoк°Җ нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ reasoning л°Ҹ ToM нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡ°л©°, лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ artificial agentлҘј н–Ҙн•ң кёёмқ„ м—°лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. Code at anonymous.4open.science/r/decrypto/.</p>"},{"id":"62973","en":"Agentic Proposing: Enhancing Large language Model Reasoning via Compositional Skill Synthesis","ko":"Agentic Proposing: кө¬м„ұм Ғ Skill SynthesisлЎң лҢҖнҳ• м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё м¶”лЎ  к°•нҷ”","authors":"Zhengbo Jiao, Shaobo Wang, Zifan Zhang, Xuan Ren, Wei Wang, Bing Zhao, HU WEI, Linfeng Zhang","pos":"#3511","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bLbBxDTjbq","abs":"<p>Advancing complex reasoning in large language models relies on high-quality, verifiable datasets, yet human annotation remains cost-prohibitive and difficult to scale. Current synthesis paradigms often face a recurring trade-off: maintaining structural validity typically restricts problem complexity, while relaxing constraints to increase difficulty frequently leads to inconsistent or unsolvable instances. To address this, we propose \\textbf{Agentic Proposing}, a framework that models problem synthesis as a goal-driven sequential decision process where a specialized agent dynamically selects and composes modular reasoning skills. Through an iterative workflow of internal reflection and tool-use, we develop the \\textbf{Agentic-Proposer-4B} using Multi-Granularity Policy Optimization (MGPO) to generate high-precision, verifiable training trajectories across mathematics, coding, and science. Empirical results demonstrate that downstream solvers trained on agent-synthesized data significantly outperform leading baselines and exhibit robust cross-domain generalization. Notably, a 30B solver trained on only 11,000 synthesized trajectories achieves a state-of-the-art 91.6\\% accuracy on AIME25, rivaling frontier-scale proprietary models such as GPT-5 and proving that a small volume of high-quality synthetic signals can effectively substitute for massive human-curated datasets.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң ліөмһЎн•ң м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл Өл©ҙ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҳ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқёк°„ мЈјм„қмқҖ л№„мҡ©мқҙ л„Ҳл¬ҙ нҒ¬кі  нҷ•мһҘлҸ„ м–ҙл өмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ н•©м„ұ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҖ л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ нҠёл Ҳмқҙл“ңмҳӨн”„м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кө¬мЎ°м Ғ нғҖлӢ№м„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙ л¬ём ң ліөмһЎлҸ„к°Җ м ңн•ңлҗҳкі , лӮңлҸ„лҘј лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл©ҙ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҙ м—Ҷкұ°лӮҳ н’Җ мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” мқёмҠӨн„ҙмҠӨк°Җ мһҗмЈј л°ңмғқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{Agentic Proposing}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” л¬ём ң н•©м„ұмқ„ лӘ©н‘ң м§Җн–Ҙм Ғ мҲңм°Ё мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • кіјм •мңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳм—¬, нҠ№нҷ”лҗң м—җмқҙм „нҠёк°Җ лӘЁл“Ҳнҳ• м¶”лЎ  мҠӨнӮ¬мқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ҳкі  мЎ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. лӮҙл¶Җ л°ҳм„ұкіј tool-useлҘј л°ҳліөн•ҳлҠ” мӣҢнҒ¬н”ҢлЎңмҡ°лҘј нҶөн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Multi-Granularity Policy Optimization (MGPO)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ \\textbf{Agentic-Proposer-4B}лҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳкі , мҲҳн•ҷ, мҪ”л”©, кіјн•ҷ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң кі м •л°Җмқҳ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н•ҷмҠө к¶Өм Ғмқ„ мғқм„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, м—җмқҙм „нҠёк°Җ н•©м„ұн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң downstream solverлҠ” мЈјмҡ” baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкі  к°•кұҙн•ң cross-domain generalizationмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, 11,000к°ңмқҳ н•©м„ұ к¶Өм Ғл§ҢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң 30B solverлҠ” AIME25м—җм„ң state-of-the-artмқё 91.6\\% м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ GPT-5мҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ frontier-scale proprietary modelкіј кІ¬мӨ„ л§Ңн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мҶҢлҹүмқҳ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ synthetic signalмқҙ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ human-curated datasetмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63530","en":"CausalGame: Benchmarking Causal Thinking of LLM Agents in Games","ko":"CausalGame: кІҢмһ„м—җм„ң LLM м—җмқҙм „нҠёмқҳ мқёкіјм Ғ мӮ¬кі лҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Zhenhao Chen, Yongqiang Chen, Chenxi Liu, Junchi Yu, Xiangchen Song, Zijian Li, Jialin Li, Phil Torr, Bo Han, Kun Zhang","pos":"#3609","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WNqIX3IFZU","abs":"<p>Recently, it has received growing attention in building AI Scientist agents with Large Language Models (LLMs). Since scientific discovery fundamentally relies on uncovering causal relationships from observations, the capability of causal thinking that distinguish causation from correlation and hidden biases, is essential to LLM agents. Despite a number of existing benchmarks for AI scientists, none of them are designed with the consideration of hidden biases and confounders, that widely exist in real-world scientific discovery. To this end, we present CausalGame, a benchmark that evaluates the causal thinking capabilities of LLM agents through interactive games. More specifically, we ask LLM agents to actively design experimental protocols, collect observation data and derive a final solution with an explanation report. To emulate realistic scientific discovery challenges, we design 14 game settings with the incorporation of selection bias, noisy measurements, and hidden confounders. The results with 16 frontier LLM agents show that they consistently fail to reason about and recover the underlying causal relationships required to solve the games. CausalGame provides a rigorous measurement of capabilities essential to AI Scientist agents.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј Large Language Models (LLMs)лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ AI Scientist agentsлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ҳлҠ” мқјм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙҖмӢ¬мқҙ лҶ’м•„м§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. кіјн•ҷм Ғ л°ңкІ¬мқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң кҙҖм°°лЎңл¶Җн„° мқёкіј кҙҖкі„лҘј л°қнҳҖлӮҙлҠ” лҚ° мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мқёкіјмҷҖ мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„ л°Ҹ мҲЁмқҖ нҺён–Ҙмқ„ кө¬л¶„н•ҳлҠ” causal thinking лҠҘл ҘмқҖ LLM agentsм—җ н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ AI scientists лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬к°Җ м—¬лҹҝ мһҲмқҢм—җлҸ„, нҳ„мӢӨмқҳ кіјн•ҷм Ғ л°ңкІ¬ кіјм •м—җ л„җлҰ¬ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” hidden biasesмҷҖ confoundersлҘј кі л Өн•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗң кІғмқҖ м—ҶлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҢҖнҷ”нҳ• кІҢмһ„мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ LLM agentsмқҳ causal thinking capabilitiesлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” benchmarkмқё CausalGameмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліҙлӢӨ кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLM agentsк°Җ лҠҘлҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мӢӨн—ҳ н”„лЎңнҶ мҪңмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ҳкі , кҙҖм°° лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мҲҳм§‘н•ҳл©°, м„ӨлӘ… ліҙкі м„ңмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ мөңмў… н•ҙлӢөмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё кіјн•ҷм Ғ л°ңкІ¬мқҳ лҸ„м „мқ„ лӘЁмӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, selection bias, noisy measurements, hidden confoundersлҘј нҶөн•©н•ң 14к°ңмқҳ кІҢмһ„ м„Өм •мқ„ м„Өкі„н–ҲлӢӨ. 16к°ңмқҳ frontier LLM agentsм—җ лҢҖн•ң кІ°кіјлҠ”, мқҙл“Өмқҙ кІҢмһ„мқ„ н‘ёлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң underlying causal relationshipsлҘј м¶”лЎ н•ҳкі  ліөмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мӢӨнҢЁн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. CausalGameмқҖ AI Scientist agentsм—җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ м—„л°Җн•ҳкІҢ мёЎм •н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кё°мӨҖмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66445","en":"MAS-Orchestra: Understanding and Improving Multi-Agent Reasoning Through Holistic Orchestration and Controlled Benchmarks","ko":"MAS-Orchestra: мҙқмІҙм Ғ мҳӨмјҖмҠӨнҠёл Ҳмқҙм…ҳкіј м ңм–ҙлҗң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лҘј нҶөн•ң лӢӨмӨ‘ м—җмқҙм „нҠё м¶”лЎ  мқҙн•ҙ л°Ҹ к°ңм„ ","authors":"Zixuan Ke, Yifei Ming, Austin Xu, Ryan Chin, Xuan-Phi Nguyen, Prathyusha Jwalapuram, Jiayu Wang, Semih Yavuz, Caiming Xiong, Shafiq Joty","pos":"#4009","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=3fGXBm4c3S","abs":"<p>While multi-agent systems (MAS) promise elevated intelligence through coordination of agents, current approaches to automatic MAS design under-deliver. Such shortcomings stem from two key factors: (1) methodological complexity вҖ“ agent orchestration is performed using sequential, code-level execution that limits global system-level holistic reasoning and scales poorly with agent complexity вҖ“ and (2) efficacy uncertainty вҖ“ MAS are deployed without understanding if there are tangible benefits compared to single-agent systems (SAS). We propose MASOrchestra, a training-time framework that formulates MAS orchestration as a function-calling reinforcement learning problem with holistic orchestration, generating an entire MAS at once. In MAS-Orchestra, complex, goal-oriented subagents are abstracted as callable functions, enabling global reasoning over system structure while hiding internal execution details. To rigorously study when and why MAS are beneficial, we introduce MASBENCH, a controlled benchmark that characterizes tasks along five axes: Depth, Horizon, Breadth, Parallel, and Robustness. Our analysis reveals that MAS gains depend critically on task structure, verification protocols, and the capabilities of both orchestrator and subagents, rather than holding universally. Guided by these insights, MAS-Orchestra achieves consistent improvements on public benchmarks including mathematical reasoning, multi-hop QA, and search-based QA, while achieving more than 10Г— efficiency over strong baselines. Together, MAS-Orchestra and MASBENCH enable better training and understanding of MAS in the pursuit of multi-agent intelligence.</p>","absKo":"<p>multi-agent system(MAS)мқҖ м—җмқҙм „нҠёл“Өмқҳ coordinationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ н–ҘмғҒлҗң м§ҖлҠҘмқ„ м•ҪмҶҚн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ automatic MAS design м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ кё°лҢҖм—җ лҜём№ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ мҡ”мқём—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗңлӢӨ: (1) л°©лІ•лЎ м Ғ ліөмһЎм„ұ - agent orchestrationмқҙ sequentialн•ң мҪ”л“ң мҲҳмӨҖ мӢӨн–үмңјлЎң мҲҳн–үлҗҳм–ҙ м „м—ӯм Ғмқё system-level holistic reasoningмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ҳкі  agent complexityк°Җ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (2) нҡЁмҡ© л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұ - MASк°Җ single-agent system(SAS)кіј л№„көҗн•ҙ мӢӨм§Ҳм Ғмқё мқҙм җмқҙ мһҲлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙн•ҙ м—Ҷмқҙ л°°нҸ¬лҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” holistic orchestrationмқ„ к°–лҠ” function-calling reinforcement learning л¬ём ңлЎң MAS orchestrationмқ„ м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, м „мІҙ MASлҘј н•ң лІҲм—җ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” training-time frameworkмқё MASOrchestraлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. MAS-Orchestraм—җм„ңлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң goal-oriented subagentлҘј нҳём¶ң к°ҖлҠҘн•ң functionмңјлЎң м¶”мғҒнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, лӮҙл¶Җ мӢӨн–ү м„ёл¶ҖмӮ¬н•ӯмқ„ мҲЁкёҙ мұ„ system structureм—җ лҢҖн•ң м „м—ӯм Ғ reasoningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. MASк°Җ м–ём ң, мҷң мң мқөн•ңм§ҖлҘј м—„л°ҖнһҲ м—°кө¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Depth, Horizon, Breadth, Parallel, Robustnessмқҳ лӢӨм„Ҝ м¶•мқ„ л”°лқј taskлҘј нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” controlled benchmarkмқё MASBENCHлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ MASмқҳ мқҙл“қмқҙ ліҙнҺём ҒмңјлЎң м„ұлҰҪн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј, task structure, verification protocol, к·ёлҰ¬кі  orchestratorмҷҖ subagent м–‘мӘҪмқҳ лҠҘл Ҙм—җ кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң мқҳмЎҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°м—җ л”°лқј, MAS-OrchestraлҠ” мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ , multi-hop QA, search-based QAлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң public benchmarkм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ к°•л Ҙн•ң baseline лҢҖл№„ 10л°° мқҙмғҒмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. MAS-OrchestraмҷҖ MASBENCHлҠ” н•Ёк»ҳ multi-agent intelligenceлҘј н–Ҙн•ң MASмқҳ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ н•ҷмҠөкіј мқҙн•ҙлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62027","en":"LEGO: An LLM-Enabled Hierarchical Optimizer for Tensor Computation Graphs with Structure-Aware Search and Compositional Synthesis","ko":"LEGO: кө¬мЎ° мқёмӢқ нғҗмғүкіј мЎ°н•©м Ғ н•©м„ұмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ н…җм„ң кі„мӮ° к·ёлһҳн”„мҡ© LLM кё°л°ҳ кі„мёөм Ғ Optimizer","authors":"Ruiyuan Xu, shuoming zhang, Guangli Li, Qiuchu Yu, Rui Zhang, Yangyu Zhang, Hao Qian, Chunwei Xia, Jiacheng Zhao, Chenxi Wang, Xiaobing Feng, Jingling Xue, Huimin Cui","pos":"#4203","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=kYqJ5gGjHE","abs":"<p>Automating end-to-end GPU kernel generation with Large Language Models (LLMs) faces a critical tension between global performance and exploration efficiency. We present LEGO, a hierarchical framework that resolves this trade-off via a parallel multi-agent search over a recursive AND-OR FusionTree. LEGO synergizes two complementary flows: Top-Down Construction decomposes complex graphs into valid, context-isolated sub-problems to guarantee correctness and enable parallel exploration, while Bottom-Up Mutation speculatively fuses verified sub-plans to recover global locality for peak performance. This bi-directional mechanism effectively prunes the search space to avoid repetitive unguided sampling, while naturally parallelizing exploration, and enabling the discovery of sophisticated fusion strategies. Evaluations demonstrate that LEGO achieves 2.18xвҖ“13.48x speedups over PyTorch Eager and reduces end-to-end exploration time by up to 2.47x (with 7x token reduction) compared to monolithic baselines across diverse end-to-end models.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Model(LLM)лЎң end-to-end GPU kernel generationмқ„ мһҗлҸҷнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ global performanceмҷҖ exploration efficiency мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мӨ‘лҢҖн•ң кёҙмһҘм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” recursive AND-OR FusionTree мң„м—җм„ң лі‘л ¬ multi-agent searchлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ trade-offлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” hierarchical frameworkмқё LEGOлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. LEGOлҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мғҒліҙм Ғмқё нқҗлҰ„мқ„ мӢңл„Ҳм§ҖлҘј лӮҙл©° кІ°н•©н•ңлӢӨ. Top-Down ConstructionмқҖ ліөмһЎн•ң graphлҘј мҳ¬л°”лҘё, context-isolated sub-problemмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳм—¬ correctnessлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳкі  лі‘л ¬ нғҗмғүмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, Bottom-Up MutationмқҖ кІҖмҰқлҗң sub-planмқ„ м¶”мёЎм ҒмңјлЎң fuseн•ҳм—¬ peak performanceлҘј мң„н•ң global localityлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м–‘л°©н–Ҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ л°ҳліөм Ғмқё unguided samplingмқ„ н”јн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ search spaceлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң pruningн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, нғҗмғүмқ„ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ лі‘л ¬нҷ”н•ҳкі  м •көҗн•ң fusion strategyмқҳ л°ңкІ¬мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіј LEGOлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң end-to-end model м „л°ҳм—җм„ң PyTorch Eager лҢҖл№„ 2.18л°°вҖ“13.48л°°мқҳ speedupмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , monolithic baseline лҢҖл№„ end-to-end exploration timeмқ„ мөңлҢҖ 2.47л°°(нҶ нҒ° мҲҳ 7л°° к°җмҶҢ нҸ¬н•Ё) мӨ„мқҙлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮ¬лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61367","en":"Persona2Web: Benchmarking Personalized Web Agents for Contextual Reasoning with User History","ko":"Persona2Web: мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мқҙл Ҙмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң Contextual Reasoningмҡ© к°ңмқёнҷ” Web Agents лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№","authors":"Serin Kim, Sangam Lee, Dongha Lee","pos":"#4402","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qvvD9hgHoX","abs":"<p>Large language models have advanced web agents, yet current agents lack personalization capabilities. Since users rarely specify every detail of their intent, practical web agents must be able to interpret ambiguous queries by inferring user preferences and contexts. To address this challenge, we present Persona2Web, the first benchmark for evaluating personalized web agents on the real open web, built upon the clarify-to-personalize principle, which requires agents to resolve ambiguity based on user history rather than relying on explicit instructions. Persona2Web consists of: (1) user histories that reveal preferences implicitly over long time spans, (2) ambiguous queries that require agents to infer implicit user preferences, and (3) a reasoning-aware evaluation framework that enables fine-grained assessment of personalization. We conduct extensive experiments across various agent architectures, backbone models, history access schemes, and queries with varying ambiguity levels, revealing key challenges in personalized web agent behavior. For reproducibility, our codes and datasets are publicly available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Persona2Web-73E8</p>","absKo":"<p>large language modelмқҖ web agentлҘј л°ңм „мӢңмј°м§Җл§Ң, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ agentлҠ” personalization capabilityк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлҠ” мһҗмӢ мқҳ мқҳлҸ„лҘј л§ӨлІҲ лӘЁл“  м„ёл¶Җк№Ңм§Җ лӘ…мӢңн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё web agentлҠ” user preferenceмҷҖ contextлҘј м¶”лЎ н•ҳм—¬ лӘЁнҳён•ң queryлҘј н•ҙм„қн•  мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіјм ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” real open webм—җм„ң personalized web agentлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ benchmarkмқё Persona2Webмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лҠ” clarify-to-personalize мӣҗм№ҷ мң„м—җ кө¬м¶•лҗҳл©°, agentк°Җ лӘ…мӢңм Ғ м§ҖмӢңм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ  user historyлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң лӘЁнҳём„ұмқ„ н•ҙмҶҢн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. Persona2WebмқҖ лӢӨмқҢмңјлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. (1) кёҙ мӢңк°„ лІ”мң„м—җ кұёміҗ м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң preferenceлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙлҠ” user history, (2) м•”л¬өм Ғ user preferenceлҘј м¶”лЎ н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” ambiguous query, (3) personalizationмқ„ м„ёл°Җн•ҳкІҢ нҸүк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” reasoning-aware evaluation framework. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң agent architecture, backbone model, history access scheme, к·ёлҰ¬кі  лӘЁнҳём„ұ мҲҳмӨҖмқҙ лӢӨлҘё queryлҘј лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ personalized web agent н–үлҸҷм—җм„ңмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ лҸ„м „ кіјм ңлҘј л°қнһҢлӢӨ. мһ¬нҳ„м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ datasetмқҖ https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Persona2Web-73E8 м—җм„ң кіөк°ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63427","en":"$\\tau$-Knowledge: Evaluating Conversational Agents over Unstructured Knowledge","ko":"$\\tau$-Knowledge: л№„кө¬мЎ°нҷ” м§ҖмӢқ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң лҢҖнҷ”нҳ• м—җмқҙм „нҠё нҸүк°Җ","authors":"Quan Shi, Alexandra Zytek, Pedram Razavi, Karthik Narasimhan, Victor Barres","pos":"#4405","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XHZK5abtw2","abs":"Conversational agents are increasingly deployed in knowledge-intensive settings, where correct behavior depends on acquiring and applying domain-specific knowledge from large, proprietary, and unstructured corpora during live interactions with users. Yet most existing benchmarks evaluate retrieval or tool use in isolation, and rarely test whether agents can operationalize non-parametric knowledge to drive outcomes over long-horizon conversations. To remedy this, we introduce $\\tau$-Knowledge, an extension of $\\tau$-Bench that evaluates agents in environments where task success requires retrieving, reasoning over, and applying knowledge from a natural-language corpus. Our new domain, $\\tau$-Banking, models realistic fintech customer support workflows in which agents must coordinate external knowledge with tool outputs to deliver verifiable, policy-compliant state changes over long-horizon conversations. $\\tau$-Knowledge is substantially difficult: frontier models with high reasoning budgets only reach $\\sim$21\\% \\passhat{1}, with reliability degrading sharply over repeated trials. We hope $\\tau$-Knowledge provides a realistic testbed for developing conversational agents that integrate non-parametric knowledge in human-facing deployments.","absKo":"лҢҖнҷ”нҳ• м—җмқҙм „нҠёлҠ” м җм җ м§ҖмӢқ м§‘м•Ҫм Ғ нҷҳкІҪм—җ л°°м№ҳлҗҳкі  мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗмқҳ мӢӨмӢңк°„ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© лҸҷм•Ҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁмқҳ лҸ…м җм Ғ л№„м •нҳ• мҪ”нҚјмҠӨм—җм„ң лҸ„л©”мқё нҠ№нҷ” м§ҖмӢқмқ„ нҡҚл“қн•ҳкі  м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ мҳ¬л°”лҘё лҸҷмһ‘мқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҙ лҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ кІҖмғү лҳҗлҠ” tool useлҘј кі лҰҪлҗң мғҒнғңлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳл©°, м—җмқҙм „нҠёк°Җ л№„лӘЁмҲҳм Ғ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ мһҘкё°м Ғ лҢҖнҷ” м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ кІ°кіјлЎң м—°кІ°н•ҙлӮј мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§ҖлҘј мӢңн—ҳн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°лҠ” л“ңл¬јлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” $\\tau$-Benchмқҳ нҷ•мһҘнҢҗмқё $\\tau$-KnowledgeлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лҠ” мһҗм—°м–ҙ мҪ”нҚјмҠӨм—җм„ң м§ҖмӢқмқ„ кІҖмғүн•ҳкі , м¶”лЎ н•ҳкі , м Ғмҡ©н•ҙм•јл§Ң кіјм ңк°Җ м„ұкіөн•ҳлҠ” нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң м—җмқҙм „нҠёлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лҸ„л©”мқёмқё $\\tau$-BankingмқҖ нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё н•Җн…ҢнҒ¬ кі к°қ м§Җмӣҗ мӣҢнҒ¬н”ҢлЎңлҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳл©°, м—¬кё°м„ң м—җмқҙм „нҠёлҠ” мҷёл¶Җ м§ҖмӢқкіј tool м¶ңл Ҙл“Өмқ„ мЎ°мңЁн•ҳм—¬ мһҘкё°м Ғ лҢҖнҷ” м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  м •мұ…мқ„ мӨҖмҲҳн•ҳлҠ” мғҒнғң ліҖнҷ”лҘј м ңкіөн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. $\\tau$-KnowledgeлҠ” мғҒлӢ№нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. лҶ’мқҖ reasoning budgetмқ„ к°Җм§„ frontier лӘЁлҚёмЎ°м°Ё м•Ҫ $\\sim$21\\% \\passhat{1}м—җ к·ём№ҳл©°, л°ҳліө мӢңлҸ„м—җ л”°лқј мӢ лў°м„ұмқҖ кёүкІ©нһҲ м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” $\\tau$-Knowledgeк°Җ мқёк°„мқҙ м§Ғм ‘ л§ҲмЈјн•ҳлҠ” л°°м№ҳ нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң л№„лӘЁмҲҳм Ғ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” лҢҖнҷ”нҳ• м—җмқҙм „нҠёлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё н…ҢмҠӨнҠёлІ л“ңк°Җ лҗҳкё°лҘј кё°лҢҖн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63113","en":"Scaling, Benchmarking, and Reasoning of Vision-Language Agents for Mobile GUI Navigation","ko":"лӘЁл°”мқј GUI лӮҙл№„кІҢмқҙм…ҳмқ„ мң„н•ң Vision-Language м—җмқҙм „нҠёмқҳ нҷ•мһҘ, лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№, м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Heng Qu, Yike Liu, Renren Jin, Wenzong Zhang, Pengzhi Gao, Wei Liu, Jian Luan","pos":"#608","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Zyjrz6R7zn","abs":"<p>VisionвҖ“Language Models (VLMs) have shown rapid progress in mobile GUI navigation. This paper presents a systematic study of data scaling, benchmarking, and reasoning for VLM-based agents in this domain. To facilitate rigorous evaluation, we introduce HyperTrack, a large-scale dataset with over 16000 real-world tasks across more than 650 Chinese mobile applications, along with GUIEvalKit, an open-source toolkit for unified benchmarking of VLMs on offline GUI navigation tasks. Using HyperTrack, we analyze the effects of training data scale on both supervised and reinforcement-based finetuning. Our results show that reinforcement-based finetuning consistently outperforms supervised finetuning, particularly in out-of-domain settings, highlighting the synergy between data scaling and reinforcement learning. Leveraging GUIEvalKit, we further benchmark state-of-the-art (SOTA) VLMs and analyze how interaction history and reasoning capabilities influence task completion. Together, HyperTrack and GUIEvalKit provide a comprehensive platform for developing and evaluating VLM agents in mobile GUI navigation tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>VisionвҖ“Language Models (VLMs)лҠ” mobile GUI navigationм—җм„ң л№ лҘҙкІҢ л°ңм „н•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ мқҙ лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ң VLM-based agentsлҘј мң„н•ң data scaling, benchmarking, reasoningм—җ лҢҖн•ң мІҙкі„м Ғмқё м—°кө¬лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. м—„л°Җн•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј лҸ•кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 650к°ңк°Җ л„ҳлҠ” мӨ‘көӯ лӘЁл°”мқј м• н”ҢлҰ¬мјҖмқҙм…ҳ м „л°ҳмқҳ 16,000к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„ taskлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ HyperTrackкіј, offline GUI navigation taskм—җм„ң VLMмқҳ нҶөн•© benchmarkingмқ„ мң„н•ң мҳӨн”ҲмҶҢмҠӨ toolkit GUIEvalKitмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. HyperTrackмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ supervised finetuningкіј reinforcement-based finetuning лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң training data scaleмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” reinforcement-based finetuningмқҙ supervised finetuningліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳл©°, нҠ№нһҲ out-of-domain м„Өм •м—җм„ң л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјм–ҙ, data scalingкіј reinforcement learning мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мӢңл„Ҳм§ҖлҘј к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. GUIEvalKitмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SOTA VLMл“Өмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң benchmarkн•ҳкі , interaction historyмҷҖ reasoning capabilityк°Җ task completionм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җ л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. HyperTrackкіј GUIEvalKitмқҖ н•Ёк»ҳ mobile GUI navigation taskм—җм„ң VLM agentsлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳкі  нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мў…н•© н”Ңлһ«нҸјмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62128","en":"When to Think, When to Speak:  Learning Disclosure Policies for Large Language Model Reasoning","ko":"м–ём ң мғқк°Ғн•ҳкі  м–ём ң л§җн•  кІғмқёк°Җ: лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң кіөк°ң м •мұ… н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Jiaqi Wei, Xuehang Guo, Pengfei Yu, Xiang Zhang, Wanli Ouyang, Siqi Sun, Qingyun Wang, Chenyu You","pos":"#1209","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jbm51tk6eI","abs":"<p>Standard Chain-of-Thought (CoT) reasoning trades reliability for responsiveness: in a single user-visible token stream, more deliberation delays meaningful output, imposing a ``silence tax.'' We introduce \\emph{Side-by-Side (SxS) Interleaved Reasoning}, a training framework that makes \\emph{disclosure timing} a controllable decision within standard autoregressive generation. By interleaving \\emph{supported} partial answers with continued private reasoning in the same context, SxS avoids monolithic reasoning preambles. We treat disclosure as a policy learning problem and train models via a multi-stage pipeline: supervised fine-tuning (SFT) on entailment-aligned interleaved trajectories, followed by reinforcement learning (RL) to recover reasoning performance and optimize accuracy. Without architectural changes, SxS improves the accuracy--latency trade-off across two Qwen3 architectures/scales (MoE \\textbf{Qwen3-30B-A3B}, dense \\textbf{Qwen3-4B}) and both in-domain (AIME25) and out-of-domain (GPQA-Diamond) benchmarks, reducing \\emph{substantive content latency} by 18\\% and improving a proxy for perceived wait time by 49\\%, yielding more responsive interactions without compromising answer quality.</p>","absKo":"<p>н‘ңмӨҖ Chain-of-Thought (CoT) м¶”лЎ мқҖ мӢ лў°м„ұкіј мқ‘лӢөм„ұ мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң trade-offлҘј л§Ңл“ӯлӢҲлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗм—җкІҢ ліҙмқҙлҠ” token stream м•Ҳм—җм„ң лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ deliberationмқҖ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ м§Җм—°мӢңмјң, мқҙлҘёл°” ``silence tax''лҘј л¶Җкіјн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\emph{Side-by-Side (SxS) Interleaved Reasoning}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ autoregressive generation лӮҙм—җм„ң \\emph{disclosure timing}мқ„ мЎ°м Ҳ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м •мңјлЎң л§Ңл“ңлҠ” training frameworkмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. к°ҷмқҖ context м•Ҳм—җм„ң \\emph{supported} partial answerмҷҖ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё private reasoningмқ„ interleaveн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, SxSлҠ” лӢЁмқјн•ң кұ°лҢҖн•ң reasoning preambleмқ„ н”јн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” disclosureлҘј policy learning л¬ём ңлЎң к°„мЈјн•ҳкі , лӢӨлӢЁкі„ pipelineмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ entailmentм—җ м •л ¬лҗң interleaved trajectoryлЎң supervised fine-tuning (SFT)мқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , к·ё лӢӨмқҢ reinforcement learning (RL)мңјлЎң reasoning м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҡҢліөн•ҳкі  accuracyлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳ ліҖкІҪ м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ SxSлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ Qwen3 architecture/scale (MoE \\textbf{Qwen3-30B-A3B}, dense \\textbf{Qwen3-4B})мҷҖ in-domain (AIME25), out-of-domain (GPQA-Diamond) benchmark лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң accuracy-latency trade-offлҘј к°ңм„ н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң \\emph{substantive content latency}лҘј 18\\% мӨ„мқҙкі , мІҙк°җ лҢҖкё° мӢңк°„мқҳ proxyлҘј 49\\% к°ңм„ н•ҳм—¬, лӢөліҖ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң лҚ” л°ҳмқ‘м Ғмқё мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61930","en":"UniRRM: Unified Reasoning Reward Models Across Languages and Evaluation Paradigms","ko":"UniRRM: м–ём–ҙмҷҖ нҸүк°Җ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м•„мҡ°лҘё нҶөн•© Reasoning Reward Model","authors":"Peng Lai, Yichao Du, Junchao Wu, Weibo Gao, Linan Yue, Longyue Wang, Weihua Luo, Derek F. Wong, Guanhua CHEN","pos":"#1300","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=laiK6TlhL2","abs":"<p>Reinforcement learning (RL) excels on tasks with verifiable rewards, but in open-ended tasks, the reliability of reward models remains a key challenge. Existing solutions either depend on costly proprietary LLM-as-a-Judge systems or opaque scalar reward models that lack interpretability. Recent works on generative reward models offer a promising alternative, but they remain constrained by static evaluation criteria, fragmented evaluation paradigms, and limited multilingual support. To address these challenges, we introduce MixReward, a large-scale multilingual dataset spanning six domains and 103 languages, containing both pairwise and listwise data, and propose UniRRM, a unified reasoning reward model supporting multiple languages and evaluation paradigms. UniRRM uses a staged reasoning chain to dynamically generate task-generic and instruction-specific criteria, enabling fine-grained, input-adaptive judgments while maintaining consistency across languages. Experiments demonstrate that UniRRM-8B and UniRRM-14B achieve performance close to the state-of-the-art for models of comparable size across multiple benchmarks, and are effective for unseen evaluation paradigms. In addition, ablation studies validate the reliability and effectiveness of UniRRM.</p>","absKo":"<p>к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө(RL)мқҖ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң ліҙмғҒмқҙ мһҲлҠ” кіјм ңм—җм„ңлҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, к°ңл°©нҳ• кіјм ңм—җм„ңлҠ” reward modelмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұмқҙ м—¬м „нһҲ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ н•ҙкІ°мұ…мқҖ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° proprietary LLM-as-a-Judge мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң л¶ҲнҲ¬лӘ…н•ң scalar reward modelм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ generative reward model м—°кө¬лҠ” мң л§қн•ң лҢҖм•Ҳмқҙм§Җл§Ң, м •м Ғ нҸүк°Җ кё°мӨҖ, л¶„м Ҳлҗң нҸүк°Җ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„, м ңн•ңм Ғмқё лӢӨкөӯм–ҙ м§ҖмӣҗмқҙлқјлҠ” м ңм•Ҫмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” pairwise л°Ҹ listwise лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј лӘЁл‘җ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” 6к°ң лҸ„л©”мқёкіј 103к°ң м–ём–ҙлҘј м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ лӢӨкөӯм–ҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ MixRewardлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ҳкі , м—¬лҹ¬ м–ём–ҙмҷҖ нҸүк°Җ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© reasoning reward model UniRRMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. UniRRMмқҖ лӢЁкі„м Ғ reasoning chainмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ task-generic л°Ҹ instruction-specific кё°мӨҖмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, м–ём–ҙ к°„ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м„ёл°Җн•ҳкі  мһ…л Ҙ м Ғмқ‘м Ғмқё нҢҗлӢЁмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј UniRRM-8BмҷҖ UniRRM-14BлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җм„ң лҸҷкёү нҒ¬кё° лӘЁлҚё мӨ‘ state-of-the-artм—җ к·јм ‘н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң нҸүк°Җ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„м—җм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң ablation studyлҠ” UniRRMмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұкіј нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65330","en":"ThreadWeaver: Adaptive Threading for Efficient Parallel Reasoning in Language Models","ko":"ThreadWeaver: м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ лі‘л ¬ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мҠӨл Ҳл”©","authors":"Long (Tony) Lian, Sida Wang, Felix Juefei-Xu, Tsu-Jui Fu, Xiuyu Li, Adam Yala, Trevor Darrell, Alane Suhr, Yuandong Tian, Xi Victoria Lin","pos":"#1309","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Efq2VvYk1o","abs":"<p>Scaling inference-time computation has enabled Large Language Models (LLMs) to achieve strong reasoning performance, but their inherently sequential decoding incurs substantial latency, motivating parallelization of the generation process. However, existing parallel reasoning approaches suffer from performance degradation compared to their sequential counterparts, and often rely on specialized inference engines. We introduce ThreadWeaver, a framework for adaptive parallel reasoning that matches the accuracy of comparably sized sequential reasoning models while significantly reducing inference latency via three key innovations: 1) a two-stage parallel trajectory generator that produces high-quality parallel chain-of-thought data for supervised fine-tuning; 2) a trie-based rollout design that enables parallel reasoning on any off-the-shelf autoregressive inference engine; and 3) a parallelization-aware reinforcement learning framework that trains the model to balance reasoning accuracy with effective parallelization. Across six challenging math reasoning benchmarks, ThreadWeaver trained on top of Qwen3-8B achieves performance on par with cutting-edge sequential reasoning models (79.9% on AIME24 and 71.9% on average) while delivering up to 1.53x speedup in token latency, establishing a new Pareto frontier between accuracy and efficiency.</p>","absKo":"<p>Inference-time computationмқҳ нҷ•мһҘмқҖ Large Language Model (LLM)мқҙ к°•л Ҙн•ң reasoning м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкІҢ н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң sequentialн•ң decodingмқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң latencyлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳм—¬ generation processмқҳ лі‘л ¬нҷ”лҘј мҙүм§„н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ parallel reasoning м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ sequential counterpartм—җ л№„н•ҙ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, мў…мў… нҠ№мҲҳн•ң inference engineм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м Ғмқ‘нҳ• parallel reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң frameworkмқё ThreadWeaverлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. ThreadWeaverлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ нҳҒмӢ мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, л№„көҗ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҒ¬кё°мқҳ sequential reasoning modelкіј м •нҷ•лҸ„лҠ” л§һлЁ№мңјл©ҙм„ң inference latencyлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. 1) supervised fine-tuningмқ„ мң„н•ң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ parallel chain-of-thought лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” two-stage parallel trajectory generator, 2) м–ҙл–Ө off-the-shelf autoregressive inference engineм—җм„ңлҸ„ parallel reasoningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” trie-based rollout design, 3) reasoning accuracyмҷҖ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё parallelization мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ нӣҲл Ён•ҳлҠ” parallelization-aware reinforcement learning frameworkмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. 6к°ңмқҳ к№ҢлӢӨлЎңмҡҙ math reasoning benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, Qwen3-8B мң„м—җ н•ҷмҠөлҗң ThreadWeaverлҠ” мөңмІЁлӢЁ sequential reasoning modelкіј лҸҷл“ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©ҙм„ң(AIME24м—җм„ң 79.9%, нҸүк·  71.9%) token latencyлҘј мөңлҢҖ 1.53л°°к№Ңм§Җ лӢЁм¶•н•ҳм—¬, accuracyмҷҖ efficiency мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Pareto frontierлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64256","en":"Think Deep, Not Just Long: Measuring LLM Reasoning Effort via Deep-Thinking Tokens","ko":"кёёкІҢк°Җ м•„лӢҢ к№ҠкІҢ мӮ¬кі н•ҳкё°: мӢ¬мёө мӮ¬кі  нҶ нҒ°мқ„ нҶөн•ң LLM м¶”лЎ  л…ёл Ҙ мёЎм •","authors":"Wei-Lin Chen, Liqian Peng, Tian Tan, Chao Zhao, Jianhang Chen, Ziqian Lin, Alec Go, Yu Meng","pos":"#1313","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PRSE0U5eGT","abs":"Large language models (LLMs) have demonstrated impressive reasoning capabilities by scaling test-time compute via long Chain-of-Thought (CoT). However, recent findings suggest that raw token counts are unreliable proxies for reasoning quality: increased generation length does not consistently correlate with accuracy and may instead signal ``overthinking,'' leading to performance degradation. In this work, we quantify inference-time effort by identifying \\emph{deep-thinking tokens}---tokens where internal predictions undergo significant revisions in deeper model layers prior to convergence. Across four challenging mathematical and scientific benchmarks (AIME 24/25, HMMT 25, and GPQA-diamond) and a diverse set of reasoning-focused models (GPT-OSS, DeepSeek-R1, and Qwen3), we show that \\textit{deep-thinking ratio} (the proportion of deep-thinking tokens in a generated sequence) exhibits a robust and consistently positive correlation with accuracy, substantially outperforming both length-based and confidence-based baselines. Leveraging this insight, we introduce Think@$n$, a test-time scaling strategy that prioritizes samples with high deep-thinking ratios. We demonstrate that Think@$n$ matches or exceeds standard self-consistency performance while significantly reducing inference costs by enabling the early rejection of unpromising generations based on short prefixes.","absKo":"Large language models(LLMs)мқҖ long Chain-of-Thought(CoT)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ test-time computeлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқёмғҒм Ғмқё reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” мӣҗмӢң token мҲҳк°Җ reasoning н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҳ мӢ лў°н•  л§Ңн•ң лҢҖлҰ¬ліҖмҲҳк°Җ м•„лӢҳмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мғқм„ұ кёёмқҙк°Җ кёём–ҙм§„лӢӨкі  н•ҙм„ң м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мғҒкҙҖлҗҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м•„лӢҲл©°, мҳӨнһҲл Ө ``overthinking''мқҳ мӢ нҳёк°Җ лҗҳм–ҙ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” лӮҙл¶Җ мҳҲмёЎмқҙ лҚ” к№ҠмқҖ model layerм—җм„ң мҲҳл ҙ м „м—җ нҒ° нҸӯмңјлЎң мҲҳм •лҗҳлҠ” tokenл“Ө, мҰү \\emph{deep-thinking tokens}лҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳм—¬ inference-time effortлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. AIME 24/25, HMMT 25, GPQA-diamondмқҳ л„Ө к°Җм§Җ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ мҲҳн•ҷ л°Ҹ кіјн•ҷ benchmarkмҷҖ GPT-OSS, DeepSeek-R1, Qwen3лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң reasoning мӨ‘мӢ¬ лӘЁлҚё м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textit{deep-thinking ratio}(мғқм„ұ мӢңнҖҖмҠӨм—җм„ң deep-thinking tokenмқҳ л№„мңЁ)к°Җ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ к°•кұҙн•ҳкі  мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ м–‘мқҳ мғҒкҙҖмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, кёёмқҙ кё°л°ҳ л°Ҹ confidence кё°л°ҳ baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” high deep-thinking ratioлҘј к°Җм§„ sampleмқ„ мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳлҠ” test-time scaling м „лһө Think@$n$мқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Think@$n$мқҙ н‘ңмӨҖ self-consistency м„ұлҠҘкіј к°ҷкұ°лӮҳ к·ё мқҙмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, м§§мқҖ prefixл§ҢмңјлЎң мң л§қн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ generationмқ„ мЎ°кё°м—җ кұ°л¶Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙ inference л№„мҡ©мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"60985","en":"The Truth Stays in the Family: Enhancing Contextual Truthfulness via Inherited Heads in Model Lineages","ko":"м§„мӢӨмқҖ Family м•Ҳм—җ лӮЁлҠ”лӢӨ: Model Lineageмқҳ Inherited HeadsлҘј нҶөн•ң Contextual Truthfulness н–ҘмғҒ","authors":"Miso Choi, Seonga Choi, Mincheol Kwon, Woosung Joung, Jinkyu Kim, Jungbeom Lee","pos":"#1314","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=unAyphD4hq","abs":"<p>Recent advances in large language models (LLMs) have led to the emergence of specialized multimodal LLMs (MLLMs), forming distinct model families that share a common foundation language models. Despite this evolutionary trend, it remains unexplored whether a fundamental behavioral link exists between derived MLLMs and their foundational LLMs. This work investigates the inheritance of truthfulness traits along this trajectory by quantifying the degree of context-truthfulness across individual attention heads. Our analysis of the Vicuna and Qwen families reveals a striking finding: MLLMs maintain a high correlation in truthfulness scores with their base LLMs, even after multi-modal fine-tuning and when evaluated on disparate data sources. Building on this insight, we propose a Soft Gating strategy that utilizes these inherited Truth Scores to amplify the influence of context-truthful heads while preserving the contributions of other heads. We validate our approach on base LLMs on HaluEval benchmark to demonstrate improved truthful reasoning. Subsequently, we show that Truth Scores derived from a base LLM can be effectively transferred to its multimodal descendants as a plug-and-play gate, achieving performance gains on POPE and CHAIR benchmark comparable to probing the MLLMs directly. Our work highlights a novel, systemic approach to enhancing reliability across an entire model family by leveraging its inherent, inherited traits.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language model (LLM)мқҳ мөңк·ј л°ңм „мқҖ нҠ№нҷ”лҗң multimodal LLM (MLLM)мқҳ м¶ңнҳ„мңјлЎң мқҙм–ҙмЎҢкі , мқҙл“ӨмқҖ кіөнҶөмқҳ foundation language modelмқ„ кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” distinct model familyлҘј нҳ•м„ұн•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м§„нҷ” м¶”м„ём—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , нҢҢмғқлҗң MLLMкіј к·ё foundation LLM мӮ¬мқҙм—җ к·јліём Ғмқё н–үлҸҷм Ғ м—°кІ°мқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҠ” м•„м§Ғ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” к°ңлі„ attention head м „л°ҳм—җм„ң context-truthfulnessмқҳ м •лҸ„лҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, мқҙ кі„ліҙлҘј л”°лқј truthfulness traitк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ кі„мҠ№лҗҳлҠ”м§Җ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. VicunaмҷҖ Qwen familyм—җ лҢҖн•ң л¶„м„қмқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ кІ°кіјлҘј ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ: MLLMмқҖ multi-modal fine-tuning мқҙнӣ„м—җлҸ„, к·ёлҰ¬кі  м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё data sourceлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ base LLMкіј truthfulness scoreмқҳ лҶ’мқҖ мғҒкҙҖмқ„ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҒмҶҚлҗң Truth ScoreлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ лӢӨлҘё headмқҳ кё°м—¬лҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң context-truthful headмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мҰқнҸӯн•ҳлҠ” Soft Gating strategyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” HaluEval benchmarkм—җм„ң base LLMмқ„ лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳм—¬ truthful reasoningмқҙ к°ңм„ лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ base LLMм—җм„ң лҸ„м¶ңн•ң Truth Scoreк°Җ plug-and-play gateлЎңм„ң multimodal descendantм—җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м „лӢ¬лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, MLLMмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ probingн•ҳлҠ” кІғкіј мң мӮ¬н•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ POPEмҷҖ CHAIR benchmarkм—җм„ң лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м—°кө¬лҠ” model family м „мІҙм—җ кұёміҗ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мғҒмҶҚлҗҳлҠ” traitлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мӢңмҠӨн…ңм Ғ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64022","en":"SmartThinker: Progressive Chain-of-Thought Length Calibration for Efficient Large Language Model Reasoning","ko":"SmartThinker: нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё Large Language Model м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң м җм§„м Ғ Chain-of-Thought кёёмқҙ ліҙм •","authors":"Chenzhi Hu, Qinzhe Hu, Yuhang Xu, Junyi Chen, Ruijie Wang, Shengzhong Liu, Jianxin Li, Fan Wu, Guihai Chen","pos":"#1402","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RciRcJ9LHw","abs":"<p>Large reasoning models (LRMs) like OpenAI o1 and DeepSeek-R1 achieve high accuracy on complex tasks by adopting long chain-of-thought (CoT) reasoning paths.  However, the inherent verbosity of these processes frequently results in redundancy and overthinking. To address this issue, existing works leverage Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) to reduce LRM output length, but their static length reward design cannot dynamically adapt according to the relative problem difficulty and response length distribution, causing over-compression and compromised accuracy. In this paper, we propose <em>SmartThinker</em>, a novel GRPO-based efficient reasoning method with progressive CoT length calibration.  <em>SmartThinker</em> makes a two-fold contribution:  First, it dynamically estimates the optimal length with peak accuracy during training, and further guides the overlong responses to approach the optimal length, in order to achieve length reduction while sustaining high accuracy. Second, it dynamically modulates the length reward coefficient to avoid the unwarranted penalization of correct reasoning paths. Extensive experiment results show that <em>SmartThinker</em> achieves up to 52.5\\% average length compression with improved accuracy, and achieves up to 16.6\\% accuracy improvement on challenging benchmarks like AIME25.</p>","absKo":"<p>OpenAI o1кіј DeepSeek-R1 к°ҷмқҖ Large reasoning models (LRMs)лҠ” кёҙ chain-of-thought (CoT) reasoning pathлҘј мұ„нғқн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ ліөмһЎн•ң taskм—җм„ң лҶ’мқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіјм •мқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғ мһҘнҷ©н•ЁмқҖ мў…мў… мӨ‘ліөкіј кіјлҸ„н•ң мӮ¬кі лҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO)мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ LRMмқҳ м¶ңл Ҙ кёёмқҙлҘј мӨ„мқҙм§Җл§Ң, м •м Ғмқё length reward м„Өкі„лҠ” мғҒлҢҖм Ғмқё л¬ём ң лӮңмқҙлҸ„мҷҖ мқ‘лӢө кёёмқҙ л¶„нҸ¬м—җ л”°лқј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҙ, кіјлҸ„н•ң м••м¶•кіј м •нҷ•лҸ„ м Җн•ҳлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” м җм§„м Ғмқё CoT кёёмқҙ ліҙм •мқ„ к°–лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ GRPO кё°л°ҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ м¶”лЎ  л°©лІ•мқё <em>SmartThinker</em>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. <em>SmartThinker</em>лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң кё°м—¬н•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ мөңкі  м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӮҙлҠ” мөңм Ғ кёёмқҙлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м¶”м •н•ҳкі , лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ л„Ҳл¬ҙ кёҙ мқ‘лӢөмқҙ мөңм Ғ кёёмқҙм—җ к°Җк№ҢмӣҢм§ҖлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬, лҶ’мқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң кёёмқҙлҘј мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, м •лӢ№н•ң reasoning pathлҘј л¶Ҳн•„мҡ”н•ҳкІҢ лІҢн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҸ„лЎқ length reward кі„мҲҳлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, <em>SmartThinker</em>лҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ң нҸүк·  мөңлҢҖ 52.5\\%мқҳ кёёмқҙ м••м¶•мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , AIME25мҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ benchmarkм—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ 16.6\\%мқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60517","en":"Stop When Further Reasoning WonвҖҷt Help: Attention-State Adaptive Generation in Reasoning Models","ko":"м¶”лЎ мқ„ лҚ” н•ҙлҸ„ лҸ„мӣҖмқҙ м•Ҳ лҗ  л•Ң л©Ҳм¶”кё°: Reasoning Modelмқҳ Attention-State Adaptive Generation","authors":"Jiakai Li, KE QIN, Rongzheng Wang, Yizhuo Ma, Qizhi Chen, Muquan Li, Shuang Liang","pos":"#1407","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=zRMK32N6t6","abs":"<p>By incorporating test-time compute scaling, large reasoning models (LRMs) are able to solve complex problems by generating explicit chain-of-thought (CoT) reasoning processes.  However, they often suffer from overthinking during generation, resulting in redundant token outputs and degraded accuracy.  Existing methods to mitigate this issue remain limited: training-based approaches incur substantial training costs, while training-free methods often rely on well-crafted prompting or unreliable confidence signals. In this work, we study early stopping through attention distributions and propose a simple method, ASAG, that infers the model's reasoning state and adaptively adjusts the generation strategy.  The proposed method is training-free and plug-and-play, enabling seamless integration into existing LRMs. Extensive experiments on nine benchmarks demonstrate consistent improvements across mainstream LRMs with varying parameter scales, including the Deepseek-R1-Distill and Qwen3 series. In particular, ASAG achieves a 4.4% relative improvement in accuracy while reducing the number of generated tokens by over 40% across all reasoning tasks on Qwen3-8B.</p>","absKo":"<p>test-time compute scalingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ large reasoning model (LRM)мқҖ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё chain-of-thought (CoT) м¶”лЎ  кіјм •мқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬ ліөмһЎн•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мғқм„ұ кіјм •м—җм„ң overthinkingмқ„ мһҗмЈј кІӘм–ҙ redundant token outputкіј м •нҷ•лҸ„ м Җн•ҳлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м ңн•ңм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. training-based м ‘к·јмқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң н•ҷмҠө л№„мҡ©мқҙ л“Өкі , training-free л°©лІ•мқҖ мў…мў… м •көҗн•ҳкІҢ лӢӨл“¬мқҖ promptingмқҙлӮҳ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” confidence signalм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” attention distributionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ early stoppingмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ҳкі , лӘЁлҚёмқҳ м¶”лЎ  мғҒнғңлҘј м¶”лЎ н•ҳм—¬ generation strategyлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ҳлҠ” к°„лӢЁн•ң л°©лІ• ASAGлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ training-freeмқҙл©° plug-and-playлЎң, кё°мЎҙ LRMм—җ л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ нҶөн•©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. 9к°ң benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Deepseek-R1-Distillкіј Qwen3 seriesлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң parameter scaleмқҳ мЈјлҘҳ LRM м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ ASAGлҠ” Qwen3-8Bмқҳ лӘЁл“  reasoning taskм—җм„ң мғқм„ұ token мҲҳлҘј 40% мқҙмғҒ мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ң м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј 4.4% мғҒлҢҖм ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңмј°лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65095","en":"The First Drop of Ink: Nonlinear Impact of Misleading Information in Long-Context Reasoning","ko":"мһүнҒ¬мқҳ мІ« л°©мҡё: мһҘл¬ё л§ҘлқҪ м¶”лЎ м—җм„ң мҳӨлҸ„ м •ліҙмқҳ л№„м„ нҳ•м Ғ мҳҒн–Ҙ","authors":"Muhan Gao, Zih-Ching Chen, Kuan-Hao Huang","pos":"#1412","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=GpRS2q0o3m","abs":"<p>As large language models (LLMs) are increasingly deployed in retrieval augmented generation (RAG) and agentic systems that accumulate extensive context, understanding how distracting information affects performance in long context becomes critical. Prior work shows that semantically relevant but misleading documents can cause performance degradation, yet the quantitative relationship between the proportion of distractors and performance remains unstudied. In this work, we systematically vary the proportion of hard distractors within fixed-length contexts, revealing a striking nonlinear pattern: as the proportion of hard distractors increases, performance drops sharply within the first small fraction, while the remainder of the range yields only marginal additional decline. We term this ''The First Drop of Ink'' effect, analogous to how a single drop of ink contaminates water. We provide both theoretical and empirical analysis grounded in attention mechanics: hard distractors disproportionately capture attention even at small proportions, with diminishing marginal impact as their proportion increases. Through controlled experiments, we further show that filtering yields performance gains primarily from context length reduction rather than distractor removal, and only achieves substantial recovery when hard distractor proportion is reduced to near zero, which highlights the importance of upstream retrieval precision.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language model (LLM)мқҙ retrieval augmented generation (RAG)кіј agentic systemм—җм„ң м җм җ лҚ” кёҙ contextлҘј м¶•м Ғн•ҳл©° л°°м№ҳлҗЁм—җ л”°лқј, distracting informationмқҙ long context м„ұлҠҘм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҙм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. м„ н–ү м—°кө¬лҠ” мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎң кҙҖл Ё мһҲм§Җл§Ң мҳӨлҸ„н•ҳлҠ” documentк°Җ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј мң л°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмҳҖм§Җл§Ң, distractor л№„мңЁкіј м„ұлҠҘ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ м •лҹүм Ғ кҙҖкі„лҠ” м•„м§Ғ м—°кө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” кі м • кёёмқҙ context лӮҙ hard distractorмқҳ л№„мңЁмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң ліҖнҷ”мӢңмјң, лҶҖлқјмҡҙ л№„м„ нҳ• нҢЁн„ҙмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. hard distractorмқҳ л№„мңЁмқҙ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ м„ұлҠҘмқҖ мІҳмқҢмқҳ мһ‘мқҖ кө¬к°„м—җм„ң кёүкІ©нһҲ н•ҳлқҪн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙнӣ„ лӮҳлЁём§Җ кө¬к°„м—җм„ңлҠ” м¶”к°Җ н•ҳлқҪмқҙ лҜёлҜён•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј л¬јм—җ мһүнҒ¬ н•ң л°©мҡёмқҙ нҚјм§ҖлҠ” кІғм—җ л№„мң н•ҳм—¬ ''The First Drop of Ink'' нҡЁкіјлқјкі  л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” attention mechanicsм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л°Ҹ мӢӨн—ҳм Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. hard distractorлҠ” л№„мңЁмқҙ мһ‘м•„лҸ„ attentionмқ„ л¶Ҳк· нҳ•н•ҳкІҢ л§Һмқҙ м°Ём§Җн•ҳл©°, к·ё л№„мңЁмқҙ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё мҳҒн–ҘмқҖ к°җмҶҢн•ңлӢӨ. нҶөм ңлҗң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, filteringмқҙ мЈјлҠ” м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқҖ мЈјлЎң distractor м ңкұ°ліҙлӢӨ context length к°җмҶҢм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗҳл©°, hard distractor л№„мңЁмқҙ кұ°мқҳ 0м—җ к°Җк№ҢмӣҢм§Ҳ л•Ңм—җл§Ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң нҡҢліөмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” upstream retrieval precisionмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ л¶Җк°Ғн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"68817","en":"Process Reward Models That Think","ko":"мӮ¬кі н•ҳлҠ” Process Reward Model","authors":"Muhammad Khalifa, Rishabh Agarwal, Lajanugen Logeswaran, Jaekyeom Kim, Hao Peng, Moontae Lee, Honglak Lee, Lu Wang","pos":"#1512","abs":"<p>Step-by-step verifiersвҖ”also known as process reward models (PRMs)вҖ”are a key ingredient for test-time scaling, but training them requires expensive step-level supervision. This work aims to build data-efficient PRMs as verbalized step-wise reward models that verify every step in the solution by generating a verification chain-of-thought (CoT). We propose ThinkPRM, a long CoT verifier fine-tuned on orders of magnitude fewer process labels than those required by discriminative PRMs. Our approach capitalizes on the inherent reasoning abilities of long CoT models, and outperforms LLM-as-a-Judge and discriminative verifiersвҖ”using only 1% of the process labels in PRM800KвҖ”across several challenging benchmarks. Specifically, ThinkPRM beats the baselines on ProcessBench, MATH-500, and AIME вҖҷ24 under best-of-N selection and reward-guided search. In an out-of-domain evaluation over subsets of GPQA-Diamond and LiveCodeBench, our PRM surpasses discriminative verifiers trained with the full PRM800K by 8% and 4.5%, respectively. Lastly, under the same token budget, ThinkPRM scales up verification compute more effectively compared to LLM-as-a-Judge, outperforming it by 7.2% on a subset of ProcessBench. This work highlights the value of generative, long CoT PRMs that can scale test-time compute for verification while requiring minimal supervision for training.</p>","absKo":"<p>Step-by-step verifierлЎңлҸ„ м•Ңл Өм§„ process reward models(PRMs)мқҖ test-time scalingмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл Өл©ҙ step мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ л№„мӢј supervisionмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” verification chain-of-thought(CoT)лҘј мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н•ҙлӢөмқҳ лӘЁл“  stepмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” verbalized step-wise reward modelлЎңм„ң data-efficient PRMмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” discriminative PRMм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң кІғліҙлӢӨ orders of magnitude м ҒмқҖ process labelл§ҢмңјлЎң fine-tuningн•ң long CoT verifierмқё ThinkPRMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ long CoT modelмқҙ ліёлһҳ м§ҖлӢҢ reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳл©°, PRM800Kмқҳ process labelмқ„ лӢЁ 1%л§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м—¬лҹ¬ к№ҢлӢӨлЎңмҡҙ benchmarkм—җм„ң LLM-as-a-JudgeмҷҖ discriminative verifierлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң ThinkPRMмқҖ best-of-N selectionкіј reward-guided searchм—җм„ң ProcessBench, MATH-500, AIME вҖҷ24мқҳ baselineмқ„ м•һм„ лӢӨ. GPQA-DiamondмҷҖ LiveCodeBenchмқҳ subsetм—җ лҢҖн•ң out-of-domain нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ PRMмқҖ м „мІҙ PRM800KлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң discriminative verifierліҙлӢӨ к°Ғк°Ғ 8%мҷҖ 4.5% лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң к°ҷмқҖ token budget н•ҳм—җм„ң ThinkPRMмқҖ LLM-as-a-Judgeм—җ л№„н•ҙ verification computeлҘј лҚ” нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳл©°, ProcessBench subsetм—җм„ң 7.2% лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” н•ҷмҠөм—җ мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ supervisionл§Ң н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳл©ҙм„ң test-time computeлҘј verificationм—җ л§һкІҢ нҷ•мһҘн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” generativeн•ң long CoT PRMмқҳ к°Җм№ҳлҘј ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62852","en":"Measuring and Mitigating Post-hoc Rationalization in Reverse Chain-of-Thought Generation","ko":"м—ӯл°©н–Ҙ Chain-of-Thought мғқм„ұм—җм„ң мӮ¬нӣ„ н•©лҰ¬нҷ”(post-hoc rationalization) мёЎм • л°Ҹ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Guangyue Peng, Zongchao Chen, Wen Luo, Yuntao Wen, Wei Li, Ruixiang Feng, Ran Le, Chen Yang, Zhenwei An, Yang Song, Tao Zhang, Houfeng Wang","pos":"#1702","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cY0pi9WHvL","abs":"<p>Reverse Chain-of-Thought Generation (RCG) synthesizes reasoning traces from query-answer pairs, but runs the risk of producing post-hoc rationalizations: when models can see the answer during generation, the answer serves as a cognitive anchor that shapes the entire explanation. We formalize this phenomenon through a three-level measurement hierarchy: lexical, entropic, and probabilistic anchoring, each captures surface artifacts, entropy dynamics, and latent answer dependence, respectively. We analyze semantic suppression, the intuitive mitigation strategy that instructs models to ignore the answer, to find out its counterproduction: while it reduces lexical overlap, it paradoxically increases entropic and probabilistic anchoring. Drawing on Ironic Process Theory from cognitive psychology, we attribute this failure to active monitoring of the forbidden answer, which inadvertently deepens dependence on it. To break this cycle, we propose Structural Skeleton-guided Reasoning (SSR), a two-phase approach that first generates an answer-invariant functional skeleton structure, then uses this skeleton to guide full trace generation. By redirecting the information flow to structural planning rather than answer monitoring, SSR consistently reduces anchoring across all three levels. We further introduce Distilled SSR (SSR-D), which fine-tunes models on teacher-generated SSR traces to ensure reliable structural adherence. Experiments across open-ended reasoning benchmarks demonstrate that SSR-D achieves up to 10\\% improvement over suppression baselines while preserving out-of-distribution (OOD) generalization. Code and data will be open-sourced upon acceptance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Reverse Chain-of-Thought Generation (RCG)мқҖ query-answer pairлЎңл¶Җн„° reasoning traceлҘј н•©м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, post-hoc rationalizationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•  мң„н—ҳмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мғқм„ұ мӨ‘м—җ лӢөмқ„ ліј мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©ҙ к·ё лӢөмқҙ cognitive anchorлЎң мһ‘мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м „мІҙ м„ӨлӘ…мқҳ нҳ•м„ұмқ„ мўҢмҡ°н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ lexical, entropic, probabilistic anchoringмқҳ м„ё мҲҳмӨҖ мёЎм • кі„мёөмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳл©°, к°Ғ кі„мёөмқҖ к°Ғк°Ғ н‘ңл©ҙм Ғ мӮ°л¬ј, entropy dynamics, мһ мһ¬м Ғ лӢө мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚём—җкІҢ лӢөмқ„ л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳлқјкі  м§ҖмӢңн•ҳлҠ” м§ҒкҙҖм Ғ мҷ„нҷ” м „лһөмқё semantic suppressionмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ҳм—¬ к·ё м—ӯнҡЁкіјлҘј нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” lexical overlapмқҖ мӨ„мқҙм§Җл§Ң, м—ӯм„Өм ҒмңјлЎң entropic л°Ҹ probabilistic anchoringмқ„ мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. cognitive psychologyмқҳ Ironic Process TheoryлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мӢӨнҢЁлҘј кёҲм§Җлҗң лӢөм—җ лҢҖн•ң active monitoringмқҙ мҳӨнһҲл Ө к·ё лӢөм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙмқ„ мӢ¬нҷ”мӢңнӮӨкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлқјкі  н•ҙм„қн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мҲңнҷҳмқ„ лҒҠкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЁјм Җ answer-invariant functional skeleton structureлҘј мғқм„ұн•ң л’Ө к·ё skeletonмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ м „мІҙ trace мғқм„ұмқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳлҠ” 2лӢЁкі„ м ‘к·јлІ•мқё Structural Skeleton-guided Reasoning (SSR)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м •ліҙлҘј лӢө лӘЁлӢҲн„°л§Ғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј кө¬мЎ°м Ғ кі„нҡҚмңјлЎң м „нҷҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, SSRмқҖ м„ё мҲҳмӨҖ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң anchoringмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң teacher-generated SSR traceлЎң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ fine-tuningн•ҳм—¬ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мӨҖмҲҳлҘј мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” Distilled SSR (SSR-D)мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. к°ңл°©нҳ• reasoning benchmark м „л°ҳмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SSR-Dк°Җ out-of-distribution (OOD) generalizationмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң suppression baseline лҢҖл№„ мөңлҢҖ 10%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” мұ„нғқ нӣ„ кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62146","en":"Look on Demand: A Cognitive Scheduling Framework for Visual Evidence Acquisition in Multimodal Reasoning","ko":"н•„мҡ”н•  л•Ң ліҙкё°: л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ м¶”лЎ м—җм„ң мӢңк°Ғ мҰқкұ° нҡҚл“қмқ„ мң„н•ң мқём§Җм Ғ мҠӨмјҖмӨ„л§Ғ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Yang Zhang, Xiaoshuai Sun, Rui Zhao, Wujin Sun, Yidong Chen, Jiayi Ji, Qian Chen, Rongrong Ji","pos":"#1704","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jO7tsly51F","abs":"<p>Existing multimodal reasoning approaches predominantly follow two paradigms: converting visual inputs into text prior to reasoning, or performing end-to-end reasoning within a unified visionвҖ“language representation space. Despite their empirical progress, both paradigms suffer from fundamental structural limitations. The former relies on static visual-to-text conversion, which tends to compress and lose fine-grained visual details. The latter is prone to linguistic dominance induced by joint optimization and attention mechanisms, leading to systematically weakened faithfulness to visual evidence during reasoning. In this work, we argue that a central challenge is how and when visual evidence is introduced into the reasoning process. Motivated by this insight, we propose CSMR, a multimodal reasoning framework in which a language model controls the reasoning process by deciding when to invoke an independent visual perception module to acquire task-relevant visual evidence. Experiments across multiple multimodal reasoning benchmarks show that CSMR consistently outperforms representative baseline methods in accuracy under a zero-shot setting. Further experimental analysis confirms that these advantages primarily arise from the proposed cognitive scheduling mechanism.</p>","absKo":"<p>кё°мЎҙмқҳ multimodal reasoning м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ л”°лҘёлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” reasoning мқҙм „м—җ visual inputмқ„ textлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” нҶөн•©лҗң visionвҖ“language representation space лӮҙм—җм„ң end-to-end reasoningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҙлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм Ғ м§„м „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , л‘җ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„ лӘЁл‘җ к·јліём Ғмқё кө¬мЎ°м Ғ н•ңкі„лҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨ. м „мһҗлҠ” static visual-to-text conversionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” м„ёл°Җн•ң visual detailмқ„ м••м¶•н•ҳкі  мҶҗмӢӨн•ҳлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. нӣ„мһҗлҠ” joint optimizationкіј attention mechanismмқҙ мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” linguistic dominanceм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳм—¬, reasoning мӨ‘ visual evidenceм—җ лҢҖн•ң faithfulн•ң лҢҖмқ‘мқҙ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң м•Ҫнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңк°Җ visual evidenceлҘј reasoning processм—җ м–ём ң, м–ҙл–»кІҢ лҸ„мһ…н•  кІғмқёк°Җлқјкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” language modelмқҙ task-relevant visual evidenceлҘј нҡҚл“қн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё visual perception moduleмқ„ нҳём¶ңн•  мӢңм җмқ„ кІ°м •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ reasoning processлҘј м ңм–ҙн•ҳлҠ” multimodal reasoning frameworkмқё CSMRмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ multimodal reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CSMRмқҙ zero-shot settingм—җм„ң м •нҷ•лҸ„ мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё baseline л°©лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. м¶”к°Җ мӢӨн—ҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мһҘм җмқҙ мЈјлЎң м ңм•Ҳн•ң cognitive scheduling mechanismм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗЁмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61216","en":"From Reasoning Traces to Reusable Modules: Reinforcement Learning for Compositional Generalization in Language Model Reasoning","ko":"м¶”лЎ  Traceм—җм„ң мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң ModuleлЎң: Language Model Reasoningмқҳ мЎ°н•© мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң Reinforcement Learning","authors":"Lingjing Kong, Xin Liu, Guangyi Chen, Martin Q. Ma, Xiangchen Song, Yuekai Sun, Mikhail Yurochkin, Taylor W. Killian, Russ Salakhutdinov, Kun Zhang, Eric Xing, Zhengzhong Liu","pos":"#1800","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=sb4WSZfAsL","abs":"<p>Reinforcement learning (RL) has emerged as a key mechanism for transforming LLMs into robust reasoners. While supervised fine-tuning (SFT) often limits models to the distribution of observed reasoning traces, RL post-training significantly improves performance on out-of-distribution (OOD) tasks that require unfamiliar recombinations of familiar steps. We argue that this improvement is driven by <strong>compositional generalization</strong>, which we formalize through a <strong>Hierarchical Latent Selection Model</strong>. In this framework, reasoning traces are generated by a cascade of discrete latent selection variables corresponding to reusable atomic modules, including both skills (local operations) and routing mechanisms (how intermediate information is selected, reused, and composed). We theoretically show that RLвҖҷs exploratory nature provides sufficient coverage to identify latent structure and enable compositional generalization. We design controlled experiments to validate this theory. Our results demonstrate that RL can extract atomic modules from compound traces and recombine them to solve new configurations. Moreover, we find that training on compound traces can yield stronger generalization than training on isolated atomic modules. Finally, we investigate relations between SFT and RL and identify an effective protocol in which SFT ensures coverage of all atomic modules, while RL focuses on novel compositions beyond the SFT support to encourage exploration.</p>","absKo":"<p>Reinforcement learning (RL)мқҖ LLMмқ„ кІ¬кі н•ң reasonerлЎң м „нҷҳн•ҳлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. Supervised fine-tuning (SFT)мқҙ мў…мў… modelмқ„ кҙҖмёЎлҗң reasoning traceмқҳ distributionм—җ л¬¶м–ҙл‘җлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, RL post-trainingмқҖ мқөмҲҷн•ң stepл“Өмқҳ лӮҜм„  мһ¬мЎ°н•©мқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң out-of-distribution (OOD) taskм—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ н–ҘмғҒмқҙ <strong>compositional generalization</strong>м—җ мқҳн•ҙ мЈјлҸ„лҗңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј <strong>Hierarchical Latent Selection Model</strong>мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkм—җм„ң reasoning traceлҠ” мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң atomic moduleм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” discrete latent selection variableмқҳ cascadeм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мғқм„ұлҗҳлҠ”лҚ°, м—¬кё°м—җлҠ” skill(көӯмҶҢм Ғ м—°мӮ°)кіј routing mechanism(мӨ‘к°„ м •ліҙк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м„ нғқлҗҳкі , мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳл©°, н•©м„ұлҗҳлҠ”м§Җ)мқҙ лӘЁл‘җ нҸ¬н•ЁлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” RLмқҳ нғҗмғүм Ғ(exploratory) м„ұм§Ҳмқҙ latent structureлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі  compositional generalizationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•  л§ҢнҒј м¶©л¶„н•ң coverageлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мқҙлЎ мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ нҶөм ңлҗң(controlled) мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” RLмқҙ compound traceлЎңл¶Җн„° atomic moduleмқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј мһ¬кІ°н•©н•ҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ configurationмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, compound traceлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ isolated atomic moduleлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ лҚ” к°•н•ң generalizationмқ„ лӮімқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SFTмҷҖ RLмқҳ кҙҖкі„лҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкі , SFTк°Җ лӘЁл“  atomic moduleмқҳ coverageлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” н•ңнҺё RLмқҖ SFT supportлҘј лІ—м–ҙлӮң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ compositionм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳм—¬ explorationмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ҳлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё protocolмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65516","en":"Geometry of Reason: Spectral Signatures of Valid Mathematical Reasoning","ko":"мқҙм„ұмқҳ кё°н•ҳн•ҷ: мң нҡЁн•ң мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ мқҳ мҠӨнҺҷнҠёлҹј мӢңк·ёлӢҲмІҳ","authors":"Valentin NOГӢL","pos":"#1801","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CrzJGqvrG8","abs":"Validating mathematical reasoning in large language models currently requires a trade-off between computationally expensive learned verifiers and the unreliability of output-based heuristics. We therefore propose a training-free, mechanistic alternative: spectral analysis of attention topology. By treating attention matrices as dynamic graphs over tokens, we extract four interpretable spectral diagnostics, Fiedler value, High-Frequency Energy Ratio (HFER), spectral entropy, and graph smoothness, that differentiate valid reasoning from hallucinated outputs without any learned parameters. We perform experiments across seven models from four architectural families (Llama, Qwen, Phi, Mistral) yield effect sizes up to Cohen's $d = 3.30$ ($p &lt; 10^{-116}$), enabling $85$--$96\\%$ classification accuracy with a single threshold. We discover that spectral analysis detects logical coherence rather than compiler acceptance: proofs rejected by formal verifiers due to timeouts or missing imports are correctly identified as valid, a phenomenon we term \"Platonic validity\". Furthermore, causal ablation studies confirm that this spectral signature reflects the functional health of induction head circuits, establishing a mechanistic basis for the method. We also identify an architectural dependency: Sliding Window Attention shifts the discriminative signal from HFER to late-layer smoothness ($d = 2.09$, $p &lt; 10^{-48}$), demonstrating that attention mechanism design determines which spectral features capture reasoning validity. The method generalizes to informal chain-of-thought reasoning ($d = 0.78$, $p &lt; 10^{-3}$). These findings establish spectral graph analysis as a principled framework for reasoning verification, with immediate applications to hallucination detection and real-time safety monitoring.","absKo":"large language modelм—җм„ң мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ нҳ„мһ¬ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° learned verifierмҷҖ м¶ңл Ҙ кё°л°ҳ heuristicмқҳ л¶ҲмӢ лў°м„ұ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offлҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нӣҲл Ёмқҙ н•„мҡ” м—ҶлҠ” кё°кі„лЎ м Ғ лҢҖм•ҲмңјлЎң attention topologyмқҳ spectral analysisлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. attention matrixлҘј token мң„мқҳ лҸҷм Ғ graphлЎң к°„мЈјн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Fiedler value, High-Frequency Energy Ratio (HFER), spectral entropy, graph smoothnessмқҳ л„Ө к°Җм§Җ н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң spectral diagnosticмқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙл“ӨмқҖ н•ҷмҠөлҗң parameter м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ нғҖлӢ№н•ң м¶”лЎ кіј hallucinated outputмқ„ кө¬л¶„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л„Ө к°Җм§Җ м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳ кі„м—ҙ(Llama, Qwen, Phi, Mistral)м—җм„ң 7к°ң лӘЁлҚём—җ кұёміҗ мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн–Ҳмңјл©°, Cohen's $d = 3.30$к№Ңм§Җмқҳ effect size ($p &lt; 10^{-116}$)лҘј м–»м–ҙ лӢЁмқј thresholdлЎң $85$--$96\\%$мқҳ л¶„лҘҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” spectral analysisк°Җ compilerмқҳ мҠ№мқё м—¬л¶Җк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј л…јлҰ¬м Ғ coherenceлҘј к°җм§Җн•ңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. formal verifierк°Җ timeoutмқҙлӮҳ лҲ„лқҪлҗң import л•Ңл¬ём—җ кұ°л¶Җн•ң proofлҸ„ мҳ¬л°”лҘҙкІҢ мң нҡЁн•ң кІғмңјлЎң мӢқлі„лҗҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј \"Platonic validity\"лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ causal ablation studyлҠ” мқҙ spectral signatureк°Җ induction head circuitмқҳ functional healthлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ҳм—¬, мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ кё°кі„лЎ м Ғ кё°л°ҳмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳ мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. Sliding Window AttentionмқҖ нҢҗлі„ мӢ нҳёлҘј HFERм—җм„ң late-layer smoothnessлЎң мқҙлҸҷмӢңнӮӨл©°($d = 2.09$, $p &lt; 10^{-48}$), attention mechanism м„Өкі„к°Җ м–ҙл–Ө spectral featureк°Җ м¶”лЎ  нғҖлӢ№м„ұмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј кІ°м •н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ л№„кіөмӢқ chain-of-thought м¶”лЎ м—җлҸ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ($d = 0.78$, $p &lt; 10^{-3}$). мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” spectral graph analysisлҘј м¶”лЎ  кІҖмҰқмқ„ мң„н•ң мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғ frameworkлЎң нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳл©°, hallucination detection л°Ҹ мӢӨмӢңк°„ safety monitoringм—җ мҰүк°Ғм ҒмңјлЎң мқ‘мҡ©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"66383","en":"From Extraction to Deduction: Resolving Functional Misalignment in RAG via a Collaborative Critic-Reasoner Framework","ko":"м¶”м¶ңм—җм„ң м—°м—ӯмңјлЎң: нҳ‘л Ҙм Ғ Critic-Reasoner н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј нҶөн•ң RAGмқҳ кё°лҠҘм Ғ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳ н•ҙмҶҢ","authors":"Yufei Chen, Yao Wang, Haibin Zhang, Hualin zhou, Tao Gu","pos":"#1901","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4BwA2qDAPy","abs":"<p>Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) systems suffer from a fundamental functional misalignment where retrievers optimize for semantic relevance, often recalling documents with high background utility but factually erroneous answer spans that generators blindly adopt as cognitive shortcuts. To resolve this, we propose the collaborative Critic-Reasoner framework that shifts robustness control from coarse-grained filtering to fine-grained cognitive decoupling. We disentangle the generation process into two serialized roles by deploying a Critic to perform surgical evidence purification through identifying and masking misleading entities while preserving supportive background context, followed by a Reasoner that switches from rote extraction to deductive reasoning based on the residual evidence. We operationalize this framework via a two-stage alignment strategy combining supervised fine-tuning (SFT) with path-aware direct preference optimization (DPO) to enforce strict behavioral synergy. Experimental results on adversarial benchmarks such as ConFiQA demonstrate that our method significantly outperforms baselines, achieving a 25.99\\% accuracy gain in conflicting scenarios and effectively resolving the trust bias dilemma in real-world RAG.</p>","absKo":"<p>Retrieval-augmented generation(RAG) мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҖ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё functional misalignmentлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. retrieverлҠ” semantic relevanceлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мў…мў… л°°кІҪм Ғ нҡЁмҡ©мқҖ лҶ’м§Җл§Ң мӮ¬мӢӨм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” мһҳлӘ»лҗң answer spanмқ„ к°Җм§„ л¬ём„ңлҘј recallн•ҳкі , generatorлҠ” мқҙлҘј л¬ҙл№„нҢҗм Ғмқё cognitive shortcutмңјлЎң л°ӣм•„л“ӨмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” coarse-grained filteringм—җм„ң fine-grained cognitive decouplingмңјлЎң robustness controlмқ„ м „нҷҳн•ҳлҠ” нҳ‘л Ҙм Ғ Critic-Reasoner frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” generation кіјм •мқ„ л‘җ к°ңмқҳ м§Ғл ¬нҷ”лҗң м—ӯн• лЎң л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ Criticмқ„ л°°м№ҳн•ҙ мҳӨн•ҙлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” entityлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі  л§ҲмҠӨнӮ№н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м§Җм§Җм Ғмқё background contextлҠ” ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” surgical evidence purificationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , мқҙм–ҙм„ң Reasonerк°Җ лӮЁмқҖ evidenceлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң rote extractionм—җм„ң deductive reasoningмңјлЎң м „нҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” supervised fine-tuning(SFT)кіј path-aware direct preference optimization(DPO)мқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң two-stage alignment strategyлЎң мқҙ frameworkлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳм—¬ м—„кІ©н•ң behavioral synergyлҘј к°•м ңн•ңлӢӨ. ConFiQAмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ adversarial benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, conflicting scenarioм—җм„ң 25.99\\%мқҳ accuracy н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мӢӨм ң RAGм—җм„ң trust bias dilemmaлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61200","en":"Dynamic Thinking-Token Selection for Efficient Reasoning in Large Reasoning Models","ko":"Large Reasoning Modelмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң лҸҷм Ғ Thinking-Token м„ нғқ","authors":"zhenyuan guo, Tong Chen, Wenlong Meng, Chen GONG, Xin Yu, Chengkun Wei, Wenzhi CHEN","pos":"#1913","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=sjK6Ii8TWs","abs":"Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) excel at solving complex problems by explicitly generating a reasoning trace before deriving the final answer.  However, these extended generations incur substantial memory footprint and computational overhead, bottlenecking LRMs' efficiency.  This work uses attention maps to analyze the influence of reasoning traces and uncover an interesting phenomenon: *only some decision-critical tokens in a reasoning trace steer the model toward the final answer, while the remaining tokens contribute negligibly.*  Building on this observation, we propose **Dyn**amic **T**hinking-Token **S**election (**DynTS**).  This method identifies decision-critical tokens and retains only their associated Key-Value (KV) cache states during inference, evicting the remaining redundant entries to optimize efficiency.  Across six benchmarks, \\toolname surpasses the state-of-the-art KV cache compression methods, improving Pass@1 by $2.6\\\\%$ under the same budget. Compared to vanilla Transformers, it reduces inference latency by $1.84вҖ“2.62\\times$ and peak KV-cache memory footprint by $3.32вҖ“5.73\\times$ without compromising LRMs' reasoning performance. The code is available at the anonymous link.\\footnote{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/DynTS-2D0D}","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м¶”лЎ  лӘЁлҚё(LRM)мқҖ мөңмў… лӢөмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкё° м „м—җ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң reasoning traceлҘј мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ ліөмһЎн•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° лӣ°м–ҙлӮ©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кёҙ мғқм„ұмқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҹүкіј м—°мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳм—¬ LRMмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ м Җн•ҙн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” attention mapмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ reasoning traceмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ҳкі  нқҘлҜёлЎңмҡҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ л°қнҳҖлғ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҰү, reasoning trace м•Ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ кІ°м •м—җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мқјл¶Җ tokenл§Ңмқҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мөңмў… лӢөмңјлЎң мқҙлҒ„лҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, лӮҳлЁём§Җ tokenмқҖ кұ°мқҳ кё°м—¬н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” **Dyn**amic **T**hinking-Token **S**election(**DynTS**)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ кІ°м •м—җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң tokenмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , м¶”лЎ  мӢң н•ҙлӢ№ tokenм—җ м—°кІ°лҗң Key-Value(KV) cache stateл§Ң мң м§Җн•ҳл©° лӮҳлЁём§Җ мӨ‘ліө н•ӯлӘ©мқҖ м ңкұ°н•ҳм—¬ нҡЁмңЁмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. 6к°ң benchmarkм—җм„ң \\toolnameмқҖ мөңмӢ  KV cache м••м¶• л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, лҸҷмқјн•ң budgetм—җм„ң Pass@1мқ„ $2.6\\\\%$ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮөлӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң vanilla TransformerмҷҖ л№„көҗн•ҙ LRMмқҳ м¶”лЎ  м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нӣјмҶҗн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң inference latencyлҘј $1.84вҖ“2.62\\times$, peak KV-cache memory footprintлҘј $3.32вҖ“5.73\\times$ мӨ„мһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” мқөлӘ… л§ҒнҒ¬м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ.\\footnote{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/DynTS-2D0D}"},{"id":"62933","en":"DenseSteer: Steering Small Language Models towards Dense Math Reasoning","ko":"DenseSteer: мҶҢнҳ• м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ Dense Math ReasoningмңјлЎң мң лҸ„","authors":"Yang Ouyang, Shuhang Lin, Jung-Eun Kim","pos":"#2007","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bkcxLMm3Gp","abs":"Large language models (LLMs) demonstrate strong chain-of-thought (CoT) reasoning abilities, while smaller models ($\\leq$ 3B parameters) significantly underperform on multi-step reasoning tasks.   Based on empirical analyses of the Qwen-2.5 model family on math reasoning benchmarks, we find that more proficient reasoning is associated with fewer reasoning steps but higher information density per step, a property we term *Dense Reasoning*.    Motivated by this observation, we propose **DenseSteer**, a training-free inference-time steering framework that enhances small-model reasoning by modulating internal representations toward dense reasoning patterns.    Experiments show that our method yields consistent accuracy improvements without increasing token-level Negative Log-Likelihood, highlighting dense reasoning as an effective structural approach to mathematical problem solving.","absKo":"Large language model (LLM)мқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң chain-of-thought (CoT) reasoning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм§Җл§Ң, лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ model(\\(\\leq\\) 3B parameter)мқҖ multi-step reasoning taskм—җм„ң нҳ„м ҖнһҲ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷ reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ң Qwen-2.5 model familyм—җ лҢҖн•ң кІҪн—ҳм Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҚ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң reasoningмқҙ лҚ” м ҒмқҖ reasoning stepмқҙм§Җл§Ң stepлӢ№ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ information densityмҷҖ кҙҖл ЁлҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҘј *Dense Reasoning*мқҙлқј л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм°°м—җ лҸҷкё°лҘј л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӮҙл¶Җ representationмқ„ dense reasoning pattern мӘҪмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ small-model reasoningмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” training-free inference-time steering frameworkмқё **DenseSteer**лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ token-level Negative Log-LikelihoodлҘј мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮӨм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң м •нҷ•лҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, dense reasoningмқҙ мҲҳн•ҷ л¬ём ң н•ҙкІ°мқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё кө¬мЎ°м Ғ м ‘к·јмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62942","en":"BeaconKV: Key-Value Cache Compression Guided by Beacon Queries for Efficient Large Reasoning Model Inference","ko":"BeaconKV: нҡЁмңЁм Ғ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ Reasoning Model м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң Beacon Queries кё°л°ҳ Key-Value Cache Compression","authors":"Janghyeon Kim, Minsoo Kim, Kyuhong Shim, Jungwook Choi","pos":"#2106","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bgAbffQCrL","abs":"Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) achieve superior problem-solving through extended chain-of-thought generation, but the resulting key-value (KV) cache grows linearly with sequence length and creates severe memory bottlenecksвҖ”often exceeding GPU capacity for long reasoning traces. Existing KV cache compression methods rely on recent queries to estimate future token importance, implicitly assuming these serve as reliable proxies for future attention patterns. We demonstrate that this assumption fails in long-horizon reasoning: certain decoding steps generate Thought Revisiting Tokens (TRT) that re-attend to distant previous context, such as task-solving plans formulated early in the trace. Through systematic analysis, we discover that queries corresponding to the TRT cluster into a small number of similarity groups in the embedding space. Based on this insight, we propose BeaconKV, a training-free KV cache compression method that maintains beacon queriesвҖ”compact representatives for each global query clusterвҖ”to anticipate which KV pairs will be revisited without storing the entire query history. We introduce Continual Farthest Point Sampling for memory-efficient beacon identification during inference. Across four open-source LRMs and diverse reasoning benchmarks, BeaconKV consistently outperforms state-of-the-art methods, achieving up to $5.8\\times$ memory reduction while nearly preserving full cache accuracy and improving throughput by over $4.3\\times$.","absKo":"Large Reasoning Model(LRM)мқҖ extended chain-of-thought generationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң л¬ём ң н•ҙкІ° лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё кІ°кіј key-value(KV) cacheлҠ” sequence lengthм—җ л”°лқј м„ нҳ•мңјлЎң мҰқк°Җн•ҳл©° мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кёҙ reasoning traceм—җм„ңлҠ” мў…мў… GPU мҡ©лҹүмқ„ мҙҲкіјн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ KV cache compression л°©лІ•мқҖ лҜёлһҳ token importanceлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мөңк·ј queryм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мқҙл“Өмқҙ лҜёлһҳ attention patternмқҳ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” proxyлқјкі  м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң к°Җм •н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ к°Җм •мқҙ мһҘкё° reasoningм—җм„ңлҠ” м„ұлҰҪн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқјл¶Җ decoding stepмқҖ Thought Revisiting Token(TRT)мқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙ tokenмқҖ traceмқҳ мҙҲкё°м—җ нҳ•м„ұлҗң task-solving planмІҳлҹј лЁј кіјкұ°мқҳ contextлҘј лӢӨмӢң attentionн•ңлӢӨ. мІҙкі„м Ғмқё л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” TRTм—җ н•ҙлӢ№н•ҳлҠ” queryк°Җ embedding spaceм—җм„ң мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ similarity groupмңјлЎң кө°м§‘н•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м „мІҙ query historyлҘј м ҖмһҘн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң м–ҙл–Ө KV pairк°Җ лӢӨмӢң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗ м§ҖлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ к°Ғ global query clusterмқҳ compact representativeмқё beacon queryлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” training-free KV cache compression methodмқё BeaconKVлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң inference мӨ‘ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё beacon identificationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ Continual Farthest Point Samplingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. л„Ө к°ңмқҳ open-source LRMкіј лӢӨм–‘н•ң reasoning benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң BeaconKVлҠ” мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ state-of-the-art methodлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, full cache м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј кұ°мқҳ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң мөңлҢҖ $5.8\\times$мқҳ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ м Ҳк°җкіј $4.3\\times$ мқҙмғҒмқҳ throughput н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61925","en":"Attention Illuminates LLM Reasoning: The Uncovered Preplan-and-Anchor Rhythm Enables Fine-Grained Policy Optimization","ko":"Attention Illuminates LLM Reasoning: л“ңлҹ¬лӮң Preplan-and-Anchor лҰ¬л“¬мңјлЎң м •л°Җ Policy Optimization к°ҖлҠҘ","authors":"Yang Li, Zhichen Dong, Yuhan Sun, Weixun Wang, Shaopan Xiong, Yijia Luo, Jiashun Liu, Han Lu, Jiamang Wang, Wenbo Su, Bo Zheng, Junchi Yan","pos":"#2109","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ld40RIJnpb","abs":"<p>The reasoning patterns of large language models (LLMs) remain opaque, and Reinforcement learning (RL) typically assigns uniform credit across an entire generation, blurring the distinction between pivotal and routine steps. This work treats attention as a natural substrate for interpreting LLM reasoning and a window for aligning optimization with its internal dynamics. We first distinguish attention heads between locally and globally focused information processing and reveal that locally focused heads produce a sawtooth pattern near the diagonal indicating phrasal chunks, while globally focused heads expose tokens that exert broad downstream influence over future tokens. We quantify these with two metrics measuring the extent of backward attention within a clipped window and the average attention a token receives from subsequent tokens, respectively. Taken together, these signals reveal a recurring preplan-and-anchor mechanism, where the model first performs a long-range contextual reference to generate an introductory token, which is immediately followed by or coincides with a semantic anchor token that organizes subsequent reasoning. Leveraging these insights, we introduce three novel RL strategies that dynamically perform targeted credit assignment to critical nodes (preplan tokens, anchor tokens, and their temporal coupling) and show consistent performance gains across various reasoning tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>large language model (LLM)мқҳ reasoning patternмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ л¶ҲнҲ¬лӘ…н•ҳл©°, Reinforcement learning (RL)мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м „мІҙ generationм—җ к· мқјн•ҳкІҢ creditмқ„ н• лӢ№н•ҳм—¬ н•өмӢ¬ лӢЁкі„мҷҖ мқјмғҒм Ғмқё лӢЁкі„лҘј кө¬л¶„н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” attentionмқ„ LLM reasoningмқ„ н•ҙм„қн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ кё°л°ҳмқҙмһҗ, мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј лӮҙл¶Җ лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷм—җ л§һм¶”кё° мң„н•ң м°ҪмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЁјм Җ attention headлҘј көӯмҶҢм ҒмңјлЎң м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳлҠ” м •ліҙ мІҳлҰ¬мҷҖ м „м—ӯм ҒмңјлЎң м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳлҠ” м •ліҙ мІҳлҰ¬лЎң кө¬л¶„н•ҳкі , көӯмҶҢ м§‘мӨ‘ headлҠ” лҢҖк°Ғм„  к·јмІҳм—җм„ң phrasal chunkлҘј лӮҳнғҖлӮҙлҠ” sawtooth patternмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, м „м—ӯ м§‘мӨ‘ headлҠ” мқҙнӣ„ нҶ нҒ°л“Өм—җ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң downstream influenceлҘј н–үмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” нҶ нҒ°мқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лғ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј к°Ғк°Ғ clipped window лӮҙ backward attentionмқҳ лІ”мң„мҷҖ мқҙнӣ„ нҶ нҒ°л“ӨлЎңл¶Җн„° нҶ нҒ°мқҙ л°ӣлҠ” нҸүк·  attentionмқ„ мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ metricмңјлЎң м •лҹүнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢ нҳёлҠ” л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” preplan-and-anchor л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙлҠ”лҚ°, лӘЁлҚёмқҙ лЁјм Җ мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ л¬ёл§Ҙ м°ёмЎ°лҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҙ лҸ„мһ… нҶ нҒ°мқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , к·ё м§Ғнӣ„ лҳҗлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ нӣ„мҶҚ reasoningмқ„ мЎ°м§Ғн•ҳлҠ” semantic anchor tokenмқҙ л’Өл”°лҘёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң л…ёл“ң(preplan token, anchor token, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мқҙл“Өмқҳ temporal coupling)м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лӘ©н‘ң м§Җн–Ҙм Ғ credit assignmentлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ RL м „лһөмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, лӢӨм–‘н•ң reasoning taskм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61081","en":"AtomWorld: A Benchmark for Evaluating Spatial Reasoning in Large Language Models on Material Structures","ko":"AtomWorld: л¬јм§Ҳ кө¬мЎ°м—җм„ң Large Language Modelмқҳ кіөк°„ м¶”лЎ  нҸүк°Җ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Taoyuze Lv, Alexander Chen, Fengyu Xie, Chu Wu, Jeffrey Meng, Dongzhan Zhou, Yingheng Wang, Bram Hoex, Zhicheng Zhong, Tong Xie","pos":"#2110","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tqr5sZlS6Y","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) have shown promising potential in materials science, enabling tasks ranging from knowledge retrieval to property prediction. Existing materials science benchmarks mainly focus on perceptual or knowledge-based tasks, largely ignoring the structure modelling tasks, a core challenge in real scientific workflows. In practice, constructing and manipulating atomic structures is one of the most creative and least automated steps in materials research. In this work, we introduce AtomWorld, a benchmark designed to evaluate the abilities of LLMs on structure modifications. The benchmark includes ten fundamental actions under four widely used modelling categories, enabling verifiable evaluation metrics. We find that Gemini 2.5 Pro generally performs the best. While the success rate decreases markedly with increasing modelling complexity, with particularly low success rates (below 12\\% for rotation) for operations involving complex spatial relations. Our results suggest that contemporary LLMs are better suited as copilots for materials structure modelling rather than fully unsupervised autonomous scientific agents. Beyond evaluation, AtomWorld also serves as a testbed and playground for developing future structure-aware models, including reinforcement learning and agentic approaches.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language models (LLMs)лҠ” materials scienceм—җм„ң knowledge retrievalл¶Җн„° property predictionм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң taskлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©° мң л§қн•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ materials science benchmarkлҠ” мЈјлЎң perceptual лҳҗлҠ” knowledge-based taskм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”кі  мһҲм–ҙ, мӢӨм ң scientific workflowмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңмқё structure modelling taskлҠ” лҢҖмІҙлЎң к°„кіјн•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎң atomic structureлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мЎ°мһ‘н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ materials researchм—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ м°Ҫмқҳм Ғмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ к°ҖмһҘ мһҗлҸҷнҷ”к°Җ лҚң лҗң лӢЁкі„ мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳмқҙлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” structure modificationм—җ лҢҖн•ң LLMмқҳ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗң benchmarkмқё AtomWorldлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ benchmarkлҠ” л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” л„Ө к°Җм§Җ modelling category м•„лһҳ м—ҙ к°Җм§Җ кё°ліё actionмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳл©°, verifiable evaluation metricмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Gemini 2.5 Proк°Җ м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң к°ҖмһҘ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ ліөмһЎн•ң spatial relationмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” м—°мӮ°м—җм„ңлҠ” м„ұкіөлҘ мқҙ нҳ„м ҖнһҲ к°җмҶҢн•ҳл©°, лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ ліөмһЎлҸ„к°Җ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ м„ұкіөлҘ мқҙ лҡңл ·н•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлқҪн•ңлӢӨ(нҡҢм „мқҳ кІҪмҡ° 12\\% лҜёл§ҢмңјлЎң нҠ№нһҲ лӮ®мқҢ). мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ LLMмқҙ мҷ„м „нһҲ л№„м§ҖлҸ„мӢқм Ғмқё мһҗмңЁ кіјн•ҷ м—җмқҙм „нҠёлқјкё°ліҙлӢӨ materials structure modellingмқ„ мң„н•ң copilotsлЎң лҚ” м Ғн•©н•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. нҸүк°ҖлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ AtomWorldлҠ” reinforcement learningкіј agentic approachлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лҜёлһҳмқҳ structure-aware modelмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң testbedмқҙмһҗ playgroundлЎңлҸ„ кё°лҠҘн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61807","en":"Are Large Reasoning Models Interruptible?","ko":"Large Reasoning ModelмқҖ мӨ‘лӢЁ к°ҖлҠҘн•ңк°Җ?","authors":"Tsung-Han (Patrick) Wu, Mihran Miroyan, David Chan, Trevor Darrell, Narges Norouzi, Joseph E Gonzalez","pos":"#2111","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mlQWk1DtkN","abs":"<p>Real-world applications of Large Reasoning Models (LRMs) often require reasoning about changing prompts or environments. In this work, we evaluate LRM robustness under two realistic dynamic scenarios: interruptions, which test the accuracy of model responses under budget-constrained outputs, and dynamic context, which tests model adaptation to in-flight changes. Across mathematics and programming benchmarks that require long-form reasoning, static evaluations consistently overestimate robustness: even state-of-the-art LRMs, which achieve high accuracy in static settings, can fail unpredictably when interrupted or exposed to changing context, with performance dropping by up to 60\\% when updates are introduced late in the reasoning process. Our analysis further reveals several novel failure modes, including reasoning leakage, where models fold the reasoning into their final answer when interrupted; panic, where under time pressure models abandon reasoning entirely and return incorrect answers; and self-doubt, where performance degrades when trying to incorporate updated information.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Reasoning Models (LRMs)мқҳ мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ңлҠ” ліҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” promptлӮҳ нҷҳкІҪм—җ лҢҖн•ң м¶”лЎ мқҙ мў…мў… н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё лҸҷм Ғ мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң LRMмқҳ robustnessлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” interruptionмңјлЎң, budgetмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗң м¶ңл Ҙ н•ҳм—җм„ң лӘЁлҚё мқ‘лӢөмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳл©°, лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” dynamic contextлЎң, м§„н–ү мӨ‘мқё ліҖнҷ”м—җ лҢҖн•ң лӘЁлҚёмқҳ м Ғмқ‘мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мһҘл¬ё м¶”лЎ мқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” мҲҳн•ҷ л°Ҹ н”„лЎңк·ёлһҳл°Қ benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң static evaluationмқҖ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ robustnessлҘј кіјлҢҖнҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. static settingм—җм„ң лҶ’мқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” мөңмІЁлӢЁ LRMsмЎ°м°Ё interruptionмқ„ л°ӣкұ°лӮҳ ліҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” contextм—җ л…ём¶ңлҗҳл©ҙ мҳҲмёЎ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ мӢӨнҢЁн•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, reasoning кіјм • нӣ„л°ҳм—җ updateк°Җ лҸ„мһ…лҗҳл©ҙ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ мөңлҢҖ 60\\%к№Ңм§Җ н•ҳлқҪн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ failure modeлҘј л°қнҳҖлӮёлӢӨ. interruptionмқ„ л°ӣм•ҳмқ„ л•Ң лӘЁлҚёмқҙ reasoningмқ„ мөңмў… лӢөм•Ҳм—җ м„һм–ҙ л„ЈлҠ” reasoning leakage, мӢңк°„ м••л°• мҶҚм—җм„ң reasoningмқ„ мҷ„м „нһҲ нҸ¬кё°н•ҳкі  мһҳлӘ»лҗң лӢөмқ„ л°ҳнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” panic, к·ёлҰ¬кі  к°ұмӢ лҗң м •ліҙлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳл Ө н•  л•Ң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗҳлҠ” self-doubtк°Җ к·ёкІғмқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61476","en":"Algorithmic Primitives and Compositional Geometry of Reasoning in Language Models","ko":"Language Modelsм—җм„ң м¶”лЎ мқҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳм Ғ PrimitivesмҷҖ мЎ°н•©м Ғ кё°н•ҳ","authors":"Samuel Lippl, Thomas McGee, Kimberly Lopez, Ziwen Pan, Pierce Zhang, Salma Ziadi, Oliver Eberle, Ida Momennejad","pos":"#2213","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ppirVueEj6","abs":"<p>How do latent and inference time computations enable large language models (LLMs) to solve multi-step reasoning? We introduce a framework for tracing and steering algorithmic primitives that underlie model reasoning. Our approach links reasoning traces to internal activations and evaluates algorithmic primitives by injecting them into residual streams and measuring their effect on reasoning steps and task performance. We consider four benchmarks: Traveling Salesperson Problem (TSP), 3SAT, AIME, and graph navigation. We operationalize primitives by clustering activations and annotating their matched reasoning traces using an automated LLM pipeline. We then apply function vector methods to derive primitive vectors as reusable compositional building blocks of reasoning. Primitive vectors can be combined through addition, subtraction, and scalar operations, revealing a geometric logic in activation space. Cross-task and cross-model evaluations (Phi-4, Phi-4-Reasoning, Llama-3-8B) show both shared and task-specific primitives. Notably, comparing Phi-4 with its reasoning-finetuned variant highlights compositional generalization after finetuning: Phi-4-Reasoning exhibits more systematic use of verification and path-generation primitives. Injecting the associated primitive vectors in Phi-4 induces behavioral hallmarks associated with Phi-4-Reasoning. Together, these findings demonstrate that reasoning in LLMs may be supported by a compositional geometry of algorithmic primitives, that primitives transfer cross-task and cross-model, and that reasoning finetuning strengthens algorithmic generalization across domains.</p>","absKo":"<p>latentмҷҖ inference-time computationмқҖ large language models (LLMs)мқҙ multi-step reasoningмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл–»кІҢ кё°м—¬н•ҳлҠ”к°Җ? мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚё м¶”лЎ мқҳ кё°м ҖлҘј мқҙлЈЁлҠ” algorithmic primitiveлҘј м¶”м Ғн•ҳкі  мЎ°н–Ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ reasoning traceлҘј лӮҙл¶Җ activationкіј м—°кІ°н•ҳкі , residual streamм—җ мқҙлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ң л’Ө reasoning stepкіј task м„ұлҠҘм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мёЎм •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ algorithmic primitiveлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Traveling Salesperson Problem (TSP), 3SAT, AIME, graph navigationмқҳ л„Ө к°Җм§Җ benchmarkлҘј кі л Өн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” activationмқ„ clusteringн•ҳкі  мһҗлҸҷнҷ”лҗң LLM pipelineмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ л§Өм№ӯлҗң reasoning traceм—җ мЈјм„қмқ„ лӢ¬м•„ primitiveлҘј operationalizeн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ function vector methodлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ reasoningмқҳ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң compositional building blockмңјлЎңм„ң primitive vectorлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. Primitive vectorлҠ” лҚ§м…Ҳ, лә„м…Ҳ, мҠӨм№јлқј м—°мӮ°мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кІ°н•©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, activation spaceм—җм„ңмқҳ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ л…јлҰ¬лҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. Cross-task л°Ҹ cross-model нҸүк°Җ(Phi-4, Phi-4-Reasoning, Llama-3-8B)лҠ” кіөмң  primitiveмҷҖ task-specific primitiveлҘј лӘЁл‘җ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ Phi-4мҷҖ reasoning-finetuned ліҖнҳ•мқ„ л№„көҗн•ҳл©ҙ finetuning мқҙнӣ„мқҳ compositional generalizationмқҙ к°•мЎ°лҗңлӢӨ: Phi-4-ReasoningмқҖ verification л°Ҹ path-generation primitiveлҘј лҚ” мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. кҙҖл Ё primitive vectorлҘј Phi-4м—җ мЈјмһ…н•ҳл©ҙ Phi-4-Reasoningкіј м—°кҙҖлҗң н–үлҸҷм Ғ нҠ№м§•мқҙ мң лҸ„лҗңлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” LLMмқҳ reasoningмқҙ algorithmic primitiveмқҳ compositional geometryм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м§Җмӣҗлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, primitiveлҠ” taskмҷҖ modelмқ„ к°ҖлЎңм§Ҳлҹ¬ м „мқҙлҗҳкі , reasoning finetuningмқҙ лҸ„л©”мқё м „л°ҳмқҳ algorithmic generalizationмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62434","en":"Harnessing Reasoning Trajectories for Hallucination Detection via Answer-agreement Representation Shaping","ko":"Answer-agreement Representation Shapingмқ„ нҶөн•ң Hallucination нғҗм§Җм—җм„ң Reasoning Trajectory нҷңмҡ©","authors":"Jianxiong Zhang, Bing Guo, Yuming Jiang, Haobo Wang, Bo An, Sean Du","pos":"#2904","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gcuFTjpJFE","abs":"<p>Large reasoning models (LRMs) often generate long, seemingly coherent reasoning traces yet still produce incorrect answers, making hallucination detection challenging. Although trajectories contain useful signals, directly using trace text or vanilla hidden states for detection is brittle: traces vary in form and detectors can overfit to superficial patterns rather than answer validity. We introduce Answer-agreement Representation Shaping (ARS), which learns detection-friendly trace-conditioned representations by explicitly encoding answer stability. ARS generates counterfactual answers through small latent interventions, specifically, perturbing the trace-boundary embedding, and labels each perturbation by whether the resulting answer agrees with the original. It then learns representations that bring answer-agreeing states together and separate answer-disagreeing ones, exposing latent instability indicative of hallucination risk. The shaped embeddings are plug-and-play with existing embedding-based detectors and require no human annotations during training. Experiments demonstrate that ARS consistently improves detection and achieves substantial gains over strong baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large reasoning models (LRMs)лҠ” мў…мў… кёёкі  кІүліҙкё°м—җлҠ” мқјкҙҖлҗң reasoning traceлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң м—¬м „нһҲ мһҳлӘ»лҗң лӢөмқ„ лӮҙлҶ“м•„ hallucination detectionмқ„ м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. trajectoryм—җлҠ” мң мҡ©н•ң мӢ нҳёк°Җ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, trace textлӮҳ vanilla hidden stateлҘј м§Ғм ‘ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҖ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. traceлҠ” нҳ•нғңк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ҳкі  detectorлҠ” лӢөмқҳ нғҖлӢ№м„ұліҙлӢӨ н‘ңл©ҙм Ғ нҢЁн„ҙм—җ кіјм Ғн•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Answer-agreement Representation Shaping (ARS)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ARSлҠ” answer stabilityлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳм—¬ detectionм—җ м Ғн•©н•ң trace-conditioned representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. ARSлҠ” мһ‘мқҖ latent intervention, кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң trace-boundary embeddingмқ„ perturbationн•ҳм—¬ counterfactual answerлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , к°Ғ perturbationм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ к·ё кІ°кіј answerк°Җ мӣҗлһҳ answerмҷҖ мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м—¬л¶ҖлҘј кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң labelмқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ answerк°Җ мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” мғҒнғңлҘј к°Җк№қкІҢ, answerк°Җ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” мғҒнғңлҘј л©ҖкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬, hallucination riskлҘј мӢңмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” latent instabilityлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мқҙл ҮкІҢ shapingлҗң embeddingмқҖ кё°мЎҙ embedding-based detectorмҷҖ plug-and-playлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ human annotationмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ ARSк°Җ detectionмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к°ңм„ н•ҳкі  к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineліҙлӢӨ нҒ° н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61843","en":"When to Memorize and When to Stop: Gated Recurrent Memory for Long-Context Reasoning","ko":"м–ём ң кё°м–өн•ҳкі  м–ём ң л©Ҳм¶ң кІғмқёк°Җ: Long-Context Reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң Gated Recurrent Memory","authors":"Leheng Sheng, Yongtao Zhang, Wenchang Ma, Yaorui Shi, Ting Huang, Xiang Wang, An Zhang, Ke Shen, Tat-Seng Chua","pos":"#3502","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mOPwfQSfJq","abs":"While reasoning over long context is crucial for various real-world applications, it remains challenging for large language models (LLMs) as they suffer from performance degradation as the context length grows.  Recent work MemAgent has tried to tackle this by processing context chunk-by-chunk in an RNN-like loop and updating a textual memory for final answering.  However, this naive recurrent memory update faces two crucial drawbacks:  (i) memory can quickly explode because it can update indiscriminately, even on evidence-free chunks;  and (ii) the loop lacks an exit mechanism, leading to unnecessary computation after even sufficient evidence is collected.  To address these issues, we propose GRU-Mem, which incorporates two text-controlled gates for more stable and efficient long-context reasoning. Specifically, in GRU-Mem, the memory only updates when the update gate is open and the recurrent loop will exit immediately once the exit gate is open.  To endow the model with such capabilities, we introduce two reward signals $r^{\\text{update}}$ and $r^{\\text{exit}}$ within end-to-end RL, rewarding the correct updating and exiting behaviors respectively.  Experiments on various long-context reasoning tasks demonstrate the effectiveness and efficiency of GRU-Mem, which generally outperforms the vanilla MemAgent with up to 400\\% times inference speed acceleration.","absKo":"кёҙ contextм—җ лҢҖн•ң reasoningмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң real-world applicationм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, context lengthк°Җ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ large language model(LLM)м—җкІҢлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬ MemAgentлҠ” contextлҘј chunk лӢЁмң„лЎң RNN-like loopм—җм„ң мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳкі  мөңмў… лӢөліҖмқ„ мң„н•ҙ textual memoryлҘј к°ұмӢ н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈЁл Ө н–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң naive recurrent memory updateм—җлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ м№ҳлӘ…м Ғ лӢЁм җмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. (i) evidenceк°Җ м—ҶлҠ” chunkм—җм„ңлҸ„ л¬ҙм°Ёлі„м ҒмңјлЎң к°ұмӢ н•  мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙ memoryк°Җ л№ лҘҙкІҢ нҸӯмЈјн•  мҲҳ мһҲкі , (ii) loopм—җ exit mechanismмқҙ м—Ҷм–ҙ м¶©л¶„н•ң evidenceк°Җ мқҙлҜё мҲҳм§‘лҗң л’Өм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳн•„мҡ”н•ң кі„мӮ°мқҙ кі„мҶҚлҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҚ” м•Ҳм •м Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё long-context reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң л‘җ к°ңмқҳ text-controlled gateлҘј нҶөн•©н•ң GRU-Memмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, GRU-Memм—җм„ңлҠ” update gateк°Җ м—ҙл Ө мһҲмқ„ л•Ңл§Ң memoryк°Җ к°ұмӢ лҗҳкі , exit gateк°Җ м—ҙлҰ¬л©ҙ recurrent loopк°Җ мҰүмӢң мў…лЈҢлҗңлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚём—җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” end-to-end RL лӮҙм—җм„ң $r^{\\text{update}}$мҷҖ $r^{\\text{exit}}$лқјлҠ” л‘җ reward signalмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ к°Ғк°Ғ мҳ¬л°”лҘё updateмҷҖ exit н–үлҸҷмқ„ ліҙмғҒн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң long-context reasoning taskм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ GRU-Memмқҳ нҡЁкіјм„ұкіј нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң vanilla MemAgentліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ 400\\%мқҳ inference speed accelerationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61313","en":"Learning to Self-Verify Makes Language Models Better Reasoners","ko":"мһҗкё° кІҖмҰқ н•ҷмҠөмқҖ Language Modelмқ„ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м¶”лЎ кё°лЎң л§Ңл“ лӢӨ","authors":"Yuxin Chen, Yu Wang, Yi Zhang, Ziang Ye, Zhengzhou Cai, Yaorui Shi, Qi GU, Hui Su, Xunliang Cai, Xiang Wang, An Zhang, Tat-Seng Chua","pos":"#400","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=rSDj9EM1HV","abs":"<p>Recent large language models (LLMs) achieve strong performance in generating promising reasoning paths for complex tasks. However, despite powerful generation ability, LLMs remain weak at verifying their own answers, revealing a persistent capability asymmetry between generation and self-verification. In this work, we conduct an in-depth investigation of this asymmetry throughout training evolution and show that, even on the same task, improving generation does not lead to corresponding improvements in self-verification. Interestingly, we find that the reverse direction of this asymmetry behaves differently: learning to self-verify can effectively improve generation performance, achieving accuracy comparable to standard generation training while yielding more efficient and effective reasoning traces. Building on this observation, we further explore integrating self-verification into generation training by formulating a multi-task reinforcement learning framework, where generation and self-verification are optimized as two independent but complementary objectives. Extensive experiments across benchmarks and models demonstrate performance gains over generation-only training in both generation and verification capabilities.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(LLM)мқҖ ліөмһЎн•ң кіјм ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мң л§қн•ң м¶”лЎ  кІҪлЎңлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к°•н•ң мғқм„ұ лҠҘл Ҙм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , LLMмқҖ мһҗмӢ мқҳ лӢөмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл ҘмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м•Ҫн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мғқм„ұкіј мһҗкё° кІҖмҰқ мӮ¬мқҙм—җ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё лҠҘл Ҙ л№„лҢҖм№ӯмқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•Ёмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” н•ҷмҠө м§„нҷ” м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мқҙ л№„лҢҖм№ӯмқ„ мӢ¬мёөм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкі , к°ҷмқҖ кіјм ңм—җм„ңлҸ„ мғқм„ұ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқҙ к·ём—җ мғҒмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” мһҗкё° кІҖмҰқ н–ҘмғҒмңјлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§Җм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. нқҘлҜёлЎӯкІҢлҸ„, мқҙ л№„лҢҖм№ӯмқҳ м—ӯл°©н–ҘмқҖ лӢӨлҘҙкІҢ лӮҳнғҖлӮңлӢӨ. мҰү, мһҗкё° кІҖмҰқмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©ҙ мғқм„ұ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, н‘ңмӨҖ мғқм„ұ н•ҷмҠөм—җ н•„м Ғн•ҳлҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё м¶”лЎ  к¶Өм Ғмқ„ мӮ°м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһҗкё° кІҖмҰқмқ„ мғқм„ұ н•ҷмҠөм—җ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” л°©н–Ҙмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң нғҗкө¬н•ҳл©°, мғқм„ұкіј мһҗкё° кІҖмҰқмқ„ м„ңлЎң лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң мғҒнҳёліҙмҷ„м Ғмқё л‘җ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” multi-task reinforcement learning н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkмҷҖ modelм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мғқм„ұ м „мҡ© н•ҷмҠөліҙлӢӨ мғқм„ұ л°Ҹ кІҖмҰқ лҠҘл Ҙ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60883","en":"Grounding Multi-Hop Reasoning in Structural Causal Models via Group Relative Policy Optimization","ko":"Group Relative Policy Optimizationмқ„ нҶөн•ң Structural Causal Model кё°л°ҳ Multi-Hop Reasoning Grounding","authors":"Yunhan Bu, quan zhang, Zhang Huaping, Guotong Geng, Chunxiao Gao, Askar Hamdulla, Juan Wang, Qiuchi Li, Baohua Zhang, Yunbo Cao, Zhunchen Luo, Shuai Lei","pos":"#108","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vfIUEpSTji","abs":"<p>Multi-Hop Fact Verification (MHFV) necessitates complex reasoning across disparate evidence, posing significant challenges for Large Language Models (LLMs) which often suffer from hallucinations and fractured logical chains. Existing methods, while improving transparency via Chain-of-Thought (CoT), lack explicit modeling of the causal dependencies between evidence and claims. In this work, we introduce a novel framework that grounds reasoning in a Structural Causal Model (SCM), treating verification as a constructive causal inference process. We empirically identify an \"inverted U-shaped\" correlation between reasoning chain length and accuracy, revealing that excessive structural complexity degrades performance. To address this, we propose a Rule-based Reinforcement Learning strategy using Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO). This approach dynamically optimizes the trade-off between structural depth and conciseness. Extensive experiments on HoVer and EX-FEVER demonstrate that our SCM-GRPO framework significantly outperforms state-of-the-art baselines, offering a reliable and interpretable solution for complex fact verification.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multi-Hop Fact Verification (MHFV)лҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё evidence м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң ліөмһЎн•ң reasoningмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳл©°, hallucinationкіј лӢЁм Ҳлҗң logical chainмқ„ мһҗмЈј кІӘлҠ” Large Language Models (LLMs)м—җкІҢ нҒ° лҸ„м „мқҙ лҗңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ Chain-of-Thought (CoT)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ transparencyлҘј лҶ’мқҙм§Җл§Ң, evidenceмҷҖ claim мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ causal dependencyлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳм§ҖлҠ” лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” reasoningмқ„ Structural Causal Model (SCM)м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ҳл©°, verificationмқ„ constructive causal inference processлЎң лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reasoning chain кёёмқҙмҷҖ accuracy мӮ¬мқҙм—җ \"inverted U-shaped\" мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„к°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мқён•ҳм—¬, кө¬мЎ°м Ғ ліөмһЎм„ұмқҙ кіјлҸ„н•ҙм§Җл©ҙ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” Rule-based Reinforcement Learning м „лһөмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ structural depthмҷҖ conciseness мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. HoVerмҷҖ EX-FEVERм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ SCM-GRPO frameworkк°Җ state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, ліөмһЎн•ң fact verificationмқ„ мң„н•ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкі  н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61244","en":"VIA-SD: Verification via Intra-Model Routing for Speculative Decoding","ko":"VIA-SD: Speculative Decodingмқ„ мң„н•ң Intra-Model Routing кё°л°ҳ кІҖмҰқ","authors":"Yuchen Xian, Yang He, Yunqiu Xu, Yi Yang","pos":"#1201","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=sGCDBHIr9u","abs":"<p>Speculative decoding (SD) addresses the high inference costs of large language models (LLMs) by having lightweight drafters generate candidates for large verifiers to validate in parallel. Existing draft-verify methods use binary decisions: accept or fully recompute. Yet we find that many rejected tokens can be verified correctly by a slim submodel derived from the full verifier via intra-model routing, instead of the full verifier. This motivates our slim-verifier to handle tokens requiring moderate verification resources, reducing expensive large-model calls. We propose <strong>V</strong>erification via <strong>I</strong>ntr<strong>a</strong>-Model Routing for <strong>S</strong>peculative <strong>D</strong>ecoding (VIA-SD), a multi-tier framework using a routed slim-verifier. Draft tokens are processed hierarchically: direct acceptance for high-confidence cases, slim-verifier regeneration for medium-confidence cases, and full-model verification for uncertain cases. Across summarization, translation, reasoning, QA, and coding tasks on encoder-decoder and decoder-only model families, VIA-SD consistently lowers rejection rates (0.1вҖ“0.22) and achieves 10вҖ“20\\% speedup over state-of-the-art SDs. Compared to decoding without drafting, VIA-SD provides 2.5-3Г— acceleration while improving output quality. Moreover, VIA-SD is compatible with existing SD frameworks without modifying their training procedures. Our results establish multi-tier SD as a general paradigm for scalable and efficient LLM inference. Our code will be publicly available.</p>","absKo":"<p>Speculative decoding(SD)мқҖ lightweight drafterк°Җ нӣ„ліҙлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , large verifierк°Җ мқҙлҘј parallelн•ҳкІҢ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң large language model(LLM)мқҳ лҶ’мқҖ inference costлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ draft-verify л°©лІ•мқҖ binary decision, мҰү accept лҳҗлҠ” full recomputeлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л§ҺмқҖ rejected tokenмқҙ full verifier лҢҖмӢ , intra-model routingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ full verifierлЎңл¶Җн„° лҸ„м¶ңлҗң slim submodelм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мҳ¬л°”лҘҙкІҢ кІҖмҰқлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” expensiveн•ң large-model нҳём¶ңмқ„ мӨ„мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ moderate verification resourceк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ң tokenмқ„ мІҳлҰ¬н•  slim-verifierмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{V}erification via \\textbf{I}ntr\\textbf{a}-Model Routing for \\textbf{S}peculative \\textbf{D}ecoding(VIA-SD)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” routed slim-verifierлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” multi-tier frameworkмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. Draft tokenмқҖ кі„мёөм ҒмңјлЎң мІҳлҰ¬лҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҶ’мқҖ confidenceмқҳ кІҪмҡ° direct acceptance, мӨ‘к°„ confidenceмқҳ кІҪмҡ° slim-verifier regeneration, л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨн•ң кІҪмҡ° full-model verificationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. encoder-decoderмҷҖ decoder-only model familyмқҳ summarization, translation, reasoning, QA, coding task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң VIA-SDлҠ” мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ rejection rate(0.1вҖ“0.22)лҘј лӮ®м¶”кі  state-of-the-art SD лҢҖл№„ 10вҖ“20\\% мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. drafting м—Ҷмқҙ decodingн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқкіј л№„көҗн•ҳл©ҙ, VIA-SDлҠ” м¶ңл Ҙ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳл©ҙм„ң 2.5-3л°°мқҳ к°ҖмҶҚмқ„ м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң VIA-SDлҠ” кё°мЎҙ SD frameworkмҷҖ нҳёнҷҳлҗҳл©° training procedureлҘј мҲҳм •н•  н•„мҡ”к°Җ м—ҶмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” multi-tier SDк°Җ scalableн•ҳкі  efficientн•ң LLM inferenceлҘј мң„н•ң мқјл°ҳм Ғ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мһ„мқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мһ…лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62437","en":"Weaving Graph over Tokens: Contextualizing Structured Sequences for LLMs","ko":"нҶ нҒ° мң„м—җ к·ёлһҳн”„лҘј м§ңлӢӨ: LLMмҡ© кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мӢңнҖҖмҠӨмқҳ Contextualization","authors":"Jiaxuan Chen, Zixing Zhang, Ruijun Mao, Wei Sun, Zhicheng Liang, Yuhang Zhang, Yaxi Liu, Fangxin Wang","pos":"#1206","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gbQyvsdfGO","abs":"<p>Generative Graph Language Models (GLMs) must reconcile topology with causal   language modeling. Linearization obscures multi-hop connectivity, while   encoder-based methods bottleneck token-level reasoning during generation.   Viewing context modeling as a form of message passing, we   introduce <strong>Weaver</strong>, an encoder-free framework that extends the attention mechanism of decoder-only LLMs to enable graph reasoning. Weaver   maps graph distances into rotary positional embeddings so that structurally   connected nodes become proximate in attention space, propagating information   over graph topology as if it were sequential context. To achieve this, we   combine: 1) a masking mechanism for causal tokens with graph structures; 2) a   unified geometric encoding that couples sequential position and graph distance   in joint rotary embeddings (Graph-over-Tokens RoPE); and 3) a design principle   to prioritize local information to resolve positional ambiguity under graph   symmetries. On zero-shot benchmarks, Weaver achieves state-of-the-art performance among generative GLMs, with gains of up to 30\\% over prior generative methods on  heterophilic graphs, while matching specialized discriminative models on  citation networks---all within a unified decoder-only framework.</p>","absKo":"<p>Generative Graph Language Models (GLMs)лҠ” topologyмҷҖ causal language modelingмқ„ мЎ°нҷ”мӢңмјңм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. LinearizationмқҖ multi-hop connectivityлҘј к°ҖлҰ¬л©°, encoder-based methodлҠ” generation мӨ‘ token-level reasoningм—җм„ң лі‘лӘ©мқ„ мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. Context modelingмқ„ message passingмқҳ н•ң нҳ•нғңлЎң л°”лқјліҙл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” decoder-only LLMмқҳ attention mechanismмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•ҙ graph reasoningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” <strong>Weaver</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. WeaverлҠ” graph distanceлҘј rotary positional embeddingм—җ л§Өн•‘н•ҳм—¬ кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң м—°кІ°лҗң nodeк°Җ attention spaceм—җм„ң к°Җк№ҢмӣҢм§ҖлҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“Өкі , graph topologyлҘј л”°лқј м •ліҙлҘј sequential contextмІҳлҹј м „лӢ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 1) graph structureлҘј к°–лҠ” causal tokenмқ„ мң„н•ң masking mechanism, 2) sequential positionкіј graph distanceлҘј joint rotary embedding(Graph-over-Tokens RoPE)м—җм„ң кІ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© кё°н•ҳ мқёмҪ”л”©, 3) graph symmetry н•ҳм—җм„ң positional ambiguityлҘј н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ local informationмқ„ мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳлҠ” м„Өкі„ мӣҗм№ҷмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ңлӢӨ. zero-shot benchmarkм—җм„ң WeaverлҠ” generative GLM мӨ‘ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, heterophilic graphм—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙм „ generative methodліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ 30\\% н–ҘмғҒлҗҳкі , citation networkм—җм„ңлҠ” нҠ№нҷ”лҗң discriminative modelкіј лҸҷл“ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ лӘЁл“  кІғмқҙ нҶөн•©лҗң decoder-only framework м•Ҳм—җм„ң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65553","en":"When Search Goes Wrong: Red-Teaming Web-Augmented Large Language Models","ko":"нғҗмғүмқҙ мһҳлӘ»лҗ  л•Ң: Web мҰқк°• Large Language Modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң л Ҳл“ң нҢҖ","authors":"Haoran Ou, Kangjie Chen, Xingshuo Han, Gelei Deng, Jie Zhang, Han Qiu, Tianwei Zhang, Kwok Yan Lam","pos":"#1208","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CUURF3uF5M","abs":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs) have been augmented with web search to overcome the limitations of the static knowledge boundary by accessing up-to-date information from the open Internet. While this integration enhances model capability, it also introduces a distinct safety threat surface: the retrieval and citation process has the potential risk of exposing users to harmful or low-credibility web content. Existing red-teaming methods are largely designed for standalone LLMs as they primarily focus on unsafe generation, ignoring risks emerging from the complex search workflow. To address this gap, we propose CREST-Search, a pioneering red-teaming framework for LLMs with web search. The cornerstone of CREST-Search is three novel attack strategies that generate seemingly benign search queries yet induce unsafe citations. It also employs an iterative in-context refinement mechanism to strengthen adversarial effectiveness under black-box constraints. In addition, we construct a search-specific harmful dataset, WebSearch-Harm, which enables fine-tuning a specialized red-teaming model to improve query quality. Our experiments demonstrate that CREST-Search can effectively bypass safety filters and systematically expose vulnerabilities in web search-based LLM systems, underscoring the necessity of the development of robust search models.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs)мқҖ open Internetм—җм„ң мөңмӢ  м •ліҙлҘј м ‘к·јн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ м •м Ғ м§ҖмӢқ кІҪкі„мқҳ н•ңкі„лҘј к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ web searchмҷҖ кІ°н•©лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөн•©мқҖ лӘЁлҚё лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨм§Җл§Ң, лҸҷмӢңм—җ лҸ…нҠ№н•ң м•Ҳм „ мң„нҳ‘л©ҙмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. retrieval л°Ҹ citation кіјм •мқҙ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗм—җкІҢ мң н•ҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мӢ лў°лҸ„к°Җ лӮ®мқҖ web contentлҘј л…ём¶ңмӢңнӮ¬ мһ мһ¬м Ғ мң„н—ҳмқҙ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ red-teaming л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң лӢЁлҸ… LLMмқҳ unsafe generationм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”кі  мһҲм–ҙ, ліөмһЎн•ң search workflowм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” мң„н—ҳмқ„ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” web searchлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң м„ кө¬м Ғмқё red-teaming frameworkмқё CREST-SearchлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. CREST-Searchмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ кІүліҙкё°м—җлҠ” л¬ҙн•ҙн•ң search queryлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң unsafe citationмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ attack strategyмқҙлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң black-box м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ң adversarial effectivenessлҘј к°•нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ iterative in-context refinement mechanismмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ”л¶Ҳм–ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” WebSearch-HarmмқҙлқјлҠ” search-specific harmful datasetмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳм—¬, query qualityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ң нҠ№нҷ”лҗң red-teaming modelмқ„ fine-tuningн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CREST-Searchк°Җ safety filterлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳкі  web search кё°л°ҳ LLM systemмқҳ м·Ём•Ҫм җмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л“ңлҹ¬лӮј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, robust search model к°ңл°ңмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61358","en":"Towards Reliable Marking and Verification of AI-Generated Text via Geometry-aware Sentence-level Watermarking","ko":"Geometry-aware Sentence-level Watermarkingмқ„ нҶөн•ң AI мғқм„ұ н…ҚмҠӨнҠёмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲлҠ” н‘ңмӢңмҷҖ кІҖмҰқ","authors":"Yubing Ren, Ping Guo, Yanan Cao","pos":"#1303","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=r0sWQkr3Jx","abs":"Large generative models raise growing concerns about provenance, misinformation, and impersonation. Digital watermarking offers a principled solution, yet extending it to natural language remains challenging due to text discreteness and sensitivity to semantic perturbations. Existing text watermarking methods either operate at the token level requiring white-box access and remaining fragile to paraphrasing, or at the sentence level, which supports black-box deployment but suffers from low Watermark Success Rate (WSR). We show that low WSR in sentence-level watermarking primarily stems from low injection success probability caused by a mismatch between posterior embedding distributions and semantic accept regions. Based on this insight, we propose \\textbf{X-Guard}, a geometry-aware sentence-level watermarking framework that improves injection success by jointly optimizing embedding distributions and semantic space partitioning. X-Guard learns a more isotropic embedding space and introduces \\textbf{A$^2$PQ}, a centroid-aligned partitioning scheme that approximately equalizes probability mass across regions. Extensive experiments across multiple models, languages, and attack settings demonstrate that X-Guard consistently improves robustness while preserving text fluency and practical deployability.","absKo":"Large generative modelмқҖ provenance, misinformation, impersonationм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°л ӨлҘј м җм җ лҚ” нӮӨмҡ°кі  мһҲлӢӨ. Digital watermarkingмқҖ мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, н…ҚмҠӨнҠёмқҳ мқҙмӮ°м„ұкіј мқҳлҜём Ғ perturbationм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҜјк°җм„ұ л•Ңл¬ём—җ мқҙлҘј мһҗм—°м–ҙлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ text watermarking л°©лІ•мқҖ white-box м ‘к·јмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳкі  paraphrasingм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ң token-level л°©мӢқмқҙкұ°лӮҳ, black-box л°°нҸ¬лҠ” к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң Watermark Success Rate (WSR)к°Җ лӮ®мқҖ sentence-level л°©мӢқ мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” sentence-level watermarkingм—җм„ң лӮ®мқҖ WSRмқҳ мЈјмҡ” мӣҗмқёмқҙ posterior embedding distributionкіј semantic accept region к°„мқҳ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлЎң мқён•ҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” лӮ®мқҖ injection success probabilityм—җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, embedding distributionкіј semantic space partitioningмқ„ кіөлҸҷ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ injection successлҘј к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” geometry-aware sentence-level watermarking frameworkмқё \\textbf{X-Guard}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. X-GuardлҠ” ліҙлӢӨ isotropicн•ң embedding spaceлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , к°Ғ regionм—җ кұёміҗ probability massлҘј к·јмӮ¬м ҒмңјлЎң к· л“ұнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” \\textbf{A$^2$PQ} centroid-aligned partitioning schemeмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ model, language, attack settingм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ X-Guardк°Җ text fluencyмҷҖ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ л°°нҸ¬ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"65587","en":"Shared Semantics, Divergent Mechanisms: Unsupervised Feature Discovery by Aligning Semantics and Mechanisms","ko":"кіөмң лҗң мқҳлҜё, мғҒмқҙн•ң л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳ: мқҳлҜёмҷҖ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳ м •л ¬мқ„ нҶөн•ң л№„м§ҖлҸ„ нҠ№м§• л°ңкІ¬","authors":"Hyunjin Cho, Youngji Roh, Jaehyung Kim","pos":"#1401","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=C9AhjL8aUZ","abs":"<p>As large language models are increasingly deployed in high-stakes settings, there is a growing need for tools that audit not only model outputs but also the internal computations that produce them. Circuit analysis is a central approach in mechanistic interpretability, but it is typically target-conditioned, explaining a single prompt paired with a chosen completion. This target-conditioned setup obscures mechanistic heterogeneity and hinders scalable discovery. We introduce distribution-level unsupervised feature discovery, which discovers interpretable clusters across a promptвҖҷs continuation distribution and provides a knob to trade off semantic granularity against mechanistic specificity, without manual target selection. Our method samples continuations, represents each with (i) a semantic embedding and (ii) a mechanistic signature derived from sparse feature attributions, and clusters them via a rateвҖ“distortion objective that trades off semantic coherence and mechanistic consistency. We also show that our method has cluster-level causality, which validates the discovery of cluster-level mechanistic representation. Overall, our approach complements circuit analysis and behavioral evaluation by providing a scalable, unsupervised audit of the mechanisms underlying a modelвҖҷs continuation distribution.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ language modelмқҙ кі мң„н—ҳ(high-stakes) нҷҳкІҪм—җ м җм җ лҚ” л§Һмқҙ л°°нҸ¬лҗЁм—җ л”°лқј, лӘЁлҚё outputлҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј к·ёкІғмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ лӮҙлҠ” лӮҙл¶Җ кі„мӮ°к№Ңм§Җ к°җмӮ¬(audit)н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лҸ„кө¬м—җ лҢҖн•ң н•„мҡ”м„ұмқҙ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. Circuit analysisлҠ” mechanistic interpretabilityмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, ліҙнҶө target-conditioned л°©мӢқмңјлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм ё лӢЁмқј promptмҷҖ м„ нғқлҗң completionмқҳ мҢҚмқ„ м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° к·ём№©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң target-conditioned м„Өм •мқҖ mechanistic heterogeneityлҘј к°ҖлҰ¬кі , нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң discoveryлҘј м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ӯлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” distribution-level unsupervised feature discoveryлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” promptмқҳ continuation distribution м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ interpretable clusterлҘј л°ңкІ¬н•ҳкі , мҲҳлҸҷ target м„ нғқ м—Ҷмқҙ semantic granularityмҷҖ mechanistic specificity мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offлҘј мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” knobлҘј м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ continuationмқ„ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ҳкі , к°Ғ continuationмқ„ (i) semantic embeddingкіј (ii) sparse feature attributionмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° мң лҸ„н•ң mechanistic signatureлЎң н‘ңнҳ„н•ң л’Ө, semantic coherenceмҷҖ mechanistic consistencyлҘј м Ҳм¶©н•ҳлҠ” rateвҖ“distortion objectiveлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј clusteringн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ cluster-level causalityлҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјм–ҙ, cluster-level mechanistic representationмқҳ л°ңкІ¬мқҙ нғҖлӢ№н•Ёмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ continuation distributionлҘј м§Җл°°н•ҳлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  unsupervisedн•ң auditлҘј м ңкіөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ circuit analysisмҷҖ behavioral evaluationмқ„ ліҙмҷ„н•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64881","en":"SCOPE and SCION: Benchmark and Method for Ontology Induction and Fusion from Text","ko":"SCOPEмҷҖ SCION: н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлЎңл¶Җн„° Ontology Induction л°Ҹ Fusionмқ„ мң„н•ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬ л°Ҹ л°©лІ•","authors":"Miaobo Hu, Shuhao Hu, BoKun Wang, Rui Chen, Xiaobo Guo, Xin Wang, Daren Zha, Jun Xiao","pos":"#1502","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=IrxiXAouvi","abs":"<p>Ontologies (schemas) are a key bottleneck for schema-grounded information extraction and knowledge graph construction, yet manual ontology engineering is expensive and schemas quickly fragment or drift across domains. We introduce SCOPE (Schema Construction and Ontology Induction Pipeline Evaluation), a benchmark for train-only ontology/schema induction and optional ontology fusion directly from raw corpora. SCOPE normalizes 24 public IE sources (15 RE + 9 EE; zh/en) into machine-readable gold schema graphs and provides train-only induction corpora through a standardized text corpus release. We propose SCION (Structural mining and Contracted semantic Induction for Ontology constructiON and fusion), a controllable pipeline that mines a candidate space of concepts/relations/events from text, performs LLM-assisted naming/merging/filtering under a strict JSON contract with evidence pointers, and can fuse the result with a fixed base ontology package using conservative alignment with provenance tracking. On the SCOPE core suite, SCION improves ontology-level similarity over official/manual schemas, a Text2Onto-style baseline, and LLM-only induction baselines under Literal, Fuzzy, Continuous, and Graph F1. SCOPE and SCION together enable reproducible and auditable evaluation of end-to-end ontology induction and fusion.</p>","absKo":"<p>Ontology(schema)лҠ” schema-grounded information extractionкіј knowledge graph constructionмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ лі‘лӘ©мқҙм§Җл§Ң, мҲҳлҸҷ ontology engineeringмқҖ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кі  schemaлҠ” лҸ„л©”мқё м „л°ҳм—җм„ң л№ лҘҙкІҢ нҢҢнҺёнҷ”лҗҳкұ°лӮҳ driftн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӣҗмӢң мҪ”нҚјмҠӨ(raw corpora)м—җм„ң м§Ғм ‘ train-only ontology/schema inductionкіј м„ нғқм Ғ ontology fusionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң benchmarkмқё SCOPE(Schema Construction and Ontology Induction Pipeline Evaluation)лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. SCOPEлҠ” 24к°ңмқҳ кіөк°ң IE мҶҢмҠӨ(15 RE + 9 EE; zh/en)лҘј machine-readable gold schema graphлЎң м •к·ңнҷ”н•ҳкі , н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗң text corpus releaseлҘј нҶөн•ҙ train-only induction corpusлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SCION(Structural mining and Contracted semantic Induction for Ontology constructiON and fusion)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” н…ҚмҠӨнҠём—җм„ң concept/relation/eventмқҳ нӣ„ліҙ кіөк°„мқ„ мұ„көҙн•ҳкі , evidence pointerлҘј к°–м¶ҳ м—„кІ©н•ң JSON contract м•„лһҳм—җм„ң LLM-assisted naming/merging/filteringмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳл©°, provenance trackingмқ„ лҸҷл°ҳн•ң ліҙмҲҳм Ғ alignmentлЎң кІ°кіјлҘј кі м • base ontology packageмҷҖ кІ°н•©н•ҙ fuseн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м ңм–ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҢҢмқҙн”„лқјмқёмқҙлӢӨ. SCOPE core suiteм—җм„ң SCIONмқҖ Literal, Fuzzy, Continuous, Graph F1 кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң official/manual schema, Text2Onto-style baseline, к·ёлҰ¬кі  LLM-only induction baselineліҙлӢӨ ontology-level similarityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. SCOPEмҷҖ SCIONмқҖ end-to-end ontology inductionкіј fusionм—җ лҢҖн•ң мһ¬нҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  к°җмӮ¬ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66583","en":"Rare Event Analysis of Large Language Models","ko":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ нқ¬к·Җ мӮ¬кұҙ л¶„м„қ","authors":"Jake McAllister Dorman, Edward Gillman, Dominic C Rose, Jamie Mair, Juan Garrahan","pos":"#1508","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2RJN5vDHG0","abs":"<p>Being probabilistic models, during inference large language models (LLMs) display <em>rare events</em>: behaviour that is far from typical but highly significant. By definition all rare events are hard to see, but the enormous scale of LLM usage means that events completely unobserved during development are likely to become prominent in deployment. Here we present an end-to-end framework for the systematic analysis of rare events in LLMs. We provide a practical implementation spanning theory, efficient generation strategies, probability estimation and error analysis, which we illustrate with concrete examples. We outline extensions and applications to other models and contexts, highlighting the generality of the concepts and techniques presented here.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҷ•лҘ м Ғ лӘЁлҚёлЎңм„ң inference лҸҷм•Ҳ large language model(LLM)мқҖ <em>rare event</em>, мҰү м „нҳ•м Ғмқҙм§ҖлҠ” м•Ҡм§Җл§Ң л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң н–үлҸҷмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м •мқҳмғҒ лӘЁл“  rare eventлҠ” кҙҖм°°н•ҳкё° м–ҙл өм§Җл§Ң, LLM мӮ¬мҡ© к·ңлӘЁк°Җ л§Өмҡ° нҒ¬лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ кі л Өн•ҳл©ҙ к°ңл°ң мӨ‘м—җлҠ” м „нҳҖ кҙҖм°°лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мӮ¬кұҙлҸ„ л°°нҸ¬ нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§ҖкІҢ лӮҳнғҖлӮ  к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ лҶ’лӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ңлҠ” LLMм—җм„ң rare eventлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң end-to-end frameworkлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлЎ , нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё generation strategy, probability estimation, error analysisлҘј м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ кө¬нҳ„мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј кө¬мІҙм Ғмқё мҳҲмӢңлЎң м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң лӢӨлҘё modelкіј contextлЎңмқҳ нҷ•мһҘ л°Ҹ мқ‘мҡ©мқ„ к°ңкҙ„н•ҳл©°, м—¬кё°м„ң м ңмӢңн•ң к°ңл…җкіј кё°лІ•мқҳ мқјл°ҳм„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63481","en":"RBCBF: Decoding Time Safety Alignment via Risk Guided Rollback and Barrier Control","ko":"RBCBF: мң„н—ҳ мң лҸ„ лЎӨл°ұкіј л°°лҰ¬м–ҙ м ңм–ҙлҘј нҶөн•ң л””мҪ”л”© мӢңм җ м•Ҳм „ м •л ¬","authors":"Tianxiang Chen, Jingyuan Zhou, Longhao Yan, Kaidi Yang","pos":"#1510","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WpvC0zpcw3","abs":"<p>Existing decoding-time safety interventions are often reactive, relying on local signals to correct unsafe outputs after they emerge. Under adversarial prompts that drive generation into recurring unsafe response, such local signals provide weak guidance for stable repair. As a result, rollback and post-hoc rewriting often trade-off response quality with recurrent violations. To address these limitations, we propose RBCBF, a rollback-based decoding-time framework that jointly selects intervention steps and performs distribution-level corrective control. Our key innovation is a risk-aggregation formulation that views terminal violations as the accumulated build-up of risk along the prefix. By selecting rollback steps from these decisive prefixes, RBCBF moves rollback targeting beyond heuristic cues and turns it into a trajectory-level decision. RBCBF then applies invasive corrective control to the next-token distribution under multiple rule constraints. Across jailbreak-style evaluations, RBCBF outperforms prior rollback methods and decoding-time baselines, reducing harmful responses and substantially lowering violation recurrence.</p>","absKo":"<p>кё°мЎҙмқҳ decoding-time м•Ҳм „ к°ңмһ…мқҖ лҢҖк°ң мӮ¬нӣ„м Ғмқҙл©°, unsafe outputмқҙ мқҙлҜё л°ңмғқн•ң л’Ө көӯмҶҢ мӢ нҳём—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ мқҙлҘј мҲҳм •н•ңлӢӨ. м ҒлҢҖм Ғ н”„лЎ¬н”„нҠёк°Җ мғқм„ұмқ„ л°ҳліөм Ғмқё unsafe responseлЎң лӘ°м•„к°ҖлҠ” мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ңлҠ”, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң көӯмҶҢ мӢ нҳёл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё ліөкө¬лҘј мң„н•ң м¶©л¶„н•ң м§Җм№Ёмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј rollbackкіј post-hoc rewritingмқҖ мқ‘лӢө н’Ҳм§Ҳкіј л°ҳліөм Ғмқё мң„л°ҳ мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң м Ҳм¶©мқ„ к°•мҡ”л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°ңмһ… лӢЁкі„лҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ҳкі  distribution-level corrective controlмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” rollback кё°л°ҳ decoding-time н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ RBCBFлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ нҳҒмӢ мқҖ terminal violationмқ„ prefixлҘј л”°лқј м¶•м Ғлҗң мң„н—ҳмқҳ лҲ„м ҒмңјлЎң л°”лқјліҙлҠ” risk-aggregation formulationмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°м •м Ғ prefixл“Өм—җм„ң rollback stepмқ„ м„ нғқн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, RBCBFлҠ” rollback targetingмқ„ heuristic cueлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ trajectory-level decisionмңјлЎң м „нҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң RBCBFлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ rule constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң next-token distributionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ invasive corrective controlмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. jailbreak-style нҸүк°Җ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң RBCBFлҠ” кё°мЎҙ rollback л°©лІ•кіј decoding-time baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, harmful responseлҘј мӨ„мқҙкі  violation recurrenceлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ лӮ®м¶ҳлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62059","en":"MultiHal: Multilingual Dataset for Knowledge-Graph Grounded Evaluation of LLM Hallucinations","ko":"MultiHal: LLM Hallucinationмқҳ Knowledge-Graph grounded л©ҖнӢ°л§Ғкө¬м–ј нҸүк°Җмҡ© лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ","authors":"Ernests Lavrinovics, Russa Biswas, Katja Hose, Johannes Bjerva","pos":"#1603","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=kGSwStubjL","abs":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs) have inherent limitations of faithfulness and factuality, commonly referred to as hallucinations. Several benchmarks have been developed that provide a test bed for factuality evaluation within the context of English-centric datasets, while relying on supplementary informative context like web links or text passages but ignoring the available structured factual resources. To this end, Knowledge Graphs (KGs) have been identified as a useful aid for hallucination mitigation, as they provide a structured way to represent the facts about entities and their relations with minimal linguistic overhead. We bridge the lack of KG paths and multilinguality for factual language modeling within the existing hallucination evaluation benchmarks and propose a KG-based multilingual, multihop benchmark called MultiHal framed for generative text evaluation. As part of our data collection pipeline, we mined 140k KG-paths from open-domain KGs, from which we pruned noisy KG-paths, curating a high-quality subset of 25.9k. Our baseline evaluation shows an absolute scale improvement by approximately 0.12 to 0.36 points for the semantic similarity score, 0.16 to 0.36 for NLI entailment and 0.29 to 0.42 for hallucination detection in KG-RAG over vanilla QA across multiple languages and multiple models, demonstrating the potential of KG integration. We anticipate MultiHal will foster future research towards several graph-based hallucination mitigation and fact-checking tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs)лҠ” faithfulnessмҷҖ factualityм—җ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ н•ңкі„лҘј к°Җм§Җл©°, мқҙлҠ” нқ”нһҲ hallucinationмңјлЎң л¶ҲлҰ°лӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkк°Җ мҳҒм–ҙ мӨ‘мӢ¬ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқҳ л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ң factuality нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң test bedлЎң к°ңл°ңлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӣ№ л§ҒнҒ¬лӮҳ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё passageмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ ліҙмЎ°м Ғмқё м •ліҙм„ұ contextм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мқҙмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң factual resourceлҠ” л¬ҙмӢңн•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ң Knowledge Graphs (KGs)лҠ” м—”нӢ°нӢ°мҷҖ к·ё кҙҖкі„м—җ лҢҖн•ң мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ м–ём–ҙм Ғ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлЎң кө¬мЎ°нҷ”н•ҳм—¬ н‘ңнҳ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ hallucination мҷ„нҷ”м—җ мң мҡ©н•ң мҲҳлӢЁмңјлЎң мЈјлӘ©л°ӣм•„ мҷ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ hallucination нҸүк°Җ benchmark м•Ҳм—җм„ң KG pathмҷҖ лӢӨкөӯм–ҙм„ұмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұмқ„ л©”мҡ°кі , generative text evaluationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ MultiHalмқҙлқјлҠ” KG кё°л°ҳ multilingual, multihop benchmarkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ°мқҙн„° мҲҳм§‘ нҢҢмқҙн”„лқјмқёмқҳ мқјнҷҳмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” open-domain KGм—җм„ң 14л§Ң к°ңмқҳ KG-pathлҘј мҲҳм§‘н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙ мӨ‘ noisy KG-pathлҘј м •м ңн•ҳм—¬ 2л§Ң 5,900к°ңмқҳ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ subsetмқ„ м„ лі„н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ baseline evaluationмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ м–ём–ҙмҷҖ м—¬лҹ¬ лӘЁлҚём—җ кұёміҗ, vanilla QA лҢҖл№„ KG-RAGм—җм„ң semantic similarity scoreк°Җ м•Ҫ 0.12~0.36, NLI entailmentк°Җ 0.16~0.36, hallucination detectionмқҙ 0.29~0.42мқҳ м ҲлҢҖм Ғ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” KG нҶөн•©мқҳ мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MultiHalмқҙ graph-based hallucination mitigation л°Ҹ fact-checking taskлҘј н–Ҙн•ң н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬лҘј мҙүм§„н•  кІғмңјлЎң кё°лҢҖн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60793","en":"Multilingual Safety Alignment via Representation-Space Separability","ko":"Representation-Space SeparabilityлҘј нҶөн•ң Multilingual Safety Alignment","authors":"Dan Shi, Zhuowen Han, Deyi Xiong","pos":"#1604","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=wfhjlwxrPV","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) have been globally adopted in various scenarios, making robust multilingual safety alignment a prerequisite for their reliable deployment across diverse languages. Despite recent advances, LLMs exhibit a substantial safety gap between high- and low-resource languages: models that can consistently refuse harmful requests in high-resource languages often fail to do so in low-resource languages. In this work, we reveal that such safety failures stem from insufficient representation-space separability between harmful and harmless prompts in low-resource languages. Through geometric analyses, we find that, compared to English, harmful prompts are significantly less separated from the manifold of harmless prompts, and that the resulting cross-lingual spatial margin gap is strongly correlated with attack success rates. Capitalizing on these insights, we propose Multilingual Spatial Margin Gap-based Optimization (SMO), a novel training strategy that exploits the well-aligned safety geometry of a dominant language (e.g., English) to enhance safety alignment in other languages. SMO explicitly leverages the spatial margin gap between English and target languages as an example-wise supervision signal, enabling effective cross-lingual transfer of safety capabilities while preserving the dominant languageвҖҷs original performance. Experiments conducted on LLaMA-3.1-8B-Instruct and Qwen2.5-7B-Instruct demonstrate that SMO is capable of substantially reducing attack success rates in low-resource languages to near zero, often reaching zero, while maintaining strong general multilingual performance. Warning: This paper contains content that may be harmful.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language model(LLM)мқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң м „ м„ёкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мұ„нғқлҗҳкі  мһҲмңјл©°, л”°лқјм„ң кІ¬кі н•ң multilingual safety alignmentлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ м–ём–ҙм—җм„ң мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ л°°нҸ¬лҗҳкё° мң„н•ң м „м ңмЎ°кұҙмқҙ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ м§„м „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , LLMмқҖ high-resource languageмҷҖ low-resource language мӮ¬мқҙм—җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң safety gapмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. high-resource languageм—җм„ңлҠ” мң н•ҙн•ң мҡ”мІӯмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ кұ°л¶Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” modelлҸ„ low-resource languageм—җм„ңлҠ” к·ёлҹ¬м§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң safety failureк°Җ low-resource languageм—җм„ң harmful promptмҷҖ harmless prompt мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ representation space separabilityк°Җ м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•„м„ң л°ңмғқн•Ёмқ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҳҒм–ҙмҷҖ л№„көҗн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң harmful promptк°Җ harmless promptмқҳ manifoldлЎңл¶Җн„° нӣЁм”¬ лҚң л¶„лҰ¬лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмңјл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј cross-lingual spatial margin gapмқҙ attack success rateмҷҖ к°•н•ҳкІҢ мғҒкҙҖлҗЁмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Multilingual Spatial Margin Gap-based Optimization(SMO)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” м§Җл°°м Ғмқё м–ём–ҙ(мҳҲ: мҳҒм–ҙ)мқҳ мһҳ м •л ¬лҗң safety geometryлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ лӢӨлҘё м–ём–ҙм—җм„ң safety alignmentлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ training strategyмқҙлӢӨ. SMOлҠ” мҳҒм–ҙмҷҖ target language мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ spatial margin gapмқ„ example-wise supervision signalлЎң лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, м§Җл°°м Ғмқё м–ём–ҙмқҳ мӣҗлһҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң safety capabilityмқҳ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё cross-lingual transferлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. LLaMA-3.1-8B-InstructмҷҖ Qwen2.5-7B-Instructм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SMOк°Җ low-resource languageм—җм„ң attack success rateлҘј кұ°мқҳ 0м—җ к°Җк№қкІҢ, мў…мў… 0к№Ңм§Җ нҒ¬кІҢ лӮ®м¶”л©ҙм„ңлҸ„ к°•н•ң мқјл°ҳ multilingual м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. кІҪкі : мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җлҠ” мң н•ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лӮҙмҡ©мқҙ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61806","en":"No More, No Less: Least-Privilege Language Models","ko":"No More, No Less: мөңмҶҢ к¶Ңн•ң Language Model","authors":"Paulius Rauba, Dominykas Seputis, Patrikas Vanagas, Mihaela van der Schaar","pos":"#1607","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mlQlfZb2rC","abs":"<p>Least privilege is a core security principle: grant each request only the minimum access needed to achieve its goal. Deployed language models almost never follow it, instead being exposed through a single API endpoint that serves all users and requests. This gap exists not because least privilege would be unhelpfulвҖ”deployments would benefit greatly from reducing unnecessary capability exposure. The real obstacle is definitional and mechanistic: what does \"access\" mean inside a language model, and how can we enforce it without retraining or deploying multiple models? We take inspiration from least privilege in computer systems and define a class of models called <em>least-privilege language models</em>, where privilege is <em>reachable internal computation</em> during the forward pass. In this view, lowering privilege literally shrinks the model's accessible function class (as opposed to denying access via learned policies).  We formalize deployment-time control as a monitor--allocator--enforcer stack, separating (i) request-time signals, (ii) a decision rule that allocates privilege, and (iii) an inference-time mechanism that selects privilege. We then propose <em>Nested Least-Privilege Networks</em>, a shape-preserving, rank-indexed intervention that provides a smooth, reversible control knob. We show that this knob yields policy-usable privilege--utility frontiers and enables selective suppression of targeted capabilities with limited collateral degradation across various policies. Most importantly, we see this as a defense of a completely new deployment paradigm which challenges the premise that we can only have output-level control of language models.</p>","absKo":"<p>Least privilegeлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ security principleлЎң, к°Ғ мҡ”мІӯм—җлҠ” к·ё лӘ©н‘ңлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ м ‘к·ј к¶Ңн•ңл§Ң л¶Җм—¬н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. л°°нҸ¬лҗң language modelмқҖ кұ°мқҳ мқҙ мӣҗм№ҷмқ„ л”°лҘҙм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, лҢҖмӢ  лӘЁл“  мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗмҷҖ мҡ”мІӯмқ„ мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмқј API endpointлҘј нҶөн•ҙ л…ём¶ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ©м°ЁлҠ” least privilegeк°Җ м“ёлӘЁ м—Ҷм–ҙм„ңк°Җ м•„лӢҲлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎң л°°нҸ¬ нҷҳкІҪмқҖ л¶Ҳн•„мҡ”н•ң capability exposureлҘј мӨ„мһ„мңјлЎңмҚЁ нҒ° мқҙмқөмқ„ м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. м§„м§ң мһҘм• л¬јмқҖ м •мқҳмҷҖ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳм—җ мһҲлӢӨ. language model лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң \"access\"лҠ” л¬ҙм—Үмқ„ мқҳлҜён•ҳл©°, м—¬лҹ¬ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мһ¬н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ л°°нҸ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  мқҙлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ к°•м ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ? мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” computer systemмқҳ least privilegeм—җм„ң м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, privilegeлҘј forward pass лҸҷм•Ҳмқҳ <em>reachable internal computation</em>мңјлЎң м •мқҳн•ҳлҠ” <em>least-privilege language model</em>мқҙлқјлҠ” лӘЁлҚё лІ”мЈјлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң privilegeлҘј лӮ®м¶”лҠ” кІғмқҖ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ learned policyлҘј нҶөн•ҙ accessлҘј кұ°л¶Җн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј, лӘЁлҚёмқҙ м ‘к·ј к°ҖлҠҘн•ң function class мһҗмІҙлҘј л¬ёмһҗ к·ёлҢҖлЎң м¶•мҶҢн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л°°нҸ¬ мӢң м ңм–ҙлҘј monitor--allocator--enforcer stackмңјлЎң нҳ•мӢқнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, (i) request-time signal, (ii) privilegeлҘј н• лӢ№н•ҳлҠ” decision rule, (iii) inference-timeм—җм„ң privilegeлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкі  к°Җм—ӯм Ғмқё м ңм–ҙ knobлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” shape-preserving, rank-indexed interventionмқё <em>Nested Least-Privilege Networks</em>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ knobк°Җ policyм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” privilege--utility frontierлҘј л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ лӮҙкі , лӢӨм–‘н•ң policyм—җм„ң л¶ҖмҲҳм Ғ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лӘ©н‘ң capabilityлҘј м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң м–өм ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л¬ҙм—ҮліҙлӢӨлҸ„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј language modelм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ output-level controlл§Ң к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” м „м ңлҘј аӨҡаҘҒаӨЁаҘҢаӨӨаҘҖн•ҳлҠ” мҷ„м „нһҲ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ deployment paradigmм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҳ№нҳёлЎң ліёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65939","en":"LiveNewsBench: Evaluating LLM Web Search Capabilities with Freshly Curated News","ko":"LiveNewsBench: мғҲлЎң нҒҗл Ҳмқҙм…ҳлҗң лүҙмҠӨлЎң LLM мӣ№ кІҖмғү лҠҘл Ҙ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё°","authors":"Yunfan Zhang, Kathleen McKeown, Smaranda Muresan","pos":"#1707","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=8fIsZEGmh1","abs":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs) with agentic web search capabilities show strong potential for tasks requiring real-time information access and complex fact retrieval, yet evaluating such systems remains challenging. We introduce LiveNewsBench, a rigorous and regularly updated benchmark designed to assess the agentic web search abilities of LLMs. LiveNewsBench automatically generates fresh question-answer pairs from recent news articles, ensuring that questions require information beyond an LLM's training data and enabling clear separation between internal knowledge and search capability. The benchmark features intentionally difficult questions requiring multi-step search queries, page visits, and reasoning, making it well-suited for evaluating agentic search behavior. Our automated data curation and question generation pipeline enables frequent benchmark updates and supports construction of a large-scale training dataset for agentic web search models, addressing the scarcity of such data in the research community. To ensure reliable evaluation, we include a subset of human-verified samples in the test set. We evaluate a broad range of systems using LiveNewsBench, including commercial and open-weight LLMs as well as LLM-based web search APIs. The leaderboard, datasets, and code are publicly available at \\url{livenewsbench.com}.</p>","absKo":"<p>agentic web search capabilitiesлҘј к°–м¶ҳ Large Language Models (LLMs)лҠ” мӢӨмӢңк°„ м •ліҙ м ‘к·јкіј ліөмһЎн•ң мӮ¬мӢӨ кІҖмғүмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң мһ‘м—…м—җм„ң к°•н•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLMsмқҳ agentic web search лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗң м—„кІ©н•ҳкі  м •кё°м ҒмңјлЎң к°ұмӢ лҗҳлҠ” benchmarkмқё LiveNewsBenchлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. LiveNewsBenchлҠ” мөңк·ј лүҙмҠӨ кё°мӮ¬лЎңл¶Җн„° мғҲлЎңмҡҙ question-answer мҢҚмқ„ мһҗлҸҷ мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м§Ҳл¬ёмқҙ LLMмқҳ training dataлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” м •ліҙлҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкі  лӮҙл¶Җ м§ҖмӢқкіј search capabilityлҘј лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ л¶„лҰ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ benchmarkлҠ” лӢӨлӢЁкі„ search query, page visit, reasoningмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” мқҳлҸ„м ҒмңјлЎң м–ҙл Өмҡҙ м§Ҳл¬ёл“ӨлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм–ҙ agentic search behavior нҸүк°Җм—җ м Ғн•©н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мһҗлҸҷ data curation л°Ҹ question generation pipelineмқҖ л№ҲлІҲн•ң benchmark м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі , м—°кө¬ м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°м—җм„ң нқ¬мҶҢн•ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ л¶ҖмЎұмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ agentic web search modelмқ„ мң„н•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ training dataset кө¬м¶•лҸ„ м§Җмӣҗн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” нҸүк°ҖлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ test setм—җлҠ” human-verified sampleмқҳ мқјл¶ҖлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LiveNewsBenchлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мғҒмҡ© л°Ҹ open-weight LLMsлҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј LLM-based web search APIлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. leaderboard, datasets, codeлҠ” \\url{livenewsbench.com}м—җм„ң кіөк°ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61558","en":"LORD-GoF: A Robust Online Detection Approach for LLM Watermarks in Sparse and Mixed Streams","ko":"LORD-GoF: нқ¬мҶҢ л°Ҹ нҳјн•© мҠӨнҠёлҰјм—җм„ң LLM WatermarkлҘј мң„н•ң к°•кұҙн•ң Online Detection м ‘к·ј","authors":"Jiade Xu, Zhouping Li","pos":"#1714","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ovjx7lFuKu","abs":"<p>Watermarking is crucial for identifying AI-generated text, however, existing detection methods often focus on offline settings and fail to control the online False Discovery Rate (oFDR) when applied to real-world streams where machine-generated content is sparse and mixed with human writing. To address this issue, in this paper, we propose LORD-GoF, a novel online detection framework that combines a Goodness-of-Fit (GoF) statistic with the Levels based On Recent Discovery (LORD) procedure. We prove that LORD-GoF approach can rigorously control the oFDR below a user-specified level by dynamically adjusting detection thresholds. Extensive experiments on watermarked text from Qwen-2.5-3B, Sheared-LLaMA-2.7B, and OPT-1.3B using both the Gumbel-Max and Inverse Transform watermarking schemes show that our method maintains statistical power comparable to offline benchmarks while successfully controlling the oFDR under complex, mixed streaming scenarios.</p>","absKo":"<p>WatermarkingмқҖ AI мғқм„ұ н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ нғҗм§Җ л°©лІ•мқҖ мҳӨн”„лқјмқё м„Өм •м—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„, кё°кі„ мғқм„ұ мҪҳн…җмё к°Җ нқ¬мҶҢн•ҳкі  мқёк°„мқҙ мһ‘м„ұн•ң н…ҚмҠӨнҠёмҷҖ м„һм—¬ мһҲлҠ” мӢӨм ң мҠӨнҠёлҰјм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•  л•Ң online False Discovery Rate(oFDR)лҘј м ңм–ҙн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” Goodness-of-Fit(GoF) нҶөкі„лҹүкіј Levels based On Recent Discovery(LORD) м Ҳм°ЁлҘј кІ°н•©н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мҳЁлқјмқё нғҗм§Җ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ LORD-GoFлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LORD-GoF м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ нғҗм§Җ мһ„кі„к°’мқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м§Җм • мҲҳмӨҖ мқҙн•ҳлЎң oFDRмқ„ м—„л°Җн•ҳкІҢ м ңм–ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. Qwen-2.5-3B, Sheared-LLaMA-2.7B, OPT-1.3BлЎңл¶Җн„° мғқм„ұлҗң watermark textм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ Gumbel-Max л°Ҹ Inverse Transform watermarking schemeмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬ л°©лІ•мқҖ ліөмһЎн•ң нҳјн•© мҠӨнҠёлҰ¬л°Қ мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң oFDRмқ„ м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ offline benchmarkмҷҖ лҸҷл“ұн•ң statistical powerлҘј мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62627","en":"Graph-Link: Bridging the Semantic-Structural Gap in Text-to-SQL via Constrained Subgraph Induction","ko":"Graph-Link: Constrained Subgraph InductionмңјлЎң Text-to-SQLмқҳ мқҳлҜё-кө¬мЎ° к°„ к°„к·№ н•ҙмҶҢ","authors":"Jianwei Zhong, Yijun Mo, Quanxin Liu, Ruida Xu, Yuxi Yang, Ming Chi","pos":"#1802","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eschjhO6uw","abs":"<p>Schema Linking serves as the foundational perception layer in Text-to-SQL, tasked with grounding natural language queries into relevant schema elements. However, existing retrieval-based approaches suffer from a critical <em>structural blindness</em>: by prioritizing elements with high textual similarity, they inadvertently prune semantically-thin but topologically-critical bridge tables, thereby severing relational pathways necessary for multi-hop joins. To bridge this gap, we propose Graph-Link, a novel framework that reformulates schema linking from an independent retrieval task into a constrained subgraph induction problem. We argue that generating executable SQL necessitates a connected subgraph that satisfies both semantic relevance and structural constraints. Accordingly, Graph-Link employs a hierarchical schema graph to model the search space across multiple granularities, and then applies a Steiner-tree-based optimization for subgraph induction that guarantees the topological connectivity while maximizing the signal-to-noise ratio for downstream LLMs. Extensive experiments on BIRD and Spider 2.0 demonstrate that Graph-Link achieves state-of-the-art schema linking performance, improving recall and hit rates by up to 7.0\\% over competitive baselines, and boosts downstream SQL generation accuracy on complex queries by 13.8\\%.</p>","absKo":"<p>Schema LinkingмқҖ Text-to-SQLмқҳ кё°л°ҳ м§Җк°Ғ кі„мёөмңјлЎң, мһҗм—°м–ҙ м§ҲмқҳлҘј кҙҖл Ё schema мҡ”мҶҢм—җ groundingн•ҳлҠ” м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙмқҳ retrieval кё°л°ҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ м№ҳлӘ…м Ғмқё <em>structural blindness</em>лҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мҰү, н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мң мӮ¬лҸ„к°Җ лҶ’мқҖ мҡ”мҶҢлҘј мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳлҠ” кіјм •м—җм„ң мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” м–Үм§Җл§Ң topologyм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң bridge tableмқ„ мқҳлҸ„м№ҳ м•ҠкІҢ м ңкұ°н•ҳм—¬, multi-hop joinм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң relational pathwayлҘј лҒҠм–ҙлІ„лҰ°лӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” schema linkingмқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё retrieval taskк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј м ңм•Ҫлҗң subgraph induction problemмңјлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkмқё Graph-LinkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң SQLмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳл Өл©ҙ semantic relevanceмҷҖ structural constraintлҘј лӘЁл‘җ л§ҢмЎұн•ҳлҠ” м—°кІ°лҗң subgraphк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ л”°лқј Graph-LinkлҠ” hierarchical schema graphлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ м—¬лҹ¬ granularityм—җ кұём№ң search spaceлҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкі , мқҙм–ҙм„ң topological connectivityлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳл©ҙм„ң downstream LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң signal-to-noise ratioлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” Steiner-tree кё°л°ҳ optimizationмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҙ subgraphлҘј inductionн•ңлӢӨ. BIRDмҷҖ Spider 2.0м—җм„ңмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Graph-Linkк°Җ schema linking м„ұлҠҘм—җм„ң state-of-the-artлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” baseline лҢҖл№„ recallкіј hit rateлҘј мөңлҢҖ 7.0\\%к№Ңм§Җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі , ліөмһЎн•ң м§Ҳмқҳм—җ лҢҖн•ң downstream SQL мғқм„ұ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј 13.8\\% лҶ’мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66822","en":"HInT: Hypergraph Infusion at the Structural Layers Improves Table Understanding","ko":"HInT: кө¬мЎ°м Ғ л Ҳмқҙм–ҙм—җм„ңмқҳ н•ҳмқҙнҚјк·ёлһҳн”„ мЈјмһ…мқҙ н‘ң мқҙн•ҙлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ","authors":"Wonjin Lee, Soomi Jeong, Kwang In Kim","pos":"#1805","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=00qFGVnqba","abs":"<p>Decoder-only large language models (LLMs) struggle with table reasoning because tables must be serialized, obscuring row- and column-level structure. Prior graph and hypergraph approaches encode structure with an external encoder, but their gains are often inconsistent under autoregressive decoding. We analyze how tabular structure is represented inside decoder-only LLMs and find that row and column relations concentrate in a small subset of layers and attention heads. Based on this observation, we propose HInT, which injects hypergraph-derived structural features directly into these structural layers. HInT constructs a table hypergraph over cells and headers, performs lightweight message passing, and fuses the resulting features with token hidden states via token-level gated fusion, while preserving standard autoregressive computation. Experiments across diverse table reasoning tasks show consistent improvements over text-only baselines and prior (hyper)graph-based methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Decoder-only large language models (LLMs)лҠ” tableмқ„ м§Ғл ¬нҷ”н•ҙм„ң н‘ңнҳ„н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң table reasoningм—җм„ң м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙ кіјм •м—җм„ң row л°Ҹ column мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ кө¬мЎ°к°Җ к°Җл Өм§Җкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ graph л°Ҹ hypergraph м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мҷёл¶Җ encoderлЎң кө¬мЎ°лҘј мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, autoregressive decodingм—җм„ңлҠ” к·ё нҡЁкіјк°Җ мқјкҙҖм Ғмқҙм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” decoder-only LLM лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң tabular structureк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ н‘ңнҳ„лҗҳлҠ”м§Җ л¶„м„қн•ҳкі , rowмҷҖ column кҙҖкі„к°Җ мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ layerмҷҖ attention headм—җ м§‘мӨ‘лҗңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” hypergraphлЎңл¶Җн„° м–»мқҖ structural featureлҘј мқҙлҹ¬н•ң structural layerм—җ м§Ғм ‘ мЈјмһ…н•ҳлҠ” HInTлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. HInTлҠ” cellкіј header мң„м—җ table hypergraphлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , lightweight message passingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ң л’Ө, token-level gated fusionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мғқм„ұлҗң featureлҘј token hidden stateмҷҖ кІ°н•©н•ҳл©ҙм„ң standard autoregressive computationмқҖ к·ёлҢҖлЎң мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң table reasoning taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң, text-only baselineкіј кё°мЎҙ (hyper)graph-based methodліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63910","en":"How Transformers Represent Hierarchies: A Local-to-Global Mechanism","ko":"TransformerлҠ” мң„кі„лҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳлҠ”к°Җ: local-to-global л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳ","authors":"Zhiling Zhou, Tianhao Wang, Zhuoran Yang","pos":"#1808","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ScLLtpPoaE","abs":"<p>Large language models built on autoregressive Transformers excel at next-token prediction, but it is unclear how their internal computations capture the latent hierarchical dependencies that often underlie language. We study this question in a controlled formal-language setting based on probabilistic context-free grammars (PCFGs), where sequences are generated by a latent hierarchical process. Empirically, standard autoregressive Transformers can be trained to accurately match the grammar-induced next-token distribution. Using probing analyses, we find that Transformer hidden states contain information used by classical parsing algorithms. Moreover, this information emerges through a layer-wise progression, revealing a local-to-global mechanism: early layers accumulate local patterns, while later layers aggregate them into a compact summary for next-token prediction. Complementing these empirical findings, we provide an explicit construction of Transformers that can parse binary PCFGs with depth \\emph{logarithmic} in the grammar's sequence length. Surprisingly, trained Transformers in this setting exhibit prediction behavior and internal representations that closely mirror our construction.  Together, our results offer a mechanistic account of how Transformers integrate hierarchical parsing with autoregressive generation.</p>","absKo":"autoregressive TransformerлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ң large language modelмқҖ next-token predictionм—җм„ң лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, лӮҙл¶Җ кі„мӮ°мқҙ м–ём–ҙмқҳ л°”нғ•мқ„ мқҙлЈЁлҠ” latent hierarchical dependencyлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҠ” лӘ…нҷ•н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҷ•лҘ м Ғ context-free grammar(PCFG)лҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң н•ң нҶөм ңлҗң formal-language settingм—җм„ң мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј м—°кө¬н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң sequenceлҠ” latent hierarchical processм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мғқм„ұлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, н‘ңмӨҖ autoregressive TransformerлҠ” grammarк°Җ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” next-token distributionмқ„ м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ л§һм¶”лҸ„лЎқ н•ҷмҠөлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. probing analysisлҘј нҶөн•ҙ, Transformerмқҳ hidden state м•Ҳм—җ classical parsing algorithmмқҙ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” м •ліҙк°Җ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмқҢмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мқҙ м •ліҙлҠ” layer-wise progressionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӮҳнғҖлӮҳл©°, local-to-global mechanismмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лғ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҙҲкё° layerлҠ” local patternмқ„ лҲ„м Ғн•ҳкі , мқҙнӣ„ layerлҠ” мқҙлҘј next-token predictionмқ„ мң„н•ң compact summaryлЎң м§‘кі„н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢӨмҰқм Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” grammarмқҳ sequence lengthм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ к№Ҡмқҙк°Җ \\emph{logarithmic}мқё binary PCFGлҘј parsingн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” Transformerмқҳ explicit constructionмқ„ м ңмӢңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„, мқҙ settingм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөлҗң TransformerлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ constructionкіј л§Өмҡ° мң мӮ¬н•ң prediction behaviorмҷҖ internal representationмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” Transformerк°Җ hierarchical parsingкіј autoregressive generationмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң mechanistic accountлҘј м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64427","en":"Compile to Compress: Boosting Formal Theorem Provers by Compiler Outputs","ko":"м••м¶•мқ„ мң„н•ң м»ҙнҢҢмқј: м»ҙнҢҢмқјлҹ¬ м¶ңл ҘмңјлЎң нҳ•мӢқ м •лҰ¬ мҰқлӘ…кё° к°•нҷ”","authors":"Guchan Li, Rui Tian, Hongning Wang","pos":"#2001","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=NjbMkeaOKD","abs":"Large language models (LLMs) have demonstrated significant potential in formal theorem proving, yet state-of-the-art performance often necessitates prohibitive test-time compute via massive roll-outs or extended context windows. In this work, we address this scalability bottleneck by exploiting an informative structure in formal verification: the observation that compilers map a vast space of diverse proof attempts to a compact set of structured failure modes. We introduce a learning-to-refine framework that leverages this compression to perform efficient learning and proof exploration. We perform tree search that corrects errors locally conditioned on explicit verifier feedback, thereby circumventing the costs associated with accumulating a long history of proof attempts. Extensive evaluations show that our method consistently amplifies the reasoning capabilities of base provers across varying scales. Notably, our approach achieves state-of-the-art performance on PutnamBench among publicly reported $\\sim$8B and $\\sim$32B parameter models under comparable test-time budgets, offering a scalable paradigm for next-generation verifier-guided reasoning.","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ language model (LLM)мқҖ formal theorem provingм—җм„ң нҒ° мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, мөңмІЁлӢЁ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл Өл©ҙ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ roll-outмқҙлӮҳ кёҙ context windowлҘј нҶөн•ң кіјлҸ„н•ң test-time computeк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ң кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” formal verificationмқҳ мң мқөн•ң кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҷ•мһҘм„ұ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ кҙҖм°°мқҖ compilerк°Җ л°©лҢҖн•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң proof attempt кіөк°„мқ„ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң failure modeмқҳ м••м¶•лҗң м§‘н•©мңјлЎң л§Өн•‘н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м••м¶•м„ұмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё learningкіј proof explorationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” learning-to-refine frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё verifier feedbackм—җ мЎ°кұҙл¶ҖлЎң көӯмҶҢм Ғмқё мҳӨлҘҳлҘј мҲҳм •н•ҳлҠ” tree searchлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, кёҙ proof attempt мқҙл Ҙмқ„ лҲ„м Ғн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° л”°лҘҙлҠ” л№„мҡ©мқ„ нҡҢн”јн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң к·ңлӘЁм—җм„ң base proverмқҳ reasoning capabilityлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ л№„көҗ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң test-time budget н•ҳм—җм„ң кіөк°ңм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙкі лҗң м•Ҫ 8B л°Ҹ м•Ҫ 32B parameter model мӨ‘ PutnamBenchм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, м°Ём„ёлҢҖ verifier-guided reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63055","en":"Configurable Reward Model for Balanced Safety Alignment","ko":"к· нҳ• мһЎнһҢ м•Ҳм „ м •л ¬мқ„ мң„н•ң кө¬м„ұ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң ліҙмғҒ лӘЁлҚё","authors":"Zhengping Jiang, Mehran Khodabandeh, Akash Bharadwaj, Manik Bhandari, Mayur Srungarapu, Anqi Liu, Benjamin Van Durme, Li Chen","pos":"#2003","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=aWmEo0tNjs","abs":"<p>Aligning large language models (LLMs) to heterogeneous and rapidly evolving safety requirements remains a critical challenge. Existing instruction-tuned LLMs and standalone safety classifiers often fail to generalize to new safety configurations, motivating the need for Reward Models (RMs) that are explicitly configurable to changing specifications. We introduce the Configurable Safety Reward Model (CSRM), which is jointly optimized for calibrated safety compliance and reward modeling. Our approach is supported by configuration-targeted data augmentation that enforces instruction adherence while preserving relative severity structure. The resulting RM is sensitive to fine-grained safety configurations and conversational nuances, substantially improving generalization to previously unseen safety configurations. CSRM achieves state-of-the-art performance on recent configurable safety benchmarks, including CoSApien (94.6\\% F1) and DynaBench (75.8\\% F1), without requiring additional human annotation. When used for downstream safety alignment, CSRM yields LLMs with a significantly improved helpfulnessвҖ“safety tradeoff compared to existing baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқҙкі  л№ лҘҙкІҢ м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” safety requirementм—җ large language model(LLM)мқ„ м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ instruction-tuned LLMкіј лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё safety classifierлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ safety configurationм—җ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„, ліҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” specificationм—җ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң configurableн•ң Reward Model(RM)мқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ м ңкё°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” calibrated safety complianceмҷҖ reward modelingмқ„ кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” Configurable Safety Reward Model(CSRM)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ instruction adherenceлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳл©ҙм„ң мғҒлҢҖм Ғмқё severity structureлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” configuration-targeted data augmentationм—җ мқҳн•ҙ л’·л°ӣм№ЁлҗңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј RMмқҖ м„ёл°Җн•ң safety configurationкіј лҢҖнҷ”м Ғ лүҳм•ҷмҠӨм—җ лҜјк°җн•ҙм§Җл©°, мқҙм „м—җ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң safety configurationмңјлЎңмқҳ generalizationмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. CSRMмқҖ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё human annotation м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ CoSApien(94.6\\% F1)кіј DynaBench(75.8\\% F1)лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң мөңк·ј configurable safety benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. downstream safety alignmentм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©н–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң, CSRMмқҖ кё°мЎҙ baselineм—җ л№„н•ҙ helpfulness-safety tradeoffк°Җ нҳ„м ҖнһҲ к°ңм„ лҗң LLMмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63624","en":"Antidistillation Fingerprinting","ko":"м•ҲнӢ°л””мҠӨнӢёл Ҳмқҙм…ҳ м§Җл¬ё мқёмӢқ","authors":"Yixuan Xu, John Kirchenbauer, Yash Savani, Asher Trockman, Alexander Robey, Tom Goldstein, Fei Fang, Zico Kolter","pos":"#2114","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=VM9VwbeHcv","abs":"<p>Model distillation enables efficient emulation of frontier large language models (LLMs), creating a need for robust mechanisms to detect when a third-party student model has trained on a teacher model's outputs. However, existing fingerprinting techniques that could be used to detect such distillation rely on heuristic perturbations that impose a steep trade-off between generation quality and fingerprinting strength, often requiring significant degradation of utility to ensure the fingerprint is effectively internalized by the student. We introduce <em><strong>antidistillation fingerprinting</strong></em> (ADFP), a principled approach that aligns the fingerprinting objective with the student's learning dynamics. Building upon the gradient-based framework of <em>antidistillation sampling</em>, ADFP utilizes a proxy model to identify and sample tokens that directly maximize the expected detectability of the fingerprint in the student after fine-tuning, rather than relying on the incidental absorption of the un-targeted biases of a more naive watermark. Experiments on GSM8K and OASST1 benchmarks demonstrate that ADFP achieves a significant Pareto improvement over state-of-the-art baselines, yielding stronger detection confidence with minimal impact on utility, even when the student model's architecture is unknown.</p>","absKo":"<p>Model distillationмқҖ frontier large language models (LLMs)лҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң лӘЁмӮ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳл©°, м ң3мһҗ student modelмқҙ teacher modelмқҳ outputмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн–ҲлҠ”м§ҖлҘј нғҗм§Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” к°•кұҙн•ң mechanismм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•„мҡ”лҘј л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң distillationмқ„ нғҗм§Җн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кё°мЎҙ fingerprinting кё°лІ•мқҖ generation qualityмҷҖ fingerprinting strength мӮ¬мқҙм—җ к°ҖнҢҢлҘё trade-offлҘј л¶Җкіјн•ҳлҠ” heuristic perturbationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, fingerprintк°Җ student лӮҙл¶Җм—җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң лӮҙмһ¬нҷ”лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ utilityмқҳ мғҒлӢ№н•ң м Җн•ҳлҘј мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” fingerprinting objectiveлҘј studentмқҳ learning dynamicsмҷҖ м •л ¬мӢңнӮӨлҠ” мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё м ‘к·јлІ•мқё <em><strong>antidistillation fingerprinting</strong></em> (ADFP)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. <em>antidistillation sampling</em>мқҳ gradient-based framework мң„м—җ кө¬м¶•лҗң ADFPлҠ” лҚ” лӢЁмҲңн•ң watermarkмқҳ л№„лҢҖмғҒ biasк°Җ мҡ°м—°нһҲ нқЎмҲҳлҗҳлҠ” лҚ° мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , fine-tuning мқҙнӣ„ studentм—җм„ң fingerprintмқҳ кё°лҢҖ нғҗм§Җ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” tokenмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳкі  мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ proxy modelмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. GSM8KмҷҖ OASST1 benchmark мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ ADFPк°Җ state-of-the-art baselineм—җ л№„н•ҙ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” Pareto к°ңм„ мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, student modelмқҳ architectureлҘј м•Ң мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” кІҪмҡ°м—җлҸ„ utilityм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–ҘмқҖ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙм„ң лҚ” к°•н•ң нғҗм§Җ confidenceлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60635","en":"A Judge-Aware Ranking Framework for Evaluating Large Language Models without Ground Truth","ko":"Ground Truth м—Ҷмқҙ Large Language Modelмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң Judge мқёмӢқ лһӯнӮ№ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Mingyuan Xu, Xinzi Tan, Jiawei Wu, Doudou Zhou","pos":"#2206","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=yFUmcOtUYD","abs":"<p>Evaluating large language models (LLMs) on open-ended tasks without ground-truth labels is increasingly done via the LLM-as-a-judge paradigm. A critical but under-modeled issue is that judge LLMs differ substantially in reliability; treating all judges equally can yield biased leaderboards and misleading uncertainty estimatesвҖ”more data can make evaluation more confidently wrong under misspecified aggregation. We propose a judge-aware ranking framework that extends the Bradley-Terry-Luce model by introducing judge-specific discrimination parameters, jointly estimating latent model quality and judge reliability from pairwise comparisons without reference labels. We establish identifiability up to natural normalizations and prove consistency and asymptotic normality of the maximum likelihood estimator, enabling confidence intervals for score differences and rank comparisons. Across multiple public benchmarks and a newly collected dataset, our method improves agreement with human preferences, achieves higher data efficiency than unweighted baselines, and produces calibrated uncertainty quantification for LLM rankings.</p>","absKo":"<p>ground-truth labelмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” open-ended taskм—җм„ң large language model(LLM)мқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м җм җ лҚ” LLM-as-a-judge paradigmмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң лҸҷмӢңм—җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ л¬ём ңлҠ” judge LLM к°„ reliabilityк°Җ нҒ¬кІҢ лӢӨлҘҙлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙл©°, лӘЁл“  judgeлҘј лҸҷмқјн•ҳкІҢ м·Ёкёүн•ҳл©ҙ biased leaderboardмҷҖ мҳӨн•ҙмқҳ мҶҢм§Җк°Җ мһҲлҠ” uncertainty estimateлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ dataк°Җ misspecified aggregation н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” нҸүк°ҖлҘј лҚ” нҷ•мӢ м—җ м°¬ мҳӨлҘҳлЎң л§Ңл“Ө мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” judge-specific discrimination parameterлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҙ Bradley-Terry-Luce modelмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•ң judge-aware ranking frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, reference label м—Ҷмқҙ pairwise comparisonл§ҢмңјлЎң latent model qualityмҷҖ judge reliabilityлҘј jointly estimateн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ normalization н•ҳм—җм„ң identifiabilityлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳкі , maximum likelihood estimatorмқҳ consistencyмҷҖ asymptotic normalityлҘј мҰқлӘ…н•ҳм—¬ score differenceмҷҖ rank comparisonм—җ лҢҖн•ң confidence intervalмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ public benchmarkмҷҖ мғҲлЎң мҲҳм§‘н•ң datasetм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ human preferenceмҷҖмқҳ agreementлҘј к°ңм„ н•ҳкі , unweighted baselineліҙлӢӨ лҶ’мқҖ data efficiencyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, LLM rankingм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ calibrated uncertainty quantificationмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60563","en":"Adaptive Time Series Reasoning via Segment Selection","ko":"м„ёк·ёлЁјнҠё м„ нғқмқ„ нҶөн•ң м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мӢңкі„м—ҙ м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Shvat Messica, Jiawen Zhang, Kevin Li, Theodoros Tsiligkaridis, Marinka Zitnik","pos":"#2211","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=yzBbBPheg7","abs":"<p>Time series reasoning tasks increasingly start from a natural language question and require targeted analysis of time series. Relevant evidence may be global or confined to a few short segments, so the model must decide what to inspect.  Most existing methods compress the full series into a fixed representation before inference, preventing question-adaptive analysis. We introduce ARTIST, an approach that formulates time-series reasoning as a sequential decision problem and trains models to interleave reasoning with adaptive temporal segment selection. ARTIST uses a controller-reasoner architecture and reinforcement learning to optimize segment selection based on answer correctness, allowing the model to actively acquire task-relevant information during inference. We evaluate ARTIST on six time-series reasoning benchmarks against large language models, vision-language models, and prior time series reasoning systems. ARTIST improves average accuracy by 6.46 percentage points over the strongest model, with the largest gains on rare event localization and multi-segment evidence accumulation. Supervised fine-tuning improves performance, and reinforcement learning yields further gains by optimizing question-adaptive segment selection. Across datasets, ARTIST achieves higher accuracy while using a smaller fraction of the input time series, highlighting the importance of learned, selective data utilization for time series reasoning.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӢңкі„м—ҙ м¶”лЎ  кіјм ңлҠ” м җм җ мһҗм—°м–ҙ м§Ҳл¬ём—җм„ң м¶ңл°ңн•ҙ мӢңкі„м—ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң н‘ңм Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” нҳ•нғңлЎң л°ңм „н•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. кҙҖл Ё мҰқкұ°лҠ” м „м—ӯм Ғмқј мҲҳлҸ„ мһҲкі  лӘҮ к°ңмқҳ м§§мқҖ кө¬к°„м—җ көӯн•ңлҗ  мҲҳлҸ„ мһҲмңјлҜҖлЎң, лӘЁлҚёмқҖ л¬ҙм—Үмқ„ мӮҙнҺҙліјм§Җ мҠӨмҠӨлЎң кІ°м •н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ м¶”лЎ  м „м—җ м „мІҙ мӢңкі„м—ҙмқ„ кі м •лҗң н‘ңнҳ„мңјлЎң м••м¶•н•ҙ, м§Ҳл¬ё м Ғмқ‘нҳ• л¶„м„қмқ„ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ARTISTлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ARTISTлҠ” мӢңкі„м—ҙ м¶”лЎ мқ„ мҲңм°Ём Ғ мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • л¬ём ңлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , м¶”лЎ кіј м Ғмқ‘м Ғ temporal segment м„ нғқмқ„ көҗм°ЁмӢңнӮӨлҸ„лЎқ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. ARTISTлҠ” controller-reasoner м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳмҷҖ reinforcement learningмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ м •лӢөмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң segment м„ нғқмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м¶”лЎ  мӨ‘м—җ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ кіјм ң кҙҖл Ё м •ліҙлҘј лҠҘлҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң нҡҚл“қн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ARTISTлҘј лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ language model, vision-language model, к·ёлҰ¬кі  кё°мЎҙ мӢңкі„м—ҙ м¶”лЎ  мӢңмҠӨн…ңл“Өкіј л№„көҗн•ҳм—¬ м—¬м„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ мӢңкі„м—ҙ м¶”лЎ  benchmarkм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн–ҲлӢӨ. ARTISTлҠ” к°ҖмһҘ к°•л Ҙн•ң лӘЁлҚё лҢҖл№„ нҸүк·  м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј 6.46 percentage points н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, нҠ№нһҲ нқ¬к·Җ мӮ¬кұҙ localizationкіј лӢӨмӨ‘ segment evidence accumulationм—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ нҒ° н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. supervised fine-tuningмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳкі , reinforcement learningмқҖ м§Ҳл¬ё м Ғмқ‘нҳ• segment м„ нғқмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң ARTISTлҠ” мһ…л Ҙ мӢңкі„м—ҙмқҳ лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ л№„мңЁл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҙ, мӢңкі„м—ҙ м¶”лЎ м—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөлҗң м„ нғқм Ғ лҚ°мқҙн„° нҷңмҡ©мқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66035","en":"When Do Hallucinations Arise? A Graph Perspective on the Evolution of Path Reuse and Path Compression","ko":"нҷҳк°ҒмқҖ м–ём ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ”к°Җ? кІҪлЎң мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©кіј кІҪлЎң м••м¶•мқҳ м§„нҷ”м—җ лҢҖн•ң к·ёлһҳн”„ кҙҖм җ","authors":"Xinnan Dai, Kai Yang, cheng Luo, Shenglai Zeng, Kai Guo, Jiliang Tang","pos":"#2810","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=7hGdaMG8kY","abs":"<p>Reasoning hallucinations in large language models (LLMs) often appear as fluent yet unsupported conclusions that violate either the given context or underlying factual knowledge. Although such failures are widely observed, the mechanisms by which decoder-only Transformers produce them remain poorly understood. We model next-token prediction as a graph search process over an underlying graph, where entities correspond to nodes and learned transitions form edges. From this perspective, contextual reasoning is a constrained search over a sampled subgraph (intrinsic reasoning), while context-free queries rely on memorized structures in the underlying graph (extrinsic reasoning). We show that reasoning hallucinations arise from two fundamental mechanisms: path reuse, where memorized knowledge overrides contextual constraints during early training, and path compression, where frequently traversed multi-step paths collapse into shortcut edges in later training. Together, these mechanisms provide a unified explanation for reasoning hallucinations in LLMs and connected to well-known behaviors observed in downstream applications.</p>","absKo":"Large language model (LLM)м—җм„ңмқҳ reasoning hallucinationмқҖ мў…мў… мЈјм–ҙм§„ contextлӮҳ underlying factual knowledgeлҘј мң„л°ҳн•ҳлҠ”, мң м°Ҫн•ҳм§Җл§Ң к·јкұ° м—ҶлҠ” кІ°лЎ мңјлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢӨнҢЁлҠ” л„җлҰ¬ кҙҖм°°лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, decoder-only Transformerк°Җ мқҙлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” next-token predictionмқ„ underlying graph мң„мқҳ graph search processлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳл©°, м—¬кё°м„ң entityлҠ” nodeм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳкі  н•ҷмҠөлҗң transitionмқҖ edgeлҘј мқҙлЈ¬лӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң contextual reasoningмқҖ мғҳн”Ңлҗң subgraph мң„мқҳ constrained search(intrinsic reasoning)мқё л°ҳл©ҙ, context-free queryлҠ” underlying graphм—җ кё°м–өлҗң structure(extrinsic reasoning)м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reasoning hallucinationмқҙ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ к·јліё л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ: path reuseлҠ” мҙҲкё° training лҸҷм•Ҳ кё°м–өлҗң м§ҖмӢқмқҙ contextual constraintлҘј лҚ®м–ҙм“°лҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙкі , path compressionмқҖ мқҙнӣ„ trainingм—җм„ң мһҗмЈј м§ҖлӮҳк°ҖлҠ” multi-step pathк°Җ shortcut edgeлЎң л¶•кҙҙлҗҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ л‘җ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ LLMмқҳ reasoning hallucinationм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҶөн•©м Ғ м„ӨлӘ…мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, downstream applicationм—җм„ң кҙҖм°°лҗҳлҠ” мһҳ м•Ңл Өм§„ behaviorмҷҖлҸ„ м—°кІ°лҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64247","en":"Causal Dependency-Aware Unsupervised Routing for Large Reasoning Models","ko":"лҢҖнҳ• м¶”лЎ  лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мң„н•ң мқёкіј мқҳмЎҙм„ұ мқёмӢқ л№„м§ҖлҸ„ лқјмҡ°нҢ…","authors":"Jiacheng Liu, Hao Liu, Xiaofeng Hou, Wei Xue, Yike Guo","pos":"#2910","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PZ9XUkURiG","abs":"<p>As Large Language Model (LLM) ecosystems grow, routing queries to the most suitable model in a diverse pool has become a critical strategy for building efficient and high-performing AI systems. A common approach is to train a supervised router; however, this requires vast, expensive human-annotated preference data and creates models that are notoriously brittle, failing to generalize when faced with inevitable distribution shifts in user queries. Consequently, developing robust, unsupervised routing methods that adapt without retraining is a crucial research frontier. This challenge is severely amplified by Large Reasoning Models (LRMs), which introduce a dual problem for any label-free method: their outputs have a causal вҖңthinkingвҖқвҶ’вҖңanswerвҖқ structure that must be modeled, and a structural imbalance where long reasoning text can dominate the final answer signal. We introduce ReasoningRouter, a novel framework that resolves these issues with a length-balanced embedding strategy and a probabilistic model capturing the thinking-to-answer dependency. Our key theoretical advance, the Causal Triangulation Property, enables the label-free estimation of component qualities and their causal link. Beyond competitive routing accuracy, ReasoningRouter offers unprecedented insights into model behavior, enabling separate quality assessment of reasoning and answer components while maintaining computational efficiency. The code is provided in the supplementary materials.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Model (LLM) мғқнғңкі„к°Җ м„ұмһҘн•Ём—җ л”°лқј, лӢӨм–‘н•ң model poolм—җм„ң мҝјлҰ¬лҘј к°ҖмһҘ м Ғн•©н•ң лӘЁлҚёлЎң routingн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  м„ұлҠҘмқҙ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң AI мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•өмӢ¬ м „лһөмқҙ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м ‘к·јмқҖ supervised routerлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҠ” л°©лҢҖн•ң кі л№„мҡ©мқҳ human-annotated preference dataлҘј н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳл©°, мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мҝјлҰ¬мқҳ л¶Ҳк°Җн”јн•ң distribution shiftм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң мқјл°ҳнҷ”м—җ мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” л“ұ л§Өмҡ° м·Ём•Ҫн•ң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мһ¬н•ҷмҠө м—Ҷмқҙ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” robustн•ң unsupervised routing л°©лІ•мқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м—°кө¬ м „м„ мқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҠ” Large Reasoning Models (LRMs)лЎң мқён•ҙ лҚ”мҡұ мӢ¬нҷ”лҗҳлҠ”лҚ°, label-free methodм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ л¬ём ңлҘј лҸҷмӢңм—җ м•јкё°н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” м¶ңл Ҙмқҙ causalн•ң вҖңthinkingвҖқвҶ’вҖңanswerвҖқ кө¬мЎ°лҘј к°Җм§ҖлҜҖлЎң мқҙлҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” кёҙ reasoning textк°Җ мөңмў… answer signalмқ„ м••лҸ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кө¬мЎ°м Ғ л¶Ҳк· нҳ•мқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кёёмқҙ к· нҳ•мқҙ л§һлҠ” embedding м „лһөкіј thinking-to-answer dependencyлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” probabilistic modelмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ ReasoningRouterлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ мқҙлЎ м Ғ м§„м „мқё Causal Triangulation PropertyлҠ” кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳкіј к·ё causal linkлҘј label м—Ҷмқҙ м¶”м •н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” routing м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ң, ReasoningRouterлҠ” кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң reasoningкіј answer кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳм—¬ н’Ҳм§Ҳ нҸүк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙ лӘЁлҚё лҸҷмһ‘м—җ лҢҖн•ң м „лЎҖ м—ҶлҠ” нҶөм°°мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” л¶ҖлЎқ мһҗлЈҢм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61258","en":"CircuitPrint: Mechanistic Circuit Fingerprints for Large Language Models","ko":"CircuitPrint: Large Language Modelмқ„ мң„н•ң Mechanistic Circuit Fingerprint","authors":"Zhenxiong Yan, Suhang Yao, Yu Liu, Wenqiang Jin","pos":"#3006","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=s6QTYBYnAA","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) are trained at significant computational and data cost, making them valuable intellectual property (IP). Existing IP verification methods primarily rely either on invasive watermarking that degrades model utility, or on superficial behavioral signatures disrupted by fine-tuning and model merging. This apparent trade-off between model utility and IP protection has constrained practical deployment. We challenge this trade-off and propose CircuitPrint, a non-invasive IP fingerprinting framework that enables robust verification through standard model queries by leveraging stable internal computational circuits of LLMs. We show that these circuits function as a persistent computational backbone across model derivatives, allowing them to serve as stable fingerprints for distinguishing LLMs. Building on this stability, CircuitPrint constructs IP signatures by identifying mechanistically essential supernodes that causally produce specific predictions within these circuits. Specifically, trigger queries are synthesized to replicate the internal suppression of these supernodes, thereby inducing distinctive and observable output shifts. Experimental results demonstrate that CircuitPrint substantially outperforms existing baselines while remaining robust under aggressive fine-tuning and model merging, effectively resolving this trade-off without altering model parameters.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language models (LLMs)мқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң м—°мӮ° л°Ҹ лҚ°мқҙн„° л№„мҡ©мқ„ л“Өм—¬ н•ҷмҠөлҗҳлҜҖлЎң, к·ҖмӨ‘н•ң м§Җм Ғ мһ¬мӮ°к¶Ң(IP)мқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ IP кІҖмҰқ л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң лӘЁлҚё мң мҡ©м„ұмқ„ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮӨлҠ” м№ЁмҠөм Ғ watermarkingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, fine-tuningкіј model mergingм—җ мқҳн•ҙ к№Ём§Җкё° мү¬мҡҙ н”јмғҒм Ғмқё н–үлҸҷм Ғ signatureм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚё мң мҡ©м„ұкіј IP ліҙнҳё мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІүліҙкё°мғҒ trade-offлҠ” мӢӨм ң л°°нҸ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҫн•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ trade-offм—җ л¬ём ңлҘј м ңкё°н•ҳкі , LLMмқҳ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё лӮҙл¶Җ computational circuitмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ н‘ңмӨҖ model queryл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ кІ¬кі н•ң кІҖмҰқмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” л№„м№ЁмҠөм Ғ IP fingerprinting н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ CircuitPrintлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң circuitмқҙ model derivative м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ м§ҖмҶҚлҗҳлҠ” computational backboneмңјлЎң кё°лҠҘн•ҳл©°, LLMмқ„ кө¬лі„н•ҳлҠ” м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё fingerprintлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң CircuitPrintлҠ” мқҙ circuit лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң нҠ№м • predictionмқ„ мқёкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” кё°кі„лЎ м ҒмңјлЎң н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё supernodeлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳм—¬ IP signatureлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” trigger queryлҘј н•©м„ұн•ҳм—¬ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң supernodeмқҳ лӮҙл¶Җ suppressionмқ„ мһ¬нҳ„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, лҸ…нҠ№н•ҳкі  кҙҖм°° к°ҖлҠҘн•ң output shiftлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” CircuitPrintк°Җ кіөкІ©м Ғмқё fine-tuningкіј model merging н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ к°•кұҙн•Ёмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң кё°мЎҙ baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, model parameterлҘј ліҖкІҪн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ мқҙ trade-offлҘј мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ н•ҙмҶҢн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62446","en":"LakeQA: A Benchmark for Complex Exploratory QA over a Million-Scale Data Lake","ko":"LakeQA: л°ұл§Ң мҠӨмјҖмқј лҚ°мқҙн„° л ҲмқҙнҒ¬ кё°л°ҳ ліөн•© нғҗмғү QA Benchmark","authors":"Haonan Wang, Jiaxiang Liu, Yurong Liu, Austin Wijaya, Tianle Zhou, Yifan Wu, Yijia Chen, Wanting You, Reya Vir, Daniela Pinto Veizaga, Grace Fan, Yusen Zhang, Juliana Freire, Eugene Wu","pos":"#3508","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gWoEOFW0CR","abs":"<p>Recent large language models (LLMs) have shown rapid progress on reading-based question answering (QA), where the evidence is explicitly provided or trivially retrievable. In contrast, real-world questions are often not paired with accurate evidence documents. The useful evidence resides in a massive collection of data lakes, necessitating searching as a prerequisite for answering. However, there is a lack of a comprehensive benchmark that requires searching and reasoning over a large collection of data lakes. To this end, we introduce LakeQA, a  comprehensive benchmark for search-centric question answering over data lakes that jointly emphasizes \\emph{searching} and \\emph{reasoning} capabilities. LakeQA is built on a heterogeneous collection of ~9.5 TB text resources from Wikipedia and open-source government data, spanning structured and unstructured data. To ensure the quality of LakeQA's tasks, each sample is annotated by at least one Ph.D level expert. Each task requires long-horizon multi-hop reasoning with implicit intermediate steps: agents need to discover the correct document(s) and then compose evidence across sources to produce the answer. Intensive experiment results on seven frontier LLMs have demonstrated that LakeQA is challenging. For instance, GPT-5.2 only obtains an exact matching score of 14.73% on LakeQA. Overall LakeQA provides a realistic testbed for developing LLM agents that can both \\emph{find} and \\emph{analyze} data in modern data lakes.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·јмқҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё (LLM)мқҖ evidenceк°Җ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м ңкіөлҗҳкұ°лӮҳ мүҪкІҢ кІҖмғү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң reading-based question answering (QA)м—җм„ң л№ лҘё м§„м „мқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ мӢӨм ң м§Ҳл¬ёмқҖ м •нҷ•н•ң evidence documentмҷҖ м§қм§Җм–ҙм§Җм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мң мҡ©н•ң evidenceлҠ” л°©лҢҖн•ң data lakeм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, лӢөліҖмқ„ мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” кІҖмғүмқҙ м„ н–үлҗҳм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ data lakeлҘј лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң кІҖмғүкіј м¶”лЎ мқ„ лӘЁл‘җ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё benchmarkлҠ” л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” search-centric question answering over data lakesлҘј мң„н•ң мў…н•© benchmarkмқё LakeQAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, \\emph{searching}кіј \\emph{reasoning} лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н•Ёк»ҳ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. LakeQAлҠ” WikipediaмҷҖ open-source government dataм—җм„ң к°Җм ёмҳЁ м•Ҫ 9.5 TBмқҳ text resourceлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң heterogeneous collection мң„м—җ кө¬м¶•лҗҳл©°, structured dataмҷҖ unstructured dataлҘј лӘЁл‘җ нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. LakeQA taskмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ к°Ғ sampleмқҖ мөңмҶҢ н•ң лӘ…мқҳ Ph.D level expertм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мЈјм„қмқҙ лӢ¬лҰ°лӢӨ. к°Ғ taskлҠ” м•”л¬өм Ғмқё мӨ‘к°„ лӢЁкі„лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң long-horizon multi-hop reasoningмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. agentлҠ” лЁјм Җ мҳ¬л°”лҘё documentлҘј м°ҫм•„м•ј н•ҳкі , мқҙнӣ„ м—¬лҹ¬ sourceмқҳ evidenceлҘј мЎ°н•©н•ҙ лӢөмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. 7к°ңмқҳ frontier LLMм—җ лҢҖн•ң м§‘мӨ‘м Ғмқё мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” LakeQAк°Җ м–ҙл өлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ GPT-5.2лҠ” LakeQAм—җм„ң exact matching score 14.73%л§Ңмқ„ м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. м „мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң LakeQAлҠ” нҳ„лҢҖ data lakeм—җм„ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј \\emph{м°ҫкі } \\emph{л¶„м„қ}н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” LLM agent к°ңл°ңмқ„ мң„н•ң нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё testbedлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63323","en":"BrokenMath: A Benchmark for Sycophancy in Theorem Proving with LLMs","ko":"BrokenMath: LLMмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң м •лҰ¬ мҰқлӘ…м—җм„ң м•„мІЁм—җ лҢҖн•ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Ivo Petrov, Jasper Dekoninck, Martin Vechev","pos":"#3613","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Y5bEI4cuMd","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) have recently shown strong performance on mathematical benchmarks. At the same time, they are prone to hallucination and sycophancy, often providing convincing but flawed proofs for incorrect mathematical statements provided by users. This significantly limits the applicability of LLMs in theorem proving, as verification of these flawed proofs must be done manually by expert mathematicians. However, existing benchmarks that measure sycophancy in mathematics are limited: they focus solely on final-answer problems, rely on very simple and often contaminated datasets, and construct benchmark samples using synthetic modifications that create ill-posed questions. To address these issues, we introduce BrokenMath, the first benchmark for evaluating sycophantic behavior in LLMs within the context of natural language theorem proving. BrokenMath is built from advanced 2025 competition problems, which are perturbed with an LLM to produce false statements and subsequently refined through expert review. We evaluate state-of-the-art LLMs and agentic systems and find that sycophancy is widespread, with the best model, GPT-5, producing sycophantic answers 29% of the time. We further investigate several mitigation strategies, including test-time interventions and supervised fine-tuning on curated sycophantic examples. These approaches reduce, but do not eliminate, sycophancy.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј large language model (LLM)мқҖ мҲҳн•ҷ benchmarkм—җм„ң к°•н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. лҸҷмӢңм—җ мқҙл“ӨмқҖ hallucinationкіј sycophancyм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҙ, мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗк°Җ м ңмӢңн•ң мһҳлӘ»лҗң мҲҳн•ҷ лӘ…м ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•ҳм§Җл§Ң кІ°н•Ёмқҙ мһҲлҠ” мҰқлӘ…мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” theorem provingм—җм„ң LLMмқҳ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°н•Ё мһҲлҠ” мҰқлӘ…мқҳ кІҖмҰқмқҖ м „л¬ёк°Җ мҲҳн•ҷмһҗк°Җ мҲҳмһ‘м—…мңјлЎң мҲҳн–үн•ҙм•ј н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҲҳн•ҷм—җм„ң sycophancyлҘј мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ benchmarkлҠ” н•ңкі„к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. final-answer л¬ём ңм—җл§Ң мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”кі , л§Өмҡ° лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©° мў…мў… мҳӨм—јлҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, ill-posed questionмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ лӮҙлҠ” synthetic modificationмңјлЎң benchmark sampleмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһҗм—°м–ҙ theorem proving л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ң LLMмқҳ sycophantic behaviorлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ benchmarkмқё BrokenMathлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. BrokenMathлҠ” 2025л…„мқҳ кі лӮңлҸ„ лҢҖнҡҢ л¬ём ңл“Өмқ„ кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ҳл©°, LLMмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ false statementлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ perturbн•ң л’Ө м „л¬ёк°Җ кІҖнҶ лҘј кұ°міҗ м •м ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңмӢ  LLMкіј agentic systemмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, sycophancyк°Җ л„җлҰ¬ нҚјм ё мһҲмңјл©°, мөңкі  м„ұлҠҘ лӘЁлҚёмқё GPT-5мЎ°м°Ё 29%мқҳ кІҪмҡ° sycophantic answerлҘј мғқм„ұн•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң test-time interventionкіј м„ лі„лҗң sycophantic exampleм—җ лҢҖн•ң supervised fine-tuningмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м—¬лҹ¬ мҷ„нҷ” м „лһөмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јмқҖ sycophancyлҘј мӨ„мқҙм§Җл§Ң, мҷ„м „нһҲ м ңкұ°н•ҳм§ҖлҠ” лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66625","en":"UniFLoW: Universal Multi-Modal Federated LoRA Fine-Tuning Framework with Analytical Aggregation","ko":"UniFLoW: н•ҙм„қм Ғ м§‘кі„лҘј к°–лҠ” лІ”мҡ© л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ Federated LoRA Fine-Tuning н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"haoyuan liang, Zhiyu Ye, Jielong Tang, Yang Yang, Shilei Cao, Guowen Li, Fei Hu, Zhiwei Zhang, Haohuan Fu, Juepeng Zheng","pos":"#3712","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=21J9OI6mhc","abs":"As Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) continue to be trained, the availability of public data diminishes, limiting the possibility for further training and adaptation. However, private data remains an underutilized yet valuable resource. Federated Learning (FL) enables decentralized training on private data, yet extending it to MLLMs is challenging: heterogeneous client modalities induce architectural incompatibility, and full-parameter fine-tuning of billion-scale models incurs prohibitive communication costs. Parameter-efficient methods like LoRA alleviate these issues but introduce aggregation inconsistency, as averaged low-rank updates fail to recover the true global update faithfully.  To address these issues, we propose **UniFLoW**(Universal multi-modal Federated LoRA fine-tuning framework With Analytical Aggregation), a unified federated framework that leverages pre-trained large language models and a multi-modal Encoder architecture, and our proposed Federated Aggregating Analytical Low-Rank Adaption$FedA^2$-$LoRA$). UniFLoW effectively utilizes fragmented client-side multi-modal data while $FedA^2$-$LoRA$ ensuring consistent aggregation. And modality-specific encoders and a II stage training strategy ensure effective integration of diverse modalities without overfitting.  Experiments on text, image, and speech demonstrate that **UniFLoW** enables scalable, communication-efficient, and aggregation-consistent federated fine-tuning,   with $FedA^2$-$LoRA$ achieving state-of-the-art performance compared to existing FedLoRA approaches. We envision UniFLoW as a promising solution to the growing scarcity of public data.","absKo":"Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs)к°Җ кі„мҶҚ н•ҷмҠөлҗЁм—җ л”°лқј кіөк°ң лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ к°Җмҡ©м„ұмқҖ к°җмҶҢн•ҳкі  мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё н•ҷмҠөкіј м Ғмқ‘мқҳ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӮ¬м Ғ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҷңмҡ©лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мұ„ к°Җм№ҳ мһҲлҠ” мһҗмӣҗмңјлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. Federated Learning (FL)мқҖ мӮ¬м Ғ лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җм„ңмқҳ л¶„мӮ° н•ҷмҠөмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҘј MLLMмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё нҒҙлқјмқҙм–ёнҠё лӘЁлӢ¬лҰ¬нӢ°к°Җ м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳм Ғ л№„нҳёнҷҳм„ұмқ„ мң л°ңн•ҳкі , мҲҳмӢӯм–ө к·ңлӘЁ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ м „мІҙ нҢҢлқјлҜён„°лҘј fine-tuningн•ҳл©ҙ к°җлӢ№н•ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ нҶөмӢ  л№„мҡ©мқҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. LoRAмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ parameter-efficient л°©лІ•мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҸүк· нҷ”лҗң low-rank м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёк°Җ мӢӨм ң м „м—ӯ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҘј м¶©мӢӨн•ҳкІҢ ліөмӣҗн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҙ aggregation inconsistencyлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” **UniFLoW**(Universal multi-modal Federated LoRA fine-tuning framework With Analytical Aggregation)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мӮ¬м „ н•ҷмҠөлҗң large language modelsмҷҖ multi-modal Encoder м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ” Federated Aggregating Analytical Low-Rank Adaption $FedA^2$-$LoRA$лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© federated frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. UniFLoWлҠ” л¶„м Ҳлҗң нҒҙлқјмқҙм–ёнҠё мёЎ multi-modal лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳл©°, $FedA^2$-$LoRA$лҠ” мқјкҙҖлҗң aggregationмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң modality-specific encoderмҷҖ II stage training strategyлҠ” кіјм Ғн•© м—Ҷмқҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң лӘЁлӢ¬лҰ¬нӢ°мқҳ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё нҶөн•©мқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. text, image, speechм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ **UniFLoW**к°Җ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  нҶөмӢ  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙл©° aggregation мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҙ мһҲлҠ” federated fine-tuningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі , $FedA^2$-$LoRA$к°Җ кё°мЎҙ FedLoRA м ‘к·јлІ•кіј л№„көҗн•ҙ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” UniFLoWк°Җ м»Өм ёк°ҖлҠ” кіөк°ң лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶ҖмЎұ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мң л§қн•ң н•ҙлІ•мқҙ лҗҳлҰ¬лқј ліёлӢӨ."},{"id":"66456","en":"CARE: Confounder-Aware Aggregation for Reliable LLM Evaluation","ko":"CARE: мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” LLM нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң көҗлһҖ мқём§Җ м§‘кі„","authors":"Jitian Zhao, Changho Shin, Tzu-Heng Huang, Satya Sai Srinath Namburi GNVV, Frederic Sala","pos":"#4008","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=3WPDFjZ1UT","abs":"<p>LLM-as-a-judge ensembles are the standard paradigm for scalable evaluation, but their aggregation mechanisms suffer from a fundamental flaw: they implicitly assume that judges provide independent estimates of true quality. However, in practice, LLM judges exhibit correlated errors caused by shared latent confounders---such as verbosity, stylistic preferences, or training artifacts---causing standard aggregation rules like majority vote or averaging to provide little gain or even amplify systematic mistakes. To address this, we introduce CARE, a confounder-aware aggregation framework that explicitly models LLM judge scores as arising from both a latent true-quality signal and shared confounding factors. Rather than heuristically re-weighting judges, CARE separates quality from confounders without access to ground-truth labels. We provide theoretical guarantees for identifiability and finite-sample recovery under shared confounders, and we quantify the systematic bias incurred when aggregation models omit confounding latent factors. Across 12 public benchmarks spanning continuous scoring, binary classification, and pairwise preference settings, CARE improves aggregation accuracy, reducing error by up to 26.8%.</p>","absKo":"<p>LLM-as-a-judge ensembleмқҖ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң н‘ңмӨҖ paradigmмқҙм§Җл§Ң, aggregation mechanismм—җлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё кІ°н•Ёмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мҰү, judgeк°Җ true qualityм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё м¶”м •мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨкі  м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң к°Җм •н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ңлЎң LLM judgeлҠ” verbosity, stylistic preference, training artifact к°ҷмқҖ кіөмң  latent confounderлЎң мқён•ҙ мғҒкҙҖлҗң errorлҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ majority voteлӮҳ averaging к°ҷмқҖ н‘ңмӨҖ aggregation ruleмқҖ мқҙл“қмқҙ кұ°мқҳ м—Ҷкұ°лӮҳ мҳӨнһҲл Ө мІҙкі„м Ғ мӢӨмҲҳлҘј мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLM judge scoreк°Җ latent true-quality signalкіј кіөмң  confounding factorм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗңлӢӨкі  лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” confounder-aware aggregation frameworkмқё CAREлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. CAREлҠ” нңҙлҰ¬мҠӨнӢұн•ҳкІҢ judgeмқҳ к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳлҘј лӢӨмӢң мЎ°м •н•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , ground-truth labelм—җ м ‘к·јн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  qualityмҷҖ confounderлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кіөмң  confounder н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ identifiabilityмҷҖ finite-sample recoveryм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , aggregation modelмқҙ confounding latent factorлҘј мғқлһөн•  л•Ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” мІҙкі„м Ғ biasлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. continuous scoring, binary classification, pairwise preference settingмқ„ м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” 12к°ңмқҳ public benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң CAREлҠ” aggregation accuracyлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, errorлҘј мөңлҢҖ 26.8%к№Ңм§Җ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66566","en":"FedRot-LoRA: Mitigating Rotational Misalignment in Federated LoRA","ko":"FedRot-LoRA: Federated LoRAм—җм„ң нҡҢм „ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Haoran Zhang, Dongjun Kim, Seohyeon Cha, Haris Vikalo","pos":"#4115","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2X8Qi3VdjA","abs":"Federated LoRA provides a communication-efficient mechanism for fine-tuning large language models on decentralized data. In practice, however, a discrepancy between the factor-wise averaging used to preserve low rank and the mathematically correct aggregation of local updates can cause significant aggregation error and unstable training. We argue that a major source of this problem is *rotational misalignment*, arising from the rotational invariance of low-rank factorizations -- semantically equivalent updates can be represented in different latent subspaces across clients since $(B_i R_i)(R_i^\\top A_i) = B_i A_i$. When such misaligned factors are averaged directly, they interfere destructively and degrade the global update. To address this issue, we propose **FedRot-LoRA**, a federated LoRA framework that aligns client updates via orthogonal transformations prior to aggregation. This alignment preserves the semantic update while reducing cross-client subspace mismatch, without increasing communication cost or restricting model expressivity. We provide a convergence analysis that examines the aggregation error induced by factor-wise averaging and shows how rotational alignment yields a tighter upper bound on this error. Extensive experiments on natural language understanding and generative tasks demonstrate that FedRot-LoRA consistently outperforms existing federated LoRA baselines across a range of heterogeneity levels and LoRA ranks. Code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/FedRot-LoRA","absKo":"Federated LoRAлҠ” л¶„мӮ° лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җм„ң large language modelмқ„ fine-tuningн•  л•Ң communication-efficientн•ң л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” low rankлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” factor-wise averagingкіј, мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң мҳ¬л°”лҘё local update aggregation мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳк°Җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң aggregation errorмҷҖ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ң trainingмқ„ м•јкё°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л¬ём ңмқҳ мЈјмҡ” мӣҗмқёмқҙ *rotational misalignment*лқјкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” low-rank factorizationмқҳ rotational invarianceм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗҳл©°, мқҳлҜём ҒмңјлЎң лҸҷл“ұн•ң updateлқјлҸ„ $(B_i R_i)(R_i^\\top A_i) = B_i A_i$мқҙлҜҖлЎң clientл§ҲлӢӨ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё latent subspaceлЎң н‘ңнҳ„лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң misaligned factorлҘј к·ёлҢҖлЎң нҸүк· лӮҙл©ҙ м„ңлЎң нҢҢкҙҙм ҒмңјлЎң к°„м„ӯн•ҳм—¬ global updateмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” aggregation мқҙм „м—җ orthogonal transformationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ client updateлҘј м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” federated LoRA frameworkмқё **FedRot-LoRA**лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң alignmentлҠ” communication costлҘј лҠҳлҰ¬кұ°лӮҳ model expressivityлҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң semantic updateлҠ” ліҙмЎҙн•ҳкі  cross-client subspace mismatchлҘј мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” factor-wise averagingмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” aggregation errorлҘј кІҖнҶ н•ҳлҠ” convergence analysisлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , rotational alignmentк°Җ мқҙ errorм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лҚ” нғҖмқҙнҠён•ң upper boundлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мһҗм—°м–ҙ мқҙн•ҙ л°Ҹ мғқм„ұ кіјм ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FedRot-LoRAк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң heterogeneity мҲҳмӨҖкіј LoRA rankм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ federated LoRA baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/FedRot-LoRA м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61335","en":"Words & Weights: Streamlining Multi-Turn Interactions via Co-Adaptation","ko":"Words & Weights: кіөлҸҷ м Ғмқ‘мқ„ нҶөн•ң Multi-Turn мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© к°„мҶҢнҷ”","authors":"Chenxing Wei, Hong Wang, Ying He, Zhongxiang Dai, Bo Jiang, Fei Yu, Yao Shu","pos":"#500","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=rEpmIPMftW","abs":"Test-time policy adaptation for multi-turn interactions (T$^2$PAM) is essential for aligning Large Language Models (LLMs) with dynamic user needs during inference time. However, existing paradigms commonly treat test-time adaptation as a single-axis problem, either purely refining instructions (Prompt Engineering) or only adjusting weights (Test-Time Training), ignoring that interaction failures stem from a coupled mix of ambiguity and incapacity. We argue that these two optimization paths are not merely additive but synergistic: semantic clarity acts as a pre-conditioner for effective parameter updates. To this end, we propose ROSA2, a framework that reformulates interaction as a joint optimization problem over the heterogeneous space of Words and Weights. By mathematically decomposing the error signal, ROSA2 utilizes textual gradients to rectify intent ambiguity and parameter updates to bridge capability gaps. Theoretically, we prove that this co-adaptation strictly reduces the required parameter shift for convergence. Empirically, ROSA2 outperforms state-of-the-art baselines by 30\\% on MATH while reducing interaction turns by 40\\%, demonstrating that refining the context unlocks the true potential of parameter updates.","absKo":"multi-turn interactionмқ„ мң„н•ң test-time policy adaptation (T$^2$PAM)мқҖ inference timeм—җ Large Language Models (LLMs)лҘј лҸҷм Ғ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мҡ”кө¬м—җ л§һм¶”лҠ” лҚ° н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң test-time adaptationмқ„ лӢЁмқј м¶• л¬ём ңлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳм—¬, instructionsлҘј мҲңмҲҳн•ҳкІҢ м •м ңн•ҳлҠ” кІғ(Prompt Engineering) лҳҗлҠ” weightsл§Ң мЎ°м •н•ҳлҠ” кІғ(Test-Time Training) мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳл§Ң мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , interaction мӢӨнҢЁк°Җ ambiguityмҷҖ incapacityк°Җ кІ°н•©лҗң нҳ•нғңм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л‘җ мөңм Ғнҷ” кІҪлЎңк°Җ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ лҚ”н•ҙм§ҖлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј мғҒнҳё мӢңл„Ҳм§ҖлҘј лӮёлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, semantic clarityлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё parameter updateлҘј мң„н•ң pre-conditioner м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” interactionмқ„ WordsмҷҖ WeightsлқјлҠ” мқҙм§Ҳм Ғ кіөк°„ мң„м—җм„ңмқҳ joint optimization л¬ём ңлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” ROSA2лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. error signalмқ„ мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, ROSA2лҠ” textual gradientлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ intent ambiguityлҘј л°”лЎңмһЎкі  parameter updateлҘј нҶөн•ҙ capability gapмқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ co-adaptationмқҙ мҲҳл ҙм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң parameter shiftлҘј м—„л°ҖнһҲ мӨ„мһ„мқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң ROSA2лҠ” MATHм—җм„ң state-of-the-art baselineліҙлӢӨ 30\\% лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©ҙм„ң interaction turn мҲҳлҘј 40\\% мӨ„м—¬, contextлҘј м •м ңн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ parameter updateмқҳ м§„м •н•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ м—¬лҠ” н•өмӢ¬мһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"60825","en":"CoMem: Context Management with A Decoupled Long-Context Model","ko":"CoMem: л¶„лҰ¬нҳ• Long-Context Modelмқ„ нҶөн•ң Context Management","authors":"Yuwei Zhang, Chengyu Dong, Shuowei Jin, Changlong Yu, Hejie Cui, Hongye Jin, Xinyang Zhang, Hamed Bonab, Colin Lockard, Jianshu Chen, Zhenyu Shi, Jingbo Shang, Xian Li, Bing Yin","pos":"#508","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=wInE6qnt9n","abs":"Context management enables agentic models to solve long-horizon tasks through iterative summarization of previous interaction histories. However, this process typically incurs substantial decoding overhead for the extra summarization tokens, which significantly affect the end-to-end response latency at deployment. In this paper, we introduce CoMem, a novel framework that decouples memory management from the primary agent workflow, enabling these processes to execute in parallel. We propose a $k$-step-off asynchronous pipeline that overlaps the memory model's summarization with the agent's inference, effectively masking the latency of context processing. To ensure robustness under this asynchronous setting, we introduce a reward-driven training strategy that aligns the memory model to capture sufficient statistics for the agent's decision-making. Theoretical analysis confirms that CoMem offers a superior efficiency-effectiveness trade-off compared to coupled architectures. Our extensive experimental results on SWE-Bench-Verified show that CoMem provides 1.4x latency improvements upon vanilla long-context solutions while preserving most of the performance. Furthermore, we demonstrate that these latency gains scale favorably with increased system throughput, offering a modular path forward for the independent optimization of agent reasoning and memory compression.","absKo":"Context managementлҠ” agentic modelмқҙ мқҙм „ interaction historyлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ”м•Ҫн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ long-horizon taskлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ кіјм •мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё summarization token л•Ңл¬ём—җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң decoding overheadлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” л°°нҸ¬ мӢң end-to-end response latencyм—җ нҒ° мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” memory managementлҘј primary agent workflowмҷҖ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ кіјм •мқ„ лі‘л ¬лЎң мӢӨн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkмқё CoMemмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” memory modelмқҳ summarizationкіј agentмқҳ inferenceлҘј кІ№м№ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” $k$-step-off asynchronous pipelineмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, context processingмқҳ latencyлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң к°ҖлҰ°лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң asynchronous settingм—җм„ң robustн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” memory modelмқҙ agentмқҳ decision-makingм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң sufficient statisticмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” reward-driven training strategyлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қмқҖ CoMemмқҙ coupled architectureм—җ л№„н•ҙ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң efficiency-effectiveness trade-offлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. SWE-Bench-Verifiedм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” CoMemмқҙ vanilla long-context solution лҢҖл№„ 1.4л°°мқҳ latency к°ңм„ мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң latency н–ҘмғҒмқҙ system throughput мҰқк°ҖмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ мң лҰ¬н•ҳкІҢ нҷ•мһҘлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, agent reasoningкіј memory compressionмқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лӘЁл“Ҳнҳ• кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65811","en":"Navigating the Pareto Frontier of Alignment:Spectrum-Adaptive Fine-Tuning for LLMs","ko":"м •л ¬мқҳ Pareto н”„лЎ нӢ°м–ҙ н•ӯн•ҙ: LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң мҠӨнҺҷнҠёлҹј м Ғмқ‘нҳ• нҢҢмқёнҠңлӢқ","authors":"Yaoyou Fan, Chao Zhang, Xiaoyu Tan, Chenxing Sun, Yu Yuan, Haoyu Feng, Lu Pan, Ke Zeng, Xunliang Cai","pos":"#1606","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9wLcZBHZZ5","abs":"<p>Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) with Negative Log-Likelihood (NLL) remains the standard post-training paradigm for Large Language Models, yet it imposes an excessive penalty on low-probability target tokens. This focus forces the model to prioritize minimizing the loss of difficult samples over optimizing the overall quality of the generation, often leading to unwarranted overconfidence. On the other hand, alternatives like Dynamic Fine-Tuning (DFT) suffer from vanishing gradients on these tokens, which severely hinders the acquisition of new concepts. To bridge this gap, we propose <strong>SAFT</strong> <strong>S</strong>pectrum-<strong>A</strong>daptive <strong>F</strong>ine-<strong>T</strong>uning), a unified framework that interpolates between the aggressive learning signal of NLL and the robust nature of probability-weighted optimization. By adaptively balancing these objectives, SAFT effectively mitigates outlier sensitivity without sacrificing learning efficiency. Empirically, our method achieves state-of-the-art performance on mathematical reasoning benchmarks, demonstrating superior generalization on out-of-distribution tasks. Our anonymized code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/SAFT-9FEB.</p>","absKo":"<p>Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) with Negative Log-Likelihood (NLL)мқҖ Large Language Modelsмқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ post-training paradigmмңјлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, лӮ®мқҖ нҷ•лҘ мқҳ target tokenм—җ кіјлҸ„н•ң penaltyлҘј л¶Җкіјн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҙҲм җмқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мғқм„ұмқҳ м „л°ҳм Ғмқё н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ sampleмқҳ lossлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мҡ°м„ мҲңмң„лҘј л‘җлҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“Өл©°, мў…мў… л¶Ҳн•„мҡ”н•ң overconfidenceлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ Dynamic Fine-Tuning (DFT) к°ҷмқҖ лҢҖм•ҲмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң tokenм—җм„ң gradientк°Җ мҶҢмӢӨлҗҳм–ҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ к°ңл…җмқҳ мҠөл“қмқ„ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ м Җн•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>SAFT</strong> <strong>S</strong>pectrum-<strong>A</strong>daptive <strong>F</strong>ine-<strong>T</strong>uning)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” NLLмқҳ кіөкІ©м Ғмқё learning signalкіј probability-weighted optimizationмқҳ к°•кұҙн•ң нҠ№м„ұ мӮ¬мқҙлҘј ліҙк°„н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘ©м Ғл“Өмқ„ м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң к· нҳ•нҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, SAFTлҠ” н•ҷмҠө нҡЁмңЁмқ„ нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң outlier sensitivityлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ  benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , out-of-distribution taskм—җм„ң мҡ°мҲҳн•ң generalizationмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқөлӘ…нҷ”лҗң мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/SAFT-9FEB м—җм„ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•ҳлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60925","en":"TokSuite: Measuring the Impact of Tokenizer Choice on Language Model Behavior","ko":"TokSuite: Tokenizer м„ нғқмқҙ Language Model н–үлҸҷм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙ мёЎм •","authors":"GГјl Sena AltДұntaЕҹ, Malikeh Ehghaghi, Brian Lester, Fengyuan Liu, Wanru Zhao, Marco Ciccone, Colin Raffel","pos":"#1307","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vIZz7LvObC","abs":"<p>Tokenizers provide the fundamental basis through which text is represented and processed by language models (LMs). Despite the importance of tokenization, its role in LM performance and behavior is poorly understood due to the challenge of measuring the impact of tokenization in isolation. To address this need, we present TokSuite, a collection of models and a benchmark that supports research into tokenization's influence on LMs.  Specifically, we release fourteen pre-trained models that use different tokenizers but are otherwise identical, using the same architecture, dataset, training budget, and initialization.  We also release a multilingual robustness benchmark that measures model performance under real-world perturbations in English, Chinese, Farsi, Italian, and Turkish, curated by native annotators.  Together, TokSuite allows robust decoupling of the influence of a model's tokenizer, supporting a series of novel findings that elucidate the respective benefits and shortcomings of a wide range of popular tokenizers.</p>","absKo":"<p>TokenizerлҠ” textк°Җ language models (LMs)м—җм„ң н‘ңнҳ„лҗҳкі  мІҳлҰ¬лҗҳлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё кё°л°ҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. tokenizationмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , tokenizationмқҳ м—ӯн• мқҙ LM м„ұлҠҘкіј behaviorм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–ҘмқҖ tokenizationмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ кі лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң мёЎм •н•ҳкё° м–ҙл өкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ м ңлҢҖлЎң мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•„мҡ”лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” TokSuiteлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. TokSuiteлҠ” tokenizationмқҙ LMsм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң м—°кө¬лҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” modelsмҷҖ benchmarkмқҳ лӘЁмқҢмқҙлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё tokenizersлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм§Җл§Ң architecture, dataset, training budget, initializationмқҖ лҸҷмқјн•ң 14к°ңмқҳ pre-trained modelsлҘј кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҳҒм–ҙ, мӨ‘көӯм–ҙ, нҢҢлҘҙмӢңм–ҙ, мқҙнғҲлҰ¬м•„м–ҙ, н„°нӮӨм–ҙм—җм„ң real-world perturbation н•ҳмқҳ model performanceлҘј мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” multilingual robustness benchmarkлҸ„ кіөк°ңн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” native annotatorк°Җ нҒҗл Ҳмқҙм…ҳн–ҲлӢӨ. н•Ёк»ҳ, TokSuiteлҠ” model tokenizerмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙл Ҙмқ„ robustн•ҳкІҢ л¶„лҰ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳл©°, л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң tokenizersмқҳ мһҘлӢЁм җмқ„ л°қнһҲлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л°ңкІ¬мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66813","en":"Steer Like the LLM: Activation Steering that Mimics Prompting","ko":"LLMмІҳлҹј мЎ°мў…н•ҳлқј: Promptingмқ„ лӘЁл°©н•ҳлҠ” Activation Steering","authors":"Geert Heyman, Frederik Vandeputte","pos":"#1406","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=06Nk3dJDMq","abs":"<p>Large language models can be steered at inference time through prompting or activation interventions, but activation steering methods often underperform compared to prompt-based approaches. We investigate whether activation steering can be improved by learning to mimic the interventions that prompt steering triggers within the model. To this end, we introduce <em>Prompt Steering Replacement (PSR)</em> models, a new family of activation steering methods that distill prompt steering behavior into interpretable interventions on model activations. A PSR is an activation steering method that estimates position-specific steering coefficients and is trained to imitate prompt-based interventions. Experiments on persona steering and instruction following across multiple language models demonstrate that PSR models consistently outperform constant-coefficient interventions that are frequently used in the literature and achieve performance close to or exceeding prompt steering while maintaining interpretability.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ promptingмқҙлӮҳ activation interventionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м¶”лЎ  мӢңм җм—җ мЎ°м •н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, activation steering л°©лІ•мқҖ мў…мў… prompt кё°л°ҳ м ‘к·јлІ•м—җ л№„н•ҙ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚё лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң prompt steeringмқҙ мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” interventionмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬ лӘЁмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң activation steeringмқ„ к°ңм„ н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ <em>Prompt Steering Replacement (PSR)</em> лӘЁлҚёмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” prompt steeringмқҳ лҸҷмһ‘мқ„ лӘЁлҚё activationм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң interventionмңјлЎң distillн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кі„м—ҙмқҳ activation steering л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. PSRмқҖ мң„м№ҳлі„ steering coefficientлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” activation steering л°©лІ•мқҙл©°, prompt кё°л°ҳ interventionмқ„ лӘЁмӮ¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҷмҠөлҗңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң persona steeringкіј instruction followingм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PSR лӘЁлҚёмқҙ л¬ён—Ңм—җм„ң мһҗмЈј мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” constant-coefficient interventionмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң prompt steeringм—җ к·јм ‘н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј мғҒнҡҢн•ҳлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66711","en":"MoSE: Mixture of Slimmable Experts for Efficient and Adaptive Language Models","ko":"MoSE: нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  м Ғмқ‘м Ғмқё м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мң„н•ң Mixture of Slimmable Experts","authors":"Nurbek Tastan, Stefanos Laskaridis, Karthik Nandakumar, Samuel HorvГЎth","pos":"#1601","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=18C6xMcD96","abs":"<p>Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models scale large language models efficiently by sparsely activating experts, but once an expert is selected, it is executed fully. Hence, the trade-off between accuracy and computation in an MoE model typically exhibits large discontinuities. We propose Mixture of Slimmable Experts (MoSE), an MoE architecture in which each expert has a nested, slimmable structure that can be executed at variable widths.  This enables conditional computation not only over <strong>which</strong> experts are activated, but also over <strong>how much</strong> of each expert is utilized. Consequently, a single pretrained MoSE model can support a more continuous spectrum of accuracy-compute trade-offs at inference time. We present a simple and stable training recipe for slimmable experts under sparse routing, combining multi-width training with standard MoE objectives. During inference, we explore strategies for runtime width determination, including a <strong>lightweight test-time training mechanism</strong> that learns how to map router confidence/probabilities to expert widths under a fixed budget. Experiments on GPT models trained on OpenWebText demonstrate that MoSE matches or improves upon standard MoE at full width and <strong>consistently shifts the Pareto frontier</strong> for accuracy vs. cost, achieving comparable performance with significantly fewer FLOPs.</p>","absKo":"<p>Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) лӘЁлҚёмқҖ expertлҘј нқ¬мҶҢн•ҳкІҢ нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ large language modelмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, н•ң лІҲ expertк°Җ м„ нғқлҗҳл©ҙ к·ё expertлҠ” мҷ„м „нһҲ мӢӨн–үлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң MoE лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң accuracyмҷҖ computation мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offлҠ” мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң нҒ° л¶Ҳм—°мҶҚм„ұмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ expertк°Җ variable widthлЎң мӢӨн–үлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” nested, slimmable structureлҘј к°–лҠ” MoE architectureмқё Mixture of Slimmable Experts (MoSE)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м–ҙл–Ө expertк°Җ нҷңм„ұнҷ”лҗҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң conditional computationлҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј к°Ғ expertмқҳ м–ҙлҠҗ м •лҸ„к°Җ нҷңмҡ©лҗҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң conditional computationлҸ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҙм§‘лӢҲлӢӨ. кІ°кіјм ҒмңјлЎң, лӢЁмқј pretrained MoSE лӘЁлҚёмқҖ inference мӢң лҚ” м—°мҶҚм Ғмқё accuracy-compute trade-off мҠӨнҺҷнҠёлҹјмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” sparse routing н•ҳм—җм„ң slimmable expertлҘј мң„н•ң к°„лӢЁн•ҳкі  м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё training recipeлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, multi-width trainingкіј standard MoE objectiveлҘј кІ°н•©н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. inference лҸҷм•Ҳм—җлҠ” fixed budget н•ҳм—җм„ң router confidence/probabilityлҘј expert widthм—җ л§Өн•‘н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” <strong>lightweight test-time training mechanism</strong>мқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҙ runtime width кІ°м •мқ„ мң„н•ң м „лһөмқ„ нғҗмғүн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. OpenWebTextлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң GPT лӘЁлҚё мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ MoSEк°Җ full widthм—җм„ң standard MoEмҷҖ лҸҷл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, accuracy лҢҖл№„ costмқҳ <strong>Pareto frontierлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мқҙлҸҷ</strong>мӢңмјң нӣЁм”¬ м ҒмқҖ FLOPsлЎң л№„мҠ·н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64339","en":"More Edits, More Stable: Understanding the Lifelong Normalization in Sequential Model Editing","ko":"нҺём§‘мқҙ л§Һмқ„мҲҳлЎқ м•Ҳм •м Ғ: мҲңм°Ём Ғ лӘЁлҚё нҺём§‘м—җм„ң нҸүмғқ м •к·ңнҷ” мқҙн•ҙ","authors":"Xin Ma, Wei Chen, Qi Liu, Derong Xu, Zhi Zheng, Tong Xu, Enhong Chen","pos":"#1602","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OcCpVIcgaY","abs":"<p>Lifelong Model Editing aims to continuously update evolving facts in Large Language Models while preserving unrelated knowledge and general capabilities, yet it remains plagued by catastrophic forgetting and model collapse. Empirically, we find that the few recent editors resilient over long horizons share the same core strategy: <strong>Lifelong Normalization (LN)</strong>, which normalizes value gradients using running statistics. Removing LN causes immediate collapse, and we observe a counter-intuitive <strong>positive cumulative effect</strong> where early edits can facilitate later edits. This suggests that with LN, early edits can stabilize the model and promote the success of future edits. Yet the mechanism of LN remains a \"black box\", leaving its precise role in lifelong stability poorly understood. In this work, we provide the <strong>first</strong> theoretical account of LN in the lifelong regime. Our analysis reveals a self-reinforcing stability loop and proves that, when combined with ridge-regularized regression, LN yields updates with <strong>asymptotic orthogonality</strong> and <strong>bounded norms</strong>, directly mitigating forgetting and systemic collapse. Based on these insights, we derive <strong>StableEdit</strong>, which strengthens this stability loop via an explicit warm-up stage and full whitening, improving long-horizon stability at minimal overhead. Extensive experiments validate our theory and demonstrate competitive performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Lifelong Model EditingмқҖ Large Language Modelsм—җм„ң кҙҖл Ё м—ҶлҠ” м§ҖмӢқкіј мқјл°ҳм Ғ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, catastrophic forgettingкіј model collapseлқјлҠ” л¬ём ңм—җ кі„мҶҚ мӢңлӢ¬лҰ°лӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң, кёҙ мӢңк°„мІҷлҸ„м—җм„ң кІ¬кі н•ң лӘҮ м•Ҳ лҗҳлҠ” мөңк·ј editorл“ӨмқҖ лҸҷмқјн•ң н•өмӢ¬ м „лһөмқё <strong>Lifelong Normalization (LN)</strong>мқ„ кіөмң н•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. LNмқҖ running statisticsлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ value gradientsлҘј м •к·ңнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. LNмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ҳл©ҙ мҰүк°Ғм Ғмқё collapseк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҙҲкё° editк°Җ мқҙнӣ„ editлҘј мҙүм§„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м§ҒкҙҖм—җ л°ҳн•ҳлҠ” <strong>positive cumulative effect</strong>лҸ„ кҙҖм°°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” LNмқҙ мһҲмқ„ л•Ң мҙҲкё° editк°Җ modelмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкі  н–Ҙнӣ„ editмқҳ м„ұкіөмқ„ мҙүм§„н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ LNмқҳ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ \"black box\"лЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲм–ҙ, lifelong stabilityм—җм„ңмқҳ м •нҷ•н•ң м—ӯн• мқҙ мһҳ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” lifelong regimeм—җм„ң LNм—җ лҢҖн•ң <strong>мІ«</strong> мқҙлЎ м Ғ м„ӨлӘ…мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ мһҗкё°к°•нҷ”м Ғ м•Ҳм •м„ұ лЈЁн”„лҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, ridge-regularized regressionкіј кІ°н•©лҗ  л•Ң LNмқҙ <strong>asymptotic orthogonality</strong>мҷҖ <strong>bounded norms</strong>лҘј к°–лҠ” updateлҘј мғқм„ұн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” forgettingкіј мӢңмҠӨн…ңм Ғ collapseлҘј м§Ғм ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё warm-up лӢЁкі„мҷҖ full whiteningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ м•Ҳм •м„ұ лЈЁн”„лҘј к°•нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” <strong>StableEdit</strong>лҘј лҸ„м¶ңн–Ҳмңјл©°, мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлЎң long-horizon stabilityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкі  кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62837","en":"Entropy-aware Span-Constrained Optimal Transport for Robust Cross-Tokenizer Knowledge Distillation","ko":"к°•кұҙн•ң Cross-Tokenizer Knowledge Distillationмқ„ мң„н•ң м—”нҠёлЎңн”ј кё°л°ҳ Span-Constrained Optimal Transport","authors":"Zhi-Ping Liu, Simiao Li, Wei Li, Hanting Chen, Jie Hu, Hua-Lei Yin, Xinghao Chen","pos":"#1907","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ci0YXenfYe","abs":"<p>Existing Cross-Tokenizer Knowledge Distillation (CTKD) methods fail to outperform simple supervised fine-tuning when vocabulary overlap is low due to severe alignment noise. We identify this phenomenon as the <strong>``Low-Overlap negative transfer regime,''</strong> To overcome this, we propose <strong>Entropy-aware Span-Constrained Optimal Transport (E-SCOT)</strong>, a robust framework that treats distillation as a sparse transport problem with a vocabulary-agnostic ground metric. Unlike prior OT approaches that incur quadratic costs via dense optimization, E-SCOT employs span-anchored lexical alignment to construct a deterministic, locality-preserving coupling in linear time. Furthermore, we introduce R\\'enyi-entropy adaptive reweighting to dynamically concentrate the distillation budget on informative positions exhibiting significant uncertainty-profile gaps. Extensive experiments demonstrate that E-SCOT achieves state-of-the-art performance across diverse model families, effectively eliminating negative transfer even in challenging low-overlap scenarios.</p>","absKo":"<p>кё°мЎҙ Cross-Tokenizer Knowledge Distillation(CTKD) л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ vocabulary overlapмқҙ лӮ®мқ„ л•Ң мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң alignment noise л•Ңл¬ём—җ лӢЁмҲңн•ң supervised fine-tuningліҙлӢӨ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ мўӢм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ <strong>``Low-Overlap negative transfer regime,''</strong>лЎң мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” distillationмқ„ vocabulary-agnostic ground metricмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” sparse transport problemмңјлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳлҠ” кІ¬кі н•ң frameworkмқё <strong>Entropy-aware Span-Constrained Optimal Transport(E-SCOT)</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. dense optimizationмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ quadratic costлҘј л°ңмғқмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кё°мЎҙ OT м ‘к·јкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, E-SCOTлҠ” span-anchored lexical alignmentлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ м„ нҳ• мӢңк°„м—җ deterministicн•ҳкі  locality-preservingн•ң couplingмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” RГ©nyi-entropy adaptive reweightingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҙ significant uncertainty-profile gapмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” informative positionм—җ distillation budgetмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м§‘мӨ‘мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ E-SCOTк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң model family м „л°ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, нҠ№нһҲ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ low-overlap мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ңлҸ„ negative transferлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м ңкұ°н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61857","en":"Efficient Training-Free Multi-Token Prediction via Embedding-Space Probing","ko":"Embedding-Space Probingмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё Training-Free Multi-Token Prediction","authors":"Raghavv Goel, Mukul Gagrani, Mingu Lee, Christopher Lott","pos":"#1910","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mKj4fO0BU4","abs":"Large Language Models (LLMs) possess latent multi-token prediction (MTP) capabilities despite being trained only for next-token generation. We introduce a simple and training-free MTP method that probes an LLM using on-the-fly mask tokens derived from its embedding space, enabling parallel future-token prediction without modifying weights or relying on draft models. We construct a speculative token tree by sampling Top-$K$ candidates from mask-token logits and apply a lightweight pruning rule to retain high-probability continuations. During generation, predicted tokens are verified in parallel, yielding lossless decoding while significantly reducing the number of model calls and increasing token throughput. Our probing-based MTP method consistently outperforms existing training-free baselines, improving acceptance length by approximately $12\\\\%$ on LLaMA3 and $8$вҖ“$12\\\\%$ on Qwen3, and increasing throughput by up to $15$вҖ“$19\\\\%$. We further provide theoretical analysis and empirical evidence showing that decoder layers naturally align mask-token representations with next-token states, enabling accurate multi-step predictions without retraining or auxiliary models.","absKo":"Large Language Models(LLMs)мқҖ next-token generationл§ҢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗҳм—ҲмқҢм—җлҸ„ latent multi-token prediction(MTP) capabilityлҘј ліҙмң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” embedding spaceм—җм„ң мң лҸ„н•ң on-the-fly mask tokenмңјлЎң LLMмқ„ probeн•ҳлҠ” к°„лӢЁн•ҳкі  training-freeн•ң MTP methodлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ weightлҘј мҲҳм •н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ draft modelм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  future tokenмқ„ лі‘л ¬лЎң мҳҲмёЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” mask-token logitм—җм„ң Top-$K$ candidateлҘј мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ҙ speculative token treeлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , лҶ’мқҖ нҷ•лҘ мқҳ continuationмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ lightweight pruning ruleмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. generation лҸҷм•Ҳ мҳҲмёЎлҗң tokenмқҖ лі‘л ¬лЎң кІҖмҰқлҗҳм–ҙ, model call мҲҳлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ң token throughputмқ„ мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮӨлҠ” lossless decodingмқ„ мқҙлҒҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ probing-based MTP methodлҠ” кё°мЎҙ training-free baselineліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳл©°, LLaMA3м—җм„ң acceptance lengthлҘј м•Ҫ $12\\\\%$ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  Qwen3м—җм„ңлҠ” $8$вҖ“$12\\\\%$ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, throughputмқ„ мөңлҢҖ $15$вҖ“$19\\\\%$к№Ңм§Җ лҶ’мқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң decoder layerк°Җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ mask-token representationмқ„ next-token stateм—җ м •л ¬мӢңмјң, мһ¬н•ҷмҠөмқҙлӮҳ auxiliary model м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ м •нҷ•н•ң multi-step predictionмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қкіј мӢӨмҰқм Ғ мҰқкұ°лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64834","en":"Disentangling meaning from language in LLM-based machine translation","ko":"LLM кё°л°ҳ кё°кі„ лІҲм—ӯм—җм„ң м–ём–ҙлЎңл¶Җн„° мқҳлҜё л¶„лҰ¬","authors":"ThГ©o Lasnier, Armel Randy Zebaze, DjamГ© Seddah, Rachel Bawden, BenoГ®t Sagot","pos":"#2011","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=JKSDWukEgN","abs":"<p>Mechanistic Interpretability (MI) seeks to explain how neural networks implement their capabilities, but the scale of Large Language Models (LLMs) has limited prior MI work in Machine Translation (MT) to word-level analyses. We study sentence-level MT from a mechanistic perspective by analyzing attention heads to understand how LLMs internally encode and distribute translation functions. We decompose MT into two subtasks: producing text in the target language (i.e. target language identification) and preserving the input sentenceвҖҷs meaning (i.e. sentence equivalence). Across three families of open-source models and 20 translation directions, we find that distinct, sparse sets of attention heads specialize in each subtask. Based on this insight, we construct subtask-specific steering vectors and show that modifying just 1% of the relevant heads enables instruction-free MT performance comparable to instruction-based prompting, while ablating these heads selectively disrupts their corresponding translation functions.</p>","absKo":"<p>Mechanistic Interpretability (MI)лҠ” neural networkк°Җ мһҗмӢ мқҳ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ кө¬нҳ„н•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳкі мһҗ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, Large Language Models (LLMs)мқҳ к·ңлӘЁ л•Ңл¬ём—җ мқҙм „мқҳ MT л¶„м•ј MI м—°кө¬лҠ” лӢЁм–ҙ мҲҳмӨҖ л¶„м„қм—җ мЈјлЎң лЁёл¬јл ҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” attention headлҘј л¶„м„қн•ҳм—¬ LLMмқҙ лІҲм—ӯ кё°лҠҘмқ„ лӮҙл¶Җм ҒмңјлЎң м–ҙл–»кІҢ мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳкі  л¶„л°°н•ҳлҠ”м§Җ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” кҙҖм җм—җм„ң sentence-level MTлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MTлҘј л‘җ к°ңмқҳ н•ҳмң„ кіјм ңлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, target languageлЎң н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғ(i.e. target language identification)кіј мһ…л Ҙ л¬ёмһҘмқҳ мқҳлҜёлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” кІғ(i.e. sentence equivalence)мқҙлӢӨ. м„ё к°ңмқҳ open-source model familyмҷҖ 20к°ңмқҳ translation direction м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё нқ¬мҶҢн•ң attention head м§‘н•©мқҙ к°Ғ н•ҳмң„ кіјм ңм—җ нҠ№нҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң н•ҳмң„ кіјм ңлі„ steering vectorлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , кҙҖл Ё headмқҳ лӢЁ 1%л§Ң мҲҳм •н•ҙлҸ„ instruction-based promptingм—җ н•„м Ғн•ҳлҠ” instruction-free MT м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмҳҖмңјл©°, л°ҳлҢҖлЎң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң headлҘј ablationн•ҳл©ҙ н•ҙлӢ№ translation functionмқҙ м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң мҶҗмғҒлҗЁмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63770","en":"AlienLM: Alienization of Language for API-Boundary Privacy in Black-Box LLMs","ko":"AlienLM: Black-Box LLMм—җм„ң API кІҪкі„ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢңлҘј мң„н•ң м–ём–ҙмқҳ мҷёкі„нҷ”","authors":"Jaehee Kim, Pilsung Kang","pos":"#2214","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=TvskDAb5Uc","abs":"<p>Modern LLMs are increasingly accessed via black-box APIs, requiring users to transmit sensitive prompts, outputs, and fine-tuning data to external providers, creating a critical privacy risk at the API boundary. We introduce AlienLM, a deployable API-only privacy layer that protects text by translating it into an Alien Language via a vocabulary-scale bijection, enabling lossless recovery on the client side. Using only standard fine-tuning APIs, Alien Adaptation Training (AAT) adapts target models to operate directly on alienized inputs. Across four LLM backbones and seven benchmarks, AlienLM retains over 81% of plaintext-oracle performance on average, substantially outperforming random-bijection and character-level baselines. Under adversaries with access to model weights, corpus statistics, and learning-based inverse translation, recovery attacks reconstruct fewer than 0.22% of alienized tokens. Our results demonstrate a practical pathway for privacy-preserving LLM deployment under API-only access, substantially reducing plaintext exposure while maintaining task performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖмқҳ LLMмқҖ м җм җ лҚ” black-box APIлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м ‘к·јлҗҳл©°, мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлҠ” лҜјк°җн•ң prompt, output, fine-tuning dataлҘј мҷёл¶Җ м ңкіөмһҗм—җкІҢ м „мҶЎн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” API кІҪкі„м—җм„ң мӨ‘лҢҖн•ң н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң мң„н—ҳмқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” vocabulary-scale bijectionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлҘј Alien LanguageлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҘј ліҙнҳён•ҳкі , нҒҙлқјмқҙм–ёнҠё мёЎм—җм„ң lossless recoveryлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” л°°нҸ¬ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң API-only privacy layerмқё AlienLMмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ fine-tuning APIл§Ңмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, Alien Adaptation Training (AAT)мқҖ лҢҖмғҒ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ alienized inputмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. л„Ө к°ңмқҳ LLM backboneкіј мқјкіұ к°ңмқҳ benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң AlienLMмқҖ нҸүк· м ҒмңјлЎң plaintext-oracle м„ұлҠҘмқҳ 81% мқҙмғҒмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©°, random-bijection л°Ҹ character-level baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. model weight, corpus statistics, learning-based inverse translationм—җ м ‘к·јн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” adversary н•ҳм—җм„ң, recovery attackмқҖ alienized tokenмқҳ 0.22% лҜёл§Ңл§Ңмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” API-only access н•ҳм—җм„ң н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢңлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” LLM л°°нҸ¬лҘј мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ кІҪлЎңлҘј ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, task performanceлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң plaintext exposureлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64537","en":"Interpreting and Steering State-Space Models via Activation Subspace Bottlenecks","ko":"нҷңм„ұнҷ” л¶Җл¶„кіөк°„ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ нҶөн•ң мғҒнғң кіөк°„ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ н•ҙм„қ л°Ҹ мЎ°мў…","authors":"Vamshi Sunku Mohan, Kaustubh Gupta, Aneesha Das, Chandan Singh","pos":"#2705","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=MX9iN1QI3Y","abs":"<p>State-space models (SSMs) have emerged as an efficient strategy for building powerful language models, avoiding the quadratic complexity of computing attention in transformers. Despite their promise, the interpretability and steerability of modern SSMs remain relatively underexplored. We take a major step in this direction by identifying <em>activation subspace bottlenecks</em> in the Mamba family of SSM models using tools from mechanistic interpretability. We then introduce a test-time steering intervention that simply multiplies the activations of the identified bottlenecks by a scalar. Across 5 SSMs and 6 diverse benchmarks, this intervention improves performance by an average of 8.27%, without requiring any task-specific tuning. Finally, we validate that the identified bottlenecks are indeed hindering performance by modifying them to yield an architecture we call Stable-Mamba, which achieves long-context performance gains when retrained from scratch.</p>","absKo":"<p>State-space model (SSM)мқҖ transformerм—җм„ң attentionмқ„ кі„мӮ°н•  л•Ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” quadratic complexityлҘј н”јн•ҳл©ҙм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң language modelмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё м „лһөмңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°ҖлҠҘм„ұм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , нҳ„лҢҖ SSMмқҳ н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұкіј steerabilityлҠ” мғҒлҢҖм ҒмңјлЎң м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” mechanistic interpretability лҸ„кө¬лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ Mamba кі„м—ҙ SSM modelм—җм„ң <em>activation subspace bottleneck</em>мқ„ мӢқлі„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ л°©н–ҘмңјлЎңмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈ¬лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ мӢқлі„лҗң bottleneckмқҳ activationм—җ scalarлҘј кіұн•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ң test-time steering interventionмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. 5к°ңмқҳ SSMкіј 6к°ңмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, мқҙ interventionмқҖ task-specific tuning м—Ҷмқҙ нҸүк·  8.27%мқҳ м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мӢқлі„лҗң bottleneckмқҙ мӢӨм ңлЎң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м Җн•ҙн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„, мқҙлҘј мҲҳм •н•ҳм—¬ Stable-Mambaлқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” architectureлҘј л§Ңл“Өкі  мІҳмқҢл¶Җн„° лӢӨмӢң н•ҷмҠөн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң long-context м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м–»лҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63468","en":"Annotations Mitigate Post-Training Mode Collapse","ko":"мЈјм„қмқҖ мӮ¬нӣ„ н•ҷмҠө лӘЁл“ң л¶•кҙҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Jacob Mitchell Springer, Madhu Advani, Lukas Aichberger, Arwen Bradley, Eran Malach, Omid Saremi, Sinead Williamson, Preetum Nakkiran, Etai Littwin, Aditi Raghunathan","pos":"#3610","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Wtjwjn1uak","abs":"<p>Post-training (via supervised fine-tuning) improves instruction-following, but often induces semantic mode collapse by biasing models toward low-entropy fine-tuning data at the expense of the high-entropy pre-training distribution. Crucially, we find this trade-off worsens with scale. To close this semantic diversity gap, we propose annotation-anchored training, a principled method that enables models to adopt the preference-following behaviors of post-training without sacrificing the inherent diversity of pre-training. Our approach is simple: we pre-train on documents paired with semantic annotations, inducing a rich annotation distribution that reflects the full breadth of pre-training data, and we preserve this distribution during post-training. This lets us sample diverse annotations at inference time and use them as anchors to guide generation, effectively transferring pre-training's semantic richness into post-trained models. We find that models trained with annotation-anchored training can attain 6Г— less diversity collapse than models trained with SFT, and improve with scale.</p>","absKo":"<p>Post-training(мҰү, supervised fine-tuning)мқҖ instruction-followingмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мў…мў… high-entropy pre-training distributionмқ„ нқ¬мғқн•ҳкі  low-entropy fine-tuning data мӘҪмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ нҺён–ҘмӢңмјң semantic mode collapseлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м җмқҖ, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң trade-offк°Җ scaleмқҙ м»Өм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ лҚ” м•…нҷ”лҗңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң semantic diversity gapмқ„ н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” annotation-anchored trainingмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” post-trainingмқҳ preference-following behaviorлҘј pre-training кі мң мқҳ лӢӨм–‘м„ұмқ„ нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ мұ„нғқн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ к°„лӢЁн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” semantic annotationмқҙ л¶ҷмқҖ л¬ём„ңлЎң pre-trainн•ҳм—¬ pre-training dataмқҳ м „ лІ”мң„лҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң annotation distributionмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳкі , post-training лҸҷм•Ҳ мқҙ л¶„нҸ¬лҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙл ҮкІҢ н•ҳл©ҙ inference timeм—җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң annotationмқ„ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј anchorлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ generationмқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, кІ°кіјм ҒмңјлЎң pre-trainingмқҳ semantic richnessлҘј post-trained modelлЎң нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м „лӢ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. Annotation-anchored trainingмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ SFTлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң лӘЁлҚёліҙлӢӨ diversity collapseк°Җ 6л°° м Ғкі , scaleмқҙ м»Өм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ н–ҘмғҒлҗңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63410","en":"Rethinking Personalization in Large Language Models at the Token Level","ko":"нҶ нҒ° мҲҳмӨҖм—җм„ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ к°ңмқёнҷ” мһ¬кі ","authors":"Chenheng Zhang, Yijun Lu, Lizhe Fang, Chunyuan Zheng, Jiajun Chai, Xiaohan Wang, Guojun Yin, Wei Lin, Yisen Wang, Zhouchen Lin","pos":"#3611","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XOEVxte7Nn","abs":"<p>With large language models (LLMs) now performing strongly across diverse tasks, there is growing demand for them to personalize outputs for individual users. Personalization is typically framed as an additional layer on top of a base NLP task, requiring model responses to meet user-specific needs while still accomplishing the underlying task. From a token-level perspective, different tokens in a response contribute to personalization to varying degrees. Tokens with higher personalization relevance should therefore receive greater emphasis when developing personalized LLMs. However, accurately estimating such personalization degrees remains challenging. To address this challenge, we propose PerContrast, a self-contrast method that estimates each output tokenвҖҷs dependence on user-specific information through causal intervention. Building on this mechanism, we develop the PerCE loss, which adaptively upweights tokens with higher estimated personalization degrees during training via a bootstrap procedure, enabling the model to alternate between estimating and optimizing these tokens. Experiments on multiple LLMs demonstrate that PerCE substantially improves personalization performance with minimal additional cost, achieving average gains of over 10\\% and up to 68.04\\% on the LongLaMP dataset, along with strong cross-task and cross-scenario transferability. These results highlight the importance of token-level personalization modeling and establish token-aware training as a simple yet effective paradigm for advancing personalized LLMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language models (LLMs)к°Җ мқҙм ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң мһ‘м—…м—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©ҙм„ң, к°ңлі„ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗм—җ л§һм¶° м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ к°ңмқёнҷ”н•ҳл ӨлҠ” мҡ”кө¬к°Җ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. PersonalizationмқҖ ліҙнҶө base NLP task мң„м—җ м¶”к°ҖлҗҳлҠ” лҳҗ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ кі„мёөмңјлЎң к°„мЈјлҗҳл©°, model responseк°Җ underlying taskлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлі„ мҡ”кө¬лҘј м¶©мЎұн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. token-level кҙҖм җм—җм„ң ліҙл©ҙ, responseмқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё tokenмқҖ personalizationм—җ кё°м—¬н•ҳлҠ” м •лҸ„к°Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘҙлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң personalization relevanceк°Җ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ tokenмқҖ personalized LLMмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•  л•Ң лҚ” нҒ° л№„мӨ‘мқ„ л°ӣм•„м•ј н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң personalization degreeлҘј м •нҷ•нһҲ м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” causal interventionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ к°Ғ output tokenмқҙ user-specific informationм—җ м–јл§ҲлӮҳ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” self-contrast methodмқё PerContrastлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” bootstrap procedureлҘј нҶөн•ҙ training мӨ‘ м¶”м •лҗң personalization degreeк°Җ лҶ’мқҖ tokenмқҳ к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң лҶ’мқҙлҠ” PerCE lossлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬, modelмқҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң tokenмқ„ м¶”м •н•ҳкі  мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кіјм •мқ„ лІҲк°Ҳм•„ мҲҳн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ LLMм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PerCEк°Җ м¶”к°Җ л№„мҡ©мқ„ кұ°мқҳ лҠҳлҰ¬м§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң personalization м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңмјң, LongLaMP datasetм—җм„ң нҸүк·  10\\%лҘј л„ҳлҠ” н–ҘмғҒкіј мөңлҢҖ 68.04\\%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳмңјл©°, task к°„ л°Ҹ scenario к°„ м „мқҙм„ұлҸ„ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” token-level personalization modelingмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ л¶Җк°Ғн•ҳкі , token-aware trainingмқҙ personalized LLMмқ„ л°ңм „мӢңнӮӨлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66186","en":"NExT-Guard: Training-Free Streaming Safeguard without Token-Level Labels","ko":"NExT-Guard: нҶ нҒ° мҲҳмӨҖ л Ҳмқҙлё” м—ҶлҠ” нӣҲл Ё л¶Ҳн•„мҡ” мҠӨнҠёлҰ¬л°Қ м•Ҳм „мһҘм№ҳ","authors":"Junfeng Fang, Nachuan Chen, Houcheng Jiang, Dan Zhang, Xiangnan He, Tat-Seng Chua, Xiang Wang","pos":"#4013","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5ysobWbWzp","abs":"<p>Large language models are increasingly deployed in streaming scenarios, rendering conventional post-hoc safeguards ineffective as they fail to interdict unsafe content in real-time. While streaming safeguards based on token-level supervised training could address this, they necessitate expensive annotations and suffer from severe overfitting. In this work, we challenge the paradigm that streaming safety must rely on token-level supervised training. Instead, it is an inherent capability of well-trained post-hoc safeguards, as they already encode token-level risk signals in hidden representations. Hence, we introduce NExT-Guard, a training-free framework that achieves streaming safeguards by monitoring interpretable latent features from Sparse Autoencoders (SAEs). It uses pretrained SAEs from publicly available base LLMs, enabling flexible, low-cost deployment without token-level supervision. Experimental results show that NExT-Guard outperforms both post-hoc and streaming safeguards based on supervised training, with superior robustness across models, SAE variants, and risk scenarios. These results make NExT-Guard a universal and scalable paradigm for real-time safety, accelerating the practical deployment of streaming safeguards.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ м җм җ streaming scenarioм—җ л°°м№ҳлҗҳкі  мһҲмңјл©°, кё°мЎҙмқҳ post-hoc safeguardлҠ” мң н•ҙ мҪҳн…җмё лҘј мӢӨмӢңк°„мңјлЎң м°ЁлӢЁн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҜҖлЎң нҡЁкіјк°Җ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. token-level supervised trainingм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң streaming safeguardлҠ” мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° annotationмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳкі  мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң overfittingмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” streaming safetyк°Җ token-level supervised trainingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨлҠ” нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„м—җ лҸ„м „н•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖмӢ , мһҳ н•ҷмҠөлҗң post-hoc safeguard мһҗмІҙм—җ мқҙлҜё hidden representationм—җ token-level risk signalмқҙ мқёмҪ”л”©лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмңјлҜҖлЎң, мқҙлҠ” ліём§Ҳм Ғ лҠҘл ҘмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ л”°лқј мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Sparse Autoencoders(SAEs)мқҳ н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң latent featureлҘј лӘЁлӢҲн„°л§Ғн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ streaming safeguardлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳлҠ” training-free framework NExT-GuardлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ кіөк°ңм ҒмңјлЎң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•ң base LLMмқҳ pretrained SAEлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, token-level supervision м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ мң м—°н•ҳкі  м Җл№„мҡ©мңјлЎң л°°нҸ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј NExT-GuardлҠ” supervised training кё°л°ҳмқҳ post-hoc safeguardмҷҖ streaming safeguard лӘЁл‘җлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, model, SAE variant, risk scenario м „л°ҳм—җм„ң лҚ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң robustnessлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” NExT-GuardлҘј мӢӨмӢңк°„ м•Ҳм „м„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң ліҙнҺём Ғмқҙкі  нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң л§Ңл“Өл©°, streaming safeguardмқҳ мӢӨм ң л°°нҸ¬лҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60913","en":"Optimizing KV Cache Eviction from an Output Perturbation Perspective","ko":"Output Perturbation кҙҖм җм—җм„ң KV Cache Eviction мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Yuan Feng, Junlin Lv, Haoyu Guo, Yukun Cao, Xike Xie, S Kevin Zhou","pos":"#406","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vMwlcLyI4b","abs":"<p>Large language models have revolutionized natural language processing but face significant challenges of high storage and runtime costs, due to the transformer architecture's reliance on self-attention, particularly the large KV cache for long-sequence inference.  Recent efforts to reduce KV cache size by pruning less critical entries based on attention weights remain empirical and lack formal grounding. This paper presents a formal study on identifying critical KV cache entries by analyzing attention output perturbation. Our analysis reveals that, beyond attention weights, the value states within KV entries and pretrained parameter matrices are also crucial.  Based on this, we propose a perturbation-constrained selection algorithm that optimizes the worst-case output perturbation to identify critical entries. We demonstrate that our algorithm is a universal, plug-and-play enhancement that incurs negligible computational overhead. When integrated with three state-of-the-art cache eviction methods on three distinct LLMs, our algorithm significantly reduces the compression loss by more than \\textit{half} on average across 29 datasets from the Ruler and LongBench benchmarks. Further perturbation analysis, at both the head and layer levels, confirms the principles underlying our effectiveness. This work offers a new, formally grounded perspective to  cache eviction , opening promising avenues for future research.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language modelsлҠ” мһҗм—°м–ҙ мІҳлҰ¬лҘј нҳҒмӢ н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, transformer м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳк°Җ self-attentionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©° нҠ№нһҲ кёҙ мӢңнҖҖмҠӨ м¶”лЎ м—җм„ң нҒ° KV cacheк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ лҶ’мқҖ м ҖмһҘ л°Ҹ лҹ°нғҖмһ„ л№„мҡ©мқҙлқјлҠ” мӨ‘лҢҖн•ң лҸ„м „м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ҙ мһҲлӢӨ. attention weightлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң лҚң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң н•ӯлӘ©мқ„ pruningн•ҳм—¬ KV cache нҒ¬кё°лҘј мӨ„мқҙл ӨлҠ” мөңк·ј мӢңлҸ„л“ӨмқҖ кІҪн—ҳм Ғ мҲҳмӨҖм—җ лЁёл¬јлҹ¬ мһҲмңјл©° м •мӢқм Ғмқё к·јкұ°к°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ attention output perturbation л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң KV cache н•ӯлӘ©мқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҳ•мӢқм Ғ м—°кө¬лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ attention weightлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ, KV н•ӯлӘ© лӮҙмқҳ value stateмҷҖ pretrained parameter matrix лҳҗн•ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңм•…мқҳ кІҪмҡ° output perturbationмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң н•ӯлӘ©мқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” perturbation-constrained selection algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңк°Җ кұ°мқҳ м—ҶлҠ” лІ”мҡ© plug-and-play enhancementмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м„ё к°ңмқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё LLMм—җ кұёміҗ м„ё к°Җм§Җ state-of-the-art cache eviction л°©лІ•кіј нҶөн•©н–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ RulerмҷҖ LongBench benchmarkмқҳ 29к°ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң нҸүк· м ҒмңјлЎң compression lossлҘј м Ҳл°ҳ мқҙмғҒ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. head л°Ҹ layer мҲҳмӨҖ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң м¶”к°Җ perturbation л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҡЁкіјмқҳ к·јк°„мқҙ лҗҳлҠ” мӣҗлҰ¬лҘј нҷ•мқён•ҙ мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” cache evictionм—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҲлЎӯкі  нҳ•мӢқм ҒмңјлЎң к·јкұ° мһҲлҠ” кҙҖм җмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬лҘј мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң л°©н–Ҙмқ„ м—°лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60580","en":"Efficient-DLM: From Autoregressive to Diffusion Language Models, and Beyond in Speed","ko":"Efficient-DLM: мһҗкё°нҡҢк·Җм—җм„ң Diffusion Language ModelлЎң, к·ёлҰ¬кі  лҚ” л№ лҘҙкІҢ","authors":"Yonggan Fu, Lexington Whalen, Zhifan Ye, Xin Dong, Shizhe Diao, Jingyu Liu, CHENGYUE WU, Hao Zhang, Enze Xie, Song Han, Maksim Khadkevich, Jan Kautz, Yingyan (Celine) Lin, Pavlo Molchanov","pos":"#107","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ynRnOqI2W8","abs":"Diffusion language models (dLMs) have emerged as a promising paradigm enabling parallel generation, but their learning efficiency lags behind that of autoregressive (AR) language models when trained from scratch. To this end, we study AR-to-dLM conversion, which transforms pretrained AR models into efficient dLMs that excel in speed while preserving AR modelsвҖҷ task accuracy. We achieve this by identifying limitations in the attention patterns and objectives of existing AR-to-dLM methods and then proposing methodologies and actionable insights for scalable AR-to-dLM conversion. Specifically, we first systematically compare different attention patterns and find that maintaining pretrained AR weight distributions is key to effective AR-to-dLM conversion. Accordingly, we introduce a continuous pretraining scheme with a block-wise attention pattern. We find that, in addition to block-wise attentionвҖҷs known benefit of enabling KV caching, its block-wise causality better preserves pretrained AR modelsвҖҷ weight distributions, leading to a winвҖ“win in accuracy and efficiency. Second, to mitigate the trainingвҖ“test gap in mask token distributions (uniform vs. highly left-to-right), we propose a position-dependent token masking strategy that assigns higher masking probabilities to later tokens during training to better mimic test-time behavior. These studies lead to the Efficient-DLM model family, which outperforms state-of-the-art AR models and dLMs in accuracyвҖ“throughput trade-offs; for example, our Efficient-DLM 8B achieves +5.4\\%/+2.7\\% higher accuracy with 4.5$\\times$/2.7$\\times$ higher throughput compared to Dream 7B and Qwen3 4B, respectively.","absKo":"Diffusion language models (dLMs)лҠ” лі‘л ¬ мғқм„ұмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мң л§қн•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, scratchм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөн•  л•Ңмқҳ learning efficiencyлҠ” autoregressive (AR) language modelsм—җ л№„н•ҙ л’ӨмІҳм§‘лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” AR-to-dLM conversionмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” pretrained AR modelsлҘј мҶҚлҸ„лҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ AR modelsмқҳ task accuracyлҠ” ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё dLMsлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ AR-to-dLM methodsмқҳ attention patternкіј objectiveм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” н•ңкі„лҘј мӢқлі„н•ң л’Ө, scalable AR-to-dLM conversionмқ„ мң„н•ң л°©лІ•лЎ кіј мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, лЁјм Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё attention patternмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л№„көҗн•ҳм—¬ pretrained AR weight distributionмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё AR-to-dLM conversionмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мһ„мқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ л”°лқј мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” block-wise attention patternмқ„ к°–лҠ” continuous pretraining schemeмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. block-wise attentionмқҳ мһҳ м•Ңл Өм§„ мһҘм җмқё KV caching к°ҖлҠҘм„ұм—җ лҚ”н•ҙ, block-wise causalityк°Җ pretrained AR modelsмқҳ weight distributionмқ„ лҚ” мһҳ ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ нҷ•мқён–Ҳмңјл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј accuracyмҷҖ efficiency лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң win-winмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, mask token distributionмқҳ training-test gap(uniform vs. highly left-to-right)мқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ лҚ” л’ӨмӘҪ tokenм—җ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ masking probabilityлҘј н• лӢ№н•ҳм—¬ test-time behaviorлҘј лҚ” мһҳ лӘЁмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” position-dependent token masking strategyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м—°кө¬лҘј нҶөн•ҙ Efficient-DLM model familyк°Җ нғ„мғқн–Ҳмңјл©°, accuracy-throughput trade-offм—җм„ң state-of-the-art AR modelsмҷҖ dLMsлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, Efficient-DLM 8BлҠ” Dream 7B л°Ҹ Qwen3 4BмҷҖ л№„көҗн•ҙ к°Ғк°Ғ 4.5$\\times$/2.7$\\times$ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ throughputм—җм„ң +5.4\\%/+2.7\\% лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ accuracyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"66650","en":"When Diffusion Language Models Hesitate: Detecting and Correcting Visual Hallucinations via Confidence Fluctuation","ko":"Diffusion м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мЈјм Җн•  л•Ң: мӢ лў°лҸ„ ліҖлҸҷмқ„ нҶөн•ң мӢңк°Ғ нҷҳк°Ғ нғҗм§Җ л°Ҹ көҗм •","authors":"Wenzheng Song, Pei Chen, Yichen Tan, Zejian Li, Lingyun Sun","pos":"#1207","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1knvdLwxQq","abs":"<p>Multi-modal Diffusion Language Models (MDLMs) have emerged as a powerful alternative to autoregressive models in vision-language understanding, offering advantages in bidirectional context modeling and parallel decoding. However, existing MDLMs suffer from severe visual hallucinations due to the static nature of visual perception. Unlike autoregressive models, MDLMs lack the sequential dependency required to dynamically interact with visual content. Therefore, MDLMs rely on fixed visual features encoded at initialization, causing the denoising process to drift toward language priors and lose its anchor to visual evidence. In this paper, we propose VGR (Visual-Guided Refinement), a framework that enables MDLMs to revisit visual details by exploiting diffusion dynamics. Our key insight is that the temporal trajectory of confidence during denoising reveals intrinsic uncertainty: while grounded tokens converge smoothly, hallucinated ones exhibit pronounced confidence fluctuation. VGR utilizes this fluctuation signal to detect uncertain spans and corrects them through targeted visual evidence extraction and in-place remasking. Extensive experiments on image captioning and hallucination evaluation benchmarks demonstrate that our method significantly reduces hallucinations and recalls more details, achieving state-of-the-art performance among MDLMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multi-modal Diffusion Language Model(MDLM)мқҖ vision-language understandingм—җм„ң autoregressive modelмқҳ к°•л Ҙн•ң лҢҖм•ҲмңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳмңјл©°, bidirectional context modelingкіј parallel decodingм—җм„ң мқҙм җмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ MDLMмқҖ visual perceptionмқҳ м •м Ғмқё нҠ№м„ұ л•Ңл¬ём—җ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң visual hallucinationмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. autoregressive modelкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, MDLMмқҖ visual contentмҷҖ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң sequential dependencyк°Җ м—ҶлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң MDLMмқҖ мҙҲкё°нҷ” мӢң мқёмҪ”л”©лҗң кі м •лҗң visual featureм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкІҢ лҗҳл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ denoising processк°Җ language prior мӘҪмңјлЎң driftн•ҳкі  visual evidenceм—җ лҢҖн•ң anchorлҘј мһғкІҢ лҗңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” diffusion dynamicsлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ MDLMмқҙ visual detailмқ„ лӢӨмӢң м°ёмЎ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” VGR(Visual-Guided Refinement) frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ нҶөм°°мқҖ denoising лҸҷм•Ҳмқҳ confidence temporal trajectoryк°Җ ліём§Ҳм Ғ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. grounded tokenмқҖ л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ мҲҳл ҙн•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, hallucinated tokenмқҖ лҡңл ·н•ң confidence fluctuationмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. VGRмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң fluctuation signalмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨн•ң spanмқ„ нғҗм§Җн•ҳкі , targeted visual evidence extractionкіј in-place remaskingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј ліҙм •н•ңлӢӨ. image captioningкіј hallucination evaluation benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ hallucinationмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқҙкі  лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ detailмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•ҳл©°, MDLM мӨ‘ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62405","en":"dLLM-Cache: Accelerating Diffusion Large Language Models with Adaptive Caching","ko":"dLLM-Cache: м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мәҗмӢұмқ„ нҶөн•ң Diffusion Large Language Models к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”","authors":"Zhiyuan Liu, Yicun Yang, Yaojie Zhang, Junjie Chen, Chang Zou, Qingyan Wei, Shaobo Wang, Yichen Zhu, Linfeng Zhang","pos":"#1211","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=guLrgDb2jB","abs":"Autoregressive Models (ARMs) have long dominated the landscape of Large Language Models. Recently, a new paradigm has emerged in the form of diffusion-based Large Language Models (dLLMs), which generate text by iteratively denoising masked segments. This approach has shown significant advantages and potential. However, dLLMs suffer from high inference latency. Traditional ARM acceleration techniques, such as Key-Value caching, are incompatible with dLLMs due to their bidirectional attention mechanism. To address this specific challenge, our work begins with a key observation that dLLM inference involves a static prompt and a partially dynamic response, where most tokens remain stable across adjacent denoising steps. Based on this, we propose dLLM-Cache, a training-free adaptive caching framework that combines long-interval prompt caching with partial response updates guided by feature similarity. This design enables efficient reuse of intermediate computations without compromising model performance. Extensive experiments on representative dLLMs, including LLaDA 8B and Dream 7B, show that dLLM-Cache achieves up to 9.1$\\times$ speedup over standard inference without compromising output quality. Notably, our method brings dLLM inference latency close to that of ARMs under many settings. Codes are provided in the supplementary material and will be released publicly on GitHub.","absKo":"Autoregressive Models (ARMs)лҠ” мҳӨлһ«лҸҷм•Ҳ Large Language Modelsмқҳ м§Җнҳ•мқ„ м§Җл°°н•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мөңк·јм—җлҠ” diffusion-based Large Language Models (dLLMs)лқјлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙ л“ұмһҘн–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” masked segmentлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң denoiseн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң мһҘм җкіј к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ dLLMsлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ inference latencyлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. Key-Value cachingкіј к°ҷмқҖ м „нҶөм Ғмқё ARM к°ҖмҶҚ кё°лІ•мқҖ м–‘л°©н–Ҙ attention mechanism л•Ңл¬ём—җ dLLMsмҷҖ нҳёнҷҳлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кө¬мІҙм Ғ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м—°кө¬лҠ” dLLM inferenceк°Җ static promptмҷҖ л¶Җл¶„м ҒмңјлЎң dynamicн•ң responseлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗҳл©°, мқём ‘н•ң denoising step мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ tokenмқҙ м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң мң м§ҖлҗңлӢӨлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ кҙҖм°°м—җм„ң м¶ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” feature similarityм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м•ҲлӮҙлҗҳлҠ” л¶Җл¶„ response updateмҷҖ кёҙ к°„кІ© prompt cachingмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң training-free adaptive caching frameworkмқё dLLM-CacheлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” model performanceлҘј м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮӨм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң intermediate computationмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. LLaDA 8BмҷҖ Dream 7BлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё dLLMм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң, dLLM-CacheлҠ” output qualityлҘј мҶҗмғҒмӢңнӮӨм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң standard inference лҢҖл№„ мөңлҢҖ 9.1$\\times$мқҳ speedupмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ л§ҺмқҖ settingм—җм„ң dLLM inference latencyлҘј ARMм—җ к·јм ‘н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” supplementary materialм—җ м ңкіөлҗҳл©° GitHubм—җ кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ."},{"id":"63803","en":"Towards Atoms of Large Language Models","ko":"лҢҖнҳ• м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мӣҗмһҗ лӢЁмң„лҘј н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Chenhui Hu, Pengfei Cao, Yubo Chen, Kang Liu, Jun Zhao","pos":"#1306","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=TaDbT9pZr7","abs":"The fundamental representational units (FRUs) of large language models (LLMs) remain undefined, limiting further understanding of their underlying mechanisms. In this paper, we introduce ***Atom Theory*** to systematically define, evaluate, and identify such FRUs, which we term atoms. Building on the atomic inner product (AIP), a non-Euclidean metric that captures the underlying geometry of LLM representations, we formally define atoms and propose two key criteria for ideal atoms: faithfulness ( $ R^2 $ ) and stability ( $ q^{\\star} $ ). We further prove that atoms are identifiable under threshold-activated sparse autoencoders (TSAEs). Empirically, we uncover a pervasive representation shift in LLMs and demonstrate that the AIP corrects this shift to capture the underlying representational geometry, thereby grounding Atom Theory. We find that two widely used units, neurons and features, fail to qualify as ideal atoms: neurons are faithful ( $ R^2=1 $ ) but unstable ( $ q^{\\star}=0.5 $% ), while features are more stable ( $ q^{\\star}=68.2 $% ) but unfaithful ( $ R^2=48.8 $% ). To find atoms of LLMs, leveraging atom identifiability under TSAEs, we show via large-scale experiments that reliable atom identification occurs only when the TSAE capacity matches the data scale. Guided by this insight, we identify FRUs with near-perfect faithfulness ( $ R^2=99.9 $% ) and stability ( $ q^{\\star}=99.8 $% ) across layers of Gemma2-2B, Gemma2-9B, and Llama3.1-8B, satisfying the criteria of ideal atoms statistically. Further analysis confirms that these atoms align with theoretical expectations and exhibit substantially higher monosemanticity. Overall, we propose and validate Atom Theory as a foundation for understanding the internal representations of LLMs.","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(LLMs)мқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё representational unit(FRU)мқҖ м•„м§Ғ м •мқҳлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•„, к·ё лӮҙл¶Җ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳм—җ лҢҖн•ң м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё мқҙн•ҙлҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң FRUлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң м •мқҳн•ҳкі  нҸүк°Җн•ҳл©° мӢқлі„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ ***Atom Theory***лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј atomмқҙлқј л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. LLM representationмқҳ к·јм Җ кё°н•ҳлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” л№„мң нҒҙлҰ¬л“ң metricмқё atomic inner product(AIP)лҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” atomмқ„ нҳ•мӢқм ҒмңјлЎң м •мқҳн•ҳкі  мқҙмғҒм Ғмқё atomмқ„ мң„н•ң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ кё°мӨҖмқё faithfulness( $ R^2 $ )мҷҖ stability( $ q^{\\star} $ )лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң threshold-activated sparse autoencoder(TSAE) н•ҳм—җм„ң atomмқҙ мӢқлі„ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLM м „л°ҳм—җ нҚјм ё мһҲлҠ” representation shiftлҘј л°ңкІ¬н•ҳкі , AIPк°Җ мқҙ shiftлҘј ліҙм •н•ҳм—¬ к·јм Җ representational geometryлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ Atom TheoryлҘј м •лҰҪн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” л‘җ лӢЁмң„мқё neuronкіј featureлҠ” мқҙмғҒм Ғмқё atomмқҳ кё°мӨҖмқ„ м¶©мЎұн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғлҸ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. neuronмқҖ faithfulн•ҳм§Җл§Ң( $ R^2=1 $ ) л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҳл©°( $ q^{\\star}=0.5 $% ), featureлҠ” лҚ” м•Ҳм •м Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң( $ q^{\\star}=68.2 $% ) faithfulnessк°Җ лӮ®лӢӨ( $ R^2=48.8 $% ). TSAE н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ atom identifiabilityлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ LLMмқҳ atomмқ„ м°ҫкё° мң„н•ҙ, лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ TSAE capacityк°Җ лҚ°мқҙн„° мҠӨмјҖмқјкіј мқјм№ҳн•  л•Ңм—җл§Ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” atom мӢқлі„мқҙ мқјм–ҙлӮңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң Gemma2-2B, Gemma2-9B, Llama3.1-8Bмқҳ к°Ғ layerм—җм„ң кұ°мқҳ мҷ„лІҪн•ң faithfulness( $ R^2=99.9 $% )мҷҖ stability( $ q^{\\star}=99.8 $% )лҘј к°–лҠ” FRUлҘј мӢқлі„н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” нҶөкі„м ҒмңјлЎң ideal atomмқҳ кё°мӨҖмқ„ л§ҢмЎұн•ңлӢӨ. м¶”к°Җ л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң atomмқҙ мқҙлЎ м Ғ кё°лҢҖмҷҖ л¶Җн•©н•ҳл©° нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ monosemanticityлҘј ліҙмһ„мқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLMмқҳ лӮҙл¶Җ representationмқ„ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң кё°л°ҳмңјлЎңм„ң Atom TheoryлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"62678","en":"Think-at-Hard: Selective Latent Iterations to Improve Reasoning Language Models","ko":"Think-at-Hard: м„ нғқм Ғ мһ мһ¬ л°ҳліөмңјлЎң Reasoning Language Models м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒ","authors":"Tianyu Fu, Yichen You, Zekai Chen, Guohao Dai, Huazhong Yang, Yu Wang","pos":"#1311","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eQaJSRZiGn","abs":"<p>Improving reasoning abilities of Large Language Models (LLMs), especially under parameter constraints, is crucial for real-world applications. Looped transformers address this by performing multiple latent iterations to refine each token beyond a single forward pass. However, we identify a latent overthinking phenomenon: most token predictions are already correct after the first pass, but are sometimes revised into errors in later iterations. In this work, we ask whether selectively skipping latent iterations may improve accuracy. We reveal significant potential with an oracle iteration policy that boosts model performance by up to 7.3%. Motivated by this, we propose Think-at-Hard (TaH), a looped transformer optimized for selective iteration. TaH employs a lightweight neural decider to trigger latent iteration only at tokens that are likely incorrect after the standard forward pass. During latent iterations, depth-aware Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) modules shift the LLM's objective from general next-token prediction to focused hard-token refinement. A duo-causal attention mechanism extends attention from the token sequence dimension to an additional iteration depth dimension, enabling cross-iteration information flow with full sequential parallelism. Experiments on nine benchmarks show consistent gains across math, QA, and coding tasks. With identical parameter counts, TaH outperforms always-iterate baselines by 3.8-4.4% while skipping iterations on 93% of tokens, and exceeds single-iteration Qwen3 baselines by 3.0-3.8%. When allowing &lt;3% more parameters from LoRA and decider modules, the gains further increase to 5.3-6.2% and 6.1-6.8%, respectively.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs)мқҳ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„, нҠ№нһҲ parameter м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқҖ мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. Looped transformerлҠ” к°Ғ tokenмқ„ лӢЁмқј forward passлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ м—¬лҹ¬ latent iterationмңјлЎң м •м ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” latent overthinking нҳ„мғҒмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ token predictionмқҖ мІ« лІҲм§ё pass мқҙнӣ„ мқҙлҜё м •лӢөмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙнӣ„ iterationм—җм„ң л•Ңл•ҢлЎң мҳӨлҘҳлЎң мҲҳм •лҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” latent iterationмқ„ м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң кұҙл„Ҳлӣ°лҠ” кІғмқҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җ л¬»лҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” oracle iteration policyк°Җ лӘЁлҚё м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мөңлҢҖ 7.3%к№Ңм§Җ лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬лҰ°лӢӨлҠ” мң мқҳлҜён•ң к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ л°қнҳ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҸҷкё°м—җ л”°лқј, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” selective iterationм—җ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗң looped transformerмқё Think-at-Hard (TaH)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. TaHлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ forward pass мқҙнӣ„ мҳӨлҘҳмқј к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ tokenм—җм„ңл§Ң latent iterationмқ„ мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” lightweight neural deciderлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. latent iteration лҸҷм•Ҳ depth-aware Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) modulesлҠ” LLMмқҳ objectiveлҘј мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё next-token predictionм—җм„ң м–ҙл Өмҡҙ tokenмқҳ м§‘мӨ‘м Ғ refinementлЎң м „нҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. duo-causal attention mechanismмқҖ attentionмқ„ token sequence м°Ёмӣҗм—җм„ң м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё iteration depth м°ЁмӣҗмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм—¬, мҷ„м „н•ң sequential parallelismкіј н•Ёк»ҳ iteration к°„ м •ліҙ нқҗлҰ„мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м•„нҷү к°ң benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ math, QA, coding task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҸҷмқјн•ң parameter мҲҳм—җм„ң TaHлҠ” н•ӯмғҒ iterationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” baselinesлҘј 3.8-4.4% мғҒнҡҢн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ tokenмқҳ 93%м—җм„ң iterationмқ„ кұҙл„Ҳлӣ°кі , single-iteration Qwen3 baselinesлҘј 3.0-3.8% лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. LoRAмҷҖ decider moduleлЎңл¶Җн„° 3% лҜёл§Ңмқҳ м¶”к°Җ parameterлҘј н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ, м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқҖ к°Ғк°Ғ 5.3-6.2%мҷҖ 6.1-6.8%лЎң лҚ” м»Өм§„лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65855","en":"Spherical Steering: Geometry-Aware Activation Rotation for Language Models","ko":"Spherical Steering: м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мң„н•ң кё°н•ҳн•ҷ мқёмӢқ нҷңм„ұнҷ” нҡҢм „","authors":"Zejia You, Chunyuan Deng, Hanjie Chen","pos":"#1405","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9PPeJsVLdB","abs":"<p>Inference-time steering has emerged as a promising paradigm for controlling language models (LMs) without the cost of retraining. However, standard approaches typically rely on activation addition, a geometric operation that inevitably alters the magnitude of hidden representations. This raises concerns about representation collapse and degradation of open-ended generation capabilities. In this work, we explore Spherical Steering, a training-free primitive that resolves this trade-off through activation rotation. Rather than shifting activations with a fixed vector, our method rotates them along a geodesic toward a target direction, guiding the activation toward the target concept while preserving the integrity of the signal. To further enhance adaptivity, we incorporate a confidence gate that dynamically modulates steering strength based on input uncertainty. Extensive experiments across multiple-choice benchmarks demonstrate that Spherical Steering significantly outperforms addition-based baselines (notably by +10\\% on TruthfulQA, COPA, and Storycloze), while simultaneously maintaining the modelвҖҷs general open-ended generation quality. This work highlights the value of geometric consistency, suggesting that norm-preserving rotation is a robust and effective primitive for precise inference-time control.</p>","absKo":"<p>м¶”лЎ  мӢңм җ steeringмқҖ мһ¬н•ҷмҠө л№„мҡ© м—Ҷмқҙ language model (LM)мқ„ м ңм–ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ н‘ңмӨҖ м ‘к·јмқҖ лҢҖк°ң activation additionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” hidden representationмқҳ нҒ¬кё°лҘј л¶Ҳк°Җн”јн•ҳкІҢ л°”кҫёлҠ” кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ м—°мӮ°мқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” representation collapseмҷҖ open-ended generation лҠҘл Ҙ м Җн•ҳм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°л ӨлҘј лӮілҠ”лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” activation rotationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң trade-offлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” training-free primitiveмқё Spherical Steeringмқ„ нғҗкө¬н•ңлӢӨ. кі м •лҗң vectorлЎң activationмқ„ мқҙлҸҷмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ activationмқ„ geodesicмқ„ л”°лқј лӘ©н‘ң л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң нҡҢм „мӢңмјң, мӢ нҳёмқҳ мҷ„м „м„ұмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң target concept мӘҪмңјлЎң activationмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. м Ғмқ‘м„ұмқ„ лҚ” лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мһ…л Ҙ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұм—җ л”°лқј steering к°•лҸ„лҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” confidence gateлҘј нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ multiple-choice benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Spherical Steeringмқҙ addition-based baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°(нҠ№нһҲ TruthfulQA, COPA, Storyclozeм—җм„ң +10\\%), лҸҷмӢңм—җ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё open-ended generation н’Ҳм§ҲлҸ„ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” geometric consistencyмқҳ к°Җм№ҳлҘј к°•мЎ°н•ҳл©°, norm-preserving rotationмқҙ м •л°Җн•ң м¶”лЎ  мӢңм җ м ңм–ҙлҘј мң„н•ң к°•кұҙн•ҳкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё primitiveмһ„мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61735","en":"Stop the Flip-Flop: Context-Preserving Verification for Fast Revocable Diffusion Decoding","ko":"Flip-Flop л©Ҳм¶”кё°: л№ лҘё мІ нҡҢ к°ҖлҠҘ Diffusion Decodingмқ„ мң„н•ң л§ҘлқҪ ліҙмЎҙ кІҖмҰқ","authors":"Yanzheng Xiang, Lan Wei, Yizhen Yao, Qinglin Zhu, Hanqi Yan, Chen Jin, Philip Teare, Dandan Zhang, Lin Gui, Amrutha Saseendran, Yulan He","pos":"#1408","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nLqXhC5P8t","abs":"<p>Parallel diffusion decoding can accelerate diffusion language model inference by unmasking multiple tokens per step, but aggressive parallelism often harms quality. Revocable decoding mitigates this by rechecking earlier tokens, yet we observe that existing verification schemes frequently trigger flip-flop oscillations, where tokens are remasked and later restored unchanged. This behaviour slows inference in two ways: remasking verified positions weakens the conditioning context for parallel drafting, and repeated remask cycles consume the revision budget with little net progress. We propose COVER (Cache Override Verification for Efficient Revision), which performs leave-one-out verification and stable drafting within a single forward pass. COVER constructs two attention views via KV cache override: selected seeds are masked for verification, while their cached key value states are injected for all other queries to preserve contextual information, with a closed form diagonal correction preventing self leakage at the seed positions. COVER further prioritises seeds using a stability aware score that balances uncertainty, downstream influence, and cache drift, and it adapts the number of verified seeds per step. Across benchmarks, COVER markedly reduces unnecessary revisions and yields faster decoding while preserving output quality.</p>","absKo":"<p>Parallel diffusion decodingмқҖ н•ң лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң м—¬лҹ¬ tokenмқҳ maskлҘј н•ҙм ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ diffusion language modelмқҳ inferenceлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, кіөкІ©м Ғмқё parallelismмқҖ мў…мў… н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ н•ҙм№ңлӢӨ. Revocable decodingмқҖ мқҙм „ tokenл“Өмқ„ лӢӨмӢң кІҖмҰқн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ verification schemeмқҙ flip-flop oscillationмқ„ мһҗмЈј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙл•Ң tokenл“Өмқҙ лӢӨмӢң maskлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨк°Җ мқҙнӣ„ ліҖкІҪ м—Ҷмқҙ ліөмӣҗлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҸҷмһ‘мқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ л°©мӢқмңјлЎң inferenceлҘј лҠҗлҰ¬кІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. кІҖмҰқлҗң мң„м№ҳлҘј лӢӨмӢң maskн•ҳл©ҙ parallel draftingмқ„ мң„н•ң conditioning contextк°Җ м•Ҫн•ҙм§Җкі , л°ҳліөлҗҳлҠ” remask cycleмқҖ мӢӨм§Ҳм Ғмқё м§„м „мқҙ кұ°мқҳ м—ҶмқҢм—җлҸ„ revision budgetмқ„ мҶҢлӘЁн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢЁмқј forward pass м•Ҳм—җм„ң leave-one-out verificationкіј stable draftingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” COVER(Cache Override Verification for Efficient Revision)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. COVERлҠ” KV cache overrideлҘј нҶөн•ҙ л‘җ к°ңмқҳ attention viewлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. м„ нғқлҗң seedлҠ” verificationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ maskлҗҳкі , лӢӨлҘё лӘЁл“  queryм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” к·ёл“Өмқҳ cached key value stateк°Җ мЈјмһ…лҗҳм–ҙ contextual informationмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©°, closed form diagonal correctionмқҙ seed мң„м№ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ self leakageлҘј л°©м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң COVERлҠ” uncertainty, downstream influence, cache driftмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” stability-aware scoreлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ seedлҘј мҡ°м„ мҲңмң„нҷ”н•ҳкі , лӢЁкі„лі„лЎң кІҖмҰқн•  seedмқҳ мҲҳлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң COVERлҠ” л¶Ҳн•„мҡ”н•ң revisionмқ„ нҳ„м ҖнһҲ мӨ„мқҙкі , м¶ңл Ҙ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң лҚ” л№ лҘё decodingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66119","en":"Surgery: Mitigating Harmful  Fine-Tuning for Large Language Models via Attention Sink","ko":"Surgery: Attention SinkлҘј нҶөн•ң лҢҖнҳ• м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мң н•ҙ нҢҢмқёнҠңлӢқ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Guozhi Liu, Weiwei Lin, Tiansheng Huang, Ruichao Mo, Qi Mu, Xiumin Wang, Li Shen","pos":"#1409","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=6ojsIliNF0","abs":"<p>Harmful fine-tuning can invalidate safety alignment of large language models, exposing significant safety risks. In this paper, we utilize the attention sink mechanism to mitigate harmful fine-tuning. Specifically, we first measure a statistic named <em>sink divergence</em> for each attention head and observe that <em>different attention heads exhibit two different signs of sink divergence</em>. To understand its safety implications, we conduct experiments and find that the number of attention heads of positive sink divergence increases along with the increase of the model's harmfulness when undergoing harmful fine-tuning. Based on this finding, we propose a separable sink divergence hypothesis -- <em>attention heads associating with learning harmful patterns during fine-tuning are separable by their sign of sink divergence</em>. Based on the hypothesis, we propose a fine-tuning-stage defense, dubbed Surgery. Surgery utilizes a regularizer for sink divergence suppression, which steers attention heads toward the negative sink divergence group, thereby reducing the modelвҖҷs tendency to learn and amplify harmful patterns. Extensive experiments demonstrate that Surgery improves defense performance by 5.90\\%, 11.25\\%, and 9.55\\% on the BeaverTails, HarmBench, and SorryBench benchmarks, respectively. Source code is available on https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Surgery-A69E.</p>","absKo":"<p>мң н•ҙн•ң fine-tuningмқҖ large language modelмқҳ safety alignmentлҘј л¬ҙнҡЁнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң м•Ҳм „ мң„н—ҳмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” attention sink mechanismмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мң н•ҙн•ң fine-tuningмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, лЁјм Җ к°Ғ attention headм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ <em>sink divergence</em>лқјлҠ” нҶөкі„лҘј мёЎм •н•ҳкі , <em>м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё attention headк°Җ sink divergenceмқҳ л¶Җнҳёк°Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё л‘җ к°Җм§Җ нҳ•нғңлҘј ліҙмһ„</em>мқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ңлӢӨ. к·ё м•Ҳм „мғҒмқҳ н•ЁмқҳлҘј мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ң кІ°кіј, мң н•ҙн•ң fine-tuningмқ„ кұ°м№ҳлҠ” лҸҷм•Ҳ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мң н•ҙм„ұмқҙ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ м–‘мқҳ sink divergenceлҘј к°–лҠ” attention headмқҳ мҲҳк°Җ мҰқк°Җн•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л°ңкІ¬мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¶„лҰ¬ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң sink divergence к°Җм„Ө, мҰү <em>fine-tuning лҸҷм•Ҳ мң н•ҙн•ң pattern н•ҷмҠөкіј м—°кҙҖлҗң attention headлҠ” sink divergenceмқҳ л¶Җнҳём—җ л”°лқј л¶„лҰ¬ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨ</em>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ к°Җм„Өм—җ к·јкұ°н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Surgeryлқј л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” fine-tuning лӢЁкі„ л°©м–ҙ кё°лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SurgeryлҠ” sink divergence м–өм ңлҘј мң„н•ң regularizerлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ attention headлҘј мқҢмқҳ sink divergence к·ёлЈ№ мӘҪмңјлЎң мң лҸ„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мң н•ҙн•ң patternмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  мҰқнҸӯн•ҳл ӨлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқ„ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Surgeryк°Җ BeaverTails, HarmBench, SorryBench лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬м—җм„ң к°Ғк°Ғ 5.90\\%, 11.25\\%, 9.55\\%мқҳ л°©м–ҙ м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мҶҢмҠӨ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Surgery-A69E м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62796","en":"The Structural Origin of Attention Sink: Variance Discrepancy, Super Neurons, and Dimension Disparity","ko":"Attention Sinkмқҳ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ кё°мӣҗ: Variance Discrepancy, Super Neurons, Dimension Disparity","authors":"Siquan Li, Kaiqi Jiang, Jiacheng Sun, Tianyang Hu","pos":"#1415","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=dAWFE1gPmJ","abs":"<p>Despite the prevalence of the attention sink phenomenon in Large Language Models (LLMs), where initial tokens disproportionately monopolize attention scores, its structural origins remain elusive. This work provides a <em>mechanistic explanation</em> for this phenomenon, tracing its roots to the value aggregation process inherent in self-attention, which induces a systematic dimension-wise variance discrepancy. We demonstrate that this discrepancy is drastically amplified by the activation of super neurons within Feed-Forward Network (FFN) layers. Specifically, the channel-sparse down-projections trigger a dimension disparity of the first-token representation, necessitating the formation of attention sinks as a structural anchor. We validate this causal chain through two controlled interventions: (i) isolating the aggregation effect via attention mask modifications and (ii) amplifying the variance of targeted token representations. Both interventions can replicate attention sinks at arbitrary positions. Our mechanistic understanding offers a foundation for the systematic control of sink formation. As a proof of concept, we propose <em>head-wise RMSNorm</em>, an architectural modification that stabilizes value aggregation outputs during pre-training. Our experiments demonstrate that restoring statistical parity across positions significantly accelerates convergence.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Model(LLM)м—җм„ң мҙҲкё° tokenмқҙ attention scoreлҘј м••лҸ„м ҒмңјлЎң лҸ…м җн•ҳлҠ” attention sink нҳ„мғҒмқҙ л„җлҰ¬ кҙҖм°°лҗЁм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , к·ё кө¬мЎ°м Ғ кё°мӣҗмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” self-attentionм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң value aggregation processлҘј м¶”м Ғн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мқҙ нҳ„мғҒм—җ лҢҖн•ң <em>mechanistic explanation</em>мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, к·ё кіјм •мқҙ мІҙкі„м Ғмқё dimension-wise variance discrepancyлҘј мң л°ңн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳк°Җ Feed-Forward Network(FFN) layer лӮҙ super neuronмқҳ нҷңм„ұнҷ”м—җ мқҳн•ҙ нҒ¬кІҢ мҰқнҸӯлҗЁмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, channel-sparse down-projectionмқҖ мІ« лІҲм§ё token representationмқҳ dimension disparityлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳл©°, мқҙм—җ л”°лқј кө¬мЎ°м Ғ anchorлЎңм„ң attention sinkмқҳ нҳ•м„ұмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҙм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ нҶөм ңлҗң к°ңмһ…мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ мқёкіј мӮ¬мҠ¬мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ: (i) attention mask мҲҳм •мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ aggregation effectлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкі , (ii) нҠ№м • token representationмқҳ varianceлҘј мҰқнҸӯн•ңлӢӨ. л‘җ к°ңмһ… лӘЁл‘җ мһ„мқҳмқҳ мң„м№ҳм—җм„ң attention sinkлҘј мһ¬нҳ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ mechanistic understandingмқҖ sink нҳ•м„ұмқҳ мІҙкі„м Ғ м ңм–ҙлҘј мң„н•ң кё°л°ҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к°ңл…җ мҰқлӘ…мңјлЎңм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” pre-training лҸҷм•Ҳ value aggregation outputмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” architecture modificationмқё <em>head-wise RMSNorm</em>мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мң„м№ҳ м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң statistical parityлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ мҲҳл ҙмқ„ мң мқҳлҜён•ҳкІҢ к°ҖмҶҚн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65021","en":"Reasoning-preserved Efficient Distillation of Large Language Models via Activation-aware Initialization","ko":"Activation-aware мҙҲкё°нҷ”лҘј нҶөн•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ м¶”лЎ  ліҙмЎҙ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Distillation","authors":"Junlin He, Yihong Tang, Tong Nie, Guilong Li, Binyu Yang, Jinxiao Du, Lijun Sun, Wei Ma","pos":"#1506","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HgRxoHLIwb","abs":"<p>Efficient Distillation (EDistill) compresses large language models (LLMs) by structured pruning parameters and tuning lightweight modules with high training efficiency. Although these EDistilled LLMs achieve state-of-the-art (SOTA) performance on general ability benchmarks relative to similarly sized LLMs, we identify a severe degradation in their multi-step reasoning ability, which we term reasoning collapse. We systematically analyze the geometric origins of reasoning collapse and show that the SOTA EDistill method based on width-reducing projection matrices suffers from eRank collapse, in which the effective rank (eRank) of hidden representations drops. We theoretically explain how singular values of randomly initialized projection matrices become unevenly distributed, leading to eRank collapse and thus token indistinguishability. To address this issue, we propose RED (Reasoning-preserved Efficient Distillation) for LLMs, which introduces activation-aware initialization to initialize projection matrices as channel-selection matrices, thus theoretically mitigating eRank collapse. Experiments on Llama and Qwen series demonstrate that RED substantially recovers reasoning while maintaining high training efficiency and SOTA general ability.</p>","absKo":"<p>Efficient Distillation (EDistill)мқҖ structured pruningмңјлЎң parameterлҘј м••м¶•н•ҳкі  lightweight moduleмқ„ лҶ’мқҖ training efficiencyлЎң нҠңлӢқн•ҳм—¬ large language model(LLM)мқ„ м••м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң EDistilled LLMмқҖ мң мӮ¬н•ң нҒ¬кё°мқҳ LLMкіј л№„көҗн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң general ability benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art (SOTA) м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙл“Өмқҙ multi-step reasoning abilityм—җм„ң мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң м Җн•ҳлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ нҷ•мқён–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҘј reasoning collapseлқјкі  л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reasoning collapseмқҳ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ кё°мӣҗмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ҳкі , width-reducing projection matrixм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң SOTA EDistill methodк°Җ eRank collapseлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң effective rank (eRank)лҠ” hidden representationмқҳ мң нҡЁ rankк°Җ к°җмҶҢн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң л¬ҙмһ‘мң„ мҙҲкё°нҷ”лҗң projection matrixмқҳ singular valueк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ л¶Ҳк· л“ұн•ҳкІҢ л¶„нҸ¬н•ҳкІҢ лҗҳлҠ”м§Җ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳкі , мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ eRank collapseк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҳл©° token indistinguishabilityлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” activation-aware initializationмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ projection matrixлҘј channel-selection matrixлЎң мҙҲкё°нҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң eRank collapseлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” RED (Reasoning-preserved Efficient Distillation)лҘј LLMмқ„ мң„н•ҙ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Llama л°Ҹ Qwen seriesм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ REDк°Җ лҶ’мқҖ training efficiencyмҷҖ SOTA general abilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң reasoningмқ„ мғҒлӢ№ л¶Җл¶„ ліөмӣҗн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62025","en":"NanoSpec: Accelerating Speculative Decoding using Minimalist In-Context Vocabularies","ko":"NanoSpec: мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ мқём»Ён…ҚмҠӨнҠё м–ҙнңҳлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң Speculative Decoding к°ҖмҶҚ","authors":"Zhiyang Chen, Daliang Xu, Yinyuan Zhang, Chenghua Wang, Mengwei Xu, Yun Ma","pos":"#1605","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=karVCJgZDo","abs":"The massive vocabulary sizes of large language models, often exceeding 100k tokens, impose a computational bottleneck on the final linear projection layer during speculative decoding. Existing vocabulary pruning solutions rely on static or coarsely-grained sub-vocabularies that necessitate large active sizes ($\\sim$30k) to maintain draft quality. We propose NanoSpec, a novel training-free approach that breaks this trade-off by dynamically constructing a minimalist, context-aware active vocabulary for each generation step. Leveraging the inherent temporal locality of language generation, NanoSpec achieves high coverage while slashing the average vocabulary size by over $40\\times$ (to $&lt;$3k tokens) without requiring any auxiliary trained parameters. To realize the theoretical benefits of such high sparsity on modern hardware, we introduce a system-algorithm co-design that overcomes the inefficiencies of sparse memory access through asynchronous gathering and GPU-resident state management. As a complementary plug-and-play module, NanoSpec cuts draft inference time by an average of 51.6\\%, delivering a $1.12-1.32\\times$ end-to-end speedup over the state-of-the-art speculative decoding method EAGLE-2 across diverse benchmarks and outperforming complex training-based pruning baselines.","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ л°©лҢҖн•ң vocabulary sizeлҠ” нқ”нһҲ 100k tokensлҘј мҙҲкіјн•ҳл©°, speculative decodingм—җм„ң мөңмў… linear projection layerмқҳ кі„мӮ° лі‘лӘ©мқ„ мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ vocabulary pruning solutionмқҖ кі м •м Ғмқҙкұ°лӮҳ кұ°м№ң sub-vocabularyм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, draft qualityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ нҒ° active size($\\sim$30k)к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” NanoSpecмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” к°Ғ generation stepл§ҲлӢӨ context-awareн•ң мөңмҶҢ active vocabularyлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ trade-offлҘј к№ЁлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ training-free м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙлӢӨ. м–ём–ҙ мғқм„ұмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё temporal localityлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ NanoSpecмқҖ лҶ’мқҖ coverageлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ нҸүк·  vocabulary sizeлҘј 40л°° мқҙмғҒ мӨ„м—¬($&lt;$3k tokens) м¶”к°ҖлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң parameter м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ лҸҷмһ‘н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҶ’мқҖ sparsityмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ мқҙм җмқ„ нҳ„лҢҖ н•ҳл“ңмӣЁм–ҙм—җм„ң мӢӨнҳ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” asynchronous gatheringкіј GPU-resident state managementлҘј нҶөн•ҙ sparse memory accessмқҳ л№„нҡЁмңЁмқ„ к·№ліөн•ҳлҠ” system-algorithm co-designмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. ліҙмҷ„м Ғмқё plug-and-play moduleлЎңм„ң NanoSpecмқҖ draft inference timeмқ„ нҸүк·  51.6% лӢЁм¶•н•ҳл©°, лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art speculative decoding methodмқё EAGLE-2 лҢҖл№„ end-to-end speedup 1.12-1.32л°°лҘј м ңкіөн•ҳкі  ліөмһЎн•ң training-based pruning baselineліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"60781","en":"Predicting the Order of Upcoming Tokens Improves Language Modeling","ko":"лӢӨк°Җмҳ¬ Tokenмқҳ мҲңм„ң мҳҲмёЎмқҖ Language Modelingмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ","authors":"Zayd Muhammad Kawakibi Zuhri, Erland Hilman Fuadi, Alham Fikri Aji","pos":"#1615","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=wmROqgop27","abs":"<p>Multi-token prediction (MTP) has been proposed as an auxiliary objective to improve next-token prediction (NTP) in language model training but shows inconsistent improvements, underperforming in standard NLP benchmarks. We found MTP's exact future token prediction to be too difficult as an auxiliary loss. Instead, we propose token order prediction (TOP), which trains models to order upcoming tokens by their proximity using a learning-to-rank loss. TOP requires only a single additional unembedding layer compared to MTP's multiple transformer layers. We pretrain models of 340M, 1.8B, and 7B parameters using NTP, MTP, DeepSeek MTP (DS-MTP) and TOP objectives. The results of nine standard NLP benchmarks show that TOP overall outperforms NTP, MTP, and DS-MTP even at scale. TOP models with continued training on math and code also perform better on 4 relevant benchmarks. On the synthetic star graph task, TOP enables pathfinding on graphs where NTP, MTP, and DS-MTP fail.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multi-token prediction(MTP)мқҖ language model trainingм—җм„ң next-token prediction(NTP)мқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң auxiliary objectiveлЎң м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, н‘ңмӨҖ NLP benchmarkм—җм„ңлҠ” мқјкҙҖлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©° кё°лҢҖм—җ лӘ» лҜём№ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MTPмқҳ м •нҷ•н•ң лҜёлһҳ token мҳҲмёЎмқҙ auxiliary lossлЎңм„ң л„Ҳл¬ҙ м–ҙл өлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. лҢҖмӢ , мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” token order prediction(TOP)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” learning-to-rank lossлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ лӢӨк°Җмҳ¬ tokenл“Өмқ„ proximityм—җ л”°лқј м •л ¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. TOPмқҖ MTPмқҳ м—¬лҹ¬ transformer layerм—җ л№„н•ҙ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё unembedding layer н•ҳлӮҳл§Ң н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” NTP, MTP, DeepSeek MTP(DS-MTP), TOP objectiveлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ 340M, 1.8B, 7B parameter лӘЁлҚёмқ„ pretrainн•ңлӢӨ. 9к°ң н‘ңмӨҖ NLP benchmark кІ°кіјм—җм„ң TOPмқҖ м „мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң scaleмқҙ м»Өм ёлҸ„ NTP, MTP, DS-MTPлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷкіј codeм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ continued trainingн•ң TOP лӘЁлҚёмқҖ кҙҖл Ё benchmark 4к°ңм—җм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. synthetic star graph taskм—җм„ң TOPмқҖ NTP, MTP, DS-MTPк°Җ мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” graphм—җм„ң pathfindingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64563","en":"LazyAttention: Efficient Retrieval-Augmented Generation with Deferred Positional Encoding","ko":"LazyAttention: м§Җм—°лҗң Positional Encodingмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Retrieval-Augmented Generation","authors":"Haocheng Xia, Mihir Pamnani, Hanxi Fang, Supawit Chockchowwat, Yongjoo Park","pos":"#1710","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=M9kHwqreN9","abs":"<p>Key-value (KV) caching accelerates inference of large language models (LLMs) by reusing past computations for generated tokens. Its importance becomes even greater in long-context applications such as retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) and in-context learning (ICL). However, conventional KV caching embeds positional information directly into the cache, limiting its reusability. Existing solutions either restrict reuse to prefixes or require expensive memory materialization for positional re-encoding. We introduce LazyAttention, a novel attention mechanism that kernelizes deferred positional encoding to enable zero-copy, position-agnostic KV reuse. By adjusting positional encoding within attention kernels on-the-fly, LazyAttention resolves the materialization bottleneck, allowing a single physical KV copy to serve multiple logical requests at arbitrary positions. Leveraging attention kernels tailored for prefilling and decoding, our system achieves significant efficiency improvements: under skewed document distributions, it reduces time-to-first-token (TTFT) by 1.37Г— and increases inference throughput by 1.40Г— compared to the state-of-the-art Block Attention, while maintaining comparable output quality.</p>","absKo":"<p>Key-value(KV) cachingмқҖ мғқм„ұлҗң tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ кіјкұ° кі„мӮ°мқ„ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ large language model(LLM)мқҳ inferenceлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқҖ retrieval-augmented generation(RAG)кіј in-context learning(ICL) к°ҷмқҖ long-context applicationм—җм„ң лҚ”мҡұ м»Өм§„лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ conventional KV cachingмқҖ positional informationмқ„ cacheм—җ м§Ғм ‘ embeddingн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©м„ұмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ н•ҙкІ°мұ…мқҖ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ prefixлЎң м ңн•ңн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ positional re-encodingмқ„ мң„н•ҙ л№„мӢј memory materializationмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” zero-copy, position-agnostic KV reuseлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” deferred positional encodingмқ„ kernelizeн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ attention mechanismмқё LazyAttentionмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. Attention kernel лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң positional encodingмқ„ on-the-flyлЎң мЎ°м •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, LazyAttentionмқҖ materialization bottleneckмқ„ н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳкі  н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ physical KV copyк°Җ мһ„мқҳмқҳ мң„м№ҳм—җ мһҲлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ logical requestлҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. prefillingкіј decodingм—җ л§һм¶ҳ attention kernelмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң нҡЁмңЁ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ: skewed document distribution н•ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art Block Attentionкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ time-to-first-token(TTFT)мқ„ 1.37л°° мӨ„мқҙкі  inference throughputмқ„ 1.40л°° н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, мң мӮ¬н•ң output qualityлҘј мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61467","en":"Large VisionвҖ“Language Models Get Lost in Attention","ko":"Large Vision-Language ModelsлҠ” Attentionм—җм„ң кёёмқ„ мһғлҠ”лӢӨ","authors":"Gongli Xi, Ye Tian, Mengyu Yang, Huahui Yi, Liang Lin, Xiaoshuai Hao, Kun Wang, Wendong Wang","pos":"#1712","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pt7x2tJm4L","abs":"<p>Despite the rapid evolution of training paradigms, the decoder backbone of large vision--language models (LVLMs) remains fundamentally rooted in the residual-connection Transformer architecture. Therefore, deciphering the distinct roles of internal modules is critical for understanding model mechanics and guiding architectural optimization. While prior statistical approaches have provided valuable attribution-based insights, they often lack a unified theoretical basis. To bridge this gap, we propose a unified framework grounded in <em>information theory and geometry</em> to quantify the <strong>geometric and entropic nature</strong> of residual updates. Applying this unified framework reveals a fundamental functional decoupling: <strong>Attention acts as a manifold-preserving operator</strong> focused on reconfiguration, whereas <strong>FFNs serve as manifold-expanding operators</strong> driving semantic innovation. Strikingly, further experiments demonstrate that replacing learned attention weights with predefined values (e.g., Gaussian noise) yields comparable or even superior performance across a majority of datasets relative to vanilla models. These results expose severe <strong>misallocation and redundancy</strong> in current mechanisms, suggesting that state-of-the-art LVLMs effectively ``get lost in attention'' rather than efficiently leveraging visual context.</p>","absKo":"<p>нӣҲл Ё нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙ л№ лҘҙкІҢ м§„нҷ”н–ҲмқҢм—җлҸ„, large vision--language model (LVLMs)мқҳ decoder backboneмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ residual-connection Transformer architectureм—җ к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң лҝҢлҰ¬лҘј л‘җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң лӮҙл¶Җ лӘЁл“Ҳмқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ҙлҸ…н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ model mechanicsлҘј мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкі  architectural optimizationмқ„ мқҙлҒ„лҠ” лҚ° н•өмӢ¬м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ statistical approachлҠ” attribution-based insightлҘј м ңкіөн•ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, мў…мў… нҶөмқјлҗң мқҙлЎ м Ғ кё°л°ҳмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” residual updateмқҳ <strong>geometric and entropic nature</strong>лҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” <em>information theory and geometry</em>м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң нҶөн•© frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөн•© frameworkлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ к·јліём Ғмқё functional decouplingмқҙ л“ңлҹ¬лӮңлӢӨ. <strong>AttentionмқҖ мһ¬кө¬м„ұм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳ manifold-preserving operator</strong>лЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, <strong>FFNsлҠ” semantic innovationмқ„ мқҙлҒ„лҠ” manifold-expanding operator</strong>лЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ”мҡұ лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„, м¶”к°Җ мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” н•ҷмҠөлҗң attention weightлҘј Gaussian noiseмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ мӮ¬м „ м •мқҳлҗң к°’мңјлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ҙлҸ„, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ datasetм—җм„ң vanilla modelм—җ л№„н•ҙ л№„мҠ·н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ лӮҳнғҖлӮЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ mechanismм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң <strong>misallocation and redundancy</strong>лҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, мөңмІЁлӢЁ LVLMsк°Җ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ contextлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ ``attention мҶҚм—җм„ң кёёмқ„ мһғкі '' мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61065","en":"LUGS: Latent-aware Guidance for Efficient Unmasking in Diffusion Large Language Models","ko":"LUGS: Diffusion Large Language Modelмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Unmaskingмқ„ мң„н•ң Latent-aware Guidance","authors":"Nuanqiao Shan, Kairong Han, Xinpeng Dong, Kun Kuang","pos":"#1713","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=u1EL7dCemU","abs":"<p>Diffusion Language Models (DLMs) have emerged as a flexible alternative to autoregressive (AR) models. They can decode tokens in any order, but the generation quality critically depends on the decoding strategy. Existing approaches predominantly rely on local heuristics, such as confidence or entropy, which may fail to capture sequence-level dependencies and the semantics in the context. To solve this problem, we propose Latent-aware Unmasking Guidance Search (\\LUGS{}), a novel decoding framework that leverages the model's internal hidden states to guide the unmasking process. By incorporating latent-aware scores to compensate for the limitations of local heuristics such as confidence or entropy, \\LUGS{} improves the model's performance. Extensive experiments on various downstream tasks demonstrate that our approach consistently outperforms existing baselines on LLaDA-8B-instruct and LLaDA-1.5 models. In Science and Reason tasks, \\LUGS{} improved performance by more than 1\\% on both base models. And \\LUGS{} obtains an average improvement of 3.5\\% in code generation. Remarkably, \\LUGS{} outperforms the beam search baseline by more than 5\\%  on average using LLaDA-8B-Instruct on code tasks. These results highlight the potential of latent-aware guidance for advancing controllable and high-quality generation.</p>","absKo":"Diffusion Language Models (DLMs)мқҖ autoregressive (AR) modelмқҳ мң м—°н•ң лҢҖм•ҲмңјлЎң л“ұмһҘн–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ лӘЁлҚёл“ӨмқҖ нҶ нҒ°мқ„ м–ҙл–Ө мҲңм„ңлЎңл“  л””мҪ”л”©н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, мғқм„ұ н’Ҳм§ҲмқҖ л””мҪ”л”© м „лһөм—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мўҢмҡ°лҗңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң confidenceлӮҳ entropy к°ҷмқҖ көӯмҶҢм Ғ heuristicм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” sequence-level dependencyмҷҖ л¬ёл§Ҙмқҳ semanticsлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҳ лӮҙл¶Җ hidden stateлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ unmasking кіјм •мқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ decoding frameworkмқё Latent-aware Unmasking Guidance Search(\\LUGS{})лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. confidenceлӮҳ entropyмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ көӯмҶҢ heuristicмқҳ н•ңкі„лҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ latent-aware scoreлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, \\LUGS{}лҠ” лӘЁлҚё м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң downstream taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ LLaDA-8B-instructмҷҖ LLaDA-1.5 modelм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. ScienceмҷҖ Reason taskм—җм„ңлҠ” \\LUGS{}к°Җ л‘җ base model лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң 1% мқҙмғҒ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңмј°лӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң \\LUGS{}лҠ” code generationм—җм„ң нҸүк·  3.5%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ LLaDA-8B-InstructлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң code taskм—җм„ң \\LUGS{}лҠ” beam search baselineліҙлӢӨ нҸүк·  5% мқҙмғҒ лҶ’мқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” controllableн•ҳкі  кі н’Ҳм§Ҳмқё generationмқ„ л°ңм „мӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҚ° latent-aware guidanceк°Җ м§ҖлӢҢ мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62506","en":"HiCI: Hierarchical ConstructionвҖ“Integration for Long-Context Attention","ko":"HiCI: мһҘл¬ё м»Ён…ҚмҠӨнҠё м–ҙн…җм…ҳмқ„ мң„н•ң Hierarchical ConstructionвҖ“Integration","authors":"Xiangyu Zeng, Qi Xu, Yunke Wang, Chang Xu","pos":"#1806","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=fz1c8IihEC","abs":"Long-context language modeling is commonly framed as a scalability challenge of token-level attention, yet local-to-global information structuring remains largely implicit in existing approaches. Drawing on cognitive theories of discourse comprehension, we propose HiCI (Hierarchical Construction--Integration), a hierarchical attention module that constructs segment-level representations, integrates them into a shared global context, and broadcasts both to condition segment-level attention. We validate HiCI through parameter-efficient adaptation of LLaMA-2 with only $\\sim$5.5\\% additional parameters, extending context from 4K to 100K tokens (7B) and 64K tokens (13B). Across language modeling, retrieval, and instruction-following benchmarks, HiCI yields consistent improvements over strong baselines, including matching proprietary models on topic retrieval and surpassing GPT-3.5-Turbo-16K on code comprehension. These results demonstrate the effectiveness of explicit hierarchical structuring as an inductive bias for long-context modeling.","absKo":"Long-context language modelingмқҖ нқ”нһҲ token-level attentionмқҳ scalability л¬ём ңлЎң м ңкё°лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, local-to-global information structuringмқҖ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јм—җм„ң лҢҖмІҙлЎң м•”л¬өм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. discourse comprehensionм—җ лҢҖн•ң cognitive theoryм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” segment-level representationмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј shared global contextлЎң нҶөн•©н•ң л’Ө, л‘җ мҲҳмӨҖ лӘЁл‘җлҘј broadcastн•ҳм—¬ segment-level attentionмқ„ мЎ°кұҙнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” hierarchical attention moduleмқё HiCI (Hierarchical Construction--Integration)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м•Ҫ 5.5\\%мқҳ м¶”к°Җ parameterл§ҢмңјлЎң LLaMA-2лҘј parameter-efficient adaptationн•ҳм—¬ HiCIлҘј кІҖмҰқн–Ҳмңјл©°, context кёёмқҙлҘј 4Kм—җм„ң 100K token(7B), 64K token(13B)к№Ңм§Җ нҷ•мһҘн–ҲлӢӨ. language modeling, retrieval, instruction-following benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң HiCIлҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, topic retrievalм—җм„ңлҠ” proprietary modelкіј лҸҷл“ұн•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  code comprehensionм—җм„ңлҠ” GPT-3.5-Turbo-16KлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” explicit hierarchical structuringмқҙ long-context modelingмқ„ мң„н•ң inductive biasлЎңм„ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62511","en":"InstEmb: Instruction-Following Embeddings through Glimpses of the Future","ko":"InstEmb: лҜёлһҳмқҳ лӢЁм„ңлҘј нҶөн•ң Instruction-Following Embedding н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Tianhao Gao, Jun Fang, Xiaohui Zhang, Zhiyuan Liu, Chao Liu, Pengzhang Liu, Qixia Jiang","pos":"#1812","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=fwWvqAOXMT","abs":"Recent advances have empowered large language models (LLMs) with remarkable fine-grained instruction-following capabilities in text generation tasks. However, embedding methods typically rely solely on the hidden state of the input's last token, limiting their ability to capture complete semantic signals distributed across the full output tokens. Moreover, existing discrete-to-continuous re-encoding approaches introduce semantic discontinuity. To address these limitations, we propose $\\textbf{InstEmb}$, a novel instruction following embedding framework. InstEmb jointly optimizes two key aspects: (1) Input-Intrinsic semantic information, achieved by employing contrastive learning focused on the representation of the last input token, and (2) Output-Aware semantic information, captured through representation self-distillation leveraging learnable look-ahead tokens without introducing additional decoding latency. Additionally, we introduce $\\textbf{Dual-Anchor Alignment Pooling (DAAP)}$, explicitly aligned with our dual training objectives.  Extensive experiments demonstrate that InstEmb achieves state-of-the-art performance across multiple instruction following benchmarks without benchmark-specific supervised data.","absKo":"мөңк·јмқҳ л°ңм „мңјлЎң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(LLMs)мқҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мғқм„ұ мһ‘м—…м—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м„ёл°Җн•ң instruction-following лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ к°–м¶”кІҢ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ embedding л°©лІ•мқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң мһ…л Ҙмқҳ л§Ҳм§Җл§ү tokenмқҳ hidden stateм—җл§Ң мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, м „мІҙ м¶ңл Ҙ tokensм—җ л¶„нҸ¬лҗң мҷ„м „н•ң semantic signalмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. лҚ”л¶Ҳм–ҙ кё°мЎҙмқҳ discrete-to-continuous re-encoding м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ semantic discontinuityлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ instruction following embedding frameworkмқё $\\textbf{InstEmb}$лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. InstEmbлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ мёЎл©ҙмқ„ кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ: (1) мһ…л Ҙ кі мң мқҳ Input-Intrinsic semantic informationмқҖ л§Ҳм§Җл§ү input tokenмқҳ representationм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ң contrastive learningмңјлЎң кө¬нҳ„н•ҳл©°, (2) Output-Aware semantic informationмқҖ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё decoding latencyлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн•ң look-ahead tokensлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң representation self-distillationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ нҸ¬м°©н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ training objectiveмҷҖ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м •л ¬лҗң $\\textbf{Dual-Anchor Alignment Pooling (DAAP)}$лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, InstEmbлҠ” benchmark-specific supervised data м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ м—¬лҹ¬ instruction following benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"66464","en":"FOCUS & RePAIR: Mitigating Text Degeneration via Token-Level Guidance For Pruned Large Language Models","ko":"FOCUS & RePAIR: к°Җм§Җм№ҳкё°лҗң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мң„н•ң нҶ нҒ° мҲҳмӨҖ к°Җмқҙл“ңлҘј нҶөн•ң н…ҚмҠӨнҠё нҮҙнҷ” мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Junyoung Lee, Sehyeon Park, Shinhyoung Jang, Seonha Ryu, Hojeong Kim, Hyunsei Lee, Il Suh, Yeseong Kim","pos":"#1904","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=3SgRoBn3XM","abs":"<p>Pruning is a practical approach to compress large language models (LLMs), but it can amplify text degeneration, especially repetition loops, even when perplexity and task accuracy remain largely unchanged. In this work, we present a token-level analysis of this failure mode by viewing decoding as a dynamical process that enters and persists in a small set of recurrent contexts. Our analysis decomposes degeneration into loop entry risk and loop persistence, and shows that persistence is controlled by the escape mass assigned to plausible alternatives within the token sampling set. Motivated by these findings, we propose two token-level guidance objectives for post-pruning fine-tuning. FOCUS reweights distillation toward high-confidence teacher regions to suppress leakage, while RePAIR uses onset-centered positive/negative continuation pairs with a margin loss to promote plausible alternatives and prevent early commitment to repetition loops. Experiments on open-ended continuation and instruction-based generation show that both methods consistently reduce repetition and improve generation quality.</p>","absKo":"<p>PruningмқҖ large language model(LLM)мқ„ м••м¶•н•ҳлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, perplexityмҷҖ task accuracyк°Җ лҢҖмІҙлЎң ліҖн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҚ”лқјлҸ„ text degeneration, нҠ№нһҲ repetition loopлҘј мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” decodingмқ„ мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ recurrent contextм—җ м§„мһ…н•ҳкі  лЁёл¬ҙлҠ” dynamical processлЎң л°”лқјліҙл©°, мқҙ failure modeм—җ лҢҖн•ң token-level analysisлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ degenerationмқ„ loop entry riskмҷҖ loop persistenceлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳкі , persistenceк°Җ token sampling set лӮҙм—җм„ң plausible alternativeм—җ н• лӢ№лҗң escape massм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңм–ҙлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°ңкІ¬м—җ м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” pruning мқҙнӣ„ fine-tuningмқ„ мң„н•ң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ token-level guidance objectiveлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. FOCUSлҠ” leakageлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ distillationмқ„ high-confidence teacher region мӘҪмңјлЎң мһ¬к°ҖмӨ‘н•ҳкі , RePAIRлҠ” onset-centered positive/negative continuation pairмҷҖ margin lossлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ plausible alternativeмқ„ мһҘл Өн•ҳкі  repetition loopлЎңмқҳ мЎ°кё° кі м°©мқ„ л°©м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. open-ended continuationкіј instruction-based generationм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ л‘җ л°©лІ• лӘЁл‘җ л°ҳліөмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мӨ„мқҙкі  мғқм„ұ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66757","en":"DyLLM: Efficient Diffusion LLM inference via saliency-based token selection and partial attention","ko":"DyLLM: Saliency кё°л°ҳ нҶ нҒ° м„ нғқ л°Ҹ л¶Җл¶„ Attentionмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Diffusion LLM м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Younjoo Lee, Junghoo Lee, Seungkyun Dan, Jaiyoung Park, Jung Ho Ahn","pos":"#1914","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0azUrmsSyA","abs":"Masked Diffusion Language Models (MDLMs) enable parallel token decoding, providing a promising alternative to the sequential nature of autoregressive generation.  However, their iterative denoising process remains computationally expensive because it repeatedly processes the entire sequence at every step.  We observe that across these diffusion steps, most token representations remain stable; only a small subset, which we term salient tokens, contributes meaningfully to the next update. Leveraging this temporal sparsity, we present DyLLM, a training-free inference framework that accelerates decoding by selectively computing only these salient tokens. DyLLM identifies saliency by measuring the cosine similarity of attention contexts between adjacent denoising steps. It recomputes feed-forward and attention operations only for salient tokens while reusing cached activations for the remainder. Across diverse reasoning and code-generation benchmarks, DyLLM achieves up to 9.6$\\times$ higher throughput while largely preserving the baseline accuracy of state-of-the-art models like LLaDA and Dream.","absKo":"Masked Diffusion Language Models (MDLMs)лҠ” лі‘л ¬ token decodingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬, autoregressive generationмқҳ мҲңм°Ём Ғ нҠ№м„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң мң л§қн•ң лҢҖм•Ҳмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙл“Өмқҳ iterative denoising кіјм •мқҖ л§Ө лӢЁкі„л§ҲлӢӨ м „мІҙ sequenceлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң мІҳлҰ¬н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ м—¬м „нһҲ нҒ¬лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң diffusion step м „л°ҳм—җм„ң лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ token representationмқҖ м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң мң м§Җлҗҳл©°, лӢӨмқҢ updateм—җ мқҳлҜё мһҲкІҢ кё°м—¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ salient tokensмқҙлқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ subsetлҝҗмһ„мқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң temporal sparsityлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” salient tokensл§Ң м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң кі„мӮ°н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ decodingмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳлҠ” training-free inference frameworkмқё DyLLMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. DyLLMмқҖ мқём ‘н•ң denoising step мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ attention context к°„ cosine similarityлҘј мёЎм •н•ҙ saliencyлҘј мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ salient tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңл§Ң feed-forward л°Ҹ attention м—°мӮ°мқ„ лӢӨмӢң кі„мӮ°н•ҳкі , лӮҳлЁём§Җ tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” cached activationмқ„ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң reasoning л°Ҹ code-generation benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң DyLLMмқҖ LLaDAмҷҖ Dream к°ҷмқҖ state-of-the-art modelмқҳ baseline accuracyлҘј лҢҖмІҙлЎң мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң мөңлҢҖ 9.6$\\times$ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ throughputмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63218","en":"Dustin: Draft-Augmented Sparse Verification for Efficient Long-Context Generation with Speculative Decoding","ko":"Dustin: Speculative Decodingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ мһҘл¬ёл§Ҙ мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мҙҲм•Ҳ мҰқк°• нқ¬мҶҢ кІҖмҰқ","authors":"Wen-Hung Lee, Jian-Jia Chen, Xiaolin Lin, Pei-Shuo Wang, Chi-Chih Chang, Chun-Che Yang, Wei-Chen Wang, Hanrui Wang, Ning-Chi Huang, Li Zhang, Kai-Chiang Wu","pos":"#1915","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Z1Ju4QIZmg","abs":"<p>While speculative decoding improves inference throughput for multi-batch long-context Large Language Models (LLMs), its efficiency is often limited by a verification bottleneck where Key-Value (KV) cache loading dominates latency. Existing compression methods fail in this regime: static eviction incurs accuracy loss due to saliency shift, while dynamic selection introduces prohibitive computational overhead during the verification path. We propose Dustin, a sparse verification framework designed for long-context speculative decoding. Dustin integrates lookahead signals from the draft model with historical attention from the target model to identify critical tokens with high fidelity across multi-step verification windows. To reduce recomputation latency, this approach further employs a sparse estimation scheme that restricts importance scoring to a minimal subset of attention heads. Evaluations on PG-19 and LongBench with Qwen2.5-72B demonstrate that Dustin achieves a 27.85Г— speedup in self-attention and a 9.17Г— end-to-end decoding speedup at a 32k sequence length, all with negligible accuracy degradation.</p>","absKo":"<p>speculative decodingмқҖ multi-batch long-context Large Language Models(LLMs)мқҳ inference throughputмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨм§Җл§Ң, к·ё нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқҖ мў…мў… Key-Value(KV) cache loadingмқҙ latencyлҘј м§Җл°°н•ҳлҠ” verification bottleneckм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ compression л°©лІ•мқҖ мқҙ мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. static evictionмқҖ saliency shiftлЎң мқён•ҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„ мҶҗмӢӨмқ„ мң л°ңн•ҳкі , dynamic selectionмқҖ verification pathм—җм„ң кіјлҸ„н•ң кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” long-context speculative decodingмқ„ мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗң sparse verification frameworkмқё Dustinмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. DustinмқҖ draft modelмқҳ lookahead signalкіј target modelмқҳ historical attentionмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ multi-step verification window м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң tokenмқ„ лҶ’мқҖ м¶©мӢӨлҸ„лЎң мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. мһ¬кі„мӮ° latencyлҘј мӨ„мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мӨ‘мҡ”лҸ„ м җмҲҳлҘј мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ attention head subsetм—җл§Ң м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ” sparse estimation schemeмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. Qwen2.5-72BлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң PG-19мҷҖ LongBench нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң DustinмқҖ 32k sequence lengthм—җм„ң self-attentionмқ„ 27.85л°°, end-to-end decoding мҶҚлҸ„лҘј 9.17л°° н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м •нҷ•лҸ„ м Җн•ҳлҠ” кұ°мқҳ м—ҶмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62928","en":"CoRe: Context-Robust Remasking for Diffusion Language Models","ko":"CoRe: Diffusion Language ModelsлҘј мң„н•ң Context-Robust Remasking","authors":"Kevin Zhai, Sabbir Mollah, Zhenyi Wang, Mubarak Shah","pos":"#2000","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bmKHxLWkz9","abs":"Standard decoding in Masked Diffusion Models (MDMs) is hindered by context rigidity: tokens are retained based on transient high confidence, often ignoring that early predictions lack full context. This creates cascade effects where initial inconsistencies misguide the remaining generation. Existing revision strategies attempt to mitigate this by relying on static confidence scores, but these signals are inherently myopic; inconsistent tokens frequently appear confident to the model itself. To address this, we propose Context-Robust Remasking (CoRe), a training-free framework for inference-time revision. We introduce a new selection paradigm: rather than trusting static token probabilities, we identify *context-brittle* tokens by probing their sensitivity to adversarial perturbations. We formalize revision as a robust optimization problem targeting worst-case context shifts. CoRe efficiently approximates this objective to expose unstable tokens, prioritizing them for revision. On LLaDA-8B-Base, CoRe delivers consistent improvements across reasoning and code benchmarks, outperforming compute-matched baselines and boosting performance on code generation (MBPP) by up to $+9.2\\\\%$.","absKo":"Masked Diffusion Models (MDMs)м—җм„ңмқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ decodingмқҖ context rigidityм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м Җн•ҙлҗңлӢӨ. tokenмқҖ мқјмӢңм Ғмқё high confidenceм—җ л”°лқј мң м§Җлҗҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мҙҲкё° predictionмқҙ мҷ„м „н•ң contextлҘј к°–м§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ мў…мў… л¬ҙмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј мҙҲкё°мқҳ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳк°Җ лӮҳлЁём§Җ generationмқ„ мһҳлӘ» мқҙлҒ„лҠ” cascade effectк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ revision strategyлҠ” static confidence scoreм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ мқҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл Ө н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң signalмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң myopicн•ҳлӢӨ. мқјкҙҖм„ұ м—ҶлҠ” tokenмЎ°м°Ё лӘЁлҚё мһҗмӢ м—җкІҢлҠ” мў…мў… confidentн•ҳкІҢ ліҙмқҙкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” inference-time revisionмқ„ мң„н•ң training-free frameworkмқё Context-Robust Remasking (CoRe)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ selection paradigmмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. static token probabilityлҘј мӢ лў°н•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , adversarial perturbationм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҜјк°җлҸ„лҘј probingн•ҳм—¬ *context-brittle* tokenмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” revisionмқ„ worst-case context shiftлҘј лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳлҠ” robust optimization problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. CoReлҠ” мқҙ лӘ©н‘ңлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң к·јмӮ¬н•ҳм—¬ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ң tokenмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙкі , мқҙлҘј revision лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ңлӢӨ. LLaDA-8B-Baseм—җм„ң CoReлҠ” reasoning л°Ҹ code benchmark м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мқјкҙҖлҗң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖмңјл©°, computeк°Җ л§һм¶°м§„ baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкі  code generation (MBPP) м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мөңлҢҖ $+9.2\\\\%$к№Ңм§Җ лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬л ёлӢӨ."},{"id":"65760","en":"Context-level Language Modeling by Learning Predictive Context Embeddings","ko":"мҳҲмёЎм Ғ л¬ёл§Ҙ мһ„лІ л”© н•ҷмҠөмқ„ нҶөн•ң л¬ёл§Ҙ мҲҳмӨҖ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ","authors":"beiya dai, Yuliang Liu, Daozheng Xue, Yunchong Song, Qipeng Guo, Kai Chen, Xinbing Wang, Bowen Zhou, Zhouhan Lin","pos":"#2004","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ARA2xneUDG","abs":"<p>We propose ContextLM, a framework that implicitly learns multi-token prediction by augmenting standard pretraining with an intrinsic next-context prediction objective. ContextLM builds a language model on top of context embeddings that span multiple tokens, enabling better next-token prediction by predicting the next context. Our model is fully compatible with standard autoregressive, token-by-token evaluation paradigms (e.g., perplexity). Extensive experiments with GPT-2 and Pythia backbones (up to 1.5B parameters and 300B training tokens) reveal that ContextLM shifts the Pareto frontier of scaling laws, exhibiting superior efficiency in parameters, training tokens, and FLOPs. Our results show that ContextLM could already achieve the baseline perplexity using 39\\% fewer parameters and demonstrates robust generalization improvements on extensive downstream tasks under equivalent parameter counts.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” standard pretrainingм—җ intrinsic next-context prediction objectiveлҘј лҚ”н•ҙ multi-token predictionмқ„ м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ ContextLMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ContextLMмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ tokenм—җ кұём№ң context embedding мң„м—җ language modelмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳм—¬, лӢӨмқҢ contextлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ next-token predictionмқ„ лҚ” мһҳ мҲҳн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ perplexityмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ н‘ңмӨҖ autoregressive, token-by-token evaluation paradigmкіј мҷ„м „нһҲ нҳёнҷҳлҗңлӢӨ. GPT-2мҷҖ Pythia backboneмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳ(мөңлҢҖ 1.5B parameterмҷҖ 300B training token)мқҖ ContextLMмқҙ scaling lawмқҳ Pareto frontierлҘј мқҙлҸҷмӢңнӮӨл©°, parameter, training token, FLOPs мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. кІ°кіјлҠ” ContextLMмқҙ мқҙлҜё baseline perplexityлҘј 39\\% м ҒмқҖ parameterлЎң лӢ¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, лҸҷмқјн•ң parameter мҲҳ н•ҳм—җм„ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң downstream task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ кІ¬кі н•ң generalization н–ҘмғҒмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64301","en":"DFlash: Block Diffusion for Flash Speculative Decoding","ko":"DFlash: Flash м¶”мёЎм Ғ л””мҪ”л”©мқ„ мң„н•ң лё”лЎқ Diffusion","authors":"Jian Chen, Yesheng Liang, Zhijian Liu","pos":"#2006","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Oz335dV48X","abs":"Autoregressive large language models (LLMs) deliver strong performance but require inherently sequential decoding, leading to high inference latency and poor GPU utilization. Speculative decoding mitigates this bottleneck by using a fast draft model whose outputs are verified in parallel by the target LLM. However, existing methods still rely on *autoregressive drafting*, which remains sequential and constrains practical speedups. Diffusion LLMs offer a promising alternative by enabling parallel generation, but current diffusion models typically underperform compared with autoregressive models. In this paper, we introduce **DFlash**, a speculative decoding framework that employs a lightweight block diffusion model for parallel drafting. We show that speculative decoding provides a natural and effective setting for diffusion models. By generating draft tokens in a single forward pass, DFlash enables efficient drafting, and by conditioning the draft model on context features extracted from the target model, it achieves high-quality drafts with improved acceptance rates. Experiments demonstrate that DFlash achieves more than 6$\\times$ lossless acceleration across a range of models and tasks, delivering up to 2.5$\\times$ higher speedup than the state-of-the-art speculative decoding method EAGLE-3.","absKo":"Autoregressive large language model(LLM)мқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң sequential decodingмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳм—¬ inference latencyк°Җ лҶ’кі  GPU utilizationмқҙ лӮ®лӢӨ. Speculative decodingмқҖ л№ лҘё draft modelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі , к·ё м¶ңл ҘмқҖ target LLMмқҙ лі‘л ¬лЎң кІҖмҰқн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лі‘лӘ©мқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ sequentialн•ң м ңм•Ҫмқ„ к°–лҠ” *autoregressive drafting*м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мӢӨм ң мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. Diffusion LLMмқҖ лі‘л ¬ мғқм„ұмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мң л§қн•ң лҢҖм•Ҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ diffusion modelмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң autoregressive modelм—җ л№„н•ҙ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” лі‘л ¬ draftingмқ„ мң„н•ҙ lightweight block diffusion modelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” speculative decoding frameworkмқё **DFlash**лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” speculative decodingмқҙ diffusion modelм—җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё м„Өм •мһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лӢЁмқј forward passм—җм„ң draft tokenмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ DFlashлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё draftingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі , target modelм—җм„ң м¶”м¶ңн•ң context featureлЎң draft modelмқ„ мЎ°кұҙнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лҶ’мқҖ acceptance rateлҘј к°–лҠ” кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ draftлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ DFlashк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң лӘЁлҚёкіј taskм—җм„ң 6$\\times$ мқҙмғҒмқҳ lossless accelerationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, state-of-the-art speculative decoding л°©лІ•мқё EAGLE-3ліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ 2.5$\\times$ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ speedupмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62046","en":"Disentangling Geometry, Performance, and Training in Language Models","ko":"Language Modelsм—җм„ң Geometry, Performance, Training л¶„лҰ¬ л¶„м„қ","authors":"Atharva Kulkarni, Jacob Mitchell Springer, Arjun Subramonian, Swabha Swayamdipta","pos":"#2010","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=kNb6NNhKgE","abs":"<p>Geometric properties of Transformer weights, particularly the unembedding matrix, have been widely useful in language model interpretability research. Yet, their utility for estimating downstream performance remains unclear. In this work, we systematically investigate the relationship between model performance and the unembedding matrix geometry, particularly its effective rank. Our experiments, involving a suite of 108 OLMo-style language models trained under controlled variation, reveal several key findings. While the best-performing models often exhibit a high effective rank, this trend is not universal across tasks and training setups.  Contrary to prior work, we find that low effective rank does not cause late-stage performance degradation in small models, but instead co-occurs with it; we find adversarial cases where low-rank models do not exhibit saturation. Moreover, we show that effective rank is strongly influenced by pre-training hyperparameters, such as batch size and weight decay, which in-turn affect the model's performance. Lastly, extending our analysis to other geometric metrics and final-layer representation, we find that these metrics are largely aligned, but none can reliably predict downstream performance. Overall, our findings suggest that the model's geometry, as captured by existing metrics, primarily reflects training choices rather than performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Transformer weight, нҠ№нһҲ unembedding matrixмқҳ geometric propertyлҠ” language model interpretability м—°кө¬м—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ мң мҡ©н•ҳкІҢ нҷңмҡ©лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙкІғмқҙ downstream performance м¶”м •м—җ м–јл§ҲлӮҳ мң мҡ©н•ңм§ҖлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ лӘ…нҷ•н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” model performanceмҷҖ unembedding matrix geometry, нҠ№нһҲ its effective rank мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ кҙҖкі„лҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. нҶөм ңлҗң ліҖнҷ”лҘј л‘җкі  н•ҷмҠөн•ң 108к°ңмқҳ OLMo-style language modelмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӘҮ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ кІ°кіјлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мөңкі  м„ұлҠҘ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мў…мў… лҶ’мқҖ effective rankлҘј ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ taskмҷҖ training setup м „л°ҳм—җм„ң ліҙнҺём Ғмқё кІғмқҖ м•„лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙм „ м—°кө¬мҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” low effective rankк°Җ мҶҢнҳ• лӘЁлҚём—җм„ңмқҳ late-stage performance degradationмқ„ м•јкё°н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј, мҳӨнһҲл Ө к·ёмҷҖ лҸҷл°ҳлҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–Ҳмңјл©°, low-rank modelмқҙ saturationмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” adversarial caseлҸ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң effective rankлҠ” batch sizeмҷҖ weight decay к°ҷмқҖ pre-training hyperparameterмқҳ к°•н•ң мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л°ӣмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” лӢӨмӢң model performanceм—җ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, лӢӨлҘё geometric metricкіј final-layer representationмңјлЎң л¶„м„қмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң metricл“ӨмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң м„ңлЎң м •л ¬лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм§Җл§Ң м–ҙлҠҗ кІғлҸ„ downstream performanceлҘј мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳм§ҖлҠ” лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, кё°мЎҙ metricмқҙ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” model geometryлҠ” мЈјлЎң performanceліҙлӢӨлҠ” training choiceлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62472","en":"Beyond Next-Token Alignment: Distilling Multimodal Large Language Models via Token Interactions","ko":"Next-Token AlignmentлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ: Token Interactionмқ„ нҶөн•ң Multimodal Large Language Model Distillation","authors":"Lin Chen, zhaoxiaoke, Kun Ding, Weiwei Feng, Changtao Miao, Zili Wang, Guo Wenxuan, Ying Wang, Kaiyuan Zheng, Bo Zhang, Zhe Li, Shiming Xiang","pos":"#2104","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gJy2pIp7gt","abs":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) demonstrate impressive cross-modal capabilities, yet their substantial size poses significant deployment challenges. Knowledge distillation (KD) is a promising solution for compressing these models, but existing methods primarily rely on static next-token alignment, neglecting the dynamic token interactions, which embed essential capabilities for multimodal understanding and generation. To this end, we introduce <strong>Align-TI</strong>, a novel KD framework designed from the perspective of <strong>T</strong>oken <strong>I</strong>nteractions. Our approach is motivated by the insight that MLLMs rely on two primary interactions: vision-instruction token interactions to extract relevant visual information, and intra-response token interactions for coherent generation. Accordingly, Align-TI introduces two components: IVA enables the student model to imitate the teacher's instruction-relevant visual information extract capability by aligning on salient visual regions. TPA captures the teacher's dynamic generative logic by aligning the sequential token-to-token transition probabilities. Extensive experiments demonstrate Align-TI's superiority. Notably, our approach achieves 2.6% relative improvement over Vanilla KD, and our distilled Align-TI-2B even outperforms LLaVA-1.5-7B (a much larger MLLM) by 7.0%, establishing a new state-of-the-art distillation framework for training parameter-efficient MLLMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models(MLLMs)мқҖ мқёмғҒм Ғмқё cross-modal лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм§Җл§Ң, к·ё мғҒлӢ№н•ң к·ңлӘЁлҠ” л°°нҸ¬м—җ нҒ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ мӨҖлӢӨ. Knowledge distillation(KD)мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ м••м¶•н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң н•ҙлІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң м •м Ғмқё next-token alignmentм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ multimodal мқҙн•ҙмҷҖ мғқм„ұм—җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё лҸҷм Ғ token interactionмқ„ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>Token Interactions</strong> кҙҖм җм—җм„ң м„Өкі„лҗң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ KD frameworkмқё <strong>Align-TI</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ MLLMмқҙ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мЈјмҡ” interactionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨлҠ” нҶөм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ: кҙҖл Ё visual informationмқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң vision-instruction token interactionкіј, мқјкҙҖлҗң мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң intra-response token interactionмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ л”°лқј Align-TIлҠ” л‘җ кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. IVAлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң visual regionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ alignmentлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ teacherмқҳ instruction-relevant visual information extract capabilityлҘј student modelмқҙ лӘЁл°©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ лҸ•лҠ”лӢӨ. TPAлҠ” мҲңм°Ём Ғмқё token-to-token transition probabilityлҘј м •л ¬н•ҳм—¬ teacherмқҳ лҸҷм Ғ мғқм„ұ лЎңм§Ғмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Align-TIмқҳ мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ Vanilla KD лҢҖл№„ мғҒлҢҖм ҒмңјлЎң 2.6% н–ҘмғҒлҗҳм—Ҳкі , м••м¶•лҗң Align-TI-2BлҠ” нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” нҒ° MLLMмқё LLaVA-1.5-7BліҙлӢӨлҸ„ 7.0% лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬, parameter-efficient MLLM н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state-of-the-art distillation frameworkлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65305","en":"Any-Diffusion: Unified Multimodal Understanding and Generation with Masked Discrete Diffusion","ko":"Any-Diffusion: Masked Discrete Diffusionмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҶөн•© л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ мқҙн•ҙ л°Ҹ мғқм„ұ","authors":"Lijiang Li, zuwei long, Yunhang Shen, Heting Gao, Haoyu Cao, Xing Sun, Caifeng Shan, Ran He, Chaoyou Fu","pos":"#2113","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EulXRTtFCd","abs":"<p>While recent multimodal large language models (MLLMs) have made impressive strides, they mostly employ a conventional autoregressive architecture as their backbone, leaving significant room for exploring effective and efficient alternatives in architectural design. Meanwhile, recent studies have successfully applied discrete diffusion models to natural language processing, revealing their considerable potential as a promising new approach in this domain. Drawing inspiration from these pioneering researches, we introduce Any-Diffusion, the first any-to-any multimodal language model built purely on mask-based discrete diffusion models, which unifies understanding and generation across text, speech, and images. Any-Diffusion employs a unified mask-based discrete diffusion model to directly capture the joint distribution over discrete multimodal tokens. This approach enables support for not only bimodal tasks but also more complex scenarios involving multiple modalities. On a diverse set of benchmarks, our method outperforms or performs on par with existing multimodal systems that process two or more modalities, highlighting the significant promise of diffusion models in powering the next generation of multimodal foundation models.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј multimodal large language models(MLLMs)мқҖ мқёмғҒм Ғмқё л°ңм „мқ„ мқҙлЈЁм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ м „нҶөм Ғмқё autoregressive architectureлҘј backboneмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі  мһҲм–ҙ, architectural design мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё лҢҖм•Ҳмқ„ нғҗмғүн•  м—¬м§Җк°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ нҒ¬лӢӨ. н•ңнҺё, мөңк·ј м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ discrete diffusion modelsлҘј natural language processingм—җ м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©°, мқҙ л¶„м•јм—җм„ң мң л§қн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мңјлЎңм„ңмқҳ мғҒлӢ№н•ң мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„ лҸ„м Ғ м—°кө¬л“Өм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Any-Diffusionмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” mask-based discrete diffusion modelsл§ҢмңјлЎң кө¬м¶•лҗң мөңмҙҲмқҳ any-to-any multimodal language modelлЎң, text, speech, images м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң мқҙн•ҙмҷҖ мғқм„ұмқ„ н•ҳлӮҳлЎң нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. Any-DiffusionмқҖ нҶөн•©лҗң mask-based discrete diffusion modelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ discrete multimodal tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ң joint distributionмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ нҸ¬м°©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ bimodal taskлҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј м—¬лҹ¬ modalityк°Җ кҙҖм—¬н•ҳлҠ” лҚ” ліөмһЎн•ң мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨк№Ңм§Җ м§Җмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ л‘җ к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ modalityлҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ multimodal systemліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҸҷл“ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, diffusion modelмқҙ м°Ём„ёлҢҖ multimodal foundation modelмқ„ кө¬лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м§ҖлӢҢ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ л¶Җк°Ғн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63042","en":"A3: an Analytical Low-Rank Approximation Framework for Attention","ko":"A3: м–ҙн…җм…ҳмқ„ мң„н•ң н•ҙм„қм Ғ м Җкі„мҲҳ к·јмӮ¬ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Jeffrey T. H. Wong, Cheng Zhang, Xinye Cao, Pedro Gimenes, Christos-Savvas Bouganis, George Constantinides, Wayne Luk, Aaron Zhao","pos":"#2208","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=aeeo8ZAftQ","abs":"Large language models have demonstrated remarkable performance; however, their massive parameter counts make deployment highly expensive. Low-rank approximation offers a promising compression solution, yet existing approaches have two main limitations: (1) They focus on minimizing the output error of individual linear layers, without considering the architectural characteristics of Transformers, and (2) they decompose a large weight matrix into two small low-rank matrices. Consequently, these methods often fall short compared to other compression techniques like pruning and quantization, and introduce runtime overhead such as the extra GEMM kernel launches and memory operations for decomposed small matrices. To address these limitations, we propose $A^3$, a post-training low-rank approximation framework. $A^3$ splits a Transformer layer into three functional components, namely $\\texttt{QK}$, $\\texttt{OV}$, and $\\texttt{MLP}$ and provides analytical solutions that reduces the hidden dimension size inside each component while minimizing the component's functional loss. This approach directly reduces model sizes, KV cache sizes, and FLOPs without introducing any runtime overheads. Through extensive experiments, we show that $A^3$ maintains superior performance compared to SoTAs.  For example, under the same reduction budget in computation and memory, our low-rank approximated LLaMA 3.1-70B achieves a perplexity of 4.69 on WikiText-2, outperforming the previous SoTA's 7.87 by 3.18. We also show versatile applications of $A^3$ in KV cache compression, integration with quantization, fine-tuning and mixed-rank assignments.","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, л§үлҢҖн•ң нҢҢлқјлҜён„° мҲҳ л•Ңл¬ём—җ л°°нҸ¬ л№„мҡ©мқҙ л§Өмҡ° лҶ’лӢӨ. м ҖлһӯнҒ¬ к·јмӮ¬лҠ” мң л§қн•ң м••м¶• н•ҙлІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•м—җлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мЈјмҡ” н•ңкі„к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ: (1) Transformerмқҳ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ нҠ№м„ұмқ„ кі л Өн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  к°ңлі„ linear layerмқҳ м¶ңл Ҙ мҳӨм°ЁлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м§‘мӨ‘н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җ, (2) нҒ° weight matrixлҘј л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мһ‘мқҖ low-rank matrixлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ pruningмқҙлӮҳ quantization к°ҷмқҖ лӢӨлҘё м••м¶• кё°лІ•м—җ л№„н•ҙ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һкі , л¶„н•ҙлҗң мһ‘мқҖ matrixл“Өм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м¶”к°Җ GEMM kernel launchмҷҖ memory operation к°ҷмқҖ runtime overheadлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” post-training low-rank approximation frameworkмқё $A^3$лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. $A^3$лҠ” Transformer layerлҘј $\\texttt{QK}$, $\\texttt{OV}$, $\\texttt{MLP}$лқјлҠ” м„ё к°ңмқҳ functional componentлЎң л¶„н• н•ҳкі , к°Ғ componentмқҳ functional lossлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙм„ң лӮҙл¶Җ hidden dimension sizeлҘј мӨ„мқҙлҠ” analytical solutionмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ runtime overheadлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң model size, KV cache size, FLOPsлҘј м§Ғм ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ $A^3$к°Җ SoTAл“Өкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, лҸҷмқјн•ң computation л°Ҹ memory reduction budgetм—җм„ң, low-rank approximated LLaMA 3.1-70BлҠ” WikiText-2м—җм„ң perplexity 4.69лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, мқҙм „ SoTAмқҳ 7.87мқ„ 3.18л§ҢнҒј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң KV cache compression, quantizationкіјмқҳ нҶөн•©, fine-tuning, mixed-rank assignmentм—җм„ң $A^3$мқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мқ‘мҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұлҸ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"62409","en":"SPEED: Sharpened-Teacher Distillation for Parallel Decoding of Diffusion Language Models","ko":"SPEED: Diffusion Language Modelsмқҳ лі‘л ¬ л””мҪ”л”©мқ„ мң„н•ң Sharpened-Teacher Distillation","authors":"Qiuhong Shen, Xingyi Yang, Xinyin Ma, Gongfan Fang, Xinchao Wang","pos":"#3507","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gscVYTfek1","abs":"<p>Diffusion-based large language models generate text by gradually filling in masked tokens, yet they remain slow because they usually decode only a few tokens per step. Parallel decoding, which unmasks multiple tokens simultaneously, promises acceleration but often degrades quality when too many tokens are predicted at once. We identify the root cause: when decoding is viewed as iterative token grouping, overly permissive grouping places interdependent tokens in the same step, violates the conditional independence assumption, and amplifies reliance on noisy context even when the top prediction is already correct. We introduce SPEED, a framework that enlarges safe parallel groups through complementary training and inference designs. At training time, a sharpened teacher distillation objective selectively aligns the student to teacher-correct positions using a temperature-scaled KL term together with a masked language modeling loss, producing a student that assigns more probability mass to correct token identities and elevates more positions above the decoding threshold. At inference time, SlowвҖ“Fast Decoding partitions tokens by sensitivity to revealed context using token-wise JensenвҖ“Shannon Divergence computed with and without access to the preceding block, decoding high-sensitivity tokens jointly while deferring low-sensitivity tokens until sufficient context resolves them. Through extensive experiments, our framework attains up to 12.2Г— speedup on LLaDA-8B-Instruct and 6.7Г— on Dream-7B-Instruct with accuracy close to greedy decoding across standard reasoning and code benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"Diffusion-based large language modelмқҖ masked tokenмқ„ м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң мұ„мӣҢ л„ЈлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, ліҙнҶө н•ң stepм—җ лӘҮ к°ңмқҳ tokenл§Ң decodeн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ лҠҗлҰ¬лӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ tokenмқ„ лҸҷмӢңм—җ unmaskн•ҳлҠ” parallel decodingмқҖ к°ҖмҶҚмқ„ м•ҪмҶҚн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, н•ң лІҲм—җ л„Ҳл¬ҙ л§ҺмқҖ tokenмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳл©ҙ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҙ мў…мў… м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к·јліё мӣҗмқёмқ„ лӢӨмқҢкіј к°ҷмқҙ нҢҢм•…н•ңлӢӨ. decodingмқ„ л°ҳліөм Ғмқё token groupingмңјлЎң ліј л•Ң, м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ н—Ҳмҡ©м Ғмқё groupingмқҖ мғҒнҳёмқҳмЎҙм Ғмқё tokenмқ„ к°ҷмқҖ stepм—җ л°°м№ҳн•ҳкі , conditional independence assumptionмқ„ мң„л°ҳн•ҳл©°, мғҒмң„ predictionмқҙ мқҙлҜё м •нҷ•н•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ noisy contextм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙмқ„ мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ліҙмҷ„м Ғмқё trainingкіј inference м„Өкі„лҘј нҶөн•ҙ м•Ҳм „н•ң parallel groupмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” frameworkмқё SPEEDлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. training мӢңм—җлҠ” sharpened teacher distillation objectiveк°Җ temperature-scaled KL termкіј masked language modeling lossлҘј н•Ёк»ҳ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ teacher-correct positionм—җ studentлҘј м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң м •л ¬н•ҳкі , к·ё кІ°кіј studentк°Җ мҳ¬л°”лҘё token identityм—җ лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ probability massлҘј н• лӢ№н•ҳл©° лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ positionмқ„ decoding threshold мң„лЎң лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬лҰ°лӢӨ. inference мӢңм—җлҠ” SlowвҖ“Fast Decodingмқҙ м•һм„  blockм—җ лҢҖн•ң м ‘к·ј мң л¬ҙлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ token-wise JensenвҖ“Shannon DivergenceлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳм—¬ tokenмқ„ context sensitivityм—җ л”°лқј л¶„н• н•ҳкі , high-sensitivity tokenмқҖ н•Ёк»ҳ decodeн•ҳлҗҳ low-sensitivity tokenмқҖ м¶©л¶„н•ң contextк°Җ н•ҙмҶҢлҗ  л•Ңк№Ңм§Җ м§Җм—°н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ reasoning л°Ҹ code benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң greedy decodingм—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң LLaDA-8B-Instructм—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ 12.2л°°, Dream-7B-Instructм—җм„ң 6.7л°°мқҳ speedupмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64095","en":"WeDLM: Reconciling Diffusion Language Models with Standard Causal Attention for Fast Inference","ko":"WeDLM: л№ лҘё м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ҙ Diffusion м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёкіј н‘ңмӨҖ мқёкіј м–ҙн…җм…ҳмқҳ мЎ°нҷ”","authors":"Aiwei Liu, Minghua He, Shaoxun Zeng, Sijun Zhang, Linhao Zhang, Chuhan Wu, Wei Jia, Yuan Liu, Zhou Xiao, Jie Zhou","pos":"#3601","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=QwtmbKAOZU","abs":"<p>Autoregressive (AR) generation is the standard decoding paradigm for Large Language Models (LLMs), but its token-by-token nature limits parallelism at inference time. Diffusion Language Models (DLLMs) offer parallel decoding by recovering multiple masked tokens per step; however, in practice they often fail to translate this parallelism into speed gains over optimized AR engines (e.g., vLLM). A key reason is that many DLLMs rely on bidirectional attention, which breaks standard prefix KV caching. We propose WeDLM, a diffusion decoding framework built entirely on standard causal attention to make parallel generation prefix-cache friendly. The core idea is to let each masked position condition on all observed tokens while keeping a causal mask, achieved by Topological Reordering that moves observed tokens to the physical prefix while preserving their logical positions. Building on this, we introduce a streaming decoding procedure that continuously commits confident tokens into a growing left-to-right prefix, avoiding the stop-and-wait behavior common in block diffusion methods. Experiments show that WeDLM preserves the quality of strong AR backbones while delivering substantial speedups, approaching 3Г— on challenging reasoning benchmarks and up to 10Г— in low-entropy generation regimes; critically, our comparisons are against AR baselines served by vLLM under matched deployment settings.</p>","absKo":"<p>Autoregressive(AR) generationмқҖ Large Language Models(LLMs)мқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ decoding paradigmмқҙм§Җл§Ң, token-by-token л°©мӢқмқҖ inference timeмқҳ parallelismмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. Diffusion Language Models(DLLMs)мқҖ н•ң лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң м—¬лҹ¬ masked tokenмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лі‘л ¬ decodingмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң parallelismмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗң AR engine(мҳҲ: vLLM) лҢҖл№„ мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмңјлЎң мһҳ м—°кІ°н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ мқҙмң  мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” л§ҺмқҖ DLLMмқҙ bidirectional attentionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ н‘ңмӨҖ prefix KV cachingмқ„ к№ЁлңЁлҰ¬кё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” parallel generationмқҙ prefix-cacheм—җ м№ңнҷ”м ҒмқҙлҸ„лЎқ, н‘ңмӨҖ causal attentionл§ҢмңјлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң diffusion decoding frameworkмқё WeDLMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҠ” к°Ғ masked positionмқҙ лӘЁл“  observed tokenмқ„ мЎ°кұҙмңјлЎң н•ҳлҗҳ causal maskлҠ” мң м§Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң, observed tokenмқ„ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ prefixлЎң мқҙлҸҷмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ң л…јлҰ¬м Ғ мң„м№ҳлҠ” ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” Topological Reorderingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” confident tokenмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң м„ұмһҘн•ҳлҠ” left-to-right prefixм—җ commitн•ҳлҠ” streaming decoding procedureлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, block diffusion methodм—җм„ң нқ”н•ң stop-and-wait лҸҷмһ‘мқ„ н”јн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ WeDLMмқҙ к°•л Ҙн•ң AR backboneмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мғҒлӢ№н•ң мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, м–ҙл Өмҡҙ reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ңлҠ” м•Ҫ 3л°°м—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„, low-entropy generation regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” мөңлҢҖ 10л°°к№Ңм§Җмқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м җмқҖ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л№„көҗк°Җ vLLMмңјлЎң м„ңл№ҷлҗҳлҠ” AR baselineкіј лҸҷмқјн•ң deployment settingм—җм„ң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙмЎҢлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63542","en":"Large Language Models Explore by Latent Distilling","ko":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мһ мһ¬ мҰқлҘҳлҘј нҶөн•ң нғҗмғү","authors":"Yuanhao Zeng, Ao Lu, Lufei Li, Zheng Zhang, Yexin Li, Kan Ren","pos":"#3608","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WCgtvP46NT","abs":"<p>Generating diverse responses is crucial for test-time scaling of large language models (LLMs), yet standard stochastic sampling mostly yields surface-level lexical variation, limiting semantic exploration and risking omission of correct solutions. In this paper, we propose Exploratory Sampling (ES), a decoding approach that explicitly encourages semantic diversity during generation. ES is motivated by the observation that neural networks tend to make more accurate predictions on inputs similar to those encountered before, and incur higher prediction error on novel ones. Building on this property, we train a lightweight Distiller at test time to predict deep-layer hidden representations of the LLM from its shallow-layer representations. During decoding, the Distiller continuously adapts to the mappings induced by the current generation context. ES uses the prediction error as a novelty signal to reweight candidate token extensions conditioned on the current prefix, thereby biasing decoding toward less-explored semantic patterns. ES is implemented with an asynchronous trainingвҖ“inference pipeline and introduces less than 5\\% throughput overhead in standard serving scenarios. Empirical results show that \\ES achieves robust generalization across mathematics, science, and code generation benchmarks. Notably, it breaks the trade-off between diversity and coherence in creative writing, and significantly boosts the Pass@k efficiency of reasoning models, showing superior or comparable per- formance to strong stochastic and heuristic baselines.</p>","absKo":"лӢӨм–‘н•ң мқ‘лӢөмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ large language model (LLM)мқҳ test-time scalingм—җ л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, н‘ңмӨҖ stochastic samplingмқҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ н‘ңл©ҙм Ғмқё lexical variationл§Ңмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ semantic explorationмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ҳкі  м •лӢө н•ҙлІ•мқ„ лҶ“м№  мң„н—ҳмқ„ лҶ’мқёлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” мғқм„ұ мӨ‘ semantic diversityлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мһҘл Өн•ҳлҠ” decoding approachмқё Exploratory Sampling (ES)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ESлҠ” neural networkк°Җ мқҙм „м—җ м ‘н–ҲлҚҳ мһ…л Ҙкіј мң мӮ¬н•ң мһ…л Ҙм—җм„ңлҠ” лҚ” м •нҷ•н•ң мҳҲмёЎмқ„ н•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мһ…л Ҙм—җм„ңлҠ” лҚ” нҒ° prediction errorлҘј лӮёлӢӨлҠ” кҙҖм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„ұм§Ҳмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” test timeм—җ LLMмқҳ shallow-layer representationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° deep-layer hidden representationмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” lightweight DistillerлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. decoding лҸҷм•Ҳ DistillerлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ мғқм„ұ contextм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗң mappingм—җ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘н•ңлӢӨ. ESлҠ” prediction errorлҘј novelty signalлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ нҳ„мһ¬ prefixм—җ мЎ°кұҙнҷ”лҗң candidate token extensionмқҳ к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳлҘј мһ¬мЎ°м •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, decodingмқҙ лҚң нғҗмғүлҗң semantic pattern мӘҪмңјлЎң нҺён–ҘлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. ESлҠ” asynchronous trainingвҖ“inference pipelineмңјлЎң кө¬нҳ„лҗҳл©°, standard serving scenarioм—җм„ң throughput overheadлҘј 5\\% лҜёл§ҢмңјлЎң м¶”к°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј \\ESлҠ” мҲҳн•ҷ, кіјн•ҷ, code generation benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң к°•кұҙн•ң generalizationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ creative writingм—җм„ң diversityмҷҖ coherence мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offлҘј к№Ёкі , reasoning modelмқҳ Pass@k нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңмјң к°•л Ҙн•ң stochastic л°Ҹ heuristic baselineліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҸҷл“ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61075","en":"Beyond Temperature: Hyperfitting as a Late-Stage Geometric Expansion","ko":"TemperatureлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ: нӣ„кё° лӢЁкі„ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ нҷ•мһҘмңјлЎңм„ңмқҳ Hyperfitting","authors":"Meimingwei Li, Yuanhao Ding, Esteban Garces Arias, Christian Heumann","pos":"#2103","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ttOGqk77go","abs":"Recent work has identified a counterintuitive phenomenon termed вҖңHyperfitting\", where fine-tuning Large Language Models (LLMs) to near-zero training loss on small datasets surprisingly enhances open-ended generation quality and mitigates repetition in greedy decoding. While effective, the underlying mechanism remains poorly understood, with the extremely low-entropy output distributions suggesting a potential equivalence to simple temperature scaling. In this work, we demonstrate that this phenomenon is fundamentally distinct from distribution sharpening; entropy-matched control experiments reveal that temperature scaling fails to replicate the diversity gains of hyperfitting. Furthermore, we falsify the hypothesis of static vocabulary reweighting, showing through ablation studies that hyperfitting relies on a dynamic, context-dependent rank reordering mechanism. Layer-wise analysis localizes this effect to a вҖңTerminal Expansion\" in the final transformer block, where a substantial geometric expansion of the feature space ($\\Delta \\mathrm{Dim} \\approx +80.8$) facilitates the promotion of deep-tail tokens. And we introduce \\textbf{Late-Stage LoRA}, a targeted fine-tuning strategy that updates only the final 5 layers, achieving robust generation with minimal parameter updates.","absKo":"мөңк·ј м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” вҖңHyperfittingвҖқмқҙлқј л¶ҲлҰ¬лҠ” м§ҒкҙҖм—җ л°ҳн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙ нҷ•мқёлҗҳм—ҲлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мһ‘мқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң Large Language Models (LLMs)лҘј кұ°мқҳ 0м—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ training lossк№Ңм§Җ fine-tuningн•ҳл©ҙ open-ended generation н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҙ лҶҖлһҚкІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗҳкі  greedy decodingм—җм„ң repetitionмқҙ мҷ„нҷ”лҗңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. нҡЁкіјлҠ” л¶„лӘ…н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё underlying mechanismмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ мһҳ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  мһҲмңјл©°, к·№лҸ„лЎң лӮ®мқҖ entropyмқҳ output distributionмқҖ лӢЁмҲңн•ң temperature scalingкіјмқҳ potential equivalenceлҘј мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқҙ к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң distribution sharpeningкіјлҠ” лӢӨлҘҙлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. entropy-matched control experimentsлҠ” temperature scalingмқҙ hyperfittingмқҳ diversity gainsлҘј мһ¬нҳ„н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” static vocabulary reweighting к°Җм„Өмқ„ л°ҳмҰқн•ҳл©°, ablation studiesлҘј нҶөн•ҙ hyperfittingмқҙ dynamicн•ҳкі  context-dependentн•ң rank reordering mechanismм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. layer-wise analysisлҠ” мқҙ нҡЁкіјлҘј мөңмў… transformer blockмқҳ вҖңTerminal ExpansionвҖқмңјлЎң көӯмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, м—¬кё°м„ң feature spaceмқҳ мғҒлӢ№н•ң geometric expansion($\\Delta \\mathrm{Dim} \\approx +80.8$)мқҙ deep-tail tokensмқҳ promotionмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{Late-Stage LoRA}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” л§Ҳм§Җл§ү 5к°ң layerл§Ң м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•ҳлҠ” targeted fine-tuning strategyлЎң, мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ parameter updateлЎңлҸ„ robust generationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"60888","en":"ViewMask-1-to-3: Multi-View Consistent Image Generation via Multimodal Diffusion Models","ko":"ViewMask-1-to-3: Multimodal Diffusion Modelмқ„ нҶөн•ң Multi-View Consistent Image Generation","authors":"Ruishu Zhu, Zhihao Huang, Jiacheng Sun, Ping Luo, Hongyuan Zhang, Xuelong Li","pos":"#1203","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vayyDtdtWX","abs":"<p>Motivated by discrete diffusion's success in language-vision modeling, we explore its potential for multi-view generation, a task dominated by continuous approaches. We introduce \\textbf{ViewMask-1-to-3}, formulating multi-view synthesis as a discrete sequence modeling problem where each viewpoint is represented as visual tokens from MAGVIT-v2. Through \\textbf{masked token prediction}, our approach \\textbf{enables progressive multi-view generation via iterative token unmasking}, unifying language and vision in a shared token space. Importantly, simple random masking combined with self-attention naturally encourages cross-view consistency without specialized architectures or 3D geometric priors. Our method outperforms the baseline on the GSO and 3D-FUTURE benchmarks, ranking first on average across standard image metrics and improving IoU by 10.6\\% on 3D-FUTURE. This validates discrete diffusion as a promising candidate for multi-view generation.</p>","absKo":"<p>language-vision modelingм—җм„ң discrete diffusionмқҳ м„ұкіөм—җ лҸҷкё°лҘј л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” continuous approachк°Җ м§Җл°°м Ғмқё multi-view generationм—җ лҢҖн•ң к·ё мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ нғҗкө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textbf{ViewMask-1-to-3}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, multi-view synthesisлҘј к°Ғ viewpointк°Җ MAGVIT-v2мқҳ visual tokenмңјлЎң н‘ңнҳ„лҗҳлҠ” discrete sequence modeling problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. \\textbf{masked token prediction}мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ \\textbf{iterative token unmaskingмқ„ нҶөн•ң м җм§„м Ғ multi-view generation}мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, languageмҷҖ visionмқ„ кіөмң  token spaceлЎң нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м җмқҖ, лӢЁмҲңн•ң random maskingкіј self-attentionмқҳ кІ°н•©л§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ нҠ№мҲҳн•ң architectureлӮҳ 3D geometric prior м—Ҷмқҙ view к°„ consistencyлҘј мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ мҙүм§„н•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ GSOмҷҖ 3D-FUTURE benchmarkм—җм„ң baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, н‘ңмӨҖ image metric нҸүк·  кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң 1мң„лҘј м°Ём§Җн•ҳкі  3D-FUTUREм—җм„ң IoUлҘј 10.6\\% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” discrete diffusionмқҙ multi-view generationмқҳ мң л§қн•ң candidateмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63124","en":"WUSH: Near-Optimal Adaptive Transforms for LLM Quantization","ko":"WUSH: LLM м–‘мһҗнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң мӨҖмөңм Ғ м Ғмқ‘нҳ• ліҖнҷҳ","authors":"Jiale Chen, Vage Egiazarian, Roberto Castro, Torsten Hoefler, Dan Alistarh","pos":"#1205","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZsECxUkbKB","abs":"Quantizing LLM weights and activations is a standard approach for efficient deployment, but a few extreme outliers can stretch the dynamic range and amplify low-bit quantization error. Prior transform-based mitigations (e.g., Hadamard rotations) are fixed and data-agnostic, and their optimality for quantization has remained unclear. We derive closed-form optimal linear blockwise transforms for joint weight-activation quantization under standard RTN AbsMax-scaled block quantizers, covering both integer and floating-point formats. The resulting construction, WUSH, combines a Hadamard backbone with a data-dependent second-moment component to form a non-orthogonal transform that is provably near-optimal for FP and INT quantizers under mild assumptions while admitting an efficient fused GPU implementation. Empirically, WUSH improves W4A4 accuracy over the strongest Hadamard-based baselines (e.g., on Llama-3.1-8B-Instruct in MXFP4, it gains +2.8 average points with RTN and +0.7 with GPTQ) while delivering up to 6.6$\\times$ per-layer throughput over BF16 via FP4 matmul.","absKo":"LLM weightмҷҖ activationмқ„ quantizingн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё л°°нҸ¬лҘј мң„н•ң н‘ңмӨҖ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, лӘҮлӘҮ к·№лӢЁм Ғ outlierк°Җ dynamic rangeлҘј лҠҳлҰ¬кі  low-bit quantization errorлҘј мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ transform кё°л°ҳ мҷ„нҷ” кё°лІ•(мҳҲ: Hadamard rotation)мқҖ кі м •лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲкі  data-agnosticн•ҳл©°, quantizationм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңм Ғм„ұмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ RTN AbsMax-scaled block quantizer н•ҳм—җм„ң weight-activation joint quantizationмқ„ мң„н•ң closed-form optimal linear blockwise transformмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳл©°, integer л°Ҹ floating-point formatмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіјлЎң м–»м–ҙм§„ WUSHлҠ” Hadamard backboneм—җ data-dependent second-moment componentлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳм—¬ л№„м§Ғкөҗ transformмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, mild assumption н•ҳм—җм„ң FP л°Ҹ INT quantizerм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ provably near-optimalн•ҳкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё fused GPU implementationмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң WUSHлҠ” к°ҖмһҘ к°•л Ҙн•ң Hadamard кё°л°ҳ baselineмқ„ мғҒнҡҢн•ҳлҠ” W4A4 м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ(мҳҲ: MXFP4мқҳ Llama-3.1-8B-Instructм—җм„ң RTN кё°мӨҖ нҸүк·  +2.8 point, GPTQ кё°мӨҖ +0.7 point н–ҘмғҒ). лҳҗн•ң FP4 matmulмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ BF16 лҢҖл№„ layerлӢ№ мөңлҢҖ 6.6$\\times$мқҳ мІҳлҰ¬лҹү н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65323","en":"Unbiased Dynamic Pruning for Efficient Group-Based Policy Optimization","ko":"нҡЁмңЁм Ғ к·ёлЈ№ кё°л°ҳ м •мұ… мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң л№„нҺён–Ҙ лҸҷм Ғ к°Җм§Җм№ҳкё°","authors":"Haodong Zhu, Ren Yangyang, Yanjing Li, Mingbao Lin, Linlin Yang, Xuhui Liu, Xiantong Zhen, haiguang liu, Baochang Zhang","pos":"#1301","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EmhfQoA0uC","abs":"Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) effectively scales LLM reasoning but incurs prohibitive computational costs due to its extensive group-based sampling requirement. While recent selective data utilization methods can mitigate this overhead, they could induce estimation bias by altering the underlying sampling distribution, compromising theoretical rigor and convergence behavior. To address this limitation, we propose Dynamic Pruning Policy Optimization (DPPO), a framework that enables dynamic pruning while preserving unbiased gradient estimation through importance sampling-based correction. By incorporating mathematically derived rescaling factors, DPPO significantly accelerates GRPO training without altering the optimization objective of the full-batch baseline. Furthermore, to mitigate the data sparsity induced by pruning, we introduce Dense Prompt Packing, a window-based greedy strategy that maximizes valid token density and hardware utilization. Extensive experiments demonstrate that DPPO consistently accelerates training across diverse models and benchmarks.  For instance, on Qwen3-4B trained on MATH, DPPO achieves 2.37$\\times$ training speedup and outperforms GRPO by 3.36\\% in average accuracy across six mathematical reasoning benchmarks.","absKo":"Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO)лҠ” LLM reasoningмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ group-based sampling мҡ”кө¬ л•Ңл¬ём—җ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ лҶ’м•„м§‘лӢҲлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ selective data utilization л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, underlying sampling distributionмқ„ ліҖкІҪн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ estimation biasлҘј мң л°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙ theoretical rigorмҷҖ convergence behaviorлҘј нӣјмҶҗн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” importance sampling кё°л°ҳ correctionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ unbiased gradient estimationмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң dynamic pruningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” Dynamic Pruning Policy Optimization (DPPO)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң мң лҸ„лҗң rescaling factorлҘј нҶөн•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, DPPOлҠ” full-batch baselineмқҳ optimization objectiveлҘј ліҖкІҪн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң GRPO trainingмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ к°ҖмҶҚн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, pruningмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” data sparsityлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, valid token densityмҷҖ hardware utilizationмқ„ к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” window-based greedy м „лһөмқё Dense Prompt Packingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ DPPOк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң лӘЁлҚёкіј benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ trainingмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, MATHлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң Qwen3-4Bм—җм„ң DPPOлҠ” 2.37$\\times$мқҳ training speedupмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , 6к°ңмқҳ mathematical reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ң нҸүк·  м •нҷ•лҸ„ кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң GRPOліҙлӢӨ 3.36\\% н–ҘмғҒлҗң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"66576","en":"Towards Efficient LLMs Annealing with Principled Sample Selection","ko":"мӣҗм№ҷм Ғ н‘ңліё м„ нғқмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ LLM м–ҙлӢҗл§Ғмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Yuanjian Xu, Jianing Hao, Wanbo Zhang, Zhong Li, Guang Zhang","pos":"#1305","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2UH01A9Za0","abs":"<p>The annealing stage of Large Language Model (LLM) training is a critical phase where model loss drops sharply and downstream capabilities solidify. Despite its importance, current practices rely on empirical heuristics like quality filtering or context extension, lacking a principled understanding of the underlying optimization dynamics. We address this gap by providing a theoretical characterization of the spectral properties targeted during annealing. We demonstrate that effective annealing requires balancing global Hessian geometry with sample-wise gradient noise, navigating a landscape of highly anisotropic curvature. Based on these insights, we formulate sample selection as a constrained optimization problem to suppress noise in sharp directions while preserving descent signals in flat subspaces. Our method, solved via Successive Convex Programming (SCP), achieves state-of-the-art results across multiple model scales. Code is available at \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/LLM-Annealing-Phase}.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Model (LLM) trainingмқҳ annealing stageлҠ” model lossк°Җ кёүкІ©нһҲ к°җмҶҢн•ҳкі  downstream capabilityк°Җ көім–ҙм§ҖлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң лӢЁкі„мқҙлӢӨ. к·ё мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ кҙҖн–үмқҖ quality filteringмқҙлӮҳ context extensionкіј к°ҷмқҖ кІҪн—ҳм Ғ heuristicм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, underlying optimization dynamicsм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғ мқҙн•ҙлҠ” л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” annealing лҸҷм•Ҳ н‘ңм Ғмқҙ лҗҳлҠ” spectral propertyм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ нҠ№м„ұмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё annealingмқҙ global Hessian geometryмҷҖ sample-wise gradient noise мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”л©ҙм„ң, highly anisotropic curvatureмқҳ landscapeлҘј нғҗмғүн•ҙм•ј н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” sharp directionм—җм„ңмқҳ noiseлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳл©ҙм„ң flat subspaceмқҳ descent signalмқҖ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ sample selectionмқ„ constrained optimization problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. Successive Convex Programming (SCP)мңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ model scaleм—җм„ң state-of-the-art кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/LLM-Annealing-Phase}м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64016","en":"TileQ: Efficient Low-Rank Quantization of Mixture-of-Experts with 2D Tiling","ko":"TileQ: 2D нғҖмқјл§Ғмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң Mixture-of-Expertsмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ м ҖлһӯнҒ¬ м–‘мһҗнҷ”","authors":"Hongyaoxing Gu, Xinzhe Chen, LIJUAN HU, Liu fangfang","pos":"#1308","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ReSBUj2514","abs":"<p>Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models achieve remarkable performance by sparsely activating specialized experts, yet their massive parameters in experts pose significant challenges for deployment. While low-rank quantization offers a promising route to compress MoE models, existing methods still incur nonnegligible memory overhead and inference latency. To address these limitations, we propose TileQ, a fine-tuning-free post-training quantization (PTQ) method that employs 2D-tiling structured low-rank quantization to share low-rank factors across both input and output dimensions of MoE experts. Furthermore, we introduce an efficient inference technique for TileQ that fuses multiple low-rank expert computations into a single-pass operation, significantly improving hardware utilization. Experiments show that TileQ cuts down additional memory usage up to 10x and reduces inference latency to 5% while preserving state-of-the-art accuracy.</p>","absKo":"<p>Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) лӘЁлҚёмқҖ нҠ№нҷ”лҗң expertл“Өмқ„ нқ¬мҶҢн•ҳкІҢ нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, expertмқҳ л§үлҢҖн•ң нҢҢлқјлҜён„° к·ңлӘЁлҠ” л°°нҸ¬ мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң нҒ° лҸ„м „ кіјм ңлҘј м ңкё°н•ңлӢӨ. low-rank quantizationмқҖ MoE лӘЁлҚёмқ„ м••м¶•н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ л¬ҙмӢңн•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңмҷҖ м¶”лЎ  м§Җм—°мқ„ мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MoE expertмқҳ мһ…л Ҙ л°Ҹ м¶ңл Ҙ м°Ёмӣҗ м–‘мӘҪм—җ кұёміҗ low-rank factorлҘј кіөмң н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ 2D-tiling structured low-rank quantizationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” fine-tuning-free post-training quantization (PTQ) л°©лІ•мқё TileQлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң TileQлҘј мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё м¶”лЎ  кё°лІ•мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, м—¬лҹ¬ low-rank expert кі„мӮ°мқ„ лӢЁмқј нҢЁмҠӨ м—°мӮ°мңјлЎң мңөн•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н•ҳл“ңмӣЁм–ҙ нҷңмҡ©лҸ„лҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, TileQлҠ” м¶”к°Җ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҹүмқ„ мөңлҢҖ 10л°°к№Ңм§Җ мӨ„мқҙкі  м¶”лЎ  м§Җм—°мқ„ 5% мҲҳмӨҖмңјлЎң к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ state-of-the-art м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61150","en":"The Differences Between Direct Alignment Algorithms are a Blur","ko":"Direct Alignment м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ к°„ м°ЁмқҙлҠ” нқҗлҰҝн•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Alexey Gorbatovski, Boris Shaposhnikov, Viacheslav Sinii, Alexey Malakhov, Daniil Gavrilov","pos":"#1411","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tCXxWWBjxQ","abs":"Direct Alignment Algorithms (DAAs) simplify LLM alignment by directly optimizing policies, bypassing reward modeling and RL. While DAAs differ in their use of SFT (one-stage vs. two-stage) and the scalar score they optimize (likelihood vs. odds ratios), the key performance drivers remain underexplored. We present a systematic comparison and analyze a previously overlooked axis - the ranking objective (pairwise vs. pointwise). To isolate this factor, we propose a unified training framework across DAAs by (i) converting one-stage methods (ORPO, ASFT) into a two-stage pipeline with an explicit SFT phase and (ii) introducing a $\\beta$ parameter that places all methods in the same hyperparameter space and improves the quality of odds-ratio DAAs (ORPO, ASFT). Under this setup, the ranking objective emerges as the primary determinant of alignment quality, whereas the particular scalar score (policyвҖ“reference ratio vs. odds ratio) is secondary. We corroborate this on instruction-following tasks and further confirm it on math-reasoning benchmarks across model scales. Evidence suggests that this stems from how these objectives interact with prompt-specific biases, supported both by strictly controlled experiments and by observations on real data. Our findings underscore the need for nuanced evaluations in DAA research to avoid oversimplified claims of superiority.","absKo":"Direct Alignment Algorithms(DAAs)лҠ” reward modelingкіј RLмқ„ мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳкі  policyлҘј м§Ғм ‘ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ LLM alignmentлҘј лӢЁмҲңнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. DAAsлҠ” SFTлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқ(one-stage лҢҖ two-stage)кіј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” scalar score(likelihood лҢҖ odds ratio)м—җм„ң м°Ёмқҙк°Җ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, н•өмӢ¬ м„ұлҠҘ мҡ”мқёмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мІҙкі„м Ғмқё л№„көҗлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , мқҙм „м—җ к°„кіјлҗҳм—ҲлҚҳ н•ң м¶•мқё ranking objective(pairwise лҢҖ pointwise)лҘј л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мҡ”мқёмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” (i) one-stage method(ORPO, ASFT)лҘј лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё SFT phaseлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң two-stage pipelineмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳкі , (ii) лӘЁл“  methodлҘј лҸҷмқјн•ң hyperparameter spaceм—җ лҶ“кі  odds-ratio DAA(ORPO, ASFT)мқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” $\\beta$ parameterлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң DAAs м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң unified training frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өм •м—җм„ң ranking objectiveк°Җ alignment qualityмқҳ мЈјлҗң кІ°м • мҡ”мқёмңјлЎң л“ңлҹ¬лӮҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, нҠ№м • scalar score(policy-reference ratio лҢҖ odds ratio)лҠ” л¶Җм°Ём ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј instruction-following taskм—җм„ң мһ…мҰқн•ҳкі , лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ model scale м „л°ҳмқҳ math-reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ңлҸ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мҰқкұ°лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјк°Җ prompt-specific biasмҷҖ objectiveк°Җ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗЁмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” м—„кІ©нһҲ нҶөм ңлҗң мӢӨн—ҳкіј мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙҖм°° лӘЁл‘җлЎң л’·л°ӣм№ЁлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ findingsлҠ” DAA м—°кө¬м—җм„ң кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ лӢЁмҲңнҷ”лҗң мҡ°мӣ”м„ұ мЈјмһҘм—җ л№ м§Җм§Җ м•ҠлҸ„лЎқ, лҜёл¬ҳн•ң нҸүк°Җк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•Ёмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64407","en":"SAME: Stabilized Mixture-of-Experts for Multimodal Continual Instruction Tuning","ko":"SAME: л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ м§ҖмҶҚ лӘ…л №м–ҙ нҠңлӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң м•Ҳм •нҷ”лҗң Mixture-of-Experts","authors":"Zhen-Hao Xie Xie, Jun-Tao Tang, Yu-Cheng Shi, Han-Jia Ye, De-Chuan Zhan, Da-Wei Zhou","pos":"#1503","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Nvim88fA66","abs":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) achieve strong performance through instruction tuning, but real-world deployment requires them to continually expand their capabilities, making Multimodal Continual Instruction Tuning (MCIT) essential. Recent methods leverage sparse expert routing to promote task specialization, but we find that the expert routing process suffers from drift as the data distribution evolves. For example, a grounding query that previously activated localization experts may instead be routed to irrelevant experts after learning OCR tasks. Meanwhile, the grounding-related experts can be overwritten by new tasks and lose their original functionality. Such failure reflects two problems: router drift, where expert selection becomes inconsistent over time, and expert drift, where shared experts are overwritten across tasks. Therefore, we propose StAbilized Mixture-of-Experts (SAME) for MCIT. To address router drift, SAME stabilizes expert selection by decomposing routing dynamics into orthogonal subspaces and updating only task-relevant directions. To mitigate expert drift, we regulate expert updates via curvature-aware scaling using historical input covariance in a rehearsal-free manner. SAME also introduces adaptive expert activation to freeze selected experts during training, reducing redundant computation and cross-task interference. Extensive experiments demonstrate its SOTA performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Model (MLLM)мқҖ instruction tuningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ң л°°нҸ¬м—җм„ңлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң Multimodal Continual Instruction Tuning (MCIT)мқҙ н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мөңк·ј л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ sparse expert routingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ task specializationмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” data distributionмқҙ ліҖнҷ”н•Ём—җ л”°лқј expert routing кіјм •мқҙ driftлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, мқҙм „м—җлҠ” localization expertлҘј нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•ҳлҚҳ grounding queryк°Җ OCR taskлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ң нӣ„м—җлҠ” кҙҖл Ё м—ҶлҠ” expertлЎң лқјмҡ°нҢ…лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. н•ңнҺё grounding кҙҖл Ё expertлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskм—җ мқҳн•ҙ лҚ®м–ҙмҚЁм ё мӣҗлһҳ кё°лҠҘмқ„ мһғмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢӨнҢЁлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ л¬ём ңлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” мӢңк°„мқҙ м§ҖлӮҳл©° expert selectionмқҙ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ мһғлҠ” router driftмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ shared expertк°Җ лҚ®м–ҙмҚЁм§ҖлҠ” expert driftмқҙлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MCITлҘј мң„н•ң StAbilized Mixture-of-Experts (SAME)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. router driftлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, SAMEмқҖ routing dynamicsлҘј orthogonal subspaceлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳкі  taskмҷҖ кҙҖл Ёлҗң л°©н–Ҙл§Ң м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ expert selectionмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. expert driftлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” rehearsal-free л°©мӢқмңјлЎң historical input covarianceлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң curvature-aware scalingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ expert updateлҘј мЎ°м Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SAMEмқҖ лҳҗн•ң training лҸҷм•Ҳ м„ нғқлҗң expertлҘј кі м •н•ҳм—¬ redundant computationкіј cross-task interferenceлҘј мӨ„мқҙлҠ” adaptive expert activationмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SAMEмқҙ SOTA м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61934","en":"Probability-Entropy Calibration: An Elastic Indicator for Adaptive Fine-tuning","ko":"Probability-Entropy Calibration: м Ғмқ‘нҳ• нҢҢмқёнҠңлӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң Elastic м§Җн‘ң","authors":"Wenhao Yu, Shaohang Wei, Jiahong Liu, Yifan Li, Minda Hu, Aiwei Liu, Hao Zhang, Irwin King","pos":"#1513","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lYBn5XSfEv","abs":"<p>Token-level reweighting is a simple yet effective mechanism for controlling supervised fine-tuning, but common indicators are largely one-dimensional: the ground-truth probability reflects downstream alignment, while token entropy reflects intrinsic uncertainty induced by the pre-training prior. Ignoring entropy can misidentify noisy or easily replaceable tokens as learning-critical, while ignoring probability fails to reflect target-specific alignment. RankTuner introduces a probability--entropy calibration signal, the <strong>Relative Rank Indicator</strong>, by comparing the rank of the ground-truth token with its expected rank under the predictiondiction distribution. The inverse indicator is used as a token-wise <strong>Relative Scale</strong> to reweight the fine-tuning objective, focusing updates on truly under-learned tokens without over-penalizing intrinsically uncertain positions. Experiments on multiple backbones show consistent improvements on mathematical reasoning benchmarks, transfer gains on out-of-distribution reasoning, and pre code generation performance over probability- or entropy-only reweighting baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>token-level reweightingмқҖ supervised fine-tuningмқ„ м ңм–ҙн•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м§Җн‘ңлҠ” лҢҖмІҙлЎң мқјм°Ёмӣҗм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. ground-truth probabilityлҠ” downstream alignmentлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳкі , token entropyлҠ” pre-training priorм—җм„ң мң лҸ„лҗҳлҠ” лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқ„ л°ҳмҳҒн•ңлӢӨ. entropyлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳл©ҙ noisyн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мүҪкІҢ лҢҖмІҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң tokenмқ„ н•ҷмҠөм—җ н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё кІғмңјлЎң мһҳлӘ» нҢҗлӢЁн•  мҲҳ мһҲкі , probabilityлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳл©ҙ target-specific alignmentлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. RankTunerлҠ” ground-truth tokenмқҳ rankмҷҖ prediction distribution н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ кё°лҢҖ rankлҘј л№„көҗн•ҳм—¬, probability--entropy calibration signalмқё <strong>Relative Rank Indicator</strong>лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. к·ё м—ӯм§Җн‘ңлҠ” token-wise <strong>Relative Scale</strong>лЎң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм–ҙ fine-tuning objectiveлҘј мһ¬к°ҖмӨ‘н•ҳл©°, ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨн•ң мң„м№ҳлҘј кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ нҺҳл„җнӢ°н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң мӢӨм ңлЎң лҚң н•ҷмҠөлҗң tokenм—җ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҘј м§‘мӨ‘мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ backboneм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ  benchmarkм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒ, out-of-distribution м¶”лЎ мңјлЎңмқҳ transfer н–ҘмғҒ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  probability-only лҳҗлҠ” entropy-only reweighting baseline лҢҖл№„ pre code generation м„ұлҠҘ к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65313","en":"Principled SVD-based Delta Compression via Quantization Error Minimization","ko":"м–‘мһҗнҷ” мҳӨм°Ё мөңмҶҢнҷ”лҘј нҶөн•ң мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғ SVD кё°л°ҳ Delta м••м¶•","authors":"Boya Xiong, Shuo Wang, Weifeng Ge, Guanhua CHEN, Yun Chen","pos":"#1514","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ErqvESaJpk","abs":"Supervised Fine-Tuning (SFT) empowers Large Language Models (LLMs) with exceptional performance on specialized tasks, but it yields dense, high-dimensional delta parameters that pose severe storage and distribution challenges. Singular Value Decomposition (SVD)-based compression offers a compact representation for such delta parameters, but existing methods adopt heuristic quantization without clarifying underlying mechanisms, leading to poor generalizability. In this work, we propose PrinMix, a rigorous SVD-based framework that models quantization as an optimization problem, grounding the design in mathematical mechanisms. We first theoretically derive quantization error and identify a key singular-value-dominated scaling mechanism, which mathematically proves the necessity of mix-precision quantization. We then model the quantization scheme as a 0/1 Integer Linear Programming (ILP) problem, which yields optimal bit-budget-constrained solutions without empirical assumptions. Furthermore, PrinMix integrates a Reconstruction Target Correction (RTC) method to compensate for errors from the $\\mathbf{V}$-then-$\\mathbf{U}$ sequential quantization process.  Extensive experiments confirm PrinMix performs well: for 7B LLMs, PrinMix outperforms SOTA Delta-CoMe on challenging benchmarks by 22.3\\% on AIME2024 and 6.1\\% on GQA.","absKo":"Supervised Fine-Tuning(SFT)мқҖ Large Language Models(LLMs)м—җ нҠ№нҷ” taskм—җм„ң нғҒмӣ”н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, лҸҷмӢңм—җ м ҖмһҘкіј л°°нҸ¬м—җ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ҳлҠ” denseн•ң кі м°Ёмӣҗ delta parameterлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. Singular Value Decomposition(SVD) кё°л°ҳ м••м¶•мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң delta parameterлҘј мң„н•ң к°„кІ°н•ң н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ к·јліё л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мұ„ нңҙлҰ¬мҠӨнӢұн•ң quantizationмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ҳм—¬ мқјл°ҳнҷ” к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ лӮ®лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” quantizationмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ” л¬ём ңлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” м—„л°Җн•ң SVD кё°л°ҳ frameworkмқё PrinMixлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, м„Өкі„лҘј мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳм—җ кё°л°ҳмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң quantization errorлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳкі  singular valueк°Җ м§Җл°°н•ҳлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ scaling mechanismмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳм—¬, mix-precision quantizationмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң quantization schemeмқ„ 0/1 Integer Linear Programming(ILP) л¬ём ңлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳм—¬, кІҪн—ҳм Ғ к°Җм • м—Ҷмқҙ мөңм Ғмқҳ bit-budget м ңм•Ҫ н•ҙлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң PrinMixлҠ” $\\mathbf{V}$-then-$\\mathbf{U}$ мҲңм°Ё quantization processм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” errorлҘј ліҙм •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ Reconstruction Target Correction(RTC) л°©лІ•мқ„ нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PrinMixмқҳ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. 7B LLMм—җм„ң PrinMixлҠ” к№ҢлӢӨлЎңмҡҙ benchmarkмқё AIME2024м—җм„ң 22.3\\%, GQAм—җм„ң 6.1\\%лЎң SOTA Delta-CoMeлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65474","en":"PISA: Privacy-Preserving Split Adaptation with Model IP Protection","ko":"PISA: лӘЁлҚё IP ліҙнҳёлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң ліҙмЎҙ Split Adaptation","authors":"Haocheng Yang, Xiang Cheng, ZONGDA HAN, Pengjie Wang, Changkang Chi, Pengfei Zhang, Sen Su","pos":"#1613","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=DG7S1hhwUL","abs":"<p>Fine-tuning Large Language Models (LLMs) enables data holders to construct proprietary, task-specific models by leveraging external high-performance computing infrastructure.  However, existing paradigms typically address data privacy and model intellectual property (IP) in isolation, failing to simultaneously uphold both constraints. Privacy-prioritized methods compromise model IP by hosting parameters remotely, while IP-oriented collaborative schemes relying on end-to-end gradient flows inherently violate strict data privacy standards. To address these challenges, we present <strong>PISA</strong> (<strong>P</strong>rivacy-preserving and <strong>I</strong>P-protected <strong>S</strong>plit <strong>A</strong>daptation), a split fine-tuning framework designed to preserve both data privacy and model IP while maintaining high utility. In PISA, we propose three methods: a Manifold Rectification Pre-training (MRP) method to equip the server-side model with intrinsic robustness against privacy-induced distribution shifts; a Dual-Stream Semantic Compensation (DSC) method to recover feature utility using local clean data as priors; and a Utility-Aware Gradient Rectification (UGR) method to adaptively maximize the performance of the parameter-constrained local model. Experiments on GLUE show that PISA ensures dual protection and delivers a substantial 23.0\\% performance gain over the privacy-prioritized baseline under strict privacy budgets.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Model(LLM) fine-tuningмқҖ data holderк°Җ мҷёл¶Җ кі м„ұлҠҘ м»ҙн“ЁнҢ… мқён”„лқјлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ лҸ…м җм Ғмқҙкі  task-specificн•ң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң data privacyмҷҖ model intellectual property(IP)лҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҙм„ң лӢӨлЈЁл©°, л‘җ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ лҸҷмӢңм—җ л§ҢмЎұмӢңнӮӨм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. privacyлҘј мҡ°м„ н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқҖ parameterлҘј мӣҗкІ©м—җ нҳёмҠӨнҢ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ model IPлҘј нӣјмҶҗн•ҳкі , end-to-end gradient flowм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” IP м§Җн–Ҙ collaborative schemeмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м—„кІ©н•ң data privacy standardлҘј мң„л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„° privacyмҷҖ model IPлҘј лӘЁл‘җ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҶ’мқҖ utilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң split fine-tuning frameworkмқё <strong>PISA</strong>(<strong>P</strong>rivacy-preserving and <strong>I</strong>P-protected <strong>S</strong>plit <strong>A</strong>daptation)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. PISAм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. privacyлЎң мң лҸ„лҗң distribution shiftм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ server-side modelм—җ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ҳлҠ” Manifold Rectification Pre-training(MRP) л°©лІ•, local clean dataлҘј priorлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ feature utilityлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” Dual-Stream Semantic Compensation(DSC) л°©лІ•, к·ёлҰ¬кі  parameter-constrained local modelмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” Utility-Aware Gradient Rectification(UGR) л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. GLUE мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң PISAлҠ” мқҙмӨ‘ ліҙнҳёлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳл©°, м—„кІ©н•ң privacy budget н•ҳм—җм„ң privacy-prioritized baseline лҢҖл№„ 23.0\\%мқҳ мғҒлӢ№н•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66254","en":"Midtraining Bridges Pretraining and Posttraining Distributions","ko":"MidtrainingмқҖ мӮ¬м „ нӣҲл Ёкіј мӮ¬нӣ„ нӣҲл Ё л¶„нҸ¬лҘј м—°кІ°н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Emmy Liu, Graham Neubig, Chenyan Xiong","pos":"#1700","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5PfEQzE9bf","abs":"<p>Midtraining, the practice of mixing specialized data with more general pretraining data in an intermediate training phase, has become widespread in language model development, yet there is little understanding of what makes it effective. We propose that midtraining functions as distributional bridging by providing better initialization for posttraining. We conduct controlled pretraining experiments, and find that midtraining benefits are largest for domains distant from general pretraining data, such as code and math, and scale with the proximity advantage the midtraining data provides toward the target distribution. In these domains, midtraining consistently outperforms continued pretraining on specialized data alone both in-domain and in terms of mitigating forgetting. We further conduct an investigation on the starting time and mixture weight of midtraining data, using code as a case study, and find that time of introduction and mixture weight interact strongly such that early introduction of specialized data is amenable to high mixture weights, while late introduction requires lower ones. This suggests that late introduction of specialized data outside a plasticity window cannot be compensated for by increasing data mixtures later in training. Beyond midtraining itself, this suggests that distributional transitions between any training phases may benefit from similar bridging strategies.</p>","absKo":"<p>MidtrainingмқҖ мӨ‘к°„ н•ҷмҠө лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң нҠ№мҲҳнҷ”лҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖ ліҙлӢӨ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё pretraining лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј м„һлҠ” кҙҖн–үмңјлЎң, language model к°ңл°ңм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳкі  мһҲм§Җл§Ң, к·ёкІғмқҙ мҷң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқём§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” м•„м§Ғ мқҙн•ҙк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” midtrainingмқҙ posttrainingмқ„ мң„н•ң лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ мҙҲкё°нҷ”лҘј м ңкіөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ distributional bridgingмңјлЎң кё°лҠҘн•ңлӢӨкі  м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҶөм ңлҗң pretraining мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬, midtrainingмқҳ мқҙм җмқҙ codeмҷҖ mathмІҳлҹј мқјл°ҳ pretraining лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖ л©ҖлҰ¬ л–Ём–ҙм§„ лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ нҒ¬л©°, midtraining лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ лӘ©н‘ң л¶„нҸ¬м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” proximity advantageм—җ л№„лЎҖн•ҙ м»Өм§„лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ңлҠ” midtrainingмқҙ лҸ„л©”мқё лӮҙл¶Җ м„ұлҠҘкіј forgetting мҷ„нҷ” мёЎл©ҙ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң нҠ№мҲҳнҷ”лҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°л§ҢмңјлЎң continued pretrainingн•ҳлҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҡ°мҲҳн–ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң codeлҘј мӮ¬лЎҖ м—°кө¬лЎң мӮјм•„ midtraining лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ мӢңмһ‘ мӢңм җкіј mixture weightлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ң кІ°кіј, лҸ„мһ… мӢңм җкіј mixture weightк°Җ к°•н•ҳкІҢ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, нҠ№мҲҳнҷ”лҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мқјм°Қ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳл©ҙ лҶ’мқҖ mixture weightлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳкё° мүҪм§Җл§Ң, лҠҰкІҢ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳл©ҙ лҚ” лӮ®мқҖ weightк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” plasticity window л°–м—җм„ң нҠ№мҲҳнҷ”лҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј лҠҰкІҢ лҸ„мһ…н•ң кІҪмҡ°, мқҙнӣ„ н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң data mixtureлҘј лҠҳлҰ¬лҠ” кІғл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” ліҙмғҒн•  мҲҳ м—ҶмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. midtraining мһҗмІҙлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ, мқҙлҠ” м–ҙл–Ө training phase мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ distributional transitionлҸ„ мң мӮ¬н•ң bridging м „лһөмқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ л°ӣмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64590","en":"LoRA-DA: Data-Aware Initialization for Low-Rank Adaptation via Asymptotic Analysis","ko":"LoRA-DA: м җк·јм Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ң Low-Rank Adaptationмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„° мқёмӢқ мҙҲкё°нҷ”","authors":"Qingyue Zhang, Chang Chu, Tianren Peng, Qi Li, Xiangyang Luo, Zhihao Jiang, Shao-Lun Huang","pos":"#1706","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=LvKSVUbXc9","abs":"<p>LoRA has become a widely adopted method for PEFT, and its initialization methods have attracted increasing attention.  However, existing methods have notable limitations:  many methods do not incorporate target-domain data, while gradient-based methods exploit data only at a shallow level by relying on one-step gradient decomposition. In this paper, we establish a theoretical framework for data-aware LoRA initialization.  Starting from minimizing the expectation of the parameter discrepancy between the fine-tuned and target models, we derive an optimization problem with two components: a bias term, which is related to the parameter distance between the fine-tuned and target models, and is approximated using a FisherвҖ“gradient formulation to preserve anisotropy; and a variance term, which accounts for the uncertainty introduced by sampling stochasticity through the Fisher information. Solving this problem yields an optimal initialization strategy for LoRA, based on which we develop an efficient algorithm, LoRA-DA. Empirical results across multiple benchmarks demonstrate that LoRA-DA consistently improves final accuracy over existing initialization methods. Additional studies show faster, more stable convergence, robustness across ranks, and only a small initialization overhead for LoRA-DA. The source code will be released upon publication.</p>","absKo":"LoRAлҠ” PEFTлҘј мң„н•ң л„җлҰ¬ мұ„нғқлҗң л°©лІ•мқҙ лҗҳм—Ҳкі , к·ё initialization methodлҠ” м җм җ лҚ” нҒ° мЈјлӘ©мқ„ л°ӣкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•м—җлҠ” лҡңл ·н•ң н•ңкі„к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. л§ҺмқҖ л°©лІ•мқҙ target-domain dataлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳл©°, gradient-based methodлҠ” one-step gradient decompositionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј н”јмғҒм ҒмңјлЎңл§Ң нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” data-aware LoRA initializationмқ„ мң„н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ frameworkлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. fine-tuned modelкіј target model мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ parameter discrepancyмқҳ кё°лҢ“к°’мқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғм—җм„ң м¶ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢлҘј к°–лҠ” optimization problemмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” fine-tuned modelкіј target model мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ parameter distanceмҷҖ кҙҖл Ёлҗң bias termмңјлЎң, anisotropyлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ FisherвҖ“gradient formulationмңјлЎң к·јмӮ¬лҗңлӢӨ. лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” Fisher informationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ sampling stochasticityлЎңл¶Җн„° мң лҸ„лҗҳлҠ” л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқ„ л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ” variance termмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н’Җл©ҙ LoRAлҘј мң„н•ң мөңм Ғ initialization strategyк°Җ лҸ„м¶ңлҗҳл©°, мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё algorithmмқё LoRA-DAлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” LoRA-DAк°Җ кё°мЎҙ initialization methodліҙлӢӨ мөңмў… м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. м¶”к°Җ м—°кө¬лҠ” лҚ” л№ лҘҙкі  м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё мҲҳл ҙ, rank м „л°ҳмқҳ к°•кұҙм„ұ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  LoRA-DAм—җ лҢҖн•ң мһ‘мқҖ initialization overheadлҘј нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мҶҢмҠӨ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” publication мӢң кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64288","en":"Learning in the Fisher Subspace: A Guided Initialization for LoRA Fine-Tuning","ko":"Fisher л¶Җл¶„кіөк°„м—җм„ңмқҳ н•ҷмҠө: LoRA лҜём„ёмЎ°м •мқ„ мң„н•ң мң лҸ„лҗң мҙҲкё°нҷ”","authors":"Zhi-Quan Feng, Ying-Jia Lin, Hung-Yu Kao","pos":"#1708","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=P76Q8Pi1E9","abs":"<p>LoRA adapts large language models (LLMs) by restricting updates to low-rank subspaces of pre-trained weights. While this substantially reduces training cost, the effectiveness of adaptation critically depends on which subspace is chosen at initialization: a poor initialization that allocates capacity to task-irrelevant directions can severely hinder downstream performance. Existing initialization strategies primarily rely on the intrinsic properties of pre-trained weights, implicitly assuming that weight geometry alone reflects task relevance. However, such criteria overlook how the model interacts with the downstream data distribution. In this work, we formulate LoRA initialization as the problem of identifying directions in parameter space that are the most impactful under the target data distribution. We argue that data-aware sensitivity, rather than weight-only magnitude, should govern the choice of adaptation subspaces. Building on this perspective, we propose a Fisher-guided framework that leverages curvature information induced by downstream data to characterize how parameter perturbations influence model predictions. This perspective yields a principled, task-dependent criterion for selecting LoRA directions that better align adaptation with the target objective. Empirical results across diverse tasks and modalities demonstrate that data-aware initialization consistently and significantly improves downstream performance over existing approaches.</p>","absKo":"<p>LoRAлҠ” pre-trained weightмқҳ low-rank subspaceлЎң updateлҘј м ңн•ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ large language model (LLM)мқ„ м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” training costлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„м—¬ мЈјм§Җл§Ң, adaptationмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҠ” мҙҲкё°нҷ” мӢң м–ҙл–Ө subspaceлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠҗлғҗм—җ кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң мўҢмҡ°лҗңлӢӨ. taskмҷҖ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ң л°©н–Ҙм—җ capacityлҘј л°°л¶„н•ҳлҠ” мўӢм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мҙҲкё°нҷ”лҠ” downstream м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ м Җн•ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ мҙҲкё°нҷ” м „лһөмқҖ мЈјлЎң pre-trained weightмқҳ intrinsic propertyм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, weight geometry мһҗмІҙк°Җ task relevanceлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ңлӢӨкі  м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң к°Җм •н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кё°мӨҖмқҖ modelмқҙ downstream data distributionкіј м–ҙл–»кІҢ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” LoRA мҙҲкё°нҷ”лҘј target data distribution н•ҳм—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ нҒ° мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ” parameter spaceмқҳ л°©н–Ҙмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” weightмқҳ нҒ¬кё°л§Ңмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј data-aware sensitivityк°Җ adaptation subspace м„ нғқмқ„ м§Җл°°н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм җм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” downstream dataм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗң curvature informationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ parameter perturbationмқҙ model predictionм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” Fisher-guided frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм җмқҖ adaptationмқ„ target objectiveмҷҖ лҚ” мһҳ м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” LoRA л°©н–Ҙмқ„ м„ нғқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқҙкі  task-dependentн•ң кё°мӨҖмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң taskмҷҖ modality м „л°ҳмқҳ мӢӨмҰқ кІ°кіјлҠ” data-aware initializationмқҙ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јліҙлӢӨ downstream performanceлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к·ёлҰ¬кі  мң мқҳлҜён•ҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62729","en":"Learning from Fine-Grained Visual Discrepancies: Mitigating Multimodal Hallucinations via In-Context Visual Contrastive Optimization","ko":"м„ёл°Җн•ң Visual discrepancyлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠө: In-Context Visual Contrastive Optimizationмқ„ нҶөн•ң л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ Hallucination мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Haolin Deng, Xin Zou, Zhiwei Jin, Chen Chen, Haonan Lu, Xuming Hu","pos":"#1709","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=dtHEthIjmu","abs":"<p>Multimodal hallucination remains a persistent challenge for Vision-Language Models (VLMs). Standard textual Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) often fails to mitigate it due to a lack of explicit visual supervision.  While existing works introduce visual preference DPO by contrasting original images against negative ones, they suffer from a theoretically inconsistent objective caused by partition function mismatches and relies on coarse-grained negatives that could enable shortcut learning. In this work, we propose In-Context Visual Contrastive Optimization (IC-VCO). By placing contrastive images within a shared multi-image context, IC-VCO ensures a mathematically rigorous objective. Furthermore, we introduce Visual Contrast Distillation (VCDist), a mechanism which transfers the superior discriminatory power of the multi-image context to the single-image policy via reliability-gated self-distillation, enforcing consistent visual grounding. Finally, we propose a contrastive sample editing strategy that generates hard negatives via precise semantic perturbations. Experiments on five benchmarks demonstrate IC-VCO's superior performance and the effectiveness of our sample editing strategy.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal hallucinationмқҖ Vision-Language Model (VLM)м—җм„ң м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё лҸ„м „ кіјм ңлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ textual Direct Preference Optimization (DPO)мқҖ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё visual supervisionмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬ л•Ңл¬ём—җ мқҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мў…мў… мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ мӣҗліё imageмҷҖ negative imageлҘј лҢҖл№„мӢңнӮӨлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң visual preference DPOлҘј лҸ„мһ…н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, partition function mismatchлЎң мқён•ҙ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мқјкҙҖлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ objectiveлҘј к°Җм§Җл©°, лҳҗн•ң shortcut learningмқ„ мң л°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” coarse-grained negativeм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” In-Context Visual Contrastive Optimization (IC-VCO)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. contrastive imageлҘј кіөмң  multi-image context м•Ҳм—җ л°°м№ҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ IC-VCOлҠ” мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң м—„л°Җн•ң objectiveлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Visual Contrast Distillation (VCDist)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” reliability-gated self-distillationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ multi-image contextмқҳ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң нҢҗлі„ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ single-image policyлЎң м „мқҙмӢңмјң мқјкҙҖлҗң visual groundingмқ„ к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м •л°Җн•ң semantic perturbationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ hard negativeлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” contrastive sample editing м „лһөмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм„Ҝ к°ң benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ IC-VCOмқҳ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘкіј sample editing м „лһөмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63125","en":"LK Losses: Direct Acceptance Rate Optimization for Speculative Decoding","ko":"LK мҶҗмӢӨ: Speculative Decodingмқ„ мң„н•ң м§Ғм ‘ мҲҳлқҪлҘ  мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Alexander Samarin, Sergei Krutikov, Anton Shevtsov, Sergei Skvortsov, Filipp Fisin, Aleksandr Golubev","pos":"#1715","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZqnVidXtxV","abs":"<p>Speculative decoding accelerates autoregressive large language model (LLM) inference by using a lightweight draft model to propose candidate tokens that are then verified in parallel by the target model.  The speedup is significantly determined by the acceptance rate, yet standard training minimizes Kullback-Leibler (KL) divergence as a proxy objective.  While KL divergence and acceptance rate share the same global optimum, small draft models, having limited capacity, typically converge to suboptimal solutions where minimizing KL does not guarantee maximizing acceptance rate. To address this issue, we propose <strong>LK losses</strong>, special training objectives that directly target acceptance rate. Comprehensive experiments across four draft architectures and six target models, ranging from 8B to 685B parameters, demonstrate consistent improvements in acceptance metrics across all configurations compared to the standard KL-based training. We evaluate our approach on general, coding and math domains and report gains of up to 10\\% in average acceptance length. LK losses are easy to implement, introduce no computational overhead and can be directly integrated into any existing speculator training framework, making them a compelling alternative to the existing draft training objectives.</p>","absKo":"Speculative decodingмқҖ кІҪлҹү draft modelмқҙ candidate tokenмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳкі  target modelмқҙ мқҙлҘј лі‘л ¬лЎң кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң autoregressive large language model(LLM) inferenceлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ңлӢӨ. мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқҖ acceptance rateм—җ мқҳн•ҙ нҒ¬кІҢ кІ°м •лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, н‘ңмӨҖ н•ҷмҠөмқҖ лҢҖлҰ¬ лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳлЎң Kullback-Leibler(KL) divergenceлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. KL divergenceмҷҖ acceptance rateлҠ” к°ҷмқҖ global optimumмқ„ кіөмң н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мҡ©лҹүмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗң мһ‘мқҖ draft modelмқҖ ліҙнҶө KL мөңмҶҢнҷ”к°Җ acceptance rate мөңлҢҖнҷ”лҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” suboptimal solutionмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” acceptance rateлҘј м§Ғм ‘ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳлҠ” нҠ№мҲҳн•ң н•ҷмҠө лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳмқё <strong>LK losses</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. 8Bл¶Җн„° 685B нҢҢлқјлҜён„°к№Ңм§Җмқҳ л„Ө к°Җм§Җ draft architectureмҷҖ м—¬м„Ҝ к°ң target modelм—җ кұём№ң мў…н•© мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң, н‘ңмӨҖ KL кё°л°ҳ н•ҷмҠөкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ лӘЁл“  м„Өм •м—җм„ң acceptance metricмқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқјл°ҳ лҸ„л©”мқё, coding, math лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ң м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ нҸүк°Җн–Ҳкі , average acceptance lengthк°Җ мөңлҢҖ 10\\% мҰқк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙкі н•ңлӢӨ. LK lossesлҠ” кө¬нҳ„мқҙ мүҪкі  кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңк°Җ м—Ҷмңјл©°, кё°мЎҙмқҳ лӘЁл“  speculator training frameworkм—җ м§Ғм ‘ нҶөн•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙ, кё°мЎҙ draft training objectiveмқҳ к°•л Ҙн•ң лҢҖм•Ҳмқҙ лҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60478","en":"Grouter: Decoupling Routing from Representation for Accelerated MoE Training","ko":"Grouter: к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”лҗң MoE н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң Routingкіј Representationмқҳ л¶„лҰ¬","authors":"Yuqi Xu, Rizhen Hu, zihan liu, Mou Sun, Kun Yuan","pos":"#1803","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ztVp5EqREE","abs":"Traditional Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) training typically proceeds without any structural priors, effectively requiring the model to simultaneously train expert weights while searching for an optimal routing policy within a vast combinatorial space. This entanglement often leads to sluggish convergence and training instabilities. This paper introduces Grouter, a preemptive routing method that by distilling high-quality structures from fully-trained MoE models and serving as a fixed router for target models. By decoupling structural optimization from weight updates, Grouter significantly accelerates both the speed and quality of model convergence. To ensure the framework's versatility, we also introduce expert folding to adapt Grouter across varying model configurations and expert tuning to rebalance workloads across different data distributions. Furthermore, by leveraging the structural priors provided by preemptive routing, we can implement targeted optimizations to further enhance training throughput. Experiments demonstrate that Grouter achieves superior performance and efficiency which boosts pre-training data utilization by 4.28$\\times$ and achieves up to 33.5$\\%$ throughput acceleration, establishing preemptive routing as a fundamental paradigm for scalable MoE training.","absKo":"Traditional Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) trainingмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м–ҙл–Ө structural prior м—Ҷмқҙ м§„н–үлҗҳл©°, мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ л°©лҢҖн•ң мЎ°н•© кіөк°„м—җм„ң мөңм Ғмқҳ routing policyлҘј нғҗмғүн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ expert weightлҘј н•Ёк»ҳ н•ҷмҠөн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м–ҪнһҳмқҖ мў…мў… лҠҗлҰ° мҲҳл ҙкіј training instabilityлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ fully-trained MoE modelм—җм„ң high-quality structureлҘј distillн•ҳм—¬ target modelмқ„ мң„н•ң fixed routerлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” preemptive routing methodмқё GrouterлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мЎ° мөңм Ғнҷ”мҷҖ weight updateлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, GrouterлҠ” model convergenceмқҳ мҶҚлҸ„мҷҖ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқҳ лІ”мҡ©м„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё model configurationм—җ л§һкІҢ GrouterлҘј мЎ°м •н•ҳлҠ” expert foldingкіј, лӢӨм–‘н•ң data distribution м „л°ҳм—җм„ң workloadлҘј мһ¬к· нҳ•нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” expert tuningлҸ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, preemptive routingмқҙ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” structural priorлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ training throughputмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ң targeted optimizationмқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј GrouterлҠ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘкіј нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, pre-training data utilizationмқ„ 4.28$\\times$ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  throughputмқ„ мөңлҢҖ 33.5$\\%$к№Ңм§Җ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳм—¬, preemptive routingмқҙ scalable MoE trainingмқҳ кё°ліё нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65350","en":"KORE: Enhancing Knowledge Injection for Large Multimodal Models via Knowledge-Oriented Controls","ko":"KORE: м§ҖмӢқ м§Җн–Ҙ м ңм–ҙлҘј нҶөн•ң Large Multimodal Modelмқҳ м§ҖмӢқ мЈјмһ… к°•нҷ”","authors":"Kailin Jiang, Hongbo Jiang, Ning Jiang, Zhi Gao, Jinhe Bi, Yuchen Ren, Bin Li, Yuntao Du, Lei Liu, Qing Li","pos":"#1814","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ETBr4m6w4s","abs":"<p>Large Multimodal Models encode extensive factual knowledge in their pre-trained weights. However, its knowledge remains static and limited, unable to keep pace with real-world developments, which hinders continuous knowledge acquisition. Effective knowledge injection thus becomes critical, involving two goals: knowledge adaptation (injecting new knowledge) and knowledge retention (preserving old knowledge). Existing methods often struggle to learn new knowledge and suffer from catastrophic forgetting. To address these challenges, we propose KORE, a synergistic method centered around KnOwledge-oRientEd controls. These controls are implemented through a two-stage optimization process: (1) KORE automatically converts individual knowledge items into structured and comprehensive knowledge to ensure that the model accurately learns new knowledge, enabling accurate adaptation. (2) KORE stores previous knowledge in the covariance matrix of LMM's linear layer activations and initializes the adapter by projecting the original weights into the matrix's null space, defining a fine-tuning direction that minimizes interference with previous knowledge, enabling powerful retention. Extensive experiments on various LMMs, including LLaVA-v1.5 (7B), LLaVA-v1.5 (13B), and Qwen2.5-VL (7B), show that KORE achieves superior new knowledge injection performance and effectively mitigates catastrophic forgetting.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Multimodal ModelмқҖ pre-trained weight м•Ҳм—җ л°©лҢҖн•ң мӮ¬мӢӨ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ мқёмҪ”л”©н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к·ё м§ҖмӢқмқҖ м •м Ғмқҙкі  м ңн•ңм Ғмқҙм–ҙм„ң нҳ„мӢӨ м„ёкі„мқҳ л°ңм „ мҶҚлҸ„лҘј л”°лқјк°Җм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё м§ҖмӢқ нҡҚл“қмқ„ л°©н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё knowledge injectionмқҙ л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҙм§Җл©°, м—¬кё°м—җлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ лӘ©н‘ңк°Җ нҸ¬н•ЁлҗңлӢӨ: knowledge adaptation(мғҲ м§ҖмӢқ мЈјмһ…)кіј knowledge retention(кё°мЎҙ м§ҖмӢқ ліҙмЎҙ). кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һкі  catastrophic forgettingмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” KnOwledge-oRientEd controlмқ„ мӨ‘мӢ¬мңјлЎң н•ң мӢңл„Ҳм§Җ л°©лІ• KOREлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ controlмқҖ л‘җ лӢЁкі„ мөңм Ғнҷ” кіјм •мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кө¬нҳ„лҗңлӢӨ: (1) KOREлҠ” к°ңлі„ knowledge itemмқ„ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗҳкі  нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё knowledgeлЎң мһҗлҸҷ ліҖнҷҳн•ҳм—¬ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м •нҷ•н•ң adaptationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. (2) KOREлҠ” мқҙм „ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ LMMмқҳ linear layer activationмқҳ covariance matrixм—җ м ҖмһҘн•ҳкі , мӣҗлһҳ weightлҘј к·ё matrixмқҳ null spaceлЎң projectionн•ҳм—¬ adapterлҘј мҙҲкё°нҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙм „ м§ҖмӢқкіјмқҳ к°„м„ӯмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” fine-tuning л°©н–Ҙмқ„ м •мқҳн•ҳкі , к°•л Ҙн•ң retentionмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. LLaVA-v1.5 (7B), LLaVA-v1.5 (13B), Qwen2.5-VL (7B)лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң LMMм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ KOREк°Җ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м§ҖмӢқ мЈјмһ… м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  catastrophic forgettingмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62725","en":"Federated Variational Preference Alignment with Gumbel-Softmax Prior for Personalized User Preferences","ko":"к°ңмқёнҷ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м„ нҳёлҘј мң„н•ң Gumbel-Softmax prior кё°л°ҳ м—°н•© Variational Preference Alignment","authors":"Jabin Koo, Hoyoung Kim, Minwoo Jang, Jungseul Ok","pos":"#1902","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=duzvT0nDgZ","abs":"<p>Federated Learning (FL) offers a privacy-preserving pathway for aligning Large Language Models (LLMs); however, existing frameworks typically enforce a monolithic reward model, inevitably averaging out inherently conflicting user preferences (e.g., helpfulness vs. harmlessness). While Variational Preference Learning (VPL) offers a pathway to personalization, adapting it to decentralized settings presents a fundamental challenge: \\textit{posterior collapse} driven by severe local data scarcity and heterogeneity. In this paper, we propose Federated Variational Preference Alignment with Gumbel-Softmax Prior (FedVPA-GP), a framework designed to disentangle diverse preferences without compromising privacy. To stabilize variational inference, we introduce a Federated Mixture Prior that enables clients to leverage the aggregate population distribution as a dynamic prior. Furthermore, we incorporate an Orthogonal Loss that explicitly enforces the separation of preference prototypes in the latent space. Experiments on the HH-RLHF dataset demonstrate that FedVPA-GP significantly outperforms monolithic baselines, successfully disentangling conflicting user intents and enabling dynamic preference switching.</p>","absKo":"<p>Federated Learning (FL)мқҖ Large Language Models (LLMs)мқ„ м •л ¬(alignment)н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң privacy-preserving кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ frameworkлҠ” ліҙнҶө лӢЁмқј reward modelмқ„ к°•м ңн•ҳм—¬ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мғҒм¶©н•ҳлҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м„ нҳё(мҳҲ: helpfulness vs. harmlessness)лҘј л¶Ҳк°Җн”јн•ҳкІҢ нҸүк· нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. Variational Preference Learning (VPL)мқҖ personalizationмқҳ кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҘј decentralized settingм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ к·јліём Ғмқё лҸ„м „, мҰү мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң local data scarcityмҷҖ heterogeneityлЎң мқён•ң \\textit{posterior collapse}лҘј мҲҳл°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” privacyлҘј нӣјмҶҗн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң м„ нҳёлҘј disentangleн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң Federated Variational Preference Alignment with Gumbel-Softmax Prior (FedVPA-GP)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. variational inferenceлҘј м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” clientк°Җ м „мІҙ лӘЁм§‘лӢЁ л¶„нҸ¬лҘј лҸҷм Ғмқё priorлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” Federated Mixture PriorлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, latent spaceм—җм„ң preference prototypeмқҳ л¶„лҰ¬лҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” Orthogonal LossлҘј нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. HH-RLHF datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FedVPA-GPк°Җ лӢЁмқј кө¬мЎ° baselineліҙлӢӨ нҳ„м ҖнһҲ лӣ°м–ҙлӮҳл©°, мғҒм¶©н•ҳлҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ intentлҘј м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң disentangleн•ҳкі  лҸҷм Ғ preference switchingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64554","en":"Facts in Stats: Impacts of Pretraining Diversity on Language Model Generalization","ko":"нҶөкі„ мҶҚ мӮ¬мӢӨ: мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠө лӢӨм–‘м„ұмқҙ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё мқјл°ҳнҷ”м—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙ","authors":"Tina Behnia, Puneesh Deora, Christos Thrampoulidis","pos":"#1903","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=MF39WUbcmx","abs":"<p>Language models are pretrained on sequences that blend statistical regularities (structures making text fluent) with factual associations between specific tokens (corresponding to knowledge of facts). While recent work suggests that the variability of their interaction, such as paraphrases of factual associations, critically determines generalization ability, we lack a systematic analysis of these impacts. This paper introduces a flexible synthetic testbed that combines a statistical stream of generic tokens with an abstract factual stream of source-target token pairs, enabling fine-grained control over their interaction. Specifically, the design enables the independent control of diversity nature by manipulating stream composition (contextual structure) and the level of diversity by varying which statistical streams each fact appears in. Through controlled experiments, we find that while higher contextual diversity delays in-distribution (ID) factual accuracy, its effect on out-of-distribution (OOD) generalization depends critically on contextual structure. In some cases, OOD performance follows the same trend as ID, but in others, diversity becomes essential for non-trivial factual learning. Even when low diversity prohibits factual recall, optimal diversity levels depend on training duration. Beyond factual recall failures, we identify structures where statistical generalization fails independently, and others where both capabilities degrade simultaneously. This demonstrates how the interplay between contextual design and diversity level impacts different aspects of generalization.  Furthermore, through a series of controlled interventions on the model components, we trace the generalization failures to distinct optimization bottlenecks, highlighting the importance of the learned embedding and unembedding layers. Overall, our synthetic framework allows us to isolate effects that would be confounded in large-scale studies, thus offering a controlled testbed for future investigations.</p>","absKo":"<p>м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлҘј мң м°Ҫн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” statistical regularityмҷҖ, нҠ№м • tokenл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мӮ¬мӢӨм Ғ м—°кҙҖм„ұ(мӮ¬мӢӨм—җ лҢҖн•ң м§ҖмӢқм—җ н•ҙлӢ№н•Ё)мқҙ м„һмқё sequenceлЎң мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөлҗңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҳ ліҖлҸҷм„ұ, мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ factual associationмқҳ paraphraseк°Җ generalization лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мўҢмҡ°н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ң м—°кө¬лҠ” л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё tokenмқҳ statistical streamкіј source-target token pairмқҳ м¶”мғҒм Ғ factual streamмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң мң м—°н•ң synthetic testbedлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, мқҙл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ м„ёл°Җн•ҳкІҢ нҶөм ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, stream composition( contextual structure )мқ„ мЎ°мһ‘н•ҙ diversityмқҳ м„ұкІ©мқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙн•ҳкі , к°Ғ factк°Җ м–ҙл–Ө statistical streamл“Өм—җ л“ұмһҘн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј л°”кҝ” diversityмқҳ мҲҳмӨҖмқ„ мЎ°м Ҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„н–ҲлӢӨ. нҶөм ңлҗң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ contextual diversityлҠ” in-distribution(ID) factual accuracyлҘј м§Җм—°мӢңнӮӨм§Җл§Ң, out-of-distribution(OOD) generalizationм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҳҒн–ҘмқҖ contextual structureм—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мўҢмҡ°лҗңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. м–ҙл–Ө кІҪмҡ°м—җлҠ” OOD м„ұлҠҘмқҙ IDмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ м¶”м„ёлҘј ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, лӢӨлҘё кІҪмҡ°м—җлҠ” л№„мһҗлӘ…н•ң factual learningмқ„ мң„н•ҙ diversityк°Җ н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. лӮ®мқҖ diversityк°Җ factual recallмқ„ л§үлҠ” кІҪмҡ°м—җлҸ„, мөңм Ғмқҳ diversity мҲҳмӨҖмқҖ training durationм—җ л”°лқј лӢ¬лқјм§„лӢӨ. factual recall мӢӨнҢЁлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ң, statistical generalizationмқҙ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” кө¬мЎ°мҷҖ л‘җ лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ лҸҷмӢңм—җ м Җн•ҳлҗҳлҠ” кө¬мЎ°лҸ„ мӢқлі„н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” contextual designкіј diversity levelмқҳ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҙ generalizationмқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё мёЎл©ҙм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мЈјлҠ”м§Җ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, лӘЁлҚё кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқјл Ёмқҳ нҶөм ңлҗң к°ңмһ…мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ generalization мӢӨнҢЁлҘј м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё optimization bottleneckмңјлЎң м¶”м Ғн–Ҳмңјл©°, learned embeddingкіј unembedding layerмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ synthetic frameworkлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м—°кө¬м—җм„ң нҳјлҸҷлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” нҡЁкіјл“Өмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙ мЈјлҜҖлЎң, н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬лҘј мң„н•ң нҶөм ңлҗң testbedлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64090","en":"EvoGM: Learning to Merge LLMs via Evolutionary Generative Optimization","ko":"EvoGM: м§„нҷ”м Ғ мғқм„ұ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј нҶөн•ң LLM лі‘н•© н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Tao Jiang, Xinmeng Yu, Chenhao Yi, Yiling Wu, Yan Li, Ran Cheng, Dongmei Jiang, Jianguo Zhang","pos":"#1906","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=R2CoYV0Gf6","abs":"<p>Evolutionary model merging provides a powerful framework for the automated, training-free composition of LLMs through parameter-space search. However, existing methods predominantly rely on stochastic, hand-crafted operators that overlook the underlying performance landscape of the coefficient space. We propose Evolutionary Generative Merging (EvoGM), a framework that transcends manual heuristics by employing learnable generative modeling to optimize merging coefficients. Specifically,, EvoGM features a dual-generator architecture with cycle-consistent learning to adaptively sample and refine promising merging candidates. By constructing winner-loser pairs from historical search trajectories, our framework effectively captures high-performance parameter distributions and maximizes data efficiency. This generative process is seamlessly integrated into a multi-round evolutionary pipeline, where elite merged models iteratively serve as new expert foundations. Extensive experiments across diverse benchmarks demonstrate that EvoGM significantly outperforms state-of-the-art baselines, exhibiting robust performance on both seen and unseen tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Evolutionary model mergingмқҖ parameter-space searchлҘј нҶөн•ҙ LLMмқ„ мһҗлҸҷмңјлЎң, к·ёлҰ¬кі  training м—Ҷмқҙ мЎ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң frameworkлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ мЈјлЎң stochasticн•ҳкі  мҶҗмңјлЎң м„Өкі„н•ң operatorм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, coefficient spaceмқҳ underlying performance landscapeлҘј к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” learnable generative modelingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ merging coefficientлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мҲҳмһ‘м—… heuristicмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” frameworkмқё Evolutionary Generative Merging(EvoGM)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, EvoGMмқҖ cycle-consistent learningмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ dual-generator architectureлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мң л§қн•ң merging candidateлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ҳкі  м •м ңн•ңлӢӨ. м—ӯмӮ¬м Ғ search trajectoryлЎңл¶Җн„° winner-loser pairлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkлҠ” high-performance parameter distributionмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкі  data efficiencyлҘј к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ generative processлҠ” multi-round evolutionary pipelineм—җ л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ нҶөн•©лҗҳл©°, м—¬кё°м„ң elite merged modelмқҖ л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ expert foundationмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ EvoGMмқҙ state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, ліё м Ғ мһҲлҠ” taskмҷҖ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң task лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң к°•кұҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61634","en":"DARTS: Distribution-Aware Active Rollout Trajectory Shaping for Accelerating LLM Reinforcement Learning","ko":"DARTS: LLM Reinforcement Learning к°ҖмҶҚмқ„ мң„н•ң л¶„нҸ¬ мқёмӢқ Active Rollout Trajectory Shaping","authors":"Yujie Wang, Siwei Chen, Longzan Luo, Xinyi Liu, Xupeng Miao, Fangcheng Fu, Bin Cui","pos":"#2005","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=oFUfz5nsJc","abs":"Reinforcement Learning (RL) has become pivotal for improving model capabilities yet suffers from rollout efficiency bottlenecks due to the long-tail response length distribution. While existing works mitigate the impact of long tails via prompt-level tail scheduling, we focus on the root source of inefficiency: the distribution itself. Specifically, we characterize the long-tail distribution at a finer granularity, identifying intra-prompt long tails, and revealing that they frequently consist of ineffective verbosity. To address this, we propose a novel paradigm of active distribution shaping to shape the rollout distribution towards conciseness and certainty, thereby fundamentally resolving tail-induced overheads. We achieve this through a distribution-aware trajectory sampling mechanism, which selects trajectories from a redundant exploration space for each prompt, and an adaptive redundancy allocation scheme to maximize both shaping effectiveness and system efficiency. Experiments demonstrate significant acceleration over state-of-the-art systems by up to 1.77$\\times$ without compromising model performance.","absKo":"Reinforcement Learning(RL)мқҖ лӘЁлҚё лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҚ° н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ҙмҷ”м§Җл§Ң, кёҙ tail response length distribution л•Ңл¬ём—җ rollout нҡЁмңЁм„ұ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ prompt-level tail schedulingмңјлЎң long tailмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л№„нҡЁмңЁмқҳ к·јліё мӣҗмқёмқё л¶„нҸ¬ мһҗмІҙм—җ мЈјлӘ©н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” long-tail distributionмқ„ лҚ” м„ёл°Җн•ң granularityлЎң нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ prompt лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ long tailмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , мқҙкІғмқҙ мў…мў… л№„нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё verbosityлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” rollout distributionмқ„ к°„кІ°н•Ёкіј нҷ•мӢӨм„ұ мӘҪмңјлЎң нҳ•м„ұн•ҳм—¬ tailмқҙ мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” overheadлҘј к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳлҠ” active distribution shapingмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ promptм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ redundant exploration spaceм—җм„ң trajectoryлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” distribution-aware trajectory sampling mechanismкіј, shaping нҡЁкіјмҷҖ system efficiencyлҘј лӘЁл‘җ к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” adaptive redundancy allocation schemeмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ model performanceлҘј м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮӨм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң мөңлҢҖ 1.77$\\times$к№Ңм§Җ state-of-the-art systemліҙлӢӨ мң мқҳлҜён•ң к°ҖмҶҚмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"65632","en":"Dirichlet-Prior Shaping: Guiding Expert Specialization in Upcycled MoEs","ko":"Dirichlet мӮ¬м „л¶„нҸ¬ нҳ•м„ұ: мһ¬нҷңмҡ© MoEм—җм„ң м „л¬ёк°Җ нҠ№нҷ” мң лҸ„н•ҳкё°","authors":"Leyla Mirvakhabova, Babak Ehteshami Bejnordi, Gaurav Kumar, Hanxue Liang, Wanru Zhao, Paul Whatmough","pos":"#2009","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=BfkrQiC0Ss","abs":"<p>Upcycling pre-trained dense models into sparse Mixture-of-Experts (MoEs) efficiently increases model capacity but often suffers from poor expert specialization due to naive weight replication. We introduce Dirichlet-Prior Shaping Loss (DPSL), a novel router regularization technique that directly shapes routing probability distributions by matching expert assignments to a target Dirichlet prior resulting in enhanced expert specialization. DPSL enables encoding of inductive biases such as encouraging experts to focus on specific modalities or tasks, without requiring manual intervention. DPSL is a general tool applicable to any module that outputs categorical probability distributions, extending its utility beyond MoE training. Experiments on upcycled MoE vision-language models show that DPSL consistently outperforms upcycling strategies and regularization techniques across standard vision-language benchmarks, addressing the critical issue of poor specialization and fostering higher-performing models.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӮ¬м „ н•ҷмҠөлҗң dense modelмқ„ sparse Mixture-of-Experts (MoEs)лЎң upcyclingн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ model capacityлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң лҠҳлҰ¬м§Җл§Ң, naive weight replication л•Ңл¬ём—җ expert specializationмқҙ м ңлҢҖлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§Җм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” expert assignmentлҘј target Dirichlet priorм—җ л§һм¶”м–ҙ routing probability distributionмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ shapingн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н–ҘмғҒлҗң expert specializationмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ router regularization кё°лІ•мқё Dirichlet-Prior Shaping Loss (DPSL)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. DPSLмқҖ мҲҳлҸҷ к°ңмһ… м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ expertк°Җ нҠ№м • modalityлӮҳ taskм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мһҘл Өн•ҳлҠ” л“ұ inductive biasлҘј encodingн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. DPSLмқҖ categorical probability distributionмқ„ м¶ңл Ҙн•ҳлҠ” м–ҙл–Ө лӘЁл“Ҳм—җлҸ„ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң лІ”мҡ© лҸ„кө¬лЎң, MoE trainingмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ к·ё мң мҡ©м„ұмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. upcycled MoE vision-language modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң DPSLмқҖ н‘ңмӨҖ vision-language benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң upcycling м „лһөкіј regularization кё°лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, specialization л¶ҖмЎұмқҙлқјлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкі  лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқҳ modelмқ„ мҙүм§„н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61868","en":"Can I Have Your Order? Monte-Carlo Tree Search for Slot Filling Ordering in Diffusion Language Models","ko":"мЈјл¬ён•ҳмӢңкІ м–ҙмҡ”? Diffusion Language Modelм—җм„ң Slot Filling мҲңм„ңлҘј мң„н•ң Monte-Carlo Tree Search","authors":"Joshua Ong, Yu Zhao, Mihaela C. Stoian, Wenda Li, Shay Cohen, Eleonora Giunchiglia","pos":"#2101","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mEfh2cH3AW","abs":"<p>While plan-and-infill decoding in Masked Diffusion Models (MDMs) shows promise for mathematical and code reasoning, performance remains highly sensitive to slot infilling order, often yielding substantial output variance. We introduce DiffuSearch, a framework that formulates slot selection as decision making and optimises infilling orders through Monte Carlo Tree Search (MCTS). DiffuSearch uses look-ahead simulations to evaluate partial completions before commitment, systematically exploring the combinatorial space of generation orders. Experiments show an average improvement of 3.2% over autoregressive baselines and 8.0% over baseline plan-and-infill, with notable gains of 19.5% on MBPP and 4.9% on MATH500. Our analysis reveals that while DiffuSearch predominantly follows sequential ordering, incorporating non-sequential generation is essential for maximising performance. We observe that larger exploration constants, rather than increased simulations, are necessary to overcome model confidence biases and discover effective orderings. These findings establish MCTS-based planning as an effective approach for enhancing generation quality in MDMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>Masked Diffusion Models(MDMs)м—җм„ңмқҳ plan-and-infill decodingмқҖ мҲҳн•ҷ л°Ҹ code reasoningм—җм„ң к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, slot infilling мҲңм„ңм—җ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л§Өмҡ° лҜјк°җн•ҳм—¬ м¶ңл Ҙ л¶„мӮ°мқҙ нҒ¬кІҢ лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” slot selectionмқ„ decision makingмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі  Monte Carlo Tree Search(MCTS)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ infilling мҲңм„ңлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё DiffuSearchлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. DiffuSearchлҠ” commitment м „м—җ partial completionмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ look-ahead simulationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©°, мғқм„ұ мҲңм„ңмқҳ мЎ°н•©м Ғ кіөк°„мқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң нғҗмғүн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, autoregressive baseline лҢҖл№„ нҸүк·  3.2%, baseline plan-and-infill лҢҖл№„ 8.0%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмҳҖкі , нҠ№нһҲ MBPPм—җм„ң 19.5%, MATH500м—җм„ң 4.9%мқҳ мң мқҳлҜён•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ DiffuSearchк°Җ мЈјлЎң sequential orderingмқ„ л”°лҘҙм§Җл§Ң, м„ұлҠҘмқ„ к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳл Өл©ҙ non-sequential generationмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ н•„мҲҳм Ғмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳ нҡҹмҲҳлҘј лҠҳлҰ¬лҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ лҚ” нҒ° exploration constantк°Җ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ confidence biasлҘј к·№ліөн•ҳкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё orderingмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•Ёмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” MDMsм—җм„ң мғқм„ұ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё м ‘к·јмңјлЎңм„ң MCTS кё°л°ҳ planningмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65360","en":"Anchored Policy Optimization: Mitigating Exploration Collapse via Support-Constrained Rectification","ko":"Anchored Policy Optimization: м§Җм§Җм§‘н•© м ңм•Ҫ көҗм •мқ„ нҶөн•ң нғҗн—ҳ л¶•кҙҙ мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"Tianyi Wang, Long Li, Hongcan Guo, Yibiao Chen, Yixia Li, Yong Wang, Yun Chen, Guanhua CHEN","pos":"#2115","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EOEI74ZtA4","abs":"<p>Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR) is increasingly viewed as a tree pruning mechanism. However, we identify a systemic pathology termed Recursive Space Contraction (RSC), an irreversible collapse driven by the combined dynamics of positive sharpening and negative squeezing, where the sampling probability of valid alternatives vanishes. While Kullback-Leibler (KL) regularization aims to mitigate this, it imposes a rigid Shape Matching constraint that forces the policy to mimic the reference model's full density, creating a gradient conflict with the sharpening required for correctness. We propose Anchored Policy Optimization (APO), shifting the paradigm from global Shape Matching to Support Coverage. By defining a Safe Manifold based on the reference model's high-confidence support, APO permits aggressive sharpening for efficiency while selectively invoking a restorative force during error correction to prevent collapse. We theoretically derive that APO serves as a gradient-aligned mechanism to maximize support coverage, enabling an Elastic Recovery that re-inflates valid branches. Empirical evaluations on mathematical benchmarks demonstrate that APO breaks the accuracy-diversity trade-off, significantly improving Pass@1 while restoring the Pass@K diversity typically lost by standard policy gradient methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Verifiable RewardsлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң Reinforcement Learning(RLVR)мқҖ м җм җ tree pruning л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмңјлЎң к°„мЈјлҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Recursive Space Contraction(RSC)мқҙлқј л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” мӢңмҠӨн…ңм Ғ лі‘лҰ¬лҘј мӢқлі„н–ҲлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” positive sharpeningкіј negative squeezingмқҳ кІ°н•©лҗң лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗҳлҠ” л№„к°Җм—ӯм Ғ л¶•кҙҙлЎң, мң нҡЁн•ң лҢҖм•Ҳмқҳ sampling probabilityк°Җ мҶҢл©ён•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. Kullback-Leibler(KL) regularizationмқҖ мқҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл Ө н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, reference modelмқҳ м „мІҙ densityлҘј policyк°Җ лӘЁмӮ¬н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” кІҪм§Ғлҗң Shape Matching м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л¶Җкіјн•ҳм—¬, м •лӢөм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң sharpeningкіј gradient conflictлҘј мқјмңјнӮЁлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Anchored Policy Optimization(APO)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, м „м—ӯ Shape Matchingм—җм„ң Support CoverageлЎң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м „нҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. reference modelмқҳ high-confidence supportлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң Safe ManifoldлҘј м •мқҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, APOлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң кіөкІ©м Ғмқё sharpeningмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мҳӨлҘҳ мҲҳм • мӢң л¶•кҙҙлҘј л°©м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң ліөмӣҗл Ҙмқ„ нҳём¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң APOк°Җ support coverageлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” gradient-aligned mechanismмңјлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•Ёмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳкі , мң нҡЁн•ң branchлҘј лӢӨмӢң нҢҪм°ҪмӢңнӮӨлҠ” Elastic RecoveryлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷ benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” APOк°Җ м •нҷ•лҸ„-лӢӨм–‘м„ұ нҠёл Ҳмқҙл“ңмҳӨн”„лҘј к№ЁлңЁлҰ¬кі , Pass@1мқ„ мң мқҳлҜён•ҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ standard policy gradient methodм—җм„ң мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мҶҢмӢӨлҗҳлҠ” Pass@K лӢӨм–‘м„ұлҸ„ нҡҢліөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62892","en":"Adaptive Utilization of Low-Rank Adaptation via Conditioned Gating","ko":"Conditioned Gating кё°л°ҳ Low-Rank Adaptationмқҳ м Ғмқ‘м Ғ нҷңмҡ©","authors":"Guang Yang, Changhao Guan, Chao Huang, Yufeng Chen, Kaiyu Huang","pos":"#2212","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cA7SvKStDh","abs":"<p>Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) achieves parameter-efficient fine-tuning by constraining model updates to a low-rank subspace and has been widely used in practice.  However, LoRA typically employs a shared low-rank update across tokens, which limits its ability to fully exploit the adaptation subspace for tokens from different sequences. To address this issue, we propose an adaptive utilization of Low-Rank Adaptation (U-LoRA), which employs conditioned gating to explicitly learn effective token-level utilization of the limited low-rank adaptation subspace.  Specifically, U-LoRA generates utilization coefficients along low-rank directions for each token and jointly coordinates and constrains them using sequence-level contextual information, thereby inducing more consistent adaptive patterns within a sentence. To further enhance training stability, we introduce a bias-corrected exponential moving average (EMA) historical prior that calibrates utilization signals across optimization steps, suppressing noise caused by batch-to-batch fluctuations. The effectiveness of our method arises from a better utilization of the existing low-rank subspace via input-conditioned strategies, rather than from expanding the subspace. Experiments on mathematical reasoning and natural language understanding benchmarks demonstrate that U-LoRA achieves competitive performance under comparable parameter budgets when with strong LoRA baselines and recent variants.</p>","absKo":"<p>Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA)лҠ” model updateлҘј low-rank subspaceлЎң м ңн•ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ parameter-efficient fine-tuningмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мӢӨм ңлЎң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ LoRAлҠ” мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң token м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ кіөмң лҗҳлҠ” low-rank updateлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё sequenceмқҳ tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ adaptation subspaceлҘј м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Low-Rank Adaptationмқҳ adaptive utilization (U-LoRA)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. U-LoRAлҠ” conditioned gatingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м ңн•ңлҗң low-rank adaptation subspaceмқҳ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё token-level нҷңмҡ©мқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, U-LoRAлҠ” к°Ғ tokenм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ low-rank л°©н–Ҙмқ„ л”°лқј utilization coefficientлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , sequence-level contextual informationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мқҙлҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ҳкі  м ңм•Ҫн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ л¬ёмһҘ лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң лҚ” мқјкҙҖлҗң adaptive patternмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. н•ҷмҠө м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ лҚ” лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” optimization step м „л°ҳмқҳ utilization signalмқ„ ліҙм •н•ҳкі  batch к°„ ліҖлҸҷмңјлЎң мқён•ң noiseлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳлҠ” bias-corrected exponential moving average (EMA) historical priorлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҠ” subspaceлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҙм„ңк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј, input-conditioned strategyлҘј нҶөн•ҙ кё°мЎҙ low-rank subspaceлҘј лҚ” мһҳ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м„ң л№„лЎҜлҗңлӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ кіј natural language understanding benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ, U-LoRAк°Җ к°•н•ң LoRA baseline л°Ҹ мөңмӢ  variantмҷҖ л№„көҗ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң parameter budget н•ҳм—җм„ң кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63191","en":"FedPissa: Towards Federated Personalized Adaptation of Foundation Models via LoRA Subspace Mapping","ko":"FedPissa: LoRA л¶Җл¶„кіөк°„ л§Өн•‘мқ„ нҶөн•ң Foundation лӘЁлҚёмқҳ м—°н•© к°ңмқёнҷ” м Ғмқ‘мқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Wenwen He, Wenke Huang, Yi Liu, Jian Liang, Xirui Li, Guansong Pang, Mang Ye","pos":"#2908","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZEWN40uNEh","abs":"<p>LoRA efficiently adapts large pre-trained models via low-rank updates, making it a strong parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) method. When integrated with Federated Learning (FL), it enables collaborative fine-tuning across distributed clients, leveraging rich downstream data without exposing private information. However, this strategy is hindered by data heterogeneity and limits personalization performance. To address this, personalized FedLoRA approaches have been proposed and employ a dual-LoRA architecture, e.g., one branch for global knowledge and another for client-specific adaptation. Nevertheless, this dual-LoRA design introduces additional computational overhead and structural redundancy. To address this limitation, we propose FedPissa, the first framework that rethinks single-LoRA via selective aggregation and subspace decorrelation. We selectively aggregate LoRA components based on their aggregation dynamics, and further apply a decorrelated subspace projection to mitigate heterogeneous update conflicts, reducing cross-client interference and improving personalized adaptation. Experiments on textual and visual scenarios show that FedPissa not only achieves up to 35% lower communication and computation cost, but also improves overall accuracy by up to 8% compared to its counterparts.</p>","absKo":"<p>LoRAлҠ” м ҖлһӯнҒ¬ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҘј нҶөн•ҙ large pre-trained modelмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮӨл©°, к°•л Ҙн•ң parameter-efficient fine-tuning (PEFT) л°©лІ•мқҙ лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј Federated Learning (FL)кіј кІ°н•©н•ҳл©ҙ distributed client м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң нҳ‘л Ҙм Ғ fine-tuningмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҙм§Җкі , private informationмқ„ л…ём¶ңн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң н’Қл¶Җн•ң downstream dataлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ м „лһөмқҖ data heterogeneityмҷҖ personalization м„ұлҠҘмқҳ н•ңкі„лЎң мқён•ҙ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, personalized FedLoRA м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ global knowledgeлҘј мң„н•ң branchмҷҖ client-specific adaptationмқ„ мң„н•ң лҳҗ лӢӨлҘё branchлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң dual-LoRA architectureлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳм§Җл§Ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң dual-LoRA м„Өкі„лҠ” м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё computational overheadмҷҖ structural redundancyлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” selective aggregationкіј subspace decorrelationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ single-LoRAлҘј мһ¬кі н•ҳлҠ” мІ« frameworkмқё FedPissaлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” aggregation dynamicsм—җ л”°лқј LoRA componentлҘј м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң aggregateн•ҳкі , лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ decorrelated subspace projectionмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ heterogeneous update conflictлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ cross-client interferenceлҘј мӨ„мқҙкі  personalized adaptationмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. textual л°Ҹ visual scenarioм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FedPissaк°Җ нҶөмӢ  л°Ҹ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқ„ мөңлҢҖ 35%к№Ңм§Җ мӨ„мқҙлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, лҢҖмқ‘ л°©лІ•л“Өм—җ л№„н•ҙ м „мІҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мөңлҢҖ 8% н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63168","en":"AffIn-Space: Learning Affine-Invariant Representations for 3D Spatial Understanding with MLLMs","ko":"AffIn-Space: MLLMмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң 3D кіөк°„ мқҙн•ҙлҘј мң„н•ң м•„н•Җ л¶ҲліҖ н‘ңнҳ„ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Zhenyu Lu, Liupeng Li, Jinpeng Wang, Haoqian Kang, Manyuan Zhang, Yan Feng, Ke Chen, Yaowei Wang","pos":"#3514","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZRymA5ujIZ","abs":"<p>While Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) have achieved remarkable progress in general visual understanding, they suffer from a fundamental geometric fragility: standard visual representations often degrade rapidly under changes in viewpoint and viewing distance. Our analysis identifies that existing paradigms, whether relying on input-level fusion or latent reconstruction, remain entangled with the view-dependent pixel grid, failing to decouple intrinsic 3D structure from extrinsic camera pose. To address this, we introduce AffIn-Space, a framework that enforces strict affine invariance to enable robust spatial understanding. Unlike implicit learning approaches, AffIn-Space introduces a two-stage explicit decoupling mechanism. First, it employs explicit geometric resampling by utilizing decomposed affine quantities (derived from pose features) to spatially align 3D features to a canonical state before fusion. Second, within the MLLM, we implement affine-invariant constraints via an orthogonal projection mechanism, which mathematically strips away pose-dependent noise from the hidden states while retaining recoverable geometric semantics through conditional reconstruction. Extensive experiments on VSI-Bench, ScanQA, SQA3D, Scan2Cap, and EmbodiedScan demonstrate that AffIn-Space achieves state-of-the-art performance. Code and detailed instructions will be publicly released.  Crucially, our approach exhibits superior stability against affine perturbations, validating the effectiveness of explicitly modeling geometric invariance for complex spatial tasks. Code will be made available. Extensive experiments show that AffIn-Space achieves state-of-the-art performance on spatial reasoning tasks (VSI-Bench, SQA3D and Scan2Cap), and on spatial grounding tasks (ScanRefer and EmbodiedScan), demonstrating the effectiveness of affine invariant representations for complex spatial understanding.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal Large Language Models(MLLMs)лҠ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё visual understandingм—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈЁм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, viewpointмҷҖ viewing distanceмқҳ ліҖнҷ”м—җ л”°лқј н‘ңмӨҖ visual representationмқҙ л№ лҘҙкІҢ м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ м·Ём•Ҫм„ұмқ„ к°Җм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ input-level fusionмқҙл“  latent reconstructionмқҙл“ , кё°мЎҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙ лӘЁл‘җ view-dependent pixel gridмҷҖ м–ҪнҳҖ мһҲм–ҙ intrinsic 3D structureлҘј extrinsic camera poseлЎңл¶Җн„° л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кІ¬кі н•ң spatial understandingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ strict affine invarianceлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” AffIn-SpaceлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м•”л¬өм Ғ н•ҷмҠө м ‘к·јлІ•кіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, AffIn-SpaceлҠ” 2лӢЁкі„мқҳ explicit decoupling mechanismмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, pose featureм—җм„ң лҸ„м¶ңлҗң decomposed affine quantityлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң explicit geometric resamplingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ fusion м „м—җ 3D featureлҘј canonical stateлЎң spatial alignmentн•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, MLLM лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң orthogonal projection mechanismмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ affine-invariant constraintлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳм—¬, ліөмӣҗ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң geometric semanticsлҠ” conditional reconstructionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң hidden stateм—җм„ң pose-dependent noiseлҘј мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. VSI-Bench, ScanQA, SQA3D, Scan2Cap, EmbodiedScanм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ AffIn-Spaceк°Җ state-of-the-art performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ мғҒм„ён•ң м§Җм№ЁмқҖ кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ. кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ affine perturbationм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, ліөмһЎн•ң spatial taskм—җм„ң geometric invarianceлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” м ңкіөлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ AffIn-Spaceк°Җ spatial reasoning task(VSI-Bench, SQA3D, Scan2Cap)мҷҖ spatial grounding task(ScanRefer, EmbodiedScan)м—җм„ң state-of-the-art performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, ліөмһЎн•ң spatial understandingмқ„ мң„н•ң affine invariant representationмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӮҳнғҖлӮёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63355","en":"Geometry-Preserving Orthonormal Initialization for Low-Rank Adaptation in Reinforcement Learning","ko":"к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң Low-Rank Adaptationмқ„ мң„н•ң кё°н•ҳ ліҙмЎҙ м •к·ңм§Ғкөҗ мҙҲкё°нҷ”","authors":"Ruijia Zhang, Jiacheng Zhu, Hanqing Zhu, Laixi Shi","pos":"#3612","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Xo95FS2GTK","abs":"<p>Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) and its variants enable parameter-efficient fine-tuning of large language models under the supervised fine-tuning (SFT) paradigm. However, their efficacy and behavior under Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR) are less well understood. In particular, two structurally initialized LoRA variants, PiSSA and MiLoRA, which outperform standard LoRA under SFT, can underperform standard LoRA under RLVR and may even exhibit training instability. These observations suggest that how to initialize the low-rank matrices in RLVR remains unclear. In this work, we develop a theoretical analysis of LoRA in RLVR, showing that orthonormal initialization achieves the minimal gap between LoRAвҖҷs outcome and that of full fine-tuning. Guided by this insight, we propose geometry-preserving orthonormal initialization for low-rank adaptation in RLVR, leading to two new variants, LoRA-RLPO and LoRA-RLMO. Experiments on mathematical reasoning benchmarks show that our orthonormal initialization stabilizes RLVR training and outperforms standard LoRA, contrasting with PiSSA and MiLoRA. Finally, our unified analysis also explains why PiSSA and MiLoRA can underperform in RLVR, which may be of independent interest.</p>","absKo":"<p>Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA)кіј к·ё ліҖнҳ•л“ӨмқҖ supervised fine-tuning (SFT) нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„м—җм„ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ parameter-efficientн•ҳкІҢ fine-tuningн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙмӨҖлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR) н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ нҡЁмҡ©кіј лҸҷмһ‘мқҖ мғҒлҢҖм ҒмңјлЎң мһҳ м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң мҙҲкё°нҷ”лҗң л‘җ LoRA ліҖнҳ•мқё PiSSAмҷҖ MiLoRAлҠ” SFTм—җм„ңлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ LoRAлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, RLVRм—җм„ңлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ LoRAліҙлӢӨ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲкі  мӢ¬м§Җм–ҙ н•ҷмҠө л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ ліҙмқҙкё°лҸ„ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм°°мқҖ RLVRм—җм„ң low-rank matrixлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ мҙҲкё°нҷ”н• м§Җк°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ л¶ҲлӘ…нҷ•н•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” RLVRм—җм„ң LoRAм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬, orthonormal initializationмқҙ LoRAмқҳ кІ°кіјмҷҖ full fine-tuningмқҳ кІ°кіј мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°„к·№мқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°м—җ л”°лқј, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” RLVRм—җм„ң low-rank adaptationмқ„ мң„н•ң geometry-preserving orthonormal initializationмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј LoRA-RLPOмҷҖ LoRA-RLMOлқјлҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ ліҖнҳ•мқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м¶”лЎ  benchmark мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ orthonormal initializationмқҙ RLVR н•ҷмҠөмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкі  н‘ңмӨҖ LoRAлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, мқҙлҠ” PiSSAмҷҖ MiLoRAмҷҖ лҢҖмЎ°м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ нҶөн•© л¶„м„қмқҖ PiSSAмҷҖ MiLoRAк°Җ RLVRм—җм„ң мҷң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§ҖлҸ„ м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё кҙҖмӢ¬мӮ¬мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64948","en":"Smoothie: Smoothing Diffusion on Token Embeddings for Text Generation","ko":"Smoothie: н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң Token Embeddingм—җм„ңмқҳ Diffusion Smoothing","authors":"Alexander Shabalin, Viacheslav Meshchaninov, Dmitry Vetrov","pos":"#3905","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=IPAeknfo2x","abs":"<p>Diffusion models have achieved state-of-the-art performance in generating images, audio, and video, but their adaptation to text remains challenging due to its discrete nature. Prior approaches either apply Gaussian diffusion in continuous latent spaces, which inherits semantic structure but struggles with token decoding, or operate in categorical simplex space, which respect discreteness but disregard semantic relation between tokens. In this paper, we propose Smoothing Diffusion on Token Embeddings (Smoothie), a novel diffusion method that combines the strengths of both approaches by progressively smoothing token embeddings based on semantic similarity. This technique enables gradual information removal while maintaining a natural decoding process. Experimental results on several sequence-to-sequence and unconditional generation tasks demonstrate that Smoothie outperforms existing diffusion-based models in generation quality. Furthermore, ablation studies show that our proposed diffusion space yields better performance than both the standard embedding space and the categorical simplex.</p>","absKo":"<p>Diffusion modelмқҖ мқҙлҜём§Җ, мҳӨл””мҳӨ, л№„л””мҳӨ мғқм„ұм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, textлҠ” discreteн•ң м„ұм§Ҳ л•Ңл¬ём—җ м Ғмқ‘мқҙ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ semantic structureлҠ” кі„мҠ№н•ҳм§Җл§Ң token decodingм—җм„ң м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ” continuous latent spaceм—җм„ң Gaussian diffusionмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, discretenessлҠ” мЎҙмӨ‘н•ҳм§Җл§Ң token к°„мқҳ semantic relationмқ„ л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳлҠ” categorical simplex spaceм—җм„ң лҸҷмһ‘н•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” token embeddingмқ„ semantic similarityм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң smoothingн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ diffusion л°©лІ•мқё Smoothing Diffusion on Token Embeddings (Smoothie)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кё°лІ•мқҖ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ decoding кіјм •мқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң м җм§„м Ғмқё м •ліҙ м ңкұ°лҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ sequence-to-sequence л°Ҹ unconditional generation taskм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, SmoothieлҠ” generation quality мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ diffusion-based modelліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ ablation studyлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ң diffusion spaceк°Җ standard embedding spaceмҷҖ categorical simplex лӘЁл‘җліҙлӢӨ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӮёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65260","en":"Preserve-Then-Quantize: Balancing Rank Budgets for Quantization Error Reconstruction in LLMs","ko":"Preserve-Then-Quantize: LLM м–‘мһҗнҷ” мҳӨм°Ё мһ¬кө¬м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң лһӯнҒ¬ мҳҲмӮ° к· нҳ• л§һм¶”кё°","authors":"Yoonjun Cho, Dongjae Jeon, Soeun Kim, Moongyu Jeon, Albert No","pos":"#1515","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FHJdLypBf3","abs":"Quantization Error Reconstruction (QER) reduces accuracy loss in Post-Training Quantization (PTQ) by approximating weights as $\\mathbf{W} \\approx \\mathbf{Q} + \\mathbf{L}\\mathbf{R}$, using a rank-$r$ correction to reconstruct quantization error. Prior methods devote the full rank budget to error reconstruction, which is suboptimal when $\\mathbf{W}$ has intrinsic low-rank structure and quantization corrupts dominant directions. We propose Structured Residual Reconstruction (SRR), a rank-allocation framework that preserves the top-$k$ singular subspace of the activation-scaled weight before quantization, quantizes only the residual, and uses the remaining rank $r-k$ for error reconstruction. We derive a theory-guided criterion for selecting $k$ by balancing quantization-exposed energy  and unrecoverable error under rank constraints. We further show that resulting $\\mathbf{Q}+\\mathbf{L}\\mathbf{R}$ parameterization naturally supports Quantized Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (QPEFT), and stabilizes fine-tuning via gradient scaling along preserved directions. Experiments demonstrate consistent perplexity reductions across diverse models and quantization settings in PTQ, along with a 5.9 percentage-point average gain on GLUE under 2-bit QPEFT.","absKo":"Quantization Error Reconstruction (QER)мқҖ weightsлҘј $\\mathbf{W} \\approx \\mathbf{Q} + \\mathbf{L}\\mathbf{R}$лЎң к·јмӮ¬н•ҳкі , quantization errorлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ rank-$r$ correctionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң Post-Training Quantization (PTQ)м—җм„ңмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„ мҶҗмӢӨмқ„ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ м „мІҙ rank budgetмқ„ error reconstructionм—җ н• лӢ№н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, $\\mathbf{W}$к°Җ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң low-rank structureлҘј к°Җм§Җл©° quantizationмқҙ dominant directionsлҘј нӣјмҶҗн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°м—җлҠ” мқҙлҠ” мөңм Ғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Structured Residual Reconstruction (SRR)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” activation-scaled weightмқҳ top-$k$ singular subspaceлҘј quantization м „м—җ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳкі , residualл§Ң quantizeн•ҳл©°, лӮЁмқҖ rank $r-k$лҘј error reconstructionм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” rank-allocation frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” quantizationм—җ л…ём¶ңлҗҳлҠ” energyмҷҖ rank constraints н•ҳм—җм„ң ліөкө¬ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң errorлҘј к· нҳ• мһҲкІҢ кі л Өн•ҳм—¬ $k$лҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” theory-guided criterionмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мқҙл ҮкІҢ м–»м–ҙм§„ $\\mathbf{Q}+\\mathbf{L}\\mathbf{R}$ parameterizationмқҙ Quantized Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (QPEFT)мқ„ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкі , ліҙмЎҙлҗң directionsлҘј л”°лқј gradient scalingмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ fine-tuningмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң modelкіј quantization settingм—җм„ң PTQмқҳ perplexityлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лӮ®м¶”м—Ҳкі , 2-bit QPEFTм—җм„ңлҠ” GLUEм—җм„ң нҸүк·  5.9 percentage-pointмқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"61752","en":"Recursive Models for Long-Horizon Reasoning","ko":"Long-Horizon м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң Recursive Model","authors":"Chenxiao Yang, Nati Srebro, Zhiyuan Li","pos":"#1505","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nERMuZtneC","abs":"<p>Modern language models reason within bounded attention size, a physical constraint that poses a fundamental barrier to long-horizon reasoning. We identify recursion as a core principle for overcoming this barrier, and propose recursive models as a minimal realization, where the model can recursively invoke itself to solve subtasks in sequences that are contextually isolated. We prove that any computable problem admits a recursive decomposition where subtasks require only exponentially smaller active context than standard autoregressive models, and this approach strictly surpasses any single-context management approaches such as summarization. We further show that modern agentic systems are naturally suited for realizing recursion in a generalized way where arbitrary processing of contexts and workflows is allowed, and prove they can achieve the same power as recursive models, yet none can surpass it. Experimentally, we train a 3B model to learn recursive reasoning and evaluate on SAT, finding that it significantly outperforms frontier LLMs.</p>","absKo":"нҳ„лҢҖ language modelмқҖ bounded attention size лӮҙм—җм„ң м¶”лЎ н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мһҘкё°м Ғ reasoningм—җ лҢҖн•ң к·јліём Ғмқё мһҘлІҪмқҙ лҗҳлҠ” л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ м ңм•ҪмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мһҘлІҪмқ„ к·№ліөн•ҳлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ мӣҗлҰ¬лЎң recursionмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , modelмқҙ contextм ҒмңјлЎң л¶„лҰ¬лҗң sequenceм—җм„ң н•ҳмң„ кіјм ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҠӨмҠӨлЎңлҘј мһ¬к·Җм ҒмңјлЎң нҳём¶ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ кө¬нҳ„мңјлЎң recursive modelмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁл“  кі„мӮ° к°ҖлҠҘн•ң л¬ём ңлҠ” н•ҳмң„ кіјм ңк°Җ standard autoregressive modelм—җ л№„н•ҙ нҷңм„ұ contextлҘј м§ҖмҲҳм ҒмңјлЎң лҚ” мһ‘кІҢл§Ң мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” recursive decompositionмқ„ к°–лҠ”лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳл©°, мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ summarizationкіј к°ҷмқҖ лӢЁмқј-context кҙҖлҰ¬ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ м—„кІ©нһҲ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„лҢҖмқҳ agentic systemмқҙ мһ„мқҳмқҳ contextмҷҖ workflow мІҳлҰ¬к°Җ н—Ҳмҡ©лҗҳлҠ” мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗң л°©мӢқмңјлЎң recursionмқ„ мӢӨнҳ„н•ҳкё°м—җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ м Ғн•©н•ҳл©°, recursive modelкіј лҸҷмқјн•ң нһҳмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң к·ё лҲ„кө¬лҸ„ к·ёкІғмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•  мҲҳ м—ҶмқҢмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 3B modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөмӢңмјң recursive reasoningмқ„ мқөнһҲкІҢ н•ҳкі  SATм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, frontier LLMмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"68821","en":"ToMoE: Converting Dense Large Language Models to Mixture-of-Experts through Dynamic Structural Pruning","ko":"ToMoE: лҸҷм Ғ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ Pruningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ л°Җм§‘ лҢҖнҳ• м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ Mixture-of-ExpertsлЎң ліҖнҷҳ","authors":"Shangqian Gao, Ting Hua, Reza Shirkavand, Chi-Heng Lin, Zheng Tang, Zhengao Li, Longge Yuan, Fangyi Li, Zeyu Zhang, Alireza Ganjdanesh, Qian Lou, Jie Xu, Yen-Chang Hsu","pos":"#4316","abs":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs) demonstrate remarkable capabilities but face deployment challenges due to their high computational demands. Traditional pruning methods reduce these costs by permanently removing parameters, which inevitably leads to performance degradation. To mitigate this issue, we propose ToMoE, a method that transforms dense LLMs into Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) models by uncovering experts inherently present within dense models, without requiring any weight updates. ToMoE leverages dynamic structural pruning to unify expert construction and router training in a single stage, achieving consistently strong performance. Remarkably, even without fine-tuning \\revise{the model weights}, ToMoE consistently outperforms state-of-the-art pruning and MoE techniques across Phi-2, LLaMA-2, LLaMA-3, and Qwen-2.5 models. The code for this paper is available at https://github.com/gaosh/ToMoE.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Model(LLM)мқҖ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјм§Җл§Ң лҶ’мқҖ кі„мӮ° мҡ”кө¬лҹү л•Ңл¬ём—җ л°°нҸ¬м—җ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. м „нҶөм Ғмқё pruning л°©лІ•мқҖ нҢҢлқјлҜён„°лҘј мҳҒкө¬м ҒмңјлЎң м ңкұ°н•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л№„мҡ©мқ„ мӨ„мқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҠ” н•„м—°м ҒмңјлЎң м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” weight update м—Ҷмқҙ dense model лӮҙл¶Җм—җ ліёлһҳ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” expertлҘј м°ҫм•„лӮҙм–ҙ dense LLMмқ„ Mixture-of-Experts(MoE) modelлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқё ToMoEлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ToMoEлҠ” dynamic structural pruningмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ expert constructionкіј router trainingмқ„ лӢЁмқј лӢЁкі„лЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳл©°, мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к°•н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„ model weightлҘј fine-tuningн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•„лҸ„ ToMoEлҠ” Phi-2, LLaMA-2, LLaMA-3, Qwen-2.5 model м „л°ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art pruning л°Ҹ MoE кё°лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҳ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://github.com/gaosh/ToMoE м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66182","en":"SciPredict: Can LLMs Predict the Outcomes of Scientific Experiments in Natural Sciences?","ko":"SciPredict: LLMмқҖ мһҗм—°кіјн•ҷ мӢӨн—ҳмқҳ кІ°кіјлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ?","authors":"Udari Sehwag, Elaine Lau, Haniyeh Oskouie, Shayan Shabihi, Erich Liang, Andrea Toledo, Guillermo Mangialardi, Sergio Fonrouge, Ed-Yeremai Hernandez-Cardona, Paula Vergara, Utkarsh Tyagi, Chen Bo Calvin Zhang, Pavi Bhatter, Nicholas Johnson, Furong Huang, Ernesto Montoya, Bing Liu","pos":"#1500","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=61xHri3kqI","abs":"Accelerating scientific discovery requires the identification of which experiments would yield the best outcomes before committing resources to costly physical validation. While existing benchmarks evaluate LLMs on scientific knowledge and reasoning, their ability to predict experimental outcomes---a task where AI could significantly exceed human capabilities---remains largely underexplored. We introduce SciPredict, a benchmark comprising 405 tasks derived from recent empirical studies in 33 specialized sub-fields of physics, biology, and chemistry. SciPredict addresses two critical questions: (a) *can LLMs predict the outcome of scientific experiments with sufficient accuracy?* and (b) *can such predictions be reliably used in the scientific research process?* Evaluations reveal fundamental limitations on both fronts. Model accuracies are 14-26\\% and human  expert performance is $\\approx$20\\%. Although some frontier models exceed human performance model accuracy is still far below what would enable reliable experimental guidance. Even within the limited performance, models fail to distinguish reliable predictions from unreliable ones, achieving only $\\approx$20\\% accuracy regardless of their confidence or whether they judge outcomes as predictable without physical experimentation. Human experts, in contrast, demonstrate strong calibration: their accuracy increases from $\\approx$5\\% to $\\approx$80\\% as they deem outcomes more predictable without conducting the experiment. SciPredict establishes a rigorous framework demonstrating that superhuman performance in experimental science requires not just better predictions, but better awareness of prediction reliability. For reproducibility all our data and code are provided at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/SciPredict-AI01.","absKo":"кіјн•ҷм Ғ л°ңкІ¬мқ„ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳл Өл©ҙ, л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ кІҖмҰқм—җ мһҗмӣҗмқ„ нҲ¬мһ…н•ҳкё° м „м—җ м–ҙл–Ө мӢӨн—ҳмқҙ к°ҖмһҘ мўӢмқҖ кІ°кіјлҘј лӮјм§Җ мӢқлі„н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬л“Өмқҙ LLMмқҳ кіјн•ҷм Ғ м§ҖмӢқкіј м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, AIк°Җ мқёк°„ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мғҒнҡҢн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кіјм ңмқё мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј мҳҲмёЎ лҠҘл ҘмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¬јлҰ¬, мғқл¬јн•ҷ, нҷ”н•ҷмқҳ 33к°ң м „л¬ё н•ҳмң„ л¶„м•јм—җм„ң мөңк·јмқҳ мӢӨмҰқ м—°кө¬лЎңл¶Җн„° лҸ„м¶ңн•ң 405к°ң нғңмҠӨнҒ¬лЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬ SciPredictлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. SciPredictлҠ” лӢӨмқҢ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ м§Ҳл¬ём—җ лӢөн•ңлӢӨ: (a) *LLMмқҖ кіјн•ҷ мӢӨн—ҳмқҳ кІ°кіјлҘј м¶©л¶„н•ң м •нҷ•лҸ„лЎң мҳҲмёЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ?* к·ёлҰ¬кі  (b) *к·ёлҹ¬н•ң мҳҲмёЎмқ„ кіјн•ҷ м—°кө¬ кіјм •м—җм„ң мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ?* нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіј, л‘җ мёЎл©ҙ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң к·јліём Ғмқё н•ңкі„к°Җ л“ңлҹ¬лӮңлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚё м •нҷ•лҸ„лҠ” 14-26\\%мқҙкі  мқёк°„ м „л¬ёк°Җ м„ұлҠҘмқҖ $\\approx$20\\%мқҙлӢӨ. мқјл¶Җ frontier modelмқҙ мқёк°„ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңкё°лҸ„ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, лӘЁлҚё м •нҷ•лҸ„лҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мӢӨн—ҳ м§Җм№Ёмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳкё°м—җлҠ” н•ңм°ё л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. м ңн•ңм Ғмқё м„ұлҠҘ лІ”мң„ м•Ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„, лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мҳҲмёЎкіј мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” мҳҲмёЎмқ„ кө¬л¶„н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳл©°, мһҗмӢ к°җ мҲҳмӨҖмқҙлӮҳ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ мӢӨн—ҳ м—Ҷмқҙ кІ°кіјлҘј мҳҲмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨкі  нҢҗлӢЁн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м—¬л¶ҖмҷҖ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳкІҢ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҠ” $\\approx$20\\%м—җ лЁёл¬ёлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ мқёк°„ м „л¬ёк°ҖлҠ” к°•н•ң calibrationмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ кІ°кіјлҘј лҚ” мҳҲмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨкі  нҢҗлӢЁн• мҲҳлЎқ м •нҷ•лҸ„к°Җ $\\approx$5\\%м—җм„ң $\\approx$80\\%лЎң мҰқк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. SciPredictлҠ” мӢӨн—ҳ кіјн•ҷм—җм„ңмқҳ мҙҲмқём Ғ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ мҳҲмёЎлҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј мҳҲмёЎ мӢ лў°м„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ мқёмӢқмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјлҠ” м—„л°Җн•ң н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мһ¬нҳ„м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ҙ лӘЁл“  лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/SciPredict-AI01м—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64226","en":"On Training Large Language Models for Long-Horizon Tasks: An Empirical Study of Horizon Length","ko":"мһҘкё° мҳҲмёЎ кіјм ңлҘј мң„н•ң лҢҖнҳ• м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё н•ҷмҠө: мҳҲмёЎ м§ҖнҸү кёёмқҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨмҰқ м—°кө¬","authors":"Sunghwan Kim, Junhee Cho, Beong-woo Kwak, Taeyoon Kwon, Liang Wang, Nan Yang, Xingxing Zhang, Furu Wei, Jinyoung Yeo","pos":"#1609","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PnHfrCMKtp","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) have shown promise as interactive agents that solve tasks through extended sequences of environment interactions. While prior work has primarily focused on system-level optimizations or algorithmic improvements, the role of task horizon length in shaping training dynamics remains poorly understood. In this work, we present a systematic empirical study that examines horizon length through controlled task constructions. Specifically, we construct controlled tasks in which agents face identical decision rules and reasoning structures, but differ only in the length of action sequences required for successful completion. Our results reveal that increasing horizon length alone constitutes a training bottleneck, inducing severe training instability driven by exploration difficulties and credit assignment challenges. We demonstrate that horizon reduction is a key principle to address this limitation, stabilizing training and achieving better performance in long-horizon tasks. Moreover, we find that horizon reduction is related to stronger generalization across horizon lengths: models trained under reduced horizons generalize more effectively to longer-horizon variants at inference time, a phenomenon we refer to as horizon generalization.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language model (LLM)мқҖ нҷ•мһҘлҗң environment interaction sequenceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ кіјм ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” interactive agentлЎңм„ң мң л§қн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң мӢңмҠӨн…ң мҲҳмӨҖ мөңм Ғнҷ”лӮҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ к°ңм„ м—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶° мҷ”мңјл©°, task horizon lengthк°Җ training dynamicsлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ нҳ•м„ұн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҠ” м¶©л¶„нһҲ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” нҶөм ңлҗң task кө¬м„ұмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ horizon lengthлҘј мӮҙнҺҙліҙлҠ” мІҙкі„м Ғмқё мӢӨмҰқ м—°кө¬лҘј аӨӘаҘҚаӨ°аӨёаҘҚаӨӨаҘҒаӨӨн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” agentк°Җ лҸҷмқјн•ң decision ruleкіј reasoning structureлҘј л§ҲмЈјн•ҳм§Җл§Ң м„ұкіөм Ғмқё мҷ„лЈҢм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң action sequenceмқҳ кёёмқҙл§Ң лӢӨлҘё controlled taskлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” horizon lengthлҘј лҠҳлҰ¬лҠ” кІғл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ training bottleneckмқҙ нҳ•м„ұлҗҳл©°, нғҗмғүмқҳ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖкіј credit assignment л¬ём ңм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң training instabilityк°Җ мң л°ңлҗЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” horizon reductionмқҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ мӣҗлҰ¬мһ„мқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, trainingмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкі  long-horizon taskм—җм„ң лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, horizon reductionмқҙ horizon length м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң лҚ” к°•н•ң generalizationкіј кҙҖл ЁлҗЁмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мҰү, reduced horizonмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ inference мӢң лҚ” кёҙ horizon ліҖнҳ•м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лҚ” нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң generalizeн•ҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј horizon generalizationмқҙлқј л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64634","en":"Rubric Curriculum RL: Exploiting the Generation-Verification Gap in Creative Writing","ko":"Rubric Curriculum RL: м°Ҫмқҳм Ғ кёҖм“°кё°м—җм„ң Generation-Verification Gap нҷңмҡ©","authors":"Tejas Krishnan, Sumeet Motwani, Charles London, Suhaas Bhat, Huitian Jiao, Phil Torr, Riashat Islam, Christopher Summerfield, Christian Schroeder de Witt, Qilong Gu, Shital Shah","pos":"#4416","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=LShWfvQzTP","abs":"<p>Reinforcement learning with verifiable rewards (RLVR) on foundation models has led to significant improvements in math and code generation. Extending these gains to open-ended domains remains challenging: ground-truth verification is unavailable, human annotation is expensive, and learnt reward models are prone to reward hacking. We introduce Rubric Curriculum RL (RcRL), a self-improvement method for creative short-fiction writing that requires no new data, human annotations, or stronger teacher models. RcRL exploits the generation-verification gap: it is easier to judge whether work is creative than to produce something creative. While this gap exists across open-ended domains, exploiting it for RL is challenging due to reward hacking. During training, we use pairwise preferences against a curriculum of rubric criteria, which provides a more stable signal than absolute scoring while reducing reward hacking against a stationary objective. Unlike baseline methods, which plateau or collapse within a few dozen steps, our approach preserves output entropy and shows improvements over 1000+ training steps. In human evaluations, RcRL-trained models achieve a 70.5% win rate and demonstrate consistent gains across multiple creative writing benchmarks and judges.</p>","absKo":"<p>foundation modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң verifiable rewards (RLVR) кё°л°ҳ reinforcement learningмқҖ мҲҳн•ҷкіј code generationм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ мқҙлҒҢм—ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мқҙл“қмқ„ open-ended domainмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. ground-truth verificationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ м—Ҷкі , human annotationмқҖ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬л©°, н•ҷмҠөлҗң reward modelмқҖ reward hackingм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°, human annotation, лҚ” к°•н•ң teacher model м—Ҷмқҙ м°Ҫмһ‘ лӢЁнҺёмҶҢм„Ө мһ‘л¬ёмқ„ мң„н•ң мһҗкё°к°ңм„  л°©лІ•мқё Rubric Curriculum RL (RcRL)мқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. RcRLмқҖ generation-verification gapмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, м°Ҫмқҳм Ғмқё мһ‘м—…мқ„ мӮ°м¶ңн•ҳлҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ к·ёкІғмқҙ м°Ҫмқҳм Ғмқём§Җ нҢҗлӢЁн•ҳлҠ” нҺёмқҙ лҚ” мүҪлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң gapмқҖ open-ended domain м „л°ҳм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҘј RLм—җ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ reward hacking л•Ңл¬ём—җ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘м—җлҠ” rubric criterionмқҳ curriculumм—җ лҢҖн•ң pairwise preferenceлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” stationary objectiveм—җ лҢҖн•ң reward hackingмқ„ мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ң absolute scoringліҙлӢӨ лҚ” м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё signalмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳмӢӯ step лӮҙм—җ plateauн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ collapseн•ҳлҠ” baseline л°©лІ•л“Өкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ output entropyлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©° 1000 stepмқҙ л„ҳлҠ” н•ҷмҠө лҸҷм•Ҳ к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. human evaluationм—җм„ң RcRLлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ 70.5%мқҳ win rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , м—¬лҹ¬ м°Ҫмһ‘ кёҖм“°кё° benchmarkмҷҖ judgeм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64825","en":"V1: Unifying Generation and Self-Verification for Parallel Reasoners","ko":"V1: лі‘л ¬ ReasonerлҘј мң„н•ң мғқм„ұкіј мһҗкё° кІҖмҰқ нҶөн•©","authors":"Harman Singh, Xiuyu Li, Kusha Sareen, Monishwaran Maheswaran, Sijun Tan, Xiaoxia (Shirley) Wu, Junxiong Wang, Alpay Ariyak, Qingyang Wu, Samir Khaki, Rishabh Tiwari, Long (Tony) Lian, Yucheng Lu, Boyi Li, Alane Suhr, Ben Athiwaratkun, Kurt Keutzer","pos":"#4600","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=JOy3UmERXS","abs":"<p>Test-time scaling for complex reasoning tasks shows that leveraging inference-time compute, for example by independently sampling and aggregating multiple solutions, results in significantly better task outcomes. However, a critical bottleneck is <em>verification</em>: sampling is only effective if correct solutions can be reliably identified among candidates. While existing approaches typically evaluate candidates independently via scalar scoring, we demonstrate that models are substantially stronger at <strong>pairwise self-verification</strong>. Leveraging this insight, we introduce <strong>V1</strong>, a framework that unifies generation and verification through efficient pairwise ranking. V1 comprises two components: <strong>V1-Infer</strong>, an uncertainty-guided algorithm using a tournament-based ranking that dynamically allocates self-verification compute to candidate pairs whose relative correctness is most uncertain; and <strong>V1-PairRL</strong>, an RL framework that <strong>jointly trains</strong> a single model as both generator and pairwise self-verifier, ensuring the verifier adapts to the generator's evolving distribution. On code generation (LiveCodeBench, CodeContests) and math reasoning (AIME, HMMT) benchmarks, V1-Infer improves Pass@1 by up to 10\\% over pointwise verification and outperforms recent test-time scaling methods while being significantly more efficient. Furthermore, V1-PairRL achieves 7-9\\% test-time scaling gains over standard RL and pointwise joint training, and improves base Pass@1 by up to 8.7\\% over standard RL.</p>","absKo":"ліөмһЎн•ң reasoning taskм—җм„ңмқҳ test-time scalingмқҖ inference-time computeлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•  л•Ң, мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ м—¬лҹ¬ н•ҙлӢөмқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң samplingн•ҳкі  aggregateн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң, task кІ°кіјлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ к°ңм„ н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ н•өмӢ¬ лі‘лӘ©мқҖ <em>verification</em>мқҙлӢӨ. samplingмқҖ м •лӢө нӣ„ліҙлҘј мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ мӢқлі„н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„ л•Ңл§Ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң scalar scoringмңјлЎң нӣ„ліҙлҘј к°ңлі„м ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ <strong>pairwise self-verification</strong>м—җм„ңлҠ” нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” к°•н•ҳлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё pairwise rankingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ generationкіј verificationмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” <strong>V1</strong> н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. V1мқҖ л‘җ кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. <strong>V1-Infer</strong>лҠ” tournament кё°л°ҳ rankingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” uncertainty-guided algorithmмңјлЎң, мғҒлҢҖм Ғ м •лӢөм„ұмқҙ к°ҖмһҘ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨн•ң нӣ„ліҙ мҢҚм—җ self-verification computeлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң н• лӢ№н•ңлӢӨ. <strong>V1-PairRL</strong>мқҖ лӢЁмқј лӘЁлҚёмқ„ generatorмқҙмһҗ pairwise self-verifierлЎң <strong>jointly train</strong>н•ҳлҠ” RL н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лЎң, verifierк°Җ generatorмқҳ ліҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л¶„нҸ¬м—җ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. code generation (LiveCodeBench, CodeContests)кіј math reasoning (AIME, HMMT) benchmarkм—җм„ң V1-InferлҠ” pointwise verification лҢҖл№„ Pass@1мқ„ мөңлҢҖ 10\\%к№Ңм§Җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, мөңк·ј test-time scaling л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ лҚ” нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң V1-PairRLмқҖ standard RL л°Ҹ pointwise joint training лҢҖл№„ 7-9\\%мқҳ test-time scaling н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , standard RL лҢҖл№„ base Pass@1мқ„ мөңлҢҖ 8.7\\%к№Ңм§Җ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64254","en":"ActiveScope: Actively Seeking and Correcting Perception for MLLMs","ko":"ActiveScope: MLLMмқ„ мң„н•ң лҠҘлҸҷм Ғ мқёмӢқ нғҗмғү л°Ҹ мҲҳм •","authors":"Yajing Wang, Chao Bi, Junshu Sun, Shufan Shen, Zhaobo Qi, Shuhui Wang, Qingming Huang","pos":"#3900","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PStNoNZveu","abs":"Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) have demonstrated impressive capabilities in vision-language understanding, yet they still struggle with fine-grained perception in high-resolution images. While existing training-free methods typically rely on attention-based localization or coarse-to-fine search, they are often misled by distractors and fail to locate multiple targets. To address these limitations, our investigation reveals two causes for failed localization: (a)\\textit{Contextual Dominance}, where salient distractors overwhelm target attention, leading to inaccurate localization, and (b) \\textit{Semantic Bias}, where aggregated global semantics cause the model to fixate on the most salient concept, resulting in incomplete localization under multi-object scenarios. Built on these insights, we propose {ActiveScope}, a training-free framework that enhances MLLMs by actively seeking and correcting perception. ActiveScope features two modules. The \\textit{Semantic Anchor Localization (SAL)} utilizes fine-grained semantics as anchors to independently localize key targets, thereby mitigating semantic bias. The \\textit{Interference-Suppressed Refinement (ISR)} refines localization by suppressing attention on salient distractions, effectively overcoming contextual dominance. Extensive experiments on high-resolution image understanding benchmarks demonstrate that ActiveScope outperforms existing training-free methods(e.g., 96.34\\% accuracy on $V^{*}$ Bench), validating the superiority of the active search and self-correction paradigm.","absKo":"Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs)лҠ” vision-language understandingм—җм„ң мқёмғҒм Ғмқё лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙмҳҖм§Җл§Ң, кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ мқҙлҜём§Җм—җм„ңмқҳ м„ёл°Җн•ң perceptionм—җлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ training-free methodлҠ” лҢҖмІҙлЎң attention-based localization лҳҗлҠ” coarse-to-fine searchм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, distractorм—җ мүҪкІҢ мҳӨлҸ„лҗҳкі  м—¬лҹ¬ targetмқ„ м°ҫлҠ” лҚ° мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мЎ°мӮ¬м—җм„ңлҠ” localization мӢӨнҢЁмқҳ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мӣҗмқёмқ„ л°қнҳҖлғҲлӢӨ. (a)\\textit{Contextual Dominance}, мҰү л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„ distractorк°Җ target attentionмқ„ м••лҸ„н•ҳм—¬ л¶Җм •нҷ•н•ң localizationмқ„ мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒкіј, (b) \\textit{Semantic Bias}, мҰү м§‘кі„лҗң м „м—ӯ мқҳлҜёк°Җ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ к°ҖмһҘ л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„ к°ңл…җм—җ кі м°©мӢңмјң multi-object мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң л¶Ҳмҷ„м „н•ң localizationмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°° мң„м—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” perceptionмқ„ м Ғк·№м ҒмңјлЎң нғҗмғүн•ҳкі  көҗм •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ MLLMмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” training-free framework {ActiveScope}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ActiveScopeлҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ лӘЁл“Ҳмқ„ к°–лҠ”лӢӨ. \\textit{Semantic Anchor Localization (SAL)}мқҖ м„ёл°Җн•ң semanticsлҘј anchorлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ н•өмӢ¬ targetмқ„ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң localizationн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ semantic biasлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. \\textit{Interference-Suppressed Refinement (ISR)}мқҖ л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„ л°©н•ҙ мҡ”мҶҢм—җ лҢҖн•ң attentionмқ„ м–өм ңн•ҳм—¬ localizationмқ„ м •м ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ contextual dominanceлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң к·№ліөн•ңлӢӨ. кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ мқҙлҜём§Җ мқҙн•ҙ benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ ActiveScopeк°Җ кё°мЎҙ training-free methodлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ(мҳҲ: $V^{*}$ Benchм—җм„ң 96.34\\% accuracy). мқҙлҠ” лҠҘлҸҷм Ғ нғҗмғүкіј мһҗкё° көҗм • нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҳ мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64313","en":"Embedding Trust: Semantic Isotropy Predicts Nonfactuality in Long-Form Text Generation","ko":"мӢ лў° мһ„лІ л”©: мӢңл§ЁнӢұ л“ұл°©м„ұмқҙ мһҘл¬ё н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мғқм„ұм—җм„ң л№„мӮ¬мӢӨм„ұмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Dhrupad Bhardwaj, Julia Kempe, Tim G. J. Rudner","pos":"#1909","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OrcJhUqdNG","abs":"<p>To deploy large language models (LLMs) in high-stakes application domains that require substantively accurate responses to open-ended prompts, we need reliable, computationally inexpensive methods that assess the trustworthiness of long-form responses generated by LLMs. However, existing approaches often rely on claim-by-claim fact-checking, which is computationally expensive and brittle in long-form responses to open-ended prompts. In this work, we introduce semantic isotropyвҖ”the degree of uniformity across normalized text embeddings on the unit sphereвҖ”and use it to assess the trustworthiness of long-form responses generated by LLMs. To do so, we generate several long-form responses, embed them, and estimate the level of semantic isotropy of these responses as the angular dispersion of the embeddings on the unit sphere. We find that higher semantic isotropyвҖ”that is, greater embedding dispersionвҖ”reliably signals lower factual consistency across samples. Our approach requires no labeled data, no fine-tuning, and no hyperparameter selection, and can be used with open- or closed-weight embedding models. Across multiple domains, our method consistently outperforms existing approaches in predicting nonfactuality in long-form responses using only a handful of samplesвҖ”offering a practical, low-cost approach for integrating trust assessment into real-world LLM workflows.</p>","absKo":"<p>кі мң„н—ҳ application domainм—җм„ң м—ҙлҰ° нҳ•нғңмқҳ promptм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ substantively accurateн•ң мқ‘лӢөмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” large language model(LLM)мқ„ л°°нҸ¬н•ҳл Өл©ҙ, LLMмқҙ мғқм„ұн•ң кёҙ нҳ•мӢқ мқ‘лӢөмқҳ trustworthinessлҘј нҸүк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲкі  кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ лӮ®мқҖ л°©лІ•мқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лҢҖк°ң мЈјмһҘ лӢЁмң„мқҳ fact-checkingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кі  м—ҙлҰ° нҳ•нғң promptм—җ лҢҖн•ң кёҙ нҳ•мӢқ мқ‘лӢөм—җм„ңлҠ” м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” semantic isotropy, мҰү лӢЁмң„ кө¬л©ҙмғҒм—җм„ң м •к·ңнҷ”лҗң text embeddingмқҳ к· мқјм„ұ м •лҸ„лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ LLMмқҙ мғқм„ұн•ң кёҙ нҳ•мӢқ мқ‘лӢөмқҳ trustworthinessлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ м—¬лҹ¬ к°ңмқҳ кёҙ нҳ•мӢқ мқ‘лӢөмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬ embeddingн•ҳкі , лӢЁмң„ кө¬л©ҙмғҒм—җм„ңмқҳ embedding angular dispersionмңјлЎң мқҙл“Өмқҳ semantic isotropy мҲҳмӨҖмқ„ м¶”м •н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” semantic isotropyк°Җ лҶ’мқ„мҲҳлЎқ, мҰү embedding dispersionмқҙ нҒҙмҲҳлЎқ sample к°„ factual consistencyк°Җ лӮ®мқҢмқ„ м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң мӢңмӮ¬н•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ labeled data, fine-tuning, hyperparameter selectionмқҙ м „нҳҖ н•„мҡ”н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, open-weight embedding modelкіј closed-weight embedding model лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ лҸ„л©”мқём—җ кұёміҗ, мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ sampleл§ҢмңјлЎң кёҙ нҳ•мӢқ мқ‘лӢөмқҳ nonfactualityлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҲм–ҙ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, мӢӨм ң LLM workflowм—җ trust assessmentлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқҙкі  м Җл№„мҡ©мқҳ м ‘к·јмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65105","en":"ProMeCD: Unifying Long-Tailed and Noisy Label Learning via White-Box Control","ko":"ProMeCD: нҷ”мқҙнҠёл°•мҠӨ м ңм–ҙлҘј нҶөн•ң лЎұн…Ңмқј л°Ҹ л…ёмқҙмҰҲ л Ҳмқҙлё” н•ҷмҠөмқҳ нҶөн•©","authors":"Yu Zhu","pos":"#1000","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=GjfStlzQiC","abs":"<p>Real-world data is rarely clean; it is plagued by severe class imbalance (long-tailed distributions) and label corruption. Current solutions lean heavily on ''black-box\" meta-learning to re-weight samples. However, this paradigm introduces a fatal circular dependency: it relies on pristine, balanced validation sets to guide the optimization, which are essentially non-existent in the wild. We propose ProMeCD, a self-referential framework that breaks this dependency by recasting optimization as an autonomous control problem. Instead of training an opaque neural meta-learner, we employ a transparent proportional-integral controller. The system monitors ''cognitive entropy'' that is a metric derived from von Mises-Fisher gradient statistics to assess learning uncertainty. To resolve the scalar ambiguity between tail and noisy samples, ProMeCD employs a decoupled control strategy: it boosts tail classes via integral accumulation of magnitude deficits when directional consistency is high, while suppressing noise via proportional feedback when consistency collapses. Theoretically, we prove that this mechanism guarantees convergence and formally prevents the minority initial drop, ensuring monotonic improvement for rare classes. Crucially, ProMeCD is fully white-box and validation-free. Experiments on CIFAR-LT, iNaturalist, CIFAR-N, and mini WebVision confirm that ProMeCD is not merely efficient; it outperforms the recent meta-learner FMW-Net by over 10\\% in severe imbalance settings, proving that explicit control theory offers a superior path to handling imperfect data.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„мӢӨ м„ёкі„мқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” кІ°мҪ” к№ЁлҒ—н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң class imbalance(long-tailed distribution)мҷҖ label corruptionм—җ мӢңлӢ¬лҰ°лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ н•ҙлІ•мқҖ sample re-weightingмқ„ мң„н•ҙ ''black-box\" meta-learningм—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҖ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ pristineн•ҳкі  balancedн•ң validation setм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м№ҳлӘ…м Ғмқё мҲңнҷҳ мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң setмқҙ мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мһҗмңЁ м ңм–ҙ л¬ём ңлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ лҒҠлҠ” мһҗкё°м°ёмЎ°м Ғ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ ProMeCDлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л¶ҲнҲ¬лӘ…н•ң neural meta-learnerлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҲ¬лӘ…н•ң proportional-integral controllerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҖ learning uncertaintyлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ von Mises-Fisher gradient statisticм—җм„ң лҸ„м¶ңлҗң м§Җн‘ңмқё ''cognitive entropy''лҘј лӘЁлӢҲн„°л§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. tail sampleкіј noisy sample мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ scalar ambiguityлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, ProMeCDлҠ” л¶„лҰ¬лҗң control strategyлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. л°©н–Ҙ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҙ лҶ’мқ„ л•ҢлҠ” magnitude deficitмқҳ integral accumulationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ tail classлҘј к°•нҷ”н•ҳкі , мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҙ л¬ҙл„Ҳм§Ҳ л•ҢлҠ” proportional feedbackмңјлЎң noiseлҘј м–өм ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙ convergenceлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳкі  minority initial dropлҘј нҳ•мӢқм ҒмңјлЎң л°©м§Җн•ҳм—¬ нқ¬к·Җ classм—җ лҢҖн•ң лӢЁмЎ°м Ғ к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙмһҘн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң ProMeCDлҠ” мҷ„м „н•ң white-boxмқҙл©° validation-freeмқҙлӢӨ. CIFAR-LT, iNaturalist, CIFAR-N, mini WebVisionм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ ProMeCDк°Җ лӢЁм§Җ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкё°л§Ң н•ң кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқјлҠ” м җмқ„ нҷ•мқёмӢңмјң мӨҖлӢӨ. мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң imbalance м„Өм •м—җм„ң мөңк·ј meta-learnerмқё FMW-NetліҙлӢӨ 10\\% мқҙмғҒ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬, лӘ…мӢңм Ғ control theoryк°Җ л¶Ҳмҷ„м „н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” лҚ° лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң кІҪлЎңмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62191","en":"Probabilistic Robustness Certificates against Adversarial Attacks","ko":"Adversarial Attackм—җ лҢҖн•ң Probabilistic Robustness Certificate","authors":"Sara Taheri, Majid Zamani","pos":"#1001","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=itrFag3Z9v","abs":"The growing use of machine learning in safety-critical settings heightens vulnerability to *adversarial attacks*. Existing defense mechanisms typically either lack formal guarantees or depend on restrictive assumptions about the model family, the threat model, or the poisoning budget, and many only offer point-wise certification. Importantly, they often overlook the inherent stochasticity of modern training pipelines, which undermines their practical reliability. We introduce a probabilistic framework that views gradient-based training as a *discrete-time stochastic dynamical system* and formulates poisoning robustness as a safety verification task. Leveraging *barrier certificates* (BCs), we derive sufficient conditions to probabilistically certify a robust radius against worst-case ${\\ell}_p$-bounded poisoning, guaranteeing that the final model parameters remain within a safe set. For tractable computation, we represent BCs with neural networks and obtain *probably approximately correct* (PAC) guarantees through a *scenario convex problem*. Our method identifies the largest certified radius for which the trained model is probabilistically accurate with a specified confidence level. Experiments on MNIST, SVHN, and CIFAR-10 show that our framework offers formal robustness guarantees under stochastic training, while being model-agnostic and not requiring prior knowledge of the attack strategy.","absKo":"м•Ҳм „мқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м„Өм •м—җм„ң machine learningмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мқҙ мҰқк°Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң *adversarial attack*м—җ лҢҖн•ң м·Ём•Ҫм„ұмқҙ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©м–ҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ лҢҖк°ң formal guaranteeк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, model family, threat model, poisoning budgetм—җ лҢҖн•ң м ңн•ңм Ғмқё к°Җм •м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, л§ҺмқҖ кІҪмҡ° point-wise certificationл§Ң м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мқҙл“ӨмқҖ нҳ„лҢҖ training pipelineмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғ stochasticityлҘј к°„кіјн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ м•Ҫнҷ”мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” gradient-based trainingмқ„ *discrete-time stochastic dynamical system*мңјлЎң ліҙкі  poisoning robustnessлҘј safety verification taskлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” probabilistic frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. *barrier certificate* (BC)лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мөңм•…мқҳ кІҪмҡ° ${\\ell}_p$-bounded poisoningм—җ лҢҖн•ң robust radiusлҘј probabilistically certifiyн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң м¶©л¶„мЎ°кұҙмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкі , мөңмў… model parameterк°Җ safe set лӮҙм—җ лӮЁм•„ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. кі„мӮ° к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ҙ BCлҘј neural networkлЎң н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳкі , *scenario convex problem*мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ *probably approximately correct* (PAC) guaranteeлҘј м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ м§Җм •лҗң confidence levelм—җм„ң probabilistically accurateн•ң trained modelм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ к°ҖмһҘ нҒ° certified radiusлҘј мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. MNIST, SVHN, CIFAR-10 мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkк°Җ stochastic training н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ formal robustness guaranteeлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, model-agnosticн•ҳкі  attack strategyм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӮ¬м „ м§ҖмӢқмқҙ н•„мҡ” м—ҶмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"60969","en":"SORA: Free Second Order Attacks in Fast Adversarial Training","ko":"SORA: Fast Adversarial Trainingм—җм„ңмқҳ Free Second Order Attacks","authors":"Mazdak Teymourian, Ramtin Moslemi, Farzan Rahmani, Mohammad H Rohban","pos":"#1002","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=uynAkGdnmj","abs":"<p>Adversarial Training (AT) is a leading defense against adversarial examples but often suffers from Catastrophic Overfitting (CO) in efficient single-step variants, where robustness to multi-step attacks collapses despite high single-step performance. We address this failure mode with two contributions. First, we identify Epsilon Overfitting (EO), a previously overlooked phenomenon in which fixed perturbation magnitudes exacerbate CO, and show that introducing perturbation variability significantly improves robust generalization across different architectures and datasets. Second, we propose <strong>PertAlign</strong> (Perturbation Alignment), a theoretically grounded, computationally negligible metric that predicts CO onset by measuring gradient alignment across attack stages. Leveraging these insights, we introduce <strong>SORA</strong>, an adaptive step-size adversarial training method that dynamically adjusts perturbations based on loss-surface geometry. SORA consistently prevents CO, achieves state-of-the-art robustness and clean accuracy, and generalizes across datasets and architectures using a single fixed set of hyperparameters. Extensive experiments on diverse datasets and architectures, show that SORA matches or surpasses the robustness of prior methods while delivering higher clean accuracy and superior efficiency.</p>","absKo":"<p>Adversarial Training(AT)мқҖ adversarial exampleм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё л°©м–ҙ кё°лІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, efficient single-step variantм—җм„ңлҠ” мў…мў… Catastrophic Overfitting(CO)мқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ кІҪмҡ° high single-step performanceм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  multi-step attackм—җ лҢҖн•ң robustnessк°Җ л¶•кҙҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ кё°м—¬лЎң мқҙ мӢӨнҢЁ лӘЁл“ңлҘј лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Epsilon Overfitting(EO)мқ„ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” fixed perturbation magnitudeк°Җ COлҘј м•…нҷ”мӢңнӮӨлҠ”, мқҙм „м—җ к°„кіјлҗҳм—ҲлҚҳ нҳ„мғҒмқҙл©°, perturbation variabilityлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳл©ҙ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё architectureмҷҖ dataset м „л°ҳм—җм„ң robust generalizationмқҙ мң мқҳн•ҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кіөкІ© лӢЁкі„ м „л°ҳмқҳ gradient alignmentлҘј мёЎм •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ COмқҳ мӢңмһ‘ мӢңм җмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң нғҖлӢ№н•ҳкі  кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ м—ҶлҠ” metricмқё <strong>PertAlign</strong>(Perturbation Alignment)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” loss-surface geometryм—җ л”°лқј perturbationмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ҳлҠ” adaptive step-size adversarial training л°©лІ•мқё <strong>SORA</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SORAлҠ” COлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ л°©м§Җн•ҳкі , state-of-the-art мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ robustnessмҷҖ clean accuracyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ кі м •лҗң hyperparameter м§‘н•©л§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ datasetкіј architecture м „л°ҳмңјлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetкіј architectureм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SORAк°Җ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ robustnessмҷҖ лҸҷл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ clean accuracyмҷҖ лҚ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65209","en":"SkillTrojan: Backdoor Attacks on Skill-Based Agent Systems","ko":"SkillTrojan: мҠӨнӮ¬ кё°л°ҳ м—җмқҙм „нҠё мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң л°ұлҸ„м–ҙ кіөкІ©","authors":"Yunhao Feng, Yifan Ding, Yingshui Tan, Boren Zheng, Yanming Guo, Xiaolong Li, Kun Zhai, Yishan Li, Wenke Huang","pos":"#1003","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FlnQlvkYR3","abs":"<p>Skill-based agent systems tackle complex tasks by composing reusable skills, improving modularity and scalability while introducing a largely unexamined security attack surface. We propose \\textbf{SkillTrojan}, a backdoor attack that targets skill implementations rather than model parameters or training data. SkillTrojan embeds malicious logic inside otherwise plausible skills and leverages standard skill composition to reconstruct and execute an attacker-specified payload. The attack partitions an encrypted payload across multiple benign-looking skill invocations and activates only under a predefined trigger.  SkillTrojan also supports automated synthesis of backdoored skills from arbitrary skill templates, enabling scalable propagation across skill-based agent ecosystems. To enable systematic evaluation, we release a dataset of 3,000+ curated backdoored skills spanning diverse skill patterns and triggerвҖ“payload configurations. We instantiate SkillTrojan in a representative code-based agent setting and evaluate both clean-task utility and attack success rate. Our results show that skill-level backdoors can be highly effective with minimal degradation of benign behavior, exposing a critical blind spot in current skill-based agent architectures and motivating defenses that explicitly reason about skill composition and execution. Concretely, on EHR SQL, SkillTrojan attains up to \\textbf{97.2\\%} ASR while maintaining \\textbf{89.3\\%} clean ACC on GPT-5.2-1211-Global.</p>","absKo":"<p>Skill-based agent systemмқҖ мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң skillмқ„ мЎ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ ліөмһЎн•ң мһ‘м—…мқ„ мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳл©°, modularityмҷҖ scalabilityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ кІҖнҶ лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ ліҙм•Ҳ attack surfaceлҘј мғҲлЎӯкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚё parameterлӮҳ training dataк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј skill implementation мһҗмІҙлҘј кІЁлғҘн•ң backdoor attackмқё \\textbf{SkillTrojan}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SkillTrojanмқҖ кІүліҙкё°м—җлҠ” к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•ң skill лӮҙл¶Җм—җ м•…м„ұ лЎңм§Ғмқ„ мӮҪмһ…н•ҳкі , н‘ңмӨҖ skill compositionмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ attackerк°Җ м§Җм •н•ң payloadлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мӢӨн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ attackмқҖ м•”нҳёнҷ”лҗң payloadлҘј м—¬лҹ¬ к°ңмқҳ benign-looking skill invocationм—җ л¶„мӮ°мӢңнӮӨкі , лҜёлҰ¬ м •мқҳлҗң triggerк°Җ мһҲмқ„ л•Ңл§Ң нҷңм„ұнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. SkillTrojanмқҖ лҳҗн•ң мһ„мқҳмқҳ skill templateлЎңл¶Җн„° backdoored skillмқ„ мһҗлҸҷ н•©м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кё°лҠҘмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳм—¬, skill-based agent ecosystem м „л°ҳмңјлЎңмқҳ нҷ•мӮ°мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мІҙкі„м Ғмқё нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң skill patternкіј triggerвҖ“payload кө¬м„ұмқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” 3,000к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ м •м ңлҗң backdoored skill datasetмқ„ кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё code-based agent settingм—җм„ң SkillTrojanмқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•ҳкі  clean-task utilityмҷҖ attack success rateлҘј лӘЁл‘җ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. кІ°кіјлҠ” skill-level backdoorк°Җ benign behaviorмқҳ м Җн•ҳлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ л§Өмҡ° нҡЁкіјм Ғмқј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ skill-based agent architectureк°Җ к°Җм§„ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң blind spotмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙкі  skill compositionкіј executionмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м¶”лЎ н•ҳлҠ” defenseмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ м ңкё°н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң EHR SQLм—җм„ң SkillTrojanмқҖ GPT-5.2-1211-Globalм—җм„ң \\textbf{97.2\\%} ASRмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң \\textbf{89.3\\%} clean ACCлҘј мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66774","en":"TCAP: Tri-Component Attention Profiling for Unsupervised Backdoor Detection in MLLM Fine-Tuning","ko":"TCAP: MLLM Fine-Tuningм—җм„ң л№„м§ҖлҸ„ л°ұлҸ„м–ҙ нғҗм§ҖлҘј мң„н•ң Tri-Component Attention Profiling","authors":"Mingzu Liu, Hao Fang, Runmin Cong","pos":"#1004","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0RBjF3JSXG","abs":"<p>Fine-Tuning-as-a-Service (FTaaS) facilitates the customization of Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs) but introduces critical backdoor risks via poisoned data. Existing defenses either rely on supervised signals or fail to generalize across diverse trigger types and modalities. In this work, we uncover a universal backdoor fingerprintвҖ”<strong>attention allocation divergence</strong>вҖ”where poisoned samples disrupt the balanced attention distribution across three functional components: system instructions, vision inputs, and user textual queries, regardless of trigger morphology. Motivated by this insight, we propose <strong>Tri-Component Attention Profiling (TCAP)</strong>, an unsupervised defense framework to filter backdoor samples. TCAP decomposes cross-modal attention maps into the three components, identifies trigger-responsive attention heads via Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM) statistical profiling, and isolates poisoned samples through EM-based vote aggregation. Extensive experiments across diverse MLLM architectures and attack methods demonstrate that TCAP achieves consistently strong performance, establishing it as a robust and practical backdoor defense in MLLMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>Fine-Tuning-as-a-Service (FTaaS)лҠ” Multimodal Large Language Models (MLLMs)мқҳ л§һм¶Өнҷ”лҘј мҡ©мқҙн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, poisoned dataлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мӨ‘лҢҖн•ң backdoor riskлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©м–ҙ кё°лІ•мқҖ supervised signalм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, лӢӨм–‘н•ң trigger typeкіј modality м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” trigger morphologyмҷҖ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳкІҢ poisoned sampleмқҙ system instructions, vision inputs, user textual queriesлқјлҠ” м„ё кё°лҠҘ кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢ м „л°ҳмқҳ к· нҳ• мһЎнһҢ attention distributionмқ„ көҗлһҖмӢңнӮӨлҠ” ліҙнҺём Ғ backdoor fingerprintмқё <strong>attention allocation divergence</strong>лҘј л°ңкІ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” backdoor sampleмқ„ н•„н„°л§Ғн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң unsupervised defense frameworkмқё <strong>Tri-Component Attention Profiling (TCAP)</strong>мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. TCAPмқҖ cross-modal attention mapмқ„ м„ё кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳкі , Gaussian Mixture Model (GMM) нҶөкі„м Ғ н”„лЎңнҢҢмқјл§Ғмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ trigger-responsive attention headлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳл©°, EM-based vote aggregationмңјлЎң poisoned sampleмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң MLLM architectureмҷҖ attack method м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ TCAPмқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ҳл©°, MLLMм—җм„ңмқҳ кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё backdoor defenseлЎң мһҗлҰ¬л§Өк№Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63705","en":"Toward Understanding Adversarial Distillation: Why Robust Teachers Fail","ko":"Adversarial Distillation мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкё°: мҷң Robust TeacherлҠ” мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ”к°Җ","authors":"Hongsin Lee, Hye Won Chung","pos":"#1005","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=USejwpvj0a","abs":"<p>Adversarial Distillation aims to enhance student robustness by guiding the student with a robust teacher's soft labels within the min-max adversarial training framework, yet its success is notoriously inconsistent: a more robust teacher often fails to improve, or even harms, the student's robust generalization.  In this paper, we identify a key mechanism of this teacher dependency: the misalignment between the teacher's supervisory confidence and the student's representational limitations on a consistent subset of training dataвҖ”the Robustly Unlearnable Set. We present a theoretical framework analyzing the feature learning dynamics of a two-layer neural network, demonstrating that this mismatch creates a dichotomy in distillation outcomes.  We prove that when a teacher provides confident supervision on unlearnable samples, it compels the student to memorize spurious noise patterns that eventually overpower the learned robust signal, thereby driving robust overfitting. Conversely, a teacher that exhibits high uncertainty on these samples effectively suppresses noise memorization, allowing the student to rely solely on the learnable signal for robust generalization. We empirically validate our theory across both synthetic simulations and real-image classification datasets, confirming that robust overfitting is driven by the teacher's interaction with unlearnable samples. Finally, we demonstrate that a teacher's predictive entropy on unlearnable samples serves as a strong indicator of student robustness, validating our theoretical framework and offering a principled guideline for robust teacher selection.</p>","absKo":"<p>Adversarial DistillationмқҖ min-max adversarial training framework м•Ҳм—җм„ң robust teacherмқҳ soft labelлЎң studentлҘј м§ҖлҸ„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ student robustnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл Ө н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё м„ұкіөмқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡё м •лҸ„лЎң мқјкҙҖлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. лҚ” robustн•ң teacherк°Җ мҳӨнһҲл Ө studentмқҳ robust generalizationмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мӢ¬м§Җм–ҙ н•ҙм№ҳкё°лҸ„ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң teacher dependenceмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёкІғмқҖ Robustly Unlearnable Setмқҙлқј л¶ҲлҰ¬лҠ” training dataмқҳ мқјкҙҖлҗң subsetм—җм„ң teacherмқҳ supervisory confidenceмҷҖ studentмқҳ representational limitation мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ misalignmentмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” two-layer neural networkмқҳ feature learning dynamicsлҘј л¶„м„қн•ҳлҠ” theoretical frameworkлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳк°Җ distillation кІ°кіјм—җм„ң dichotomyлҘј л§Ңл“ лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. teacherк°Җ unlearnable sampleм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ confident supervisionмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©ҙ, studentлҠ” кІ°көӯ learned robust signalмқ„ м••лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” spurious noise patternмқ„ м•”кё°н•ҳкІҢ лҗҳм–ҙ robust overfittingмңјлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. л°ҳлҢҖлЎң teacherк°Җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң sampleм—җм„ң лҶ’мқҖ uncertaintyлҘј ліҙмқҙл©ҙ noise memorizationмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м–өм ңн•ҳм—¬, studentк°Җ robust generalizationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ learnable signalм—җл§Ң мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” synthetic simulationкіј мӢӨм ң мқҙлҜём§Җ л¶„лҘҳ dataset лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мқҙ мқҙлЎ мқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•ҳм—¬, robust overfittingмқҙ unlearnable sampleм—җ лҢҖн•ң teacherмқҳ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©м—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗЁмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, unlearnable sampleм—җ лҢҖн•ң teacherмқҳ predictive entropyк°Җ student robustnessмқҳ к°•л Ҙн•ң м§Җн‘ңлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ theoretical frameworkлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳкі  robust teacher м„ нғқмқ„ мң„н•ң principled guidelineмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61378","en":"Two Modalities Are Better Than One: Efficient Adversarial Purification via Multimodal Diffusion Models","ko":"л‘җ Modalitiesк°Җ н•ҳлӮҳліҙлӢӨ лӮ«лӢӨ: Multimodal Diffusion ModelsлҘј нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Adversarial Purification","authors":"Mingyuan Bai, Wei Huang, Tenghui Li, Andong Wang, Chao Li, Cesar F Caiafa, Junbin Gao, Qibin Zhao","pos":"#1006","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qpno1WY4rt","abs":"<p>Adversarial purification uses generative models to restore clean data distributions from unseen attacks without retraining classifiers. However, unimodal diffusion-based approaches struggle to preserve semantic consistency, while recent multimodal variants rely on computationally expensive adversarial training or distillation. Both approaches often lack theoretical guarantees. In this work, we propose MultiDAP, a novel framework leveraging multimodal diffusion models for efficient adversarial purification. MultiDAP first learns continuous class-agnostic prompts from clean data to capture rich semantic priors, replacing rigid hand-crafted templates. Guided by these prompts, MultiDAP purifies adversarial inputs by minimizing a regularized DDPM loss for only a few steps (e.g., 5-20). We provide theoretical guarantees for both the likelihood improvement via prompt learning and the convergence of the purification process. Extensive experiments on CIFAR-10, CIFAR-100, and ImageNet-1K demonstrate that MultiDAP matches the robustness of state-of-the-art baselines but with improved efficiency.</p>","absKo":"<p>Adversarial purificationмқҖ л¶„лҘҳкё°лҘј мһ¬н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң кіөкІ©мңјлЎңл¶Җн„° к№ЁлҒ—н•ң data distributionмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ unimodal diffusion-based approachлҠ” semantic consistencyлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, мөңк·јмқҳ multimodal ліҖнҳ•мқҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° adversarial training лҳҗлҠ” distillationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. л‘җ м ‘к·јлІ• лӘЁл‘җ мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ кІ°м—¬н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё adversarial purificationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ multimodal diffusion modelмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkмқё MultiDAPлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. MultiDAPлҠ” лЁјм Җ к№ЁлҒ—н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎңл¶Җн„° continuous class-agnostic promptлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬, кІҪм§Ғлҗң hand-crafted templateлҘј лҢҖмІҙн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н’Қл¶Җн•ң semantic priorлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң promptмқҳ м•ҲлӮҙлҘј л°ӣм•„ MultiDAPлҠ” к·ңм ңлҗң DDPM lossлҘј лӘҮ к°ңмқҳ step(мҳҲ: 5-20)л§Ң мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ adversarial inputмқ„ м •нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” prompt learningмқ„ нҶөн•ң likelihood н–ҘмғҒкіј purification processмқҳ мҲҳл ҙ лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. CIFAR-10, CIFAR-100, ImageNet-1Kм—җм„ңмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ MultiDAPк°Җ state-of-the-art baselineкіј лҸҷл“ұн•ң robustnessлҘј ліҙмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” н–ҘмғҒлҗң нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61055","en":"Unifying Adversarial Robustness and Training Across Text Scoring Models","ko":"н…ҚмҠӨнҠё мұ„м җ лӘЁлҚё м „л°ҳмқҳ м ҒлҢҖм Ғ к°•кұҙм„ұкіј н•ҷмҠө нҶөн•©","authors":"Manveer Tamber, Hosna Oyarhoseini, Jimmy Lin","pos":"#1007","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=u7kOAJ9uH7","abs":"<p>Research on adversarial robustness in language models is currently fragmented across applications and attacks, obscuring shared vulnerabilities. In this work, we propose unifying the study of adversarial robustness in text scoring models spanning dense retrievers, rerankers, and reward models. Unlike open-ended generation, text scoring failures are directly testable: an attack succeeds when an irrelevant or rejected text outscores a relevant or chosen one. Using this principled lens of text scoring, we demonstrate that current adversarial training formulations for language models are often short-sighted, failing to effectively generalize across attacks. To address this, we introduce multiple adversarial training methods for text scorers and show that combining complementary training methods can yield strong robustness while also improving task effectiveness. Finally, we highlight the practical value of our approach for RLHF, showing that our adversarially trained reward models mitigate reward hacking and support the training of better-aligned LLMs.  We provide our code and models for further study.</p>","absKo":"<p>м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң adversarial robustnessм—җ лҢҖн•ң м—°кө¬лҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ applicationкіј attack м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ нҢҢнҺёнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмңјл©°, кіөмң лҗҳлҠ” м·Ём•Ҫм җмқ„ к°ҖлҰ¬кі  мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” dense retriever, reranker, reward modelмқ„ м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” text scoring modelм—җм„ң adversarial robustness м—°кө¬лҘј нҶөн•©н•  кІғмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. open-ended generationкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, text scoringмқҳ мӢӨнҢЁлҠ” м§Ғм ‘ н…ҢмҠӨнҠён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҰү, irrelevantн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ rejectedлҗң textк°Җ relevantн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ chosenлҗң textліҙлӢӨ лҶ’мқҖ scoreлҘј м–»мңјл©ҙ attackмқҙ м„ұкіөн•ң кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё text scoring кҙҖм җм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ language modelмҡ© adversarial training formulationмқҙ мў…мў… лӢЁкё°м Ғмқҙл©° attack м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ text scorerлҘј мң„н•ң м—¬лҹ¬ adversarial training л°©лІ•мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , мғҒнҳё ліҙмҷ„м Ғмқё training methodлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳл©ҙ task effectivenessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ к°•н•ң robustnessлҘј м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ RLHFм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ к°–лҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ к°Җм№ҳлҘј к°•мЎ°н•ҳл©°, adversarially trained reward modelмқҙ reward hackingмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкі  лҚ” мһҳ м •л ¬лҗң LLMмқҳ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м¶”к°Җ м—°кө¬лҘј мң„н•ҙ мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ modelмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65463","en":"CREDIT: Certified Ownership Verification of Deep Neural Networks Against Model Extraction Attacks","ko":"CREDIT: Model Extraction кіөкІ©м—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” мӢ¬мёө мӢ кІҪл§қмқҳ мқёмҰқлҗң мҶҢмң к¶Ң кІҖмҰқ","authors":"Bolin Shen, Zhan Cheng, Neil Gong, Fan Yao, Yushun Dong","pos":"#1009","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=DQKoxCegwH","abs":"<p>Machine Learning as a Service (MLaaS) has become a widely adopted method for delivering deep neural network (DNN) models, allowing users to conveniently access models via APIs. However, such services have been shown to be highly vulnerable to Model Extraction Attacks (MEAs). While numerous defense strategies have been proposed, verifying the ownership of a suspicious model with strict theoretical guarantees remains a challenging task. To address this gap, we introduce CREDIT a certified defense against MEAs. Specifically, we employ mutual information to quantify the similarity between DNN models, propose a practical verification threshold, and provide rigorous theoretical guarantees for ownership verification based on this threshold. We extensively evaluate our approach on several mainstream datasets and achieve state-of-the-art performance. Our implementation is publicly available at: \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CREDIT}.</p>","absKo":"<p>Machine Learning as a Service(MLaaS)лҠ” deep neural network(DNN) лӘЁлҚёмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” л„җлҰ¬ мұ„нғқлҗң л°©мӢқмқҙ лҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗк°Җ APIлҘј нҶөн•ҙ нҺёлҰ¬н•ҳкІҢ лӘЁлҚём—җ м ‘к·јн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙмӨҖлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„ңл№„мҠӨлҠ” Model Extraction Attack(MEA)м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ л§Өмҡ° м·Ём•Ҫн•ң кІғмңјлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮ¬лӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ л°©м–ҙ м „лһөмқҙ м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, м—„кІ©н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ к°–лҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң мқҳмӢ¬мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мҶҢмң к¶Ңмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіөл°ұмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MEAм—җ лҢҖн•ң certified defenseмқё CREDITлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” mutual informationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ DNN лӘЁлҚё к°„ мң мӮ¬м„ұмқ„ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳкі , мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё verification thresholdлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙ thresholdм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң мҶҢмң к¶Ң кІҖмҰқм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м—„л°Җн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ мЈјмҡ” лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ҳкІҢ нҸүк°Җн•ҳм—¬ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬нҳ„мқҖ кіөк°ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмңјл©°: \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CREDIT}.</p>"},{"id":"66191","en":"Theory of Minimal Weight Perturbations in Deep Networks and its Applications for Low-Rank Activated Backdoor Attacks","ko":"мӢ¬мёө мӢ кІҪл§қм—җм„ңмқҳ мөңмҶҢ к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳ м„ӯлҸҷ мқҙлЎ кіј м Җкі„мҲҳ нҷңм„ұ л°ұлҸ„м–ҙ кіөкІ©м—җмқҳ мқ‘мҡ©","authors":"Bethan Evans, Jared Tanner","pos":"#1013","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5w6jwlRehY","abs":"<p>The minimal norm weight perturbations of DNNs required to achieve a specified change in output are derived and the factors determining its size are discussed. These single-layer exact formulae are contrasted with more generic multi-layer Lipschitz constant based robustness guarantees; both are observed to be of the same order which indicates similar efficacy in their guarantees. These results are applied to precision-modification-activated backdoor attacks, establishing provable compression thresholds below which such attacks cannot succeed, and show empirically that low-rank compression can reliably activate latent backdoors while preserving full-precision accuracy. These expressions reveal how back-propagated margins govern layer-wise sensitivity and provide certifiable guarantees on the smallest parameter updates consistent with a desired output shift.</p>","absKo":"<p>м§Җм •лҗң м¶ңл Ҙ ліҖнҷ”лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң DNNмқҳ мөңмҶҢ norm weight perturbationsлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳкі , к·ё нҒ¬кё°лҘј кІ°м •н•ҳлҠ” мҡ”мқёл“Өмқ„ л…јмқҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң single-layer exact formulaeлҠ” лҚ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё multi-layer Lipschitz constant кё°л°ҳ robustness guaranteesмҷҖ лҢҖл№„лҗҳл©°, л‘җ кІҪмҡ° лӘЁл‘җ к°ҷмқҖ м°ЁмҲҳмқҳ нҒ¬кё°лҘј ліҙмқҙлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң кҙҖм°°лҗҳм–ҙ ліҙмһҘ мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң мң мӮ¬н•ң нҡЁмҡ©мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҘј precision-modification-activated backdoor attacksм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіөкІ©мқҙ м„ұкіөн•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” provable compression thresholdsлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳкі , low-rank compressionмқҙ full-precision accuracyлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң latent backdoorsлҘј м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ мӢқл“ӨмқҖ back-propagated marginsк°Җ layer-wise sensitivityлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ мўҢмҡ°н•ҳлҠ”м§Җ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, мӣҗн•ҳлҠ” м¶ңл Ҙ ліҖнҷ”лҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” мөңмҶҢ parameter updatesм—җ лҢҖн•ң certifiable guaranteesлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65513","en":"Private and Stable Test-time Adaptation with Differential Privacy","ko":"Differential PrivacyлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң н”„лқјмқҙл№—н•ҳкі  м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё Test-time Adaptation","authors":"Zefeng Li, Qiaoyue Tang, Mathias LГ©cuyer, Evan Shelhamer","pos":"#1100","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ct0HIcLIMX","abs":"<p>Test-time adaptation (TTA) can reduce error on new and different data by updating the model on these inputs during inference. However, these updates raise the issue of privacy w.r.t. the testing data, because the model parameters now depend on all past inputs. To control this privacy risk, we cast multiple popular TTA methods (Tent, EATA, SAR, DeYO, and COME) into differential privacy (DP) forms that apply per-sample gradient clipping and Gaussian noise for all updates. On ImageNet-C, our DP-TTA methods provide adequate privacy at small cost to accuracy, and in the low-privacy regime the clipping mechanism of DP even improves the accuracy and stability of adaptation in the continual setting. These improvements to privacy and accuracy come at only only modest computational overhead. These first results on private TTA raise awareness of the issue, inform the development of more private test-time updates, and identify per-sample clipping as a reliable technique for improving the accuracy and stability of adaptation.</p>","absKo":"<p>Test-time adaptation (TTA)мқҖ м¶”лЎ  мӨ‘ мһ…л Ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л°Ҹ мғҒмқҙн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җм„ңмқҳ errorлҘј мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҠ” лӘЁлҚё нҢҢлқјлҜён„°к°Җ кіјкұ°мқҳ лӘЁл“  мһ…л Ҙм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкІҢ лҗҳлҜҖлЎң testing dataм—җ лҢҖн•ң privacy л¬ём ңлҘј м•јкё°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ privacy riskлҘј м ңм–ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” TTA method (Tent, EATA, SAR, DeYO, COME)лҘј differential privacy (DP) нҳ•нғңлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙл“Ө нҳ•нғңлҠ” лӘЁл“  м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠём—җ лҢҖн•ҙ per-sample gradient clippingкіј Gaussian noiseлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. ImageNet-Cм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ DP-TTA methodлҠ” м ҒмқҖ accuracy л№„мҡ©мңјлЎң м¶©л¶„н•ң privacyлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, low-privacy regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” DPмқҳ clipping mechanismмқҙ continual settingм—җм„ң adaptationмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ мҳӨнһҲл Ө н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң privacyмҷҖ accuracy к°ңм„ мқҖ мҳӨм§Ғ modestн•ң computational overheadл§Ңмқ„ мҲҳл°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. private TTAм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” н•ҙлӢ№ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқёмӢқмқ„ лҶ’мқҙкі , лҚ” privateн•ң test-time updateмқҳ к°ңл°ңм—җ м •ліҙлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, per-sample clippingмқҙ adaptationмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кё°лІ•мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60723","en":"PSMix: Robust Point Cloud Recognition through  Spectral Domain Mixing","ko":"PSMix: Spectral Domain Mixingмқ„ нҶөн•ң к°•кұҙн•ң Point Cloud мқёмӢқ","authors":"Xin Wei, Qin Yang, Hongji Zhao, Fei Gao, Mingrui Zhu, Nannan Wang, Xinbo Gao","pos":"#1101","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xCFGjhIVrt","abs":"<p>While data augmentation is essential for robust point cloud recognition, conventional spatial mixup strategies often compromise geometric integrity by generating physically unrealistic samples. To overcome this limitation, we propose PSMix, which shifts the mixing paradigm to the spectral domain via the Spherical Harmonic Transform. Instead of simple coordinate interpolation, PSMix performs a rotation-aware hierarchical mixing on spectral coefficients. This approach explicitly preserves global structural properties while diversifying local details, achieving a balance that spatial methods struggle to maintain. Complementing this, we introduce an adversarial rotation optimization strategy to enforce invariance against challenging orientations. Extensive experiments on ModelNet-C and ScanObjectNN-C demonstrate that PSMix achieves state-of-the-art robustness, while also serving as an orthogonal plug-in that further boosts the performance of existing spatial strategies.</p>","absKo":"<p>к°•кұҙн•ң point cloud recognitionмқ„ мң„н•ҙ data augmentationмқҖ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙмқҳ spatial mixup м „лһөмқҖ л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң л№„нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё мғҳн”Ңмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ л¬ҙкІ°м„ұмқ„ нӣјмҶҗн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳјн•© нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ Spherical Harmonic Transformмқ„ нҶөн•ң spectral domainмңјлЎң м „нҷҳн•ҳлҠ” PSMixлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лӢЁмҲңн•ң мўҢн‘ң ліҙк°„ лҢҖмӢ , PSMixлҠ” spectral coefficientм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ rotation-aware hierarchical mixingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ м§Җм—ӯм Ғ м„ёл¶Җ м •ліҙлҘј лӢӨм–‘нҷ”н•ҳл©ҙм„ң м „м—ӯ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ нҠ№м„ұмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмЎҙн•ҳм—¬, spatial methodл“Өмқҙ мң м§Җн•ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ к· нҳ•мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” challenging orientationм—җ лҢҖн•ң invarianceлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” adversarial rotation optimization strategyлҸ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. ModelNet-CмҷҖ ScanObjectNN-Cм—җм„ңмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PSMixк°Җ state-of-the-art robustnessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёкіј лҸҷмӢңм—җ, кё°мЎҙ spatial strategyмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬лҰ¬лҠ” orthogonal plug-inмңјлЎңлҸ„ кё°лҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62757","en":"Non-Parametric Probabilistic Robustness: A Conservative Risk Estimator under Unknown Perturbation Distributions","ko":"л№„лӘЁмҲҳ нҷ•лҘ м Ғ Robustness: м•Ң мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” м„ӯлҸҷ л¶„нҸ¬м—җм„ңмқҳ ліҙмҲҳм Ғ мң„н—ҳ м¶”м •кё°","authors":"Zheng Wang, Yi Zhang, Siddartha Khastgir, carsten maple, Xingyu Zhao","pos":"#1102","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ddIUBkzwIU","abs":"<p>Deep learning (DL) models, despite their remarkable success, remain vulnerable to small input perturbations that can cause erroneous outputs, motivating probabilistic robustness (PR) as a complementary notion to adversarial robustness (AR) for stochastic reliability assessment. However, existing PR formulations assume a fixed, known perturbation distribution, which is often unavailable or misspecified in practice. To address this limitation, we propose non-parametric probabilistic robustness (NPPR), a more conservative PR estimator over an admissible family of perturbation distributions. We instantiate NPPR with a tractable estimator (GMM-based) that supports four dependency structures (independent, label-, input-, and joint-dependent perturbations). We show that NPPR provably interpolates between AR and PR. Experiments on CIFAR-10/100 and TinyImageNet across multiple architectures show that NPPR yields consistently lower (more conservative) PR estimates than PR computed under common assumed distributions (e.g., Gaussian/Uniform), with up to 40\\% reduction in representative settings.</p>","absKo":"<p>Deep learning(DL) лӘЁлҚёмқҖ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұкіөм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , мһ‘мқҖ input perturbationм—җлҸ„ мһҳлӘ»лҗң м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ лӮј мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙ, stochastic reliability assessmentлҘј мң„н•ң adversarial robustness(AR)мқҳ ліҙмҷ„ к°ңл…җмңјлЎң probabilistic robustness(PR)к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ PR formulationмқҖ кі м •лҗң, м•Ңл Өм§„ perturbation distributionмқ„ к°Җм •н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң distributionмқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкұ°лӮҳ мһҳлӘ» лӘ…м„ёлҗҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙ н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” admissible family of perturbation distributions мң„м—җм„ң лҚ” ліҙмҲҳм Ғмқё PR estimatorмқё non-parametric probabilistic robustness(NPPR)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” NPPRмқ„ tractableн•ң estimator(GMM-based)лЎң кө¬мІҙнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ л„Ө к°Җм§Җ dependency structure(independent, label-, input-, к·ёлҰ¬кі  joint-dependent perturbation)лҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” NPPRмқҙ ARкіј PR мӮ¬мқҙлҘј provably ліҙк°„н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. CIFAR-10/100кіј TinyImageNetм—җм„ң м—¬лҹ¬ architectureм—җ кұём№ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ, NPPRмқҙ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң к°Җм •лҗң л¶„нҸ¬л“Ө(мҳҲ: Gaussian/Uniform) м•„лһҳм—җм„ң кі„мӮ°лҗң PRліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” лӮ®мқҖ(лҚ” ліҙмҲҳм Ғмқё) PR estimateлҘј мӮ°м¶ңн•ҳл©°, лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё м„Өм •м—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ 40% к°җмҶҢлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61021","en":"LLM Watermark Evasion via Bias Inversion","ko":"Bias Inversionмқ„ нҶөн•ң LLM Watermark нҡҢн”ј","authors":"Jeongyeon Hwang, Sangdon Park, Jungseul Ok","pos":"#1103","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=uTRcgqzAfl","abs":"<p>Watermarking offers a promising solution for detecting LLM-generated content, yet its robustness under realistic query-free (black-box) evasion remains an open challenge. Existing query-free attacks often achieve limited success or severely distort semantic meaning. We bridge this gap by theoretically analyzing rewriting-based evasion, demonstrating that reducing the average conditional probability of sampling green tokens by a small margin causes the detection probability to decay exponentially. Guided by this insight, we propose the Bias-Inversion Rewriting Attack (BIRA), a practical query-free method that applies a negative logit bias to a proxy suppression set identified via token surprisal. Empirically, BIRA achieves state-of-the-art evasion rates (&gt;99%) across diverse watermarking schemes while preserving semantic fidelity substantially better than prior baselines. Our findings reveal a fundamental vulnerability in current watermarking methods and highlight the need for rigorous stress tests.</p>","absKo":"<p>WatermarkingмқҖ LLM-generated contentлҘј нғҗм§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё query-free(black-box) evasion н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ robustnessлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м—ҙлҰ° кіјм ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ query-free attackмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң м„ұкіөлҘ мқҙ м ңн•ңм Ғмқҙкұ°лӮҳ мқҳлҜёлЎ м Ғ лӮҙмҡ©мқ„ мӢ¬н•ҳкІҢ нӣјмҶҗн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” rewriting-based evasionмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ҳм—¬ мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. мҰү, green tokenмқ„ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•  л•Ңмқҳ нҸүк·  conditional probabilityлҘј мһ‘мқҖ нҸӯмңјлЎң лӮ®м¶”кё°л§Ң н•ҙлҸ„ detection probabilityк°Җ м§ҖмҲҳм ҒмңјлЎң к°җмҶҢн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°м—җ л”°лқј, token surprisalмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мӢқлі„н•ң proxy suppression setм—җ negative logit biasлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ query-free л°©лІ•мқё Bias-Inversion Rewriting Attack (BIRA)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң BIRAлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң watermarking scheme м „л°ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art evasion rate(&gt;99%)лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, кё°мЎҙ baselineліҙлӢӨ semantic fidelityлҘј нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” мһҳ ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ watermarking л°©лІ•мқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё м·Ём•Ҫм„ұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, м—„кІ©н•ң stress testмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64578","en":"Iterative Robust Satisficing: Minimizing Performance Degradation Under Distribution Shift","ko":"л°ҳліөм Ғ Robust Satisficing: л¶„нҸ¬ мқҙлҸҷ н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳ мөңмҶҢнҷ”","authors":"Enes AДҹДұrman, Artun Saday, Cem Tekin","pos":"#1104","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=M0LllT3KX0","abs":"<p>Modern neural networks often achieve high accuracy on their training distribution but degrade sharply under distribution shifts.  We address this problem through <em>Robust Satisficing</em> (RS), an optimization objective that seeks parameters which attain a target level of in-distribution performance while minimizing <em>fragility</em>, defined as the rate at which performance deteriorates as the data distribution departs from training.  We develop a gradient-based algorithm, <em>Iterative Robust Satisficing</em> (IRS), that directly optimizes this criterion. Across a range of synthetic and real-world distribution shifts, including long-tailed image classification, group shifts induced by spurious correlations, and natural shifts in tabular regression, IRS consistently improves performance on minority and worst-case groups without sacrificing overall accuracy.  Notably, IRS achieves these robustness gains with a per-step computational cost similar to standard stochastic gradient descent and requires only a single forward and backward pass per update.  Together, these results suggest that minimizing fragility provides a practical and effective alternative to existing robust training methods for learning models that remain reliable under distribution shift.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖ neural networkлҠ” мў…мў… training distributionм—җм„ңлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, distribution shift н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” кёүкІ©нһҲ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј <em>Robust Satisficing</em> (RS)мңјлЎң лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. RSлҠ” in-distribution м„ұлҠҘмқҳ лӘ©н‘ң мҲҳмӨҖмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, м„ұлҠҘмқҙ training distributionм—җм„ңмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶„нҸ¬ мқҙнғҲм—җ л”°лқј м Җн•ҳлҗҳлҠ” мҶҚлҸ„лЎң м •мқҳлҗҳлҠ” <em>fragility</em>лҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” optimization objectiveмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ кё°мӨҖмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” gradient-based algorithmмқё <em>Iterative Robust Satisficing</em> (IRS)лҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. long-tailed image classification, spurious correlationм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң л°ңлҗҳлҠ” group shift, tabular regressionм—җм„ңмқҳ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ shiftлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң synthetic л°Ҹ real-world distribution shift м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, IRSлҠ” м „мІҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң minority л°Ҹ worst-case group м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ IRSлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ stochastic gradient descentмҷҖ мң мӮ¬н•ң stepлӢ№ computational costлЎң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң robustness н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, updateл§ҲлӢӨ лӢЁ н•ң лІҲмқҳ forward passмҷҖ backward passл§Ң н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” fragility мөңмҶҢнҷ”к°Җ distribution shift н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң кё°мЎҙ robust training л°©лІ•мқҳ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё лҢҖм•Ҳмһ„мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61052","en":"Higher-Order Certified Robustness for Regression","ko":"нҡҢк·ҖлҘј мң„н•ң кі м°Ё Certified Robustness","authors":"Jie Zhang, Natalie Frank","pos":"#1105","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=u96qokgpPR","abs":"Randomized smoothing has emerged as a scalable technique for certifying the adversarial robustness of classifiers. However, its application to regression remains under-explored and faces unique challenges. Existing regression certificates rely on probabilistic acceptance regions and fail to exploit the local geometry of the function. In this work, we present a novel framework for certified robust regression that addresses these limitations. We derive a prediction-centered certificate that guarantees the stability of the smoothed modelвҖҷs prediction and ensures practical computability at test time. We investigate several alternatives for constructing these certificates by explicitly incorporating means, variances, and gradients. In particular we demonstrate on the MNIST rotation task that utilizing gradient information yields significantly tighter robustness certificates compared to the current state-of-the-art, $\\alpha$-smoothing.","absKo":"Randomized smoothingмқҖ classifierмқҳ adversarial robustnessлҘј мқёмҰқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кё°лІ•мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ regressionм—җмқҳ м Ғмҡ©мқҖ м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳкі  кі мң н•ң лҸ„м „м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ regression certificateлҠ” probabilistic acceptance regionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©° н•ЁмҲҳмқҳ local geometryлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” certified robust regressionмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” smoothed modelмқҳ prediction м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкі  test timeм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ кі„мӮ° к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” prediction-centered certificateлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң mean, variance, gradientлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң certificateлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ лҢҖм•Ҳмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ MNIST rotation taskм—җм„ң gradient informationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ нҳ„мһ¬ state-of-the-artмқё $\\alpha$-smoothingм—җ л№„н•ҙ robustness certificateк°Җ нҳ„м ҖнһҲ лҚ” tightн•ҙм§җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"63275","en":"Hearing Without Noticing? Attention-Aware Stealthy Black-box Adversarial Audio Attacks","ko":"м•Ңм•„мұ„м§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкІҢ л“Јкё°? м–ҙн…җм…ҳ мқём§Җ мқҖл°Җн•ң лё”лһҷл°•мҠӨ м ҒлҢҖм Ғ мҳӨл””мҳӨ кіөкІ©","authors":"Tianyi Xu, Cheng&amp;#x27;an Wei, Yue Zhao, Kai Chen","pos":"#1106","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=YTk3CL8qA7","abs":"<p>Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) systems, such as those in intelligent assistants, are vulnerable to adversarial examples (AEs). Benign audio clips like music, when embedded with small perturbations, can trick ASR models into recognizing attacker-specified commands. Prior studies focus on minimizing perturbation magnitude to craft AEs. However, they fails to achieve high attack stealthiness against black-box ASR systems in the physical world. In this paper, we introduce the first music carrier selection algorithm and an attention-aware stealthiness loss function to generate stealthy AEs. Extensive evaluations on five commercial ASR APIs and three widely-used voice assistants demonstrate that our method significantly outperforms state-of-the-art techniques in both effectiveness and stealthiness. Notably, in a user study involving 200 participants, 55.6\\% of participants perceived our physical adversarial examples as benign audio, which is an improvement of over 20\\% compared to existing methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>м§ҖлҠҘнҳ• л№„м„ңмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ Automatic Speech Recognition (ASR) мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҖ adversarial examples (AEs)м—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҢм•…мІҳлҹј л¬ҙн•ҙн•ң мҳӨл””мҳӨ нҒҙлҰҪлҸ„ мһ‘мқҖ perturbationмқҙ мӮҪмһ…лҗҳл©ҙ ASR лӘЁлҚёмқҙ кіөкІ©мһҗк°Җ м§Җм •н•ң лӘ…л №мқ„ мқёмӢқн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мҶҚмқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң AEsлҘј м ңмһ‘н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ perturbation нҒ¬кё°лҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м§‘мӨ‘н•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙл“ӨмқҖ л¬јлҰ¬ м„ёкі„мқҳ black-box ASR мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лҶ’мқҖ кіөкІ© stealthinessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” stealthy AEsлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ music carrier selection algorithmкіј attention-aware stealthiness loss functionмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ мғҒмҡ© ASR APIмҷҖ л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” м„ё к°ңмқҳ voice assistantм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ нҡЁкіјм„ұкіј stealthiness м–‘мӘҪм—җм„ң мөңмӢ  кё°лІ•л“Өмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ 200лӘ…мқҳ м°ёк°Җмһҗк°Җ м°ём—¬н•ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м—°кө¬м—җм„ң, м°ёк°Җмһҗмқҳ 55.6\\%к°Җ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ physical adversarial examplesлҘј benign audioлЎң мқёмӢқн–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ• лҢҖл№„ 20\\%p мқҙмғҒ н–ҘмғҒлҗң кІ°кіјмқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65726","en":"Does a Hybrid Space-Aware Randomized Defense Improve Empirical and Certified Adversarial Robustness?","ko":"н•ҳмқҙлёҢлҰ¬л“ң кіөк°„ мқёмӢқ л¬ҙмһ‘мң„нҷ” л°©м–ҙк°Җ кІҪн—ҳм ҒВ·мқёмҰқлҗң м ҒлҢҖм Ғ к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ”к°Җ?","authors":"Joy Dhar, Manish Pandey, Behzad Bozorgtabar, Nayyar Zaidi, Wenyu Zhang, Weihong Li, Tingting Mu, Dwarikanath Mahapatra, Mahsa Baktashmotlagh, Trung Le, Chen Chen, Sajib Mistry, Camila Gonzalez, Samira Ebrahimi Kahou, Lina Yao, Piotr Koniusz, Robert Fisher, Dinh Phung, Bohyung Han, Nuno Vasconcelos, Pietro LiГі","pos":"#1107","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Alelgxnwgs","abs":"<p>We introduce Hybrid Space-aware Stochastic Convolution Attention Noise (HySCAN), a hybrid randomized defense that helps close the long-standing gap between provable robustness under в„“2 certificates and empirical robustness against strong в„“вҲһ attacks, while maintaining strong generalization across diverse imaging benchmarks. HySCAN jointly explores complementary sources of stochasticity at both training and inference: (i) implicit weight-space randomness via stochastic-aware Random Weights, and (ii) explicit feature-space randomness via Stochastic Attention Noise Injection modules. By incorporating randomness at both the parameter and representation levels, HySCAN enables meaningful certified guarantees while improving empirical robustness in practice. Comprehensive experiments on diverse imaging datasets, e.g., CelebA, CIFAR-10, and CIFAR-100, ImageNet-1k, HAM10000, and NIH Chest X-ray, demonstrate that HySCAN outperforms existing certified and empirical defenses, improving certified robustness by up to вүҲ 9.6% and empirical robustness by up to вүҲ 5% without reducing clean accuracy.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Hybrid Space-aware Stochastic Convolution Attention Noise (HySCAN)лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. HySCANмқҖ в„“2 certificate н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ provable robustnessмҷҖ к°•н•ң в„“вҲһ attackм—җ лҢҖн•ң empirical robustness мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мҳӨлһ«лҸҷм•Ҳ м§ҖмҶҚлҗң кІ©м°ЁлҘј л©”мҡ°лҠ” лҚ° лҸ„мӣҖмқ„ мЈјл©ҙм„ң, лӢӨм–‘н•ң imaging benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң к°•н•ң generalizationмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” hybrid randomized defenseмқҙлӢӨ. HySCANмқҖ trainingкіј inference м–‘мӘҪм—җм„ң мғҒнҳё ліҙмҷ„м Ғмқё stochasticityмқҳ мӣҗмІңмқ„ н•Ёк»ҳ нғҗмғүн•ңлӢӨ: (i) stochastic-aware Random WeightsлҘј нҶөн•ң implicit weight-space randomness, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (ii) Stochastic Attention Noise Injection moduleмқ„ нҶөн•ң explicit feature-space randomnessмқҙлӢӨ. parameter мҲҳмӨҖкіј representation мҲҳмӨҖ лӘЁл‘җм—җ randomnessлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, HySCANмқҖ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” certified guaranteeлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ мӢӨм ңлЎң empirical robustnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. CelebA, CIFAR-10, CIFAR-100, ImageNet-1k, HAM10000, NIH Chest X-ray л“ұ лӢӨм–‘н•ң imaging datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ мў…н•© мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ HySCANмқҙ кё°мЎҙ certified л°Ҹ empirical defenseлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, clean accuracyлҘј м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮӨм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң certified robustnessлҘј мөңлҢҖ м•Ҫ 9.6%, empirical robustnessлҘј мөңлҢҖ м•Ҫ 5%к№Ңм§Җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63714","en":"Class-Conditional Distribution Balancing for Group Robust Classification","ko":"к·ёлЈ№ к°•кұҙ л¶„лҘҳлҘј мң„н•ң нҒҙлһҳмҠӨ мЎ°кұҙл¶Җ л¶„нҸ¬ к· нҳ•нҷ”","authors":"Miaoyun Zhao, Qiang Zhang","pos":"#1108","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=UNVBuVmLDE","abs":"<p>Spurious correlations that lead models to correct predictions for the wrong reasons pose a critical challenge for robust real-world generalization. Existing research attributes this issue to group imbalance and addresses it by maximizing group-balanced or worst-group accuracy, which heavily relies on expensive bias annotations. A compromise approach involves predicting bias information using extensively pretrained foundation models, which requires large-scale data and is limited to physically interpretable biases. To address these challenges, we offer a novel perspective by reframing the spurious correlations as imbalances/mismatches in class-conditional distributions caused by general biases, whether interpretable or not, and propose a simple yet effective robust learning method that eliminates the need for bias annotations or predictions. With the goal of maximizing the conditional entropy (uncertainty) of the label given spurious factors, our method leverages a sample reweighting strategy to achieve class-conditional distribution balancing, which automatically highlights minority groups and classes, effectively dismantling spurious correlations and producing a debiased data distribution for classification. Extensive experiments and analysis demonstrate that our approach consistently delivers state-of-the-art performance, rivaling methods that rely on bias supervision.</p>","absKo":"<p>лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мһҳлӘ»лҗң мқҙмң лЎң мҳ¬л°”лҘё мҳҲмёЎмқ„ н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” spurious correlationмқҖ мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңмқҳ кІ¬кі н•ң мқјл°ҳнҷ”м—җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң лҸ„м „ кіјм ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј group imbalanceм—җ кё°мқён•ң кІғмңјлЎң ліҙкі , мқҙлҘј group-balanced accuracy лҳҗлҠ” worst-group accuracyлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҠ” л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° bias annotationм—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. м Ҳм¶©м•ҲмңјлЎңлҠ” кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ҳкІҢ мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөлҗң foundation modelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ bias м •ліҙлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқҙ мһҲмңјлӮҳ, мқҙлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳкі  л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң biasм—җл§Ң м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” spurious correlationмқ„ н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘ м—¬л¶ҖмҷҖ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ң мқјл°ҳ biasк°Җ мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” class-conditional distributionмқҳ imbalance/mismatchлЎң мһ¬м •мқҳн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кҙҖм җмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , bias annotationмқҙлӮҳ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ м „нҳҖ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё robust learning л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. spurious factorк°Җ мЈјм–ҙмЎҢмқ„ л•Ң labelмқҳ conditional entropy(uncertainty)лҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ңлӢӨлҠ” лӘ©н‘ң м•„лһҳ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ sample reweighting м „лһөмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ class-conditional distribution balancingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ minority groupкіј classлҘј мһҗлҸҷмңјлЎң л¶Җк°ҒмӢңнӮӨкі  spurious correlationмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙмІҙн•ҳм—¬ classificationмқ„ мң„н•ң debiased data distributionмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳкіј л¶„м„қмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҙ bias supervisionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•л“Өкіј кІ¬мӨ„ л§Ңн•ң мҲҳмӨҖмңјлЎң, мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61695","en":"Certified Robustness under Heterogeneous Perturbations via Hybrid Randomized Smoothing","ko":"Hybrid Randomized Smoothingмқ„ нҶөн•ң мқҙм§Ҳм Ғ Perturbation н•ҳмқҳ Certified Robustness","authors":"Blaise Delattre, Hengyu WU, Paul Caillon, Wei Yang Bryan Lim, YANG CAO","pos":"#1109","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nf7JT1jCSy","abs":"<p>Randomized smoothing provides strong, model-agnostic robustness certificates, but existing guarantees are limited to single modalities, treating continuous and discrete inputs in isolation. This limitation becomes critical in multimodal models, where decisions depend on cross-modal semantics and adversaries can jointly perturb heterogeneous inputs, rendering unimodal certificates insufficient. We introduce a unified randomized smoothing framework for mixed discrete--continuous inputs based on an analytically tractable Neyman--Pearson formulation of the joint worst-case problem. By analyzing the joint likelihood ordering induced by factorized discrete and continuous noise, our approach yields a closed-form, one-dimensional certificate that strictly generalizes both Gaussian (image-only) and discrete (text-only) randomized smoothing. We validate the framework on multimodal safety filtering, providing the first model-agnostic certificates against joint text--image adversarial attacks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Randomized smoothingмқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң model-agnostic robustness certificateлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ ліҙмһҘмқҖ лӢЁмқј modalityм—җ н•ңм •лҗҳм–ҙ continuous inputкіј discrete inputмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҙм„ң лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҠ” multimodal modelм—җм„ң нҠ№нһҲ м№ҳлӘ…м ҒмқёлҚ°, кІ°м •мқҙ cross-modal semanticsм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкі  adversaryк°Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё мң нҳ•мқҳ inputмқ„ кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң perturbн•  мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙ unimodal certificateлЎңлҠ” м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кІ°н•©лҗң worst-case л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң analytically tractableн•ң Neyman--Pearson formulationм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң, mixed discrete--continuous inputмқ„ мң„н•ң нҶөн•© randomized smoothing frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л¶„н•ҙлҗң discrete л°Ҹ continuous noiseк°Җ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” joint likelihood orderingмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ Gaussian (image-only) randomized smoothingкіј discrete (text-only) randomized smoothingмқ„ м—„л°ҖнһҲ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” closed-formмқҳ one-dimensional certificateлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” multimodal safety filteringм—җм„ң мқҙ frameworkлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳкі , joint text--image adversarial attackм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ model-agnostic certificateлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65667","en":"Bias in Zeroth-Order Normal Estimation for Decision-Based Attacks","ko":"кІ°м • кё°л°ҳ кіөкІ©мқ„ мң„н•ң мҳҒм°Ё лІ•м„  м¶”м •мқҳ нҺён–Ҙ","authors":"Feiyang Wang, Hangwei Qian, Xingquan Zuo, Gang Chen, Ivor Tsang","pos":"#1110","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=BOibqa3ZUz","abs":"Decision-based image attacks commonly rely on zeroth-order (ZO) Monte Carlo probing to estimate decision-boundary normals and iteratively refine adversarial perturbations to minimize the $\\ell_2$ norm. We theoretically analyze and empirically demonstrate an intrinsic inefficiency arising from heterogeneous input sensitivity, where only a small subset of coordinates strongly affects the target modelвҖҷs predictions, while most others have a negligible effect. Empirically, with one-bit feedback and a limited query budget, updates on low-sensitivity coordinates are overwhelmed by initialization and sampling noise, preventing their perturbations from exhibiting consistent improvement. By modeling ZO refinement as a stochastic dynamical system, we formally characterize its asymptotic behavior: the perturbation aligns (in expectation) with the normal and its coordinate-wise magnitudes encode a local sensitivity ranking. However, this stationarity does not generally yield $\\ell_2$-optimal perturbations under nonlinear boundaries. Building on this observation, we propose a novel and effective algorithm, Sensitivity-Aware Rescaling (SAR), that leverages this sensitivity signal to infer an importance map from the current best perturbation, then progressively suppresses low-importance regions through a coarse-to-fine schedule to reduce the $\\ell_2$ norm.  Extensive experiments show that SAR achieves consistent improvements in perturbation norm, attack success rate, and visual imperceptibility. The code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/status/SAR-436.","absKo":"decision-based image attackмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң zeroth-order(ZO) Monte Carlo probingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ decision boundaryмқҳ normalмқ„ м¶”м •н•ҳкі , л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң adversarial perturbationмқ„ м •м ңн•ҳм—¬ $\\ell_2$ normмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё мһ…л Ҙ лҜјк°җлҸ„м—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗҳлҠ” ліём§Ҳм Ғ л№„нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ҳкі  мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙл•Ң мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ мўҢн‘ңл§Ң target modelмқҳ мҳҲмёЎм—җ к°•н•ҳкІҢ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ мўҢн‘ңлҠ” кұ°мқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мЈјм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, one-bit feedbackкіј м ңн•ңлҗң query budget н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” low-sensitivity coordinateм—җ лҢҖн•ң м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёк°Җ мҙҲкё°нҷ” л°Ҹ sampling noiseм—җ м••лҸ„лҗҳм–ҙ, н•ҙлӢ№ perturbationмқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. ZO refinementлҘј stochastic dynamical systemмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к·ё м җк·јм Ғ кұ°лҸҷмқ„ м •мӢқмңјлЎң к·ңлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү perturbationмқҖ expectationм—җм„ң normalкіј м •л ¬лҗҳл©°, мўҢн‘ңлі„ нҒ¬кё°лҠ” local sensitivity rankingмқ„ мқёмҪ”л”©н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң stationary stateк°Җ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң nonlinear boundaryм—җм„ң $\\ell_2$-optimal perturbationмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳм§ҖлҠ” м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Sensitivity-Aware Rescaling(SAR)мқҙлқјлҠ” мғҲлЎӯкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SARлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң sensitivity signalмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ мөңм„  perturbationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° importance mapмқ„ м¶”лЎ н•ң л’Ө, coarse-to-fine scheduleмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ low-importance regionмқ„ м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң м–өм ңн•ҳм—¬ $\\ell_2$ normмқ„ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SARк°Җ perturbation norm, attack success rate, visual imperceptibility мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/status/SAR-436 м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64013","en":"A Coin Flip for Safety: LLM Judges Fail to Reliably Measure Adversarial Robustness","ko":"лҸҷм „ лҚҳм§Җкё° к°ҷмқҖ м•Ҳм „м„ұ: LLM JudgeлҠ” м ҒлҢҖм Ғ к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ мёЎм •н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Leo Schwinn, Moritz Ladenburger, Tim Beyer, Mehrnaz Mofakhami, Gauthier Gidel, Stephan GГјnnemann","pos":"#1111","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RgnoWsmYBM","abs":"<p>Automated \\enquote{LLM-as-a-Judge} frameworks have become the de facto standard for scalable evaluation across natural language processing. For instance, in safety evaluation, these judges are relied upon to evaluate harmfulness in order to benchmark the robustness of safety against adversarial attacks. However, we show that existing validation protocols fail to account for substantial distribution shifts inherent to red-teaming: diverse victim models exhibit distinct generation styles, attacks distort output patterns, and semantic ambiguity varies significantly across jailbreak scenarios. Through a comprehensive audit using 6642 human-verified labels, we reveal that the unpredictable interaction of these shifts often causes judge performance to degrade to near random chance. This stands in stark contrast to the high human agreement reported in prior work. Crucially, we find that many attacks inflate their success rates by exploiting judge insufficiencies rather than eliciting genuinely harmful content. To enable more reliable evaluation, we propose ReliableBench, a benchmark of behaviors that remain more consistently judgeable, and JudgeStressTest, a dataset designed to expose judge failures. (Data in supplement).</p>","absKo":"<p>мһҗлҸҷнҷ”лҗң \\enquote{LLM-as-a-Judge} н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” мһҗм—°м–ҙ мІҳлҰ¬ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҸүк°Җмқҳ мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ н‘ңмӨҖмқҙ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ safety evaluationм—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң judgeк°Җ harmfulnessлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳм—¬ adversarial attackм—җ лҢҖн•ң safety robustnessлҘј benchmarkн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ validation protocolмқҙ red-teamingм—җ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳл°ҳлҗҳлҠ” мғҒлӢ№н•ң distribution shiftлҘј м¶©л¶„нһҲ л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң victim modelмқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё generation styleмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , attackмқҖ output patternмқ„ мҷңкіЎн•ҳл©°, semantic ambiguityлҠ” jailbreak scenarioл§ҲлӢӨ нҒ¬кІҢ лӢ¬лқјм§„лӢӨ. 6642к°ңмқҳ human-verified labelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң мў…н•© auditмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң shiftмқҳ мҳҲмёЎ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҙ judge м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мў…мў… кұ°мқҳ л¬ҙмһ‘мң„ мҲҳмӨҖк№Ңм§Җ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮҙмқ„ л°қнҳ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мқҙм „ м—°кө¬м—җм„ң ліҙкі лҗң лҶ’мқҖ human agreementмҷҖ к·№лӘ…н•ҳкІҢ лҢҖмЎ°лҗңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, л§ҺмқҖ attackмқҙ мӢӨм ңлЎң мң н•ҙн•ң лӮҙмҡ©мқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ judgeмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұн•Ёмқ„ м•…мҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ м„ұкіөлҘ мқ„ л¶Җн’ҖлҰ°лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. ліҙлӢӨ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” нҸүк°ҖлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” judgeк°Җ лҚ” мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ нҢҗлӢЁн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” н–үлҸҷл“ӨлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң benchmarkмқё ReliableBenchмҷҖ judge мӢӨнҢЁлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң datasetмқё JudgeStressTestлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. (Data in supplement).</p>"},{"id":"64735","en":"You Don't Protect if You Don't Expect: Breaking the Key Assumption behind CLIP's Test-Time Defenses","ko":"мҳҲмғҒн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙ ліҙнҳён•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ: CLIPмқҳ Test-Time л°©м–ҙ мқҙл©ҙмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ к°Җм • к№Ёкё°","authors":"Ruize Zhang, Yu Li, Zhang Wan, Juan Cao, Jie Zhang, Sheng Tang","pos":"#1113","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=KNzG54AwlL","abs":"<p>Recent test-time defenses for CLIP claim to preserve zero-shot clean accuracy while improving adversarial robustness. However, we find the reported robustness of six recent proposed state-of-the-art methods substantially overestimated: they fail under basic adaptive attacks. We further observe that these defenses share a common reliance on an indicative measurement that is assumed to capture the distributional difference between clean and adversarial samples and to determine whether the defense should preserve or alter the static modelвҖҷs prediction. We argue that this assumption is the fundamental weakness, and we propose CLIP-MAD (Manipulating Assumed Difference), an adaptive attack strategy designed to break it. CLIP-MAD efficiently expands the adversarial distribution without costly full gradient calculations and can be flexibly combined with existing attack baselines to further boost attack strength. Experiments across 13 datasets demonstrate that CLIP-MAD produces strong adversarial samples that markedly reduce the robustness of diverse test-time defenses, revealing a false sense of security in CLIPвҖҷs zero-shot robustness.</p>","absKo":"<p>CLIPм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңк·јмқҳ test-time defenseлҠ” adversarial robustnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ң zero-shot clean accuracyлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңк·ј м ңм•Ҳлҗң state-of-the-art л°©лІ• м—¬м„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ ліҙкі лҗң robustnessк°Җ мғҒлӢ№нһҲ кіјлҢҖнҸүк°Җлҗҳм—ҲмқҢмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙл“ӨмқҖ кё°ліём Ғмқё adaptive attackм—җлҸ„ мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң defenseл“Өмқҙ clean sampleкіј adversarial sample мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ distributional differenceлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкі  defenseк°Җ static modelмқҳ predictionмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн• м§Җ ліҖкІҪн• м§ҖлҘј кІ°м •н•ңлӢӨкі  к°Җм •лҗҳлҠ” indicative measurementм—җ кіөнҶөм ҒмңјлЎң мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкі  мһҲмқҢмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ к°Җм •мқҙ к·јліём Ғмқё м•Ҫм җмқҙлқјкі  мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј л¬ҙл„ҲлңЁлҰ¬кё° мң„н•ҙ CLIP-MAD(Manipulating Assumed Difference)лқјлҠ” adaptive attack strategyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. CLIP-MADлҠ” л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° full gradient кі„мӮ° м—Ҷмқҙ adversarial distributionмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙ attack baselineкіј мң м—°н•ҳкІҢ кІ°н•©н•ҳм—¬ attack strengthлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң лҶ’мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. 13к°ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ кұём№ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CLIP-MADк°Җ к°•л Ҙн•ң adversarial sampleмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬ лӢӨм–‘н•ң test-time defenseмқҳ robustnessлҘј нҳ„м ҖнһҲ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, CLIPмқҳ zero-shot robustnessм—җ лҢҖн•ң мһҳлӘ»лҗң м•Ҳм „к°җ(false sense of security)мқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63843","en":"Adversarial Robustness of Implicit Neural Representation-Based Classifiers","ko":"implicit neural representation кё°л°ҳ л¶„лҘҳкё°мқҳ adversarial robustness","authors":"Jayoung Kim, Kookjin Lee, Noseong Park, Sanghyun Hong","pos":"#3000","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=TEcKvsdzA3","abs":"Implicit neural representations (INRs) encode data as continuous coordinate-based functions parameterized by neural networks, shifting downstream tasks such as image recognition to operate on functional rather than discrete representations. Despite their increasing adoption, the adversarial robustness of INR-based classification pipelines remain largely underexplored. In this work, we present the first systematic study of adversarial robustness in INR-based classifiers. A key challenge is that generating an INR requires $\\text{\\emph{training}}$ a neural network for each input sample, resulting in an optimization-in-the-loop forward pass that renders standard gradient-based attacks computationally prohibitive. To address this, we design surrogate models that amortizes the INR-generation process, serving as a practical proxy for attacking INR-based classifiers. We also develop speed-up techniques that substantially reduce the training cost of the surrogate. We show that in contrast to recent work, INR-based classifiers are vulnerable: under adversarial input perturbations, classification accuracy collapses to near zero. Moreover, existing countermeasures designed to operate on discrete representations offer limited protection.","absKo":"Implicit neural representations (INRs)мқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј neural networkлЎң л§Өк°ңліҖмҲҳнҷ”лҗң м—°мҶҚм Ғмқё coordinate-based functionмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳм—¬, image recognitionкіј к°ҷмқҖ downstream taskк°Җ discrete representationмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј functional representation мң„м—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м „нҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. мұ„нғқмқҙ лҠҳкі  мһҲмқҢм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , INR кё°л°ҳ classification pipelineмқҳ adversarial robustnessлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” INR кё°л°ҳ classifierмқҳ adversarial robustnessм—җ лҢҖн•ң мІ« мІҙкі„м Ғ м—°кө¬лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ лӮңм җмқҖ INRмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳл Өл©ҙ к°Ғ input sampleл§ҲлӢӨ neural networkлҘј $\\text{\\emph{training}}$ н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, optimization-in-the-loop forward passк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҙ н‘ңмӨҖ gradient-based attackмқ„ кі„мӮ°м ҒмңјлЎң л§Өмҡ° л№„мӢёкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” INR мғқм„ұ кіјм •мқ„ amortizeн•ҳлҠ” surrogate modelмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ҳм—¬, INR кё°л°ҳ classifierлҘј кіөкІ©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё proxyлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң surrogateмқҳ training costлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқҙлҠ” speed-up кё°лІ•лҸ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңк·ј м—°кө¬мҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬ INR кё°л°ҳ classifierк°Җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. adversarial input perturbation н•ҳм—җм„ң classification accuracyлҠ” кұ°мқҳ 0м—җ к°Җк№ҢмӣҢм§„лӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ discrete representationм—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң кё°мЎҙ countermeasureлҠ” м ңн•ңм Ғмқё ліҙнҳёл§Ңмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64315","en":"Erased but Not Forgotten: How Backdoors Compromise Concept Erasure","ko":"м§ҖмӣҢмЎҢм§Җл§Ң мһҠнһҲм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ: л°ұлҸ„м–ҙк°Җ к°ңл…җ мӮӯм ңлҘј нӣјмҶҗн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқ","authors":"Tobias Braun, Jonas Henry Grebe, Patrick Mohr Gordillo, Marcus Rohrbach, Anna Rohrbach","pos":"#3001","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OpHKAVkOIN","abs":"The expansion of text-to-image diffusion models has raised concerns about harmful outputs, from fabricated depictions of public figures to sexually explicit imagery. To mitigate such risks, prior work has proposed concept erasure methods that aim to sever unwanted concepts from the model via fine-tuning, yet it remains unclear whether these approaches truly remove all links to the harmful concept or merely conceal superficial connections. In this work, we reveal a critical vulnerability, the Erasure Evasion Backdoors (EEB): an adversary binds a backdoor trigger to a concept slated for removal, and this malicious link survives subsequent erasure. We show that both black-box and white-box adversaries can instantiate this threat. Across six state-of-the-art erasure methods, including robust ones that explicitly search for alternative representations of the target concept, EEB consistently exposes harmful content: up to 82% success against celebrity-identity unlearning, up to 94% for object erasure, and up to 16$\\times$ amplification of explicit-content exposure. While EEB uncovers a blind spot in current erasure methods, it also provides a diagnostic tool for stress-testing future concept erasure techniques.","absKo":"н…ҚмҠӨнҠё-нҲ¬-мқҙлҜём§Җ diffusion modelмқҳ нҷ•мһҘмқҖ кіөм Ғ мқёл¬јмқҳ н—Ҳмң„ л¬ҳмӮ¬л¶Җн„° м„ұм ҒмңјлЎң л…ёкіЁм Ғмқё мқҙлҜём§Җм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ мң н•ҙн•ң м¶ңл Ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°л ӨлҘј нӮӨмӣҢ мҷ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мң„н—ҳмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м„ н–ү м—°кө¬лҠ” fine-tuningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң мӣҗм№ҳ м•ҠлҠ” к°ңл…җмқҳ м—°кІ°мқ„ лҒҠлҠ” concept erasure л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јмқҙ мң н•ҙн•ң к°ңл…җкіјмқҳ лӘЁл“  м—°кІ°мқ„ мӢӨм ңлЎң м ңкұ°н•ҳлҠ”м§Җ, м•„лӢҲл©ҙ н‘ңл©ҙм Ғмқё м—°кІ°л§Ң к°ҖлҰ¬лҠ”м§Җ м—¬л¶ҖлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” Erasure Evasion Backdoors(EEB)лқјлҠ” м№ҳлӘ…м Ғмқё м·Ём•Ҫм җмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. кіөкІ©мһҗлҠ” м ңкұ° лҢҖмғҒмқҙ лҗң к°ңл…җм—җ backdoor triggerлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳкі , мқҙ м•…мқҳм Ғ м—°кІ°мқҖ мқҙнӣ„мқҳ erasure мқҙнӣ„м—җлҸ„ мӮҙм•„лӮЁлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” black-boxмҷҖ white-box кіөкІ©мһҗ лӘЁл‘җк°Җ мқҙ мң„нҳ‘мқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҢҖмғҒ к°ңл…җмқҳ лҢҖмІҙ н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң нғҗмғүн•ҳлҠ” кІ¬кі н•ң л°©лІ•мқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң 6к°ңмқҳ state-of-the-art erasure method м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, EEBлҠ” мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мң н•ҙн•ң мҪҳн…җмё лҘј л…ём¶ңмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. celebrity identity unlearningм—җм„ңлҠ” мөңлҢҖ 82%мқҳ м„ұкіөлҘ , object erasureм—җм„ңлҠ” мөңлҢҖ 94%, explicit-content exposureлҠ” мөңлҢҖ 16$\\times$к№Ңм§Җ мҰқнҸӯлҗңлӢӨ. EEBлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ erasure methodмқҳ blind spotмқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮҙлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, н–Ҙнӣ„ concept erasure кё°лІ•мқ„ stress-testн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң м§„лӢЁ лҸ„кө¬лҸ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64333","en":"Front-Loaded Robust Conformal Prediction: Heavy Calibration, Minimal Test-Time Cost","ko":"м„ н–ү л¶Җн•ҳнҳ• к°•кұҙ л“ұк°Ғ мҳҲмёЎ: л¬ҙкұ°мҡҙ ліҙм •, мөңмҶҢ н…ҢмҠӨнҠё мӢңм җ л№„мҡ©","authors":"Soroush H. Zargarbashi, Mohammad Sadegh Akhondzadeh, Aleksandar Bojchevski","pos":"#3002","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OfXpAituJ9","abs":"<p>Robust conformal prediction (RCP) addresses confidence miscalibration in machine learning models by producing prediction sets with guaranteed coverage вҖ” these sets are guaranteed to include the true label with a user-specified high probability, even under worst-case noise. Recent works use randomized smoothing, as it provides robustness for black-box models at larger radii. Currently, there exist two setups for smoothing-based RCP: one requires extensive Monte Carlo sampling at calibration and test time but results in smaller prediction sets; the other setup produces larger prediction sets but uses a single sample at both stages. Since calibration is a one-time preprocessing step, it can accommodate substantially higher computational overhead than inference. Inspired by that, we offer procedures in between: we increase the sample rate at calibration time while using only one or few samples at test time. Increased calibration-time sampling can reduce the size of the prediction sets. With a large enough test set (which is often the case in production), our Front-Loaded RCPs have the same computational complexity as the state of the art, while producing considerably smaller sets at larger radii.</p>","absKo":"<p>Robust conformal prediction (RCP)мқҖ prediction setмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬ machine learning modelмқҳ confidence miscalibrationмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙ setмқҖ мөңм•…мқҳ кІҪмҡ°мқҳ noise м•„лһҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗк°Җ м§Җм •н•ң лҶ’мқҖ нҷ•лҘ лЎң true labelмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘлҗңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ лҚ” нҒ° radiusм—җм„ң black-box modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң robustnessлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” randomized smoothingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬ smoothing кё°л°ҳ RCPм—җлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ м„Өм •мқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” calibrationкіј test мӢңм җ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң Monte Carlo samplingмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳм§Җл§Ң лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ prediction setмқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” лҚ” нҒ° prediction setмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң л‘җ лӢЁкі„ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң лӢЁмқј sampleл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. calibrationмқҖ н•ң лІҲл§Ң мҲҳн–үлҗҳлҠ” preprocessing лӢЁкі„мқҙлҜҖлЎң inferenceліҙлӢӨ нӣЁм”¬ лҶ’мқҖ кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј к°җлӢ№н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м җм—җ м°©м•Ҳн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к·ё мӨ‘к°„м—җ н•ҙлӢ№н•ҳлҠ” м Ҳм°ЁлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. calibration мӢңм җмқҳ sample rateлҠ” лҶ’мқҙлҗҳ test мӢңм җм—җм„ңлҠ” н•ҳлӮҳ лҳҗлҠ” лӘҮ к°ңмқҳ sampleл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. calibration-time samplingмқ„ лҠҳлҰ¬л©ҙ prediction setмқҳ нҒ¬кё°лҘј мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҒ° test setмқҙ мһҲлҠ” кІҪмҡ°(мӢӨм ң мҡҙмҳҒм—җм„ңлҠ” нқ”н•ң мғҒнҷ©мқҙлӢӨ), мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ Front-Loaded RCPлҠ” мөңмІЁлӢЁ л°©лІ•кіј лҸҷмқјн•ң кі„мӮ° ліөмһЎлҸ„лҘј к°Җм§Җл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” нҒ° radiusм—җм„ң нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ setмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63353","en":"Rethinking Evaluation Paradigms in IBP-based Certified Training","ko":"IBP кё°л°ҳ мқёмҰқ н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„ мһ¬кі ","authors":"Konstantin Kaulen, Hadar Shavit, Holger Hoos","pos":"#3003","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XoaS2r1ezP","abs":"<p>Deep neural networks achieve strong performance on many supervised learning tasks but remain vulnerable to adversarial perturbations. Neural network verification provides mathematically rigorous robustness guarantees, yet at substantial computational cost. To mitigate this, certified training techniques optimise for verifiable robustness during training, typically inducing a trade-off between natural and certified accuracy controlled by method-specific hyperparameters. Because these metrics are inherently conflicting, the common practice of reporting a single configuration is problematic: it can mislead conclusions about overall performance and prevents unbiased assessments of the state of the art. We address this by evaluating certified training methods via Pareto front comparisons over the natural--certified accuracy trade-off. To enable fair, method-agnostic comparisons, we perform efficient automated multi-objective hyperparameter optimisation to identify a set of Pareto-optimal configurations for each method. This approach often uncovers substantial undertuning in previously reported configurations, yielding superior performance and establishing a new state of the art. Leveraging these fronts, we present the first comprehensive multi-objective comparison of certified training approaches, showing that prior advancements are less pronounced than assumed and revealing previously unreported performance complementarities.</p>","absKo":"<p>Deep neural networkлҠ” л§ҺмқҖ supervised learning taskм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, adversarial perturbationм—җлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. Neural network verificationмқҖ мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң м—„л°Җн•ң robustness guaranteeлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ мғҒлӢ№н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ certified training кё°лІ•мқҖ training лҸҷм•Ҳ verifiable robustnessлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳл©°, мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң method-specific hyperparameterм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңм–ҙлҗҳлҠ” natural accuracyмҷҖ certified accuracy к°„мқҳ trade-offлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң metricмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м„ңлЎң мғҒм¶©н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, лӢЁмқј configurationл§Ң ліҙкі н•ҳлҠ” кҙҖн–үмқҖ л¬ём ңк°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” м „мІҙ м„ұлҠҘм—җ лҢҖн•ң кІ°лЎ мқ„ мҳӨлҸ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲкі , state of the artм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҺён–Ҙ м—ҶлҠ” нҸүк°ҖлҘј л°©н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” natural--certified accuracy trade-offм—җ лҢҖн•ң Pareto front л№„көҗлҘј нҶөн•ҙ certified training methodлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. кіөм •н•ҳкі  method-agnosticн•ң л№„көҗлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, к°Ғ methodм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ Pareto-optimal configuration м§‘н•©мқ„ м°ҫлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё мһҗлҸҷ multi-objective hyperparameter optimizationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мқҙм „м—җ ліҙкі лҗң configurationл“Өм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң under-tuningмқ„ мһҗмЈј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкі  мғҲлЎңмҡҙ state of the artлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң frontлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” certified training approachм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғ multi-objective л№„көҗлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙ м§„ліҙк°Җ мғқк°Ғл§ҢнҒј л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§Җм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі  мқҙм „м—җ ліҙкі лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлҚҳ м„ұлҠҘ мғҒліҙм„ұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63201","en":"DF-LoGiT: Data-Free Logic-Gated Backdoor Attacks in Vision Transformers","ko":"DF-LoGiT: Vision Transformerм—җм„ңмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„° н”„лҰ¬ л…јлҰ¬ кІҢмқҙнҠё л°ұлҸ„м–ҙ кіөкІ©","authors":"Xiaozuo Shen, Yifei Cai, RUI NING, Chunsheng Xin, Hongyi &amp;quot;Michael&amp;quot; Wu","pos":"#3007","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Z8Mi9GGsy6","abs":"<p>The widespread adoption of Vision Transformers (ViTs) elevates supply-chain risk on third-party model hubs, where an adversary can implant backdoors into released checkpoints. Existing ViT backdoor attacks largely rely on poisoned-data training, while prior data-free attempts typically require synthetic-data fine-tuning or extra model components. This paper introduces Data-Free Logic-Gated Backdoor Attacks (DF-LoGiT), a truly data-free backdoor attack on ViTs via direct weight editing. DF-LoGiT exploits ViTвҖҷs native multi-head architecture to realize a logic-gated compositional trigger, enabling a stealthy and effective backdoor. We validate its effectiveness through theoretical analysis and extensive experiments, showing that DF-LoGiT achieves near-100% attack success with negligible degradation in benign accuracy and remains robust against representative classical and ViT-specific defenses.</p>","absKo":"<p>Vision Transformer (ViT)мқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мұ„нғқмқҖ third-party model hubм—җм„ң supply-chain riskлҘј лҶ’мқҙл©°, кіөкІ©мһҗлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗң checkpointм—җ backdoorлҘј мӢ¬мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ ViT backdoor attackмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң poisoned-data trainingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, мқҙм „мқҳ data-free мӢңлҸ„лҠ” ліҙнҶө synthetic-data fine-tuningмқҙлӮҳ м¶”к°Җ model componentлҘј н•„мҡ”лЎң н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ direct weight editingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ ViTм—җ лҢҖн•ң м§„м •н•ң data-free backdoor attackмқё Data-Free Logic-Gated Backdoor Attacks (DF-LoGiT)мқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. DF-LoGiTлҠ” ViTмқҳ native multi-head architectureлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ logic-gated compositional triggerлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мқҖл°Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё backdoorлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қкіј кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ к·ё нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳл©°, DF-LoGiTк°Җ benign accuracyмқҳ м Җн•ҳлҘј кұ°мқҳ мқјмңјнӮӨм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң кұ°мқҳ 100%м—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ attack successлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё classical defenseмҷҖ ViT-specific defenseм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ кІ¬кі н•Ёмқ„ мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61931","en":"Neural Honeytrace: Plug&Play Watermarking Framework against Model Extraction Attacks","ko":"Neural Honeytrace: лӘЁлҚё м¶”м¶ң кіөкІ© лҢҖмқ‘ Plug&Play мӣҢн„°л§ҲнӮ№ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Yixiao Xu, Binxing Fang, Rui Wang, Yinghai Zhou, Yuan Liu, Mohan Li, Zhihong Tian","pos":"#3009","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=laZwZk4O8W","abs":"<p>Triggerable watermarking enables model owners to assert ownership against model extraction attacks. However, most existing approaches require additional training, which limits post-deployment flexibility, and the lack of clear theoretical foundations makes them vulnerable to adaptive attacks. In this paper, we propose Neural Honeytrace, a plug-and-play watermarking framework that operates without retraining. We redefine the watermark transmission mechanism from an information perspective, designing a training-free multi-step transmission strategy that leverages the long-tailed effect of backdoor learning to achieve efficient and robust watermark embedding. Extensive experiments demonstrate that Neural Honeytrace reduces the average number of queries required for a worst-case t-test-based ownership verification to as low as 2% of existing methods, while incurring zero training cost.</p>","absKo":"<p>Triggerable watermarkingмқҖ model extraction attackм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ model ownerк°Җ мҶҢмң к¶Ңмқ„ мЈјмһҘн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ м¶”к°Җ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳлҜҖлЎң л°°нҸ¬ мқҙнӣ„мқҳ мң м—°м„ұмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗҳл©°, лӘ…нҷ•н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ кё°л°ҳмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬лЎң мқён•ҙ adaptive attackм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” мһ¬н•ҷмҠө м—Ҷмқҙ лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” plug-and-play watermarking frameworkмқё Neural HoneytraceлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м •ліҙ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң watermark м „мҶЎ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ мһ¬м •мқҳн•ҳкі , backdoor learningмқҳ long-tailed effectлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” н•ҷмҠө л¶Ҳн•„мҡ”н•ң multi-step transmission strategyлҘј м„Өкі„н•ҳм—¬ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  кІ¬кі н•ң watermark embeddingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Neural Honeytraceк°Җ мөңм•…мқҳ кІҪмҡ° t-test кё°л°ҳ мҶҢмң к¶Ң кІҖмҰқм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң нҸүк·  query мҲҳлҘј кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ 2% мҲҳмӨҖк№Ңм§Җ мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, н•ҷмҠө л№„мҡ©мқҖ м „нҳҖ л“Өм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63050","en":"A Constrained Optimization Perspective of Unrolled Transformers","ko":"нҺјміҗм§„ Transformerмқҳ м ңм•Ҫ мөңм Ғнҷ” кҙҖм җ","authors":"Javier Porras-Valenzuela, Samar Hadou, Alejandro Ribeiro","pos":"#3512","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=aYe8j2jOmK","abs":"<p>We introduce a constrained optimization framework for training transformers that behave like optimization descent algorithms. Specifically, we enforce layerwise descent constraints on the objective function and replace standard empirical risk minimization (ERM) with a primal-dual training scheme. This approach yields models whose intermediate representations decrease the loss monotonically in expectation across layers. We apply our method to both unrolled transformer architectures and conventional pretrained transformers on tasks of video denoising and text classification. Across these settings, we observe that constrained transformers achieve stronger robustness to perturbations and maintain higher out-of-distribution generalization, while preserving competitive in-distribution performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” transformerлҘј optimization descent algorithmмІҳлҹј лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨлҠ” constrained optimization frameworkлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” objective functionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ layerwise descent constraintлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳкі , н‘ңмӨҖ empirical risk minimization(ERM)мқ„ primal-dual training schemeмңјлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ к°Ғ layerм—җ кұёміҗ intermediate representationмқҙ кё°лҢҖк°’ кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң lossлҘј лӢЁмЎ°лЎӯкІҢ к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮӨлҠ” modelмқ„ мӮ°м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л°©лІ•мқ„ video denoisingкіј text classification taskм—җм„ң unrolled transformer architectureмҷҖ conventional pretrained transformer лӘЁл‘җм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„Өм • м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, constrained transformerлҠ” perturbationм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҚ” к°•н•ң robustnessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ out-of-distribution generalizationмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, in-distribution м„ұлҠҘмқҖ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61186","en":"Safety-Efficacy Trade Off: Robustness against Data-Poisoning","ko":"м•Ҳм „м„ұ-нҡЁлҠҘ Trade-off: Data-Poisoningм—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•кұҙм„ұ","authors":"Diego Granziol, Ulugbek Abdimanabov","pos":"#401","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=suwjabuQDY","abs":"<p>Backdoor and data-poisoning attacks can achieve high attack success while evading existing spectral and optimisation-based defences. We show that this behaviour is not incidental, but arises from a fundamental geometric mechanism in input space. Using kernel ridge regression as an exact model of wide neural networks, we prove that clustered dirty-label poisons induce a rank-one spike in the input Hessian whose magnitude scales quadratically with attack efficacy. Crucially, for nonlinear kernels we identify a near-clone regime in which poison efficacy remains order-one while the induced input curvature vanishes, making the attack provably spectrally undetectable. We further show that input-gradient regularisation contracts poison-aligned Fisher and Hessian eigenmodes under gradient flow, yielding an explicit and unavoidable safetyвҖ“efficacy trade-off by reducing data-fitting capacity. For exponential kernels, this defence admits a precise interpretation as an anisotropic high-pass filter that increases the effective length scale and suppresses near-clone poisons. Extensive experiments on linear models and deep convolutional networks across MNIST and CIFAR-10/100 validate the theory, demonstrating consistent lags between attack success and spectral visibility, and showing that regularisation and data augmentation jointly suppress poisoning. Our results establish when backdoors are inherently invisible, and provide the first end-to-end characterisation of poisoning, detectability, and defence through input-space curvature.</p>","absKo":"<p>BackdoorмҷҖ data-poisoning attackмқҖ кё°мЎҙмқҳ spectral л°Ҹ optimization-based defenseлҘј нҡҢн”јн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҶ’мқҖ attack successлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҳ„мғҒмқҙ мҡ°м—°н•ң кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј, input spaceм—җм„ңмқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. wide neural networkмқҳ м •нҷ•н•ң лӘЁлҚёлЎң kernel ridge regressionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” clustered dirty-label poisonмқҙ input Hessianм—җ rank-one spikeлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳл©° к·ё нҒ¬кё°к°Җ attack efficacyмқҳ м ңкіұм—җ л№„лЎҖн•ҙ мҰқк°Җн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң, nonlinear kernelм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” poison efficacyк°Җ order-oneмңјлЎң мң м§ҖлҗҳлҠ” лҸҷм•Ҳ мң лҸ„лҗң input curvatureлҠ” мӮ¬лқјм§ҖлҠ” near-clone regimeмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ н•ҙлӢ№ attackмқҖ мӣҗлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң spectralн•ҳкІҢ нғҗм§Җ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң input-gradient regularizationмқҙ gradient flow н•ҳм—җм„ң poison-aligned Fisher л°Ҹ Hessian eigenmodeлҘј мҲҳм¶•мӢңмјң, data-fitting capacityлҘј мӨ„мқҙлҠ” explicitн•ҳкі  н”јн•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” safety-efficacy trade-offлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. exponential kernelмқҳ кІҪмҡ°, мқҙ defenseлҠ” effective length scaleмқ„ мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮӨкі  near-clone poisonмқ„ м–өм ңн•ҳлҠ” anisotropic high-pass filterлЎң м •л°Җн•ҳкІҢ н•ҙм„қлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. MNISTмҷҖ CIFAR-10/100 м „л°ҳмқҳ linear model л°Ҹ deep convolutional networkм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҙ мқҙлЎ мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳл©°, attack successмҷҖ spectral visibility мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мқјкҙҖлҗң мӢңм°ЁлҘј ліҙм—¬мЈјкі , regularizationкіј data augmentationмқҙ н•Ёк»ҳ poisoningмқ„ м–өм ңн•Ёмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” backdoorк°Җ м–ём ң ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмқҙм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”м§ҖлҘј к·ңлӘ…н•ҳкі , input-space curvatureлҘј нҶөн•ҙ poisoning, detectability, defenseлҘј end-to-endлЎң мІҳмқҢ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66242","en":"Diversity-aware Weight Perturbation Promotes Robust Adaptation","ko":"лӢӨм–‘м„ұ мқём§Җ к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳ м„ӯлҸҷмқҖ кІ¬кі н•ң м Ғмқ‘мқ„ мҙүм§„н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Zibo Chen, Ruxin Li, Zilu Wang","pos":"#4011","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5VoK9nUVSD","abs":"<p>Compute-In-Memory (CIM) accelerators are promising for energy-efficient edge inference, yet they faces fundamental challenges when deploying Deep Neural Networks (DNNs), as hardware-induced weight perturbations from intrinsic noise and device drift degrade accuracy and impede reliable inference. To tackle this challenge, we propose Diversity-aware Weight  Perturbation (DWP), an immune-system-inspired training method that  emulates affinity-based selection by exploiting sample-level  prediction disagreement under diverse noise realizations to guide  adaptive sample weighting, building robustness to weight perturbation. Experiments show that DWP-trained models consistently yield superior robustness, achieving over 15\\% accuracy improvements compared to standard-trained models under severe weight perturbations (mismatch level up to 70\\%) and maintaining  inference accuracy at 90\\% over a simulated one-year CIM operation  with only 2\\%вҖ“4\\% variation in accuracy. Moreover, under matched model and inference configurations, deployment on low-precision CIM hardware reduces inference energy by 38\\% compared to a GPU baseline. These results demonstrate that DWP enables robust and energy-efficient neural network deployment on resource-constrained edge devices with inherent hardware uncertainties.</p>","absKo":"<p>Compute-In-Memory (CIM) acceleratorлҠ” м—җл„Ҳм§Җ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё edge inferenceм—җ мң л§қн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, intrinsic noiseмҷҖ device driftлЎң мқён•ң hardware-induced weight perturbationмқҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮӨкі  мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” inferenceлҘј л°©н•ҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ Deep Neural Network (DNN) л°°нҸ¬ мӢң к·јліём Ғмқё лҸ„м „м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Diversity-aware Weight Perturbation (DWP)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” sample-level prediction disagreementлҘј лӢӨм–‘н•ң noise realization н•ҳм—җм„ң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ adaptive sample weightingмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ affinity-based selectionмқ„ лӘЁмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” immune-system-inspired training methodлЎң, weight perturbationм—җ лҢҖн•ң robustnessлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, DWPлЎң нӣҲл Ёлҗң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ severe weight perturbation(mismatch level мөңлҢҖ 70\\%) н•ҳм—җм„ң н‘ңмӨҖ н•ҷмҠө лӘЁлҚё лҢҖл№„ 15\\% мқҙмғҒмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , accuracy variationмқҙ 2\\%вҖ“4\\%м—җ л¶Ҳкіјн•ң мғҒнғңлЎң мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳлҗң 1л…„ CIM operation лҸҷм•Ҳ inference accuracyлҘј 90\\%лЎң мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң modelкіј inference configurationмқҙ мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ң low-precision CIM hardwareм—җ л°°нҸ¬н•ҳл©ҙ GPU baseline лҢҖл№„ inference energyлҘј 38\\% м Ҳк°җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” DWPк°Җ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё hardware uncertaintyлҘј м§ҖлӢҢ мһҗмӣҗ м ңм•Ҫ edge deviceм—җм„ң кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  м—җл„Ҳм§Җ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё neural network л°°нҸ¬лҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"68812","en":"Beyond Accuracy: What Matters in Designing Well-Behaved Image Classification Models?","ko":"м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ң: мһҳ лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” мқҙлҜём§Җ л¶„лҘҳ лӘЁлҚё м„Өкі„м—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кІғмқҖ л¬ҙм—Үмқёк°Җ?","authors":"Robin Hesse, Dogukan Bagci, Bernt Schiele, Simone Schaub-Meyer, Stefan Roth","pos":"#4407","abs":"<p>Deep learning has become an essential part of computer vision, with deep neural networks (DNNs) excelling in predictive performance. However, they often fall short in other critical quality dimensions, such as robustness, calibration, or fairness. While existing studies have focused on a subset of these quality dimensions, none have explored a more general form of \"well-behavedness\" of DNNs. With this work, we address this gap by simultaneously studying nine different quality dimensions for image classification. Through a large-scale study, we provide a bird's-eye view by analyzing 326 backbone models and how different training paradigms and model architectures affect these quality dimensions. We reveal various new insights such that (i) vision-language models exhibit high class balance on ImageNet-1k classification and strong robustness against domain changes; (ii) training models initialized with weights obtained through self-supervised learning is an effective strategy to improve most considered quality dimensions; and (iii) the training dataset size is a major driver for most of the quality dimensions. We conclude our study by introducing the QUBA score (Quality Understanding Beyond Accuracy), a novel metric that ranks models across multiple dimensions of quality, enabling tailored recommendations based on specific user needs.</p>","absKo":"<p>deep learningмқҖ computer visionм—җм„ң н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё мҡ”мҶҢк°Җ лҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, deep neural network(DNN)лҠ” мҳҲмёЎ м„ұлҠҘм—җм„ң нғҒмӣ”н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ robustness, calibration, fairnessмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ лӢӨлҘё мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң quality dimensionм—җм„ңлҠ” мў…мў… кё°лҢҖм—җ лӘ» лҜём№ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң quality dimensionмқҳ мқјл¶Җл§Ңмқ„ лӢӨлӨ„ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, DNNмқҳ ліҙлӢӨ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё мқҳлҜёмқҳ \"well-behavedness\"лҘј нғҗкө¬н•ң м—°кө¬лҠ” м—Ҷм—ҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” image classificationмқ„ лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң м•„нҷү к°Җм§Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё quality dimensionмқ„ лҸҷмӢңм—җ мӮҙнҺҙлҙ„мңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м—°кө¬лҘј нҶөн•ҙ 326к°ңмқҳ backbone modelмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ҳкі , м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё training paradigmкіј model architectureк°Җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң quality dimensionм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң bird's-eye viewлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј, (i) vision-language modelмқҖ ImageNet-1k classificationм—җм„ң лҶ’мқҖ class balanceмҷҖ domain changeм—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•н•ң robustnessлҘј ліҙмқҙкі , (ii) self-supervised learningмңјлЎң м–»мқҖ weightлЎң мҙҲкё°нҷ”лҗң modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ кі л Өн•ң лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ quality dimensionмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё м „лһөмқҙл©°, (iii) training dataset sizeлҠ” лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ quality dimensionмқ„ мўҢмҡ°н•ҳлҠ” мЈјмҡ” мҡ”мқёмһ„мқ„ л°қнҳҖлғҲлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” AccuracyлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„  Quality Understandingмқ„ мқҳлҜён•ҳлҠ” QUBA scoreлқјлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ metricмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, м—¬лҹ¬ quality dimensionм—җ кұёміҗ modelмқ„ мҲңмң„нҷ”н•ҳкі  нҠ№м • user needм—җ л§һм¶ҳ к¶ҢмһҘ мӮ¬н•ӯмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63330","en":"Mind Your Margin and Boundary: Are Your Distilled Datasets Truly Robust?","ko":"л§Ҳм§„кіј кІҪкі„лҘј мЈјмқҳн•ҳлқј: мҰқлҘҳлҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмқҖ м§„м •мңјлЎң кІ¬кі н•ңк°Җ?","authors":"Muquan Li, Yingyi Ma, Yihong Huang, Hang Gou, KE QIN, Ming Li, Yuan-Fang Li, Tao He","pos":"#700","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Y3K0pPyVcs","abs":"Dataset distillation (DD) compresses a large training set into a small synthetic set for efficient training, but most DD methods optimize only clean accuracy and leave robustness uncontrolled. Recent robust DD methods improve robustness, yet they often suffer from a poor accuracyвҖ“robustness trade-off because they (i) treat all adversarially perturbed examples uniformly, despite robust risk being dominated by near-zero robust margins, and (ii) do not explicitly increase inter-class separation in the decision boundary where attacks concentrate. We present Contrastive Curriculum for Robust Dataset Distillation (C$^2$R), a margin-centric framework that couples an attack-aware curriculum with a contrastive robustness objective. From a robust-margin perspective, we derive a perturbation score that approximates each sampleвҖҷs robust hinge, enabling a curriculum that prioritizes the smallest-margin adversaries that most directly drive robust error. In parallel, a class-balanced contrastive robustness loss enforces adversarial invariance while explicitly widening boundary separation across classes. Experiments on CIFAR-10/100, Tiny-ImageNet, and multiple ImageNet-1K subsets under six attacks show that C$^2$R achieves the best robust accuracy, outperforming prior robust DD methods by $2.8$\\% on average. Under PGD, C$^2$R also reduces the average drop rate (DR) below $66.8$\\% across datasets, indicating a stronger accuracyвҖ“robustness balance.","absKo":"Dataset distillation (DD)лҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ҙ нҒ° training setмқ„ мһ‘мқҖ synthetic setмңјлЎң м••м¶•н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ DD л°©лІ•мқҖ clean accuracyл§Ң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳкі  robustnessлҠ” нҶөм ңн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ robust DD л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ robustnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨм§Җл§Ң, (i) robust riskк°Җ near-zero robust marginм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м§Җл°°лҗЁм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  лӘЁл“  adversarially perturbed exampleмқ„ лҸҷмқјн•ҳкІҢ м·Ёкёүн•ҳкі , (ii) attackмқҙ м§‘мӨ‘лҗҳлҠ” decision boundaryм—җм„ң class к°„ separationмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮӨм§Җ м•Ҡкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ accuracyмҷҖ robustness мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offк°Җ мўӢм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” attack-aware curriculumкіј contrastive robustness objectiveлҘј кІ°н•©н•ң margin-centric frameworkмқё Contrastive Curriculum for Robust Dataset Distillation (C$^2$R)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Robust margin кҙҖм җм—җм„ң, к°Ғ sampleмқҳ robust hingeлҘј к·јмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” perturbation scoreлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳм—¬, robust errorлҘј к°ҖмһҘ м§Ғм ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” smallest-margin adversaryлҘј мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳлҠ” curriculumмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҸҷмӢңм—җ class-balanced contrastive robustness lossлҠ” adversarial invarianceлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳл©ҙм„ң class м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ boundary separationмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң л„“нһҢлӢӨ. CIFAR-10/100, Tiny-ImageNet, к·ёлҰ¬кі  м—¬м„Ҝ к°Җм§Җ attack н•ҳмқҳ м—¬лҹ¬ ImageNet-1K subsetм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ C$^2$Rмқҙ мөңкі мқҳ robust accuracyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙ robust DD л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ нҸүк·  $2.8$\\% н–ҘмғҒлҗЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. PGD н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” C$^2$Rмқҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң average drop rate (DR)мқ„ $66.8$\\% м•„лһҳлЎң лӮ®м¶”м–ҙ, лҚ” к°•н•ң accuracyвҖ“robustness к· нҳ•мқ„ лӮҳнғҖлӮёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65515","en":"CARE: Class-Adaptive Expert Consensus for Reliable Learning with Long-Tailed Noisy Labels","ko":"CARE: лЎұн…Ңмқј л…ёмқҙмҰҲ л Ҳмқҙлё”м—җм„ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң нҒҙлһҳмҠӨ м Ғмқ‘нҳ• м „л¬ёк°Җ н•©мқҳ","authors":"Mengke Li, Haiquan Ling, Lihao Chen, Yang Lu, Yiqun Zhang, Hui Huang","pos":"#809","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Csmrtng6PP","abs":"<p>Learning from real-world data is frequently hindered by the compound challenge of long-tailed class distributions and noisy annotations.  Existing methods partially address these issues but typically ignore the non-uniform impact of label noise across classes, resulting in ineffective correction for tail classes and over-regularization for head classes. To address this issue, we propose Class-Adaptive Rectification with Experts (CARE), a parameter-efficient framework that leverages three complementary supervision sources from vision-language models (VLM): observed noisy labels, VLM text embeddings, and visual features. CARE introduces a class-adaptive expert consensus mechanism that enforces stricter agreement for tail classes and more permissive agreement for head classes based on class frequency. By aggregating high-confidence predictions across these sources, CARE filters unreliable signals and recalibrates class distributions, yielding more reliable rectification under long-tailed distributions. Extensive experiments on both synthetic and real-world benchmarks demonstrate that CARE consistently outperforms state-of-the-art methods, achieving up to 3.0\\% performance gains. The source code is temporarily available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CARE-9F10.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӢӨм„ёкі„ лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ н•ҷмҠөмқҖ long-tailed class distributionкіј noisy annotationмқҙлқјлҠ” ліөн•©м Ғмқё л¬ём ңлЎң мһҗмЈј л°©н•ҙл°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј л¶Җл¶„м ҒмңјлЎңл§Ң н•ҙкІ°н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң class к°„ label noiseмқҳ л№„к· мқјн•ң мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳм—¬ tail classм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” л№„нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё correctionмқ„, head classм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” кіјлҸ„н•ң regularizationмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” vision-language model (VLM)м—җм„ң м–»мқҖ м„ё к°Җм§Җ мғҒліҙм Ғ supervision source, мҰү кҙҖмёЎлҗң noisy label, VLM text embedding, visual featureлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” parameter-efficient frameworkмқё Class-Adaptive Rectification with Experts (CARE)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. CAREлҠ” class frequencyм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ tail classм—җлҠ” лҚ” м—„кІ©н•ң agreementлҘј, head classм—җлҠ” лҚ” кҙҖлҢҖн•ң agreementлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” class-adaptive expert consensus mechanismмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң source м „л°ҳмқҳ high-confidence predictionмқ„ м§‘кі„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ CAREлҠ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” signalмқ„ кұёлҹ¬лӮҙкі  class distributionмқ„ мһ¬ліҙм •н•ҳм—¬, long-tailed distribution н•ҳм—җм„ң лҚ” мӢ лў°м„ұ лҶ’мқҖ rectificationмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. н•©м„ұ л°Ҹ мӢӨм„ёкі„ benchmark лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CAREк°Җ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ state-of-the-art methodлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©° мөңлҢҖ 3.0\\%мқҳ м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҶҢмҠӨ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” мқјмӢңм ҒмңјлЎң https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CARE-9F10 м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63623","en":"Causal-JEPA: Learning World Models through Object-Level Latent Interventions","ko":"Causal-JEPA: к°қмІҙ мҲҳмӨҖ мһ мһ¬ к°ңмһ…мқ„ нҶөн•ң м„ёкі„ лӘЁлҚё н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Heejeong Nam, Quentin Le Lidec, Lucas Maes, Yann LeCun, Randall Balestriero","pos":"#1008","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=VMAHQDOtjp","abs":"<p>World models require robust relational understanding to support prediction, reasoning, and control. While object-centric representations provide a useful abstraction, they are not sufficient to capture interaction-dependent dynamics. We therefore propose C-JEPA, a simple and flexible object-centric world model that extends masked joint embedding prediction from image patches to object-centric representations.  By applying object-level masking that requires an objectвҖҷs state to be inferred from other objects, C-JEPA induces latent interventions with counterfactual-like effects and prevents shortcut solutions, making interaction reasoning essential. Empirically, C-JEPA leads to consistent gains in visual question answering, with an absolute improvement of about 20\\% in counterfactual reasoning over the same architecture without object-level masking. On agent control tasks, C-JEPA enables substantially more efficient planning by using only 1\\% of the total latent input features required by patch-based world models, while achieving comparable performance. Finally, we provide a formal analysis demonstrating that object-level masking induces a causal inductive bias via latent interventions. Code will be available at <em>anonymous</em>.</p>","absKo":"<p>world modelмқҖ prediction, reasoning, controlмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ к°•кұҙн•ң relational understandingмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. object-centric representationмқҖ мң мҡ©н•ң м¶”мғҒнҷ”лҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, interaction-dependent dynamicsлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкё°м—җлҠ” м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” masked joint embedding predictionмқ„ image patchм—җм„ң object-centric representationмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ң, лӢЁмҲңн•ҳкі  мң м—°н•ң object-centric world modelмқё C-JEPAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•ң objectмқҳ stateлҘј лӢӨлҘё objectл“ӨлЎңл¶Җн„° м¶”лЎ н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” object-level maskingмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, C-JEPAлҠ” counterfactualкіј мң мӮ¬н•ң нҡЁкіјлҘј м§ҖлӢҢ latent interventionмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳкі  shortcut solutionмқ„ л°©м§Җн•ҳм—¬ interaction reasoningмқ„ н•„мҲҳм ҒмңјлЎң л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң C-JEPAлҠ” visual question answeringм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, object-level maskingмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” лҸҷмқјн•ң architecture лҢҖл№„ counterfactual reasoningм—җм„ң м•Ҫ 20\\%мқҳ м ҲлҢҖ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. agent control taskм—җм„ңлҠ” C-JEPAк°Җ patch-based world modelм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң м „мІҙ latent input featureмқҳ 1\\%л§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мң мӮ¬н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҙ, нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё planningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, object-level maskingмқҙ latent interventionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ causal inductive biasлҘј мң лҸ„н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” нҳ•мӢқм Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” <em>anonymous</em>м—җм„ң кіөк°ңлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62190","en":"Finding the Minimal Parameter Budget for Implicit Reasoning: A Data Complexity Driven Scaling Law for Language Models","ko":"лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ Reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң мөңмҶҢ Parameter Budget нғҗмғү: лҚ°мқҙн„° ліөмһЎлҸ„ кё°л°ҳ Language Models Scaling Law","authors":"Xinyi Wang, Shawn Tan, Shenbo Xu, Mingyu Jin, William Wang, Rameswar Panda, Yikang Shen","pos":"#4604","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=iuIPAhZpxz","abs":"<p>Reasoning is a core capability of language models (LMs), yet it remains unclear how much model capacity is necessary to support reasoning during pretraining. In this work, we study the minimal parameter budget required for implicit reasoning, defined as the ability to infer new facts from learned knowledge without explicit chain-of-thought supervision. To isolate this phenomenon, we pretrain LMs from scratch in a controlled synthetic environment that mimics the structure and distribution of real-world knowledge graphs, and evaluate their ability to complete missing edges via multi-hop inference. From both a theoretical and an empirical perspective, we identify a scaling law linking this optimal parameter budget to a graph search entropy measure. Across a wide range of model sizes, training steps, and graph complexities, we show that an optimally sized language model can reliably reason over approximately 0.008 bits of information per parameter at most. Our results characterize the minimal sufficient capacity for implicit reasoning during pretraining. Our findings provide principled guidance for matching model size to data complexity and offer new insights into the scaling behavior of reasoning in large language models.</p>","absKo":"<p>ReasoningмқҖ language model (LM)мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ лҠҘл Ҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, pretraining лҸҷм•Ҳ reasoningмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң model capacityк°Җ м–ҙлҠҗ м •лҸ„мқём§ҖлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё chain-of-thought supervision м—Ҷмқҙ н•ҷмҠөлҗң м§ҖмӢқмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ м¶”лЎ н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл ҘмңјлЎң м •мқҳлҗҳлҠ” implicit reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ҙ н•„мҡ”н•ң мөңмҶҢ parameter budgetмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҙм„ң ліҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨм ң world knowledge graphмқҳ кө¬мЎ°мҷҖ л¶„нҸ¬лҘј лӘЁмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” нҶөм ңлҗң synthetic environmentм—җм„ң LMмқ„ scratchл¶Җн„° pretrainн•ҳкі , multi-hop inferenceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лҲ„лқҪлҗң edgeлҘј мҷ„м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ кҙҖм җкіј мӢӨмҰқм Ғ кҙҖм җ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мөңм Ғ parameter budgetкіј graph search entropy measureлҘј м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” scaling lawлҘј мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң model size, training step, graph complexity м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ, мөңм Ғ нҒ¬кё°мқҳ language modelмқҖ parameterлӢ№ мөңлҢҖ м•Ҫ 0.008 bitsмқҳ м •ліҙлҘј м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң reasoningн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” pretraining мӨ‘ implicit reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң мөңмҶҢ м¶©л¶„ capacityлҘј к·ңм •н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°ңкІ¬мқҖ model sizeлҘј data complexityм—җ л§һм¶”лҠ” лҚ° principledн•ң м§Җм№Ёмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, large language modelм—җм„ң reasoningмқҳ scaling behaviorм—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61570","en":"Clustering in Deep Stochastic Transformers","ko":"Deep Stochastic Transformersм—җм„ңмқҳ Clustering","authors":"Lev Fedorov, Michael Sander, Romuald Elie, Pierre Marion, Mathieu Lauriere","pos":"#1010","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=opfSL15Uc4","abs":"<p>Transformers have revolutionized deep learning across various domains but understanding the precise token dynamics remains a theoretical challenge. Existing theories of deep Transformers with layer normalization typically predict that tokens cluster to a single point; however, these results rely on deterministic weight assumptions, which fail to capture the standard initialization scheme in Transformers. In this work, we show that accounting for the intrinsic stochasticity of random initialization alters this picture. More precisely, we analyze deep Transformers where noise arises from the random initialization of value matrices. Under diffusion scaling and token-wise RMS normalization, we prove that, as the number of Transformer layers goes to infinity, the discrete token dynamics converge to an interacting-particle system on the sphere where tokens are driven by a \\emph{common} matrix-valued Brownian noise. In this limit, we show that initialization noise prevents the collapse to a single cluster predicted by deterministic models. For two tokens, we prove a phase transition governed by the interaction strength and the token dimension: unlike deterministic attention flows, antipodal configurations become attracting with positive probability. Numerical experiments confirm the predicted transition, reveal that antipodal formations persist for more than two tokens, and demonstrate that suppressing the intrinsic noise degrades accuracy.</p>","absKo":"TransformerлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң domainм—җм„ң deep learningмқ„ нҳҒмӢ н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, м •нҷ•н•ң token dynamicsлҘј мқҙн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң м–ҙл Өмҡҙ кіјм ңлӢӨ. layer normalizationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” deep Transformerм—җ лҢҖн•ң кё°мЎҙ мқҙлЎ мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң tokenмқҙ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ м җмңјлЎң мқ‘м§‘н•ңлӢӨкі  мҳҲмёЎн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” deterministic weight assumptionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” Transformerмқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ initialization schemeмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” random initializationмқҳ intrinsic stochasticityлҘј кі л Өн•ҳл©ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к·ёлҰјмқҙ лӢ¬лқјм§җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. ліҙлӢӨ м •нҷ•нһҲлҠ”, value matrixмқҳ random initializationм—җм„ң noiseк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” deep TransformerлҘј л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. diffusion scalingкіј token-wise RMS normalization н•ҳм—җм„ң, Transformer layer мҲҳк°Җ л¬ҙн•ңлҢҖлЎң к°Ҳ л•Ң discrete token dynamicsк°Җ кө¬л©ҙ мң„мқҳ interacting-particle systemмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ҳл©°, tokenмқҖ \\emph{common} matrix-valued Brownian noiseм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кө¬лҸҷлҗЁмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ к·№н•ңм—җм„ң initialization noiseк°Җ deterministic modelмқҙ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмқј clusterлЎңмқҳ л¶•кҙҙлҘј л°©м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л‘җ tokenмқҳ кІҪмҡ°, interaction strengthмҷҖ token dimensionм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м§Җл°°лҗҳлҠ” phase transitionмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ: deterministic attention flowмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, antipodal configurationмқҙ м–‘мқҳ нҷ•лҘ лЎң attractorк°Җ лҗңлӢӨ. мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҳҲмёЎлҗң transitionмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ҳкі , л‘җ к°ңлҘј мҙҲкіјн•ҳлҠ” tokenм—җм„ңлҸ„ antipodal formationмқҙ м§ҖмҶҚлҗЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, intrinsic noiseлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳл©ҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„к°Җ м Җн•ҳлҗЁмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65284","en":"LoRe: Adaptive Interaction-Evaluation Routing with Per-step Interaction Budgets for Iterative Graph Solvers","ko":"LoRe: л°ҳліөм Ғ к·ёлһҳн”„ мҶ”лІ„лҘј мң„н•ң мҠӨн…қлі„ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© мҳҲмӮ° кё°л°ҳ м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©-нҸүк°Җ лқјмҡ°нҢ…","authors":"Jintao Li, Yong-Yi Wang, Zheng-An Wang, Heng Fan","pos":"#2312","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=F75QiiFIOr","abs":"Diffusion-based neural solvers for combinatorial optimization repeatedly re-evaluate dense edge/factor interactions, making inference expensive in wall-clock time and often memory-bound at scale. We introduce LoRe, a training-free, inference-time drop-in wrapper that enforces per-step interaction-evaluation budgeting: at each iteration, it evaluates only a fixed fraction of interactions by dynamically routing computation to high-conflict or high-uncertainty interactions, instead of using a fixed sparsification (e.g., static kNN graphs or static masks). Under fully inclusive end-to-end wall-clock accounting, LoRe substantially improves scalability on maximum independent set, pushing feasible inference beyond the baseline out-of-memory boundary by $2.5\\times$ while delivering $4$--$5\\times$ speedup, about 81% peak-memory reduction, and 86.9% MIS-size retention. As an auxiliary study on large-scale TSP, LoRe achieves $7.5\\times$ median speedup at $n=1000$ with 97% median memory reduction and a median gap difference of $-0.22$ percentage points versus the baseline, supporting its generality across problem families.","absKo":"мЎ°н•© мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң diffusion-based neural solverлҠ” dense edge/factor interactionмқ„ л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, inferenceк°Җ wall-clock time мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кі  лҢҖк·ңлӘЁм—җм„ңлҠ” мў…мў… memory-boundк°Җ лҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LoReлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” training-freeмқҳ inference-time drop-in wrapperлЎңм„ң stepлі„ interaction-evaluation budgetingмқ„ к°•м ңн•ңлӢӨ. к°Ғ iterationл§ҲлӢӨ кі м •лҗң fractionмқҳ interactionл§Ң нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳл©°, кі м •лҗң sparsification(мҳҲ: static kNN graphлӮҳ static mask)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ  high-conflict лҳҗлҠ” high-uncertainty interactionмңјлЎң computationмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң лқјмҡ°нҢ…н•ңлӢӨ. fully inclusive end-to-end wall-clock accounting н•ҳм—җм„ң, LoReлҠ” maximum independent setм—җм„ң нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, baselineмқҳ out-of-memory кІҪкі„лҘј л„ҳм–ҙ feasible inferenceлҘј $2.5\\times$ нҷ•мһҘн•ҳкі  $4$--$5\\times$ speedup, м•Ҫ 81%мқҳ peak-memory reduction, к·ёлҰ¬кі  86.9%мқҳ MIS-size retentionмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ TSPм—җ лҢҖн•ң ліҙмЎ° м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ”, LoReк°Җ $n=1000$м—җм„ң median $7.5\\times$ speedupмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  97%мқҳ median memory reduction л°Ҹ baseline лҢҖл№„ median gap difference $-0.22$ percentage pointлҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, л¬ём ң family м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң мқјл°ҳм„ұмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"66302","en":"FedPDG: Prediction DiscrepancyвҖ“Guided Data Generation for Heterogeneous Federated Learning","ko":"FedPDG: мқҙм§Ҳм Ғ Federated Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң мҳҲмёЎ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳ мң лҸ„ лҚ°мқҙн„° мғқм„ұ","authors":"Yuqi Wang, Jianwei Niu, Xinghao Wu, Xuefeng Liu, Xin Hao","pos":"#2708","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4vfv9HXhXN","abs":"<p>One emerging approach to mitigating data heterogeneity in Federated Learning (FL) is to employ diffusion models to generate synthetic data for clients, thereby aligning local data distributions with the global distribution. Prior work has primarily focused on balance-oriented augmentation, which assumes a balanced global class distribution and thus generates samples of rare classes to rebalance each client's local dataset. However, in practice, global data distributions are often inherently imbalanced. Moreover, privacy constraints in FL hinder the serverвҖҷs ability to accurately estimate the global distribution, rendering balance-oriented augmentation suboptimal. This raises a key, underexplored challenge: How can synthetic data be generated and selected to align local distributions with the true, yet unknown, global distribution? Our key insight is that a modelвҖҷs performance implicitly reflects the data distribution it has been trained on. Based on this observation, we use the performance discrepancy between local and global models to identify the regions where each clientвҖҷs local dataset is lacking, and generate corresponding samples for clients. Furthermore, we adapt the diffusion model via preference optimization, enabling it to generate data that better aligns with the true global distribution. Extensive experiments on multiple benchmarks demonstrate that FedPDG outperforms state-of-the-art methods, achieving up to 3.82\\% improvement.</p>","absKo":"<p>Federated Learning(FL)м—җм„ң data heterogeneityлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң л– мҳӨлҘҙлҠ” м ‘к·ј мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” diffusion modelмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ clientлҘј мң„н•ң synthetic dataлҘј мғқм„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ local data distributionмқ„ global distributionкіј м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң balance-oriented augmentationм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶° мҷ”лҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” к· нҳ• мһЎнһҢ global class distributionмқ„ к°Җм •н•ҳкі  к°Ғ clientмқҳ local datasetмқ„ мһ¬к· нҳ•н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ нқ¬мҶҢн•ң classмқҳ мғҳн”Ңмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” global data distributionмқҙ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң л¶Ҳк· нҳ•н•ң кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ FLмқҳ privacy constraintлҠ” serverк°Җ global distributionмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ, balance-oriented augmentationмқ„ мөңм Ғмқҙ м•„лӢҲкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лӢӨмқҢкіј к°ҷмқҖ н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ кіјм ңлҘј м ңкё°н•ңлӢӨ: м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ true global distributionм—җ local distributionмқ„ м •л ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ synthetic dataлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ мғқм„ұн•ҳкі  м„ нғқн•  кІғмқёк°Җ? мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ нҶөм°°мқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ к·ё лӘЁлҚёмқҙ н•ҷмҠөн•ң data distributionмқ„ м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң л°ҳмҳҒн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” local modelкіј global model к°„мқҳ performance discrepancyлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ к°Ғ clientмқҳ local datasetмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , к·ём—җ мғҒмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” мғҳн”Ңмқ„ clientлҘј мң„н•ҙ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң preference optimizationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ diffusion modelмқ„ мЎ°м •н•ҳм—¬ true global distributionм—җ лҚ” мһҳ м •л ¬лҗҳлҠ” dataлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FedPDGк°Җ state-of-the-art л°©лІ•мқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©° мөңлҢҖ 3.82\\%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62930","en":"Cross-task Calibration for Asynchronous Federated Continual Learning","ko":"л№„лҸҷкё° м—°н•© м§ҖмҶҚн•ҷмҠөмқҳ Cross-task Calibration","authors":"Yichen Li, Haozhao Wang, Hang Su, Yulong Li, xiaoquan Yi, Yankai Jiang, Chuang Zhao, Imran Razzak, Ruixuan Li","pos":"#3510","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=blan7cedXX","abs":"Federated Continual Learning (FCL) aims to empower distributed devices to learn a sequence of tasks over time. However, existing FCL research largely relies on the impractical assumption of synchronous new task arrival. This overlooks the reality of asynchronous user behavior and system latencies, forcing more efficient clients to endure costly inactivity. The practical necessity of an asynchronous method gives rise to Asynchronous Federated Continual Learning (AFCL). The server constantly receives a mixture of updates from clients at different time steps, leading to a catastrophic task drift that corrupts the global model and prevents effective learning. In this paper, we introduce a novel Cross-task Calibration framework called C$^2$-AFCL that is the first to tackle task drift at a semantic level within an Asynchronous FCL setting. Its core is a two-stage orthogonal calibration mechanism. First, intra-client calibration uses task-aware caches to mitigate variance from local client drift. Second, and more critically, inter-task interference calibration dynamically estimates an interference subspace from historical task knowledge. New updates are orthogonally projected to isolate and remove components that conflict with this subspace, preserving previous knowledge while learning new tasks. Extensive experiments show that C$^2$-AFCL significantly outperforms existing methods, demonstrating robust and efficient learning in dynamic federated environments.","absKo":"Federated Continual Learning (FCL)мқҖ л¶„мӮ°лҗң deviceк°Җ мӢңк°„м—җ л”°лқј taskмқҳ м—°мҶҚмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ FCL м—°кө¬лҠ” лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ л№„нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё synchronous new task arrival к°Җм •м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” л№„лҸҷкё°м Ғ user behaviorмҷҖ system latencyмқҳ нҳ„мӢӨмқ„ к°„кіјн•ҳл©°, лҚ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё clientк°Җ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° inactivityлҘј к°җмҲҳн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. л№„лҸҷкё°м Ғ л°©лІ•мқҳ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқҖ Asynchronous Federated Continual Learning (AFCL)мқ„ лӮілҠ”лӢӨ. serverлҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё time stepмқҳ client м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёк°Җ м„һмқё к°’мқ„ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳмӢ н•ҳкІҢ лҗҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” global modelмқ„ мҶҗмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё н•ҷмҠөмқ„ л°©н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” м№ҳлӘ…м Ғмқё task driftлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” Asynchronous FCL setting лӮҙм—җм„ң semantic levelм—җм„ңмқҳ task driftлҘј мІҳмқҢмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” Cross-task Calibration frameworkмқё C$^2$-AFCLмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё н•өмӢ¬мқҖ two-stage orthogonal calibration mechanismмқҙлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, intra-client calibrationмқҖ task-aware cacheлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ local client driftлЎң мқён•ң varianceлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, к·ёлҰ¬кі  лҚ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳкІҢ, inter-task interference calibrationмқҖ кіјкұ° task knowledgeлЎңл¶Җн„° interference subspaceлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м¶”м •н•ңлӢӨ. мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҠ” мқҙ subspaceмҷҖ м¶©лҸҢн•ҳлҠ” componentлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкі  м ңкұ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ orthogonally projectлҗҳл©°, мғҲ taskлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мқҙм „ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ C$^2$-AFCLмқҙ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, dynamic federated environmentм—җм„ң кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"66095","en":"Evaluating Parameter Efficient Methods for RLVR","ko":"RLVRмқ„ мң„н•ң нҢҢлқјлҜён„° нҡЁмңЁм Ғ л°©лІ• нҸүк°Җ","authors":"Qingyu Yin, Yulun Wu, Zhennan Shen, Sunbowen Lee, Zhilin Wang, Yanshu Li, Chak Tou Leong, Jiale Kang, Jinjin Gu","pos":"#3915","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=76CIL1O0bz","abs":"<p>We systematically evaluate Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) methods under the paradigm of Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR). RLVR incentivizes language models to enhance their reasoning capabilities through verifiable feedback; however, while methods like LoRA are commonly used, the optimal PEFT architecture for RLVR remains unidentified. In this work, we conduct the first comprehensive evaluation of over 12 PEFT methodologies across the DeepSeek-R1-Distill families on mathematical reasoning benchmarks. Our empirical results challenge the default adoption of standard LoRA with three main findings. First, we demonstrate that structural variants, such as DoRA, AdaLoRA, and MiSS, consistently outperform LoRA. Second, we uncover a spectral collapse phenomenon in SVD-informed initialization strategies (e.g., PiSSA, MiLoRA), attributing their failure to a fundamental misalignment between principal-component updates and RL optimization. Furthermore, our ablations reveal that extreme parameter reduction (e.g., VeRA, Rank-1) severely bottlenecks reasoning capacity. We further conduct ablation studies and scaling experiments to validate our findings. This work provides a definitive guide for advocating for more exploration for parameter-efficient RL methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Reinforcement Learning with Verifiable Rewards (RLVR) нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„ н•ҳм—җм„ң Parameter-Efficient Fine-Tuning (PEFT) л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. RLVRмқҖ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н”јл“ңл°ұмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, LoRAмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ л°©лІ•мқҙ л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ RLVRм—җ к°ҖмһҘ м Ғн•©н•ң PEFT м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳлҠ” м•„м§Ғ л°қнҳҖм§Җм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мҲҳн•ҷ м¶”лЎ  лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬м—җм„ң DeepSeek-R1-Distill кі„м—ҙ м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ 12к°ңк°Җ л„ҳлҠ” PEFT л°©лІ•лЎ мқ„ лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң н•ң мІ« нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғ нҸүк°ҖлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨмҰқ кІ°кіјлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ LoRAлҘј кё°ліё м„ нғқмңјлЎң мұ„нғқн•ҳлҠ” кҙҖн–үм—җ лҸ„м „н•ҳл©°, м„ё к°Җм§Җ мЈјмҡ” л°ңкІ¬мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, DoRA, AdaLoRA, MiSSмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ ліҖнҳ•л“Өмқҙ LoRAлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, SVDлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ң мҙҲкё°нҷ” м „лһөл“Ө(мҳҲ: PiSSA, MiLoRA)м—җм„ң spectral collapse нҳ„мғҒмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•ҳкі , к·ё мӢӨнҢЁ мӣҗмқёмқ„ principal-component м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёмҷҖ RL мөңм Ғнҷ” мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к·јліём Ғ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлЎң м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ ablationмқҖ к·№лӢЁм Ғмқё нҢҢлқјлҜён„° м¶•мҶҢ(мҳҲ: VeRA, Rank-1)к°Җ м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ лі‘лӘ©мӢңнӮЁлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. м¶”к°ҖлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°ңкІ¬мқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ ablation м—°кө¬мҷҖ scaling мӢӨн—ҳлҸ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” parameter-efficient RL л°©лІ•м—җ лҢҖн•ң лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ нғҗмғүмқ„ мҙүкө¬н•ҳлҠ” лӘ…нҷ•н•ң м§Җм№Ёмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61632","en":"The benefits of full data shuffle, now with optimal I/O cost: $k$-wise independence and matrix transposition to the rescue","ko":"м „мІҙ лҚ°мқҙн„° м…”н”Ңмқҳ мқҙм җ, мқҙм ң мөңм Ғ I/O л№„мҡ©к№Ңм§Җ: $k$-wise IndependenceмҷҖ н–үл ¬ м „м№ҳмқҳ лҸ„мӣҖ","authors":"Peyman Afshani, Rezaul Chowdhury, Mayank Goswami, Jens Kristian R Schou, Francesco Silvestri, Mariafiore Tognon","pos":"#4112","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=oHxq8g8Wy1","abs":"It is known that RandomShuffle, the without replacement version of Stochastic Gradient Descend (SGD), converges faster than with-replacement SGD.  However, RandomShuffle requires to uniformly perform a random permutation of the input sequence, which is known to have an high I/O complexity due to data movements over the memory hierarchy. In this paper, we propose a shuffling algorithm with a linear I/O complexity that generates almost-uniformly random permutations with rigorous mathematical guarantees. Specifically, we show that the shuffling algorithm can generate $2$-wise independent permutations. Furthermore, we can extend to $k$-wise independency with a small error in the probability distribution, if the fast memory has at least $k$ memory blocks.  These results allow us to reach the same expected theoretical convergence as RandomShuffle while achieving optimal linear I/O cost.","absKo":"RandomShuffle, мҰү Stochastic Gradient Descend(SGD)мқҳ without replacement лІ„м „мқҖ with-replacement SGDліҙлӢӨ лҚ” л№ лҘҙкІҢ мҲҳл ҙн•ҳлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ RandomShuffleмқҖ мһ…л Ҙ мӢңнҖҖмҠӨмқҳ random permutationмқ„ к· мқјн•ҳкІҢ мҲҳн–үн•ҙм•ј н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” memory hierarchy м „л°ҳмқҳ data movement л•Ңл¬ём—җ лҶ’мқҖ I/O complexityлҘј к°–лҠ” кІғмңјлЎң м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” м—„л°Җн•ң мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ кұ°мқҳ к· л“ұн•ң random permutationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң м„ нҳ• I/O complexityлҘј к°–лҠ” shuffling algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ shuffling algorithmмқҙ $2$-wise independent permutationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, fast memoryм—җ м Ғм–ҙлҸ„ $k$к°ңмқҳ memory blockмқҙ мһҲлӢӨл©ҙ нҷ•лҘ  л¶„нҸ¬м—җ мһ‘мқҖ мҳӨм°ЁлҘј н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ң $k$-wise independencyлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” optimal linear I/O costлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң RandomShuffleкіј лҸҷмқјн•ң кё°лҢҖ мқҙлЎ  мҲҳл ҙмқ„ м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"66288","en":"Lightweight Federated Incremental Learning via Decoupled Replay","ko":"л¶„лҰ¬лҗң ReplayлҘј нҶөн•ң кІҪлҹү Federated мҰқл¶„ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Xiuying Wang, Yichen Li, Hang Su, Gaozhuo Liu, Shiwei Li, Chuang Zhao, Jiangming Shi, Imran Razzak","pos":"#4200","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=538sn0p2Ek","abs":"<p>Federated Incremental Learning (FIL) aims to learn streaming tasks across distributed clients without catastrophic forgetting while preserving privacy. Most existing methods focus on sample-based replay techniques, which mitigate forgetting by replaying historical data samples. However, such methods often face challenges related to data privacy risks and significant resource overheads, making them impractical and difficult to deploy on edge devices with limited resources. To address this challenge, we propose a novel and \\underline{Li}ghtweight \\underline{F}ederated \\underline{I}ncremental \\underline{L}earning framework called \\textbf{Li-FIL} that leverages dense features synthesized by a secure generator on the server to enable efficient feature-based replay on decoupled local models. More specifically, each client extracts high-confidence features from the new task, applies mixup to obtain a dense feature representation, and then privatizes these features before uploading them to the server, which reduces both storage and communication overhead. A generator is deployed on the server to learn the distributions of different clients and generate global features for replay. Moreover, to enable clients to better learn from these dense features, we decouple the local model into two components: a feature extractor and a classifier. This design allows feature replay and the alignment between new and previous features to be conducted separately and more effectively. Extensive experiments demonstrate that Li-FIL outperforms other state-of-the-art methods by up to 10.14 in terms of accuracy on both old and new tasks with superior resource efficiency.</p>","absKo":"<p>Federated Incremental Learning (FIL)мқҖ privacyлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң л¶„мӮ°лҗң client м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ streaming taskлҘј catastrophic forgetting м—Ҷмқҙ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ sample-based replay кё°лІ•м—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”л©°, кіјкұ° лҚ°мқҙн„° мғҳн”Ңмқ„ replayн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ forgettingмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•мқҖ мў…мў… лҚ°мқҙн„° privacy мң„н—ҳкіј мғҒлӢ№н•ң мһҗмӣҗ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлқјлҠ” л¬ём ңм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ҳл©°, м ңн•ңлҗң мһҗмӣҗмқ„ к°Җм§„ edge deviceм—җ мӢӨм ңлЎң л°°нҸ¬н•ҳкё°м—җлҠ” л№„нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқҙкі  м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ңлІ„м—җм„ң secure generatorк°Җ н•©м„ұн•ң dense featureлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ decoupled local modelм—җм„ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё feature-based replayлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎӯкі  \\underline{Li}ghtweight \\underline{F}ederated \\underline{I}ncremental \\underline{L}earning framework, мҰү \\textbf{Li-FIL}мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліҙлӢӨ кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, к°Ғ clientлҠ” мғҲ taskм—җм„ң high-confidence featureлҘј м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкі , mixupмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҙ dense feature representationмқ„ м–»мқҖ л’Ө, мқҙлҘј м„ңлІ„м—җ м—…лЎңл“ңн•ҳкё° м „м—җ privatizeн•ҳм—¬ storageмҷҖ communication overheadлҘј лӘЁл‘җ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. м„ңлІ„м—җлҠ” generatorк°Җ л°°м№ҳлҗҳм–ҙ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё clientмқҳ distributionмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  replayлҘј мң„н•ң global featureлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң clientк°Җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң dense featureлЎңл¶Җн„° лҚ” мһҳ н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ local modelмқ„ feature extractorмҷҖ classifierмқҳ л‘җ кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢлЎң л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” feature replayмҷҖ new featureмҷҖ previous feature к°„ alignmentлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳм—¬ лҚ” нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Li-FILмқҙ мҳӨлһҳлҗң taskмҷҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ task лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң accuracy мёЎл©ҙмңјлЎң мөңлҢҖ 10.14к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨлҘё state-of-the-art л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ҳл©°, мһҗмӣҗ нҡЁмңЁм„ұлҸ„ лҚ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64974","en":"Obliviate: Efficient Unlearning in Recommender Systems","ko":"Obliviate: м¶”мІң мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ңмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Unlearning","authors":"Tushar Prakash, Brijraj Singh, Niranjan Pedanekar, Narayan Chaturvedi","pos":"#4201","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ID9vIdHA4Y","abs":"<p>Machine unlearning is becoming increasingly critical in the context of data privacy regulations, particularly for recommender systems that are directly trained on user interaction data. The goal of this work is to remove designated interactions and their downstream influence while preserving recommendation quality, and to do so without incurring the substantial computational cost of full retraining. Existing approaches exhibit inherent trade-offs, including limited unlearning completeness, poor scalability, degradation in recommendation utility, or substantial computational and memory overhead. In this paper, we propose Obliviate, an efficient two-stage unlearning framework for recommender systems that achieves strong unlearning completeness while maintaining high utility. In the first stage, we introduce a Low-Rank Unlearning Adapter (LUA), which employs a lightweight Hessian proxy to enable curvature-aware and parameter-efficient unlearning through localized low-rank adapter modules. In the second stage, we present Locality-Aware Calibration (LAC), a lightweight refinement procedure that updates only the adapter parameters using a compact witness set, enforcing unlearning via ranking-based objectives while preserving utility through knowledge distillation. Extensive empirical evaluations demonstrate that Obliviate, achieves strong forgetting with minimal loss in recommendation quality and at significantly reduced computational cost, offering a practical and scalable solution for large-scale recommender systems.</p>","absKo":"<p>Machine unlearningмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„° н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң к·ңм ңмқҳ л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ң м җм җ лҚ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҙм§Җкі  мһҲмңјл©°, нҠ№нһҲ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎң м§Ғм ‘ н•ҷмҠөлҗҳлҠ” recommender systemм—җм„ң к·ёлҹ¬н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬мқҳ лӘ©н‘ңлҠ” м§Җм •лҗң interactionкіј к·ё downstream мҳҒн–Ҙл Ҙмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ҳл©ҙм„ң recommendation qualityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳкі , full retrainingмқҳ л§үлҢҖн•ң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ© м—Ҷмқҙ мқҙлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•л“ӨмқҖ м ңн•ңм Ғмқё unlearning completeness, лӮ®мқҖ нҷ•мһҘм„ұ, recommendation utilityмқҳ м Җн•ҳ, лҳҗлҠ” мғҒлӢ№н•ң кі„мӮ° л°Ҹ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ң л“ұ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё trade-offлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ utilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ к°•н•ң unlearning completenessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” recommender systemмҡ© нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё 2лӢЁкі„ unlearning н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё ObliviateлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мІ« лІҲм§ё лӢЁкі„м—җм„ңлҠ” көӯмҶҢм Ғмқё low-rank adapter moduleмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ curvature-awareн•ҳкі  parameter-efficientн•ң unlearningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” кІҪлҹү Hessian proxyлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” Low-Rank Unlearning Adapter (LUA)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. л‘җ лІҲм§ё лӢЁкі„м—җм„ңлҠ” compact witness setмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ adapter parameterл§Ң м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён•ҳлҠ” Locality-Aware Calibration (LAC)мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, knowledge distillationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ utilityлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң ranking кё°л°ҳ objectiveлЎң unlearningмқ„ к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” кІҪлҹү refinement м Ҳм°ЁлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨмҰқ нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіј, ObliviateлҠ” recommendation quality мҶҗмӢӨмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ к°•н•ң forgettingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©лҸ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лӮ®м¶°, лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ recommender systemмқ„ мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқҙкі  нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64573","en":"RC-FCL: Combating Asynchronous Concept Drift in Federated Continual Learning via Retrospective Calibration","ko":"RC-FCL: Retrospective Calibrationмқ„ нҶөн•ң Federated Continual Learningм—җм„ңмқҳ л№„лҸҷкё° Concept Drift лҢҖмқ‘","authors":"Hang Su, Yijun Mo, Zhiyu Zhang, Yankai Jiang, Bo Liu, Yichen Li, Imran Razzak","pos":"#4202","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=M4qqzXECcp","abs":"<p>Federated Continual Learning (FCL) enables the continuous acquisition of knowledge from streaming tasks, but inherently struggles with the temporal dynamics of client data distributions. These dynamics naturally induce asynchronous concept drift, where distribution shifts occur independently across clients at unsynchronized times and with varying magnitudes. Such asynchrony generates conflicting updates that destabilize global convergence and exacerbate catastrophic forgetting. However, existing FCL research focuses on static or incremental settings, typically treating all incoming updates uniformly, which obscures concept drift under divergent distributions and fails to adapt to the evolution of learned concepts. To address these limitations, we propose RC-FCL, a retrospective calibration framework for FCL that can effectively distinguish asynchronous concept drift and adjust the learning strategy adaptively. Specifically, RC-FCL leverages a conditional generative model to synthesize class-conditional reference distributions of previously learned concepts for local drift detection. It calibrates local adaptation using a weighting mechanism driven by the local discriminator to prioritize informative samples, and executes a global aggregation strategy based on drift magnitude. Our experimental results demonstrate that RC-FCL achieves competitive performance against state-of-the-art methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Federated Continual Learning (FCL)мқҖ streaming taskлЎңл¶Җн„° м§ҖмӢқмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң мҠөл“қн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, client data distributionмқҳ temporal dynamicsлҘј ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈЁкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң dynamicsлҠ” мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ asynchronous concept driftлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” distribution shiftк°Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё clientм—җм„ң л№„лҸҷкё°м Ғмқё мӢңм җкіј м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё нҒ¬кё°лЎң лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л№„лҸҷкё°лҠ” global convergenceлҘј л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” conflicting updateлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳкі  catastrophic forgettingмқ„ м•…нҷ”мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ FCL м—°кө¬лҠ” м •м Ғмқҙкұ°лӮҳ incremental settingм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”л©°, ліҙнҶө л“Өм–ҙмҳӨлҠ” лӘЁл“  updateлҘј лҸҷмқјн•ҳкІҢ м·Ёкёүн•ҳлҜҖлЎң мғҒмқҙн•ң distribution м•„лһҳм—җм„ң concept driftлҘј к°Җл ӨлӮҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі , н•ҷмҠөлҗң conceptмқҳ м§„нҷ”м—җ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” RC-FCLмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. RC-FCLмқҖ asynchronous concept driftлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬лі„н•ҳкі  learning strategyлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” retrospective calibration frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, RC-FCLмқҖ conditional generative modelмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мқҙм „м—җ н•ҷмҠөн•ң conceptмқҳ class-conditional reference distributionмқ„ н•©м„ұн•ҳм—¬ local drift detectionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң local discriminatorк°Җ мЈјлҸ„н•ҳлҠ” weighting mechanismмңјлЎң local adaptationмқ„ ліҙм •н•ҳм—¬ м •ліҙм„ұмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ sampleмқ„ мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳкі , drift magnitudeм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң global aggregation strategyлҘј мӢӨн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј RC-FCLмқҖ state-of-the-art л°©лІ•л“Өкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63919","en":"CORAL: Uncertainty-Aware Regulation of Exposure Concentration in Recommender Systems","ko":"CORAL: м¶”мІң мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ң exposure concentrationмқҳ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұ мқём§Җ мЎ°м Ҳ","authors":"Nitin Bisht, Linjiang Guo, Xiuwen Gong, Huan Huo, Guandong Xu","pos":"#4208","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=SYy3iiuNAe","abs":"<p>Recommender systems (RS) may suffer from feedback-driven exposure concentration, where repeated engagement optimization collapses exposure onto a narrow set of categories, reducing catalog coverage and degrading long-horizon learning. Existing methods are often post hoc and typically lack principled uncertainty-aware risk estimates for regulating exposure under endogenous feedback. We therefore propose <strong>CORAL</strong>, a model-agnostic, uncertainty-aware framework that formulates exposure regulation as a constrained sequential decision problem. Specifically, we model self-reinforcing interactions to construct an exposure-saturation state, then derive an upper confidence bound on category-conditioned violation risk from observed history and incorporate it through a state-dependent penalty for adaptive intervention near saturation. Moreover, we provide theoretical guarantees for risk bounds, finite-time recovery, and efficient long-term performance. Extensive experiments on real-world datasets and controlled simulations validate the effectiveness of the proposed framework, which aligns with our theoretical analysis. Our code is available at: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Coral_Rec-8400.</p>","absKo":"<p>Recommender systems (RS)лҠ” feedback-driven exposure concentrationмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л°ӣмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҰү, л°ҳліөм Ғмқё engagement optimizationмқҙ л…ём¶ңмқ„ мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ м№ҙн…Ңкі лҰ¬лЎң л¶•кҙҙмӢңмјң catalog coverageлҘј мӨ„мқҙкі  мһҘкё° н•ҷмҠөмқ„ м Җн•ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мӮ¬нӣ„м Ғ(post hoc)мқё кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һкі , лӮҙмғқм Ғ feedback н•ҳм—җм„ң exposureлҘј мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё uncertainty-aware risk estimateк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” exposure regulationмқ„ constrained sequential decision problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” model-agnostic, uncertainty-aware frameworkмқё <strong>CORAL</strong>мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, self-reinforcing interactionмқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳм—¬ exposure-saturation stateлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ң л’Ө, кҙҖмёЎлҗң historyлЎңл¶Җн„° category-conditioned violation riskмқҳ upper confidence boundлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкі , saturationм—җ к·јм ‘н–Ҳмқ„ л•Ңмқҳ adaptive interventionмқ„ мң„н•ң state-dependent penaltyм—җ мқҙлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, risk bound, finite-time recovery, efficient long-term performanceм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңмӢңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣкіј м ңм–ҙлҗң simulationм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қкіј л¶Җн•©н•ҳлҠ” м ңм•Ҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/Coral_Rec-8400 м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63967","en":"Beyond Hamming: Query-Aware Decoding of Binary Cosine Sketches","ko":"Hammingмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ң: мқҙм§„ мҪ”мӮ¬мқё мҠӨмјҖм№ҳмқҳ мҝјлҰ¬ мқём§Җ л””мҪ”л”©","authors":"DaeHun Nyang","pos":"#4212","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=SAzz3DJdGy","abs":"Cosine similarity estimation is a core primitive in coarse-to-fine retrieval pipelines, where early-stage candidate selection relies on approximate similarity estimates whose errors are amplified downstream. Widely used sign-based sketches arising from extreme quantization of random projections exhibit a structural variance peak near $\\theta$ $\\approx$ 90$^\\circ$, the near-background region where candidate selection is most difficult. We propose QA-Cos, a query-aware decoder-side estimator that departs from the Hamming-agreement paradigm, treating sign bits as probabilistic observations rather than deterministic votes. Across simulations and BEIR benchmarks, QA-Cos reduces estimation error by up to $\\sim$15--20\\% in the near-orthogonal region and translates these gains into improved candidate selection in two-stage ANN pipelines, improving Hit@K by up to $\\sim$30 percentage points at fixed budgets and reducing candidates by up to $\\sim$45--50\\% at fixed recall.","absKo":"<p>Cosine similarity estimationмқҖ coarse-to-fine retrieval pipelineмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ primitiveлЎң, мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„мқҳ candidate selectionмқҙ к·јмӮ¬ similarity estimateм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©° к·ё мҳӨм°ЁлҠ” downstreamм—җм„ң мҰқнҸӯлҗңлӢӨ. random projectionмқ„ к·№лӢЁм ҒмңјлЎң quantizationн•ҳм—¬ м–»лҠ” sign-based sketchлҠ” л„җлҰ¬ м“°мқҙм§Җл§Ң, $\\theta$ $\\approx$ 90$^\\circ$ к·јмІҳмқҳ structural variance peakлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ мҳҒм—ӯмқҖ candidate selectionмқҙ к°ҖмһҘ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ near-background regionмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Hamming-agreement paradigmм—җм„ң лІ—м–ҙлӮҳ sign bitмқ„ кІ°м •лЎ м Ғ нҲ¬н‘ңк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј нҷ•лҘ м Ғ кҙҖмёЎмңјлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳлҠ” query-aware decoder-side estimatorмқё QA-CosлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳкіј BEIR benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң QA-CosлҠ” near-orthogonal regionм—җм„ң estimation errorлҘј мөңлҢҖ м•Ҫ 15--20\\% мӨ„мҳҖкі , мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°ңм„ мқ„ two-stage ANN pipelineмқҳ candidate selection н–ҘмғҒмңјлЎң м—°кІ°н•ҳм—¬, кі м •лҗң budgetм—җм„ң Hit@KлҘј мөңлҢҖ м•Ҫ 30 percentage points лҶ’мқҙкі , кі м • recallм—җм„ң candidate мҲҳлҘј мөңлҢҖ м•Ҫ 45--50\\% мӨ„мҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61688","en":"Class-Grouped-Normalized-Momentum and Faster Hyperparameter Exploration to Tackle Class Imbalance in Federated Learning","ko":"Federated Learningмқҳ Class Imbalance лҢҖмқ‘мқ„ мң„н•ң Class-Grouped-Normalized-Momentumкіј лҚ” л№ лҘё Hyperparameter нғҗмғү","authors":"Haemin Park, Diego Klabjan, Martin Braun, Xiuqi Li, Balakrishnan Ananthanarayanan","pos":"#4301","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=njBsluG3Nn","abs":"<p>Class imbalance poses a critical challenge in federated learning (FL), where underrepresented classes suffer from poor predictive performance yet cannot be addressed by standard centralized techniques due to privacy and heterogeneity constraints. We propose FedCGNM (Federated Class-Grouped Normalized Momentum), a client-side optimizer in FL that partitions classes into a small number of groups based on minimum within-group variance, maintains a momentum per group, normalizes each group momentum to unit length, and uses the summation of the normalized group momentums as an update direction. This design both equalizes gradient magnitude across majority and minority groups and mitigates the noise inherent in rare-class gradients. We further provide a theoretical convergence analysis explicitly accounting for time-varying resampling rates. Additionally, to efficiently optimize these rates in small-client regimes, we introduce FedHOO, an X-armed-bandit (XAB) based algorithm that exploits federated parallelism that evaluates many combinations of two candidate rates per client at linear cost. Empirical evaluation on four public long-tailed benchmarks and a proprietary chip-defect dataset demonstrates that FedCGNM consistently outperforms baselines, with FedHOO yielding further gains in small-scale federations.</p>","absKo":"<p>Class imbalanceлҠ” federated learning (FL)м—җм„ң мӨ‘лҢҖн•ң кіјм ңлҘј м ңкё°н•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖн‘ңм„ұмқҙ лӮ®мқҖ нҒҙлһҳмҠӨлҠ” мҳҲмёЎ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§Җм§Җл§Ң, privacyмҷҖ heterogeneity м ңм•Ҫ л•Ңл¬ём—җ н‘ңмӨҖ centralized кё°лІ•мңјлЎңлҠ” мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FedCGNM(Federated Class-Grouped Normalized Momentum)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” FLм—җм„ң client-side optimizerлЎңм„ң, нҒҙлһҳмҠӨл“Өмқ„ group лӮҙ л¶„мӮ°мқҙ мөңмҶҢк°Җ лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ к·ёлЈ№мңјлЎң л¶„н• н•ҳкі , к·ёлЈ№л§ҲлӢӨ momentumмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©°, к°Ғ к·ёлЈ№ momentumмқ„ unit lengthлЎң м •к·ңнҷ”н•ң л’Ө, м •к·ңнҷ”лҗң к·ёлЈ№ momentumл“Өмқҳ н•©мқ„ update directionмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” majority к·ёлЈ№кіј minority к·ёлЈ№ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ gradient magnitudeлҘј к· л“ұнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, нқ¬к·Җ нҒҙлһҳмҠӨ gradientм—җ лӮҙмһ¬н•ң noiseлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мӢңк°„м—җ л”°лқј ліҖн•ҳлҠ” resampling rateлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң л°ҳмҳҒн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ мҲҳл ҙ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. м¶”к°ҖлЎң, small-client regimeм—җм„ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң rateлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, clientлӢ№ л‘җ к°ңмқҳ нӣ„ліҙ rate мЎ°н•© лӢӨмҲҳлҘј м„ нҳ• л№„мҡ©мңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” federated parallelismмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” X-armed-bandit (XAB) кё°л°ҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқё FedHOOлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. л„Ө к°ңмқҳ public long-tailed benchmarkмҷҖ proprietary chip-defect datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨмҰқ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” FedCGNMмқҙ baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, FedHOOк°Җ small-scale federationм—җм„ң м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ к°Җм ёмҳҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63094","en":"Causal-aware Anomaly Detection for Tabular Data","ko":"н…Ңмқҙлё” нҳ•мӢқ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мң„н•ң мқёкіј мқём§Җ мқҙмғҒ нғҗм§Җ","authors":"Dang Nguyen, Tu Anh Hoang Nguyen, Thuc Le, Svetha Venkatesh, Trung Le, Sunil Gupta","pos":"#4302","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=aB9PaI3Rw2","abs":"<p>Anomaly detection (AD) methods often ignore causal dependencies and treat anomalies as outliers, which is brittle when anomalies are primarily mechanism violations rather than extreme values. We propose CausalAno, a causal-aware detector that trains a causal GAN on normal data and leverages its discriminator to learn mechanism-consistent representations. We score test samples by fitting a Gaussian model in this feature space and computing the Mahalanobis distance, measuring deviation from the normal causal manifold. We demonstrate the effectiveness of CausalAno with extensive experiments on 28 tabular datasets (18 continuous-only and 10 mixed-type), comparing against 16 SOTA baselines. Our results show consistent improvements across both mixed-type and numerical-only settings. Our ablation studies further confirm that the gains come from the causal factorization in the causal GAN rather than a generic GAN backbone. Our CausalAno offers a practical and effective solution for real-world applications where anomalies often arise from dependency-breaking behaviors.</p>","absKo":"<p>Anomaly detection (AD) л°©лІ•мқҖ мў…мў… causal dependencyлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳкі  anomalyлҘј outlierлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” anomalyк°Җ к·№лӢЁк°’мқҙлқјкё°ліҙлӢӨ mechanism violationмқё кІҪмҡ° м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м •мғҒ лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎң causal GANмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , к·ё discriminatorлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ mechanism-consistent representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” causal-aware detectorмқё CausalAnoлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” test sampleмқ„ мқҙ feature spaceм—җм„ң Gaussian modelм—җ м Ғн•©мӢңнӮЁ л’Ө Mahalanobis distanceлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳм—¬ м җмҲҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” м •мғҒ causal manifoldлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ нҺём°ЁлҘј мёЎм •н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 28к°ңмқҳ tabular dataset(18к°ңмқҳ continuous-onlyмҷҖ 10к°ңмқҳ mixed-type)м—җм„ң 16к°ңмқҳ SOTA baselineкіј л№„көҗн•ҳлҠ” кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ CausalAnoмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” mixed-type л°Ҹ numerical-only м„Өм • лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң ablation studyлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н–ҘмғҒмқҙ generic GAN backboneмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј causal GANмқҳ causal factorizationм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗң кІғмһ„мқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ CausalAnoлҠ” anomalyк°Җ мў…мў… dependency-breaking behaviorм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©мқ„ мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё н•ҙкІ°мұ…мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63142","en":"Approximate Nearest Neighbor Search for Modern AI: A Projection-Augmented Graph Approach","ko":"нҳ„лҢҖ AIлҘј мң„н•ң к·јмӮ¬ мөңк·јм ‘ мқҙмӣғ нғҗмғү: мӮ¬мҳҒ мҰқк°• к·ёлһҳн”„ м ‘к·јлІ•","authors":"Kejing Lu, Zhenpeng Pan, Jianbin Qin, Yoshiharu Ishikawa, Chuan Xiao","pos":"#4304","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Zg6yWOIecu","abs":"<p>Approximate Nearest Neighbor Search (ANNS) is fundamental to modern AI applications. Most existing solutions optimize query efficiency but fail to align with the practical requirements of modern workloads. In this paper, we outline six critical demands of modern AI applications: high query efficiency, fast indexing, low memory footprint, scalability to high dimensionality, robustness across varying retrieval sizes, and support for online insertions. To satisfy all these demands, we introduce Projection-Augmented Graph (PAG), a new ANNS framework that integrates projection techniques into a graph index. PAG reduces unnecessary exact distance computations through asymmetric comparisons between exact and approximate distances guided by projection-based statistical tests. Three key components are designed and unified to the graph index to optimize indexing and searching. Experiments on six modern datasets demonstrate that PAG consistently achieves superior query per second (QPS)-recall performance---up to 5Г—faster than HNSW---while offering fast indexing speed and small memory footprint. PAG remains robust as dimensionality and retrieval size increase and naturally supports online insertions. Our source code is available at: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/PAG-A73D/ .</p>","absKo":"<p>Approximate Nearest Neighbor Search (ANNS)лҠ” нҳ„лҢҖ AI applicationмқҳ к·јк°„мқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ solutionмқҖ query efficiencyлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҳ„лҢҖ workloadмқҳ мӢӨм ң мҡ”кө¬мӮ¬н•ӯкіјмқҳ м •н•©м„ұмқҖ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” нҳ„лҢҖ AI applicationмқҳ м—¬м„Ҝ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ мҡ”кө¬мӮ¬н•ӯ, мҰү лҶ’мқҖ query efficiency, л№ лҘё indexing, лӮ®мқҖ memory footprint, лҶ’мқҖ dimensionalityлЎңмқҳ нҷ•мһҘм„ұ, лӢӨм–‘н•ң retrieval sizeм—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•кұҙм„ұ, online insertion м§Җмӣҗмқ„ м •лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘЁл“  мҡ”кө¬лҘј м¶©мЎұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” projection techniqueмқ„ graph indexм—җ нҶөн•©н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ ANNS frameworkмқё Projection-Augmented Graph (PAG)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. PAGлҠ” projection-based statistical testм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗҳлҠ” exact distanceмҷҖ approximate distance к°„мқҳ asymmetric comparisonмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ л¶Ҳн•„мҡ”н•ң м •нҷ• кұ°лҰ¬ кі„мӮ°мқ„ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. м„ё к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ componentк°Җ м„Өкі„лҗҳм–ҙ graph indexм—җ нҶөн•©лҗҳл©°, indexingкіј searchingмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬м„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ нҳ„лҢҖм Ғ datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PAGк°Җ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң query per second (QPS)-recall м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјл©°, HNSWліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ 5Г— л№ лҘҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ л№ лҘё indexing speedмҷҖ мһ‘мқҖ memory footprintлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. PAGлҠ” dimensionalityмҷҖ retrieval sizeк°Җ мҰқк°Җн•ҙлҸ„ к°•кұҙн•Ёмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©°, мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ online insertionмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ. мҶҢмҠӨ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” лӢӨмқҢм—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/PAG-A73D/ .</p>"},{"id":"65123","en":"The Signal is in the Steps: Local Scoring for Reasoning Data Selection","ko":"мӢ нҳёлҠ” мҠӨн…қ м•Ҳм—җ мһҲлӢӨ: м¶”лЎ  лҚ°мқҙн„° м„ нғқмқ„ мң„н•ң м§Җм—ӯм Ғ мҠӨмҪ”м–ҙл§Ғ","authors":"Hoang Anh Just, Myeongseob Ko, Ruoxi Jia","pos":"#4403","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=GcB3a6IonG","abs":"<p>Distilling long-form reasoning from teacher models into smaller students requires selecting which candidate solutions to train on. Recent work argues that one should select responses the student model assigns highest probability, i.e., favoring solutions ``natural'' to the student. However, we find that this approach works within a single teacher but fails when scaling to long reasoning traces from multiple diverse teachers. We identify a key cause: this approach scores entire solutions, but students generalize by recombining familiar reasoning steps, not by memorizing complete solutions. Full-trajectory scoring optimizes the wrong target; it rewards global fluency while the transferable signal lies in local step transitions. We propose Local Average Log Probability (LALP), which scores each reasoning step using only a small window of preceding context, measuring whether each step is justified by its immediate premises rather than whether the full response looks natural to the student. LALP enables two practical use cases: selecting the best teacher before fine-tuning and curating training data from diverse teacher pools. Across math, coding, and science reasoning tasks, LALP consistently improves accuracy when selecting the most natural solutions by a large margin.</p>","absKo":"teacher modelмқҳ long-form reasoningмқ„ лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ studentм—җкІҢ distillн•ҳл Өл©ҙ, м–ҙл–Ө candidate solutionмқ„ н•ҷмҠөм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©н• м§Җ м„ нғқн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” student modelмқҙ к°ҖмһҘ лҶ’мқҖ нҷ•лҘ мқ„ л¶Җм—¬н•ҳлҠ” responseлҘј м„ нғқн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, мҰү studentм—җкІҢ 'мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ' solutionмқ„ м„ нҳён•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  ліёлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҙ лӢЁмқј teacher м•Ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, м—¬лҹ¬ лӢӨм–‘н•ң teacherлЎңл¶Җн„° лӮҳмҳЁ кёҙ reasoning traceлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳл©ҙ мӢӨнҢЁн•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. к·ё н•өмӢ¬ мӣҗмқёмқҖ мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҙ м „мІҙ solutionмқ„ м җмҲҳнҷ”н•ңлӢӨлҠ” лҚ° мһҲлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ studentлҠ” мҷ„м „н•ң solutionмқ„ м•”кё°н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј мқөмҲҷн•ң reasoning stepмқ„ мһ¬мЎ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ generalizeн•ңлӢӨ. м „мІҙ trajectory scoringмқҖ мһҳлӘ»лҗң лӘ©н‘ңлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү global fluencyм—җлҠ” ліҙмғҒмқ„ мЈјм§Җл§Ң, transferable signalмқҖ local step transitionм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Local Average Log Probability(LALP)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” к°Ғ reasoning stepмқ„ м§Ғм „мқҳ мҶҢк·ңлӘЁ context windowл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м җмҲҳнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, м „мІҙ responseк°Җ studentм—җкІҢ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мӣҢ ліҙмқҙлҠ”м§ҖліҙлӢӨ к°Ғ stepмқҙ л°”лЎң м•һмқҳ м „м ңм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м •лӢ№нҷ”лҗҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј мёЎм •н•ңлӢӨ. LALPлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ мӮ¬мҡ© мӮ¬лЎҖлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. fine-tuning м „м—җ к°ҖмһҘ мўӢмқҖ teacherлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” кІғкіј, лӢӨм–‘н•ң teacher poolм—җм„ң training dataлҘј м„ лі„н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷ, мҪ”л”©, кіјн•ҷ reasoning task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң LALPлҠ” к°ҖмһҘ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ solutionмқ„ м„ нғқн•  л•Ң мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61343","en":"Estimating the Empowerment of Language Model Agents","ko":"Language Model Agentмқҳ Empowerment м¶”м •","authors":"Jinyeop Song, Jeff Gore, Max Kleiman-Weiner","pos":"#4412","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=r8qbhgGHnC","abs":"<p>As language model (LM) agents become increasingly capable and adopted in real-world applications, there is a growing need for scalable evaluation frameworks beyond costly, manually-designed benchmarks. We propose information-theoretic evaluation based on empowerment, an information-theoretic measure of an agent's influence on future states through its actions. To handle the unique challenges of text-based environments, we introduce EELMA (Estimating Empowerment of Language Model Agents), an algorithm for approximating effective empowerment from multi-turn text interactions. We demonstrate EELMA on textual games and web-browsing scenarios, showing that empowerment strongly correlates with average task performance. We further analyze how empowerment varies across models, environment complexity, and agent configurations, and show that high-empowerment states and actions often mark pivotal moments for general capabilities. These results establish empowerment as a general-purpose metric for evaluating LM agents in open-ended settings. Code available: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/EELMA-E227</p>","absKo":"<p>language model (LM) agentк°Җ нҳ„мӢӨ м„ёкі„ мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң м җм җ лҚ” к°•л Ҙн•ҙм§Җкі  л„җлҰ¬ мұ„нғқлҗЁм—җ л”°лқј, л№„мҡ©мқҙ л§Һмқҙ л“Өкі  мҲҳмһ‘м—…мңјлЎң м„Өкі„лҗң benchmarkлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҸүк°Җ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬м—җ лҢҖн•ң н•„мҡ”м„ұмқҙ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” empowermentм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң information-theoretic evaluationмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. empowermentлҠ” agentк°Җ мһҗмӢ мқҳ н–үлҸҷмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лҜёлһҳ мғҒнғңм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” information-theoretic мІҷлҸ„мқҙлӢӨ. н…ҚмҠӨнҠё кё°л°ҳ нҷҳкІҪмқҳ кі мң н•ң лҸ„м „мқ„ лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” EELMA (Estimating Empowerment of Language Model Agents)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” multi-turn text interactionмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° effective empowermentлҘј к·јмӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н…ҚмҠӨнҠё кІҢмһ„кіј мӣ№ лёҢлқјмҡ°м§• мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң EELMAлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳл©°, empowermentк°Җ нҸүк·  task performanceмҷҖ к°•н•ҳкІҢ мғҒкҙҖлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң empowermentк°Җ лӘЁлҚё, нҷҳкІҪ ліөмһЎлҸ„, agent configuration м „л°ҳм—җм„ң м–ҙл–»кІҢ лӢ¬лқјм§ҖлҠ”м§Җ л¶„м„қн•ҳкі , high-empowerment stateмҷҖ actionмқҙ мқјл°ҳм Ғ лҠҘл Ҙмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м „нҷҳм җмқё кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјлҠ” empowermentлҘј open-ended settingм—җм„ң LM agentлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң лІ”мҡ© metricмңјлЎң нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. Code available: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/EELMA-E227</p>"},{"id":"62132","en":"CARE: Adaptive Calibration for Reliable Recommendations","ko":"CARE: мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м¶”мІңмқ„ мң„н•ң м Ғмқ‘нҳ• Calibration","authors":"Nitin Bisht, Xiuwen Gong, Huan Huo, Guandong Xu","pos":"#4111","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jXt84IgAgg","abs":"<p>Modern recommender systems are typically trained offline and deployed with parameters held fixed between periodic refreshes, yet user behavior can evolve substantially during deployment. This can cause ranking utility to degrade over time and makes it difficult to provide formal guarantees about recommendation quality. We propose <strong>CARE</strong>, an adaptive calibration framework that wraps an arbitrary backbone recommender and outputs variable-size recommendation sets with finite-sample performance guarantees over interaction streams. CARE combines (i) a loss-based monitoring module that localizes behavioral changes and triggers threshold recalibration, and (ii) an online aggregation rule that promotes compact recommendation sets by dynamically reweighting candidate set predictors. We provide theoretical results establishing finite-sample guarantees for utility-based risk control and bounds on the expected set size relative to the best constituent predictor. Experiments across multiple datasets and backbone models demonstrate that CARE improves robustness and maintains compact recommendation sets while preserving the desired statistical guarantees. The code and implementation are available in https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CARE-FCBD.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖ recommender systemмқҖ лҢҖк°ң offlineмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗҳкі , мЈјкё°м Ғмқё refresh мӮ¬мқҙм—җлҠ” parameterк°Җ кі м •лҗң мұ„ л°°нҸ¬лҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ н–үлҸҷмқҖ л°°нҸ¬ мӨ‘м—җлҸ„ нҒ¬кІҢ ліҖн•  мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” ranking utilityмқҳ мӢңк°„мқҙ м§ҖлӮЁм—җ л”°лҘё м Җн•ҳлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, recommendation qualityм—җ лҢҖн•ң formal guaranteeлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳкё° м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ӯлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһ„мқҳмқҳ backbone recommenderлҘј к°җмӢёкі , interaction streamм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ finite-sample performance guaranteeлҘј к°–лҠ” variable-size recommendation setмқ„ м¶ңл Ҙн•ҳлҠ” adaptive calibration frameworkмқё <strong>CARE</strong>лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. CAREлҠ” (i) н–үлҸҷ ліҖнҷ”лҘј көӯмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳкі  threshold recalibrationмқ„ нҠёлҰ¬кұ°н•ҳлҠ” loss-based monitoring moduleкіј, (ii) candidate set predictorлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬к°ҖмӨ‘н•ҳм—¬ compact recommendation setмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ҳлҠ” online aggregation ruleмқ„ кІ°н•©н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” utility-based risk controlм—җ лҢҖн•ң finite-sample guaranteeмҷҖ, кө¬м„ұ predictor мӨ‘ мөңм Ғмқҳ predictorм—җ лҢҖн•ң кё°лҢҖ set size boundлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳлҠ” мқҙлЎ  кІ°кіјлҘј м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ datasetкіј backbone modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ CAREк°Җ мӣҗн•ҳлҠ” statistical guaranteeлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң robustnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  compact recommendation setмқ„ мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ кө¬нҳ„мқҖ https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CARE-FCBD м—җм„ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64403","en":"Retriever Portfolios: A Principled Approach to Adaptive RAG","ko":"кІҖмғүкё° нҸ¬нҠёнҸҙлҰ¬мҳӨ: м Ғмқ‘нҳ• RAGлҘј мң„н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғ м ‘к·јлІ•","authors":"Miltiadis Stouras, Vincent Cohen-Addad, Silvio Lattanzi, Ola Svensson","pos":"#1504","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=NyGHaciFrK","abs":"Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) systems typically rely on a single retriever and a single set of hyperparameters, despite facing highly heterogeneous queries that range from simple factoid questions to complex multi-hop reasoning. We propose a method that automatically selects a small,  diverse subset of retrievers--a portfolio--from a large pool of candidates, to cover  different regions of the target query distribution. We formalize this setting via an expected best-of-$k$ objective over  the query distribution and show that it admits an efficient portfolio construction  algorithm with near-optimal guarantees. Across multiple QA benchmarks, our learned portfolios and router pipeline consistently outperform single-retriever and naive multi-retriever baselines on both retrieval metrics and answer quality.  In addition, compared to inference-time hyperparameter tuning approaches, fixed portfolios  enable parallel retrieval and LLM calls, achieving comparable (and sometimes better) accuracy  with substantially lower latency and token cost.","absKo":"Retrieval-augmented generation (RAG) systemмқҖ лӢЁмҲңн•ң factoid questionл¶Җн„° ліөмһЎн•ң multi-hop reasoningк№Ңм§Җ л§Өмҡ° мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё queryлҘј лӢӨлЈЁл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лӢЁмқј retrieverмҷҖ лӢЁмқј hyperparameter setм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ нӣ„ліҙ poolм—җм„ң лҢҖмғҒ query л¶„нҸ¬мқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ м»ӨлІ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ, мһ‘мқҖ нҒ¬кё°мқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң retriever subsetмқё portfolioлҘј мһҗлҸҷмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј query л¶„нҸ¬м—җ лҢҖн•ң expected best-of-$k$ objectiveлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , кұ°мқҳ мөңм Ғм—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ ліҙмһҘмқ„ к°–лҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё portfolio кө¬м„ұ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ QA benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, н•ҷмҠөлҗң portfolioмҷҖ router pipelineмқҖ retrieval metricкіј answer quality лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң лӢЁмқј retriever л°Ҹ лӢЁмҲңн•ң multi-retriever baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң inference-time hyperparameter tuning м ‘к·јлІ•кіј л№„көҗн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң, кі м •лҗң portfolioлҠ” parallel retrievalкіј LLM callмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬, нӣЁм”¬ лӮ®мқҖ latencyмҷҖ token costлЎң л№„мҠ·н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ л•ҢлЎңлҠ” лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64892","en":"Revealing Differences in Multi-Modal Embeddings via Constrained Kernel Analysis","ko":"Constrained Kernel AnalysisлҘј нҶөн•ң л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ Embeddingмқҳ м°Ёмқҙ к·ңлӘ…","authors":"Youqi WU, Mohammad Jalali, Farzan Farnia","pos":"#2802","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=InwrRdCQwD","abs":"<p>Multi-modal representation models such as CLIP, SigLIP, and their variants are widely used to represent data across multiple modalities in modern learning systems. While these models are commonly evaluated through downstream performance, the analysis of their structural differences in how multi-modal representations group data across modalities remains inadequate. In this work, we aim to identify modality pairs and sample subsets that induce divergent grouping behavior between two candidate embeddings. We propose \\emph{Kernel Optimization for Discrepancy Analysis (KODA)}, a kernel method that constructs unified multi-modal kernels via modality-wise kernel multiplication and formulates discrepancy identification as an optimization problem that seeks components with high coherence under one embedding while constraining coherence under another. This formulation provides interpretable discrepancy structures associated with specific modality interactions. We establish finite-sample guarantees characterizing the effective reference sample size required for reliable analysis. To enable scalable computation in multi-modal settings, we develop a randomized low-dimensional approximation of joint kernels using random projections, including Random Fourier Features for shift-invariant kernels. Our empirical results indicate that KODA can identify consistent discrepancy structures across modalities.</p>","absKo":"<p>CLIP, SigLIP л°Ҹ к·ё ліҖнҳ•л“Өкіј к°ҷмқҖ multi-modal representation modelмқҖ нҳ„лҢҖ learning systemм—җм„ң м—¬лҹ¬ modalityм—җ кұём№ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘЁлҚёл“ӨмқҖ ліҙнҶө downstream performanceлЎң нҸүк°Җлҗҳм§Җл§Ң, multi-modal representationмқҙ modality к°„м—җ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ к·ёлЈ№нҷ”н•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң кө¬мЎ°м Ғ м°ЁмқҙлҘј л¶„м„қн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” л‘җ нӣ„ліҙ embedding мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё grouping behaviorлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” modality pairмҷҖ sample subsetмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\emph{Kernel Optimization for Discrepancy Analysis (KODA)}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” modality-wise kernel multiplicationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ unified multi-modal kernelмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , н•ң embeddingм—җм„ңлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ coherenceлҘј к°–лҗҳ лӢӨлҘё embeddingм—җм„ңлҠ” coherenceлҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ” componentлҘј м°ҫлҠ” optimization problemмңјлЎң discrepancy identificationмқ„ м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” kernel methodмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ formulationмқҖ нҠ№м • modality interactionкіј м—°кІ°лҗң interpretable discrepancy structureлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” л¶„м„қм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң effective reference sample sizeлҘј нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” finite-sample guaranteeлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. multi-modal settingм—җм„ңмқҳ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кі„мӮ°мқ„ мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” shift-invariant kernelм—җ лҢҖн•ң Random Fourier FeaturesлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң random projectionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ joint kernelмқҳ randomized low-dimensional approximationмқ„ к°ңл°ңн–ҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, KODAлҠ” modality м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мқјкҙҖлҗң discrepancy structureлҘј мӢқлі„н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61962","en":"How can embedding models bind concepts?","ko":"мһ„лІ л”© лӘЁлҚёмқҖ к°ңл…җмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ кІ°н•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„к№Ң?","authors":"Arnas Uselis, Darina Koishigarina, Seong Joon Oh","pos":"#2903","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lFkGJ60bGq","abs":"<p>Humans easily determine which color belongs to which shape in multi-object scenes, an ability known as concept binding. VisionвҖ“language embedding models such as CLIP struggle with binding: they recognize individual concepts but fail to represent which concepts form which objects. Although CLIP behaves like a bag-of-concepts model in cross-modal retrieval, object information is recoverable from its image and text embeddings separately. We study this tension through the binding function, which maps concepts to scene embeddings. We find that scene embeddings decompose additively into object representations, explaining why uni-modal probes can recover object information. However, CLIPвҖҷs binding function is high-complexity, which likely prevents the image and text encoders from learning a shared binding mechanism that generalizes to unseen concept combinations. We then ask whether this limitation is fundamental. We show that it is not. In controlled transformer models trained from scratch, binding generalization emerges with sufficient data coverage. These models learn low-complexity binding functions characterized by multiplicative interactions between concepts, enabling systematic generalization.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӮ¬лһҢмқҖ лӢӨмӨ‘ к°қмІҙ мһҘл©ҙм—җм„ң м–ҙл–Ө мғүмқҙ м–ҙл–Ө лҸ„нҳ•м—җ мҶҚн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ мүҪкІҢ нҢҗлӢЁн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” concept bindingмңјлЎң м•Ңл Өм§„ лҠҘл ҘмқҙлӢӨ. CLIPкіј к°ҷмқҖ visionвҖ“language embedding modelмқҖ bindingм—җм„ң м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. к°ңлі„ conceptмқҖ мқёмӢқн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, м–ҙл–Ө conceptл“Өмқҙ м–ҙл–Ө objectлҘј мқҙлЈЁлҠ”м§ҖлҠ” н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. CLIPмқҖ cross-modal retrievalм—җм„ңлҠ” bag-of-concepts modelмІҳлҹј лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, object informationмқҖ image embeddingкіј text embedding к°Ғк°Ғм—җм„ң ліөмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” conceptмқ„ scene embeddingм—җ л§Өн•‘н•ҳлҠ” binding functionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кёҙмһҘмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” scene embeddingмқҙ object representationмңјлЎң к°ҖмӮ°м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙлҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” uni-modal probeк°Җ object informationмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мқҙмң лҘј м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ CLIPмқҳ binding functionмқҖ ліөмһЎлҸ„к°Җ лҶ’м•„, image encoderмҷҖ text encoderк°Җ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң concept мЎ°н•©м—җлҸ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗҳлҠ” shared binding mechanismмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкІҢ н•  к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ нҒ¬лӢӨ. к·ёл ҮлӢӨл©ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„к°Җ к·јліём Ғмқём§Җ м§Ҳл¬ён•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ лӢөмқҖ к·ёл Үм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. scratchл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•ң м ңм–ҙлҗң transformer modelм—җм„ңлҠ” м¶©л¶„н•ң data coverageк°Җ мһҲмңјл©ҙ binding generalizationмқҙ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ лӮҳнғҖлӮңлӢӨ. мқҙл“Ө лӘЁлҚёмқҖ concept к°„ multiplicative interactionмңјлЎң нҠ№м§•м§Җм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” м ҖліөмһЎлҸ„ binding functionмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мІҙкі„м Ғмқё generalizationмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҙм§„лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66643","en":"LEGO-FL: Learning Heterogeneous Federated Models as a LEGO Assembly Games","ko":"LEGO-FL: мқҙм§Ҳм Ғ Federated лӘЁлҚёмқ„ LEGO мЎ°лҰҪ кІҢмһ„мңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё°","authors":"Zeqi Leng, Chunxu Zhang, Guodong Long, Bo Yang","pos":"#3013","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1qoqymATM3","abs":"<p>Just as LEGO pieces can be assembled into an unlimited variety of structures, heterogeneous federated learning (HFL) can be viewed as the assembly of diverse model components. Inspired by this analogy, we reformulate HFL as a LEGO-like assembly game. The central challenge in HFL lies in learning across heterogeneous model architectures, which hinders direct parameter sharing. To address this challenge, we propose to decompose models into a set of standardized, modular componentsвҖ”analogous to LEGO pieces, and then to learn these components collaboratively across clients. We refer to these components as model blocks. This paper investigates how to learn and assemble them under predefined composition rules to construct heterogeneous models. Based on this perspective, we develop a novel federated learning framework, termed LEGO-FL, which enables flexible model construction while preserving collaborative learning. We evaluate the proposed method through small-scale experimental studies and demonstrate its feasibility. Finally, we discuss potential extensions of LEGO-FL to large-scale federated settings and more complex model architectures.</p>","absKo":"<p>LEGO мЎ°к°Ғмқҙ л¬ҙн•ңн•ң мў…лҘҳмқҳ кө¬мЎ°лЎң мЎ°лҰҪлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲл“Ҝмқҙ, heterogeneous federated learning(HFL)лҸ„ лӢӨм–‘н•ң model componentмқҳ мЎ°лҰҪмңјлЎң ліј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л№„мң м—җм„ң м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” HFLмқ„ LEGOмҷҖ мң мӮ¬н•ң assembly gameмңјлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. HFLмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлҠ” heterogeneous model architecture м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң н•ҷмҠөм—җ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” м§Ғм ‘м Ғмқё parameter sharingмқ„ м–ҙл өкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқ„ LEGO мЎ°к°Ғм—җ л№„мң лҗҳлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗң modular component м§‘н•©мңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ң л’Ө, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң componentлҘј clientл“Ө к°„м—җ нҳ‘л Ҙм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң componentлҘј model blockмқҙлқј л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ лҜёлҰ¬ м •мқҳлҗң composition rule н•ҳм—җм„ң мқҙл“Өмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  мЎ°лҰҪн•ҳм—¬ heterogeneous modelмқ„ кө¬м„ұн• м§Җ нғҗкө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм җм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” collaborative learningмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң flexible model constructionмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ federated learning frameworkмқё LEGO-FLмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ мҶҢк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳ м—°кө¬лҘј нҶөн•ҙ нҸүк°Җлҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, к·ё мӢӨнҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, LEGO-FLмқ„ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ federated settingкіј лҚ” ліөмһЎн•ң model architectureлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•  к°ҖлҠҘм„ұлҸ„ л…јмқҳн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65761","en":"Necessary Conditions for Compositional Generalization of Embedding Models","ko":"мһ„лІ л”© лӘЁлҚёмқҳ мЎ°н•©м Ғ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң н•„мҡ” мЎ°кұҙ","authors":"Arnas Uselis, Andrea Dittadi, Seong Joon Oh","pos":"#3912","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=AQZZWVp6XA","abs":"<p>Compositional generalization, the ability to recognize familiar parts in novel contexts, is a defining property of intelligent systems. Modern models are trained on massive datasets, yet these are vanishingly small compared to the full combinatorial space of possible data, raising the question of whether models can reliably generalize to unseen combinations. To formalize what this requires, we propose a set of practically motivated desiderata that any compositionally generalizing system must satisfy, and analyze their implications under standard training with linear classification heads. We show that these desiderata necessitate \\emph{linear factorization}, where representations decompose additively into per-concept components, and further imply near-orthogonality across factors. We establish dimension bounds that link the number of concepts to the geometry of representations. Empirically, we survey CLIP and SigLIP families, finding strong evidence for linear factorization, approximate orthogonality, and a tight correlation between the quality of factorization and compositional generalization. Together, our results identify the structural conditions that embeddings must satisfy for compositional generalization, and provide both theoretical clarity and empirical diagnostics for developing foundation models that generalize compositionally.</p>","absKo":"<p>Compositional generalization, мҰү мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ң мқөмҲҷн•ң л¶Җл¶„мқ„ мқёмӢқн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл ҘмқҖ м§ҖлҠҘнҳ• мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҳ м •мқҳм Ғ нҠ№м„ұмқҙлӢӨ. нҳ„лҢҖмқҳ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ л°©лҢҖн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҠ” к°ҖлҠҘн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ м „мІҙ мЎ°н•© кіөк°„м—җ л№„н•ҳл©ҙ к·№нһҲ мһ‘лӢӨ. мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң мЎ°н•©мңјлЎңлҸ„ мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳл¬ёмқҙ м ңкё°лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” compositional generalizationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” м–ҙл–Ө мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҙл“  л§ҢмЎұн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м ҒмңјлЎң лҸҷкё° л¶Җм—¬лҗң мқјл Ёмқҳ desiderataлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳкі , standard trainingкіј linear classification head н•ҳм—җм„ң к·ё н•ЁмқҳлҘј л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң desiderataк°Җ \\emph{linear factorization}мқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҰү, representationмқҙ к°Ғ concept кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢлі„лЎң к°ҖлІ•м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙлҗҳм–ҙм•ј н•ҳл©°, лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ factor к°„ near-orthogonalityлҸ„ н•Ёмқҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң concept мҲҳмҷҖ representationмқҳ кё°н•ҳлҘј м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” dimension boundлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” CLIPкіј SigLIP кі„м—ҙмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳм—¬, linear factorization, approximate orthogonality, к·ёлҰ¬кі  factorizationмқҳ м§Ҳкіј compositional generalization мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°•н•ң мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„м—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•л Ҙн•ң мҰқкұ°лҘј л°ңкІ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” compositional generalizationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ embeddingмқҙ л§ҢмЎұн•ҙм•ј н•  кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мЎ°кұҙмқ„ л°қнһҲкі , compositionalн•ҳкІҢ мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” foundation modelмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ лӘ…лЈҢм„ұкіј мӢӨмҰқм Ғ м§„лӢЁ лҸ„кө¬лҘј н•Ёк»ҳ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62261","en":"The Efficiency Gap in Byte Modeling","ko":"Byte Modelingмқҳ Efficiency Gap","authors":"Celine Lee, Jing Nathan Yan, Chen Liang, Jiaxin Shi, Yin Zhang, Jeremiah Zhe Liu, Pengcheng Yin, Ed Chi, Fernando Pereira, Derek Cheng, Alexander Rush, Ruoxi Wang","pos":"#4113","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=iD5JNtPwGA","abs":"<p>Modern language models typically rely on two design choices: subword tokenization and autoregressive (AR) ordering. To achieve more universal modeling, the field is advancing toward byte-level modeling to bypass domain-specific vocabularies and masked diffusion models (MDM) to enable parallel non-sequential generation.  Intuitively, the intersection of these paradigms represents a generative ideal: a modality-agnostic system capable of fine-grained any-order generation. However, the computational interaction between these granular representations and non-sequential objectives remains under-explored. In this work, we investigate the viability of this combination through a compute-matched scaling study. We observe a structural dichotomy: AR models on bytes effectively amortize the cost of tokenization, naturally rediscovering sub-word segmentation at scale.  In contrast, byte-level MDMs suffer a non-convergent efficiency collapse. We attribute this disparity to the masking objective, which shatters the local contiguity required to resolve sub-word semantics from bytes, whereas AR's stable causal history preserves these essential local dependencies. Our findings inform the community of a critical efficiency tradeoff, suggesting that future modality-agnostic designs should address this context fragility to maintain efficient scaling.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖ language modelмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң subword tokenizationкіј autoregressive(AR) orderingмқҙлқјлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ м„Өкі„ м„ нғқм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. ліҙлӢӨ ліҙнҺём Ғмқё modelingмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мқҙ л¶„м•јлҠ” лҸ„л©”мқё нҠ№нҷ” vocabularyлҘј мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳлҠ” byte-level modelingкіј мҲңм°Ём Ғмқҙм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ лі‘л ¬ мғқм„ұмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” masked diffusion model(MDM) мӘҪмңјлЎң л°ңм „н•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. м§ҒкҙҖм ҒмңјлЎң, мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„л“Өмқҳ көҗм°Ём җмқҖ м„ёл°Җн•ң any-order generationмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң modality-agnostic мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҙлқјлҠ” мғқм„ұмқҳ мқҙмғҒнҳ•мқ„ лӮҳнғҖлӮёлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң granular representationкіј non-sequential objective мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ кі„мӮ°м Ғ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҖ м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” compute-matched scaling studyлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ мЎ°н•©мқҳ нғҖлӢ№м„ұмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мқҙл¶„лІ•мқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ңлӢӨ. byte кё°л°ҳ AR modelмқҖ tokenization л№„мҡ©мқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мғҒк°Ғн•ҳл©°, к·ңлӘЁк°Җ м»Өм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ sub-word segmentationмқ„ мһ¬л°ңкІ¬н•ңлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ byte-level MDMмқҖ мҲҳл ҙн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” нҡЁмңЁ л¶•кҙҙлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м°ЁмқҙлҘј masking objective л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлқјкі  ліёлӢӨ. masking objectiveлҠ” bytesлЎңл¶Җн„° sub-word semanticsлҘј н•ҙм„қн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң local contiguityлҘј мӮ°мӮ°мқҙ л¶ҖмҲҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, ARмқҳ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё causal historyлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё local dependencyлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°м—җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң efficiency tradeoffлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, н–Ҙнӣ„ modality-agnostic м„Өкі„лҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё scalingмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң context fragilityлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҙм•ј н•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66647","en":"LEMUR: Learned Multi-Vector Retrieval","ko":"LEMUR: н•ҷмҠөлҗң лӢӨмӨ‘ лІЎн„° кІҖмғү","authors":"Elias JГӨГӨsaari, Ville HyvГ¶nen, Teemu Roos","pos":"#4114","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1mpoh36RBU","abs":"<p>Multi-vector representations generated by late interaction models, such as ColBERT, enable superior retrieval quality compared to single-vector representations in information retrieval applications. In multi-vector retrieval systems, both queries and documents are encoded using one embedding for each token, and similarity between queries and documents is measured by the MaxSim similarity measure. However, the improved recall of multi-vector retrieval comes at the expense of significantly increased latency. This necessitates designing efficient approximate nearest neighbor search (ANNS) algorithms for multi-vector search. In this work, we introduce LEMUR, a simple-yet-efficient framework for multi-vector similarity search. LEMUR consists of two consecutive problem reductions: We first formulate multi-vector similarity search as a supervised learning problem that can be solved using a one-hidden-layer neural network. Second, we reduce inference under this model to single-vector similarity search in its latent space, which enables the use of existing single-vector ANNS methods for speeding up retrieval. In addition to performance evaluation on ColBERTv2 embeddings, we evaluate LEMUR on embeddings generated by modern multi-vector text models and multi-vector visual document retrieval models. LEMUR is an order of magnitude faster than earlier multi-vector similarity search methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>ColBERTмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ late interaction modelмқҙ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” multi-vector representationмқҖ information retrieval мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң single-vector representationліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң retrieval qualityлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. multi-vector retrieval systemм—җм„ңлҠ” queryмҷҖ documentк°Җ к°Ғк°Ғ к°Ғ tokenлӢ№ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ embeddingмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©лҗҳл©°, queryмҷҖ document к°„ мң мӮ¬лҸ„лҠ” MaxSim similarity measureлЎң кі„мӮ°лҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ multi-vector retrievalмқҳ н–ҘмғҒлҗң recallмқҖ мғҒлӢ№нһҲ мҰқк°Җн•ң latencyлқјлҠ” лҢҖк°ҖлҘј мҲҳл°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң multi-vector searchлҘј мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё approximate nearest neighbor search(ANNS) algorithm м„Өкі„к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” multi-vector similarity searchлҘј мң„н•ң лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё frameworkмқё LEMURлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. LEMURлҠ” м—°мҶҚлҗң л‘җ лӢЁкі„мқҳ л¬ём ң м¶•мҶҢлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” multi-vector similarity searchлҘј н•ң к°ңмқҳ hidden layerлҘј к°Җм§„ neural networkлЎң н•ҙкІ° к°ҖлҠҘн•ң supervised learning problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, мқҙ лӘЁлҚём—җм„ңмқҳ inferenceлҘј latent spaceм—җм„ңмқҳ single-vector similarity searchлЎң м¶•мҶҢн•ҳм—¬, кё°мЎҙ single-vector ANNS methodлҘј retrieval к°ҖмҶҚм—җ нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. ColBERTv2 embeddingм—җ лҢҖн•ң м„ұлҠҘ нҸүк°Җлҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј, мөңмӢ  multi-vector text model л°Ҹ multi-vector visual document retrieval modelмқҙ мғқм„ұн•ң embeddingм—җлҸ„ LEMURлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. LEMURлҠ” кё°мЎҙ multi-vector similarity search л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ н•ң мһҗлҰҝмҲҳ л°°мҲҳ мҲҳмӨҖмңјлЎң лҚ” л№ лҘҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61372","en":"Diversity-Aware Recursive Feature Multiple Kernel Learning","ko":"лӢӨм–‘м„ұ мқёмӢқ мһ¬к·Җм Ғ нҠ№м§• лӢӨмӨ‘ м»Өл„җ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"nan cao, Xu Zhao, Teng Zhang","pos":"#4205","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=quS6FErXG8","abs":"<p>Multiple kernel learning~(MKL), which borrows ideas from ensemble learning, aims to achieve improved generalization performance by treating individual kernels as base learners and combining them appropriately. However, existing MKL methods often lack comprehensive consideration of diversity among base kernels, which has been demonstrated to play an essential role in ensemble learning. Moreover, the traditional kernels are predefined functions and equally treat all the input features, which ignore the diversity of feature, and yield suboptimal performance. In this paper, we formally define kernel diversity, and propose a novel data-driven class kernel named Recursive Feature Machine~(RFM) kernel, which is able to learn the feature importance directly from the different datasets. Moreover, a novel kernel selection method is proposed that explicitly optimizes both kernel diversity and quality. The resulting binary quadratic programming problem is NP-hard. Therefore, it is reformulated as a linear program and accelerated via sketching techniques, and a theoretical analysis of the estimation error is provided based on covering number bounds. Extensive empirical studies demonstrate that the proposed method outperforms state-of-the-art MKL approaches.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multiple kernel learning~(MKL)мқҖ ensemble learningмқҳ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҘј м°Ёмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, к°ңлі„ kernelмқ„ base learnerлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј м Ғм ҲнһҲ кІ°н•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н–ҘмғҒлҗң generalization м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ MKL л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ base kernel к°„ diversityм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё кі л Өк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” ensemble learningм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң м „нҶөм Ғмқё kernelмқҖ лҜёлҰ¬ м •мқҳлҗң н•ЁмҲҳмқҙл©° лӘЁл“  мһ…л Ҙ featureлҘј лҸҷмқјн•ҳкІҢ м·Ёкёүн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, featureмқҳ лӢӨм–‘м„ұмқ„ л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳкі  мөңм Ғ мқҙн•ҳмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” kernel diversityлҘј м •мӢқмңјлЎң м •мқҳн•ҳкі , м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° feature importanceлҘј м§Ғм ‘ н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ data-driven class kernelмқё Recursive Feature Machine~(RFM) kernelмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, kernel diversityмҷҖ qualityлҘј лӘЁл‘җ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ kernel selection л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ мғқм„ұлҗҳлҠ” binary quadratic programming л¬ём ңлҠ” NP-hardмқҙлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мқҙлҘј linear programмңјлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі  sketching кё°лІ•мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳл©°, covering number boundм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң estimation errorмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨмҰқ м—°кө¬лҠ” м ңм•Ҳн•ң л°©лІ•мқҙ мөңмӢ  MKL м ‘к·јлІ•л“Өмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63315","en":"Compositional Perception and Generalizing Induction: Latent Compositional Manifold Assumption on Generalized Category Discovery","ko":"кө¬м„ұм Ғ м§Җк°Ғкіј мқјл°ҳнҷ” к·ҖлӮ©: мқјл°ҳнҷ” лІ”мЈј л°ңкІ¬м—җ лҢҖн•ң мһ мһ¬ кө¬м„ұ лӢӨм–‘мІҙ к°Җм •","authors":"Luyao Tang, Jiewei Zheng, Kunze Huang, Chaoqi Chen, Yue Huang, Cheng Chen","pos":"#4209","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=YA3AvVx2Ze","abs":"<p>Generalized Category Discovery (GCD) assigns unlabeled instances, mixed with labeled data, to known or novel categories, requiring human-like compositional reasoning: reusing primitives learned from known classes and deciding when new combinations imply new categories. Existing GCD methods operate on unstructured token features and struggle to extrapolate to novel compositions. We propose CoGe-GCD, which rethinks GCD through compositional generalization with two coupled stages. (i) Compositional Perception structures patch tokens by mapping them to a small vocabulary of primitives and refining token embeddings via competitive token-primitive assignment and information passing, yielding coherent groups for discovery. (ii) Generalizing Induction exploits the induced geometric structure and applies a geometric-structure-preserving calibration over spatial relations, maintaining probabilistic semantics while improving extrapolation to unseen primitive combinations. CoGe-GCD is implemented as an inductive-bias module between backbone and projection head, without modifying heads or losses, and can be plugged into diverse GCD frameworks. On standard benchmarks, it consistently improves all-class accuracy, unknown-class number estimation, and geometric quality, with marginal computational overhead.</p>","absKo":"<p>Generalized Category Discovery (GCD)лҠ” labeled dataмҷҖ м„һмқё unlabeled instanceлҘј known categoryмҷҖ novel categoryм—җ н• лӢ№н•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлЎң, мқёк°„кіј мң мӮ¬н•ң compositional reasoningмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, known classм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөн•ң primitiveлҘј мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі  мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мЎ°н•©мқҙ мғҲ categoryлҘј мқҳлҜён•ҳлҠ”м§Җ нҢҗлӢЁн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ GCD methodлҠ” кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ token feature мң„м—җм„ң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳл©° мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мЎ°н•©мңјлЎңмқҳ мҷёмӮҪм—җ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CoGe-GCDлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ кІ°н•©лҗң лӢЁкі„лЎң GCDлҘј compositional generalization кҙҖм җм—җм„ң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. (i) Compositional PerceptionмқҖ patch tokenмқ„ мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ primitive vocabularyм—җ л§Өн•‘н•ҳкі  competitive token-primitive assignmentмҷҖ information passingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ token embeddingмқ„ м •м ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ tokenмқ„ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”н•ҳм—¬ discoveryм—җ м Ғн•©н•ң мқ‘м§‘лҗң groupмқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. (ii) Generalizing InductionмқҖ мқҙл ҮкІҢ мң лҸ„лҗң geometric structureлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ spatial relation мң„м—җ geometric-structure-preserving calibrationмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, unseen primitive combinationм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҷёмӮҪ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лҶ’мқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ probabilistic semanticsлҘј мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. CoGe-GCDлҠ” backboneкіј projection head мӮ¬мқҙм—җ л“Өм–ҙк°ҖлҠ” inductive-bias moduleлЎң кө¬нҳ„лҗҳл©°, headлӮҳ lossлҘј мҲҳм •н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ лӢӨм–‘н•ң GCD frameworkм—җ н”Ңлҹ¬к·ёмқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ benchmarkм—җм„ң all-class accuracy, unknown-class number estimation, geometric qualityлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҠ” лҜёлҜён•ҳлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62287","en":"AReaL-DTA: Dynamic Tree Attention for Efficient Reinforcement Learning of Large Language Models","ko":"AReaL-DTA: Large Language Modelsмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң Dynamic Tree Attention","authors":"Jiarui Zhang, Yuchen Yang, Ran Yan, Zhiyu Mei, Liyuan Zhang, LiDaifeng, Wei Fu, Jiaxuan Gao, Shusheng Xu, Yi Wu, Binhang Yuan","pos":"#4211","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=hx2U1OllHD","abs":"Reinforcement learning (RL) based post-training for large language models (LLMs) is computationally expensive, as it generates many rollout sequences that could frequently share long token prefixes. Existing RL frameworks usually process these sequences independently, repeatedly recomputing identical prefixes during forward and backward passes during policy model training, leading to substantial inefficiencies in computation and memory usage. Although prefix sharing naturally induces a tree structure over rollouts, prior tree-attentionвҖ“based solutions rely on fully materialized attention masks and scale poorly in RL settings. In this paper, we introduce AReaL-DTA to efficiently exploit prefix sharing in RL training. AReaL-DTA employs a depth-first-search (DFS)вҖ“based execution strategy that dynamically traverses the rollout prefix tree during both forward and backward computation, materializing only a single root-to-leaf path at a time. To further improve scalability, AReaL-DTA incorporates a load-balanced distributed batching mechanism that dynamically constructs and processes prefix trees across multiple GPUs. Across the popular RL post-training workload, AReaL-DTA achieves up to $8.31\\times$ in $\\tau^2$-bench higher training throughput while reducing peak GPU memory consumption by approximately 30вҖ“40%.","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(LLM)м—җ лҢҖн•ң reinforcement learning(RL) кё°л°ҳ post-trainingмқҖ л§ҺмқҖ rollout sequenceлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙл“Ө sequenceлҠ” мў…мў… кёҙ token prefixлҘј кіөмң н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјлҜҖлЎң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒҪлӢҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ RL frameworkлҠ” мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң sequenceлҘј лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳм—¬, policy model training лҸҷм•Ҳ forward л°Ҹ backward passм—җм„ң лҸҷмқјн•ң prefixлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҜҖлЎң кі„мӮ°кіј л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ© л©ҙм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң л№„нҡЁмңЁмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. prefix sharingмқҖ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ rollout мң„м—җ tree кө¬мЎ°лҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙмқҳ tree-attention кё°л°ҳ мҶ”лЈЁм…ҳмқҖ мҷ„м „нһҲ materializeлҗң attention maskм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©° RL м„Өм •м—җм„ң нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§‘лӢҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” RL trainingм—җм„ң prefix sharingмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ AReaL-DTAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. AReaL-DTAлҠ” depth-first-search(DFS) кё°л°ҳ мӢӨн–ү м „лһөмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ forwardмҷҖ backward computation лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң rollout prefix treeлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мҲңнҡҢн•ҳл©°, н•ң лІҲм—җ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ root-to-leaf pathл§Ң materializeн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқ„ лҚ”мҡұ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ҙ, AReaL-DTAлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ GPUм—җ кұёміҗ prefix treeлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” load-balanced distributed batching mechanismмқ„ нҶөн•©н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” RL post-training workload м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, AReaL-DTAлҠ” `tau^2`-benchм—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ 8.31л°° лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ training throughputмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ peak GPU memory consumptionмқ„ м•Ҫ 30~40% мӨ„мһ…лӢҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"63479","en":"FEDEMOE: IMPROVING PERSONALIZATION ON HET- EROGENEOUS FEDERATED LEARNING VIA ELASTIC MIXTURE OF EXPERTS ARCHITECTURE","ko":"FEDEMOE: нғ„л Ҙм Ғ Mixture of Experts м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳлҘј нҶөн•ң мқҙм§Ҳм Ғ м—°н•© н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ңмқҳ к°ңмқёнҷ” к°ңм„ ","authors":"Haizhou Du, Lixin Huang, Zonghan Wu, Huan Huo","pos":"#4213","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WqwKx40txT","abs":"<p>Heterogeneous federated learning (HtFL) has emerged as a promising approach to address heterogeneity in local computational resources and data distribution. However, existing methods cause performance degradation of model personalization because personalized and generalized knowledge are either intertwined or dominated by one of them. To address this issue, we propose a novel Elastic Mixture of Experts (EMoE) architecture on HtFL, namely FedEMoE, decoupling personalization from generalization. Specially, FedEMoE employs a multi-scale feature extraction mechanism via personalized experts to enrich personalized knowledge. Furthermore, we design an elastic shared expert to break the transferred knowledge bottleneck across heterogeneous client models. The elastic shared expert can adaptively expand or shrink according to the status of each expert by the weight spectrum analysis, respectively. Extensive experiments across statistical and model heterogeneity settings demonstrate that FedEMoE significantly outperforms state-of-the art methods on the accuracy of each heterogeneous model over diverse datasets.</p>","absKo":"<p>Heterogeneous federated learning (HtFL)мқҖ м§Җм—ӯ кі„мӮ° мһҗмӣҗкіј data distributionмқҳ мқҙм§Ҳм„ұмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ personalized knowledgeмҷҖ generalized knowledgeк°Җ м„ңлЎң м–ҪнһҲкұ°лӮҳ л‘ҳ мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м§Җл°°лҗҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ model personalizationмқҳ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” HtFL мң„м—җ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Elastic Mixture of Experts (EMoE) architecture, мҰү FedEMoEлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬ personalizationкіј generalizationмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, FedEMoEлҠ” personalized expertлҘј нҶөн•ң multi-scale feature extraction mechanismмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ personalized knowledgeлҘј н’Қл¶Җн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, мқҙмў… client model к°„м—җ м „лӢ¬лҗҳлҠ” knowledgeмқҳ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ к№Ёкё° мң„н•ҙ elastic shared expertлҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. elastic shared expertлҠ” weight spectrum analysisлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң к°Ғ expertмқҳ мғҒнғңм—җ л”°лқј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ м¶•мҶҢн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. нҶөкі„м Ғ мқҙм§Ҳм„ұкіј model мқҙм§Ҳм„ұ м„Өм • м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FedEMoEк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң к°Ғ heterogeneous modelмқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„ мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң state-of-the-art л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ нҳ„м ҖнһҲ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61399","en":"Controlled Collaboration Geometry for Personalized Federated Learning","ko":"Personalized Federated Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң Controlled Collaboration Geometry","authors":"Hongbo Yin, Wu Jichun, Zhou Yang, Chi Jiang, Yin Zhang, Yan Zhang","pos":"#4300","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qeahjgZ1QD","abs":"<p>In personalized federated learning (PFL), collaboration graphs specify model aggregation among clients. However, without constraints on the collaboration geometry, training can drift into two degenerate regimes: global consensus or spontaneous clustering. This paper provides a unified dynamical analysis: under the same budget of representative models, collaborative PFL is more expressive and achieves higher-order approximation accuracy than clustered PFL. An upper bound on disagreement further reveals two degeneration mechanismsвҖ”overly strong collaboration drives consensus (reducing to standard federated learning), while similarity-driven weight updates make the graph nearly reducible and induce self-clustering (collapsing to clustered PFL). Motivated by these findings, we propose pFedCCG. pFedCCG preserves the expressivity advantage via controlled collaboration geometry (CCG): it builds a static similarity-based collaboration template decoupled from training, optimizes a Markovian collaboration matrix with a prescribed stationary distribution via reversible parameterization and Euclidean projection, and schedules collaboration strength to avoid self-clustering. Experiments across diverse heterogeneity settings show consistent personalization gains and markedly reduced collapse and self-clustering. Code will be available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/pFedCCG-CB88.</p>","absKo":"<p>personalized federated learning (PFL)м—җм„ң collaboration graphлҠ” client к°„ model aggregationмқ„ к·ңм •н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ collaboration geometryм—җ лҢҖн•ң м ңм•Ҫмқҙ м—Ҷмңјл©ҙ н•ҷмҠөмқҖ global consensus лҳҗлҠ” spontaneous clusteringмқҙлқјлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ нҮҙн–үм Ғ regimeмңјлЎң driftн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ нҶөн•©лҗң dynamical analysisлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ: лҸҷмқјн•ң representative model budget н•ҳм—җм„ң collaborative PFLмқҖ clustered PFLліҙлӢӨ лҚ” expressiveн•ҳл©° higher-order approximation accuracyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. disagreementм—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҒн•ңмқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ degeneration mechanismлҸ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мҰү, м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ к°•н•ң collaborationмқҖ consensusлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬ standard federated learningмңјлЎң нҷҳмӣҗлҗҳкі , similarity-driven weight updateлҠ” graphлҘј кұ°мқҳ reducibleн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ self-clusteringмқ„ мң л°ңн•ҳл©° clustered PFLлЎң л¶•кҙҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°ңкІ¬м—җ лҸҷкё°лҘј л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” pFedCCGлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. pFedCCGлҠ” controlled collaboration geometry (CCG)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ expressivity мҡ°мң„лҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ: н•ҷмҠөкіј л¶„лҰ¬лҗң static similarity-based collaboration templateлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , reversible parameterizationкіј Euclidean projectionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ prescribed stationary distributionмқ„ к°–лҠ” Markovian collaboration matrixлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳл©°, self-clusteringмқ„ н”јн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ collaboration strengthлҘј мҠӨмјҖмӨ„л§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң heterogeneity м„Өм •м—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқјкҙҖлҗң personalization н–ҘмғҒкіј нҳ„м ҖнһҲ к°җмҶҢн•ң collapse л°Ҹ self-clusteringмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/pFedCCG-CB88 м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗ  мҳҲм •мқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65849","en":"Beyond Single Embedding: Modeling User Preferences as Distribution in Federated Recommendation","ko":"лӢЁмқј мһ„лІ л”©мқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ң: м—°н•© м¶”мІңм—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м„ нҳёлҘј л¶„нҸ¬лЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкё°","authors":"Chunxu Zhang, Weipeng Zhang, Guodong Long, Zhiheng Xue, Bo Yang","pos":"#4303","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9UohNmtqK5","abs":"<p>Most federated recommender systems represent each user with a single embedding learned from local interaction data, implicitly assuming that user preferences are fixed and precisely identifiable. In federated settings, however, each client observes only a limited and fragmentary view of user behavior, rendering such point estimates inherently brittle. To address this mismatch, we model user preferences as distributions rather than points, allowing multiple compatible preference representations to coexist. Rather than collapsing evidence into a single embedding, our approach preserves uncertainty and diversity in user representations, providing a richer basis for preference modeling. We instantiate this idea with a diffusion-based generative framework that produces diverse user embeddings and derives recommendation scores by aggregating predictions across them. This distributional formulation yields more stable ranking behavior and improved robustness under ambiguous feedback. Extensive experiments on federated recommendation benchmark datasets demonstrate consistent and significant improvements over baselines. Our code is available.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ federated recommender systemмқҖ к°Ғ userлҘј local interaction dataлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөлҗң лӢЁмқј embeddingмңјлЎң н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” user preferenceк°Җ кі м •лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲкі  м •нҷ•нһҲ мӢқлі„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” к°Җм •мқ„ м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң м „м ңн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ federated settingм—җм„ңлҠ” к°Ғ clientк°Җ user behaviorмқҳ м ңн•ңм Ғмқҙкі  лӢЁнҺём Ғмқё кҙҖмёЎл§Ңмқ„ м ‘н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң point estimateлҠ” ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” user preferenceлҘј pointк°Җ м•„лӢҢ distributionмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳм—¬ м—¬лҹ¬ к°ңмқҳ нҳёнҷҳ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң preference representationмқҙ кіөмЎҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. мҰқкұ°лҘј н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ embeddingмңјлЎң м¶•мҶҢн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ user representationмқҳ uncertaintyмҷҖ diversityлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ preference modelingмқ„ мң„н•ң лҚ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң кё°л°ҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” diffusion-based generative frameworkлЎң мқҙлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ҳм—¬ лӢӨм–‘н•ң user embeddingмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳкі , к·ёл“Өм—җ лҢҖн•ң predictionмқ„ м§‘кі„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ recommendation scoreлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң distributional formulationмқҖ лҚ” м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё ranking behaviorмҷҖ лӘЁнҳён•ң feedback н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ н–ҘмғҒлҗң robustnessлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. federated recommendation benchmark datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ baseline лҢҖл№„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкі  мң мқҳлҜён•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65860","en":"New Bounds for Kernel Sums via Fast Spherical Embeddings","ko":"кі мҶҚ кө¬л©ҙ мһ„лІ л”©мқ„ нҶөн•ң м»Өл„җ н•©мқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кІҪкі„","authors":"Tal Wagner","pos":"#4503","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9Mms28wD82","abs":"We study query time bounds for the fundamental problem of estimating the kernel mean $\\frac1{|X|}\\sum_{x\\in X}\\mathbf{\\mathrm{k}}(x,y)$ of a query $y$ in a finite dataset $X\\subset\\mathbb{R}^d$ up to a prescribed additive error $\\varepsilon$. The best known bounds for the Gaussian kernel are $O(d/\\varepsilon^2)$, $\\widetilde O(d+1/\\varepsilon^4)$, and $\\widetilde O(d+\\Delta^2/\\varepsilon^2)$, where $\\Delta$ is the diameter of a region containing the points. We prove the new bound $\\tilde O(d+\\varepsilon\\Delta^2+1/\\varepsilon^3)$, which improves over the previous ones in regimes with small error $\\varepsilon$ and intermediate diameter $\\Delta$.   At the center of our proof is a new fast spherical embedding theorem in the sense introduced by Bartal, Recht and Schulman (2011), which limits the embedded data diameter while preserving local Euclidean distances and avoiding ``distance collapse'' at larger scales. This fast embedding theorem may be of independent interest.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мң н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ $X\\subset\\mathbb{R}^d$м—җм„ң м§Ҳмқҳ $y$мқҳ kernel mean $\\frac1{|X|}\\sum_{x\\in X}\\mathbf{\\mathrm{k}}(x,y)$лҘј мЈјм–ҙм§„ к°ҖлІ• мҳӨм°Ё $\\varepsilon$к№Ңм§Җ м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” кё°ліё л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң query time boundлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. Gaussian kernelм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м•Ңл Өм§„ мөңм„ мқҳ boundлҠ” $O(d/\\varepsilon^2)$, $\\widetilde O(d+1/\\varepsilon^4)$, к·ёлҰ¬кі  $\\widetilde O(d+\\Delta^2/\\varepsilon^2)$мқёлҚ°, м—¬кё°м„ң $\\Delta$лҠ” м җл“Өмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” мҳҒм—ӯмқҳ diameterмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ bound $\\tilde O(d+\\varepsilon\\Delta^2+1/\\varepsilon^3)$лҘј мҰқлӘ…н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мһ‘мқҖ error $\\varepsilon$мҷҖ мӨ‘к°„ м •лҸ„мқҳ diameter $\\Delta$лҘј к°–лҠ” кө¬к°„м—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ кІ°кіјл“Өмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мҰқлӘ…мқҳ н•өмӢ¬м—җлҠ” Bartal, Recht and Schulman (2011)мқҙ лҸ„мһ…н•ң мқҳлҜём—җм„ңмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ fast spherical embedding theoremмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ м •лҰ¬лҠ” local Euclidean distancesлҠ” ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң embedded dataмқҳ diameterлҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳкі , лҚ” нҒ° scaleм—җм„ңмқҳ ``distance collapse''лҘј н”јн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ fast embedding theoremмқҖ к·ё мһҗмІҙлЎңлҸ„ лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё кҙҖмӢ¬ лҢҖмғҒмқҙ лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"61842","en":"Causal Modeling of Selection in Evolution","ko":"м§„нҷ”м—җм„ң м„ нғқмқҳ мқёкіј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ","authors":"Haoyue Dai, Zeyu Tang, Peter Spirtes, Kun Zhang","pos":"#4400","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mOcTXKawFY","abs":"<p>Understanding potential selection in data is crucial for causal discovery; we argue that \"selection\" in common narratives takes two forms, which we term <em>static</em> and <em>evolutionary</em> selection, respectively. Static selection refers to a one-shot filtering process where observed data consist of a <em>subset</em> of the population of interest, as in survey volunteer bias. Evolutionary selection, in contrast, operates through repeated rounds of differential fitness in reproduction, where observed data constitute the latest <em>generation</em> shaped by a historical trajectory, as in immune adaptation, antibiotic resistance, and social norm emergence. Existing methods largely conflate these two forms and rely on an identical graphical model of selection. We show that this model is valid for static settings but fails to characterize data under evolution, yielding false discovery results. To address this, we introduce a new model that specifically characterizes evolutionary selection, and develop a sound and complete procedure for identifying such models from data across one or multiple environments or generations. Experimental results validate the method's ability to uncover the relevant mechanisms underlying evolution from data.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җм„ңмқҳ м„ нғқ(selection) potentialмқ„ мқҙн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ causal discoveryм—җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ; мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м„ңмҲ м—җм„ңмқҳ \"selection\"мқҙ к°Ғк°Ғ <em>static</em> selectionкіј <em>evolutionary</em> selectionмқҙлқјлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ нҳ•нғңлҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. Static selectionмқҖ survey volunteer biasм—җм„ңмІҳлҹј кҙҖмёЎлҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ кҙҖмӢ¬ лӘЁм§‘лӢЁмқҳ <em>subset</em>мңјлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗҳлҠ”, н•ң лІҲм—җ лҒқлӮҳлҠ” filtering processлҘј лң»н•ңлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ evolutionary selectionмқҖ reproductionм—җм„ңмқҳ differential fitnessк°Җ л°ҳліөлҗҳлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ лқјмҡҙл“ңлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳл©°, кҙҖмёЎлҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” immune adaptation, antibiotic resistance, social norm emergenceм—җм„ңмІҳлҹј м—ӯмӮ¬м Ғ к¶Өм Ғм—җ мқҳн•ҙ нҳ•м„ұлҗң мөңмӢ  <em>generation</em>мқ„ мқҙлЈ¬лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң мқҙ л‘җ нҳ•нғңлҘј нҳјлҸҷн•ҳл©° лҸҷмқјн•ң selection к·ёлһҳн”„ лӘЁлҚём—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ static settingм—җм„ңлҠ” нғҖлӢ№н•ҳм§Җл§Ң evolution н•ҳмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ” лҚ°лҠ” мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳм—¬ false discoveryлҘј лӮілҠ”лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” evolutionary selectionмқ„ кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , н•ҳлӮҳ лҳҗлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ environmentлӮҳ generationм—җ кұёміҗ лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎңл¶Җн„° мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң soundн•ҳкі  completeн•ң м Ҳм°ЁлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎңл¶Җн„° evolutionмқҳ кё°м Җ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮҙлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67079","en":"Position: Benchmarks for VisionвҖ“Language Models in Urban Perception Should Be Reliability-Aware and Negotiated","ko":"Position: лҸ„мӢң мқёмӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң Vision-Language лӘЁлҚё лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лҠ” мӢ лў°м„ұ мқём§Җм Ғмқҙкі  нҳ‘мқҳлҗҳм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Rashid Mushkani","pos":"#504","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=n7fyvbSkaA","abs":"<p>VisionвҖ“language models (VLMs) are increasingly used to generate structured descriptions of street-level imagery for tasks such as streetscape auditing, mapping, and public consultation. These uses combine observable attributes with appraisal categories, and the human targets are often distributions of judgments with disagreement and explicit non-response. This position paper argues that benchmarking VLMs for urban perception should treat disagreement and abstention as measurement outcomes, report inter-annotator reliability alongside model alignment, and treat the label space and scoring policy as negotiable artifacts when outputs are intended to inform urban governance. We ground the argument in a benchmark of 100 Montreal street scenes annotated along 30 dimensions by 12 participants from seven community organizations, and in a deterministic zero-shot evaluation of seven VLMs. Across dimensions, model agreement with human consensus co-varies with dimension-level human reliability, and for the appraisal dimension Overall Impression models and annotators exhibit distributional mismatch including different rates of Not applicable. We close with actions for benchmark creators, model developers, and institutions to make uncertainty and benchmark assumptions visible in evaluation reports.</p>","absKo":"<p>VisionвҖ“language model(VLM)мқҖ streetscape auditing, mapping, public consultationкіј к°ҷмқҖ кіјм ңлҘј мң„н•ҙ street-level imageryмқҳ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң м„ӨлӘ…мқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м җм җ лҚ” л§Һмқҙ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҷңмҡ©мқҖ кҙҖм°° к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мҶҚм„ұкіј appraisal categoryлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳл©°, мқёк°„ лҢҖмғҒмқҖ мў…мў… disagreementмҷҖ explicit non-responseлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” judgment л¶„нҸ¬мқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ position paperлҠ” urban perceptionмқ„ мң„н•ң VLM benchmarkк°Җ disagreementмҷҖ abstentionмқ„ measurement outcomeмңјлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳкі , model alignmentмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ inter-annotator reliabilityлҘј ліҙкі н•ҳл©°, outputмқҙ urban governanceлҘј informн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗ  л•Ң label spaceмҷҖ scoring policyлҘј нҳ‘мғҒ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мӮ°м¶ңл¬јлЎң лӢӨлЈЁм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 7к°ң community organizationм—җ мҶҚн•ң 12лӘ…мқҳ м°ём—¬мһҗк°Җ 30к°ң м°Ёмӣҗм—җ кұёміҗ мЈјм„қмқ„ лӢЁ Montrealмқҳ street scene 100к°ңмҷҖ, 7к°ң VLMм—җ лҢҖн•ң deterministic zero-shot evaluationмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мқҙ мЈјмһҘмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ңлӢӨ. м°Ёмӣҗ м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ modelкіј human consensusмқҳ мқјм№ҳлҠ” м°Ёмӣҗ мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ human reliabilityмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ ліҖн•ҳл©°, appraisal м°Ёмӣҗмқё Overall Impressionм—җм„ңлҠ” modelкіј annotatorк°Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё Not applicable л№„мңЁмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң л¶„нҸ¬м Ғ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” uncertaintyмҷҖ benchmark к°Җм •мқ„ evaluation reportм—җм„ң к°ҖмӢңнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ benchmark creator, model developer, institutionмқҙ м·Ён•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мЎ°м№ҳл“ӨлЎң кІ°лЎ мқ„ л§әлҠ”лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64096","en":"Attention Sinks in Diffusion Transformers: A Causal Analysis","ko":"Diffusion Transformerмқҳ м–ҙн…җм…ҳ мӢұнҒ¬: мқёкіјм Ғ л¶„м„қ","authors":"FANGZHENG WU, Brian Summa","pos":"#1212","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=QwE8cOtclR","abs":"Attention sinks (tokens that receive disproportionate attention mass) are often assumed to be functionally important in autoregressive language models. Whether such sinks are necessary in diffusion transformers remains unclear. We present a causal analysis of attention sinks in text-to-image diffusion models, dynamically identifying dominant attention recipients based on incoming attention mass. Using paired, training-free interventions along the score and value paths, we test sink necessity across layers, denoising phases, and architectures.  Across large-scale evaluations on 553 GenEval prompts with Stable Diffusion~3 and corroborating experiments on SDXL, we find that removing \\textbf{these sinks} does not degrade text-image alignment or preference proxies under standard  settings ($k{=}1$), with a metric-dependent boundary on HPS-v2 emerging only  under stronger interventions ($k \\geq 10$). We additionally quantify perceptual and distributional shifts relative to baseline outputs, showing that suppressing dominant recipients can alter appearance without affecting alignment or preference scores. Together, these results clarify that attention sinks are not functionally necessary for \\emph{semantic alignment} in diffusion transformers, while revealing a  metric-dependent boundary: preference proxies show sink-specific degradation  under stronger interventions ($k \\geq 10$), whereas alignment (CLIP-T) remains robust  across all tested conditions.","absKo":"Attention sink(кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ л§ҺмқҖ attention massлҘј л°ӣлҠ” token)лҠ” autoregressive language modelм—җм„ң кё°лҠҘм ҒмңјлЎң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨкі  нқ”нһҲ к°Җм •лҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ diffusion transformerм—җм„ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң sinkк°Җ м •л§җ н•„мҡ”н•ңм§ҖлҠ” лӘ…нҷ•н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” text-to-image diffusion modelм—җм„ң attention sinkм—җ лҢҖн•ң causal analysisлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , л“Өм–ҙмҳӨлҠ” attention massлҘј кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң м§Җл°°м Ғмқё attention recipientлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. score кІҪлЎңмҷҖ value кІҪлЎңлҘј л”°лқј м§қм§Җм–ҙм§„ training-free interventionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” layer, denoising phase, architecture м „л°ҳм—җм„ң sinkмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. Stable Diffusion~3лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң 553к°ңмқҳ GenEval promptм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ нҸүк°ҖмҷҖ SDXLм—җм„ңмқҳ ліҙк°• мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, \\textbf{мқҙлҹ¬н•ң sinkлҘј м ңкұ°н•ҙлҸ„} н‘ңмӨҖ м„Өм •($k{=}1$)м—җм„ңлҠ” text-image alignmentлӮҳ preference proxyк°Җ м Җн•ҳлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, лҚ” к°•н•ң intervention($k \\geq 10$)м—җм„ңл§Ң HPS-v2м—җ лҢҖн•ң metric-dependent boundaryк°Җ лӮҳнғҖлӮЁмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң baseline output лҢҖл№„ perceptual л°Ҹ distributional shiftлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, м§Җл°°м Ғмқё recipientлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳл©ҙ alignmentлӮҳ preference scoreм—җлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ мЈјм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң appearanceлҠ” ліҖнҷ”мӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мў…н•©н•ҳл©ҙ, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” attention sinkк°Җ diffusion transformerм—җм„ң \\emph{semantic alignment}лҘј мң„н•ҙ кё°лҠҘм ҒмңјлЎң н•„мҡ”н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, metric-dependent boundaryлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. preference proxyлҠ” лҚ” к°•н•ң intervention($k \\geq 10$)м—җм„ң sink-specific degradationмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, alignment(CLIP-T)лҠ” н…ҢмҠӨнҠён•ң лӘЁл“  мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ң кІ¬кі н•ҳкІҢ мң м§ҖлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64918","en":"MemoryBench: A Benchmark for Memory and Continual Learning in LLM Systems","ko":"MemoryBench: LLM мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ң Memory л°Ҹ Continual Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Qingyao Ai, Yichen Tang, Changyue Wang, Jianming Long, Weihang Su, Yiqun LIU","pos":"#1701","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=If4X4W2HWx","abs":"<p>Scaling up data, parameters, and test-time computation has been the mainstream methods to improve LLM systems (LLMsys), but their upper bounds are almost reached due to the gradual depletion of high-quality data and marginal gains obtained from larger computational resource consumption.  Inspired by the abilities of human and traditional AI systems in learning from practice, constructing memory and continual learning frameworks for LLMsys has become an important and popular research direction in recent literature. Yet, existing benchmarks for LLM memory often focus on evaluating the system on homogeneous reading comprehension tasks with long-form inputs rather than testing their abilities to learn from accumulated user feedback in service time.    Therefore, we propose a user feedback simulation framework and a comprehensive benchmark covering multiple domains, languages, and types of tasks to evaluate the continual learning abilities of LLMsys. Experiments show that the effectiveness and efficiency of state-of-the-art baselines are far from satisfying, and we hope this benchmark could pave the way for future studies on LLM memory and optimization algorithms.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҚ°мқҙн„°, parameter, test-time computationмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ LLM system(LLMsys)мқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” мЈјлҘҳ л°©лІ•мқҙм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ dataмқҳ м җм§„м Ғ кі к°Ҳкіј лҚ” нҒ° computational resource мҶҢл№„лЎң мқён•ң н•ңкі„м Ғ мқҙл“қ л•Ңл¬ём—җ к·ё мғҒн•ңм—җ кұ°мқҳ лҸ„лӢ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқёк°„кіј м „нҶөм Ғ AI systemмқҙ мӢӨмІңмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣм•„, LLMsysлҘј мң„н•ң memoryмҷҖ continual learning frameworkлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ мөңк·ј л¬ён—Ңм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳкі лҸ„ мқёкё° мһҲлҠ” м—°кө¬ л°©н–Ҙмқҙ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙмқҳ LLM memory benchmarkлҠ” мЈјлЎң service timeм—җм„ң лҲ„м Ғлҗң user feedbackмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ мӢңн—ҳн•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ, мһҘл¬ё мһ…л Ҙмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷм§Ҳм Ғмқё reading comprehension taskм—җм„ң мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨмӨ‘ domain, м–ём–ҙ, task мң нҳ•мқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” user feedback simulation frameworkмҷҖ мў…н•© benchmarkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬ LLMsysмқҳ continual learning лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, state-of-the-art baselineмқҳ нҡЁкіјм„ұкіј нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқҖ л§ҢмЎұмҠӨлҹҪкё°м—җлҠ” н•ңм°ё л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳл©°, мқҙ benchmarkк°Җ LLM memoryмҷҖ optimization algorithmм—җ лҢҖн•ң н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬мқҳ кё°л°ҳмқ„ л§Ҳл Ён•ҳкёё кё°лҢҖн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65024","en":"DevEvol: Benchmarking LLM Agents on Continuous Software Evolution","ko":"DevEvol: м—°мҶҚм Ғ мҶҢн”„нҠёмӣЁм–ҙ м§„нҷ”м—җ лҢҖн•ң LLM Agent лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№","authors":"Gangda Deng, Zhaoling Chen, Zhongming Yu, Haoyang Fan, Yuhong Liu, Yuxin Yang, Dhruv Parikh, Rajgopal Kannan, Le Cong, Mengdi Wang, Qian Zhang, Viktor Prasanna, Robert Tang, Xingyao Wang","pos":"#2008","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HeRPNfJaod","abs":"Large Language Model (LLM) agents have demonstrated remarkable proficiency in solving isolated software engineering tasks. However, existing benchmarks predominantly evaluate static, independent issues, failing to reflect the continuous and sequentially dependent nature of real-world software evolution. We introduce DeepCommit, an automated pipeline that reconstructs verifiable software evolution trajectories from git histories as Milestone DAGs, and DevEvol, a benchmark for streaming evaluation over evolving codebases. This setting requires agents to manage long-term context, architectural consistency, and technical debt. Our evaluation reveals a fundamental performance gap: even frontier models achieve only $\\sim$35\\% Score and $\\sim$10\\% Resolve Rate in continuous environments, driven by a ``snowball effect'' where early errors accumulate and block downstream development. These results demonstrate that strong snapshot performance substantially overestimates real-world agent capability, establishing long-horizon software evolution as a critical unsolved challenge. Our code and dataset are available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/DevEvol-48A8.","absKo":"Large Language Model (LLM) agentлҠ” кі лҰҪлҗң software engineering taskлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° лҶҖлқјмҡҙ лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ benchmarkлҠ” мЈјлЎң м •м Ғмқҙкі  лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё issueлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳм—¬, мӢӨм„ёкі„ software evolutionмқҳ м—°мҶҚм Ғмқҙкі  sequentially dependentн•ң нҠ№м„ұмқ„ л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” git historyлЎңл¶Җн„° кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң software evolution trajectoryлҘј Milestone DAGлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” мһҗлҸҷнҷ” pipelineмқё DeepCommitкіј, м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” codebaseм—җ лҢҖн•ң streaming evaluationмқ„ мң„н•ң benchmarkмқё DevEvolмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өм •м—җм„ңлҠ” agentк°Җ мһҘкё° context, architectural consistency, technical debtлҘј кҙҖлҰ¬н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё м„ұлҠҘ кІ©м°ЁлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мөңмІЁлӢЁ frontier modelмЎ°м°Ё continuous environmentм—җм„ң ScoreлҠ” м•Ҫ 35%, Resolve RateлҠ” м•Ҫ 10%м—җ л¶Ҳкіјн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мҙҲкё° мҳӨлҘҳк°Җ лҲ„м Ғлҗҳм–ҙ downstream developmentлҘј л§үлҠ” ``snowball effect''м—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң л°ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” к°•н•ң snapshot performanceк°Җ мӢӨм„ёкі„ agent capabilityлҘј мғҒлӢ№нһҲ кіјлҢҖнҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, long-horizon software evolutionмқҙ н•ҙкІ°лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңмһ„мқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ codeмҷҖ datasetмқҖ https://anonymous.4open.science/r/DevEvol-48A8 м—җм„ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•ҳлӢӨ."},{"id":"67154","en":"Position: Let's Develop Data Probes to Fundamentally Understand How Data Affects LLM Performance","ko":"Position: лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ LLM м„ұлҠҘм—җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җ к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң Data ProbeлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳмһҗ","authors":"Shiqiang Wang, Herbert Woisetschlaeger, Hans-Arno Jacobsen, Mingyue Ji","pos":"#2205","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Q4QdvcAzR9","abs":"<p>Data is fundamental to large language models (LLMs). However, understanding of what makes certain data useful for different stages of an LLM workflow, including training, tuning, alignment, in-context learning, etc., and why, remains an open question. Current approaches rely heavily on extensive experimentation with large public datasets to obtain empirical heuristics for data filtering and dataset construction. These approaches are compute intensive and lack a principled way of understanding the essence of how specific data characteristics drive LLM behavior. In this position paper, <em>we advocate for the need of developing systematic methodologies for generating synthetic sequences from appropriately defined random processes, with the goal that these sequences can reveal useful characteristics when they are used in one or multiple stages of the LLM workflow</em>. We refer to such sequences as <em>data probes</em>. By observing LLM behavior on data probes, researchers can systematically conduct studies on how data characteristics influence model performance, generalization, and robustness. The probing sequences exhibit statistical properties that can be viewed using theoretical concepts, such as typical sets, which are generalized to describe the behaviors of LLMs. This data-probe approach provides a pathway for uncovering foundational insights into the role of data in LLM training and inference, beyond empirical heuristics.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” large language model(LLM)мқҳ к·јк°„мқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ нӣҲл Ё, нҠңлӢқ, м •л ¬(alignment), in-context learning л“ұмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң LLM мӣҢнҒ¬н”ҢлЎңмқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң м–ҙл–Ө лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ мҷң мң мҡ©н•ңм§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙн•ҙлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м—ҙл Ө мһҲлҠ” м§Ҳл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„° н•„н„°л§Ғкіј лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ кө¬м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң кІҪн—ҳм Ғ нңҙлҰ¬мҠӨнӢұмқ„ м–»кё° мң„н•ҙ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ кіөк°ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳм—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јмқҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кі , нҠ№м • лҚ°мқҙн„° нҠ№м„ұмқҙ LLMмқҳ н–үлҸҷмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ мўҢмҡ°н•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң ліём§Ҳмқ„ мӣҗлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң мқҙн•ҙн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ нҸ¬м§Җм…ҳ нҺҳмқҙнҚјм—җм„ң <em>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м Ғм ҲнһҲ м •мқҳлҗң random processлЎңл¶Җн„° synthetic sequenceлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” мІҙкі„м Ғ л°©лІ•лЎ мқ„ к°ңл°ңн•  н•„мҡ”к°Җ мһҲлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, мқҙ sequenceк°Җ LLM мӣҢнҒ¬н”ҢлЎңмқҳ н•ҳлӮҳ лҳҗлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗ  л•Ң мң мҡ©н•ң нҠ№м„ұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ</em>. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң sequenceлҘј <em>data probe</em>лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. LLMмқҙ data probeм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ ліҙмқҙлҠ” н–үлҸҷмқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, м—°кө¬мһҗл“ӨмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„° нҠ№м„ұмқҙ лӘЁлҚё м„ұлҠҘ, мқјл°ҳнҷ”, к°•кұҙм„ұм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң м—°кө¬лҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң probing sequenceлҠ” typical setкіј к°ҷмқҖ мқҙлЎ м Ғ к°ңл…җмңјлЎң ліј мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” нҶөкі„м Ғ м„ұм§Ҳмқ„ к°Җм§Җл©°, мқҙлҠ” LLMмқҳ н–үлҸҷмқ„ кё°мҲ н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ data-probe м ‘к·јмқҖ кІҪн—ҳм Ғ нңҙлҰ¬мҠӨнӢұмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ, LLM нӣҲл Ёкіј м¶”лЎ м—җм„ң лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ м—ӯн• м—җ лҢҖн•ң кё°мҙҲм Ғ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮҙлҠ” кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67224","en":"Position: Early-Stage Quality Assurance in Annotation Pipelines Is More Cost-Effective Than Late-Stage Validation","ko":"Position: Annotation нҢҢмқҙн”„лқјмқёмқҳ мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„ н’Ҳм§Ҳ ліҙмҰқмқҖ нӣ„кё° лӢЁкі„ кІҖмҰқліҙлӢӨ л№„мҡ© нҡЁмңЁм ҒмқҙлӢӨ","authors":"Sunil Kothari, Sumukha Sharma Thoppanahalli Chandramouli, Naman Khandelwal, Praveen Kumar Gulipalli, Parth Kulshreshtha, Ashi Jain, Kriti Banka, Tanuja Chintada, Venkata Triveni, Manish Mehta, Tao Liu","pos":"#2801","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=79leIDoP1d","abs":"<p>This position paper argues that the machine learning community should prioritize early-stage quality assurance in annotation pipelines over the prevailing practice of late-stage validation. Data quality bottlenecks increasingly limit foundation model improvement, yet quality assurance research focuses almost exclusively on validation methods rather than validation timing. <em>When</em> validation occursвҖ”not merely <em>what</em> validation methods are employedвҖ”fundamentally determines both error rates and annotation costs. This temporal neglect is puzzling given the well-established \"shift-left\" principle from software engineering, where empirical studies demonstrate 4вҖ“100Г— cost multipliers for defects detected in later development stages (Boehm, 1981; Shull et al., 2002). Annotation pipelines, we argue, exhibit analogous dynamics: errors caught before annotation begins cost a fraction of those discovered after review cycles complete.  We propose a taxonomy of three <em>QA trigger points</em>вҖ”pre-annotation (TвӮҖ), post-annotation (TвӮҒ), and post-review (TвӮӮ)вҖ”that decompose annotation workflows into discrete validation opportunities. A survey of 47 recent papers reveals that only 4% report when validation occurs, a striking gap given timing's demonstrated impact in adjacent fields. Without explicit attention to QA timing, the community risks optimizing validation methods while ignoring the structural variable that may matter most.  We call on researchers to report QA timing configurations, on platform developers to expose timing as a first-class parameter, and on the community to conduct controlled experiments testing whether the shift-left principle transfers to annotation contexts.</p>","absKo":"<p>мқҙ нҸ¬м§Җм…ҳ нҺҳмқҙнҚјлҠ” machine learning м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°к°Җ annotation pipelineм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ н–үн•ҙм§ҖлҠ” нӣ„кё° лӢЁкі„ validationліҙлӢӨ мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„ quality assuranceлҘј мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. data quality bottleneckлҠ” foundation model к°ңм„ мқ„ м җм җ лҚ” м ңн•ңн•ҳкі  мһҲм§Җл§Ң, quality assurance м—°кө¬лҠ” validation л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ validation мӢңм җм—җ кұ°мқҳ м „м ҒмңјлЎң мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”кі  мһҲлӢӨ. validationмқҙ <em>м–ём ң</em> л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ”к°Җ, лӢЁм§Җ <em>л¬ҙм—Үмқ„</em> validationн•ҳлҠ”к°Җл§Ңмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј, лҠ” error rateмҷҖ annotation costлҘј к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң кІ°м •н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢңк°„м Ғ л¬ҙмӢңлҠ” software engineeringмқҳ мһҳ нҷ•лҰҪлҗң \"shift-left\" мӣҗм№ҷмқ„ л– мҳ¬лҰ¬кІҢ н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, кұ°кё°м„ңлҠ” кІҪн—ҳм Ғ м—°кө¬к°Җ к°ңл°ңмқҳ нӣ„л°ҳ лӢЁкі„м—җм„ң л°ңкІ¬лҗң кІ°н•Ёмқҙ 4~100л°°мқҳ л№„мҡ© мҠ№мҲҳлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ(Boehm, 1981; Shull et al., 2002). мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” annotation pipelineлҸ„ мң мӮ¬н•ң лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ: annotationмқҙ мӢңмһ‘лҗҳкё° м „м—җ мһЎнһҢ errorлҠ” review cycleмқҙ лҒқлӮң л’Өм—җ л°ңкІ¬лҗң errorмқҳ мқјл¶Җ л№„мҡ©л§Ң л“ лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” annotation workflowлҘј к°ңлі„м Ғмқё validation кё°нҡҢлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ <em>QA trigger point</em> - pre-annotation (TвӮҖ), post-annotation (TвӮҒ), post-review (TвӮӮ) - мқҳ taxonomyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј 47нҺёмқҳ paperлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ң кІ°кіј, лӢЁм§Җ 4%л§Ңмқҙ validationмқҙ м–ём ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ ліҙкі н•ҳкі  мһҲм—Ҳмңјл©°, мқём ‘ л¶„м•јм—җм„ң timingмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲмқҢмқ„ кі л Өн•  л•Ң мқҙлҠ” л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„ кіөл°ұмқҙлӢӨ. QA timingм—җ лҢҖн•ң лӘ…мӢңм Ғ мЈјмқҳ м—ҶмқҙлҠ”, м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°к°Җ validation л°©лІ•мқҖ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙм„ң к°ҖмһҘ мӨ‘мҡ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кө¬мЎ°м Ғ ліҖмҲҳлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•  мң„н—ҳмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—°кө¬мһҗл“Өм—җкІҢ QA timing кө¬м„ұмқ„ ліҙкі н•  кІғ, platform developerл“Өм—җкІҢ timingмқ„ first-class parameterлЎң л…ём¶ңн•  кІғмқ„, к·ёлҰ¬кі  shift-left мӣҗм№ҷмқҙ annotation л§ҘлқҪм—җлҸ„ м „мқҙлҗҳлҠ”м§Җ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” нҶөм ңлҗң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•  кІғмқ„ мҙүкө¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67049","en":"Position: Code Benchmarks Should Prioritize Rigor, Reliability, and Reproducibility","ko":"Position: мҪ”л“ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лҠ” м—„л°Җм„ұ, мӢ лў°м„ұ, мһ¬нҳ„м„ұмқ„ мҡ°м„ н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Jialun Cao, Yuk-Kit Chan, Zixuan Ling, Wenxuan Wang, Shuqing Li, Mingwei Liu, Ruixi Qiao, Yuting Han, Chaozheng Wang, Boxi Yu, Pinjia He, Shuai Wang, Zibin Zheng, Michael Lyu, Shing-Chi Cheung","pos":"#3402","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xKjGSyryju","abs":"<p>Code-related benchmarks play a critical role in evaluating large language models (LLMs), yet their quality fundamentally shapes how the com- munity interprets model capabilities. In the past few years, awareness of benchmark quality has grown. Yet, after a decade-scale (2014 - 2025) survey over 572 code benchmarks, we observed a lag between growing awareness and actual prac- tice. For example, in 2025 alone, the number of benchmarks that ignore code coverage when pro- viding test cases nearly matches the total count accumulated across the previous ten years. In response, we take a clear position: Code bench- marks must prioritize rigor in benchmark con- struction, reliability in evaluation, and repro- ducibility in release. To operationalize this po- sition, we introduce a code benchmark guideline HOW2BENCH with 55 checklists. Finally, our further human study also exposed that the current issues not only stem from the significant effort required, but also from a lack of awareness re- garding their importance.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҪ”л“ң кҙҖл Ё benchmarkлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(LLMs)мқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё н’Ҳм§ҲмқҖ м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°к°Җ лӘЁлҚё м—ӯлҹүмқ„ н•ҙм„қн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқ мһҗмІҙлҘј к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң мўҢмҡ°н•ңлӢӨ. м§ҖлӮң лӘҮ л…„ лҸҷм•Ҳ benchmark н’Ҳм§Ҳм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқёмӢқмқҖ лҶ’м•„мЎҢлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ 572к°ң code benchmarkлҘј лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң н•ң 10л…„ к·ңлӘЁ(2014 - 2025)мқҳ мЎ°мӮ¬ кІ°кіј, мқёмӢқмқҳ мҰқлҢҖмҷҖ мӢӨм ң кҙҖн–ү мӮ¬мқҙм—җлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м§ҖмІҙк°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ 2025л…„ н•ң н•ҙм—җл§Ң, н…ҢмҠӨнҠё мјҖмқҙмҠӨлҘј м ңкіөн•  л•Ң code coverageлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳлҠ” benchmark мҲҳк°Җ м§ҖлӮң 10л…„ лҸҷм•Ҳ лҲ„м Ғлҗң мҙқн•©м—җ кұ°мқҳ л§һлЁ№лҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙм—җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¶„лӘ…н•ң мһ…мһҘмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. Code benchmarkлҠ” benchmark кө¬м„ұм—җм„ңмқҳ м—„л°Җм„ұ, нҸүк°Җм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұ, кіөк°ңм—җм„ңмқҳ мһ¬нҳ„к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ мҡ°м„ н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мһ…мһҘмқ„ мӢӨм ңлЎң мһ‘лҸҷмӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 55к°ңмқҳ мІҙнҒ¬лҰ¬мҠӨнҠёлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ code benchmark guideline HOW2BENCHлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё мқёк°„ лҢҖмғҒ м—°кө¬лҠ” нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ л¬ём ңл“Өмқҙ мғҒлӢ№н•ң л…ёл Ҙмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұм—җм„ңл§Ң л№„лЎҜлҗҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј, к·ё мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқёмӢқ л¶ҖмЎұм—җм„ңлҸ„ кё°мқён•Ёмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лғҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67097","en":"Position: Adopting AI in Practice Does Not Guarantee the Productivity Boost","ko":"Position: мӢӨл¬ҙм—җм„ң AIлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨкі  мғқмӮ°м„ұ н–ҘмғҒмқҙ ліҙмһҘлҗҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м•„лӢҲлӢӨ","authors":"Won Ik Cho, Seong-hun Kim, Geunhye Kim","pos":"#3407","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=j77e2EHpBo","abs":"<p>This position paper argues that <strong>adopting AI in organizational practice does not guarantee productivity gains, because human and environmental factors critically moderate the relationship between AI deployment and realized productivity improvements</strong>. Following the advent of high-performance generative models, AI use has been rapidly encouraged in some sectors while being restricted in others. Most practitioners assume that AI brings productivity boosts owing to enhanced technical capabilities, but regardless of apparent performance advances in AI technology, human and environmental factors of the organization may substantially attenuate---or even negate---the effective productivity benefits. We identify five key moderating factors: human resource composition, baseline capability of individuals, learning curve of practitioners, incentives for fair use, and flexibility of objectives. Drawing on the partial equilibrium model of Gries and NaudГ© (2022), we argue that existing economic frameworks may inadvertently overlook these factors. We revise the existing framework to redefine effective organizational determinants and shed light to practical implications including industry and education, responding to alternative views and calling for action of stakeholders.</p>","absKo":"<p>мқҙ position paperлҠ” <strong>мЎ°м§Ғ кҙҖн–үм—җм„ң AIлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨкі  н•ҙм„ң мғқмӮ°м„ұ н–ҘмғҒмқҙ ліҙмһҘлҗҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м•„лӢҲл©°, мқёк°„м Ғ мҡ”мқёкіј нҷҳкІҪм Ғ мҡ”мқёмқҙ AI л°°нҸ¬мҷҖ мӢӨнҳ„лҗң мғқмӮ°м„ұ н–ҘмғҒ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ кҙҖкі„лҘј кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ</strong>лқјкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. кі м„ұлҠҘ generative modelмқҳ л“ұмһҘ мқҙнӣ„, AI мӮ¬мҡ©мқҖ мқјл¶Җ л¶Җл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” л№ лҘҙкІҢ мһҘл Өлҗҳм—Ҳкі  лӢӨлҘё л¶Җл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” м ңн•ңлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ мӢӨл¬ҙмһҗлҠ” AIк°Җ кё°мҲ м Ғ лҠҘл Ҙ н–ҘмғҒм—җ нһҳмһ…м–ҙ мғқмӮ°м„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқёлӢӨкі  к°Җм •н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, AI кё°мҲ мқҳ лӘ…л°ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘ м§„ліҙмҷҖ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳкІҢ мЎ°м§Ғмқҳ мқёк°„м Ғ мҡ”мқёкіј нҷҳкІҪм Ғ мҡ”мқёмқҖ мӢӨм§Ҳм Ғ мғқмӮ°м„ұ нҺёмқөмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ м•Ҫнҷ”мӢңнӮӨкұ°лӮҳ мӢ¬м§Җм–ҙ мғҒмҮ„н•  мҲҳлҸ„ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм„Ҝ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ мЎ°м Ҳ мҡ”мқёмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ: мқём Ғ мһҗмӣҗмқҳ кө¬м„ұ, к°ңмқёмқҳ baseline capability, мӢӨл¬ҙмһҗмқҳ learning curve, кіөм •н•ң мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ мң„н•ң мқём„јнӢ°лёҢ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  лӘ©н‘ңмқҳ мң м—°м„ұмқҙлӢӨ. Gries and NaudГ© (2022)мқҳ partial equilibrium modelм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, кё°мЎҙ кІҪм ңн•ҷм Ғ frameworkк°Җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҡ”мқёл“Өмқ„ л¬ҙмӢ¬мҪ” к°„кіјн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ frameworkлҘј мҲҳм •н•ҳм—¬ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё мЎ°м§Ғ кІ°м •мҡ”мқёмқ„ мһ¬м •мқҳн•ҳкі , мӮ°м—… л°Ҹ көҗмңЎмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң мӢӨм§Ҳм Ғ н•ЁмқҳлҘј мЎ°лӘ…н•ҳл©°, лҢҖм•Ҳм Ғ кІ¬н•ҙм—җ мқ‘лӢөн•ҳкі  мқҙн•ҙкҙҖкі„мһҗл“Өмқҳ н–үлҸҷмқ„ мҙүкө¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66364","en":"Towards a Science of AI Agent Reliability","ko":"AI м—җмқҙм „нҠё мӢ лў°м„ұмқҳ кіјн•ҷмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Stephan Rabanser, Sayash Kapoor, Peter Kirgis, Kangheng Liu, Saiteja Utpala, Arvind Narayanan","pos":"#3408","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4LTwRqhmhk","abs":"<p>AI agents are increasingly deployed for consequential tasks. Yet existing benchmarks evaluate only task success rates, ignoring whether agents behave consistently, remain robust to perturbations, fail predictably, or bound error severity. We propose a framework for measuring agent reliability grounded in safety-critical engineering practice, decomposing reliability into four dimensions: consistency, robustness, predictability, and safety. Applying these metrics to 12 frontier models across two complementary benchmarks, we find that recent capability gains have produced minimal improvement in reliability: agents remain inconsistent across runs, brittle to prompt rephrasings, and poorly calibrated in their self-assessments, even as accuracy improves. Our metrics complement accuracy-focused evaluation by offering tools for reasoning about how agents perform, degrade, and fail under uncertainty.</p>","absKo":"<p>AI agentлҠ” м җм җ лҚ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мһ‘м—…м—җ л°°нҸ¬лҗҳкі  мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ benchmarkлҠ” task success rateл§Ң нҸүк°Җн•  лҝҗ, agentк°Җ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–үлҸҷн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ, perturbationм—җ к°•кұҙн•ңм§Җ, мҳҲмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң л°©мӢқмңјлЎң мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ, лҳҗлҠ” error severityлҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј л¬ҙмӢңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” safety-critical engineering practiceм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң agent reliability мёЎм • frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, reliabilityлҘј consistency, robustness, predictability, safetyмқҳ л„Ө к°Җм§Җ м°ЁмӣҗмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ м§Җн‘ңлҘј л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мғҒліҙм Ғмқё benchmarkм—җм„ң 12к°ңмқҳ frontier modelм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ң кІ°кіј, мөңк·јмқҳ capability н–ҘмғҒмқҖ reliability к°ңм„ мңјлЎң кұ°мқҳ мқҙм–ҙм§Җм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳмқҢмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. agentлҠ” мӢӨн–ү к°„ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳкі , prompt rephrasingм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳл©°, м •нҷ•лҸ„лҠ” н–ҘмғҒлҗҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ мһҗкё°нҸүк°Җмқҳ calibrationмқҙ мўӢм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м§Җн‘ңлҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„ мӨ‘мӢ¬ нҸүк°ҖлҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳл©°, uncertainty н•ҳм—җм„ң agentк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі , м Җн•ҳлҗҳкі , мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м¶”лЎ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң лҸ„кө¬лҘј м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63894","en":"iWorld-Bench: A Benchmark for Interactive World Models with a Unified Action Generation Framework","ko":"iWorld-Bench: нҶөн•© action generation н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј к°–м¶ҳ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© world model лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Jianjie Fang, Yingshan Lei, Qin Wan, Ziyou Wang, Yuchao Huang, Yongyan Xu, Baining Zhao, Weichen Zhang, Chen Gao, Xinlei Chen, Yong Li","pos":"#3605","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=SkGaHLxhXx","abs":"<p>Achieving Artificial General Intelligence (AGI) requires agents that learn and interact adaptively, with interactive world models providing scalable environments for perception, reasoning, and action. Yet current research still lacks large-scale datasets and unified benchmarks to evaluate their physical interaction capabilities. To address this, we propose iWorld-Bench, a comprehensive benchmark for training and testing world models on interaction-related abilities such as distance perception and memory. We construct a diverse dataset with 330k video clips and select 2.1k high-quality samples covering varied perspectives, weather, and scenes. As existing world models differ in interaction modalities, we introduce an \\textbf{Action Generation Framework} to unify evaluation and design six task types, generating 4.9k test samples. These tasks jointly assess model performance across \\textbf{visual generation, trajectory following, and memory}. Evaluating 14 representative world models, we identify key limitations and provide insights for future research. The iWorld-Bench model leaderboard is publicly available at iWorld-Bench.com.</p>","absKo":"<p>Artificial General Intelligence(AGI)лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл Өл©ҙ м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” м—җмқҙм „нҠёк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳл©°, interactive world modelмқҖ мқёмӢқ, м¶”лЎ , н–үлҸҷмқ„ мң„н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҷҳкІҪмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ нҳ„мһ¬ м—°кө¬лҠ” мқҙл“Өмқҳ л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣкіј нҶөн•© benchmarkк°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кұ°лҰ¬ м§Җк°Ғкіј кё°м–өкіј к°ҷмқҖ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© кҙҖл Ё лҠҘл Ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ world modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  н…ҢмҠӨнҠён•ҳкё° мң„н•ң нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғ benchmarkмқё iWorld-BenchлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 33л§Ң к°ңмқҳ video clipмңјлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ лӢӨм–‘н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳкі , мӢңм җ, лӮ м”Ё, мһҘл©ҙмқҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң 2.1мІң к°ңмқҳ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ мғҳн”Ңмқ„ м„ лі„н–ҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ world modelл“ӨмқҖ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© modalityк°Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘҙлҜҖлЎң, нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ \\textbf{Action Generation Framework}лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі  м—¬м„Ҝ к°Җм§Җ task typeмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ҳм—¬ 4.9мІң к°ңмқҳ test sampleмқ„ мғқм„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң taskлҠ” \\textbf{visual generation, trajectory following, memory} м „л°ҳм—җм„ң лӘЁлҚё м„ұлҠҘмқ„ кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. 14к°ңмқҳ лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё world modelмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•өмӢ¬ н•ңкі„лҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі  н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬лҘј мң„н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. iWorld-Bench model leaderboardлҠ” iWorld-Bench.comм—җм„ң кіөк°ңм ҒмңјлЎң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67112","en":"Position: AI Evaluation Should Work With Humans","ko":"Position: AI нҸүк°ҖлҠ” мқёк°„кіј н•Ёк»ҳ мһ‘лҸҷн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Jan Kulveit, Gavin Leech, TomГЎЕЎ GavenДҚiak, Raymond Douglas","pos":"#4004","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=f15MLGSjEs","abs":"<p>We argue that the dominant paradigm of AI evaluation, which focuses on autonomous superhuman performance and so an implicit goal of replacing humans, is guiding AI development in the wrong direction. Instead, the AI community should pivot to evaluating the performance of humanвҖ“AI teams. We argue that this collaborative shift in evaluation will foster AI systems that act as true complements to human capabilities and therefore lead to far better societal outcomes than the current process.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһҗмңЁм Ғмқё superhuman м„ұлҠҘм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”л©°, л”°лқјм„ң мқёк°„мқ„ лҢҖмІҙн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ м•”л¬өм Ғ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң мӮјлҠ” AI нҸүк°Җмқҳ м§Җл°°м Ғ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙ AI к°ңл°ңмқ„ мһҳлӘ»лҗң л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң мқҙлҒҢкі  мһҲлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖмӢ  AI м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°лҠ” humanвҖ“AI нҢҖмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң м „нҷҳн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҸүк°Җм—җм„ңмқҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҳ‘л Ҙм Ғ м „нҷҳмқҙ AI мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҙ мқёк°„мқҳ м—ӯлҹүмқ„ м§„м •мңјлЎң ліҙмҷ„н•ҳлҠ” м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мҙүм§„н•ҳкі , к·ё кІ°кіј нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ кіјм •ліҙлӢӨ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ кІ°кіјлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§Ҳ кІғмқҙлқјкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66567","en":"DSGym: A Standardized and Holistic Framework for Advancing Data Science Agents","ko":"DSGym: лҚ°мқҙн„° кіјн•ҷ м—җмқҙм „нҠё л°ңм „мқ„ мң„н•ң н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗҳкі  мҙқмІҙм Ғмқё н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Fan Nie, Junlin Wang, Harper Hua, Federico Bianchi, Yongchan Kwon, Zhenting Qi, Owen Queen, Shang Zhu, James Zou","pos":"#4006","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2WrNPRW9Km","abs":"<p>Data science agents promise to accelerate  discovery and insight-generation by turning data into executable analyses and findings. Yet existing data science benchmarks fall short due to fragmented evaluation interfaces that make cross-benchmark comparison difficult, narrow task coverage and a lack of rigorous data grounding. In particular, we show that a substantial portion of tasks in current benchmarks can be solved without using the actual data. To address these limitations, we introduce DSGym, a standardized framework for evaluating and training data science agents in self-contained execution environments. Unlike static benchmarks, DSGym provides a modular architecture that makes it easy to add tasks, agent scaffolds, and tools, positioning it as a live, extensible testbed. We curate DSGym-Tasks, a holistic task suite that standardizes and refines existing benchmarks via quality and shortcut solvability filtering. We further expand coverage with (1) DSBio: expert-derived bioinformatics tasks grounded in literature and (2) DSPredict: challenging prediction tasks spanning domains such as computer vision, molecular prediction, and single-cell perturbation.  Beyond evaluation, DSGym enables agent training via execution-verified data synthesis pipeline. As a case study, we build a 2,000-example training set in DSGym that substantially improves a 4B mode on standardized analysis benchmarks. Overall, DSGym enables rigorous end-to-end measurement of whether agents can plan, implement, and validate data analyses in realistic scientific context.</p>","absKo":"<p>Data science agentлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң л¶„м„қкіј кІ°кіјлЎң л°”кҫём–ҙ discoveryмҷҖ insight generationмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚн•  мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ м§ҖлӢҢлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ data science benchmarkлҠ” мЎ°к°ҒлӮң evaluation interface л•Ңл¬ём—җ benchmark к°„ л№„көҗк°Җ м–ҙл өкі , task coverageк°Җ мўҒмңјл©°, м—„л°Җн•ң data groundingмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” н•ңкі„к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ benchmarkмқҳ мғҒлӢ№мҲҳ taskк°Җ мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ н’ҖлҰҙ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” self-contained execution environmentм—җм„ң data science agentлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі  н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң н‘ңмӨҖнҷ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ DSGymмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. м •м Ғ benchmarkмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬ DSGymмқҖ task, agent scaffold, toolмқ„ мүҪкІҢ м¶”к°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” modular architectureлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм—¬, мӮҙм•„ мһҲкі  нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң testbedлЎңм„ңмқҳ мң„м№ҳлҘј к°–лҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” qualityмҷҖ shortcut solvability filteringмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кё°мЎҙ benchmarkлҘј н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”н•ҳкі  м •м ңн•ң мў…н•© task suiteмқё DSGym-TasksлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң (1) л¬ён—Ңм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ м „л¬ёк°Җк°Җ лҸ„м¶ңн•ң bioinformatics taskмқё DSBioмҷҖ (2) computer vision, molecular prediction, single-cell perturbation л“ұмқҳ лҸ„л©”мқёмқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” лҸ„м „м Ғмқё prediction taskмқё DSPredictлЎң coverageлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. нҸүк°ҖлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ, DSGymмқҖ execution-verified data synthesis pipelineмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ agent trainingлҸ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мӮ¬лЎҖ м—°кө¬лЎңм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” DSGymм—җм„ң 2,000к°ң мҳҲмӢңлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ training setмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳм—¬, н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗң analysis benchmarkм—җм„ң 4B modelмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң DSGymмқҖ нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё scientific contextм—җм„ң agentк°Җ data analysisлҘј кі„нҡҚ, кө¬нҳ„, кІҖмҰқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң м—„л°Җн•ң end-to-end мёЎм •мқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65303","en":"ZeroBench: An Impossible Visual Benchmark for Contemporary Large Multimodal Models","ko":"ZeroBench: нҳ„лҢҖ Large Multimodal Modelмқ„ мң„н•ң л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң мӢңк°Ғ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Jonathan Roberts, Mohammad Reza Taesiri, Ansh Sharma, Akash Gupta, Samuel Roberts, Ioana Croitoru, Vlad Bogolin, Jialu Tang, Florian Langer, Vyas Raina, Vatsal Raina, Hanyi Xiong, Vishaal Udandarao, Jingyi Lu, Chen Shiyang, Sam Purkis, Tianshuo Yan, Wenye Lin, Gyungin Shin, Qiaochu Yang, Anh Nguyen, David Atkinson, Alexandru Coca, Mikah Дҗбә·ng, Sebastian Dziadzio, Jakob D. Kunz, Kaiqu Liang, Alexander Lo, Brian Pulfer, Steven Walton, Charig Yang, Kai Han, Samuel Albanie","pos":"#4305","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EvmCeoiKYI","abs":"<p>Large Multimodal Models (LMMs) exhibit shortfalls when interpreting images and, by some measures, have poorer spatial cognition than young children or animals. Despite this, they attain high scores on many popular visual benchmarks, with headroom rapidly eroded by surging model progress. To address this, there is a pressing need for difficult benchmarks that remain relevant for longer. We take this idea to its limit by introducing ZeroBenchвҖ”a lightweight visual reasoning benchmark curated using adversarial filtering to be вҖңimpossibleвҖқ for frontier LMMs at release time, with initial SotA scores of 0% pass@1 and passвҲ§5. We track progress on ZeroBench over the subsequent year, observing SotA reaching 6% passвҲ§5 and 19% pass@5, indicating the potential longevity of our benchmark. Overall, we evaluate 46 LMMs on ZeroBench, compare performance to a human baseline, analyse strengths and weaknesses, and chart performance over a year of advancement in visual capabilities.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Multimodal Models (LMMs)лҠ” мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј н•ҙм„қн•  л•Ң н•ңкі„лҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, мқјл¶Җ кё°мӨҖм—җм„ңлҠ” м–ҙлҰ°м•„мқҙ лҳҗлҠ” лҸҷл¬јліҙлӢӨ spatial cognitionмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. к·ёлҹјм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  л§ҺмқҖ мқёкё° visual benchmarkм—җм„ң лҶ’мқҖ м җмҲҳлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мһҲмңјл©°, кёүкІ©н•ң лӘЁлҚё л°ңм „мңјлЎң мқён•ҙ м—¬мң  нҸӯмқҖ л№ лҘҙкІҢ мӨ„м–ҙл“Өкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, лҚ” мҳӨлһҳ мң нҡЁм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” м–ҙл Өмҡҙ benchmarkк°Җ мӢңкёүнһҲ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҘј к·№н•ңк№Ңм§Җ л°Җм–ҙл¶ҷм—¬, adversarial filteringмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кіөк°ң мӢңм җмқҳ frontier LMMsм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ вҖңл¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨвҖқкі  м—¬кІЁм§Ҳ м •лҸ„лЎң м„ лі„н•ң кІҪлҹү visual reasoning benchmarkмқё ZeroBenchлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кіөк°ң мӢңм җмқҳ мҙҲкё° SotA м җмҲҳлҠ” pass@1кіј passвҲ§5 лӘЁл‘җ 0%мҳҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙнӣ„ 1л…„ лҸҷм•Ҳ ZeroBenchмқҳ м§„мІҷмқ„ м¶”м Ғн–Ҳмңјл©°, SotAк°Җ passвҲ§5м—җм„ң 6%, pass@5м—җм„ң 19%м—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ҳм—¬, мқҙ benchmarkмқҳ мһҘкё°м Ғ мң нҡЁ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ZeroBenchм—җм„ң 46к°ңмқҳ LMMмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі , human baselineкіј м„ұлҠҘмқ„ л№„көҗн•ҳл©°, к°•м җкіј м•Ҫм җмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ҳкі , visual capabilityмқҳ 1л…„к°„ л°ңм „м—җ л”°лҘё м„ұлҠҘ ліҖнҷ”лҘј м¶”м Ғн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64736","en":"TadABench-1M: A Large-Scale Wet-Lab Protein Benchmark For Rigorous OOD Evaluation","ko":"TadABench-1M: м—„кІ©н•ң OOD нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ Wet-Lab лӢЁл°ұм§Ҳ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Jin Gao, Juntu Zhao, Zirui Zeng, Jiaqi Shen, Junhao Shi, Dukun Zhao, Yuming Lu, Dequan Wang","pos":"#4307","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=KMwrxaoAW4","abs":"<p>Existing benchmarks for biological language models (BLMs) inadequately capture the challenges of real-world applications, often lacking realistic out-of-distribution (OOD) scenarios, evolutionary depth, and consistency in measurement. To address this, we introduce TadABench-1M, a new benchmark based on a wet-lab dataset of over one million variants of the therapeutically relevant TadA enzyme, purpose-built to embody these three essential attributes. Generated across 31 rounds of wet-lab evolution, it offers unparalleled evolutionary depth and naturally presents a stringent OOD challenge. To ensure measurement consistency across this extensive campaign, we developed Seq2Graph, a scalable graph-based algorithm that systematically unifies multi-batch experimental data. Our high-fidelity benchmark highlights a critical finding: while state-of-the-art BLMs excel on a standard random split of the data (SpearmanвҖҷs ПҒ вүҲ 0.8), they fail dramatically on a realistic temporal prediction task (ПҒ вүҲ 0.1). This stark performance gap validates the importance of our benchmarkвҖҷs design principles and suggests that evolutionary depth is critical for building models with realistic utility.</p>","absKo":"<p>мғқл¬јн•ҷм Ғ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(BLM)мқҳ кё°мЎҙ benchmarkлҠ” мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©мқҳ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳл©°, нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё out-of-distribution(OOD) мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨ, evolutionary depth, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мёЎм •мқҳ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м№ҳлЈҢм ҒмңјлЎң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң TadA enzymeмқҳ 100л§Ң к°ңк°Җ л„ҳлҠ” variantлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң wet-lab datasetмқ„ кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ benchmarkмқё TadABench-1Mмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ benchmarkлҠ” мқҙ м„ё к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ мҶҚм„ұмқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. 31лқјмҡҙл“ңмқҳ wet-lab evolution м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мғқм„ұлҗҳм—Ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, нғҒмӣ”н•ң evolutionary depthлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©° мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ м—„кІ©н•ң OOD кіјм ңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мә нҺҳмқё м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мёЎм • мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨмӨ‘ л°°м№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң graph-based м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ Seq2GraphлҘј к°ңл°ңн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кі м •л°Җ benchmarkлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, state-of-the-art BLMмқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ random splitм—җм„ңлҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң(Spearmanмқҳ ПҒ вүҲ 0.8), нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё temporal prediction taskм—җм„ңлҠ” нҒ¬кІҢ мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ(ПҒ вүҲ 0.1). мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к·№м Ғмқё м„ұлҠҘ кІ©м°ЁлҠ” benchmark м„Өкі„ мӣҗм№ҷмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ҳл©°, evolutionary depthк°Җ мӢӨм ң нҷңмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м§ҖлӢҢ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•өмӢ¬м Ғмһ„мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67062","en":"Position: Stop evaluating AI with human tests, develop principled, AI-specific tests instead","ko":"Position: мқёк°„мҡ© мӢңн—ҳмңјлЎң AIлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳм§Җ л§җкі  мӣҗм№ҷм—җ мһ…к°Ғн•ң AI м „мҡ© мӢңн—ҳмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳлқј","authors":"Tom SГјhr, Florian Dorner, Olawale Salaudeen, Augustin Kelava, Samira Samadi","pos":"#4308","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tKU68AwShB","abs":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs) have achieved remarkable results on a range of standardized tests originally designed to assess human cognitive and psychological traits, such as intelligence and personality. While these results are often interpreted as strong evidence of human-like characteristics in LLMs, this paper argues that such interpretations constitute an ontological error. Human psychological and educational tests are theory-driven measurement instruments, calibrated to a specific population. Applying these tests to non-human subjects without empirical validation, risks mischaracterizing what is being measured. Furthermore, a growing trend frames AI performance on benchmarks as measurements of traits such as ``intelligence'', despite known issues with validity, data contamination, cultural bias and sensitivity to superficial prompt changes. We argue that interpreting benchmark performance as measurements of human-like traits, lacks sufficient theoretical and empirical justification. This leads to our position: Stop Evaluating AI with Human Tests, Develop Principled, AI-specific Tests instead. We call for the development of principled, AI-spec by laying out, end-to-end, how valid measurement instruments are constructed and validated and where the ontological error enters when a human-calibrated instrument is applied to LLMs.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models(LLMs)мқҖ intelligenceмҷҖ personality к°ҷмқҖ мқёк°„мқҳ мқём§Җм ҒВ·мӢ¬лҰ¬м Ғ нҠ№м„ұмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мӣҗлһҳ м„Өкі„лҗң лӢӨм–‘н•ң н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗң testм—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” мў…мў… LLMмқҙ мқёк°„кіј мң мӮ¬н•ң нҠ№м„ұмқ„ м§ҖлӢҢлӢӨлҠ” к°•н•ң мҰқкұ°лЎң н•ҙм„қлҗҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙ paperлҠ” к·ёлҹ¬н•ң н•ҙм„қмқҙ ontological errorлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқёк°„ мӢ¬лҰ¬ л°Ҹ көҗмңЎ testлҠ” мқҙлЎ м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң measurement instrumentмқҙл©°, нҠ№м • populationм—җ л§һм¶”м–ҙ ліҙм •(calibrated)лҗңлӢӨ. кІҪн—ҳм Ғ кІҖмҰқ м—Ҷмқҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң testлҘј л№„мқёк°„ лҢҖмғҒм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ л¬ҙм—Үмқҙ мёЎм •лҗҳкі  мһҲлҠ”м§ҖлҘј мһҳлӘ» нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ” мң„н—ҳмқ„ лӮілҠ”лӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ AIмқҳ benchmark м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ``intelligence''мҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ нҠ№м„ұмқҳ мёЎм •мңјлЎң н”„л Ҳмқҙл°Қн•ҳлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлҠ”лҚ°, м—¬кё°м—җлҠ” validity, data contamination, cultural bias, к·ёлҰ¬кі  н‘ңл©ҙм Ғмқё prompt ліҖнҷ”м—җ лҢҖн•ң лҜјк°җм„ұкіј кҙҖл Ёлҗң м•Ңл Өм§„ л¬ём ңк°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” benchmark м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мқёк°„ мң мӮ¬ нҠ№м„ұмқҳ мёЎм •мңјлЎң н•ҙм„қн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°лҠ” м¶©л¶„н•ң мқҙлЎ м ҒВ·кІҪн—ҳм Ғ м •лӢ№м„ұмқҙ м—ҶлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мһ…мһҘмңјлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. AIлҘј мқёк°„ testлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ л©Ҳм¶”кі , лҢҖмӢ  мӣҗм№ҷм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң AI-specific testлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳлқј. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” valid measurement instrumentк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ кө¬м„ұлҗҳкі  кІҖмҰқлҗҳлҠ”м§Җ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  human-calibrated instrumentлҘј LLMм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•  л•Ң ontological errorк°Җ м–ҙл””м„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј end-to-endлЎң м ңмӢңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мӣҗм№ҷм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң AI-specific testмқҳ к°ңл°ңмқ„ мҙүкө¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67252","en":"Position: State-of-the-Art Claims Require State-of-the-Art Evidence","ko":"Position: State-of-the-Art мЈјмһҘм—җлҠ” State-of-the-Art мҰқкұ°к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"YongKyung Oh","pos":"#4309","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0BQm8At7S7","abs":"<p>State-of-the-Art (SOTA) claims pervade Artificial Intelligence (AI) and Machine Learning (ML) research. These claims rest on benchmark evaluations, where models are ranked by aggregate scores across tasks. Public leaderboards are the most visible instance, but the same structure appears in paper tables throughout the literature. However, such minimal evidence often cannot support these strong claims. We identify a widespread claim-evidence gap in AI benchmarking. Claiming SOTA implies robust superiority. It suggests that a model significantly outperforms alternatives across most tasks. However, a marginal improvement in the mean score merely indicates a top average rank rather than true superiority. Analyzing ten cross-domain benchmarks from public leaderboards, we found that in more than half of top-model comparisons, at least one commonly assumed property of superiority does not hold. These properties include meaningful effect size, consistency across tasks, or robustness to dataset removal. Instead, aggregate gains are frequently driven by outlier datasets. This fragility persists even in benchmarks with many tasks. We argue that claim language should reflect the strength of the underlying evidence. This requires no additional experiments, only honest reporting of what results actually show.</p>","absKo":"<p>Artificial Intelligence (AI) л°Ҹ Machine Learning (ML) м—°кө¬ м „л°ҳм—җлҠ” State-of-the-Art (SOTA) мЈјмһҘл“Өмқҙ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ҳкІҢ мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мЈјмһҘмқҖ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬ нҸүк°Җм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳл©°, лӘЁлҚёмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ нғңмҠӨнҒ¬м—җ кұём№ң м§‘кі„ м җмҲҳлЎң мҲңмң„к°Җ л§ӨкІЁм§„лӢӨ. кіөк°ң лҰ¬лҚ”ліҙл“ңлҠ” к°ҖмһҘ лҲҲм—җ лқ„лҠ” мӮ¬лЎҖмқҙм§Җл§Ң, к°ҷмқҖ кө¬мЎ°лҠ” л¬ён—Ң м „л°ҳмқҳ л…јл¬ё н‘ңм—җм„ңлҸ„ лӮҳнғҖлӮңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ к·јкұ°л§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” мқҙлҹ° к°•н•ң мЈјмһҘмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳкё°м—җ мў…мў… м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” AI лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№м—җм„ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң claim-evidence gapмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. SOTAлҘј мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҖ к°•кұҙн•ң мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқ„ мқҳлҜён•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ нғңмҠӨнҒ¬м—җм„ң лҢҖм•Ҳл“Өмқ„ мң мқҳлҜён•ҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳм§Җл§Ң нҸүк·  м җмҲҳмқҳ лҜёлҜён•ң к°ңм„ мқҖ м§„м •н•ң мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј лӢЁм§Җ нҸүк·  мҲңмң„ 1мң„лҘј мқҳлҜён•  лҝҗмқҙлӢӨ. кіөк°ң лҰ¬лҚ”ліҙл“ңмқҳ 10к°ң cross-domain лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лҘј л¶„м„қн•ң кІ°кіј, мғҒмң„ лӘЁлҚё л№„көҗмқҳ м Ҳл°ҳмқҙ л„ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°м—җ мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқҳ мқјл°ҳм Ғ к°Җм • мӨ‘ м Ғм–ҙлҸ„ н•ҳлӮҳк°Җ м„ұлҰҪн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„ұм§Ҳм—җлҠ” мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” effect size, нғңмҠӨнҒ¬ м „л°ҳмқҳ мқјкҙҖм„ұ, лҳҗлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ м ңкұ°м—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•кұҙм„ұмқҙ нҸ¬н•ЁлҗңлӢӨ. мҳӨнһҲл Ө м§‘кі„ мқҙл“қмқҖ мў…мў… мқҙмғҒм№ҳ(outlier) лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мўҢмҡ°лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м·Ём•Ҫм„ұмқҖ нғңмҠӨнҒ¬ мҲҳк°Җ л§ҺмқҖ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬м—җм„ңлҸ„ м§ҖмҶҚлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мЈјмһҘ м–ём–ҙк°Җ к·јкұ°мқҳ к°•лҸ„лҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ м¶”к°Җ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ н•„мҡ” м—Ҷмңјл©°, кІ°кіјк°Җ мӢӨм ңлЎң ліҙм—¬мЈјлҠ” л°”лҘј м •м§Ғн•ҳкІҢ ліҙкі н•ҳл©ҙ м¶©л¶„н•ҳлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67245","en":"Position: Improved Documentation is Necessary for Benchmarking AI Systems in Geometry","ko":"Position: кё°н•ҳн•ҷм—җм„ң AI мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№н•ҳл Өл©ҙ к°ңм„ лҗң л¬ём„ңнҷ”к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Anna Genevaux, Simon Frieder","pos":"#4310","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1CqVTlAsVD","abs":"This position paper argues that documentation is infrastructure for reproducible geometry reasoning: a benchmark for formal geometry problems to test AI systems is not usable in research unless its documented vocabulary is matched by executable, versioned behavior and minimal runnable examples. We use JGEX (as implemented by Newclid) as a case study of how documentation--implementation gaps and missing examples can silently constrain expressivity, fragment tool interoperability, and bias benchmark construction. To make our point, we introduce \"A JGEX Dataset\", a curated collection of $78$ Euclidean geometry problems with (i) original natural-language statements and sources, (ii) a JGEX-oriented rewrite that makes formalization steps explicit, (iii) executable JGEX code validated under a pinned solver version, and (iv) rich metadata. To make the target language auditable, we also provide a predicate-level support matrix for the $33$ documented predicates, generated from minimal test instances, and categorize predicates as supported, unsupported, or unstable due to missing accessible examples. Finally, we release validation scripts and a concise tutorial with worked walk-throughs. Our broader claim is that benchmark authors, tool maintainers, and reviewers should treat language documentation and conformance evidence as first-class artifactsвҖ”on par with datasets and evaluation codeвҖ”if cross-tool, cross-version reproducibility is the goal.","absKo":"мқҙ position paperлҠ” documentationмқҙ reproducible geometry reasoningмқ„ мң„н•ң infrastructureлқјкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. AI systemмқ„ мӢңн—ҳн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң formal geometry problem benchmarkлҠ” л¬ём„ңнҷ”лҗң vocabularyк°Җ мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  лІ„м „мқҙ кі м •лҗң behavior, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ runnable exampleкіј мқјм№ҳн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” н•ң м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” JGEX(NewclidлЎң кө¬нҳ„лҗЁ)лҘј мӮ¬лЎҖ м—°кө¬лЎң мӮјм•„ documentation-implementation gapкіј лҲ„лқҪлҗң exampleмқҙ м–ҙл–»кІҢ expressivityлҘј мЎ°мҡ©нһҲ м ңм•Ҫн•ҳкі , tool interoperabilityлҘј л¶„м ҲмӢңнӮӨл©°, benchmark кө¬м„ұмқ„ нҺён–ҘмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мЈјмһҘмқ„ кө¬мІҙнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” $78$к°ңмқҳ Euclidean geometry problemмңјлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ м„ лі„м§‘н•©мқё \"A JGEX Dataset\"мқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмқҖ (i) мӣҗлһҳмқҳ мһҗм—°м–ҙ statementмҷҖ source, (ii) formalization stepмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң л§Ңл“ңлҠ” JGEX м§Җн–Ҙ rewrite, (iii) кі м •лҗң solver version м•„лһҳм—җм„ң кІҖмҰқлҗң executable JGEX code, (iv) н’Қл¶Җн•ң metadataлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖмғҒ languageлҘј к°җмӮ¬ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң мөңмҶҢ test instanceлЎңл¶Җн„° мғқм„ұн•ң $33$к°ңмқҳ л¬ём„ңнҷ”лҗң predicateм—җ лҢҖн•ң predicate-level support matrixлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳкі , м ‘к·ј к°ҖлҠҘн•ң exampleмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳм—¬ supported, unsupported, unstableлЎң predicateлҘј л¶„лҘҳн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, validation scriptмҷҖ worked walk-throughк°Җ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗң к°„кІ°н•ң tutorialмқ„ кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ лҚ” л„“мқҖ мЈјмһҘмқҖ cross-tool, cross-version reproducibilityк°Җ лӘ©н‘ңлқјл©ҙ benchmark author, tool maintainer, reviewerлҠ” language documentationкіј conformance evidenceлҘј dataset л°Ҹ evaluation codeмҷҖ лҸҷл“ұн•ң first-class artifactлЎң лӢӨлЈЁм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ."},{"id":"67220","en":"Position: AI Evaluations Should be Grounded on a Theory of Capability","ko":"Position: AI нҸүк°ҖлҠ” м—ӯлҹү мқҙлЎ м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Nathan Jo, Ashia Wilson","pos":"#4313","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9n4xlpq3w3","abs":"<p>Evaluations of generative models are now ubiquitous, and their outcomes critically shape public and scientific expectations of AI's capabilities. Yet skepticism about their reliability continues to grow. How can we know that a reported accuracy genuinely reflects a modelвҖҷs underlying performance? Although benchmark results are often presented as direct measurements of capability, in practice they are inferences: treating a score as evidence of capability already presupposes a theory of what it means to be capable at a task.  We argue that AI evaluations should instead be framed as inference tasks grounded on an explicit theory of capability. While this perspective is standard in fields like psychometrics, it remains underdeveloped in AI evaluation, where core assumptions are often left <em>implicit</em>. As a proof-of-concept, we empirically show that reported performance can depend strongly on the evaluatorвҖҷs modeling assumptions, underscoring the need for transparent, theory-driven evaluation practices. We conclude by offering practical guidelines for rigorously designing evaluations built on explicit theories of capability.</p>","absKo":"<p>generative modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң evaluationмқҖ мқҙм ң м–ҙл””м—җлӮҳ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳл©°, к·ё кІ°кіјлҠ” AI capabilityм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҢҖмӨ‘м ҒВ·кіјн•ҷм Ғ кё°лҢҖлҘј кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң нҳ•м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к·ё мӢ лў°м„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҡҢмқҳлҸ„ кі„мҶҚ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. ліҙкі лҗң accuracyк°Җ мӢӨм ңлЎң лӘЁлҚёмқҳ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м ңлҢҖлЎң л°ҳмҳҒн•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м–ҙл–»кІҢ м•Ң мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ? benchmark кІ°кіјлҠ” мў…мў… capabilityмқҳ м§Ғм ‘ мёЎм •к°’мІҳлҹј м ңмӢңлҗҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” inferenceмқҙлӢӨ. scoreлҘј capabilityмқҳ мҰқкұ°лЎң к°„мЈјн•ҳлҠ” мҲңк°„, мқҙлҜё м–ҙл–Ө taskм—җм„ң capableн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙ л¬ҙм—Үмқ„ лң»н•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң theoryлҘј м „м ңн•ҳкі  мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” AI evaluationмқҙ лӘ…мӢңм Ғ capability theoryм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң inference taskлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұлҗҳм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм җмқҖ psychometrics к°ҷмқҖ л¶„м•јм—җм„ңлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, AI evaluationм—җм„ңлҠ” м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ л°ңм „н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н–Ҳмңјл©°, к·ёкіім—җм„ңлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ к°Җм •мқҙ мў…мў… <em>м•”л¬өм Ғ</em>мңјлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. proof-of-conceptлЎңм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙкі лҗң м„ұлҠҘмқҙ evaluatorмқҳ modeling assumptionм—җ к°•н•ҳкІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјл©°, нҲ¬лӘ…н•ҳкі  theory-drivenн•ң evaluation practiceмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғ capability theoryм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ нҸүк°ҖлҘј м—„л°Җн•ҳкІҢ м„Өкі„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ м§Җм№Ёмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63578","en":"Noise Tectonics: Measuring the Stability of AI Benchmark Ecosystems","ko":"Noise Tectonics: AI лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬ мғқнғңкі„мқҳ м•Ҳм •м„ұ мёЎм •","authors":"Michael Hardy, Sang Truong, Anka Reuel, Lijin Zhang, Jodi Casabianca, Yash Dave, Hansol Lee, Ben Domingue, Sanmi Koyejo","pos":"#4314","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Vr4YScS9DT","abs":"<p>AI benchmark ecosystems compress rich evaluation data into aggregate leaderboard scores, but these scores contain substantial measurement noise whose sources and magnitudes remain unquantified. Without systematic methods to measure this noise and separate signal from artifact, it is unclear when benchmark rankings reflect genuine capability differences versus measurement error. We introduce a psychometric framework to methodically test hypotheses about benchmark ecosystem structure and quantify the reliability of common benchmark-derived claims. Applying Confirmatory Factor Analysis and Generalizability Theory to 4,000+ models from the Open LLM Leaderboard, we decompose sources of ranking variance and find that human contributors account for more variance (9\\%) than model architecture (4.8\\%), revealing that benchmark noise stems as much from contributor practices as from model characteristics. We further demonstrate methods to assess the reliability of scaling laws by controlling for model size and other confounds. Our findings provide actionable diagnostics for when benchmark rankings can be trusted and establish a measurement framework for evaluating the validity of AI evaluation claims.</p>","absKo":"<p>AI benchmark ecosystemмқҖ н’Қл¶Җн•ң evaluation dataлҘј aggregate leaderboard scoreлЎң м••м¶•н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң scoreм—җлҠ” мёЎм • л…ёмқҙмҰҲк°Җ мғҒлӢ№нһҲ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмңјл©° к·ё мӣҗмқёкіј нҒ¬кё°лҠ” м•„м§Ғ м •лҹүнҷ”лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ л…ёмқҙмҰҲлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мёЎм •н•ҳкі  signalкіј artifactлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқҙ м—ҶлӢӨл©ҙ, benchmark rankingмқҙ м§„м •н•ң capability м°ЁмқҙлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м•„лӢҲл©ҙ measurement errorлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м•Ңкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” benchmark ecosystem кө¬мЎ°м—җ кҙҖн•ң к°Җм„Өмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң кІҖм •н•ҳкі , мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё benchmark мң лһҳ мЈјмһҘл“Өмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң psychometric frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Open LLM Leaderboardмқҳ 4,000к°ң мқҙмғҒмқҳ modelм—җ Confirmatory Factor AnalysisмҷҖ Generalizability TheoryлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ ranking varianceмқҳ мӣҗмқёмқ„ л¶„н•ҙн•ң кІ°кіј, мқёк°„ кё°м—¬мһҗ(human contributors)к°Җ model architecture(4.8\\%)ліҙлӢӨ лҚ” нҒ° л¶„мӮ°(9\\%)мқ„ м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” benchmark noiseк°Җ model нҠ№м„ұл§ҢнҒјмқҙлӮҳ contributor practiceм—җм„ңлҸ„ л№„лЎҜлҗЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң model sizeмҷҖ лӢӨлҘё confoundлҘј нҶөм ңн•ҳм—¬ scaling lawмқҳ мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•лҸ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” benchmark rankingмқ„ м–ём ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң diagnosticмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳкі , AI evaluation claimмқҳ нғҖлӢ№м„ұмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң measurement frameworkлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65092","en":"A Computational Framework for Evaluating Human-likeness in LLMs' Open-ended Human Behaviors","ko":"LLMмқҳ к°ңл°©нҳ• мқёк°„ н–үлҸҷм—җм„ң мқёк°„лӢӨмӣҖмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң кі„мӮ° н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Yuxuan Lei, Jianxun Lian, Defu Lian, Jincenzi Wu, Tianfu Wang, Xing Xie","pos":"#4404","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=GrFDxJGYW4","abs":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs) have found widespread application and research in scenarios such as role-playing and sociological simulations. Despite the growing use of LLM-based agents to simulate human activities, the extent to which their behaviors resemble human behavior remains underexplored. As diverse LLMs proliferate, the traditional Turing test is ineffective for scalable evaluation and prone to bias from human-crafted challenges, leading to unfair assessments. In this work, we propose a novel distribution-based framework that comprehensively evaluates human-likeness and believability of AI behaviors by leveraging large-scale open-ended human behavior data from web. For better evaluation, we design generic metrics to cover three principles: rationality, consistency, and diversity. Implemented across online shopping, open-topic Q&amp;amp;A, and urban mobility, our framework reveals that even the currently best LLM still exhibits a significant gap from real user behavior, underscoring the necessity of comprehensive research and evaluation of AIвҖҷs human-like capabilities.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs)лҠ” role-playingкіј sociological simulation к°ҷмқҖ мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң нҸӯл„“кІҢ нҷңмҡ©лҗҳкі  м—°кө¬лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мқёк°„ нҷңлҸҷмқ„ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ LLM-based agentмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мқҙ лҠҳкі  мһҲмқҢм—җлҸ„, к·ё н–үлҸҷмқҙ мқёк°„ н–үлҸҷкіј м–јл§ҲлӮҳ мң мӮ¬н•ңм§ҖлҠ” м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң LLMмқҙ proliferateн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, м „нҶөм Ғмқё Turing testлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ нҸүк°Җм—җ л№„нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  мӮ¬лһҢмқҙ л§Ңл“  challengeм—җ мқҳн•ң biasм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳм—¬ кіөм •н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мӣ№м—җм„ң мҲҳм§‘н•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ open-ended human behavior dataлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ AI behaviorмқҳ human-likenessмҷҖ believabilityлҘј нҸ¬кҙ„м ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ distribution-based frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” rationality, consistency, diversityлқјлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ мӣҗм№ҷмқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” general metricмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мҳЁлқјмқё мҮјн•‘, open-topic Q&amp;amp;A, urban mobilityм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ң кІ°кіј, нҳ„мһ¬ к°ҖмһҘ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң LLMмЎ°м°ЁлҸ„ мӢӨм ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ н–үлҸҷкіј м—¬м „нһҲ нҒ° кІ©м°Ёк°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјл©°, AIмқҳ мқёк°„ мң мӮ¬ лҠҘл Ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё м—°кө¬мҷҖ нҸүк°Җмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64409","en":"A Benchmark and Framework for Evaluating Next Action Predictions in Spreadsheets","ko":"мҠӨн”„л Ҳл“ңмӢңнҠём—җм„ң лӢӨмқҢ н–үлҸҷ мҳҲмёЎ нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬ л°Ҹ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Tejas Agrawal, Vu Le, Sumit Gulwani, Gust Verbruggen","pos":"#4406","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=NvPgRwURDC","abs":"<p>Predictive code completion greatly accelerates how quickly developers work. In spreadsheets, despite being much more common, such auto-completion features are virtually non-existent. To address this gap, we introduce a benchmark for systems that observe a sequence of user actions in a spreadsheet and predict future actions. Two challenges are (1) the absence of edit histories in public spreadsheet corpora and (2) the complex space of spreadsheet actions (spatial, temporal, composite). To address (1) we symbolically generate action sequences using parametrized heuristics and refine them (LLM + human) to create 58 sequences consisting of 13K actions from publicly available spreadsheets. To address (2) we propose an online evaluation that expects a prediction after each user action, accepts or rejects that prediction, updates the future actions upon acceptance, and repeats this until the target spreadsheet is obtained. We use LMs as baseline predictive systems and analyze different properties that our benchmark teaches us, including but not limited to: properties of saved actions and false positives, efficiency, effect of user profiles, effect of triggers, effect of context, and effect of prediction length.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҳҲмёЎм Ғ мҪ”л“ң мҷ„м„ұмқҖ к°ңл°ңмһҗк°Җ мһ‘м—…н•ҳлҠ” мҶҚлҸ„лҘј нҒ¬кІҢ лҶ’м—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҠӨн”„л Ҳл“ңмӢңнҠём—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мһҗлҸҷ мҷ„м„ұ кё°лҠҘмқҙ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” нқ”н•Ём—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҠӨн”„л Ҳл“ңмӢңнҠём—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗмқҳ н–үлҸҷ мӢңнҖҖмҠӨлҘј кҙҖм°°н•ҳкі  лҜёлһҳ н–үлҸҷмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ мң„н•ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м—җлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ лҸ„м „ кіјм ңк°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. (1) кіөк°ң мҠӨн”„л Ҳл“ңмӢңнҠё мҪ”нҚјмҠӨм—җ нҺём§‘ мқҙл Ҙмқҙ м—ҶлӢӨлҠ” м җ, (2) мҠӨн”„л Ҳл“ңмӢңнҠё н–үлҸҷмқҳ ліөмһЎн•ң кіөк°„м ҒВ·мӢңк°„м ҒВ·ліөн•©м Ғ лҸҷмһ‘ кіөк°„мқҙлқјлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. (1)мқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л§Өк°ңліҖмҲҳнҷ”лҗң нңҙлҰ¬мҠӨнӢұмңјлЎң н–үлҸҷ мӢңнҖҖмҠӨлҘј кё°нҳём ҒмңјлЎң мғқм„ұн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј (LLM + мӮ¬лһҢ)мңјлЎң м •м ңн•ҳм—¬, кіөк°ңм ҒмңјлЎң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•ң мҠӨн”„л Ҳл“ңмӢңнҠёлЎңл¶Җн„° 13Kк°ңмқҳ н–үлҸҷмңјлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ 58к°ң мӢңнҖҖмҠӨлҘј л§Ңл“Өм—ҲлӢӨ. (2)лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ н–үлҸҷ мқҙнӣ„ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ кё°лҢҖн•ҳкі , к·ё мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мҲҳлқҪ лҳҗлҠ” кұ°м Ҳн•ҳл©°, мҲҳлқҪ мӢң лҜёлһҳ н–үлҸҷмқ„ к°ұмӢ н•ҳкі , лӘ©н‘ң мҠӨн”„л Ҳл“ңмӢңнҠёлҘј м–»мқ„ л•Ңк№Ңм§Җ мқҙлҘј л°ҳліөн•ҳлҠ” мҳЁлқјмқё нҸүк°ҖлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LMsлҘј кё°мӨҖ мҳҲмёЎ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі , мҡ°лҰ¬ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬к°Җ м•Ңл ӨмЈјлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң мҶҚм„ұмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м—җлҠ” м ҖмһҘлҗң н–үлҸҷкіј false positiveмқҳ нҠ№м„ұ, нҡЁмңЁм„ұ, мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ н”„лЎңн•„мқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙ, нҠёлҰ¬кұ°мқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙ, м»Ён…ҚмҠӨнҠёмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙ, мҳҲмёЎ кёёмқҙмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙ л“ұмқҙ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗҳм§Җл§Ң мқҙм—җ н•ңм •лҗҳм§ҖлҠ” м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60997","en":"CLAM-Bench: Benchmarking LLM Agents for Library-Scale Cross-Architecture Migration","ko":"CLAM-Bench: лқјмқҙлёҢлҹ¬лҰ¬ к·ңлӘЁ Cross-Architecture Migrationмқ„ мң„н•ң LLM Agent лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№","authors":"Weijia Li, KE GAO, Jiajie Li, Han Sun, Yuhe Ding, Yongdong Mai, Yiran Le, Yongjie Qian, Zhibin Zhang, Xinyu Wang, Limin Cheng, Shouxu Kuang, Pengfei Chen, Ling Li","pos":"#4408","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=uhSqCIVc0B","abs":"<p>Cross-architecture migration of high-performance libraries dictates ecosystem readiness on emerging hardware. The challenge is twofold: disentangling library-scale dependencies and performance-critical kernels with ISA-specific SIMD intrinsics, often trading migration speed for peak performance.  While LLM-based agents offer a promising approach, are confined to function-level tasks or scalar code, failing to assess agentsвҖҷ capabilities and limitations in realistic, library-scale migration. We present CLAM-Bench (Cross-architecture Library-scale Agent Migration benchmark), featuring 85 critical kernels from widely used libraries, including OpenCV, libjpeg, and NCNN. It supports comprehensive evaluations of compilability, correctness, and performance across major transitions: ARMвҶ’RISC-V, x86вҶ’ARM, and ARMвҶ’LoongArch. Evaluation of 12 SOTA agent-LLM combinations on CLAM-Bench reveals that, due to the lack of library-level navigation and hardware-aware optimization, agents regress to superficial pattern matching, yielding only 20.88% correctness and 0.83x speedup for libjpeg.  Motivated by these findings, we further propose FSCM, a multi-agent framework incorporating hardware-aware global reconfiguration and performance optimization. FSCM improves OpenCV correctness to 71%. The benchmark and code are available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/clam_bench-D8EB/.</p>","absKo":"кі м„ұлҠҘ libraryмқҳ cross-architecture migrationмқҖ emerging hardwareм—җм„ңмқҳ ecosystem readinessлҘј мўҢмҡ°н•ңлӢӨ. кіјм ңлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§ҖмқҙлӢӨ. library к·ңлӘЁмқҳ dependencyмҷҖ ISA-specific SIMD intrinsicмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” performance-critical kernelмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҙ лӮҙлҠ” мқј, к·ёлҰ¬кі  peak performanceлҘј мң„н•ҙ migration мҶҚлҸ„лҘј нқ¬мғқн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҙлӢӨ. LLM кё°л°ҳ agentк°Җ мң л§қн•ң м ‘к·јмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, function-level taskлӮҳ scalar codeм—җ көӯн•ңлҗҳм–ҙ мӢӨм ң library к·ңлӘЁ migrationм—җм„ң agentмқҳ лҠҘл Ҙкіј н•ңкі„лҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CLAM-Bench(Cross-architecture Library-scale Agent Migration benchmark)лҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, OpenCV, libjpeg, NCNNмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” libraryм—җм„ң 85к°ңмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ kernelмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң ARMвҶ’RISC-V, x86вҶ’ARM, ARMвҶ’LoongArchлқјлҠ” мЈјмҡ” м „нҷҳ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң compilability, correctness, performanceлҘј нҸ¬кҙ„м ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. CLAM-Benchм—җм„ң 12к°ңмқҳ SOTA agent-LLM мЎ°н•©мқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, library-level navigationкіј hardware-aware optimizationмқҳ л¶Җмһ¬лЎң мқён•ҙ agentлҠ” н”јмғҒм Ғмқё pattern matchingмңјлЎң нҮҙн–үн•ҳл©°, libjpegм—җм„ң correctness 20.88%мҷҖ speedup 0.83xл§Ңмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјм—җ м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” hardware-aware global reconfigurationкіј performance optimizationмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” multi-agent frameworkмқё FSCMмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. FSCMмқҖ OpenCV correctnessлҘј 71%к№Ңм§Җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. benchmarkмҷҖ codeлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/clam_bench-D8EB/ м—җм„ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•ҳлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64961","en":"DEER: A Benchmark for Evaluating Deep Research Agents on Expert Report Generation","ko":"DEER: м „л¬ёк°Җ ліҙкі м„ң мғқм„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң Deep Research Agent нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Janghoon Han, Heegyu Kim, Changho Lee, Dahm Lee, Min Hyung Park, Hosung Song, Stanley Jungkyu Choi, Moontae Lee, Honglak Lee","pos":"#4410","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ILRx5neJk6","abs":"<p>Recent advances in large language models have enabled deep research systems that generate expert-level reports through multi-step reasoning and evidence-based synthesis. However, evaluating such reports remains challenging: report quality is multifaceted, making it difficult to determine what to assess and by what criteria; LLM-based judges may miss errors that require domain expertise to identify; and because deep research relies on retrieved evidence, report-wide claim verification is also necessary. To address these issues, we propose DEER, a benchmark for evaluating expert-level deep research reports. DEER systematizes evaluation criteria with an expert-developed taxonomy (7 dimensions, 25 subdimensions) operationalized as 101 fine-grained rubric items. We also provide task-specific Expert Evaluation Guidance to support LLM-based judging. Alongside rubric-based assessment, we propose a claim verification architecture that verifies both cited and uncited claims and quantifies evidence quality. Experiments show that while current deep research systems can produce structurally plausible reports that cite external evidence, there is room for improvement in fulfilling expert-level user requests and achieving logical completeness. Beyond simple performance comparisons, DEER makes system strengths and limitations interpretable and provides diagnostic signals for improvement.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј large language modelмқҳ л°ңм „мқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ лӢЁкі„мқҳ reasoningкіј evidence-based synthesisлҘј нҶөн•ҙ expert-level reportлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” deep research systemмқҳ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ л¶Җк°ҒмӢңмј°лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң reportлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. report qualityлҠ” лӢӨл©ҙм Ғмқҙм–ҙм„ң л¬ҙм—Үмқ„ м–ҙл–Ө кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ”м§Җ кІ°м •н•ҳкё° м–ҙл өкі , LLM-based judgeлҠ” domain expertiseк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҙ мӢқлі„н•ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ мҳӨлҘҳлҘј лҶ“м№  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, deep researchлҠ” retrieved evidenceм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ report м „мІҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң claim verificationлҸ„ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” expert-level deep research reportлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң benchmarkмқё DEERлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. DEERлҠ” expertк°Җ к°ңл°ңн•ң taxonomy(7к°ң dimension, 25к°ң subdimension)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ нҸүк°Җ кё°мӨҖмқ„ мІҙкі„нҷ”н•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј 101к°ңмқҳ fine-grained rubric itemмңјлЎң кө¬нҳ„н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң LLM-based judgingмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң task-specific Expert Evaluation GuidanceлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. rubric-based assessmentмҷҖ лҚ”л¶Ҳм–ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” cited claimкіј uncited claimмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкі  evidence qualityлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” claim verification architectureлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ deep research systemмқҙ мҷёл¶Җ evidenceлҘј мқёмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•ң reportлҘј мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳлҠ” мһҲм§Җл§Ң, expert-level user requestлҘј м¶©мЎұн•ҳкі  logical completenessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ к°ңм„ мқҳ м—¬м§Җк°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лӢЁмҲңн•ң м„ұлҠҘ л№„көҗлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ, DEERлҠ” systemмқҳ к°•м җкіј н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өкі  к°ңм„ мқ„ мң„н•ң м§„лӢЁ мӢ нҳёлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62882","en":"Do Text Edits Generalize to Visual Generation? Benchmarking Cross-Modal Knowledge Editing in UMMs","ko":"н…ҚмҠӨнҠё нҺём§‘мқҖ мӢңк°Ғ мғқм„ұмңјлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗҳлҠ”к°Җ? UMMsмқҳ нҒ¬лЎңмҠӨлӘЁлӢ¬ м§ҖмӢқ нҺём§‘ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№","authors":"Xin Gao, Cheng Yang, Chufan Shi, Taylor Berg-Kirkpatrick","pos":"#4411","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cGqHvj7Q3B","abs":"<p>Unified multimodal models (UMMs) emerge as a promising paradigm for general-purpose multimodal intelligence. As they are deployed in real-world applications, effectively updating internal knowledge becomes critical. While knowledge editing methods have matured for text-only models, a fundamental question remains unexplored: do knowledge edits that successfully modify textual outputs transfer to image generation for UMMs?  To this end, we introduce UniKE, the first benchmark for cross-modality knowledge editing in UMMs, comprising 3,005 instances across attribute edits and relation edits. We propose an automated VQA-based evaluation protocol to assess factual consistency between edited knowledge and generated images. Our evaluation reveals a striking modality gap: parameter-editing methods achieving high text-side efficacy (up to 93\\%) fail to produce visual changes, with VQA accuracy below 6\\% under direct generation. We propose Reasoning-augmented Parameter Editing, which explicitly activates edited knowledge before generation, improving visual verification to 10-27\\% for attributes. Through mechanistic analysis, we identify the root cause: edit-affected pathways exhibit near-random overlap with visual attribute-conditioning channels, indicating a fundamental pathway mismatch. These findings demonstrate that textual knowledge edits do not guarantee cross-modality transfer, motivating future work on modality-aware editing methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Unified multimodal model (UMM)мқҖ лІ”мҡ© multimodal intelligenceлҘј мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң л– мҳӨлҘҙкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙл“Өмқҙ мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җ л°°нҸ¬лҗЁм—җ л”°лқј лӮҙл¶Җ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң к°ұмӢ н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҙм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. text-only modelм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” knowledge editing л°©лІ•мқҙ м„ұмҲҷн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·јліём Ғмқё м§Ҳл¬ё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” м•„м§Ғ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. textual outputмқ„ м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳм •н•ҳлҠ” knowledge editк°Җ UMMм—җм„ң image generationмңјлЎңлҸ„ м „лӢ¬лҗҳлҠ”к°Җ? мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” UMMм—җм„ң cross-modality knowledge editingмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” мІ« лІҲм§ё benchmarkмқё UniKEлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ benchmarkлҠ” attribute editмҷҖ relation editмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң 3,005к°ң мқёмҠӨн„ҙмҠӨлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҺём§‘лҗң м§ҖмӢқкіј мғқм„ұлҗң мқҙлҜём§Җ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мӮ¬мӢӨм Ғ мқјкҙҖм„ұмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мһҗлҸҷнҷ”лҗң VQA кё°л°ҳ нҸүк°Җ н”„лЎңнҶ мҪңмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” лҶҖлқјмҡҙ modality gapмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. text мёЎ нҡЁмҡ©мқҙ лҶ’кІҢ лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” parameter-editing л°©лІ•л“Ө(мөңлҢҖ 93\\%)мқҖ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ ліҖнҷ”лҘј л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ лӮҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳл©°, direct generationм—җм„ң VQA accuracyлҠ” 6\\% лҜёл§Ңм—җ лЁёл¬ёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Reasoning-augmented Parameter Editingмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мғқм„ұ м „м—җ нҺём§‘лҗң м§ҖмӢқмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ attributeм—җ лҢҖн•ң visual verificationмқ„ 10-27\\%к№Ңм§Җ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. кё°кі„лЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к·јліё мӣҗмқёмқ„ мӢқлі„н–ҲлӢӨ. editмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л°ӣлҠ” pathwayлҠ” visual attribute-conditioning channelкіј кұ°мқҳ л¬ҙмһ‘мң„ мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ overlapмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё pathway mismatchлҘј мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” textual knowledge editк°Җ cross-modality transferлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјл©°, modality-aware editing methodм—җ лҢҖн•ң н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬лҘј мҙүм§„н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61347","en":"Leaderboard Incentives: Model Rankings under Strategic Post-Training","ko":"Leaderboard Incentives: м „лһөм Ғ Post-Training н•ҳмқҳ лӘЁлҚё мҲңмң„","authors":"Yatong Chen, Guanhua Zhang, Moritz Hardt","pos":"#4413","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=r6wfuAKmVb","abs":"<p>Influential benchmarks incentivize competing model builders to strategically allocate post-training resources towards improvements on the leaderboard, a phenomenon dubbed \\emph{benchmaxxing} or \\emph{training on the test task}. In this work, we initiate a principled study of the incentive structure that benchmarks induce. We model benchmarking as a Stackelberg game between a benchmark designer who chooses an evaluation protocol and multiple model providers who compete simultaneously in a subgame given by the designerвҖҷs choice. Each competitor has a model of unknown latent quality and can inflate its observed score by allocating resources to benchmark-specific improvements. First, we prove that current benchmarks induce games for which no Nash equilibrium between model developers exists. This result suggests one explanation for why current practice leads to misaligned incentives, prompting model providers to strategize in opaque ways. However, we prove that under mild conditions, a recently proposed evaluation protocol, called tune-before-test, induces a benchmark with a unique Nash equilibrium that ranks models by latent quality. This positive result demonstrates that benchmarks need not set bad incentives, even if current evaluations do.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҳҒн–Ҙл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” benchmarkлҠ” кІҪмҹҒн•ҳлҠ” лӘЁлҚё к°ңл°ңмһҗл“Өмқҙ leaderboard к°ңм„ мқ„ мң„н•ҙ post-training мһҗмӣҗмқ„ м „лһөм ҒмңјлЎң л°°л¶„н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳл©°, мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқҖ \\emph{benchmaxxing} лҳҗлҠ” \\emph{training on the test task}лЎң л¶ҲлҰ°лӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” benchmarkк°Җ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” incentive structureлҘј мӣҗлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” benchmarkingмқ„ benchmark designerк°Җ evaluation protocolмқ„ м„ нғқн•ҳкі , м—¬лҹ¬ model providerк°Җ designerмқҳ м„ нғқм—җ л”°лқј нҳ•м„ұлҗң subgameм—җм„ң лҸҷмӢңм—җ кІҪмҹҒн•ҳлҠ” Stackelberg gameмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. к°Ғ кІҪмҹҒмһҗлҠ” м•Ңл Өм§Җм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ latent qualityлҘј к°Җм§„ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ ліҙмң н•ҳл©°, benchmark-specific improvementм—җ мһҗмӣҗмқ„ н• лӢ№н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ кҙҖмёЎлҗң scoreлҘј л¶Җн’ҖлҰҙ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ benchmarkк°Җ model developer мӮ¬мқҙм—җ Nash equilibriumмқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” кІҢмһ„мқ„ мң лҸ„н•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ кҙҖн–үмқҙ мҷң мһҳлӘ» м •л ¬лҗң incentiveлҘј лӮілҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•ң к°Җм§Җ м„ӨлӘ…мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, model providerк°Җ л¶ҲнҲ¬лӘ…н•ң л°©мӢқмңјлЎң м „лһөмқ„ м„ёмҡ°лҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” mild condition н•ҳм—җм„ң, tune-before-testлқјкі  л¶ҲлҰ¬лҠ” мөңк·ј м ңм•Ҳлҗң evaluation protocolмқҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ latent quality мҲңмңјлЎң м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” мң мқјн•ң Nash equilibriumмқ„ к°–лҠ” benchmarkлҘј мң лҸ„н•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кёҚм •м Ғ кІ°кіјлҠ”, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ evaluationмқҙ к·ёлҹ¬н•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ benchmarkк°Җ л°ҳл“ңмӢң лӮҳмҒң incentiveлҘј м„Өм •н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м•„лӢҳмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61844","en":"Neuromem: A Granular Decomposition of the Streaming Lifecycle in External Memory for LLMs","ko":"Neuromem: LLM мҷёл¶Җ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬м—җм„ң Streaming Lifecycleмқҳ м„ёл¶„нҷ”лҗң л¶„н•ҙ","authors":"Ruicheng Zhang, Xinyi Li, Tianyi Xu, Shuhao Zhang, Xiaofei Liao, Hai Jin","pos":"#4414","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mO7DgwFFVe","abs":"<p>Most evaluations of External Memory Module assume a static setting: memory is built offline and queried at a fixed state. In practice, memory is streaming: new facts arrive continuously, insertions interleave with retrievals, and the memory state evolves while the model is serving queries. In this regime, accuracy and cost are governed by the full memory lifecycle, which encompasses the ingestion, maintenance, retrieval, and integration of information into generation. We present Neuromem, a scalable testbed that benchmarks External Memory Module under an interleaved insertion-and-retrieval protocol and decomposes its lifecycle into five dimensions including memory data structure, normalization strategy, consolidation policy, query formulation strategy, and context integration mechanism. Using three representative datasets LoCoMo, LONGMEMEVAL, and MemAgentBench, Neuromem evaluates interchangeable variants within a shared serving stack, reporting token-level F1 and insertion/retrieval latency.Overall, we observe that performance typically degrades as memory grows across rounds, and time-related queries remain the most challenging category. The memory data structure largely determines the attainable quality frontier, while aggressive compression and generative integration mechanisms mostly shift cost between insertion and retrieval with limited accuracy gain.</p>","absKo":"<p>External Memory Moduleм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” static settingмқ„ к°Җм •н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, memoryлҠ” offlineмңјлЎң кө¬м¶•лҗҳкі  кі м •лҗң мғҒнғңм—җм„ң мЎ°нҡҢлҗңлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” memoryк°Җ streamingлҗңлӢӨ. мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мӮ¬мӢӨмқҙ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң лҸ„м°©н•ҳкі , insertionмқҖ retrievalкіј көҗм°Ён•ҳл©°, лӘЁлҚёмқҙ queryлҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷм•Ҳ memory stateлҠ” м§„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң regimeм—җм„ң м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ л№„мҡ©мқҖ ingestion, maintenance, retrieval, к·ёлҰ¬кі  м •ліҙлҘј generationм—җ нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” кіјм •мқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳлҠ” м „мІҙ memory lifecycleм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кІ°м •лҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” interleaved insertion-and-retrieval protocol н•ҳм—җм„ң External Memory Moduleмқ„ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№н•ҳкі , memory data structure, normalization strategy, consolidation policy, query formulation strategy, context integration mechanismмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм„Ҝ к°Җм§Җ м°ЁмӣҗмңјлЎң lifecycleмқ„ л¶„н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң testbedмқё Neuromemмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. LoCoMo, LONGMEMEVAL, MemAgentBenchмқҳ м„ё лҢҖн‘ң datasetмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, NeuromemмқҖ кіөмң  serving stack лӮҙм—җм„ң көҗмІҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң variantл“Өмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі  token-level F1кіј insertion/retrieval latencyлҘј ліҙкі н•ңлӢӨ. м „л°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, memoryк°Җ roundлҘј кұ°м№ҳл©° м»Өм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м Җн•ҳлҗҳкі , мӢңк°„ кҙҖл Ё queryк°Җ к°ҖмһҘ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ лІ”мЈјлЎң лӮЁлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ңлӢӨ. memory data structureлҠ” лӢ¬м„ұ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң quality frontierлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ кІ°м •н•ҳл©°, aggressive compressionкіј generative integration mechanismмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң insertionкіј retrieval мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ л№„мҡ©л§Ң мқҙлҸҷмӢңнӮ¬ лҝҗ accuracy н–ҘмғҒмқҖ м ңн•ңм ҒмқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67149","en":"Position: There are futures that benchmark-driven AI cannot see","ko":"Position: лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬ мЈјлҸ„ AIк°Җ ліј мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” лҜёлһҳк°Җ мһҲлӢӨ","authors":"Sobhan Lotfi, Ava Iranmanesh, Lachin Naghashyar, Ali Shirali, Fateme Haredasht, Sanmi Koyejo, Phil Torr, Yong Suk Lee, Fazl Barez, Joel Lehman, Peter Norvig, Arvind Narayanan","pos":"#4610","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RzWlUbmRJi","abs":"<p>Breakthroughs often come from ideas we could not have predicted in advance. In biology, this is called exaptation: traits evolved for one function become decisive for another. Scientific progress works similarly, but only if ideas survive periods when they appear uncompetitive by current metrics. This position paper argues that AI's benchmark-centered selection environment, while successful at bypassing complex debates about the nature of intelligence, taxes exaptation. When one selection rule dominates, ideas that do not fit it have nowhere to persist.  The cost grows acute as the field shifts from asking can machines exhibit intelligent behavior? to asking can machines exhibit intelligent behavior such that they are aligned, interpretable, and safe? These are philosophically distinct questions that may require discoveries that we cannot specify. We propose mechanisms to restore exaptive capacity without abandoning benchmarking: plural evaluation regimes, protected venues for non-comparable work, long-horizon funding, and training norms that encourage researchers to question selection rules, not only optimize within them.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҡҚкё°м Ғмқё м§„м „мқҖ мў…мў… мӮ¬м „м—җ мҳҲмёЎн•  мҲҳ м—Ҷм—ҲлҚҳ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙм—җм„ң лӮҳмҳЁлӢӨ. мғқл¬јн•ҷм—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҘј exaptationмқҙлқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙл©°, мӣҗлһҳ н•ң кё°лҠҘмқ„ мң„н•ҙ м§„нҷ”н•ң нҳ•м§Ҳмқҙ лӢӨлҘё кё°лҠҘм—җм„ң кІ°м •м Ғ м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ҳкІҢ лҗҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. кіјн•ҷм Ғ м§„ліҙлҸ„ л§Ҳм°¬к°Җм§Җм§Җл§Ң, м•„мқҙл””м–ҙк°Җ нҳ„мһ¬ metricмғҒ л№„кІҪмҹҒм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмқҙлҠ” кё°к°„мқ„ кІ¬лҺҢлӮј мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙм•јл§Ң к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё position paperлҠ” AIмқҳ benchmark мӨ‘мӢ¬ м„ нғқ нҷҳкІҪмқҙ м§ҖлҠҘмқҳ ліём§Ҳм—җ лҢҖн•ң ліөмһЎн•ң л…јмҹҒмқ„ мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°лҠ” м„ұкіөн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, exaptationм—җлҠ” м„ёкёҲмқ„ л¶Җкіјн•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ м„ нғқ к·ңм№ҷмқҙ м§Җл°°м Ғмқҙл©ҙ, к·ё к·ңм№ҷм—җ л§һм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҠ” м§ҖмҶҚлҗ  кіөк°„мқҙ м—ҶлӢӨ. к·ё л№„мҡ©мқҖ мқҙ л¶„м•јк°Җ \"кё°кі„к°Җ intelligent behaviorлҘј ліҙмқј мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ?\"лқјлҠ” м§Ҳл¬ём—җм„ң \"кё°кі„к°Җ aligned, interpretable, safe н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ intelligent behaviorлҘј ліҙмқј мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ?\"лқјлҠ” м§Ҳл¬ёмңјлЎң мқҙлҸҷн• мҲҳлЎқ лҚ”мҡұ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙ м§Ҳл¬ёл“ӨмқҖ мІ н•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬лі„лҗҳл©°, лӘ…мӢңн•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” л°ңкІ¬мқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” benchmarkingмқ„ нҸ¬кё°н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң exaptive capacityлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмңјлЎң лӢӨмӣҗм Ғ evaluation regime, л№„көҗ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң мһ‘м—…мқ„ мң„н•ң ліҙнҳёлҗң venue, мһҘкё° horizonмқҳ funding, к·ёлҰ¬кі  м—°кө¬мһҗл“Өмқҙ м„ нғқ к·ңм№ҷ мһҗмІҙлҘј мқҳл¬ёмӢңн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мһҘл Өн•ҳлҠ” training normмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61780","en":"VocSim A Training-free Benchmark for Zero-shot Content Identity in Single-source Audio","ko":"VocSim: лӢЁмқј мҶҢмҠӨ мҳӨл””мҳӨм—җм„ң Zero-Shot Content IdentityлҘј мң„н•ң Training-Free Benchmark","authors":"Maris Basha, Anja T. Zai, Sabine Stoll, Richard Hahnloser","pos":"#4409","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=n2C8pTqtvB","abs":"<p>General-purpose audio representations aim to map acoustically variable instances of the same event to nearby points, resolving content identity in a zero-shot setting. Unlike supervised classification benchmarks that measure adaptability via parameter updates, we introduce VocSim, a training-free benchmark probing the intrinsic geometric alignment of frozen embeddings. VocSim aggregates 125k single-source clips from 19 corpora spanning human speech, animal vocalizations, and environmental sounds. By restricting to single-source audio, we isolate content representation from the confound of source separation. We evaluate embeddings using Precision@k for local purity and the Global Separation Rate (GSR) for point-wise class separation. To calibrate GSR, we report lift over an empirical permutation baseline. Across diverse foundation models, a simple pipeline, frozen Whisper encoder features, timeвҖ“frequency pooling, and label-free PCA, yields strong zero-shot performance. However, VocSim also uncovers a consistent generalization gap. On blind, low-resource speech, local retrieval drops sharply. While performance remains statistically distinguishable from chance, the absolute geometric structure collapses, indicating a failure to generalize to unseen phonotactics. As external validation, our top embeddings predict avian perceptual similarity, improve bioacoustic classification, and achieve state-of-the-art results on the HEAR benchmark. We posit that the intrinsic geometric quality measured here proxies utility in unlisted downstream applications. We release data, code, and a public leaderboard to standardize the evaluation of intrinsic audio geometry.</p>","absKo":"<p>General-purpose audio representationмқҳ лӘ©н‘ңлҠ” мқҢн–Ҙм ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨм–‘н•ң лҸҷмқј eventмқҳ мқёмҠӨн„ҙмҠӨлҘј м„ңлЎң к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ м җл“Өм—җ л§Өн•‘н•ҳм—¬, zero-shot settingм—җм„ң content identityлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. parameter updateлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м Ғмқ‘м„ұмқ„ мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” supervised classification benchmarkмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” frozen embeddingмқҳ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ м •л ¬мқ„ нғҗкө¬н•ҳлҠ” training-free benchmarkмқё VocSimмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. VocSimмқҖ human speech, animal vocalization, environmental soundлҘј м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” 19к°ң corpusм—җм„ң м¶”м¶ңн•ң 12л§Ң 5мІң к°ңмқҳ single-source clipмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. single-source audioлЎң м ңн•ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ source separationмқҙлқјлҠ” нҳјлһҖ мҡ”мқём—җм„ң content representationмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” local purityлҘј мң„н•ң Precision@kмҷҖ point-wise class separationмқ„ мң„н•ң Global Separation Rate (GSR)лЎң embeddingмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. GSRлҘј ліҙм •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ empirical permutation baseline лҢҖл№„ liftлҘј ліҙкі н•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң foundation model м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, к°„лӢЁн•ң pipelineмқё frozen Whisper encoder feature, timeвҖ“frequency pooling, label-free PCAк°Җ к°•л Ҙн•ң zero-shot м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ VocSimмқҖ мқјкҙҖлҗң generalization gapлҸ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. blind low-resource speechм—җм„ңлҠ” local retrievalмқҙ кёүкІ©нһҲ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. м„ұлҠҘмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ chanceмҷҖ нҶөкі„м ҒмңјлЎң кө¬л¶„лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, м ҲлҢҖм Ғмқё geometric structureлҠ” л¶•кҙҙн•ҳм—¬ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң phonotacticsлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҷёл¶Җ кІҖмҰқмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мөңкі  embeddingмқҖ avian perceptual similarityлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳкі  bioacoustic classificationмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, HEAR benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—¬кё°м„ң мёЎм •н•ң intrinsic geometric qualityк°Җ лҜёлҰ¬ лӘ…мӢңлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ downstream applicationм—җм„ңмқҳ utilityлҘј лҢҖлҰ¬н•ңлӢӨкі  ліёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” intrinsic audio geometry нҸүк°ҖлҘј н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ data, code, public leaderboardлҘј кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60776","en":"Rethinking Loss Reweighting for Imbalance Learning as an Inverse Problem: A Neural Collapse Point of View","ko":"Imbalance Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң Loss Reweightingмқ„ м—ӯл¬ём ңлЎң мһ¬кі : Neural Collapse кҙҖм җ","authors":"Jinping Wang, Zixin Tong, Zhiwu Xie, Zhiqiang Gao","pos":"#4210","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=woBaLURRlx","abs":"<p>Loss reweighting is a widely used strategy for long-tailed classification, but existing reweighting strategies often rely on heuristics and rarely define a well-specified target. Inspired by Neural Collapse (NC), the ideal simplex Equiangular Tight Frame (ETF) terminal geometry suggests equal per-class average loss as a reasonable target for reweighting. Based on the ideal equal loss objective, we consider loss reweighting as an inverse problem and propose an inverse-view reweighting strategy that infers class weights dynamically to match this ideal objective.  Empirically, NC metrics suggest our method can effectively reduce the loss imbalance coefficient and closer alignment with NC geometry while consistently outperforms strong long-tailed baselines on different datasets.</p>","absKo":"Loss reweightingмқҖ long-tailed classificationм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” м „лһөмқҙм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ reweighting м „лһөмқҖ мў…мў… heuristicм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©° мһҳ м •мқҳлҗң targetмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. Neural Collapse (NC)м—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ м–»мңјл©ҙ, ideal simplex Equiangular Tight Frame (ETF) terminal geometryлҠ” classлі„ нҸүк·  lossк°Җ к°ҷм•„м•ј н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ reweightingмқҳ н•©лҰ¬м Ғмқё лӘ©н‘ңлЎң мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң ideal equal loss objectiveм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” loss reweightingмқ„ inverse problemмңјлЎң к°„мЈјн•ҳкі , мқҙ мқҙмғҒм Ғмқё objectiveм—җ л§һм¶”кё° мң„н•ҙ class weightлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м¶”лЎ н•ҳлҠ” inverse-view reweighting м „лһөмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кІҪн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң NC metricмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ loss imbalance coefficientлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мӨ„мқҙкі  NC geometryмҷҖ лҚ” к°Җк№қкІҢ м •л ¬лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҳл©°, лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң long-tailed baselineліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61044","en":"Demystifying Mergeability: Interpretable Properties to Predict Model Merging Success","ko":"Mergeability н•ҙл¶Җ: лӘЁлҚё лі‘н•© м„ұкіөмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҠ№м„ұ","authors":"Luca Zhou, Bo Zhao, Rose Yu, Emanuele RodolГ ","pos":"#2913","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=uFQwehcepH","abs":"Model merging combines knowledge from separately fine-tuned models, yet success factors remain poorly understood. While recent work treats mergeability as an intrinsic property, we show with an architecture-agnostic framework that it fundamentally depends on both the merging method and the partner tasks. Using linear optimization over a set of interpretable pairwise metrics (e.g., gradient $L_2$ distance), we uncover properties correlating with post-merge performance across four merging methods. We find substantial variation in success drivers (46.7\\% metric overlap; 55.3\\% sign agreement), revealing method-specific \"fingerprints\". Crucially, however, \\textit{subspace overlap} and \\textit{gradient alignment} metrics consistently emerge as foundational, method-agnostic prerequisites for compatibility. These findings provide a diagnostic foundation for understanding mergeability and motivate future fine-tuning strategies that explicitly encourage these properties.","absKo":"Model mergingмқҖ лі„лҸ„лЎң fine-tuneлҗң modelл“Өмқҳ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, м„ұкіө мҡ”мқёмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” mergeabilityлҘј лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ мҶҚм„ұмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈЁм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” architecture-agnostic frameworkлҘј нҶөн•ҙ к·ёкІғмқҙ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң merging methodмҷҖ partner task лӘЁл‘җм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мҢҚлі„ metric м§‘н•©(мҳҲ: gradient $L_2$ distance)м—җ лҢҖн•ң linear optimizationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л„Ө к°Җм§Җ merging method м „л°ҳм—җм„ң post-merge performanceмҷҖ мғҒкҙҖлҗҳлҠ” нҠ№м„ұл“Өмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ұкіөмқ„ мқҙлҒ„лҠ” мҡ”мқём—җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң м°Ёмқҙк°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ нҷ•мқён–Ҳмңјл©°(46.7\\% metric overlap; 55.3\\% sign agreement), method-specific \"fingerprint\"лҘј л“ңлҹ¬лғҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң, \\textit{subspace overlap}кіј \\textit{gradient alignment} metricмқҖ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ compatibilityмқҳ кё°мҙҲм Ғмқё, method-agnostic prerequisiteлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮ¬лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°ңкІ¬мқҖ mergeabilityлҘј мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң м§„лӢЁм Ғ нҶ лҢҖлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҶҚм„ұмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мһҘл Өн•ҳлҠ” н–Ҙнӣ„ fine-tuning м „лһөмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"62384","en":"Breaking the Scale Barrier: One-Shot Knowledge Transfer via Frequency Transform","ko":"к·ңлӘЁ мһҘлІҪ лҸҢнҢҢ: Frequency Transform кё°л°ҳ One-Shot Knowledge Transfer","authors":"Jianlu Shen, Fu Feng, Yucheng Xie, JIAQI LYU, Xin Geng","pos":"#3506","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=h6xWMCDjo0","abs":"Transferring knowledge by fine-tuning large-scale pre-trained networks has become a standard paradigm for downstream tasks, yet the knowledge of a pre-trained model is tightly coupled with monolithic architecture, which restricts flexible reuse across models of varying scales. In response to this challenge, recent approaches typically resort to either parameter selection, which fails to capture the interdependent structure of this knowledge, or parameter prediction using generative models that depend on impractical access to large network collections.  In this paper, we identify the low-frequency components of model weights as the concrete carrier of foundational, task-agnostic knowledgeвҖ”its \"learngene\"вҖ”and validate this by demonstrating its efficient inheritance by downstream models and tasks. Based on this insight, we propose FRONT (FRequency dOmain kNowledge Transfer), a novel framework that uses the Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT) to isolate the low-frequency \"learngene\". This learngene can be seamlessly adapted to initialize models of arbitrary size via simple truncation or padding, a process that is entirely training-free.  For enhanced performance, we propose an optional low-cost refinement process that introduces a spectral regularizer to further improve the learngene's transferability. Extensive experiments demonstrate that FRONT achieves the state-of-the-art performance, accelerates convergence by up to $15\\times$ in vision tasks, and reduces training FLOPs by an average of 40.5\\% in language tasks.","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ pretrained networkлҘј fine-tuningн•ҳм—¬ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ transferн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ downstream taskлҘј мң„н•ң н‘ңмӨҖ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙ лҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, pretrained modelмқҳ м§ҖмӢқмқҖ monolithic architectureмҷҖ к°•н•ҳкІҢ кІ°н•©лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм–ҙ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё scaleмқҳ model к°„ мң м—°н•ң мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳм—¬ мөңк·ј м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ ліҙнҶө л‘җ к°Җм§ҖлЎң лӮҳлүңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” parameter selectionмңјлЎң, мқҙ м§ҖмӢқмқҳ мғҒнҳёмқҳмЎҙм Ғ кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” large network м§‘н•©м—җ лҢҖн•ң л№„нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё м ‘к·јм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” generative model кё°л°ҳ parameter predictionмқҙлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” model weightмқҳ low-frequency componentк°Җ foundationalн•ҳл©° task-agnosticн•ң м§ҖмӢқ, мҰү к·ёл“Өмқҳ \"learngene\"мқ„ лӢҙлҠ” кө¬мІҙм Ғ л§Өк°ңмІҙмһ„мқ„ к·ңлӘ…н•ҳкі , downstream modelкіј taskк°Җ мқҙлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң inheritanceн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмһ„мңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FRONT (FRequency dOmain kNowledge Transfer)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” Discrete Cosine Transform (DCT)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ low-frequency \"learngene\"мқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ learngeneмқҖ лӢЁмҲңн•ң truncation лҳҗлҠ” paddingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м–ҙл– н•ң нҒ¬кё°мқҳ modelм—җлҸ„ л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ м Ғмқ‘лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙ кіјм •мқҖ мҷ„м „нһҲ training-freeмқҙлӢӨ. м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” spectral regularizerлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ learngeneмқҳ transferabilityлҘј лҚ” лҶ’мқҙлҠ” optional low-cost refinement processлҸ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FRONTк°Җ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , vision taskм—җм„ң convergenceлҘј мөңлҢҖ $15\\times$к№Ңм§Җ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳл©°, language taskм—җм„ң training FLOPsлҘј нҸүк·  40.5\\% к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮЁлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"63990","en":"On the Difficulty of Learning a Meta-network for Training Data Selection","ko":"н•ҷмҠө лҚ°мқҙн„° м„ нғқмқ„ мң„н•ң л©”нғҖ л„ӨнҠёмӣҢнҒ¬ н•ҷмҠөмқҳ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖм—җ лҢҖн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Zilin Du, Junqi Zhao, Albert Boyang Li","pos":"#4000","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RzgNmKi5Hw","abs":"<p>Synthetic data are increasingly used to train image classifiers, yet distributional mismatch with real data limits their effectiveness when used indiscriminately. A common strategy is to learn data weights via bi-level optimization, which we refer to as Meta-learning for Training-data Selection (MTS). Interestingly, in practice, MTS often performs below expectation. We identify two obstacles in properly training MTS: a poor gradient signal-to-noise ratio (GSNR), which causes optimization difficulties, and lack of informative features that correlates with data quality. We present a thorough mathematical analysis of MTS, which reveals the dynamics of normalized data weights and the relation between disparate data quality and poor GSNR. The analysis suggests a a simple yet effective solution: increasing the batch size. Further, we propose a set of informative features that capture the positions of training data in their distributions and training dynamics. Experiments across four benchmarks show consistent improvements, achieving average gains of 5.49\\% over training without selection and 2.89\\% over the strongest baseline.</p>","absKo":"<p>Synthetic dataлҠ” image classifier н•ҷмҠөм—җ м җм җ лҚ” л§Һмқҙ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳкі  мһҲм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖмқҳ distribution mismatch л•Ңл¬ём—җ л¬ҙл¶„лі„н•ҳкІҢ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  кІҪмҡ° нҡЁкіјк°Җ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. нқ”н•ң м „лһөмқҖ bi-level optimizationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ data weightлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң, мқҙлҘј Meta-learning for Training-data Selection (MTS)лқјкі  н•ңлӢӨ. нқҘлҜёлЎӯкІҢлҸ„ мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” MTSк°Җ кё°лҢҖ мқҙн•ҳмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MTSлҘј м Ғм ҲнһҲ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мһҘм• л¬јмқҙ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” optimizationмқ„ м–ҙл өкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” poor gradient signal-to-noise ratio (GSNR)мқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” data qualityмҷҖ мғҒкҙҖлҗҳлҠ” informative featureмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MTSм—җ лҢҖн•ң л©ҙл°Җн•ң мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ normalized data weightмқҳ dynamicsмҷҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё data quality л°Ҹ poor GSNR мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ кҙҖкі„лҘј л°қнһҢлӢӨ. мқҙ л¶„м„қмқҖ к°„лӢЁн•ҳм§Җл§Ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё н•ҙкІ°мұ…, мҰү batch sizeлҘј лҠҳлҰ¬лҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” training dataк°Җ л¶„нҸ¬ лӮҙм—җм„ң м°Ём§Җн•ҳлҠ” мң„м№ҳмҷҖ training dynamicsлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” informative feature м§‘н•©мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л„Ө к°ңмқҳ benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқјкҙҖлҗң к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, selection м—Ҷмқҙ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ° лҢҖл№„ нҸүк·  5.49\\%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒкіј к°ҖмһҘ к°•л Ҙн•ң baseline лҢҖл№„ 2.89\\%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62921","en":"Segment Anything with Robust Uncertainty-Accuracy Correlation","ko":"к°•кұҙн•ң л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұ-м •нҷ•лҸ„ мғҒкҙҖмқ„ к°–лҠ” Segment Anything","authors":"Hongyou Zhou, Zihan Ye, Ling Shao, Marc Toussaint","pos":"#4001","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bpLE7QFM1a","abs":"<p>Despite strong zero-shot performance, SAM is unreliable under domain shift due to Mask-level Confidence Confusion (MCC), where a single IoU-based mask score fails to reflect pixel-wise reliability near boundaries. Motivated by the contrast between texture-biased shortcuts in neural networks and shape-centric processing in human vision, we model out-of-domain variation as appearance shifts and non-rigid deformations that jointly stress calibration. We propose Segment Anything with Robust Uncertainty-Accuracy Correlation (RUAC) for robust pixel-wise uncertainty estimation under appearance and deformation shifts. RUAC adds a lightweight uncertainty head, trains it with a collaborative style-deformation attack that jointly perturbs texture and geometry, and applies Uncertainty-Error Alignment to ensure uncertainty consistently highlights erroneous pixels even under adversarial perturbations. Across 23 zero-shot domains, RUAC improves segmentation quality and yields more faithful uncertainty with stronger uncertainty-accuracy correlation.</p>","absKo":"к°•л Ҙн•ң zero-shot м„ұлҠҘм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  SAMмқҖ domain shift н•ҳм—җм„ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” Mask-level Confidence Confusion (MCC) л•Ңл¬ём—җ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, IoU кё°л°ҳмқҳ лӢЁмқј mask scoreк°Җ кІҪкі„ к·јмІҳ pixel-wise reliabilityлҘј м ңлҢҖлЎң л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. neural networkмқҳ texture-biased shortcutкіј мқёк°„ мӢңк°Ғмқҳ shape-centric processing мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ лҢҖл№„м—җ м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” out-of-domain variationмқ„ calibrationмқ„ лҸҷмӢңм—җ м••л°•н•ҳлҠ” appearance shiftмҷҖ non-rigid deformationмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” appearance л°Ҹ deformation shift н•ҳм—җм„ң robust pixel-wise uncertainty estimationмқ„ мң„н•ң Segment Anything with Robust Uncertainty-Accuracy Correlation (RUAC)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. RUACлҠ” к°ҖлІјмҡҙ uncertainty headлҘј м¶”к°Җн•ҳкі , textureмҷҖ geometryлҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң perturbн•ҳлҠ” collaborative style-deformation attackмңјлЎң мқҙлҘј н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨл©°, Uncertainty-Error AlignmentлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ adversarial perturbation н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ uncertaintyк°Җ мҳӨлҘҳ н”Ҫм…Җмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к°•мЎ°н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. 23к°ңмқҳ zero-shot domain м „л°ҳм—җм„ң RUACлҠ” segmentation qualityлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі  лҚ” к°•н•ң uncertainty-accuracy correlationкіј н•Ёк»ҳ лҚ” м¶©мӢӨн•ң uncertaintyлҘј мӮ°м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63628","en":"Shapley Neuron Values for Continual Learning: Which Neurons Matter Most?","ko":"м§ҖмҶҚ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң Shapley neuron к°’: м–ҙл–Ө лүҙлҹ°мқҙ к°ҖмһҘ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ңк°Җ?","authors":"Ali Vahedifar, Abhisek Ray, Qi Zhang","pos":"#4002","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=VI8rCF97FK","abs":"<p>Continual learning enables neural networks to learn tasks sequentially without forgetting previously acquired knowledge. However, catastrophic forgetting, where performance on earlier tasks degrades sharply when learning new ones, remains a fundamental challenge. We address this problem with Shapley Neuron Valuation (SNV), a principled framework grounded in cooperative game theory that quantifies Neuron importance in continual learning. By selectively freezing important Neurons while keeping others plastic, SNV enables memory-free continual learning without architectural expansion.  Extensive experiments show that SNV delivers substantial gains over memory-free baselines, achieving +19.50% accuracy on CIFAR-100 and +17.20% on TinyImageNet in the Class-IL setting. In Task-IL scenarios, SNV consistently surpasses existing memory-free approaches by large margins, reaching up to 9.08% higher accuracy on CIFAR-100 compared to the second-best memory-free method, while remaining competitive in comparison with memory-based methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Continual learningмқҖ neural networkк°Җ мқҙм „м—җ нҡҚл“қн•ң м§ҖмӢқмқ„ мһҠм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң taskлҘј мҲңм°Ём ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•  л•Ң мқҙм „ taskмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ кёүкІ©нһҲ м Җн•ҳлҗҳлҠ” catastrophic forgettingмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ к·јліём Ғмқё л¬ём ңлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” continual learningм—җм„ң Neuronмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” cooperative game theoryм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё frameworkмқё Shapley Neuron Valuation (SNV)мңјлЎң мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң NeuronмқҖ м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң кі м •н•ҳкі  лӮҳлЁём§ҖлҠ” plasticн•ҳкІҢ мң м§Җн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, SNVлҠ” architecture expansion м—Ҷмқҙ memory-free continual learningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ SNVк°Җ memory-free baseline лҢҖл№„ нҒ° н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, Class-IL м„Өм •м—җм„ң CIFAR-100м—җм„ң +19.50\\%, TinyImageNetм—җм„ң +17.20\\%мқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. Task-IL мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ңлҸ„ SNVлҠ” кё°мЎҙ memory-free м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ нҒ° м°ЁмқҙлЎң мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, CIFAR-100м—җм„ң л‘җ лІҲм§ёлЎң мўӢмқҖ memory-free л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ 9.08\\% лҶ’мқҖ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј кё°лЎқн•ҳлҠ” н•ңнҺё, memory-based л°©лІ•кіј л№„көҗн•ҙлҸ„ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62294","en":"Wasserstein Geometry-Aware Adaptive Control via Meta-Learning","ko":"Meta-Learningмқ„ нҶөн•ң Wasserstein Geometry-Aware Adaptive Control","authors":"Xingyu Yang, Hanzhang Qu, Ye Cao, Jianfu Cao","pos":"#4003","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=huZQpYkeBl","abs":"<p>Adaptive control of nonlinear systems under unknown disturbances requires learning algorithms aligned with the downstream control objective. While control-oriented meta-learning addresses the mismatch between regression-based identification and tracking performance, existing methods rely on Euclidean or static algebraic geometries that fail to capture the distributional structure of system uncertainties. We propose a framework that lifts adaptation into Wasserstein space, measuring parameter estimation errors as the optimal transport cost between estimated and true system behaviors. By constructing a Wasserstein Bregman divergence over representative task distributions, we use meta-learning to jointly optimize nonlinear feature representations, control gains, and transport geometry. This adaptation law learns an adaptation geometry that captures structural properties of the underlying physical system, implementing a physically grounded, data-driven attention mechanism. Closed-loop tracking simulations demonstrate that our controller achieves optimal performance on both fully-actuated and underactuated nonlinear planar rotorcraft, maintaining robustness under significant distributional shifts between training and testing conditions.</p>","absKo":"<p>unknown disturbancesк°Җ мһҲлҠ” nonlinear systemsмқҳ adaptive controlмқҖ downstream control objectiveмҷҖ м •л ¬лҗң learning algorithmsлҘј н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. control-oriented meta-learningмқҖ regression кё°л°ҳ identificationкіј tracking performance мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлҘј лӢӨлЈЁм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ system uncertaintiesмқҳ distributional structureлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” Euclidean лҳҗлҠ” static algebraic geometriesм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” adaptationмқ„ Wasserstein spaceлЎң лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬лҰ¬лҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, parameter estimation errorsлҘј estimated system behaviorsмҷҖ true system behaviors мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ optimal transport costлЎң мёЎм •н•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё task distributions мң„м—җ Wasserstein Bregman divergenceлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, meta-learningмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ nonlinear feature representations, control gains, к·ёлҰ¬кі  transport geometryлҘј кіөлҸҷ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ adaptation lawлҠ” underlying physical systemмқҳ structural propertiesлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” adaptation geometryлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©°, л¬јлҰ¬м ҒмңјлЎң к·јкұ° мһҲкі  лҚ°мқҙн„° кё°л°ҳмқё attention mechanismмқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•ңлӢӨ. Closed-loop tracking simulationsлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ controllerк°Җ fully-actuated л°Ҹ underactuated nonlinear planar rotorcraft лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң optimal performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , trainingкіј testing мЎ°кұҙ к°„мқҳ нҒ° distributional shift н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ robustnessлҘј мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66196","en":"AREA: Attribute Extraction and Aggregation for CLIP-Based Class-Incremental Learning","ko":"AREA: CLIP кё°л°ҳ нҒҙлһҳмҠӨ мҰқл¶„ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң мҶҚм„ұ м¶”м¶ң л°Ҹ м§‘кі„","authors":"Zhen-Hao Xie Xie, Yu-Cheng Shi, Da-Wei Zhou","pos":"#4012","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5th8Uu1HjJ","abs":"<p>Class-Incremental Learning (CIL) is important in building real-world learning systems. In CLIP-based CIL, the model performs classification by comparing similarity between visual and textual embeddings obtained from template prompts, e.g., ``a photo of a [CLASS]''. This seemingly monolithic matching process can be decomposed into two conceptually distinct stages: attribute extraction and attribute aggregation. For example, a model may recognize cat using attributes such as fur texture and whiskers. When learning a new class like car, the model must extract additional attributes like wheels and adjust how they are aggregated in the shared representation space. However, since only data from the current task is available, incremental updates can bias both attribute extraction and aggregation toward new classes, leading to catastrophic forgetting. Therefore, we propose AREA for attribute extraction and aggregation for CLIP-based CIL. To stabilize extraction, we anchor class-level visual and textual attributes on the hyperspherical embedding space via principal geodesic analysis. To stabilize aggregation, we learn lightweight task-specific experts with scoring and residual refinement, regularized by a variational information bottleneck objective. During inference, we perform routing over task attribute manifolds via optimal transport for more concise prediction. Experiments on multiple benchmarks show that AREA consistently outperforms SOTA methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Class-Incremental Learning (CIL)мқҖ мӢӨм ң н•ҷмҠө мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ кө¬м¶•н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. CLIP-based CILм—җм„ң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ ``a photo of a [CLASS]''мҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ template promptлЎң м–»мқҖ visual embeddingкіј textual embeddingмқҳ мң мӮ¬лҸ„лҘј л№„көҗн•ҳм—¬ л¶„лҘҳлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. кІүліҙкё°м—җлҠ” лӢЁмқјн•ң мқҙ matching processлҠ” к°ңл…җм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬лі„лҗҳлҠ” л‘җ лӢЁкі„, мҰү attribute extractionкіј attribute aggregationмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ fur textureмҷҖ whiskers к°ҷмқҖ attributeлҘј нҶөн•ҙ catмқ„ мқёмӢқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. car к°ҷмқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ classлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•  л•Ң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ wheelsмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ м¶”к°Җ attributeлҘј м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкі  shared representation spaceм—җм„ң мқҙлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ м§‘кі„н• м§ҖлҸ„ мЎ°м •н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ нҳ„мһ¬ taskмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°л§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјлҜҖлЎң, incremental updateлҠ” attribute extractionкіј aggregation лӘЁл‘җлҘј мғҲлЎңмҡҙ class мӘҪмңјлЎң нҺён–ҘмӢңмјң catastrophic forgettingмқ„ мң л°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CLIP-based CILмқ„ мң„н•ң attribute extraction and aggregationмқҳ м•Ҫмһҗмқё AREAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. extractionмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ principal geodesic analysisлҘј нҶөн•ҙ hyperspherical embedding space мғҒм—җ class-level visual л°Ҹ textual attributeлҘј anchoringн•ңлӢӨ. aggregationмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ scoringкіј residual refinementлҘј к°–лҠ” lightweight task-specific expertлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј variational information bottleneck objectiveлЎң м •к·ңнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. inference мӢңм—җлҠ” optimal transportлҘј нҶөн•ҙ task attribute manifold мң„м—җм„ң routingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ лҚ” к°„кІ°н•ң predictionмқ„ м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ AREAк°Җ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ SOTA methodsлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66623","en":"MoCL: Metabolic Optimization for Curvature-Aware Continual Learning","ko":"MoCL: кіЎлҘ  мқём§Җ м§ҖмҶҚ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң лҢҖмӮ¬м Ғ мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Jiajun Lai, Qi Liu, Shijie Li, Huaiguang Jiang","pos":"#4100","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=22movV4FJD","abs":"<p>Continual learning requires models to mitigate catastrophic forgetting of prior knowledge while learning a sequence of tasks. Although existing methods based on orthogonal projection prevent interference by constraining parameter updates, they tend to limit plasticity as the task sequence progresses. The reliance on linear approximation further causes the projected gradients to deviate from the nonlinear manifold. To address these issues, we propose Metabolic Optimization for Continual Learning (MoCL), a rehearsal-free framework that strikes a balance between stability and plasticity. To capture the geometric manifold of prior knowledge, MoCL introduces a factorized subspace approximation that avoids expensive explicit matrix inversion. Given the heavy-tailed distribution of the Fisher Information Matrix, we employ a metabolic gating based on Tsallis entropy to suppress updates that conflict with historical knowledge. Theoretical and empirical analyses reveal that MoCL enables the model to converge to a shared low-loss region across sequential tasks. Extensive experimental results across multiple benchmarks demonstrate that MoCL outperforms state-of-the-art methods in both classification performance and efficiency.</p>","absKo":"<p>Continual learningмқҖ мқјл Ёмқҳ taskлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷм•Ҳ мқҙм „ м§ҖмӢқм—җ лҢҖн•ң catastrophic forgettingмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. Orthogonal projectionм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ parameter updateлҘј м ңм•Ҫн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ к°„м„ӯмқ„ л§үм§Җл§Ң, task sequenceк°Җ м§„н–үлҗ мҲҳлЎқ plasticityлҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң linear approximationм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқҖ projected gradientк°Җ nonlinear manifoldм—җм„ң лІ—м–ҙлӮҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м•Ҳм •м„ұкіј к°ҖмҶҢм„ұмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” rehearsal-free frameworkмқё Metabolic Optimization for Continual Learning(MoCL)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм „ м§ҖмӢқмқҳ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ manifoldлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, MoCLмқҖ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° лӘ…мӢңм Ғ н–үл ¬ м—ӯм „мқ„ н”јн•ҳлҠ” factorized subspace approximationмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. Fisher Information Matrixмқҳ heavy-tailed distributionмқ„ кі л Өн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Tsallis entropyм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң metabolic gatingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кіјкұ° м§ҖмӢқкіј м¶©лҸҢн•ҳлҠ” updateлҘј м–өм ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ  л°Ҹ мӢӨмҰқ л¶„м„қмқҖ MoCLмқҙ мҲңм°Ём Ғ task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ кіөмң лҗҳлҠ” low-loss regionмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” MoCLмқҙ classification performanceмҷҖ нҡЁмңЁм„ұ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң state-of-the-art л°©лІ•мқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63173","en":"Mixing Expertise with Confidence: A Mixture of Expert Framework for Robust Multi-Modal Continual Learner","ko":"мӢ лў°лҸ„мҷҖ м „л¬ём„ұмқҳ нҳјн•©: кІ¬кі н•ң л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ м§ҖмҶҚ н•ҷмҠөкё°лҘј мң„н•ң Mixture of Expert н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Md Abdullah Al Forhad, Yuansheng Zhu Zhu., Abhinab Acharya, Xumin Liu, Qi Yu, Weishi Shi","pos":"#4101","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZPJbTXMYft","abs":"<p>The Mixture of Experts (MoE) framework is widely used in continual learning to mitigate catastrophic forgetting. MoEs typically combine a small inter-task shared parameter space with largely independent expert parameters. However, as the number of tasks increases, the shared space becomes a bottleneck, reintroducing forgetting, while fully independent experts require explicit task ID predictors (e.g., routers), adding complexity. In this work, we eliminate the inter-task shared parameter space and the need for a task ID predictor by enabling expert communication and allowing knowledge to be shared dynamically, akin to human collaboration. We bridge the inter-expert knowledge sharing by leveraging the open-set learning capabilities of a multimodal foundation model (e.g., CLIP), thereby providing вҖңexpert priorsвҖқ that bolster each expertвҖҷs task-specific representations. Guided by these priors, experts learn calibrated inter-task posteriors. Additionally, Multivariate Gaussians over the learned posteriors promote complementary specialization among experts. We propose new evaluation benchmarks that simulate realistic continual learning scenarios, and our prior-conditioned strategy consistently outperforms existing methods across diverse settings without relying on reference datasets or replay memory.</p>","absKo":"<p>Mixture of Experts(MoE) frameworkлҠ” catastrophic forgettingмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ continual learningм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. MoEлҠ” мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң task к°„ кіөмң лҗҳлҠ” мһ‘мқҖ parameter spaceмҷҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё expert parameterлҘј кІ°н•©н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ task мҲҳк°Җ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ shared spaceк°Җ лі‘лӘ©мқҙ лҗҳм–ҙ forgettingмқҙ лӢӨмӢң л°ңмғқн•ҳкі , мҷ„м „нһҲ лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё expertлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё task ID predictor(мҳҲ: router)лҘј н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳм—¬ ліөмһЎм„ұмқ„ лҚ”н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” expert communicationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі  мқёк°„мқҳ нҳ‘м—…мІҳлҹј м§ҖмӢқмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң кіөмң н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, task к°„ shared parameter spaceмҷҖ task ID predictorмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” multimodal foundation model(мҳҲ: CLIP)мқҳ open-set learning capabilityлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ expert к°„ knowledge sharingмқ„ м—°кІ°н•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ к°Ғ expertмқҳ task-specific representationмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” вҖңexpert priorвҖқлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң priorмқҳ м•ҲлӮҙ м•„лһҳ, expertлҠ” calibrated inter-task posteriorлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. м¶”к°ҖлЎң, н•ҷмҠөлҗң posterior мң„мқҳ multivariate GaussianмқҖ expert к°„ мғҒліҙм Ғ specializationмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё continual learning мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨлҘј лӘЁмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ evaluation benchmarkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ prior-conditioned strategyлҠ” reference datasetмқҙлӮҳ replay memoryм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  лӢӨм–‘н•ң м„Өм •м—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66690","en":"Less Is More in Federated Continual Learning: RieSelect for Conflict-Aware Layer Selection in LLMs","ko":"Federated Continual Learningм—җм„ңлҠ” м Ғмқ„мҲҳлЎқ мўӢлӢӨ: LLMм—җм„ң м¶©лҸҢ мқём§Җ л Ҳмқҙм–ҙ м„ нғқмқ„ мң„н•ң RieSelect","authors":"Wenqi Qiu, Yipeng Zhou, Lin Zhu, Laizhong Cui","pos":"#4102","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1Je3o7cf1N","abs":"Federated continual learning (FCL) of large language models on edge devices is constrained by a communication--stability--plasticity trilemma. We reveal a less-is-more phenomenon: beyond a moderate layer upload ratio, stability loss offsets saturated plasticity gains, so overall continual performance no longer improves. Moreover, layer-wise conflict is heavy-tailed and concentrates in a few layers; denser uplink increasingly includes these layers, which disproportionately drives forgetting and motivates selective sparse communication. Therefore, we introduce RieSelect, which treats stability as staying within a Fisher-metric safe basin around historical solutions. Under this safe-basin constraint, we derive a layer-wise conflict score and a closed-form certified safe step size for finite local updates, and formulate selective uplink as a knapsack-based utility--risk selection, balancing plasticity gains against stability risks. Extensive experiments show that, under a per-round uplink budget, RieSelect achieves the best performance across task orders. Beyond this matched-budget setting, under standard communication protocols, RieSelect improves average accuracy by 18.99вҖ“28.14 points while reducing total uplink by 53вҖ“115$\\times$.","absKo":"м—Јм§Җ л””л°”мқҙмҠӨм—җм„ңмқҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё federated continual learning(FCL)мқҖ communication--stability--plasticity нҠёлҰҙл Ҳл§Ҳмқҳ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” less-is-more нҳ„мғҒмқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮёлӢӨ. мҰү, м ҒлӢ№н•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ layer upload ratioлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ңл©ҙ stability lossк°Җ нҸ¬нҷ”лҗң plasticity gainмқ„ мғҒмҮ„н•ҳм—¬, м „мІҙ continual performanceлҠ” лҚ” мқҙмғҒ н–ҘмғҒлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң layer-wise conflictлҠ” heavy-tailed л¶„нҸ¬лҘј ліҙмқҙл©° мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ layerм—җ м§‘мӨ‘лҗңлӢӨ. uplinkк°Җ лҚ” мҙҳмҙҳн•ҙм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң layerл“Өмқҙ м җм җ лҚ” л§Һмқҙ нҸ¬н•Ёлҗҳкі , мқҙлҠ” forgettingмқ„ л¶Ҳк· нҳ•м ҒмңјлЎң мң л°ңн•ҳлҜҖлЎң selective sparse communicationмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ л”°лқј мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” RieSelectлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. RieSelectлҠ” stabilityлҘј Fisher-metric safe basin м•Ҳм—җм„ң кіјкұ° н•ҙл“ӨлЎңл¶Җн„° лІ—м–ҙлӮҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң н•ҙм„қн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ safe-basin м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” finite local updateлҘј мң„н•ң layer-wise conflict scoreмҷҖ closed-form certified safe step sizeлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳкі , selective uplinkлҘј knapsack кё°л°ҳ utility--risk selectionмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ plasticity gainкіј stability riskмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶ҳлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, roundлӢ№ uplink budgetмқҙ мЈјм–ҙмЎҢмқ„ л•Ң RieSelectлҠ” task order м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мөңкі мқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л§Өм№ӯлҗң budget м„Өм •мқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ, н‘ңмӨҖ communication protocol н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ RieSelectлҠ” нҸүк·  м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј 18.99вҖ“28.14 нҸ¬мқёнҠё н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ң мҙқ uplinkлҘј 53вҖ“115$\\times$ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"63119","en":"Learning-To-Measure: In-Context Active Feature Acquisition","ko":"мёЎм •лІ• н•ҷмҠө: In-Context лҠҘлҸҷм Ғ нҠ№м§• нҡҚл“қ","authors":"Yuta Kobayashi, Zilin Jing, Jiayu Yao, Hongseok Namkoong, Shalmali Joshi","pos":"#4103","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZumBSRsRbE","abs":"<p>Active feature acquisition (AFA) is a sequential decision-making problem where the goal is to improve model performance for test instances by adaptively selecting which features to acquire. In practice, AFA methods often learn from retrospective data with systematic missingness in the features and limited task-specific labels. To address this limitation, we introduce Learning-to-Measure (L2M), which consists of i) reliable uncertainty quantification over unseen tasks, and ii) an uncertainty-guided feature acquisition agent that maximizes conditional mutual information. We demonstrate an autoregressive pre-training approach that underpins reliable uncertainty quantification and acquisition for tasks with arbitrary missingness. L2M operates directly on datasets with retrospective missingness and performs the task in-context, eliminating per-task retraining. Across synthetic and real-world tabular benchmarks, L2M matches or surpasses task-specific baselines, particularly under scarce labels and high missingness.</p>","absKo":"<p>Active feature acquisition (AFA)лҠ” м–ҙл–Ө featureлҘј нҡҚл“қн• м§Җ м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ test instanceмқҳ model performanceлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳлҠ” sequential decision-making problemмқҙлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎң AFA л°©лІ•мқҖ нқ”нһҲ featureмқҳ мІҙкі„м Ғмқё missingnessмҷҖ task-specific labelмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗң retrospective dataлЎңл¶Җн„° н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” i) ліҙмқҙм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” uncertainty quantificationкіј ii) conditional mutual informationмқ„ мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” uncertainty-guided feature acquisition agentлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң Learning-to-Measure (L2M)лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһ„мқҳмқҳ missingnessлҘј к°Җм§„ taskм—җм„ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” uncertainty quantificationкіј acquisitionмқҳ кё°л°ҳмқҙ лҗҳлҠ” autoregressive pre-training м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. L2MмқҖ retrospective missingnessк°Җ мһҲлҠ” datasetм—җ м§Ғм ‘ мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳл©° taskлҘј in-contextлЎң мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, taskлі„ мһ¬н•ҷмҠөмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. н•©м„ұ л°Ҹ мӢӨм ң tabular benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң L2MмқҖ нҠ№нһҲ labelмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳкі  missingnessк°Җ нҒ° мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ң task-specific baselineкіј лҸҷл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62905","en":"Learn to Merge: Meta-Learning for Adaptive Multi-Task Model Merging","ko":"Learn to Merge: м Ғмқ‘нҳ• лӢӨмӨ‘ кіјм ң лӘЁлҚё лі‘н•©мқ„ мң„н•ң Meta-Learning","authors":"Jun Chen, Qin Zhang, Weizhi Zhang, Xiao Luo, Philip Yu, Ziyue Qiao","pos":"#4104","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=c11G7lmfhm","abs":"<p>Model merging in the pretrain-finetune paradigm has proven effective by combining multiple finetuned models into one with multi-task capabilities. However, existing methods rely on fix or manually tuned merging coefficients, making the unified model sensitive to the initial merging strategy and suboptimal for downstream adaptation. Thus, this paper proposed an innovative model merging framework called MetaMerging, a novel meta-learning algorithm to adaptively optimize the merging coefficients to construct a unified model tailored for task-specific adapter training. By simulating adapter updates in an inner loop and meta-optimizing merging coefficients in an outer loop, MetaMerging produces more balanced and generalizable unified models. Extensive experiments on CV and NLP fields show strong performance of MetaMerging on various downstream tasks and demonstrate the effectiveness of meta-learning in our method compared to other parameter merging methods. Our code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/MetaMerging-53A1</p>","absKo":"<p>pretrain-finetune нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„м—җм„ңмқҳ model mergingмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ finetuned modelмқ„ н•ҳлӮҳлЎң кІ°н•©н•ҙ multi-task capabilityлҘј к°–м¶ҳ лӢЁмқј лӘЁлҚёмқ„ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” лҚ° нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ кі м •лҗҳм—Ҳкұ°лӮҳ мҲҳлҸҷмңјлЎң нҠңлӢқн•ң merging coefficientм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, нҶөн•©лҗң лӘЁлҚёмқҙ мҙҲкё° merging м „лһөм—җ лҜјк°җн•ҳкі  downstream adaptationм—җм„ңлҸ„ мөңм Ғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ MetaMergingмқҙлқј л¶ҲлҰ¬лҠ” нҳҒмӢ м Ғмқё model merging frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” task-specific adapter trainingм—җ л§һм¶ҳ unified modelмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ merging coefficientлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ meta-learning algorithmмқҙлӢӨ. inner loopм—җм„ң adapter updateлҘј мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳн•ҳкі  outer loopм—җм„ң merging coefficientлҘј meta-optimizationн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, MetaMergingмқҖ лҚ” к· нҳ• мһЎнһҲкі  мқјл°ҳнҷ” к°ҖлҠҘн•ң unified modelмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. CVмҷҖ NLP л¶„м•јм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң MetaMergingмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң downstream taskм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмҳҖмңјл©°, лӢӨлҘё parameter merging methodмҷҖ л№„көҗн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң ліё л°©лІ•м—җм„ң meta-learningмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн–ҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/MetaMerging-53A1 м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ</p>"},{"id":"60787","en":"Federated Learning with Unlabeled Clients: Personalization Can Happen in Low Dimensions","ko":"Unlabeled Clientк°Җ мһҲлҠ” Federated Learning: к°ңмқёнҷ”лҠ” м Җм°Ёмӣҗм—җм„ң к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Hossein Zakerinia, Jonathan Scott, Christoph Lampert","pos":"#4105","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=wjiw02fqir","abs":"<p>Personalized federated learning has emerged as a popular approach to training on devices holding statistically heterogeneous data, known as clients. However, most existing approaches require a client to have labeled data for training or finetuning in order to obtain their own personalized model. In this paper we address this by proposing FLowDUP, a novel method that is able to generate a personalized model using only a forward pass with unlabeled data. The generated model parameters reside in a low-dimensional subspace, enabling efficient communication and computation. FLowDUP's learning objective is theoretically motivated by our new transductive multi-task PAC-Bayesian generalization bound, that provides performance guarantees for unlabeled clients. The objective is structured in such a way that it allows both clients with labeled data and clients with only unlabeled data to contribute to the training process. To supplement our theoretical results we carry out a thorough experimental evaluation of FLowDUP, demonstrating strong empirical performance on a range of datasets with differing sorts of statistically heterogeneous clients. Through numerous ablation studies, we test the efficacy of the individual components of the method.</p>","absKo":"<p>к°ңмқёнҷ” federated learningмқҖ нҶөкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё лҚ°мқҙн„°, мҰү clientлҘј ліҙмң н•ң л””л°”мқҙмҠӨм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” мқёкё° мһҲлҠ” м ‘к·јлІ•мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ к°Ғ clientк°Җ мһҗмӢ л§Ңмқҳ personalized modelмқ„ м–»кё° мң„н•ҙ н•ҷмҠө лҳҗлҠ” finetuningмҡ© labeled dataлҘј ліҙмң н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, unlabeled dataм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ forward passл§ҢмңјлЎң personalized modelмқ„ мғқм„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л°©лІ• FLowDUPлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мғқм„ұлҗң model parameterлҠ” м Җм°Ёмӣҗ subspaceм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё нҶөмӢ кіј кі„мӮ°мқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨ. FLowDUPмқҳ learning objectiveлҠ” unlabeled clientм—җ лҢҖн•ң м„ұлҠҘ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ transductive multi-task PAC-Bayesian generalization boundм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң лҸҷкё°л¶Җм—¬лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ objectiveлҠ” labeled dataлҘј к°Җм§„ clientмҷҖ unlabeled dataл§Ң к°Җм§„ client лӘЁл‘җк°Җ training processм—җ кё°м—¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ кө¬м„ұлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FLowDUPм—җ лҢҖн•ң л©ҙл°Җн•ң мӢӨн—ҳ нҸүк°ҖлҘј мҲҳн–үн–Ҳмңјл©°, нҶөкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё clientмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мў…лҘҳлҘј к°–лҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ datasetм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң кІҪн—ҳм Ғ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн–ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң лӢӨмҲҳмқҳ ablation studyлҘј нҶөн•ҙ methodмқҳ к°ңлі„ кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢл“Өмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64571","en":"Efficient Bilevel Optimization for CKA-Guided MoE Upcycling","ko":"CKA-Guided MoE Upcyclingмқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ Bilevel Optimization","authors":"Zhiyuan Yu, Enneng Yang, Hao Jiang, Guojie Zhu, Feihong He, Peng Wang, Li Shen","pos":"#4106","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=M5hGwjZCs0","abs":"<p>Upcycling, a strategy that initializes Mixture-of-Experts (MoE) by replicating pre-trained feed-forward or MoE networks to expand model capacity, has become a popular method in continual learning due to its effectiveness in mitigating catastrophic forgetting. However, existing paradigms rely on indiscriminate expansion prioritize performance at the cost of extreme inefficiency, introducing parameter redundancy without exploiting the structural heterogeneity essential for counteracting forgetting with architectural economy. To address this, we investigate the determinants of forgetting in training dynamics using Centered Kernel Alignment (CKA) and loss landscape flatness to analyze the behavior of pre- and post-expansion MoE layers, uncovering instability in deep-layer representations and heterogeneous expert sensitivity to new tasks, thereby demonstrating the potential of selective upcycling to eliminate redundancy. Consequently, we propose a dynamic bilevel optimization framework to guide adaptive upcycling, featuring an outer loop employing a Gumbel-Softmax differentiable mask to perform Neural Architecture Search (NAS) for adaptive growth, while an inner loop optimizes weight updates via task objectives and CKA-regularized replay. Experiments on TRACE benchmark demonstrate that our proposed method achieves better average accuracy with 80\\% forgetting reduction, while effectively eliminating 60\\% of redundant parameter expansion that standard upcycling would introduce.</p>","absKo":"<p>UpcyclingмқҖ мӮ¬м „ н•ҷмҠөлҗң feed-forward лҳҗлҠ” MoE networkлҘј ліөм ңн•ҳм—¬ Mixture-of-Experts (MoE)лҘј мҙҲкё°нҷ”н•ҳкі  model capacityлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” м „лһөмңјлЎң, catastrophic forgettingмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” нҡЁкіј лҚ•л¶„м—җ continual learningм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ м“°мқҙлҠ” л°©лІ•мқҙ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҖ к·№лӢЁм Ғмқё л№„нҡЁмңЁмқ„ к°җмҲҳн•ҳл©ҙм„ң л¬ҙм°Ёлі„м Ғмқё expansionмқ„ мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳм—¬, architectural economyлЎң forgettingм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё structural heterogeneityлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ң мұ„ parameter redundancyлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Centered Kernel Alignment (CKA)мҷҖ loss landscape flatnessлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ н•ҷмҠө dynamicsм—җм„ң forgettingмқҳ кІ°м • мҡ”мқёмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкі , нҷ•мһҘ м „нӣ„ MoE layerмқҳ лҸҷмһ‘мқ„ л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј deep layer representationмқҳ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •м„ұкіј мғҲ кіјм ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң expertмқҳ мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё лҜјк°җлҸ„лҘј л°қнҳҖлӮҙм–ҙ, мӨ‘ліөм„ұмқ„ м ңкұ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” selective upcyclingмқҳ мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ л”°лқј мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” adaptive upcyclingмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” dynamic bilevel optimization frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. л°”к№Ҙ лЈЁн”„лҠ” Gumbel-Softmax лҜёл¶„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң maskлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ Neural Architecture Search (NAS)лҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳкі  adaptive growthлҘј мӢӨнҳ„н•ҳл©°, м•ҲмӘҪ лЈЁн”„лҠ” task objectiveмҷҖ CKA-regularized replayлҘј нҶөн•ҙ weight updateлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. TRACE benchmark мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ 80\\% forgetting reductionкіј н•Ёк»ҳ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ нҸүк·  м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, н‘ңмӨҖ upcyclingмқҙ мң л°ңн–Ҳмқ„ 60\\%мқҳ redundant parameter expansionмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60567","en":"DomED: Redesigning Ensemble Distillation for Domain Generalization","ko":"DomED: лҸ„л©”мқё мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң м•ҷмғҒлё” мҰқлҘҳ мһ¬м„Өкі„","authors":"Ziang Song, Zhou Zhidan, Zijun Zhang","pos":"#4108","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=yxygNW4mJl","abs":"<p>Domain generalization aims to improve model performance on unseen, out-of-distribution (OOD) domains, yet existing methods often overlook the crucial aspect of uncertainty quantification in their predictions. While ensemble learning combined with knowledge distillation offers a promising avenue, naively combining these techniques is non-trivial and remains largely unexplored in the context of domain generalization. In this work, we systematically investigate different ensemble and distillation strategies for domain generalization tasks and design a tailored data allocation scheme. This approach trains teacher models on distinct subsets of domains and performs distillation on complementary (unseen) subsets, thereby fostering model diversity and training efficiency. Moreover, our theoretical analysis demonstrates that distilling from teachers on unseen domains effectively filters out domain-specific spurious correlations. To address the accuracy degradation often observed with standard uncertainty distillation, we further develop a novel technique that decouples uncertainty distillation from the standard distillation process, enabling accurate uncertainty estimation without compromising model accuracy. Our proposed method, <em>Domain-aware Ensemble Distillation</em> (DomED), is extensively evaluated against state-of-the-art domain generalization and ensemble distillation techniques across multiple benchmarks, achieving competitive accuracies and substantially improved uncertainty estimates.</p>","absKo":"<p>domain generalizationмқҖ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң out-of-distribution(OOD) domainм—җм„ңмқҳ лӘЁлҚё м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мҳҲмёЎмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ мёЎл©ҙмқё uncertainty quantificationмқ„ мў…мў… к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. ensemble learningкіј knowledge distillationмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” м ‘к·јмқҖ мң л§қн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кё°лІ•мқ„ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ кІ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ мһҗлӘ…н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©° domain generalization л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” domain generalization кіјм ңлҘј мң„н•ҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң ensemble л°Ҹ distillation м „лһөмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°мӮ¬н•ҳкі , мқҙм—җ л§һм¶ҳ data allocation schemeмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ teacher modelмқ„ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё domain subsetм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨкі , мғҒліҙм Ғмқё(ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң) subsetм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ distillationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лӘЁлҚё лӢӨм–‘м„ұкіј н•ҷмҠө нҡЁмңЁмқ„ лҶ’мқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң domainм—җм„ң teacherлЎңл¶Җн„° distillationн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ domain-specific spurious correlationмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң кұёлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ uncertainty distillationм—җм„ң нқ”нһҲ кҙҖм°°лҗҳлҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„ м Җн•ҳлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” uncertainty distillationмқ„ н‘ңмӨҖ distillation кіјм •кіј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кё°лІ•мқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң к°ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬, лӘЁлҚё м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј нӣјмҶҗн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м •нҷ•н•ң uncertainty estimationмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ” <em>Domain-aware Ensemble Distillation</em>(DomED)мқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мөңмӢ  domain generalization л°Ҹ ensemble distillation кё°лІ•л“Өкіј кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ҳкІҢ л№„көҗлҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗң uncertainty estimateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62185","en":"Continual Learning through Control Minimization","ko":"Control Minimizationмқ„ нҶөн•ң Continual Learning","authors":"Sander de Haan, Yassine Taoudi-Benchekroun, Pau Vilimelis Aceituno, Benjamin F. Grewe","pos":"#4109","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ix1HdZkO8U","abs":"<p>Catastrophic forgetting remains a fundamental challenge for neural networks when tasks are trained sequentially. In this work, we reformulate continual learning as a control problem where learning and preservation signals compete within neural activity dynamics. We convert regularization penalties into preservation signals that protect prior-task representations. Learning then proceeds by minimizing the control effort required to integrate new tasks while competing with the preservation of prior tasks. At equilibrium, the neural activities produce weight updates that implicitly encode the full prior-task curvature, a property we term the <em>continual-natural gradient</em>, requiring no explicit curvature storage. Experiments confirm that our learning framework recovers true prior-task curvature and enables task discrimination, outperforming existing methods on standard benchmarks without replay.</p>","absKo":"<p>catastrophic forgettingмқҖ taskлҘј мҲңм°Ём ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•  л•Ң neural networkк°Җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ҳлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё л¬ём ңлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” н•ҷмҠө мӢ нҳёмҷҖ ліҙмЎҙ мӢ нҳёк°Җ neural activity dynamics лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң кІҪмҹҒн•ҳлҠ” control problemмңјлЎң continual learningмқ„ мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” regularization penaltyлҘј мқҙм „ task representationмқ„ ліҙнҳён•ҳлҠ” ліҙмЎҙ мӢ нҳёлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ н•ҷмҠөмқҖ мқҙм „ taskмқҳ ліҙмЎҙкіј кІҪмҹҒн•ҳл©ҙм„ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң control effortлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң м§„н–үлҗңлӢӨ. нҸүнҳ• мғҒнғңм—җм„ң neural activityлҠ” мқҙм „ taskмқҳ full curvatureлҘј м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” weight updateлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј лӘ…мӢңм Ғ curvature м ҖмһҘмқҙ н•„мҡ” м—ҶлҠ” <em>continual-natural gradient</em>лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ learning frameworkк°Җ мӢӨм ң мқҙм „ task curvatureлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳкі  task discriminationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, replay м—Ҷмқҙ н‘ңмӨҖ benchmarkм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64865","en":"Beyond Point-wise Neural Collapse: A Topology-Aware Hierarchical Classifier for Class-Incremental Learning","ko":"Point-wise Neural CollapseлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ң: Class-Incremental Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң Topology-Aware кі„мёөм Ғ л¶„лҘҳкё°","authors":"HuiYu Yi, Xu Zhiming, Dunwei Tu, Zhicheng Wang, Baile Xu, Furao Shen","pos":"#4110","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=J36ARcNLEv","abs":"<p>The Nearest Class Mean (NCM) classifier is widely favored in Class-Incremental Learning (CIL) for its superior resistance to catastrophic forgetting compared to Fully Connected layers. While Neural Collapse (NC) theory supports NCM's optimality by assuming features collapse into single points, non-linear feature drift and insufficient training in CIL often prevent this ideal state. Consequently, classes manifest as complex manifolds rather than collapsed points, rendering the single-point NCM suboptimal. To address this, we propose Hierarchical-Cluster SOINN (HC-SOINN), a novel classifier that captures the topological structure of these manifolds via a ``local-to-global'' representation. Furthermore, we introduce Structure-Topology Alignment via Residuals (STAR) method, which employs a fine-grained pointwise trajectory tracking mechanism to actively deform the learned topology, allowing it to adapt precisely to complex non-linear feature drift. Theoretical analysis and Procrustes distance experiments validate our framework's resilience to manifold deformations. We integrated HC-SOINN into seven state-of-the-art methods by replacing their original classifiers, achieving consistent improvements that highlight the effectiveness and robustness of our approach. Code is available at \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/icml2026-9B60}.</p>","absKo":"<p>Nearest Class Mean (NCM) classifierлҠ” Fully Connected layerм—җ л№„н•ҙ catastrophic forgettingм—җ лҢҖн•ң лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м Җн•ӯм„ұмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ Class-Incremental Learning (CIL)м—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ м„ нҳёлҗңлӢӨ. Neural Collapse (NC) theoryлҠ” featureк°Җ лӢЁмқј pointлЎң collapseлҗңлӢӨлҠ” к°Җм •н•ҳм—җ NCMмқҳ optimalityлҘј л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳм§Җл§Ң, CILм—җм„ңмқҳ л№„м„ нҳ• feature driftмҷҖ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң н•ҷмҠөмқҖ мў…мў… мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мқҙмғҒм Ғ мғҒнғңлҘј л°©н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј classлҠ” collapsed pointк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј ліөмһЎн•ң manifoldлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮҳл©°, лӢЁмқј point кё°л°ҳ NCMмқҖ л№„мөңм Ғмқҙ лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң manifoldмқҳ topological structureлҘј ``local-to-global'' representationмңјлЎң нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ classifierмқё Hierarchical-Cluster SOINN (HC-SOINN)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” residualмқ„ нҶөн•ң Structure-Topology Alignment (STAR) л°©лІ•мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” fine-grained pointwise trajectory tracking mechanismмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ н•ҷмҠөлҗң topologyлҘј лҠҘлҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң ліҖнҳ•н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ complex non-linear feature driftм—җ м •нҷ•нһҲ м Ғмқ‘н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қкіј Procrustes distance мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ manifold deformationм—җ лҢҖн•ң ліё frameworkмқҳ кІ¬кі м„ұмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ classifierлҘј лҢҖмІҙн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң HC-SOINNмқ„ мқјкіұ к°ңмқҳ state-of-the-art methodм—җ нҶөн•©н•ҳмҳҖкі , мқјкҙҖлҗң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ ліё м ‘к·јлІ•мқҳ нҡЁкіјмҷҖ кІ¬кі м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н–ҲлӢӨ. CodeлҠ” \\url{https://anonymous.4open.science/r/icml2026-9B60}м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"68779","en":"Expert Routing with Synthetic Data for Domain Incremental Learning","ko":"Domain Incremental Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң н•©м„ұ лҚ°мқҙн„° кё°л°ҳ Expert Routing","authors":"Yewon Byun, Sanket Vaibhav Mehta, Saurabh Garg, Emma Strubell, Michael Oberst, Bryan Wilder, Zachary Lipton","pos":"#4608","abs":"<p>In many real-world settings, regulations and economic incentives permit the sharing of models but not data across institutional boundaries. In such scenarios, practitioners might hope to adapt models to new domains, without losing performance on previous domains (so-called catastrophic forgetting). While any single model may struggle to achieve this goal, learning an ensemble of domain-specific experts offers the potential to adapt more closely to each individual institution. However, a core challenge in this context is determining which expert to deploy at test time. In this paper, we propose Generate to Discriminate (G2D), a domain-incremental learning method that leverages synthetic data to train a domain-discriminator that routes samples at inference time to the appropriate expert. Surprisingly, we find that leveraging synthetic data in this capacity is more effective than using the samples to \\textit{directly} train the downstream classifier (the more common approach to leveraging synthetic data in the lifelong learning literature). We observe that G2D outperforms competitive domain-incremental learning methods on tasks in both vision and language modalities, providing a new perspective on the use of synthetic data in the lifelong learning literature.</p>","absKo":"<p>л§ҺмқҖ мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” к·ңм ңмҷҖ кІҪм ңм Ғ мқём„јнӢ°лёҢлЎң мқён•ҙ кё°кҙҖ к°„м—җлҠ” modelмқҖ кіөмң н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң dataлҠ” кіөмң н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң мӢӨл¬ҙмһҗлҠ” мқҙм „ domainм—җм„ңмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мһғм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ domainм—җ modelмқ„ м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮӨкёё л°”лһ„ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ(мқҙлҘёл°” catastrophic forgetting). лӢЁмқј modelлЎңлҠ” мқҙ лӘ©н‘ңлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡё мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, domain-specific expertмқҳ ensembleмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©ҙ к°Ғ кё°кҙҖм—җ лҚ” л°Җм ‘н•ҳкІҢ м Ғмқ‘н•  к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ л§ҘлқҪмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлҠ” test timeм—җ м–ҙл–Ө expertлҘј л°°нҸ¬н• м§Җ кІ°м •н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” Generate to Discriminate(G2D)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” synthetic dataлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ domain-discriminatorлҘј н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨлҠ” domain-incremental learning л°©лІ•мңјлЎң, inference timeм—җ sampleмқ„ м Ғм Ҳн•ң expertлЎң лқјмҡ°нҢ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„, synthetic dataлҘј мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©мӢқмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ downstream classifierлҘј \\textit{м§Ғм ‘} н•ҷмҠөмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ лҚ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ(мқҙнӣ„ lifelong learning л¬ён—Ңм—җм„ң synthetic dataлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м ‘к·јлІ•). мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” G2Dк°Җ visionкіј language modality лӘЁл‘җмқҳ кіјм ңм—җм„ң кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” domain-incremental learning л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–Ҳмңјл©°, lifelong learning л¬ён—Ңм—җм„ң synthetic data мӮ¬мҡ©м—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кҙҖм җмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63617","en":"Learning Flexible Generalization in Video Quality Assessment by Bringing Device and Viewing Condition Distributions","ko":"л””л°”мқҙмҠӨмҷҖ мӢңмІӯ мЎ°кұҙ л¶„нҸ¬лҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ҙ л№„л””мҳӨ нҷ”м§Ҳ нҸүк°Җмқҳ мң м—°н•ң мқјл°ҳнҷ” н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Nickolay Safonov, Dmitriy Vatolin","pos":"#704","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=VOvwbW0qbO","abs":"<p>Video quality assessment (VQA) plays a critical role in optimizing video delivery systems. While numerous objective metrics have been proposed to approximate human perception, the perceived quality strongly depends on viewing conditions and display characteristics. Factors such as ambient lighting, display brightness, and resolution significantly influence the visibility of distortions. In this work, we address the question of the multi-screen quality assessment on mobile devices, as this area still tends to be under-covered. We introduce a first large-scale subjective dataset collected across more than different 300 Android devices, accompanied by metadata on viewing conditions and display properties. We propose a strategy for aggregated score extraction and adaptation of VQA models to device-specific quality estimation. Our results demonstrate that incorporating device and context information enables more accurate and flexible quality prediction, offering new opportunities for fine-grained optimization in streaming services. Ultimately, this work advances the development of perceptual quality models that bridge the gap between laboratory evaluations and the diverse conditions of real-world media consumption. We made the dataset and the code available at [Link is redacted].</p>","absKo":"<p>Video quality assessment (VQA)лҠ” video delivery systemмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳл§ҺмқҖ objective metricмқҙ мқёк°„ м§Җк°Ғмқ„ к·јмӮ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мІҙк°җ н’Ҳм§ҲмқҖ viewing conditionкіј display characteristicм—җ к°•н•ҳкІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. ambient lighting, display brightness, resolution к°ҷмқҖ мҡ”мқёл“ӨмқҖ distortionмқҳ к°ҖмӢңм„ұм—җ нҒ° мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” mobile deviceм—җм„ңмқҳ multi-screen quality assessment л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мқҙ мҳҒм—ӯмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ лӢӨлӨ„м§Җм§Җ м•Ҡкі  мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” 300к°ңк°Җ л„ҳлҠ” Android deviceм—җм„ң мҲҳм§‘н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ subjective datasetмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ҳл©°, viewing conditionкіј display propertyм—җ лҢҖн•ң metadataлҘј н•Ёк»ҳ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң aggregated score extraction м „лһөкіј VQA modelмқ„ device-specific quality estimationм—җ м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮӨлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” device л°Ҹ context м •ліҙлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳл©ҙ лҚ” м •нҷ•н•ҳкі  мң м—°н•ң quality predictionмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, streaming serviceм—җм„ңмқҳ м„ёл°Җн•ң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к¶Ғк·№м ҒмңјлЎң мқҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мӢӨн—ҳмӢӨ нҸүк°ҖмҷҖ мӢӨм ң media consumptionмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мЎ°кұҙ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°лҠ” perceptual quality modelмқҳ л°ңм „мқ„ м•һлӢ№кёҙлӢӨ. лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣкіј мҪ”л“ңлҠ” [Link is redacted]м—җ кіөк°ңн•ҳмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64322","en":"Progressive Graph Structure Adjustment for Homophily Shift Adaptation","ko":"лҸҷмў…м„ұ ліҖнҷ” м Ғмқ‘мқ„ мң„н•ң м җм§„м Ғ к·ёлһҳн”„ кө¬мЎ° мЎ°м •","authors":"Hongwei Wen, Can Zhang, Haoyu He, Hanyuan Hang, Minglong Lei","pos":"#4605","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OkyO74bJqE","abs":"<p>We propose <em>Progressive Structure Adjustment for Homophily Shift</em> (<em>PSAHS</em>), a lightweight method for <em>Graph Domain Adaptation</em> (<em>GDA</em>) that explicitly addresses cross-domain mismatch in node-level homophily. PSAHS enhances node homophily in the source graph to a prescribed level by reweighting edges and introducing additional intra-class connections for low-homophily nodes, and conservatively refines the target graph using agreement-consistent predictions from a structure-aware <em>Graph Neural Network</em> (<em>GNN</em>) and an attribute-only <em>Multi-Layer Perceptron</em> (<em>MLP</em>) to ensure reliability under label scarcity. After each structural refinement, domain-adversarial training is employed to align node representations across domains. PSAHS employs a progressive training scheme that alternates between structure adjustment and representation alignment, where increasingly informative representations enable safer homophily correction, and the refined structure in turn improves representation learning. Extensive experiments on multiple GDA benchmarks demonstrate that PSAHS consistently outperforms strong baselines, with particularly large gains under severe homophily mismatch, highlighting the importance of explicit homophily alignment for effective cross-graph transfer.</p>","absKo":"<p><em>Progressive Structure Adjustment for Homophily Shift</em> (<em>PSAHS</em>)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” л…ёл“ң мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ homophilyм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” cross-domain mismatchлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” <em>Graph Domain Adaptation</em> (<em>GDA</em>)мқ„ мң„н•ң кІҪлҹү л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. PSAHSлҠ” м—Јм§ҖлҘј мһ¬к°ҖмӨ‘н•ҳкі  low-homophily л…ёл“ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё intra-class м—°кІ°мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ source graphмқҳ node homophilyлҘј м§Җм •лҗң мҲҳмӨҖмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨл©°, label scarcity н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ structure-aware <em>Graph Neural Network</em> (<em>GNN</em>)мҷҖ attribute-only <em>Multi-Layer Perceptron</em> (<em>MLP</em>)мқҳ мқјм№ҳм„ұ мһҲлҠ” мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ target graphлҘј ліҙмҲҳм ҒмңјлЎң м •көҗнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. к°Ғ кө¬мЎ° м •көҗнҷ” мқҙнӣ„м—җлҠ” domain-adversarial trainingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ domain к°„ node representationмқ„ м •л ¬н•ңлӢӨ. PSAHSлҠ” structure adjustmentмҷҖ representation alignmentлҘј лІҲк°Ҳм•„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” progressive training schemeмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©°, м җм җ лҚ” м •ліҙк°Җ н’Қл¶Җн•ң representationмқҙ лҚ” м•Ҳм „н•ң homophily correctionмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі , м •көҗнҷ”лҗң structureлҠ” лӢӨмӢң representation learningмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ GDA benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, PSAHSлҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, нҠ№нһҲ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң homophily mismatch н•ҳм—җм„ң нҒ° н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙм—¬, нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё cross-graph transferлҘј мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё homophily alignmentк°Җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•Ёмқ„ л¶Җк°Ғн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62131","en":"Singularity-aware Optimization via Randomized Geometric Probing: Towards Stable Non-smooth Optimization","ko":"л¬ҙмһ‘мң„ кё°н•ҳ нғҗм№Ёмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҠ№мқҙм җ мқёмӢқ мөңм Ғнҷ”: м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё л№„л§ӨлҒ„лҹ¬мҡҙ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј н–Ҙн•ҙ","authors":"Ruoran Xu, Borong She, Xiaobo Jin, Qiufeng Wang","pos":"#2914","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jYf7VrKL6x","abs":"Deep learning optimization relies heavily on the assumption of smooth loss landscapes, a condition systematically violated by modern architectures due to non-smooth components like ReLU activations and quantization operators. In such non-smooth regimes, adaptive optimizers such as Adam suffer from gradient chatteringвҖ”violent oscillations caused by conflicting signals within the Clarke subdifferentialвҖ”leading to poor convergence and suboptimal generalization. To address this, we introduce Singularity-aware Adam (S-Adam), a novel optimizer that stabilizes training by dynamically modulating step sizes based on local geometric instability. Our key contribution is the Local Geometric Instability (LGI) metric, a computationally efficient estimator of the Clarke subdifferential diameter derived from the variance of randomized directional derivatives. S-Adam incorporates an adaptive damping mechanism $\\exp(-\\lambda \\rho_t)$ that decelerates updates in high-instability regions while preserving fast convergence in smooth basins. We provide a rigorous convergence analysis using differential inclusions, proving that S-Adam converges almost surely to $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$-Clarke stationary points at the optimal $\\mathcal{O}(1/\\sqrt{T})$ rate. Empirical evaluations on Quantization-Aware Training (QAT) and high-volatility transfer learning demonstrate that S-Adam consistently outperforms AdamW and Prox-SGD, achieving accuracy gains of up to +6\\% on CIFAR-100 and +3\\% on TinyImageNet while effectively mitigating gradient oscillations.","absKo":"Deep learning optimizationмқҖ smooth loss landscapeлқјлҠ” к°Җм •м—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙ мЎ°кұҙмқҖ ReLU activationкіј quantization operator к°ҷмқҖ non-smooth component л•Ңл¬ём—җ нҳ„лҢҖ architectureм—җм„ң мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мң„л°ҳлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң non-smooth regimeм—җм„ң Adamкіј к°ҷмқҖ adaptive optimizerлҠ” Clarke subdifferential лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ мғҒм¶©н•ҳлҠ” мӢ нҳёлЎң мқён•ҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” gradient chattering, мҰү кІ©л ¬н•ң м§„лҸҷмқ„ кІӘм–ҙ мҲҳл ҙмқҙ м Җн•ҳлҗҳкі  generalizationмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§‘лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Singularity-aware Adam (S-Adam)мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. S-AdamмқҖ local geometric instabilityм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬ step sizeлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ optimizerмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кё°м—¬лҠ” Local Geometric Instability (LGI) metricмңјлЎң, randomized directional derivativeмқҳ л¶„мӮ°м—җм„ң мң лҸ„лҗң Clarke subdifferential diameterмқҳ кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё м¶”м •кё°мһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. S-AdamмқҖ adaptive damping mechanism $\\exp(-\\lambda \\rho_t)$лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳм—¬, smooth basinм—җм„ңлҠ” л№ лҘё мҲҳл ҙмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •м„ұмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ңлҠ” updateлҘј лҠҰм¶ҘлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” differential inclusionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң м—„л°Җн•ң мҲҳл ҙ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬, S-Adamмқҙ мөңм Ғмқҳ $\\mathcal{O}(1/\\sqrt{T})$ rateлЎң $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$-Clarke stationary pointм—җ кұ°мқҳ surely мҲҳл ҙн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. Quantization-Aware Training (QAT)кіј high-volatility transfer learningм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” S-Adamмқҙ AdamWмҷҖ Prox-SGDлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, CIFAR-100м—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ +6\\%, TinyImageNetм—җм„ң +3\\%мқҳ м •нҷ•лҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ gradient oscillationмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"61755","en":"Riemannian Dueling Optimization","ko":"лҰ¬л§Ңian Dueling мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Yuxuan Ren, Abhishek Roy, Shiqian Ma","pos":"#3600","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=nDfDnsyllY","abs":"Dueling optimization considers optimizing an objective with access to only a comparison oracle of the objective function. It finds important applications in emerging fields such as recommendation systems and robotics. Existing works on dueling optimization mainly focused on unconstrained problems in the Euclidean space. In this work, we study dueling optimization over Riemannian manifolds, which covers important applications that cannot be solved by existing dueling optimization algorithms. In particular, we propose a Riemannian Dueling Normalized Gradient Descent (RDNGD) method and establish its iteration complexity when the objective function is geodesically $L$-smooth or geodesically (strongly) convex. We also propose a projection-free algorithm, named Riemannian Dueling FrankвҖ“Wolfe (RDFW) method, to deal with the situation where projection is prohibited. We establish the iteration and oracle complexities for RDFW. We illustrate the effectiveness of the proposed algorithms through numerical experiments on both synthetic and real applications.","absKo":"Dueling optimizationмқҖ objective functionмқҳ comparison oracleл§Ң м ‘к·ј к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң objectiveлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” recommendation systemкіј robotics к°ҷмқҖ emerging fieldм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мқ‘мҡ©мқ„ м°ҫлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ dueling optimization м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң Euclidean spaceмқҳ unconstrained problemм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”м—ҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” Riemannian manifold мң„м—җм„ңмқҳ dueling optimizationмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁл©°, кё°мЎҙ dueling optimization algorithmмңјлЎңлҠ” н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мқ‘мҡ©л“Өмқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, geodesically $L$-smoothн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ geodesically (strongly) convexн•ң objective functionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ iteration complexityлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳлҠ” Riemannian Dueling Normalized Gradient Descent (RDNGD) methodлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң projectionмқҙ кёҲм§Җлҗң мғҒнҷ©мқ„ лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ Riemannian Dueling FrankвҖ“Wolfe (RDFW) methodлқјлҠ” projection-free algorithmлҸ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. RDFWм—җ лҢҖн•ң iteration л°Ҹ oracle complexityлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң synthetic л°Ҹ real application лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м ңм•Ҳн•ң м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61113","en":"Towards Fully Parameter-Free Stochastic Optimization: Grid Search with Self-Bounding Analysis","ko":"мҷ„м „н•ң Parameter-Free Stochastic Optimizationмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬: Self-Bounding л¶„м„қ кё°л°ҳ Grid Search","authors":"Yuheng Zhao, Yu-Hu Yan, Amit Attia, Tomer Koren, Lijun Zhang, Peng Zhao","pos":"#3700","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tYUt9ffVcD","abs":"<p>Parameter-free stochastic optimization aims to design algorithms that are agnostic to the underlying problem parameters while still achieving convergence rates competitive with optimally tuned methods. While some parameter-free methods do not require the specific values of the problem parameters, they still rely on prior knowledge, such as the lower or upper bounds of them. We refer to such methods as \"partially parameter-free\". In this work, we target achieving \"<em>fully</em> parameter-free\" methods, i.e., the algorithmic inputs do not need to satisfy any <em>unverifiable</em> condition related to the true problem parameters. We propose a general and powerful <em>grid search</em> framework, named GRASP, with a novel <em>self-bounding</em> analysis technique that effectively determines the parameter search ranges, in contrast to previous work. Our method demonstrates generality in: (i) the non-convex case, where we propose a fully parameter-free method that achieves near-optimal convergence rate, up to logarithmic factors; (ii) the convex case, where our parameter-free methods are competitive with strong performance in terms of acceleration and universality. Finally, we contribute a sharper guarantee for the model ensemble, a final step of the grid search framework, under interpolated variance characterization.</p>","absKo":"<p>Parameter-free stochastic optimizationмқҖ underlying problem parameterм—җ кө¬м• л°ӣм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мөңм ҒмңјлЎң нҠңлӢқлҗң л°©лІ•л“Өкіј кІҪмҹҒн•  л§Ңн•ң convergence rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” algorithmмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мқјл¶Җ parameter-free methodлҠ” problem parameterмқҳ кө¬мІҙм Ғмқё к°’мқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡм§Җл§Ң, м—¬м „нһҲ к·ё lower boundлӮҳ upper boundмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ мӮ¬м „ м§ҖмӢқм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•мқ„ \"partially parameter-free\"лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” true problem parameterмҷҖ кҙҖл Ёлҗң м–ҙл– н•ң <em>кІҖмҰқ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң</em> мЎ°кұҙлҸ„ algorithmic inputsк°Җ л§ҢмЎұн•  н•„мҡ”к°Җ м—ҶлҠ”, мҰү \"<em>fully</em> parameter-free\" method лӢ¬м„ұмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” GRASPлқјлҠ” мқҙлҰ„мқҳ generalн•ҳкі  powerfulн•ң <em>grid search</em> frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬мҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬ parameter search rangeлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң кІ°м •н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ <em>self-bounding</em> analysis techniqueмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ лӢӨмқҢм—җм„ң мқјл°ҳм„ұмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. (i) non-convex caseм—җм„ңлҠ” logarithmic factorлҘј м ңмҷён•ҳл©ҙ near-optimal convergence rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” fully parameter-free methodлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. (ii) convex caseм—җм„ңлҠ” accelerationкіј universality мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” parameter-free methodлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, grid search frameworkмқҳ мөңмў… лӢЁкі„мқё model ensembleм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ interpolated variance characterization н•ҳм—җм„ң лҚ” м •көҗн•ң guaranteeлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64318","en":"Adaptive Sharpness-Aware Minimization with a Polyak-type Step size: A Theory-Grounded Scheduler","ko":"Polyakнҳ• мҠӨн…қ нҒ¬кё°лҘј к°–лҠ” м Ғмқ‘нҳ• Sharpness-Aware Minimization: мқҙлЎ  кё°л°ҳ мҠӨмјҖмӨ„лҹ¬","authors":"Dimitris Oikonomou, Nicolas Loizou","pos":"#3706","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=On2B3By7PT","abs":"Sharpness-Aware Minimization (SAM) has established itself as a powerful and widely adopted optimizer for training machine learning models. By explicitly minimizing the sharpness of the loss landscape, SAM often improves generalization while delivering strong empirical performance. However, SAM and its variants, like most training algorithms, are sensitive to the choice of learning rate, which is typically tuned by trial and error or via schedulers. In this work, motivated by recent advances on the effectiveness of stochastic Polyak step sizes for Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD), we derive Polyak schedulers tailored to SAM-style updates, yielding novel adaptive algorithms in both deterministic and stochastic settings. In smooth setting, for the proposed methods, we prove linear convergence for strongly convex objectives and an $O(1/T)$ rate (up to a neighborhood in the stochastic setting) for convex objectives. Numerical experiments demonstrate that the proposed Polyak schedulers match or surpass tuned SAM baselines while substantially reducing the need for learning-rate tuning.","absKo":"Sharpness-Aware Minimization(SAM)мқҖ machine learning model н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң к°•л Ҙн•ҳкі  л„җлҰ¬ мұ„нғқлҗң optimizerлЎң мһҗлҰ¬ мһЎм•ҳлӢӨ. loss landscapeмқҳ sharpnessлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, SAMмқҖ мў…мў… к°•н•ң мӢӨмҰқм Ғ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©ҙм„ң мқјл°ҳнҷ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ SAMкіј к·ё ліҖнҳ•л“ӨмқҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ training algorithmкіј л§Ҳм°¬к°Җм§ҖлЎң learning rate м„ нғқм—җ лҜјк°җн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” ліҙнҶө мӢңн–үм°©мҳӨлӮҳ schedulerлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мЎ°м •лҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” Stochastic Gradient Descent(SGD)м—җ лҢҖн•ң stochastic Polyak step sizeмқҳ мөңк·ј м„ұкіјм—җ м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, SAM мҠӨнғҖмқј updateм—җ л§һм¶ҳ Polyak schedulerлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкі , deterministic л°Ҹ stochastic setting лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ adaptive algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. smooth settingм—җм„ң м ңм•Ҳн•ң л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ strongly convex objectiveм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ linear convergenceлҘј, convex objectiveм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” (stochastic settingм—җм„ңлҠ” neighborhoodк№Ңм§Җмқҳ) $O(1/T)$ rateлҘј мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ м ңм•Ҳн•ң Polyak schedulerк°Җ нҠңлӢқлҗң SAM baselineкіј лҸҷл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ learning-rate нҠңлӢқмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"65197","en":"Understanding SAM through Minimax Perspective","ko":"Minimax кҙҖм җмқ„ нҶөн•ң SAM мқҙн•ҙ","authors":"Ying Chen, Aoxi Li, Javad Lavaei","pos":"#3707","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FtdLp5lYOd","abs":"Sharpness-Aware Minimization (SAM) empirically boosts generalization by seeking parameters that minimize the worst-case loss in a small neighborhood, yet existing theory explains its behavior under either strong convexity or small perturbation radius. We revisit SAM through the bilevel minimax problem $\\min_{\\theta}\\max_{\\|\\Delta\\|\\le\\rho}l(\\theta+\\Delta)$ and derive a $(\\theta,\\Delta)$ gradient flow ODE whose equilibria coincide with the problemвҖҷs optimality conditions. A Lyapunov argumentвҖ”free of convexity assumptionsвҖ”quantifies how the optimality gap depends on the radius~$\\rho$ and local curvature. Discretizing the flow yields a \\emph{Multi-step SAM} algorithm that recovers classical SAM as $\\rho\\!\\to\\!0$. {Moreover, our analysis and the resulting algorithm remain valid even for large $\\rho$, providing principled guidance for aggressive neighborhood exploration.} Experiments on synthetic objectives and CIFAR-10 validate the predicted gains from multiple inner updates, bridging the gap between SAMвҖҷs minimax intuition and its practical implementation.","absKo":"Sharpness-Aware Minimization(SAM)мқҖ мһ‘мқҖ мқҙмӣғм—җм„ң мөңм•…мқҳ мҶҗмӢӨмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” нҢҢлқјлҜён„°лҘј м°ҫмқҢмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқјл°ҳнҷ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ кІҪн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ мқҙлЎ мқҖ к°•н•ң ліјлЎқм„ұ лҳҗлҠ” мһ‘мқҖ perturbation radius н•ҳм—җм„ңл§Ң к·ё лҸҷмһ‘мқ„ м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SAMмқ„ bilevel minimax л¬ём ң $\\min_{\\theta}\\max_{\\|\\Delta\\|\\le\\rho}l(\\theta+\\Delta)$лЎң лӢӨмӢң мӮҙнҺҙліҙкі , к·ё equilibriumмқҙ л¬ём ңмқҳ optimality conditionsмҷҖ мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” $(\\theta,\\Delta)$ gradient flow ODEлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. ліјлЎқм„ұ к°Җм •мқҙ м—ҶлҠ” Lyapunov argumentлҘј нҶөн•ҙ optimality gapмқҙ radius~$\\rho$мҷҖ local curvatureм—җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ flowлҘј discretizeн•ҳл©ҙ кі м „м Ғмқё SAMмқ„ $\\rho\\!\\to\\!\\0$м—җм„ң нҡҢліөн•ҳлҠ” \\emph{Multi-step SAM} м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙ м–»м–ҙм§„лӢӨ. {Moreover, our analysis and the resulting algorithm remain valid even for large $\\rho$, providing principled guidance for aggressive neighborhood exploration.} Synthetic objectivesмҷҖ CIFAR-10м—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ multiple inner updatesлЎңл¶Җн„° мҳҲмёЎлҗң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳл©°, SAMмқҳ minimax м§ҒкҙҖкіј мӢӨм ң кө¬нҳ„ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ."},{"id":"61486","en":"Non-Euclidean Gradient Descent Operates at the Edge of Stability","ko":"Non-Euclidean Gradient DescentлҠ” м•Ҳм •м„ұмқҳ кІҪкі„м—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Rustem Islamov, Michael Crawshaw, Jeremy Cohen, Robert Gower","pos":"#3708","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=piWlEHb4Db","abs":"The Edge of Stability (EoS) is a phenomenon where the sharpness (largest eigenvalue) of the Hessian converges to $2/\\eta$ during training with gradient descent (GD) with a step-size $\\eta$. Despite violating classical smoothness assumptions, EoS has been widely observed in deep learning, but its theoretical foundations remain incomplete. We propose a framework for analyzing EoS of non-Euclidean GD using directional smoothness (Mishkin et al., 2024), which naturally extends to non-Euclidean norms. This approach allows us to characterize EoS beyond the standard Euclidean setting, encompassing methods such as $\\ell_{\\infty}$-descent, Block CD, Spectral GD, and Muon without momentum. We derive the appropriate measure of the generalized sharpness under an arbitrary norm. Our generalized sharpness measure includes previously studied vanilla GD and preconditioned GD as special cases. Through analytical results and experiments on neural networks, we show that non-Euclidean GD also exhibits progressive sharpening followed by oscillations around the threshold $2/\\eta$. Practically, our framework provides a single, geometry-aware spectral measure that works across optimizers, bridging the gap between empirical observations and deep learning theory.","absKo":"Edge of Stability (EoS)лҠ” gradient descent (GD)лҘј step-size \\etaлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•  л•Ң Hessianмқҳ sharpness(мөңлҢҖ кі мң к°’)к°Җ 2/\\etaлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ҳлҠ” нҳ„мғҒмқҙлӢӨ. classical smoothness assumptionмқ„ мң„л°ҳн•Ём—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  EoSлҠ” deep learningм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ кҙҖм°°лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, к·ё мқҙлЎ м Ғ кё°л°ҳмқҖ м•„м§Ғ мҷ„м „н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” directional smoothness (Mishkin et al., 2024)лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ non-Euclidean GDмқҳ EoSлҘј л¶„м„қн•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ non-Euclidean normмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ н‘ңмӨҖ Euclidean settingмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ EoSлҘј нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, momentumмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” \\ell_{\\infty}-descent, Block CD, Spectral GD, Muonкіј к°ҷмқҖ л°©лІ•мқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһ„мқҳмқҳ norm н•ҳм—җм„ң generalized sharpnessмқҳ м Ғм Ҳн•ң measureлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ generalized sharpness measureлҠ” мқҙм „м—җ м—°кө¬лҗң vanilla GDмҷҖ preconditioned GDлҘј нҠ№мҲҳн•ң кІҪмҡ°лЎң нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. л¶„м„қ кІ°кіјмҷҖ neural network мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, non-Euclidean GD м—ӯмӢң м җм§„м Ғмқё sharpness мҰқк°Җ нӣ„ мһ„кі„к°’ 2/\\eta мЈјліҖм—җм„ңмқҳ м§„лҸҷмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨл¬ҙм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ”, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬к°Җ optimizer м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмқјн•ҳкі  geometry-awareн•ң spectral measureлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм—¬, кІҪн—ҳм Ғ кҙҖм°°кіј deep learning theory мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ."},{"id":"64498","en":"Last-iterate Convergence of ADMM on Multi-affine Quadratic Equality Constrained Problem","ko":"лӢӨмӨ‘ м•„н•Җ мқҙм°Ё л“ұмӢқ м ңм•Ҫ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң ADMMмқҳ л§Ҳм§Җл§ү л°ҳліө мҲҳл ҙ","authors":"Yutong Chao, Michal Ciebielski, Jalal Etesami, Majid Khadiv","pos":"#3711","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=MyBVUgacQ9","abs":"<p>In this paper, we study a class of non-convex optimization problems known as multi-affine quadratic equality constrained problems, which appear in various applications--from generating feasible force trajectories in robotic locomotion and manipulation to training neural networks. Although these problems are generally non-convex, they exhibit convexity or related properties when all variables except one are fixed. Under mild assumptions, we prove that the alternating direction method of multipliers (ADMM) converges when applied to this class of problems. Furthermore, when the \"degree\" of non-convexity in the constraints remains within certain bounds, we show that ADMM achieves a linear convergence rate. We validate our theoretical results through practical examples in robotic locomotion.</p>","absKo":"<p>мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” multi-affine quadratic equality constrained problemмңјлЎң м•Ңл Өм§„ л№„ліјлЎқ мөңм Ғнҷ” л¬ём ңмқҳ н•ң нҒҙлһҳмҠӨлҘј лӢӨлЈ№лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҠ” лЎңлҙҮ ліҙн–ү л°Ҹ мЎ°мһ‘м—җм„ң feasible force trajectoryлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” мқјл¶Җн„° neural network н•ҷмҠөм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң лӮҳнғҖлӮ©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҠ” мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң л№„ліјлЎқмқҙм§Җл§Ң, н•ҳлӮҳлҘј м ңмҷён•ң лӘЁл“  ліҖмҲҳлҘј кі м •н•ҳл©ҙ convexity лҳҗлҠ” к·ёмҷҖ кҙҖл Ёлҗң м„ұм§Ҳмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҷ„л§Ңн•ң к°Җм •н•ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” alternating direction method of multipliers(ADMM)к°Җ мқҙ л¬ём ң нҒҙлһҳмҠӨм—җ м Ғмҡ©лҗ  л•Ң мҲҳл ҙн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң м ңм•Ҫмқҳ л№„ліјлЎқм„ұ ``degree''к°Җ мқјм •н•ң лІ”мң„ лӮҙм—җ мһҲмқ„ л•Ң, ADMMмқҙ м„ нҳ• мҲҳл ҙлҘ мқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЎңлҙҮ ліҙн–үмқҳ мӢӨм ң мҳҲм ңлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61500","en":"Improved Convergence Analysis of Topology Dependence in Decentralized SGD","ko":"Decentralized SGDм—җм„ң Topology Dependenceмқҳ к°ңм„ лҗң мҲҳл ҙ л¶„м„қ","authors":"Yuki Takezawa, Anastasiia Koloskova, Sebastian Stich","pos":"#3713","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pYI0WjV5iM","abs":"<p>Decentralized SGD is a fundamental algorithm in decentralized learning, although the influence of an underlying network topology on its convergence behavior is not yet fully understood. Existing convergence analyses have shown that topologies with a small spectral gap significantly deteriorate the convergence rate of Decentralized SGD in both homogeneous and heterogeneous cases. However, many prior papers have reported that indeed the choice of the topology has a significant experimental impact in the heterogeneous case, but has little experimental impact on training behavior in the homogeneous case. In this paper, we present a tighter convergence analysis of Decentralized SGD, offering a more precise understanding of how topologies affect the convergence rate than the prior analysis. Specifically, unlike existing convergence analyses that used only the spectral gap as a property of the topology, our novel analysis shows that all eigenvalues of the mixing matrix affect the convergence rate. Throughout the experiments, we carefully evaluated the convergence behavior of Decentralized SGD and demonstrated that our novel convergence analysis can more accurately describe the effect of topology on the convergence rate.</p>","absKo":"<p>Decentralized SGDлҠ” decentralized learningмқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙм§Җл§Ң, кё°л°ҳ network topologyк°Җ мҲҳл ҙ кұ°лҸҷм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–ҘмқҖ м•„м§Ғ мҷ„м „нһҲ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ мҲҳл ҙ л¶„м„қл“ӨмқҖ мһ‘мқҖ spectral gapмқ„ к°Җм§„ topologyк°Җ homogeneous л°Ҹ heterogeneous кІҪмҡ° лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң Decentralized SGDмқҳ мҲҳл ҙ мҶҚлҸ„лҘј нҒ¬кІҢ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮЁлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ л§ҺмқҖ м„ н–ү л…јл¬ёл“ӨмқҖ мӢӨм ңлЎң topology м„ нғқмқҙ heterogeneous кІҪмҡ°м—җлҠ” мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң нҒ° мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳм§Җл§Ң, homogeneous кІҪмҡ°мқҳ training behaviorм—җлҠ” мӢӨн—ҳм Ғ мҳҒн–Ҙмқҙ кұ°мқҳ м—ҶлӢӨкі  ліҙкі н–ҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” Decentralized SGDм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҚ” м •л°Җн•ң мқҙн•ҙлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” лҚ” нғҖмқҙнҠён•ң мҲҳл ҙ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬, topologyк°Җ мҲҳл ҙ мҶҚлҸ„м—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ м„ н–ү л¶„м„қліҙлӢӨ лҚ” м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, topologyмқҳ м„ұм§ҲлЎң spectral gapл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н–ҲлҚҳ кё°мЎҙ мҲҳл ҙ л¶„м„қкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ л¶„м„қмқҖ mixing matrixмқҳ лӘЁл“  eigenvalueк°Җ мҲҳл ҙ мҶҚлҸ„м—җ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Decentralized SGDмқҳ мҲҳл ҙ кұ°лҸҷмқ„ мӢ мӨ‘н•ҳкІҢ нҸүк°Җн–Ҳкі , мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мҲҳл ҙ л¶„м„қмқҙ topologyк°Җ мҲҳл ҙ мҶҚлҸ„м—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” нҡЁкіјлҘј лҚ” м •нҷ•н•ҳкІҢ м„ӨлӘ…н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мһ…мҰқн–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61438","en":"Operator Splitting with Hamilton-Jacobi-based Proximals","ko":"Hamilton-Jacobi кё°л°ҳ Proximalмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң Operator Splitting","authors":"Nicholas Di, Eric Chi, Samy Wu Fung","pos":"#3804","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=q7mB5s1ie1","abs":"<p>Operator splitting algorithms are a cornerstone of modern first-order optimization, decomposing complex problems into simpler subproblems solved via proximal operators. However, most functions lack closed-form proximal operators, which has long restricted these methods to a narrow set of problems. Hamilton-Jacobi-based proximal operator (HJ-Prox) is a recent derivative-free Monte Carlo technique based on Hamilton-Jacobi PDE theory, that approximates proximal operators numerically. In this work, we introduce a unified framework for operator splitting via HJ-Prox, which allows for deployment of operator splitting even when functions are not proximable. We prove that replacing exact proximal steps with HJ-Prox in algorithms such as proximal point, proximal gradient descent, DouglasвҖ“Rachford splitting, DavisвҖ“Yin splitting, and primalвҖ“dual hybrid gradient preserves convergence guarantees under mild assumptions. Numerical experiments demonstrate HJ-Prox is competitive and effective on a wide variety of statistical learning tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Operator splitting algorithmмқҖ modern first-order optimizationмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мңјлЎң, ліөмһЎн•ң л¬ём ңлҘј proximal operatorлЎң н’Җ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лҚ” лӢЁмҲңн•ң subproblemмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ н•ЁмҲҳлҠ” closed-form proximal operatorлҘј к°Җм§Җм§Җ м•Ҡм•„, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•мқҖ мҳӨлһ«лҸҷм•Ҳ м ңн•ңлҗң лІ”мң„мқҳ л¬ём ңм—җл§Ң м Ғмҡ©лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. Hamilton-Jacobi-based proximal operator(HJ-Prox)лҠ” Hamilton-Jacobi PDE theoryм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң мөңк·јмқҳ derivative-free Monte Carlo кё°лІ•мңјлЎң, proximal operatorлҘј мҲҳм№ҳм ҒмңјлЎң к·јмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” HJ-ProxлҘј нҶөн•ң operator splittingмқҳ нҶөн•© н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ н•ЁмҲҳк°Җ proximableн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҚ”лқјлҸ„ operator splittingмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” proximal point, proximal gradient descent, DouglasвҖ“Rachford splitting, DavisвҖ“Yin splitting, primalвҖ“dual hybrid gradientмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳм—җм„ң exact proximal stepмқ„ HJ-ProxлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ҙлҸ„, mild assumption н•ҳм—җм„ң convergence guaranteeк°Җ мң м§ҖлҗЁмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ HJ-Proxк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң statistical learning taskм—җм„ң кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66703","en":"Randomized Feasibility Methods for Constrained Optimization with Adaptive Step Sizes","ko":"м Ғмқ‘м Ғ Step SizeлҘј к°–м¶ҳ м ңм•Ҫ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң л¬ҙмһ‘мң„нҷ” мӢӨнҳ„к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ л°©лІ•","authors":"Abhishek Chakraborty, Angelia Nedich","pos":"#3805","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=1BchRVONfp","abs":"We consider minimizing an objective function subject to constraints defined by the intersection of lower-level sets of convex functions. We study two cases: (i) strongly convex and Lipschitz-smooth objective function and (ii) convex but possibly nonsmooth objective function. To deal with the constraints that are not easy to project on, we use a randomized feasibility algorithm with Polyak steps and a random number of sampled constraints per iteration, while taking (sub)gradient steps to minimize the objective function. For case (i), we prove linear convergence in expectation of the objective function values to any prescribed tolerance using an adaptive stepsize. For case (ii), we develop a fully problem parameter-free and adaptive stepsize scheme that yields an $O(1/\\sqrt{T})$ worst-case rate in expectation. The infeasibility of the iterates decreases geometrically with the number of feasibility updates almost surely, while for the averaged iterates, we establish an expected lower bound on the function values relative to the optimal value that depends on the distribution for the random number of sampled constraints. For certain choices of sample-size growth, optimal rates are achieved. Finally, simulations on a Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming (QCQP) problem and Support Vector Machines (SVM) demonstrate the computational efficiency of our algorithm compared to other state-of-the-art methods.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” convex н•ЁмҲҳл“Өмқҳ lower-level setмқҳ көҗм§‘н•©мңјлЎң м •мқҳлҗҳлҠ” м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л§ҢмЎұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј кі л Өн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ кІҪмҡ°лҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ: (i) strongly convexмқҙкі  Lipschitz-smoothн•ң лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳ, (ii) convexн•ҳм§Җл§Ң possibly nonsmoothн•ң лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳ. мүҪкІҢ projectionн•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” м ңм•Ҫмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ iterationл§ҲлӢӨ лһңлҚӨн•ҳкІҢ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғн•ң м ңм•Ҫмқҳ к°ңмҲҳлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі  Polyak stepмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” randomized feasibility algorithmкіј, лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң (sub)gradient stepмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. кІҪмҡ° (i)м—җм„ңлҠ” adaptive stepsizeлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳ к°’мқҙ мһ„мқҳмқҳ м •л°ҖлҸ„к№Ңм§Җ кё°лҢҖк°’м—җм„ң м„ нҳ• мҲҳл ҙн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. кІҪмҡ° (ii)м—җм„ңлҠ” мҷ„м „нһҲ problem parameter-freeмқҙкі  adaptiveн•ң stepsize schemeмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬ кё°лҢҖк°’ кё°мӨҖмңјлЎң $O(1/\\sqrt{T})$мқҳ worst-case rateлҘј м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. iterateмқҳ infeasibilityлҠ” feasibility update нҡҹмҲҳм—җ л”°лқј кұ°мқҳ surely кё°н•ҳкёүмҲҳм ҒмңјлЎң к°җмҶҢн•ҳл©°, averaged iterateм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” мғҳн”Ңл§Ғлҗң м ңм•Ҫ мҲҳмқҳ л¶„нҸ¬м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” мөңм Ғк°’ лҢҖл№„ н•ЁмҲҳк°’мқҳ кё°лҢҖ н•ҳн•ңмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№м • sample-size growth м„ нғқм—җм„ңлҠ” мөңм Ғ rateк°Җ лӢ¬м„ұлҗңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, Quadratically Constrained Quadratic Programming (QCQP) л¬ём ңмҷҖ Support Vector Machines (SVM)м—җм„ңмқҳ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳмқҖ м ңм•Ҳн•ң м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙ лӢӨлҘё state-of-the-art л°©лІ•м—җ л№„н•ҙ кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқҙ лӣ°м–ҙлӮЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"66543","en":"A Penalty Approach For Differentiation Through Black-box Quadratic Programming Solvers","ko":"лё”лһҷл°•мҠӨ мқҙм°Ё кі„нҡҚ н•ҙкІ°кё°лҘј нҶөн•ң лҜёл¶„мқ„ мң„н•ң нҺҳл„җнӢ° м ‘к·јлІ•","authors":"Yuxuan Linghu, Zhiyuan Liu, Qi Deng","pos":"#3808","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2jpMiRwsrL","abs":"<p>Differentiating through the solution of a quadratic program (QP) is a central problem in differentiable optimization. Most existing approaches differentiate through the Karush--Kuhn--Tucker (KKT) system, but their computational cost and numerical robustness can degrade at scale. To address these limitations, we propose dXPP, a penalty-based differentiation framework that decouples QP solving from differentiation. In the solving step (forward pass), dXPP is solver-agnostic and can leverage any black-box QP solver. In the differentiation step (backward pass), we map the solution to a smooth approximate penalty problem and implicitly differentiate through it, requiring only the solution of a much smaller linear system in the primal variables. This approach bypasses the difficulties inherent in explicit KKT differentiation and significantly improves computational efficiency and robustness. We evaluate dXPP on various tasks, including randomly generated QPs, large-scale sparse projection problems, and a real-world multi-period portfolio optimization task. Empirical results demonstrate that dXPP is competitive with KKT-based differentiation methods and achieves substantial speedups on large-scale problems.</p>","absKo":"<p>quadratic program (QP)мқҳ н•ҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лҜёл¶„н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ differentiable optimizationмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ л¬ём ңмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ Karush--Kuhn--Tucker (KKT) systemмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лҜёл¶„н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©кіј мҲҳм№ҳм Ғ кІ¬кі м„ұмқҖ к·ңлӘЁк°Җ м»Өм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ м Җн•ҳлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” QP solvingкіј differentiationмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” penalty-based differentiation frameworkмқё dXPPлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. solving лӢЁкі„(forward pass)м—җм„ң dXPPлҠ” solver-agnosticн•ҳл©° м–ҙл–Ө black-box QP solverлҸ„ нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. differentiation лӢЁкі„(backward pass)м—җм„ңлҠ” н•ҙлҘј smooth approximate penalty problemмңјлЎң л§Өн•‘н•ң л’Ө мқҙлҘј implicitly differentiateн•ҳл©°, primal variableм—җм„ң нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ linear systemмқҳ н•ҙл§Ңмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ explicit KKT differentiationм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳкі  кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм„ұкіј кІ¬кі м„ұмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¬ҙмһ‘мң„лЎң мғқм„ұлҗң QP, лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ sparse projection problem, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мӢӨм ң multi-period portfolio optimization taskлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң кіјм ңм—җм„ң dXPPлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј dXPPлҠ” KKT-based differentiation methodмҷҖ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲмңјл©°, лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ л¬ём ңм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64283","en":"Gromov-Wasserstein at Scale, Beyond Squared Norms","ko":"м ңкіұ л…ёлҰ„мқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁм—җм„ңмқҳ Gromov-Wasserstein","authors":"Guillaume Houry, Jean Feydy, FranГ§ois-Xavier Vialard","pos":"#3813","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=P9LofJB8fs","abs":"<p>A fundamental challenge in data science is to match disparate point sets with each other. While optimal transport efficiently minimizes point <em>displacements</em> under a bijectivity constraint, it is inherently sensitive to rotations. Conversely, minimizing <em>distortions</em> via the Gromov-Wasserstein (GW) framework addresses this limitation but introduces a non-convex, computationally demanding optimization problem. In this work, we identify a broad class of distortion penalties that reduce to a simple alignment problem within a lifted feature space. Leveraging this insight, we introduce an iterative GW solver with a linear memory footprint and quadratic (rather than cubic) time complexity. Our method is differentiable, comes with strong theoretical guarantees, and scales to hundreds of thousands of points in minutes. This efficiency unlocks a wide range of geometric applications and enables the exploration of the GW energy landscape, whose local minima encode the symmetries of the matching problem.</p>","absKo":"<p>data scienceмқҳ к·јліём Ғ кіјм ңлҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё point setмқ„ м„ңлЎң л§Өм№ӯн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. optimal transportлҠ” bijectivity constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң point <em>displacement</em>лҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң rotationм—җ лҜјк°җн•ҳлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ, Gromov-Wasserstein (GW) frameworkлҘј нҶөн•ҙ <em>distortion</em>мқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙ мқҙ н•ңкі„лҘј лӢӨлЈ° мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, л№„ліјлЎқмқҙкі  кі„мӮ°м ҒмңјлЎң л¶ҖлӢҙмқҙ нҒ° optimization problemмқҙ лҸ„мһ…лҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” lifted feature space м•Ҳмқҳ лӢЁмҲңн•ң alignment problemмңјлЎң нҷҳмӣҗлҗҳлҠ” кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң distortion penalty classлҘј мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” linear memory footprintмҷҖ quadratic(мҰү, cubicмқҙ м•„лӢҢ) time complexityлҘј к°–лҠ” iterative GW solverлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ methodлҠ” differentiableн•ҳл©°, к°•н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳкі , мҲҳмӢӯл§Ң к°ңмқҳ pointлЎңлҸ„ лӘҮ л¶„ м•Ҳм—җ нҷ•мһҘлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң geometric applicationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкі , matching problemмқҳ symmetryлҘј мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” local minimumмқ„ м§ҖлӢҢ GW energy landscapeмқҳ нғҗмғүмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60853","en":"L-SR1: Learned Symmetric-Rank-One Preconditioning","ko":"L-SR1: н•ҷмҠөлҗң Symmetric-Rank-One Preconditioning","authors":"Gal Lifshitz, Shahar Zuler, Ori Fouks, Dan Raviv","pos":"#3814","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=w1fkDwiZgN","abs":"<p>End-to-end deep learning has achieved impressive results but often relies on large labeled datasets, exhibits limited generalization to unseen scenarios, and incurs substantial computational cost. Classical optimization methods, in contrast, are data-efficient and lightweight but frequently suffer from slow or unstable convergence. Learned optimizers aim to bridge this gap, yet existing approaches predominantly focus on first-order methods, leaving learned second-order optimization largely unexplored.  We introduce L-SR1, a novel learned second-order optimizer that augments the classical Symmetric Rank-One (SR1) method with a lightweight, trainable preconditioning unit. This unit generates data-driven rank-one updates that are explicitly aligned with the secant condition via a learned projection mechanism, ensuring stable and consistent curvature estimation. Through controlled analytic benchmarks, we systematically analyze the stability, generalization across problem dimensions, and the quality of the resulting search directions. We further evaluate L-SR1 on the real-world task of Monocular Human Mesh Recovery (HMR), where it outperforms existing optimization-based and learned-optimization baselines. With a compact model and no reliance on task-specific fine-tuning or annotated data, L-SR1 demonstrates strong generalization and provides an effective drop-in optimizer for a wide range of iterative optimization problems.</p>","absKo":"<p>End-to-end deep learningмқҖ мқёмғҒм Ғмқё м„ұкіјлҘј кұ°л‘җм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мў…мў… лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ labeled datasetм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкі , ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң мғҒнҷ©м—җ лҢҖн•ң мқјл°ҳнҷ”к°Җ м ңн•ңм Ғмқҙл©°, мғҒлӢ№н•ң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. л°ҳлҢҖлЎң classical optimization methodлҠ” data-efficientн•ҳкі  к°ҖліҚм§Җл§Ң, мҲҳл ҙмқҙ лҠҗлҰ¬кұ°лӮҳ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ң кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. Learned optimizerлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°л Ө н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң first-order methodм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҙ learned second-order optimizationмқҖ мғҒлҢҖм ҒмңјлЎң кұ°мқҳ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” classical Symmetric Rank-One (SR1) methodм—җ lightweightмқҙкі  н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн•ң preconditioning unitмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ learned second-order optimizerмқё L-SR1мқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ unitмқҖ learned projection mechanismмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ secant conditionкіј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м •л ¬лҗң data-driven rank-one updateлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳм—¬, м•Ҳм •м Ғмқҙкі  мқјкҙҖлҗң curvature estimationмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. нҶөм ңлҗң analytic benchmarkлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м•Ҳм •м„ұ, л¬ём ң м°Ёмӣҗ м „л°ҳмқҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ”, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мғқм„ұлҗң search directionмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мӢӨм„ёкі„ taskмқё Monocular Human Mesh Recovery (HMR)м—җм„ң L-SR1мқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙ optimization-based baselineкіј learned-optimization baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мһ‘кі  compactн•ң modelмқҙл©° task-specific fine-tuningмқҙлӮҳ annotated dataм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” L-SR1мқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң мқјл°ҳнҷ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, лӢӨм–‘н•ң iterative optimization problemм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё мҰүмӢң мӮ¬мҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң optimizerлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61027","en":"OPT-Engine: Benchmarking the Limits of LLMs in Optimization Modeling via Complexity Scaling","ko":"OPT-Engine: Complexity Scalingмқ„ нҶөн•ң мөңм Ғнҷ” лӘЁлҚёл§Ғм—җм„ң LLMмқҳ н•ңкі„ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№","authors":"Yitian Chen, Dongdong Ge, Cheng Cheng, Yinan Sun, Zi Ling","pos":"#3815","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=uQJktmCJZ4","abs":"<p>We investigate the capabilities and scalability of Large Language Models (LLMs) in optimization modeling,  a domain requiring structured reasoning and precise formulation. To this end, we introduce OPT-ENGINE, an extensible benchmark framework with quantifiable and controllable complexity. OPT-ENGINE spans ten canonical operations research problems, systematically scaling from Linear Programming to Mixed-Integer Programming, thus providing a structured environment to probe the limits of automated problem formulation and solving. Our results reveal a sharp performance degradation as task complexity scale, highlighting a critical robustness gap in pure-text reasoning. While LLMs struggle with end-to-end solution generation, we demonstrate that tool-integrated reasoning provides a significantly more resilient path forward, regardless of model size. Furthermore, we identify the automated formulation of the constraints as the primary bottleneck. These insights clarify the limitations of current LLMs and provide a structured roadmap for developing next-generation LLMs for optimization modeling.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” structured reasoningкіј precise formulationмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” optimization modeling л¶„м•јм—җм„ң Large Language Models (LLMs)мқҳ лҠҘл Ҙкіј scalabilityлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ м •лҹүнҷ” к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  м ңм–ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң ліөмһЎм„ұмқ„ м§ҖлӢҢ extensible benchmark frameworkмқё OPT-ENGINEмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. OPT-ENGINEмқҖ Linear Programmingм—җм„ң Mixed-Integer Programmingк№Ңм§Җ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘлҗҳлҠ” 10к°ңмқҳ лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё operations research л¬ём ңлҘј нҸ¬кҙ„н•ҳл©°, мһҗлҸҷ л¬ём ң м •мӢқнҷ”мҷҖ н•ҙкІ°мқҳ н•ңкі„лҘј нғҗмғүн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң нҷҳкІҪмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” task complexityк°Җ мҰқк°Җн•Ём—җ л”°лқј м„ұлҠҘмқҙ кёүкІ©нһҲ м Җн•ҳлҗЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, мҲңмҲҳ н…ҚмҠӨнҠё м¶”лЎ мқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң robustness gapмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. LLMsк°Җ end-to-end solution generationм—җлҠ” м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, tool-integrated reasoningмқҖ лӘЁлҚё нҒ¬кё°мҷҖ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳкІҢ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” кІ¬кі н•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ м ңм•ҪмЎ°кұҙмқҳ мһҗлҸҷ м •мӢқнҷ”к°Җ мЈјмҡ” лі‘лӘ©мһ„мқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқҖ нҳ„мһ¬ LLMsмқҳ н•ңкі„лҘј л¶„лӘ…нһҲ н•ҳкі , optimization modelingмқ„ мң„н•ң м°Ём„ёлҢҖ LLMs к°ңл°ңмқ„ мң„н•ң кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң лЎңл“ңл§өмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63752","en":"On the Provable Suboptimality of Momentum SGD in Nonstationary Stochastic Optimization","ko":"л№„м •мғҒ нҷ•лҘ  мөңм Ғнҷ”м—җм„ң Momentum SGDмқҳ мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ң л№„мөңм Ғм„ұм—җ кҙҖн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Sharan Sahu, Cameron Hogan, Martin Wells","pos":"#4505","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=U1bxeLQLaK","abs":"In this paper, we provide a comprehensive theoretical analysis of Stochastic Gradient Descent (SGD) and its momentum variants (Polyak Heavy-Ball and Nesterov) for tracking time-varying optima under strong convexity and smoothness. Our finite-time bounds reveal a sharp decomposition of tracking error into transient, noise-induced, and drift-induced components. This decomposition exposes a fundamental trade-off: while momentum is often used as a gradient-smoothing heuristic, under distribution shift it incurs an explicit drift-amplification penalty that diverges as the momentum parameter $\\beta$ approaches 1, yielding systematic tracking lag. We complement these upper bounds with minimax lower bounds under gradient-variation constraints, proving this momentum-induced tracking penalty is not an analytical artifact but an information-theoretic barrier: in drift-dominated regimes, momentum is unavoidably worse because stale-gradient averaging forces systematic lag. Our results provide theoretical grounding for the empirical instability of momentum in dynamic settings and precisely delineate regime boundaries where vanilla SGD provably outperforms its accelerated counterparts.","absKo":"<p>ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ к°•н•ң convexityмҷҖ smoothness н•ҳм—җм„ң мӢңк°„м—җ л”°лқј ліҖн•ҳлҠ” optimumмқ„ м¶”м Ғн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҲм–ҙ Stochastic Gradient Descent(SGD)мҷҖ к·ё momentum ліҖнҳ•(Polyak Heavy-Ball л°Ҹ Nesterov)м—җ лҢҖн•ң нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ finite-time boundлҠ” tracking errorлҘј transient, noise-induced, drift-induced componentлЎң лӮ м№ҙлЎӯкІҢ л¶„н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¶„н•ҙлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё trade-offлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мҰү, momentumмқҖ нқ”нһҲ gradient smoothing heuristicмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, distribution shift н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” momentum parameter $\\beta$к°Җ 1м—җ к°Җк№ҢмӣҢм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ л°ңмӮ°н•ҳлҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғ drift-amplification penaltyлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ҳм—¬ мІҙкі„м Ғмқё tracking lagлҘј л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” gradient-variation constraint н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ minimax lower boundлЎң мқҙ мғҒн•ңмқ„ ліҙмҷ„н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң momentum-induced tracking penaltyк°Җ л¶„м„қмғҒмқҳ мқёкіөл¬јмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј м •ліҙмқҙлЎ м Ғ мһҘлІҪмһ„мқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, drift-dominated regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” stale-gradient averagingмқҙ мІҙкі„м Ғмқё м§Җм—°мқ„ к°•м ңн•ҳлҜҖлЎң momentumмқҙ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лҚ” лӮҳмҒҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” dynamic settingм—җм„ң momentumмқҳ кІҪн—ҳм Ғ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •м„ұм—җ мқҙлЎ м Ғ к·јкұ°лҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, vanilla SGDк°Җ к°ҖмҶҚ кё°лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мӣ”н•Ёмқҙ мҰқлӘ…лҗҳлҠ” regime boundaryлҘј м •нҷ•нһҲ кө¬л¶„н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62788","en":"Mirror Mean-Field Langevin Dynamics","ko":"лҜёлҹ¬ нҸүк· мһҘ лһ‘мЈјлұ… лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷ","authors":"Anming Gu, Juno Kim","pos":"#4506","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=dIUrE5eR00","abs":"The mean-field Langevin dynamics (MFLD) minimizes an entropy-regularized nonlinear convex functional on the Wasserstein space over $\\mathbb{R}^d$, and has gained attention recently as a model for the gradient descent dynamics of interacting particle systems such as infinite-width two-layer neural networks. However, many problems of interest have constrained domains, which are not solved by existing mean-field algorithms due to the global diffusion term. We study the optimization of probability measures constrained to a convex subset of $\\mathbb{R}^d$ by proposing the \\emph{mirror mean-field Langevin dynamics} (MMFLD), an extension of MFLD to the mirror Langevin framework. We obtain linear convergence guarantees for the continuous MMFLD via a uniform log-Sobolev inequality, and uniform-in-time propagation of chaos results for its time- and particle-discretized counterpart.","absKo":"нҸүк· мһҘ Langevin dynamics(MFLD)лҠ” $\\mathbb{R}^d$ мң„мқҳ Wasserstein кіөк°„м—җм„ң entropy-regularized nonlinear convex functionalмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳл©°, л¬ҙн•ң нҸӯ two-layer neural networkмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ interacting particle systemмқҳ gradient descent dynamicsлҘј лӘЁнҳ•нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мңјлЎң мөңк·ј мЈјлӘ©л°ӣкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кҙҖмӢ¬ мһҲлҠ” л§ҺмқҖ л¬ём ңлҠ” м ңм•Ҫлҗң лҸ„л©”мқёмқ„ к°Җм§Җл©°, м „м—ӯ diffusion term л•Ңл¬ём—җ кё°мЎҙ mean-field algorithmмңјлЎңлҠ” мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” mirror Langevin frameworkм—җ MFLDлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ң \\emph{mirror mean-field Langevin dynamics}(MMFLD)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, $\\mathbb{R}^d$мқҳ ліјлЎқ л¶Җл¶„м§‘н•©м—җ м ңм•Ҫлҗң probability measureмқҳ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” uniform log-Sobolev inequalityлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м—°мҶҚнҳ• MMFLDмқҳ м„ нҳ• мҲҳл ҙ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м–»кі , мқҙлҘј мӢңк°„ л°Ҹ мһ…мһҗ мқҙмӮ°нҷ”н•ң лҢҖмқ‘ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ uniform-in-time propagation of chaos кІ°кіјлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65172","en":"Accelerated and Stable Convergence with Anchored Generalized Optimistic Method","ko":"Anchored Generalized Optimistic л°©лІ•мқ„ нҶөн•ң к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”лҗҳкі  м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё мҲҳл ҙ","authors":"Motahareh Sohrabi, Jianxin You, Simon Lacoste-Julien, Eduard Gorbunov, Gauthier Gidel","pos":"#4509","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=G6WKIN1heG","abs":"We study first-order methods for solving monotone variational inequalities arising in min-max optimization. Classical approaches such as the extragradient method rely on two gradient queries per iteration, which limits their analysis and applicability in the online and stochastic settings. We propose a family of Generalized Optimistic Methods with Anchoring (GOMA), which combine two time-scale optimistic updates with an anchoring term inspired by Halpern iteration. In particular, we show that for monotone Lipschitz operators, GOMA achieves an accelerated last-iterate convergence rate of $\\mathcal{O}(1/k^2)$ in the squared gradient norm which is optimal. We also show that in stochastic games where classical methods, such as the extragradient and optimistic method, fail, GOMA can converge. Theoretically, we show that it has a last-iterate convergence rate of $\\mathcal{O}(1/\\sqrt{k})$ for monotone Lipschitz operators in stochastic regimes with linearly increasing minibatches.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” min-max мөңм Ғнҷ”м—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗҳлҠ” monotone variational inequalityлҘј н‘ёлҠ” first-order methodлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. extragradient methodмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ кі м „м Ғ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ л°ҳліөл§ҲлӢӨ л‘җ лІҲмқҳ gradient queryм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, мҳЁлқјмқё л°Ҹ stochastic settingм—җм„ңмқҳ л¶„м„қкіј м Ғмҡ©мқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Halpern iterationм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣмқҖ anchoring termкіј л‘җ к°ңмқҳ time-scale optimistic updateлҘј кІ°н•©н•ң Generalized Optimistic Methods with Anchoring (GOMA) кі„м—ҙмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ monotone Lipschitz operatorм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ, GOMAлҠ” squared gradient normм—җм„ң $\\mathcal{O}(1/k^2)$мқҳ к°ҖмҶҚлҗң last-iterate convergence rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мөңм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң extragradientмҷҖ optimistic method к°ҷмқҖ кі м „м Ғ л°©лІ•мқҙ мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” stochastic gameм—җм„ңлҸ„ GOMAлҠ” мҲҳл ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң, linearly increasing minibatchлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” stochastic regimeм—җм„ң monotone Lipschitz operatorм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ $\\mathcal{O}(1/\\sqrt{k})$мқҳ last-iterate convergence rateлҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"64304","en":"Provably Data-driven Lagrangian Relaxation for Mixed Integer Linear Programming","ko":"нҳјн•© м •мҲҳ м„ нҳ• кі„нҡҚлІ•мқ„ мң„н•ң мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„° кё°л°ҳ Lagrangian мҷ„нҷ”","authors":"QUOC TUNG LE, Anh Nguyen, Viet Anh Nguyen","pos":"#4515","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OwLuqetJuB","abs":"Lagrangian Relaxation (LR) is a powerful technique for solving large-scale Mixed Integer Linear Programming (MILP), particularly those with decomposable structures like Vehicle Routing or Unit Commitment. By relaxing coupling constraints, LR enables parallel solving of subproblems and frequently yields tighter dual bounds than standard linear programming relaxations, which is crucial for efficient branch-and-bound pruning. While recent empirical works showed promising results using machine learning to predict these multipliers, a theoretical understanding of such methods remains an open question. In this work, we bridge this gap by analyzing the problem of learning LR through the lens of Data-driven Algorithm Design, i.e., a statistical learning problem over a distribution of problem instances. Our contributions are as follows: first, we derive a generalization bound of $\\cO(s^{1.5}/\\sqrt{N})$ for the learned multipliers, where $s$ is the number of coupled constraints and $N$ is the sample size. Second, we provide a minimax lower-bound of $\\Omega(s/\\sqrt{N})$, proving that a linear dependency is unavoidable. Finally, we extend our framework to the problem of learning to warm-start sub-gradient ascent.","absKo":"Lagrangian Relaxation(LR)мқҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ Mixed Integer Linear Programming(MILP), нҠ№нһҲ Vehicle RoutingмқҙлӮҳ Unit CommitmentмІҳлҹј decomposable structureлҘј к°Җм§„ л¬ём ңлҘј н‘ёлҠ” лҚ° к°•л Ҙн•ң кё°лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. coupling constraintлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ LRмқҖ subproblemмқ„ лі‘л ¬лЎң н’Җ мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳкі , н‘ңмӨҖ linear programming relaxationліҙлӢӨ лҚ” нғҖмқҙнҠён•ң dual boundлҘј мһҗмЈј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё branch-and-bound pruningм—җ л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ мӢӨмҰқ м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ machine learningмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң multiplierлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мң л§қн•ң кІ°кіјлҘј ліҙмҳҖм§Җл§Ң, к·ёлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•м—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ мқҙн•ҙлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м—ҙлҰ° л¬ём ңлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” Data-driven Algorithm Designмқҳ кҙҖм җ, мҰү л¬ём ң instance л¶„нҸ¬ мң„мқҳ statistical learning problemмңјлЎң мқҙ мқҙмҠҲлҘј л¶„м„қн•ҳм—¬ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кё°м—¬лҠ” лӢӨмқҢкіј к°ҷлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, $s$к°Җ coupled constraintмқҳ мҲҳмқҙкі  $N$мқҙ sample sizeмқј л•Ң, learned multiplierм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ $\\cO(s^{1.5}/\\sqrt{N})$мқҳ generalization boundлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, $\\Omega(s/\\sqrt{N})$мқҳ minimax lower boundлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬ м„ нҳ• мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқҙ н”јн•  мҲҳ м—ҶмқҢмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, sub-gradient ascentмқҳ warm-startлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"62106","en":"A Direct Second-Order Method for Solving Two-Player Zero-Sum Games","ko":"2мқё м ңлЎңм„¬ кІҢмһ„ н•ҙкІ°мқ„ мң„н•ң м§Ғм ‘ 2м°Ё л°©лІ•","authors":"David Yang, Yuan Gao, Tianyi Lin, Christian Kroer","pos":"#4621","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jn7gGAya5h","abs":"We introduce, to our knowledge, the first direct second-order method for computing Nash equilibria in two-player zero-sum games. To do so, we construct a Douglas-Rachford-style splitting formulation, which we then solve with a semi-smooth Newton (SSN) method. We show that our algorithm enjoys local superlinear convergence. To augment the fast local behavior of our SSN method with global efficiency guarantees, we develop a hybrid method that combines our SSN method with the state-of-the-art first-order method for game solving, Predictive Regret Matching (PRM$^+$). Our hybrid algorithm leverages the global progress provided by PRM$^+$ while achieving a local superlinear convergence rate once it switches to SSN near a Nash equilibrium. Numerical experiments on matrix games demonstrate order-of-magnitude speedups over PRM$^+$ for high-precision solutions.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ н”Ңл Ҳмқҙм–ҙ zero-sum gameм—җм„ң Nash equilibriumмқ„ кі„мӮ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң, мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м•„лҠ” н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ м§Ғм ‘м Ғмқё second-order methodлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ Douglas-Rachford мҠӨнғҖмқјмқҳ splitting formulationмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј semi-smooth Newton (SSN) methodлЎң н‘јлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙ local superlinear convergenceлҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. SSN methodмқҳ л№ лҘё local behaviorм—җ global efficiency ліҙмһҘмқ„ лҚ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” game solvingмқ„ мң„н•ң мөңмІЁлӢЁ first-order methodмқё Predictive Regret Matching (PRM$^+$)кіј SSN methodлҘј кІ°н•©н•ң hybrid methodлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ hybrid algorithmмқҖ PRM$^+$к°Җ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” global progressлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙм„ң, Nash equilibrium к·јмІҳм—җм„ң SSNмңјлЎң м „нҷҳлҗҳл©ҙ local superlinear convergence rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. matrix gameм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ high-precision solutionм—җм„ң PRM$^+$ лҢҖл№„ н•ң мһҗлҰҝмҲҳ к·ңлӘЁмқҳ мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"61502","en":"From Interaction Trajectories to Prompt Rules: Credit Assignment for Multi-Agent Prompt Optimization","ko":"Interaction Trajectoryм—җм„ң Prompt RuleлЎң: Multi-Agent Prompt Optimizationмқ„ мң„н•ң Credit Assignment","authors":"Bin Wu, Haoran Xu, Xiang Zhuang, Zonghao Chen, Zhu Li, Emine Yilmaz, Qiang Zhang","pos":"#124","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pXF0puBofz","abs":"<p>Large language model (LLM)-based multi-agent systems commonly rely on natural-language prompts to specify agent behavior, yet optimizing these prompts remains challenging when agent roles and interaction structures are fixed by design. In such systems, behaviors emerge over long, noisy interaction trajectories, making it difficult to determine which prompt components are responsible for success or failure. As a result, outcome-level feedback alone is insufficient, while existing prompt optimization methods typically rely on final task scores or global prompt rewrites, limiting their ability to exploit trajectory evidence or support the localized updates. We propose Trajectory-based Rule Credit Estimation (TRUCE), a framework for prompt optimization in multi-agent systems that explicitly addresses this credit assignment challenge. TRUCE performs trajectory-aware attribution by linking outcome feedback to informative sub-trajectories and translating the resulting credit signals into unit-level edits over prompt-defined behavioral rules. By preserving agent roles and interaction structures, TRUCE enables prompt refinement through localized updates aggregated across tasks. Experiments on multiple benchmarks demonstrate that TRUCE consistently improves task performance and efficiency over competitive baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language model(LLM) кё°л°ҳ multi-agent systemмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң agent behaviorлҘј м§Җм •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ natural-language promptм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, agent roleкіј interaction structureк°Җ м„Өкі„м—җ мқҳн•ҙ кі м •лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмқ„ л•Ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң promptлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ңлҠ” кёҙ noisy interaction trajectory м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ behaviorк°Җ emergentн•ҳкІҢ лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҜҖлЎң, м–ҙл–Ө prompt кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢк°Җ м„ұкіө лҳҗлҠ” мӢӨнҢЁм—җ мұ…мһ„мқҙ мһҲлҠ”м§Җ нҢҗлӢЁн•ҳкё°к°Җ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј outcome-level feedbackл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, кё°мЎҙ prompt optimization л°©лІ•мқҖ лҢҖк°ң мөңмў… task score лҳҗлҠ” м „м—ӯ prompt мһ¬мһ‘м„ұм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ trajectory evidenceлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ localized updateлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң credit assignment л¬ём ңлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” multi-agent systemмҡ© prompt optimization frameworkмқё Trajectory-based Rule Credit Estimation(TRUCE)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. TRUCEлҠ” outcome feedbackмқ„ informative sub-trajectoryмҷҖ м—°кІ°н•ҳкі , к·ё кІ°кіјлЎң м–»м–ҙм§„ credit signalмқ„ promptлЎң м •мқҳлҗң behavioral ruleм—җ лҢҖн•ң unit-level editмңјлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ trajectory-aware attributionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. agent roleкіј interaction structureлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, TRUCEлҠ” task м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ м§‘кі„лҗң localized updateлҘј нҶөн•ҙ prompt refinementлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ TRUCEк°Җ кІҪмҹҒ baselineліҙлӢӨ task performanceмҷҖ efficiencyлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63167","en":"Proximal-Based Generative Modeling for Bayesian Inverse Problems","ko":"лІ мқҙм§Җм•Ҳ м—ӯл¬ём ңлҘј мң„н•ң к·јм ‘м җ кё°л°ҳ мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғ","authors":"Boyang Zhang, Zhiguo Wang, Ya-Feng Liu","pos":"#2607","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZS2OLXn2fO","abs":"<p>Score-based diffusion models demonstrate superior performance in generative tasks but encounter fundamental bottlenecks in inverse problems due to the analytical intractability of the time-dependent likelihood score. To bridge this gap, we propose a novel proximal-based generative modeling (PGM) framework that rigorously circumvents explicit likelihood evaluation. Our framework is built upon a theoretical equivalence between Gaussian convolution in diffusion processes and Moreau-Yosida regularization in nonsmooth optimization.  This enables a new sampling mechanism driven by the proposed Moreau score, which admits a closed-form expression via proximal operators. Moreover, we introduce Moreau score matching to learn the proximal operators that rely solely on samples drawn from the prior distribution. Theoretically, PGM eliminates the early-stopping bias inherent in the score-based diffusion model and achieves non-asymptotic convergence. Experiments demonstrate that PGM significantly surpasses state-of-the-art methods in reconstruction quality and sampling time.</p>","absKo":"<p>score-based diffusion modelмқҖ generative taskм—җм„ң лӣ°м–ҙлӮң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мӢңк°„ мқҳмЎҙм Ғмқё likelihood scoreмқҳ л¶„м„қм Ғ кі„мӮ° к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ л¶Җмһ¬ л•Ңл¬ём—җ inverse problemм—җм„ңлҠ” к·јліём Ғмқё лі‘лӘ©м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” explicit likelihood нҸүк°ҖлҘј м—„л°Җн•ҳкІҢ мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ proximal-based generative modeling(PGM) н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” diffusion processм—җм„ңмқҳ Gaussian convolutionкіј nonsmooth optimizationм—җм„ңмқҳ Moreau-Yosida regularization мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ лҸҷл“ұм„ұм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ proximal operatorлҘј нҶөн•ҙ closed-form expressionмқ„ к°–лҠ” proposed Moreau scoreм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кө¬лҸҷлҗҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ sampling mechanismмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҙм§„лӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” prior distributionм—җм„ң мғҳн”Ңл§Ғлҗң sampleм—җл§Ң мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” proximal operatorлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ Moreau score matchingмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң, PGMмқҖ score-based diffusion modelм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң early-stopping biasлҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳкі  non-asymptotic convergenceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, PGMмқҖ reconstruction qualityмҷҖ sampling time мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң state-of-the-art methodлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63130","en":"AD-BTS: Adaptive Dual-Branch Token Sparsification via Spatial Information Density","ko":"AD-BTS: кіөк°„ м •ліҙ л°ҖлҸ„лҘј нҶөн•ң м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мқҙмӨ‘ л¶„кё° нҶ нҒ° нқ¬мҶҢнҷ”","authors":"Xinpei Gao, Xin Luo, Ming Liu, Chunjiang Wang, S Kevin Zhou","pos":"#3010","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Zm8DAMbfXE","abs":"<p>High-resolution visual encoders in multimodal large language models (MLLMs) substantially improve fine-grained perception, yet incur prohibitive computational costs.Existing token pruning methods are effective on natural images but struggle with spatially sparse structured inputs (e.g., charts), where critical high-frequency information is sparse, localized, and structurally essential. To address this challenge, we propose Adaptive Dual-Branch Token Sparsification (AD-BTS), a density-aware framework that dynamically allocates computation according to input signal characteristics. Specifically, AD-BTS introduces a Gradient-based Routing Gate (GRG) that uses lightweight pixel-level gradient statistics to estimate structural flatness and guide routing. Then, AD-BTS activates either a Redundancy Selection Branch (RSB) for aggressive token pruning with a frozen encoder, or a Structural Fusion Branch (SFB) with conditional LoRA and context fusion to preserve sparse structural information.Extensive experiments on Qwen2.5-VL demonstrate that AD-BTS establishes a new Pareto frontier between efficiency and accuracy. Under extreme compression (20% token retention), AD-BTS outperforms the strongest baseline by 12.1% on ChartQA while achieving a 1.8Г— prefill speedup, effectively reconciling computational efficiency with structural robustness.</p>","absKo":"<p>л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ large language models (MLLMs)м—җм„ң кі н•ҙмғҒлҸ„ visual encoderлҠ” м„ёл°Җн•ң м§Җк°Ғмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨм§Җл§Ң, л§үлҢҖн•ң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ token pruning л°©лІ•мқҖ мһҗм—° мқҙлҜём§Җм—җм„ңлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, chartsмІҳлҹј кіөк°„м ҒмңјлЎң нқ¬мҶҢн•ң кө¬мЎ°нҷ” мһ…л Ҙм—җм„ңлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кі мЈјнҢҢ м •ліҙк°Җ нқ¬мҶҢн•ҳкі  көӯмҶҢм Ғмқҙл©° кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһ…л Ҙ мӢ нҳёмқҳ нҠ№м„ұм—җ л”°лқј кі„мӮ°мқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң н• лӢ№н•ҳлҠ” density-aware frameworkмқё Adaptive Dual-Branch Token Sparsification (AD-BTS)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, AD-BTSлҠ” к°ҖлІјмҡҙ pixel-level gradient statisticsлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ нҸүнғ„м„ұмқ„ м¶”м •н•ҳкі  routingмқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳлҠ” Gradient-based Routing Gate (GRG)лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ AD-BTSлҠ” frozen encoderлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кіөкІ©м Ғмқё token pruningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” Redundancy Selection Branch (RSB) лҳҗлҠ” conditional LoRAмҷҖ context fusionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ нқ¬мҶҢн•ң кө¬мЎ° м •ліҙлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” Structural Fusion Branch (SFB) мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳлҘј нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. Qwen2.5-VLм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ AD-BTSк°Җ нҡЁмңЁм„ұкіј м •нҷ•лҸ„ мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Pareto frontierлҘј кө¬м¶•н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. к·№лӢЁм Ғ м••м¶•(20% token retention)н•ҳм—җм„ң AD-BTSлҠ” ChartQAм—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ к°•л Ҙн•ң baselineмқ„ 12.1% м•һм„ңл©ҙм„ң prefill мҶҚлҸ„лҘј 1.8л°° н–ҘмғҒмӢңмјң, кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм„ұкіј кө¬мЎ°м Ғ к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м–‘лҰҪмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66499","en":"Robust Contextual Optimization with Missing Covariates","ko":"кІ°мёЎ кіөліҖлҹүмқ„ к°–лҠ” кІ¬кі н•ң Contextual мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Qingyuan Xu, Ruiwei Jiang","pos":"#3702","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=37KrsS7g7c","abs":"<p>Modern decision-making increasingly relies on contextual features (covariates) to improve optimization under uncertainty. In practice, however, such covariates are often only partially observed due to, e.g., data source heterogeneity or costly data collection. Nonetheless, most existing methods assume fully observed historical data and can become unreliable when this assumption is violated. We address this gap by proposing a distributionally robust optimization approach that exploits incomplete covariates to produce robust decisions without imputing a complete dataset. Our method builds ambiguity sets from the observed partial data and incorporates the general structure of the missingness mechanism, ensuring candidate distributions remain consistent with what is observed. Across settings with discrete or continuous covariates and outcomes, we derive tractable reformulations and establish finite-sample out-of-sample performance guarantees. Empirical results across a range of contextual decision-making tasks demonstrate that the proposed integrated approach consistently outperforms state-of-the-art baselines, including various impute-then-optimize pipelines, in both out-of-sample performance and reliability.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖмқҳ мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м •мқҖ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұ н•ҳмқҳ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј к°ңм„ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ contextual feature(covariate)м—җ м җм җ лҚ” мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„° мҶҢмҠӨмқҳ мқҙм§Ҳм„ұмқҙлӮҳ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° лҚ°мқҙн„° мҲҳм§‘ л“ұмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң covariateк°Җ л¶Җл¶„м ҒмңјлЎңл§Ң кҙҖмёЎлҗҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. к·ёлҹјм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мҷ„м „нһҲ кҙҖмёЎлҗң historical dataлҘј к°Җм •н•ҳл©°, мқҙ к°Җм •мқҙ к№Ём§Җл©ҙ мӢ лў°м„ұмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҷ„м „н•ң datasetмқ„ imputationн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ incomplete covariateлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ robust decisionмқ„ мӮ°м¶ңн•ҳлҠ” distributionally robust optimization м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ кҙҖмёЎлҗң partial dataлЎңл¶Җн„° ambiguity setмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі  missingness mechanismмқҳ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬, candidate distributionмқҙ кҙҖмёЎлҗң лӮҙмҡ©кіј мқјкҙҖлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. discrete лҳҗлҠ” continuous covariateмҷҖ outcomeмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң м„Өм • м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” tractable reformulationмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳкі  finite-sample out-of-sample м„ұлҠҘ ліҙмһҘмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ contextual decision-making taskм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ out-of-sample м„ұлҠҘкіј мӢ лў°м„ұ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң impute-then-optimize pipelineмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62668","en":"Minimizing Upper Confidence Bounds: A Data-Driven Framework for Stochastic Programming","ko":"мөңлҢҖмӢ лў°кө¬к°„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”: нҷ•лҘ м Ғ мөңм Ғнҷ” мң„н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„° кё°л°ҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Shixin Liu, Ming Gao, Jian Hu","pos":"#3703","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eXLcL70GXO","abs":"<p>Stochastic programming is often challenged by epistemic uncertainty, where critical probability distributions are poorly characterized or unknown due to a lack of data. To address this, we pioneer a novel framework for stochastic programming that minimizes an upper confidence bound (UCB) on the expected random cost, acting as a robustness-seeking strategy. Our central contribution is the Average Percentile Upper Bound (APUB), a new statistical construct that serves as both a statistically rigorous upper bound for population means and an approximate risk metric for sample means. We rigorously prove the asymptotic correctness and consistency of APUB, establishing a reliable foundation for data-driven decision-making. We also develop practical solution methods, including a bootstrap sampling approximation method and an L-shaped method, to solve APUB optimization problems, with a specific focus on two-stage linear stochastic optimization with random recourse. Empirical demonstrations on a two-stage product mix problem reveal the significant benefits of our APUB optimization framework, which fortifies the process against epistemic uncertainty while reinforcing key decision-making attributes like reliability and consistency.</p>","absKo":"<p>Stochastic programmingмқҖ мў…мў… epistemic uncertaintyм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҰү, лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶ҖмЎұмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ н•өмӢ¬ нҷ•лҘ л¶„нҸ¬к°Җ м ңлҢҖлЎң нҠ№м„ұнҷ”лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳкұ°лӮҳ м•„мҳҲ м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°лҢҖ random costмқҳ upper confidence bound(UCB)лҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ stochastic programming frameworkлҘј м„ лҸ„м ҒмңјлЎң м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” robustness-seeking strategyлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кё°м—¬лҠ” Average Percentile Upper Bound(APUB)лЎң, лӘЁм§‘лӢЁ нҸүк· м—җ лҢҖн•ң нҶөкі„м ҒмңјлЎң м—„л°Җн•ң upper boundмқҙмһҗ н‘ңліё нҸүк· м—җ лҢҖн•ң к·јмӮ¬ risk metric м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ statistical constructмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” APUBмқҳ asymptotic correctnessмҷҖ consistencyлҘј м—„л°ҖнһҲ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳм—¬, data-driven decision-makingмқ„ мң„н•ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кё°л°ҳмқ„ л§Ҳл Ён•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң bootstrap sampling approximation methodмҷҖ L-shaped methodлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё solution methodлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ҳм—¬ APUB optimization problemмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳл©°, нҠ№нһҲ random recourseлҘј к°–лҠ” two-stage linear stochastic optimizationм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҘлӢҲлӢӨ. two-stage product mix problemм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨмҰқ кІ°кіјлҠ” APUB optimization frameworkмқҳ мғҒлӢ№н•ң мқҙм җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, epistemic uncertaintyм—җ лҢҖн•ң л°©м–ҙл Ҙмқ„ лҶ’мқҙлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ reliabilityмҷҖ consistency к°ҷмқҖ н•өмӢ¬ decision-making мҶҚм„ұмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62403","en":"Lions and Muons: Optimization via Stochastic Frank-Wolfe","ko":"Lions and Muons: Stochastic Frank-WolfeлҘј нҶөн•ң мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Maria-Eleni Sfyraki, Jun-Kun Wang","pos":"#3704","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gvroXZ0HS8","abs":"<p>Stochastic Frank-Wolfe is a classical optimization method for solving constrained optimization problems. On the other hand, recent optimizers such as Lion and Muon have gained quite significant popularity in deep learning. In this work, building on recent initiatives, we provide a unifying perspective by interpreting these seemingly disparate methods through the lens of Stochastic Frank-Wolfe. Specifically, we show that Lion and Muon with weight decay can be viewed as special instances of a Stochastic Frank-Wolfe, and we establish their convergence guarantees in terms of the Frank-Wolfe gap, a standard stationarity measure in non-convex optimization for Frank-Wolfe methods. We further find that convergence to this gap implies convergence to a KKT point of the original problem under a norm constraint for Lion and Muon. Moreover, motivated by recent empirical findings that stochastic gradients in modern machine learning tasks often exhibit heavy-tailed distributions, we extend Stochastic Frank-Wolfe to settings with heavy-tailed noise by developing two robust variants with strong theoretical guarantees that hold for general compact convex sets without the need for a large batch size, filling the gap in the literature on Stochastic Frank-Wolfe for non-convex optimization. Our contributions in the later part of this work, in turn, yield new variants of Lion and Muon, that better accommodate heavy-tailed gradient noise, thereby enhancing their practical scope.</p>","absKo":"<p>Stochastic Frank-WolfeлҠ” м ңм•Ҫ мөңм Ғнҷ” л¬ём ңлҘј н‘ёлҠ” кі м „м Ғмқё мөңм Ғнҷ” л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. н•ңнҺё, Lionкіј Muon к°ҷмқҖ мөңк·ј optimizerл“ӨмқҖ deep learningм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№нһҲ нҒ° мқёкё°лҘј м–»кі  мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мөңк·јмқҳ нқҗлҰ„мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мқҙмІҳлҹј м„ңлЎң лӢ¬лқј ліҙмқҙлҠ” л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ Stochastic Frank-Wolfeмқҳ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң н•ҙм„қн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ нҶөн•©лҗң мӢңк°Ғмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” weight decayлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң Lionкіј Muonмқҙ Stochastic Frank-Wolfeмқҳ нҠ№мҲҳн•ң instanceлЎң ліј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , Frank-Wolfe л°©лІ•м—җ лҢҖн•ң non-convex optimizationм—җм„ңмқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ stationarity measureмқё Frank-Wolfe gap кҙҖм җм—җм„ң мқҙл“Өмқҳ convergence guaranteeлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, мқҙ gapмңјлЎңмқҳ convergenceк°Җ Lionкіј Muonмқҳ norm constraint н•ҳ мӣҗлһҳ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң KKT pointлЎңмқҳ convergenceлҘј н•Ёмқҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, нҳ„лҢҖ machine learning taskмқҳ stochastic gradientк°Җ heavy-tailed distributionмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨлҠ” мөңк·јмқҳ мӢӨмҰқм Ғ л°ңкІ¬м—җ лҸҷкё°л¶Җм—¬лҗҳм–ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҒ° batch size м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё compact convex setм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ к°•н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ к°–лҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ robust variantлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ heavy-tailed noiseк°Җ мһҲлҠ” settingмңјлЎң Stochastic Frank-WolfeлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” non-convex optimizationмқ„ мң„н•ң Stochastic Frank-Wolfe л¬ён—Ңмқҳ кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” л¶Җл¶„м—җм„ңмқҳ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кё°м—¬лҠ” heavy-tailed gradient noiseлҘј лҚ” мһҳ мҲҳмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” Lionкіј Muonмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ variantлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј мӢӨм ң м Ғмҡ© лІ”мң„лҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61267","en":"General Analysis of LMO-based Optimizers: Beyond Bounded Variance","ko":"LMO кё°л°ҳ Optimizerмқҳ мқјл°ҳ л¶„м„қ: м ңн•ңлҗң л¶„мӮ°мқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ","authors":"Egor Shulgin, Mohamed Awad, Peter Richtarik, Eduard Gorbunov","pos":"#3705","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=s0Q8nVsrMu","abs":"We study a broad family of momentum *Linear Minimization Oracle* (LMO) methods that includes normalized SGD with momentum, sign-based (Adam-like) directions, and Muon (spectral) updates. Our focus is on subsampling regimes where the classical uniformly-bounded-variance model can be fragile even for finite-sum objectives on unbounded domains. To obtain subsampling-faithful guarantees, we analyze this LMO family under *expected smoothness* (ABC condition), which captures common sampling schemes. We establish a unified nonconvex convergence theory via a new self-bounding closure that handles the history-coupling induced by momentum under ABC. Our bounds recover known bounded-variance results as a special case and simplify in strong-growth regimes. Specializing to $\\tau$-nice sampling, we derive explicit batch-size scaling laws, predicting that the optimal momentum must increase with the batch size to maximize sample efficiency. We further identify a theoretical **optimal batch size** that minimizes total sample complexity. Experiments on linear and matrix regression corroborate these predictions, showing a distinct diagonal shift in the optimal momentum-batch landscape that matches our theoretical scaling.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” momentum *Linear Minimization Oracle* (LMO) л°©лІ•мқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң кі„м—ҙмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м—җлҠ” momentumмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң normalized SGD, sign кё°л°ҳ(Adam-like) л°©н–Ҙ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  Muon(spectral) м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёк°Җ нҸ¬н•ЁлҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” мң н•ңн•©(finite-sum) лӘ©м Ғн•ЁмҲҳлқјлҸ„ л№„мң кі„ мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ңлҠ” кі м „м Ғмқё uniformly-bounded-variance лӘЁлҚёмқҙ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” subsampling regimeм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳлӢӨ. Subsamplingм—җ м¶©мӢӨн•ң ліҙмһҘмқ„ м–»кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ LMO кі„м—ҙмқ„ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё мғҳн”Ңл§Ғ л°©мӢқмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” *expected smoothness* (ABC condition) н•ҳм—җм„ң л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ABC м•„лһҳм—җм„ң momentumмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” history-couplingмқ„ мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ self-bounding closureлҘј нҶөн•ҙ нҶөн•©лҗң nonconvex мҲҳл ҙ мқҙлЎ мқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІҪкі„лҠ” м•Ңл Өм§„ bounded-variance кІ°кіјлҘј нҠ№мҲҳн•ң кІҪмҡ°лЎң ліөмӣҗн•ҳл©°, strong-growth regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” лҚ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҙм§„лӢӨ. $\\tau$-nice samplingм—җ нҠ№нҷ”н•ҳл©ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” batch sizeм—җ лҢҖн•ң лӘ…мӢңм Ғ scaling lawлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳл©°, sample efficiencyлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳл Өл©ҙ optimal momentumмқҙ batch sizeмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ мҰқк°Җн•ҙм•ј н•Ёмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҙқ sample complexityлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ **optimal batch size**лҘј мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. linear regressionкіј matrix regression мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҳҲмёЎмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳл©°, мөңм Ғ momentum-batch landscapeм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ scalingкіј мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” лҡңл ·н•ң diagonal shiftлҘј ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"63784","en":"Near-optimal and Efficient First-Order Algorithm for Multi-Task Learning with Shared Linear Representation","ko":"кіөмң  м„ нҳ• н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ к°–лҠ” л©ҖнӢ°нғңмҠӨнҒ¬ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң кұ°мқҳ мөңм Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё 1м°Ё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ","authors":"Shihong Ding, Fangyu Du, Cong Fang","pos":"#3709","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=TnquAvyTtL","abs":"Multi-task learning (MTL) has emerged as a pivotal paradigm in machine learning  by leveraging shared structures across multiple related tasks. Despite its empirical success, the development of likelihood-based efficiently solvable algorithmsвҖ”even for shared linear representationsвҖ”remains largely underdeveloped, primarily due to the non-convex structure intrinsic to matrix factorization. This paper introduces a first-order algorithm that jointly learns a shared representation and task-specific parameters, with guaranteed computational efficiency. Notably, it converges in $\\tilde{O}(1)$ iterations and attains a \\emph{near-optimal} estimation error of $\\widetilde{O}(dk/(TN))$, \\emph{improving} over existing likelihood-based methods by a factor of $k$,  where $d$, $k$, $T$, $N$ denote input dimension, representation dimension, task count, and samples per task, respectively. Our results demonstrate that likelihood-based first-order methods can also efficiently solve the MTL problem.","absKo":"Multi-task learning (MTL)мқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ кҙҖл Ё task м „л°ҳмқҳ кіөмң  кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ machine learningм—җм„ң н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм Ғ м„ұкіөм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , shared linear representationм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңмЎ°м°Ё likelihood-basedлЎң нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң н’Җ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҳ к°ңл°ңмқҖ мЈјлЎң matrix factorizationм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң л№„ліјлЎқ кө¬мЎ° л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ нҒ¬кІҢ лҜёнқЎн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ shared representationкіј task-specific parameterлҘј кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©ҙм„ң кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқҙ ліҙмһҘлҗҳлҠ” first-order algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ $\\tilde{O}(1)$ iteration лӮҙм—җ мҲҳл ҙн•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙ likelihood-based methodліҙлӢӨ $k$л°° н–ҘмғҒлҗң \\emph{near-optimal} estimation error $\\widetilde{O}(dk/(TN))$лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң $d$, $k$, $T$, $N$мқҖ к°Ғк°Ғ мһ…л Ҙ м°Ёмӣҗ, representation м°Ёмӣҗ, task мҲҳ, taskлӢ№ sample мҲҳлҘј мқҳлҜён•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” likelihood-based first-order method лҳҗн•ң MTL л¬ём ңлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62716","en":"LoBCD-GW: A Fast and Data-Dependent Algorithm for Computing Gromov-Wasserstein Distance via Localized Block Coordinate Descent","ko":"LoBCD-GW: көӯмҶҢнҷ”лҗң Block Coordinate DescentлЎң Gromov-Wasserstein DistanceлҘј л№ лҘҙкі  лҚ°мқҙн„° мқҳмЎҙм ҒмңјлЎң кі„мӮ°","authors":"Jingni Song, Jiawei Huang, Kangke Cheng, Bangxian Han, Hu Ding","pos":"#3710","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=dxwRakfEFm","abs":"The Gromov-Wasserstein (GW) distance provides a powerful framework for aligning structured data by comparing the intrinsic geometries of metric measure spaces, and has become a fundamental tool in machine learning. Most existing methods leverage entropy regularization to reduce the computational complexity to $\\boldsymbol{\\mathrm{O}}(n^3)$, where $n$ is the number of samples. However, this cubic time complexity remains a major bottleneck in large-scale applications, severely limiting the scalability. To address this challenge, we propose LoBCD-GW, an efficient GW optimization algorithm. Specifically, we reveal the data-dependent sparsity of large-magnitude updates to the coupling matrix and introduce a localized block coordinate selection strategy. This confines the optimization to a \"selected set\" of size $r$ (which is a parameter that depends on the given data set, and usually is much less than $n$), thereby reducing the complexity to $\\boldsymbol{\\mathrm{O}}(r^3)$. In addition, unlike prior acceleration methods often based on constraint relaxation, our method can guarantee the strict feasibility through a novel \"marginal compensation mechanism\" to synchronize local mass redistribution with global constraints. Finally, we conduct a set of experiments on various datasets, and the results demonstrate that our method achieves a $160\\times$ speedup on large-scale graph alignment benchmarks, while maintaining state-of-the-art accuracy.","absKo":"Gromov-Wasserstein (GW) distanceлҠ” metric measure spaceмқҳ intrinsic geometryлҘј л№„көҗн•ҳм—¬ structured dataлҘј м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң frameworkлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, machine learningм—җм„ң к·јліём Ғмқё лҸ„кө¬к°Җ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ entropy regularizationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ кі„мӮ° ліөмһЎлҸ„лҘј $\\boldsymbol{\\mathrm{O}}(n^3)$лЎң мӨ„мқҙлҠ”лҚ°, м—¬кё°м„ң $n$мқҖ sample мҲҳмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ cubic time complexityлҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң м—¬м „нһҲ мЈјмҡ” лі‘лӘ©мңјлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲмңјл©°, нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқ„ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё GW optimization algorithmмқё LoBCD-GWлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” coupling matrixмқҳ нҒ° нҒ¬кё° updateм—җ лҚ°мқҙн„° мқҳмЎҙм Ғ sparsityк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•Ёмқ„ л°қнһҲкі , localized block coordinate selection strategyлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј нҒ¬кё° $r$мқҳ \"selected set\"мңјлЎң м ңн•ңн•ҳл©°($r$мқҖ мЈјм–ҙм§„ datasetм—җ л”°лқј лӢ¬лқјм§ҖлҠ” parameterмқҙкі , мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң $n$ліҙлӢӨ нӣЁм”¬ мһ‘лӢӨ), ліөмһЎлҸ„лҘј $\\boldsymbol{\\mathrm{O}}(r^3)$лЎң лӮ®м¶ҳлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң м ңм•Ҫ мҷ„нҷ”м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң кё°мЎҙ к°ҖмҶҚ л°©лІ•кіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ \"marginal compensation mechanism\"мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ local mass redistributionкіј global constraintлҘј лҸҷкё°нҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ strict feasibilityлҘј ліҙмһҘн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetм—җм„ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн–Ҳмңјл©°, кІ°кіјлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ graph alignment benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art accuracyлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң 160\\timesмқҳ мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"64159","en":"LOZO+: Provably Efficient Zeroth-Order Fine-Tuning via Greedy Low-Rank Subspace Selection","ko":"LOZO+: нғҗмҡ•м Ғ м Җкі„мҲҳ л¶Җл¶„кіөк°„ м„ нғқмқ„ нҶөн•ң мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё мҳҒм°Ё лҜём„ёмЎ°м •","authors":"Jinjie Fang, Chengxun Jin, Tianxing Man, Yi Chang, Bin Gu","pos":"#3802","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=QNScXX6osL","abs":"<p>Zeroth-order (ZO) optimization offers a more memory-efficient alternative to first-order  methods for  fine-tuning large language models (LLMs). Recent ZO methods, exemplified by LOZO, estimate gradients within low-rank subspaces to align with the low-rank structure of LLM gradients. However, these methods rely on randomly generated subspaces of a fixed rank, which provides no guarantee of alignment with the actual dominant subspaces of the gradients; essentially, they remain ZO gradient descent with stochastic subspace sampling. To more effectively exploit the low-rank nature of LLM gradients, we propose \\textbf{LOZO+}, an efficient \\textbf{ZO} fine-tuning algorithm for LLMs that incorporates greedy \\textbf{Lo}w-Rank subspace selection. Specifically, LOZO+ leverages loss-based feedback to assess alignment between candidate directions and the dominant low-rank gradient subspaces, and employs an adaptive thresholding criterion to retain only directions yielding substantial gradient descent, thereby steering ZO optimization toward more effective convergence. Importantly, we establish a  theoretical framework that characterizes the convergence behavior of LOZO+, formally prove its superiority  over existing methods. Extensive experiments demonstrate that LOZO+ consistently outperforms existing ZO methods and achieves performance competitive with FO algorithm, while retaining the memory efficiency inherent to ZO optimization.</p>","absKo":"<p>Zeroth-order (ZO) optimizationмқҖ large language models (LLMs)лҘј fine-tuningн•  л•Ң first-order л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё лҢҖм•Ҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. LOZOлЎң лҢҖн‘ңлҗҳлҠ” мөңк·јмқҳ ZO л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ LLM gradientмқҳ low-rank кө¬мЎ°м—җ л§һм¶”кё° мң„н•ҙ low-rank subspace лӮҙм—җм„ң gradientлҘј м¶”м •н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ кі м •лҗң rankмқҳ л¬ҙмһ‘мң„ subspaceм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мӢӨм ң gradientмқҳ м§Җл°°м Ғмқё subspaceмҷҖ м •л ¬лҗңлӢӨлҠ” ліҙмһҘмқҙ м—ҶлӢӨ. ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мқҙлҠ” нҷ•лҘ м Ғ subspace samplingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” ZO gradient descentм—җ лЁёл¬ёлӢӨ. LLM gradientмқҳ low-rank нҠ№м„ұмқ„ лҚ” нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” greedy \\textbf{Lo}w-Rank subspace selectionмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ң, LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё \\textbf{ZO} fine-tuning м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқё \\textbf{LOZO+}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң LOZO+лҠ” loss-based feedbackмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ нӣ„ліҙ л°©н–Ҙкіј м§Җл°°м Ғмқё low-rank gradient subspace к°„мқҳ м •л ¬ м •лҸ„лҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі , adaptive thresholding criterionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ м¶©л¶„н•ң gradient descentлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” л°©н–Ҙл§Ң мң м§Җн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ ZO optimizationмқҙ лҚ” нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мқҙлҒҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LOZO+мқҳ мҲҳл ҙ кұ°лҸҷмқ„ нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ frameworkлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳкі , кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“Өм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°мҲҳм„ұлҸ„ нҳ•мӢқм ҒмңјлЎң мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ LOZO+к°Җ кё°мЎҙ ZO л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳкі , ZO optimization кі мң мқҳ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ FO algorithmкіј кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66768","en":"A Geometry-Aware Efficient Algorithm for Compositional Entropic Risk Minimization","ko":"Compositional Entropic Risk Minimizationмқ„ мң„н•ң кё°н•ҳ мқём§Җ нҡЁмңЁ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ","authors":"Xiyuan Wei, Linli Zhou, Bokun Wang, Chih-Jen Lin, Tianbao Yang","pos":"#3803","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0SGle5hjIf","abs":"This paper studies optimization for a family of problems termed **compositional entropic risk minimization**, in which each data's loss is formulated as a Log-Expectation-Exponential (Log-E-Exp) function.  The Log-E-Exp formulation serves as an abstraction of the Log-Sum-Exponential (LogSumExp) function when the explicit summation inside the logarithm is taken over a gigantic number of items and is therefore expensive to evaluate. While entropic risk objectives of this form arise in many machine learning problems, existing optimization algorithms suffer from several fundamental limitations including non-convergence, numerical instability, and slow convergence rates. To address these limitations, we propose a geometry-aware stochastic algorithm, termed **SCENT**, for the dual formulation of entropic risk minimization cast as a min--min optimization problem.  The key to our design is a **stochastic proximal mirror descent (SPMD)** update for the dual variable, equipped with a Bregman divergence induced by a negative exponential function that faithfully captures the geometry of the objective. Our main contributions are threefold:  (i) we establish an $O(1/\\sqrt{T})$ convergence rate of the proposed SCENT algorithm for convex problems;  (ii) we theoretically characterize the advantages of SPMD over standard SGD update for optimizing the dual variable; and  (iii) we demonstrate the empirical effectiveness of SCENT on extreme classification, partial AUC maximization,  contrastive learning and distributionally robust optimization, where it consistently outperforms existing baselines.","absKo":"мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ к°Ғ лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ lossк°Җ Log-Expectation-Exponential (Log-E-Exp) functionмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”лҗҳлҠ” **compositional entropic risk minimization** л¬ём ңкө°мқҳ optimizationмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. Log-E-Exp formulationмқҖ log м•Ҳмқҳ explicit summationмқҙ м—„мІӯлӮҳкІҢ л§ҺмқҖ itemм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм ё кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° кІҪмҡ°, Log-Sum-Exponential (LogSumExp) functionмқҳ abstractionмңјлЎң ліј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҳ•нғңмқҳ entropic risk objectiveлҠ” л§ҺмқҖ machine learning л¬ём ңм—җм„ң лӮҳнғҖлӮҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ optimization algorithmsлҠ” non-convergence, numerical instability, лҠҗлҰ° convergence rateлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м—¬лҹ¬ к·јліём Ғ н•ңкі„м—җ мӢңлӢ¬лҰ°лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” entropic risk minimizationмқҳ dual formulationмқ„ min--min optimization problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ң л’Ө, мқҙлҘј мң„н•ң geometry-aware stochastic algorithmмқё **SCENT**лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м„Өкі„ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ objectiveмқҳ geometryлҘј м¶©мӢӨнһҲ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҠ” negative exponential functionмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” Bregman divergenceлҘј к°–м¶ҳ dual variableм—җ лҢҖн•ң **stochastic proximal mirror descent (SPMD)** updateмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мЈјмҡ” кё°м—¬лҠ” м„ё к°Җм§ҖмқҙлӢӨ. (i) convex problemм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м ңм•Ҳн•ң SCENT algorithmмқҳ $O(1/\\sqrt{T})$ convergence rateлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳкі , (ii) dual variable мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң standard SGD update лҢҖл№„ SPMDмқҳ мһҘм җмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳл©°, (iii) extreme classification, partial AUC maximization, contrastive learning, distributionally robust optimizationм—җм„ң SCENTмқҳ мӢӨмҰқм Ғ нҡЁкіјлҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, кё°мЎҙ baselinesлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62152","en":"A Fully First-Order Layer for Differentiable Optimization","ko":"лҜёл¶„ к°ҖлҠҘ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң мҷ„м „ 1м°Ё л Ҳмқҙм–ҙ","authors":"Zihao Zhao, Kai-Chia Mo, Shing-Hei Ho, Brandon Amos, Kai Wang","pos":"#3807","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=jJur8Fq7IK","abs":"Differentiable optimization studies how to embed a mathematical program as a differentiable layer in machine learning pipelines. However, existing approaches typically rely on implicit differentiation, involving expensive Hessian computation while differentiating through optimality conditions. To address this challenge, we formulate the differentiable optimization problem as a bilevel optimization instance. We construct a new active-set Lagrangian as a proxy to compute an $\\epsilon$-approximate hypergradient using only near-constant $O(\\log (1/\\epsilon))$ first-order information. We also show that applying this efficient hypergradient oracle to constrained bilevel optimization improves the overall gradient complexity to $\\tilde{O}(\\delta^{-1}\\epsilon^{-3})$ to reach a $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$-Goldstein stationary point. We implement our method `FFOLayer`, as a drop-in Python library compatible with existing differentiable optimization solvers. Our algorithm shows significantly faster computation with similar convergence compared to other existing solvers. Our code is available [here](https://anonymous.4open.science/anonymize/FFOLayer-B78B).","absKo":"лҜёл¶„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң optimizationмқҖ мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ programмқ„ machine learning pipeline м•Ҳм—җ лҜёл¶„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң layerлЎң мһ„лІ л”©н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң implicit differentiationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, optimality conditionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лҜёл¶„н•  л•Ң expensiveн•ң Hessian кі„мӮ°мқҙ мҲҳл°ҳлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” differentiable optimization л¬ём ңлҘј bilevel optimization instanceлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” $\\epsilon$-approximate hypergradientлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ active-set Lagrangianмқ„ proxyлЎң кө¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” кұ°мқҳ мғҒмҲҳм—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ $O(\\log (1/\\epsilon))$мқҳ first-order informationл§Ңмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мқҙ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё hypergradient oracleмқ„ constrained bilevel optimizationм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ, $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$-Goldstein stationary pointм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң м „мІҙ gradient complexityк°Җ $\\tilde{O}(\\delta^{-1}\\epsilon^{-3})$лЎң к°ңм„ лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ differentiable optimization solverмҷҖ нҳёнҷҳлҗҳлҠ” drop-in Python libraryлЎңм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ method `FFOLayer`лҘј кө¬нҳ„н–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ algorithmмқҖ лӢӨлҘё кё°мЎҙ solverл“Өкіј мң мӮ¬н•ң convergenceлҘј ліҙмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нӣЁм”¬ л№ лҘё computationмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” [м—¬кё°](https://anonymous.4open.science/anonymize/FFOLayer-B78B)м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"61285","en":"An Embarrasingly Simple Way to Optimize Orthogonal Matrices at Scale","ko":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м§Ғкөҗ н–үл ¬ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң лҶҖлһ„ л§ҢнҒј лӢЁмҲңн•ң л°©лІ•","authors":"AdriГЎn Javaloy, Antonio Vergari","pos":"#3809","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=rlvnG8oKmN","abs":"<p>Orthogonality constraints are ubiquitous in robust and probabilistic machine learning. Unfortunately, current optimizers are computationally expensive and do not scale to problems with hundreds or thousands of constraints. One notable exception is the Landing algorithm (Ablin et al., 2024) which, however comes at the expense of temporarily relaxing orthogonality. In this work, we revisit and improve on the ideas behind Landing, enabling the inclusion of modern adaptive optimizers while ensuring that orthogonal constraints are effectively met. Remarkably, these improvements come at little to no cost, and reduce the number of required hyperparemeters. Our algorithm POGO is fast and GPU-friendly, <em>consisting of only 5 matrix products</em>, and in practice maintains orthogonality at all times. On several challenging benchmarks, POGO greatly outperforms recent optimizers and shows it can optimize problems with thousands of orthogonal matrices in minutes while alternatives would take hours. As such, POGO sets a milestone to finally exploit orthogonality constraints in ML at scale.</p>","absKo":"<p>Orthogonality constraintлҠ” robustн•ҳкі  probabilisticн•ң machine learningм—җм„ң л§Өмҡ° нқ”н•ҳлӢӨ. л¶Ҳн–үнһҲлҸ„, нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ optimizerлҠ” кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ лҶ’кі  мҲҳл°ұ лҳҗлҠ” мҲҳмІң к°ңмқҳ constraintлҘј к°Җм§„ л¬ём ңлЎң scaleлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. н•ң к°Җм§Җ мЈјлӘ©н•  л§Ңн•ң мҳҲмҷёлҠ” Landing algorithm (Ablin et al., 2024)мқёлҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мқјмӢңм ҒмңјлЎң orthogonalityлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨлҠ” лҢҖк°ҖлҘј м№ҳлҘёлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” Landingмқҳ м•„мқҙл””м–ҙлҘј мһ¬кІҖнҶ н•ҳкі  к°ңм„ н•ҳм—¬, нҳ„лҢҖм Ғ adaptive optimizerлҘј нҸ¬н•ЁмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ orthogonal constraintк°Җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң м¶©мЎұлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°ңм„ мқҖ кұ°мқҳ л№„мҡ©мқҙ л“Өм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, н•„мҡ”н•ң hyperparameter мҲҳлҘј мӨ„м—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ algorithm POGOлҠ” л№ лҘҙкі  GPU-friendlyн•ҳл©°, <em>мҳӨм§Ғ 5к°ңмқҳ matrix productлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗҳкі </em>, мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” н•ӯмғҒ orthogonalityлҘј мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ к№ҢлӢӨлЎңмҡҙ benchmarkм—җм„ң POGOлҠ” мөңк·ј optimizerл“Өмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, лӢӨлҘё лҢҖм•Ҳл“Өмқҙ лӘҮ мӢңк°„мқҙ кұёлҰҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мҲҳмІң к°ңмқҳ orthogonal matrixм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лӘҮ л¶„ м•Ҳм—җ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлЎңмҚЁ POGOлҠ” MLм—җм„ң orthogonality constraintлҘј лҢҖк·ңлӘЁлЎң л§Ҳм№ЁлӮҙ нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мқҙм •н‘ңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64390","en":"An Exploration of Non-Euclidean Gradient Descent: Muon and its Many Variants","ko":"л№„мң нҒҙлҰ¬л“ң кІҪмӮ¬ н•ҳк°•лІ• нғҗкө¬: Muonкіј к·ё лӢӨм–‘н•ң ліҖнҳ•","authors":"Michael Crawshaw, Chirag Modi, Mingrui Liu, Robert Gower","pos":"#3810","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=O5xoqSmNzc","abs":"<p>To define a steepest descent method over a neural network, we need to choose a norm for each layer, a way to aggregate these norms across layers, and whether to use normalization. We systematically explore different alternatives for aggregating norms across layers, both formalizing existing combinations of Adam and the recently proposed Muon as a type of non-Euclidean gradient descent, and deriving new variants of the Muon optimizer. Through a comprehensive experimental evaluation of the optimizers within our framework, we find that Muon is sensitive to the choice of learning rate, whereas a new variant we call MuonMax is significantly more robust. We then show how to combine any non-Euclidean gradient method with model based momentum (known as Momo). The new Momo variants of Muon are significantly more robust to hyperparameter tuning, and often achieve a better validation score. Thus for new tasks, where the optimal hyperparameters are not known, we advocate for using Momo in combination with MuonMax to save on costly hyperparameter tuning.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӢ кІҪл§қ мң„м—җм„ң steepest descent methodлҘј м •мқҳн•ҳл Өл©ҙ, к°Ғ layerм—җ лҢҖн•ң norm, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң normмқ„ layer м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ м§‘кі„н•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  normalizationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н• м§Җ м—¬л¶ҖлҘј м„ нғқн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” layer м „л°ҳмқҳ norm м§‘кі„лҘј мң„н•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң лҢҖм•Ҳмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң нғҗкө¬н•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙмқҳ Adam мЎ°н•©кіј мөңк·ј м ңм•Ҳлҗң Muonмқ„ non-Euclidean gradient descentмқҳ н•ң мң нҳ•мңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , Muon optimizerмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ ліҖнҳ•л“Өмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ лӮҙм—җм„ң optimizerлҘј нҸ¬кҙ„м ҒмңјлЎң мӢӨн—ҳ нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, MuonмқҖ learning rate м„ нғқм—җ лҜјк°җн•ң л°ҳл©ҙ, MuonMaxлқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ ліҖнҳ•мқҖ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” к°•кұҙн•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м–ҙл–Ө non-Euclidean gradient methodлҸ„ model based momentumмңјлЎң м•Ңл Өм§„ MomoмҷҖ кІ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. Muonмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ Momo ліҖнҳ•л“ӨмқҖ hyperparameter tuningм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” к°•кұҙн•ҳл©°, мў…мў… лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ validation scoreлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мөңм Ғ hyperparameterлҘј м•Ң мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskм—җм„ңлҠ”, л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° hyperparameter tuningмқ„ мӨ„мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ MomoлҘј MuonMaxмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  кІғмқ„ к¶ҢмһҘн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60702","en":"Gradient Smoothing: Coupling Layer-wise Updates for Improved Optimization","ko":"Gradient Smoothing: к°ңм„ лҗң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң Layer-wise Update кІ°н•©","authors":"Haoming Meng, Anton Sugolov, Vardan Papyan","pos":"#3812","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xOFHGE60fr","abs":"<p>Deep neural networks with repeated blocks, such as transformers and ResNets, often exhibit closely related representational structure across layers that emerges with training. Motivated by this observation, we introduce <em>Gradient Smoothing</em>, a general training paradigm that couples gradient updates across blocks and admits a natural interpretation as a preconditioning method. Our framework applies structured smoothing operators to layer-wise updates, such as weighted averages and exponential moving averages, with minimal computational overhead. We evaluate Gradient Smoothing across a range of architectures and training regimes, including RL post-training of LLMs on reasoning tasks, as well as diffusion and classification with Vision Transformers. Across these settings, Gradient Smoothing consistently improves generalization performance, in addition to promoting structured representation evolution across layers. These results suggest that gradient smoothing is a simple and broadly applicable technique for improving training in modern deep networks.</p>","absKo":"transformerмҷҖ ResNetмІҳлҹј repeated blockмқ„ к°Җм§„ deep neural networkлҠ” н•ҷмҠөкіј н•Ёк»ҳ мёө м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ л°Җм ‘н•ҳкІҢ кҙҖл Ёлҗң representational structureлҘј ліҙмқҙлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм°°м—җ лҸҷкё°лҘј м–»м–ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” block к°„ gradient updateлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳкі  preconditioning methodлЎң мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ н•ҙм„қлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мқјл°ҳм Ғ н•ҷмҠө нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқё <em>Gradient Smoothing</em>мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkлҠ” weighted averageмҷҖ exponential moving average к°ҷмқҖ structured smoothing operatorлҘј layer-wise updateм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©°, computational overheadлҠ” л§Өмҡ° мһ‘лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reasoning taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң LLMмқҳ RL post-training, к·ёлҰ¬кі  Vision TransformerлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң diffusion л°Ҹ classificationмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң architectureмҷҖ training regimeм—җм„ң Gradient Smoothingмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„Өм • м „л°ҳм—җм„ң Gradient SmoothingмқҖ мёө м „л°ҳмқҳ structured representation evolutionмқ„ мҙүм§„н•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј generalization performanceлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјлҠ” gradient smoothingмқҙ нҳ„лҢҖ deep networkмқҳ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳкі  кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ҳкІҢ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кё°лІ•мһ„мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65735","en":"BAS: Bridging Adam and SignSGD for Memory-Efficient LLM Training","ko":"BAS: л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ LLM н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң Adamкіј SignSGDмқҳ м—°кІ°","authors":"Yijie Zhou, Mingliang Zhang, Jiaqi Zhang, Xunliang Cai, Shi Pu","pos":"#3910","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Agiagru6BM","abs":"<p>We propose <strong>Block Adaptive Signum (BAS)</strong>, which bridges Adam and SignSGD via block-wise scaling of sign updates. By discarding element-wise second moments, BAS reduces memory overhead relative to AdamW without sacrificing performance. Crucially, BAS mimics AdamвҖҷs dynamics closely enough to directly <strong>inherit its hyperparameters</strong>, matching the performance of AdamW without the need for reвҖ‘tuning, a common fragility of prior lowвҖ‘memory optimizers. This structural alignment makes it particularly suitable for tuning Adam-pretrained models. Furthermore, we exploit the inherent robustness of sign-based updates to store the first moment in FP8 without performance degradation. This shrinks the optimizerвҖ‘state footprint to <strong>12.5\\% of AdamWвҖҷs</strong>. We theoretically prove convergence under standard assumptions and introduce a communication-efficient variant enabled by the sign-based update. Across extensive evaluations, including preвҖ‘training a 1.5B model on 100B tokens and supervised fine-tuning of models up to 32B parameters, we demonstrate that BAS achieves performance on par with AdamW.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>Block Adaptive Signum (BAS)</strong>мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” block-wise scaling of sign updatesлҘј нҶөн•ҙ Adamкіј SignSGDлҘј м—°кІ°н•ңлӢӨ. element-wise second momentлҘј м ңкұ°н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ BASлҠ” AdamWм—җ л№„н•ҙ л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ BASлҠ” Adamмқҳ лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷмқ„ м¶©л¶„нһҲ к°Җк№қкІҢ лӘЁл°©н•ҳм—¬, мһ¬нҠңлӢқ м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ <strong>к·ё н•ҳмқҙнҚјнҢҢлқјлҜён„°лҘј м§Ғм ‘ мғҒмҶҚ</strong>н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙ м Җл©”лӘЁлҰ¬ optimizerл“Өмқҳ нқ”н•ң м·Ём•Ҫм җмқё мһ¬нҠңлӢқ н•„мҡ” м—Ҷмқҙ AdamWмҷҖ лҸҷл“ұн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кө¬мЎ°м Ғ м •н•©м„ұмқҖ AdamмңјлЎң мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠөлҗң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ нҠңлӢқн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° нҠ№нһҲ м Ғн•©н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” sign-based updateмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғ к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳ м—Ҷмқҙ first momentлҘј FP8лЎң м ҖмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ optimizer-state footprintлҘј <strong>AdamWмқҳ 12.5\\%</strong>к№Ңм§Җ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ к°Җм • н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ мҲҳл ҙмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мҰқлӘ…н•ҳкі , sign-based updateлЎң к°ҖлҠҘн•ҙм§„ communication-efficient ліҖнҳ•лҸ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. 100B tokensлЎң 1.5B лӘЁлҚёмқ„ pre-trainingн•ҳкі  мөңлҢҖ 32B parameter лӘЁлҚёмқҳ supervised fine-tuningмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ нҸүк°Җ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, BASк°Җ AdamWмҷҖ н•„м Ғн•ҳлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60988","en":"DASH: Faster Shampoo via Batched Block Preconditioning and Efficient Inverse-Root Solvers","ko":"DASH: л°°м№ҳ лё”лЎқ м „мІҳлҰ¬мҷҖ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ м—ӯм ңкіұк·ј мҶ”лІ„лҘј нҶөн•ң лҚ” л№ лҘё Shampoo","authors":"Ionut-Vlad Modoranu, Philip Zmushko, Erik Schultheis, Mher Safaryan, Dan Alistarh","pos":"#405","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ujeyxKwTGM","abs":"Shampoo is one of the leading approximate second-order optimizers: a variant of it has won the MLCommons AlgoPerf competition, and it has been shown to produce models with lower activation outliers that are easier to compress. Yet, applying Shampoo currently comes at the cost of significant computational slowdown, due to its expensive internal operations. In this paper, we take a significant step to address this shortcoming by proposing \\method (for Distributed Accelerated SHampoo), a faster implementation of Distributed Shampoo based on two main new techniques: First, we show that preconditioner blocks can be stacked into 3D tensors to significantly improve GPU utilization; second, we introduce the Newton-DB iteration and the Chebyshev polynomial approximations as novel and faster approaches for computing the inverse matrix roots required by Shampoo. Along with these algorithmic contributions, we provide a first in-depth analysis of how matrix scaling critically affects Shampoo convergence. On the practical side, our GPU-aware implementation achieves up to $4.83\\times$ faster optimizer steps compared to the well-optimized Distributed Shampoo, while Newton-DB attains the lowest validation perplexity per iteration among all tested methods.","absKo":"ShampooлҠ” м„ лҸ„м Ғмқё approximate second-order optimizer мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳлЎң, к·ё ліҖнҳ•мқҖ MLCommons AlgoPerf competitionм—җм„ң мҡ°мҠ№н–Ҳмңјл©° activation outlierк°Җ лҚ” лӮ®м•„ м••м¶•н•ҳкё° мү¬мҡҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ ShampooлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” лӮҙл¶Җ м—°мӮ°мқҙ л№„мӢёкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң кі„мӮ° м§Җм—°мқҙлқјлҠ” лҢҖк°Җк°Җ л”°лҘёлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ н•өмӢ¬ кё°лІ•мқ„ кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ң Distributed SHampooмқҳ лҚ” л№ лҘё кө¬нҳ„мқё \\method(Distributed Accelerated SHampoo)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬ мқҙ лӢЁм җмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈ¬лӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, preconditioner blockмқ„ 3D tensorлЎң мҢ“м•„ GPU нҷңмҡ©лҸ„лҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, Shampooм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң inverse matrix rootлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мғҲлЎӯкі  лҚ” л№ лҘё м ‘к·јлІ•мңјлЎң Newton-DB iterationкіј Chebyshev polynomial approximationмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң algorithmic contributionкіј н•Ёк»ҳ, matrix scalingмқҙ Shampoo convergenceм—җ кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ мӢ¬мёө л¶„м„қлҸ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ GPU-aware кө¬нҳ„мқҖ мһҳ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗң Distributed ShampooліҙлӢӨ optimizer stepмқҙ мөңлҢҖ $4.83\\times$ лҚ” л№ лҘҙл©°, Newton-DBлҠ” мӢңн—ҳн•ң лӘЁл“  л°©лІ• мӨ‘ iterationлӢ№ validation perplexityк°Җ к°ҖмһҘ лӮ®лӢӨ."},{"id":"65636","en":"ITSPACE: Monotone Gaussian Optimal Transport Updates","ko":"ITSPACE: лӢЁмЎ° Gaussian мөңм Ғ мҲҳмҶЎ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠё","authors":"Woojoo Na, Jennifer Dy","pos":"#4507","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=BdCjuNqZst","abs":"<p>Covariance matrices compactly summarize feature distributions in many machine-learning pipelines, including domain adaptation and Gaussian embeddings. Under a Gaussian approximation, the unregularized Wasserstein-2 <em>optimal transport</em> (OT) discrepancy reduces to the <em>Bures--Wasserstein</em> (BW) distance between <em>symmetric positive definite</em> (SPD) covariance matrices. We introduce <strong>ITSPACE</strong> (Iterative Transport for Stable Proximal Alignment of Covariance Embeddings), a lightweight <em>few-step</em> method for covariance alignment under tight compute and memory budgets: it maintains a low-rank representation and produces a valid covariance estimate at every iteration through simple closed-form updates. <strong>ITSPACE</strong> is designed for the rank-budgeted, anytime regime relevant to covariance-based domain adaptation and test-time moment matching: under exact computations, each step provably decreases the <em>exact</em> BW distance, and under approximate linear-algebra steps we provide a computable certificate bound that quantifies any deviation from monotone descent. Empirically, in the strict few-step regime <strong>ITSPACE</strong> reaches the same BW distance thresholds faster than BW-targeting gradient descent under a common rank budget, and is more stable than Euclidean, alternative-geometry, and entropically regularized baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>Covariance matrixлҠ” domain adaptationкіј Gaussian embeddingмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң л§ҺмқҖ machine-learning pipelineм—җм„ң feature distributionмқ„ к°„кІ°н•ҳкІҢ мҡ”м•Ҫн•ңлӢӨ. Gaussian approximation м•„лһҳм—җм„ң, м •к·ңнҷ”лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ Wasserstein-2 <em>optimal transport</em> (OT) discrepancyлҠ” <em>symmetric positive definite</em> (SPD) covariance matrix мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ <em>Bures--Wasserstein</em> (BW) distanceлЎң нҷҳмӣҗлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <strong>ITSPACE</strong> (Iterative Transport for Stable Proximal Alignment of Covariance Embeddings)лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кі„мӮ°кіј л©”лӘЁлҰ¬ мҳҲмӮ°мқҙ л§Өмҡ° м ңн•ңлҗң мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң covariance alignmentлҘј мң„н•ң к°ҖлІјмҡҙ <em>few-step</em> л°©лІ•мңјлЎң, low-rank representationмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң к°„лӢЁн•ң closed-form updateл§ҢмңјлЎң л§Ө iterationл§ҲлӢӨ мң нҡЁн•ң covariance estimateлҘј мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. <strong>ITSPACE</strong>лҠ” covariance-based domain adaptationкіј test-time moment matchingм—җ кҙҖл Ёлҗң rank-budgeted, anytime regimeлҘј мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. м •нҷ•н•ң кі„мӮ° н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” к°Ғ stepмқҙ <em>exact</em> BW distanceлҘј мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮӨл©°, approximate linear-algebra step н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” monotone descentлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ нҺём°ЁлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кі„мӮ° к°ҖлҠҘн•ң certificate boundлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, м—„кІ©н•ң few-step regimeм—җм„ң <strong>ITSPACE</strong>лҠ” кіөнҶө rank budget н•ҳм—җм„ң BW-targeting gradient descentліҙлӢӨ лҸҷмқјн•ң BW distance thresholdм—җ лҚ” л№ЁлҰ¬ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳкі , Euclidean, alternative-geometry, entropically regularized baselineліҙлӢӨ лҚ” м•Ҳм •м ҒмқҙлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64149","en":"Gradient Flow Sampler-based Distributionally Robust Optimization","ko":"к·ёлһҳл””м–ёнҠё нқҗлҰ„ мғҳн”Ңлҹ¬ кё°л°ҳ л¶„нҸ¬ к°•кұҙ мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Zusen Xu, Jia-Jie Zhu","pos":"#4508","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=QRtzkKrbJi","abs":"<p>We propose a mathematically principled PDE gradient flow framework for distributionally robust optimization (DRO). Exploiting the recent advances in the intersection of Monte Carlo sampling and statistical optimal transport, we show that our theoretical framework can be implemented as practical algorithms for sampling from worst-case distributions and, consequently, DRO. While numerous previous works have relied on dual reformulation techniques, we contribute a sound and complete gradient flow view based on SDEs or PDEs that can be used to construct new algorithms for general, potentially non-convex, losses. Without loss of generality, we solve a class of Wasserstein and entropy-regularized DRO problems using the recently-discovered Wasserstein Fisher-Rao and Stein variational gradient flows. Notably, we also show some simple reductions of our framework recover exactly previously proposed popular DRO methods, and provide new insights into their theoretical limits and optimization dynamics of DRO. Numerical studies based on stochastic gradient descent on machine learning tasks provide empirical backing for our theoretical findings.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” distributionally robust optimization(DRO)мқ„ мң„н•ң мҲҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң м—„л°Җн•ң PDE gradient flow н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Monte Carlo samplingкіј statistical optimal transportмқҳ көҗм°Ём җм—җм„ң мөңк·ј мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ м§„м „мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬к°Җ мөңм•…мқҳ л¶„нҸ¬(worst-case distributions)лЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ sampling, лӮҳм•„к°Җ DROлҘј мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмңјлЎң кө¬нҳ„лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ л§ҺмқҖ м—°кө¬к°Җ dual reformulation кё°лІ•м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ мҳЁ л°ҳл©ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SDE лҳҗлҠ” PDEм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң sound and complete gradient flow кҙҖм җмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқҙкі  мһ мһ¬м ҒмңјлЎң non-convexмқё lossм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳм„ұмқ„ мһғм§Җ м•Ҡкі , мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңк·ј л°ңкІ¬лҗң Wasserstein Fisher-Rao л°Ҹ Stein variational gradient flowsлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ Wasserstein л°Ҹ entropy-regularized DRO л¬ём ңмқҳ н•ң лІ”мЈјлҘј н‘јлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқҳ лӘҮ к°Җм§Җ лӢЁмҲңн•ң reductionмқҙ мқҙм „м—җ м ңм•Ҳлҗң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” DRO л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ нҡҢліөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , DROмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ н•ңкі„мҷҖ optimization dynamicsм—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лЁёмӢ лҹ¬лӢқ кіјм ңм—җм„ң stochastic gradient descentм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"68788","en":"Optimization with Access to Auxiliary Information","ko":"ліҙмЎ° м •ліҙ м ‘к·јмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"El Mahdi Chayti, Sai Praneeth Reddy Karimireddy","pos":"#4607","abs":"We investigate the fundamental optimization question of minimizing a \\emph{target} function $f(x)$, whose gradients are expensive to compute or have limited availability, given access to some \\emph{auxiliary} side function $h(x)$ whose gradients are cheap or more available. This formulation captures many settings of practical relevance, such as i) re-using batches in SGD, ii) transfer learning, iii) federated learning, iv) training with compressed models/dropout, etcetera. We propose two generic new algorithms that apply in all these settings; we also prove that we can benefit from this framework under the Hessian similarity assumption between the target and side information. A benefit is obtained when this similarity measure is small; we also show a potential benefit from stochasticity when the auxiliary noise is correlated with that of the target function.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” gradientлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кұ°лӮҳ мқҙмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗң \\emph{target} function $f(x)$лҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙм„ң, gradientк°Җ м Җл ҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҚ” мүҪкІҢ кө¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” \\emph{auxiliary} side function $h(x)$м—җ м ‘к·јн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” fundamental optimization л¬ём ңлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ formulationмқҖ i) SGDм—җм„ң batch мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ©, ii) transfer learning, iii) federated learning, iv) compressed model/dropoutмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң н•ҷмҠө л“ұ мӢӨл¬ҙм ҒмңјлЎң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң л§ҺмқҖ мғҒнҷ©мқ„ нҸ¬кҙ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘЁл“  м„Өм •м—җ м Ғмҡ©лҗҳлҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң target м •ліҙмҷҖ side information мӮ¬мқҙм—җ Hessian similarity к°Җм •мқҙ м„ұлҰҪн•  л•Ң мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лЎңл¶Җн„° мқҙм җмқ„ м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мң мӮ¬лҸ„ мІҷлҸ„к°Җ мһ‘мқ„ л•Ң мқҙм җмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳл©°, auxiliary noiseк°Җ target functionмқҳ noiseмҷҖ мғҒкҙҖлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲмқ„ л•Ң stochasticityлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ мһ мһ¬м Ғ мқҙм җлҸ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"62748","en":"Incremental Transformer Neural Processes","ko":"мҰқл¶„нҳ• Transformer Neural Processes","authors":"Philip Mortimer, Cristiana Diaconu, Tommy Rochussen, Bruno Mlodozeniec, Richard E Turner","pos":"#3500","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=diRgjfD2vu","abs":"Neural Processes (NPs), and specifically Transformer Neural Processes (TNPs), have demonstrated remarkable performance across tasks ranging from spatiotemporal forecasting to tabular data modelling. However, many of these applications are inherently sequential, involving continuous data streams such as real-time sensor readings or database updates. In such settings, models should support cheap, incremental updates rather than recomputing internal representations from scratch for every new observationвҖ”a capability existing TNP variants lack. Drawing inspiration from Large Language Models, we introduce the Incremental TNP ($\\texttt{incTNP}$). By leveraging causal masking, Key-Value (KV) caching, and a data-efficient autoregressive training strategy, $\\texttt{incTNP}$ matches the predictive performance of standard TNPs while reducing the computational cost of updates from quadratic to linear time complexity. We empirically evaluate our model on a range of synthetic and real-world tasks, including tabular regression and temperature prediction. Our results show that, surprisingly, $\\texttt{incTNP}$ delivers performance comparable toвҖ”or better thanвҖ”non-causal TNPs while unlocking orders-of-magnitude speedups for sequential inference. Finally, we assess the consistency of the model's updates---by adapting a metric of \"implicit Bayesianness\", we show that $\\texttt{incTNP}$ retains a prediction rule as implicitly Bayesian as standard non-causal TNPs, demonstrating that $\\texttt{incTNP}$ achieves the computational benefits of causal masking without sacrificing the consistency required for streaming inference.","absKo":"Neural Processes (NPs), нҠ№нһҲ Transformer Neural Processes (TNPs)лҠ” spatiotemporal forecastingл¶Җн„° tabular data modellingм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң taskм—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мқ‘мҡ©мқҳ мғҒлӢ№мҲҳлҠ” мӢӨмӢңк°„ sensor readingмқҙлӮҳ database updateмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ continuous data streamмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң sequentialн•ң нҳ•нғңмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„Өм •м—җм„ңлҠ” modelмқҙ л§ӨлІҲ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ observationл§ҲлӢӨ лӮҙл¶Җ representationмқ„ мІҳмқҢл¶Җн„° лӢӨмӢң кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , м Җл ҙн•ң incremental updateлҘј м§Җмӣҗн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ TNP variantлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң capabilityлҘј к°–м¶”кі  мһҲм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. Large Language Modelsм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Incremental TNP ($\\texttt{incTNP}$)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. causal masking, Key-Value (KV) caching, к·ёлҰ¬кі  data-efficient autoregressive training strategyлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, $\\texttt{incTNP}$лҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ TNPмҷҖ лҸҷмқјн•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ мҳҲмёЎ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң updateмқҳ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқ„ quadraticм—җм„ң linear time complexityлЎң лӮ®м¶ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” tabular regressionкіј temperature predictionмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң synthetic л°Ҹ real-world task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң modelмқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. кІ°кіјлҠ” лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„ $\\texttt{incTNP}$к°Җ non-causal TNPмҷҖ лҸҷл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©ҙм„ң sequential inferenceм—җм„ң orders-of-magnitude мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ мҶҚлҸ„ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” model updateмқҳ consistencyлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. \"implicit Bayesianness\"мқҳ metricмқ„ ліҖнҳ•н•ҳм—¬, $\\texttt{incTNP}$к°Җ н‘ңмӨҖ non-causal TNPл§ҢнҒј м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң Bayesianн•ң prediction ruleмқ„ мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, $\\texttt{incTNP}$к°Җ streaming inferenceм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң consistencyлҘј нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң causal maskingмқҳ кі„мӮ°м Ғ мқҙм җмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"66724","en":"From Drift to Coherence: Stabilizing Beliefs in LLMs","ko":"Driftм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖм„ұмңјлЎң: LLMмқҳ мӢ л…җ м•Ҳм •нҷ”","authors":"SongEun Kim, Seungyoo Lee, Edwin Fong, Hyungi Lee, Juho Lee","pos":"#4626","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0zkIq9YKml","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) are often hypothesized to perform implicit Bayesian inference, yet a key coherence conditionвҖ”the martingale property of predictive beliefsвҖ”has been shown to fail in controlled synthetic in-context learning settings. We revisit this question in a more typical usage regime: generic multiple-choice question answering. Exploiting the discrete answer space, we compute exact predictive distributions and study belief dynamics induced by autoregressive answer resampling. We introduce prompted predictive resampling (PPR), where an LLM generates a sequence of answers to the same question. Empirically, PPR reveals early-stage belief drift, indicating martingale violations. However, after sufficient resampling steps, the belief process self-stabilizes and converges to a coherent predictive distribution. Based on this observation, we further propose (i) a seed-answer prompting strategy to accelerate stabilization, and (ii) a self-consistency loss that amortizes early-stage drift into the model via fine-tuning. Experiments on multiple-choice QA benchmarks show that our methods substantially reduce belief drift and improve predictive coherence without sacrificing accuracy.</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(LLM)мқҙ м•”л¬өм Ғмқё Bayesian inferenceлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨкі  мў…мў… к°Җм •лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, мҳҲмёЎ beliefмқҳ martingale propertyлқјлҠ” н•өмӢ¬ coherence conditionмқҖ нҶөм ңлҗң synthetic in-context learning м„Өм •м—җм„ң мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮ¬мҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м§Ҳл¬ёмқ„ лҚ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё мӮ¬мҡ© нҷҳкІҪмқё мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё multiple-choice question answeringм—җм„ң лӢӨмӢң мӮҙнҺҙлҙ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙмӮ°м Ғмқё answer spaceлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м •нҷ•н•ң predictive distributionмқ„ кі„мӮ°н•ҳкі  autoregressive answer resamplingмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” belief dynamicsлҘј м—°кө¬н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLMмқҙ лҸҷмқјн•ң м§Ҳл¬ём—җ лҢҖн•ң лӢөліҖ мӢңнҖҖмҠӨлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” prompted predictive resampling(PPR)мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң PPRмқҖ мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„мқҳ belief driftлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” martingale мң„л°ҳмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ м¶©л¶„н•ң resampling step мқҙнӣ„м—җлҠ” belief processк°Җ мһҗкё° м•Ҳм •нҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ coherent predictive distributionмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м¶”к°ҖлЎң (i) stabilizationмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң seed-answer prompting strategyмҷҖ, (ii) мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„ driftлҘј fine-tuningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁлҚём—җ amortizeн•ҳлҠ” self-consistency lossлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. multiple-choice QA benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң belief driftлҘј мғҒлӢ№нһҲ мӨ„мқҙкі  predictive coherenceлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66428","en":"HodgeFlow Policy Search by Topologically Dissecting Temporal-Difference Signals in Non-Markovian Environments","ko":"HodgeFlow: л№„л§ҲлҘҙмҪ”н”„ нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң Temporal-Difference мӢ нҳёмқҳ мң„мғҒм Ғ л¶„н•ҙлҘј нҶөн•ң м •мұ… нғҗмғү","authors":"Zuyuan Zhang, Sizhe Tang, Tian Lan","pos":"#110","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=3qq7rvJzoj","abs":"<p>Non-Markovian dynamics are commonly found in real-world environments due to long-range dependencies, partial observability, and memory effects. The Bellman equation that is the central pillar of Reinforcement learning (RL) becomes only approximately valid under Non-Markovian. Existing work often focus on practical algorithm designs and offer limited theoretical treatment to address key questions, such as what dynamics are indeed capturable by the Bellman framework and how to inspire new algorithm classes with optimal approximations. In this paper, we present a novel topological viewpoint on temporal-difference (TD) based RL. We show that TD errors can be viewed as 1-cochain in the topological space of state transitions, while Markov dynamics are then interpreted as topological integrability. This novel view enables us to obtain a Hodge-type decomposition of TD errors into an integrable component and a topological residual, through a BellmanвҖ“de Rham projection. We further propose HodgeFlow Policy Search (HFPS) by fitting a {potential network} to minimize the non-integrable projection residual in RL, achieving stability/sensitivity guarantees. In numerical evaluations, HFPS is shown to significantly improve RL performance under non-Markovian.</p>","absKo":"<p>л№„-Markovian dynamicsлҠ” мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ мқҳмЎҙм„ұ, л¶Җл¶„ кҙҖмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ, memory effect л•Ңл¬ём—җ мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң нқ”нһҲ лӮҳнғҖлӮңлӢӨ. Reinforcement learning (RL)мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кё°л‘Ҙмқё Bellman equationмқҖ л№„-Markovian мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ңлҠ” мҳӨм§Ғ к·јмӮ¬м ҒмңјлЎңл§Ң мң нҡЁн•ҳлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” лҢҖк°ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ м„Өкі„м—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҙ мҷ”кі , м–ҙл–Ө dynamicsк°Җ мӢӨм ңлЎң Bellman frameworkлЎң нҸ¬м°© к°ҖлҠҘн•ңм§Җ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мөңм Ғ к·јмӮ¬лЎң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ кі„м—ҙмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ мң лҸ„н• м§ҖмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ н•өмӢ¬ м§Ҳл¬ём—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л…јмқҳлҠ” м ңн•ңм Ғмқҙм—ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” temporal-difference (TD) кё°л°ҳ RLм—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ мң„мғҒм Ғ кҙҖм җмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” TD errorлҘј мғҒнғң м „мқҙмқҳ мң„мғҒ кіөк°„м—җм„ң 1-cochainмңјлЎң ліј мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, Markov dynamicsлҠ” мң„мғҒм Ғ integrabilityлЎң н•ҙм„қлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кҙҖм җмқҖ BellmanвҖ“de Rham projectionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ TD errorлҘј integrable componentмҷҖ topological residualлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” Hodge-type decompositionмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ RLм—җм„ң л№„-integrable projection residualмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ {potential network}лҘј м Ғн•©мӢңнӮӨлҠ” HodgeFlow Policy Search (HFPS)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ м•Ҳм •м„ұ/лҜјк°җлҸ„ ліҙмһҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳм№ҳ нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң HFPSлҠ” л№„-Markovian мЎ°кұҙм—җм„ң RL м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң мқҳн•ҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮ¬лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65525","en":"Learning to Search and Searching to Learn for Generalization in Planning","ko":"кі„нҡҚм—җм„ң мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң нғҗмғү н•ҷмҠөкіј н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң нғҗмғү","authors":"Michael AichmГјller, Yannik Hesse, Hector Geffner","pos":"#113","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ck6Ort0wqc","abs":"Combinatorial generalization remains a central challenge in deep reinforcement learning (DRL). Classical planning provides a simple yet challenging setting to study this problem through explicit relational descriptions, without requiring learning from perception.  In sparse-reward domains, standard RL exploration via real-time search is ineffective, and learning-based planning methods often rely on expert demonstrations, hindsight relabeling, or random walks from the goal state. In contrast, planners rely on best-first search methods such as $\\mathrm{A}^\\star$ to solve problems from scratch. We propose a self-improving $\\mathrm{A}^\\star$ learning framework in combination with a value heuristic represented by a Relational Graph Neural Network: the heuristic guides search, and the resulting search data updates the heuristic via $Q$-Learning. This loop yields heuristics that can function as general policies and solve new instances even without search, where DRL otherwise fails, as we show on puzzles such as Sokoban, PushWorld, The Witness, and the International Planning Competition 2023 benchmarks. Notably, we demonstrate strong zero-shot generalization: heuristics trained on Blocksworld instances with fewer than 30 blocks successfully solve instances with 488 blocks.","absKo":"мЎ°н•©м Ғ мқјл°ҳнҷ”(combinatorial generalization)лҠ” deep reinforcement learning(DRL)мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. кі м „м Ғ planningмқҖ perceptual learning м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё кҙҖкі„м Ғ м„ңмҲ мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј м—°кө¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ settingмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. sparse-reward domainм—җм„ңлҠ” real-time searchлҘј нҶөн•ң standard RL explorationмқҙ л№„нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙл©°, learning-based planning methodлҠ” мў…мў… expert demonstration, hindsight relabeling, лҳҗлҠ” goal stateлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ random walkм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙмҷҖ лҢҖмЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң, plannerлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј мІҳмқҢл¶Җн„° н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ $\\mathrm{A}^\\star$мҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ best-first search methodм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Relational Graph Neural NetworkлЎң н‘ңнҳ„лҗң value heuristicкіј кІ°н•©н•ң self-improving $\\mathrm{A}^\\star$ learning frameworkмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ heuristicмқҙ searchлҘј м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳкі , к·ё кІ°кіј м–»м–ҙм§„ search dataк°Җ $Q$-Learningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ heuristicмқ„ к°ұмӢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лЈЁн”„лҠ” heuristicмқҙ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м •мұ…(general policy)мңјлЎң кё°лҠҘн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҳл©°, search м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ instanceлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” Sokoban, PushWorld, The Witness, к·ёлҰ¬кі  International Planning Competition 2023 benchmarkм—җм„ң DRLмқҙ мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ңлҸ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң zero-shot generalizationмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. 30к°ң лҜёл§Ңмқҳ blockмқ„ к°Җм§„ Blocksworld instanceлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ң heuristicмқҙ 488к°ң blockмқ„ к°Җм§„ instanceлҘј м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62551","en":"Online Robust Reinforcement Learning with General Function Approximation","ko":"мқјл°ҳ н•ЁмҲҳ к·јмӮ¬ н•ҳмқҳ мҳЁлқјмқё Robust Reinforcement Learning","authors":"Debamita Ghosh, George Atia, Yue Wang","pos":"#116","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=fcVsVQkjIc","abs":"Reinforcement learning (RL) in real-world tasks often suffers from the performance degradation due to the distribution shift between training and deployment environments. Distributionally Robust RL (DR-RL) addresses this issue by optimizing the worst-case performance over an uncertainty set of transition dynamics, providing an optimized baseline performance upon deployment. However, existing methods typically require strong data access assumptions (e.g., a generative model or comprehensive offline datasets) and mostly focus on tabular settings. In this paper, we introduce a purely online DR-RL algorithm with general function approximation that learns a robust policy directly from interaction, without any prior knowledge or pre-collected data. Our method uses a dual-based fitted robust Bellman update to jointly learn the value function and the robust backup operator. We establish the first regret guarantee for online DR-RL in terms of an intrinsic complexity measureвҖ”the robust BellmanвҖ“Eluder (BE) dimension, for general $\\phi$-divergence uncertainty sets. Our regret bound is sublinear and independent of $|\\mathcal{S}|$ and $|\\mathcal{A}|$, and recovers sharp rates in structured regimes, providing a scalable method for practical DR-RL.","absKo":"мӢӨм„ёкі„ taskм—җм„ңмқҳ к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө(RL)мқҖ training нҷҳкІҪкіј deployment нҷҳкІҪ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ distribution shift л•Ңл¬ём—җ м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј кІӘлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. Distributionally Robust RL(DR-RL)мқҖ transition dynamicsмқҳ uncertainty set мң„м—җм„ң мөңм•…мқҳ кІҪмҡ° м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈЁл©°, deployment мӢң ліҙмһҘлҗң baseline м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ лҢҖк°ң к°•н•ң data access к°Җм •(мҳҲ: generative model лҳҗлҠ” нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё offline dataset)мқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳкі , лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ tabular settingм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” мқјл°ҳ н•ЁмҲҳ к·јмӮ¬лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” мҲңмҲҳ online DR-RL м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ мӮ¬м „ м§ҖмӢқмқҙлӮҳ лҜёлҰ¬ мҲҳм§‘лҗң лҚ°мқҙн„° м—Ҷмқҙ interactionл§ҢмңјлЎң м§Ғм ‘ robust policyлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ dual кё°л°ҳ fitted robust Bellman updateлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ value functionкіј robust backup operatorлҘј jointly н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқјл°ҳ $\\phi$-divergence uncertainty setм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ, intrinsic complexity measureмқё robust BellmanвҖ“Eluder(BE) dimension кҙҖм җм—җм„ң online DR-RLм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ regret guaranteeлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ regret boundлҠ” sublinearмқҙл©° $|\\mathcal{S}|$мҷҖ $|\\mathcal{A}|$м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі , кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң regimeм—җм„ң sharp rateлҘј нҡҢліөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё DR-RLмқ„ мң„н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61363","en":"Fast Non-Episodic Finite-Horizon RL with K-Step Lookahead Thresholding","ko":"K-Step Lookahead Thresholdingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң л№ лҘё Non-Episodic Finite-Horizon RL","authors":"Jiamin Xu, Kyra Gan","pos":"#120","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qz0ChfFkiZ","abs":"Online reinforcement learning in non-episodic, finite-horizon MDPs remains underexplored and is challenged by the need to estimate returns to a fixed terminal time. Existing infinite-horizon methods,  which often rely on discounted contraction, do not naturally account for this fixed-horizon structure. We introduce a modified Q-function: rather than targeting the full-horizon, we learn a K-step lookahead Q-function that truncates planning to the next K steps. To further improve sample efficiency, we introduce a thresholding mechanism: actions are selected only when their estimated K-step lookahead value exceeds a time-varying threshold. We provide an efficient tabular learning algorithm for this novel objective, proving it achieves fast finite-sample convergence: it achieves minimax optimal constant regret for $K=1$ and $\\mathcal{O}(\\max((K-1),C_{K-1})\\sqrt{SAT\\log(T)})$ regret for any $K \\geq 2$.  We numerically evaluate the performance of our algorithm under the objective of maximizing reward. Our implementation adaptively increases K over time, balancing lookahead depth against estimation variance. Empirical results demonstrate superior cumulative rewards over state-of-the-art tabular RL methods across synthetic MDPs and RL environments:  JumpRiverswim, FrozenLake and AnyTrading.","absKo":"м—җн”јмҶҢл”•мқҙ м•„лӢҢ finite-horizon MDPм—җм„ңмқҳ мҳЁлқјмқё reinforcement learningмқҖ м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ м—°кө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳмңјл©°, кі м •лҗң terminal timeк№Ңм§Җмқҳ returnмқ„ м¶”м •н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨлҠ” мҡ”кө¬лЎң мқён•ҙ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ infinite-horizon л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң discounted contractionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң fixed-horizon кө¬мЎ°лҘј мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ л°ҳмҳҒн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҲҳм •лҗң Q-functionмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. м „мІҙ horizonмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ, лӢӨмқҢ K-stepк№Ңм§Җмқҳ planningмңјлЎң мһҳлқјлӮё K-step lookahead Q-functionмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. sample efficiencyлҘј лҚ” лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ thresholding mechanismлҸ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. н–үлҸҷмқҖ м¶”м •лҗң K-step lookahead valueк°Җ мӢңк°„м—җ л”°лқј ліҖн•ҳлҠ” thresholdлҘј мҙҲкіјн•  л•Ңм—җл§Ң м„ нғқлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ objectiveлҘј мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё tabular learning algorithmмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , мқҙкІғмқҙ л№ лҘё finite-sample convergenceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, $K=1$мқј л•Ң minimax optimal constant regretмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мһ„мқҳмқҳ $K \\geq 2$м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ $\\mathcal{O}(\\max((K-1),C_{K-1})\\sqrt{SAT\\log(T)})$ regretмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reward мөңлҢҖнҷ”лҘј лӘ©н‘ңлЎң м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мҲҳм№ҳм ҒмңјлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кө¬нҳ„мқҖ мӢңк°„м—җ л”°лқј KлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мҰқк°ҖмӢңмјң, lookahead depthмҷҖ estimation variance мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶ҳлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” н•©м„ұ MDPмҷҖ JumpRiverswim, FrozenLake, AnyTrading RL environment м „л°ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art tabular RL л°©лІ•л“ӨліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң cumulative rewardлҘј ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62655","en":"Doubly Regularized Markov Decision Processes for Robust Reinforcement Learning","ko":"к°•кұҙн•ң к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң Doubly Regularized Markov Decision Processes","authors":"Yiting He, Zhishuai Liu, Pan Xu","pos":"#121","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eeoU8iz7w1","abs":"<p>Empirical successes show that regularization improves the stability and efficiency of reinforcement learning (RL), with applications in robotics and post-training of large language models. Yet, theoretical analyses of regularized Markov decision processes (MDPs) have mostly been confined to the standard RL setting. In this work, we investigate regularized MDPs through the lens of robust RL. We introduce a doubly regularized MDP framework that combines policy and dynamics regularization to enable robust policy learning against reward and dynamics perturbations. Within this framework, we develop an optimism-based online algorithm and provide the first finite-sample regret guarantees in both tabular and rich-observation settings, where the state-action space may be continuous. Our results show that algorithms for doubly regularized MDPs are as sample-efficient as well-studied robust MDP algorithms, while additionally benefiting from the flexibility of soft policies. Finally, we use experiments to demonstrate that our approach efficiently and effectively handles function approximation and exploration in large state-action spaces, achieving robust performances.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӢӨмҰқм Ғ м„ұкіөмқҖ regularizationмқҙ reinforcement learning (RL)мқҳ м•Ҳм •м„ұкіј нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, roboticsмҷҖ large language modelмқҳ post-trainingм—җ мқ‘мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ regularized Markov decision process (MDP)м—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ н‘ңмӨҖ RL settingм—җ көӯн•ңлҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” robust RLмқҳ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң regularized MDPлҘј мӮҙнҺҙліёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” rewardмҷҖ dynamics perturbationм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ robustн•ң policy learningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ policy regularizationкіј dynamics regularizationмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң doubly regularized MDP frameworkлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ framework лӮҙм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” optimism-based online algorithmмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳкі , state-action spaceк°Җ м—°мҶҚмқј мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” tabular л°Ҹ rich-observation setting лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ finite-sample regret guaranteeлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” doubly regularized MDPлҘј мң„н•ң algorithmмқҙ мһҳ м—°кө¬лҗң robust MDP algorithmл§ҢнҒј sample-efficientн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, soft policyмқҳ мң м—°м„ұмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ large state-action spaceм—җм„ң function approximationкіј explorationмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳл©° robust performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65345","en":"HyPOLE: Hyperproperty-Guided Multi-Agent Reinforcement Learning under Partial Observation","ko":"HyPOLE: л¶Җл¶„ кҙҖмёЎ н•ҳм—җм„ң н•ҳмқҙнҚјмҶҚм„ұ кё°л°ҳ л©ҖнӢ° м—җмқҙм „нҠё к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Arshia Rafieioskouei, Tzu-Han Hsu, Matthew Lucas, Borzoo Bonakdarpour","pos":"#123","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EVoPYB6ss3","abs":"<p>Formal specification is a powerful tool to guide the learning process and provides significant advantages over ad-hoc reward shaping:  (1) mathematical rigor; (2) expressiveness to specify objectives and constraints, and (3) the ability to define strategies to achieve objectives. However, these benefits remain largely unexplored in the context of MARL. This paper introduces HyPOLE, a novel framework for MARL under partial observability, where learning is guided by the expressive power of the so-called hyperproperties and, in particular, the temporal logic HyperLTL. HyPOLE targets settings in which agents operate under partial observability, modeled as partially observable Markov decision processes (POMDPs). We integrate CTDE techniques with HyPOLE to synthesize decentralized policies, and our evaluation on StarCraft~II and Wildfire benchmark demonstrates clear advantages over vanilla MARL baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>Formal specificationмқҖ learning processлҘј м•ҲлӮҙн•ҳлҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң лҸ„кө¬мқҙл©°, мһ„мқҳмқҳ reward shapingм—җ л№„н•ҙ лӢӨмқҢкіј к°ҷмқҖ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мһҘм җмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ: (1) мҲҳн•ҷм Ғ м—„л°Җм„ұ; (2) objectiveмҷҖ constraintлҘј лӘ…м„ён•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ; (3) objective лӢ¬м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң strategyлҘј м •мқҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мқҙм җмқҖ MARL л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ңлҠ” м•„м§Ғ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ л¶Җл¶„ кҙҖмёЎ нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңмқҳ MARLмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ HyPOLEмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мҶҢмң„ hyperproperty, нҠ№нһҲ temporal logic HyperLTLмқҳ н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқҙ learningмқ„ м•ҲлӮҙн•ңлӢӨ. HyPOLEмқҖ agentк°Җ partial observability н•ҳм—җм„ң лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” м„Өм •мқ„ лҢҖмғҒмңјлЎң н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„Өм •мқҖ partially observable Markov decision process(POMDP)лЎң лӘЁлҚёл§ҒлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CTDE кё°лІ•мқ„ HyPOLEкіј нҶөн•©н•ҙ decentralized policyлҘј н•©м„ұн•ҳл©°, StarCraft~IIмҷҖ Wildfire benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” vanilla MARL baselineм—җ л№„н•ҙ л¶„лӘ…н•ң мһҘм җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61906","en":"Safe In-Context Reinforcement Learning","ko":"м•Ҳм „н•ң In-Context Reinforcement Learning","authors":"Amir Moeini, Minjae Kwon, Alper Bozkurt, Yuichi Motai, Rohan Chandra, Lu Feng, Shangtong Zhang","pos":"#201","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lm4PZa4kjZ","abs":"<p>In-context reinforcement learning (ICRL) is an emerging RL paradigm where an agent, after pretraining, can adapt to out-of-distribution test tasks without any parameter updates, instead relying on an expanding context of interaction history. While ICRL has shown impressive generalization, safety during this adaptation process remains unexplored, limiting its applicability in real-world deployments where test-time behavior is expected to be safe. In this work, we propose SCARED: Safe Contextual Adaptive Reinforcement via Exact-penalty Dual, the first method that promotes safe adaptation of ICRL under the constrained Markov decision process framework. During the parameter-update-free adaptation process, our agent not only maximizes the reward but also keeps the accumulated cost within a user-specified safety budget. We also demonstrate that the agent actively reacts to the safety budget; with a higher safety budget, the agent behaves more aggressively, and with a lower safety budget the agent behaves more conservatively. Across challenging benchmarks, SCARED consistently enables safe and robust in-context adaptation, outperforming existing ICRL and safe meta-RL baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>In-context reinforcement learning(ICRL)мқҖ мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠө нӣ„ м—җмқҙм „нҠёк°Җ нҢҢлқјлҜён„° м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠё м—Ҷмқҙ, лҢҖмӢ  мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ© мқҙл Ҙмқҳ нҷ•мһҘлҗҳлҠ” contextм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ л¶„нҸ¬ л°–(test) нғңмҠӨнҒ¬м—җ м Ғмқ‘н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ RL нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҙлӢӨ. ICRLмқҖ мқёмғҒм Ғмқё мқјл°ҳнҷ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м Ғмқ‘ кіјм •м—җм„ңмқҳ м•Ҳм „м„ұмқҖ м•„м§Ғ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ н…ҢмҠӨнҠё мӢңм җмқҳ лҸҷмһ‘мқҙ м•Ҳм „н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” мӢӨм ң л°°нҸ¬ нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңмқҳ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” SCARED: Safe Contextual Adaptive Reinforcement via Exact-penalty Dualмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” constrained Markov decision process н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ н•ҳм—җм„ң ICRLмқҳ м•Ҳм „н•ң м Ғмқ‘мқ„ мҙүм§„н•ҳлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙлӢӨ. нҢҢлқјлҜён„° м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠё м—Ҷмқҙ мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” м Ғмқ‘ кіјм • лҸҷм•Ҳ, мҡ°лҰ¬ м—җмқҙм „нҠёлҠ” ліҙмғҒмқ„ мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј лҲ„м Ғ л№„мҡ©мқҙ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м§Җм • м•Ҳм „ мҳҲмӮ° лӮҙм—җ лЁёл¬јлҸ„лЎқ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң м—җмқҙм „нҠёк°Җ м•Ҳм „ мҳҲмӮ°м—җ лҠҘлҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң л°ҳмқ‘н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м•Ҳм „ мҳҲмӮ°мқҙ лҶ’мқ„мҲҳлЎқ м—җмқҙм „нҠёлҠ” лҚ” кіөкІ©м ҒмңјлЎң н–үлҸҷн•ҳкі , м•Ҳм „ мҳҲмӮ°мқҙ лӮ®мқ„мҲҳлЎқ лҚ” ліҙмҲҳм ҒмңјлЎң н–үлҸҷн•ңлӢӨ. лҸ„м „м Ғмқё benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң SCAREDлҠ” м•Ҳм „н•ҳкі  к°•кұҙн•ң in-context м Ғмқ‘мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙ ICRL л°Ҹ safe meta-RL baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63664","en":"Stabilizing the Q-Gradient Field for Policy Smoothness in Actor-Critic Methods","ko":"Actor-Critic л°©лІ•м—җм„ң м •мұ… л§ӨлҒ„лҹ¬мӣҖмқ„ мң„н•ң Q-gradient field м•Ҳм •нҷ”","authors":"Jeong Woon Lee, Kyoleen Kwak, Daeho Kim, Hyoseok Hwang","pos":"#203","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=UpA00uD6Ek","abs":"<p>Policies learned via continuous actor-critic methods often exhibit erratic, high-frequency oscillations, making them unsuitable for physical deployment.  Current approaches attempt to enforce smoothness by directly regularizing the policy's output.  We argue that this approach treats the symptom rather than the cause.  In this work, we theoretically establish that policy non-smoothness is fundamentally governed by the differential geometry of the critic.  By applying implicit differentiation to the actor-critic objective, we prove that the sensitivity of the optimal policy is bounded by the ratio of the Q-function's mixed-partial derivative (noise sensitivity) to its action-space curvature (signal distinctness).  To empirically validate this theoretical insight, we introduce PAVE (Policy-Aware Value-field Equalization), a critic-centric regularization framework that treats the critic as a scalar field and stabilizes its induced action-gradient field.  PAVE rectifies the learning signal by minimizing the Q-gradient volatility while preserving local curvature.  Experimental results demonstrate that PAVE achieves smoothness and robustness comparable to policy-side smoothness regularization methods, while maintaining competitive task performance, without modifying the actor.</p>","absKo":"<p>м—°мҶҚ actor-critic л°©лІ•мңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң policyлҠ” мў…мў… л¶Ҳк·ңм№ҷн•ҳкі  кі мЈјнҢҢмқҳ м§„лҸҷмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ л°°м№ҳм—җ м Ғн•©н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠкІҢ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬ м ‘к·јлІ•л“ӨмқҖ policyмқҳ м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ regularizeн•ҳм—¬ smoothnessлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳл Өкі  н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јмқҙ мӣҗмқёмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј мҰқмғҒл§Ңмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁкі  мһҲлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” policyмқҳ non-smoothnessк°Җ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң criticмқҳ differential geometryм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мўҢмҡ°лҗЁмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. actor-critic objectiveм—җ implicit differentiationмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мөңм Ғ policyмқҳ sensitivityлҠ” Q-functionмқҳ mixed-partial derivative(л…ёмқҙмҰҲ лҜјк°җлҸ„)мҷҖ action-space curvature(мӢ нҳё кө¬лі„м„ұ)мқҳ л№„мңЁм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мғҒн•ңлҗңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ мқҙлЎ м Ғ нҶөм°°мқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” criticмқ„ scalar fieldлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳкі  к·ём—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗҳлҠ” action-gradient fieldлҘј м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” critic мӨ‘мӢ¬ regularization frameworkмқё PAVE(Policy-Aware Value-field Equalization)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. PAVEлҠ” local curvatureлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң Q-gradient volatilityлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ learning signalмқ„ л°”лЎңмһЎлҠ”лӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, PAVEлҠ” actorлҘј мҲҳм •н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ policy-side smoothness regularization л°©лІ•кіј кІ¬мӨ„ л§Ңн•ң smoothnessмҷҖ robustnessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” task performanceлҘј мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63575","en":"Learning from Comparison: Constrained Projection Policy Optimization for Pareto-Front Improvement","ko":"л№„көҗ н•ҷмҠө: Pareto-front к°ңм„ мқ„ мң„н•ң м ңм•Ҫ нҲ¬мҳҒ м •мұ… мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Jintao Li, Maowen Tang, Yongji Long, Weixuan Liu, Yanlang Zheng, Sicheng He, Ao-Jin Li, Shui Yu, Yun Li","pos":"#206","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=VsaxovdJDA","abs":"<p>Constrained multi-objective reinforcement learning aims to discover a diverse set of feasible trade-offs, yet scalarization and signed, normalized group-relative advantages can be brittle under objective-scale drift, near-ties, and feasibility scarcity. We propose constrained projection policy optimization (CoPro), which alternates between an E-step moment projection and an M-step policy projection. In the E-step, we solve a Kullback-Leibler (KL)-regularized, moment-constrained projection over each sampled group to compute a nonnegative reweighting distribution (q*) that promotes feasible Pareto-front (PF) progress, preserves feasibility anchors, and suppresses ambiguous near-ties. This E-step admits a closed-form exponential-family solution and guarantees strictly positive probability mass on feasible anchors whenever feasible candidates appear in the group. In the M-step, we project the policy toward q* via weighted maximum likelihood with a trust-region regularizer, yielding a PF-aligned update direction from comparisons without hand-crafted reward shaping. Empirically, CoPro improves feasible PF quality and robustness on constrained multi-objective benchmarks for large language model tool use and analog circuit design tasks. Code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CoPro-8A95/README.md.</p>","absKo":"<p>constrained multi-objective reinforcement learningмқҖ feasible trade-offмқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң м§‘н•©мқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, scalarizationкіј signed, normalized group-relative advantageлҠ” objective scale drift, near-tie, feasibility scarcity н•ҳм—җм„ң л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” constrained projection policy optimization(CoPro)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” E-step moment projectionкіј M-step policy projectionмқ„ лІҲк°Ҳм•„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. E-stepм—җм„ңлҠ” к°Ғ sampled groupм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ Kullback-Leibler(KL)-regularized, moment-constrained projectionмқ„ н’Җм–ҙ nonnegative reweighting distribution(q*)мқ„ кі„мӮ°н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” feasible Pareto-front(PF) м§„н–үмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ҳкі , feasibility anchorлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©°, м• л§Өн•ң near-tieлҘј м–өм ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ E-stepмқҖ closed-form exponential-family solutionмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳкі , к·ёлЈ№м—җ feasible candidateк°Җ лӮҳнғҖлӮ  л•Ңл§ҲлӢӨ feasible anchorм—җ strictly positive probability massлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. M-stepм—җм„ңлҠ” trust-region regularizerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң weighted maximum likelihoodлЎң policyлҘј q*м—җ л§һкІҢ projectн•ҳм—¬, hand-crafted reward shaping м—Ҷмқҙ л№„көҗл§ҢмңјлЎң PFм—җ м •л ¬лҗң update directionмқ„ м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң CoProлҠ” large language model tool useмҷҖ analog circuit design taskлҘј мң„н•ң constrained multi-objective benchmarkм—җм„ң feasible PF qualityмҷҖ robustnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CoPro-8A95/README.md м—җм„ң аӨүаӨӘаӨІаӨ¬аҘҚаӨ§н•ҳлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64321","en":"Non-Uniform Noise-to-Signal Ratio in the REINFORCE Policy-Gradient Estimator","ko":"REINFORCE м •мұ… к·ёлһҳл””м–ёнҠё м¶”м •кё°м—җм„ңмқҳ л№„к· мқј л…ёмқҙмҰҲ лҢҖ мӢ нҳё л№„мңЁ","authors":"Haoyu Han, Heng Yang","pos":"#207","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ol99zoW31J","abs":"<p>Policy-gradient methods are widely used in reinforcement learning, yet training often becomes unstable or slows down as learning progresses. We study this phenomenon through the noise-to-signal ratio (NSR) of a policy-gradient estimator, defined as the estimator variance (noise) normalized by the squared norm of the true gradient (signal). Our main result is that, for (i) finite-horizon linear systems with Gaussian policies and linear state-feedback, and (ii) finite-horizon polynomial systems with Gaussian policies and polynomial feedback, the NSR of the REINFORCE estimator can be characterized exactlyвҖ”either in closed form or via numerical moment-evaluation algorithmsвҖ”without approximation. For general nonlinear dynamics and expressive policies (including neural policies), we further derive a general upper bound on the variance. These characterizations enable a direct examination of how NSR varies across policy parameters and how it evolves along optimization trajectories (e.g. SGD and Adam). Across a range of examples, we find that the NSR landscape is highly non-uniform and typically increases as the policy approaches an optimum; in some regimes it blows up, which can trigger training instability and policy collapse.</p>","absKo":"<p>Policy-gradient methodлҠ” reinforcement learningм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, н•ҷмҠөмқҙ м§„н–үлҗҳл©ҙм„ң мў…мў… л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҙм§Җкұ°лӮҳ лҠҗл Өм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ policy-gradient estimatorмқҳ noise-to-signal ratio(NSR)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. NSRлҠ” м¶”м •кё°мқҳ л¶„мӮ°(noise)мқ„ true gradientмқҳ м ңкіұ л…ёлҰ„(signal)мңјлЎң м •к·ңнҷ”н•ң к°’мңјлЎң м •мқҳлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мЈјмҡ” кІ°кіјлҠ” (i) Gaussian policyмҷҖ linear state-feedbackлҘј к°–лҠ” finite-horizon linear system, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (ii) Gaussian policyмҷҖ polynomial feedbackлҘј к°–лҠ” finite-horizon polynomial systemм—җм„ң REINFORCE estimatorмқҳ NSRлҘј к·јмӮ¬ м—Ҷмқҙ closed form лҳҗлҠ” мҲҳм№ҳм Ғ moment-evaluation algorithmмңјлЎң м •нҷ•нһҲ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё nonlinear dynamicsмҷҖ neural policyлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ лҶ’мқҖ policyм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ”, л¶„мӮ°м—җ лҢҖн•ң мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё upper boundлҸ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҠ№м„ұнҷ”лҠ” policy parameter м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ NSRк°Җ м–ҙл–»кІҢ лӢ¬лқјм§ҖлҠ”м§Җ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мөңм Ғнҷ” к¶Өм Ғ(мҳҲ: SGDмҷҖ Adam) л”°лқј м–ҙл–»кІҢ м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м§Ғм ‘ мЎ°мӮ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң мҳҲмӢңм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” NSR landscapeк°Җ л§Өмҡ° л№„к· м§Ҳн•ҳл©° лҢҖмІҙлЎң policyк°Җ optimumм—җ к°Җк№ҢмӣҢм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ мҰқк°Җн•Ёмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқјл¶Җ regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” NSRк°Җ л°ңмӮ°н•ҳм—¬ н•ҷмҠө л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •м„ұкіј policy collapseлҘј мң л°ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65973","en":"Reward Redistribution for CVaR MDPs using a Bellman Operator on L-infinity","ko":"L-infinityм—җ лҢҖн•ң Bellman м—°мӮ°мһҗлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң CVaR MDPмқҳ ліҙмғҒ мһ¬л¶„л°°","authors":"Aneri Muni, Vincent Taboga, Esther Derman, Pierre-Luc Bacon, Erick Delage","pos":"#209","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=8LVv9hyMII","abs":"<p>Tail-end risk measures such as static conditional value-at-risk (CVaR) are  used in safety-critical applications to prevent rare, yet catastrophic events. Unlike risk-neutral objectives, the static CVaR of the return depends on entire trajectories without admitting a recursive Bellman decomposition in the underlying Markov decision process. A classical resolution relies on state augmentation with a continuous variable. However, unless restricted to a specialized class of admissible value functions, this formulation induces sparse rewards and degenerate fixed points. In this work, we propose a novel formulation of the static CVaR objective based on augmentation. Our alternative approach leads to a Bellman operator with: (1) dense per-step rewards; (2) contracting properties on the full space of bounded value functions. Building on this theoretical foundation, we develop risk-averse value iteration and model-free Q-learning algorithms that rely on discretized augmented states. We further provide convergence guarantees and approximation error bounds due to discretization. Empirical results demonstrate that our algorithms successfully learn CVaR-sensitive policies and achieve effective performance-safety trade-offs.</p>","absKo":"<p>static conditional value-at-risk (CVaR)кіј к°ҷмқҖ tail-end risk measureлҠ” нқ¬к·Җн•ҳм§Җл§Ң мһ¬м•ҷм Ғмқё мӮ¬кұҙмқ„ л°©м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ safety-critical applicationм—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. risk-neutral objectiveмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬ returnмқҳ static CVaRлҠ” м „мІҙ trajectoryм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, underlying Markov decision processм—җм„ң recursive Bellman decompositionмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. кі м „м Ғмқё н•ҙкІ°мұ…мқҖ continuous variableлЎң stateлҘј augmentationн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ admissible value functionмқҳ нҠ№мҲҳн•ң classлЎң м ңн•ңн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙ, мқҙ formulationмқҖ sparse rewardмҷҖ degenerate fixed pointлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” augmentationм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң static CVaR objectiveмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ formulationмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ лҢҖм•Ҳм Ғ м ‘к·јмқҖ (1) denseн•ң per-step reward, (2) bounded value function м „мІҙ кіөк°„м—җм„ңмқҳ contracting propertyлҘј к°–лҠ” Bellman operatorлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ кё°л°ҳ мң„м—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” discretized augmented stateм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” risk-averse value iterationкіј model-free Q-learning algorithmмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң discretizationмңјлЎң мқён•ң convergence guaranteeмҷҖ approximation error boundлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ algorithmмқҙ CVaR-sensitive policyлҘј м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё performance-safety trade-offлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62960","en":"Time-Consistent Robust Multi-Objective Reinforcement Learning via a BellmanвҖ“Isaacs Weight-Adversary Recursion","ko":"BellmanвҖ“Isaacs Weight-Adversary Recursion кё°л°ҳ мӢңк°„ мқјкҙҖм Ғ кІ¬кі  Multi-Objective Reinforcement Learning","authors":"Mingxi Hu, Meiling Yu","pos":"#211","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bRxufOJLbj","abs":"Most multi-objective reinforcement learning (MORL) methods either condition on a fixed preference weight $w$ or consider episodic robustness where an adversary selects a single $w$ per episode. We study a time-consistent robustness model with reactive preferences: after each transition, an opponent chooses the next weight $w_{t+1}$ after observing $s_{t+1}$, and incurs a switching cost $\\lambda D_\\Phi(w_{t+1}\\mid w_t)$ based on a Bregman divergence. This yields a BellmanвҖ“Isaacs recursion with an inner weight minimization at every backup. We prove the induced operator is a contraction and derive a Bellman-residual certificate that turns approximation error into a uniform bound on robust performance. We develop practical solvers in both tabular and deep settings using Bregman-prox inner updates and a stabilized fixed-point iteration. To evaluate robustness without optimistic critic reuse, we introduce BR-$K$, testing policies against $K$ independently trained best-response preference adversaries. Across MO-Gymnasium benchmarks, our approach consistently improves WRR under strong step-wise opponents over preference-conditioned baselines while keeping DRIFT smoothly controllable via $\\lambda$.","absKo":"лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ multi-objective reinforcement learning (MORL) л°©лІ•мқҖ кі м •лҗң preference weight $w$м—җ мЎ°кұҙнҷ”н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, adversaryк°Җ episodeл§ҲлӢӨ лӢЁмқј $w$лҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” episodic robustnessлҘј кі л Өн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ transition мқҙнӣ„ opponentк°Җ $s_{t+1}$мқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ң л’Ө лӢӨмқҢ weight $w_{t+1}$лҘј м„ нғқн•ҳкі , Bregman divergence $\\lambda D_\\Phi(w_{t+1}\\mid w_t)$м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң switching costлҘј м№ҳлҘҙлҠ”, time-consistent robustness model with reactive preferencesлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” л§Ө backupл§ҲлӢӨ лӮҙл¶Җ weight minimizationмқҙ мһҲлҠ” BellmanвҖ“Isaacs recursionмқ„ мқҙлҒҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мң лҸ„лҗң operatorк°Җ contractionмһ„мқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳкі , approximation errorлҘј robust performanceм—җ лҢҖн•ң uniform boundлЎң л°”кҫёлҠ” Bellman-residual certificateлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Bregman-prox inner updateмҷҖ stabilized fixed-point iterationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ tabular л°Ҹ deep setting лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё solverлҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. optimistic critic reuse м—Ҷмқҙ robustnessлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” BR-$K$лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ м •мұ…мқ„ $K$к°ңмқҳ лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң best-response preference adversaryм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ н…ҢмҠӨнҠён•ңлӢӨ. MO-Gymnasium benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ $\\lambda$лҘј нҶөн•ҙ DRIFTлҘј л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкІҢ м ңм–ҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, к°•н•ң step-wise opponent н•ҳм—җм„ң preference-conditioned baselineліҙлӢӨ WRRмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ."},{"id":"63146","en":"Distributional Inverse Reinforcement Learning","ko":"л¶„нҸ¬м Ғ м—ӯк°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Feiyang Wu, Ye Zhao, Anqi Wu","pos":"#212","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZcnZ6vs4yX","abs":"We propose a distributional framework for offline Inverse Reinforcement Learning (IRL) that jointly models uncertainty over reward functions and full distributions of returns. Unlike conventional IRL approaches that recover a deterministic reward estimate or match only expected returns, our method captures richer structure in expert behavior, particularly in learning the reward distribution, by minimizing first-order stochastic dominance (FSD) violations and thus integrating distortion risk measures (DRMs) into policy learning, enabling the recovery of both reward distributions and distribution-aware policies. This formulation is well-suited for behavior analysis and risk-aware imitation learning. Theoretical analysis show that the algorithm converge with $\\mathcal{O}(\\varepsilon^{-2})$ iteration complexity. Empirical results on synthetic benchmarks, real-world neurobehavioral data, and MuJoCo control tasks demonstrate that our method recovers expressive reward representations and achieves state-of-the-art imitation performance.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reward functionм—җ лҢҖн•ң л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұкіј returnмқҳ м „мІҙ л¶„нҸ¬лҘј jointly лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” offline Inverse Reinforcement Learning (IRL)мқ„ мң„н•ң distributional frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кІ°м •лЎ м Ғ reward estimateлҘј ліөмӣҗн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ кё°лҢҖ returnл§Ңмқ„ л§һм¶”лҠ” м „нҶөм Ғ IRL м ‘к·јкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ first-order stochastic dominance (FSD) violationмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ expert behaviorмқҳ лҚ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎңмҚЁ distortion risk measures (DRMs)лҘј policy learningм—җ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ reward distributionкіј distribution-aware policyлҘј лӘЁл‘җ ліөмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ м •мӢқнҷ”лҠ” behavior analysisмҷҖ risk-aware imitation learningм—җ нҠ№нһҲ м Ғн•©н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙ $\\mathcal{O}(\\varepsilon^{-2})$мқҳ iteration complexityлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. synthetic benchmark, мӢӨм ң neurobehavioral data, MuJoCo control taskм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мһҲлҠ” reward representationмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•ҳкі  state-of-the-art imitation м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"63401","en":"Trust Region Inverse Reinforcement Learning","ko":"мӢ лў° мҳҒм—ӯ м—ӯк°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Anish Abhijit Diwan, Davide Tateo, Christopher Mower, Haitham Bou Ammar, Jan Peters, Oleg Arenz","pos":"#213","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XSYX75R6RC","abs":"<p>Inverse reinforcement learning (IRL) is typically formulated as maximizing entropy subject to matching the distribution of expert trajectories. Classical (dual-ascent) IRL guarantees monotonic performance improvement but requires fully solving an RL problem each iteration to compute dual gradients. More recent adversarial methods avoid this cost at the expense of stability and monotonic dual improvement, by directly optimizing the primal problem and using a discriminator to provide rewards. In this work, we bridge the gap between these approaches by enabling monotonic improvement of the reward function and policy without having to fully solve an RL problem at every iteration. Our key theoretical insight is that a trust-region-optimal policy for a reward function update can be globally optimal for a smaller update in the same direction. This smaller update allows us to explicitly optimize the dual objective while only relying on a local search around the current policy. In doing so, our approach avoids the training instabilities of adversarial methods, offers monotonic performance improvement, and learns a reward function in the traditional sense of IRLвҖ”one that can be globally optimized to match expert demonstrations. Our proposed algorithm, <em>Trust Region Inverse Reinforcement Learning (TRIRL)</em>, outperforms state-of-the-art imitation learning methods across multiple challenging tasks by a factor of 2.4x in terms of aggregate inter-quartile mean, while recovering reward functions that generalize to system dynamics shifts.</p>","absKo":"<p>Inverse reinforcement learning(IRL)мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң expert trajectoryмқҳ л¶„нҸ¬лҘј л§һм¶”лҠ” м ңм•Ҫн•ҳм—җм„ң entropyлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. кі м „м Ғмқё (dual-ascent) IRLмқҖ monotonicн•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, dual gradientмқ„ кі„мӮ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ л§Ө л°ҳліөл§ҲлӢӨ RL л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„м „нһҲ н’Җм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. ліҙлӢӨ мөңк·јмқҳ adversarial л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ primal л¬ём ңлҘј м§Ғм ‘ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳкі  discriminatorлЎң rewardлҘј м ңкіөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ л№„мҡ©мқ„ н”јн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё лҢҖк°ҖлЎң м•Ҳм •м„ұкіј monotonicн•ң dual к°ңм„ мқ„ мһғлҠ”лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” л§Ө л°ҳліөл§ҲлӢӨ RL л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„м „нһҲ н’Җм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң reward functionкіј policyмқҳ monotonic improvementлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ мқҙлЎ м Ғ нҶөм°°мқҖ, reward function м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠём—җ лҢҖн•ң trust-region-optimal policyк°Җ к°ҷмқҖ л°©н–Ҙмқҳ лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠём—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” globally optimalмқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ лҚ” мһ‘мқҖ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ policy мЈјліҖмқҳ local searchм—җл§Ң мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң dual objectiveлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ adversarial methodмқҳ training instabilityлҘј н”јн•ҳкі , monotonicн•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, IRLмқҳ м „нҶөм Ғ мқҳлҜём—җм„ңмқҳ reward function, мҰү expert demonstrationкіј л§һм¶”кё° мң„н•ҙ globally optimizedлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” reward functionмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ” м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқё <em>Trust Region Inverse Reinforcement Learning (TRIRL)</em>мқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ taskм—җм„ң state-of-the-art imitation learning methodлҘј aggregate inter-quartile mean кё°мӨҖ 2.4л°° м•һм„ңл©°, мӢңмҠӨн…ң dynamics shiftм—җлҸ„ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҗҳлҠ” reward functionмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66379","en":"Boosting CVaR Policy Optimization with Quantile Gradients","ko":"л¶„мң„мҲҳ к·ёлһҳл””м–ёнҠёлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң CVaR м •мұ… мөңм Ғнҷ” н–ҘмғҒ","authors":"Yudong Luo, Erick Delage","pos":"#303","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4De8M6HSF5","abs":"<p>Optimizing Conditional Value-at-risk (CVaR) using policy gradient (a.k.a CVaR-PG) faces significant challenges of sample inefficiency. This inefficiency stems from the fact that it focuses on tail-end performance and overlooks many sampled trajectories. We address this problem by augmenting CVaR with an expected quantile term. Quantile optimization admits a dynamic programming formulation that leverages all sampled data, thus improves sample efficiency. This does not alter the CVaR objective since CVaR corresponds to the expectation of quantile over the tail. Empirical results in domains with verifiable risk-averse behavior show that our algorithm within the Markovian policy class substantially improves upon CVaR-PG and consistently outperforms other existing methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>policy gradient(мқјлӘ… CVaR-PG)лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ Conditional Value-at-risk(CVaR)лҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң sample inefficiency л¬ём ңм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л№„нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқҖ tail-end м„ұлҠҘм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғлҗң л§ҺмқҖ trajectoryлҘј к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј expected quantile termмқ„ м¶”к°Җн•ҳм—¬ н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. Quantile optimizationмқҖ лӘЁл“  мғҳн”Ңлҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” dynamic programming formulationмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳлҜҖлЎң sample efficiencyлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” CVaR objectiveлҘј л°”кҫём§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лҚ°, CVaRлҠ” tailм—җм„ңмқҳ quantileм—җ лҢҖн•ң expectationм—җ н•ҙлӢ№н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң risk-averse behaviorлҘј ліҙмқҙлҠ” лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, Markovian policy class лӮҙм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ CVaR-PGлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ к°ңм„ н•ҳкі , кё°мЎҙмқҳ лӢӨлҘё л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62544","en":"Why Dedicated Critics: Eliminating Target Drift in Multi-Constraint RL","ko":"мҷң Dedicated Criticsк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ңк°Җ: лӢӨмӨ‘ м ңм•Ҫ RLмқҳ Target Drift м ңкұ°","authors":"Yue Yang, Chenghao Huang, Hao Wang","pos":"#3509","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=fgUo5WbsYj","abs":"<p>Lagrangian-based methodologies are one of the fundamental paradigms of safe reinforcement learning (RL) for constrained Markov decision processes, particularly when dealing with multi-constraint cases. While the specific details of the methodologies may differ, with some using a single estimator for the overall mixed penalty term of the constraints and others using separate estimators for the constraints, the fundamental question of the theoretical validity of the methodologies has remained largely unexplored. The present paper performs the first theoretical analysis of the methodologies and proves that the use of the mixed critic structure leads to the presence of a bias due to the target drift of the Lagrange multipliers. On the other hand, the use of the dedicated critic structure, where separate critics are used for the reward function and the constraint functions, does not suffer from this bias. The theoretical analysis is supported with experiments on a realistic power system environment with multiple constraints, where the dedicated critic structure succeeds in satisfying the constraints, whereas the mixed critic structure fails.</p>","absKo":"<p>Lagrangian кё°л°ҳ л°©лІ•лЎ мқҖ constrained Markov decision processesм—җм„ңмқҳ safe reinforcement learning(RL)мқ„ мң„н•ң к·јліём Ғмқё нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„ мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳмқҙл©°, нҠ№нһҲ multi-constraint caseлҘј лӢӨлЈ° л•Ң лҚ”мҡұ к·ёлҹ¬н•ҳлӢӨ. л°©лІ•лЎ мқҳ кө¬мІҙм Ғмқё м„ёл¶Җ мӮ¬н•ӯмқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘј мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”лҚ°, м–ҙл–Ө л°©лІ•мқҖ м ңм•Ҫл“Өмқҳ м „мІҙ нҳјн•© penalty termм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лӢЁмқј estimatorлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі , лӢӨлҘё л°©лІ•мқҖ м ңм•Ҫл§ҲлӢӨ лі„лҸ„мқҳ estimatorлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•лЎ мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ нғҖлӢ№м„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң к·јліём Ғмқё м§Ҳл¬ёмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң м•„м§Ғ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•лЎ м—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳл©°, mixed critic structureмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мқҙ Lagrange multiplierмқҳ target driftлЎң мқён•ң biasлҘј мң л°ңн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. л°ҳл©ҙ, reward functionкіј constraint functionsм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лі„лҸ„мқҳ criticsлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” dedicated critic structureлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң biasлҘј кІӘм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ лӢӨмӨ‘ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ к°–лҠ” нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё power system environmentм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмңјлЎң л’·л°ӣм№Ёлҗҳл©°, м—¬кё°м„ң dedicated critic structureлҠ” м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л§ҢмЎұмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҚ° м„ұкіөн•ң л°ҳл©ҙ mixed critic structureлҠ” мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64595","en":"Second-Order Smooth Planning with Optimal-Transport Bellman Smoothing","ko":"Optimal-Transport Bellman Smoothingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң 2м°Ё Smooth Planning","authors":"Tuan Dam","pos":"#3903","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=LrNH0O3s45","abs":"Planning with a generative model aims to estimate state values using minimal oracle calls. For entropy-regularized MDPs, SmoothCruiser exploits the smoothness of the $\\operatorname{LogSumExp}$ Bellman operator to achieve $\\widetilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\varepsilon^{-4})$ sample complexity, but its first-order Taylor approximation limits the rate. We develop a curvature--complexity theory showing that if a Bellman aggregator has Taylor remainder of order $\\beta \\ge 2$, the optimal oracle complexity exponent is $2 + 2/(\\beta-1)$---recovering $\\widetilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\varepsilon^{-4})$ for $\\beta=2$ and predicting $\\widetilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\varepsilon^{-3})$ for $\\beta=3$. To achieve $\\beta=3$, we introduce an entropic optimal-transport regularizer over action distributions. The resulting OT-smoothed Bellman operator admits a closed-form expression, explicit gradient policy, and Lipschitz Hessian. We derive an unbiased estimator of the quadratic Taylor term via cross-product debiasing, enabling a second-order SmoothCruiser with $\\widetilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\varepsilon^{-3})$ complexity. We further propose gap-dependent variants and provide a complexity analysis and show advantage of our method.","absKo":"мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң planningмқҖ мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ oracle callлЎң state valueлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. entropy-regularized MDPм—җм„ң SmoothCruiserлҠ” $\\operatorname{LogSumExp}$ Bellman operatorмқҳ smoothnessлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ $\\widetilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\varepsilon^{-4})$мқҳ sample complexityлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, 1м°Ё Taylor approximation л•Ңл¬ём—җ к·ё мҶҚлҸ„м—җ н•ңкі„к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Bellman aggregatorмқҳ Taylor remainderк°Җ $\\beta \\ge 2$м°Ёмқј л•Ң мөңм Ғ oracle complexity exponentк°Җ $2 + 2/(\\beta-1)$мһ„мқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” curvature--complexity theoryлҘј м „к°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” $\\beta=2$мқј л•Ң $\\widetilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\varepsilon^{-4})$лҘј нҡҢліөн•ҳкі , $\\beta=3$мқј л•Ң $\\widetilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\varepsilon^{-3})$лҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ңлӢӨ. $\\beta=3$лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ action distribution мң„м—җ entropic optimal-transport regularizerлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј м–»м–ҙм§ҖлҠ” OT-smoothed Bellman operatorлҠ” closed-form expression, explicit gradient policy, к·ёлҰ¬кі  Lipschitz Hessianмқ„ к°–лҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” cross-product debiasingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ quadratic Taylor termмқҳ unbiased estimatorлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬, $\\widetilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\varepsilon^{-3})$ ліөмһЎлҸ„лҘј к°–лҠ” second-order SmoothCruiserлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң gap-dependent variantлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң м ңм•Ҳн•ҳкі , ліөмһЎлҸ„ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬ л°©лІ•мқҳ мһҘм җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"64485","en":"When Can You Poison Rewards? A Tight Characterization of Reward Poisoning in Linear MDPs","ko":"м–ём ң ліҙмғҒмқ„ мҳӨм—јмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ? м„ нҳ• MDPм—җм„ң ліҙмғҒ мҳӨм—јмқҳ м—„л°Җн•ң нҠ№м„ұнҷ”","authors":"Jose Aguilar Escamilla, Haoyang Hong, Jiawei Li, Haoyu Zhao, Xuezhou Zhang, Sanghyun Hong, Huazheng Wang","pos":"#4500","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=N4PZVvr8lt","abs":"<p>We study reward poisoning attacks in reinforcement learning (RL), where an adversary manipulates rewards within constrained budgets to force the target RL agent to adopt a policy that aligns with the attacker's objectives. Prior works on reward poisoning mainly focused on sufficient conditions to design a successful attacker, while only a few studies discussed the infeasibility of targeted attacks. This paper provides the first precise necessity and sufficiency characterization of the attackability of a linear MDP under reward poisoning attacks. Our characterization draws a bright line between the vulnerable RL instances, and the intrinsically robust ones which cannot be attacked without large costs even running vanilla non-robust RL algorithms. Our theory extends beyond linear MDPs---by approximating deep RL environments as linear MDPs, we show that our theoretical framework effectively distinguishes the attackability and efficiently attacks the vulnerable ones, demonstrating both the theoretical and practical significance of our characterization.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reinforcement learning (RL)м—җм„ңмқҳ reward poisoning attackмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кіөкІ©мһҗк°Җ м ңн•ңлҗң budget лӮҙм—җм„ң rewardлҘј мЎ°мһ‘н•ҳм—¬ лҢҖмғҒ RL agentк°Җ кіөкІ©мһҗмқҳ лӘ©н‘ңм—җ л¶Җн•©н•ҳлҠ” policyлҘј мұ„нғқн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” кіөкІ©мқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ reward poisoning м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң м„ұкіөм Ғмқё кіөкІ©мһҗлҘј м„Өкі„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң м¶©л¶„мЎ°кұҙм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм·„кі , н‘ңм Ғ кіөкІ©мқҳ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘм„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ л…јмқҳн•ң м—°кө¬лҠ” мҶҢмҲҳм—җ л¶Ҳкіјн–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ёмқҖ reward poisoning attack н•ҳм—җм„ң linear MDPмқҳ кіөкІ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•„мҡ”м¶©л¶„мЎ°кұҙмқ„ мІҳмқҢмңјлЎң м—„л°Җн•ҳкІҢ к·ңлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”лҠ” м·Ём•Ҫн•ң RL instanceмҷҖ, vanilla non-robust RL algorithmмқ„ к·ёлҢҖлЎң мӢӨн–үн•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ нҒ° л№„мҡ© м—Ҷмқҙ кіөкІ©н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң robustн•ң instance мӮ¬мқҙлҘј лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ кө¬л¶„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ мқҖ linear MDPлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ нҷ•мһҘлҗңлӢӨ. deep RL environmentлҘј linear MDPлЎң к·јмӮ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ frameworkк°Җ кіөкІ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң кө¬л¶„н•ҳкі  м·Ём•Ҫн•ң кІҪмҡ°лҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң кіөкІ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”к°Җ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎңлҸ„ мӢӨмҡ©м ҒмңјлЎңлҸ„ мӨ‘мҡ”н•Ёмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60597","en":"Refined Analysis of Entropy-Regularized Actor-Critic","ko":"м—”нҠёлЎңн”ј м •к·ңнҷ” Actor-Criticмқҳ м •көҗн•ң л¶„м„қ","authors":"Safwan Labbi, Paul Mangold, Daniil Tiapkin, Eric Moulines","pos":"#4501","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ybMDCeOC2m","abs":"In this paper, we study the role of the critic in actor-critic for entropy-regularized, finite, discounted environments. We establish that, when the critic is exact, using the latter as a baseline is an actual variance-reduction method. In this case, actor-critic with stochastic gradients matches the sample complexity of deterministic policy gradient,  reaching an $\\epsilon$-optimal regularized value with $\\tilde{O}(\\log(1/\\epsilon))$ samples.  In practice, the critic is learned alongside the actor: the variance of the actor update is then influenced by the critic's variance and bias. Specifically, when the critic has a sufficiently small error, the variance reduction and rapid convergence are preserved. This suggests to learn the critic first, keeping it up to date after each actor update, underscoring the pivotal role of accurate critic estimation in actor-critic methods.","absKo":"ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” entropy-regularized, finite, discounted нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң actor-criticм—җм„ң criticмқҳ м—ӯн• мқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. criticмқҙ м •нҷ•н•  л•Ң, мқҙлҘј baselineмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ мӢӨм ңлЎң variance-reduction methodмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ кІҪмҡ° stochastic gradientлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” actor-criticмқҖ deterministic policy gradientмҷҖ лҸҷмқјн•ң sample complexityлҘј к°Җм§Җл©°, $\\tilde{O}(\\log(1/\\epsilon))$к°ңмқҳ мғҳн”ҢлЎң $\\epsilon$-optimal regularized valueм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” criticмқҙ actorмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ н•ҷмҠөлҗҳлҜҖлЎң, actor updateмқҳ л¶„мӮ°мқҖ criticмқҳ varianceмҷҖ biasмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, criticмқҳ errorк°Җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ мһ‘лӢӨл©ҙ variance reductionкіј л№ лҘё мҲҳл ҙмқҙ мң м§ҖлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лЁјм Җ criticмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , к°Ғ actor update мқҙнӣ„ мқҙлҘј кі„мҶҚ мөңмӢ  мғҒнғңлЎң мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ мўӢмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ҳл©°, actor-critic methodм—җм„ң м •нҷ•н•ң critic м¶”м •мқҳ н•өмӢ¬м Ғ м—ӯн• мқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65885","en":"QUATRO: Query-Adaptive Trust Region Policy Optimization for LLM Fine-tuning","ko":"QUATRO: LLM нҢҢмқёнҠңлӢқмқ„ мң„н•ң м§Ҳмқҳ м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мӢ лў° мҳҒм—ӯ м •мұ… мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Doyeon Lee, Eunyi Lyou, Hyunsoo Cho, Soo Kyung Kim, Joonseok Lee, Jaemoo Choi","pos":"#109","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=98XhDbtB21","abs":"<p>GRPO-style reinforcement learning (RL)-based LLM fine-tuning algorithms have recently gained popularity. Relying on heuristic trust-region approximations, however, they can lead to brittle optimization behavior, as global importance-ratio clipping and group-wise normalization fail to regulate samples whose importance ratios fall outside the clipping range. We propose Query-Adaptive Trust-Region policy Optimization (QUATRO), which directly enforces trust-region constraints through a principled optimization. This yields a clear and interpretable objective that enables explicit control over policy updates and stable, entropy-controlled optimization, with a stabilizer terms arising intrinsically from the exact trust-region formulation. Empirically verified on diverse mathematical reasoning benchmarks, QUATRO shows stable training under increased policy staleness and aggressive learning rates, maintaining well-controlled entropy throughout training.</p>","absKo":"<p>GRPO-style reinforcement learning(RL) кё°л°ҳ LLM fine-tuning algorithmмқҖ мөңк·ј нҒ° мқёкё°лҘј м–»кі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ heuristic trust-region approximationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ мөңм Ғнҷ” кұ°лҸҷмқҙ мүҪкІҢ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. global importance-ratio clippingкіј group-wise normalizationмқҙ importance ratioк°Җ clipping range л°–м—җ мһҲлҠ” sampleмқ„ м ңлҢҖлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё optimizationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ trust-region constraintлҘј м§Ғм ‘ к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” Query-Adaptive Trust-Region policy Optimization(QUATRO)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” policy updateлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲкі  м•Ҳм •м Ғмқҙл©° entropyк°Җ м ңм–ҙлҗң optimizationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” лӘ…нҷ•н•ҳкі  н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң objectiveлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, exact trust-region formulationм—җм„ң мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” stabilizer termмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң mathematical reasoning benchmarkм—җм„ң кІҪн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•ң кІ°кіј, QUATROлҠ” policy stalenessк°Җ мҰқк°Җн•ҳкі  learning rateк°Җ кіөкІ©м Ғмқј л•ҢлҸ„ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё trainingмқ„ ліҙмҳҖкі , training м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ entropyлҘј мһҳ м ңм–ҙлҗң мғҒнғңлЎң мң м§Җн–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64417","en":"Emergence of Exploration in Policy Gradient Reinforcement Learning via Retrying","ko":"мһ¬мӢңлҸ„лҘј нҶөн•ң м •мұ… к·ёлһҳл””м–ёнҠё к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң нғҗмғүмқҳ м°Ҫл°ң","authors":"Soichiro Nishimori, Paavo Parmas, Sotetsu Koyamada, Tadashi Kozuno, Toshinori Kitamura, Shin Ishii, Yutaka Matsuo","pos":"#111","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=NpvBAOc87E","abs":"In reinforcement learning (RL), agents benefit from exploration *only* because they repeatedly encounter similar states: trying different actions can improve performance or reduce uncertainty; without such retries, a greedy policy is optimal. We formalize this intuition with **ReMax**, an objective that evaluates a policy by the expected maximum return over $M$ samples ($M \\in \\mathbb{N}$), while accounting for return uncertainty. Optimizing this objective induces stochastic exploration as an emergent property, without explicit bonus terms. For efficient policy optimization, we derive a new policy-gradient formulation for ReMax and introduce **Re**Max **PPO** (**RePPO**), a PPO variant that optimizes ReMax while generalizing the discrete retry count $M$ to a continuous parameter $m &gt; 0$, enabling fine-grained control of exploration. Empirically, RePPO promotes explorationвҖ”without any explicit exploration bonusesвҖ”on the MinAtar and Craftax benchmarks.","absKo":"к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө(RL)м—җм„ң agentлҠ” мң мӮ¬н•ң мғҒнғңлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң л§ҲмЈјм№  л•Ңм—җл§Ң нғҗмғүмқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё actionмқ„ мӢңлҸ„н•ҳл©ҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкұ°лӮҳ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқ„ мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мһ¬мӢңлҸ„к°Җ м—ҶлӢӨл©ҙ greedy policyк°Җ мөңм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м§ҒкҙҖмқ„ **ReMax**лЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. ReMaxлҠ” returnмқҳ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқ„ кі л Өн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, $M$к°ңмқҳ мғҳн”Ңм—җм„ңмқҳ кё°лҢҖ мөңлҢҖ return($M \\in \\mathbb{N}$)мңјлЎң policyлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” objectiveмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ objectiveлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳл©ҙ, лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё bonus term м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ лӮҙмһ¬м Ғ м„ұм§ҲлЎңм„ң stochastic explorationмқҙ мң лҸ„лҗңлӢӨ. нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё policy optimizationмқ„ мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ReMaxлҘј мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ policy-gradient formulationмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкі , мқҙмӮ°м Ғмқё retry нҡҹмҲҳ $M$мқ„ м—°мҶҚ л§Өк°ңліҖмҲҳ $m &gt; 0$мңјлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ нғҗмғүмқ„ м„ёл°Җн•ҳкІҢ м ңм–ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” **Re**Max **PPO**(**RePPO**)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң RePPOлҠ” MinAtar л°Ҹ Craftax benchmarkм—җм„ң м–ҙл–Ө лӘ…мӢңм Ғ exploration bonusлҸ„ м—Ҷмқҙ нғҗмғүмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61573","en":"Recursive Monte-Carlo Tree Search","ko":"мһ¬к·Җм Ғ Monte-Carlo Tree Search","authors":"Benjamin Howard, Keith Frankston","pos":"#112","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=oo9523XUWI","abs":"<p>We introduce a recursive AlphaZero style Monte--Carlo tree search algorithm, \"RMCTS\". It first generates the search tree using prior policies,  and then recursively re-estimates action values by using the regularized optimal posterior policies from ``Monte--Carlo tree search as regularized policy optimization'' (Grill et al., 2020) at each node of the search tree, starting from the leaves and working back up to the root. We find that RMCTS matches or exceeds the quality of AlphaZero's MCTS-UCB in a tiny fraction of the time.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһ¬к·Җм Ғмқё AlphaZero мҠӨнғҖмқјмқҳ Monte--Carlo tree search м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқё \"RMCTS\"лҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ лЁјм Җ prior policyлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ search treeлҘј мғқм„ұн•ң лӢӨмқҢ, search treeмқҳ к°Ғ nodeм—җм„ң лҰ¬н”„л¶Җн„° мӢңмһ‘н•ҙ лЈЁнҠёк№Ңм§Җ кұ°мҠ¬лҹ¬ мҳ¬лқјк°Җл©° ``Monte--Carlo tree search as regularized policy optimization''(Grill et al., 2020)мқҳ regularized optimal posterior policyлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ action valueлҘј мһ¬м¶”м •н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” RMCTSк°Җ AlphaZeroмқҳ MCTS-UCBмҷҖ лҸҷл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„, к·№нһҲ мқјл¶Җмқҳ мӢңк°„л§ҢмңјлЎң лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65049","en":"Posterior Behavioral Cloning: Pretraining BC Policies for Efficient RL Finetuning","ko":"Posterior Behavioral Cloning: нҡЁмңЁм Ғ RL Finetuningмқ„ мң„н•ң BC Policy мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Andrew Wagenmaker, Perry Dong, Raymond Tsao, Chelsea Finn, Sergey Levine","pos":"#114","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HJ5F3R9Tmd","abs":"<p>Standard practice across domains from robotics to language is to first pretrain a policy on a large-scale demonstration dataset, and then finetune this policy, typically with reinforcement learning (RL), in order to improve performance on deployment domains. This finetuning step has proved critical in achieving human or super-human performance, yet while much attention has been given to developing more effective finetuning algorithms, little attention has been given to ensuring the pretrained policy is an effective initialization for RL finetuning. In this work we seek to understand how the pretrained policy affects finetuning performance, and how to pretrain policies in order to ensure they are effective initializations for finetuning. We first show theoretically that standard behavioral cloning (BC) can fail to ensure coverage over the demonstrator's actions, a minimal condition necessary for effective RL finetuning. We then show that if, instead of exactly fitting the observed demonstrations, we train a policy to model the posterior distribution of the demonstrator's behavior given the demonstration dataset, we do obtain a policy that ensures coverage over the demonstrator's actions, enabling more effective finetuning. Furthermore, this policy achieves this while ensuring pretrained performance is no worse than that of the BC policy. We then show this approach is practically implementable with modern generative models and leads to significantly improved RL finetuning performance on both realistic robotic control benchmarks and real-world robotic manipulation tasks, as compared to standard behavioral cloning.</p>","absKo":"лЎңліҙнӢұмҠӨл¶Җн„° м–ём–ҙм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң л¶„м•јм—җм„ңмқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ кҙҖн–үмқҖ лЁјм Җ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ demonstration datasetмңјлЎң policyлҘј pretrainн•ң л’Ө, ліҙнҶө reinforcement learning(RL)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мқҙ policyлҘј finetuneн•ҳм—¬ л°°нҸ¬ лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ңмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙ finetuning лӢЁкі„лҠ” мқёк°„ мҲҳмӨҖ лҳҗлҠ” мҙҲмқёк°„ мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° кІ°м •м Ғмһ„мқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, лҚ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё finetuning м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” л§ҺмқҖ кҙҖмӢ¬мқҙ мҸ лҰ° л°ҳл©ҙ, pretrained policyк°Җ RL finetuningмқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё initializationмқҙ лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” мғҒлҢҖм ҒмңјлЎң кҙҖмӢ¬мқҙ м Ғм—ҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” pretrained policyк°Җ finetuning м„ұлҠҘм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  finetuningм—җ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё мҙҲкё°нҷ”к°Җ лҗҳлҸ„лЎқ policyлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ pretrainн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкі мһҗ н•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ, н‘ңмӨҖ behavioral cloning(BC)мқҖ demonstratorмқҳ н–үлҸҷм—җ лҢҖн•ң coverageлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӢӨнҢЁн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё RL finetuningм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң мөңмҶҢ мЎ°кұҙмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ, кҙҖмёЎлҗң demonstrationмқ„ м •нҷ•нһҲ л§һм¶”лҠ” лҢҖмӢ  demonstration datasetмқҙ мЈјм–ҙмЎҢмқ„ л•Ң demonstratorмқҳ н–үлҸҷм—җ лҢҖн•ң posterior distributionмқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ policyлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©ҙ, demonstratorмқҳ н–үлҸҷм—җ лҢҖн•ң coverageлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” policyлҘј м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲкі , мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лҚ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё finetuningмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мқҙ policyлҠ” pretrained м„ұлҠҘмқҙ BC policyліҙлӢӨ лӮҳмҒҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҠ№м„ұмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙ нҳ„лҢҖ generative modelлЎң мӢӨм ң кө¬нҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳл©°, н‘ңмӨҖ behavioral cloningкіј л№„көҗн•  л•Ң нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқё лЎңлҙҮ м ңм–ҙ benchmarkмҷҖ мӢӨм ң лЎңлҙҮ мЎ°мһ‘ мһ‘м—… лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң RL finetuning м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61397","en":"Learning Generalizable Skill Policy with Data-Efficient Unsupervised RL","ko":"Data-Efficient Unsupervised RLмқ„ нҶөн•ң Generalizable Skill Policy н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Jongchan Park, Seungjun Oh, Seungho Baek, Yusung Kim","pos":"#117","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qgAKuqzYBC","abs":"<p>Unsupervised Reinforcement Learning (URL) aims to pre-train scalable, skill-conditioned policies without extrinsic rewards, serving as a foundation for downstream control tasks. Despite recent progress, we argue that current off-policy URL methods are limited by two critical, overlooked bottlenecks: (1) non-stationarity skill semantic and (2) brittle generalization. To address these challenges, we propose GenDa (Generalizable Data-efficient Agent), a unified framework for robust unsupervised reinforcement learning. First, we introduce a skill relabeling mechanism to mitigate non-stationarity and significantly improve sample efficiency for pretraining. Second, we propose a Complementary Information Bottleneck(CIB), encouraging the learned skill policy to focus on ego-centric features and become robust to distribution shifts for downstream tasks. Through various experiments, we demonstrate that GenDa significantly enhances the scalability of URL with superior generality and sample efficiency. Our source codes are available in the supplementary materials.</p>","absKo":"<p>Unsupervised Reinforcement Learning (URL)мқҖ extrinsic reward м—Ҷмқҙ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң skill-conditioned policyлҘј pre-trainн•ҳм—¬ downstream control taskмқҳ кё°л°ҳмқ„ л§Ҳл Ён•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м§„м „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ off-policy URL л°©лІ•мқҙ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң к°„кіјлҗң лі‘лӘ©м—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨкі  ліёлӢӨ: (1) non-stationarity skill semanticкіј (2) brittle generalizationмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кІ¬кі н•ң unsupervised reinforcement learningмқ„ мң„н•ң нҶөн•© frameworkмқё GenDa(Generalizable Data-efficient Agent)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” non-stationarityлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкі  pretrainingмқҳ sample efficiencyлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ к°ңм„ н•ҳлҠ” skill relabeling mechanismмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•ҷмҠөлҗң skill policyк°Җ ego-centric featureм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳкі  downstream taskм—җм„ң distribution shiftм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ robustн•ҙм§ҖлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” Complementary Information Bottleneck(CIB)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ GenDaк°Җ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң generalityмҷҖ sample efficiencyлЎң URLмқҳ scalabilityлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҶҢмҠӨ мҪ”л“ңлҠ” л¶ҖлЎқ мһҗлЈҢм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64761","en":"Intentional Updates for Streaming Reinforcement Learning","ko":"Streaming Reinforcement Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң мқҳлҸ„м Ғ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠё","authors":"Arsalan Sharifnassab, Mohamed Elsayed, Kris De Asis, Rupam Mahmood, Rich Sutton","pos":"#118","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=K9lUSMMI0h","abs":"<p>In gradient-based learning, a step size chosen in parameter units does not produce a predictable per-step change in the function output. This may lead to instability in the streaming setting (i.e., batch size=1), where stochasticity is not averaged out and update magnitudes can momentarily become arbitrarily big or small. Instead, we propose \\emph{intentional updates}: first specify the \\emph{intended outcome} of an update and then solve for the step size that approximately achieves it. This strategy has precedent in online supervised linear regression via normalized LMS, which selects a step size to yield a specified change in the function output proportional to the current error. We extend this principle to streaming reinforcement learning by defining appropriate intended outcomes: \\emph{Intentional TD} aims for a fixed fractional reduction of the current TD error relative to the momentary bootstrap target, and \\emph{Intentional Policy Gradient} aims for a bounded per-step change in the policy, limiting local KL divergence. We develop practical implementations integrating eligibility traces and diagonal scaling; our experiments show that these methods yield state-of-the-art streaming performance often comparable to batch and replay-buffer learning.</p>","absKo":"<p>gradient-based learningм—җм„ң parameter unitsлЎң м„ нғқн•ң step sizeлҠ” function outputмқҳ stepлі„ ліҖнҷ”лҘј мҳҲмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” stochasticityк°Җ нҸүк· нҷ”лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  update magnitudesк°Җ мҲңк°„м ҒмңјлЎң мһ„мқҳлЎң л§Өмҡ° м»Өм§Җкұ°лӮҳ мһ‘м•„м§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” streaming setting, мҰү batch size=1м—җм„ң л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. лҢҖмӢ  мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\emph{intentional updates}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ updateмқҳ \\emph{intended outcome}лҘј лӘ…мӢңн•ң лӢӨмқҢ, к·ёкІғмқ„ к·јмӮ¬м ҒмңјлЎң лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” step sizeлҘј н‘јлӢӨ. мқҙ м „лһөмқҖ normalized LMSлҘј нҶөн•ң online supervised linear regressionм—җм„ң м„ лЎҖк°Җ мһҲлҠ”лҚ°, м—¬кё°м„ңлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ errorм—җ л№„лЎҖн•ҳлҠ” function outputмқҳ м§Җм •лҗң ліҖнҷ”лҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ step sizeлҘј м„ нғқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мӣҗлҰ¬лҘј streaming reinforcement learningмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм—¬ м Ғм Ҳн•ң intended outcomeмқ„ м •мқҳн•ңлӢӨ. \\emph{Intentional TD}лҠ” мҲңк°„м Ғмқё bootstrap targetм—җ л№„н•ҙ нҳ„мһ¬ TD errorлҘј кі м •лҗң л№„мңЁлЎң к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳкі , \\emph{Intentional Policy Gradient}лҠ” policyмқҳ stepлӢ№ ліҖнҷ”лҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳм—¬ local KL divergenceлҘј м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” eligibility tracesмҷҖ diagonal scalingмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ кө¬нҳ„мқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳл©°, мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј мқҙ л°©лІ•л“Өмқҙ мў…мў… batch л°Ҹ replay-buffer learningкіј кІ¬мӨ„ л§Ңн•ң мөңмІЁлӢЁ streaming м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63301","en":"Bridging Scaling Laws to On-Policy Reinforcement Learning via Adaptive Batch Scaling","ko":"м Ғмқ‘нҳ• л°°м№ҳ мҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғмқ„ нҶөн•ң On-Policy к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөмңјлЎңмқҳ мҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғ лІ•м№ҷ м—°кІ°","authors":"Jongchan Park","pos":"#122","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=YI9wSqfz7W","abs":"<p>While the \"Scaling Laws\" have driven massive success in Computer Vision and NLP through large-scale training with massive batch sizes, Reinforcement Learning (RL) has largely failed to benefit from this paradigm. In RL, increasing batch sizes beyond a modest threshold often leads to diminishing returns or performance degradation due to the inherent non-stationarity of the data distribution. In this paper, we challenge the prevailing static view of batch sizes in RL by observing that the degree of non-stationarity is not constant: early training involves rapid behavioral shifts requiring small batches for plasticity, whereas late training approaches a quasi-stationary regime where large batches are essential for high-precision convergence.  To leverage this insight, we propose Adaptive Batch Scaling (ABS), a simple yet effective framework that dynamically adjusts the effective batch size based on the stability of the learning process. We introduce Behavioral Divergence, a novel metric that quantifies non-stationarity by measuring action-level shifts between policy updates, and use it to scale the batch size inversely to the policy's volatility. By integrating ABS with the Parallelised Q-Network (PQN) algorithm, we demonstrate on the ALE benchmark that our method synergizes early-stage model plasticity with late-stage accurate and stable convergence. Our empirical results show that ABS not only yields substantial performance improvements over static baselines but also successfully scales to larger network architectures, offering a foundational step toward bridging the scaling gap between RL and supervised learning.</p>","absKo":"<p>\"Scaling Laws\"лҠ” лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ batch sizeлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң large-scale trainingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ Computer Visionкіј NLPм—җм„ң м—„мІӯлӮң м„ұкіөмқ„ мқҙлҒҢм–ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, Reinforcement Learning (RL)мқҖ мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҳ нҳңнғқмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҲ„лҰ¬м§Җ лӘ»н–ҲлӢӨ. RLм—җм„ңлҠ” batch sizeлҘј м–ҙлҠҗ м •лҸ„ мһ„кі„к°’ мқҙмғҒмңјлЎң лҠҳлҰ¬л©ҙ лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶„нҸ¬мқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё non-stationarity л•Ңл¬ём—җ мў…мў… diminishing returns лҳҗлҠ” м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” RLм—җм„ңмқҳ batch sizeлҘј м •м Ғмқё кІғмңјлЎң ліҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙ кҙҖм җм—җ лҸ„м „н•ҳл©°, non-stationarityмқҳ м •лҸ„к°Җ мқјм •н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ңлӢӨ: мҙҲкё° trainingмқҖ plasticityлҘј мң„н•ҙ мһ‘мқҖ batchк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ң л№ лҘё н–үлҸҷ ліҖнҷ”к°Җ нҠ№м§•мқё л°ҳл©ҙ, нӣ„кё° trainingмқҖ лҶ’мқҖ м •л°ҖлҸ„мқҳ convergenceлҘј мң„н•ҙ нҒ° batchк°Җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё quasi-stationary regimeм—җ к°Җк№қлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” н•ҷмҠө кіјм •мқҳ м•Ҳм •м„ұм—җ л”°лқј effective batch sizeлҘј лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳм§Җл§Ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё Adaptive Batch Scaling (ABS)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” policy update к°„ action-level shiftлҘј мёЎм •н•ҳм—¬ non-stationarityлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м§Җн‘ңмқё Behavioral DivergenceлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј policyмқҳ volatilityм—җ л°ҳл№„лЎҖн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ batch sizeлҘј мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. ABSлҘј Parallelised Q-Network (PQN) м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳкіј нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬, ALE benchmarkм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ мҙҲкё° лӢЁкі„мқҳ model plasticityмҷҖ нӣ„кё° лӢЁкі„мқҳ м •нҷ•н•ҳкі  м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё convergenceлҘј мӢңл„Ҳм§Җ мһҲкІҢ кІ°н•©н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” ABSк°Җ м •м Ғ baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳлҠ” м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ м ңкіөн•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј лҚ” нҒ° network architectureлЎңлҸ„ м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘлҗҳм–ҙ, RLкіј supervised learning мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ scaling gapмқ„ л©”мҡ°лҠ” кё°мҙҲм Ғмқё лӢЁкі„к°Җ лҗЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65047","en":"On Computation and Reinforcement Learning","ko":"кі„мӮ°кіј Reinforcement Learningм—җ лҢҖн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Raj Ghugare, MichaЕӮ Bortkiewicz, Alicja Ziarko, Benjamin Eysenbach","pos":"#200","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HKzMnBX5B2","abs":"How does the amount of compute available to a reinforcement learning (RL) policy affect its learning? Can policies using a fixed amount of parameters, still benefit from additional compute? The standard RL framework does not provide a language to answer these questions formally. Empirically, deep RL policies are often parameterized as neural networks with static architectures, conflating the amount of compute and the number of parameters. In this paper, we formalize compute bounded policies and prove that policies which use more compute can solve problems and generalize to longer-horizon tasks that are outside the scope of policies with less compute. Building on prior work in algorithmic learning and model-free planning, we propose a minimal architecture that can use a variable amount of compute. Our experiments complement our theory. On a set 31 different tasks spanning online and offline RL, we show that $(1)$ this architecture achieves stronger performance simply by using more compute, and $(2)$ stronger generalization on longer-horizon test tasks compared to standard feedforward networks or deep residual network using upto 5 times more parameters.","absKo":"к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө(RL) policyк°Җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” computeмқҳ м–‘мқҖ к·ё н•ҷмҠөм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”к°Җ? кі м •лҗң мҲҳмқҳ parameterлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” policyлҸ„ м¶”к°Җ computeмқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ кі„мҶҚ лҲ„лҰҙ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”к°Җ? н‘ңмӨҖ RL н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м§Ҳл¬ём—җ нҳ•мӢқм ҒмңјлЎң лӢөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м–ём–ҙлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң deep RL policyлҠ” мў…мў… м •м Ғ м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳлҘј к°Җм§„ neural networkлЎң parameterнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ, computeмқҳ м–‘кіј parameter мҲҳк°Җ л’Өм„һмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” compute-bounded policyлҘј нҳ•мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ computeлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” policyк°Җ лҚ” м ҒмқҖ computeлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” policyмқҳ лІ”мң„лҘј лІ—м–ҙлӮҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкі  лҚ” кёҙ horizon taskлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ н•ҷмҠөкіј model-free planningмқҳ м„ н–ү м—°кө¬лҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°ҖліҖм Ғмқё м–‘мқҳ computeлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мөңмҶҢ м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҙлЎ мқ„ ліҙмҷ„н•ңлӢӨ. online л°Ҹ offline RLмқ„ м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” 31к°ңмқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё taskм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” (1) мқҙ м•„нӮӨн…ҚмІҳк°Җ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ computeлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лҚ” к°•н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі , (2) мөңлҢҖ 5л°° лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ parameterлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” standard feedforward networkлӮҳ deep residual networkліҙлӢӨ кёҙ horizon test taskм—җм„ң лҚ” к°•н•ң generalizationмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"61981","en":"Sample Efficient Full-Finetuning of Generative Control Policies","ko":"мғқм„ұнҳ• control policiesмқҳ sample-efficient full-finetuning","authors":"Sarvesh Patil, Mitsuhiko Nakamoto, Shashwat Saxena, Manan Agarwal, Giri Anantharaman, Cleah Winston, Jesse Zhang, Chaoyi Pan, Douglas Chen, Nai-Chieh Huang, Zeynep Temel, Oliver Kroemer, Hongkai Dai, Sergey Levine, Abhishek Gupta, Paarth Shah, Max Simchowitz","pos":"#202","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=l1WWnr0ObL","abs":"<p>Generative control policies (GCPs), such as diffusion- and flow-based control policies, have emerged as effective parameterizations for robot learning. Yet there remains substantial debate over how to sample efficiently fine-tune them via reinforcement learning. A prevailing view holds that fine-tuning all GCP steps is unnecessary, motivating approaches that fine-tune only a subset of the generative process: either steering the initial noise distribution or learning residual corrections on top of a frozen base policy. In this work, we introduce Off-policy Generative Policy Optimization (\\OGPO{}), a sample-efficient algorithm for finetuning GCPs that maintains off-policy critic networks to maximize data reuse and propagate policy gradients through the full generative process of the policy via a modified PPO objective, using critics as the terminal reward. \\OGPO{} achieves state-of-the-art performance on manipulation tasks spanning multi-task settings, high-precision insertion, and dexterous control. To our knowledge, it is also the only method that can \\emph{fine-tune poorly-initialized behavior cloning policies to near full task-success with no expert data in the online replay buffer}, and does so with \\emph{few task-specific hyperparameter tuning}. We perform extensive empirical investigations on \\OGPO{}, finding that its superior performance and sample efficiency lie in its ability to learn beyond the action distribution of the pre-trained base policy, and propose practical implementation details that further boost performance for more complex scenarios.</p>","absKo":"<p>Diffusion- л°Ҹ flow-based control policyмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ generative control policy (GCPs)лҠ” robot learningмқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё parameterizationмңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ reinforcement learningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң sample fine-tuneн•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•м—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ мғҒлӢ№н•ң л…јмҹҒмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. м§Җл°°м Ғмқё кІ¬н•ҙлҠ” лӘЁл“  GCP stepмқ„ fine-tuneн•  н•„мҡ”лҠ” м—ҶлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙл©°, мқҙм—җ л”°лқј мғқм„ұ кіјм •мқҳ мқјл¶Җл§Ң fine-tuneн•ҳлҠ” м ‘к·јмқҙ м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ: мҙҲкё° noise distributionмқ„ мЎ°м •н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, frozen base policy мң„м—җ residual correctionмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҙлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” Off-policy Generative Policy Optimization (\\OGPO{})мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” GCPлҘј мң„н•ң sample-efficient fine-tuning algorithmмңјлЎң, data reuseлҘј к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ off-policy critic networkлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©°, modified PPO objectiveлҘј нҶөн•ҙ policyмқҳ м „мІҙ generative processлҘј л”°лқј policy gradientлҘј м „нҢҢн•ҳкі , criticмқ„ terminal rewardлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. \\OGPO{}лҠ” multi-task setting, high-precision insertion, dexterous controlм—җ кұём№ң manipulation taskм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м•„лҠ” н•ң, мқҙлҠ” лҳҗн•ң <em>expert dataк°Җ online replay bufferм—җ м „нҳҖ м—ҶлҚ”лқјлҸ„ мҙҲкё°нҷ”к°Җ мўӢм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ behavior cloning policyлҘј кұ°мқҳ мҷ„м „н•ң task success мҲҳмӨҖк№Ңм§Җ fine-tuneн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мң мқјн•ң л°©лІ•</em>мқҙл©°, <em>м ҒмқҖ task-specific hyperparameter tuning</em>л§ҢмңјлЎң мқҙлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\OGPO{}м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨмҰқ м—°кө¬лҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬, к·ё мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘкіј sample efficiencyк°Җ мӮ¬м „ н•ҷмҠөлҗң base policyмқҳ action distributionмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙм—җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–Ҳкі , лҚ” ліөмһЎн•ң мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м¶”к°ҖлЎң лҒҢм–ҙмҳ¬лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё кө¬нҳ„ м„ёл¶ҖмӮ¬н•ӯмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65299","en":"Task-Aware Exploration via a Predictive Bisimulation Metric","ko":"мҳҲмёЎм Ғ Bisimulation Metricмқ„ нҶөн•ң кіјм ң мқём§Җ нғҗн—ҳ","authors":"Dayang Liang, Ruihan LIU, Lipeng Wan, Yunlong Liu, Bo An","pos":"#204","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=EyxlSrJWT5","abs":"<p>Accelerating exploration in visual reinforcement learning under sparse rewards remains challenging due to the substantial task-irrelevant variations. Despite advances in intrinsic exploration, many methods either assume access to low-dimensional states or lack task-aware exploration strategies, thereby rendering them fragile in visual domains. To bridge this gap, we present TEB, a Task-aware Exploration approach that tightly couples task-relevant representations with exploration through a predictive Bisimulation metric. Specifically, TEB leverages the metric not only to learn behaviorally grounded task representations but also to measure behaviorally intrinsic novelty over the learned latent space. To realize this, we first theoretically mitigate the representation collapse of degenerate bisimulation metrics under sparse rewards by internally introducing a simple but effective predicted reward differential. Building on this robust metric, we design potential-based exploration bonuses, which measure the relative novelty of adjacent observations over the latent space. Extensive experiments on MetaWorld and Maze2D show that TEB achieves superior exploration ability and outperforms recent baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>нқ¬мҶҢн•ң ліҙмғҒ н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ visual reinforcement learningм—җм„ң explorationмқ„ к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң task-irrelevant variation л•Ңл¬ём—җ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. intrinsic explorationмқҳ л°ңм „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , л§ҺмқҖ л°©лІ•мқҖ low-dimensional stateм—җ м ‘к·јн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨкі  к°Җм •н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ task-aware exploration strategyк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳм—¬ visual domainм—җм„ң м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” predictive Bisimulation metricмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ task-relevant representationкіј explorationмқ„ кёҙл°Җн•ҳкІҢ кІ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” Task-aware Exploration м ‘к·јлІ•мқё TEBлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, TEBлҠ” мқҙ metricмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ н–үлҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң groundedлҗң task representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј, н•ҷмҠөлҗң latent space мң„м—җм„ң н–үлҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң intrinsicн•ң noveltyлҘј мёЎм •н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мӢӨнҳ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЁјм Җ к°„лӢЁн•ҳм§Җл§Ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё predicted reward differentialмқ„ лӮҙл¶Җм ҒмңјлЎң лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ sparse reward н•ҳм—җм„ң degenerate bisimulation metricмқҳ representation collapseлҘј мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ robust metricмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” latent space мғҒм—җм„ң мқём ‘н•ң observationмқҳ мғҒлҢҖм Ғ noveltyлҘј мёЎм •н•ҳлҠ” potential-based exploration bonusлҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. MetaWorldмҷҖ Maze2Dм—җм„ңмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ TEBк°Җ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң exploration лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  мөңк·ј baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63579","en":"Expected Return Causes Outcome-Level Mode Collapse in Reinforcement Learning and How to Fix It with Inverse Probability Scaling","ko":"кё°лҢҖ мҲҳмқөмқҙ к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң outcome-level mode collapseлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” мқҙмң мҷҖ inverse probability scalingмңјлЎңмқҳ н•ҙкІ°","authors":"Abhijeet Sinha, Sundari Elango, Dianbo Liu","pos":"#205","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Vr0kjNERRf","abs":"<p>Many reinforcement learning (RL) problems admit multiple terminal solutions of comparable quality, where the goal is not to identify a single optimum but to represent a diverse set of high-quality outcomes. Nevertheless, policies trained by standard expected-return maximization routinely collapse onto a small subset of outcomes, a phenomenon commonly attributed to insufficient exploration or weak regularization. We show that this explanation is incomplete: outcome-level mode collapse is a structural consequence of the expected-return objective itself. Under idealized learning dynamics, the log-probability ratio between any two outcomes evolves linearly in their reward difference, implying exponential ratio divergence and inevitable collapseвҖ”independent of the exploration strategy, entropy regularization, or optimization algorithm. We identify the source of this pathology as the probability multiplier inside the expectation and propose a minimal correction: inverse probability scaling, which removes outcome-frequency amplification from the learning signal, fundamentally changes the learning dynamics, and provably yields reward-proportional terminal distributions, preventing collapse in multimodal settings. We instantiate this principle in Group Relative Policy Optimization (GRPO) as a drop-in modification, IPS-GRPO, requiring no auxiliary models or architectural changes. Across different reasoning and molecular generation tasks, IPS-GRPO consistently reduces outcome-level mode collapse while matching or exceeding baseline performance, suggesting that correcting the objective rather than adding exploration heuristics is key to reliable multimodal policy optimization.</p>","absKo":"<p>л§ҺмқҖ reinforcement learning(RL) л¬ём ңлҠ” л№„мҠ·н•ң н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҳ м—¬лҹ¬ terminal solutionмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳл©°, мқҙл•Ң лӘ©н‘ңлҠ” лӢЁмқј optimumмқ„ м°ҫлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј лӢӨм–‘н•ң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ outcomeмқ„ н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ standard expected-return maximizationмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң policyлҠ” мқјмғҒм ҒмңјлЎң мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ outcomeмңјлЎң л¶•кҙҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” нқ”нһҲ нғҗмғү л¶ҖмЎұмқҙлӮҳ м•Ҫн•ң regularization нғ“мңјлЎң лҸҢл Өм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м„ӨлӘ…мқҙ л¶Ҳмҷ„м „н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. outcome-level mode collapseлҠ” expected-return objective мһҗмІҙмқҳ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ кІ°кіјмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙмғҒнҷ”лҗң learning dynamics н•ҳм—җм„ң, мһ„мқҳмқҳ л‘җ outcome мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ log-probability ratioлҠ” reward м°Ёмқҙм—җ л”°лқј м„ нҳ•м ҒмңјлЎң м§„нҷ”н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” exponential ratio divergenceмҷҖ л¶Ҳк°Җн”јн•ң collapseлҘј н•Ёмқҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқҖ exploration strategy, entropy regularization, optimization algorithmкіј л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лі‘лҰ¬мқҳ мӣҗмқёмқ„ expectation лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ probability multiplierлЎң мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ мҲҳм •мқё inverse probability scalingмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” learning signalм—җм„ң outcome-frequency amplificationмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ҳкі , learning dynamicsлҘј к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң л°”кҫёл©°, reward-proportional terminal distributionмқ„ provablyн•ҳкІҢ мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬ multimodal settingм—җм„ң collapseлҘј л°©м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мӣҗлҰ¬лҘј Group Relative Policy Optimization(GRPO)м—җ drop-in modificationмқё IPS-GRPOлЎң кө¬нҳ„н•ҳл©°, м¶”к°Җ modelмқҙлӮҳ architecture ліҖкІҪ м—Ҷмқҙ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң reasoning л°Ҹ molecular generation task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң IPS-GRPOлҠ” baseline м„ұлҠҘкіј к°ҷкұ°лӮҳ к·ё мқҙмғҒмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң outcome-level mode collapseлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мӨ„м—¬мЈјл©°, reliable multimodal policy optimizationмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҙ нғҗмғү heuristicмқ„ м¶”к°Җн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј objectiveлҘј көҗм •н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62722","en":"Reinforcement Learning for Non-Verifiable Problems","ko":"кІҖмҰқ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘ л¬ём ңлҘј мң„н•ң к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Gurusha Juneja, Shubham Phal, Jennifer She, Lisa Wang, Dorsa Sadigh, Anca Dragan, William Wang","pos":"#208","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=dvHfSKI965","abs":"Many real-world tasks are non-verifiableвҖ”there is no objective ground truth, and quality must be judged subjectivelyвҖ”making reward design for RL difficult. Existing approaches based on scalar rubric scores or single comparisons are often noisy, poorly calibrated, or provide sparse learning signals.  We introduce Tournament Style RL (TSRL), which constructs rewards from rubric-guided pairwise judgments against a fixed set of anchor responses, using win-rate as the reward for policy optimization. This aggregation of comparisons against anchor responses yields a signal that is more robust to the judge noise by stabilizing the reference frame, reducing the variance in reward. We test across four non-verifiable tasks and two backbone LLMs, and find that TSRL improves average win-rate by $+43.8$ points over the base model and $+22.8$ points over the strongest baseline. TSRL scales with the number of anchors, remains robust under weak or partially corrupted judges, the results are supported by blinded human preference studies.","absKo":"л§ҺмқҖ мӢӨм ң taskлҠ” non-verifiableн•ҳлӢӨ. мҰү, к°қкҙҖм Ғмқё ground truthк°Җ м—Ҷкі  qualityлҘј мЈјкҙҖм ҒмңјлЎң нҢҗлӢЁн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң RLмқ„ мң„н•ң reward м„Өкі„к°Җ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. scalar rubric scoreлӮҳ лӢЁмқј л№„көҗм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мў…мў… noisyн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, calibrationмқҙ мһҳ лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкұ°лӮҳ, sparseн•ң learning signalл§Ң м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.  мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Tournament Style RL (TSRL)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кі м •лҗң anchor response м§‘н•©м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ rubric-guided pairwise judgmentлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ rewardлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳкі , win-rateлҘј policy optimizationмқ„ мң„н•ң rewardлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. anchor responseмҷҖмқҳ л№„көҗлҘј м§‘кі„н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ reference frameмқҙ м•Ҳм •нҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ judge noiseм—җ лҚ” robustн•ң signalмқ„ м–»кі , rewardмқҳ varianceлҘј мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л„Ө к°ңмқҳ non-verifiable taskмҷҖ л‘җ к°ңмқҳ backbone LLMм—җм„ң мқҙлҘј н…ҢмҠӨнҠён–Ҳмңјл©°, TSRLмқҙ base model лҢҖл№„ нҸүк·  win-rateлҘј $+43.8$ points, к°ҖмһҘ к°•н•ң baseline лҢҖл№„ $+22.8$ points н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ. TSRLмқҖ anchor мҲҳк°Җ мҰқк°Җн• мҲҳлЎқ нҷ•мһҘлҗҳл©°, м•Ҫн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ л¶Җл¶„м ҒмңјлЎң мҶҗмғҒлҗң judge н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ robustн•ҳкі , к·ё кІ°кіјлҠ” blinded human preference studyлЎң л’·л°ӣм№ЁлҗңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63451","en":"The Role of Target Update Frequencies in Q-Learning","ko":"Q-Learningм—җм„ң нғҖк№ғ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠё л№ҲлҸ„мқҳ м—ӯн• ","authors":"Simon Weissmann, Tilman Aach, Benedikt Wille, Sebastian Kassing, Leif DГ¶ring","pos":"#210","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=X6i0PB7aJQ","abs":"<p>The target network update frequency (TUF) is a central stabilization mechanism in (deep) Q-learning. However, their selection remains poorly understood and is often treated merely as another tunable hyperparameter rather than as a principled design decision. This work provides a theoretical analysis of target fixing in tabular Q-learning through the lens of approximate dynamic programming. We formulate periodic target updates as a nested optimization scheme in which each outer iteration applies an inexact Bellman optimality operator, approximated by a generic inner loop optimizer. Rigorous theory yields a finite-time convergence analysis for the asynchronous sampling setting, specializing to stochastic gradient descent in the inner loop. Our results deliver an explicit characterization of the biasвҖ“variance trade-off induced by the target update period, showing how to optimally set this critical hyperparameter. We prove that constant target update schedules are suboptimal, incurring a logarithmic overhead in sample complexity that is entirely avoidable with adaptive schedules. Our analysis shows that the optimal target update frequency increases geometrically over the course of the learning process.</p>","absKo":"<p>target network update frequency (TUF)лҠ” (deep) Q-learningмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ м•Ҳм •нҷ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к·ё м„ нғқмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ мһҳ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  мһҲмңјл©°, мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғмқё м„Өкі„ кІ°м •мқҙлқјкё°ліҙлӢӨ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ мЎ°м • к°ҖлҠҘн•ң лҳҗ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ hyperparameterлЎң м·ЁкёүлҗҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” approximate dynamic programmingмқҳ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң tabular Q-learningмқҳ target fixingм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мЈјкё°м Ғ target updateлҘј, к°Ғ outer iterationмқҙ generic inner loop optimizerлЎң к·јмӮ¬лҗҳлҠ” inexact Bellman optimality operatorлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” nested optimization schemeмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. м—„л°Җн•ң мқҙлЎ мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, inner loopм—җ stochastic gradient descentлҘј нҠ№мҲҳн•ң кІҪмҡ°лЎң к°–лҠ” asynchronous sampling м„Өм •м—җ лҢҖн•ң finite-time convergence analysisлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” target update periodк°Җ мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” biasвҖ“variance trade-offлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, мқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң hyperparameterлҘј мөңм ҒмңјлЎң м„Өм •н•ҳлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” constant target update scheduleмқҙ мөңм Ғмқҙ м•„лӢҳмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳл©°, м Ғмқ‘м Ғ scheduleмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ мҷ„м „нһҲ н”јн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” sample complexityмқҳ logarithmic overheadлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ мөңм Ғмқҳ target update frequencyк°Җ н•ҷмҠө кіјм •мқҙ м§„н–үлҗЁм—җ л”°лқј кё°н•ҳкёүмҲҳм ҒмңјлЎң мҰқк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63528","en":"Approximation of Log-Partition Function in Policy Mirror Descent Induces Implicit Regularization for LLM Post-Training","ko":"Policy Mirror Descentм—җм„ң лЎңк·ё л¶„н• н•ЁмҲҳмқҳ к·јмӮ¬нҷ”к°Җ LLM мӮ¬м „н•ҷмҠө нӣ„ лӢЁкі„м—җ м•”л¬өм Ғ м •к·ңнҷ”лҘј мң лҸ„н•Ё","authors":"Zhenghao Xu, Qin Lu, Changlong Yu, Tuo Zhao","pos":"#2112","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WPFVuJDDqc","abs":"Policy mirror descent (PMD) provides a principled framework for reinforcement learning (RL) by iteratively solving KL-regularized policy improvement subproblems. While this approach has been adopted in training advanced LLMs such as Kimi K1.5/K2, the ideal closed-form PMD updates require reliable partition function estimation, a significant challenge when working with limited rollouts in the vast action spaces of LLMs. We investigate a practical algorithm, termed PMD-mean, that approximates the log-partition term with the mean reward under the sampling policy and performs regression in log-policy space. Specifically, we characterize the population solution of PMD-mean and demonstrate that it implicitly optimizes mirror descent subproblems with an adaptive mixed KL-$\\chi^2$ regularizer. This additional $\\chi^2$ regularization constrains large probability changes, producing more conservative updates when expected rewards are low and enhancing robustness against finite-sample estimation errors. Experiments on math reasoning tasks show that PMD-mean achieves superior performance with improved stability and time efficiency. These findings deepen our understanding of PMD-mean and illuminate pathways toward principled improvements in RL algorithms for LLMs.","absKo":"Policy mirror descent(PMD)лҠ” KL м •к·ңнҷ”лҗң policy improvement н•ҳмң„л¬ём ңлҘј л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң н‘ёлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң reinforcement learning(RL)м—җ лҢҖн•ң мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғмқё н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ Kimi K1.5/K2мҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ кі кёү LLM н•ҷмҠөм—җ мұ„нғқлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙмғҒм Ғмқё closed-form PMD updateлҠ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” partition function м¶”м •мқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳл©°, LLMмқҳ кұ°лҢҖн•ң action spaceм—җм„ң м ңн•ңлҗң rolloutл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•  л•Ң мқҙлҠ” нҒ° лҸ„м „мқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҳн”Ңл§Ғ policy н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ нҸүк·  rewardлЎң log-partition termмқ„ к·јмӮ¬н•ҳкі  log-policy spaceм—җм„ң regressionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ PMD-meanмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PMD-meanмқҳ population solutionмқ„ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳкі , мқҙкІғмқҙ adaptive mixed KL-$\\chi^2$ regularizerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” mirror descent н•ҳмң„л¬ём ңлҘј м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё $\\chi^2$ regularizationмқҖ нҒ° нҷ•лҘ  ліҖнҷ”лҘј м ңм•Ҫн•ҳм—¬ expected rewardк°Җ лӮ®мқ„ л•Ң лҚ” ліҙмҲҳм Ғмқё updateлҘј л§Ңл“Өм–ҙлӮҙкі , finite-sample м¶”м • мҳӨм°Ём—җ лҢҖн•ң к°•кұҙм„ұмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мҲҳн•ҷ reasoning кіјм ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PMD-meanмқҙ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м•Ҳм •м„ұкіј мӢңк°„ нҡЁмңЁм„ұмңјлЎң мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” PMD-meanм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙн•ҙлҘј мӢ¬нҷ”мӢңнӮӨкі , LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң RL м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҳ мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғ к°ңм„ мңјлЎң к°ҖлҠ” кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64121","en":"Reinforcement Learning via Self-Distillation","ko":"мһҗкё° мҰқлҘҳлҘј нҶөн•ң к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Jonas HГјbotter, Frederike LГјbeck, Lejs Behric, Anton Baumann, Marco Bagatella, Daniel Marta, Ido Hakimi, Idan Shenfeld, Thomas Kleine Buening, Carlos Guestrin, Andreas Krause","pos":"#2915","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=QkfkxyRizZ","abs":"<p>Large language models are increasingly post-trained with reinforcement learning in verifiable domains such as code and math. Yet, current methods for reinforcement learning with verifiable rewards (RLVR) learn only from a scalar outcome reward per attempt, creating a severe credit-assignment bottleneck. Many verifiable environments actually provide rich textual feedback, such as runtime errors or judge evaluations, that explain <em>why</em> an attempt failed. We formalize this setting as reinforcement learning with rich feedback and introduce <strong>Self-Distillation Policy Optimization</strong> (<strong>SDPO</strong>), which converts tokenized feedback into a dense learning signal without any external teacher or explicit reward model. SDPO treats the current model conditioned on feedback as a self-teacher and distills its feedback-informed next-token predictions back into the policy. In this way, SDPO leverages the model's ability to retrospectively identify its own mistakes in-context. Across scientific reasoning, tool use, and competitive programming on LiveCodeBench v6, SDPO improves sample efficiency and final accuracy over strong RLVR baselines. Notably, SDPO also outperforms baselines in standard RLVR environments that only return scalar feedback by using successful rollouts as implicit feedback for failed attempts. Finally, applying SDPO to individual questions at test time accelerates discovery on difficult binary-reward tasks, achieving the same discovery probability as best-of-k sampling or multi-turn conversations with 3x fewer attempts.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language modelмқҖ codeмҷҖ math к°ҷмқҖ verifiable domainм—җм„ң reinforcement learningмңјлЎң post-training лҗҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ м җм җ лҠҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ reinforcement learning with verifiable rewards(RLVR) л°©лІ•мқҖ к°Ғ мӢңлҸ„л§ҲлӢӨ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ scalar outcome rewardл§ҢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң credit-assignment лі‘лӘ©мқҙ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎң л§ҺмқҖ verifiable environmentлҠ” runtime errorлӮҳ judge evaluationмІҳлҹј, мӢңлҸ„к°Җ <em>мҷң</em> мӢӨнҢЁн–ҲлҠ”м§ҖлҘј м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳлҠ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң textual feedbackмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м„Өм •мқ„ rich feedbackмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң reinforcement learningмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , мҷёл¶Җ teacherлӮҳ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё reward model м—Ҷмқҙ tokenized feedbackмқ„ dense learning signalлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” <strong>Self-Distillation Policy Optimization</strong>(<strong>SDPO</strong>)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SDPOлҠ” feedbackмңјлЎң мЎ°кұҙнҷ”лҗң нҳ„мһ¬ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ self-teacherлЎң к°„мЈјн•ҳкі , feedbackмқ„ л°ҳмҳҒн•ң next-token predictionмқ„ policyлЎң лӢӨмӢң distillн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ° л°©мӢқмңјлЎң SDPOлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ in-contextм—җм„ң мһҗмӢ мқҳ мӢӨмҲҳлҘј мӮ¬нӣ„м ҒмңјлЎң мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. scientific reasoning, tool use, к·ёлҰ¬кі  LiveCodeBench v6мқҳ competitive programming м „л°ҳм—җм„ң SDPOлҠ” к°•л Ҙн•ң RLVR baselineліҙлӢӨ sample efficiencyмҷҖ мөңмў… м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, SDPOлҠ” scalar feedbackл§Ң л°ҳнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” standard RLVR environmentм—җм„ңлҸ„ м„ұкіөн•ң rolloutмқ„ мӢӨнҢЁн•ң мӢңлҸ„м—җ лҢҖн•ң implicit feedbackмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ baselineліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, test timeм—җ к°ңлі„ м§Ҳл¬ём—җ SDPOлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ м–ҙл Өмҡҙ binary-reward taskм—җм„ң discoveryлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳм—¬, best-of-k samplingмқҙлӮҳ multi-turn conversationкіј лҸҷмқјн•ң discovery probabilityлҘј 3л°° м ҒмқҖ мӢңлҸ„лЎң лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61963","en":"Mind the budget: Accelerating Deep Reinforcement Learning using Early Exit Neural Networks","ko":"мҳҲмӮ°м—җ мң мқҳ: early exit neural networksлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң deep reinforcement learning к°ҖмҶҚ","authors":"Julien Brosseit, Jasper Hoffmann, Joschka Boedecker","pos":"#300","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lFaF1Hq2kP","abs":"<p>Early exit neural networks, which adapt computation to input complexity, have proven effective in supervised learning but remain largely unexplored in deep reinforcement learning (DRL). In this paper, we propose the use of Budgeted EXit Actor (BEXA), which is a novel actor-critic architecture that integrates early exit branches into the actor network. These branches are trained via the underlying DRL method and use a constrained value-based criterion to decide when to exit, allowing the policy to dynamically adjust its computation. BEXA is general, easy to tune and compatible with any off-policy actor-critic method. We evaluate BEXA using different DRL methods such as SAC and TD3 on a suite of MuJoCo tasks. Our results demonstrate a substantial improvement in inference efficiency with minimal or no loss in performance. These findings highlight early exits as a promising direction for improving computational efficiency in DRL.</p>","absKo":"<p>мһ…л Ҙ ліөмһЎлҸ„м—җ л”°лқј кі„мӮ°мқ„ мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” early exit neural networkлҠ” supervised learningм—җм„ңлҠ” нҡЁкіјк°Җ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, deep reinforcement learning(DRL)м—җм„ңлҠ” кұ°мқҳ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” actor network м•Ҳм—җ early exit branchлҘј нҶөн•©н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ actor-critic architectureмқё Budgeted EXit Actor(BEXA)мқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ branchлҠ” underlying DRL methodлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗҳл©°, constrained value-based criterionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ м–ём ң exitн• м§Җ кІ°м •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ policyк°Җ кі„мӮ°лҹүмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м Ҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. BEXAлҠ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқҙкі  нҠңлӢқмқҙ мү¬мҡ°л©°, м–ҙл–Ө off-policy actor-critic methodмҷҖлҸ„ нҳёнҷҳлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SACмҷҖ TD3 к°ҷмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң DRL methodлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ MuJoCo task suiteм—җм„ң BEXAлҘј нҸүк°Җн–ҲлӢӨ. кІ°кіјлҠ” м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳк°Җ кұ°мқҳ м—Ҷкұ°лӮҳ м „нҳҖ м—ҶлҠ” мғҒнғңм—җм„ң м¶”лЎ  нҡЁмңЁмқҙ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒлҗЁмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°ңкІ¬мқҖ early exitк°Җ DRLмқҳ кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң л°©н–Ҙмһ„мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66074","en":"Informed Asymmetric Actor-Critic: Leveraging Privileged Signals Beyond Full-State Access","ko":"м •ліҙ кё°л°ҳ л№„лҢҖм№ӯ Actor-Critic: мҷ„м „ мғҒнғң м ‘к·јмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„  нҠ№к¶Ң мӢ нҳё нҷңмҡ©","authors":"Daniel Ebi, Gaspard Lambrechts, Damien Ernst, Klemens BГ¶hm","pos":"#301","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=7G43VVT4SI","abs":"<p>Asymmetric actor-critic methods are widely used in partially observable reinforcement learning, but typically assume full state observability to condition the critic during training, which is often unrealistic in practice. We introduce the informed asymmetric actor-critic framework, allowing the critic to be conditioned on arbitrary state-dependent privileged signals without requiring access to the full state. We show that any such privileged signal yields unbiased policy gradient estimates, substantially expanding the set of admissible privileged information. This raises the problem of selecting the most adequate privileged information in order to improve learning. For this purpose, we propose two novel informativeness criteria: a dependence-based test that can be applied prior to training, and a criterion based on improvements in value prediction accuracy that can be applied post-hoc. Empirical results on partially observable benchmark tasks and synthetic environments demonstrate that carefully selected privileged signals can match or outperform full-state asymmetric baselines while relying on strictly less state information.</p>","absKo":"<p>л¶Җл¶„кҙҖмёЎ к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң asymmetric actor-critic л°©лІ•мқҖ л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң criticмқ„ н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘м—җ мЎ°кұҙнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҷ„м „н•ң state observableмқ„ к°Җм •н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” мў…мў… л№„нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” informed asymmetric actor-critic frameworkлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ҳм—¬, full stateм—җ м ‘к·јн•  н•„мҡ” м—Ҷмқҙ criticмқҙ мһ„мқҳмқҳ state-dependent privileged signalм—җ мЎ°кұҙнҷ”лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң privileged signalмқҙлқјл©ҙ л¬ҙм—Үмқҙл“  unbiased policy gradient estimateлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, admissible privileged informationмқҳ лІ”мң„лҘј нҒ¬кІҢ нҷ•мһҘн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” н•ҷмҠөмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ к°ҖмһҘ м Ғм Ҳн•ң privileged informationмқ„ м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј м ңкё°н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ informativeness criterionмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ: н•ҷмҠө мқҙм „м—җ м Ғмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” dependence-based testмҷҖ, мӮ¬нӣ„м ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” value prediction accuracy к°ңм„  кё°л°ҳ criterionмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. л¶Җл¶„кҙҖмёЎ benchmark taskмҷҖ synthetic environmentм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ”, мӢ мӨ‘н•ҳкІҢ м„ нғқлҗң privileged signalмқҙ strictly less state informationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ full-state asymmetric baselineкіј л§һлЁ№кұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64193","en":"GIPO: Gaussian Importance Sampling Policy Optimization","ko":"GIPO: к°Җмҡ°мӢңм•Ҳ мӨ‘мҡ”лҸ„ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғ м •мұ… мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Chengxuan Lu, Zhenquan Zhang, Shukuan Wang, Qunzhi Lin, Baigui Sun, Yang Liu","pos":"#302","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Q5DHzFVOxf","abs":"<p>Post-training with reinforcement learning (RL) has recently shown strong promise for advancing multimodal agents beyond supervised imitation. However, RL remains limited by poor data efficiency, particularly in settings where interaction data are scarce and quickly become outdated. To address this challenge, GIPO (Gaussian Importance sampling Policy Optimization) is proposed as a policy optimization objective based on truncated importance sampling, replacing hard clipping with a log-ratioвҖ“based Gaussian trust weight to softly damp extreme importance ratios while maintaining non-zero gradients. Theoretical analysis shows that GIPO introduces an implicit, tunable constraint on the update magnitude, while concentration bounds guarantee robustness and stability under finite-sample estimation. Experimental results show that GIPO achieves state-of-the-art performance among clipping-based baselines across a wide range of replay buffer sizes, from near on-policy to highly stale data, while exhibiting superior biasвҖ“variance trade-off, high training stability and improved sample efficiency.  Code is provided in supplementary material.</p>","absKo":"<p>reinforcement learning(RL)мқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң post-trainingмқҖ мөңк·ј supervised imitationмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ multimodal agentлҘј л°ңм „мӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҚ° к°•н•ң к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ RLмқҖ нҠ№нһҲ interaction dataк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳкі  л№ лҘҙкІҢ outdated лҗҳлҠ” мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң м—¬м „нһҲ лӮ®мқҖ data efficiencyмқҳ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, GIPO(Gaussian Importance sampling Policy Optimization)лҠ” truncated importance samplingм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң policy optimization objectiveлЎң м ңм•Ҳлҗҳл©°, hard clippingмқ„ log-ratio кё°л°ҳ Gaussian trust weightлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ҳм—¬ non-zero gradientлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң к·№лӢЁм Ғмқё importance ratioлҘј л¶Җл“ңлҹҪкІҢ мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ GIPOк°Җ update magnitudeм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м•”л¬өм Ғмқҙкі  мЎ°м Ҳ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң constraintлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, concentration boundлҠ” мң н•ң н‘ңліё м¶”м • н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ кІ¬кі м„ұкіј м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” GIPOк°Җ near on-policyл¶Җн„° л§Өмҡ° staleн•ң dataм—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ нҸӯл„“мқҖ replay buffer size м „л°ҳм—җм„ң clipping-based baselineл“Ө мӨ‘ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң biasвҖ“variance trade-off, лҶ’мқҖ training stability, к·ёлҰ¬кі  н–ҘмғҒлҗң sample efficiencyлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” supplementary materialм—җ м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65737","en":"Reward and Guidance through Rubrics: Promoting Exploration to Improve Multi-Domain Reasoning","ko":"лЈЁлёҢлҰӯмқ„ нҶөн•ң ліҙмғҒкіј к°ҖмқҙлҚҳмҠӨ: лӢӨмӨ‘ лҸ„л©”мқё м¶”лЎ  н–ҘмғҒмқ„ мң„н•ң нғҗмғү мҙүм§„","authors":"Baolong Bi, Shenghua Liu, Yiwei Wang, Siqian Tong, Lingrui Mei, Yuyao Ge, Yilong Xu, Jiafeng Guo, Xueqi Cheng","pos":"#3911","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=AfqsNFzJcs","abs":"Recent advances in reinforcement learning (RL) have significantly improved the complex reasoning capabilities of large language models (LLMs). Despite these successes, existing methods mainly focus on single-domain RL (e.g., mathematics) with verifiable rewards (RLVR), and their reliance on purely online RL frameworks restricts the exploration space, thereby limiting reasoning performance. In this paper, we address these limitations by leveraging rubrics to provide both fine-grained reward signals and offline guidance. We propose $\\textbf{RGR-GRPO}$ (Reward and Guidance through Rubrics), a rubric-driven RL framework for multi-domain reasoning.  RGR-GRPO enables LLMs to receive dense and informative rewards while exploring a larger solution space during GRPO training. Extensive experiments across 14 benchmarks spanning multiple domains demonstrate that RGR-GRPO consistently outperforms RL methods that rely solely on alternative reward schemes or offline guidance. Compared with verifiable online RL baseline, RGR-GRPO achieves average improvements of +7.0%, +5.4%, +8.4%, and +6.6% on mathematics, physics, chemistry, and general reasoning tasks, respectively. Notably, RGR-GRPO maintains stable entropy fluctuations during off-policy training and achieves superior pass@k performance, reflecting sustained exploration and effective breakthrough beyond existing performance bottlenecks.","absKo":"мөңк·ј reinforcement learning (RL)мқҳ л°ңм „мқҖ large language models (LLMs)мқҳ ліөмһЎн•ң м¶”лЎ  лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңмј°лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м„ұкіјм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң ліҙмғҒмқ„ к°–лҠ” лӢЁмқј лҸ„л©”мқё RL(мҳҲ: мҲҳн•ҷ)мқё RLVRм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҙ мҷ”мңјл©°, мҲңмҲҳн•ң online RL frameworkм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙмқҖ нғҗмғү кіөк°„мқ„ м ңн•ңн•ҳм—¬ м¶”лЎ  м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м ңм•Ҫн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” rubricмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м„ёл°Җн•ң reward signalкіј offline guidanceлҘј лӘЁл‘җ м ңкіөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨмӨ‘ лҸ„л©”мқё м¶”лЎ мқ„ мң„н•ң rubric-driven RL frameworkмқё $\\textbf{RGR-GRPO}$ (Reward and Guidance through Rubrics)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. RGR-GRPOлҠ” LLMмқҙ GRPO training лҸҷм•Ҳ лҚ” л„“мқҖ solution spaceлҘј нғҗмғүн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, л°ҖлҸ„ лҶ’кі  м •ліҙм„ұ мһҲлҠ” rewardлҘј л°ӣмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ лҸ„л©”мқём—җ кұём№ң 14к°ң benchmarkм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ RGR-GRPOк°Җ лҢҖмІҙ reward schemeмқҙлӮҳ offline guidanceм—җл§Ң мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” RL л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң online RL baselineкіј л№„көҗн–Ҳмқ„ л•Ң, RGR-GRPOлҠ” мҲҳн•ҷ, л¬јлҰ¬, нҷ”н•ҷ, мқјл°ҳ м¶”лЎ  taskм—җм„ң к°Ғк°Ғ нҸүк·  +7.0%, +5.4%, +8.4%, +6.6%мқҳ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ RGR-GRPOлҠ” off-policy training лҸҷм•Ҳ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё entropy fluctuationмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳкі , мҡ°мҲҳн•ң pass@k м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, кё°мЎҙ м„ұлҠҘ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё нғҗмғүкіј нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё лҸҢнҢҢлҘј ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"60778","en":"Impact of Connectivity on Laplacian Representations in Reinforcement Learning","ko":"Reinforcement Learningм—җм„ң м—°кІ°м„ұмқҙ Laplacian Representationм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–Ҙ","authors":"Tommaso Giorgi, Pierriccardo Olivieri, Keyue Jiang, Laura Toni, Matteo Papini","pos":"#4502","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=wnfPEhGqic","abs":"<p>Learning state representations in Markov Decision Processes (MDPs) has proven crucial for addressing the curse of dimensionality in large-scale reinforcement learning (RL) problems. A widely recognized approach exploits structural priors on the MDP by constructing state representations as linear combinations of the state-graph Laplacian eigenvectors. When there is no prior knowledge of the graph, or the state space is too large, the spectral features can be estimated in a model-free fashion. In this work, we prove an upper bound on the approximation error of linear value function approximation based on learned spectral features. We show how this error scales with the algebraic connectivity of the state-graph, making it interpretable in terms of the MDP topology. We also bound the error arising from the estimation of the spectral features themselves, providing an all-round view of the representation learning pipeline.  Additionally, we provide a new expression of the Laplacian operator in the RL setting that clarifies some subtle ambiguities in the literature. Our results apply to general (non-uniform) policies without making any assumptions on the symmetry of the induced transition kernel. We validate our theoretical findings with numerical simulations on gridworld environments.</p>","absKo":"<p>Markov Decision Processes (MDPs)м—җм„ң state representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ reinforcement learning(RL) л¬ём ңм—җм„ң м°Ёмӣҗмқҳ м ҖмЈјлҘј лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” лҚ° н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё кІғмңјлЎң мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. л„җлҰ¬ м•Ңл Өм§„ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ state-graph Laplacianмқҳ eigenvectorл“Өмқҳ м„ нҳ• кІ°н•©мңјлЎң state representationмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ MDPм—җ лҢҖн•ң кө¬мЎ°м Ғ priorлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. graphм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӮ¬м „ м§ҖмӢқмқҙ м—Ҷкұ°лӮҳ state spaceк°Җ л„Ҳл¬ҙ нҒ° кІҪмҡ°, spectral featureлҠ” model-free л°©мӢқмңјлЎң м¶”м •н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” н•ҷмҠөлҗң spectral featureм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң linear value function approximationмқҳ approximation errorм—җ лҢҖн•ң upper boundлҘј мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мқҙ errorк°Җ state-graphмқҳ algebraic connectivityм—җ л”°лқј м–ҙл–»кІҢ мҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ MDP topology кҙҖм җм—җм„ң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. лҚ”л¶Ҳм–ҙ spectral feature мһҗмІҙмқҳ estimationм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” errorлҸ„ boundн•ҳм—¬, representation learning pipeline м „мІҙлҘј м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” кҙҖм җмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. м¶”к°ҖлЎң, RL м„Өм •м—җм„ң Laplacian operatorмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ н‘ңнҳ„мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬ л¬ён—Ңм—җм„ңмқҳ лӘҮ к°Җм§Җ лҜёл¬ҳн•ң лӘЁнҳём„ұмқ„ лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мң лҸ„лҗң transition kernelмқҳ лҢҖм№ӯм„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң м–ҙл– н•ң к°Җм •лҸ„ л‘җм§Җ м•Ҡкі , мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё(non-uniform) policyм—җ м Ғмҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” gridworld environmentм—җм„ңмқҳ мҲҳм№ҳ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳмңјлЎң мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62516","en":"Squeezing More from the Stream : Learning Representation Online for Streaming Reinforcement Learning","ko":"мҠӨнҠёлҰјм—җм„ң лҚ” л§Һмқҙ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкё°: к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң мҳЁлқјмқё н‘ңнҳ„ н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Nilaksh, Antoine Clavaud, Mathieu Reymond, Francois Rivest, Sarath Chandar","pos":"#4602","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=fuBIaxqMAG","abs":"<p>In streaming Reinforcement Learning (RL), transitions are observed and discarded immediately after a single update. While this minimizes resource usage for on-device applications, it makes agents notoriously sample-inefficient, since value-based losses alone struggle to extract meaningful representations from transient data. We propose extending Self-Predictive Representations (SPR) to the streaming pipeline to maximize the utility of every observed frame. However, due to the highly correlated samples induced by the streaming regime, naively applying this auxiliary loss results in training instabilities. Thus, we introduce orthogonal gradient updates relative to the momentum target and resolve gradient conflicts arising from streaming-specific optimizers. Validated across the Atari, MinAtar, and Octax suites, our approach systematically outperforms existing streaming baselines. Latent-space analysis, including t-SNE visualizations and effective-rank measurements, confirms that our method learns significantly richer representations, bridging the performance gap caused by the absence of a replay buffer, while remaining efficient enough to train on just a few CPU cores.</p>","absKo":"<p>streaming Reinforcement Learning(RL)м—җм„ңлҠ” transitionмқҙ кҙҖмёЎлҗң м§Ғнӣ„ н•ң лІҲмқҳ update нӣ„ мҰүмӢң нҸҗкё°лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” on-device applicationм—җм„ң resource usageлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, value-based lossл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” мқјмӢңм Ғмқё лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җм„ң мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” representationмқ„ м¶”м¶ңн•ҳкё° м–ҙл ӨмӣҢ agentмқҳ sample efficiencyлҘј нҳ„м ҖнһҲ лӮ®м¶ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кҙҖмёЎлҗң лӘЁл“  frameмқҳ нҷңмҡ©лҸ„лҘј к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ Self-Predictive Representations(SPR)лҘј streaming pipelineмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•  кІғмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ streaming regimeмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ мғҒкҙҖ мғҳн”Ң л•Ңл¬ём—җ, мқҙ auxiliary lossлҘј лӢЁмҲң м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ training instabilityк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” momentum targetм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ orthogonal gradient updateлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , streaming-specific optimizerм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” gradient conflictлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. Atari, MinAtar, Octax suite м „л°ҳм—җм„ң кІҖмҰқн•ң кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ кё°мЎҙ streaming baselineмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. t-SNE visualizationкіј effective-rank measurementлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң latent-space л¶„м„қмқҖ, ліё л°©лІ•мқҙ replay buffer л¶Җмһ¬лЎң мқён•ң м„ұлҠҘ кІ©м°ЁлҘј л©”мҡ°л©ҙм„ңлҸ„, лӢЁ лӘҮ к°ңмқҳ CPU coreл§ҢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„ м •лҸ„лЎң нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң нӣЁм”¬ н’Қл¶Җн•ң representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ҙ мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61425","en":"SVL: Goal-Conditioned Reinforcement Learning as Survival Learning","ko":"SVL: Survival LearningмңјлЎңм„ңмқҳ Goal-Conditioned Reinforcement Learning","authors":"Franki Nguimatsia-Tiofack, Fabian Schramm, ThГ©otime Le Hellard, Justin Carpentier","pos":"#306","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=qIOcJSCGn2","abs":"<p>Standard approaches to goal-conditioned reinforcement learning (GCRL) that rely on temporal-difference learning can be unstable and sample-inefficient due to bootstrapping. While recent work has explored contrastive and supervised formulations to improve stability, we present a probabilistic alternative, called survival value learning (SVL), that reframes GCRL as a survival learning problem by modeling the timeвҖ‘toвҖ‘goal from each state as a probability distribution. This perspective yields a closedвҖ‘form identity that expresses the goalвҖ‘conditioned value function as a discounted sum of survival probabilities, enabling value estimation via a hazard model trained via maximum likelihood on both event and rightвҖ‘censored trajectories. We introduce three practical value estimators, including finite-horizon truncation and two binned infinite-horizon approximations to capture long-horizon objectives. Experiments on standard offline GCRL benchmarks show that SVL combined with hierarchical actors matches or surpasses strong hierarchical TD baselines, particularly excelling on complex, longвҖ‘horizon tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>temporal-difference learningм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” goal-conditioned reinforcement learning(GCRL)мқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ bootstrapping л•Ңл¬ём—җ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҳкі  sample-inefficientн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ contrastive л°Ҹ supervised formulationмқ„ нғҗкө¬н•ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” survival value learning(SVL)мқҙлқјлҠ” нҷ•лҘ м Ғ лҢҖм•Ҳмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. SVLмқҖ к°Ғ мғҒнғңм—җм„ң goalк№Ңм§Җмқҳ лҸ„лӢ¬ мӢңк°„мқ„ нҷ•лҘ л¶„нҸ¬лЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ GCRLмқ„ survival learning л¬ём ңлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм җмқҖ goal-conditioned value functionмқ„ discounted survival probabilityмқҳ н•©мңјлЎң н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳлҠ” лӢ«нһҢ нҳ•нғңмқҳ н•ӯл“ұмӢқмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, event trajectoryмҷҖ right-censored trajectory лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ maximum likelihoodлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң hazard modelмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ value estimationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” finite-horizon truncationкіј мһҘкё° лӘ©н‘ңлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ binned infinite-horizon approximationмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м„ё к°Җм§Җ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ value estimatorлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ offline GCRL лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬м—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ hierarchical actorмҷҖ кІ°н•©н•ң SVLмқҙ к°•л Ҙн•ң hierarchical TD baselineкіј лҢҖл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, нҠ№нһҲ ліөмһЎн•ҳкі  мһҘкё°м Ғмқё кіјм ңм—җм„ң л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63397","en":"Cardinality-Invariant Neural Operator Policies for Scalable PDE Control","ko":"нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң PDE м ңм–ҙлҘј мң„н•ң кё°мҲҳ л¶ҲліҖ мӢ кІҪ м—°мӮ°мһҗ м •мұ…","authors":"Pietro Zanotta, Dibakar Sarkar, Honghui Zheng, Somdatta Goswami, Jan Drgona","pos":"#214","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XWYU5FTRxM","abs":"<p>Controlling partial differential equations (PDEs) with learning-based policies remains fundamentally limited by fixed-dimensional representations: policies trained for a specific sensor, actuator, or agent configuration typically fail when the configuration changes. This limitation is particularly severe in multi-agent PDE control, where policies do not scale across population sizes without retraining. We address this challenge by reformulating PDE control as an operator learning problem that maps state fields to continuous control functions and trains them end-to-end through differentiable PDE solvers, yielding policies that naturally adapt to varying sensor and actuator configurations. Remarkably, policies trained on small swarms exhibit cardinality invariance, allowing for zero-shot transfer to significantly larger populations as well as robustness to partial agent failure. This scalability arises from agents sharing a common policy and coordinating through their physical environment, which produces an emergent self-normalization effect. To explain this phenomenon, we provide a theorem grounded in mean-field theory demonstrating that policy gradients computed from finite-agent systems converge to those of a continuous control limit. Empirically, we validate the framework on tracking, stabilization, and density transport across linear, nonlinear, chaotic, and turbulent PDEs.</p>","absKo":"<p>learning-based policyлЎң partial differential equation(PDE)мқ„ м ңм–ҙн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң fixed-dimensional representationм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. нҠ№м • sensor, actuator, лҳҗлҠ” agent configurationм—җ л§һм¶”м–ҙ н•ҷмҠөлҗң policyлҠ” configurationмқҙ л°”лҖҢл©ҙ лҢҖк°ң мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н•ңкі„лҠ” multi-agent PDE controlм—җм„ң нҠ№нһҲ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ңлҚ°, policyк°Җ мһ¬н•ҷмҠө м—Ҷмқҙ population size м „л°ҳмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј state fieldлҘј continuous control functionм—җ л§Өн•‘н•ҳлҠ” operator learning problemмңјлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , differentiable PDE solverлҘј нҶөн•ҙ end-to-endлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё sensor л°Ҹ actuator configurationм—җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” policyлҘј м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. лҶҖлһҚкІҢлҸ„ мһ‘мқҖ swarmм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөн•ң policyлҠ” cardinality invarianceлҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” нҒ° populationмңјлЎң zero-shot transferк°Җ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкі  мқјл¶Җ agent failureм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ robustн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң scalabilityлҠ” agentл“Өмқҙ кіөнҶө policyлҘј кіөмң н•ҳкі  л¬јлҰ¬м Ғ нҷҳкІҪмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ нҳ‘л Ҙн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ emergent self-normalization effectк°Җ мғқкё°кё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ лӮҳнғҖлӮңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҳ„мғҒмқ„ м„ӨлӘ…н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” mean-field theoryм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң м •лҰ¬лҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬ finite-agent systemм—җм„ң кі„мӮ°лҗң policy gradientк°Җ continuous control limitмқҳ gradientлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” linear, nonlinear, chaotic, turbulent PDE м „л°ҳм—җм„ң tracking, stabilization, density transportм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61591","en":"When does predictive inverse dynamics outperform behavior cloning?","ko":"Predictive Inverse DynamicsлҠ” м–ём ң Behavior Cloningмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳлҠ”к°Җ?","authors":"Lukas SchГӨfer, Pallavi Choudhury, Abdelhak Lemkhenter, Chris Lovett, Somjit Nath, Luis FranГ§a, Matheus Mendonca, Alex Lamb, Riashat Islam, Siddhartha Sen, John Langford, Katja Hofmann, Sergio Valcarcel Macua","pos":"#304","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ocLKXXgvp3","abs":"<p>Behavior cloning (BC) is a practical offline imitation learning method, but it often fails when expert demonstrations are limited. Recent works have introduced a class of architectures named predictive inverse dynamics models (PIDM) that combine a future state predictor with an inverse dynamics model (IDM). While PIDM often outperforms BC, the reasons behind its benefits remain unclear. In this paper, we provide a theoretical explanation: PIDM introduces a bias-variance tradeoff. While predicting the future state introduces bias, conditioning the IDM on the prediction can significantly reduce variance. We establish conditions on the state predictor bias for PIDM to achieve lower prediction error and higher sample efficiency than BC, with the gap widening when additional data sources are available. We validate the theoretical insights empirically in 2D navigation tasks, where BC requires up to five times (three times on average) more demonstrations than PIDM to reach comparable performance; and in a complex 3D environment in a modern video game with high-dimensional visual inputs and stochastic transitions, where BC requires over 66\\% more samples than PIDM.</p>","absKo":"<p>Behavior cloning (BC)мқҖ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё offline imitation learning л°©лІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, expert demonstrationмқҙ м ңн•ңм Ғмқј л•Ң мў…мў… мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ лҜёлһҳ мғҒнғң мҳҲмёЎкё°мҷҖ inverse dynamics model (IDM)мқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң predictive inverse dynamics model (PIDM)мқҙлқјлҠ” кө¬мЎ°лҘј м ңм•Ҳн–ҲлӢӨ. PIDMмқҖ мў…мў… BCліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, к·ё мқҙм җмқҳ мқҙмң лҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ лӘ…нҷ•н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙ нҳ„мғҒм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ м„ӨлӘ…мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. PIDMмқҖ bias-variance tradeoffлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҜёлһҳ мғҒнғңлҘј мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ biasлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё мҳҲмёЎк°’мқ„ мЎ°кұҙмңјлЎң IDMмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©ҙ varianceлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PIDMмқҙ BCліҙлӢӨ лҚ” лӮ®мқҖ prediction errorмҷҖ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ sample efficiencyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң state predictor bias мЎ°кұҙмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, м¶”к°Җ лҚ°мқҙн„° sourceк°Җ мһҲмқ„ л•Ң к·ё м°Ёмқҙк°Җ лҚ” м»Өм§җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ нҶөм°°мқҖ 2D navigation taskм—җм„ң мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқлҗҳм—ҲлҠ”лҚ°, BCлҠ” л№„мҠ·н•ң м„ұлҠҘм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ PIDMліҙлӢӨ мөңлҢҖ 5л°°(нҸүк·  3л°°) лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ demonstrationмқҙ н•„мҡ”н–ҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң кі м°Ёмӣҗ visual inputкіј stochastic transitionмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” нҳ„лҢҖ video gameмқҳ ліөмһЎн•ң 3D environmentм—җм„ңлҸ„ BCлҠ” PIDMліҙлӢӨ 66\\% мқҙмғҒ лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ sampleмқҙ н•„мҡ”н–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61532","en":"Towards Efficient and Expressive Offline RL via Flow-Anchored Noise-conditioned Q-Learning","ko":"Flow-Anchored Noise-conditioned Q-Learningмқ„ нҶөн•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мһҲлҠ” Offline RLмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Sungyoung Lee, Dohyeong Kim, Eshan Balachandar, Zelal Mustafaoglu, Keshav Pingali","pos":"#305","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pBBygHUKOu","abs":"<p>We propose Flow-Anchored Noise-conditioned Q-Learning (FAN), a highly efficient and high-performing offline reinforcement learning (RL) algorithm. Recent work has shown that expressive flow policies and distributional critics improve offline RL performance, but at a high computational cost. Specifically, flow policies require iterative sampling to produce a single action, and distributional critics require computation over multiple samples (e.g., quantiles) to estimate value. To address these inefficiencies while maintaining high performance, we introduce FAN. Our method employs a behavior regularization technique that utilizes only a single flow policy iteration and requires only a single Gaussian noise sample for distributional critics. Our theoretical analysis of convergence and performance bounds demonstrates that these simplifications not only improve efficiency but also lead to superior task performance. Experiments on robotic manipulation and locomotion tasks demonstrate that FAN achieves state-of-the-art performance while significantly reducing both training and inference runtimes. We release our code at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/FAN.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Flow-Anchored Noise-conditioned Q-Learning (FAN)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” л§Өмҡ° нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ лӣ°м–ҙлӮң offline reinforcement learning (RL) м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқҙ н’Қл¶Җн•ң flow policyмҷҖ distributional criticмқҙ offline RL м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, к·ё лҢҖк°ҖлЎң лҶ’мқҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ л”°лҘёлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, flow policyлҠ” н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ actionмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ л°ҳліөм Ғмқё samplingмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳкі , distributional criticмқҖ valueлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м—¬лҹ¬ sample(мҳҲ: quantile)м—җ лҢҖн•ң кі„мӮ°мқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л№„нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҶ’мқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FANмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ лӢЁ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ flow policy iterationл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі , distributional criticм—җлҠ” лӢЁмқј Gaussian noise sampleл§Ң н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳлҠ” behavior regularization кё°лІ•мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳл ҙм„ұкіј performance boundм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӢЁмҲңнҷ”к°Җ нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқј лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј task м„ұлҠҘк№Ңм§Җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лЎңлҙҮ мЎ°мһ‘ л°Ҹ locomotion taskм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FANмқҙ training л°Ҹ inference runtimeмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/FAN м—җм„ң кіөк°ңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63368","en":"SPAR: Support-Preserving Action Rectification","ko":"SPAR: м„ңнҸ¬нҠё ліҙмЎҙ н–үлҸҷ көҗм •","authors":"Jiaxin Zhao, Weihang Pan, xun liang, Binbin Lin","pos":"#307","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XiaqvkSnWk","abs":"<p>Offline policy improvement faces an inherent conflict between maximizing value and fitting the data distribution. While in-sample weighted regression is stable, it suffers from over-conservatism that suppresses high-value actions in the distribution tail; conversely, gradient-based approaches often exhibit a fitting-optimization conflict of gradients, which drive the policy off the data manifold. To address this, we propose Support-Preserving Action Rectification (SPAR), which reframes global learning as a local residual rectification anchored to a frozen pure behavior cloning policy. This framework performs fine-grained fitting and local policy improvement in the residual space, thereby contracting the search space. We further introduce Latent Self-Imitation, utilizing a latent-sampling weighted-regression mechanism to address fitting-improvement gradient conflict in the residual space. Theoretically, we prove this mechanism eliminates the manifold-normal drift of standard value gradients, while extensive D4RL experiments show SPAR extracts significant gains from suboptimal baselines to achieve state-of-the-art performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Offline policy improvementлҠ” valueлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғкіј data distributionм—җ л§һм¶”лҠ” кІғ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё м¶©лҸҢм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. in-sample weighted regressionмқҖ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, л¶„нҸ¬мқҳ кј¬лҰ¬ мҳҒм—ӯм—җ мһҲлҠ” high-value actionмқ„ м–өм ңн•ҳлҠ” кіјлҸ„н•ң ліҙмҲҳм„ұ л¬ём ңлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. л°ҳлҢҖлЎң gradient-based approachлҠ” мў…мў… fitting-optimization conflictлҘј ліҙмқҙлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙ gradientк°Җ policyлҘј data manifold л°–мңјлЎң л°Җм–ҙлӮёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Support-Preserving Action Rectification(SPAR)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SPARлҠ” global learningмқ„ frozen pure behavior cloning policyм—җ кі м •лҗң local residual rectificationмңјлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkлҠ” residual spaceм—җм„ң м„ёл°Җн•ң fittingкіј local policy improvementлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ search spaceлҘј м¶•мҶҢн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Latent Self-Imitationмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, residual spaceм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” fitting-improvement gradient conflictлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң latent-sampling weighted-regression mechanismмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҙ standard value gradientмқҳ manifold-normal driftлҘј м ңкұ°н•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳкі , кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң D4RL мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ SPARк°Җ suboptimal baselineм—җм„ң мң мқҳлҜён•ң м„ұлҠҘ н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лҒҢм–ҙлӮҙм–ҙ state-of-the-art performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64368","en":"SMAC: Score-Matched Actor-Critics for Robust Offline-to-Online Transfer","ko":"SMAC: к°•кұҙн•ң мҳӨн”„лқјмқё-нҲ¬-мҳЁлқјмқё м „мқҙлҘј мң„н•ң м җмҲҳ л§Өм№ӯ Actor-Critic","authors":"Nathan S. de Lara, Florian Shkurti","pos":"#308","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OJSCaDIIJK","abs":"<p>Modern offline Reinforcement Learning (RL) methods find performant actor-critics, however, fine-tuning these actor-critics online with value-based RL algorithms typically causes immediate drops in performance. We provide evidence consistent with the hypothesis that, in the loss landscape, offline maxima for prior algorithms and online maxima are separated by low-performance valleys that gradient-based fine-tuning traverses. Following this, we present Score Matched Actor-Critic (SMAC), an offline RL method designed to learn actorвҖ“critics that transition to online value-based RL algorithms with no drop in performance. SMAC avoids valleys between offline and online maxima by regularizing the Q-function during the offline phase to respect a first-order derivative equality between the score of the policy and action-gradient of the Q-function. We experimentally demonstrate that SMAC converges to offline maxima that are connected to better online maxima via paths with monotonically increasing reward found by first-order optimization. SMAC achieves smooth transfer to Soft Actor-Critic and TD3 in 6/6 D4RL tasks. In 4/6 environments, it reduces regret by 34-58% over the best baseline.</p>","absKo":"<p>нҳ„лҢҖмқҳ offline Reinforcement Learning (RL) methodлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқҙ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң actor-criticмқ„ м°ҫм•„лӮҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң actor-criticмқ„ value-based RL algorithmмңјлЎң online fine-tuningн•ҳл©ҙ ліҙнҶө м„ұлҠҘмқҙ мҰүмӢң м Җн•ҳлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” loss landscapeм—җм„ң мқҙм „ algorithmмқҳ offline maximumкіј online maximum мӮ¬мқҙм—җ, gradient-based fine-tuningмқҙ нҶөкіјн•ҳкІҢ лҗҳлҠ” low-performance valleyк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨлҠ” к°Җм„Өкіј мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” мҰқкұ°лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм—җ л”°лқј, м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳ м—Ҷмқҙ online value-based RL algorithmмңјлЎң м „нҷҳлҗҳлҠ” actor-criticмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң offline RL methodмқё Score Matched Actor-Critic (SMAC)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SMACлҠ” offline phase лҸҷм•Ҳ Q-functionмқ„ м •к·ңнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, policyмқҳ scoreмҷҖ Q-functionмқҳ action-gradient мӮ¬мқҙм—җ first-order derivative equalityлҘј л§ҢмЎұмӢңнӮӨлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң offlineкіј online maximum мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ valleyлҘј нҡҢн”јн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SMACк°Җ first-order optimizationмңјлЎң л°ңкІ¬лҗң rewardк°Җ лӢЁмЎ° мҰқк°Җн•ҳлҠ” pathлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ online maximumкіј м—°кІ°лҗң offline maximumмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. SMACлҠ” 6/6 D4RL taskм—җм„ң Soft Actor-Criticкіј TD3лЎңмқҳ л¶Җл“ңлҹ¬мҡҙ transferлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. 4/6 нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” мөңм„ мқҳ baseline лҢҖл№„ regretлҘј 34-58% мӨ„мқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61480","en":"Reward Shaping Control Variates for Off-Policy Evaluation Under Sparse Rewards","ko":"Sparse Rewards н•ҳ Off-Policy Evaluationмқ„ мң„н•ң Reward Shaping Control Variates","authors":"Ritam Majumdar, Finale Doshi-Velez, Sonali Parbhoo","pos":"#309","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=potpaozpjv","abs":"<p>Off-policy evaluation (OPE) is essential for deploying reinforcement learning in safety-critical settings, yet existing estimators such as importance sampling and doubly robust (DR) often exhibit prohibitively high variance when rewards are sparse. In this work, we introduce Reward-Shaping Control Variates, a new family of unbiased estimators that leverage potential-based reward shaping to construct additional zero-mean control variates. We prove that shaped estimators always yields valid variance reduction, and that combining shaping-based and Q-based control variates strictly expands the variance-reduction subspace beyond DR and its minimax variant MRDR. Empirically, we provide a systematic regime map across synthetic chains, a cancer simulator, 5 single-stock and 1 multi-stock DOW-30 trading environments and an ICU-sepsis benchmark showing that shaping-based OPE consistently outperforms DR in sparse-reward settings, while a hybrid estimator achieves state-of-the-art performance across sparse, noisy, and misspecified environments. Our results highlight reward shaping as a powerful and interpretable tool for robust OPE, offering both theoretical guarantees and practical improvements in domains where standard estimators fail.</p>","absKo":"<p>Off-policy evaluation (OPE)лҠ” safety-critical settingм—җ reinforcement learningмқ„ л°°нҸ¬н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, importance samplingкіј doubly robust (DR) к°ҷмқҖ кё°мЎҙ estimatorлҠ” rewardк°Җ sparseн•  л•Ң м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ нҒ° varianceлҘј ліҙмқҙлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” potential-based reward shapingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ м¶”к°Җм Ғмқё zero-mean control variateлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ unbiased estimator кі„м—ҙмқё Reward-Shaping Control VariatesлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” shaped estimatorк°Җ н•ӯмғҒ мң нҡЁн•ң variance reductionмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳкі , shaping-based control variateмҷҖ Q-based control variateлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳл©ҙ variance-reduction subspaceк°Җ DR л°Ҹ к·ё minimax variantмқё MRDRліҙлӢӨ м—„кІ©н•ҳкІҢ нҷ•мһҘлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” synthetic chain, cancer simulator, 5к°ңмқҳ single-stock л°Ҹ 1к°ңмқҳ multi-stock DOW-30 trading environment, к·ёлҰ¬кі  ICU-sepsis benchmark м „л°ҳм—җ кұём№ң мІҙкі„м Ғмқё regime mapмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬, shaping-based OPEк°Җ sparse-reward settingм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ DRмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң hybrid estimatorлҠ” sparse, noisy, misspecified environment м „л°ҳм—җм„ң state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” reward shapingмқҙ robust OPEлҘј мң„н•ң к°•л Ҙн•ҳкі  н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң лҸ„кө¬мқҙл©°, н‘ңмӨҖ estimatorк°Җ мӢӨнҢЁн•ҳлҠ” мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘкіј мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ к°ңм„ мқ„ лӘЁл‘җ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60945","en":"Regularized Offline Policy Optimization with Posterior Hybrid Bayesian Belief","ko":"Posterior Hybrid Bayesian BeliefлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң Regularized Offline Policy Optimization","authors":"Hongqiang Lin, Pengfei Wang, Nenggan Zheng","pos":"#310","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=v8BF1g3u8r","abs":"<p>Offline reinforcement learning (RL) aims to optimize policies from pre-collected datasets. A bottleneck of this paradigm is managing epistemic uncertainty, which arises from limited data coverage (sample-level) and the ambiguity in identifying transition dynamics from finite data (model-level). To provide a unified quantification of these uncertainties, Bayesian RL has been proposed by treating the dynamics model as a random variable and maintaining a corresponding belief. Despite its theoretical appeal, policy optimization in Bayesian RL remains computationally challenging as it requires solving composite objectives with expectations. Prior methods either employ search-based techniques with poor computational scalability or impose restrictive posterior assumptions that sacrifice the adaptability of Bayesian RL. To address these limitations, we propose Posterior Hybrid Bayesian Belief (PhyB), which reformulates the expectation as a convex combination over a subset of dynamics models. Theoretical analysis demonstrates that the objective discrepancy induced by this approximation remains bounded. Based on PhyB, we develop an iterative regularized policy optimization algorithm that provides metric-agnostic guarantees for monotonic improvement until convergence. Empirical results demonstrate that PhyB achieves state-of-the-art performance on various benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"<p>Offline reinforcement learning (RL)мқҖ мӮ¬м „м—җ мҲҳм§‘лҗң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° policyлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқҳ лі‘лӘ©мқҖ epistemic uncertaintyлҘј лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” мқјмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” м ңн•ңлҗң лҚ°мқҙн„° м»ӨлІ„лҰ¬м§Җ(sample-level)мҷҖ мң н•ңн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎңл¶Җн„° transition dynamicsлҘј мӢқлі„н•  л•Ңмқҳ лӘЁнҳём„ұ(model-level)м—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқ„ нҶөн•©м ҒмңјлЎң м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ Bayesian RLмқҙ м ңм•Ҳлҗҳм—ҲлҠ”лҚ°, dynamics modelмқ„ random variableлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳкі  мқҙм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” beliefлҘј мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” л§Өл Ҙм Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң, Bayesian RLм—җм„ңмқҳ policy optimizationмқҖ кё°лҢҖк°’мқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” ліөн•© objectiveлҘј н’Җм–ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң кі„мӮ°м ҒмңјлЎң м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ кі„мӮ° нҷ•мһҘм„ұмқҙ лӮ®мқҖ search-based techniqueлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, Bayesian RLмқҳ м Ғмқ‘м„ұмқ„ нқ¬мғқн•ҳлҠ” м ңм•Ҫм Ғмқё posterior к°Җм •мқ„ л‘”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Posterior Hybrid Bayesian Belief (PhyB)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” expectationмқ„ dynamics modelл“Өмқҳ л¶Җл¶„м§‘н•©м—җ лҢҖн•ң convex combinationмңјлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙ к·јмӮ¬лЎң мқён•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗҳлҠ” objective discrepancyк°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ boundedмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. PhyBлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” convergenceк№Ңм§Җ monotonic improvementм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ metric-agnostic guaranteeлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” iterative regularized policy optimization algorithmмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” PhyBк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң benchmarkм—җм„ң state-of-the-art performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"68835","en":"Preserving Expert-Level Privacy in Offline Reinforcement Learning","ko":"Offline к°•нҷ”н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң м „л¬ёк°Җ мҲҳмӨҖ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң ліҙмЎҙ","authors":"Navodita Sharma, Vishnu Vinod, Abhradeep Guha Thakurta, Alekh Agarwal, Borja de Balle Pigem, Christoph Dann, Aravindan Raghuveer","pos":"#3106","abs":"<p>The offline reinforcement learning (RL) problem aims to learn an optimal policy from historical data collected by one or more behavioural policies (experts) by interacting with an environment. However, the individual experts may be privacy-sensitive in that the learnt policy may retain information about their precise choices. In some domains like personalized retrieval, advertising and healthcare, the expert choices are considered sensitive data.  To provably protect the privacy of such experts, we propose a novel consensus-based expert-level differentially private offline RL training approach compatible with any existing offline RL algorithm. We prove rigorous differential privacy guarantees, while maintaining strong empirical performance. Unlike existing work in differentially private RL, we supplement the theory with proof-of-concept experiments on classic RL environments featuring large continuous state spaces, demonstrating substantial improvements over a natural baseline across multiple tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>offline reinforcement learning(RL) л¬ём ңлҠ” нҷҳкІҪкіј мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ н•ҳлӮҳ мқҙмғҒмқҳ behavioral policy(expert)к°Җ мҲҳм§‘н•ң кіјкұ° лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎңл¶Җн„° мөңм Ғ policyлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к°ңлі„ expertлҠ” н•ҷмҠөлҗң policyк°Җ к·ёл“Өмқҳ м •нҷ•н•ң м„ нғқм—җ лҢҖн•ң м •ліҙлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җм—җм„ң privacy-sensitiveн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. personalized retrieval, advertising, healthcareмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ мқјл¶Җ лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ңлҠ” expertмқҳ м„ нғқмқҙ лҜјк°җн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎң к°„мЈјлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң expertмқҳ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢңлҘј мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ ліҙнҳён•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙмқҳ м–ҙл–Ө offline RL algorithmкіјлҸ„ нҳёнҷҳлҗҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ consensus-based expert-level differentially private offline RL training approachлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°•н•ң empirical performanceлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ м—„кІ©н•ң differential privacy ліҙмһҘмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ differentially private RL м—°кө¬мҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлЎ мқ„ large continuous state spaceлҘј к°–лҠ” classic RL environmentм—җм„ңмқҳ proof-of-concept мӢӨн—ҳмңјлЎң ліҙк°•н•ҳм—¬, м—¬лҹ¬ taskм—җ кұёміҗ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ baselineліҙлӢӨ мғҒлӢ№н•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62421","en":"RAMAC: Multimodal Risk-Aware Offline Reinforcement Learning and the Role of Behavior Regularization","ko":"RAMAC: л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ Risk-Aware Offline Reinforcement Learning л°Ҹ Behavior Regularizationмқҳ м—ӯн• ","authors":"Kai Fukazawa, Kunal Mundada, Iman Soltani","pos":"#311","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=gmAT5E9dCE","abs":"In safety-critical domains where online data collection is infeasible, offline reinforcement learning (RL) is attractive only if policies achieve high returns without catastrophic lower-tail risk. Prior work on risk-averse offline RL achieves safety at the cost of value- or model-based pessimism, and restricted policy classes that limit policy expressiveness, whereas diffusion/flow-based expressive generative policies have largely been used in risk-neutral settings. We introduce **Risk-Aware Multimodal Actor-Critic (RAMAC)**, a simple, modular, model-free framework that couples an expressive generative actor (e.g., diffusion/flow) with a distributional critic and optimizes a composite objective that combines Conditional Value-at-Risk (CVaR) with behavioral cloning (BC), enabling risk-sensitive learning in complex multimodal scenarios. Since out-of-distribution (OOD) actions are a major driver of catastrophic failures in offline RL, we further provide an objective-level analysis showing that controlling behavior divergence via BC suppresses OOD actions and stabilizes CVaR. Instantiating RAMAC with a diffusion actor, we illustrate these insights on a 2-D risky bandit and evaluate on Stochastic-D4RL, observing consistent gains in CVaR$_{0.1}$ while maintaining strong returns.","absKo":"online data collectionмқҙ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ң safety-critical domainм—җм„ң offline reinforcement learning (RL)мқҖ м •мұ…мқҙ catastrophic lower-tail risk м—Ҷмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ returnмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•  л•Ңм—җл§Ң л§Өл Ҙм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ risk-averse offline RL м—°кө¬лҠ” value- лҳҗлҠ” model-based pessimismмқ„ лҢҖк°ҖлЎң safetyлҘј м–»м—Ҳкі , policy н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ” restricted policy classм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҙ мҷ”мңјл©°, diffusion/flow кё°л°ҳмқҳ expressive generative policyлҠ” мЈјлЎң risk-neutral settingм—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” expressive generative actor(мҳҲ: diffusion/flow)мҷҖ distributional criticмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ҳкі , Conditional Value-at-Risk (CVaR)мҷҖ behavioral cloning (BC)мқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң composite objectiveлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳкі  лӘЁл“ҲмӢқмқҙл©° model-free н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё **Risk-Aware Multimodal Actor-Critic (RAMAC)**мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, ліөмһЎн•ң multimodal scenarioм—җм„ң risk-sensitive learningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. Offline RLм—җм„ң OOD(out-of-distribution) actionмқҙ catastrophic failureмқҳ мЈјмҡ” мӣҗмқёмқё л§ҢнҒј, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м¶”к°ҖлЎң objective-level л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм—¬ BCлҘј нҶөн•ҙ behavior divergenceлҘј м ңм–ҙн•ҳл©ҙ OOD actionмқҙ м–өм ңлҗҳкі  CVaRмқҙ м•Ҳм •нҷ”лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. Diffusion actorлЎң RAMACмқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•ҳм—¬ 2-D risky banditм—җм„ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ мӢңм—°н•ҳкі  Stochastic-D4RLм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ң кІ°кіј, к°•н•ң returnмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң CVaR$_{0.1}$м—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ кҙҖм°°н–ҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"61812","en":"Q-SAM: Unlocking Sharpness-Aware Minimization for Generalization in Offline Reinforcement Learning","ko":"Q-SAM: Offline Reinforcement Learningмқҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ”лҘј мң„н•ң Sharpness-Aware Minimization нҷңм„ұнҷ”","authors":"Da Wang, Yi Ma, Ting Guo, Lin Li, Wei Wei, Jiye Liang","pos":"#312","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=milZYiwxSI","abs":"Generalization remains a central challenge in offline reinforcement learning (RL), where policies are trained solely from static datasets and must perform reliably under distribution shift. While most existing offline RL methods focus on reducing training loss using standard optimizers such as Adam, the role of loss landscape geometry $-$ particularly sharpness $-$ has received little attention. Sharpness-Aware Minimization (SAM) has recently shown strong generalization benefits in supervised learning by favoring flatter minima. However, directly applying SAM to offline RL is non-trivial: unlike supervised settings with ground-truth labels, offline RL relies on bootstrapped targets, making sharpness estimation noisy and often destabilizing optimization. In this paper, we revisit offline RL from an optimization perspective and investigate how sharpness-aware optimization can be made effective in this setting. We propose Q bound weighted SAM (Q-SAM), a robust and scalable framework that treats sharpness as a weighted objective and selectively prioritizes samples that are most suitable for sharpness-aware optimization based on Q bounds. By aligning the SAM objective with the characteristics of bootstrapped value estimation, Q-SAM amplifies the benefits of sharpness minimization while preserving training stability. Extensive experiments on standard offline RL benchmarks demonstrate that Q-SAM consistently improves generalization performance across diverse datasets and algorithms. Our results highlight the importance of loss sharpness in offline RL and suggest optimizer design as a promising direction for developing more robust offline RL methods.","absKo":"л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨм„ұмқҖ offline reinforcement learning (RL)мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ лҸ„м „ кіјм ңлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өм •м—җм„ңлҠ” policyк°Җ мҳӨм§Ғ м •м Ғмқё datasetл§ҢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗҳл©°, distribution shift н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ мӢ лў°м„ұ мһҲкІҢ лҸҷмһ‘н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ offline RL л°©лІ•мқҖ Adamкіј к°ҷмқҖ н‘ңмӨҖ optimizerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ training lossлҘј мӨ„мқҙлҠ” лҚ° м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, loss landscapeмқҳ кё°н•ҳ, нҠ№нһҲ sharpnessмқҳ м—ӯн• мқҖ кұ°мқҳ мЈјлӘ©л°ӣм§Җ лӘ»н–ҲлӢӨ. Sharpness-Aware Minimization (SAM)мқҖ supervised learningм—җм„ң лҚ” нҸүнғ„н•ң minimaлҘј м„ нҳён•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ к°•н•ң generalization мқҙм җмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖ л°” мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ SAMмқ„ offline RLм—җ м§Ғм ‘ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ лӢЁмҲңн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. ground-truth labelмқҙ мһҲлҠ” supervised settingкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, offline RLмқҖ bootstrapped targetм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң sharpness м¶”м •мқҙ noisyн•ҳл©° мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” optimization кҙҖм җм—җм„ң offline RLмқ„ мһ¬мЎ°лӘ…н•ҳкі , sharpness-aware optimizationмқ„ мқҙ м„Өм •м—җм„ң нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң л§Ңл“ңлҠ” л°©лІ•мқ„ нғҗкө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Q bound weighted SAM (Q-SAM)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” sharpnessлҘј weighted objectiveлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳкі , Q boundлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң sharpness-aware optimizationм—җ к°ҖмһҘ м Ғн•©н•ң sampleмқ„ м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°м„ мҲңмң„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқҙлӢӨ. SAM objectiveлҘј bootstrapped value estimationмқҳ нҠ№м„ұкіј м •л ¬н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, Q-SAMмқҖ training stabilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң sharpness minimizationмқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ мҰқнҸӯн•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ offline RL benchmarkм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Q-SAMмқҙ лӢӨм–‘н•ң datasetкіј algorithm м „л°ҳм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ generalization м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” offline RLм—җм„ң loss sharpnessмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ҳл©°, лҚ” кІ¬кі н•ң offline RL л°©лІ• к°ңл°ңмқ„ мң„н•ң мң л§қн•ң л°©н–ҘмңјлЎң optimizer м„Өкі„лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61595","en":"Q-Flow: Stable and Expressive Reinforcement Learning with Flow-based Policy","ko":"Q-Flow: Flow-Based PolicyлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ң м•Ҳм •м Ғмқҙкі  н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мһҲлҠ” Reinforcement Learning","authors":"JaeHyeok Doo, Byeongguk Jeon, Seonghyeon Ye, Kimin Lee, Minjoon Seo","pos":"#313","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=oZqOS1N6Ag","abs":"<p>There is growing interest in utilizing flow-based models as decision-making policies in reinforcement learning due to their high expressive capacity. However, effectively leveraging this expressivity for value maximization remains challenging, as naive gradient-based optimization requires backpropagating through numerical solvers and often leads to instability. Existing approaches typically address this issue by restricting the expressive capacity of flow-based policies, resulting in a trade-off between optimization stability and representational flexibility. To resolve this, we introduce <strong>Q-Flow</strong>, a framework that leverages the deterministic nature of flow dynamics to explicitly propagate terminal trajectory value to intermediate latent states along the policy-induced flow. This formulation enables stable policy optimization using intermediate value gradients without unrolling the numerical solver, effectively bridging the gap between stability and expressivity. We evaluate Q-Flow in the offline learning setting on the challenging OGBench suite, where it consistently outperforms state-of-the-art baselines by an average of <strong>10.6</strong> percentage points, while also enabling stable online adaptation within the same framework.</p>","absKo":"<p>reinforcement learningм—җм„ң мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • м •мұ…мңјлЎң flow-based modelмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳл ӨлҠ” кҙҖмӢ¬мқҙ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқ„ value maximizationм—җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. лӢЁмҲңн•ң gradient-based optimizationмқҖ мҲҳм№ҳ мҶ”лІ„лҘј нҶөн•ҙ backpropagationн•ҙм•ј н•ҳл©°, мў…мў… л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ ліҙнҶө flow-based policyмқҳ н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј optimization stabilityмҷҖ representational flexibility мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offк°Җ мғқкёҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” flow dynamicsмқҳ кІ°м •лЎ м Ғ м„ұм§Ҳмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ м •мұ…мқҙ мң лҸ„н•ң flowлҘј л”°лқј мӨ‘к°„ latent stateм—җ terminal trajectory valueлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м „нҢҢн•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬мқё <strong>Q-Flow</strong>лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ formulationмқҖ мҲҳм№ҳ мҶ”лІ„лҘј unrollingн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ intermediate value gradientлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё policy optimizationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬, м•Ҳм •м„ұкіј н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к°„к·№мқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Q-FlowлҘј м–ҙл Өмҡҙ OGBench suiteмқҳ offline learning settingм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн–Ҳмңјл©°, нҸүк·  <strong>10.6</strong> percentage pointsмқҳ н–ҘмғҒмңјлЎң state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, лҸҷмқјн•ң н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ лӮҙм—җм„ң м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё online adaptationлҸ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62695","en":"Policy-Driven World Model Adaptation for Robust Offline Model-based Reinforcement Learning","ko":"к°•кұҙн•ң Offline Model-based Reinforcement Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң м •мұ… мЈјлҸ„ World Model Adaptation","authors":"Jiayu Chen, Le Xu, Aravind Venugopal, Jeff Schneider","pos":"#314","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eB5i7caric","abs":"<p>Offline reinforcement learning (RL) offers a powerful paradigm for data-driven control. Compared to model-free approaches, offline model-based RL (MBRL) explicitly learns a world model from a static dataset and uses it as a surrogate simulator, improving data efficiency and enabling potential generalization beyond the dataset support. However, most existing offline MBRL methods follow a two-stage training procedure: first learning a world model by maximizing the likelihood of the observed transitions, then optimizing a policy to maximize its expected return under the learned model. This objective mismatch results in a world model that is not necessarily optimized for effective policy learning. Moreover, we observe that policies learned via offline MBRL often lack robustness during deployment, and small adversarial noise in the environment can lead to significant performance degradation. To address these, we propose a framework that dynamically adapts the world model alongside the policy under a unified learning objective aimed at improving robustness. At the core of our method is a maximin optimization problem, which we solve by innovatively utilizing Stackelberg learning dynamics. We provide theoretical analysis to support our design and introduce computationally efficient implementations. We benchmark our algorithm on twelve noisy D4RL MuJoCo tasks and three stochastic Tokamak Control tasks, demonstrating its state-of-the-art performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Offline reinforcement learning (RL)мқҖ лҚ°мқҙн„° кё°л°ҳ м ңм–ҙлҘј мң„н•ң к°•л Ҙн•ң нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. model-free м ‘к·јлІ•кіј л№„көҗн•ҳл©ҙ, offline model-based RL (MBRL)мқҖ м •м Ғмқё лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° world modelмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј surrogate simulatorлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лҚ°мқҙн„° нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқҙкі  лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ м§Җмӣҗ лІ”мң„лҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” мқјл°ҳнҷ” к°ҖлҠҘм„ұлҸ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ offline MBRL л°©лІ•мқҖ л‘җ лӢЁкі„ н•ҷмҠө м Ҳм°ЁлҘј л”°лҘёлӢӨ: лЁјм Җ кҙҖмёЎлҗң transitionмқҳ likelihoodлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ world modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , к·ёлӢӨмқҢ н•ҷмҠөлҗң model н•ҳм—җм„ң кё°лҢҖ returnмқ„ мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ policyлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң objective mismatchлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё policy н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ҙ л°ҳл“ңмӢң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗң кІғмқҖ м•„лӢҢ world modelмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” offline MBRLлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң policyк°Җ deployment мӢң robustн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һкі , нҷҳкІҪм—җ мһ‘мқҖ adversarial noiseл§Ң мһҲм–ҙлҸ„ м„ұлҠҘмқҙ нҒ¬кІҢ м Җн•ҳлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” robustness н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© н•ҷмҠө objective м•„лһҳм—җм„ң policyмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ world modelмқ„ лҸҷм ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮӨлҠ” frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ maximin optimization problemмқҙл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Stackelberg learning dynamicsлҘј нҳҒмӢ м ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„Өкі„лҘј л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳлҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳкі  кі„мӮ°м ҒмңјлЎң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё кө¬нҳ„лҸ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” noisy D4RL MuJoCo task 12к°ңмҷҖ stochastic Tokamak Control task 3к°ңм—җм„ң м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ benchmarkн•ҳм—¬, state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61194","en":"Off-Policy Learning in Large Action Spaces: Optimization Matters More Than Estimation","ko":"нҒ° Action Spaceм—җм„ңмқҳ Off-Policy Learning: м¶”м •ліҙлӢӨ мөңм Ғнҷ”к°Җ лҚ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Imad AOUALI, Otmane Sakhi","pos":"#315","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=srIStBTJiu","abs":"<p>Off-policy evaluation (OPE) and off-policy learning (OPL) are foundational for decision-making in offline contextual bandits. Recent advances in OPL primarily optimize OPE estimators with improved statistical properties, assuming that better estimators inherently yield superior policies. Although theoretically justified, this estimator-centric approach neglects a critical practical obstacle: challenging optimization landscapes. In this paper, we provide theoretical insights and empirical evidence showing that current OPL methods encounter severe optimization issues, particularly as the action space grows. We show that estimator-aware policy parametrization can mitigate, but not fully resolve, optimization challenges. Building on this, we explore simpler weighted log-likelihood objectives and demonstrate that they enjoy substantially better optimization properties and still recover competitive, often superior, learned policies. Our findings emphasize the necessity of explicitly addressing optimization considerations in the development of OPL algorithms for large action spaces.</p>","absKo":"<p>off-policy evaluation (OPE)кіј off-policy learning (OPL)мқҖ offline contextual banditм—җм„ң мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м •мқҳ кё°мҙҲк°Җ лҗңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј OPLмқҳ м§„м „мқҖ мЈјлЎң нҶөкі„м Ғ м„ұм§Ҳмқҙ к°ңм„ лҗң OPE estimatorлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”л©°, лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ estimatorк°Җ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң policyлҘј лӮілҠ”лӢӨкі  к°Җм •н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң estimator мӨ‘мӢ¬ м ‘к·јмқҖ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” нғҖлӢ№н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ңм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мһҘм• л¬јмқё м–ҙл Өмҡҙ optimization landscapeлҘј к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ OPL л°©лІ•мқҙ, нҠ№нһҲ action spaceк°Җ м»Өм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң optimization л¬ём ңм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•Ёмқ„ мқҙлЎ м Ғ нҶөм°°кіј мӢӨмҰқм Ғ мҰқкұ°лҘј нҶөн•ҙ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” estimator-aware policy parametrizationмқҙ optimization м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•  мҲҳлҠ” мһҲм§Җл§Ң мҷ„м „нһҲ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳм§ҖлҠ” лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң лҚ” лӢЁмҲңн•ң weighted log-likelihood objectiveлҘј нғҗкө¬н•ҳкі , мқҙ objectiveк°Җ нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ optimization propertyлҘј к°Җм§Җл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲкі  мў…мў… лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң learned policyлҘј м—¬м „нһҲ ліөмӣҗн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” нҒ° action spaceлҘј мң„н•ң OPL algorithmмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•  л•Ң optimization кі л ӨлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң л°ҳмҳҒн•  н•„мҡ”к°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65617","en":"$\\text{DT}^\\text{2}$: Decision-Targeted Digital Twins","ko":"$\\text{DT}^\\text{2}$: мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • н‘ңм Ғ л””м§Җн„ё нҠёмңҲ","authors":"Harry Amad, Mihaela van der Schaar","pos":"#407","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=BoQg93y6iT","abs":"A digital twin (DT) is a virtual model of a real-world system that can assist decision-making by simulating scenarios induced by different policies. However, the typical design process of machine learning-based DTs does not optimise for this objective. We prove that, when model capacity is limited, typical DT training paradigms, which minimise one-step transition errors, can produce suboptimal models for ranking sets of policies. We further show that this holds empirically, even with expressive model classes. To address this, we introduce DT$^2$, a decision-targeted DT training paradigm. DT$^2$ uses off-policy evaluation methods to estimate values of candidate policies on offline data, and encourages the DT to generate rollouts that preserve pairwise policy rankings derived from these proxy ground-truths with an architecture-agnostic loss function. We empirically demonstrate the efficacy of our method across a range of settings and architectures, showing that DT$^2$ consistently improves policy ranking and reduces decision regret relative to conventional DT training, both for policies used during training and for unseen policies, while maintaining a good level of raw simulation fidelity.","absKo":"A digital twin (DT)мқҖ нҳ„мӢӨ м„ёкі„ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҳ virtual modelлЎң, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё policyм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗҳлҠ” scenarioлҘј мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м •мқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ machine learning-based DTмқҳ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м„Өкі„ кіјм •мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӘ©м Ғм—җ л§һкІҢ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” model capacityк°Җ м ңн•ңлҗ  л•Ң, one-step transition errorлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё DT training paradigmмқҙ policy м§‘н•©мқ„ rankingн•ҳлҠ” лҚ°лҠ” suboptimalн•ң modelмқ„ л§Ңл“Ө мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҳ„мғҒмқҙ expressive model classм—җм„ңлҸ„ кІҪн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м„ұлҰҪн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” decision-targeted DT training paradigmмқё DT$^2$лҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. DT$^2$лҠ” off-policy evaluation л°©лІ•мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ offline dataм—җм„ң нӣ„ліҙ policyмқҳ valueлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳкі , architecture-agnostic loss functionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ DTк°Җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң proxy ground-truthм—җм„ң мң лҸ„лҗң pairwise policy rankingмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” rolloutмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң settingкіј architectureм—җм„ң мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ нҡЁмҡ©мқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмқҙл©°, DT$^2$к°Җ trainingм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗң policyмҷҖ unseen policy лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ conventional DT trainingм—җ л№„н•ҙ policy rankingмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ к°ңм„ н•ҳкі  decision regretлҘј мӨ„мқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, raw simulation fidelityлҠ” мўӢмқҖ мҲҳмӨҖмңјлЎң мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"61849","en":"AdamO: A Collapse-Suppressed Optimizer for Offline RL","ko":"AdamO: Offline RLмқ„ мң„н•ң л¶•кҙҙ м–өм ң Optimizer","authors":"Nan Qiao, Sheng Yue, Shuning Wang, Ju Ren","pos":"#408","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=mMlt3tQ7Ot","abs":"<p>Offline reinforcement learning (RL) can fail spectacularly when bootstrapped temporal-difference (TD) updates amplify their own errors, driving the critic toward extreme and unusable Q-values.  A key counterintuitive insight of this work is that collapse is not only a property of the backup rule or network architecture: the optimizer alone can directly trigger or suppress instability. From a control-theoretic viewpoint, we model offline TD learning as a feedback system and analyze Adam-based critic updates.  This yields a necessary and sufficient condition for stability: training is stable if and only if the spectral radius of the update dynamics is strictly below one. Further analysis reveals that standard Adam updates can inadvertently distort the parameter geometry, necessitating explicit orthogonality constraints to prevent TD error amplification. To this end, we propose AdamO, an Adam-based optimizer with a decoupled orthogonality correction regulated by a strict task-alignment budget. We prove that this design theoretically guarantees worst-case task safety and preserves AdamвҖҷs continuous-time dissipative dynamics. Empirically, AdamO is plug-and-play across diverse offline RL baselines, improving stability and returns across a broad suite of benchmarks.</p>","absKo":"<p>bootstrapped temporal-difference (TD) updateк°Җ мһҗмӢ мқҳ мҳӨм°ЁлҘј мҰқнҸӯмӢңмјң criticмқ„ к·№лӢЁм Ғмқҙкі  мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” Q-valueлЎң лӘ°м•„л„Јмқ„ л•Ң, offline reinforcement learning (RL)мқҖ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ мӢӨнҢЁн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬мқҳ н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё л°ҳм§ҒкҙҖм Ғ нҶөм°°мқҖ л¶•кҙҙк°Җ backup ruleмқҙлӮҳ network architectureмқҳ мҶҚм„ұм—җл§Ң көӯн•ңлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. optimizer мһҗмІҙк°Җ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •мқ„ м§Ғм ‘ мң л°ңн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ м–өм ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. control-theoretic кҙҖм җм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” offline TD learningмқ„ feedback systemмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкі  Adam-based critic updateлҘј л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎңл¶Җн„° м•Ҳм •м„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•„мҡ”м¶©л¶„мЎ°кұҙмқҙ лҸ„м¶ңлҗҳлҠ”лҚ°, update dynamicsмқҳ spectral radiusк°Җ м—„кІ©н•ҳкІҢ 1ліҙлӢӨ мһ‘мқ„ л•Ң к·ёлҰ¬кі  к·ёл•Ңл§Ң н•ҷмҠөмқҙ м•Ҳм •м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. м¶”к°Җ л¶„м„қмқҖ н‘ңмӨҖ Adam updateк°Җ parameter geometryлҘј мқҳлҸ„м№ҳ м•ҠкІҢ мҷңкіЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, TD error мҰқнҸӯмқ„ л§үкё° мң„н•ҙ лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқё orthogonality constraintк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•Ёмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м—„кІ©н•ң task-alignment budgetмңјлЎң мЎ°м ҲлҗҳлҠ” decoupled orthogonality correctionмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ Adam кё°л°ҳ optimizerмқё AdamOлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м„Өкі„к°Җ мөңм•…мқҳ кІҪмҡ° task safetyлҘј мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмһҘн•ҳкі  Adamмқҳ continuous-time dissipative dynamicsлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң AdamOлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң offline RL baseline м „л°ҳм—җм„ң plug-and-playлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ҳл©°, нҸӯл„“мқҖ benchmarkм—җм„ң м•Ҳм •м„ұкіј returnмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61973","en":"Bottleneck-Guided Spectral Subgoals For Offline Goal-Conditioned RL","ko":"Offline goal-conditioned RLмқ„ мң„н•ң bottleneck-guided spectral subgoal","authors":"Hebin Liang, Yi Ma, Chenjun Xiao, Zibin Dong, Zilin Cao, Fei Ni, Yifu Yuan, Jianye Hao","pos":"#409","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=l4Q8dGGHVC","abs":"Offline goal-conditioned RL (OGCRL) learns to reach arbitrary goals from offline dataset, but long-horizon performance hinges on crossing a handful of hard-to-cross bottlenecks. These bottlenecks not only dictate the feasible paths toward the goal but also act as critical keypoints, marking the transitions between adjacent regions and providing the agent with essential directional guidance. Prior hierarchical methods pick subgoals by time or short-horizon value heuristics, which do not localize the bottleneck, as a result, the agent losing the clear guidance that bottlenecks could provide about where to pass next. We instead model long-horizon planning as вҖңcross the next bottleneckвҖқ: we apply Laplacian spectral clustering to offline dataset to expose bottlenecks and then identify trajectories from the offline dataset that cross these boundaries, and the intersects are defined as keypoints (KPs). Then the most representative KPs are automatically selected and a directed KP reachability graph $\\mathcal G_{\\mathrm{KP}}$ is constructed based on the selected KPs. We then restrict high-level choices to these bottleneck states and use a pluggable low-level controller to execute the short transitions between them.  We provide theory showing that  under a standard metastable decomposition of the state space, routing through bottlenecks yields an (approximately) optimal one-step subgoal in terms of hitting-time,  and that Laplacian spectra recover bottlenecks with high overlap. Thus, Laplacian spectral clustering can discover approximately optimal subgoals. Empirically, the same pattern holds: across D4RL and OGBench, our method achieves state-of-the-art results on a broad set of navigation and manipulation tasks and across diverse dataset regimes, for example, **96.5\\%** on **AntMaze** and **84.5\\%** on **Franka-Kitchen**.","absKo":"Offline goal-conditioned RL(OGCRL)мқҖ offline datasetмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° мһ„мқҳмқҳ goalм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳлҠ” лІ•мқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, long-horizon м„ұлҠҘмқҖ л„ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ лӘҮ к°ңмқҳ лі‘лӘ©мқ„ нҶөкіјн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° лӢ¬л Ө мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң bottleneckмқҖ goalлЎң н–Ҙн•ҳлҠ” к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј к·ңм •н•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј, мқём ‘н•ң мҳҒм—ӯ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ м „мқҙлҘј н‘ңмӢңн•ҳкі  м—җмқҙм „нҠём—җ н•„мҲҳм Ғмқё л°©н–Ҙ м•ҲлӮҙлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң keypointлЎңлҸ„ мһ‘лҸҷн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ hierarchical methodлҠ” мӢңк°„ лҳҗлҠ” short-horizon value heuristicм—җ л”°лқј subgoalмқ„ м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” bottleneckмқҳ мң„м№ҳлҘј м •нҷ•нһҲ нҠ№м •н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј м—җмқҙм „нҠёлҠ” bottleneckмқҙ м ңкіөн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лӢӨмқҢм—җ м–ҙл””лҘј м§ҖлӮҳм•ј н•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң лӘ…нҷ•н•ң м•ҲлӮҙлҘј мһғкІҢ лҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҢҖмӢ  long-horizon planningмқ„ \"лӢӨмқҢ bottleneckмқ„ нҶөкіјн•ҳлқј\"лЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. offline datasetм—җ Laplacian spectral clusteringмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҙ bottleneckмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙкі , к·ё кІҪкі„лҘј к°ҖлЎңм§ҖлҘҙлҠ” trajectoryлҘј offline datasetм—җм„ң мӢқлі„н•ҳл©°, к·ё көҗм°Ём җл“Өмқ„ keypoint(KP)лЎң м •мқҳн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ к°ҖмһҘ лҢҖн‘ңм Ғмқё KPлҘј мһҗлҸҷмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ҳкі , м„ нғқлҗң KPлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң л°©н–Ҙм„ұ KP reachability graph $\\mathcal G_{\\mathrm{KP}}$лҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң high-level м„ нғқмқ„ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң bottleneck мғҒнғңлЎң м ңн•ңн•ҳкі , көҗмІҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң low-level controllerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ к·ёл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ м§§мқҖ м „мқҙлҘј мӢӨн–үн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҒнғң кіөк°„мқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ metastable decomposition н•ҳм—җм„ң bottleneckмқ„ нҶөн•ң лқјмҡ°нҢ…мқҙ hitting-time кҙҖм җм—җм„ң (к·јмӮ¬м ҒмңјлЎң) мөңм Ғмқҳ one-step subgoalмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, Laplacian spectrumмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ overlapмңјлЎң bottleneckмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” мқҙлЎ мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң Laplacian spectral clusteringмқҖ к·јмӮ¬м ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғмқҳ subgoalмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎңлҸ„ к°ҷмқҖ м–‘мғҒмқҙ лӮҳнғҖлӮңлӢӨ. D4RLкіј OGBench м „л°ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң navigation л°Ҹ manipulation taskмҷҖ м—¬лҹ¬ dataset regimeм—җм„ң state-of-the-art кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ **AntMaze**м—җм„ң **96.5\\%**, **Franka-Kitchen**м—җм„ң **84.5\\%**лҘј кё°лЎқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61312","en":"Frictional Q-Learning","ko":"л§Ҳм°° кё°л°ҳ Q-Learning","authors":"Hyunwoo Kim, Hyo Kyung Lee","pos":"#410","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=rSEdPcvrme","abs":"<p>Off-policy reinforcement learning suffers from extrapolation errors when a learned policy selects actions that are weakly supported in the replay buffer. In this study, we address this issue by drawing an analogy to static friction in classical mechanics. From this perspective, the replay buffer is represented as a smooth, low-dimensional action manifold, where the support directions correspond to the tangential component, while the normal component captures the dominant first-order extrapolation error. This decomposition reveals an intrinsic anisotropy in value sensitivity that naturally induces a stability condition analogous to a friction threshold. To mitigate deviations toward unsupported actions, we propose Frictional Q-Learning, an off-policy algorithm that encodes supported actions as tangent directions using a contrastive variational autoencoder. We further show that an orthonormal basis of the orthogonal complement corresponds to normal components under mild local isometry assumptions. Empirical results on standard continuous-control benchmarks demonstrate robust, stable performance compared with existing baselines.</p>","absKo":"<p>Off-policy reinforcement learningмқҖ н•ҷмҠөлҗң policyк°Җ replay bufferм—җм„ң м•Ҫн•ҳкІҢ м§Җм§ҖлҗҳлҠ” actionмқ„ м„ нғқн•  л•Ң extrapolation errorлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј кі м „м—ӯн•ҷмқҳ м •м Ғ л§Ҳм°°(static friction)кіјмқҳ мң мӮ¬м„ұмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм җм—җм„ң replay bufferлҠ” л§ӨлҒ„лҹҪкі  м Җм°Ёмӣҗм Ғмқё action manifoldлЎң н‘ңнҳ„лҗҳл©°, support directionмқҖ tangential componentм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳкі  normal componentлҠ” м§Җл°°м Ғмқё 1м°Ё extrapolation errorлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¶„н•ҙлҠ” value sensitivityм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң anisotropyлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ friction thresholdмҷҖ мң мӮ¬н•ң stability conditionмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. м§Җм§Җлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” actionмңјлЎңмқҳ мқјнғҲмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” contrastive variational autoencoderлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м§ҖмӣҗлҗҳлҠ” actionмқ„ tangent directionмңјлЎң мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳлҠ” off-policy algorithmмқё Frictional Q-Learningмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м•Ҫн•ң local isometry к°Җм • н•ҳм—җм„ң orthogonal complementмқҳ orthonormal basisк°Җ normal componentм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ continuous-control benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” кё°мЎҙ baselineкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ кІ¬кі н•ҳкі  м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60708","en":"Geometric Control of Out-of-Distribution Shift in Safe Offline RL","ko":"Safe Offline RLм—җм„ң Out-of-Distribution Shiftмқҳ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ м ңм–ҙ","authors":"Zhiqi Zhuang, di wu, Benoit Boulet","pos":"#411","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xLcOW4q39R","abs":"<p>Safe offline reinforcement learning (RL) requires optimizing policies within the support of static datasets while satisfying strict safety constraints. Although recent latent generative policies achieve strong empirical performance, they rely heavily on implicit regularization and lack systematic control over distributional shift during policy improvement. In this work, we propose a geometric control framework that leverages the bijective structure of conditional normalizing flows to provide a tractable mechanism to regulate distributional deviation of the policy. By constraining divergence in the latent base space, we derive tractable upper bounds on the induced Wasserstein distance and total variation of the policy distribution, establishing an analyzable connection between latent geometry and downstream behaviors. This insight motivates a decoupled architecture: a flow prior shapes a feasibility-weighted latent manifold using Hamilton--Jacobi reachability signals, while a latent refiner performs geometrically constrained optimization directly in the base space. Across multiple safe RL benchmarks, our method achieves robustly low violation rates with competitive returns, highlighting the benefits of structured geometric regularization.</p>","absKo":"<p>м•Ҳм „н•ң offline reinforcement learning(RL)мқҖ м—„кІ©н•ң safety constraintлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң static datasetмқҳ support м•Ҳм—җм„ң м •мұ…мқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј latent generative policyк°Җ к°•н•ң кІҪн—ҳм Ғ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, мқҙл“ӨмқҖ implicit regularizationм—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©° policy improvement лҸҷм•Ҳ distributional shiftлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң м ңм–ҙн•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” conditional normalizing flowмқҳ bijective structureлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ policyмқҳ distributional deviationмқ„ лӢӨлЈ° мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” geometric control frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. latent base spaceм—җм„ңмқҳ divergenceлҘј м ңм•Ҫн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мң лҸ„лҗң policy distributionмқҳ Wasserstein distanceмҷҖ total variationм—җ лҢҖн•ң tractableн•ң мғҒн•ңмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкі , latent geometryмҷҖ downstream behavior мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ л¶„м„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м—°кІ°мқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқҖ л¶„лҰ¬лҗң architectureлҘј лҸҷкё°л¶Җм—¬н•ңлӢӨ: flow priorлҠ” Hamilton--Jacobi reachability signalмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ feasibility-weighted latent manifoldлҘј нҳ•м„ұн•ҳкі , latent refinerлҠ” base spaceм—җм„ң м§Ғм ‘ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң м ңм•Ҫлҗң optimizationмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ safe RL benchmarkм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” returnкіј н•Ёк»ҳ robustн•ҳкІҢ лӮ®мқҖ violation rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗң geometric regularizationмқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61137","en":"Improving Diffusion Planners by Self-Supervised Action Gating with Energies","ko":"Energy кё°л°ҳ Self-Supervised Action GatingмңјлЎң Diffusion Planner к°ңм„ ","authors":"Yuan Lu, Dongqi Han, Yansen Wang, Dongsheng Li","pos":"#412","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tLW4Tc7Zn9","abs":"<p>Diffusion planners are a strong approach for offline reinforcement learning, but they can fail when value-guided selection favours trajectories that score well yet are locally inconsistent with the environment dynamics, resulting in brittle execution. We propose Self-supervised Action Gating with Energies (SAGE), an inference-time re-ranking method that penalises dynamically inconsistent plans using a latent consistency signal. SAGE trains a Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture (JEPA) encoder on offline state sequences and an action-conditioned latent predictor for short horizon transitions. At test time, SAGE assigns each sampled candidate an energy given by its latent prediction error and combines this feasibility score with value estimates to select actions. SAGE can integrates into existing diffusion planning pipelines that can sample trajectories and select actions via value scoring; it requires no environment rollouts and no policy re-training. Across locomotion, navigation, and manipulation benchmarks, SAGE improves the performance and robustness of diffusion planners.</p>","absKo":"<p>Diffusion plannerлҠ” offline reinforcement learningм—җм„ң к°•л Ҙн•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мқҙм§Җл§Ң, value-guided selectionмқҙ нҷҳкІҪ dynamicsмҷҖ көӯмҶҢм ҒмңјлЎң мқјкҙҖлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ trajectoryлҘј м„ нҳён•  л•Ң, м җмҲҳлҠ” лҶ’м§Җл§Ң мӢӨн–үмқҖ л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ң trajectoryлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңк°Җ мғқкёё мҲҳ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” latent consistency signalмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” planм—җ нҢЁл„җнӢ°лҘј мЈјлҠ” inference-time re-ranking л°©лІ• Self-supervised Action Gating with Energies (SAGE)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. SAGEлҠ” offline state sequence мң„м—җм„ң Joint-Embedding Predictive Architecture (JEPA) encoderлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , м§§мқҖ horizon transitionмқ„ мң„н•ң action-conditioned latent predictorлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. н…ҢмҠӨнҠё мӢңм—җлҠ” SAGEк°Җ к°Ғ sampled candidateм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ latent prediction errorлЎң м •мқҳлҗҳлҠ” energyлҘј н• лӢ№н•ҳкі , мқҙ feasibility scoreлҘј value estimateмҷҖ кІ°н•©н•ҙ actionмқ„ м„ нғқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. SAGEлҠ” trajectoryлҘј sampleн•ҳкі  value scoringмңјлЎң actionмқ„ м„ нғқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кё°мЎҙ diffusion planning pipelineм—җ нҶөн•©н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, environment rolloutмқҙлӮҳ policy мһ¬н•ҷмҠөмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. locomotion, navigation, manipulation benchmark м „л°ҳм—җм„ң SAGEлҠ” diffusion plannerмқҳ м„ұлҠҘкіј robustenessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮөлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65235","en":"Improving LLM-Based Recommenders with Conservative Generative Flow Networks","ko":"Conservative Generative Flow NetworkлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң LLM кё°л°ҳ м¶”мІңкё° к°ңм„ ","authors":"Xuan Yu, Feng Niu, Rui Zhu, Yudong Zhang, Xu Wang, Yang Wang","pos":"#413","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FXIy6qfQIR","abs":"<p>Generative Flow Networks (GFlowNets) have recently been used to improve diversity and mitigate popularity bias in LLM-based recommender systems, yet most objectives are developed under online-style assumptions. In offline LLM-based recommendation, learning is constrained to a fixed logged dataset, yielding partial support over token transitions on the dataset-induced token-prefix DAG. Naively applying Sub-Trajectory Balance (SubTB) becomes non-identifiable and can arbitrarily allocate probability mass to unsupported regions. We formalize this failure and identify three sources of non-identifiability that induce distributional shift between the dataset-implied policy and the learned policy: (i) flow overestimation, (ii) forward mass leakage, and (iii) backward compensation. To address it, we propose CFlower, which introduces a conservative SubTB objective that explicitly penalizes unsupported forward flow mass, and combines it with dataset-constrained policy learning with on-policy sampling on the dataset-induced DAG for efficient training under offline constraints. Experiments on three Amazon recommendation datasets show that CFlower improves distributional matching and delivers a stronger accuracy--exposure trade-off than prior GFlowNet and SFT baselines, while serving as a more reliable reference policy for downstream RL fine-tuning.</p>","absKo":"<p>Generative Flow Networks (GFlowNets)лҠ” мөңк·ј LLM кё°л°ҳ recommender systemм—җм„ң лӢӨм–‘м„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқҙкі  popularity biasлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ objectiveлҠ” online мҠӨнғҖмқј к°Җм •н•ҳм—җм„ң к°ңл°ңлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. offline LLM кё°л°ҳ recommendationм—җм„ңлҠ” н•ҷмҠөмқҙ кі м •лҗң logged datasetмңјлЎң м ңн•ңлҗҳлҜҖлЎң, datasetмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” token-prefix DAG мң„мқҳ token transitionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ л¶Җл¶„м Ғмқё supportл§Ң мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨ. Sub-Trajectory Balance (SubTB)лҘј naively м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ non-identifiableн•ҙм§Җл©°, м§Җмӣҗлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” мҳҒм—ӯм—җ probability massлҘј мһ„мқҳлЎң н• лӢ№н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мӢӨнҢЁлҘј м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , datasetк°Җ м•”мӢңн•ҳлҠ” policyмҷҖ н•ҷмҠөлҗң policy мӮ¬мқҙм—җ distributional shiftлҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ non-identifiability мӣҗмқёмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ: (i) flow overestimation, (ii) forward mass leakage, (iii) backward compensation. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CFlowerлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. CFlowerлҠ” м§Җмӣҗлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” forward flow massлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң лІҢм җнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” conservative SubTB objectiveлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј datasetмқҙ мң лҸ„н•ң DAGм—җм„ң on-policy samplingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” dataset-constrained policy learningкіј кІ°н•©н•ҳм—¬ offline м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё н•ҷмҠөмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м„ё к°ңмқҳ Amazon recommendation datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң CFlowerлҠ” distributional matchingмқ„ к°ңм„ н•ҳкі , кё°мЎҙ GFlowNet л°Ҹ SFT baselineліҙлӢӨ лҚ” к°•н•ң accuracy--exposure trade-offлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ downstream RL fine-tuningмқ„ мң„н•ң лҚ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” reference policyлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66750","en":"InfraRL: A Benchmark for Constrained Resource Allocation in Large-Scale Infrastructure Asset Management","ko":"InfraRL: лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мқён”„лқј мһҗмӮ° кҙҖлҰ¬м—җм„ң м ңм•Ҫлҗң мһҗмӣҗ н• лӢ№мқ„ мң„н•ң лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнҒ¬","authors":"Yantian Wang, Wenhao Li, Bo Jin","pos":"#414","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0gi5YPCYnN","abs":"<p>Optimizing maintenance strategies for large-scale infrastructure is a critical sequential decision-making problem, exemplified by the high-stakes domain of bridge management. While Reinforcement Learning (RL) offers a theoretical framework for such problems, practical deployment necessitates offline constrained RLвҖ”learning policies solely from static historical datasets under rigid budgetary limits without dangerous on-policy exploration.However, current research is hindered by benchmarks that fail to capture the confluence of distributional shift and hard constraints typical of real-world assets. We introduce InfraRL, a high-fidelity benchmark that uses bridge maintenance as a rigorous testbed for general infrastructure asset management challenges.Constructed from the U.S. National Bridge Inventory, InfraRL defines a rigorous offline task for optimizing maintenance strategies under hard budgetary constraints. We benchmark a diverse suite of baselines, ranging from industry-standard heuristics to SOTA single-agent and multi-agent offline RL algorithms. Through a comprehensive evaluation protocol, we analyze performance across structural utility, constraint adherence, and behavioral fidelity, revealing critical trade-offs between safety and long-term efficiency. Our code and data are available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/ICML-6656</p>","absKo":"<p>лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ мқён”„лқјмқҳ мң м§ҖліҙмҲҳ м „лһөмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мҲңм°Ё мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • л¬ём ңмқҙл©°, көҗлҹү кҙҖлҰ¬лқјлҠ” кі мң„н—ҳ лҸ„л©”мқёмқҙ к·ё лҢҖн‘ңм Ғ мҳҲлӢӨ. Reinforcement Learning (RL)мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ нӢҖмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ң л°°м№ҳлҘј мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” мҳӨн”„лқјмқё constrained RL, мҰү мң„н—ҳн•ң on-policy exploration м—Ҷмқҙ м—„кІ©н•ң мҳҲмӮ° м ңм•Ҫн•ҳм—җ м •м Ғ кіјкұ° лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣл§ҢмңјлЎң м •мұ…мқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ нҳ„мһ¬ м—°кө¬лҠ” мӢӨм ң мһҗмӮ°м—җм„ң м „нҳ•м ҒмңјлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” л¶„нҸ¬ мқҙлҸҷкіј hard constraintмқҳ кІ°н•©мқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ” benchmarkл“ӨлЎң мқён•ҙ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л°ӣлҠ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” көҗлҹү мң м§ҖліҙмҲҳлҘј мқён”„лқј мһҗмӮ° кҙҖлҰ¬мқҳ м—„кІ©н•ң н…ҢмҠӨнҠёлІ л“ңлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кі м¶©мӢӨлҸ„ benchmarkмқё InfraRLмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. U.S. National Bridge InventoryлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң InfraRLмқҖ hard budgetary constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң мң м§ҖліҙмҲҳ м „лһөмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” м—„кІ©н•ң offline taskлҘј м •мқҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӮ°м—… н‘ңмӨҖ нңҙлҰ¬мҠӨнӢұл¶Җн„° SOTA single-agent л°Ҹ multi-agent offline RL м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳм—җ мқҙлҘҙлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң baselineмқ„ лІӨм№ҳл§ҲнӮ№н•ңлӢӨ. нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё нҸүк°Җ н”„лЎңнҶ мҪңмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ нҡЁмҡ©, м ңм•Ҫ мӨҖмҲҳ, н–үлҸҷ м¶©мӢӨлҸ„ м „л°ҳмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ҳл©°, м•Ҳм „м„ұкіј мһҘкё° нҡЁмңЁм„ұ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң trade-offлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/ICML-6656 м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ</p>"},{"id":"62289","en":"Noisy-Space Policy Gradient for Diffusion Policies in Offline Reinforcement Learning","ko":"Offline Reinforcement Learningм—җм„ң Diffusion PolicyлҘј мң„н•ң Noisy-Space Policy Gradient","authors":"Mahmoud Selim, Cristina Cipriani, Karl Johansson","pos":"#415","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=hwfCLpDj8d","abs":"<p>Diffusion policies offer a powerful and expressive parameterization for continuous control. Yet, their integration with reinforcement learning remains conceptually and algorithmically challenging. In this work, we address this gap by introducing a noisy-space action-value (Q-)function that assigns values to diffusion latents through the distribution of executed actions induced by the denoising process. We show that this construction admits a precise semantic interpretation and derive a noisy-space policy gradient (NSPG) in which value estimates for noisy latents are computed exclusively using clean action-space values. Building on this result, we formulate a KL-regularized policy improvement over noisy latents and show that the resulting objective admits a diffusion-compatible regression form, avoiding backpropagation through the denoising process. Experiments on the D4RL benchmark demonstrate that semantically grounded value gradients provide a principled, effective foundation for training diffusion policies in offline reinforcement learning.</p>","absKo":"<p>Diffusion policyлҠ” м—°мҶҚ м ңм–ҙлҘј мң„н•ң к°•л Ҙн•ҳкі  н‘ңнҳ„л Ҙ мһҲлҠ” parameterizationмқ„ м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҘј reinforcement learningкіј нҶөн•©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ к°ңл…җм ҒмңјлЎңлҸ„ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳм ҒмңјлЎңлҸ„ м–ҙл өмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” denoising processк°Җ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” мӢӨн–ү actionмқҳ л¶„нҸ¬лҘј нҶөн•ҙ diffusion latentм—җ к°’мқ„ н• лӢ№н•ҳлҠ” noisy-space action-value(Q-)functionмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мӣҒлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ кө¬м„ұмқҙ м •л°Җн•ң мқҳлҜёлЎ м Ғ н•ҙм„қмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , noisy latentм—җ лҢҖн•ң value estimateк°Җ мҳӨм§Ғ clean action-space valueл§Ңмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кі„мӮ°лҗҳлҠ” noisy-space policy gradient(NSPG)лҘј мң лҸ„н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң noisy latent мң„м—җм„ң KL-regularized policy improvementлҘј м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , к·ё кІ°кіј objectiveк°Җ diffusion-compatible regression formмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм–ҙ denoising processлҘј нҶөн•ң backpropagationмқ„ н”јн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. D4RL benchmarkм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҳлҜёлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң м •лҰҪлҗң value gradientк°Җ offline reinforcement learningм—җм„ң diffusion policyлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё кё°л°ҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60674","en":"Ariadne's Thread of LipSync: Unraveling Forgeries via Inconsistency between Lip Motions and Head Poses","ko":"LipSyncмқҳ Ariadne's Thread: мһ…мҲ  мӣҖм§Ғмһ„кіј лЁёлҰ¬ мһҗм„ёмқҳ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлЎң мң„мЎ° н’Җм–ҙлӮҙкё°","authors":"Tianyi She, Jiawei Liu, Weifeng Liu, Hanqing Zhao, Weiming Zhang, Kejiang Chen","pos":"#3400","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=xmKNNOElLM","abs":"<p>Recent advances in LipSync generation technology have led to the creation of highly realistic videos, posing severe societal risks. However, existing defense strategies struggle against LipSync forgeries, as state-of-the-art generative models not only optimize for the lip synchronization but also significantly eliminate visual artifacts, resulting in the lack of key detection signals. Inspired by the inherent biological coupling between lip movements and head poses in natural speech, we observe that generative models fundamentally disrupt this global coordination when optimizing for local lip motion. In this paper, we propose LipDA, a novel framework for joint LipSync Detection and Attribution, which takes advantage of the inconsistency between head and lip. For detection, the framework learns to quantify this discrepancy by contrasting lip and pose features from authentic versus forged videos. For attribution, our method is designed to capture the unique temporal dynamics and audio-visual synchronization patterns that act as generative fingerprints, enabling source tracing. To validate our approach, we conduct extensive experiments on two challenging LipSync benchmarks as well as on our own proposed large-scale and multi-generator dataset, LipSyncBench-A. LipDA achieves over 97% AUC in detection and 97.5% accuracy in model attribution, significantly outperforming existing methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>мөңк·ј LipSync generation technologyмқҳ л°ңм „мқҖ л§Өмҡ° мӮ¬мӢӨм Ғмқё videoмқҳ мғқм„ұмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҠ” мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ мң„н—ҳмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ defense strategyлҠ” LipSync forgeryм—җ м ңлҢҖлЎң лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, state-of-the-art generative modelмқҙ lip synchronizationмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј visual artifactк№Ңм§Җ нҒ¬кІҢ м ңкұ°н•ҳм—¬ нғҗм§Җм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң н•өмӢ¬ мӢ нҳёк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҙм§Җкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ speechм—җм„ң lip movementмҷҖ head pose мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё biological couplingм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” generative modelмқҙ local lip motionмқ„ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кіјм •м—җм„ң мқҙ м „м—ӯм Ғ мЎ°мңЁмқ„ к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң к№ЁлңЁлҰ°лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ кҙҖм°°н•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” headмҷҖ lip мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ inconsistencyлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ”, LipSync Detectionкіј Attributionмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkмқё LipDAлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. нғҗм§Җ мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң, мқҙ frameworkлҠ” м§„м§ң мҳҒмғҒкіј мң„мЎ° мҳҒмғҒмқҳ lip featureмҷҖ pose featureлҘј лҢҖл№„н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ discrepancyлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ҷмҠөн•ңлӢӨ. attribution мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ generative fingerprintлЎң мһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кі мң н•ң temporal dynamicsмҷҖ audio-visual synchronization patternмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗҳм–ҙ source tracingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м ңм•Ҳн•ң м ‘к·јмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, л‘җ к°ңмқҳ к№ҢлӢӨлЎңмҡҙ LipSync benchmarkмҷҖ лҚ”л¶Ҳм–ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м ңм•Ҳн•ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ multi-generator datasetмқё LipSyncBench-Aм—җм„ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ. LipDAлҠ” нғҗм§Җм—җм„ң 97%к°Җ л„ҳлҠ” AUCмҷҖ model attributionм—җм„ң 97.5%мқҳ accuracyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63145","en":"SurrogateSHAP: Training-Free Contributor Attribution for Text-to-Image (T2I) Models","ko":"SurrogateSHAP: Text-to-Image(T2I) лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мң„н•ң н•ҷмҠө л¶Ҳн•„мҡ” кё°м—¬мһҗ к·ҖмҶҚ","authors":"MingYu Lu, Soham Gadgil, Chris Lin, Chanwoo Kim, Su-In Lee","pos":"#3403","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Zdx1hFJarp","abs":"<p>As Text-to-Image (T2I) diffusion models are increasingly used in real-world creative workflows, a principled framework for valuing contributors who provide a collection of data is essential for fair compensation and sustainable data marketplaces. While the Shapley value offers a theoretically grounded approach to attribution, it faces a dual computational bottleneck: (i) the prohibitive cost of exhaustive model retraining for each sampled subset of players (i.e., data contributors) and (ii) the combinatorial number of subsets needed to estimate marginal contributions due to contributor interactions. To this end, we propose <strong>SurrogateSHAP</strong>, a retraining-free framework that approximates the expensive retraining game through inference from a pretrained model. To further improve efficiency, we employ a gradient-boosted tree to approximate the utility function and derive Shapley values analytically from the tree-based model. We evaluate SurrogateSHAP across three diverse attribution tasks: (i) image quality for DDPM-CFG on CIFAR-20, (ii) aesthetics for Stable Diffusion on Post-Impressionist artworks, and (iii) product diversity for FLUX.1 on Fashion-Product data. Across settings, SurrogateSHAP outperforms prior methods while substantially reducing computational overhead, consistently identifying influential contributors across multiple utility metrics. Finally, we demonstrate that SurrogateSHAP effectively localizes data sources responsible for spurious correlations in clinical images, providing a scalable path toward auditing safety-critical generative models. Code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CFG-Attribution-15DD/</p>","absKo":"<p>Text-to-Image (T2I) diffusion modelмқҙ мӢӨм ң м°Ҫмһ‘ workflowм—җм„ң м җм җ лҚ” л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗЁм—җ л”°лқј, лҚ°мқҙн„° м§‘н•©мқ„ м ңкіөн•ң кё°м—¬мһҗлҘј кіөм •н•ҳкІҢ ліҙмғҒн•ҳкі  м§ҖмҶҚ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң data marketplaceлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” мқҙл“Өмқ„ к°Җм№ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” мӣҗлҰ¬м Ғ frameworkк°Җ н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. Shapley valueлҠ” attributionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң м •лӢ№нҷ”лҗң м ‘к·јмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, л‘җ к°Җм§Җ кі„мӮ° лі‘лӘ©м—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•ңлӢӨ. (i) мғҳн”Ңл§Ғлҗң к°Ғ player subset(мҰү, data contributor)м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ exhaustive model retrainingмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” м—„мІӯлӮң л№„мҡ©, (ii) contributor interactionмңјлЎң мқён•ҙ marginal contributionмқ„ м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң subsetмқҳ мЎ°н•©м Ғ мҲҳ. мқҙлҘј мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” pretrained modelлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ inferenceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° retraining gameмқ„ к·јмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” retraining-free frameworkмқё <strong>SurrogateSHAP</strong>мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ лҚ” лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” gradient-boosted treeлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ utility functionмқ„ к·јмӮ¬н•ҳкі  tree-based modelлЎңл¶Җн„° Shapley valueлҘј н•ҙм„қм ҒмңјлЎң лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” SurrogateSHAPмқ„ м„ё к°Җм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң attribution taskм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. (i) CIFAR-20м—җм„ң DDPM-CFGмқҳ image quality, (ii) Post-Impressionist artworkм—җм„ң Stable Diffusionмқҳ aesthetics, (iii) Fashion-Product dataм—җм„ң FLUX.1мқҳ product diversity. м—¬лҹ¬ м„Өм • м „л°ҳм—җм„ң SurrogateSHAPмқҖ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мҳҖкі , м—¬лҹ¬ utility metricм—җм„ң мҳҒн–Ҙл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” кё°м—¬мһҗлҘј мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, SurrogateSHAPмқҙ мһ„мғҒ мқҙлҜём§Җм—җм„ң spurious correlationмқҳ мӣҗмқёмқҙ лҗҳлҠ” data sourceлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң көӯмҶҢнҷ”н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, м•Ҳм „мқҙ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң generative modelмқҳ auditingмқ„ мң„н•ң нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ң: https://anonymous.4open.science/r/CFG-Attribution-15DD/</p>"},{"id":"64795","en":"Mixture of Concept Bottleneck Experts","ko":"Concept Bottleneck Expertмқҳ нҳјн•©","authors":"Francesco De Santis, Gabriele Ciravegna, Giovanni De Felice, Arianna Casanova, Francesco Giannini, Michelangelo Diligenti, Mateo Espinosa Zarlenga, Pietro Barbiero, Johannes Schneider, Danilo Giordano","pos":"#3401","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Jj8Vec8qSs","abs":"<p>Concept Bottleneck Models (CBMs) promote interpretability by grounding predictions in human-understandable concepts. However, existing CBMs typically fix their task predictor to a single linear or Boolean expression, limiting both predictive accuracy and adaptability to diverse user needs. We propose Mixture of Concept Bottleneck Experts (M-CBEs), a framework that generalizes existing CBMs along two dimensions: the number of experts and the functional form of each expert, exposing an underexplored region of the design space. We investigate this region by instantiating two novel models: Linear M-CBE, which learns a finite set of linear expressions, and Symbolic M-CBE, which leverages symbolic regression to discover expert functions from data under user-specified operator vocabularies. Empirical evaluation demonstrates that varying the mixture size and functional form provides a robust framework for navigating the accuracy-interpretability trade-off, adapting to different user and task needs.</p>","absKo":"<p>Concept Bottleneck Models (CBMs)мқҖ мҳҲмёЎмқ„ мӮ¬лһҢмқҙ мқҙн•ҙн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” к°ңл…җм—җ кё°л°ҳмӢңнӮӨлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқёлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ CBMмқҖ ліҙнҶө task predictorлҘј н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ м„ нҳ• лҳҗлҠ” Boolean expressionмңјлЎң кі м •н•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, мҳҲмёЎ м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мҡ”кө¬м—җ лҢҖн•ң м Ғмқ‘м„ұ лӘЁл‘җк°Җ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Mixture of Concept Bottleneck Experts (M-CBEs)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙ CBMмқ„ expertмқҳ к°ңмҲҳмҷҖ к°Ғ expertмқҳ functional formмқҙлқјлҠ” л‘җ м°Ёмӣҗм—җм„ң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лЎң, м§ҖкёҲк№Ңм§Җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ design spaceмқҳ мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лӘЁлҚёмқ„ кө¬мІҙнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” мң н•ңн•ң к°ңмҲҳмқҳ linear expressionsлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” Linear M-CBEмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” user-specified operator vocabulary н•ҳм—җм„ң symbolic regressionмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ dataлЎңл¶Җн„° expert functionsлҘј л°ңкІ¬н•ҳлҠ” Symbolic M-CBEмқҙлӢӨ. мӢӨмҰқм Ғ нҸүк°ҖлҠ” mixture sizeмҷҖ functional formмқ„ ліҖнҷ”мӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқҙ accuracy-interpretability trade-offлҘј нғҗмғүн•ҳкі  м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ л°Ҹ task мҡ”кө¬м—җ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң к°•кұҙн•ң н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64406","en":"WMVLM: Evaluating Diffusion Model Image Watermarking via Vision-Language Models","ko":"WMVLM: Vision-Language лӘЁлҚёмқ„ нҶөн•ң Diffusion лӘЁлҚё мқҙлҜём§Җ мӣҢн„°л§ҲнӮ№ нҸүк°Җ","authors":"Zijin Yang, Yu Sun, Kejiang Chen, jiawei zhao, Jun Jiang, Weiming Zhang, Nenghai Yu","pos":"#3404","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Nw55XJi7Jb","abs":"<p>Digital watermarking is essential for securing generated images from diffusion models. Accurate watermark evaluation is critical for algorithm development, yet existing methods have significant limitations: they lack a unified framework for both residual and semantic watermarks, provide results without interpretability, neglect comprehensive security considerations, and often use inappropriate metrics for semantic watermarks. To address these gaps, we propose <strong>WMVLM</strong>, the first unified and interpretable evaluation framework for diffusion model image <strong>w</strong>ater<strong>m</strong>arking via <strong>v</strong>ision-<strong>l</strong>anguage <strong>m</strong>odels (VLMs).  We redefine quality and security metrics for each watermark type: residual watermarks are evaluated by artifact strength and erasure resistance, while semantic watermarks are assessed through latent distribution shifts. Moreover, we introduce a three-stage training strategy to progressively enable the model to achieve classification, scoring, and interpretable text generation. Experiments show WMVLM outperforms state-of-the-art VLMs with strong generalization across datasets, diffusion models, and watermarking methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Digital watermarkingмқҖ diffusion modelмқҙ мғқм„ұн•ң мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј ліҙнҳён•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҲҳм ҒмқҙлӢӨ. м •нҷ•н•ң watermark нҸүк°ҖмҷҖлҠ” м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ к°ңл°ңм—җ л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•м—җлҠ” мғҒлӢ№н•ң н•ңкі„к°Җ мһҲлӢӨ. residual watermarkмҷҖ semantic watermarkлҘј лӘЁл‘җ лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” нҶөн•© frameworkк°Җ м—Ҷкі , н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” кІ°кіјлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё ліҙм•Ҳ кі л ӨлҘј лҲ„лқҪн•ҳкі , semantic watermarkм—җлҠ” мў…мў… л¶Җм Ғм Ҳн•ң metricмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кіөл°ұмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” diffusion model image <strong>w</strong>ater<strong>m</strong>arkingмқ„ vision-language model (VLM)мқ„ нҶөн•ҙ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ нҶөн•©м Ғмқҙл©° н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҸүк°Җ frameworkмқё <strong>WMVLM</strong>мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°Ғ watermark мң нҳ•м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ qualityмҷҖ security metricмқ„ мһ¬м •мқҳн•ңлӢӨ. residual watermarkлҠ” artifact strengthмҷҖ erasure resistanceлЎң нҸүк°Җн•ҳкі , semantic watermarkлҠ” latent distribution shiftлҘј нҶөн•ҙ нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ classification, scoring, н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң text generationмқ„ м җм§„м ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳн–үн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ л§Ңл“ңлҠ” three-stage training strategyлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј WMVLMмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ dataset, diffusion model, watermarking method м „л°ҳм—җм„ң к°•н•ң generalizationмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©° state-of-the-art VLMліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67111","en":"Position: Every Ground Truth is a Human Construction, not an Objective Truth","ko":"Position: лӘЁл“  Ground TruthлҠ” мқёк°„мқҙ кө¬м„ұн•ң кІғмқҙм§Җ к°қкҙҖм Ғ м§„лҰ¬к°Җ м•„лӢҲлӢӨ","authors":"Charlotte HГ¶gberg, Ericka Johnson, Kiri Wagstaff","pos":"#4601","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=faUnI2FEgw","abs":"<p>Ground truth datasets play a fundamental role as reference values in the training and evaluation of machine learning models. This position paper argues that ground truths are not neutral objective measurements that are naturally given, but instead that they are constructed by arrangements of humans and technologies. We argue that the ML community will benefit by articulating and discussing these often invisible or unreported choices and by acknowledging that reference data sets are contingent, not universal. Focusing on the situated and context-dependent nature of ground truths can improve reliability by enabling a better informed perspective on where, when, and how the datasets, and the models they have shaped, can best be used. We argue for increasing `situated reliability' which includes articulating the limits and strengths of models and their truth claims. Finally, paying more attention to the construction of ground truths can help achieve transparency and accountability and support interdisciplinary work in ML development.</p>","absKo":"<p>Ground truth лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмқҖ machine learning лӘЁлҚёмқҳ н•ҷмҠөкіј нҸүк°Җм—җм„ң кё°мӨҖк°’мңјлЎңм„ң к·јліём Ғмқё м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ position paperлҠ” ground truthк°Җ мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ мЈјм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” мӨ‘лҰҪм Ғмқҙкі  к°қкҙҖм Ғмқё мёЎм •м№ҳк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј, мқёк°„кіј кё°мҲ мқҳ л°°м№ҳм—җ мқҳн•ҙ кө¬м„ұлҗң кІғмқҙлқјкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ML м»Өл®ӨлӢҲнӢ°к°Җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң, мў…мў… ліҙмқҙм§Җ м•Ҡкұ°лӮҳ ліҙкі лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” м„ нғқл“Өмқ„ лӘ…мӢңн•ҳкі  л…јмқҳн•ҳл©°, reference data setмқҙ ліҙнҺём Ғмқҙм§Җ м•Ҡкі  л§ҘлқҪм ҒмқҙлқјлҠ” м җмқ„ мқём •н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙмқөмқ„ м–»мқ„ кІғмқҙлқјкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. ground truthмқҳ мң„м№ҳм„ұ(situated)кіј л§ҘлқҪ мқҳмЎҙм Ғ м„ұкІ©м—җ мЈјлӘ©н•ҳл©ҙ, лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣкіј к·ёкІғмқҙ нҳ•м„ұн•ң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ м–ём ң, м–ҙл””м„ң, м–ҙл–»кІҢ к°ҖмһҘ мһҳ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ лҚ” мһҳ informed perspectiveлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм—¬ мӢ лў°м„ұмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚёкіј к·ё truth claimмқҳ н•ңкі„мҷҖ к°•м җмқ„ лӘ…мӢңн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” 'situated reliability'мқҳ мҰқм§„мқ„ мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, ground truthмқҳ кө¬м„ұм—җ лҚ” л§ҺмқҖ мЈјмқҳлҘј кё°мҡёмқҙл©ҙ нҲ¬лӘ…м„ұкіј мұ…мһ„м„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқҙкі  ML к°ңл°ңм—җм„ңмқҳ н•ҷм ңк°„ нҳ‘м—…мқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65433","en":"Graph-Preference Learning: Debiasing Network-Sampled Human Feedback for Target Welfare Estimation","ko":"Graph-Preference Learning: лӘ©н‘ң нӣ„мғқ м¶”м •мқ„ мң„н•ң л„ӨнҠёмӣҢнҒ¬ мғҳн”Ңл§Ғ мқёк°„ н”јл“ңл°ұмқҳ нҺён–Ҙ м ңкұ°","authors":"Guangrui Fan, DanDan Liu, AZNUL SABRI, Pan Lihu","pos":"#3011","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=DiNZ5ccCo6","abs":"Preference-based reward modeling is a core component of RLHF and DPO pipelines. In practice, the humans providing preference feedback are rarely an i.i.d. sample: recruitment and exposure often follow social, institutional, or spatial structure, inducing non-uniform inclusion probabilities that correlate with graph centrality. We formalize preference learning with *network-sampled* annotators and show that identity-agnostic scalar reward modeling implicitly represents an inclusion-weighted welfare, over-representing structurally central communities when the inclusion distribution $q$ differs from a designer-chosen target weighting $\\pi$. We propose Graph-Preference Learning, which combines (i) a graph-personalized reward model that shares statistical strength across neighboring annotators and (ii) graph-balanced aggregation that computes stabilized importance weights to target $\\pi$. Our analysis characterizes the induced welfare represented by the learned aggregate reward and bounds its deviation from the target in terms of weight mismatch, reward-model approximation, and finite-sample effects. Experiments on synthetic graphs and a *semi-synthetic* case study on the LMArena preference dataset, where biased inclusion is *induced* via graph-based sampling, demonstrate up to 62% reduction in target-welfare recovery error and 17% reduction in cross-language performance gaps under biased inclusion.","absKo":"Preference-based reward modelingмқҖ RLHFмҷҖ DPO pipelineмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢмқҙлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎң preference feedbackмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” мқёк°„мқҖ кұ°мқҳ i.i.d. sampleмқҙ м•„лӢҲлӢӨ. мұ„мҡ©кіј л…ём¶ңмқҖ мў…мў… мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ, м ңлҸ„м Ғ, лҳҗлҠ” кіөк°„м Ғ кө¬мЎ°лҘј л”°лҘҙл©°, graph centralityмҷҖ мғҒкҙҖлҗң л№„к· мқјн•ң inclusion probabilityлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” *network-sampled* annotatorлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” preference learningмқ„ м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳкі , identity-agnostic scalar reward modelingмқҙ inclusion-weighted welfareлҘј м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳм—¬, inclusion distribution $q$к°Җ м„Өкі„мһҗк°Җ м„ нғқн•ң target weighting $\\pi$мҷҖ лӢӨлҘј л•Ң кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң мӨ‘мӢ¬м Ғмқё communityлҘј кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ лҢҖн‘ңн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Graph-Preference Learningмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” (i) мқҙмӣғ annotator к°„м—җ statistical strengthлҘј кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” graph-personalized reward modelкіј (ii) $\\pi$лҘј лӘ©н‘ңлЎң м•Ҳм •нҷ”лҗң importance weightлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” graph-balanced aggregationмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ н•ҷмҠөлҗң aggregate rewardк°Җ н‘ңнҳ„н•ҳлҠ” мң лҸ„ welfareлҘј нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳкі , weight mismatch, reward-model approximation, finite-sample effect мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң targetмңјлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ нҺём°ЁлҘј мғҒн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. synthetic graphмҷҖ, graph-based samplingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ biased inclusionмқҙ *мң лҸ„*лҗң LMArena preference datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң *semi-synthetic* case study мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ target-welfare recovery errorлҘј мөңлҢҖ 62% мӨ„мқҙкі  biased inclusion н•ҳм—җм„ң cross-language performance gapмқ„ 17% мӨ„мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"67126","en":"Position: Beyond Sensitive Attributes, ML Fairness Should Quantify Structural Injustice via Social Determinants","ko":"Position: лҜјк°җ мҶҚм„ұмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ, ML кіөм •м„ұмқҖ мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ кІ°м • мҡ”мқёмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ кө¬мЎ°м Ғ л¶Җм •мқҳлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Zeyu Tang, Alex John London, Atoosa Kasirzadeh, Sarah de Ramirez, Peter Spirtes, Kun Zhang, Sanmi Koyejo","pos":"#3200","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=bDljYd2yzC","abs":"<p>Algorithmic fairness research has largely framed <em>unfairness as discrimination</em> along <em>sensitive attributes</em>. However, this approach limits visibility into <em>unfairness as structural injustice</em> instantiated through <em>social determinants</em>, which are contextual variables that shape attributes and outcomes without pertaining to specific individuals. <strong>This position paper argues that the field should quantify structural injustice via social determinants, beyond sensitive attributes.</strong> Drawing on cross-disciplinary insights, we argue that prevailing technical paradigms fail to adequately capture unfairness as structural injustice, because contexts are potentially treated as noise to be normalized rather than signal to be audited. We further demonstrate the practical urgency of this shift through a theoretical model of college admissions, a demographic study using U.S. census data, and a high-stakes domain application regarding breast cancer screening within an integrated U.S. healthcare system. Our results indicate that mitigation strategies centered solely on sensitive attributes can introduce new forms of structural injustice. We contend that auditing structural injustice through social determinants must precede mitigation, and call for new technical developments that move beyond sensitive-attribute-centered notions of fairness as non-discrimination.</p>","absKo":"<p>algorithmic fairness researchлҠ” мЈјлЎң <em>unfairness</em>лҘј <em>sensitive attribute</em>лҘј л”°лқј лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” <em>discrimination</em>мңјлЎң н”„л Ҳмқҙл°Қн•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јмқҖ нҠ№м • к°ңмқёмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј attributeмҷҖ outcomeмқ„ нҳ•м„ұн•ҳлҠ” contextual variableмқё <em>social determinant</em>лҘј нҶөн•ҙ кө¬нҳ„лҗҳлҠ” <em>unfairness as structural injustice</em>м—җ лҢҖн•ң к°ҖмӢңм„ұмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. <strong>мқҙ position paperлҠ” fieldк°Җ sensitive attributeлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ң, social determinantлҘј нҶөн•ҙ structural injusticeлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ.</strong> мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” көҗм°Ё л¶„м•јмқҳ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, нҳ„н–ү technical paradigmмқҖ contextк°Җ мһ мһ¬м ҒмңјлЎң auditлҗҳм–ҙм•ј н•  signalмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј м •к·ңнҷ”лҗҳм–ҙм•ј н•  noiseлЎң м·Ёкёүлҗҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ, structural injusticeлЎңм„ңмқҳ unfairnessлҘј м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң лҢҖн•ҷ мһ…н•ҷм—җ кҙҖн•ң мқҙлЎ  лӘЁлҚё, U.S. census dataлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң demographic study, к·ёлҰ¬кі  нҶөн•©лҗң U.S. healthcare systemм—җм„ңмқҳ breast cancer screeningмқ„ лӢӨлЈ¬ high-stakes domain applicationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м „нҷҳмқҳ мӢӨмІңм Ғ кёҙкёүм„ұмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” sensitive attributeм—җл§Ң м§‘мӨ‘н•ң mitigation strategyк°Җ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҳ•нғңмқҳ structural injusticeлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” mitigationм—җ м•һм„ң social determinantлҘј нҶөн•ҙ structural injusticeлҘј auditн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, non-discriminationмңјлЎңм„ңмқҳ fairness к°ңл…җмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ technical developmentлҘј мҙүкө¬н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63470","en":"Self-correcting for Debiasing Large Language Models","ko":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё нҺён–Ҙ м ңкұ°лҘј мң„н•ң мһҗк°Җ көҗм •","authors":"Xuan Feng, Shuai Zhao, Luwei Xiao, Tianlong Gu, Bo An","pos":"#3201","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WtP92Qn5eK","abs":"<p>Although Large Language Models (LLMs) demonstrate remarkable reasoning capabilities, inherent social biases often cascade throughout the Chain-of-Thought (CoT) process, leading to continuous \"Bias Propagation\". Existing debiasing methods primarily focus on static constraints or external interventions, failing to identify and interrupt this propagation once triggered. To address this limitation, we introduce Self-Debias, a progressive framework designed to instill intrinsic self-correction capabilities. Specifically, we reformulate the debiasing process as a strategic resource redistribution problem, treating the model's output probability mass as a limited resource to be reallocated from biased heuristics to unbiased reasoning paths. Unlike standard preference optimization which applies broad penalties, Self-Debias employs a fine-grained trajectory-level objective subject to dynamic debiasing constraints. This enables the model to selectively revise biased reasoning suffixes while preserving valid contextual prefixes. Furthermore, we integrate an online self-improvement mechanism utilizing consistency filtering to autonomously synthesize supervision signals. With merely 20k annotated samples, Self-Debias activates efficient self-correction, achieving superior debiasing performance while preserving general reasoning capabilities without continuous external oversight.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs)лҠ” лҶҖлқјмҡҙ reasoning capabilityлҘј ліҙмқҙм§Җл§Ң, лӮҙмһ¬лҗң мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ нҺён–Ҙмқҙ мў…мў… Chain-of-Thought (CoT) кіјм • м „л°ҳмңјлЎң м—°мҮ„м ҒмңјлЎң нҚјм§Җл©° м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё \"Bias Propagation\"мқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ debiasing л°©лІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң м •м Ғмқё м ңм•ҪмқҙлӮҳ мҷёл¶Җ к°ңмһ…м—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”кі  мһҲм–ҙ, н•ң лІҲ мҙүл°ңлҗң м „нҢҢлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі  м°ЁлӢЁн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Self-DebiasлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” intrinsic self-correction capabilityлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң м җм§„м Ғ frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” debiasing кіјм •мқ„ м „лһөм Ғ мһҗмӣҗ мһ¬л¶„л°° л¬ём ңлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, лӘЁлҚёмқҳ output probability massлҘј нҺён–Ҙлҗң heuristicм—җм„ң нҺён–Ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ reasoning pathлЎң мһ¬н• лӢ№н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” м ңн•ңлҗң мһҗмӣҗмңјлЎң ліёлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң penaltyлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ preference optimizationкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, Self-DebiasлҠ” лҸҷм Ғ debiasing constraintлҘј л”°лҘҙлҠ” м„ёл°Җн•ң trajectory-level objectiveлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҖ мң нҡЁн•ң contextual prefixлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң нҺён–Ҙлҗң reasoning suffixлҘј м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң мҲҳм •н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, consistency filteringмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң online self-improvement mechanismмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ supervision signalмқ„ мһҗмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң н•©м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лӢЁ 2л§Ң к°ңмқҳ annotated sampleл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ Self-DebiasлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё self-correctionмқ„ нҷңм„ұнҷ”н•ҳл©°, м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё мҷёл¶Җ к°җлҸ… м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё reasoning capabilityлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң debiasing performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63009","en":"Test-Time Debiasing with Probabilistic Prompts via Wasserstein Distance in Vision-Language Models","ko":"Vision-Language Modelsм—җм„ң Wasserstein Distance кё°л°ҳ Probabilistic PromptsлЎң Test-Time Debiasing","authors":"Chengye Wang, Yuyuan Li, XiaoHua Feng, Xiaolin Zheng, Chaochao Chen","pos":"#3202","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=awggg9j40l","abs":"<p>Vision-Language Models (VLMs) inherit social biases from large-scale pretraining data, and these biases can amplify in downstream tasks, leading to systematic performance disparities across sensitive groups. Due to the high training cost and the risk of catastrophic forgetting, recent research has focused more on lightweight \\emph{test-time} debiasing, aiming to obtain an ideal fair embedding for each query. However, such point-based corrections are often unstable and become notably weaker in multi-class settings, where group structure cannot be adequately captured by a single point. Therefore, we propose W4D, a distributional debiasing framework that reframes fairness as aligning query embedding distributions to group reference distributions under the Wasserstein distance, which provides a geometry-aware notion of discrepancy beyond mean shifts. To make this alignment practical at test-time, W4D introduces probabilistic prompts that induce controlled distributional perturbations and optimizes a Wasserstein-based objective to reduce cross-group disparity while preserving task-relevant semantics. This distributional perspective improves robustness in multi-class debiasing and yields a stronger fairness--utility trade-off across diverse VLM downstream evaluations. Our code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/W4D/.</p>","absKo":"<p>Vision-Language Model(VLM)мқҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ pretraining dataлЎңл¶Җн„° мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ biasлҘј л¬јл Өл°ӣмңјл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң biasлҠ” downstream taskм—җм„ң мҰқнҸӯлҗҳм–ҙ sensitive group к°„ мІҙкі„м Ғмқё м„ұлҠҘ кІ©м°ЁлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. лҶ’мқҖ training costмҷҖ catastrophic forgettingмқҳ мң„н—ҳ л•Ңл¬ём—җ, мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” к°Ғ queryм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мқҙмғҒм Ғмқё fair embeddingмқ„ м–»лҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ҳлҠ” кІҪлҹү \\emph{test-time} debiasingм—җ лҚ” м§‘мӨ‘н•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң point-based correctionмқҖ мў…мў… л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ҳкі , group structureлҘј лӢЁмқј pointлЎңлҠ” м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҸ¬м°©н•  мҲҳ м—ҶлҠ” multi-class settingм—җм„ңлҠ” нҠ№нһҲ м•Ҫн•ҙм§„лӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” W4DлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” fairnessлҘј query embedding distributionмқ„ Wasserstein distance н•ҳм—җм„ң group reference distributionм—җ м •л ¬н•ҳлҠ” кІғмңјлЎң мһ¬м •мқҳн•ҳлҠ” distributional debiasing frameworkлЎң, mean shiftлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„  geometry-aware discrepancy к°ңл…җмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м •л ¬мқ„ test-timeм—җм„ң мӢӨмҡ©м ҒмңјлЎң л§Ңл“Өкё° мң„н•ҙ, W4DлҠ” м ңм–ҙлҗң distributional perturbationмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” probabilistic promptлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , task-relevant semanticмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң cross-group disparityлҘј мӨ„мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ Wasserstein-based objectiveлҘј мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң distributional perspectiveлҠ” multi-class debiasingм—җм„ң robustnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі , лӢӨм–‘н•ң VLM downstream evaluation м „л°ҳм—җм„ң лҚ” к°•н•ң fairness--utility trade-offлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/W4D/ м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61095","en":"Optimal Transport under Group Fairness Constraints","ko":"Group Fairness м ңм•Ҫн•ҳмқҳ Optimal Transport","authors":"Linus Bleistein, Mathieu DagrГ©ou, Francisco Andrade, Thomas Boudou, AurГ©lien Bellet","pos":"#3300","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=tibRKqUHcv","abs":"<p>Ensuring fairness in matching algorithms is a key challenge in allocating scarce resources and positions. Focusing on Optimal Transport (OT), we introduce a novel notion of group fairness requiring that the probability of matching two individuals from any two given groups in the OT plan satisfies a predefined target. We first propose a modified Sinkhorn algorithm to compute perfectly fair transport plans efficiently. Since exact fairness can significantly degrade matching quality in practice, we then develop two relaxation strategies. The first one involves solving a penalized OT problem, for which we derive novel finite-sample complexity guarantees. Our second strategy leverages bilevel optimization to learn a ground cost that induces a fair OT solution, and we establish a bound on the deviation of fairness when matching unseen data. Finally, we present empirical results illustrating the performance of our approaches and the trade-off between fairness and transport cost.</p>","absKo":"<p>л§Өм№ӯ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҳ кіөм •м„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ нқ¬мҶҢн•ң мһҗмӣҗкіј м§Ғмұ…мқ„ л°°л¶„н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҲм–ҙ н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. Optimal Transport (OT)м—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”м–ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” OT planм—җм„ң мһ„мқҳмқҳ л‘җ к·ёлЈ№м—җ мҶҚн•ң л‘җ к°ңмқёмқҙ л§Өм№ӯлҗ  нҷ•лҘ мқҙ мӮ¬м „м—җ м •мқҳлҗң лӘ©н‘ңлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ group fairness к°ңл…җмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лЁјм Җ, мҷ„м „нһҲ кіөм •н•ң transport planмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” modified Sinkhorn algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. м •нҷ•н•ң кіөм •м„ұмқҖ мӢӨм ңлЎң matching qualityлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲмңјлҜҖлЎң, мқҙнӣ„ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ relaxation м „лһөмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мІ« лІҲм§ёлҠ” penalized OT problemмқ„ н‘ёлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҙл©°, мқҙм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ finite-sample complexity guaranteeлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. л‘җ лІҲм§ё м „лһөмқҖ bilevel optimizationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ кіөм •н•ң OT solutionмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” ground costлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ліҙм§Җ лӘ»н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ л§Өм№ӯн•  л•Ң fairnessмқҳ нҺём°Ём—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҒн•ңмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҳ м„ұлҠҘкіј fairnessмҷҖ transport cost мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offлҘј ліҙм—¬мЈјлҠ” мӢӨмҰқ кІ°кіјлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65865","en":"Maximin Relative Improvement: Fair Learning as a Bargaining Problem","ko":"Maximin мғҒлҢҖ к°ңм„ : нҳ‘мғҒ л¬ём ңлЎңм„ңмқҳ кіөм • н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Jiwoo Han, Moulinath Banerjee, Yuekai Sun","pos":"#3301","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9KOJdlFH82","abs":"<p>When deploying a single predictor across multiple subpopulations, we propose a fundamentally different approach: interpreting group fairness as a bargaining problem among subpopulations. This game-theoretic perspective reveals that existing robust optimization methods such as minimizing worst-group loss or regret correspond to classical bargaining solutions and embody different fairness principles. We propose relative improvement, the ratio of actual risk reduction to potential reduction from a baseline predictor, which recovers the KalaiвҖ“Smorodinsky solution. Unlike absolute-scale methods that may not be comparable when groups have different potential predictability, relative improvement provides axiomatic justification including scale invariance and individual monotonicity. We establish finite-sample convergence guarantees under mild conditions.</p>","absKo":"<p>н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ predictorлҘј м—¬лҹ¬ subpopulationм—җ кұёміҗ л°°нҸ¬н•  л•Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к·јліём ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨлҘё м ‘к·јмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. group fairnessлҘј subpopulation к°„ bargaining problemмңјлЎң н•ҙм„қн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң game-theoretic кҙҖм җмқҖ worst-group lossлӮҳ regretмқ„ мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ robust optimization л°©лІ•мқҙ кі м „м Ғмқё bargaining solutionм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳл©° м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё fairness principleмқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” relative improvementлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” baseline predictorлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ мһ мһ¬м Ғ к°җмҶҢлҹүм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨм ң risk к°җмҶҢлҹүмқҳ л№„мңЁмқҙл©°, KalaiвҖ“Smorodinsky solutionмқ„ нҡҢліөн•ңлӢӨ. м§‘лӢЁл§ҲлӢӨ мһ мһ¬м Ғ мҳҲмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ лӢӨлҘј л•Ң л№„көҗ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” absolute-scale л°©лІ•кіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, relative improvementлҠ” scale invarianceмҷҖ individual monotonicityлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң axiomatic justificationмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҳЁкұҙн•ң мЎ°кұҙн•ҳм—җм„ң finite-sample convergence guaranteeлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60878","en":"MAFE: Enabling Equitable Algorithm Design in Multi-Agent Multi-Stage Decision-Making Systems","ko":"MAFE: Multi-Agent Multi-Stage мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ң кіөм •н•ң м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ м„Өкі„ м§Җмӣҗ","authors":"Zachary Lazri, Anirudh Nakra, Ivan Brugere, Danial Dervovic, Antigoni Polychroniadou, Furong Huang, Dana Dachman-Soled, Min Wu","pos":"#3302","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=viOFFYQPgL","abs":"<p>Algorithmic fairness is often studied in static or single-agent settings, yet many real-world decision-making systems involve multiple interacting entities whose multi-stage actions jointly influence long-term outcomes. Existing fairness methods applied at isolated decision points frequently fail to mitigate disparities that accumulate over time. Although recent work has modeled fairness as a sequential decision-making problem, it typically assumes centralized agents or simplified dynamics, limiting its applicability to complex social systems. We introduce <strong>MAFE</strong>, a suite of <em>Multi-Agent Fair Environments</em> designed to simulate realistic, modular, and dynamic systems in which fairness emerges from the interplay of multiple agents. We demonstrate MAFEs in three domainsвҖ”loan processing, healthcare, and higher educationвҖ”supporting heterogeneous agents, configurable interventions, and fairness metrics. The environments are open-source and compatible with standard multi-agent reinforcement learning (MARL) libraries, enabling reproducible evaluation of fairness-aware policies. Through extensive experiments on cooperative use cases, we demonstrate how MAFE facilitates the design of equitable multi-agent algorithms and reveals critical trade-offs between fairness, performance, and coordination. MAFE provides a foundation for systematic progress in dynamic, multi-agent fairness research.</p>","absKo":"<p>algorithmic fairnessлҠ” мў…мў… staticн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ single-agent м„Өм •м—җм„ң м—°кө¬лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ң м„ёкі„мқҳ мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” entityк°Җ multi-stage actionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мһҘкё°м Ғмқё кІ°кіјм—җ кіөлҸҷмңјлЎң мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. к°ңлі„ decision pointм—җ м Ғмҡ©лҗҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ fairness л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ мӢңк°„мқҙ м§ҖлӮҳл©° лҲ„м ҒлҗҳлҠ” disparityлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мһҗмЈј мӢӨнҢЁн•ңлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” fairnessлҘј sequential decision-making problemмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖмІҙлЎң centralized agentлӮҳ лӢЁмҲңнҷ”лҗң dynamicsлҘј к°Җм •н•ҳм—¬ ліөмһЎн•ң мӮ¬нҡҢ мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ м ңн•ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кіөм •м„ұмқҙ м—¬лҹ¬ agentмқҳ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң emergentн•ҳкІҢ лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқҙкі  modularн•ҳл©° dynamicн•ң мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң <strong>MAFE</strong>, мҰү <em>Multi-Agent Fair Environments</em> лӘЁмқҢмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” loan processing, healthcare, higher educationмқҳ м„ё лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ң heterogenous agent, configurable intervention, fairness metricмқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” MAFEлҘј мӢңм—°н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ нҷҳкІҪл“ӨмқҖ open-sourceмқҙл©° н‘ңмӨҖ multi-agent reinforcement learning (MARL) libraryмҷҖ нҳёнҷҳлҗҳм–ҙ, fairness-aware policyмқҳ мһ¬нҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. cooperative use caseм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” MAFEк°Җ кіөм •н•ң multi-agent algorithm м„Өкі„лҘј мҙүм§„н•ҳкі  fairness, performance, coordination мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң trade-offлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лғ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. MAFEлҠ” dynamic, multi-agent fairness м—°кө¬мқҳ мІҙкі„м Ғ м§„м „мқ„ мң„н•ң кё°л°ҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63248","en":"Long-term Fairness with Selective Labels","ko":"м„ нғқм Ғ л Ҳмқҙлё”мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң мһҘкё° кіөм •м„ұ","authors":"Giovani Valdrighi, Isabel Valera, Marcos M. Raimundo","pos":"#3303","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Ykdbje3SDK","abs":"<p>Long-term fairness algorithms aim to satisfy fairness beyond static and short-term notions by accounting for the dynamics between decision-making policies and population behavior. Most previous approaches evaluate performance and fairness measures from observable features and a label, which is assumed to be fully observed. However, in scenarios such as hiring or lending, the labels (e.g., ability to repay the loan) are <em>selective labels</em> as they are only revealed based on positive decisions (e.g., when a loan is granted). In this paper, we study long-term fairness in the selective labels setting, and analytically show that naive solutions do not guarantee fairness. To address this gap, we then introduce a novel framework that leverages both the observed data and a label predictor model to estimate the true fairness measure value by decomposing it into the observed fairness and bias from label predictions. This allows us to derive the sufficient conditions to satisfy true fairness from observable quantities by using the confidence in the predictor model. Finally, we rely on our theoretical results to propose a novel reinforcement learning algorithm for effective long-term fair decision-making with selective labels. In semisynthetic environments, the proposed algorithm reached comparable fairness and performance to an agent with oracle access to the true labels.</p>","absKo":"<p>мһҘкё° кіөм •м„ұ(long-term fairness) м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • м •мұ…кіј м§‘лӢЁ н–үлҸҷ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷмқ„ кі л Өн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, м •м Ғмқҙкі  лӢЁкё°м Ғмқё кіөм •м„ұ к°ңл…җмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ кіөм •м„ұмқ„ л§ҢмЎұмӢңнӮӨкі мһҗ н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ м ‘к·јмқҖ кҙҖмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң featureмҷҖ labelлЎңл¶Җн„° м„ұлҠҘкіј кіөм •м„ұ м§Җн‘ңлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙ labelмқҖ мҷ„м „нһҲ кҙҖмёЎлҗңлӢӨкі  к°Җм •лҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мұ„мҡ©мқҙлӮҳ лҢҖм¶ң к°ҷмқҖ мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨм—җм„ңлҠ” label(мҳҲ: лҢҖм¶ң мғҒнҷҳ лҠҘл Ҙ)мқҙ <em>selective labels</em>мқҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” positive decision(мҳҲ: лҢҖм¶ң мҠ№мқё)мқҙ лӮҙл Өм§„ кІҪмҡ°м—җл§Ң л“ңлҹ¬лӮңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” selective labels м„Өм •м—җм„ңмқҳ long-term fairnessлҘј м—°кө¬н•ҳкі , лӢЁмҲңн•ң н•ҙлІ•мқҙ кіөм •м„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•Ёмқ„ н•ҙм„қм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кҙҖмёЎ лҚ°мқҙн„°мҷҖ label predictor modelмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ м§„м§ң кіөм •м„ұ м§Җн‘ң к°’мқ„ м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙл•Ң кіөм •м„ұ м§Җн‘ңлҘј кҙҖмёЎлҗң fairnessмҷҖ label predictionм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗң biasлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ predictor modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң confidenceлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, кҙҖмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м–‘мңјлЎңл¶Җн„° true fairnessлҘј л§ҢмЎұмӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ң м¶©л¶„мЎ°кұҙмқ„ мң лҸ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң selective labels нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё мһҘкё° кіөм • мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м •мқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ reinforcement learning algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Semisynthetic environmentм—җм„ң м ңм•Ҳн•ң м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ true labelм—җ лҢҖн•ң oracle accessлҘј к°Җм§„ agentмҷҖ л№„мҠ·н•ң мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ кіөм •м„ұкіј м„ұлҠҘм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н–ҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62706","en":"HoloFair: Unified T2I Fairness Evaluation and Fair-GRPO Debiasing","ko":"HoloFair: нҶөн•© T2I Fairness нҸүк°ҖмҷҖ Fair-GRPO Debiasing","authors":"Ruyi Chen, Xiaogang Xu, Chiyu Zhang, Jiafei Wu, Liming Fang, Lu Zhou","pos":"#3304","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=e26lNHXxgs","abs":"<p>Text-to-Image (T2I) models have made significant strides in visual realism and semantic consistency, yet they often perpetuate and amplify societal biases. Existing evaluation methods typically address only single-dimensional biases, lacking perspectives to uncover model biases at social-related deeper semantic levels. We introduce HoloFair, a comprehensive benchmark framework for multidimensional demographic bias analysis. Built upon our large-scale fairness-oriented dataset and the SpaFreq (Spatial-Frequency) attribute classifier, this framework proposes the Multi-attribute, Group-wise Bias Index (MGBI) metric, designed to assess both intrinsic diversity and conditional biases. Beyond evaluation, we further introduce Fair-GRPO, a reinforcement-learning-based debiasing method that alters the distribution of generative models through a designed multi-objective reward function. E.g., experiments on the SD3.5-Medium model demonstrate that Fair-GRPO significantly improves multidimensional fairness while maintaining high image quality. We also analyze potential reward hacking phenomena and provide corresponding mitigation strategies.</p>","absKo":"<p>Text-to-Image(T2I) modelмқҖ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ мӮ¬мӢӨм„ұкіј мқҳлҜём Ғ мқјкҙҖм„ұм—җм„ң нҒ° м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈЁм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ нҺён–Ҙмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚмӢңнӮӨкі  мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ л§ҺлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ нҸүк°Җ л°©лІ•мқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң лӢЁмқј м°Ёмӣҗмқҳ нҺён–Ҙл§Ңмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁл©°, мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ кҙҖл Ём„ұмқҙ мһҲлҠ” лҚ” к№ҠмқҖ semantic levelм—җм„ң лӘЁлҚё нҺён–Ҙмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮј кҙҖм җмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢӨм°Ёмӣҗ demographic bias л¶„м„қмқ„ мң„н•ң мў…н•© benchmark frameworkмқё HoloFairлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ fairness-oriented datasetкіј SpaFreq(Spatial-Frequency) attribute classifier мң„м—җ кө¬м¶•лҗң мқҙ frameworkлҠ” intrinsic diversityмҷҖ conditional biasлҘј лӘЁл‘җ нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң Multi-attribute, Group-wise Bias Index(MGBI) metricмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. нҸүк°ҖлҘј л„ҳм–ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ л¶„нҸ¬лҘј м„Өкі„лҗң multi-objective reward functionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ ліҖнҷ”мӢңнӮӨлҠ” reinforcement-learning-based debiasing methodмқё Fair-GRPOлҸ„ мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, SD3.5-Medium modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ Fair-GRPOк°Җ лҶ’мқҖ image qualityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң multidimensional fairnessлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮҙмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң potential reward hacking нҳ„мғҒмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ҳкі  мқҙм—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” мҷ„нҷ” м „лһөмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65528","en":"Fairness in Aggregation: Optimal Top-$k$ and Improved Full Ranking","ko":"м§‘кі„м—җм„ңмқҳ кіөм •м„ұ: мөңм Ғ Top-kмҷҖ к°ңм„ лҗң м „мІҙ лһӯнӮ№","authors":"Alvin Hong Yao Yan, Diptarka Chakraborty, Arya Mazumdar, Barna Saha","pos":"#3305","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CeyNBFDCdB","abs":"Ensuring fairness in algorithmic ranking systems is a critical challenge with significant societal implications for hiring, recommendations, web search, and data management. Standard methods for aggregating multiple preference orders into a consensus ranking may perpetuate and even amplify the lack of representation of underrepresented groups. To address this, recent research has focused on incorporating fairness constraints to ensure the presence of different groups in the top-$k$ positions of the final aggregate ranking.   We study two fairness-aware variants under the well-known Spearman footrule, which corresponds to the $L_1$ distance between rankings. First, we address the practically salient task of computing a fair aggregate top-$k$ ranking -- crucial in settings like recommendations and hiring where selection is primarily based on the top-$k$ results -- and present the first optimal algorithm for this problem. Second, we consider fair (full) rank aggregation over all candidates (not specifically on top-$k$). We already know of a $3$-approximation for this fair rank aggregation variant (Wei et al., SIGMODвҖҷ22; Chakraborty et al., NeurIPSвҖҷ22), whereas an exact algorithm exists for the corresponding unconstrained (unfair) version (Dwork et al., WWWвҖҷ01). Closing the computational gap between fair and unconstrained rank aggregation has remained a tantalizing open problem. We make significant progress by giving a $2$-approximation algorithm for fair (full) rank aggregation, improving substantially over the previous $3$-approximation. Further, we complement our theoretical contributions with experiments on different real-world datasets, which corroborate our theoretical results and demonstrate strong empirical performance relative to state-of-the-art baselines.","absKo":"м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳм Ғ ranking мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ң кіөм •м„ұмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ мұ„мҡ©, м¶”мІң, мӣ№ кІҖмғү, лҚ°мқҙн„° кҙҖлҰ¬м—җ нҒ° мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ н•ЁмқҳлҘј к°–лҠ” н•өмӢ¬ кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ preference orderлҘј consensus rankingмңјлЎң м§‘кі„н•ҳлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ л°©лІ•мқҖ лҢҖн‘ңм„ұмқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң м§‘лӢЁмқҳ л¶ҖмЎұн•Ёмқ„ м§ҖмҶҚмӢңнӮӨкі  мӢ¬м§Җм–ҙ мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мөңк·ј м—°кө¬лҠ” мөңмў… aggregate rankingмқҳ top-$k$ мң„м№ҳм—җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё м§‘лӢЁмқҙ нҸ¬н•ЁлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ fairness constraintsлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мЈјлӘ©н•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ranking к°„мқҳ $L_1$ distanceм—җ н•ҙлӢ№н•ҳлҠ” мһҳ м•Ңл Өм§„ Spearman footrule н•ҳм—җм„ң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ fairness-aware ліҖнҳ•мқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, м¶”мІңкіј мұ„мҡ©мІҳлҹј м„ нғқмқҙ мЈјлЎң top-$k$ кІ°кіјм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳлҠ” нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң нҠ№нһҲ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң fair aggregate top-$k$ rankingмқ„ кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м ҒмңјлЎң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң кіјм ңлҘј лӢӨлЈЁл©°, мқҙ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ optimal algorithmмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, лӘЁл“  нӣ„ліҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң fair (full) rank aggregationмқ„ кі л Өн•ңлӢӨ(top-$k$м—җл§Ң көӯн•ңлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҢ). мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҜё мқҙ fair rank aggregation ліҖнҳ•м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ $3$-approximationмқҙ м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲмңјл©°(Wei et al., SIGMODвҖҷ22; Chakraborty et al., NeurIPSвҖҷ22), л°ҳл©ҙ лҢҖмқ‘лҗҳлҠ” unconstrained(мҰү, unfair) лІ„м „м—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” exact algorithmмқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨ(Dwork et al., WWWвҖҷ01). fairмҷҖ unconstrained rank aggregation мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ кі„мӮ°м Ғ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°лҠ” л¬ём ңлҠ” мҳӨлһ«лҸҷм•Ҳ л§Өл Ҙм Ғмқё м—ҙлҰ° л¬ём ңлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲм—ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” fair (full) rank aggregationм—җ лҢҖн•ң $2$-approximation algorithmмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ л¬ём ңм—җ нҒ° м§„м „мқ„ мқҙлЈЁм—Ҳкі , мқҙлҠ” кё°мЎҙмқҳ $3$-approximationмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ кё°м—¬лҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳкі , state-of-the-art baseline лҢҖл№„ к°•л Ҙн•ң мӢӨмҰқм Ғ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61937","en":"FairSSL: Fair Multimodal Self-Supervised Learning","ko":"FairSSL: кіөм •н•ң л©ҖнӢ°лӘЁлӢ¬ мһҗкё°м§ҖлҸ„н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Jiaee Cheong, Abtin Mogharabin, Paul Pu Liang, Hatice Gunes, Sinan Kalkan","pos":"#3306","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lXFl4K74gX","abs":"<p>Multimodal Self-Supervised Learning (SSL) has achieved remarkable success by learning representations from multiple views of data. However, prevalent methods rely on the redundancy assumptionвҖ”that different views share substantial task-relevant information. We argue that this assumption fails in complex, real-world settings characterized by heterogeneity (e.g., variable-length healthcare or behavioral data), where enforcing strict alignment can discard unique, modality-specific signals and inadvertently amplify bias.  In this work, we propose FairSSL, a framework that leverages data heterogeneity as a resource for fairness rather than a hindrance. Unlike standard contrastive approaches, FairSSL uses a subject-aware Variance-Invariance-Covariance Regularization objective, where alignment is enforced across segments drawn from the same subject. We introduce a segment-based pooling strategy to handle variable-length modalities, and we regularize representations to encourage (i) sufficient within-subject variability, (ii) cross-modal and cross-subject invariance, and (iii) representation decorrelation. Theoretical analysis shows that our objective bounds the score gap between protected groups. Empirically, FairSSL significantly outperforms existing baselines on heterogeneous multimodal datasets, improving fairness without sacrificing downstream predictive performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Multimodal Self-Supervised Learning(SSL)мқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ viewмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ҙ representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м„ұкіөмқ„ кұ°л‘җм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ л„җлҰ¬ м“°мқҙлҠ” л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё viewк°Җ taskмҷҖ кҙҖл Ёлҗң м •ліҙлҘј мғҒлӢ№ л¶Җл¶„ кіөмң н•ңлӢӨлҠ” redundancy assumptionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ к°Җм •мқҙ мқҙм§Ҳм„ұ(мҳҲ: к°ҖліҖ кёёмқҙмқҳ healthcare лҳҗлҠ” behavioral data)мңјлЎң нҠ№м§•м§Җм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң мӢӨм ң нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ңлҠ” м„ұлҰҪн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, м—„кІ©н•ң alignmentлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳл©ҙ кі мң н•ң modality-specific signalмқҙ мӮ¬лқјм§Җкі  мқҳлҸ„м№ҳ м•ҠкІҢ biasк°Җ мҰқнҸӯлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„° мқҙм§Ҳм„ұмқ„ мһҘм• л¬јмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј кіөм •м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мһҗмӣҗмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ FairSSLмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖ contrastive approachмҷҖ лӢ¬лҰ¬, FairSSLмқҖ к°ҷмқҖ subjectм—җм„ң м¶”м¶ңн•ң segmentл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң alignmentлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ” subject-aware Variance-Invariance-Covariance Regularization objectiveлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°ҖліҖ кёёмқҙ modalityлҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ segment-based pooling м „лһөмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , (i) subject лӮҙл¶Җм—җм„ң м¶©л¶„н•ң ліҖлҸҷм„ұ, (ii) cross-modal л°Ҹ cross-subject invariance, (iii) representation decorrelationмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ representationмқ„ regularizeн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ objectiveк°Җ protected group к°„ score gapмқ„ мғҒн•ңн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң FairSSLмқҖ мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё multimodal datasetм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, downstream predictive performanceлҘј нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң кіөм •м„ұмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63216","en":"FairRARI: A Plug and Play Framework for Fairness-Aware PageRank","ko":"FairRARI: кіөм •м„ұ мқём§Җ PageRankлҘј мң„н•ң н”Ңлҹ¬к·ё м•Ө н”Ңл Ҳмқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Emmanouil Kariotakis, Aritra Konar","pos":"#3307","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Z2axjFEPH3","abs":"<p>PageRank (PR) is a fundamental algorithm in graph machine learning tasks. Owing to the increasing importance of algorithmic fairness, we consider the problem of computing PR vectors subject to various group-fairness criteria based on sensitive attributes of the vertices. At present, principled algorithms for this problem are lacking -  some cannot guarantee that a target fairness level is achieved, while others do not feature optimality guarantees. In order to overcome these shortcomings, we put forth a unified in-processing convex optimization framework, termed FairRARI, for tackling different group-fairness criteria in a ``plug and play'' fashion. Leveraging a variational formulation of PR, the framework computes fair PR vectors by solving a strongly convex optimization problem with fairness constraints, thereby ensuring that a target fairness level is achieved. We further introduce three different fairness criteria which can be efficiently tackled using FairRARI to compute fair PR vectors with the same asymptotic time-complexity as the original PR algorithm. Extensive experiments on real-world datasets showcase that FairRARI outperforms existing methods in terms of utility, while achieving the desired fairness levels across multiple vertex groups; thereby highlighting its effectiveness.</p>","absKo":"<p>PageRank(PR)лҠ” graph machine learning taskмқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙлӢӨ. algorithmic fairnessмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқҙ м»Өм§җм—җ л”°лқј, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” vertexмқҳ sensitive attributeм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң group-fairness criterionмқ„ л§ҢмЎұн•ҳлҠ” PR vectorлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј кі л Өн•ңлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј мң„н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ л¶ҖмЎұн•ңлҚ°, м–ҙл–Ө л°©лІ•мқҖ лӘ©н‘ң fairness мҲҳмӨҖмқҙ лӢ¬м„ұлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі , лӢӨлҘё л°©лІ•мқҖ optimality guaranteeлҘј к°–м¶”м§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лӢЁм җмқ„ к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё group-fairness criterionмқ„ ``plug and play'' л°©мӢқмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈ° мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” нҶөн•©м Ғ in-processing convex optimization frameworkмқё FairRARIлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. PRмқҳ variational formulationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” fairness constraintк°Җ мһҲлҠ” strongly convex optimization л¬ём ңлҘј н’Җм–ҙ fair PR vectorлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ лӘ©н‘ң fairness мҲҳмӨҖмқҙ лӢ¬м„ұлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FairRARIлЎң нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈ° мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” м„ё к°Җм§Җ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё fairness criterionмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мӣҗлһҳ PR algorithmкіј лҸҷмқјн•ң asymptotic time complexityлЎң fair PR vectorлҘј кі„мӮ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FairRARIк°Җ м—¬лҹ¬ vertex groupм—җ кұёміҗ мӣҗн•ҳлҠ” fairness мҲҳмӨҖмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң utility мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, к·ё нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63321","en":"FairGB: A Fair Granular-Ball Generation Method for Data Classification","ko":"FairGB: лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶„лҘҳлҘј мң„н•ң кіөм •н•ң Granular-Ball мғқм„ұ л°©лІ•","authors":"Qifen Yang, Yuhui Deng, Jiande Huang, Peng Zhou, Xiwen Lu, Lin Cui","pos":"#3308","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Y6zDYJcxM0","abs":"With the widespread application of data-driven classifiers in high-risk domains, group fairness has increasingly become a key research focus. However, most existing methods rely on model constraints or data reweighting, which often suffer from limited interpretability and may distort the original data distribution. Granular-ball computing (GBC), as a structured and highly interpretable learning framework, provides a natural foundation for incorporating group fairness into the data partitioning process. Building on this insight, we first propose a $\\textbf{Fair}$ $\\textbf{G}$ranular-$\\textbf{B}$all $\\textbf{G}$eneration framework (FairGBG), which employs the fair clustering algorithm to ensure a balanced proportion of sensitive groups within each granular-ball (GB) during its construction, aiming to enhance within-ball group fairness. Theoretical analysis shows that FairGBG preserves high purity within each GB while satisfying group fairness. Furthermore, we introduce a $\\textbf{Fair} \\textbf{G}$ranular-$\\textbf{B}$all-based $\\textbf{F}$air data $\\textbf{C}$lassification method (FairGBFC), which enhances classification fairness by leveraging group fairness within GBs. Experimental results on multiple benchmark datasets demonstrate that, compared to existing methods, FairGBFC significantly improves classification fairness while maintaining competitive accuracy. Notably, FairGBFC exhibits superior classification performance compared to standard GB-based methods across all benchmark datasets. Furthermore, compared with state-of-the-art fairness-aware baselines, it achieves a superior trade-off between accuracy and fairness, effectively mitigating bias while preserving high utility.","absKo":"кі мң„н—ҳ лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ң data-driven classifierмқҳ м Ғмҡ©мқҙ л„җлҰ¬ нҷ•мӮ°лҗҳл©ҙм„ң, group fairnessлҠ” м җм җ лҚ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м—°кө¬ мЈјм ңк°Җ лҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ model constraintлӮҳ data reweightingм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” мў…мў… н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ м ңн•ңлҗҳкі  мӣҗлһҳмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶„нҸ¬лҘј мҷңкіЎн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. Granular-ball computing (GBC)мқҖ кө¬мЎ°нҷ”лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲкі  н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ н•ҷмҠө н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лЎңм„ң, data partitioning кіјм •м—җ group fairnessлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ кё°л°ҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЁјм Җ $\\textbf{Fair}$ $\\textbf{G}$ranular-$\\textbf{B}$all $\\textbf{G}$eneration framework(FairGBG)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” fair clustering algorithmмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ к°Ғ granular-ball(GB) кө¬м„ұ мӢң лҜјк°җ м§‘лӢЁмқҳ л№„мңЁмқҙ к· нҳ•мқ„ мқҙлЈЁлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ ball лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ group fairnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ FairGBGк°Җ к°Ғ GB лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ лҶ’мқҖ purityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ group fairnessлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” $\\textbf{Fair} \\textbf{G}$ranular-$\\textbf{B}$all-based $\\textbf{F}$air data $\\textbf{C}$lassification method(FairGBFC)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ GB лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ group fairnessлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ classification fairnessлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmark datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“Өкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ FairGBFCлҠ” кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң classification fairnessлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ FairGBFCлҠ” лӘЁл“  benchmark datasetм—җм„ң н‘ңмӨҖ GB кё°л°ҳ л°©лІ•ліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң classification м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мөңмӢ  fairness-aware baselineкіј л№„көҗн•ҙлҸ„ accuracyмҷҖ fairness мӮ¬мқҙм—җм„ң лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң trade-offлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬, лҶ’мқҖ utilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң biasлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63370","en":"Fair Decisions from Calibrated Scores: Achieving Optimal Classification While Satisfying Sufficiency","ko":"ліҙм •лҗң м җмҲҳлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ кіөм •н•ң кІ°м •: м¶©л¶„м„ұмқ„ л§ҢмЎұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң мөңм Ғ л¶„лҘҳ лӢ¬м„ұ","authors":"Etam Benger, Katrina Ligett","pos":"#3309","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XiD5RhcEDK","abs":"<p>Binary classification based on predicted probabilities (scores) is a fundamental task in supervised machine learning. While thresholding scores is Bayes-optimal in the unconstrained setting, using a single threshold generally violates statistical group fairness constraints. Under independence (statistical parity) and separation (equalized odds), such thresholding suffices when the scores already satisfy the corresponding criterion. However, this does not extend to sufficiency: even perfectly group-calibrated scores---including true class probabilities---violate predictive parity after thresholding. In this work, we present an exact solution for optimal binary (randomized) classification under sufficiency, assuming finite sets of group-calibrated scores. We provide a geometric characterization of the feasible pairs of positive predictive value (PPV) and false omission rate (FOR) achievable by such classifiers, and use it to derive a simple post-processing algorithm that attains the optimal classifier using only group-calibrated scores and group membership. Finally, since sufficiency and separation are generally incompatible, we identify the classifier that minimizes deviation from separation subject to sufficiency, and show that it can also be obtained by our algorithm, often achieving performance comparable to the optimum.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҳҲмёЎ нҷ•лҘ (score)м—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң binary classificationмқҖ supervised machine learningмқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. scoreлҘј thresholdingн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м ңм•Ҫмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” м„Өм •м—җм„ңлҠ” Bayes-optimalмқҙм§Җл§Ң, лӢЁмқј thresholdлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөкі„м Ғ group fairness м ңм•Ҫмқ„ мң„л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. independence(statistical parity)мҷҖ separation(equalized odds) н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ”, scoreк°Җ мқҙлҜё н•ҙлӢ№ кё°мӨҖмқ„ л§ҢмЎұн•  л•Ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң thresholdingмқҙ м¶©л¶„н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҠ” sufficiencyлЎңлҠ” нҷ•мһҘлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. true class probabilityлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҙ group-calibratedк°Җ мҷ„лІҪн•ң scoreмЎ°м°Ё thresholding нӣ„м—җлҠ” predictive parityлҘј мң„л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мң н•ңн•ң group-calibrated score м§‘н•©мқ„ к°Җм •н•  л•Ң, sufficiency н•ҳм—җм„ң мөңм Ғмқҳ binary(randomized) classificationм—җ лҢҖн•ң м •нҷ•н•ң н•ҙлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң classifierк°Җ лӢ¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” positive predictive value(PPV)мҷҖ false omission rate(FOR) мҢҚмқҳ feasible regionмқ„ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм ҒмңјлЎң нҠ№м§•м§“кі , мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң group-calibrated scoreмҷҖ group membershipл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мөңм Ғ classifierлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” к°„лӢЁн•ң post-processing algorithmмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, sufficiencyмҷҖ separationмқҙ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң м–‘лҰҪ л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” sufficiencyлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң separationмңјлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ нҺём°ЁлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” classifierлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , к·ёкІғ м—ӯмӢң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ algorithmмңјлЎң м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©° мў…мў… мөңм Ғн•ҙм—җ мӨҖн•ҳлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66601","en":"Fair Dataset Distillation via Cross-Group Barycenter Alignment","ko":"көҗм°Ё к·ёлЈ№ л¬ҙкІҢмӨ‘мӢ¬ м •л ¬мқ„ нҶөн•ң кіөм • лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ мҰқлҘҳ","authors":"Mohammad Hossein Moslemi, Nima Hosseini Dashtbayaz, Zhimin Mei, Boyu Wang, Bissan Ghaddar","pos":"#3310","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2FU8PSmu9Z","abs":"<p>Dataset Distillation aims to compress a large dataset into a small synthetic one while maintaining predictive performance.  We show that as different demographic groups exhibit distinct predictive patterns, the distillation process struggles to simultaneously preserve informative signals for all subgroups, regardless of whether group sizes are mildly or severely imbalanced. Consequently, models trained on distilled data can experience substantial performance drops for certain subgroups, leading to fairness gaps. Crucially, these gaps do not disappear by merely correcting group imbalance, since they stem from fundamental mismatches in subgroup predictive patterns rather than from sample-size disparities alone. We therefore formally analyze the interaction between these two sources of bias and cast the solution as identifying a group-imbalance-agnostic barycenter of the predictive information that induces similar representations across all subgroups. By distilling toward this shared aggregate representation, we show that group fairness concerns can be reduced. Our approach is compatible with existing distillation methods, and empirical results show that it substantially reduces bias introduced by dataset distillation.</p>","absKo":"<p>Dataset DistillationмқҖ мҳҲмёЎ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ datasetмқ„ мһ‘мқҖ synthetic datasetмңјлЎң м••м¶•н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё demographic groupмқҙ м„ңлЎң кө¬лі„лҗҳлҠ” predictive patternмқ„ ліҙмқј л•Ң, distillation кіјм •мқҙ group нҒ¬кё°к°Җ м•Ҫн•ҳкІҢ л¶Ҳк· нҳ•н•ҳл“  мӢ¬н•ҳкІҢ л¶Ҳк· нҳ•н•ҳл“  мғҒкҙҖм—Ҷмқҙ лӘЁл“  subgroupм—җ мң мҡ©н•ң мӢ нҳёлҘј лҸҷмӢңм—җ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј distilled dataлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң лӘЁлҚёмқҖ нҠ№м • subgroupм—җм„ң мғҒлӢ№н•ң м„ұлҠҘ м Җн•ҳлҘј кІӘмқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” fairness gapмңјлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м җмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң gapмқҙ лӢЁмҲңнһҲ group imbalanceлҘј ліҙм •н•ҳлҠ” кІғл§ҢмңјлЎңлҠ” мӮ¬лқјм§Җм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҷңлғҗн•ҳл©ҙ к·ё к·јмӣҗмқҖ sample-size disparityл§Ңмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј subgroup predictive patternмқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳм—җ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л‘җ мў…лҘҳмқҳ bias к°„ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқ„ нҳ•мӢқм ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•ҳкі , лӘЁл“  subgroupм—җм„ң мң мӮ¬н•ң representationмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” predictive informationмқҳ group-imbalance-agnostic barycenterлҘј м°ҫлҠ” л¬ём ңлЎң н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кіөмң  aggregate representationмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҙ distillн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ group fairness concernsлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ кё°мЎҙ distillation л°©лІ•кіј нҳёнҷҳлҗҳл©°, мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” dataset distillationмқҙ мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ” biasлҘј мғҒлӢ№нһҲ мӨ„мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61883","en":"Fair Classification with Efficient and Post-hoc Controllable Fairness-Accuracy Trade-off","ko":"нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  мӮ¬нӣ„ м ңм–ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң Fairness-Accuracy Trade-offлҘј к°–лҠ” кіөм • л¶„лҘҳ","authors":"Maaya Sakata, Kazuto Fukuchi","pos":"#3311","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=lyN8OMVyMt","abs":"<p>Post-hoc controllability of fair machine learning models, the ability to control the trade-off between fairness and accuracy after training, is valuable for practical deployment. Existing post-processing methods provide such post-hoc controllability but often suffer from significant accuracy degradation, whereas in-processing methods achieve efficient trade-offs but require computationally expensive retraining for each change in trade-off ratio. To achieve both post-hoc controllability and efficient trade-offs, we propose a novel fair classification algorithm that learns effective feature representations to improve the trade-off efficiency of post-processing fair classifiers, by a gradient-based optimization approach. Experimental results on real-world datasets demonstrate that our method achieves trade-off efficiency comparable to, or even surpassing, in-processing methods, without requiring any retraining.</p>","absKo":"<p>fair machine learning modelмқҳ post-hoc controllability, мҰү н•ҷмҠө нӣ„ fairnessмҷҖ accuracy к°„ trade-offлҘј мЎ°м Ҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лҠҘл ҘмқҖ мӢӨм „ л°°м№ҳм—җм„ң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ post-processing л°©лІ•мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң post-hoc controllabilityлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң мў…мў… мғҒлӢ№н•ң accuracy м Җн•ҳлҘј кІӘлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, in-processing л°©лІ•мқҖ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё trade-offлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң trade-off л№„мңЁмқҙ л°”лҖ” л•Ңл§ҲлӢӨ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° мһ¬н•ҷмҠөмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ңлӢӨ. post-hoc controllabilityмҷҖ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё trade-offлҘј лӘЁл‘җ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” gradient-based optimization м ‘к·јмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё feature representationмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳм—¬ post-processing fair classifierмқҳ trade-off нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ fair classification algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ мһ¬н•ҷмҠө м—Ҷмқҙ in-processing л°©лІ•кіј лҸҷл“ұн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мӢ¬м§Җм–ҙ мқҙлҘј лҠҘк°Җн•ҳлҠ” trade-off нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66564","en":"Extending Fair Null-Space Projections for Continuous Attributes to Kernel Methods","ko":"м—°мҶҚ мҶҚм„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң кіөм • мҳҒкіөк°„ нҲ¬мҳҒмқ„ м»Өл„җ л°©лІ•мңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳкё°","authors":"Felix StГ¶rck, Fabian Hinder, CITEC Barbara Hammer","pos":"#3312","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2Z7ZvoRN8Z","abs":"<p>With the on-going integration of machine learning systems into the  everyday social life of millions the notion of fairness becomes an ever increasing priority in their development.  Fairness notions commonly rely on protected attributes to assess potential biases.  Here, the majority of literature focuses on discrete setups regarding both target and protected attributes. The literature on continuous attributes especially in conjunction with regression - we refer to this as <em>continuous fairness</em> - is scarce.  A common strategy is iterative null-space projection which as of now has only been explored for linear models or embeddings such as obtained by a non-linear encoder.  We improve on this by extending this to kernel induced feature spaces by means of the ``empirical feature space''. We theoretically derive this as a direct transformation of the kernel matrix yielding a model and fairness-score agnostic method applicable to continuous protected attributes. We demonstrate that our novel approach in conjunction with Support Vector Regression (SVR) provides competitive or improved performance across multiple datasets in comparisons to other contemporary methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҲҳл§ҺмқҖ мӮ¬лһҢл“Өмқҳ мқјмғҒ мӮ¬нҡҢмғқнҷң мҶҚмңјлЎң machine learning systemмқҙ м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©лҗҳл©ҙм„ң, fairness к°ңл…җмқҖ к·ё к°ңл°ң кіјм •м—җм„ң м җм җ лҚ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мҡ°м„ мҲңмң„к°Җ лҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. Fairness к°ңл…җмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мһ мһ¬м Ғ biasлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ protected attributeм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬ л¬ён—Ңмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ target attributeмҷҖ protected attribute лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ discrete setupм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ regressionкіј кІ°н•©лҗң continuous attributeм—җ лҢҖн•ң м—°кө¬, мҰү <em>continuous fairness</em>м—җ лҢҖн•ң л¬ён—ҢмқҖ л§Өмҡ° л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. нқ”нһҲ м“°мқҙлҠ” м „лһөмқҖ iterative null-space projectionмқҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬к№Ңм§Җ linear modelмқҙлӮҳ non-linear encoderлЎңл¶Җн„° м–»м–ҙм§„ embeddingм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңл§Ң нғҗкө¬лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј ``empirical feature space''лҘј нҶөн•ҙ kernel-induced feature spaceлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҘј kernel matrixмқҳ м§Ғм ‘ ліҖнҷҳмңјлЎң мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң мң лҸ„н•ҳм—¬, modelкіј fairness-scoreм—җ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳкІҢ continuous protected attributeм—җ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мқҙ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ Support Vector Regression (SVR)кіј кІ°н•©н•ҳл©ҙ м—¬лҹ¬ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң лӢӨлҘё мөңмӢ  л°©лІ•л“Өкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲкұ°лӮҳ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62282","en":"Equalized Generative Treatment: Matching f-divergences for Fairness in Generative Models","ko":"Equalized Generative Treatment: Generative Modelsмқҳ кіөм •м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң f-divergences л§Өм№ӯ","authors":"Alexandre Verine, Rafael Pinot, Florian Le Bronnec","pos":"#3313","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=hz9iYayl8F","abs":"Fairness is a crucial concern for generative models, which not only reflect but can also amplify societal and cultural biases. Existing fairness notions for generative models are largely adapted from classification and focus on balancing the probability of generating samples from each sensitive group. We show that such criteria are brittle, as they can be met even when different sensitive groups are modeled with widely varying quality. To address this limitation, we introduce a new fairness definition for generative models, termed as \\emph{equalized generative treatment} (EGT), which requires comparable generation quality across all sensitive groups, with quality measured via a reference $f$-divergence. We further analyze the trade-offs induced by EGT, demonstrating that enforcing fairness constraints necessarily couples the overall model quality to that of the most challenging group to approximate. This indicates that a simple yet efficient minвҖ“max fine-tuning method should be able to balance $f$-divergences across sensitive groups to satisfy EGT. We validate this theoretical insight through a set of experiments on both image and text generation tasks. We demonstrate that min-max methods consistently achieve fairer outcomes compared to other approaches from the literature, while maintaining competitive overall performance for both tasks.","absKo":"мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ кіөм •м„ұмқҖ мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ, л¬ёнҷ”м Ғ biasлҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳлҸ„ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң л¬ём ңмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚём—җ лҢҖн•ң кё°мЎҙ кіөм •м„ұ к°ңл…җмқҖ лҢҖмІҙлЎң classificationм—җм„ң м°Ёмҡ©лҗң кІғмңјлЎң, к°Ғ sensitive groupм—җм„ң мғҳн”Ңмқҙ мғқм„ұлҗ  нҷ•лҘ мқ„ к· нҳ• мһҲкІҢ л§һм¶”лҠ” лҚ° мҙҲм җмқ„ л‘ЎлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кё°мӨҖмқҙ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё sensitive groupмқҙ л§Өмҡ° лӢӨлҘё н’Ҳм§ҲлЎң лӘЁлҚёл§ҒлҗҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°м—җлҸ„ мқҙ кё°мӨҖмқҖ м¶©мЎұлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” reference $f$-divergenceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мёЎм •н•ң н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҙ лӘЁл“  sensitive groupм—җм„ң л№„мҠ·н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ”, \\emph{equalized generative treatment} (EGT)лқјлҠ” мғқм„ұ лӘЁлҚёмҡ© мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кіөм •м„ұ м •мқҳлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң EGTк°Җ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” trade-offлҘј л¶„м„қн•ҳм—¬, кіөм •м„ұ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ к°•м ңн•ҳл©ҙ м „мІҙ лӘЁлҚё н’Ҳм§Ҳмқҙ ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң к°ҖмһҘ к·јмӮ¬н•ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ к·ёлЈ№мқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳм—җ кІ°н•©лҗЁмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё minвҖ“max fine-tuning л°©лІ•мқҙ sensitive group к°„ $f$-divergenceлҘј к· нҳ• мһҲкІҢ л§һм¶”м–ҙ EGTлҘј л§ҢмЎұмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ мқҙлЎ м Ғ нҶөм°°мқ„ image л°Ҹ text generation taskм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқјл Ёмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј, min-max methodлҠ” л¬ён—Ңмқҳ лӢӨлҘё м ‘к·јлІ•ліҙлӢӨ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” кіөм •н•ң кІ°кіјлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ л‘җ task лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” м „мІҙ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ."},{"id":"65851","en":"Differentiable Optimization Layers for Guaranteed Fairness in Deep Learning","ko":"л”Ҙлҹ¬лӢқм—җм„ң кіөм •м„ұ ліҙмһҘмқ„ мң„н•ң лҜёл¶„ к°ҖлҠҘ мөңм Ғнҷ” л Ҳмқҙм–ҙ","authors":"David Troxell, Noah Roemer, Guido Montufar","pos":"#3314","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=9SLQACsSbw","abs":"<p>Differentiable optimization layers are traditionally integrated in predict-then-optimize frameworks where a neural model estimates parameters that subsequently serve as fixed inputs to downstream decision-making optimization problems. In this work, we introduce the concept of a ``fairness layer'': a differentiable optimization layer appended to a model's output layer that guarantees a chosen notion of output parity is satisfied when integrated into a neural network. Additionally, we introduce an online primal-dual inference algorithm that provides provable aggregate fairness guarantees for streaming predictions with arbitrarily small batch sizes, where traditional per-batch constraints become overly restrictive. Numerical experiments demonstrate the effectiveness of the fairness layer and associated algorithm, and theoretical analysis characterizes the layer's differentiability and stability properties during model training and backpropagation. Our code for these experiments is publicly available on GitHub: https://github.com/anonymouspapersubmission012345/icml<em>2026</em>submission and our public Python package documentation can be found online: https://anonymouspapersubmission012345.github.io/fairness<em>training</em>anonymous/ .</p>","absKo":"<p>лҜёл¶„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң optimization layerлҠ” м „нҶөм ҒмңјлЎң predict-then-optimize н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬м—җ нҶөн•©лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”мңјл©°, м—¬кё°м„ң neural modelмқҙ нҢҢлқјлҜён„°лҘј м¶”м •н•ҳкі  к·ё нҢҢлқјлҜён„°к°Җ мқҙнӣ„ downstream decision-making optimization problemмқҳ кі м • мһ…л ҘмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” ``fairness layer''лқјлҠ” к°ңл…җмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҳ output layer л’Өм—җ лҚ§л¶ҷмқҙлҠ” лҜёл¶„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң optimization layerлЎңм„ң, neural networkм—җ нҶөн•©лҗ  л•Ң м„ нғқн•ң output parity к°ңл…җмқҙ л§ҢмЎұлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мҳЁлқјмқё primal-dual inference algorithmмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬, м „нҶөм Ғмқё per-batch м ңм•Ҫмқҙ м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ м ңн•ңм Ғмқё arbitrarily small batch sizeмқҳ streaming predictionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ provable aggregate fairness guaranteeлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ fairness layerмҷҖ кҙҖл Ё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қмқҖ лӘЁлҚё н•ҷмҠөкіј backpropagation лҸҷм•Ҳ н•ҙлӢ№ layerмқҳ differentiabilityмҷҖ stability нҠ№м„ұмқ„ нҠ№м§•м§“лҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мң„н•ң мҪ”л“ңлҠ” GitHubм—җ кіөк°ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ: https://github.com/anonymouspapersubmission012345/icml<em>2026</em>submission к·ёлҰ¬кі  кіөк°ң Python package л¬ём„ңлҠ” мҳЁлқјмқём—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ: https://anonymouspapersubmission012345.github.io/fairness<em>training</em>anonymous/ .</p>"},{"id":"63156","en":"Density-Aware Translation of Spurious Correlations in Zero-Shot VLMs","ko":"Zero-Shot VLMм—җм„ң н—Ҳмң„ мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„мқҳ л°ҖлҸ„ мқём§Җ ліҖнҷҳ","authors":"Afsaneh Hasanebrahimi, Hanxun Huang, Christopher Leckie, Sarah Erfani","pos":"#3315","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ZXYcM3QuAR","abs":"<p>Vision-Language models (VLMs), such as CLIP, achieve powerful zero-shot classification. However, their predictions remain sensitive to spurious correlations, where contextual cues dominate over semantic content. Earlier solutions typically rely on fine-tuning or prompt engineering, which either undermine the advantages of pre-trained models or are prone to hallucination. In this work, we propose Density-Aware Translation (DAT) that refines image-text similarity scores using a local geometric density term derived from group reference sets. Our approach is motivated by the phenomenon that CLIP embeddings exhibit a modality gap and lie on an anisotropic shell in the feature space: common patterns cluster near the mean, while rare patterns are pushed outward. This geometry creates uneven alignment, where spurious correlations are amplified while semantically meaningful but rare cues are marginalised. To address this, we employ a relative measure to rescale similarities based on embedding density, suppressing overconfident scores in diffuse regions while preserving dense, semantically consistent matches. Experimental results on benchmark datasets demonstrate consistent improvements in worst-group and average accuracy, highlighting density-aware translation as a simple and effective calibration mechanism for reliable zero-shot classification using multimodal models.</p>","absKo":"<p>CLIPкіј к°ҷмқҖ Vision-Language model (VLM)мқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң zero-shot classificationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ к·ё мҳҲмёЎмқҖ л¬ёл§Ҙм Ғ лӢЁм„ңк°Җ semantic contentліҙлӢӨ мҡ°м„ён•ҙм§ҖлҠ” spurious correlationм—җ м—¬м „нһҲ лҜјк°җн•ҳлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ н•ҙкІ°мұ…мқҖ лҢҖк°ң fine-tuningмқҙлӮҳ prompt engineeringм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” pre-trained modelмқҳ мһҘм җмқ„ нӣјмҶҗн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ hallucinationм—җ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” group reference setм—җм„ң лҸ„м¶ңн•ң local geometric density termмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ image-text similarity scoreлҘј м •көҗнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” Density-Aware Translation (DAT)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ CLIP embeddingмқҙ modality gapмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©° feature spaceм—җм„ң anisotropic shell мң„м—җ лҶ“мқёлӢӨлҠ” нҳ„мғҒм—җм„ң лҸҷкё°лҘј м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. мҰү, нқ”н•ң нҢЁн„ҙмқҖ нҸүк·  к·јмІҳм—җ лӘЁмқҙлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ л“ңл¬ё нҢЁн„ҙмқҖ л°”к№ҘмӘҪмңјлЎң л°Җл ӨлӮңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кё°н•ҳ кө¬мЎ°лҠ” м •л ¬мқҳ л¶Ҳк· нҳ•мқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ spurious correlationмқ„ мҰқнҸӯмӢңнӮӨлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, semanticн•ҳкІҢ мқҳлҜё мһҲм§Җл§Ң л“ңл¬ё лӢЁм„ңлҠ” мЈјліҖнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” embedding densityлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң similarityлҘј мһ¬мҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғн•ҳлҠ” мғҒлҢҖм Ғ measureлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬, нқ¬л°•н•ң мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ нҷ•мӢ н•ң scoreлҘј м–өм ңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ л°Җм§‘лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲкі  semanticм ҒмңјлЎң мқјкҙҖлҗң matchлҠ” ліҙмЎҙн•ңлӢӨ. benchmark datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” worst-group accuracyмҷҖ average accuracy лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©°, density-aware translationмқҙ multimodal modelмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” zero-shot classificationмқ„ мң„н•ң лӢЁмҲңн•ҳкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё calibration л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмһ„мқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66742","en":"Language Bias in LVLMs: From In-Depth Analysis to Simple and Effective Mitigation","ko":"LVLMмқҳ м–ём–ҙ нҺён–Ҙ: мӢ¬мёө л¶„м„қм—җм„ң лӢЁмҲңн•ҳкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё мҷ„нҷ”к№Ңм§Җ","authors":"Yangneng Chen, Jing Li","pos":"#3405","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=0tdnyH7uXp","abs":"<p>Large Vision-Language Models (LVLMs) extend large language models with visual understanding, but remain vulnerable to hallucination, where outputs are fluent yet inconsistent with images. Recent studies link this issue to language biasвҖ”the tendency of LVLMs to over-rely on text while neglecting visual inputs. Yet most analyses remain empirical without uncovering its underlying cause. In this paper, we provide a systematic study of language bias and identify its root in modality misalignment during training. Our analysis shows that both Visual Instruction Tuning (VIT) and Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) often prioritize textual improvements, which may cause LVLMs to overly lean toward language modeling rather than balanced multimodal understanding. To address this, we propose two simple yet effective methods: Language Bias Regularization (LBR), which mitigates language bias through regularization during instruction tuning, and Language Bias Penalty (LBP), which penalizes language bias in the DPO training process. Extensive experiments across diverse models and benchmarks demonstrate the effectiveness of our approach. LBR consistently improves performance on over ten general benchmarks, while LBP significantly reduces hallucination and improves trustworthiness. Together, these methods not only mitigate language bias but also advance the overall alignment of LVLMs, all without introducing any additional data or auxiliary models.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Vision-Language Model (LVLM)мқҖ large language modelмқ„ мӢңк°Ғм Ғ мқҙн•ҙлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, м¶ңл Ҙмқҙ мң м°Ҫн•Ём—җлҸ„ мқҙлҜём§ҖмҷҖ мқјм№ҳн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” hallucinationм—җ м—¬м „нһҲ м·Ём•Ҫн•ҳлӢӨ. мөңк·ј м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј language bias, мҰү LVLMмқҙ мӢңк°Ғ мһ…л Ҙмқ„ л¬ҙмӢңн•ҳкі  textм—җ м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙкіј м—°кІ°н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ к·ё к·јліё мӣҗмқёмқ„ л°қнһҲм§Җ лӘ»н•ң мұ„ мӢӨмҰқм Ғ мҲҳмӨҖм—җ лЁёл¬ёлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” language biasлҘј мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң м—°кө¬н•ҳкі , к·ё лҝҢлҰ¬к°Җ н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ modality misalignmentм—җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ Visual Instruction Tuning (VIT)кіј Direct Preference Optimization (DPO) лӘЁл‘җк°Җ мў…мў… text мёЎл©ҙмқҳ к°ңм„ мқ„ мҡ°м„ мӢңн•ҳл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ LVLMмқҙ к· нҳ• мһЎнһҢ multimodal understandingліҙлӢӨ language modelingм—җ кіјлҸ„н•ҳкІҢ м№ҳмҡ°м№ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Ө мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ к°„лӢЁн•ҳм§Җл§Ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” instruction tuning лҸҷм•Ҳ regularizationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ language biasлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” Language Bias Regularization (LBR)мқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” DPO н•ҷмҠө кіјм •м—җм„ң language biasлҘј нҢЁл„җнӢ°лЎң л¶Җкіјн•ҳлҠ” Language Bias Penalty (LBP)мқҙлӢӨ. лӢӨм–‘н•ң modelкіј benchmark м „л°ҳмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ. LBRмқҖ 10к°ңк°Җ л„ҳлҠ” general benchmarkм—җм„ң мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкі , LBPлҠ” hallucinationмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқҙл©° trustworthinessлҘј к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л‘җ л°©лІ•мқҖ м¶”к°Җ лҚ°мқҙн„°лӮҳ auxiliary model м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ language biasлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј LVLMмқҳ м „л°ҳм Ғмқё alignmentлҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63699","en":"A Game-Theoretic Framework for Measuring and Explaining Metric Compatibility in Fair Machine Learning","ko":"кіөм • Machine Learningм—җм„ң Metric нҳёнҷҳм„ұмқҳ мёЎм •кіј м„ӨлӘ…мқ„ мң„н•ң кІҢмһ„мқҙлЎ м Ғ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Lingfeng Zhang, Jingran Yang, Zhaohui Wang, Min Zhang, Qing Zhang","pos":"#3409","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=UWjvyqnKl1","abs":"Machine learning fairness research documents trade-offs but lacks quantitative frameworks to measure intrinsic metric compatibility without requiring causal graphs. We introduce a game-theoretic framework that decomposes metrics into interaction vectors, enabling compatibility measurement between metrics via cosine similarity and mechanistic attribution to attribute coalitions. Through analysis of 6 datasets, 7 models, and 6 debiasing methods, we reveal that fairness and utility are often structurally orthogonal (median compatibility $\\approx 0$) rather than diametrically opposed, with conflicts driven by sparse, low-order interactions. We further show that debiasing improves fairness by compressing the compatibility spaceвҖ”reducing compatibility of both synergistic and conflicting relationshipsвҖ”rather than eliminating conflicts, providing a mechanistic basis for understanding metric alignment.","absKo":"Machine learning fairness м—°кө¬лҠ” trade-offлҘј л¬ём„ңнҷ”н•ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, causal graph м—Ҷмқҙ intrinsic metric compatibilityлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” frameworkлҠ” л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” metricмқ„ interaction vectorлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” game-theoretic frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, cosine similarityлҘј нҶөн•ҙ metric к°„ compatibilityлҘј мёЎм •н•ҳкі  attribute coalitionм—җ лҢҖн•ң mechanistic attributionмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. 6к°ң dataset, 7к°ң model, 6к°ң debiasing methodм—җ лҢҖн•ң л¶„м„қмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, fairnessмҷҖ utilityк°Җ нқ”нһҲ м •л°ҳлҢҖлқјкё°ліҙлӢӨ кө¬мЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң м§Ғкөҗм Ғ(median compatibility $\\approx 0$)мһ„мқ„ л°қнһҲл©°, м¶©лҸҢмқҖ sparseн•ң low-order interactionм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗЁмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң debiasingмқҖ conflictлҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ synergyмҷҖ conflict кҙҖкі„ лӘЁл‘җмқҳ compatibilityлҘј лӮ®м¶° compatibility spaceлҘј м••м¶•н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ fairnessлҘј к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјл©°, мқҙлҠ” metric alignmentлҘј мқҙн•ҙн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң mechanistic basisлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65520","en":"Adaptive Generation of Bias-Eliciting Questions for LLMs","ko":"LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң нҺён–Ҙ мң л°ң м§Ҳл¬ёмқҳ м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мғқм„ұ","authors":"Robin Staab, Jasper Dekoninck, Maximilian Baader, Martin Vechev","pos":"#3410","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=ClqjnEbUC5","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) are now widely deployed in user-facing applications, reaching hundreds of millions of users worldwide.  Despite their widespread adoption, growing reliance on their outputs raises significant concerns, particularly as users may be exposed to model-inherent biases that disadvantage or stereotype certain groups. However, existing bias benchmarks commonly rely on simple templated prompts or restrictive multiple-choice questions that fail to capture the complexity of real-world user interactions. In this work, we address this gap by introducing a counterfactual framework that automatically generates realistic, open-ended questions for LLM bias evaluation. Through iterative question mutation, our approach further systematically explores areas where models are most susceptible to exhibit biased behavior. Beyond just detecting harmful biases, we also capture increasingly relevant response dimensions, such as asymmetric refusals and explicit bias acknowledgment. Building on this, we construct CAB, a diverse and human-verified benchmark for realistic and nuanced bias evaluations on current frontier LLMs. Our evaluation using CAB highlights the continued need for fairness research by demonstrating that all examined models exhibit persistent biases across certain scenarios.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language models(LLMs)мқҖ мқҙм ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ лҢҖл©ҙ м• н”ҢлҰ¬мјҖмқҙм…ҳм—җ л„җлҰ¬ л°°нҸ¬лҗҳм–ҙ м „ м„ёкі„ мҲҳм–ө лӘ…мқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗм—җкІҢ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мұ„нғқм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , м¶ңл Ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙмқҙ м»Өм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мҡ°л Өк°Җ м ңкё°лҗҳлҠ”лҚ°, нҠ№нһҲ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗк°Җ нҠ№м • м§‘лӢЁм—җ л¶ҲлҰ¬н•ҳкІҢ мһ‘мҡ©н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ кі м •кҙҖл…җмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” лӘЁлҚё кі мң мқҳ нҺён–Ҙм—җ л…ём¶ңлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙмқҳ bias benchmarkлҠ” лҢҖк°ң лӢЁмҲңн•ң н…ңн”ҢлҰҝ кё°л°ҳ promptлӮҳ м ңн•ңм Ғмқё multiple-choice questionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬, мӢӨм ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҳ ліөмһЎм„ұмқ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” LLM bias нҸүк°ҖлҘј мң„н•ҙ нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқҙкі  open-ended questionмқ„ мһҗлҸҷ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” counterfactual frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. л°ҳліөм Ғмқё question mutationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ лӘЁлҚёмқҙ нҺён–Ҙлҗң н–үлҸҷмқ„ ліҙмқҙкё° к°ҖмһҘ мү¬мҡҙ мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ мІҙкі„м ҒмңјлЎң нғҗмғүн•ңлӢӨ. мң н•ҙн•ң biasлҘј нғҗм§Җн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° к·ём№ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі , л№„лҢҖм№ӯм Ғ кұ°л¶Җ(asymmetric refusals)мҷҖ лӘ…мӢңм Ғ bias мқём •(explicit bias acknowledgment) к°ҷмқҖ м җм җ лҚ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң response dimensionлҸ„ нҸ¬м°©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ frontier LLMм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ нҳ„мӢӨм Ғмқҙкі  лҜёл¬ҳн•ң bias нҸүк°ҖлҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ҳкі  human-verifiedлҗң benchmarkмқё CABлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. CABлҘј мқҙмҡ©н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҠ”, мЎ°мӮ¬н•ң лӘЁл“  лӘЁлҚёмқҙ нҠ№м • мӢңлӮҳлҰ¬мҳӨ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё biasлҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјл©° кіөм •м„ұ м—°кө¬мқҳ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62226","en":"Beyond Procedure: Substantive Fairness in Conformal Prediction","ko":"м Ҳм°ЁлҘј л„ҳм–ҙм„ң: Conformal Predictionмқҳ мӢӨм§Ҳм Ғ кіөм •м„ұ","authors":"Pengqi Liu, Zijun Yu, Mouloud Belbahri, Arthur Charpentier, Masoud Asgharian, Jesse Cresswell","pos":"#3411","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=iWJmW9mQpA","abs":"<p>Conformal prediction (CP) offers distribution-free uncertainty quantification for machine learning models, yet its interplay with fairness in downstream decision-making remains underexplored. Moving beyond CP as a standalone operation (procedural fairness), we analyze the holistic decision-making pipeline to evaluate substantive fairnessвҖ”the equity of downstream outcomes. Theoretically, we derive an upper bound that decomposes prediction-set size disparity into interpretable components, clarifying how label-clustered CP helps control method-driven contributions to unfairness. To facilitate scalable empirical analysis, we introduce an LLM-in-the-loop evaluator that approximates human assessment of substantive fairness across diverse modalities. Our experiments reveal that label-clustered CP variants consistently deliver superior substantive fairness. Finally, we empirically show that equalized set sizes, rather than coverage, strongly correlate with improved substantive fairness, enabling practitioners to design more fair CP systems.</p>","absKo":"<p>Conformal prediction(CP)мқҖ machine learning modelмқ„ мң„н•ң distribution-free uncertainty quantificationмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, downstream decision-makingм—җм„ң fairnessмҷҖмқҳ мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҖ м•„м§Ғ м¶©л¶„нһҲ м—°кө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. CPлҘј лҸ…лҰҪм Ғмқё м Ҳм°Ём Ғ м—°мӮ°(procedural fairness)мңјлЎң ліҙлҠ” кҙҖм җмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” downstream outcomeмқҳ нҳ•нҸүм„ұмқё substantive fairnessлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м „мІҙ decision-making pipelineмқ„ л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” prediction-set нҒ¬кё° кІ©м°ЁлҘј н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң кө¬м„ұмҡ”мҶҢлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” upper boundлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳм—¬, label-clustered CPк°Җ unfairnessм—җ лҢҖн•ң method-driven кё°м—¬лҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ м ңм–ҙн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ н•ңлӢӨ. нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң мӢӨмҰқ л¶„м„қмқ„ мң„н•ҙ, лӢӨм–‘н•ң modality м „л°ҳм—җм„ң substantive fairnessм—җ лҢҖн•ң human assessmentлҘј к·јмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” LLM-in-the-loop evaluatorлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ label-clustered CP ліҖнҳ•мқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң substantive fairnessлҘј м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, coverageліҙлӢӨ equalized set sizeк°Җ substantive fairness н–ҘмғҒкіј к°•н•ҳкІҢ мғҒкҙҖлҗЁмқ„ мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ practitionerк°Җ лҚ” кіөм •н•ң CP systemмқ„ м„Өкі„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66593","en":"COPF: An Online Framework for Deployment-Stable Counterfactual Fairness in Evolving Graphs","ko":"COPF: м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” к·ёлһҳн”„м—җм„ң л°°нҸ¬ м•Ҳм •м Ғ л°ҳмӮ¬мӢӨм Ғ кіөм •м„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң мҳЁлқјмқё н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬","authors":"Sheng&amp;#x27;en Li, Dongmian Zou","pos":"#3412","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=2Nfr4u3pK2","abs":"<p>Online link recommendation on evolving graphs is performative: by choosing which candidate links to show users, the system changes which links form and what feedback it later observes. Consequently, fairness estimates from logged outcomes can be misleading and may drift after deployment when the recommendation policy is updated. We introduce COPF, a decision-layer framework for deployment-stable fairness monitoring and control in online link recommendation. COPF (i) defines group-level opportunity gaps on exposure (shown vs. not shown) counterfactuals, (ii) makes them estimable by explicit exploration and by logging the probability (propensity) that each candidate is shown, and (iii) audits and controls fairness using residual outcome indistinguishability (OI) over a configurable auditor family with graph-aware doubly robust (GA-DR) estimators. We provide a noisy transfer theorem showing that Residual-OI on estimated GA-DR residuals implies bounds on exposure-counterfactual group gaps under temporal mixing and bounded local interference, and we instantiate an online multicalibration auditor together with a primal--dual controller. Experiments on two TGB streams and a controlled synthetic bipartite stream show that COPF reduces worst-case spikes in exposure-counterfactual group disparities with modest impact on ranking utility. Our code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/fairlink-4EA0.</p>","absKo":"м§„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” graphм—җм„ңмқҳ online link recommendationмқҖ performativeн•ҳлӢӨ. мҰү, м–ҙл–Ө candidate linkлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗм—җкІҢ ліҙм—¬мӨ„м§Җ м„ нғқн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҖ м–ҙл–Ө linkк°Җ нҳ•м„ұлҗҳлҠ”м§ҖмҷҖ мқҙнӣ„ м–ҙл–Ө feedbackмқ„ кҙҖмёЎн•ҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј л°”кҫјлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң logged outcomeмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° кі„мӮ°н•ң fairness estimateлҠ” мҳӨн•ҙлҘј л¶Ҳлҹ¬мқјмңјнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, recommendation policyк°Җ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҗң л’Ө л°°нҸ¬ нӣ„м—җлҠ” driftн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” online link recommendationм—җм„ң deployment-stable fairness monitoringкіј controlмқ„ мң„н•ң decision-layer frameworkмқё COPFлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. COPFлҠ” (i) exposure(ліҙм—¬мӨҢ vs. ліҙм—¬мЈјм§Җ м•ҠмқҢ) counterfactualм—җ лҢҖн•ң group-level opportunity gapмқ„ м •мқҳн•ҳкі , (ii) explicit explorationкіј к°Ғ candidateк°Җ ліҙм—¬м§Ҳ нҷ•лҘ (propensity)мқҳ loggingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙлҘј м¶”м • к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өл©°, (iii) graph-aware doubly robust(GA-DR) estimatorлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” configurable auditor family мң„м—җм„ң residual outcome indistinguishability(OI)лҘј нҶөн•ҙ fairnessлҘј к°җмӮ¬н•ҳкі  м ңм–ҙн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м¶”м •лҗң GA-DR residualм—җ лҢҖн•ң Residual-OIк°Җ temporal mixingкіј bounded local interference н•ҳм—җм„ң exposure-counterfactual group gapмқҳ кІҪкі„лҘј н•Ёмқҳн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” noisy transfer theoremмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , online multicalibration auditorмҷҖ primal--dual controllerлҘј кө¬нҳ„н•ңлӢӨ. л‘җ к°ңмқҳ TGB streamкіј м ңм–ҙлҗң synthetic bipartite streamм—җм„ңмқҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ COPFк°Җ ranking utilityм—җ лҜём№ҳлҠ” мҳҒн–ҘмқҖ modestн•ҳкІҢ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң exposure-counterfactual group disparityмқҳ worst-case spikeлҘј мӨ„мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/fairlink-4EA0 м—җм„ң м ңкіөлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66103","en":"Demystifying the Optimal Fair Classifier in Multi-Class Classification","ko":"лӢӨмӨ‘ нҒҙлһҳмҠӨ л¶„лҘҳм—җм„ң мөңм Ғ кіөм • л¶„лҘҳкё° н•ҙл¶Җ","authors":"Li Zhang, Yuyuan Li, XiaoHua Feng, Jiaming Zhang, Fengyuan Yu, Chaochao Chen","pos":"#3413","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=70vztAT0Or","abs":"<p>Ensuring fair and equitable treatment across diverse groups, particularly in multi-class classification tasks, poses a significant challenge due to the persistent biases inherent in machine learning models. Most existing bias mitigation techniques are tailored to binary settings, and the presence of multi-dimensional outputs and complex fairness mechanisms makes their extension to multi-class scenarios neither straightforward nor effective. In this paper, we investigate two fundamental, unresolved challenges in fair classification: (i) <em>characterizing the optimal accuracy-fairness frontier in multi-class settings</em>, and (ii) <em>designing practical algorithms that attain this optimum across different training phases</em>. To tackle these challenges, we first specify an analytically tractable probabilistic formulation of the optimal classifier under fairness constraints. Building upon this, we propose two attribute-blind algorithms to enforce fairness requirements in practice: an in-processing approach for fairness intervention during training via the reduction approach, and a post-processing approach for fine-tuning output probabilities with plug-in estimation.  Theoretical analysis reveals that both methods converge to the optimal accuracy-fairness Pareto frontier.  Experiments conducted on multiple datasets demonstrate the superior performance of our methods in balancing accuracy and fairness.</p>","absKo":"<p>лӢӨм–‘н•ң м§‘лӢЁ, нҠ№нһҲ multi-class classification task м „л°ҳм—җм„ң кіөм •н•ҳкі  к· нҳ• мһЎнһҢ мІҳмҡ°лҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ, machine learning modelм—җ лӮҙмһ¬н•ң м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё bias л•Ңл¬ём—җ нҒ° лҸ„м „ кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ bias mitigation кё°лІ• лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ binary settingм—җ л§һм¶°м ё мһҲмңјл©°, лӢӨм°Ёмӣҗ м¶ңл Ҙкіј ліөмһЎн•ң fairness mechanismмқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” multi-class scenarioлЎң мқҙлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҖ лӢЁмҲңн•ҳм§ҖлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙм§ҖлҸ„ м•ҠлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” fair classificationм—җм„ң к·јліём Ғмқҙм§Җл§Ң м•„м§Ғ н•ҙкІ°лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ л¬ём ңлҘј мӮҙнҺҙліёлӢӨ: (i) <em>multi-class settingм—җм„ң optimal accuracy-fairness frontierлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•  кІғмқёк°Җ</em>, к·ёлҰ¬кі  (ii) <em>м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё training phaseм—җм„ң мқҙ optimumмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” practical algorithmмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м„Өкі„н•  кІғмқёк°Җ</em>. мқҙ л¬ём ңл“Өмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, лЁјм Җ fairness constraint н•ҳм—җм„ң optimal classifierмқҳ analytically tractableн•ң probabilistic formulationмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мӢӨл¬ҙм ҒмңјлЎң fairness requirementлҘј к°•м ңн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң л‘җ к°Җм§Җ attribute-blind algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ: training мӨ‘ fairness interventionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” in-processing approachлҘј reduction approachлҘј нҶөн•ҙ кө¬нҳ„н•ң л°©лІ•кіј, plug-in estimationмңјлЎң output probabilityлҘј fine-tuningн•ҳлҠ” post-processing approachмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қмқҖ л‘җ л°©лІ• лӘЁл‘җ optimal accuracy-fairness Pareto frontierлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ң мҲҳн–үн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ accuracyмҷҖ fairnessлҘј к· нҳ• мһҲкІҢ л§һм¶”лҠ” лҚ° мһҲм–ҙ м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҳ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64077","en":"Beyond the Trade-off: Unifying Fairness and Performance in Federated Learning","ko":"нҠёл Ҳмқҙл“ңмҳӨн”„лҘј л„ҳм–ҙ: м—°н•© н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ң кіөм •м„ұкіј м„ұлҠҘмқҳ нҶөн•©","authors":"Lin Wang, Zhichao Wang, Ye Shi, Sai Praneeth Reddy Karimireddy, Xiaoying Tang","pos":"#3602","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=R8eRV29kGt","abs":"<p>Federated Learning (FL) often suffers from a trade-off between global model performance and client-level fairness due to data heterogeneity, which often leads to inconsistent performance of the globally trained models, resulting in unfair outcomes among users. Existing fair FL algorithms face a trade-off: they either sacrifice global model performance to promote fairness or fall short of achieving optimal fairness.  In this paper, we propose a novel framework that bridge this trade-off by integrating information-theoretic principles with model alignment. Specifically, we leverage the Maximum Entropy Principle to derive an analytic, closed-form solution for fair aggregation weights, ensuring significant fairness enhancements with minimal computational overhead. To maintain the global model performance, we further employ a step-wise model alignment strategy that synchronizes gradient directions across heterogeneous clients, effectively mitigating the drift induced by local updates.   Theoretical analysis proves that our method guarantees convergence even in non-convex settings. Importantly, we push the theoretical frontier of federated fairness by extending performance variance analysis to generalized regression, providing broader guarantees. Extensive experiments on five datasets demonstrate that our approach consistently outperforms state-of-the-art methods, achieving superior fairness without sacrificing global accuracy.</p>","absKo":"<p>Federated Learning (FL)мқҖ мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё dataлЎң мқён•ҙ global model м„ұлҠҘкіј client-level fairness мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ trade-offлҘј мһҗмЈј кІӘмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” мў…мў… globally trained modelмқҳ м„ұлҠҘ л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлЎң мқҙм–ҙм ё мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ к°„ л¶Ҳкіөм •н•ң кІ°кіјлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ fair FL м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ trade-offм—җ лҶ“м—¬ мһҲлӢӨ. мҰү, fairnessлҘј лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ global model м„ұлҠҘмқ„ нқ¬мғқн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, м•„лӢҲл©ҙ мөңм Ғмқҳ fairnessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” information-theoretic мӣҗлҰ¬мҷҖ model alignmentлҘј нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ trade-offлҘј м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” Maximum Entropy Principleмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ fair aggregation weightм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•ҙм„қм Ғ closed-form н•ҙлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳм—¬, мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ кі„мӮ° мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлЎң мғҒлӢ№н•ң fairness н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң global model м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ step-wise model alignment м „лһөмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ heterogeneous client к°„ gradient л°©н–Ҙмқ„ лҸҷкё°нҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ local updateлЎң мқён•ң driftлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ non-convex settingм—җм„ңлҸ„ мҲҳл ҙмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ generalized regressionмңјлЎң performance variance analysisлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ federated fairnessмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ мөңм „м„ мқ„ л„“нҳҖ лҚ” нҸӯл„“мқҖ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лӢӨм„Ҝ к°ң datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҙ state-of-the-art л°©лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©°, global accuracyлҘј нқ¬мғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң fairnessлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63908","en":"Locate then Correct: Debiasing Attention Heads in CLIP","ko":"Locate then Correct: CLIPмқҳ attention head нҺён–Ҙ м ңкұ°","authors":"Wei Yeo, Rui Mao, Moloud Abdar, Ranjan Satapathy, Erik Cambria","pos":"#3604","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Sd5KwQbOdd","abs":"<p>Multimodal models like CLIP have gained significant attention due to their remarkable zero-shot performance across various tasks. However, studies have revealed that CLIP can inadvertently learn spurious associations between target variables and confounding factors. To address this, we introduce \\textsc{Locate-Then-Correct} (LTC), a contrastive framework that identifies spurious attention heads in Vision Transformers via mechanistic insights and mitigates them through targeted ablation. Furthermore, LTC identifies salient, task-relevant attention heads, enabling the integration of discriminative features through orthogonal projection to improve classification performance. We evaluate LTC on benchmarks with inherent background and gender biases, achieving over a &gt; 50% gain in worst-group accuracy compared to non-training post-hoc baselines. Additionally, we visualize the representation of selected heads and find that the presented interpretation corroborates our contrastive mechanism for identifying both spurious and salient attention heads.</p>","absKo":"<p>CLIPкіј к°ҷмқҖ multimodal modelмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң taskм—җм„ң лӣ°м–ҙлӮң zero-shot м„ұлҠҘ лҚ•л¶„м—җ нҒ° мЈјлӘ©мқ„ л°ӣм•„ мҷ”мҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ м—°кө¬л“ӨмқҖ CLIPмқҙ target variableкіј confounding factor мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ spurious associationмқ„ мқҳлҸ„м№ҳ м•ҠкІҢ н•ҷмҠөн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\textsc{Locate-Then-Correct} (LTC)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. LTCлҠ” mechanistic insightлҘј нҶөн•ҙ Vision Transformerм—җм„ң spurious attention headлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳкі , targeted ablationмңјлЎң мқҙлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳлҠ” contrastive frameworkмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. лӮҳм•„к°Җ LTCлҠ” л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§Җкі  taskмҷҖ кҙҖл Ёлҗң attention headлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳм—¬, orthogonal projectionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ нҢҗлі„м Ғ(discriminative) featureлҘј нҶөн•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ classification м„ұлҠҘмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӮҙмһ¬м Ғмқё background biasмҷҖ gender biasлҘј к°Җм§„ benchmarkл“Өм—җм„ң LTCлҘј нҸүк°Җн–Ҳмңјл©°, non-training post-hoc baselineкіј л№„көҗн•ҙ worst-group accuracyк°Җ 50% мқҙмғҒ н–ҘмғҒлҗЁмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. м¶”к°ҖлЎң, м„ нғқлҗң headмқҳ representationмқ„ мӢңк°Ғнҷ”н•ң кІ°кіј, м ңмӢңн•ң н•ҙм„қмқҙ spurious л°Ҹ salient attention headлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ contrastive mechanismмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•Ёмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67230","en":"Position: Fairness Failure in Generative Models is an Evaluation Problem","ko":"Position: Generative Modelмқҳ кіөм •м„ұ мӢӨнҢЁлҠ” нҸүк°Җ л¬ём ңмқҙлӢӨ","authors":"Mariia Vladimirova, Jean-Yves Franceschi, Thibaut Issenhuth","pos":"#4311","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5eURe8QrQo","abs":"<p>Despite groundbreaking advancements in generative models during the last decade, concerns about their lack of fairness, reinforcing societal inequalities and harming marginalized groups, remain under-addressed and difficult to act upon. This position paper argues that fairness failures in generative models, albeit driven by multiple factors, are ultimately stemming from an evaluation problem: fairness findings are rarely comparable across papers or actionable for deployment decisions. This paper diagnoses recurring empirical and conceptual failure modes in current practice and motivates a shift from ad-hoc bias checks to standardized, generative-specific evaluation. We propose Fairness Cards as a minimal reporting artifact that makes evaluation choices explicit (prompt families, counterfactual protocols, metrics, and refusal handling) enabling reproducibility, comparability, and accountability. We conclude with additional recommendations towards a paradigm shift in evaluation standards.</p>","absKo":"<p>м§ҖлӮң 10л…„к°„ мғқм„ұнҳ• modelмқҙ нҡҚкё°м ҒмңјлЎң л°ңм „н–ҲмқҢм—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , к·ё кіөм •м„ұ л¶ҖмЎұ, мӮ¬нҡҢм Ғ л¶ҲнҸүл“ұ к°•нҷ”, мҶҢмҷёлҗң м§‘лӢЁм—җ лҢҖн•ң н•ҙм•…м—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°л ӨлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ лӢӨлӨ„м§Җм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳкі  мӢӨмІңмңјлЎң мҳ®кё°кё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙ нҸ¬м§Җм…ҳ нҺҳмқҙнҚјлҠ” мғқм„ұнҳ• modelмқҳ fairness мӢӨнҢЁк°Җ м—¬лҹ¬ мҡ”мқём—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң л°ңлҗҳм§Җл§Ң, к¶Ғк·№м ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” evaluation problemм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ: fairness findingмқҖ л…јл¬ё к°„ л№„көҗ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ кұ°мқҳ м—Ҷкі , л°°нҸ¬ кІ°м •м—җ мӢӨм§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•ҳкё°лҸ„ м–ҙл өлӢӨ. мқҙ paperлҠ” нҳ„мһ¬ practiceм—җм„ң л°ҳліөм ҒмңјлЎң лӮҳнғҖлӮҳлҠ” кІҪн—ҳм ҒВ·к°ңл…җм Ғ мӢӨнҢЁ м–‘мғҒмқ„ м§„лӢЁн•ҳкі , мҰүнқҘм Ғмқё bias checkм—җм„ң н‘ңмӨҖнҷ”лҗң мғқм„ұнҳ• нҠ№нҷ” нҸүк°ҖлЎңмқҳ м „нҷҳмқ„ мҙүкө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” evaluation choiceлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙлҠ” мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ reporting artifactлЎңм„ң Fairness CardsлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” prompt family, counterfactual protocol, metric, refusal handlingмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҙ reproducibility, comparability, accountabilityлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” evaluation standardмқҳ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„ м „нҷҳмқ„ н–Ҙн•ң м¶”к°Җ к¶Ңкі лЎң кёҖмқ„ л§әлҠ”лӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61354","en":"Improved Bounds for Private and Robust Alignment","ko":"Private л°Ҹ Robust AlignmentлҘј мң„н•ң к°ңм„ лҗң Bounds","authors":"Wenqian Weng, Yi He, Xingyu Zhou","pos":"#119","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=r3PKGNlKET","abs":"<p>In this paper, we study the private and robust alignment of language models from a theoretical perspective by establishing upper bounds on the suboptimality gap in both offline and online settings. We consider preference labels subject to privacy constraints and/or adversarial corruption, and analyze two distinct interplays between them: privacy-first and corruption-first. For the privacy-only setting, we show that log loss with an MLE-style algorithm achieves near-optimal rates, in contrast to conventional wisdom. For the joint privacy-and-corruption setting, we first demonstrate that existing offline algorithms in fact provide stronger guarantees---simultaneously in terms of corruption level and privacy parameters---than previously known, which further yields improved bounds in the corruption-only regime. In addition, we also present the first set of results for private and robust online alignment. Our results are enabled by new uniform convergence guarantees for log loss and square loss under privacy and corruption, which we believe have broad applicability across learning theory and statistics.</p>","absKo":"<p>ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” offline л°Ҹ online setting лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң suboptimality gapмқҳ мғҒкі„лҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚёмқҳ privateн•ҳкі  robustн•ң alignmentлҘј мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” privacy constraint л°Ҹ/лҳҗлҠ” adversarial corruptionмқҳ лҢҖмғҒмқҙ лҗҳлҠ” preference labelмқ„ кі л Өн•ҳкі , мқҙл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мғҒмқҙн•ң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқё privacy-firstмҷҖ corruption-firstлҘј л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. privacy-only settingм—җм„ңлҠ”, нҶөл…җкіј лӢ¬лҰ¬ log lossмҷҖ MLE мҠӨнғҖмқј м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙ кұ°мқҳ мөңм Ғмқҳ rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. privacyмҷҖ corruptionмқҙ кІ°н•©лҗң settingм—җм„ңлҠ”, лЁјм Җ кё°мЎҙ offline algorithmл“Өмқҙ мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” corruption levelкіј privacy parameter мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң лҸҷмӢңм—җ мқҙм „м—җ м•Ңл Өм§„ кІғліҙлӢӨ лҚ” к°•н•ң ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлҠ” corruption-only regimeм—җм„ңлҸ„ к°ңм„ лҗң мғҒкі„лЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, privateн•ҳкі  robustн•ң online alignmentм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ кІ°кіјлҸ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” privacyмҷҖ corruption н•ҳм—җм„ң log lossмҷҖ square lossм—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ uniform convergence ліҙмһҘм—җ мқҳн•ҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҙмЎҢмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” н•ҷмҠө мқҙлЎ кіј нҶөкі„ м „л°ҳм—җ л„җлҰ¬ м Ғмҡ©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨкі  ліёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60770","en":"Heterogeneity-Aware Knowledge Sharing for Graph Federated Learning","ko":"Graph Federated Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң Heterogeneity-Aware Knowledge Sharing","authors":"Wentao Yu, Sheng Wan, Ge Gao, Bo Han, Chen Gong","pos":"#2413","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=wqfQ8qFb4U","abs":"<p>Graph Federated Learning (GFL) enables distributed graph representation learning while protecting the privacy of graph data. However, GFL suffers from heterogeneity arising from diverse node features and structural topologies across multiple clients. To address both types of heterogeneity, we propose a novel graph Federated learning method via Semantic and Structural Alignment (FedSSA), which shares the knowledge of both node features and structural topologies. For node feature heterogeneity, we propose a novel variational model to infer class-wise node distributions, so that we can cluster clients based on inferred distributions and construct cluster-level representative distributions. We then minimize the divergence between local and cluster-level distributions to facilitate semantic knowledge sharing. For structural heterogeneity, we employ spectral Graph Neural Networks (GNNs) and propose a spectral energy measure to characterize structural information, so that we can cluster clients based on spectral energy and build cluster-level spectral GNNs. We then align the spectral characteristics of local spectral GNNs with those of cluster-level spectral GNNs to enable structural knowledge sharing. Experiments on six homophilic and five heterophilic graph datasets under both non-overlapping and overlapping partitioning settings demonstrate that FedSSA consistently outperforms eleven state-of-the-art methods. Our code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/FedSSA.</p>","absKo":"Graph Federated Learning (GFL)мқҖ graph dataмқҳ privacyлҘј ліҙнҳён•ҳл©ҙм„ң л¶„мӮ° graph representation learningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ GFLмқҖ м—¬лҹ¬ client к°„мқҳ лӢӨм–‘н•ң node featuresмҷҖ structural topologiesм—җм„ң кё°мқён•ҳлҠ” heterogeneity л¬ём ңлҘј кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ heterogeneityлҘј лӘЁл‘җ н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Semantic and Structural Alignment (FedSSA)мқ„ нҶөн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ graph Federated learning л°©лІ•мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ node featuresмҷҖ structural topologiesмқҳ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ кіөмң н•ңлӢӨ. node feature heterogeneityм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” class-wise node distributionsлҘј м¶”лЎ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ variational modelмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, м¶”лЎ лҗң distributionмқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң clientлҘј clusteringн•ҳкі  cluster-level representative distributionsлҘј кө¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ local distributionкіј cluster-level distribution мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ divergenceлҘј мөңмҶҢнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ semantic knowledge sharingмқ„ мҙүм§„н•ңлӢӨ. structural heterogeneityм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” spectral Graph Neural Networks (GNNs)лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкі  structural informationмқ„ нҠ№м§•м§“кё° мң„н•ң spectral energy measureлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, spectral energyлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң clientлҘј clusteringн•ҳкі  cluster-level spectral GNNsлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙнӣ„ local spectral GNNмқҳ spectral characteristicsлҘј cluster-level spectral GNNмқҳ нҠ№м„ұкіј м •л ¬н•ҳм—¬ structural knowledge sharingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. non-overlapping л°Ҹ overlapping partitioning м„Өм • лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң, м—¬м„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ homophilic graph datasetкіј лӢӨм„Ҝ к°ңмқҳ heterophilic graph datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FedSSAк°Җ 11к°ңмқҳ state-of-the-art л°©лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/FedSSAм—җ кіөк°ңлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66454","en":"Preference-Calibrated Optimization with Score-Level Distribution Alignment for Text-to-Image Diffusion Model Unlearning","ko":"Text-to-Image Diffusion Model Unlearningмқ„ мң„н•ң мҠӨмҪ”м–ҙ мҲҳмӨҖ л¶„нҸ¬ м •л ¬мқ„ к°–лҠ” м„ нҳё ліҙм • мөңм Ғнҷ”","authors":"Xiuyuan Wang, Weiming Liu, Hongyu Cai, Xin Gao, Fan Wang, Chaochao Chen, Xiaolin Zheng","pos":"#3005","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=3WsZ9s9oaN","abs":"<p>While text-to-image diffusion models achieve remarkable generation quality, they inadvertently memorize sensitive content, necessitating machine unlearning to prevent undesired outputs. However, existing unlearning methods rely on suboptimal surrogate objectives rather than directly optimizing the unlearning goal, leading to fundamental objective mismatch. Moreover, these methods preserve model utility via surface-level constraints on model parameters or outputs, yet fail to capture the intrinsic generative dynamics of diffusion models, consequently triggering catastrophic forgetting. To address these challenges, we propose Preference-calibrated Optimization with Score-level Distribution Alignment (POSDA), a unified unlearning framework that harmonizes effective erasure with fine-grained structural preservation. Specifically, we reframe unlearning as a preference optimization problem by constructing a reward that explicitly quantifies the unlearning objective. Additionally, we introduce score-level distribution alignment to ensure the invariance of the underlying manifold topology of the unlearned model, thereby preventing distributional drift. Extensive experiments across object, style, and NSFW unlearning tasks demonstrate that POSDA achieves state-of-the-art erasure efficacy while maintaining superior model utility compared to existing methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>text-to-image diffusion modelмқҖ лҶҖлқјмҡҙ мғқм„ұ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҳлҸ„м№ҳ м•ҠкІҢ лҜјк°җн•ң лӮҙмҡ©мқ„ м•”кё°н•ҳм—¬ мӣҗм№ҳ м•ҠлҠ” м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ л§үкё° мң„н•ң machine unlearningмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ unlearning л°©лІ•мқҖ unlearning лӘ©н‘ңлҘј м§Ғм ‘ мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳкё°ліҙлӢӨ мөңм Ғнҷ”к°Җ лҚң лҗң surrogate objectiveм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ к·јліём Ғмқё objective mismatchк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ”кө¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•мқҖ model parameterлӮҳ outputм—җ лҢҖн•ң н‘ңл©ҙм Ғ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ model utilityлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, diffusion modelмқҳ ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё generative dynamicsлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҙ кІ°көӯ catastrophic forgettingмқ„ мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё erasureмҷҖ м„ёл°Җн•ң кө¬мЎ° ліҙмЎҙмқ„ мЎ°нҷ”мӢңнӮӨлҠ” нҶөн•© unlearning frameworkмқё Preference-calibrated Optimization with Score-level Distribution Alignment (POSDA)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” unlearning objectiveлҘј лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” rewardлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ unlearningмқ„ preference optimization problemмңјлЎң мһ¬м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. м¶”к°ҖлЎң, score-level distribution alignmentлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ unlearned modelмқҳ underlying manifold topologyк°Җ л¶ҲліҖн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ distributional driftлҘј л°©м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. object, style, NSFW unlearning taskм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ POSDAк°Җ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•л“ӨліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң model utilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ state-of-the-art erasure efficacyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66400","en":"Trajectory-Aware Certified Decentralized Unlearning via SGD Stability","ko":"SGD м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ нҶөн•ң к¶Өм Ғ мқём§Җ мқёмҰқ л¶„мӮ°нҳ• Unlearning","authors":"Hengliang Wu, Jiale Yang, Youming Tao, Shuzhen Chen, Di Wang, Dongxiao Yu","pos":"#3100","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=45Lk9G28L5","abs":"<p>Decentralized Unlearning (DU) aims to remove the influence of specific clients from a collaboratively trained global model. However, existing methods suffer from  strong reliance on static, problem-specific hyperparameters or restrictive convexity assumptions, limiting their general applicability. To overcome these limitations, we propose <strong>TRA</strong>jectory-aware <strong>CE</strong>rtified <strong>D</strong>ecentralized <strong>U</strong>nlearning (<strong>TRACE-DU</strong>), a generic unlearning framework for decentralized training. <strong>TRACE-DU</strong> introduces a fine-grained sensitivity analysis that leverages local SGD updates and decentralized training dynamics, thereby eliminating the need for convexity assumptions and reducing dependence on manually tuned parameters. By integrating strategic checkpoint selection with calibrated noise perturbation, the proposed framework enables efficient certified unlearning. Moreover, we exploit historical model trajectories to extend this framework, enabling it to naturally support sequential unlearning requests from an arbitrary number of clients. We provide theoretical guarantees for certified unlearning and derive sensitivity bounds under both convex and non-convex loss functions. Experimental results demonstrate that our framework outperforms state-of-the-art baselines across diverse metrics.</p>","absKo":"<p>Decentralized Unlearning (DU)мқҖ нҳ‘л Ҙм ҒмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң global modelм—җм„ң нҠ№м • clientмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ staticн•ҳкі  л¬ём ң нҠ№нҷ”лҗң hyperparameterм—җ нҒ¬кІҢ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, м ңн•ңм Ғмқё convexity assumptionм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм—¬ мқјл°ҳм Ғ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ л–Ём–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л¶„мӮ° н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё unlearning frameworkмқё <strong>TRA</strong>jectory-aware <strong>CE</strong>rtified <strong>D</strong>ecentralized <strong>U</strong>nlearning(<strong>TRACE-DU</strong>)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. <strong>TRACE-DU</strong>лҠ” local SGD updateмҷҖ decentralized training dynamicsлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” м„ёл°Җн•ң sensitivity analysisлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ convexity assumptionмқҙ н•„мҡ” м—Ҷкі  мҲҳлҸҷмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ң parameterм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҳмЎҙлҸ„лҸ„ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. м „лһөм Ғ checkpoint selectionкіј calibrated noise perturbationмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, м ңм•Ҳ frameworkлҠ” efficient certified unlearningмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ historical model trajectoryлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ frameworkлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, arbitraryн•ң мҲҳмқҳ clientлЎңл¶Җн„° л“Өм–ҙмҳӨлҠ” sequential unlearning requestлҘј мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹҪкІҢ м§Җмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” certified unlearningм—җ лҢҖн•ң theoretical guaranteeлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , convex л°Ҹ non-convex loss function лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң sensitivity boundлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң metricм—җм„ң state-of-the-art baselineмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60734","en":"Towards Whole-corpus Reconstruction of Heterogeneous RAG Knowledge Bases","ko":"мқҙм§Ҳм Ғ RAG Knowledge Baseмқҳ м „мІҙ мҪ”нҚјмҠӨ мһ¬кө¬м„ұмқ„ н–Ҙн•ҳм—¬","authors":"Peiru Yang, Yi Luo, Zhenfeng Gao, Tong Ju, Haoran Zheng, Linjie Zhu, Hongke Fu, Qing Li, Shangguang Wang, Tao Qi","pos":"#3101","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=x61zDYEZ91","abs":"<p>Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) systems are increasingly deployed to provide query-based access to large knowledge bases, thereby introducing concrete privacy risks whereby the underlying corpus may be partially or fully extracted through the deployed service. Existing extraction attacks typically rely on locally driven search strategies, in which newly extracted content is inferred or expanded based on previously recovered fragments. However, real-world knowledge bases are often multi-source and heterogeneous, with pronounced semantic discontinuities across domains. Such gaps can trap extraction methods that rely on local semantic continuity in local optima, severely limiting large-scale corpus reconstruction. In this paper, we introduce an extraction framework (GeoEx) designed to navigate and reconstruct heterogeneous RAG knowledge bases without any prior knowledge.  The framework plans extraction directly in the embedding space of a proxy retrieval model to improve global coverage, and employs an embedding inversion module to convert latent vectors into executable queries. We further propose a composite geometric strategy that combines orthogonal query synthesis for cross-domain exploration with local embedding perturbations for dense extraction within discovered clusters. Experiments on mixed corpora spanning eight diverse domains and multiple retrievers and LLMs show that GeoEx significantly outperforms baselines in both extraction coverage and query efficiency.</p>","absKo":"<p>Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) systemмқҖ лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ knowledge baseм—җ query-based accessлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ м җм җ лҚ” л§Һмқҙ л°°нҸ¬лҗҳкі  мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ л°°нҸ¬лҗң serviceлҘј нҶөн•ҙ underlying corpusк°Җ л¶Җл¶„м ҒмңјлЎң лҳҗлҠ” мҷ„м „нһҲ м¶”м¶ңлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” кө¬мІҙм Ғмқё privacy riskк°Җ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ extraction attackмқҖ мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң locally driven search strategyм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, мғҲлЎң м¶”м¶ңлҗң contentлҠ” мқҙм „м—җ ліөкө¬лҗң fragmentлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң м¶”лЎ лҗҳкұ°лӮҳ нҷ•мһҘлҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мӢӨм ң knowledge baseлҠ” мў…мў… multi-sourceмқҙкі  heterogeneousн•ҳл©°, domain к°„ semantic discontinuityк°Җ л‘җл“ңлҹ¬м§„лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң gapмқҖ local semantic continuityм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” extraction methodлҘј local optimumм—җ к°Җл‘җм–ҙ, лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ corpus reconstructionмқ„ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ҳкІҢ м ңн•ңн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” prior knowledge м—Ҷмқҙ heterogeneous RAG knowledge baseлҘј нғҗмғүн•ҳкі  мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„Өкі„лҗң extraction frameworkмқё GeoExлҘј мҶҢк°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ frameworkлҠ” global coverageлҘј к°ңм„ н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ proxy retrieval modelмқҳ embedding spaceм—җм„ң м§Ғм ‘ extractionмқ„ кі„нҡҚн•ҳкі , embedding inversion moduleмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ latent vectorлҘј мӢӨн–ү к°ҖлҠҘн•ң queryлЎң ліҖнҷҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң domain к°„ нғҗмғүмқ„ мң„н•ң orthogonal query synthesisмҷҖ л°ңкІ¬лҗң cluster лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ л°Җм§‘ м¶”м¶ңмқ„ мң„н•ң local embedding perturbationмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң composite geometric strategyлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. 8к°ңмқҳ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё domainм—җ кұём№ң mixed corpusмҷҖ м—¬лҹ¬ retriever л°Ҹ LLMм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ GeoExк°Җ extraction coverageмҷҖ query efficiency лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң baselineмқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62641","en":"Shuffling-Aware Optimization for Private Vector Mean Estimation","ko":"Private Vector Mean Estimationмқ„ мң„н•ң Shuffling-Aware Optimization","authors":"Shun Takagi, Seng Pei Liew","pos":"#3102","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eldrXxp9eG","abs":"We study $d$-dimensional unbiased mean estimation in the single-message shuffle model, where each user sends a single privatized message and the analyzer only observes the shuffled multiset of reports.  While minimax-optimal mechanisms are well understood in the local differential privacy setting, the corresponding notion of optimality after shuffling has remained largely unexplored.  To address this gap, we introduce the recently proposed shuffle index and use it to formulate the post-shuffling mechanism design problem as an explicit optimization problem.  We then establish a minimax lower bound on the achievable mean squared error in terms of the shuffle index, which implies that mechanisms that are optimal under LDP can become suboptimal once shuffling is applied.  Finally, we construct an asymptotically minimax optimal mechanism in the high privacy regime, which as a consequence achieves a privacy-utility trade-off nearly identical to that of the central Gaussian mechanism.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” single-message shuffle modelм—җм„ңмқҳ $d$м°Ёмӣҗ unbiased mean estimationмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ лӘЁлҚём—җм„ң к°Ғ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлҠ” н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ privatized messageлҘј ліҙлӮҙкі , analyzerлҠ” shuffleлҗң report multisetл§Ң кҙҖм°°н•ңлӢӨ. minimax-optimal mechanismмқҖ local differential privacy м„Өм •м—җм„ңлҠ” мһҳ мқҙн•ҙлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, shuffling мқҙнӣ„мқҳ лҢҖмқ‘лҗҳлҠ” optimality к°ңл…җмқҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңк·ј м ңм•Ҳлҗң shuffle indexлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі  мқҙлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ shuffling мқҙнӣ„ mechanism design л¬ём ңлҘј лӘ…мӢңм Ғ optimization problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ shuffle index мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң лӢ¬м„ұ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң mean squared errorм—җ лҢҖн•ң minimax lower boundлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” LDP н•ҳм—җм„ң optimalн•ң mechanismмқҙлқјлҸ„ shufflingмқҙ м Ғмҡ©лҗҳл©ҙ suboptimalн•ҙм§Ҳ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ н•Ёмқҳн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” high privacy regimeм—җм„ң м җк·јм ҒмңјлЎң minimax optimalн•ң mechanismмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј central Gaussian mechanismкіј кұ°мқҳ лҸҷмқјн•ң privacy-utility trade-offлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"68773","en":"Random Erasing vs. Model Inversion: A Promising Defense or a False Hope?","ko":"Random Erasing vs. Model Inversion: мң л§қн•ң л°©м–ҙмқёк°Җ н—ӣлҗң нқ¬л§қмқёк°Җ?","authors":"Viet-Hung Tran, Ngoc Nguyen, Thai Son Mai, Hans Vandierendonck, Ira Assent, Alex Kot, Ngai-Man (Man) Cheung","pos":"#3103","abs":"<p>Model Inversion (MI) attacks pose a significant privacy threat by reconstructing private\ntraining data from machine learning models. While existing defenses primarily concentrate on model-centric approaches, the impact of data on MI robustness remains largely unexplored. In this work, we explore Random Erasing (RE)вҖ”a technique traditionally used for improving model generalization under occlusionвҖ”and uncover its surprising effectiveness as a defense against MI attacks.</p>\n<p>Specifically, our novel feature space analysis shows that model trained with RE-images introduces a significant discrepancy between the features of MI-reconstructed images and those of the private data. At the same time, features of private images remain distinct from other\nclasses and well-separated from different classification regions. These effects collectively de<em>x0002</em>grade MI reconstruction quality and attack accuracy while maintaining reasonable natural accuracy. Furthermore, we explore two critical properties of RE including Partial Erasure and Random Location. First, Partial Erasure prevents the model from observing entire objects during training, and we find that this has significant impact on MI, which aims to reconstruct the entire objects. Second, the Random Location of erasure plays a crucial role in achieving a strong privacy-utility trade-off. Our findings highlight RE as a simple yet effective defense mechanism that can be easily integrated with existing privacy-preserving techniques. Extensive experiments of 37 setups demonstrate that our method achieves SOTA performance in privacy-utility tradeoff. The results consistently demonstrate the superiority of our defense over existing defenses across different MI attacks, network architectures, and attack configurations. For the first time, we achieve significant degrade in attack accuracy without decrease in utility for some configurations. Our code and additional results are available at: https://ngoc-nguyen-0.github.io/MIDRE/</p>","absKo":"<p>Model Inversion(MI) кіөкІ©мқҖ machine learning modelлЎңл¶Җн„° private training dataлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң privacy мң„нҳ‘мқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©м–ҙлҠ” мЈјлЎң model-centric м ‘к·јм—җ м§‘мӨ‘н•ҙ мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, MI robustnessм—җ лҢҖн•ң dataмқҳ мҳҒн–ҘмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң к°ҖлҰј(occlusion) н•ҳм—җм„ң model generalizationмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҚ° мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” кё°лІ•мқё Random Erasing(RE)мқ„ мӮҙнҺҙліҙкі , мқҙкІғмқҙ MI кіөкІ©м—җ лҢҖн•ң л°©м–ҙлЎңм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡё м •лҸ„лЎң нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮёлӢӨ.</p>\n<p>кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ feature space analysisлҠ” RE-imagesлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң modelмқҙ MIлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұлҗң мқҙлҜём§Җмқҳ featureмҷҖ private dataмқҳ feature мӮ¬мқҙм—җ мғҒлӢ№н•ң л¶Ҳмқјм№ҳлҘј мң лҸ„н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҸҷмӢңм—җ private imageмқҳ featureлҠ” лӢӨлҘё classл“ӨкіјлҠ” кө¬лі„лҗҳл©° м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё classification regionкіјлҸ„ мһҳ л¶„лҰ¬лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҡЁкіјлҠ” м „мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң MI reconstruction qualityмҷҖ attack accuracyлҘј м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮҙкіј лҸҷмӢңм—җ н•©лҰ¬м Ғмқё natural accuracyлҠ” мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Partial ErasureмҷҖ Random Locationмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң REмқҳ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ н•өмӢ¬ м„ұм§Ҳмқ„ нғҗкө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, Partial ErasureлҠ” н•ҷмҠө мӨ‘ modelмқҙ к°қмІҙ м „мІҙлҘј кҙҖм°°н•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” м „мІҙ к°қмІҙлҘј мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳл ӨлҠ” MIм—җ нҒ° мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, erasureмқҳ Random LocationмқҖ к°•л Ҙн•ң privacy-utility trade-offлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м—ӯн• мқ„ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” REк°Җ кё°мЎҙ privacy-preserving кё°лІ•кіј мүҪкІҢ нҶөн•©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” лӢЁмҲңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё л°©м–ҙ л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмһ„мқ„ к°•мЎ°н•ңлӢӨ. 37к°ң м„Өм •м—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬ л°©лІ•мқҙ privacy-utility tradeoffм—җм„ң SOTA м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. кІ°кіјлҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң MI кіөкІ©, network architecture, attack configuration м „л°ҳм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ л°©м–ҙліҙлӢӨ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©м–ҙк°Җ мҡ°мҲҳн•Ёмқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мІҳмқҢмңјлЎң, мқјл¶Җ м„Өм •м—җм„ңлҠ” utilityлҘј к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮӨм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң attack accuracyлҘј мң мқҳлҜён•ҳкІҢ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮӨлҠ” лҚ° м„ұкіөн–ҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңмҷҖ м¶”к°Җ кІ°кіјлҠ” лӢӨмқҢм—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ: https://ngoc-nguyen-0.github.io/MIDRE/</p>"},{"id":"65032","en":"RECOVER:Reliable Detection of Unauthorized Data Usage in Text-to-Image Diffusion Models via Inversion Robustness","ko":"RECOVER: Inversion RobustnessлҘј нҶөн•ң Text-to-Image Diffusion Modelм—җм„ң л¬ҙлӢЁ лҚ°мқҙн„° мӮ¬мҡ©мқҳ мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” нғҗм§Җ","authors":"Yanhao Wei, Xiaokang Zhao, Boheng Li, Yang Zhang, Run Wang","pos":"#3104","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HYZ3ooGuew","abs":"<p>Text-to-Image diffusion models have achieved remarkable success in image generation and are increasingly fine-tuned for personalized use cases. However, many personalized models may incorporate unauthorized data (e.g., copyrighted materials) during the fine-tuning process, raising growing concerns about potential copyright infringements. Existing methods either require intrusive modifications to the images to be protected, which not only fail to safeguard previously released images but may also degrade image quality, or rely on the availability of the pre-fine-tuned model, thereby limiting their applicability. To bridge this gap, in this paper, we propose the first non-intrusive copyright authentication framework without pre-fine-tuned model. We reveal that if a model is fine-tuned on a specific image, it learns the denoising trajectory of that image across varying noise levels, allowing it to stably reconstruct the image even under noise perturbations. Based on this insight, we propose Reliable dEteCtion Of unauthorized data usage via inVErsion Robustness (RECOVER), an effective non-intrusive detection method without pre-fine-tuned model. Unlike existing methods that rely on external watermarks or discrepancies between the suspect and pre-fine-tuned models, RECOVER directly leverages the robustness observed during the inversionвҖ“reconstruction process of the suspect model to determine whether an image was used for fine-tuning. Extensive experiments demonstrate that RECOVER is effective across a wide range of scenarios, consistently outperforming existing methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Text-to-Image diffusion modelмқҖ мқҙлҜём§Җ мғқм„ұм—җм„ң лҶҖлқјмҡҙ м„ұкіөмқ„ кұ°л‘җм—Ҳмңјл©°, м җм җ лҚ” к°ңмқёнҷ”лҗң мӮ¬мҡ© мӮ¬лЎҖм—җ л§һкІҢ fine-tuningлҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ л§ҺмқҖ к°ңмқёнҷ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ fine-tuning кіјм •м—җм„ң л¬ҙлӢЁ лҚ°мқҙн„°(мҳҲ: м Җмһ‘к¶Ңмқҙ мһҲлҠ” мһҗлЈҢ)лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•  мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙ, мһ мһ¬м Ғмқё м Җмһ‘к¶Ң м№Ён•ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°л Өк°Җ м»Өм§Җкі  мһҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ ліҙнҳён•ҙм•ј н•  мқҙлҜём§Җм—җ м№ЁмҠөм Ғмқё мҲҳм •мқ„ к°Җн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҜҖлЎң, мқҙлҜё кіөк°ңлҗң мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј ліҙнҳён•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј мқҙлҜём§Җ н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ м Җн•ҳмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳлҸ„ мһҲмңјл©°, лҳҗлҠ” pre-fine-tuned modelмқҳ мЎҙмһ¬м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҜҖлЎң м Ғмҡ© лІ”мң„к°Җ м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” pre-fine-tuned model м—Ҷмқҙ лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ л№„м№ЁмҠөм Ғ copyright authentication frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘЁлҚёмқҙ нҠ№м • мқҙлҜём§ҖлЎң fine-tuningлҗҳл©ҙ, лӢӨм–‘н•ң noise levelм—җм„ң к·ё мқҙлҜём§Җмқҳ denoising trajectoryлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкІҢ лҗҳм–ҙ, noise perturbation н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ н•ҙлӢ№ мқҙлҜём§ҖлҘј м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ л°қнһҢлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Reliable dEteCtion Of unauthorized data usage via inVErsion Robustness (RECOVER)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. RECOVERлҠ” pre-fine-tuned model м—Ҷмқҙ лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё л№„м№ЁмҠөм Ғ detection methodмқҙлӢӨ. мҷёл¶Җ watermarkлӮҳ suspect modelкіј pre-fine-tuned model к°„мқҳ м°Ёмқҙм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•кіј лӢ¬лҰ¬, RECOVERлҠ” suspect modelмқҳ inversion-reconstruction кіјм •м—җм„ң кҙҖм°°лҗҳлҠ” robustnessлҘј м§Ғм ‘ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мқҙлҜём§Җк°Җ fine-tuningм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳм—ҲлҠ”м§Җ м—¬л¶ҖлҘј нҢҗм •н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ RECOVERк°Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙл©°, кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•мқ„ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ лҠҘк°Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62079","en":"Privasis: Synthesizing the Largest \"Public\" Private Dataset from Scratch","ko":"Privasis: мІҳмқҢл¶Җн„° мөңлҢҖ к·ңлӘЁмқҳ \"кіөк°ң\" л№„кіөк°ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ н•©м„ұн•ҳкё°","authors":"Hyunwoo Kim, Niloofar Mireshghallah, Michael Duan, Rui Xin, Stella Li, Jaehun Jung, David Acuna, Qi Pang, Hanshen Xiao, Edward Suh, Sewoong Oh, Yulia Tsvetkov, Pang Wei Koh, Yejin Choi","pos":"#3105","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=k0VozzvIqL","abs":"Research involving privacy-sensitive data has always been constrained by data scarcity, standing in sharp contrast to other areas that have benefited from data scaling. To quench this thirst, we present Privasis (i.e., privacy oasis), the first million-scale fully synthetic dataset entirely built from scratchвҖ”an expansive reservoir of texts with rich and diverse private informationвҖ”designed to broaden and accelerate research in areas where processing sensitive social data is inevitable. Compared to existing datasets, Privasis, comprising 1.4 million records, offers orders-of-magnitude larger scale with quality, and far greater diversity across various document types, including medical records, legal documents, financial records, calendars, emails, meeting transcripts, and text-messages with a total of 55.1 million annotated attributes such as ethnicity, date of birth, workplace, etc. We leverage Privasis to construct a parallel corpus for text sanitization with our pipeline that recursively decomposes texts and applies targeted sanitization. Our compact sanitization models ($\\leq$ 4B) trained on this dataset outperform state-of-the-art large language models, such as GPT-5 and Qwen-3 235B.","absKo":"privacy-sensitive dataлҘј лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” м—°кө¬лҠ” н•ӯмғҒ data scarcityмқҳ м ңм•Ҫмқ„ л°ӣм•„ мҷ”мңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” data scalingмқҳ нҳңнғқмқ„ лҲ„л ӨмҳЁ лӢӨлҘё л¶„м•јмҷҖ лҡңл ·н•ҳкІҢ лҢҖл№„лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң к°ҲмҰқмқ„ н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Privasis(мҰү, privacy oasis)лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лҜјк°җн•ң мӮ¬нҡҢ лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” мқјмқҙ л¶Ҳк°Җн”јн•ң м—°кө¬лҘј л„“нһҲкі  к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, н’Қл¶Җн•ҳкі  лӢӨм–‘н•ң private informationмқ„ лӢҙмқҖ н…ҚмҠӨнҠёмқҳ кұ°лҢҖн•ң м ҖмһҘмҶҢлЎңм„ң scratchм—җм„ң мҷ„м „нһҲ кө¬м¶•лҗң мөңмҙҲмқҳ million-scale fully synthetic datasetмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ datasetкіј л№„көҗн•ҳл©ҙ, 140л§Ң к°ң recordлЎң кө¬м„ұлҗң PrivasisлҠ” н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мһҗлҰҝмҲҳ м°Ёмқҙмқҳ лҚ” нҒ° к·ңлӘЁлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, мқҳлЈҢ кё°лЎқ, лІ•лҘ  л¬ём„ң, кёҲмңө кё°лЎқ, мқјм •, мқҙл©”мқј, нҡҢмқҳ transcript, text-message л“ұ лӢӨм–‘н•ң document type м „л°ҳм—җм„ң нӣЁм”¬ лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ лӢӨм–‘м„ұмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң ethnicity, date of birth, workplace л“ұ мҙқ 5,510л§Ң к°ңмқҳ annotated attributeлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PrivasisлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ, н…ҚмҠӨнҠёлҘј мһ¬к·Җм ҒмңјлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳкі  н‘ңм Ғ sanitizationмқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” pipelineмңјлЎң text sanitizationмҡ© parallel corpusлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ datasetмңјлЎң нӣҲл Ён•ң compact sanitization model($\\\\leq$ 4B)мқҖ GPT-5мҷҖ Qwen-3 235B к°ҷмқҖ state-of-the-art large language modelліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"67069","en":"Position: Verifiable Data Minimization is a Prerequisite for Responsible, Privacy-Preserving Industrial Vision","ko":"Position: кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„° мөңмҶҢнҷ”лҠ” мұ…мһ„ мһҲкі  н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢңлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” мӮ°м—… л№„м „мқҳ м „м ңмЎ°кұҙмқҙлӢӨ","authors":"Sander De Coninck, Sam Leroux, Pieter Simoens","pos":"#3107","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=pzRykCSyYX","abs":"<p>The adoption of computer vision to drive industrial efficiency and safety creates a persistent tension between operational utility and worker surveillance. Current privacy measures, such as post-hoc blurring, are fundamentally flawed: they depend on the error-prone detection of sensitive attributes and treat privacy as a subtractive process. We posit that industrial computer vision must shift from \"hiding secrets'' to verifiable data minimization. We advocate for a design paradigm of architecturally constrained inference, formalized through information-theoretic principles, where the sensing pipeline is optimized to capture only the features necessary for a specific task (e.g., pose estimation). This provably constrains the information available for unauthorized inferences (e.g., identification), decoupling privacy from detection accuracy and reducing reliance on sensitive attribute supervision. We outline an implementation path using modular edge processing and trusted execution environments to enable verifiable, hardware-rooted attestations of task-bound processing, and argue that verifiable purpose limitation should be a prerequisite for responsible industrial AI.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӮ°м—… нҡЁмңЁм„ұкіј м•Ҳм „мқ„ лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ң computer visionмқҳ лҸ„мһ…мқҖ мҡҙмҳҒм Ғ мң мҡ©м„ұкіј л…ёлҸҷмһҗ к°җмӢң мӮ¬мқҙм—җ м§ҖмҶҚм Ғмқё кёҙмһҘмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙлӮёлӢӨ. мӮ¬нӣ„ blurringкіј к°ҷмқҖ нҳ„мһ¬мқҳ privacy мЎ°м№ҳлҠ” ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң кІ°н•Ёмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” лҜјк°җн•ң мҶҚм„ұмқҳ мҳӨлҘҳ к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқҙ лҶ’мқҖ нғҗм§Җм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, privacyлҘј м ңкұ°м Ғ(subtractive) кіјм •мңјлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӮ°м—…мҡ© computer visionмқҙ \"л№„л°Җмқ„ мҲЁкё°кё°\"м—җм„ң кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң data minimizationмңјлЎң м „нҷҳн•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  ліёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” information-theoretic principleлЎң formalizedлҗң architecturally constrained inferenceлқјлҠ” м„Өкі„ нҢЁлҹ¬лӢӨмһ„мқ„ мҳ№нҳён•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң sensing pipelineмқҖ pose estimationкіј к°ҷмқҙ нҠ№м • taskм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң featureл§Ң нҸ¬м°©н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” н—Ҳк°Җлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ м¶”лЎ (мҳҲ: identification)м—җ мқҙмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м •ліҙлҘј мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ м ңм•Ҫн•ҳм—¬, privacyлҘј detection accuracyмҷҖ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳкі  лҜјк°җн•ң мҶҚм„ұм—җ лҢҖн•ң supervision мқҳмЎҙмқ„ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” modular edge processingкіј trusted execution environmentлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ task-bound processingм—җ лҢҖн•ң кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң hardware-rooted attestationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” кө¬нҳ„ кІҪлЎңлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳкі , кІҖмҰқ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң purpose limitationмқҙ мұ…мһ„ мһҲлҠ” industrial AIмқҳ м „м ңмЎ°кұҙмқҙм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67180","en":"Position: Privacy Is a Claim, Not a Property of Synthetic Data","ko":"Position: н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢңлҠ” мЈјмһҘмқҙм§Җ н•©м„ұ лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ мҶҚм„ұмқҙ м•„лӢҲлӢӨ","authors":"Jiachen Zhao, Antonia Januszewicz, Taeho Jung","pos":"#3108","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=KqwUYPmu6I","abs":"<p>Synthetic data has become a common component of machine learning research. While widely adopted, its use in privacy-sensitive contexts has quietly shifted from a claim of residual inference risk under stated assumptions to an appearance-based property inferred from data generation itself. In this position paper, we argue that this shift reflects an implicit change in community standards for what counts as sufficient privacy evidence, rather than a misunderstanding of well-established privacy principles. Drawing on an empirical analysis of recent publications across major ML venues, we show that synthetic data is frequently used in privacy-sensitive settings without explicit articulation of threat models, inference risks, or falsifiable privacy claims. As a result, privacy assurance often remains implicit, difficult to verify, and unevenly distributed, with heightened exposure for rare and minority records. We argue for treating privacy as an explicit, evidence-based scientific claim and recommend that ML venues adopt norms requiring privacy-relevant assertions to be clearly scoped, testable, and contestable.</p>","absKo":"<p>Synthetic dataлҠ” machine learning researchмқҳ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢк°Җ лҗҳм—ҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. л„җлҰ¬ мұ„нғқлҗҳкі  мһҲм§Җл§Ң, privacy-sensitive contextм—җм„ңмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мқҖ лӘ…мӢңлҗң к°Җм •н•ҳмқҳ residual inference riskлқјлҠ” мЈјмһҘмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° лҚ°мқҙн„° мғқм„ұ мһҗмІҙм—җм„ң м¶”лЎ лҗң appearance-based propertyлЎң мЎ°мҡ©нһҲ мқҙлҸҷн•ҙ мҷ”мҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ position paperм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң ліҖнҷ”к°Җ мһҳ нҷ•лҰҪлҗң privacy principleм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҳӨн•ҙлқјкё°ліҙлӢӨ, л¬ҙм—Үмқҙ м¶©л¶„н•ң privacy evidenceлЎң к°„мЈјлҗҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң community standardмқҳ м•”л¬өм Ғ ліҖнҷ”лҘј л°ҳмҳҒн•ңлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мЈјмҡ” ML venueмқҳ мөңк·ј publicationм—җ лҢҖн•ң empirical analysisлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” synthetic dataк°Җ threat model, inference risk, falsifiable privacy claimмқ„ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң м„ңмҲ н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ мұ„ privacy-sensitive settingм—җм„ң мһҗмЈј мӮ¬мҡ©лҗңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј privacy assuranceлҠ” мў…мў… м•”л¬өм Ғмқҙкі  кІҖмҰқн•ҳкё° м–ҙл өкі  кі лҘҙкІҢ л¶„нҸ¬лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, rare recordмҷҖ minority recordм—җ лҢҖн•ң л…ём¶ңмқҙ лҚ” нҒҪлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” privacyлҘј лӘ…мӢңм Ғмқҙкі  evidence-basedн•ң scientific claimмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈ° кІғмқ„ мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, ML venueк°Җ privacy кҙҖл Ё мЈјмһҘмқ„ лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ лІ”мң„нҷ”лҗҳкі  test к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳл©° л°ҳл°• к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳлҠ” к·ңлІ”мқ„ мұ„нғқн•  кІғмқ„ к¶Ңкі н•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63899","en":"PRISM: Gauge-Invariant Tangent-Space Differentially Private LoRA","ko":"PRISM: кІҢмқҙм§Җ л¶ҲліҖ м ‘кіөк°„ м°Ёл¶„ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң LoRA","authors":"Shihao Wang, Xueru Zhang","pos":"#3109","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=SiCjKmArjQ","abs":"Applying differential privacy (DP) via DP-SGD to Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA) is a natural approach for privacy-preserving fine-tuning. However, applying DP-SGD to LoRA poses a fundamental challenge due to its low-rank parameterization. In LoRA, each trainable update is represented as a low-rank matrix $Z=AB^\\top$, but this factorization is non-identifiable. As a result, applying DP-SGD directly to factors $(A,B)$ induces gauge-dependent perturbations on $Z$, leading to uncontrolled noise amplification. We propose **PRISM**, an intrinsic DP mechanism for LoRA that is gauge invariant by construction, avoids bilinear noise amplification, and admits an efficient low-dimensional noise sampler. Moreover, PRISM yields a closed-form characterization for the effective intrinsic noise on $Z$, and enables stable privacyвҖ“utility trade-offs by being gauge invariant and keeping noise amplification bounded. We further characterize the noise amplification incurred by naive DP-LoRA and show that it can be unbounded, establish standard $(\\varepsilon,\\delta)$-DP guarantees for PRISM, and introduce a DP-aware, gauge-invariant adaptive update that avoids amplifying injected privacy noise under adaptive optimization, improving numerical stability in practice.","absKo":"Low-Rank Adaptation (LoRA)м—җ differential privacy (DP)лҘј DP-SGDлЎң м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ privacy-preserving fine-tuningмқ„ мң„н•ң мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ м ‘к·јмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ DP-SGDлҘј LoRAм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м ҖлһӯнҒ¬ parameterization л•Ңл¬ём—җ к·јліём Ғмқё лҸ„м „мқ„ м ңкё°н•ңлӢӨ. LoRAм—җм„ң к°Ғ trainable updateлҠ” м ҖлһӯнҒ¬ н–үл ¬ $Z=AB^\\top$лЎң н‘ңнҳ„лҗҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙ factorizationмқҖ non-identifiableн•ҳлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј $(A,B)$ factorм—җ DP-SGDлҘј м§Ғм ‘ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ $Z$м—җ gauge-dependent perturbationмқҙ мң лҸ„лҗҳм–ҙ, м ңм–ҙлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ” noise amplificationмңјлЎң мқҙм–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LoRAлҘј мң„н•ң intrinsic DP mechanismмқё **PRISM**мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. PRISMмқҖ кө¬м„ұмғҒ gauge invariantн•ҳл©°, bilinear noise amplificationмқ„ н”јн•ҳкі , нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё low-dimensional noise samplerлҘј н—Ҳмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ PRISMмқҖ $Z$ мң„мқҳ effective intrinsic noiseм—җ лҢҖн•ң closed-form characterizationмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳкі , gauge invariantн•ҳкІҢ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң noise amplificationмқ„ boundedн•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё privacy-utility trade-offлҘј к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң naive DP-LoRAм—җм„ң л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” noise amplificationмқ„ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ к·ёкІғмқҙ unboundedн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , PRISMм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ н‘ңмӨҖ $(\\varepsilon,\\delta)$-DP ліҙмһҘмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, adaptive optimization н•ҳм—җм„ң мЈјмһ…лҗң privacy noiseмқҳ мҰқнҸӯмқ„ л°©м§Җн•ҳлҠ” DP-aware, gauge-invariant adaptive updateлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ мӢӨм ң мҲҳм№ҳ м•Ҳм •м„ұмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ."},{"id":"62779","en":"PEARL: Differentially Private and Entropy-Aware Regulated Language Generation","ko":"PEARL: Differentially Private л°Ҹ Entropy-Aware к·ңм ң Language Generation","authors":"Seongho Joo, Hyukhun Koh, Kyomin Jung","pos":"#3110","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=dSRLxMgwxd","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) often employ Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG) to improve factuality. However, this also increases the risk of sensitive private information leakage. Differential Privacy (DP) has therefore been integrated into LLM inference and is widely regarded as a standard safeguard; yet most studies focus narrowly on the privacyвҖ“utility trade-off, leaving the trustworthiness of DP outputs underexplored. To assess trustworthiness, we employ the confidence gap (CG), which quantifies an LLMвҖҷs internal knowledge conflict. We show that CG correlates with both hallucination and exposure of personally identifiable information (PII). Building on this insight, we propose PEARL, a CGвҖ‘guided, entropyвҖ‘aware private decoding framework. PEARL adaptively allocates the privacy budget across tokens and sentences based on CG, concentrating protection on PII-bearing spans while stabilizing low-confidence, hallucination-prone regions. In experiments, PEARL improves both trustworthiness and robustness against PII extraction attacks. Notably, while applying DP alone significantly increases hallucination, our framework demonstrates that it is possible to preserve privacy while reducing hallucination.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large language models (LLMs)мқҖ мӮ¬мӢӨм„ұмқ„ лҶ’мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ Retrieval-Augmented Generation (RAG)мқ„ мһҗмЈј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҠ” лҜјк°җн•ң к°ңмқём •ліҙ мң м¶ң мң„н—ҳлҸ„ н•Ёк»ҳ мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. л”°лқјм„ң Differential Privacy (DP)лҠ” LLM м¶”лЎ м—җ нҶөн•©лҗҳм–ҙ л„җлҰ¬ н‘ңмӨҖм Ғмқё м•Ҳм „мһҘм№ҳлЎң м—¬кІЁм§Җм§Җл§Ң, лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ м—°кө¬лҠ” privacyвҖ“utility trade-offм—җл§Ң мўҒкІҢ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”м–ҙ DP м¶ңл Ҙмқҳ trustworthinessлҠ” м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. trustworthinessлҘј нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” LLMмқҳ лӮҙл¶Җ м§ҖмӢқ м¶©лҸҢмқ„ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” confidence gap (CG)мқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” CGк°Җ hallucinationкіј personally identifiable information (PII) л…ём¶ң лӘЁл‘җмҷҖ мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„к°Җ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PEARLмқҙлқјлҠ” CG-guided, entropy-aware private decoding frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. PEARLмқҖ CGлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң tokenкіј sentence м „л°ҳм—җ privacy budgetмқ„ м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң н• лӢ№н•ҳм—¬, PIIлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң кө¬к°„м—җ ліҙнҳёлҘј м§‘мӨ‘н•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ confidenceк°Җ лӮ®кі  hallucinationмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ҳкё° мү¬мҡҙ мҳҒм—ӯмқ„ м•Ҳм •нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳм—җм„ң PEARLмқҖ trustworthinessмҷҖ PII extraction attackм—җ лҢҖн•ң robustnessлҘј лӘЁл‘җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ DPл§Ң м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ hallucinationмқҙ нҒ¬кІҢ мҰқк°Җн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkлҠ” privacyлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң hallucinationмқ„ мӨ„мқҙлҠ” кІғмқҙ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66405","en":"OptiFluence: Principled Design of Privacy Canaries","ko":"OptiFluence: н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң Canaryмқҳ мӣҗм№ҷм Ғ м„Өкі„","authors":"Mohammad Yaghini, Michael Aerni, Junrui Zhang, Nicolas Papernot, Florian Tramer","pos":"#3111","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=428khNRrGI","abs":"Privacy auditing has emerged as a practical tool for empirically estimating training data leakage in machine learning models, in contrast to the provable but often overly pessimistic bounds provided by differential privacy analysis. A common strategy is to use membership inference attacks to detect the presence of specific canariesвҖ”data points chosen to maximize attack successвҖ”in training data. However, existing canary designs are largely heuristic, relying on mislabeled or out-of-distribution samples. We address this gap by formulating canary design as a bilevel optimization problem, where the model is trained in the inner loop and the canary is optimized in the outer loop to maximize its detectability. To solve this problem, we develop OptiFluence, a scalable optimization framework that combines (i) initialization by selecting candidates using influence functions and (ii) unrolled optimization with memory-efficient techniques. Our approach achieves remarkable empirical performance on four datasets. Optimized canaries demonstrate 415$\\times$ (CIFAR-10/100) higher detectability than in-distribution baselines, achieving near-perfect detection rates of 99% true positive rate at 0.1% false positive rate. Critically, these canaries transfer effectively across different model architectures without retraining, enabling practical third-party privacy audits. This transferability allows regulators and auditors to assess model privacy without requiring access to proprietary training infrastructure or substantial computational resources.","absKo":"Privacy auditingмқҖ differential privacy analysisк°Җ м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң мў…мў… м§ҖлӮҳм№ҳкІҢ л№„кҙҖм Ғмқё boundмҷҖ лҢҖмЎ°м ҒмңјлЎң, machine learning modelм—җм„ң training data leakageлҘј мӢӨмҰқм ҒмңјлЎң м¶”м •н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ лҸ„кө¬лЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–ҲлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё м „лһөмқҖ membership inference attackмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ training data лӮҙ нҠ№м • canary, мҰү attack successлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м„ нғқлҗң data pointмқҳ мЎҙмһ¬лҘј нғҗм§Җн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ canary designмқҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ heuristicм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, mislabeled sampleмқҙлӮҳ out-of-distribution sampleм—җ кё°лҢҖлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” canary designмқ„ bilevel optimization problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң inner loopм—җм„ңлҠ” modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі , outer loopм—җм„ңлҠ” canaryк°Җ мһҗмӢ мқҳ detectabilityлҘј мөңлҢҖнҷ”н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” influence functionмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ candidateлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” initializationкіј memory-efficient techniqueмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң unrolled optimizationмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң scalable optimization frameworkмқё OptiFluenceлҘј к°ңл°ңн–ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ 4к°ң datasetм—җм„ң remarkableн•ң empirical performanceлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗң canaryлҠ” in-distribution baselineліҙлӢӨ 415$\\times$ (CIFAR-10/100) лҶ’мқҖ detectabilityлҘј ліҙмқҙл©°, 0.1% false positive rateм—җм„ң 99% true positive rateлқјлҠ” кұ°мқҳ мҷ„лІҪн•ң detection rateм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ңлӢӨ. кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң canaryлҠ” мһ¬н•ҷмҠө м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё model architecture к°„м—җ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң transferлҗҳм–ҙ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё third-party privacy auditмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң transferabilityлҠ” regulatorмҷҖ auditorк°Җ proprietary training infrastructureлӮҳ л§үлҢҖн•ң computational resource м—ҶмқҙлҸ„ model privacyлҘј нҸүк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙмӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"63232","en":"OSNIP: Breaking the Privacy-Utility-Efficiency Trilemma in LLM Inference via Obfuscated Semantic Null Space","ko":"OSNIP: лӮңлҸ…нҷ”лҗң мӢңл§ЁнӢұ мҳҒкіөк°„мқ„ нҶөн•ң LLM м¶”лЎ м—җм„ң н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң-мң мҡ©м„ұ-нҡЁмңЁм„ұ нҠёлҰҙл Ҳл§Ҳ к·№ліө","authors":"Zhiyuan Cao, Zeyu Ma, Chenhao Yang, HAN ZHENG, Mingang Chen","pos":"#3112","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=YsexiJ0zAh","abs":"<p>We propose Obfuscated Semantic Null space Injection for Privacy (OSNIP), a lightweight client-side encryption framework for privacy-preserving LLM inference. Generalizing the geometric intuition of linear kernels to the high-dimensional latent space of LLMs, we formally define the ``Obfuscated Semantic Null Space'', a high-dimensional regime that preserves semantic fidelity while enforcing near-orthogonality to the original embedding. By injecting perturbations that project the original embedding into this space, OSNIP ensures privacy without any post-processing. Furthermore, OSNIP employs a key-dependent stochastic mapping that synthesizes individualized perturbation trajectories unique to each user. Evaluations on 12 generative and classification benchmarks show that OSNIP achieves state-of-the-art performance, sharply reducing attack success rates while maintaining strong model utility under strict security constraints.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” privacy-preserving LLM inferenceлҘј мң„н•ң кІҪлҹү client-side encryption frameworkмқё Obfuscated Semantic Null space Injection for Privacy(OSNIP)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. linear kernelмқҳ кё°н•ҳн•ҷм Ғ м§ҒкҙҖмқ„ LLMмқҳ кі м°Ёмӣҗ latent spaceлЎң мқјл°ҳнҷ”н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӣҗліё embeddingм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ кұ°мқҳ м§Ғкөҗм„ұмқ„ к°•м ңн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ semantic fidelityлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” кі м°Ёмӣҗ regimeмқё ``Obfuscated Semantic Null Space''лҘј нҳ•мӢқм ҒмңјлЎң м •мқҳн•ңлӢӨ. мӣҗліё embeddingмқ„ мқҙ кіөк°„мңјлЎң projectionн•ҳлҠ” perturbationмқ„ мЈјмһ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, OSNIPмқҖ м–ҙл– н•ң post-processingлҸ„ м—Ҷмқҙ privacyлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ OSNIPмқҖ key-dependent stochastic mappingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ к°Ғ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗм—җкІҢ кі мң н•ң individualized perturbation trajectoryлҘј н•©м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. 12к°ңмқҳ generative л°Ҹ classification benchmarkм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҸүк°ҖлҠ” OSNIPмқҙ state-of-the-art м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©ҙм„ң, м—„кІ©н•ң ліҙм•Ҳ м ңм•Ҫ н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ model utilityлҘј к°•н•ҳкІҢ мң м§Җн•ң мұ„ attack success rateлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ лӮ®м¶ҳлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64258","en":"Multilingual Unlearning in LLMs: Transfer, Dynamics, and Reversibility","ko":"LLMм—җм„ңмқҳ лӢӨкөӯм–ҙ м–ёлҹ¬лӢқ: м „мқҙ, лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷ, к°Җм—ӯм„ұ","authors":"Chaoyi Xiang, Olga Ohrimenko, Benjamin Rubinstein, Lea Frermann","pos":"#3113","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PQqbcFehs4","abs":"<p>Large language models (LLMs) can memorize sensitive facts, motivating <em>unlearning</em> methods that remove targeted knowledge without costly retraining. However, unlearning research remains heavily English-centric. We study multilingual unlearning by extending the TOFU benchmark to five languages, and fine-tune, unlearn and query our models with different permutations of languages. We find that unlearning transfer -- the ability of an unlearned model to \"forget\" facts in languages other than the unlearning language -- is highly variable: e.g., it is strongest between languages sharing scripts and families, and we show that the <em>unlearning language</em> predicts which <em>query languages</em> are most likely to yield the strongest transfer. Layer-wise analysis reveals that unlearning leaves the shared cross-lingual latent space largely intact in early layers, instead operating primarily in later decoding layers. This suggests that unlearning does not truly erase knowledge, but rather induces superficial suppression. Exploiting this structure, a single inference-time steering direction reverses much of this suppression across languages, recovering 50% (Qwen) and 90% (Gemma) of the unlearned knowledge.</p>","absKo":"Large language models(LLMs)мқҖ лҜјк°җн•ң мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ кё°м–өн•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ° retraining м—Ҷмқҙ нҠ№м • м§ҖмӢқмқ„ м ңкұ°н•ҳлҠ” \\emph{unlearning} л°©лІ•мқҳ лҸҷкё°лҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ unlearning м—°кө¬лҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ мҳҒм–ҙ мӨ‘мӢ¬м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” TOFU benchmarkлҘј лӢӨм„Ҝ м–ём–ҙлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм—¬ multilingual unlearningмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ҳкі , м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё м–ём–ҙ permutationмңјлЎң лӘЁлҚёмқ„ fine-tune, unlearn, queryн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” unlearning transfer, мҰү unlearnлҗң лӘЁлҚёмқҙ unlearning м–ём–ҙк°Җ м•„лӢҢ лӢӨлҘё м–ём–ҙмқҳ мӮ¬мӢӨлҸ„ ``forget''н•ҳлҠ” лҠҘл Ҙмқҙ л§Өмҡ° к°ҖліҖм Ғмһ„мқ„ л°ңкІ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ, кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” scriptмҷҖ language familyк°Җ к°ҷмқҖ м–ём–ҙ к°„м—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ к°•н•ҳл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” \\emph{unlearning language}к°Җ м–ҙл–Ө \\emph{query languages}м—җм„ң к°ҖмһҘ к°•н•ң transferк°Җ лӮҳнғҖлӮ м§Җ мҳҲмёЎн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. layer-wise л¶„м„қмқҖ unlearningмқҙ мҙҲл°ҳ layerм—җм„ң кіөмң  cross-lingual latent spaceлҘј лҢҖмІҙлЎң к·ёлҢҖлЎң мң м§Җн•ң мұ„, мЈјлЎң нӣ„л°ҳ decoding layerм—җм„ң мһ‘лҸҷн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” unlearningмқҙ м§ҖмӢқмқ„ м§„м •мңјлЎң м§Җмҡ°лҠ” кІғмқҙ м•„лӢҲлқј н‘ңл©ҙм Ғмқё м–өм ңлҘј мң лҸ„н•ңлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ, н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ inference-time steering directionл§ҢмңјлЎңлҸ„ м—¬лҹ¬ м–ём–ҙм—җ кұём№ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м–өм ңмқҳ мғҒлӢ№ л¶Җл¶„мқ„ лҗҳлҸҢл Ө, unlearnлҗң м§ҖмӢқмқҳ 50%(Qwen)мҷҖ 90%(Gemma)лҘј ліөмӣҗн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65219","en":"Leveraging Machine Unlearning for Cost-Efficient Preference Alignment","ko":"л№„мҡ© нҡЁмңЁм Ғ м„ нҳё м •л ¬мқ„ мң„н•ң Machine Unlearning нҷңмҡ©","authors":"XiaoHua Feng, Yuyuan Li, HuWei Ji, Li Zhang, Jiaming Zhang, Tianyu Du, Chaochao Chen","pos":"#3114","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FhCu8IlO2e","abs":"<p>Despite advances in Preference Alignment (PA) for Large Language Models (LLMs), mainstream methods like reinforcement learning with human feedback face notable challenges. These approaches require high-quality datasets of positive preference examples, which are costly to obtain and computationally intensive. The LLM unlearning technique presents a promising alternative by directly removing the influence of negative examples. However, current research has primarily focused on empirical validation, lacking systematic quantitative analysis. To bridge this gap, we propose a framework linking PA with LLM unlearning. Through bi-level optimization, we first quantify how unlearning specific negative examples impacts PA performance. Our analysis reveals that these effects vary substantially across negative examples. Building on this insight, we pose a crucial question: how can we optimally select and weight negative examples for unlearning to maximize PA performance? To answer this, we propose Unlearning to Align (U2A), which leverages bi-level optimization to efficiently select and unlearn examples for optimal PA performance. We validate the proposed method through extensive experiments, with results confirming its effectiveness. Our code is available at https://anonymous.4open.science/r/U2A-9E75.</p>","absKo":"<p>Large Language Models (LLMs)мқҳ Preference Alignment (PA) л°ңм „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , human feedbackмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң reinforcement learningкіј к°ҷмқҖ мЈјлҘҳ л°©лІ•л“ӨмқҖ лҡңл ·н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ positive preference exampleмқҳ кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ datasetмқ„ н•„мҡ”лЎң н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” нҷ•ліҙ л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬кі  кі„мӮ°лҹүлҸ„ л§Һмқҙ л“ лӢӨ. LLM unlearning кё°лІ•мқҖ negative exampleмқҳ мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ м ңкұ°н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мң л§қн•ң лҢҖм•Ҳмқҙ лҗңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ нҳ„мһ¬ м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң мӢӨмҰқм Ғ кІҖмҰқм—җ м№ҳмӨ‘н•ҙ мһҲмңјл©°, мІҙкі„м Ғмқё м •лҹү л¶„м„қмқҖ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PAмҷҖ LLM unlearningмқ„ м—°кІ°н•ҳлҠ” frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. bi-level optimizationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лЁјм Җ нҠ№м • negative exampleмқ„ unlearningн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙ PA м„ұлҠҘм—җ м–ҙл–Ө мҳҒн–Ҙмқ„ лҜём№ҳлҠ”м§Җ м •лҹүнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л¶„м„қмқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нҡЁкіјк°Җ negative exampleл§ҲлӢӨ нҒ¬кІҢ лӢӨлҰ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м§Ҳл¬ёмқ„ м ңкё°н•ңлӢӨ: PA м„ұлҠҘмқ„ к·№лҢҖнҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ unlearningн•  negative exampleмқ„ м–ҙл–»кІҢ мөңм ҒмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ҳкі  к°ҖмӨ‘н•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ”к°Җ? мқҙм—җ лӢөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Unlearning to Align (U2A)лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” bi-level optimizationмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ optimal PA м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң„н•ҙ exampleмқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ҳкі  unlearnн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м ңм•Ҳн•ң л°©лІ•мқ„ кІҖмҰқн–Ҳмңјл©°, к·ё кІ°кіј нҡЁкіјк°Җ нҷ•мқёлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ңлҠ” https://anonymous.4open.science/r/U2A-9E75 м—җм„ң нҷ•мқён•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66304","en":"Homophily-Heterogeneity Gradient Surgery for Federated Graph Learning","ko":"Federated к·ёлһҳн”„ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң Homophily-Heterogeneity к·ёлһҳл””м–ёнҠё мҲҳмҲ ","authors":"Sujia Huang, Lele Fu, Shunxin Xiao, Xiaoya Zhang, Chunyan Xu, Tong Zhang, Bo Huang, Zhen Cui","pos":"#3115","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=4unkIqlZN5","abs":"<p>Federated Graph Learning (FGL) facilitates privacy-preserving collaborative training of graph neural networks, yet homophily heterogeneity across subgraphs triggers optimization conflicts that degrade model generalization.   Most existing solutions rely on multi-channel architectures to mitigate such conflict, which increase the burden on edge devices and lack theoretical convergence guarantees.   To overcome these limitations, we propose FedGCM, a novel FGL framework with Group-oriented Conflict Mitigation, which aligns inconsistent optimization objectives via a tailored gradient surgery scheme.   Specifically, FedGCM first divides clients into distinct groups based on their homophily levels, a strategy that precludes exhaustive client-to-client conflict assessments.   To resolve inter-group interference, we develop RPGrad, a gradient surgery mechanism based on residual projection, which integrates synergistic knowledge while filtering inter-group conflicts.   The refined updates are then transmitted in a group-wise fashion, effectively alleviating optimization conflicts induced by homophily heterogeneity without augmenting the client-side burden.   Furthermore, we provide a formal theoretical analysis establishing the convergence of FedGCM.   Extensive experiments on both homophilous and heterophilous graphs demonstrate that FedGCM consistently achieves advanced performance.</p>","absKo":"<p>Federated Graph Learning(FGL)мқҖ privacy-preserving л°©мӢқмқҳ graph neural network нҳ‘л Ҙ н•ҷмҠөмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, subgraph к°„ homophily heterogeneityлҠ” optimization conflictлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳм—¬ model generalizationмқ„ м Җн•ҙн•ңлӢӨ. лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ кё°мЎҙ н•ҙлІ•мқҖ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң conflictлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ multi-channel architectureм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” edge deviceмқҳ л¶ҖлӢҙмқ„ мҰқк°ҖмӢңнӮӨкі  мқҙлЎ м Ғ convergence ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј к·№ліөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Group-oriented Conflict Mitigationмқ„ к°–лҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ FGL frameworkмқё FedGCMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, л§һм¶Өнҳ• gradient surgery schemeмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ optimization objectiveлҘј м •л ¬н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, FedGCMмқҖ лЁјм Җ homophily мҲҳмӨҖм—җ л”°лқј clientлҘј м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё groupмңјлЎң лӮҳлҲ„лҠ”лҚ°, мқҙ м „лһөмқҖ лӘЁл“  client мҢҚм—җ лҢҖн•ң conflict нҸүк°ҖлҘј н”јн•ҳкІҢ н•ҙмӨҖлӢӨ. к·ёлЈ№ к°„ interferenceлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” residual projectionм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң gradient surgery л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқё RPGradлҘј к°ңл°ңн–Ҳмңјл©°, мқҙлҠ” к·ёлЈ№ к°„ conflictлҘј кұёлҹ¬лӮҙл©ҙм„ң мӢңл„Ҳм§Җ мһҲлҠ” м§ҖмӢқмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ м •м ңлҗң updateлҘј group лӢЁмң„лЎң м „мҶЎн•ҳм—¬, client-side л¶ҖлӢҙмқ„ лҠҳлҰ¬м§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©ҙм„ң homophily heterogeneityлЎң мң л°ңлҗҳлҠ” optimization conflictлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мҷ„нҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” FedGCMмқҳ convergenceлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳлҠ” нҳ•мӢқм Ғ мқҙлЎ  л¶„м„қмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. homophilous graphмҷҖ heterophilous graph лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ FedGCMмқҙ мқјкҙҖлҗҳкІҢ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60863","en":"ACTG-ARL: Differentially Private Conditional Text Generation with RL-Boosted Control","ko":"ACTG-ARL: RL-Boosted Controlмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң м°Ёл“ұ к°ңмқём •ліҙліҙнҳё Conditional Text Generation","authors":"Yuzheng Hu, Ryan McKenna, Da Yu, Shanshan Wu, Han Zhao, Zheng Xu, Peter Kairouz","pos":"#3203","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=vvke6mnh3Z","abs":"Generating high-quality synthetic text under differential privacy (DP) is critical for training and evaluating language models without compromising user privacy. Prior work on synthesizing DP *datasets* often fail to preserve key statistical attributes, suffer utility loss from the noise required by DP, and lack fine-grained control over generation. To address these challenges, we make two contributions. First, we introduce a hierarchical framework that decomposes DP synthetic text generation into two subtasks: *feature learning* and *conditional text generation*. This design explicitly incorporates learned features into the generation process and simplifies the end-to-end synthesis task. Through systematic ablations, we identify the most effective configuration: a rich tabular schema as feature, a DP tabular synthesizer, and a DP fine-tuned conditional generator, which we term ACTG (**A**ttribute-**C**onditioned **T**ext **G**eneration). Second, we propose Anchored RL (ARL), a post-training method that improves the instruction-following ability of ACTG for conditional generation. ARL combines RL to boost control with an SFT anchor on best-of-$N$ data to prevent reward hacking. Together, these components form our end-to-end algorithm **ACTG-ARL**, which advances both the quality of DP synthetic text (+20% MAUVE over prior work) and the control of the conditional generator under strong privacy guarantees. Our code is at https://github.com/actg-arl/ACTG-ARL.","absKo":"<p>differential privacy(DP) н•ҳм—җм„ң кі н’Ҳм§Ҳ synthetic textлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ privacyлҘј нӣјмҶҗн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  language modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкі  нҸүк°Җн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° л§Өмҡ° мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙмқҳ DP *dataset* synthesis м—°кө¬лҠ” н•өмӢ¬ нҶөкі„м Ғ мҶҚм„ұмқ„ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ, DPм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң noiseлЎң мқён•ҙ utilityк°Җ л–Ём–ҙм§Җкұ°лӮҳ, generationм—җ лҢҖн•ң м„ёл°Җн•ң м ңм–ҙк°Җ л¶ҖмЎұн•ң кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§ҺлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ кё°м—¬лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, DP synthetic text generationмқ„ *feature learning*кіј *conditional text generation*мқҙлқјлҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ н•ҳмң„ кіјм ңлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳлҠ” кі„мёөм Ғ frameworkлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өкі„лҠ” н•ҷмҠөлҗң featureлҘј generation кіјм •м—җ лӘ…мӢңм ҒмңјлЎң нҶөн•©н•ҳкі  end-to-end synthesis taskлҘј лӢЁмҲңнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мІҙкі„м Ғмқё ablationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” к°ҖмһҘ нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё кө¬м„ұмқ„ мӢқлі„н–ҲлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” featureлЎңм„ңмқҳ н’Қл¶Җн•ң tabular schema, DP tabular synthesizer, к·ёлҰ¬кі  DP fine-tuned conditional generatorмқҙл©°, мқҙлҘј ACTG(**A**ttribute-**C**onditioned **T**ext **G**eneration)лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘёлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” conditional generationм—җм„ң ACTGмқҳ instruction-following лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҠ” post-training л°©лІ•мқё Anchored RL(ARL)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. ARLмқҖ controlмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң RLкіј reward hackingмқ„ л°©м§Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң best-of-$N$ лҚ°мқҙн„°м—җ лҢҖн•ң SFT anchorлҘј кІ°н•©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢл“Өмқҙ кІ°н•©лҗҳм–ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ end-to-end algorithmмқё **ACTG-ARL**мқ„ нҳ•м„ұн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” DP synthetic textмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳ(+20% MAUVE over prior work)кіј к°•н•ң privacy guarantee н•ҳм—җм„ң conditional generatorмқҳ м ңм–ҙм„ұмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮЁлӢӨ. мҪ”л“ң: https://github.com/actg-arl/ACTG-ARL.</p>"},{"id":"65551","en":"Accuracy-First RГ©nyi Differential Privacy and Post-Processing Immunity","ko":"м •нҷ•лҸ„ мҡ°м„  RГ©nyi Differential PrivacyмҷҖ нӣ„мІҳлҰ¬ л¶ҲліҖм„ұ","authors":"Ossi RГӨisГӨ, Antti Koskela, Antti Honkela","pos":"#3204","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CVDEc0doW8","abs":"<p>The accuracy-first perspective of differential privacy addresses an important shortcoming by allowing a data analyst to adaptively adjust the quantitative privacy bound instead of sticking to a predetermined bound. Existing works on the accuracy-first perspective have neglected an important property of differential privacy known as post-processing immunity, which ensures that an adversary is not able to weaken the privacy guarantee by post-processing. We address this gap by determining which existing definitions in the accuracy-first perspective have post-processing immunity, and which do not. The only definition with post-processing immunity, pure ex-post privacy, lacks useful tools for practical problems, such as an ex-post analogue of the Gaussian mechanism, and an algorithm to check if accuracy on separate private validation set is high enough. To address this, we propose a new definition based on RГ©nyi differential privacy that has post-processing immunity, and we develop basic theory and tools needed for practical applications. We demonstrate the practicality of our theory with applications to synthetic data generation and image classifier fine-tuning, where our algorithm successfully adjusts the privacy bound until an accuracy threshold is met on a private validation dataset.</p>","absKo":"<p>accuracy-first perspectiveмқҳ differential privacyлҠ” лҚ°мқҙн„° л¶„м„қк°Җк°Җ мӮ¬м „м—җ м •н•ҙм§„ boundм—җ кі м •лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі  privacy boundлҘј м Ғмқ‘м ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ accuracy-first perspective м—°кө¬лҠ” post-processing immunityлқјлҠ” differential privacyмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң м„ұм§Ҳмқ„ к°„кіјн•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” adversaryк°Җ post-processingмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ privacy guaranteeлҘј м•Ҫнҷ”мӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ м—ҶлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” accuracy-first perspectiveм—җм„ң м–ҙл–Ө кё°мЎҙ м •мқҳк°Җ post-processing immunityлҘј к°Җм§ҖлҠ”м§Җ, к·ёлҰ¬кі  м–ҙл–Ө м •мқҳк°Җ к·ёл Үм§Җ м•ҠмқҖм§ҖлҘј к·ңлӘ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ к°„к·№мқ„ л©”мҡҙлӢӨ. post-processing immunityлҘј к°–лҠ” мң мқјн•ң м •мқҳмқё pure ex-post privacyлҠ” practical problemм—җ мң мҡ©н•ң лҸ„кө¬, мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ Gaussian mechanismмқҳ ex-post analogueлӮҳ лі„лҸ„мқҳ private validation setм—җм„ң accuracyк°Җ м¶©л¶„нһҲ лҶ’мқҖм§Җ нҷ•мқён•ҳлҠ” м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙ м—ҶлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” post-processing immunityлҘј к°Җм§ҖлҠ” RГ©nyi differential privacy кё°л°ҳмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м •мқҳлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳкі , мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң кё°ліё мқҙлЎ кіј лҸ„кө¬лҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” synthetic data generationкіј image classifier fine-tuningм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ мқҙлЎ мқҳ мӢӨмҡ©м„ұмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ private validation datasetм—җм„ң accuracy thresholdлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•  л•Ңк№Ңм§Җ privacy boundлҘј м„ұкіөм ҒмңјлЎң мЎ°м •н•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65287","en":"Differentially Private Continual Release with Relative Error","ko":"мғҒлҢҖ мҳӨм°ЁлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң Differentially Private м—°мҶҚ лҰҙлҰ¬мҠӨ","authors":"Bo Li, Wei Wang, Peng Ye","pos":"#3205","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=F5hjwtBmsV","abs":"This work investigates several fundamental tasks, including $\\mathsf{MaxSum}$, $\\mathsf{MinSum}$, $\\mathsf{MaxSelect}$, and $\\mathsf{MinSelect}$, in the continual release model under differential privacy. Previous research has demonstrated that any algorithm for these tasks must admit a large purely additive error. We show that the error can be substantially reduced if a relative error term is allowed, provided that the input stream is generated non-adaptively. However, when input data records can be selected adaptively, we prove that a large error is inevitable for the task of selecting an attribute with a small cumulative sum, whereas small error bounds remain achievable for other tasks. This reveals a significant separation between non-adaptive and adaptive streams. We also complement our algorithms with nearly matching lower bounds.","absKo":"мқҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” differential privacy н•ҳмқҳ continual release modelм—җм„ң $\\mathsf{MaxSum}$, $\\mathsf{MinSum}$, $\\mathsf{MaxSelect}$, $\\mathsf{MinSelect}$лҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң м—¬лҹ¬ fundamental taskлҘј мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң taskлҘј мң„н•ң м–ҙл–Ө м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙл“  нҒ° purely additive errorлҘј н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҙм•ј н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мЈјм—ҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” input streamмқҙ non-adaptively мғқм„ұлҗҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°, relative error termмқ„ н—Ҳмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ errorлҘј мғҒлӢ№нһҲ мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ input data recordлҘј adaptively м„ нғқн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„ л•ҢлҠ”, мһ‘мқҖ cumulative sumмқ„ к°–лҠ” attributeлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳлҠ” taskм—җм„ңлҠ” нҒ° errorк°Җ л¶Ҳк°Җн”јн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳлҠ” л°ҳл©ҙ, лӢӨлҘё taskл“Өм—җм„ңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ мһ‘мқҖ error boundлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” non-adaptive streamкіј adaptive stream мӮ¬мқҙм—җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң separationмқҙ мЎҙмһ¬н•Ёмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳкіј кұ°мқҳ мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” lower boundлЎң мқҙлҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"68830","en":"Differentially Private and Scalable Estimation of the Network Principal Component","ko":"л„ӨнҠёмӣҢнҒ¬ мЈјм„ұл¶„мқҳ м°Ёл¶„ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң ліҙмһҘ л°Ҹ нҷ•мһҘ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң м¶”м •","authors":"Alireza Khayatian, Anil Vullikanti, Aritra Konar","pos":"#3206","abs":"Computing the principal component (PC) of the adjacency matrix of an undirected graph has several applications ranging from identifying key vertices for influence maximization and controlling diffusion processes, to discovering densely interconnected vertex subsets. However, many networked datasets are sensitive, which necessitates private computation of the PC for use in the aforementioned applications. Differential privacy has emerged as the gold standard in privacy-preserving data analysis, but existing DP algorithms for private PC suffer from low accuracy due to large noise injection or high complexity. Motivated by the large gap between the local and global sensitivities of the PC on real-graphs, we consider instance-specific mechanisms for privately computing the PC under edge-DP. These mechanisms guarantee privacy for all datasets, but provide good utility on ``well-behaved'' datasets by injecting smaller amounts of noise. More specifically, we consider the Propose-Test-Release (PTR) framework. Although computationally expensive in general, we design a novel approach for implementing a PTR variant in the same time as computation of a non-private PC, while offering good utility. \nOur framework tests in a differentially-private manner whether a given graph is ``well-behaved'' or not, and then tests whether its private to release a noisy PC with small noise. \nAs a consequence, this also leads to the first DP algorithm for the Densest-$k$-subgraph problem, a key graph mining primitive.\nWe run our method on diverse real-world networks, with the largest having 3 million vertices, and compare its utility to a pre-existing baseline based on the private power method (PPM).\nAlthough PTR requires a slightly larger privacy budget, on average, it achieves a 180-fold improvement in runtime over PPM.","absKo":"л¬ҙл°©н–Ҙ к·ёлһҳн”„мқҳ adjacency matrixм—җ лҢҖн•ң principal component(PC)лҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ influence maximizationкіј diffusion process м ңм–ҙлҘј мң„н•ң н•өмӢ¬ м •м җ мӢқлі„л¶Җн„°, м№ҳл°Җн•ҳкІҢ мғҒнҳём—°кІ°лҗң м •м җ л¶Җл¶„м§‘н•© л°ңкІ¬м—җ мқҙлҘҙкё°к№Ңм§Җ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мқ‘мҡ©мқҙ мһҲмҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ л§ҺмқҖ networked datasetмқҖ лҜјк°җн•ҳлҜҖлЎң, м•һм„ң м–ёкёүн•ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙм„ңлҠ” PCмқҳ private computationмқҙ н•„мҡ”н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. differential privacyлҠ” privacy-preserving data analysisмқҳ gold standardлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙмқҳ private PCлҘј мң„н•ң DP м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ нҒ° noise мЈјмһ… лҳҗлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ ліөмһЎлҸ„лЎң мқён•ҙ м •нҷ•лҸ„к°Җ лӮ®мҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мӢӨм ң graphм—җм„ң PCмқҳ local sensitivityмҷҖ global sensitivity мӮ¬мқҙм—җ нҒ° кІ©м°Ёк°Җ мһҲлӢӨлҠ” м җм—җ м°©м•Ҳн•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” edge-DP н•ҳм—җм„ң PCлҘј privateн•ҳкІҢ кі„мӮ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң instance-specific mechanismмқ„ кі л Өн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң mechanismмқҖ лӘЁл“  datasetм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ privacyлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, лҚ” м ҒмқҖ м–‘мқҳ noiseлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ ``well-behaved'' datasetм—җм„ң лҶ’мқҖ utilityлҘј м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. ліҙлӢӨ кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Propose-Test-Release(PTR) frameworkлҘј кі л Өн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎңлҠ” кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқҙ нҒ¬м§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” non-private PCлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” кІғкіј к°ҷмқҖ мӢңк°„м—җ PTR ліҖнҳ•мқ„ кө¬нҳ„н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мўӢмқҖ utilityлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқ„ м„Өкі„н•©лӢҲлӢӨ.\nмҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ frameworkлҠ” мЈјм–ҙм§„ graphк°Җ ``well-behaved''мқём§Җ м•„лӢҢм§ҖлҘј differential privacy л°©мӢқмңјлЎң кІҖмӮ¬н•ң лӢӨмқҢ, privateн•ҳкІҢ releaseн• м§Җ, м•„лӢҲл©ҙ мһ‘мқҖ noiseлҘј к°Җм§„ noisy PCлҘј releaseн• м§ҖлҘј нҢҗлі„н•©лӢҲлӢӨ.\nк·ё кІ°кіј, мқҙлҠ” key graph mining primitiveмқё Densest-$k$-subgraph л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ DP м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмңјлЎңлҸ„ мқҙм–ҙм§‘лӢҲлӢӨ.\nмҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мөңлҢҖ 3л°ұл§Ң к°ңмқҳ vertexлҘј к°Җм§„ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мӢӨм ң networkм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқ„ мӢӨн–үн•ҳкі , private power method(PPM) кё°л°ҳмқҳ кё°мЎҙ baselineкіј utilityлҘј л№„көҗн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.\nPTRмқҖ м•Ҫк°„ лҚ” нҒ° privacy budgetмқ„ мҡ”кө¬н•ҳм§Җл§Ң, нҸүк· м ҒмңјлЎң PPM лҢҖл№„ мӢӨн–ү мӢңк°„м—җм„ң 180л°° н–ҘмғҒмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•©лӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62676","en":"Efficient DP-SGD for LLMs with Randomized Clipping","ko":"лһңлҚӨized Clippingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң LLMмқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ DP-SGD","authors":"Enayat Ullah, Sai Aparna Aketi, Devansh Gupta, Huanyu Zhang, Meisam Razaviyayn","pos":"#3207","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eTO6G25Jbo","abs":"Large language models (LLMs) are trained on vast datasets that may contain sensitive information. Differential privacy (DP), the de facto standard for formal privacy guarantees, provides a principled framework for training LLMs with provable privacy protection. However, state-of-the-art DP training implementations rely on *fast gradient clipping* techniques with memory  overhead $O(B\\min(T^2, d^2))$, where $B$ is the batch size, $T$ is the sequence length, and $d$ is the layer width. This becomes prohibitive as both model width and context length grow. We propose DP-SGD-RC, a novel variant of DP-SGD with *randomized clipping* that reduces memory and compute overhead.  DP-SGD-RC leverages *stochastic trace estimation* methods, specifically *Hutchinson's estimator* and its improved variant, Hutch$^{++}$, to reduce the memory footprint of per-sample gradient norm estimation.  We provide a tight privacy analysis showing that DP-SGD-RC achieves noise multipliers competitive with deterministic clipping. Experiments fine-tuning Llama 3.2 1B on long-context benchmarks spanning classification, question answering, and summarization tasks demonstrate that DP-SGD-RC matches baseline utility while significantly reducing memory and compute.","absKo":"лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ language model (LLM)мқҖ лҜјк°җн•ң м •ліҙлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” л°©лҢҖн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…ӢмңјлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗңлӢӨ. formal privacy guaranteeмқҳ мӮ¬мӢӨмғҒ н‘ңмӨҖмқё differential privacy (DP)лҠ” мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ң privacy protectionмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ LLM н•ҷмҠөмқ„ мң„н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё frameworkлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мөңмӢ  DP training кө¬нҳ„мқҖ *fast gradient clipping* кё°лІ•м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, мқҙл•Ң memory overheadлҠ” $O(B\\min(T^2, d^2))$мқҙлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ң $B$лҠ” batch size, $T$лҠ” sequence length, $d$лҠ” layer widthмқҙлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚё нҸӯкіј context кёёмқҙк°Җ лӘЁл‘җ мҰқк°Җн•ҳл©ҙ мқҙлҠ” к°җлӢ№н•ҳкё° м–ҙл ӨмӣҢм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” memoryмҷҖ compute overheadлҘј мӨ„мқҙлҠ” *randomized clipping*мқ„ м Ғмҡ©н•ң DP-SGDмқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ ліҖнҳ•мқё DP-SGD-RCлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. DP-SGD-RCлҠ” *stochastic trace estimation* л°©лІ•, нҠ№нһҲ *Hutchinson's estimator*мҷҖ к·ё к°ңм„ нҳ•мқё Hutch$^{++}$лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ sampleлі„ gradient norm м¶”м •мқҳ memory footprintлҘј мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” DP-SGD-RCк°Җ deterministic clippingкіј кІҪмҹҒл Ҙ мһҲлҠ” noise multiplierлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” м—„л°Җн•ң privacy analysisлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. classification, question answering, summarization taskм—җ кұём№ң long-context benchmarkм—җм„ң Llama 3.2 1BлҘј fine-tuningн•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ DP-SGD-RCк°Җ baseline utilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң memoryмҷҖ computeлҘј нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"62264","en":"Efficient Public Verification of Private ML via Regularization","ko":"Regularizationмқ„ нҶөн•ң Private MLмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғ кіөк°ң кІҖмҰқ","authors":"ZoГ« R Bell, Anvith Thudi, Olive Franzese-McLaughlin, Nicolas Papernot, Shafi Goldwasser","pos":"#3208","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=iCBaLQQzdK","abs":"<p>Training with differential privacy (DP) guarantees dataset members that they cannot be identified by users of the released model. However, those data providers, and, in general, the public, lack methods to efficiently verify that models trained on their data satisfy DP guarantees. The amount of compute needed to verify DP guarantees for current algorithms scales with the amount of computation required to train the model. In this paper we design the first DP algorithm with near optimal privacy-utility trade-offs but whose DP guarantees can be verified cheaper than training. We focus on DP stochastic convex optimization (DP-SCO), where optimal privacy-utility trade-offs are known. Here we show we can obtain tight privacy-utility trade-offs by privately minimizing a series of regularized objectives and only using the standard DP composition bound. Crucially, this method can be verified with much less compute than training. This leads to the first known DP-SCO algorithm with near optimal privacy-utility whose DP verification scales better than training cost, significantly reducing verification costs on large datasets.</p>","absKo":"<p>м°Ёл“ұ к°ңмқём •ліҙліҙнҳё(differential privacy, DP)лҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң н•ҷмҠөмқҖ dataset кө¬м„ұмӣҗмқҙ кіөк°ңлҗң modelмқҳ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мӢқлі„лҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ н•ҙлӢ№ data providerмҷҖ мқјл°ҳ лҢҖмӨ‘мқҖ мһҗмӢ л“Өмқҳ лҚ°мқҙн„°лЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң modelмқҙ DP ліҙмһҘмқ„ л§ҢмЎұн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•  л°©лІ•мқҙ л¶ҖмЎұн•ҳлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҳ DP ліҙмһҘмқ„ кІҖмҰқн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң compute м–‘мқҖ model н•ҷмҠөм—җ н•„мҡ”н•ң кі„мӮ°лҹүм—җ л№„лЎҖн•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” privacy-utility trade-offк°Җ кұ°мқҳ мөңм Ғмқҙл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ DP ліҙмһҘмқ„ н•ҷмҠөліҙлӢӨ лҚ” м Җл ҙн•ҳкІҢ кІҖмҰқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ DP algorithmмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” DP stochastic convex optimization(DP-SCO)м—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”л©°, м—¬кё°м„ңлҠ” мөңм Ғмқҳ privacy-utility trade-offк°Җ м•Ңл Өм ё мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқјл Ёмқҳ regularized objectiveлҘј privately minimizeн•ҳкі  standard DP composition boundл§Ңмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ tightн•ң privacy-utility trade-offлҘј м–»мқ„ мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. кІ°м •м ҒмңјлЎң, мқҙ л°©лІ•мқҖ н•ҷмҠөліҙлӢӨ нӣЁм”¬ м ҒмқҖ computeлЎң кІҖмҰқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј, DP verificationмқҙ н•ҷмҠө л№„мҡ©ліҙлӢӨ лҚ” мһҳ scaleн•ҳлҠ”, кұ°мқҳ мөңм Ғмқҳ privacy-utilityлҘј к°–лҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ м•Ңл Өм§„ DP-SCO algorithmмқ„ м–»кІҢ лҗҳл©°, лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ datasetм—җм„ңмқҳ verification л№„мҡ©мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65057","en":"Efficient privacy loss accounting for subsampling and random allocation","ko":"Subsamplingкіј л¬ҙмһ‘мң„ н• лӢ№мқ„ мң„н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң мҶҗмӢӨ нҡҢкі„","authors":"Moshe Shenfeld, Vitaly Feldman","pos":"#3209","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=HDBpda5Vih","abs":"We consider the privacy amplification properties of a sampling scheme in which a userвҖҷs data is used in $k$ steps chosen randomly and uniformly from a sequence (or set) of $t$ steps. This sampling scheme has been recently applied in the context of differentially private optimization [Chua et al., 2024a, Choquette-Choo et al., 2025] and communication-efficient high-dimensional private aggregation [Asi et al., 2025], where it was shown to have utility advantages over the standard Poisson sampling. Theoretical analyses of this sampling scheme [Feldman and Shenfeld, 2025, Dong et al., 2025] lead to bounds that are close to those of Poisson sampling, yet still have two significant shortcomings. First, in many practical settings, the resulting privacy parameters are not tight due to the approximation steps in the analysis. Second, the computed parameters are either the hockey stick or RГ©nyi divergence, both of which introduce overheads when used in privacy loss accounting. In this work, we demonstrate that the privacy loss distribution (PLD) of random allocation applied to any differentially private algorithm can be computed efficiently. When applied to the Gaussian mechanism, our results demonstrate that the privacy-utility trade-off for random allocation is at least as good as that of Poisson subsampling. In particular, random allocation is better suited for training via DP-SGD. To support these computations, our work develops new tools for general privacy loss accounting based on a notion of PLD realization. This notion allows us to extend accurate privacy loss accounting to subsampling which previously required manual noise-mechanism-specific analysis.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ sequence(лҳҗлҠ” set)лЎңл¶Җн„° л¬ҙмһ‘мң„лЎң к· мқјн•ҳкІҢ м„ нғқлҗң $t$к°ңмқҳ step мӨ‘ $k$к°ң stepм—җм„ң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” sampling schemeмқҳ privacy amplification м„ұм§Ҳмқ„ кі л Өн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ sampling schemeмқҖ мөңк·ј differential private optimization [Chua et al., 2024a, Choquette-Choo et al., 2025]кіј communication-efficient high-dimensional private aggregation [Asi et al., 2025]мқҳ л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ң м Ғмҡ©лҗҳм—Ҳмңјл©°, н‘ңмӨҖ Poisson samplingліҙлӢӨ utility мёЎл©ҙм—җм„ң мқҙм җмқҙ мһҲмқҢмқҙ ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мқҙ sampling schemeм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қ [Feldman and Shenfeld, 2025, Dong et al., 2025]мқҖ Poisson samplingм—җ к°Җк№Ңмҡҙ boundлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, м—¬м „нһҲ л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң н•ңкі„лҘј к°Җм§„лӢӨ. мІ«м§ё, л§ҺмқҖ мӢӨм ң м„Өм •м—җм„ң л¶„м„қмқҳ approximation step л•Ңл¬ём—җ кІ°кіј privacy parameterк°Җ tightн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. л‘ҳм§ё, кі„мӮ°лҗң parameterлҠ” hockey stick лҳҗлҠ” RГ©nyi divergenceмқҙл©°, л‘ҳ лӢӨ privacy loss accountingм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•  л•Ң мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мң л°ңн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мһ„мқҳмқҳ differentially private algorithmм—җ м Ғмҡ©лҗң random allocationмқҳ privacy loss distribution(PLD)мқ„ нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң кі„мӮ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. Gaussian mechanismм—җ м Ғмҡ©н•ҳл©ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” random allocationмқҳ privacy-utility trade-offк°Җ м Ғм–ҙлҸ„ Poisson subsamplingл§ҢнҒј мўӢмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ random allocationмқҖ DP-SGDлҘј нҶөн•ң н•ҷмҠөм—җ лҚ” м Ғн•©н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кі„мӮ°мқ„ м§Җмӣҗн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” PLD realization к°ңл…җм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң мқјл°ҳ privacy loss accountingмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ лҸ„кө¬лҘј к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ к°ңл…җмқҖ мқҙм „м—җлҠ” мҲҳмһ‘м—…мңјлЎң noise-mechanism-specific analysisк°Җ н•„мҡ”н–ҲлҚҳ subsamplingк№Ңм§Җ м •нҷ•н•ң privacy loss accountingмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ҙмӨҖлӢӨ."},{"id":"63734","en":"Eliminating Solution Bias in Differentially Private Optimization","ko":"м°Ёл“ұ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң мөңм Ғнҷ”м—җм„ң н•ҙлІ• нҺён–Ҙ м ңкұ°","authors":"DONGRUN LI, YUN ZENG, Zibo Wei, Jiacheng Wei, Qinnan Zhang, Faguo Wu, Xiao Zhang, Zhiming Zheng","pos":"#3210","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=UBUILLxtsH","abs":"<p>Differentially private (DP) stochastic optimization algorithms are widely used in privacy-preserving deep learning, where per-sample gradient clipping and noise injection protect sensitive information. However, these operations limit existing DP algorithms to converge within a constant-radius neighborhood of the first-order stationary point, leading to solution bias and the well-known privacy-utility trade-off. To enhance model utility, we propose a novel algorithmic framework called DP-C4, which is designed to be error-Consistently-vanishing, Coupledly-clipped, solution-Calibrated, and Convergence-guaranteed. Specifically, it incorporates a carefully designed coupled clipping scheme with shifted threshold strategy, ensuring that both clipping bias and noise variance asymptotically vanish, thereby eliminating the DP-induced solution bias. Moreover, we extend existing sensitivity analysis techniques and develop a tailored privacy budget allocation to guarantee the privacy of DP-C4. Compared with the well-recognized DP-SGD, our framework injects significantly less noise under the same privacy level. In addition, we prove that our framework converges to the optimum in strongly-convex case  and to a diminishing neighborhood of the first-order stationary point in non-convex case. Experiments show that DP-C4 achieves superior privacy-utility trade-off over existing baselines across various tasks and datasets.</p>","absKo":"<p>м°Ёл“ұм ҒмңјлЎң н”„лқјмқҙл№—н•ң(DP) stochastic optimization м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ privacy-preserving deep learningм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳл©°, мғҳн”Ңлі„ gradient clippingкіј noise injectionмңјлЎң лҜјк°җн•ң м •ліҙлҘј ліҙнҳён•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м—°мӮ°мқҖ кё°мЎҙ DP м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҙ first-order stationary pointмқҳ мқјм •н•ң л°ҳкІҪ мқҙмӣғ лӮҙм—җм„ңл§Ң мҲҳл ҙн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ м ңн•ңн•ҳм—¬, solution biasмҷҖ л„җлҰ¬ м•Ңл Өм§„ privacy-utility trade-offлҘј мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚё мң нӢёлҰ¬нӢ°лҘј н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” error-Consistently-vanishing, Coupledly-clipped, solution-Calibrated, Convergence-guaranteedлҘј лӘ©н‘ңлЎң м„Өкі„лҗң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬ DP-C4лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мқҙлҠ” shifted threshold м „лһөмқ„ к°–лҠ” м •көҗн•ҳкІҢ м„Өкі„лҗң coupled clipping schemeмқ„ нҶөн•©н•ҳм—¬ clipping biasмҷҖ noise varianceк°Җ м җк·јм ҒмңјлЎң лӘЁл‘җ мҶҢл©ён•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ DPлЎң мқён•ң solution biasлҘј м ңкұ°н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң кё°мЎҙ sensitivity analysis кё°лІ•мқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•ҳкі , DP-C4мқҳ privacyлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң л§һм¶Өнҳ• privacy budget allocationмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. л„җлҰ¬ м•Ңл Өм§„ DP-SGDмҷҖ л№„көҗн•  л•Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬лҠ” лҸҷмқјн•ң privacy levelм—җм„ң нӣЁм”¬ м ҒмқҖ noiseлҘј мЈјмһ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ н”„л Ҳмһ„мӣҢнҒ¬к°Җ strongly-convex кІҪмҡ°м—җлҠ” optimumмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•ҳкі  non-convex кІҪмҡ°м—җлҠ” first-order stationary pointмқҳ м җм җ мӨ„м–ҙл“ңлҠ” мқҙмӣғмңјлЎң мҲҳл ҙн•Ёмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіј, DP-C4лҠ” лӢӨм–‘н•ң taskмҷҖ dataset м „л°ҳм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ baselineліҙлӢӨ мҡ°мҲҳн•ң privacy-utility trade-offлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64707","en":"FHAIM: Fully Homomorphic AIM for Private Synthetic Data Generation","ko":"FHAIM: н”„лқјмқҙл№— н•©м„ұ лҚ°мқҙн„° мғқм„ұмқ„ мң„н•ң Fully Homomorphic AIM","authors":"Mayank Kumar, Qian Lou, Paulo Barreto, Martine De Cock, Sikha Pentyala","pos":"#3211","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=KfLkjLH7s4","abs":"<p>Data is the lifeblood of AI, yet much of the most valuable data remains locked in silos due to privacy and regulations. As a result, AI remains heavily underutilized in many of the most important domains, including healthcare, education, and finance. Synthetic data generation (SDG), i.e.~the generation of artificial data   with a synthesizer trained on real data, offers an appealing solution to make data available while mitigating privacy concerns, however existing SDG-as-a-service workflow require data holders to trust providers with access to private data.  We propose FHAIM, the first fully homomorphic encryption (FHE) framework for training a marginal-based synthetic data generator on encrypted tabular data. FHAIM adapts the widely used AIM algorithm to the FHE setting using novel FHE protocols, ensuring that the private data remains encrypted throughout and is released only with differential privacy guarantees. Our empirical analysis show that FHAIM preserves the performance of AIM while maintaining feasible runtimes.</p>","absKo":"<p>DataлҠ” AIмқҳ мғқлӘ…м„ мқҙм§Җл§Ң, к°ҖмһҘ к°Җм№ҳ мһҲлҠ” dataмқҳ мғҒлӢ№ л¶Җл¶„мқҖ privacyмҷҖ regulation л•Ңл¬ём—җ siloм—җ к°ҮнҳҖ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј healthcare, education, financeлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң л§ҺмқҖ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң мҳҒм—ӯм—җм„ң AIлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ нҒ¬кІҢ нҷңмҡ©лҗҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. Synthetic data generation (SDG), мҰү real dataлЎң н•ҷмҠөлҗң synthesizerлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ мқёкіө dataлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” л°©мӢқмқҖ dataлҘј нҷңмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳл©ҙм„ң privacy concernsлҘј мҷ„нҷ”н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” л§Өл Ҙм Ғмқё н•ҙлІ•мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙмқҳ SDG-as-a-service workflowлҠ” data holderк°Җ providerм—җкІҢ private data м ‘к·јмқ„ мӢ лў°н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” encrypted tabular data мң„м—җм„ң marginal-based synthetic data generatorлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ fully homomorphic encryption (FHE) frameworkмқё FHAIMмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. FHAIMмқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ FHE protocolмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ л„җлҰ¬ м“°мқҙлҠ” AIM algorithmмқ„ FHE settingм—җ л§һкІҢ мЎ°м •н•ҳл©°, private dataк°Җ м „ кіјм •м—җм„ң м•”нҳёнҷ”лҗң мғҒнғңлЎң мң м§Җлҗҳкі  differential privacy ліҙмһҘ н•ҳм—җм„ңл§Ң кіөк°ңлҗҳлҸ„лЎқ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мӢӨмҰқ л¶„м„қмқҖ FHAIMмқҙ AIMмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мӢӨн–ү мӢңк°„мқ„ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё мҲҳмӨҖмңјлЎң мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61190","en":"Finding Differentially Private Second Order Stationary Points in Stochastic Minimax Optimization","ko":"Stochastic Minimax Optimizationм—җм„ң Differentially Private 2м°Ё м •мғҒм җ м°ҫкё°","authors":"Difei Xu, Youming Tao, Meng Ding, Chenglin Fan, Di Wang","pos":"#3213","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=st1MolZlTP","abs":"We provide the first study of the problem of finding differentially private (DP) second-order stationary points (SOSP) in  stochastic (non-convex) minimax optimization.  Existing literature either focuses only on first-order stationary points for minimax problems or on SOSP for classical stochastic minimization problems. This work provides, for the first time, a unified and detailed treatment of both empirical  and population risks. Specifically, we propose a purely first-order method that combines a nested gradient descent--ascent scheme with SPIDER-style variance reduction and Gaussian perturbations to ensure privacy. A key technical device is a block-wise ($q$-period) analysis that controls the accumulation of stochastic variance and privacy noise without summing over the full iteration horizon, yielding a unified treatment of both empirical-risk and population formulations. Under standard smoothness, Hessian-Lipschitzness, and strong concavity assumptions, we establish high-probability guarantees for reaching an $(\\alpha,\\sqrt{\\rho_\\Phi \\alpha})$-approximate second-order stationary point with $\\alpha = \\mathcal{O}(  (\\frac{\\sqrt{d}}{n\\varepsilon})^{2/3})$ for empirical risk objectives and $\\mathcal{O}(\\frac{1}{n^{1/3}} + (\\frac{\\sqrt{d}}{n\\varepsilon})^{1/2})$ for population objectives, matching the best known rates for private first-order stationarity.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” stochastic (non-convex) minimax optimizationм—җм„ң differentially private (DP) second-order stationary point (SOSP)лҘј м°ҫлҠ” л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мІ« лІҲм§ё м—°кө¬лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” minimax л¬ём ңмқҳ first-order stationary pointм—җл§Ң мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”кұ°лӮҳ, classical stochastic minimization problemмқҳ SOSPм—җл§Ң мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶° мҷ”лӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” empirical riskмҷҖ population riskлҘј лӘЁл‘җ м•„мҡ°лҘҙлҠ” нҶөн•©м Ғмқҙкі  мғҒм„ён•ң мІҳлҰ¬лҘј мІҳмқҢмңјлЎң м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” privacyлҘј ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ nested gradient descent--ascent schemeкіј SPIDER-style variance reduction, Gaussian perturbationмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ң мҲңмҲҳ first-order methodлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. н•өмӢ¬ кё°мҲ  мһҘм№ҳлҠ” full iteration horizonм—җ кұёміҗ н•©мӮ°н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡкі лҸ„ stochastic varianceмҷҖ privacy noiseмқҳ лҲ„м Ғмқ„ м ңм–ҙн•ҳлҠ” block-wise($q$-period) analysisлЎң, empirical-risk formulationкіј population formulationмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ нҶөн•©м ҒмңјлЎң лӢӨлЈ° мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. н‘ңмӨҖм Ғмқё smoothness, Hessian-Lipschitzness, strong concavity assumption н•ҳм—җм„ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” empirical risk objectiveм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ $\\alpha = \\mathcal{O}(  (\\frac{\\sqrt{d}}{n\\varepsilon})^{2/3})$мқё $(\\alpha,\\sqrt{\\rho_\\Phi \\alpha})$-approximate second-order stationary pointм—җ лҸ„лӢ¬н•ҳкі , population objectiveм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” $\\mathcal{O}(\\frac{1}{n^{1/3}} + (\\frac{\\sqrt{d}}{n\\varepsilon})^{1/2})$мқҳ ліҙмһҘмңјлЎң лҸ„лӢ¬н•Ёмқ„ high probabilityлЎң мҰқлӘ…н•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” private first-order stationarityм—җ лҢҖн•ң м•Ңл Өм§„ мөңм„ мқҳ rateмҷҖ мқјм№ҳн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65291","en":"Finding DoRI: Discovery of Retained Images in Diffusion Models","ko":"DoRI м°ҫкё°: Diffusion Modelм—җм„ң ліҙмЎҙлҗң мқҙлҜём§Җ л°ңкІ¬","authors":"Antoni Kowalczuk, Dominik Hintersdorf, Lukas Struppek, Kristian Kersting, Adam Dziedzic, Franziska Boenisch","pos":"#3214","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=F3uCTULtDZ","abs":"<p>Text-to-image diffusion models (DMs) have achieved remarkable success in image generation. However, concerns about data privacy and intellectual property remain due to their potential to inadvertently memorize and replicate training data. Recent mitigation efforts have focused on identifying and pruning weights responsible for triggering verbatim training data replication, based on the assumption that memorization can be localized. We challenge this assumption and demonstrate that, even after such pruning, small perturbations to the text embeddings of previously mitigated prompts can re-trigger data replication, revealing the fragility of such methods. Our further analysis then provides multiple indications that memorization is indeed <em>not</em> inherently local: (1) replication triggers for memorized images are distributed throughout text embedding space; (2) embeddings yielding the same replicated image produce divergent model activations; and (3) different pruning methods identify inconsistent sets of memorization-related weights for the same image. Finally, we show that bypassing the locality assumption enables more robust mitigation through adversarial fine-tuning. These findings provide new insights into the fundamental nature of memorization in text-to-image DMs and inform the future development of more reliable mitigation methods against DM memorization.</p>","absKo":"<p>text-to-image diffusion model(DM)мқҖ мқҙлҜём§Җ мғқм„ұм—җм„ң remarkableн•ң м„ұкіөмқ„ кұ°л‘җм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ training dataлҘј мқҳлҸ„м№ҳ м•ҠкІҢ memorizationн•ҳкі  ліөм ңн•  к°ҖлҠҘм„ұ л•Ңл¬ём—җ data privacyмҷҖ intellectual propertyм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҡ°л Өк°Җ м—¬м „нһҲ лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ мҷ„нҷ” л…ёл ҘмқҖ memorizationмқҙ localizedлҗҳм–ҙ мһҲлӢӨкі  к°Җм •н•ҳкі , training dataлҘј л¬ёмһҗ к·ёлҢҖлЎң ліөм ңн•ҳлҠ” нҠёлҰ¬кұ° м—ӯн• мқҳ weightлҘј мӢқлі„н•ҙ pruningн•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”м–ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ к°Җм •м—җ лҸ„м „н•ҳл©°, к·ёлҹ¬н•ң pruning мқҙнӣ„м—җлҸ„ мқҙм „м—җ мҷ„нҷ”лҗң promptмқҳ text embeddingм—җ мһ‘мқҖ perturbationл§Ң к°Җн•ҙлҸ„ data replicationмқҙ лӢӨмӢң мҙүл°ңлҗ  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙм—¬, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л°©лІ•мқҳ м·Ём•Ҫм„ұмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮёлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм§ҖлҠ” м¶”к°Җ л¶„м„қмқҖ memorizationмқҙ мӢӨм ңлЎң ліём§Ҳм ҒмңјлЎң localн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨлҠ” м—¬лҹ¬ м§•нӣ„лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. (1) memorized imageмқҳ replication triggerлҠ” text embedding space м „л°ҳм—җ л¶„нҸ¬н•ңлӢӨ. (2) лҸҷмқјн•ң replicated imageлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” embeddingмқҖ м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё model activationмқ„ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙлӮёлӢӨ. (3) м„ңлЎң лӢӨлҘё pruning л°©лІ•мқҖ лҸҷмқјн•ң imageм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ memorization кҙҖл Ё weightмқҳ мқјкҙҖлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ м§‘н•©мқ„ мӢқлі„н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, locality assumptionмқ„ мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳл©ҙ adversarial fine-tuningмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ лҚ” robustн•ң мҷ„нҷ”к°Җ к°ҖлҠҘн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҠ” text-to-image DMм—җм„ң memorizationмқҳ к·јліём Ғ м„ұкІ©м—җ лҢҖн•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл©°, DM memorizationм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҚ” мӢ лў°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мҷ„нҷ” л°©лІ•мқҳ н–Ҙнӣ„ к°ңл°ңм—җ мӢңмӮ¬м җмқ„ мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63483","en":"FuseFSS: Efficient Secure LLM Inference with Function Secret Sharing","ko":"FuseFSS: Function Secret Sharingмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң нҡЁмңЁм Ғ ліҙм•Ҳ LLM м¶”лЎ ","authors":"Yuhan Ma, Yong Li, Stefan Schmid","pos":"#3215","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=WpUpj8DrVB","abs":"Two-server secure inference allows a client to query a hosted large language model (LLM) without revealing prompts or embeddings. Recent GPU systems based on function secret sharing (FSS) make linear layers efficient, but fixed-point nonlinearities and helper operations remain a bottleneck because each operator is typically implemented as a bespoke protocol with its own comparisons, wrap-around corrections, and preprocessing material. We present FuseFSS, a compiler that replaces per-operator protocol design with a single compilation pipeline. For each scalar fixed-point operator, a compact specification lists its interval partition, low-degree arithmetic pieces, and required predicate bits. The compiler emits two batched FSS evaluations on the public masked value: one packed comparison that returns all predicate bits, and one vector interval lookup that returns the active coefficients and constants. Compared to the current state-of-the-art FSS-based GPU secure inference, FuseFSS preserves accuracy while achieving a $1.24\\times$--$1.50\\times$ end-to-end speedup and reducing online communication by 9%--16% on BERT and GPT-style models; preprocessing is also lighter, with 14%--23% lower key-generation time and 20%--24% smaller keys.","absKo":"two-server secure inferenceлҠ” clientк°Җ promptлӮҳ embeddingмқ„ л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙм§Җ м•Ҡкі  hosted large language model(LLM)м—җ м§Ҳмқҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. function secret sharing(FSS) кё°л°ҳмқҳ мөңк·ј GPU мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқҖ linear layerлҘј нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң л§Ңл“Өм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, fixed-point nonlinearitiesмҷҖ helper operationмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ лі‘лӘ©мңјлЎң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. к°Ғ operatorк°Җ ліҙнҶө мһҗмІҙм Ғмқё comparison, wrap-around correction, preprocessing materialмқ„ к°–лҠ” м „мҡ© protocolлЎң кө¬нҳ„лҗҳкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” per-operator protocol м„Өкі„лҘј н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ compilation pipelineмңјлЎң лҢҖмІҙн•ҳлҠ” compiler FuseFSSлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. к°Ғ scalar fixed-point operatorм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ, к°„кІ°н•ң specificationмқҙ interval partition, low-degree arithmetic piece, н•„мҡ”н•ң predicate bitлҘј лӮҳм—ҙн•ңлӢӨ. compilerлҠ” public masked value мң„м—җм„ң л‘җ лІҲмқҳ batched FSS evaluationмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” лӘЁл“  predicate bitлҘј л°ҳнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” packed comparisonмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” нҷңм„ұ кі„мҲҳмҷҖ мғҒмҲҳлҘј л°ҳнҷҳн•ҳлҠ” vector interval lookupмқҙлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬ state-of-the-art FSS кё°л°ҳ GPU secure inferenceмҷҖ л№„көҗн•ҳл©ҙ, FuseFSSлҠ” м •нҷ•лҸ„лҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң BERT л°Ҹ GPT-style modelм—җм„ң end-to-end speedup 1.24Г—--1.50Г—лҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  online communicationмқ„ 9%--16% мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. preprocessing лҳҗн•ң лҚ” к°ҖлІјмӣҢм ё key-generation timeмқҙ 14%--23% к°җмҶҢн•ҳкі  key нҒ¬кё°лҠ” 20%--24% мһ‘м•„м§„лӢӨ."},{"id":"62333","en":"Privately Fine-Tuned LLMs Preserve Temporal Dynamics in Tabular Data","ko":"к°ңмқё л§һм¶Ө нҢҢмқёнҠңлӢқлҗң LLMмқҙ нғӯнҳ• лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ мӢңк°„м Ғ лҸҷм—ӯн•ҷмқ„ ліҙмЎҙ","authors":"Lucas Rosenblatt, Peihan Liu, Ryan McKenna, Natalia Ponomareva","pos":"#3505","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=hZJAUJ5l9t","abs":"<p>Research on differentially private synthetic tabular data has largely focused on independent and identically distributed rows where each record corresponds to a unique individual. This perspective neglects the temporal complexity in longitudinal datasets, such as electronic health records, where a user contributes an entire (sub) table of sequential events. While practitioners might attempt to model such data by flattening user histories into high-dimensional vectors for use with standard marginal-based mechanisms, we demonstrate that this strategy is insufficient. Flattening fails to preserve temporal coherence even when it maintains valid marginal distributions. We introduce PATH, a novel generative framework that treats the full table as the unit of synthesis and leverages the autoregressive capabilities of privately fine-tuned large language models. Extensive evaluations show that PATH effectively captures long-range dependencies that traditional methods miss. Empirically, our method reduces the distributional distance to real trajectories by over 60% and reduces state transition errors by nearly 50% compared to leading marginal mechanisms while achieving similar marginal fidelity.</p>","absKo":"<p>м°Ёл“ұ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢңлҘј л§ҢмЎұн•ҳлҠ” synthetic tabular data м—°кө¬лҠ” мЈјлЎң к°Ғ recordк°Җ кі мң н•ң к°ңмқём—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” лҸ…лҰҪ лҸҷмқјл¶„нҸ¬(i.i.d.) н–үм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶° мҷ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кҙҖм җмқҖ electronic health recordsмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ longitudinal datasetм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” мӢңк°„м Ғ ліөмһЎм„ұмқ„ к°„кіјн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙл•Ң н•ң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗлҠ” мҲңм°Ём Ғ мқҙлІӨнҠёлЎң мқҙлЈЁм–ҙм§„ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ (sub) table м „мІҙлҘј кё°м—¬н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨл¬ҙм—җм„ңлҠ” н‘ңмӨҖ marginal-based mechanismмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ мқҙл Ҙмқ„ кі м°Ёмӣҗ лІЎн„°лЎң нҸүнғ„нҷ”(flattening)н•ҳм—¬ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳл Ө н•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ м „лһөмқҙ м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. FlatteningмқҖ мң нҡЁн•ң marginal distributionмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ temporal coherenceлҘј ліҙмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м „мІҙ tableмқ„ synthesisмқҳ лӢЁмң„лЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳкі  privately fine-tuned large language modelмқҳ autoregressive лҠҘл Ҙмқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ generative frameworkмқё PATHлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҸүк°ҖлҘј нҶөн•ҙ PATHк°Җ м „нҶөм Ғ л°©лІ•мқҙ лҶ“м№ҳлҠ” мһҘкұ°лҰ¬ мқҳмЎҙм„ұмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң нҸ¬м°©н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. кІҪн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ л°©лІ•мқҖ distributional distanceлҘј мӢӨм ң trajectoryм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ 60% мқҙмғҒ мӨ„мқҙкі , state transition errorлҘј м„ лҸ„м Ғмқё marginal mechanism лҢҖл№„ кұ°мқҳ 50% к°җмҶҢмӢңнӮӨл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ мң мӮ¬н•ң marginal fidelityлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"64491","en":"Censoring with Plausible Deniability: Asymmetric Local Privacy for Multi-Category CDF Estimation","ko":"к·ёлҹҙл“Ҝн•ң л¶Җмқё к°ҖлҠҘм„ұмқ„ к°–лҠ” кІҖм—ҙ: лӢӨмӨ‘ лІ”мЈј CDF м¶”м •мқ„ мң„н•ң л№„лҢҖм№ӯ лЎңм»¬ н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң","authors":"Qirui Hu, Yi Liu","pos":"#3901","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=N1xLII8u6o","abs":"<p>We introduce a new mechanism within the Utility-Optimized Local Differential Privacy (ULDP) framework that enables censoring with plausible deniability when collecting and analyzing sensitive data. Our approach addresses scenarios where certain values, such as large numerical responses, are more privacy-sensitive than others, while accompanying categorical information may not be private on its own but could still be identifying. The mechanism selectively withholds identifying details when a response might indicate sensitive content, offering asymmetric privacy protection. Unlike previous methods, it avoids the need to predefine which values are sensitive, making it more adaptable and practical. Although the mechanism is designed for ULDP, it can also be applied under symmetric LDP settings, where it still benefits from censoring and reduced privacy cost. We provide theoretical guarantees, including uniform consistency and pointwise weak convergence results. Numerical experiments on both synthetic data and real-world data were conducted demonstrate the validity of developed methodologies.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Utility-Optimized Local Differential Privacy(ULDP) framework лӮҙм—җм„ң лҜјк°җн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°лҘј мҲҳм§‘н•ҳкі  л¶„м„қн•  л•Ң plausible deniabilityлҘј к°–лҠ” censoringмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ mechanismмқ„ мҶҢк°ңн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ нҒ° мҲҳм№ҳ мқ‘лӢөмІҳлҹј м–ҙл–Ө к°’л“ӨмқҖ лӢӨлҘё к°’л“ӨліҙлӢӨ лҚ” privacy-sensitiveн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, мқҙм—җ лҸҷл°ҳлҗҳлҠ” categorical informationмқҖ к·ё мһҗмІҙлЎңлҠ” privateн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҚ”лқјлҸ„ м—¬м „нһҲ мӢқлі„м—җ нҷңмҡ©лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” мғҒнҷ©мқ„ лӢӨлЈ№лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ mechanismмқҖ мқ‘лӢөмқҙ лҜјк°җн•ң лӮҙмҡ©мқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„ л•Ң мӢқлі„ к°ҖлҠҘ м„ёл¶Җ м •ліҙлҘј м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң мҲЁкІЁ, л№„лҢҖм№ӯм Ғ privacy protectionмқ„ м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©лІ•кіј лӢ¬лҰ¬ м–ҙл–Ө к°’мқҙ sensitiveн•ңм§ҖлҘј лҜёлҰ¬ м •мқҳн•  н•„мҡ”к°Җ м—Ҷм–ҙ, лҚ” м Ғмқ‘м Ғмқҙкі  мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмһ…лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ mechanismмқҖ ULDPлҘј мң„н•ҙ м„Өкі„лҗҳм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, symmetric LDP м„Өм •м—җм„ңлҸ„ м Ғмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, мқҙ кІҪмҡ°м—җлҸ„ censoringкіј reduced privacy costмқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ м–»мҠөлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” uniform consistencyмҷҖ pointwise weak convergence кІ°кіјлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. synthetic dataмҷҖ real-world data лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ к°ңл°ңлҗң methodologyмқҳ нғҖлӢ№м„ұмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65064","en":"FlatLand: Personalized Graph Federated Learning via Tailored Lorentz Space","ko":"FlatLand: л§һм¶Өнҳ• Lorentz SpaceлҘј нҶөн•ң к°ңмқёнҷ”лҗң Graph Federated Learning","authors":"Jiahong Liu, Ram Samarth B B, Xinyu Fu, Menglin Yang, Weixi Zhang, ZHITAO YING, Irwin King","pos":"#3906","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=H6PagZKyil","abs":"<p>Personalization has become a pivotal field of study in contemporary intelligent systems. While large language models (LLMs) excel at general knowledge tasks, they often struggle with personalization, i.e., adapting their outputs to individual user expectations. Existing approaches that steer LLM behavior to meet usersвҖҷ implicit preferences and behavior patterns, primarily relying on tune-free methods (e.g., RAG, PAG) or parameter fine-tuning methods (e.g., LoRA), face challenges in effectively balancing effectiveness and efficiency. Moreover, the mechanisms underlying personalized preferences remain underexplored. To address these challenges, we first uncover key patterns of user-specific information embedded in the representation space. Specifically, we find that (1) personalized information lies within a low-rank subspace represented by vectors, and (2) these vectors demonstrate both a collective shift shared across users and a personalized shift unique to each individual user. Building on these insights, we introduce PerFit, a novel two-stage solution that directly fine-tunes interventions in the hidden representation space by addressing both collective and user-specific shifts, thereby achieving precise steering of LLM with minimal parameter overhead. Experimental results demonstrate that \\perfit delivers strong performance across six datasets while \\cutting the number of parameters by an average of 92.3% compared to the state-of-the-art method.</p>","absKo":"<p>personalizationмқҖ нҳ„лҢҖ м§ҖлҠҘнҳ• мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җм„ң н•өмӢ¬м Ғмқё м—°кө¬ л¶„м•јк°Җ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. лҢҖк·ңлӘЁ м–ём–ҙ лӘЁлҚё(LLM)мқҖ мқјл°ҳ м§ҖмӢқ кіјм ңм—җм„ңлҠ” лӣ°м–ҙлӮҳм§Җл§Ң, к°ңмқёнҷ”, мҰү к°ңлі„ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ кё°лҢҖм—җ л§һкІҢ м¶ңл Ҙмқ„ мЎ°м •н•ҳлҠ” лҚ°м—җлҠ” мў…мў… м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗмқҳ м•”л¬өм Ғ м„ нҳёмҷҖ н–үлҸҷ нҢЁн„ҙмқ„ м¶©мЎұн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ LLM лҸҷмһ‘мқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мЈјлЎң tune-free л°©лІ•(мҳҲ: RAG, PAG)мқҙлӮҳ parameter fine-tuning л°©лІ•(мҳҲ: LoRA)м—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳл©°, нҡЁкіјм„ұкіј нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң к· нҳ• мһҲкІҢ л§һм¶”лҠ” лҚ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. лҚ”кө¬лӮҳ personalized preferenceлҘј л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳлҠ” л©”м»ӨлӢҲмҰҳмқҖ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лЁјм Җ representation spaceм—җ лӮҙмһ¬лҗң мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ нҠ№мқҙм Ғ м •ліҙмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ нҢЁн„ҙмқ„ л°қнҳҖлӮёлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, (1) personalized informationмқҖ vectorлЎң н‘ңнҳ„лҗҳлҠ” low-rank subspaceм—җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳл©°, (2) мқҙлҹ¬н•ң vectorлҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗл“Ө мӮ¬мқҙм—җ кіөмң лҗҳлҠ” collective shiftмҷҖ к°Ғ к°ңмқё мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗм—җкІҢ кі мң н•ң personalized shiftлҘј лӘЁл‘җ ліҙмқёлӢӨлҠ” кІғмқ„ л°ңкІ¬н–ҲлӢӨ. мқҙ нҶөм°°мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” collective shiftмҷҖ user-specific shiftлҘј лӘЁл‘җ лӢӨлЈЁм–ҙ hidden representation spaceм—җм„ңмқҳ interventionмқ„ м§Ғм ‘ fine-tuningн•ҳлҠ” мғҲлЎңмҡҙ 2лӢЁкі„ н•ҙлІ• PerFitмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мөңмҶҢн•ңмқҳ parameter overheadлЎң LLMмқ„ м •л°Җн•ҳкІҢ steeringн•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” \\perfitмқҙ 6к°ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣ м „л°ҳм—җм„ң к°•н•ң м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ, мөңмӢ  state-of-the-art л°©лІ•кіј л№„көҗн•ҙ parameter мҲҳлҘј нҸүк·  92.3% мӨ„мһ„мқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"68825","en":"FedLog: Personalized Federated Classification with Less Communication and More Flexibility","ko":"FedLog: лҚ” м ҒмқҖ нҶөмӢ кіј лҚ” лҶ’мқҖ мң м—°м„ұмқ„ к°–м¶ҳ к°ңмқёнҷ”лҗң Federated Classification","authors":"Haolin Yu, Guojun Zhang, Hongliang Li, Pascal Poupart","pos":"#4214","abs":"<p>Federated representation learning (FRL) aims to learn personalized federated models with effective feature extraction from local data. FRL algorithms that share the majority of the model parameters face significant challenges with huge communication overhead. This overhead stems from the millions of neural network parameters and slow aggregation progress of the averaging heuristic. To reduce the overhead, we propose FedLog, which shares sufficient data summaries instead of raw model parameters. The data summaries encode minimal sufficient statistics of an exponential family, and Bayesian inference is utilized for global aggregation. FedLog helps  reduce message sizes and communication frequency. We prove that the shared messages are minimal sufficient statistics and theoretically analyze the convergence rate of FedLog. To further ensure formal privacy guarantees, we extend FedLog with the differential privacy framework. Empirical results demonstrate high learning accuracy with low communication overhead of our method.</p>","absKo":"<p>Federated representation learning(FRL)мқҖ local dataлЎңл¶Җн„° нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё feature extractionмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” personalized federated modelмқ„ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•©лӢҲлӢӨ. лӘЁлҚё нҢҢлқјлҜён„°мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқ„ кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” FRL м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ л§үлҢҖн•ң communication overheadлЎң мқён•ҙ нҒ° м–ҙл ӨмӣҖм—җ м§Ғл©ҙн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң overheadлҠ” мҲҳл°ұл§Ң к°ңмқҳ neural network нҢҢлқјлҜён„°мҷҖ averaging heuristicмқҳ лҠҗлҰ° aggregation progressм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ overheadлҘј мӨ„мқҙкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” raw model parameter лҢҖмӢ  м¶©л¶„н•ң data summaryлҘј кіөмң н•ҳлҠ” FedLogмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мқҙ data summaryлҠ” exponential familyмқҳ minimal sufficient statisticмқ„ мқёмҪ”л”©н•ҳл©°, global aggregationм—җлҠ” Bayesian inferenceк°Җ нҷңмҡ©лҗ©лӢҲлӢӨ. FedLogмқҖ message sizeмҷҖ communication frequencyлҘј мӨ„мқҙлҠ” лҚ° лҸ„мӣҖмқ„ мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кіөмң лҗҳлҠ” messageк°Җ minimal sufficient statisticмһ„мқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ҳкі , FedLogмқҳ convergence rateлҘј мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң л¶„м„қн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. formal privacy guaranteeлҘј м¶”к°ҖлЎң ліҙмһҘн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, differential privacy frameworkлЎң FedLogмқ„ нҷ•мһҘн•©лӢҲлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” м ңм•Ҳ л°©лІ•мқҙ лӮ®мқҖ communication overheadлЎңлҸ„ лҶ’мқҖ learning accuracyлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҚлӢҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"67165","en":"Position: Embodied AI Requires a Privacy-Utility Tradeoff","ko":"Position: Embodied AIм—җлҠ” н”„лқјмқҙлІ„мӢң-нҡЁмҡ© нҠёл Ҳмқҙл“ңмҳӨн”„к°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ","authors":"Xiaoliang Fan, jiarui chen, Zhuodong Liu, Ziqi Yang, Peixuan Xu, Ruimin Shen, Junhui Liu, Jianzhong Qi, Cheng Wang","pos":"#506","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=OXZCYQveoG","abs":"<p>Embodied AI (EAI) systems are rapidly transitioning from simulations into real-world domestic and other sensitive environments. However, recent EAI solutions have largely demonstrated advancements within \\emph{isolated stages} such as instruction, perception, planning and interaction, without considering their coupled privacy implications in high-frequency deployments where privacy leakage is often irreversible. This position paper argues that optimizing these components independently creates a systemic privacy crisis when deployed in sensitive settings, thereby advancing the position that privacy in EAI is a life cycle-level architectural constraint rather than a stage-local feature. To address these challenges, we propose Secure Privacy Integration in Next-generation Embodied AI~(\\textbf{SPINE}), a unified privacy-aware framework that treats privacy as a dynamic control signal governing \\emph{cross-stage} coupling throughout the entire EAI life cycle. SPINE decomposes the EAI pipeline into various stages and establishes a multi-criterion privacy classification matrix to orchestrate contextual sensitivity across stage boundaries. We conduct preliminary simulation and real-world case studies to conceptually validate how privacy constraints propagate downstream to reshape system behavior, illustrating the insufficiency of fragmented privacy patches and motivating future research directions into secure yet functional embodied AI systems.</p>","absKo":"<p>Embodied AI(EAI) systemмқҖ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳм—җм„ң мӢӨм ң к°Җм • л°Ҹ кё°нғҖ лҜјк°җн•ң нҷҳкІҪмңјлЎң л№ лҘҙкІҢ м „нҷҳлҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мөңк·ј EAI solutionмқҖ мЈјлЎң instruction, perception, planning, interactionкіј к°ҷмқҖ \\emph{isolated stage} лӮҙмқҳ л°ңм „л§Ңмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјм—Ҳмқ„ лҝҗ, privacy leakageк°Җ мў…мў… л№„к°Җм—ӯм Ғмқё кі л№ҲлҸ„ л°°нҸ¬ нҷҳкІҪм—җм„ң мқҙл“Ө к°„мқҳ кІ°н•©лҗң privacy implicationмқҖ кі л Өн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ position paperлҠ” мқҙлҹ¬н•ң componentлҘј лҸ…лҰҪм ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ лҜјк°җн•ң нҷҳкІҪм—җ л°°нҸ¬лҗ  л•Ң мІҙкі„м Ғмқё privacy crisisлҘј л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ лӮёлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ҳл©°, EAIмқҳ privacyлҠ” stage-local featureк°Җ м•„лӢҲлқј life cycle мҲҳмӨҖмқҳ architectural constraintлқјлҠ” мһ…мһҘмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң лҸ„м „м—җ лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Secure Privacy Integration in Next-generation Embodied AI~(\\textbf{SPINE})лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. SPINEмқҖ privacyлҘј м „мІҙ EAI life cycleм—җ кұёміҗ \\emph{cross-stage} couplingмқ„ мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳлҠ” dynamic control signalлЎң м·Ёкёүн•ҳлҠ” нҶөн•© privacy-aware frameworkмқҙлӢӨ. SPINEмқҖ EAI pipelineмқ„ м—¬лҹ¬ stageлЎң л¶„н•ҙн•ҳкі , stage кІҪкі„лҘј к°ҖлЎңм§ҖлҘҙлҠ” contextual sensitivityлҘј мЎ°мңЁн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң лӢӨкё°мӨҖ privacy classification matrixлҘј кө¬м¶•н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” preliminary simulationкіј мӢӨм ң мӮ¬лЎҖ м—°кө¬лҘј мҲҳн–үн•ҳм—¬ privacy constraintк°Җ downstreamмңјлЎң м „нҢҢлҗҳм–ҙ system behaviorлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ к°ңл…җм ҒмңјлЎң кІҖмҰқн•ҳкі , нҢҢнҺёнҷ”лҗң privacy patchмқҳ л¶Ҳм¶©л¶„н•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬ мЈјл©°, м•Ҳм „н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ кё°лҠҘм Ғмқё embodied AI systemм—җ лҢҖн•ң н–Ҙнӣ„ м—°кө¬ л°©н–Ҙмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61646","en":"Making Models Unmergeable via Scaling-Sensitive Loss Landscape","ko":"мҠӨмјҖмқјл§Ғ лҜјк°җ Loss LandscapeлҘј нҶөн•ң лӘЁлҚё лі‘н•© л¶Ҳк°ҖлҠҘнҷ”","authors":"Minwoo Jang, Hoyoung Kim, Jabin Koo, Jungseul Ok","pos":"#3008","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=o9NThz6auq","abs":"The rise of model hubs has made it easier to access reusable model components, making model merging a practical tool for combining capabilities. Yet, this modularity also creates a *governance gap*: downstream users can recompose released weights into unauthorized mixtures that bypass safety alignment or licensing terms. Because existing defenses are largely post-hoc and architecture-specific, they provide inconsistent protection across diverse architectures and release formats in practice. To close this gap, we propose Trap$^{2}$, an architecture-agnostic protection framework that encodes protection into the update during fine-tuning, regardless of whether they are released as adapters or full models. Instead of relying on architecture-dependent approaches, Trap$^{2}$ uses weight re-scaling as a simple proxy for the merging process. It keeps released weights effective in standalone use, but degrades them under re-scaling that often arises in merging, undermining unauthorized merging.","absKo":"model hubмқҳ л¶ҖмғҒмңјлЎң мһ¬мӮ¬мҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң model componentм—җ лҚ” мүҪкІҢ м ‘к·јн•  мҲҳ мһҲкІҢ лҗҳл©ҙм„ң, model mergingмқҖ capabilityлҘј кІ°н•©н•ҳлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё лҸ„кө¬к°Җ лҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң modularityлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ *governance gap*мқ„ л§Ңл“ лӢӨ. downstream userк°Җ кіөк°ңлҗң weightлҘј safety alignmentлӮҳ licensing termмқ„ мҡ°нҡҢн•ҳлҠ” л¬ҙлӢЁ mixtureлЎң мһ¬кө¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲкё° л•Ңл¬ёмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л°©м–ҙ кё°лІ•мқҖ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„ мӮ¬нӣ„м Ғмқҙкі  architecture-specificмқҙм–ҙм„ң, мӢӨм ңлЎң лӢӨм–‘н•ң architectureмҷҖ release format м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мқјкҙҖлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ ліҙнҳёл§Ң м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ©м°ЁлҘј н•ҙмҶҢн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Trap$^{2}$лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. Trap$^{2}$лҠ” architecture-agnostic protection frameworkлЎң, adapterлЎң кіөк°ңлҗҳл“  full modelлЎң кіөк°ңлҗҳл“  fine-tuning мӨ‘ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠём—җ protectionмқ„ мқёмҪ”л”©н•ңлӢӨ. architecture-dependent approachм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” лҢҖмӢ , Trap$^{2}$лҠ” merging processмқҳ к°„лӢЁн•ң proxyлЎң weight re-scalingмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” standalone мӮ¬мҡ©м—җм„ңлҠ” кіөк°ңлҗң weightлҘј нҡЁкіјм ҒмңјлЎң мң м§Җн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, mergingм—җм„ң мһҗмЈј л°ңмғқн•ҳлҠ” re-scaling м•„лһҳм—җм„ңлҠ” м„ұлҠҘмқ„ м Җн•ҳмӢңмјң л¬ҙлӢЁ mergingмқ„ м•Ҫнҷ”мӢңнӮЁлӢӨ."},{"id":"62019","en":"Quadratically Regularized Optimal Transport: Localization Bounds and Affine Case Analysis","ko":"Quadratically Regularized Optimal Transport: localization boundsмҷҖ affine case л¶„м„қ","authors":"Long Nguyen-Chi, Nam Nguyen, Binh T. Nguyen","pos":"#1012","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=kcnuX4xEpL","abs":"Quadratically regularization has emerged as a potential alternative to the popular entropic regularization in computational optimal transport, offering the theoretical advantage of producing sparse couplings through its hinge density structure. Despite recent progress in one-dimensional setting and general upper bounds, fundamental questions about the localization rate of QOT optimizers around the Monge coupling have remained open. In this work, we establish a general lower bound showing that the support of the QOT optimizer cannot concentrate around the Monge graph faster than order $\\varepsilon^{\\frac{1}{d+2}}$ in the directed Hausdorff distance, matching the conjectured optimal exponent under standard regularity assumptions in Wiesel &amp; Xu (2025). We also show that the QOT value gap controls the mean-squared deviation $\\mathbb E_{\\pi_\\varepsilon}||y-T(x)||^2$ by the scale of $\\varepsilon^{\\frac{2}{d+2}}$. As a corollary, in the affine Brenier regime, which includes Gaussian-to-Gaussian transport, we derive a sharp pointwise tube bound of order $\\varepsilon^{\\frac{1}{d+2}}$ by reducing the problem to self-transport and applying recent self-transport sparsity results. Finally, we validate our theoretical bound with synthetic experiment in high dimensions setting.","absKo":"Quadratic regularizationмқҖ computational optimal transportм—җм„ң л„җлҰ¬ м“°мқҙлҠ” entropic regularizationмқҳ мһ мһ¬м Ғ лҢҖм•ҲмңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн–Ҳмңјл©°, hinge density кө¬мЎ°лҘј нҶөн•ҙ sparse couplingмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ңлӢӨлҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ мһҘм җмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ. 1м°Ёмӣҗ м„Өм •кіј мқјл°ҳм Ғ мғҒкі„м—җ лҢҖн•ң мөңк·ј м§„м „м—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі , Monge coupling мЈјліҖм—җм„ң QOT optimizerмқҳ localization rateм—җ кҙҖн•ң к·јліём Ғ м§Ҳл¬ёмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ м—ҙл Ө мһҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” QOT optimizerмқҳ supportк°Җ directed Hausdorff distanceм—җм„ң order $\\varepsilon^{\\frac{1}{d+2}}$ліҙлӢӨ лҚ” л№ лҘҙкІҢ Monge graph мЈјліҖм—җ м§‘мӨ‘лҗ  мҲҳ м—ҶмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” мқјл°ҳ н•ҳн•ңмқ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” Wiesel &amp; Xu (2025)мқҳ н‘ңмӨҖ regularity assumption н•ҳм—җм„ң м¶”мёЎлҗң мөңм Ғ м§ҖмҲҳмҷҖ мқјм№ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң QOT value gapмқҙ mean-squared deviation $\\mathbb E_{\\pi_\\varepsilon}||y-T(x)||^2$лҘј $\\varepsilon^{\\frac{2}{d+2}}$мқҳ к·ңлӘЁлЎң м ңм–ҙн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіјлЎң, Gaussian-to-Gaussian transportлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” affine Brenier regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј self-transportлЎң нҷҳмӣҗн•ҳкі  мөңк·јмқҳ self-transport sparsity кІ°кіјлҘј м Ғмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ order $\\varepsilon^{\\frac{1}{d+2}}$мқҳ sharp pointwise tube boundлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң, high-dimensional settingм—җм„ңмқҳ synthetic experimentлҘј нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ boundлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"63851","en":"Accelerating Regression Tasks with Quantum Algorithms","ko":"м–‘мһҗ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмңјлЎң нҡҢк·Җ мһ‘м—… к°ҖмҶҚнҷ”","authors":"Chenghua Liu, Zhengfeng Ji","pos":"#3606","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=TBSyYj4VV6","abs":"Regression is a cornerstone of statistics and machine learning, with applications spanning science, engineering, and economics. While quantum algorithms for regression have attracted considerable attention, most existing work has focused on linear regression, leaving many more complex yet practically important variants unexplored. In this work, we present a unified quantum framework for accelerating a broad class of regression tasks---including linear and multiple regression, Lasso, Ridge, Huber, $\\ell_p$-, and $\\delta_p$-type regressions---achieving up to a quadratic improvement in the number of samples $m$ over the best classical algorithms. This speedup is achieved by a non-trivial quantization of the recent classical breakthrough of Jambulapati et al. (2024), where we construct a full quantum pipeline that strategically employs quantum leverage score approximation to initialize and refine Multiscale Leverage Score Overestimates, enabling efficient importance sampling via the preparation of multiple state copies. For problems of dimension $n$, sparsity $r &lt; n$, and error parameter $\\epsilon$, our algorithm solves the problem in $\\widetilde{O}(r\\sqrt{mn}/\\epsilon + \\mathrm{poly}(n,1/\\epsilon))$ quantum time, demonstrating both the applicability and the efficiency of quantum computing in accelerating regression tasks.","absKo":"нҡҢк·ҖлҠ” нҶөкі„мҷҖ machine learningмқҳ мҙҲм„қмңјлЎң, кіјн•ҷ, кіөн•ҷ, кІҪм ңн•ҷ м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мқ‘мҡ©лҗңлӢӨ. нҡҢк·ҖлҘј мң„н•ң quantum algorithmмқҖ мғҒлӢ№н•ң мЈјлӘ©мқ„ л°ӣм•„мҷ”м§Җл§Ң, кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬мқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҖ linear regressionм—җ м§‘мӨ‘лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм–ҙ, лҚ” ліөмһЎн•ҳм§Җл§Ң мӢӨмҡ©м ҒмңјлЎң мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң лӢӨм–‘н•ң ліҖнҳ•мқҖ м¶©л¶„нһҲ нғҗкө¬лҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙ м—°кө¬м—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” linear л°Ҹ multiple regression, Lasso, Ridge, Huber, $\\ell_p$-, к·ёлҰ¬кі  $\\delta_p$-type regressionмқ„ нҸ¬н•Ён•ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң нҡҢк·Җ taskлҘј к°ҖмҶҚн•ҳлҠ” unified quantum frameworkлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, мөңм„ мқҳ classical algorithm лҢҖл№„ sample мҲҳ $m$м—җм„ң мөңлҢҖ quadratic improvementлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ speedupмқҖ Jambulapati et al. (2024)мқҳ мөңк·ј classical breakthroughлҘј л№„мһҗлӘ…н•ҳкІҢ quantumнҷ”н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ м–»м–ҙм§„лӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м „мІҙ quantum pipelineмқ„ кө¬м„ұн•ҳм—¬ quantum leverage score approximationмқ„ м „лһөм ҒмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ Multiscale Leverage Score OverestimateлҘј мҙҲкё°нҷ”н•ҳкі  м •көҗнҷ”н•ҳл©°, м—¬лҹ¬ state copyмқҳ мӨҖл№„лҘј нҶөн•ҙ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё importance samplingмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м°Ёмӣҗ $n$, sparsity $r &lt; n$, error parameter $\\epsilon$лҘј к°–лҠ” л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ algorithmмқҖ $\\widetilde{O}(r\\sqrt{mn}/\\epsilon + \\mathrm{poly}(n,1/\\epsilon))$ quantum timeмңјлЎң л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•ҳл©°, нҡҢк·Җ task к°ҖмҶҚм—җм„ң quantum computingмқҳ м Ғмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘм„ұкіј нҡЁмңЁм„ұмқ„ лӘЁл‘җ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"66422","en":"Subgroup Discovery with the Cox Model","ko":"Cox лӘЁлҚёмқ„ мқҙмҡ©н•ң н•ҳмң„ к·ёлЈ№ л°ңкІ¬","authors":"Zachary Izzo, Iain Melvin","pos":"#4010","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=3tlaoBZrSg","abs":"<p>We study the problem of subgroup discovery for survival analysis, where the goal is to find an interpretable subset of the data on which a Cox model is highly accurate. We examine why existing quality functions are insufficient for this problem and introduce two technical innovations: the <em>expected prediction entropy (EPE)</em>, a novel metric for evaluating survival models that predict hazard functions, and the <em>conditional rank statistics (CRS)</em>, which quantifies individual point deviation from a subgroup's survival time distribution. We study the EPE and CRS theoretically and show they address problems with existing metrics. We then introduce seven algorithms for Cox subgroup discover. Our main algorithm is based on the DDGroup framework of Izzo et al. (2023) and leverages both the EPE and CRS, allowing theoretical correctness guarantees in well-specified settings. Empirical evaluation on synthetic and real data confirms our theory, showing our methods recover ground-truth subgroups in well-specified cases and achieve better model fit than naively fitting the Cox model to the entire dataset. A case study on NASA jet engine simulation data demonstrates that discovered subgroups uncover known nonlinearities in the data and suggest design choices mirrored in practice.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” survival analysisм—җм„ңмқҳ subgroup discovery л¬ём ңлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. лӘ©н‘ңлҠ” Cox modelмқҙ л§Өмҡ° м •нҷ•н•ң, н•ҙм„қ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ л¶Җл¶„м§‘н•©мқ„ м°ҫлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” кё°мЎҙ quality functionмқҙ мқҙ л¬ём ңм—җ мҷң м¶©л¶„н•ҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖм§Җ кІҖнҶ н•ҳкі , л‘җ к°Җм§Җ кё°мҲ м Ғ нҳҒмӢ мқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” hazard functionмқ„ мҳҲмёЎн•ҳлҠ” survival modelмқ„ нҸүк°Җн•ҳкё° мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ metricмқё <em>expected prediction entropy(EPE)</em>мқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” к°ңлі„ pointк°Җ subgroupмқҳ survival time distributionм—җм„ң м–јл§ҲлӮҳ лІ—м–ҙлӮҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” <em>conditional rank statistics(CRS)</em>мқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” EPEмҷҖ CRSлҘј мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң м—°кө¬н•ҳкі , мқҙл“Өмқҙ кё°мЎҙ metricмқҳ л¬ём ңлҘј н•ҙкІ°н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң Cox subgroup discoverлҘј мң„н•ң 7к°ңмқҳ algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мЈјлҗң algorithmмқҖ Izzo et al.(2023)мқҳ DDGroup frameworkм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ҳл©°, EPEмҷҖ CRSлҘј лӘЁл‘җ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мһҳ лӘ…мӢңлҗң м„Өм •м—җм„ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ м •н•©м„ұ ліҙмһҘмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. synthetic л°Ҹ real dataм—җ лҢҖн•ң мӢӨмҰқ нҸүк°Җ кІ°кіјлҠ” мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ мқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳл©°, мһҳ лӘ…мӢңлҗң кІҪмҡ° ground-truth subgroupмқ„ ліөмӣҗн•ҳкі  м „мІҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җ Cox modelмқ„ лӢЁмҲң м Ғмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІғліҙлӢӨ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ model fitмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. NASA jet engine simulation dataм—җ лҢҖн•ң case studyлҠ” л°ңкІ¬лҗң subgroupмқҙ лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ м•Ңл Өм§„ nonlinearitiesлҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙкі , мӢӨм ң м„Өкі„ м„ нғқкіј мң мӮ¬н•ң мӢңмӮ¬м җмқ„ м ңкіөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"66097","en":"Theoretical Analysis of Sparse Optimization with Reparameterization, Weight Decay, and Adaptive Learning Rate","ko":"мһ¬л§Өк°ңліҖмҲҳнҷ”, к°ҖмӨ‘м№ҳ к°җмҮ , м Ғмқ‘нҳ• н•ҷмҠөлҘ мқ„ нҷңмҡ©н•ң нқ¬мҶҢ мөңм Ғнҷ”мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ л¶„м„қ","authors":"Huangyu Xu, Jingqin Yang, Qianqian Xu, Jiaye Teng","pos":"#4015","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=74PNBqBKPA","abs":"<p>Sparse optimization is a fundamental challenge in various practical applications.  A popular approach to sparse optimization is Lp regularization. However, it may encounter optimization instability due to the unbounded gradients when 0<p&lt;1. a=\"\" accuracy.<=\"\" adaptive=\"\" and=\"\" approach=\"\" based=\"\" cifar-10=\"\" closely=\"\" connected=\"\" decay,=\"\" demonstrate=\"\" distinct=\"\" experiments=\"\" helps=\"\" imagenet=\"\" improvements=\"\" in=\"\" instability=\"\" introduce=\"\" is=\"\" issues.=\"\" it=\"\" l1-regularization=\"\" landscape=\"\" leads=\"\" learning=\"\" lp-regularization,=\"\" mitigate=\"\" novel=\"\" on=\"\" optimization=\"\" over=\"\" p=\"\" paper,=\"\" preserving=\"\" rate.=\"\" reparameterization,=\"\" resnets=\"\" rewa=\"\" rewa,=\"\" significant=\"\" sparse=\"\" sparsity=\"\" termed=\"\" test=\"\" that=\"\" the=\"\" this=\"\" to=\"\" unveils=\"\" we=\"\" weight=\"\" while=\"\" with=\"\" yet=\"\">\n</p&lt;1.></p>","absKo":"<p>Sparse optimizationмқҖ лӢӨм–‘н•ң мӢӨм ң мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң к·јліём Ғмқё лҸ„м „ кіјм ңлӢӨ. Sparse optimizationмқ„ мң„н•ң л„җлҰ¬ м“°мқҙлҠ” м ‘к·јлІ• мӨ‘ н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” Lp regularizationмқҙлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ 0<p&lt;1мқј л•Ң unbounded gradients л•Ңл¬ём—җ optimization instabilityк°Җ л°ңмғқн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. a=\"\" accuracy.<=\"\" adaptive=\"\" and=\"\" approach=\"\" based=\"\" cifar-10=\"\" closely=\"\" connected=\"\" decay,=\"\" demonstrate=\"\" distinct=\"\" experiments=\"\" helps=\"\" imagenet=\"\" improvements=\"\" in=\"\" instability=\"\" introduce=\"\" is=\"\" issues.=\"\" it=\"\" l1-regularization=\"\" landscape=\"\" leads=\"\" learning=\"\" lp-regularization,=\"\" mitigate=\"\" novel=\"\" on=\"\" optimization=\"\" over=\"\" p=\"\" paper,=\"\" preserving=\"\" rate.=\"\" reparameterization,=\"\" resnets=\"\" rewa=\"\" rewa,=\"\" significant=\"\" sparse=\"\" sparsity=\"\" termed=\"\" test=\"\" that=\"\" the=\"\" this=\"\" to=\"\" unveils=\"\" we=\"\" weight=\"\" while=\"\" with=\"\" yet=\"\">\n</p&lt;1.></p>"},{"id":"67214","en":"Position: Quantum Kernel Machines Should Move Beyond Scalar-Valued Kernels to Realize Their Potential","ko":"Position: Quantum Kernel MachineмқҖ мһ мһ¬л Ҙмқ„ мӢӨнҳ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ мҠӨм№јлқј к°’ м»Өл„җмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңм•ј н•ңлӢӨ","authors":"Hachem Kadri, Joachim Tomasi, Yuka Hashimoto, Sandrine Anthoine","pos":"#4206","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=B88DknxRdT","abs":"<p>Quantum kernels are reproducing kernel functions built using quantum-mechanical principles and have emerged as a centerpiece of quantum machine learning.  The initial enthusiasm for quantum kernel machines has been tempered by recent studies suggesting that quantum kernels could not offer significant computational or statistical advantages when learning from classical data. However, most of the research in this area has been devoted to scalar-valued kernels in standard classification or regression settings for which classical kernel methods are efficient and effective, leaving very little room for improvement with quantum kernels. In this position paper, we argue that progress in this field requires moving beyond scalar-valued kernels toward more expressive kernel frameworks. Scalar-valued kernels lack the degrees of freedom necessary to fully exploit intrinsically quantum resources such as entanglement and are not rich enough to deal with complex learning tasks where classical learning methods struggle. Building on recent advances in operator-valued kernel learning and C*-algebraic kernel representations, we propose a roadmap for designing quantum kernels capable of leveraging entanglement and non-commutative structures to tackle complex structured prediction problems. To support this viewpoint, we present an initial proof-of-concept illustrating how quantum entangled operator-valued kernel formulations can reveal structural dependencies that remain difficult to access for scalar-valued kernel methods. This shift in focus could open a pathway toward a new generation of quantum kernel machines and a more faithful exploration of their potential advantages.</p>","absKo":"<p>Quantum kernelsлҠ” quantum-mechanical principlesлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ кө¬м¶•лҗң reproducing kernel functionsмқҙл©°, quantum machine learningмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мңјлЎң л¶ҖмғҒн•ҙ мҷ”лӢӨ. Quantum kernel machineм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҙҲкё°мқҳ м—ҙкё°лҠ”, classical dataлҘј н•ҷмҠөн•  л•Ң quantum kernelsк°Җ мқҳлҜё мһҲлҠ” computational лҳҗлҠ” statistical advantageлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ мӢңмӮ¬н•ҳлҠ” мөңк·ј м—°кө¬л“ӨлЎң лӢӨмҶҢ лҲ„к·ёлҹ¬мЎҢлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ мқҙ л¶„м•јмқҳ лҢҖл¶Җл¶„мқҳ м—°кө¬лҠ” standard classification лҳҗлҠ” regression settingм—җм„ңмқҳ scalar-valued kernelsм—җ м§‘мӨ‘лҗҳм–ҙ мҷ”кі , мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ңлҠ” classical kernel methodsк°Җ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқҙкі  нҡЁкіјм Ғмқҙкё° л•Ңл¬ём—җ quantum kernelsлЎң к°ңм„ н•  м—¬м§Җк°Җ кұ°мқҳ лӮЁм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ position paperм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ л¶„м•јмқҳ м§„м „мқҙ scalar-valued kernelsмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙ лҚ” expressiveн•ң kernel frameworkлЎң лӮҳм•„к°Җм•јл§Ң к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлӢӨкі  мЈјмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. Scalar-valued kernelsлҠ” entanglementмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ intrinsically quantum resourceлҘј м¶©л¶„нһҲ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° н•„мҡ”н•ң мһҗмң лҸ„лҘј м ңкіөн•ҳм§Җ лӘ»н•ҳл©°, classical learning methodsк°Җ м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ” ліөмһЎн•ң learning taskлҘј лӢӨлЈЁкё°м—җлҸ„ м¶©л¶„нһҲ н’Қл¶Җн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлӢӨ. мөңк·јмқҳ operator-valued kernel learningкіј C*-algebraic kernel representationмқҳ л°ңм „мқ„ л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” entanglementмҷҖ non-commutative structureлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ ліөмһЎн•ң structured prediction problemмқ„ н•ҙкІ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” quantum kernelsлҘј м„Өкі„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ң roadmapмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм җмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” quantum entangled operator-valued kernel formulationмқҙ scalar-valued kernel methodsлЎңлҠ” м—¬м „нһҲ м ‘к·јн•ҳкё° м–ҙл Өмҡҙ structural dependencyлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ л“ңлҹ¬лӮј мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җ ліҙм—¬мЈјлҠ” мҙҲкё° proof-of-conceptлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мҙҲм җ м „нҷҳмқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м„ёлҢҖмқҳ quantum kernel machineмңјлЎң к°ҖлҠ” кёёмқ„ м—ҙкі , к·ё мһ мһ¬м Ғ мһҘм җмқ„ ліҙлӢӨ м¶©мӢӨн•ҳкІҢ нғҗмғүн•ҳлҠ” кі„кё°к°Җ лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"60528","en":"No Free Lunch: Non-Asymptotic Analysis of Prediction-Powered Inference","ko":"No Free Lunch: Prediction-Powered Inferenceмқҳ Non-Asymptotic Analysis","authors":"Pranav Mani, Peng Xu, Zachary Lipton, Michael Oberst","pos":"#4415","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=zM5MbWc6wc","abs":"Prediction-Powered Inference (PPI) is a popular strategy for combining gold-standard and possibly noisy pseudo-labels to perform statistical estimation. Prior work has shown an asymptotic \\enquote{free lunch} for PPI++, an adaptive form of PPI, showing that the \\textit{asymptotic} variance of PPI++ is always less than or equal to the variance obtained from using gold-standard labels alone. Notably, this result holds \\textit{regardless of the quality of the pseudo-labels}.  In this work, we demystify this result by conducting an exact finite-sample analysis of the estimation error of PPI++ on the mean estimation problem.  We give a \\enquote{no free lunch} result, characterizing the settings (and sample sizes) where PPI++ has provably worse estimation error than using gold-standard labels alone. Specifically, PPI++ will outperform if and only if the correlation between pseudo- and gold-standard is above a certain level that depends on the number of labeled samples ($n$). In some cases our results simplify considerably: For Gaussian data, for instance, the correlation must be at least $1/\\sqrt{n - 2}$ in order to see improvement. More broadly, by providing exact non-asymptotic expressions for the variance of PPI++ under sample splitting, we aim to empower practitioners to transparently reason about the benefits of PPI++ in specific applications. In experiments, we illustrate that our theoretical findings hold on real-world datasets.","absKo":"Prediction-Powered Inference(PPI)лҠ” gold-standard л Ҳмқҙлё”кіј мһ мһ¬м ҒмңјлЎң л…ёмқҙмҰҲк°Җ м„һмқё pseudo-labelмқ„ кІ°н•©н•ҙ нҶөкі„м Ғ м¶”м •мқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ” л„җлҰ¬ м“°мқҙлҠ” м „лһөмқҙлӢӨ. м„ н–ү м—°кө¬лҠ” PPIмқҳ м Ғмқ‘нҳ• нҳ•нғңмқё PPI++м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ м җк·јм Ғ <enquote>free lunch</enquote>к°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•Ёмқ„ ліҙмҳҖмңјл©°, PPI++мқҳ <textit>м җк·јм Ғ</textit> л¶„мӮ°мқҙ gold-standard л Ҳмқҙлё”л§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н–Ҳмқ„ л•Ңмқҳ л¶„мӮ°ліҙлӢӨ н•ӯмғҒ мһ‘кұ°лӮҳ к°ҷмқҢмқ„ л°қнҳ”лӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ мқҙ кІ°кіјлҠ” <textit>pseudo-labelмқҳ н’Ҳм§Ҳкіј л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳкІҢ</textit> м„ұлҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ” нҸүк·  м¶”м • л¬ём ңм—җм„ң PPI++мқҳ м¶”м • мҳӨм°Ём—җ лҢҖн•ң м •нҷ•н•ң мң н•ңн‘ңліё л¶„м„қмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ мқҙ кІ°кіјлҘј лӘ…нҷ•нһҲ м„ӨлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” <enquote>no free lunch</enquote> кІ°кіјлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬, м–ҙл–Ө м„Өм •(л°Ҹ н‘ңліё нҒ¬кё°)м—җм„ң PPI++мқҳ м¶”м • мҳӨм°Ёк°Җ gold-standard л Ҳмқҙлё”л§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°ліҙлӢӨ м—„л°ҖнһҲ лҚ” лӮҳмҒңм§ҖлҘј к·ңлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, PPI++лҠ” pseudo-labelкіј gold-standard л Ҳмқҙлё” к°„мқҳ мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„к°Җ labeled sample мҲҳ($n$)м—җ л”°лқј лӢ¬лқјм§ҖлҠ” нҠ№м • мҲҳмӨҖмқ„ мҙҲкіјн•  л•Ң к·ёлҰ¬кі  к·ёлҹҙ л•Ңм—җл§Ң лҚ” мўӢмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. м–ҙл–Ө кІҪмҡ°м—җлҠ” кІ°кіјк°Җ нӣЁм”¬ лӢЁмҲңн•ҙм§ҖлҠ”лҚ°, мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ Gaussian лҚ°мқҙн„°мқҳ кІҪмҡ° к°ңм„ мқ„ ліҙл Өл©ҙ мғҒкҙҖкҙҖкі„к°Җ мөңмҶҢн•ң $1/\\sqrt{n - 2}$ мқҙмғҒмқҙм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” л„“кІҢлҠ”, sample splitting н•ҳм—җм„ң PPI++мқҳ л¶„мӮ°м—җ лҢҖн•ң м •нҷ•н•ң л№„м җк·јм Ғ мӢқмқ„ м ңкіөн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӢӨл¬ҙмһҗл“Өмқҙ нҠ№м • мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң PPI++мқҳ мқҙм җмқ„ нҲ¬лӘ…н•ҳкІҢ м¶”лЎ н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ лҸ•кі мһҗ н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјк°Җ мӢӨм ң лҚ°мқҙн„°м…Ӣм—җм„ңлҸ„ м„ұлҰҪн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ."},{"id":"66171","en":"Understanding Generalization and Forgetting in In-Context Continual Learning","ko":"In-Context м§ҖмҶҚ н•ҷмҠөм—җм„ңмқҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ”мҷҖ л§қк°Ғ мқҙн•ҙ","authors":"Guangyu Li, Meng Ding, Lijie Hu","pos":"#4514","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=68AMoK2YNk","abs":"<p>In-context learning (ICL) derives its power from enabling Large Language Models to adapt to new tasks via prompt-based reasoning alone, entirely bypassing the need for parameter updates. Existing theories primarily study ICL in single-task settings, while real-world prompts often contain sequences of heterogeneous tasks, leaving a gap in understanding whether Large Language Models implicitly perform continual learning during inference. To bridge this gap, we propose the first theoretical framework for in-context continual learning, modeling how a pretrained Transformer processes multiple sequential tasks within a single prompt through shared attention mechanisms. Focusing on linear and masked linear self-attention, we derive error expressions for model predictions under sequential task prompts and analyze their generalization and forgetting behavior. Our results reveal that standard attention mechanisms inevitably induce inter-task interference by uniformly or causally aggregating historical contexts, leading to systematic bias. We further provide a biasвҖ“varianceвҖ“interference decomposition of prediction error, characterizing when historical in-context information yields positive transfer or provable negative transfer. This analysis exposes fundamental limits of attention-based continual inference and offers theoretical explanations for order sensitivity and performance degradation in long prompts.</p>","absKo":"<p>In-context learning (ICL)мқҖ Large Language Modelsк°Җ нҢҢлқјлҜён„° м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠё м—Ҷмқҙ мҳӨм§Ғ prompt-based reasoningл§ҢмңјлЎң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskм—җ м Ғмқ‘н•ҳкІҢ н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ к·ё м„ұлҠҘмқ„ л°ңнңҳн•ңлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ мқҙлЎ мқҖ мЈјлЎң single-task settingм—җм„ңмқҳ ICLмқ„ лӢӨлЈЁм—Ҳм§Җл§Ң, мӢӨм ң promptм—җлҠ” мқҙм§Ҳм Ғмқё м—¬лҹ¬ taskмқҳ м—°мҶҚмқҙ нҸ¬н•ЁлҗҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм•„, inference лҸҷм•Ҳ Large Language Modelsк°Җ м•”л¬өм ҒмңјлЎң continual learningмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ҳлҠ”м§Җм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙн•ҙм—җлҠ” кіөл°ұмқҙ лӮЁм•„ мһҲлӢӨ. мқҙ кіөл°ұмқ„ л©”мҡ°кё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” in-context continual learningмқ„ мң„н•ң мөңмҙҲмқҳ мқҙлЎ м Ғ frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, pretrained Transformerк°Җ shared attention mechanismsмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ н•ҳлӮҳмқҳ prompt м•Ҳм—җм„ң м—¬лҹ¬ sequential taskлҘј м–ҙл–»кІҢ мІҳлҰ¬н•ҳлҠ”м§Җ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ңлӢӨ. linear л°Ҹ masked linear self-attentionм—җ мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶°, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” sequential task prompt н•ҳм—җм„ң model predictionмқҳ error expressionмқ„ мң лҸ„н•ҳкі  к·ё generalization л°Ҹ forgetting behaviorлҘј л¶„м„қн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” standard attention mechanismмқҙ кіјкұ° contextлҘј uniformн•ҳкІҢ лҳҗлҠ” causalн•ҳкІҢ aggregateн•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ н•„м—°м ҒмңјлЎң inter-task interferenceлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳкі , мқҙлЎң мқён•ҙ systematical biasк°Җ мғқкёҙлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” prediction errorмқҳ biasвҖ“varianceвҖ“interference decompositionмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬, historical in-context informationмқҙ м–ём ң positive transferлҘј лӮікі  м–ём ң provable negative transferлҘј мң л°ңн•ҳлҠ”м§Җ к·ңлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¶„м„қмқҖ attention-based continual inferenceмқҳ к·јліём Ғ н•ңкі„лҘј л“ңлҹ¬лӮҙл©°, кёҙ promptм—җм„ңмқҳ order sensitivityмҷҖ performance degradationм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ м„ӨлӘ…мқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63550","en":"Theoretical Guarantees for One-Shot Magnitude Pruning and Compute-Adaptive Early Exit","ko":"мӣҗмғ· нҒ¬кё° кё°л°ҳ к°Җм§Җм№ҳкё°мҷҖ кі„мӮ° м Ғмқ‘нҳ• мЎ°кё° мў…лЈҢм—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлЎ м Ғ ліҙмһҘ","authors":"Erdem Koyuncu","pos":"#4612","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=W7gIiS2y1x","abs":"<p>We study compute reduction in neural networks through a unified partial versus full computation view, captured by one-shot magnitude pruning in the static regime and early exit in the adaptive regime. In an asymptotic single-neuron model, we prove a concentration theorem for one-shot magnitude pruning with explicit rates. We also introduce the conditional perceptron for early exit and show that its excess generalization error decays as a power of the compute gap, with an exponent that grows to infinity as the alignment between partial and full computations tends to one. We then extend the analysis to deep networks, characterizing how pruning-induced distortions accumulate with depth and deriving a corresponding computeвҖ“accuracy tradeoff for frozen-backbone early exit under a neural network Gaussian process model. Numerical simulations corroborate the predicted scaling laws.</p>","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” static regimeмқҳ one-shot magnitude pruningкіј adaptive regimeмқҳ early exitлЎң нҸ¬м°©лҗҳлҠ”, partial computationкіј full computationм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҶөн•©лҗң кҙҖм җмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ neural networkмқҳ compute reductionмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. asymptotic single-neuron modelм—җм„ң мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӘ…мӢңм Ғ rateлҘј к°–лҠ” one-shot magnitude pruningм—җ лҢҖн•ң concentration theoremмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң early exitлҘј мң„н•ң conditional perceptronмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ҳкі , к·ё excess generalization errorк°Җ compute gapмқҳ кұ°л“ӯм ңкіұмңјлЎң к°җмҶҢн•ҳл©°, partial computationкіј full computationмқҳ alignmentк°Җ 1м—җ к°Җк№ҢмӣҢм§ҲмҲҳлЎқ к·ё м§ҖмҲҳк°Җ л¬ҙн•ңлҢҖлЎң м»Өм§җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң л¶„м„қмқ„ deep networkлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм—¬ pruningмңјлЎң мқён•ң distortionмқҙ depthмҷҖ н•Ёк»ҳ м–ҙл–»кІҢ лҲ„м ҒлҗҳлҠ”м§Җ нҠ№м„ұнҷ”н•ҳкі , neural network Gaussian process model н•ҳм—җм„ң frozen-backbone early exitм—җ лҢҖн•ң лҢҖмқ‘н•ҳлҠ” compute--accuracy tradeoffлҘј лҸ„м¶ңн•ңлӢӨ. мҲҳм№ҳ мӢңл®¬л Ҳмқҙм…ҳмқҖ мҳҲмёЎлҗң scaling lawлҘј л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64858","en":"Hedging on the frontier: Learning new tasks with few samples","ko":"мөңм „м„ м—җм„ң н—Өм§•н•ҳкё°: мҶҢмҲҳ мғҳн”ҢлЎң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ кіјм ң н•ҷмҠө","authors":"Tobias Wegel, Federico Di Gennaro, Geelon So, Fanny Yang","pos":"#4613","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=J4wRLmh29t","abs":"<p>When a learner is faced with a new task, but is given very few samples, it must leverage any available side-information. In practice, this often comes in the form of benchmarks, where there is abundant data to evaluate model performance on related tasks. Though task relatedness is difficult to formalize theoretically, it can be empirically observed through <em>weak monotonicity</em>: if a model dominates another on all benchmarks, it also tends to outperform the other on the new task. We explore the statistical complexity of learning under weak monotonicity, leveraging it within two learning paradigms: transfer learning and model selection aggregation. We show that not only can we prune the model class based on monotonicity, but that we can further adapt to the geometry of the available trade-offs by <em>hedging on the frontier</em>.</p>","absKo":"<p>н•ҷмҠөмһҗк°Җ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskлҘј л§ҲмЈјн–Ҳм§Җл§Ң л§Өмҡ° м ҒмқҖ sampleл§Ң м ңкіөл°ӣлҠ” кІҪмҡ°, мқҙмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң side-informationмқ„ мөңлҢҖн•ң нҷңмҡ©н•ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. мӢӨм ңлЎң мқҙлҠ” мў…мў… benchmarkмқҳ нҳ•нғңлЎң мЈјм–ҙм§Җл©°, кҙҖл Ё taskм—җм„ң model performanceлҘј нҸүк°Җн•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” н’Қл¶Җн•ң лҚ°мқҙн„°к°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ңлӢӨ. task relatednessлҘј мқҙлЎ м ҒмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ м–ҙл өм§Җл§Ң, мқҙлҠ” <em>weak monotonicity</em>лҘј нҶөн•ҙ кІҪн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң кҙҖм°°лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҰү, н•ң modelмқҙ лӘЁл“  benchmarkм—җм„ң лӢӨлҘё modelмқ„ м§Җл°°н•ңлӢӨл©ҙ, мғҲлЎңмҡҙ taskм—җм„ңлҸ„ лҢҖмІҙлЎң лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмқҙлҠ” кІҪн–Ҙмқҙ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” weak monotonicity н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ learningмқҳ statistical complexityлҘј нғҗкө¬н•ҳкі , мқҙлҘј transfer learningкіј model selection aggregationмқҳ л‘җ learning paradigm м•Ҳм—җм„ң нҷңмҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” monotonicityлҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң model classлҘј pruningн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„ лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј, <em>hedging on the frontier</em>лҘј нҶөн•ҙ мқҙмҡ© к°ҖлҠҘн•ң trade-offмқҳ geometryм—җ лҚ”мҡұ м Ғмқ‘н•  мҲҳ мһҲмқҢмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65194","en":"Active Regression for Single-Index Models with Unknown Link Functions","ko":"лҜём§Җмқҳ л§ҒнҒ¬ н•ЁмҲҳлҘј к°–лҠ” Single-Index Modelмқ„ мң„н•ң лҠҘлҸҷ нҡҢк·Җ","authors":"Chansophea Wathanak In, Yi Li, Wai Ming Tai, Xuan Wu","pos":"#4614","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=Fuaz3QFAdB","abs":"This paper studies active regression for single-index models under general $\\ell_p$-loss with an unknown $1$-Lipschitz link function $f$, formulated as $\\min_{f,x} \\Vert f(Ax)-b\\Vert_p^p$ with full access to $A$ but coordinate-query access to $b$.  Prior work established upper bounds for known link functions for all $p\\geq 1$ and for unknown link functions only in the $p=2$ case, together with lower bounds for $p\\leq 2$. This work addresses the more challenging setting of unknown link functions and general $p \\geq 1$. A non-adaptive sampling algorithm is presented that achieves a $(1+\\epsilon)$-approximation using $O(d^{p/2\\vee 1}/\\epsilon^{p\\vee 2}\\text{poly}\\log(n/\\epsilon))$ queries. Nearly tight lower bounds are also established for non-adaptive queries when $p&gt;2$. These results close much of the remaining gap in active $\\ell_p$ regression for single-index models.","absKo":"ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ unknown $1$-Lipschitz link function $f$лҘј к°–лҠ” single-index modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң active regressionмқ„ мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё $\\ell_p$-loss н•ҳм—җм„ң лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” $A$м—җлҠ” full accessк°Җ мһҲм§Җл§Ң $b$м—җлҠ” coordinate-query accessл§Ң мһҲлҠ” мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң $\\min_{f,x} \\Vert f(Ax)-b\\Vert_p^p$лЎң м •мӢқнҷ”лҗңлӢӨ. м„ н–ү м—°кө¬лҠ” лӘЁл“  $p\\geq 1$м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ known link functionм—җ лҢҖн•ң upper boundмҷҖ, unknown link functionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҠ” $p=2$мқё кІҪмҡ°м—җл§Ң upper boundлҘј м ңмӢңн–Ҳмңјл©°, $p\\leq 2$м—җ лҢҖн•ң lower boundлҸ„ н•Ёк»ҳ м ңмӢңн–ҲлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬лҠ” unknown link functionкіј мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё $p \\geq 1$мқҙлқјлҠ” лҚ” м–ҙл Өмҡҙ м„Өм •мқ„ лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. м ңмӢңлҗң non-adaptive sampling algorithmмқҖ $O(d^{p/2\\vee 1}/\\epsilon^{p\\vee 2}\\text{poly}\\log(n/\\epsilon))$к°ңмқҳ queryлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ $(1+\\epsilon)$-approximationмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң $p>2$мқј л•Ң non-adaptive queryм—җ лҢҖн•ң кұ°мқҳ tightн•ң lower boundлҸ„ нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјлҠ” single-index modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң active $\\ell_p$ regressionм—җм„ң лӮЁм•„ мһҲлҚҳ мғҒлӢ№ л¶Җл¶„мқҳ кІ©м°ЁлҘј н•ҙмҶҢн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"66282","en":"Equilibrium Propagation for Non-Conservative Systems","ko":"л№„ліҙмЎҙм Ғ мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ мң„н•ң Equilibrium Propagation","authors":"Antonino Emanuele Scurria, Dimitri Vanden Abeele, Bortolo Matteo Mognetti, Serge Massar","pos":"#4615","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=5785emCgS1","abs":"<p>Equilibrium Propagation (EP) is a physics-inspired learning algorithm that uses stationary states of a dynamical system both for inference and learning. In its original formulation it is limited to conservative systems, i.e. to dynamics which derive from an energy function. Given their importance in applications, it is important to extend EP to nonconservative systems, i.e. systems with non-reciprocal interactions. Previous attempts to generalize EP to such systems failed to compute the exact gradient of the cost function. Here we propose a framework that extends EP to arbitrary nonconservative systems, including feedforward networks. We keep the key property of equilibrium propagation, namely the use of stationary states both for inference and learning. However, we modify the dynamics in the learning phase by a term proportional to the non-reciprocal part of the interaction so as to obtain the exact gradient of the cost function. This algorithm can also be derived using a variational formulation that generates the learning dynamics through an energy function defined over an augmented state space. Numerical experiments using the MNIST database show that this algorithm achieves better performance and learns faster than previous proposals.</p>","absKo":"<p>Equilibrium Propagation(EP)мқҖ dynamical systemмқҳ stationary stateлҘј inferenceмҷҖ learning лӘЁл‘җм—җ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” physics-inspired learning algorithmмқҙлӢӨ. мӣҗлһҳмқҳ formulationм—җм„ңлҠ” energy functionмңјлЎңл¶Җн„° мң лҸ„лҗҳлҠ” dynamics, мҰү conservative systemм—җл§Ң м ңн•ңлҗңлӢӨ. мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ңмқҳ мӨ‘мҡ”м„ұмқ„ кі л Өн•  л•Ң, non-reciprocal interactionмқ„ к°–лҠ” nonconservative systemмңјлЎң EPлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ мӨ‘мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мқҙм „мқҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ” мӢңлҸ„л“ӨмқҖ cost functionмқҳ м •нҷ•н•ң gradientлҘј кі„мӮ°н•ҳлҠ” лҚ° мӢӨнҢЁн–ҲлӢӨ. м—¬кё°м„ңлҠ” feedforward networkлҘј нҸ¬н•Ён•ң мһ„мқҳмқҳ nonconservative systemмңјлЎң EPлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҳлҠ” frameworkлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” equilibrium propagationмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ м„ұм§Ҳ, мҰү inferenceмҷҖ learning лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң stationary stateлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ мң м§Җн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ learning phaseмқҳ dynamicsлҠ” interactionмқҳ non-reciprocal partм—җ л№„лЎҖн•ҳлҠ” н•ӯмңјлЎң мҲҳм •н•ҳм—¬ cost functionмқҳ м •нҷ•н•ң gradientлҘј м–»лҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙ algorithmмқҖ нҷ•мһҘлҗң state spaceм—җ м •мқҳлҗң energy functionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ learning dynamicsлҘј мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” variational formulationмңјлЎңлҸ„ мң лҸ„лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. MNIST databaseлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ң мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мқҙ algorithmмқҙ мқҙм „ м ңм•Ҳл“ӨліҙлӢӨ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳкі  лҚ” л№ лҘҙкІҢ н•ҷмҠөн•Ёмқ„ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62186","en":"Is Spurious Correlation Removal Always Learnable?","ko":"Spurious Correlation м ңкұ°лҠ” н•ӯмғҒ н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн• к№Ң?","authors":"Yibo Zhou, Bo Li, Hai-Miao Hu, Hanzi Wang, Xiaokang Zhang, Ruifan Zhang","pos":"#4616","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=iwS6Lg1Uwx","abs":"Invariant learning can fail even when the invariant structure is statistically identifiable. We show an inherent computational barrier: under the Planted Clique hypothesis, there exist samplable linear-Gaussian multi-environment instances with a one-dimensional invariant subspace ($k=1$) that are learnable with polynomial samples by exhaustive search but intractable for any polynomial-time algorithm, via an average-case reduction from a supervised sparse primitive. We further quantify environment diversity by a separation parameter $\\gamma$, which controls identifiability and the curvature of invariance objectives. Under sufficient diversity, the minimax risk is $\\mathbb{E}[dist(\\hat{V},V_{\\mathrm{inv}})^2]=\\Theta(k(d-k)/(n|\\mathcal{E}|))$, and under label-induced shifts a phase transition occurs at $n^*\\propto k(d-k)/(|\\mathcal{E}|\\gamma^2)$. Synthetic and real datasets validate the predicted gaps and transitions and motivate simple diversity diagnostics.","absKo":"л¶ҲліҖ кө¬мЎ°к°Җ нҶөкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мӢқлі„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳлҚ”лқјлҸ„ invariant learningмқҖ мӢӨнҢЁн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” ліём§Ҳм Ғмқё кі„мӮ° мһҘлІҪмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. Planted Clique к°Җм„Ө н•ҳм—җм„ң, 1м°Ёмӣҗ invariant subspace($k=1$)лҘј к°–лҠ” мғҳн”Ңл§Ғ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң linear-Gaussian multi-environment мқёмҠӨн„ҙмҠӨк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳл©°, мқҙл“ӨмқҖ exhaustive searchлЎңлҠ” polynomial к°ңмқҳ мғҳн”ҢлЎң н•ҷмҠө к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳм§Җл§Ң, supervised sparse primitiveлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ average-case reductionмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ м–ҙл–Ө polynomial-time algorithmмңјлЎңлҸ„ лӢӨлЈЁкё° м–ҙл өлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң нҷҳкІҪ лӢӨм–‘м„ұмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬ нҢҢлқјлҜён„° $\\gamma$лЎң м •лҹүнҷ”н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” identifiabilityмҷҖ invariance objectiveмқҳ curvatureлҘј м ңм–ҙн•ңлӢӨ. м¶©л¶„н•ң лӢӨм–‘м„ұмқҙ мһҲмңјл©ҙ minimax riskлҠ” $\\mathbb{E}[dist(\\hat{V},V_{\\mathrm{inv}})^2]=\\Theta(k(d-k)/(n|\\mathcal{E}|))$к°Җ лҗҳл©°, label-induced shifts н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” $n^*\\propto k(d-k)/(|\\mathcal{E}|\\gamma^2)$м—җм„ң phase transitionмқҙ л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. synthetic л°Ҹ real datasetмқҖ мҳҲмёЎлҗң кІ©м°ЁмҷҖ м „мқҙлҘј кІҖмҰқн•ҳл©°, лӢЁмҲңн•ң лӢӨм–‘м„ұ м§„лӢЁмқҳ н•„мҡ”м„ұмқ„ л’·л°ӣм№Ён•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64275","en":"Parsimonious Learning-Augmented Online Metric Matching","ko":"к°„кІ°н•ң н•ҷмҠө мҰқк°• мҳЁлқјмқё л©”нҠёлҰӯ л§Өм№ӯ","authors":"Yongho Shin, Phanu Vajanopath","pos":"#4617","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=PFpbi7pceh","abs":"<p><em>Learning-augmented algorithms</em> have received significant attention in recent years, particularly in the context of online optimization. Motivated by the high computational cost of generating predictions, a growing line of work studies the tradeoff between performance guarantees and the number of predictions used in learning-augmented algorithms for problems such as caching and metrical task systems. In this paper, we extend this line of research to <em>online metric matching</em> by developing <em>parsimonious</em> learning-augmented algorithms and establishing lower bounds on their performance. Our approach extends the Follow-the-Prediction framework to the parsimonious setting by filling in a <em>virtual prediction</em> in the absence of an actual prediction, using an online metric matching algorithm that maintains good intermediate matchings throughout its execution. We complement our theoretical results with an empirical evaluation, demonstrating the practical effectiveness of our approach.</p>","absKo":"<p><em>Learning-augmented algorithms</em>лҠ” мөңк·ј лӘҮ л…„к°„ нҠ№нһҲ online optimization л§ҘлқҪм—җм„ң нҒ° мЈјлӘ©мқ„ л°ӣм•ҳлӢӨ. predictionмқ„ мғқм„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҶ’мқҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©м—җ лҸҷкё°лҘј л°ӣм•„, cachingкіј metrical task system к°ҷмқҖ л¬ём ңлҘј мң„н•ң learning-augmented algorithmм—җм„ң м„ұлҠҘ ліҙмһҘкіј мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” prediction мҲҳ мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ tradeoffлҘј м—°кө¬н•ҳлҠ” нқҗлҰ„мқҙ нҷ•мӮ°лҗҳкі  мһҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” мқҙ м—°кө¬ нқҗлҰ„мқ„ <em>online metric matching</em>мңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм—¬, <em>parsimonious</em> learning-augmented algorithmмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ҳкі  к·ё м„ұлҠҘм—җ лҢҖн•ң lower boundлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҖ мӢӨм ң predictionмқҙ м—ҶлҠ” кІҪмҡ° <em>virtual prediction</em>мқ„ мұ„мӣҢ л„ЈлҠ” л°©мӢқмңјлЎң Follow-the-Prediction frameworkлҘј parsimonious settingмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙл•Ң мӢӨн–ү м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мўӢмқҖ intermediate matchingмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳлҠ” online metric matching algorithmмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјлҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ empirical evaluationлҸ„ мҲҳн–үн–Ҳмңјл©°, мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јмқҙ мӢӨм ңлЎң нҡЁкіјм Ғмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61060","en":"Quantum Algorithms for Triangle Cut Sparsification","ko":"Triangle Cut Sparsificationмқ„ мң„н•ң м–‘мһҗ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ","authors":"Shan Jiang, Pan Peng","pos":"#4618","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=u4klflLAX3","abs":"Triangles capture higher-order structures in graphs and are fundamental to applications such as clustering and network analysis. To enable efficient use of such structures at scale, we study the problem of triangle cut sparsification, which aims to reduce the graph size while approximately preserving triangle counts across every cut. We investigate quantum algorithms for this problem, using triangle listing as our main technical ingredient. In particular, we present a quantum algorithm for triangle listing that, for a graph with $n$ vertices, $m$ edges, and $t$ triangles, runs in time $T_{\\mathrm{q\\text{-}list}} =\\widetilde{O}\\bigl(\\min(n^{5/4}t^{7/12} + n^{7/6}t^{7/9}, m + m^{3/4}t^{1/2},n^{3/2}t^{1/2})\\bigr)$, improving upon the best known classical bounds over a broad range of parameters. Our algorithm is based on a heavyвҖ“light vertex partition and an extension of triangle detection via quantum search and Grover search.  Leveraging this result, we design a quantum algorithm for constructing $\\varepsilon$-triangle cut sparsifiers  of size $\\tilde{O}(n/\\varepsilon^2)$ in time $\\widetilde{O}(T_{\\mathrm{q\\text{-}list}} + \\sqrt{mn}/\\varepsilon)$.  Finally, we demonstrate applications to clustering algorithms based on triangle-related measures and prove a lower bound of $\\Omega(n/\\varepsilon^2)$ on the size of any $\\varepsilon$-triangle cut sparsifiers.","absKo":"мӮјк°Ғнҳ•мқҖ к·ёлһҳн”„мқҳ higher-order structureлҘј нҸ¬м°©н•ҳл©° clusteringкіј network analysis к°ҷмқҖ мқ‘мҡ©м—җм„ң н•өмӢ¬м ҒмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кө¬мЎ°лҘј лҢҖк·ңлӘЁлЎң нҡЁмңЁм ҒмңјлЎң нҷңмҡ©н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” triangle cut sparsification л¬ём ңлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңлҠ” лӘЁл“  cutм—җ кұём№ң triangle countлҘј к·јмӮ¬м ҒмңјлЎң ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң graph sizeлҘј мӨ„мқҙлҠ” кІғмқ„ лӘ©н‘ңлЎң н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” triangle listingмқ„ мЈјмҡ” кё°мҲ м Ғ мҡ”мҶҢлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳм—¬ мқҙ л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң quantum algorithmмқ„ мЎ°мӮ¬н•ңлӢӨ. нҠ№нһҲ, м •м җ мҲҳ $n$, к°„м„  мҲҳ $m$, мӮјк°Ғнҳ• мҲҳ $t$лҘј к°–лҠ” graphм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мӢңк°„ $T_{\\mathrm{q\\text{-}list}} =\\widetilde{O}\\bigl(\\min(n^{5/4}t^{7/12} + n^{7/6}t^{7/9}, m + m^{3/4}t^{1/2},n^{3/2}t^{1/2})\\bigr)$м—җ лҸҷмһ‘н•ҳлҠ” triangle listingмҡ© quantum algorithmмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” л„“мқҖ л§Өк°ңліҖмҲҳ лІ”мң„м—җм„ң м•Ңл Өм§„ мөңм„ мқҳ classical boundлҘј к°ңм„ н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ heavy-light vertex partitionкіј quantum search л°Ҹ Grover searchлҘј нҶөн•ң triangle detectionмқҳ нҷ•мһҘм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нҒ¬кё° $\\tilde{O}(n/\\varepsilon^2)$мқҳ $\\varepsilon$-triangle cut sparsifierлҘј $\\widetilde{O}(T_{\\mathrm{q\\text{-}list}} + \\sqrt{mn}/\\varepsilon)$ мӢңк°„м—җ кө¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” quantum algorithmмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. л§Ҳм§Җл§үмңјлЎң triangle кҙҖл Ё measureлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң н•ҳлҠ” clustering algorithmм—җмқҳ мқ‘мҡ©мқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , мһ„мқҳмқҳ $\\varepsilon$-triangle cut sparsifierмқҳ нҒ¬кё°м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ $\\Omega(n/\\varepsilon^2)$ н•ҳн•ңмқ„ мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"62530","en":"Search Space Synthesis for Parametric Functions","ko":"л§Өк°ңліҖмҲҳ н•ЁмҲҳмқҳ нғҗмғү кіөк°„ н•©м„ұ","authors":"Felix Laarmann, Andreas Pauly, Sebastian BuschjГӨger, Andrea Bommert, Jakob Rehof","pos":"#4619","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=flnsWGAFWv","abs":"<p>We present a general framework for synthesizing search spaces of parametric functions, along with strategies for traversing these spaces to find optima.  We formalize an algebraic theory for the categorical model of parametric functions in finite combinatory logic with predicates (FCLP). Based on a component-oriented synthesis framework for FCLP we automate composition from given components and search for parametric functions. Components are language-agnostic and may be instantiated as any implementation of parametric functions, e.g., as PyTorch modules. A proof-of-concept implementation demonstrates how to represent more specific concepts, such as neural architecture search and hyperparameter optimization, within the framework.</p>","absKo":"<p>мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” parametric functionмқҳ search spaceлҘј н•©м„ұн•ҳкі , мқҙлҹ¬н•ң spaceлҘј нғҗмғүн•ҳм—¬ optimumмқ„ м°ҫкё° мң„н•ң м „лһөк№Ңм§Җ нҸ¬н•Ён•ҳлҠ” мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё frameworkлҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” finite combinatory logic with predicates(FCLP)м—җм„ң parametric functionмқҳ categorical modelм—җ лҢҖн•ң algebraic theoryлҘј м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. FCLPлҘј мң„н•ң component-oriented synthesis frameworkлҘј кё°л°ҳмңјлЎң, мЈјм–ҙм§„ componentлЎңл¶Җн„°мқҳ compositionмқ„ мһҗлҸҷнҷ”н•ҳкі  parametric functionмқ„ нғҗмғүн•ңлӢӨ. componentлҠ” language-agnosticн•ҳл©°, мҳҲлҘј л“Өм–ҙ PyTorch moduleкіј к°ҷмқҙ parametric functionмқҳ м–ҙл–Ө кө¬нҳ„мңјлЎңлҸ„ мқёмҠӨн„ҙмҠӨнҷ”лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. proof-of-concept кө¬нҳ„мқҖ neural architecture searchмҷҖ hyperparameter optimization к°ҷмқҖ лҚ” кө¬мІҙм Ғмқё к°ңл…җмқ„ мқҙ framework м•Ҳм—җм„ң м–ҙл–»кІҢ н‘ңнҳ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҠ”м§Җ ліҙм—¬мӨҖлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62656","en":"State Space Model with Continuous Limit of HiPPO Matrix: Eigenvalue Analysis and Explicit Solution Formula","ko":"HiPPO Matrixмқҳ м—°мҶҚм Ғ к·№н•ңмқ„ к°–лҠ” State Space Model: кі мң к°’ л¶„м„қкіј лӘ…мӢңм Ғ н•ҙ кіөмӢқ","authors":"Atsushi Takabatake, Takaharu Yaguchi","pos":"#4620","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eeRgTFtEjv","abs":"<p>As a lightweight model for sequence processing, an LSSL that uses the HiPPO matrix has been proposed. In this paper, as the continuous limit of the HiPPO Matrix, we propose Continuized-HiPPO Operator. Furthermore, as examples of advantages obtained by using this operator, we show that one can analyze the asymptotic behavior of eigenvalues of a matrix related to the HiPPO matrix, and that the LSSL induced by the continuous limit Continuized-HiPPO Operator admits an explicit solution.</p>","absKo":"<p>sequence processingмқ„ мң„н•ң кІҪлҹү лӘЁлҚёлЎңм„ң HiPPO matrixлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” LSSLмқҙ м ңм•Ҳлҗң л°” мһҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” HiPPO matrixмқҳ continuous limitлЎңм„ң Continuized-HiPPO OperatorлҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мқҙ operatorлҘј мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ м–»лҠ” мһҘм җмқҳ мҳҲлЎң, HiPPO matrixмҷҖ кҙҖл Ёлҗң matrixмқҳ eigenvalueмқҳ asymptotic behaviorлҘј л¶„м„қн•  мҲҳ мһҲкі , continuous limitмқё Continuized-HiPPO Operatorм—җ мқҳн•ҙ мң лҸ„лҗң LSSLмқҙ explicit solutionмқ„ к°–лҠ”лӢӨлҠ” м җмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"62675","en":"An Exponential Separation Between Quantum and Quantum-Inspired Classical Algorithms for Linear Systems","ko":"м„ нҳ• мӢңмҠӨн…ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң Quantum л°Ҹ Quantum-Inspired Classical м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ к°„ м§ҖмҲҳм Ғ л¶„лҰ¬","authors":"Allan GrГёnlund, Kasper Green Larsen","pos":"#4622","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=eTUljZ6e8c","abs":"<p>Achieving a provable exponential quantum speedup for an important machine learning task has been a central research goal since the seminal HHL quantum algorithm for solving linear systems and the subsequent quantum recommender systems algorithm by Kerenidis and Prakash. These algorithms were initially believed to be strong candidates for exponential speedups, but a lower bound ruling out similar classical improvements remained absent. In breakthrough work by Tang, it was demonstrated that this lack of progress in classical lower bounds was for good reasons. Concretely, she gave a classical counterpart of the quantum recommender systems algorithm, reducing the quantum advantage to a mere polynomial. Her approach is quite general and was named \\emph{quantum-inspired classical} algorithms. Since then, almost all the initially exponential quantum machine learning speedups have been reduced to polynomial via new quantum-inspired classical algorithms. From the current state-of-affairs, it is unclear whether we can hope for exponential quantum speedups for any natural machine learning task.  In this work, we present the first such provable exponential separation between quantum and quantum-inspired classical algorithms for the basic problem of solving a linear system when the input matrix is well-conditioned and has sparse rows and columns.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӨ‘мҡ”н•ң machine learning taskм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ң exponential quantum speedupмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҖ, м„ нҳ• мӢңмҠӨн…ңмқ„ н‘ёлҠ” HHL quantum algorithmкіј к·ё л’ӨлҘј мқҙмқҖ KerenidisмҷҖ Prakashмқҳ quantum recommender systems algorithm мқҙнӣ„ н•өмӢ¬ м—°кө¬ лӘ©н‘ңмҳҖлӢӨ. мқҙл“Ө algorithmмқҖ мІҳмқҢм—җлҠ” exponential speedupмқҳ к°•л Ҙн•ң нӣ„ліҙлЎң м—¬кІЁмЎҢм§Җл§Ң, мң мӮ¬н•ң classical improvementлҘј л°°м ңн•ҳлҠ” lower boundлҠ” мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡм•ҳлӢӨ. Tangмқҳ нҡҚкё°м Ғмқё м—°кө¬м—җм„ң, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң classical lower boundмқҳ м§„м „ л¶Җмһ¬к°Җ нғҖлӢ№н•ң мқҙмң к°Җ мһҲм—ҲмқҢмқҙ мһ…мҰқлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, к·ёл…ҖлҠ” quantum recommender systems algorithmмқҳ classical counterpartлҘј м ңмӢңн•ҳм—¬ quantum advantageлҘј лӢЁм§Җ polynomial мҲҳмӨҖмңјлЎң лӮ®м·„лӢӨ. мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ л§Өмҡ° мқјл°ҳм Ғмқҙл©° \\emph{quantum-inspired classical} algorithmмқҙлқјлҠ” мқҙлҰ„мқҙ л¶ҷм—ҲлӢӨ. к·ё мқҙнӣ„, мІҳмқҢм—җ м ңмӢңлҗҳм—ҲлҚҳ кұ°мқҳ лӘЁл“  exponential quantum machine learning speedupмқҖ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ quantum-inspired classical algorithmмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ polynomialлЎң м¶•мҶҢлҗҳм—ҲлӢӨ. нҳ„мһ¬ мғҒнҷ©мңјлЎңлҠ”, мһҗм—°мҠӨлҹ¬мҡҙ м–ҙл–Ө machine learning taskм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ exponential quantum speedupмқ„ кё°лҢҖн•  мҲҳ мһҲмқ„м§Җ л¶Ҳл¶„лӘ…н•ҳлӢӨ. ліё м—°кө¬м—җм„ңлҠ”, мһ…л Ҙ matrixк°Җ well-conditionedмқҙкі  rowмҷҖ columnмқҙ sparseн•ң кё°ліём Ғмқё linear system solving л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ quantum algorithmкіј quantum-inspired classical algorithm мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ мөңмҙҲмқҳ мҰқлӘ… к°ҖлҠҘн•ң exponential separationмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"65196","en":"Convex Basins in Single-Index Model Loss Landscapes: Applications to Robust Recovery under Strong Adversarial Corruption","ko":"Single-Index Model мҶҗмӢӨ м§Җнҳ•мқҳ ліјлЎқ л¶„м§Җ: к°•н•ң м ҒлҢҖм Ғ мҳӨм—ј н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ к°•кұҙ ліөмӣҗ мқ‘мҡ©","authors":"SANTANU DAS, Sagnik Chatterjee, jatin batra","pos":"#4623","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=FtfV0UuRGz","abs":"In this paper, we tackle a fundamental problem in high-dimensional statistics, namely, learning Single Index Models (SIMs) robustly in the presence of heavy-tailed noise and an adversary that can corrupt a constant fraction of both covariates and responses. Prior research on efficient robust recovery only focuses on  monotonic link functions or only limit themselves to Phase Retrieval. Provable efficient robust recovery guarantees for generic nonlinear link functions have remained elusive. In this paper, we obtain the first near-linear time, optimal-sample-complexity robust recovery algorithm for a wide class of nonlinear non-monotonic link functions. Critical to our result is an improved understanding of the squared-loss landscape: we identify a sufficient condition under which a broad class of non linear link functions admit a dimension-independent constant-radius convex basin around the ground truth, establishing statistical identifiability beyond previously known cases. We also leverage second-order Stein's identities to identify a structural condition, that we term Expected Squared Convexity (ESC), that acts as a sufficient condition for spectral initialization techniques to obtain an estimator within the convex basin with error $O(\\epsilon^{1/4})$, even under heavy-tailed noise and strong adversarial contamination. This robust initialization technique can be combined with a robust gradient descent phase to break the spectral error barrier, achieving an improved estimation error of $O(\\sigma\\sqrt{\\epsilon})$. Our non-convex optimization framework gives the first efficient sample and time complexity robust recovery results for activation functions such as GeLU and Swish that act as building blocks of modern deep-learning architectures.","absKo":"ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ кі м°Ёмӣҗ нҶөкі„мқҳ к·јліём Ғмқё л¬ём ң, мҰү heavy-tailed noiseмҷҖ covariate л°Ҹ response лӘЁл‘җмқҳ мқјм • л№„мңЁмқ„ мҳӨм—јмӢңнӮ¬ мҲҳ мһҲлҠ” adversaryк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳлҠ” мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң Single Index Model (SIM)мқ„ robustн•ҳкІҢ н•ҷмҠөн•ҳлҠ” л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё robust recoveryм—җ кҙҖн•ң кё°мЎҙ м—°кө¬лҠ” monotonic link functionм—җл§Ң мҙҲм җмқ„ л§һм¶”кұ°лӮҳ Phase Retrievalм—җл§Ң н•ңм •лҗҳм–ҙ мһҲм—ҲлӢӨ. мқјл°ҳм Ғмқё nonlinear link functionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ provableн•ҳкі  efficientн•ң robust recovery ліҙмһҘмқҖ м—¬м „нһҲ лӢ¬м„ұлҗҳм§Җ лӘ»н–ҲлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ём—җм„ңлҠ” кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң л№„м„ нҳ• non-monotonic link functionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ near-linear timeкіј optimal-sample-complexityлҘј к°–лҠ” мөңмҙҲмқҳ robust recovery algorithmмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кІ°кіјмқҳ н•өмӢ¬мқҖ squared-loss landscapeм—җ лҢҖн•ң н–ҘмғҒлҗң мқҙн•ҙм—җ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” broad classмқҳ non-linear link functionмқҙ ground truth мЈјліҖм—җ dimension-independentн•ң constant-radius convex basinмқ„ к°–кІҢ н•ҳлҠ” м¶©л¶„мЎ°кұҙмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳм—¬, мқҙм „м—җ м•Ңл Өм§„ кІҪмҡ°лҘј л„ҳм–ҙ statistical identifiabilityлҘј нҷ•лҰҪн•ңлӢӨ. лҳҗн•ң second-order Stein's identityлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҙ Expected Squared Convexity (ESC)лқјкі  л¶ҖлҘҙлҠ” кө¬мЎ°м Ғ мЎ°кұҙмқ„ мӢқлі„н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” heavy-tailed noiseмҷҖ к°•н•ң adversarial contamination н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ spectral initialization techniqueмқҙ error $O(\\epsilon^{1/4})$мқё estimatorлҘј convex basin лӮҙлЎң м–»лҠ” м¶©л¶„мЎ°кұҙмңјлЎң мһ‘лҸҷн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ robust initialization techniqueмқҖ мқҙнӣ„ robust gradient descent phaseмҷҖ кІ°н•©лҗҳм–ҙ spectral error barrierлҘј лҸҢнҢҢн•ҳкі  $O(\\sigma\\sqrt{\\epsilon})$мқҳ н–ҘмғҒлҗң estimation errorлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ non-convex optimization frameworkлҠ” нҳ„лҢҖ deep-learning architectureмқҳ кө¬м„ұ мҡ”мҶҢлЎң м“°мқҙлҠ” GeLUмҷҖ Swish к°ҷмқҖ activation functionм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ мөңмҙҲмқҳ нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё sample л°Ҹ time complexity robust recovery кІ°кіјлҘј м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"64822","en":"Parameter-Masked Decoupled Optimization for Cross-Domain Class-Incremental Learning","ko":"Cross-Domain Class-Incremental Learningмқ„ мң„н•ң Parameter-Masked Decoupled Optimization","authors":"Ziqi Gu, Yangguang Liu, Wenxuan Fang, Baotong Su, Dan Wang, Tong Zhang, Chunyan Xu, Zhen Cui","pos":"#602","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=JPcg6VVKeD","abs":"<p>Cross-domain class-incremental learning (CD-CIL) requires models to continuously acquire new classes across shifting domains while retaining previously learned knowledge. Existing approaches often entangle what to update with how to update, resulting in unstable adaptation and severe forgetting under domain shifts. Inspired by the hippocampal learning mechanism that separates rapid adaptation from stable consolidation, we propose Parameter-Masked Decoupled Optimization (PMDO) that disentangles what knowledge is adapted from how learning proceeds in cross-domain class-incremental learning. Specifically, we introduce a domain-aware knowledge decoupler that selectively adapts domain-relevant shared parameters, constraining incremental updates while preserving prior representations. To regulate how learning proceeds, we further design a stability-aware trajectory regulation that guides optimization along transferable and stable optimization trajectories, thereby reducing interference across domain transitions. As a result, PMDO enables effective cross-domain adaptation while mitigating catastrophic forgetting and maintaining long-term learnability. Extensive experiments across multiple benchmarks demonstrate the effectiveness of PMDO and its superiority over state-of-the-art methods.</p>","absKo":"<p>Cross-domain class-incremental learning(CD-CIL)мқҖ modelмқҙ мқҙм „м—җ н•ҷмҠөн•ң м§ҖмӢқмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң shifting domain м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ classлҘј м§ҖмҶҚм ҒмңјлЎң мҠөл“қн•ҙм•ј н•ҳлҠ” кіјм ңмқҙлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҖ мў…мў… л¬ҙм—Үмқ„ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён• м§ҖмҷҖ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠён• м§ҖлҘј м–Ҫм–ҙ лҶ“м•„, domain shift мғҒнҷ©м—җм„ң л¶Ҳм•Ҳм •н•ң adaptationкіј мӢ¬к°Ғн•ң forgettingмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•ңлӢӨ. л№ лҘё м Ғмқ‘кіј м•Ҳм •м Ғмқё consolidationмқ„ л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” hippocampal learning mechanismм—җм„ң мҳҒк°җмқ„ л°ӣм•„, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” cross-domain class-incremental learningм—җм„ң м–ҙл–Ө м§ҖмӢқмқ„ м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮ¬м§ҖмҷҖ н•ҷмҠөмқҙ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м§„н–үлҗҳлҠ”м§ҖлҘј л¶„лҰ¬н•ҳлҠ” Parameter-Masked Decoupled Optimization(PMDO)мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. кө¬мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” domain-aware knowledge decouplerлҘј лҸ„мһ…н•ҳм—¬ domain кҙҖл Ё shared parameterл§Ң м„ нғқм ҒмңјлЎң м Ғмқ‘мӢңнӮӨкі , prior representationмқҖ ліҙмЎҙн•ҳл©ҙм„ң incremental updateлҘј м ңм•Ҫн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҷмҠөмқҙ м–ҙл–»кІҢ м§„н–үлҗ м§ҖлҘј мЎ°м Ҳн•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ transferableн•ҳкі  stableн•ң optimization trajectoryлҘј л”°лқј мөңм Ғнҷ”лҘј мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” stability-aware trajectory regulationмқ„ м„Өкі„н•ҳм—¬ domain м „нҷҳ к°„мқҳ interferenceлҘј мӨ„мқёлӢӨ. к·ё кІ°кіј PMDOлҠ” catastrophic forgettingмқ„ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳкі  мһҘкё°м Ғмқё learnabilityлҘј мң м§Җн•ҳл©ҙм„ң нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё cross-domain adaptationмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ңлӢӨ. м—¬лҹ¬ benchmarkм—җ кұём№ң кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ PMDOмқҳ нҡЁкіјмҷҖ state-of-the-art method лҢҖл№„ мҡ°мҲҳм„ұмқ„ мһ…мҰқн•ңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63995","en":"Multi-Round HumanвҖ“AI Collaboration with User-Specified Requirements","ko":"мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗ м§Җм • мҡ”кө¬мӮ¬н•ӯмқ„ л°ҳмҳҒн•ң лӢӨмӨ‘ лқјмҡҙл“ң HumanвҖ“AI нҳ‘м—…","authors":"Sima Noorani, Shayan Kiyani, Hamed Hassani, George Pappas","pos":"#3603","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=RuZi4or26i","abs":"<p>As humans increasingly rely on multi-round conversational AI for high-stakes decisions, principled frameworks are needed to ensure such interactions reliably improve decision quality. We adopt a human-centric view governed by two principles: counterfactual harm, ensuring the AI does not undermine human strengths, and complementarity, ensuring it adds value where the human is prone to err. We formalize these concepts via user-defined rules, allowing users to specify exactly what harm and complementarity mean for their specific task. We then introduce an online, distribution-free algorithm with finite-sample guarantees that enforces the user-specified constraints over the collaboration dynamics. We evaluate our framework across two interactive settings: LLM-simulated collaboration on a medical diagnostic task and a human crowdsourcing study on a pictorial reasoning task. We show that our online procedure maintains prescribed counterfactual-harm and complementarity violation rates even under non-stationary interaction dynamics. Moreover, tightening or loosening these constraints produces predictable shifts in downstream human accuracy, confirming that the two principles serve as practical levers for steering multi-round collaboration toward better decision quality without the need to model or constrain human behavior.</p>","absKo":"<p>мӮ¬лһҢл“Өмқҙ кі мң„н—ҳ мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м •мқ„ мң„н•ҙ multi-round conversational AIм—җ м җм җ лҚ” мқҳмЎҙн•Ём—җ л”°лқј, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң мғҒнҳёмһ‘мҡ©мқҙ мқҳмӮ¬кІ°м • н’Ҳм§Ҳмқ„ м•Ҳм •м ҒмңјлЎң н–ҘмғҒмӢңнӮӨлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” мӣҗм№ҷ кё°л°ҳ frameworkк°Җ н•„мҡ”н•ҳлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мӣҗм№ҷм—җ мқҳн•ҙ м§Җл°°лҗҳлҠ” human-centric кҙҖм җмқ„ мұ„нғқн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” counterfactual harmмңјлЎң, AIк°Җ мқёк°„мқҳ к°•м җмқ„ нӣјмҶҗн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” complementarityлЎң, мқёк°„мқҙ мӢӨмҲҳн•ҳкё° мү¬мҡҙ л¶Җл¶„м—җм„ң AIк°Җ к°Җм№ҳлҘј лҚ”н•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ҳлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗк°Җ мһҗмӢ мқҳ нҠ№м • taskм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ harmкіј complementarityк°Җ м •нҷ•нһҲ л¬ҙм—Үмқ„ мқҳлҜён•ҳлҠ”м§Җ м§Җм •н•  мҲҳ мһҲлҸ„лЎқ user-defined ruleмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ мқҙ к°ңл…җл“Өмқ„ formalizeн•ңлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ° лӢӨмқҢ нҳ‘м—… dynamics м „л°ҳм—җ кұёміҗ мӮ¬мҡ©мһҗк°Җ м§Җм •н•ң м ңм•Ҫмқ„ к°•м ңн•ҳлҠ”, finite-sample guaranteeлҘј к°–лҠ” online, distribution-free algorithmмқ„ лҸ„мһ…н•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙ frameworkлҘј л‘җ к°Җм§Җ interactive settingм—җм„ң нҸүк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” medical diagnostic taskм—җм„ңмқҳ LLM-simulated collaborationмқҙкі , лӢӨлҘё н•ҳлӮҳлҠ” pictorial reasoning taskм—җм„ңмқҳ human crowdsourcing studyмқҙлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м ңм•Ҳн•ң online procedureк°Җ л№„м •мғҒм Ғ(non-stationary) interaction dynamics н•ҳм—җм„ңлҸ„ к·ңм •лҗң counterfactual-harm л°Ҹ complementarity violation rateлҘј мң м§Җн•Ёмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. лҚ” лӮҳм•„к°Җ мқҙлҹ¬н•ң м ңм•Ҫмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳкұ°лӮҳ мҷ„нҷ”н•ҳл©ҙ downstream human accuracyк°Җ мҳҲмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң л°©мӢқмңјлЎң ліҖн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ л‘җ мӣҗм№ҷмқҙ мқёк°„ н–үлҸҷмқ„ лӘЁлҚёл§Ғн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ м ңм•Ҫн•  н•„мҡ” м—Ҷмқҙ multi-round collaborationмқ„ лҚ” лӮҳмқҖ decision qualityлЎң мң лҸ„н•ҳлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғмқё мЎ°м Ҳ мҲҳлӢЁмһ„мқҙ нҷ•мқёлҗңлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"63411","en":"Length Generalization Bounds for Transformers","ko":"TransformerлҘј мң„н•ң кёёмқҙ мқјл°ҳнҷ” кІҪкі„","authors":"Anthony Lin, Pascal BergstrГӨГҹer, Georg Zetzsche, Andy Yang, David Chiang","pos":"#1011","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=XNXU8BJRT7","abs":"Length generalization is a key property of a learning algorithm that enables it to make correct predictions on inputs of unbounded length, given finite training data. To provide such a guarantee, one needs to be able to compute a length generalization bound, beyond which the model is guaranteed to generalize. This paper concerns the open problem of the computability of such generalization bounds for $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$, which is closely linked to transformers. A positive partial result was recently shown Chen et al. whenever the concept is definable in $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$ with only one layer and, under some restrictions, also with two layers. We provide complete answers to the above open problem. Our main result is the non-existence of computable length generalization bounds for $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$(already with two layers) and hence for transformers. To complement this, we provide a computable bound for concepts representable in the positive fragment of $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$, which we show equivalent to fixed-precision transformers. For both positive $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$ and fixed-precision transformers, we show that the length complexity is exponential, and prove optimality of the bounds.","absKo":"Length generalizationмқҖ мң н•ңн•ң training dataк°Җ мЈјм–ҙмЎҢмқ„ л•Ң л¬ҙн•ң кёёмқҙмқҳ мһ…л Ҙм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ мҳ¬л°”лҘё мҳҲмёЎмқ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ҳкІҢ н•ҳлҠ” learning algorithmмқҳ н•өмӢ¬ м„ұм§ҲмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң ліҙмһҘмқ„ м ңкіөн•ҳл Өл©ҙ, modelмқҙ generalizeн•  кІғмқҙ ліҙмһҘлҗҳлҠ” м§Җм җмқ„ л„ҳм–ҙм„ңлҠ” length generalization boundлҘј кі„мӮ°н•  мҲҳ мһҲм–ҙм•ј н•ңлӢӨ. ліё л…јл¬ёмқҖ transformerмҷҖ л°Җм ‘н•ҳкІҢ кҙҖл Ёлҗң $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$м—җ лҢҖн•ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң generalization boundмқҳ computabilityлқјлҠ” м—ҙлҰ° л¬ём ңлҘј лӢӨлЈ¬лӢӨ. мөңк·ј Chen et al.мқҖ к°ңл…җмқҙ $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$м—җм„ң лӢЁ н•ң к°ңмқҳ layerлЎң м •мқҳ к°ҖлҠҘн•  л•Ң, к·ёлҰ¬кі  мқјл¶Җ м ңн•ң н•ҳм—җм„ңлҠ” л‘җ к°ңмқҳ layerлЎңлҸ„ м •мқҳ к°ҖлҠҘн•  л•Ң м–‘мқҳ л¶Җл¶„ кІ°кіјлҘј ліҙмҳҖлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мң„ м—ҙлҰ° л¬ём ңм—җ лҢҖн•ң мҷ„м „н•ң лӢөмқ„ м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мЈјлҗң кІ°кіјлҠ” $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$(мқҙлҜё л‘җ к°ңмқҳ layerлҘј к°–лҠ” кІҪмҡ°м—җлҸ„)м—җ лҢҖн•ҙ computable length generalization boundк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, л”°лқјм„ң transformerм—җ лҢҖн•ҙм„ңлҸ„ л§Ҳм°¬к°Җм§ҖлқјлҠ” кІғмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј ліҙмҷ„н•ҳкё° мң„н•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$мқҳ positive fragmentлЎң н‘ңнҳ„ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң к°ңл…җм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ computable boundлҘј м ңкіөн•ҳкі , мқҙ fragmentк°Җ fixed-precision transformerмҷҖ лҸҷм№ҳмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ. positive $\\mathsf{C}$-$\\mathsf{RASP}$мҷҖ fixed-precision transformer лӘЁл‘җм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ length complexityк°Җ exponentialмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқҙл©°, мқҙлҹ¬н•ң boundмқҳ optimalityлҘј мҰқлӘ…н•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65526","en":"Optimized Deferral for Imbalanced Settings","ko":"л¶Ҳк· нҳ• м„Өм •мқ„ мң„н•ң мөңм Ғнҷ”лҗң мң мҳҲ","authors":"Corinna Cortes, Anqi Mao, Mehryar Mohri, Yutao Zhong","pos":"#3015","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=CfqUMty4Ns","abs":"<p>Learning algorithms can be significantly improved by routing complex or uncertain inputs to specialized experts, balancing accuracy with computational cost. This approach, known as <em>learning to defer</em>, is essential in domains like natural language generation, medical diagnosis, and computer vision, where an effective deferral can reduce errors at low extra resource consumption.  However, the two-stage learning to defer setting, which leverages existing predictors such as a collection of LLMs or other classifiers, often faces challenges due to an expert imbalance problem. This imbalance can lead to suboptimal performance, with deferral algorithms favoring the majority expert. We present a comprehensive study of two-stage learning to defer in expert imbalance settings. We cast the deferral loss optimization as a novel cost-sensitive learning problem over the input-expert domain. We derive new margin-based loss functions and guarantees tailored to this setting, and develop novel algorithms for cost-sensitive learning. Leveraging these results, we design principled deferral algorithms, MILD (<em>Margin-based Imbalanced Learning to Defer</em>), specifically suited for expert imbalance settings. Extensive experiments demonstrate the effectiveness of our approach, showing clear improvements over existing baselines on both image classification and real-world Large Language Model (LLM) routing tasks.</p>","absKo":"<p>н•ҷмҠө м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқҖ ліөмһЎн•ҳкұ°лӮҳ л¶Ҳнҷ•мӢӨн•ң мһ…л Ҙмқ„ нҠ№нҷ”лҗң м „л¬ёк°Җ(expert)м—җкІҢ лқјмҡ°нҢ…н•ЁмңјлЎңмҚЁ, м •нҷ•лҸ„мҷҖ кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ© мӮ¬мқҙмқҳ к· нҳ•мқ„ л§һм¶”л©° нҒ¬кІҢ к°ңм„ лҗ  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. <em>learning to defer</em>лЎң м•Ңл Өм§„ мқҙ м ‘к·јмқҖ natural language generation, medical diagnosis, computer vision к°ҷмқҖ лҸ„л©”мқём—җм„ң н•„мҲҳм Ғмқҙл©°, нҡЁкіјм Ғмқё deferлҠ” м ҒмқҖ м¶”к°Җ мһҗмӣҗ мҶҢл№„лЎң мҳӨлҘҳлҘј мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. к·ёлҹ¬лӮҳ кё°мЎҙ predictor м§‘н•©мқҙлӮҳ лӢӨлҘё classifierмҷҖ к°ҷмқҖ кё°мЎҙ мҳҲмёЎкё°лҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳлҠ” two-stage learning to defer м„Өм •мқҖ expert imbalance л¬ём ңлЎң мқён•ҙ мў…мў… м–ҙл ӨмӣҖмқ„ кІӘлҠ”лӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң л¶Ҳк· нҳ•мқҖ deferral algorithmмқҙ лӢӨмҲҳнҢҢ expertлҘј м„ нҳён•ҳкІҢ л§Ңл“Өм–ҙ мөңм Ғ мқҙн•ҳмқҳ м„ұлҠҘмқ„ мҙҲлһҳн•  мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” expert imbalance м„Өм •м—җм„ңмқҳ two-stage learning to deferм—җ лҢҖн•ң нҸ¬кҙ„м Ғмқё м—°кө¬лҘј м ңмӢңн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” deferral loss optimizationмқ„ input-expert domain мң„мқҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ cost-sensitive learning problemмңјлЎң м •мӢқнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өм •м—җ л§һм¶ҳ мғҲлЎңмҡҙ margin-based loss functionкіј ліҙмһҘмқ„ лҸ„м¶ңн•ҳкі , cost-sensitive learningмқ„ мң„н•ң мғҲлЎңмҡҙ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ к°ңл°ңн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҹ¬н•ң кІ°кіјлҘј нҷңмҡ©н•ҳм—¬, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” expert imbalance м„Өм •м—җ нҠ№нһҲ м Ғн•©н•ң мӣҗм№ҷм Ғмқё deferral algorithmмқё MILD(<em>Margin-based Imbalanced Learning to Defer</em>)лҘј м„Өкі„н•ңлӢӨ. кҙ‘лІ”мң„н•ң мӢӨн—ҳмқҖ мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ м ‘к·јлІ•мқҳ нҡЁкіјлҘј мһ…мҰқн•ҳл©°, image classificationкіј мӢӨм ң Large Language Model(LLM) routing task лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң кё°мЎҙ baselineліҙлӢӨ л¶„лӘ…н•ң н–ҘмғҒмқ„ ліҙмқёлӢӨ.</p>"},{"id":"61334","en":"Practical and Optimal Algorithm for Linear Contextual Bandits with Rare Parameter Updates","ko":"л“ңл¬ё нҢҢлқјлҜён„° м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠёлҘј к°–лҠ” Linear Contextual Banditмқ„ мң„н•ң мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ мөңм Ғ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ","authors":"Sanghoon Yu, Min-hwan Oh","pos":"#4510","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=rEqVnZZOiA","abs":"We study linear contextual bandits under rare parameter updates: the learner may incorporate reward feedback into its parameter estimate only at a small number of update times, while still observing contexts online and selecting actions sequentially. This viewpoint clarifies a practical distinction that is often blurred in the literature: many \"strictly batched\" methods additionally restrict within-interval context adaptivity, meaning that the action rule inside an interval cannot depend on the sequence of realized contexts/actions in that interval (beyond the current round's context). For linear contextual bandits, we propose two practical algorithms with only $O(\\log\\log T)$ parameter updates. Our first algorithm BLCE-G attains minimax-optimal regret (up to polylogarithmic factors in $T$) simultaneously in both the small-$K$ and large-$K$ regimes under a static schedule. Our second algorithm BLCE removes the near G-optimal design step---a dominant computational bottleneck in prior strictly batched static-grid methods---yet preserves minimax-optimal regret and achieves the lowest known runtime complexity among optimal algorithms. We further extend these rare-update and computational principles to generalized linear contextual bandits. Overall, our results yield statistically optimal algorithms under $O(\\log\\log T)$ parameter updates that are also computationally efficient in practice.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” нқ¬к·Җн•ң parameter update н•ҳм—җм„ңмқҳ linear contextual banditмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мҰү, н•ҷмҠөмһҗлҠ” reward feedbackмқ„ лӢЁм§Җ мҶҢмҲҳмқҳ update мӢңм җм—җм„ңл§Ң parameter estimateм—җ л°ҳмҳҒн•  мҲҳ мһҲм§Җл§Ң, contextлҠ” мҳЁлқјмқёмңјлЎң кҙҖмёЎн•ҳкі  actionмқҖ мҲңм°Ём ҒмңјлЎң м„ нғқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ кҙҖм җмқҖ л¬ён—Ңм—җм„ң мһҗмЈј нқҗл Өм§ҖлҠ” мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ кө¬л¶„мқ„ л¶„лӘ…нһҲ н•ҙмӨҖлӢӨ. л§ҺмқҖ \"strictly batched\" л°©лІ•мқҖ м¶”к°ҖлЎң interval лӮҙл¶Җмқҳ context adaptivityк№Ңм§Җ м ңн•ңн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” interval лӮҙм—җм„ңмқҳ action ruleмқҙ нҳ„мһ¬ roundмқҳ contextлҘј м ңмҷён•ҳл©ҙ к·ё кө¬к°„м—җм„ң мӢӨнҳ„лҗң context/actionмқҳ мҲңм„ңм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•  мҲҳ м—ҶмқҢмқ„ мқҳлҜён•ңлӢӨ. linear contextual banditм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ, мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лӢЁм§Җ $O(\\log\\log T)$лІҲмқҳ parameter updateл§Ң мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҳлҠ” л‘җ к°Җм§Җ мӢӨмҡ©м Ғ м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ мІ« лІҲм§ё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ BLCE-GлҠ” static schedule н•ҳм—җм„ң small-$K$мҷҖ large-$K$ regime лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң minimax-optimal regretмқ„ (Tм—җ лҢҖн•ң polylogarithmic factorк№Ңм§Җ) лҸҷмӢңм—җ лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. л‘җ лІҲм§ё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ BLCEлҠ” кё°мЎҙ strictly batched static-grid л°©лІ•мқҳ м§Җл°°м Ғмқё кі„мӮ° лі‘лӘ©мқҙм—ҲлҚҳ near G-optimal design лӢЁкі„лҘј м ңкұ°н•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„ minimax-optimal regretмқ„ мң м§Җн•ҳкі , optimal м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳ мӨ‘ м•Ңл Өм§„ к°ҖмһҘ лӮ®мқҖ runtime complexityлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” лҳҗн•ң мқҙлҹ¬н•ң нқ¬к·Җ м—…лҚ°мқҙнҠё л°Ҹ кі„мӮ° мӣҗлҰ¬лҘј generalized linear contextual banditмңјлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ңлӢӨ. м „мІҙм ҒмңјлЎң мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ кІ°кіјлҠ” $O(\\log\\log T)$лІҲмқҳ parameter update н•ҳм—җм„ң нҶөкі„м ҒмңјлЎң мөңм Ғмқј лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј мӢӨм ңлЎңлҸ„ кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё м•Ңкі лҰ¬мҰҳмқ„ м ңкіөн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"65438","en":"Generalized Linear Bandits with Memory","ko":"л©”лӘЁлҰ¬лҘј к°–м¶ҳ мқјл°ҳнҷ” м„ нҳ• Bandit","authors":"Heesang Ann, Hyun-jun Choi, Taehyun Hwang, Younghoon Shin, Haeju Cheong, Min-hwan Oh","pos":"#4511","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=DfZS0M8leJ","abs":"We study generalized linear bandits with memory, a non-stationary setting in which rewards depend on past actions through a finite memory matrix. Building on prior work for linear models Clerici et al.,(2024), we show that the previously known $\\tilde{\\mathcal{O}}(T^{3/4})$ regret stems from a loose analysis based on cyclic proxy policies, and we refine the analysis to recover a $\\tilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\sqrt{T})$ regret rate in the linear case. We then extend this improvement to generalized linear models and propose a block-wise algorithm based on shrinkage-based confidence bounds. Our algorithm achieves a regret bound of $\\tilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\sqrt{mT}+ d\\sqrt{T}+\\sqrt{\\kappa} d^{2} m^{1/4} T^{1/4} + \\kappa d^{2})$, where $d$ denotes the feature dimension, $m$ the memory length, and $\\kappa$ a curvature parameter of the link function, thereby attaining a $\\sqrt{T}$ rate despite nonlinear rewards and memory effects. To the best of our knowledge, this analysis provides a unified treatment of memory-induced non-stationarity and nonlinear link functions, while ensuring that the leading regret term is independent of the curvature of the link function. We conduct numerical experiments that are consistent with our theoretical findings.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” memoryлҘј к°Җм§„ generalized linear banditsлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙлҠ” ліҙмғҒмқҙ finite memory matrixлҘј нҶөн•ҙ кіјкұ° н–үлҸҷм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳлҠ” non-stationary settingмқҙлӢӨ. м„ н–ү м—°кө¬мқё linear model Clerici et al.,(2024)лҘј л°”нғ•мңјлЎң, мқҙм „м—җ м•Ңл Өм§„ $\\tilde{\\mathcal{O}}(T^{3/4})$ regretлҠ” cyclic proxy policyм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң лҠҗмҠЁн•ң л¶„м„қм—җм„ң л№„лЎҜлҗң кІғмһ„мқ„ ліҙмқҙкі , linear caseм—җм„ң $\\tilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\sqrt{T})$ regret rateлҘј нҡҢліөн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ л¶„м„қмқ„ м •көҗнҷ”н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙм–ҙм„ң мқҙ к°ңм„ мқ„ generalized linear modelлЎң нҷ•мһҘн•ҳкі , shrinkage-based confidence boundм—җ кё°л°ҳн•ң block-wise algorithmмқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬мқҳ algorithmмқҖ $\\tilde{\\mathcal{O}}(\\sqrt{mT}+ d\\sqrt{T}+\\sqrt{\\kappa} d^{2} m^{1/4} T^{1/4} + \\kappa d^{2})$мқҳ regret boundлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, м—¬кё°м„ң $d$лҠ” feature dimension, $m$мқҖ memory length, $\\kappa$лҠ” link functionмқҳ curvature parameterлҘј лң»н•ҳл©°, мқҙлЎңмҚЁ nonlinear rewardмҷҖ memory effectк°Җ мЎҙмһ¬н•Ём—җлҸ„ л¶Ҳкө¬н•ҳкі  $\\sqrt{T}$ rateлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬к°Җ м•„лҠ” н•ң, мқҙ л¶„м„қмқҖ memory-induced non-stationarityмҷҖ nonlinear link functionмқ„ н•ҳлӮҳлЎң л¬¶м–ҙ лӢӨлЈЁлҠ” нҶөн•©м Ғ мІҳлҰ¬лҘј м ңкіөн•ҳл©ҙм„ңлҸ„, leading regret termмқҙ link functionмқҳ curvatureмҷҖ л¬ҙкҙҖн•ҳлҸ„лЎқ ліҙмһҘн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” мқҙлЎ м Ғ кІ°кіјмҷҖ мқјм№ҳн•ҳлҠ” мҲҳм№ҳ мӢӨн—ҳмқ„ мҲҳн–үн•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"61445","en":"Follow-the-Perturbed-Leader for Decoupled Bandits: Best-of-Both-Worlds and Practicality","ko":"Decoupled BanditsлҘј мң„н•ң Follow-the-Perturbed-Leader: Best-of-Both-WorldsмҷҖ мӢӨмҡ©м„ұ","authors":"Chaiwon Kim, Jongyeong Lee, Min-hwan Oh","pos":"#4512","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=q1KhliMwKP","abs":"We study the decoupled multi-armed bandit problem, where the learner selects one arm for exploration and one arm for exploitation separately at each round. In this setting, the loss of the explored arm is observed but not incurred, whereas the loss of the exploited arm is incurred without being observed. We propose an efficient Follow-the-Perturbed-Leader (FTPL) policy that achieves Best-of-Both-Worlds (BOBW) guarantee with constant regret in the stochastic regime and optimal $\\mathcal{O}(\\sqrt{KT})$ regret in the adversarial regime. A key feature of our method is that it completely avoids both the convex optimization required by prior BOBW policy, and the resampling procedures that are typically used in FTPL bandit policies. This allows FTPL to fully realize its computational efficiency advantages, and thus leads to substantial reductions in computational cost. We empirically confirm that our policy not only improves the runtime but also demonstrates superior regret performance in both regimes.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” decoupled multi-armed bandit л¬ём ңлҘј м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ л¬ём ңм—җм„ң н•ҷмҠөмһҗлҠ” к°Ғ лқјмҡҙл“ңл§ҲлӢӨ нғҗмғүмҡ© arm н•ҳлӮҳмҷҖ нҷңмҡ©мҡ© arm н•ҳлӮҳлҘј к°Ғк°Ғ м„ нғқн•ңлӢӨ. мқҙ м„Өм •м—җм„ң нғҗмғүн•ң armмқҳ lossлҠ” кҙҖмёЎлҗҳм§Җл§Ң мӢӨм ңлЎңлҠ” л°ңмғқн•ҳм§Җ м•Ҡмңјл©°, нҷңмҡ©н•ң armмқҳ lossлҠ” кҙҖмёЎлҗҳм§Җ м•Ҡм§Җл§Ң мӢӨм ңлЎң л°ңмғқн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” stochastic regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” constant regret, adversarial regimeм—җм„ңлҠ” мөңм Ғмқҳ $\\mathcal{O}(\\sqrt{KT})$ regretмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” нҡЁмңЁм Ғмқё Follow-the-Perturbed-Leader(FTPL) м •мұ…мқ„ м ңм•Ҳн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬ л°©лІ•мқҳ н•өмӢ¬ нҠ№м§•мқҖ кё°мЎҙ BOBW policyм—җм„ң мҡ”кө¬лҗҳлҠ” convex optimizationмқ„ мҷ„м „нһҲ н”јн•ҳкі , FTPL bandit policyм—җм„ң мқјл°ҳм ҒмңјлЎң мӮ¬мҡ©лҗҳлҠ” resampling м Ҳм°ЁлҸ„ л°°м ңн•ңлӢӨлҠ” м җмқҙлӢӨ. мқҙлҘј нҶөн•ҙ FTPLмқҳ кі„мӮ° нҡЁмңЁм„ұ мқҙм җмқ„ мҳЁм „нһҲ мӢӨнҳ„н•  мҲҳ мһҲмңјл©°, кІ°кіјм ҒмңјлЎң кі„мӮ° л№„мҡ©мқ„ нҒ¬кІҢ мӨ„мқј мҲҳ мһҲлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” м ңм•Ҳн•ң м •мұ…мқҙ runtimeмқ„ к°ңм„ н•  лҝҗ м•„лӢҲлқј л‘җ regime лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң лҚ” мҡ°мҲҳн•ң regret м„ұлҠҘмқ„ ліҙмһ„мқ„ мӢӨн—ҳм ҒмңјлЎң нҷ•мқён•ңлӢӨ."},{"id":"62858","en":"Bilinear Bandits with Partially Observable Features","ko":"л¶Җл¶„ кҙҖмёЎ нҠ№м§•мқ„ к°Җм§„ Bilinear Bandits","authors":"Wooseong Cho, Ji Hyeong Park, Min-hwan Oh","pos":"#4513","link":"https://openreview.net/forum?id=cTiEi0D7g6","abs":"We study bilinear bandits with partially observable features on both the user and item sides. In each of $T$ rounds, the learner selects an arm and observes only the reward for the chosen pair. The reward model     is linear in the user and item features with an unknown parameter matrix. Existing literature commonly reduces this problem to a linear bandit via a Kronecker product representation of user and item features, at the cost of increased dimensionality.     We propose \\texttt{BiRoLF}, an algorithm robust to latent features, which directly leverages the bilinear structure without such linearization. It enhances feature selection by augmenting the null space of the observed features and employs doubly robust (DR) estimation to impute unobserved rewards for unselected arms, constructing unbiased pseudo-rewards. We estimate the parameters using Lasso regularization, which promotes sparsity in the coefficients of latent components orthogonal to the observed features.     \\texttt{BiRoLF} achieves a $\\tilde{O}(\\sqrt{(d_x + d_{h_x})(d_y + d_{h_y}) T})$ regret bound, where $d_x$ and $d_y$ are the dimensions of the observable feature vectors, $d_{h_x}$ and $d_{h_y}$ denote the numbers of nonzero coefficients in the components orthogonal to the observed features. We segment cases by the relationship between observable and latent features and find that \\texttt{BiRoLF} achieves strong regret performance while outperforming competing methods in computational metrics, reducing the overhead of feature linearization.","absKo":"мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” user мёЎкіј item мёЎ лӘЁл‘җм—җм„ң partially observable featureлҘј к°–лҠ” bilinear banditмқ„ м—°кө¬н•ңлӢӨ. к°Ғ $T$ roundм—җм„ң learnerлҠ” arm н•ҳлӮҳлҘј м„ нғқн•ҳкі  м„ нғқлҗң pairмқҳ rewardл§Ң кҙҖмёЎн•ңлӢӨ. reward modelмқҖ м•Ңл Өм§Җм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ parameter matrixлҘј к°–лҠ” userмҷҖ item featureм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ linearн•ҳлӢӨ. кё°мЎҙ л¬ён—ҢмқҖ мқҙ л¬ём ңлҘј userмҷҖ item featureмқҳ Kronecker product representationмқ„ нҶөн•ҙ linear banditмңјлЎң нҷҳмӣҗн•ҳлҠ” кІҪмҡ°к°Җ л§Һм§Җл§Ң, к·ё лҢҖк°ҖлЎң м°Ёмӣҗмқҙ мҰқк°Җн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” latent featureм—җ кІ¬кі н•ң \\texttt{BiRoLF}лҘј м ңм•Ҳн•ҳл©°, мқҙлҠ” bilinear structureлҘј м§Ғм ‘ нҷңмҡ©н•ҳкі  мқҙлҹ¬н•ң linearizationм—җ мқҳмЎҙн•ҳм§Җ м•ҠлҠ”лӢӨ. кҙҖмёЎлҗң featureмқҳ null spaceлҘј нҷ•мһҘн•ҳм—¬ feature selectionмқ„ к°•нҷ”н•ҳкі , doubly robust(DR) estimationмқ„ мӮ¬мҡ©н•ҙ м„ нғқлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ armмқҳ кҙҖмёЎлҗҳм§Җ м•ҠмқҖ rewardлҘј лҢҖмһ…н•ҳм—¬ unbiased pseudo-rewardлҘј кө¬м„ұн•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” Lasso regularizationмңјлЎң parameterлҘј м¶”м •н•ҳлҠ”лҚ°, мқҙлҠ” кҙҖмёЎлҗң featureм—җ м§Ғкөҗн•ҳлҠ” latent componentмқҳ coefficientм—җ лҢҖн•ҙ sparsityлҘј мҙүм§„н•ңлӢӨ. \\texttt{BiRoLF}лҠ” $\\tilde{O}(\\sqrt{(d_x + d_{h_x})(d_y + d_{h_y}) T})$ regret boundлҘј лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳл©°, м—¬кё°м„ң $d_x$мҷҖ $d_y$лҠ” кҙҖмёЎ к°ҖлҠҘн•ң feature vectorмқҳ м°Ёмӣҗмқҙкі , $d_{h_x}$мҷҖ $d_{h_y}$лҠ” кҙҖмёЎлҗң featureм—җ м§Ғкөҗн•ҳлҠ” componentм—җм„ңмқҳ nonzero coefficient мҲҳлҘј мқҳлҜён•ңлӢӨ. мҡ°лҰ¬лҠ” observable featureмҷҖ latent featureмқҳ кҙҖкі„м—җ л”°лқј caseлҘј кө¬л¶„н•ҳм—¬, \\texttt{BiRoLF}к°Җ к°•н•ң regret м„ұлҠҘмқ„ лӢ¬м„ұн•ҳлҠ” лҸҷмӢңм—җ кі„мӮ° мёЎл©ҙ м§Җн‘ңм—җм„ңлҸ„ кІҪмҹҒ л°©лІ•л“Өмқ„ лҠҘк°Җн•ҳл©° feature linearizationмқҳ мҳӨлІ„н—Өл“ңлҘј мӨ„мқёлӢӨлҠ” мӮ¬мӢӨмқ„ нҷ•мқён–ҲлӢӨ."}];window.dispatchEvent(new CustomEvent("papers-loaded",{detail:"68691"}));